[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Welcome to This Course!"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ Howdy, y'all!   First of all, it means a great deal to me that you've decided to check out my course on 1. e4. Thank you so much. The course's purpose is to provide you with a kick-ass repertoire that you can brandish to cause havoc for all of your opponents, as the proper way to play with the white pieces is to fight for a win right off the bat.   The first thing you will notice about the course is the enormous size of it. I've genuinely gone out of my way to cover as much ground as possible, as I believe a repertoire should cover all popular replies. Otherwise, it's not a complete repertoire. ;@@EndBracket@@ However, I don't want it to be too overwhelming for you guys either, so there is a substantial amount of clickables in the course to make the memorization less demanding.    ABOUT METhe dude behind the keyboard is IM Sebastian Mihajlov and IM and IM @@StartBracket@@yes, my sense of humor@@EndBracket@@ from Norway. My dad, a reasonably respectable chess player himself, rated around 2150, taught me this game when I was seven years old. It did not take long until I was hooked, studying daily. My best achievement as a player was to win several Norwegian Championships, notably the Junior Championship when I was 15 years old. I became an IM when I was 17 and a half.   My greatest chess strength has always been opening theory, which I studied in great depth by reading chess books. I became famous for my notorious slav, which I even drew Ding Liren with back in 2013. He was rated 2709 at the time. In the same tournament, I lost to a player around 1900, but that's another story! :D    THE STRUCTUREIn the course, you will find every possible reply from Black @@StartBracket@@except moves such as 1...a5/1...h5/1...f5, etc., as I trust your judgment against those moves@@EndBracket@@ except 1...e5 and 1... c5. Including both would give this repertoire an astronomical size, so splitting the repertoire into two halves was the only sensible thing to do.   The course was created using the Online Database, my previous theoretical knowledge, some opening books, and, most importantly, a potent engine in the cloud. Yes, the latter is crucial, as a regular laptop like mine will only run at a puny 3000 kN/s and 4CPUs, while the ones in the cloud often reach 100.000+ kN/s and 64 CPUs. The impact this difference has can't be overstated. This is an expensive affair for sure, but it's essential to provide you with the world-class analysis you guys deserve. Don't worry about everything being too complicated, though, as I have made sure that everything is thoroughly explained. The lines themselves rely a lot on what's best objectively speaking, as one would expect when using the engine as a guiding beacon.   However, there are some elements of practicality as well. For instance, if there are two excellent approaches, I will always settle for the less complicated one. Another example would be to settle for something less dangerous in exchange for simple positions to play, understand, and psychological points. A great example of this would be the Philidor Defence, where I settled for the exchange variation. I won't provide too many details here, but I will say that the positions are easy to handle while playing Black is very unfun. Other moves are more dangerous on paper, but they give Black the complications he desires.    WHY 1. e4?Being so passionate about books, I always dreamt about writing one of my own. Being a content creator on chess24, I was handed the task of creating a video series. For purely selfish reasons, I approached the project of 'Destroying the French,' as I always struggled against this opening. After the work was published, I received positive reviews, and people were eager to see more. The reasonable step was to make an entire repertoire, but this time my dream would be fulfilled, as I had the enormous task of essentially writing a book on such a massive topic. Chessable became the perfect fit.   1. e4 is considered to be 'Best by Test' by Bobby Fischer. We fight for the initiative right out of the gate; we take control over the center, grab space, and prepare for a quick kingside casting. This tends to lead to sharp, complicated, and very entertaining positions filled to the brim with tactics and positional themes that I feel are lackluster in, for example, 1. d4-positions. One example would be the positions we get in the Winawer, some of the most fascinating and complicated positions in the game of chess. This makes for an excellent way to fight for an edge with the white pieces and an excellent opportunity to strike down players with a higher rating.    HARD WORK WILL PAY OFFI know that this is a lot of work, but in chess, there are no shortcuts to reach the highest heights of the chess summit. I can assure you, however, that you will get rewarded handsomely if you do study hard and do your homework. The lines are venomous to the core, so you will give Black a tough time - as one should when playing with White! I suggest that you take your time, inhale and exhale the different ideas and plans. Ideas and plans are usually more important, as I know it's impossible to remember everything. Unless you're that guy from Suits... Some places are required memorization, though, but I do highlight that in my writing. Use the tool called online chess for all that it's worth, and test out the repertoire in games online. Analyze the games when you're done, and go back to the repertoire and check where you went wrong. I also suggest remaining anonymous, so people can't spot your new hardcore weapon ;@@EndBracket@@   I wish you the best of luck in your quest. Most of the work is done by me, so all you have to do is study it hard and learn it! You have the move-trainer at hand, so use it! It is all up to YOU! If you have any questions, feel free to contact me personally or write in the forum. I'll be happy to respond.     THANK YOU   I want to end the introduction by thanking the entire Chessable staff, you @@StartBracket@@the readers@@EndBracket@@, my family, and my great buddies Israel, Zoras, and kramnikstudent for all the incredible support along the way. I indeed couldn't have done this without you.     Regards,   Sebastian Horgen Mihajlov   Limón, Costa Rica 2021 }
*

