[Black "Czech Pirc 4...Qa5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 c6 4. f4 Qa5
{ The main move which should be no surprise. } 5. Bd3
{ This is objectively the best way to proceed, but it does contain an annoying amount of theory. My colleague and very slightly better chess player GM Wesley So advocates for  5.e5  as it is more concrete and trickier. Not a bad choice either, so feel free to investigate it. It is not as strong as the text move, though. }
5... e5 { Black's idea, and by far the most popular move. } 6. Nf3
{ Black now has three different ways of defending the pawn on d4. } 6... Bg4
{ Defending the e5 pawn with a pin is the most common way to proceed. } 7. Be3
{ This developing move is natural, defending the pawn on d4. } 7... exf4
{ The most popular alternative to the Main Line. } 8. Bxf4 Qb4
{ This is Black's most popular move, but it loses. } 9. a3
{ Go ahead, take the pawn on b2! } 9... Qxb2
{ I'm surprised that Black has played this twelve times, as it loses the queen.   9...Bxf3  Seems necessary.  10.axb4  I don't want to give away the pawn on d4, although that also gives us a great position.  10...Bxd1  11.Kxd1  Be7  12.b5  Preparing to take on c6 in the future, which will some day follow by a rook move to a6, doubling on the a-file.  12...O-O  13.Re1  Black has a nightmare of an endgame to defend. }
10. Na4 Bxf3 11. gxf3 Qxd4 12. c3
{ Black's queen is trapped, so it's not surprising that Black chose to resign here in 3/4 games. }
