[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter − 1.e4 Sidelines"]
[Black "Pirc 4...a6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6
{ Here we have arrived at the opening sequence that defines the Pirc Defense. The opening tends to lead to exciting and complicated games, which is why the opening is often utilized by higher-rated players who badly needs a win with the black pieces. On top level you won't see this opening occur often, as White has numerous dangerous ways of fighting it, making the opening a risky choice. Just like most openings, White needs to know what he's doing in order to fight for an edge, so we must be prepared! }
4. Be3 { We will play in similar fashion to the Modern Defense. } 4... a6
{ Black can choose to delay Bg7 and play a6 already here. It's suggested by IM Christof Sielecki in his Pirc Course, as he is not a fan of the fact that Bh6 often comes when Black has played Bg7, which makes sense. }
5. h3 { I think this is the best way to fight against Black's set-up. } 5...
Bg7
{ This move is the most popular move, and the suggested approach by IM Sielecki. He refrained from playing this one move earlier, but justifies the move now as we now longer can use the 'caveman approach' with Bh6 against it. An accurate summation. }
6. g4
{ A very interesting move where White aims to develop the bishop to g2 and the knight to e2. Black also needs to be careful of a potential g5-thrust. The more common 6. f4 is definitely worth investigating, and GM Wesley So goes through it in great depth in his excellent 1. e4 course. }
6... b5 { Is not accurate here, due to } 7. e5
{ The opening of the diagonal benefits us. } 7... Nfd7
{ Should be tried, but Black's position is definitely not impressive after   7...dxe5?  Leads to an awful endgame after  8.dxe5  Qxd1+  9.Rxd1  Nfd7  10.Bg2  c6  11.f4+-  White has a fantastic center and much better pieces. }
8. Bg2 { Black desired to place the bishop on b7, but we are one step ahead! }
8... c6 9. f4 O-O 10. Qf3
{ There's nothing wrong with 10. Nf3 either, but White wanted to place the knight on e2. }
10... Nb6 11. Nge2 { Look at our fantastic center! } 11... a5
{ Black attempts to create something on the queenside, but our kingside attack is just too powerful! }
12. h4 Nc4 13. h5
{ White keeps attacking and ignores the fact that the g4 pawn is hanging. }
13... Nxe3 14. Qxe3 Bxg4 15. hxg6 { White has successfully opened the h-file. }
15... fxg6 16. Rh4 Qd7 17. O-O-O
{ White's attack was decisive in Even,R - Nyvlt,Z ICCF email 2017. } *

