[Black "Pirc 4...Bg7 5.f3 a6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6
{ Here we have arrived at the opening sequence that defines the Pirc Defense. The opening tends to lead to exciting and complicated games, which is why the opening is often utilized by higher-rated players who badly needs a win with the black pieces. On top level you won't see this opening occur often, as White has numerous dangerous ways of fighting it, making the opening a risky choice. Just like most openings, White needs to know what he's doing in order to fight for an edge, so we must be prepared! }
4. Be3 { We will play in similar fashion to the Modern Defense. } 4... Bg7
{ Black keeps us guessing with this move as he can play O-O, a6 or c6! It was not easy for me to come up with something that battles all of these set-ups, but I eventually came to the conclusion that the text move is best. }
5. f3
{ We go for the set-up we saw in the Modern Defense, f3-Be3-Qd2-O-O-O etc. I had a tough time deciding which move to go for. White has so many good options against Pirc/Modern so I felt like a kid in a candy store. }
5... a6
{ Black should play a6 before castling. Black's play is similar to the Modern Defense. He plans to place a bishop on b7, a knight on d7 and will eventually follow up with c5 or b4-a5. }
6. Qd2 Nbd7 7. O-O-O
{ Black does have some alternative to the usual 7... b5, but none of them look good. Let's take a look before we head to the main move: }
7... b5
{ The exclam might be a tad exaggerated, but as we have seen Black doesn't really have alternatives.   7...e6?  Was played once by the strong English GM Gawain Jones, but Black's position is hopeless after  8.e5  The pawn isn't hanging, since Black's queen on d8 will fall in the end.  8...Ng8  A very painful move to make, but the best.  9.h4  As you are well aware of by now, the pawn-launch h4-h5 is a powerful plan in these positions. There was nothing wrong with 9. f4 like in Poulsen,M - Thomsen,T Torshavn 2000, but the text move is much stronger.  9...dxe5  The critical move and the human response. Other moves just allow us to carry out our plan, when Black is in major trouble.  10.dxe5  Bxe5  Otherwise we'll defend the pawn with f4.  11.f4  Bg7  12.g4  Taking more space on the kingside. Black now has to worry about f5 when we will open all the lines against Black's king.  12...Ngf6  13.g5  Nh5  14.Nge2  Black can't do anything about our plan of playing Bg2-Bf3-Bxh5.  14...O-O  15.Bg2  c6  16.Bf3+-  Black is completely lost as we will take on h5 followed by Ng3 next.   7...O-O ?  Surprisingly enough, over 50 players have had the guts to play this move. It loses due to concrete reasons:  8.e5  Ne8  9.h4  With our usual devastating attack.  9...dxe5  10.dxe5  Bxe5  11.h5+-  White's attack was decisive in Offenborn,H - Wagner,K GER email 2011, so Black resigned four moves later.   7...e5?  Is another poor move, when we will proceed by playing  8.g4  It's easy to play with the white pieces as all we have to do is launching a pawn storm on the kingside.  8...b5  Black has tried this move in most of the games, when the refutation is  9.dxe5  Nxe5  10.g5  We will push away Black's knights.  10...Nfd7  11.f4  Nc6   11...Ng4  looks poor after  12.Bd4  , when the knight on  g4  will get trapped one way or another.  12.h4  Black can't stop the massacre on the kingside.  12...h5  13.gxh6  Bxh6  14.h5+-  White is completely winning. I want to show the end of the Correspondence game, but I leave the theory section here.  14...gxh5  15.e5  The diagonal is opened!  15...Bf8  16.Bg2  Bb7  17.Nf3  Rg8  18.Rhe1  Black's king on e8 is in huge trouble.  18...dxe5  19.fxe5  Rxg2  This obviously loses, but Black had no defense.  20.Qxg2  Ncxe5  21.Nd5  Bxd5  22.Rxd5  Black called it a day and resigned in Shchemelev,P- Larsen,N ICCF email 2017. }
8. h4
{ It's time to start launching the pawns on the kingside. Checking IM Chessexplained's course, I realize that we have almost transposed to his f3-coverage. The difference is that Black has a bishop placed on f8 in the course which is to his advantage since Bh6 no longer comes with a tempo. }
8... Bb7 9. Kb1
{ I always approve of this prophylactic move. That being said, White's most popular choice has been 9. g4 which is also very interesting to analyze. }
9... c5
{ An interesting alternative, when we should respond with   9...h5  Is very likely to transpose to the main line after  10.Nh3  Play should lead to the main line one way or another, for example:  10...O-O  11.Ng5  c5  12.g4  And indeed, the transposition is a fact. }
10. g4 { This is the prize Black pays when not playing h5. } 10... h6
{ Makes sense, as Black can meet h5 with g5, and g5 with hxg5. } 11. Nh3
{ We just develop our stallion as Black has stopped our pawns for now. } 11...
Qc7
{ Was played in Duzhakov,I - Shomoev,A Voronezh 2016, when White's best response would have been   11...b4  Was tried in an e-mail game.  12.Ne2  Qa5  Again we can see how useful it is to have played Kb1.  13.g5  hxg5  14.Nxg5±  White is very active and eventually won a very nice e-mail game that I suggest you look up in the base. Medina,M - Burmeister,F ICCF email 2017. }
12. dxc5 Nxc5 { 12...dxc5  is met by  13.g5  hxg5  14.hxg5  . } 13. g5 hxg5 14.
Nxg5
{ Our activity and safer king grants us a clearly better position. The bishop on e3 will head to d4 and the bishop on f1 will find a nice home on h3. White can also further open the position by playing Nd5. }
