[White "Quickstarter − 1.e4 Sidelines"]
[Black "Pirc 4...Bg7 5.f3 O-O #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Be3 Bg7 5. f3 O-O 6. Qd2
{ The last remaining branch of Pirc is to consider the rest of the systems Black can play besides a6 & c6. }
6... e5 7. Nge2
{ The natural continuation since we want to take with the knight in case Black decides to capture on d4. }
7... exd4
{ Since our attack is faster and more dangerous than Black's, Black's best strategy is to fight against our center instead of launching a queenside attack. }
8. Nxd4 d5
{ Many strong GMs have played this move which strikes immediately in the center, and it's certainly an interesting try as we need to react precisely. }
9. e5
{ The obvious choice.  9.exd5?  would give Black a great position after  9...Nxd5  due to his active pieces. The knight can now move to three different squares. }
9... Ne8 10. Bg5
{ Our usual response. Black needs to decide whether or not he will weaken himself with f6 or place the queen on the poor d7-square which disturbs Black's coordination. }
10... Qd7
{ 10...f6  Is possible of course, when the game continues  11.exf6  Nxf6  12.O-O-O  Nc6   The necessary move. Slow moves like  12...a6  are met by  13.h4  when we get a powerful attack.  13.Nde2  A strong novelty. The knight is well placed on e2 where it can target the pawn on d5 with a subsequent knight jump to f4. I doubt Black will be able to save the pawn. h4 is a good move to include as well, since it will wreak havoc when it heads to h5. }
11. O-O-O
{ King safety first. After  11.f4  Black has a nice position after  11...f6! }
11... Bxe5
{ Black has to take the pawn.  11...c5  for example is met by  12.Bb5!   11...c6  doesn't help much either, when we can proceed with our usual plan of launching the h-pawn to  h5  . Perhaps it's best to include  12.Re1  before doing so. }
12. h4 { As we are a pawn down, it's important that we attack quickly. } 12...
f6 13. Bh6 Ng7
{ This position was reached in Tiemann,H - Mehlhorn,U GER email 2017, a game which Black drew. }
14. Ndb5
{ Is a fantastic improvement over  14.f4  . The point is that we want to take on  c3  with the knight, as the knight can head to  e4  from the c3-square. }
14... c6 15. f4 { Forced of course, otherwise Ndb5 is entirely pointless. }
15... Bxc3
{ 15...a6?  Loses by force after  16.fxe5  axb5  17.exf6  Rxf6  And in this position we have the fantastic blow  18.Bxb5!  This move works tactically as Black is defenseless against our forces.  18...cxb5   18...Qf7  also loses after  19.Ne4!  dxe4  20.Qd8+  Qf8  21.Bc4+  Kh8  , and now the easiest way to win is to play  22.Bg5  followed by Be7 when White wins material.  19.Nxd5  Rd6  20.Qc3+-  Black can't avoid the loss of material. }
16. Nxc3
{ Black's kingside is exposed. We will utilize this by playing g4-f5 or Be2-g4-h5 with a very dangerous attack. }
