1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Be3 Bg7 5. f3 O-O 6. Qd2
{ The last remaining branch of Pirc is to consider the rest of the systems Black can play besides a6 & c6. }
6... e5
{ Black's most popular move in the position. The idea is simple as Black wants to get counterplay against our center. In the event of  7.d5  , Black has  7...c6  when he will take on  d5  next with active play. Black's concept is interesting, but the engines are not impressed. }
7. Nge2
{ The natural continuation since we want to take with the knight in case Black decides to capture on d4. }
7... exd4
{ Since our attack is faster and more dangerous than Black's, Black's best strategy is to fight against our center instead of launching a queenside attack. }
8. Nxd4 Nc6
{ The right path forward. Black wants to quickly exchange on d4 and play Be6, when c5 and Qa5 could follow suit with some queenside play. }
9. O-O-O Nxd4 10. Bxd4 Be6 11. g4
{ A strong move. As I have mentioned, the g4-g5 plan followed by Bxg7 is a really effective plan. }
11... c5 { Is Black's most popular move in the position, but it loses... } 12.
Be3 Qa5
{ This is always played as Black needs to hurry up on the queenside if he wants to achieve something. }
13. Bh6
{ White scores a whopping 87% after this move and indeed it's very strong.  13.h4?  allows  13...d5!  when Black has lots of play. }
13... Rfd8
{ Played by GM Mamedyarov, so I will leave it as the main line.   13...Bxa2?  Loses by force due to  14.Bxg7  Kxg7  15.Nxa2  Qxa2  16.Qc3  The knight is pinned and Black can't avoid either g5 or Rxd6.  16...d5  Black has tried this move in every game, but has lost 11/11 times.  17.Rxd5  Rad8  18.g5!  Just in time!  18...Rxd5  19.exd5+-  Black's most recent loss was in Terbe,J- Abramovic,B Arad 2018. Black was rated as high as 2400! White is winning as Black loses the knight of course. }
14. Bxg7 Kxg7 15. h4 { Black can't do anything about our assault on his king. }
15... Bxa2
{ 15...h5  is simply met by  16.gxh5  with  Rhg1  and f4-f5 coming. The text move is Black's best practical chance as it requires us to make the right call. }
16. h5
{ We can simply ignore what Black is doing on the queenside since we are far away from getting mated.  16.Nxa2?  gives Black the necessary counterplay after  16...Qxa2  17.Qc3  d5  as Black now survives!  18.g5  Qa1+  19.Kd2  dxe4+  20.Bd3  was played in Najer, E - Mamedyarov, S Khanty-Mansiysk 2013, when Mamedyarov missed the draw with  20...Qa6!  The point is that the queen guards the f6-square and also controls the c4-square, meaning that Black will regain the piece due to the pin on our bishop. Black still needs to play precisely, but it is a draw with correct play. }
16... Ng8 17. hxg6 hxg6 18. Qh2
{ Black's king is naked. With Qh8+ coming followed by Rh7 Black is toast. f4-f5-g5-f6 is also an effective plan. }
