[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter − 1.e4 Sidelines"]
[Black "Nimzowitsch Defense 2...d5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nc6
{ The 'Nimzowitch Defence,' a very rare breed. That being said, it is by far the best opening out of the rare openings out there. }
2. d4 d5
{ The exclam is well-deserved because this is Black's best bet and only path to 'equality.' Black's aim is to get decent control on the light squares and later attack our center with a move like f6. The engines are surprisingly optimistic on Black's behalf, which was quite sensational to me when I took a look. }
3. e5 Bf5
{ Surprisingly enough, the position now resembles an advanced Caro-Kann. One of the key differences is that Black's f6-break is more effective because of the knight on c6. The downside to having the knight on c6 is that the c5 pawn break can't happen yet as the knight stands in the way. }
4. c3
{ Like in the other lines, we will play this move solidifying our pawn structure. }
4... f6
{ 4...Qd7  Can be played by Black, when we should respond with  5.Be2±  The play is likely to transpose to the 4... f6-line. }
5. f4 { Maintaining a strong center. } 5... Qd7
{ Black has also tried this move here, when the option of castling queenside appears. }
6. Nf3 e6
{ 6...O-O-O?  is too dangerous. After  7.b4  , our attack on the queenside is much faster when a4-Nd2-Nb3-b5 will follow suit, similar to other positions in the chapter. }
7. Be2 Nh6 8. b4
{ Making O-O-O even less tempting for Black. Also, b4 grabs queenside space, which is essentially where we will place our pieces if Black castles kingside as well. 8. a4!? with the same idea, was also strong as seen in the instructive game Kowalczyk,R - Wyzga Rybicki,W ICCF email 2018. }
8... Be7 9. O-O { Our play from here is straightforward. a4-Nbd2-Nb3-b4. } 9...
Bg6
{ Was tried by a 2300-player.  9...O-O  is met by  10.Nbd2  , with the mentioned plan. }
10. a4 O-O 11. Nbd2 { We continue with the same plan. } 11... a6
{ Black's best bet is to slow down our queenside initiative.   11...fxe5?  Was now a major error, due to  12.b5  Chasing away the knight, so we can soon capture on e5 with our stallion on f3.  12...Nd8  13.Nxe5  Qe8  14.Nxg6  Grabbing the strong bishop on g6 was a strong way to proceed, but not the only strong way.  14...hxg6  15.Nf3  Bd6  16.g3  Nf5  17.Bd3+-  Black's position had seen better days in the game Frolov,A - Ozenir,E Lvov 2018. }
12. Nb3 b6 13. a5
{ Black has gained some control, but it's still very unpleasant. } 13... Qc8
{ 13...b5?  is met by  14.Ne1!  when the knight is headed to  d3  and  c5  . On the board Black is highly passive, so we don't need to do anything fancy. }
14. h3 Nf5 15. Qe1
{ White is soon ready to carry out g4 on the kingside. Black is struggling to find moves. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter − 1.e4 Sidelines"]
[Black "Nimzowitsch Defense 2...d5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nc6
{ The 'Nimzowitch Defence,' a very rare breed. That being said, it is by far the best opening out of the rare openings out there. }
2. d4 d5
{ The exclam is well-deserved because this is Black's best bet and only path to 'equality.' Black's aim is to get decent control on the light squares and later attack our center with a move like f6. The engines are surprisingly optimistic on Black's behalf, which was quite sensational to me when I took a look. }
3. e5 Bf5
{ Surprisingly enough, the position now resembles an advanced Caro-Kann. One of the key differences is that Black's f6-break is more effective because of the knight on c6. The downside to having the knight on c6 is that the c5 pawn break can't happen yet as the knight stands in the way. }
4. c3
{ Like in the other lines, we will play this move solidifying our pawn structure. }
4... e6 5. Be2
{ This move is played very seldom. The point is that we aim to play similarly to lines we've already seen. f4-Nf3-Nbd2 etc. }
5... f6 6. f4 g5
{ I found only one game with this move, and it's not surprising that it was a correspondence game. Black goes for direct counterplay and dismantles our center. The lines that occur from here are unbelievably complicated. Black is constantly on the verge of losing, but somehow someway there are an absurd amount of resources for Black. Although I was left rather irritated when I discovered that the game fizzles into a draw in the end, it doesn't really matter. For a human player there is just too much to remember, making the task for Black practically impossible. Buckle up, the positions coming up are wild! }
7. Bh5+ Kd7
{ Black's best bet is to simply move the king away. It's indeed true that the king could become a target on d7, but it's not so easy for us to attack it yet. If Black has time, he will take on f4 and e5 when our initiative disappears. }
8. fxg5 { The best move is to play concretely and grab the pawn. } 8... fxe5 9.
Nf3
{ Not giving Black any time to rest, attacking the pawn on e5. Here Black has to be careful, as we can often play Nh4 and get rid of the defending piece on f5. c4 is also an idea in the air, opening up the file against Black's monarch. }
9... h6
{ A star move. Black doesn't waste time and goes for our throat instantly. The idea is simple, Black wants to open the h-file when his play could become overwhelming. }
10. Nxe5+
{ The most critical move, but Black has many moves to watch out for. I analyzed a lot here, but the chapter will never come to an end if I show all my analysis. Alternatives are:  10.g4!?  10.O-O!?  10.c4!? }
10... Nxe5 11. dxe5 hxg5
{ Black's idea and the best try. Other moves could be met by g4 and Rf1, when Black is in trouble as the desired counterplay down the h-file ceases to exist.   11...Ne7!?  is best handled by  12.O-O  , followed by a swift c4-Nc3. }
12. g4
{ Stopping Black's play in the h-file, and preventing Black from playing g4 himself, which could be very dangerous. }
12... Rxh5
{ A fantastic rook sacrifice, which...   12...Be4?  Is natural, but inaccurate.  13.Rf1  Black has to be careful as he will quickly be completely lost if we are able to consolidate with Be3-Nd2.  13...c6  14.c4!?  An interesting move.  14...Bxb1  Black's best move is to grab the knight according to my engine.  15.Rxb1  Qa5+  16.Kf2!  The king will be perfectly safe on g3.  16...Be7  Protecting the pawn on g5.  17.cxd5  Qxd5  18.Be3  Nh6  19.Kg3±  White's pieces are much better placed than Black's. The upcoming endgame will be tough for Black to defend. If Black moves out of the pin we should take right away. If Black doesn't move out of the pin, a move like Rf2 could be smart, forcing Black to take first. }
13. gxf5
{ We will not accept! Instead, we aim to get initiative ourselves! In fact, Black is better if we decide to be greedy and accept the offered material. }
13... g4
{ Another brilliancy, opening up the queen's diagonal.   13...Rh4!?  This move is a decent alternative to the main move. Black wants to place the rook on e4 where it will bother our king.  14.fxe6+  Kxe6   It's funny, but Black's king is well placed on  e6  for the time being...  14...Kc8  is worse, when we are clearly better after  15.Nd2  .  15.Be3  We must hurry up and complete our development.  15...Ne7   15...Re4?  loses to  16.O-O  , when Black's king is suddenly not so safe any longer.  16.Nd2  16...Nf5  Black must play directly in order to justify the monarch on e6.  17.Bf2  g4!  Moving the rook would give us Qg4, when Black can resign.  18.Rf1!  Preventing Black from playing g3.  18...Qg5  19.Qb3!   We are in time to castle queenside.  19.Qe2?  would give Black the valuable tempo of playing  19...Rxh2  , when we are busted.  19...g3  20.hxg3  Nxg3  21.O-O-O  Our king escapes and Black is forced to trade pieces. A forced sequence is:  21...Nxf1  22.Bxh4  Nxd2  A strong move, not giving us Rxf1 when we would have strong play in the f-file.  23.Rxd2  Qxe5  24.Qxb7  Bh6  Everything works out for Black, just barely.  25.Qc6+  Qd6  26.Qxa8  Bxd2+  27.Kc2!  The only chance to play for a win.  27...Bf4  28.Qxa7⩲  Black has to defend an unpleasant endgame.   13...Qe8!?  Is possible too, but I think Black gives away too much material. It's still complicated, though.  14.fxe6+  Kc8  15.Qxd5  There's no reason not to take.  15...Ne7  16.Qg2  16...Nc6  Black has to play actively, otherwise the sacrifice won't be justified.  17.Bxg5!?   Is the best shot to play for a win, as  17.O-O  leads to a 'forced' draw after 45 moves according to my analysis @@StartBracket@@don't ask!@@EndBracket@@  17...Qxe6  18.h4  Black has some counterplay, but our king will find a nice shelter behind the knight on d2.  18...Nxe5  19.Nd2  Now, it seems like Black has to head into an endgame with a pawn down.  19...Nf3+  20.Kd1  Nxg5  21.hxg5  Rxh1+  22.Qxh1  22...Be7!  The best defense.  23.Qe4±  The upcoming endgame is a draw with correct play, but not too fun to defend. }
14. fxe6+ Kc8
{ The most accurate move.  14...Ke8  is also possible, but it looks unnatural to me as the king looks weaker there than on  c8  . The game becomes rather complicated though, so feel free to investigate if you're curious! }
15. Bf4 Qh4+ 16. Ke2
{ The only move that doesn't lose, as  16.Bg3  loses to  16...Qxg3!  , winning a piece. The game from here is extremely complicated, but I feel like it's a crime to ask you to memorize everything. Still, I can't stop all the curious souls, but I want to emphasize that the chances for this to occur in a game is around 0%. It's just too difficult for a human being to find the most accurate moves, even for super-GMs... }
16... Ne7
{ Is also good enough to equalize, as seen after   16...Bc5?  Is a typical human move, but it loses.  17.Rf1   17.Qxd5  wins too, but this move is easier. Black doesn't have the required counterplay needed to make his scheme work.  17...g3  18.hxg3  Qg4+  19.Ke1+-  The game will head into an endgame, where our extra pawns decide.   16...Bh6  Leads to a favorable endgame for us after  17.Qxd5  Qd8  18.Qxd8+  Kxd8  19.Bg3±  It's not an easy position to defend, but the engine assures me that it's not lost yet for Black. }
17. Rf1 Rf5 { Black has to make sure we can't cause damage in the f-file. } 18.
Bg3 Qh5 19. Nd2 b6
{ Black has to make room for his king, preventing our cunning plan of playing Ne4-Nf6. }
20. a4 a5 21. Qb3
{ Our plan is to play Qd7+, followed by Rae1 and Kd1 when our king will be very safe.   In case of  21...Bh6  , we can take on  f5  and play  Rf1  when we maintain some initiative. Black's best move is the strong sacrifice }
21... Rxe5+ 22. Bxe5 Qxe5+ 23. Kd1 Kb7 24. Kc2
{ The position is unclear as Black's pieces are active and his king safe on b7. That being said, I would pick White as an error from Black would surely be fatal. }
