[White "Quickstarter − 1.e4 Sidelines"]
[Black "Modern Defense 3...c5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 g6 2. d4
{ As always we will take full control of the center if we get the chance. }
2... Bg7 { I'd say this move will be played against you 99/100 times... } 3.
Nc3
{ There are a bunch of different set-ups we can go for, but I think the knight move is the most critical option. The Main Line gives Black a plethora of options, which will all be covered in this chapter. }
3... c5
{ This move is not good objectively, but we must be prepared against it. } 4.
dxc5 { Taking the bait is the most critical move. } 4... Bxc3+
{ The other alternative. Black hopes to make the game unbalanced with giving away this strong bishop for a damaged pawn structure. }
5. bxc3 Qa5 { The most popular move, which requires us to play the accurate }
6. Qd4 Nf6 7. Qb4
{ Offering Black a rather depressing endgame while protecting the pawns. } 7...
Qc7
{ Black has to keep the queens on the board in order to keep matters 'complicated.' As we've seen, the resulting endings are very comfortable for us.   7...Nc6  8.Qxa5  Nxa5  9.Bd3  O-O  10.Ne2  Was a really comfortable endgame for White, when I highly encourage you to check out the instructive game Danin,A - Troyke,C Wunsiedel 2012.   7...Qxb4?!  Grabbing the pawn on e4 isn't a great idea, as our pawns on the queenside become incredibly strong, along with our bishop pair.  8.cxb4  Nxe4  9.Bb2  White's bishops and queenside majority give Black major problems in the endgame. Black's on the verge of collapse. }
8. Bd3 Nc6
{ 8...Na6  Is always met by  9.Bxa6  bxa6  10.f3  Supporting the pawn on e4.  10...a5  11.Qd4  It looks like to me that we are a clean pawn up for absolutely nothing. A nice trick to keep in mind is that  11...e5  can be met by  12.Bf4! }
9. Qa4 Qe5 { The most played move. } 10. Qa3
{ I am quite surprised by the fact that this move has only been played once, guarding the pawns on  c3  and  c5  . I suspect that White has been scared of  10...Nxe4  , but after  11.Nf3  and O-O, White's initiative becomes overwhelming.  Also, note that  11...Qxc3  loses to a queen trade and  Bb2  , when Black can't move the knight due to the hanging rook on  h8  . }
10... b6
{ Is Black's best attempt to create counterplay for the missing pawn, and it was also played in the only game I found in the base. }
11. cxb6 O-O 12. Nf3 Qb8 13. b7
{ A strong move, we shouldn't allow Black to open up the a-file. } 13... Bxb7
14. Rb1 Qc7 15. c4
{ So far, we had been following the game Sharapov,E - Skalski,M Wroclaw 2007. The text move deviates and is stronger, as we are in time to get rid of our double pawns with c5, when we will be a clean pawn up. }
