1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 d6 4. Be3 a6
{ The main tabiya of the Modern. Black aims to get quick play on the queenside, when the moves b5-Bb7-Nbd7-c5 will follow in some order. }
5. h4
{ After analyzing this line in great depth, I came to the conclusion that this was the most accurate move order that aligns with all our set-ups in the Pirc/ Modern coverage. The text move aims for a quick h5-h6, which is something Black has to prevent. }
5... h5 { The main way of stopping h5, and also the best way to do so. } 6. Nh3
{ I spent a long time in this position, wondering which move order to go for. My conclusion became to develop the knight to h3 at once, where it will quickly reach g5. From the g5-square, the knight targets f7 which opens many tactical possibilities and traps for Black to step in! Let's see how the game can proceed. }
6... b5
{ Black's usual response in the a6-Modern is to make this expansion rather quickly. }
7. Ng5 Bb7 8. Qd2
{ For the sake of our coverage, I want to suggest this move as Black can reach the main line in more ways than just this one. }
8... Nd7 9. O-O-O { Now, Black has tried a decent amount of moves. } 9... e6
{ The main move in the position and the necessary move to make before Black can play Ngf6.   9...Ngf6  won't work now due to  10.e5  when we win material after all the exchanges due to f4 in the end. Thus, in order to reach the a6-Pirc line, Black has to play e6 first.  10...dxe5  11.dxe5  Nxe5  12.Qxd8+  Rxd8  13.Rxd8+  Kxd8  14.f4  Where the f-pawn is taking a last gasp. }
10. f3
{ From here,  10...Ngf6  will transpose to the a6-Pirc, but there are some alternatives. }
10... Qe7 { Is inaccurate, as it allows us to play } 11. d5
{ When Black's pawn on e6 will become weak. } 11... Ngf6
{ 11...Ne5  Was seen in Tsydypov,Z -Dudin,G Sochi 2019, when I suggest that you play  12.dxe6  fxe6  13.g3  The bishop is on its way to h3, where it will create tons of pressure against Black's pawn on e6. }
12. dxe6 fxe6 13. Ne2
{ The knight is soon headed to f4, so Black has to get rid of the knight on g5 before it's too late. }
13... Nh7 14. Nxh7
{ Not necessary, but I like forcing preventing Black from castling kingside. }
14... Rxh7 15. Nf4 Ne5 16. Kb1
{ White has the upper hand as Black has limited activity and weak pawns on e6 and g6. His king won't be entirely safe on the queenside either, as Black's pawn on b5 can be used as a target. }
