1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 d6 4. Be3 a6
{ The main tabiya of the Modern. Black aims to get quick play on the queenside, when the moves b5-Bb7-Nbd7-c5 will follow in some order. }
5. h4
{ After analyzing this line in great depth, I came to the conclusion that this was the most accurate move order that aligns with all our set-ups in the Pirc/ Modern coverage. The text move aims for a quick h5-h6, which is something Black has to prevent. }
5... Nf6
{ Is a natural move, but it's not very good. However, many strong GMs have failed to find the refutation here... }
6. h5 { The exchange sacrifice will lead to a fantastic initiative. } 6... Nxh5
{ 6...gxh5?  Is very ugly.  7.f3  Nc6  8.Nge2  No fancy moves are required. We will simply complete our development when it will be clear that Black's inferior pawn structure on the kingside will make him suffer.  8...e5  9.Qd2!  There is no need to give Black activity by playing 9. dxe5, like in Prie,E - Frick,C Sables d'Olonne 2019.  9...exd4  10.Nxd4  Black's position looks incredibly passive.  10...Nxd4  11.Qxd4  The best move, because we would rather like to place the bishop on the g5-square.  11...Be6  12.Bg5!  The pin is very unpleasant.  12...Qe7  13.O-O-O  White's position is superior in every single way. Ne2-Ng3 will soon come, winning the pawn on h5. Black also needs to watch out for f4-e5, when the knight will fall. }
7. Rxh5
{ The exchange sac gives us a lot of play as Black has limited control of the center and a weak king. }
7... gxh5 8. Qxh5 Nd7
{ Played in two human games and a natural response. Black wants to get rid of our initiative by playing Nf6, chasing away our queen on h5.   8...c5  Is a direct way of creating counterplay, when we have to play  9.Bc4!  Attacking the pawn on f7 with an important tempo.  9...e6  10.dxc5  Black has lost another pawn and will soon succumb to the pressure. }
9. Bc4
{ There is no reason not to play this move, gaining a tempo by threatening mate on f7. }
9... O-O { Note that  9...e6  doesn't work, since the pawn on  f7  is pinned. }
10. Nf3
{ Black will soon be under a huge attack, as O-O-O and Rh1 come with great velocity. }
10... Nf6 11. Qh4 Ng4
{ Was a huge error. A better attempt would have been  11...b5  when play could follow  12.Bb3  b4  13.Ne2  , when the knight will head to  g3  , when our attack remains powerful. }
12. Bg5
{ It's difficult to defend the pawn on e7 so Black decides to sacrifice it. }
12... Qd7 13. Nd5 { A strong move, when the pawn on e7 falls. } 13... Re8 14.
O-O-O
{ White's attack was decisive and he eventually scored a nice scalp in Asis Gargatagli, H - Sjugirov, S Lichess.org INT 2021. Our theory section ends, but I want to show a pretty nice line I found:  14...h6  15.Nf4!  A strong move, threatening to play Ne6, when Black loses the strong defensive pawn on g4.  15...b5  16.Bb3  c6  17.Ne6  White breaks through.  17...fxe6  18.Qxg4  hxg5  19.Nxg5+-  Black perishes to White's attack. }
