3. d4 d6
{ 3...d5  has been seen a decent amount of times, but this makes no sense to me at all. Black is avoiding putting pressure on our center, playing something that looks like an advanced Caro-Kann or French with several tempos down. I simply suggest going for  4.c4  , applying pressure on d5 . }
4. f4
{ As we also go for this set-up in our Main Line, I felt like this was the most logical choice. The point is obvious, taking space while supporting our pawn on e5. }
4... dxe5
{ 4...Bf5  5.Nf3   5.g4  is objectively best, but there is no reason to complicate things.  5...e6  6.c3  Black has simply lost several tempos in an advanced Caro-Kann. }
5. fxe5 Bf5 6. Nf3 e6 7. Bb5+
{ We're doing some provoking ourselves, making Black put his pawn on c6. } 7...
c6 8. Bc4 Nd7 9. O-O Ne7 10. Nc3
{ Our pieces are coming out. Bd3 may follow soon, attempting to remove the bishop on f5, opening the f-file. }
10... h6 11. Qe2 Nd5
{ Attempting to complete the development before it is too late. } 12. Ne4 Be7
13. Ng3 { Attacking the bishop, when we can soon consider Nh5 ideas. } 13...
Bh7 14. Bd3 Bxd3 15. Qxd3
{ We will play Nh5 soon, with a powerful attack. c4 will also follow, removing Black's only active piece, the knight on d5. }
