[Black "Alekhine Four Pawns 6...g6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4
{ Around the time I started playing 1. e4, I consulted my good friend GM Aryan Tari about the Alekhine. He suggested me to play 4. Nf3, sharing some lines with me on how to obtain an edge. This is definitely a good move, but I somehow feel that it isn't the most critical one. The reason for this is that Black has a tendency to get slightly worse, but very playable positions. Black can play in numerous ways, and the outcome always seem to remain 'slightly worse, but that's it.' I mentioned this to Aryan recently, who agreed on my sentiment saying that he seldom acquired more than a slight edge. Having to study so many lines for a rare guest especially in Classical Chess, was not appealing to me at all, therefore I decided to investigate the other continuation that is known for being critical for Black, namely the Four Pawns Attack. }
4... Nb6 5. f4
{ Here we go. We keep our center intact, aiming for a massive space advantage. A massive pro with this system is that Black does not have many decent options at his disposal, as we soon shall see. }
5... dxe5 6. fxe5 g6
{ 6...Nc6  is the Main Line where the play continues  7.Be3  Bf5  8.Nc3  e6  9.Nf3  . This is the main tabiya in the Four Pawns Attack, and it will be examined thoroughly in the next chapter. }
7. Nc3 Bg7 8. c5
{ This is the only way to create problems for Black. If we don't do this we will get c5 slapped in our face when Black has succeeded well with his opening play. }
8... Nd5 9. Bc4 { We need to take control of this diagonal. } 9... Nxc3
{ 9...Be6  is met by  10.Qb3  With excellent chances. } 10. bxc3
{ 23 games have reached this position, but it simply looks too difficult for Black to play. It is extremely difficult for Black to fight against our center, so the position is more or less doomed to passiveness. }
10... O-O 11. Nf3 b6
{ The text move is an attempt to fight against our horde of pawns, but it fails to }
12. Ng5
{ The queen now gets a beautiful square on f3 while the knight is also creating lots of pressure against the weak pawn on f7. }
12... Bb7 13. e6 { We will now place our knight on f7. } 13... f5 14. Nf7 Qe8
15. O-O { Our knight on f7 gives us a really powerful attack. } 15... Nc6 16.
Bh6 Bxh6 17. Nxh6+ Kg7 18. Qd2
{ The knight will move back to f7, when Qh6+ followed by Ng5 is one deadly threat. We may also move our queen to g5 directly, aiming to win the f5-pawn. }
