[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter − Alekhine, Scandi, Philidor"]
[Black "Scandinavian 2...Nf6 − 4...Nb4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Nf6
{ This is the first branch of the Scandinavian Defense. Black's idea is to avoid the time loss of capturing the pawn with the queen. }
3. d4
{ The most principled approach is to take the center, just like we always do whenever we get the chance.   3.c4  is what Black wants. Here we will be getting a worse version of the 2...c6 line, lacking development after  3...c6  4.dxc6  Nxc6  White should probably head into the Panov with instead of capturing the pawn. }
3... Nxd5
{ Hilariously enough, I think Black's best choice is to take the pawn on d5 with the queen. This will transpose to   3...Qxd5  after  4.Nc3  . }
4. c4 { We will keep occupying the center. } 4... Nb4
{ It wasn't in my plans to mention this move at all, until I discovered it had been played over 700 times! It's called the Kiel Variation with a specific idea in mind: }
5. a3
{ Black's idea is seen after   5.Qa4+  N8c6  6.d5  b5!!  7.cxb5  Nd4!  8.Na3  e5  when Black has fantastic play and is already a winning advantage. However, the logical text move destroys Black's scheme completely. }
5... N4c6 6. Nf3
{ 6.Be3  has been overwhelmingly the most popular move, but I don't think Black is doing too badly after  6...e5!  7.d5  Ne7  . }
6... Bg4 7. d5 Ne5 8. Be2
{ We're simply developing our pieces. Black on the other hand, has massive issues with getting the pieces out, the bishop on f8 in particular. }
8... Bxf3 9. Bxf3 Nbd7
{ The pawn on c4 was untouchable due to the check on a4. From here we have a pleasant choice between }
10. O-O
{ Simply sacrificing the pawn is objectively the best move. When Black takes it we will follow up with Re1-Qd4-Nc3, when it seems like an impossible task for Black to get his pieces out on the board. }
