[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter − Alekhine, Scandi, Philidor"]
[Black "Scandinavian 2...Nf6 − 4...Nb6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Nf6
{ This is the first branch of the Scandinavian Defense. Black's idea is to avoid the time loss of capturing the pawn with the queen. }
3. d4 Nxd5 4. c4 { We will keep occupying the center. } 4... Nb6
{ This is Black's most active response which has seen the light of day over 7500 times!  4...Nf6  has been seen around 2000, just to compare. }
5. Nf3 Bg4
{ Pinning the knight is certainly logical, but that doesn't make it a great move. However, this is due to concrete reasons as we soon shall see. }
6. c5
{ Attacking the knight on c5 is the most concrete approach to the position. }
6... N6d7 7. Be2
{ Removing the pin while developing our pieces. Black has two main moves here, but the position remains very uncomfortable to play in practice. White has a very good score from here, while neither Stockfish or Leela survived with the black pieces when this opening was given in the Top Computer Chess Championship TCEC. }
7... e6 { Is the main move here, but Black is far from achieving equality. } 8.
h3 { Leela played h3 here, so I trust that she made the right call. } 8... Bxf3
{ This move is very engine-like, and a sad move to make. } 9. Bxf3 c6 10. O-O
{ We do not need to do anything extraordinary here. The bishop pair is ours while we have a massive space advantage. }
10... a5 { Stockfish wanted to grab some space. } 11. Bf4 Be7 12. Na3
{ I really like what Leela is doing, putting a knight on c4. } 12... O-O 13.
Nc4 Nf6 14. a3 Nbd7 15. Re1
{ Our position is just fantastic. Black needs to worry about us placing a piece on d6 , while we have other ideas like Rc1-Rc3-Rb3, attacking b7 . Rb1-b4-b5 is also a good plan. Stockfish didn't manage to save the game either, when the game went   14...Nd5  15.Bxd5  cxd5  16.Nd6  Bxd6  17.Bxd6  Re8  18.b3  h6  19.Qd3  Ra6  20.b4  Nb6  21.b5  Ra8  22.a4  White was strategically completely winning in LCZero v0.25.1-svjio-t60-3972 3813 -Stockfish 202006170741 TCEC 2020. The game went on for over a 100 more moves, but Stockfish couldn't save the position. }
