[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter − Alekhine, Scandi, Philidor"]
[Black "Scandinavian 2...Nf6 − 3...Bg4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Nf6
{ This is the first branch of the Scandinavian Defense. Black's idea is to avoid the time loss of capturing the pawn with the queen. }
3. d4 Bg4 4. f3 Bf5 5. g4
{ This is when all the fun begins. We want to cling to the extra pawn and follow up with c4-Nc3. The pawn on g4 will often go to g5, chasing away the knight on f6. It's important to distinguish between the text move and the move 5. c4.  After the move   5.c4  e6  will be played. After the further  6.Nc3  exd5  7.g4  , Black can play  7...Be6! }
5... Bg6 { The most popular move by a decent amount. } 6. c4
{ From here, Black can challenge the center in different ways, but I will only spend my time on two of them. }
6... e6
{ 180 games have seen this move, 22 have seen  6...c6  , while others have been seen twice or once. This move makes the most sense if you ask me as Black can soon develop the bishop and castle. }
7. Nc3 { Be careful not to give Black counterplay by taking on e6. } 7... Be7
{ 7...c5!?  This is a different attempt to fight against our center. It's rather easy to get confused, but normal developing moves will do once more.  8.Be3  cxd4  9.Bxd4  Nbd7  Black couldn't grab the pawn due to g5! In this position I like the thematic  10.h4!  h6  11.h5  Bh7  12.dxe6  fxe6  13.Bd3  Black's position is in dire straits with a pawn down and pretty weak king.  Out of all of the alternatives, this move has been played the most. As we have seen before,   7...Qe7  can be simply met by  8.Kf2! }
8. h4 { Utilizing our advanced pawns on the kingside. } 8... h6 9. dxe6 Nc6
{ Wasting no time. The natural   9...fxe6  can be met by  10.Bd3  , when we will play Be3-Nge2 next. I don't think Black has any compensation here. }
10. Be3 Qd6 11. h5 Bh7 12. exf7+ Kxf7 13. c5
{ Black was completely busted in Gazik, I - Krivoshey, S Hlohovec 1998.   13...Qe6  is met by  14.Qb3  Black is two pawns down with a pretty weak king. }
