1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qd8 4. d4 { Grabbing the center as we always do. }
4... Nf6
{ Other moves have been played here, but this logical move is by far the most popular in the position. Black has to play Nf6 at some point anyway, so other options are likely to transpose. }
5. Nf3 Bg4 6. h3 { More or less forcing Black to give up the bishop pair. }
6... Bxf3 7. Qxf3 c6 8. Be3 e6
{ GM Wesley So points out that White is scoring really well in the Correspondence database here, with a whopping 83%. He explains further that this opening is mostly played as an opening surprise, while ideas are rather easy to remember. I certainly agree with all of his points. The other side of the coin, as Welsey also points out, is that it seems that White gets a risk-free advantage with the bishop pair. One must remember that the Correspondence games are a decent indicator of how good a line objectively is. If White has such a decent score, the line can't be sound. }
9. Bd3
{ We now have the option of castling to either side. Black is doing fairly okay after   9.O-O-O  Bb4  10.Ne4  Nxe4  11.Qxe4  Qd5  allows Black to equalize. }
9... Nbd7 10. O-O-O
{ Once again, queenside castling is on the table. This is the way to punish Black for his rather passive play in the opening, as it's rather difficult to get counterplay when one's pieces are inactive. }
10... Bb4 11. Ne2
{ It's better to keep the knights on the board as we're going for an attack. }
11... Qa5
{ Escaping to the queenside has been done before, but it's not good. } 12. Kb1
Qd5
{ We should not exchange queens.   12...O-O-O  13.c4!  Seizing control of the center.  13...Rhe8  14.g4  We'll soon play g5, which is rather annoying for Black.  14...e5  15.Bc2  exd4  16.Nxd4  Is rather terrible for Black. }
13. Qg3 O-O-O 14. c4 { Driving away Black's pieces. } 14... Qd6 15. Bf4 Qf8 16.
Bc7 Re8 17. a3 Be7 18. Nc3
{ Black's position was a sad scheme in Sharma,D - Frendzas,P Anogia 2018, and he resigned eight moves later. }
