1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qd6 4. d4
{ We will once again take control of the center. } 4... Nf6 5. Nf3 c6 6. h3 Bf5
{ Now that the bishop can't be placed on g4, it has to be placed on f5. If Black doesn't do it now, we will play Bd3 when Black will have problems with the c8-bishop, as we saw in the alternative variations. Therefore, it's not surprising that this is the best and most played response. After this move, White has many good options up his sleeve... }
7. g3 e6 8. Nh4
{ This logical move has only been played once, which is highly surprising to me.   Most games have continued  8.Bg2  , but this allows Black to save the bishop with  8...h6  , when I doubt that we have much. }
8... Bg6
{ 8...Be4  was seen in Hoang, C Le, H Ho Chi Minh City 2014, when a simple solution is to play  9.Nxe4  Nxe4  10.Nf3  . }
9. Nxg6 hxg6 10. Bg2
{ We have transposed to a few games where   10.Bg2  was the move-order. } 10...
Qc7 { It makes a lot of sense to me to give the bishop a square on d6. } 11.
Bf4
{ This is a good move, which has a subtle trick to it. All the games I found proceeded with   11.O-O  , but I think Black has almost equalized in that line after  11...Nbd7  . }
11... Bd6 { Is the obvious move, but it has a flaw. } 12. Nb5
{ This tactical jump is the key idea of this variation. } 12... cxb5 13. Bxd6
{ The point is obviously that Black will lose an exchange if he captures our bishop on d6. }
13... Qd7 14. a3
{ This move looks kind of mysterious, but the point is that we prevent Black from playing b4 in several lines. }
14... Nc6 15. Bf4 O-O
{ 15...Nxd4  It looks like we're sacrificing a pawn, but...  16.Qd3!  Preparing to castle queenside next with a deadly initiative.  16...Nc6  Black has to give the pawn back. After something like   16...a6  17.O-O-O  Nc6  18.Qe3  Qc8  19.Bd6  , our initiative is too powerful.  17.Qxb5  a6  18.Qe2  The position has become rather open, when our two bishops are superior to Black's knights.  18...O-O  19.Rd1  Qc8  20.O-O  Our bishops give us a clearly better game. }
16. c3 Na5 { Black's only plan is to place a knight on c4. } 17. O-O Rac8 18.
h4 { Taking control of the square on g5. } 18... Nc4 19. Qe2 Nd5 20. Bg5
{ Our bishop pair is once again superior, but it should be mentioned that Black has a solid position. }
