[White "Quickstarter − Alekhine, Scandi, Philidor"]
[Black "Scandinavian 2…Qxd5 3.Nc3 Qd6 – 5…a6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qd6 4. d4
{ We will once again take control of the center. } 4... Nf6 5. Nf3 a6
{ This has been the most common move, which is not surprising. Black's idea is clear. Now that Nb5 is not a problem, he can easily start to apply pressure in the center. a6 also opens up the possibility of b5-Bb7, but Black has to be careful with that pawn launch as the pawn on b5 can be easily targeted by a4, as we've seen earlier. Black's plans are crystal clear and not easily dealt with by the unprepared player, so pay attention! }
6. g3
{ This move is rather effective, since it makes it possible to get a tempo on Black's queen with Bf4, while giving the f1-bishop a nice square on g2 where it will be rather effective. }
6... Bg4
{ The fact that this move has been played the most is not surprising, considering the fact that Black's plan is Nc6-O-O-O, when the pawn on d4 will be under pressure. }
7. h3 { I think the inclusion of h3-Bh5 favors White. } 7... Bh5
{ A common scenario in the Scandinavian is that this move is less accurate than Bxf3 due to concrete reasons, but played a lot more as it is 'trickier.' }
8. Bg2
{ We should get our pieces out before we start playing g4 followed by Ne5.   8.g4?!  Bg6  9.Ne5  would now allow  9...Nc6!  when Black gets a decent amount of activity with O-O-O next. }
8... Nc6
{ This is not the best move, but almost always played as it has been Black's idea all along. A move like   8...c6  gives us easy play with  9.Bf4  etc, similar to what we've already seen. }
9. d5
{ This straightforward response is the refutation to Black's shenanigans. }
9... Bxf3
{ I don't think it's a good idea to give up the bishop pair 'just like that,' but we must play accurately to keep our winning advantage.   9...Ne5?  Would have worked without the inclusion of h3-Bh5, but here it loses.  10.g4!  We're now out of the annoying pin.  10...Bg6  11.O-O  Nxf3+  12.Qxf3  Black was way too passive in Klek,H -Repkova, E Balatonszarszo 2017. }
10. Bxf3 Qe5+
{ Black's hoping for some counterplay against our d5-pawn as he will play O-O-O next. }
11. Kf1 { Our king will find an excellent square on g2. } 11... O-O-O 12. Kg2
e6 13. Bf4 Qf5 { On the surface everything looks fine for Black, but } 14. dxc6
{ wins! } 14... Rxd1 15. cxb7+ Kb8 16. Raxd1
{ Our pawn on b7 is too strong. One particularly strong idea is Rhe1-Re5-Ra5.   16...Bb4  is Black's best defense, but I don't think he will survive long after  17.Ne2  when Nd4-Nc6 is suddenly a threat. }
