[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter − Alekhine, Scandi, Philidor"]
[Black "Philidor 3...Nbd7"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 Nbd7 4. f4
{ Just like in the Czech Pirc, we will take full control of the center. Now we are already threatening e5 which could lead to a disaster for Black. }
4... e5
{ Played almost every game, and for good reason. Black takes some central control and stops our e5-thrust. }
5. Nf3 exd4 6. Qxd4
{ Taking with the queen has been overwhelmingly the most common response, and indeed, it's the best move in the position as we want to castle queenside. }
6... c6
{ This is a good way to fight against our e5-break in the center as Black has taken control of the d5-square and he can respond with Bc5 if we play e5. }
7. Bd2
{ My analysis concluded that this move was the strongest approach. The advantage of having the bishop on d2 is that it's harder for Black to attack it. }
7... Qb6
{ Black should neutralize our initiative by trading queens. However, this is probably the least 'Ginger-GM' move out there, as the man lives for the chaos : Therefore he suggests the center-strike  7...d5  which is more complex, but subpar objectively. }
8. O-O-O Qxd4
{ Black shouldn't trade the queens yet because he doesn't have time to deal with both Nf5 and e5. }
9. Nxd4 Nc5 10. Re1
{ Preventing Black from placing a knight on e4, and aiming to play e5. } 10...
Be7
{ 10...Nfd7  Makes e5 less dangerous, when we should grab more space with  11.g4  We have a clearly better endgame as we have a lot more space.   10...Ne6!?  An interesting try to hold off our forces.  11.Nf3  As we have the initiative we should avoid trading pieces.  11...Be7  12.e5  dxe5  13.Nxe5!  A strong move. If we would have taken with the pawn, the knight on e6 does a fantastic job of blocking the pawn, thus diminishing our initiative.  13...Nd4  Was played in the Norwegian encounter Bae,T - Byklum,B Oslo 2008.  14.Ne2!  A strong move, trading the strong knight on d4.  14...Nxe2+  15.Rxe2  O-O  16.Nxc6  Our activity gives us a winning endgame. }
11. e5 { Our strike in the center is strong. } 11... dxe5 12. fxe5 Ng4 13. Bc4
{ With e6 next, Black will soon find himself in an awful position. } 13... O-O
14. e6 { White is breaking through. } 14... f6
{ 14...fxe6  fails to  15.Nxe6  Nxe6  16.Rxe6  when Black loses material. } 15.
Nf5
{ White had played a fantastic game in Duport, N-Lehmann, M Lenk 2009. When Black plays  15...Re8  next, when we will play  16.Bf4  when a knight capture on  e7  and  Bd6  will follow suit. }
