[White "Quickstarter − Alekhine, Scandi, Philidor"]
[Black "Philidor Endgame 6…Be6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5
{ This is the best and most common way to reach the Philidor Defense, named after the famous 18th century player Francois-André Danican Philidor. }
4. dxe5 dxe5 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8 6. Bc4
{ The game has barely started, and an endgame is already here. } 6... Be6
{ I must admit that it's baffling to me that this move is the most played move in the position. Black willingly gives himself an inferior pawn structure, resulting in a position where only White can play for a win. }
7. Bxe6 fxe6 8. f3
{ Defending the pawn is the first matter of business. From here, Black has a wide range of different set-ups: }
8... a6 { Is likely to transpose to the line we just looked at, after } 9. Nh3
Bd6 { Black doesn't have anything better. } 10. Be3 Ke7 11. Nb1 b5
{ Is the alternative. Note that the similar  11...c5  is met by  12.a4  , when  Na3  follows, making it tough for Black to play  b5  . }
12. Nd2 Nbd7
{ The extra space doesn't do much for Black as we can often meet c5 with c4. }
13. Nf2 Bc5 14. Ke2 Bxe3 15. Kxe3
{ White had done everything correctly, and was rewarded with a clearly better endgame in Vrana, J -Voloshin,L Czech Republic 2013. }
