[White "Quickstarter − Alekhine, Scandi, Philidor"]
[Black "Philidor Endgame 6…Ke8"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5
{ This is the best and most common way to reach the Philidor Defense, named after the famous 18th century player Francois-André Danican Philidor. }
4. dxe5 dxe5 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8 6. Bc4
{ The game has barely started, and an endgame is already here. } 6... Ke8
{ This side-step is a logical way to defend the pawn, and the suggested reaction by Ginger-GM in "The Black Lion." }
7. f4
{ This looks like the best way to aim for an advantage, and not considered by Simon in "The Black Lion." It's not so surprising that he doesn't mention it, because the move has been seen in a few number of games. }
7... Bb4
{ A very logical move so it's not surprising its on top of the list in popularity. }
8. Bd3
{ We must defend the e4-pawn. The exclam is there because it's the only testing move. }
8... Nbd7 { With this move, Black wants to place a knight on c5. } 9. Nf3 Nc5
{ Was the position in Van Foreest,J - Bologan,V Chess.com INT 2020 when Jorden should have played }
10. O-O exf4
{ Looks nice for White after   10...Bxc3  Black's best attempt is to go for this move which leads to a marginally worse position.  11.bxc3  Nfxe4  12.Re1  The bishop pair makes things drawish of course, but our position is marginally more pleasant.  12...Nxd3!  13.cxd3  Nd6  Black has to have the option of playing Be6 if we take the pawn with the rook. The knight on d6 prevents Bf5.  14.Ba3  White's best try is to get rid of the knight.  14...Be6  15.Rxe5  Kd7  16.Bxd6  cxd6  17.Rb5  White has some pressure in the endgame, but Black should draw with accurate play of course. Note that 17.. . b6?? loses after 18. f5. }
11. Bxf4 Nxd3 12. cxd3 c6 13. a3 Be7 14. d4 { Our center gives us an edge. }
14... Be6 15. Rad1
{ It's easy to forget that Black can't castle! Our center and Black's poor king gives us the clearly better game. }
