[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter − Caro-Kann, French"]
[Black "Caro-Kann 3.exd5 cxd5 4.Bd3 g6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4
{ Our strategy during this course has always been to grab the center while we can, and this time is no different! }
2... d5
{ Black takes control of the center and poses an important question to our e4-pawn. }
3. exd5
{ After lots of thinking and consulting with some good friends of mine, I decided to head for the Exchange Variation. }
3... cxd5 4. Bd3
{ The main tabiya of the variation, developing our bishop to the active d3-square. }
4... g6
{ Some players have chosen to play this move already here, with the idea of fianchettoing the f8-bishop. With this set-up the play becomes less symmetrical, which is a typical way for a higher-rated opponent to act. The downside is that Black gets less control of the center, something that can make his position rather passive. }
5. Nf3 Bg7 6. c3
{ A move which we always play, as it's essential to support the d4-pawn. } 6...
Nh6
{ Black has this extra alternative at his disposal. It looks very odd indeed, but it's not as bad as it looks. The knight can head to f5 and from there to d6. Black can also attempt to change the light-squared bishops by playing Bf5, and he may even attempt an e5-break with the support of f6-Nf7. Once again, this approach is a typical one from someone who searches to make the game unbalanced, as the winning chances will obviously increase. }
7. O-O O-O 8. Re1
{ A move we constantly see in these positions, as it takes control of the open e-file. }
8... Nc6 9. h3
{ A strong move which limits the bishop on c8 and the knight on h6, since it controls the g4-square. }
9... f6
{ On most occasions Black has played this thematic move, but it turns out it's too rushed. }
10. c4
{ YES! c4 attacks the pawn on d5 which will damage Black's center, making e5 a lot less potent. Black has tried different moves from this position: }
10... dxc4
{ Is the move that appears at the top of the engine list, while Black also has a score of 2/3. It's indeed a logical move, as Black avoids the trouble down the a2-g8 diagonal. }
11. Bxc4+ Kh8
{ Somehow Black has played  11...Nf7  twice, which makes very little sense to me. This transposes to  10...Nf7  . With the knight on  h6  , Black can jump to the active square on  f5  . }
12. b3
{ This is a brilliant move with the plan of placing the bishop on b2 where it will defend the d4-pawn. It could also move to a3 and target the e7-pawn. }
12... Nf7
{ The alternative.   12...Nf5  A logical response is to attack our pawn. We can respond in several different ways, with my favorite move being  13.Bb2   I intended the sophisticated  13.d5  Ne5  14.Bb2  which is still strong, but I think the text move is a lot simpler.  13...e5  Black has nothing better than heading towards an endgame which is clearly worse. If not, we are allowed to play d5 which would leave Black's position in shambles.  14.dxe5  Qxd1  15.Rxd1  fxe5  16.Nbd2±  Black's poor pawn on  e5  provides us excellent winning chances. We can stop here, but I would like to provide the sample line:  16...Nfd4  17.Nxd4  Nxd4  18.Ne4  h6  19.Nd6  Kh7  20.Nf7  , with the idea of taking on  e5  followed by  Bxd4  . The drawing chances are there, but not very high. }
13. Nc3 { The logical approach usually triumphs, this is no exception. } 13...
Bf5 14. Bb2 Rc8
{ A logical move. Note that  14...e5  allows  15.Ba3!  and that   14...Nb4  is met by  15.g4! }
15. Qe2
{ We don't need to do anything fancy. With Qe2 we are planning to go Rad1. Next, we will attempt a takeover on the light squares with Be6-d5. Another plan is to play g4 and remove Black's best piece, the bishop on f5, with Ne4-Nc5 coming. }
15... Nd6 16. Rad1 Nxc4
{ The human move is to grab the bishop, but it will give us a very nice center. }
17. bxc4 Re8 { Black should defend the e7-pawn. } 18. c5 Na5 19. Ba3
{ We have a fantastic initiative with the deadly idea d5-Nd4 just around the corner. Black has to neutralize our center with  19. ..b6  , but that can be met by  20.Nb5  when Black has to give the a7-pawn. }
