[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter − Caro-Kann, French"]
[Black "Caro-Kann 3.exd5 cxd5 4.Bd3 Nc6 − 5...g6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 g6
{ Playing g6 without the knight on f6 or h6 is possible as well, as it allows Black to place the bishop on f5 as an additional option. }
6. Nf3
{ 6.Bf4  has been slightly more common, but I discovered that  6...Bh6!  is a rather annoying move to face. }
6... Bf5
{ Whenever Black has played g6, this move is a possibility. It's a very common idea, as Black wants to rid himself of the poor light-squared bishop.   6...Bg7  Has been the most common move, which should lead to a transposition to either the previous chapter or 5... Nf6 in this chapter.  7.O-O   And here one possible transposition is  7...Nf6  8.Bf4  O-O  9.Nbd2  . }
7. Bxf5 { Damaging Black's pawn structure is the way to go. } 7... gxf5 8. Bg5
{ The most critical move. We develop our bishop, while we also prevent Black from playing e7-e6. }
8... Bg7 9. O-O Nf6 { Is a standard reaction for sure. } 10. Nbd2 O-O
{ 10...Ne4  This move looks typical, when we have the surprising reaction  11.Nxe4!  We are 'correcting' Black's pawn structure, but eventually we will be able to open the position with f2-f3 which could become very dangerous as we get an open f-file and excellent control over the light squares.  11...fxe4  12.Nh4  h6  13.Be3  e6  14.g3±  We are ready to play f2-f3 with an excellent position. }
11. Ne1 { A strong move with the intent of maneuvering the knight to d3. }
11... Ne4
{ Black avoids Bxf6 while he can, but I honestly think the move just helps us.   11...e6  12.Nd3  Ne7  Occurred in Shcherbakov,R - Sosnicki,M Minsk 1998, when I think  13.Nf4⩲  looks promising for White. Options like 13. Nf3 or Kh1 were excellent too. The theme of these positions is usually that we attempt to exploit Black's lack of control of the dark squares and Black's slightly exposed kingside. After the text move we have ideas like Bxf6 followed by Nh5. The d2-knight is likely to head to f3, but it could also head to c5 via b3. }
12. Be3
{ The best move. I am less convinced by  12.Bf4  which was played in all three games as Black gets e7-e5 with a tempo. Although I will admit that White was slightly better after  12...f6  13.f3  Nxd2  14.Qxd2  e5  15.Bg3  in Schiendorfer, R - Dimov, I ICCF email 2009. }
12... f6
{ Black can play in the same fashion like against 12. Bf4. We should respond with   12...e6  Is rather similar to what we saw earlier, when a sample line is  13.Nd3  Qd7  14.Nf4  Nd6  15.Qe2±  White has a very comfortable position with tons of interesting ideas. }
13. Ndf3 { The knight is headed to the h4-square. } 13... e5
{ 13...e6  14.Nh4±  Looks very good for us as we will sooner or later push away the knight on e4. }
14. g3 { It's essential that we stop f5-f4! } 14... Ne7 15. Nh4 Qd7 16. f4
{ Beautiful positional play! Black is really struggling with the double pawns in the f-file. }
16... Bh6 17. dxe5
{ We are releasing the tension, but Black's f5-pawn will be a nice target. }
17... fxe5 18. Neg2 exf4 19. Nxf4
{ Our minor pieces work wonderfully together. It looks positionally awful to be Black here, and indeed, the advantage is around +1.00. It's worth noting that Nxd5 is a nice threat in this position! }
