[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter − Caro-Kann, French"]
[Black "Caro-Kann 3.exd5 cxd5 4.Bd3 Nc6 − 5...Qc7"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 Qc7 6. h3
{ I believe that this is the most challenging move, although there is a very interesting alternative in  6.Na3!?  The point behind the text move is to prevent Black's bishop from heading to  g4  , which is Black's standard reaction after the immediate  6.Ne2  . Black has several different reactions here, which we will take a look at in turn and order. }
6... Nf6 { It's not surprising that this is Black's most common move. } 7. Nf3
{ The right square for the knight.  7.Ne2  allows  7...e5  when it seems like Black has already equalized due to this active pieces. From this position the path is split in two: }
7... g6 { The most popular move by a long shot. } 8. Qc2
{ There's nothing wrong with  8.O-O  , but I prefer to avoid  8...Bf5  . } 8...
Bg7 9. O-O O-O
{ We have arrived at the main place of this variation. This is one of the rare instances where I provide you with an alternative, but it's because the two moves sort of intertwine in several places. }
10. Re1 Nh5
{ Black usually goes for this move straight away, intending to place the knight on  f4  , similar to the note we saw with  10...Re8  . }
11. Be3 { Black has tried different moves here: } 11... e5
{ Has been played before, but it looks kind of strange to play it in this manner.   11...f5  This was seen in a correspondence game I found, but it looks incredibly strange.  12.Na3  Is a simple reaction.  12...a6  13.Rad1  b5  14.Bd2⩲  With a good position in Brown,K-Fuchs,J ICCF email 2015. I like the plan Qc1-Nc2-Nb4 which looks strong. Bh6 may also be considered at a later stage. }
12. dxe5 Nxe5 13. Nxe5 Bxe5 14. Nd2
{ Black has only scored 0.5/3 in this position, which is a good sign for us. The drawn game was also a game where White had 200 points less. It's not a surprising result, as we get very simple play. }
14... Nf4 15. Nf3
{ We have excellent control of the d4-square, which is an important factor in positions with isolated pawns. }
15... Bg7
{ And here, I think the simplest way to proceed is to force the trade of some more pieces. }
16. Qd2 Nxd3 17. Qxd3
{ White had a strong positional advantage in Dolsonov, A - Smirnova,E Belgrade 2021. Bd4 comes next, when White will get a dream scenario of a good knight against a poor bishop. }
