[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter − Caro-Kann, French"]
[Black "Caro-Kann 3.exd5 cxd5 4.Bd3 Nc6 − 5...Nf6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 Nf6
{ After a ton of analysis, we have reached Black's main continuation in the position. This is also the approach GM Erwin L'Ami suggests in his course. }
6. Bf4 { 'The best scheme' - GM Erwin L'Ami. } 6... Qb6
{ We must consider this move which makes use of the fact that our bishop no longer stands on the c1-square. }
7. Qb3
{ The right way to defend the b2-square.  7.Na3!?  is a cool alternative, when I think  7...e5!  gives Black decent chances. }
7... Qxb3
{ The usual response.  7...Bg4  is also played a lot, which is a fancy way of reaching a position covered in our final Caro-Kann chapter. }
8. axb3 e6 9. h3
{ A nice move as it prevents Black from removing our control of the h2-b8 diagonal with a knight jump on the rim. }
9... Be7 10. b4
{ White will now push the b-pawn to b5 where it will kick the knight away from its post on c6. }
10... O-O 11. b5 Nd8 12. Nf3
{ White had done well in the opening phase of the game in Ozbilici, A-Gonen,M Konya 2017. Black's position is rather unpleasant due to how passive it is. }
