[White "Quickstarter − Caro-Kann, French"]
[Black "Caro-Kann 3.exd5 cxd5 4.Bd3 Nc6 − 5...Nf6 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 Nf6 6. Bf4 Bg4
{ The most critical variation, Black develops the bishop with a tempo. L'Ami emphasizes on how essential it is for Black to get the bishop out on the board before playing e7-e6. Positions we have seen earlier clearly shows that the Dutchman is 100% correct in his statement. Therefore, it really isn't very surprising that this is Black's most played move in the position. }
7. Qb3
{ The obvious choice as Black's bishop no longer covers the pawn on b7. } 7...
Qd7
{ Is the most natural way to guard the pawn on b7, so it's not surprising that this is the most played move and also L'Ami's choice in his course. }
8. Nd2 { Pretty much always played, intending Ngf3. } 8... e6 9. Ngf3 Bxf3
{ Giving the light-squared bishop away for the knight is played frequently by tons of strong players. }
10. Nxf3 Bd6 11. Bxd6
{ The most principled try for an advantage. However, most bishop moves are possible here, including  11.Be3!?  ,  11.Bg3  ,  11.Bd2!?  and even  11.Be5!?  . IM Irine Sukandar has beaten two decent players with the strange-looking  11.Bd2  , so I decided to have a look myself. Both games went:  11...O-O  12.Qc2  Rac8  13.a3  , and here Irine faced two different moves. One of them was  13...Na5  14.Bg5  Ne4  15.Bxe4  dxe4  16.Qxe4  h6  17.Be3  Qb5  18.Qc2  Rfe8  19.a4  Qc4  20.Qe2  and White was clearly better in Sukandar, I - Panda, S Sharjah 2019. Gunina, rated 2500, played  13...h6  , and the game went  14.O-O  Qc7  15.g3  Na5  16.Rae1  Nc4  17.Qc1  , and here Black blundered with  17.Ne4?  Instead,   17...Nxd2  18.Qxd2  looks slightly better for White.  (A very typical scenario for the arising positions in this line. Objectively, White doesn't have much. However, over the board it's just a lot easier to handle White. At the end of the day, this is what matters!) }
11... Qxd6 12. O-O O-O 13. Rfe1
{ I prefer to move the f-rook to e1 in order to have the possibility of placing the a1-rook on c1 if I so desire. }
13... Rab8
{ Black's most played move in the position. On b8, the rook is well placed for a potential b5-b4 break in the future.   13...Nd7  Some players have tried this move with Black. The idea is to prevent us from jumping to e5.  14.Re3!?  I like the idea of taking complete control over the e-file. That being said, there's not really any specific theory here. You can play in a lot of different ways!  14...a6  Black goes for the usual queenside expansion.  15.Rae1  b5  16.Qc2  We're provoking a concession in Black's camp.  16...h6  16... g6?! is inaccurate because of h4, intending h5 with a scary attack.  17.Ne5↑  White has some initiative here with ideas such as Qd2 followed by Rg3 and Bb1. We can also play f4 if Black avoids capturing our knight on e5.   13...Qc7  Is also a move that's been tried, when I suggest going for  14.Qc2  A standard way of playing. We're swinging the queen to the kingside.  14...Rac8  15.Qe2  We should of course not allow Nb4.  15...Nd7  16.g3  A recurring plan, intending to play Kg2 and launch the h-pawn forward.  16...Rfe8  17.Kg2  a6  18.h4  h6   18...b5?  would be really bad due to  19.a4!  18...Na5  is a much better possibility, but I still we're doing well after  19.Ne5  with a dangerous initiative.  19.Rad1  This move looks better than 19. Bc2 in Ni,S - Gunina,V Qinhuangdao 2018. It deserves to be mentioned that White quickly obtained a rather nice position, but in the end she made a threefold with a large advantage.  19...Na5  20.Ne5  Nxe5  Black should take the knight before we're allowed to play f4.  21.dxe5  Nc4  22.f4  b5  23.Kh3!?  I would be very scared as Black as our initiative is very scary. It's not so easy to tell how Black should obtain counterplay on the queenside, as for example  23...a5  can be answered by  24.b3  . }
14. Qd1
{ I like this move played by Ganguly, a man who's usually very well prepared. That being said,  14.Qc2  should be rather similar. }
14... Qf4
{ I'll admit that I do struggle a bit to see what Kovalenko wants by placing the queen on f4. He ended up moving the queen to f6 later in the game, but I doubt that this was intentional. It makes sense I guess to provoke g3, but why provoke a move that just helps our cause? Curious...   Other moves won't change our approach too much, unless Black plays  14...b5  which is well met by  15.b4!  Black's play on the queenside is completely halted. A very nice detail is that  15...a5  is met by  16.a4!  When we can play  b5  in case Black takes on  a4  with an excellent game. }
15. Qe2 a6 16. a3
{ A thematic move. Ganguly prepares to play against the typical break on the queenside by preventing b4. }
16... Nd7 17. Qc2
{ The queen moves out of the way for the rooks with a tempo. } 17... g6 18. Re3
{ The typical plan, doubling the rooks in the e-file! } 18... Rfe8 19. Rae1 b5
20. g3 { It's time to make the queen move. } 20... Qf6
{ 20...Qd6  21.Kg2  is also better for White, when our plan of h4-h5 still stands. }
21. Qe2 Nb6
{ Ganguly has played very well for far in Ganguly, S - Kovalenko, I Saint Louis 2019, but instead of  22.b4  , I think }
22. b3
{ Is better as Black can't jump to c4, while we also maintain the option of playing a4 at some point. Besides that, our path forward is the typical kingside attacking plan with h4-h5-Kg2. It looks tough for Black to gain counterplay on the queenside here due to our excellent control. }
