[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nc6 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. e5 Ne4 6. Ne2
{ Our strategy should be to play around the knight on e4. } 6... f6
{ Black's best move is to fight our center immediately. } 7. Nf4 Be7
{ The French GM Christian Bauer played this move with Black, a well-known expert of unusual openings. }
8. exf6
{ It's time to take the pawn now that Black can't recapture with the queen. }
8... Bxf6
{ 8...Nxf6  This is a bad approach by Black now that we have such fantastic pressure against the e6-pawn.  9.g3  Our bishop will be well-placed on g2 where it takes aim on d5, making it tough for Black to get rid of the weakness by playing e5.  9...Ne4  10.Bg2  O-O  11.O-O  ±  Just like in the similar positions we saw earlier: We will be doing well if we get Black's e5-break under control. Without e5 Black will remain passive, while the pawn on e6 will also be a nice target for our pieces. }
9. c3 O-O 10. Be2
{ The bishop needs to be placed here, since it's important that our queens aims towards d5 after dxe5. }
10... Be7 { Black decides to maneuver the bishop to the d6-square. } 11. O-O
{ 11.Bb5  was played in the strong GM encounter Tomczak, J - Bauer, C Batumi 2018, but this move makes no sense to me. If you wanted to play  Bb5  , why didn't you do it right away? White eventually won, but the advantage had decreased substantially after  11.Bb5  . }
11... Bd6 12. Nh5
{ Yet another advantage of having the knight on f4! We can return to the old plan of removing the e4-knight. This will allow us to play against the e6-pawn on the e-file. }
12... Bd7 { It really isn't easy for Black to come up with a plan. } 13. Ng3
Nf6
{ Moving the knight back looks like the lesser of two evils.   13...Nxg3  Is now bet by  14.hxg3  It's really hard for Black to play e5. A simple line is:  14...Qf6  15.Bg5  Qf7  16.c4±  There were many strong moves here. I decided to stick with my recommendation from 'Destroy the French,' @@StartBracket@@yeah, get used to me referencing my video series a lot@@EndBracket@@, as the move is thematic. We saw this move earlier. The plan is c5, so Black is pretty much forced to take when he will be left with a weak pawn on e6. }
14. Re1 Re8
{ Preparing e5 as   14...e5  would be met by two captures on  e5  followed by  Bf3  . }
15. Bb5
{ A strong move which makes it even harder for Black to play e5. The bishop can move to c2 later when we will create threats against Black's king with Qd3. }
15... a6 16. Ba4
{ I prefer to keep the bishop as I am more interested in creating an attack with Bc2 than taking and playing Ne5. }
16... Ne7 { Black needs to do something so it makes sense to prepare c5. } 17.
Bc2 c5 18. Bg5
{ Black is suffering due to his passive position and weak e6-pawn. We will soon play Qd3 followed by Ne5 with a fantastic initiative. }
