[White "Quickstarter − Caro-Kann, French"]
[Black "French For Knox 4...Bd7 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3
{ We have completed our work against Black's sidelines, so it's time to take a look at Black's main tries in the position. }
3... dxe4
{ Black captures our pawn and changes the position completely. Now the position is open, so we won't get the standard French pawn structures we have seen in earlier lines. This move can be compared to the 3... Qd8-line in the Scandinavian. Black is solid as there are no weaknesses in the pawn structure, but he does lack some space. Black intends to play c7-c5 at a later stage, which will neutralize our center. The line has been played by countless GMs, perhaps in particular by the strong German GM Georg Meier. I jokingly regard this line as a 'draw offer,' as it is used primarily as a drawing weapon. }
4. Nxe4 Bd7
{ Black has a wide range of alternatives which will be examined in the next chapter.  4...Nd7  is the main tabiya, labeled the Rubinstein Variation, and also examined at a later stage. The text move is a corny-looking move. Black wants to activate the poor French bishop by placing it on the c6-square. 'Fort Knox' is what this line is called, named after the U.S army installation in Kentucky. I suspect that the reason for this given name is the solid reputation of the line. }
5. Nf3 Bc6
{ Black's point. Other moves make no sense which the online base clearly demonstrates as the second most popular move has only been seen a bit over 20 times. The text move has been seen over 9600 times in comparison! }
6. Bd3
{ As the complications after  6.Neg5  lead nowhere, we should stick with this logical developing move. Black has tried different moves here, but the clear main move is  6...Nd7  . }
6... Be7
{ Black prepares to place the knight on f6 as he will be able to recapture with the bishop. }
7. c3 Nf6
{ 7...Nd7  is possible, when play is quite similar to the Main Line. } 8. Nxf6+
Bxf6 9. Qe2 { We're going for queenside castling! } 9... Nd7 10. Bf4 O-O
{ Black's most popular choice, but slightly risky as Black will be under a powerful attack. }
11. O-O-O { Of course! } 11... Qe7 12. h4
{ It's time to launch our pawns towards Black's king. Note that Bxh7+ is now a thematic threat. }
12... Rfe8 13. Ne5
{ 13.Bxh7?  didn't work any longer which White learned the brutal way in Gomez Gomez, F - Cruz Alvarez de Ron, D Madrid 2008. After  13...Kxh7  14.Ng5+  Kg8  15.Rh3  Nf8  16.Qg4  e5  17.dxe5  Bxe5  18.h5  Ne6  19.Be3  Nxg5  20.Bxg5  Qe6  , White resigned. }
13... Bxg2 { A risky pawn grab, but the best practical choice. } 14. Rh2
{ 14.Rhg1  is the automatic move, but after  14...Bh3!  things are less clear than what I'd prefer. }
14... Bd5 15. c4 Bc6 16. Rg1
{ Black's extra pawn helps nothing here, as our initiative is incredibly strong. }
16... Rad8 17. Bc2 Nf8 18. Be3
{ Our initiative gives us a decisive advantage as Black has no counterplay. } *

