[White "Quickstarter − Caro-Kann, French"]
[Black "French Rubinstein 4...Be7"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3
{ We have completed our work against Black's sidelines, so it's time to take a look at Black's main tries in the position. }
3... dxe4
{ Black captures our pawn and changes the position completely. Now the position is open, so we won't get the standard French pawn structures we have seen in earlier lines. }
4. Nxe4 Be7
{ This is a very sneaky move - Black prevents our usual set-up as we can no longer place the bishop on g5! }
5. Nf3 Nf6 6. Nxf6+ Bxf6 7. c3 Nd7
{ The right approach. With c7-c5 coming very quickly, Black will be able to create sufficient counterplay. }
8. Bd3 c5 { There's no time to waste for Black! } 9. O-O O-O 10. a4
{ In order to keep things simple, I want to make sure that we can transpose to the previous note in case Black takes on d4. Besides, a4 is always a useful move as it grabs space on the queenside. }
10... cxd4 11. Nxd4 a6
{ Black halts the journey of our knight on d4, as it can no longer reach b5. }
12. Re1 e5
{ 12...Nc5  This time Black doesn't get sufficient compensation!  13.Bxh7+  Kxh7  14.Qh5+  Kg8  15.Qxc5  With a pawn up. Play may continue:  15...e5  16.Nf3  Be6  17.Be3±  A pawn is a pawn! }
13. Nb3 Qc7 14. a5 { Once again we gather control over b6! } 14... Rd8 15. Qe2
Rb8
{ Black needs to find a way to develope the last of his pieces. b7-b5 is the only sensible way to do so. }
16. Qe4 g6 17. Qc4 Qxc4 18. Bxc4
{ We have reached a pleasant ending where we're in the driving seat. b7-b5 will cause a massive weakness on a6 after axb6, so Black should move the d7-knight in order to get the bishop out on the board. This will allow our knight to jump to the strong square on c5 where it will put Black under pressure. }
