[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter − Caro-Kann, French"]
[Black "French Rubinstein 4...Nd7 − 5...Be7"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4
{ Black captures our pawn and changes the position completely. Now the position is open, so we won't get the standard French pawn structures we have seen in earlier lines. This move can be compared to the 3... Qd8-line in the Scandinavian. Black is solid as there are no weaknesses in the pawn structure, but he does lack some space. Black intends to play c7-c5 at a later stage, which will neutralize our center. The line has been played by countless GMs, perhaps in particular by the strong German GM Georg Meier. I jokingly regard this line as a 'draw offer,' as it is used primarily as a drawing weapon. }
4. Nxe4
{ Before we can head to the main tabiya in the Rubinstein Variation, we must take a look at what happens if Black decides to capture on f6 with the knight. }
4... Nd7 5. Nf3 Be7 6. Bd3 Ngf6 7. Nxf6+ Nxf6
{ This move makes more sense to the human eye, but I dare to say that  7...Bxf6  is better! }
8. Qe2
{ And how do we fight against passive set-ups? You guessed it, it's by starting an attack! }
8... O-O 9. Bg5
{ This time I prefer placing the bishop on  g5  , as Black can play  9.Bf4  Nd5  with tempo which is kind of annoying. }
9... h6
{ A human instinct is to play h6 whenever a piece stands on g5.   9...Nd5  Is always met by  10.h4  And if  10...h6  11.Bd2±  Is a typical reaction. Black hasn't achieved anything of playing h6 & Nd5 in this fashion, while we have already played the attacking move h4. }
10. h4
{ We're wasting no time! Black can't take the bishop, as the open h-file will lead to mate one way or another. }
10... c5 11. O-O-O Nd5
{ The trickiest approach by Black. Other moves allow us to proceed with our attack. }
12. c4
{ An important move. The standard  12.Bd2  gives Black counterplay after  12...cxd4  , when  Qb6  and  Bf6  could follow suit. }
12... Nb4 13. dxc5
{ The point. With the knight gone from d5, we are threatening the discovery Bh7+, winning the queen. }
13... Nxd3+ 14. Rxd3 Qc7 15. Bxe7 Qxe7 16. Qe3
{ After trading some pieces we have obtained an extra pawn. We are close to winning as Black won't be able to regain it. Rhd1-Ne5-g3 is a strong way to proceed. We can also continue with g4-g5 as well. Hell, even b2-b4 could be considered at some point, but you should obviously be careful with a concession like that. }
