1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3
{ It's time to examine the main tabiya of the Rubinstein Variation. } 3... Nf6
4. Bg5
{ I am not going to head into details in this chapter, but this is my chosen weapon against the Classical Variation. }
4... dxe4 5. Nxe4 Nbd7 6. Nxf6+ Nxf6 7. Nf3
{ We have arrived at the main position of the Rubinstein. } 7... Be7
{ Certainly a logical approach, but it does look slightly passive if you ask me. }
8. Bd3 { Natural development. } 8... b6
{ A natural response by Black is to fianchetto the c8-bishop. Our reaction remains the same. }
9. Qe2 Bb7 10. O-O-O
{ Once again, I will emphasize the power of playing for an attack when we have more space.  10.O-O  is not bad by any means, but I doubt we have anything special as Black is incredibly solid. }
10... O-O 11. Kb1
{ If you have been following the course, I am sure you're aware of how much I like this prophylactic move! It's usage here is rather clear, as we are defending our vulnerable pawn on a2 which can be targeted by the thematic Bxf3 followed by Qd5. }
11... Nd5
{ Is a logical attempt to ease off the pressure.   11...Qd6  Black has drawn most games with this natural move, intending Rad8.  12.Ne5  Rad8  13.Rhe1   Topalov played  13.c4  , but Black obtained excellent compensation after  13...h6  14.Bf4  Qxd4  15.Bh7+  Kxh7  16.Rxd4  Rxd4  . Although Topalov eventually won, the position looks quite even to me. Topalov, V - Vaganian, R Novgorod 1995.  13...h6  14.Bc1  Another benefit to Kb1! We are now ready to launch our kingside pawns towards the black king!  14...Qxd4  15.g4→   Don't be tempted by  15.Bh7  , as Black has a huge amount of compensation, similarly to Topalov - Vaganian. After the text move, White had a very powerful attack in Polatel, A -Owens, J ICCF email 2015. }
12. h4
{ We should keep our bishop on  g5  as long as we can.  12.Bc1  looks logical, but after  12...Nb4  Black has a lot of play. }
12... h6 13. c4 { A very strong move that removes the annoying knight on d5. }
13... Nf6
{ 13...Bxg5  is met by  14.cxd5  which wins a pawn while Black also becomes incredibly weak on the light squares. }
14. Ne5
{ Much stronger than  14.Bc1  which was Vlcek, S - Kovacocy, P Slovakia 1999. After the text move, it's incredibly difficult for Black to find something to do. Our attack plays itself. }
14... Nd7 15. Bc2
{ Black is toast. A sample line is:  15...f6  16.Nc6  Bxc6  17.Qxe6+  Rf7  18.Bg6  Kh8  19.Qxc6  Rf8  20.Bc2  . Our bishop on  g5  is untouchable due to  Qg6  . }
