{ In my database, White scores as much as 65% in the event that Black decides to trade queens. This score seems accurate, as the endgames are quite unpleasant for Black. }
15. Qxe4 dxe4 16. Ne2 Bd7
{ 16...Na6  was seen in Forster, R - Moor, O Zug 2001, but it's just terrible after  17.c6!  Black is forced to take, when we can respond with  Ng3  or  Nc3  , intending  Nxe4  . Black has major holes in his camp. }
17. Rb1 Bc6
{ 17...Na6  is according to Kortschnoj, well-known theory. After  18.Rxb7  Nxc5  he gives  19.Rb4  and says that White is better. This is not untrue, however  19.Rc7  is much stronger! The point is to stay in the c-file. A sample line is:  19...Na6  20.Rc3  Nb4  21.Ng3  Nd5  22.Rc5  f5  23.exf6  Nxf6  24.Bc3  . The endgame looks lost for Black. }
18. Nd4 e3
{ In most games, Black has tried this move which I think is a highly logical way to proceed as Black improves the bishop on g2. However, there are alternatives.   I will not require you to memorize them though...  18...Nd7  19.Nxc6  bxc6  20.Ke2  Nxc5  21.Rb4  h5  22.Rd1  looks really good for us, as the bishop is much stronger than the knight.  Be3  comes, followed by a capture on the pawn on  e4  .   18...Na6  Makes some sense as well. We proceed with  19.Nxc6  bxc6  , and here I am a fan of  20.h4  intending  20...O-O-O  21.Rh3  , with a fantastic ending.   18...Kd7  has been seen as well, but it looks rather poor.  19.O-O  Na6  20.Rfd1  Nxc5  and here we have the tactic  21.Bxh6  with a decisive advantage. Black can't take due to  Nf5+  .   18...Bd5  allows us to jump into  d6  .  19.Nb5  Na6  20.c4  Bc6  21.Nd6+  Ke7  22.Be3  looks fantastic for us. }
19. Bxe3 Bxg2 20. Rg1 Bd5 21. Nb5
{ There's no doubt that we have the upper hand here, as we'll place a knight on d6 followed by c4. }
21... Kd8 22. c4 Bc6 23. Nd6 Ke7 24. f4
{ The endgame is very tough to defend. I leave you with a fantastic correspondence game. Enjoy!  24...Nd7  25.Rb3  Rhb8  26.Ra3  a5  27.Ke2  a4  28.Bd4  h5  29.Rag3  Ra5  30.Nxf7  Kxf7  31.Rxg6  Rh8  32.f5  Nf8  33.Rg7+  Ke8  34.f6  Kd8  35.Be3  Nd7  36.Rg8+  Rxg8  37.Rxg8+  Kc7  38.f7  b6  39.cxb6+  Kb7  40.f8Q  Nxf8  41.Rxf8  Ra8  42.Rf7+  Ka6  43.Re7  Be4  44.Bd4  Bf5  45.Kd2  a3  46.Kc3  Bb1  47.Kb4  Be4  48.Kxa3  Bb7  49.Kb4  Rd8  50.Kc3  Rf8  51.Rxe6  Rf1  52.Rd6  Rc1+  53.Kb4  Rb1+  54.Kc5  Re1  55.e6  What a masterpiece! Casier, W - Fremmegaard, J ICCF email 2018. }
