[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter − Caro-Kann, French"]
[Black "French Classical – Alekhine/Chatard #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5 Be7
{ The last branch of the 3... Nf6-line! Black gets out of the pin by simply moving the bishop in between. This has been the most popular response by Black, and is thus the main tabiya of the 4. Bg5-line. }
5. e5
{ Black targets our pawn, so we must advance. 5. Bxf6 is possible, but harmless for Black. }
5... Nfd7 6. h4 { This pawn sacrifice known as the Alekhine-Chatard Attack. }
6... c5 { Can be played, but I think it's too early due to the hole on d6. } 7.
Bxe7 Kxe7
{ Now that we saw that  7...Qxe7  doesn't really work, Black should take with the king! As strange as it looks, it might surprise you that Black's king is safer than what it looks on  e7  . }
8. Qd2
{ I am bit surprised by the fact that this natural move hasn't been played more often. Most games have continued with  8.f4  , and here I honestly think Black is okay after  8...cxd4  9.Qxd4  Qb6  10.Qxb6  Nxb6  like in Nunn, J - Seirawan, Y Cannes 1992. }
8... Nc6
{ 8...cxd4?  Is a blunder due to  9.Qg5+  And Black loses the valuable pawn on g7.  9...Ke8  10.Qxg7  Rf8  Things wouldn't have been so bad, if it wasn't for  11.Nb5+-  And the knight heads to d6. }
9. dxc5 { Black has to decide which pawn to take. } 9... Ndxe5
{ The right pawn to grab, as the e5-pawn contributed well to our attack.   9...Nxc5?  Is not the right pawn to take.  10.O-O-O  h6  Black takes control over the square on g5.  11.h5  Has a pretty neat idea to it. We're planning to use the 4h rank for our rook on h1 via h4.  11...a6  12.Nf3  b5  13.Rh4+-  Black's position is in dire straits due to the exposed king. }
10. O-O-O h5
{ Played in a recent Correspondence game. Black stops our h-pawn from advancing, takes control over g4 @@StartBracket@@it will be an outpost when we play f2-f4@@EndBracket@@, and also gives the rook on h8 some flexibility as it can move to h6. }
11. f4 Ng4
{ The logical square for the knight.   11...Ng6?  I was extremely surprised when I saw that Black had played this move. Perhaps it was a typo? Anyway, the refutation is quite instructive.  12.f5  Nge5  13.Nf3  Black's kingside is about to get blasted open.  13...Nxf3  14.gxf3  Kf8  15.fxe6  Bxe6  Giving the pawn is the lesser evil, but the resulting endgame is still completely lost.  16.Nxd5  Qxd5  17.Qxd5  Bxd5  18.Rxd5  Rd8  Black gets rid of the active rook, but the endgame is lost as the queenside majority is too strong.  19.Rxd8+  Nxd8  20.b4+-  With computer help it was a simple task for White to realize his advantage in Sikorsky,R - Loeschnauer,R ICCF email 2018. }
12. Bb5 Re8
{ Black 'castles.'  12...Kf8?  would be quite bad now due to the nice trick  13.Bxc6  bxc6  14.Ne4!  when the knight heads to  d6  . }
13. Nh3 Kf8 14. Nf2
{ Black loses the blockade on g4. The path forward will be to start an attack with g4 at some point. It looks really dangerous for Black. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter − Caro-Kann, French"]
[Black "French Classical – Alekhine/Chatard #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5 Be7
{ The last branch of the 3... Nf6-line! Black gets out of the pin by simply moving the bishop in between. This has been the most popular response by Black, and is thus the main tabiya of the 4. Bg5-line. }
5. e5
{ Black targets our pawn, so we must advance.  5.Bxf6  is possible, but harmless for Black. }
5... Nfd7 6. h4 { This pawn sacrifice known as the Alekhine-Chatard Attack. }
6... a6
{ We have finally arrived to the last sideline Black has in his arsenal. This is a very standard way of playing. Black covers the b5-square and is thus set to attack our center with c5 next. }
7. Qg4
{ The only way to disturb Black's plans as we're threatening Qxg7. Black has tried to dodge this threat in a number of ways: }
7... Bxg5
{ After a plethora of options, we have arrived to Black's most played move. }
8. hxg5 c5
{ Black has achieved c5 right away, while we have obtained an open h-file. } 9.
dxc5
{ Hopefully you're not surprised that this is our reaction! Black can now take on e5 right away or develop the knight to c6 first. }
9... Nc6 10. Nf3 Ndxe5
{ Black wins our pawn in the center, but it turns out that the open h-file is more beneficial.   10...Nxc5?  Allows the thematic trick  11.g6!  With the point  11...fxg6  12.Rxh7 }
11. Nxe5 Nxe5 12. Qg3 Ng6
{ 12...Nc6  is simply met by  13.O-O-O  with Bd3, f4 and g6 coming. } 13. Bd3
Bd7 14. O-O-O Qb8 { Black's best try is to 'trick' us into trading queens. }
15. Qe3 Ne7
{ Was Degraeve,J -Gurevich,M Belfort 1997, and here a simple solution is to go }
16. f4 { With a completely dominating position. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter − Caro-Kann, French"]
[Black "French Classical – Alekhine/Chatard #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5 Be7 5. e5 Nfd7 6. h4 Bxg5
{ This time on the menu of our 1. e4 restaurant is the Alekhine- Chatard Attack Accepted. A courageous choice, but objectively the right one. That being said, the path forward is very narrow for Black... One has to be incredibly well prepared, hence why 4... dxe4 has taken more and more over. }
7. hxg5 Qxg5 8. Nh3
{ Black has to make an incredibly important decision on where to place the queen. }
8... Qe7
{ This is by far the most logical and popular move. Unfortunately for Black, it is a bad one. }
9. Qg4 f5 { A move Black doesn't make with pleasure, but it's possible. } 10.
Qg3 Nf8
{ 10...Nc6?!  Is a mistake, due to  11.Nf4!  Which threatens both Nfxd5 and Ng6.  11...Nf8  12.O-O-O  Qf7  Black keeps the pawn on d5 protected.  13.Be2  Bd7?   A blunder.  13...Ne7  is Black's best try, and here I think we're doing well after  14.Nb5  Kd8  15.Qb3  a6  16.Na3  , with  c4  coming next.  14.Bh5!  It turns out that we can simply take on g6 due to the hanging rook on h8!  14...g6  15.Bxg6!  Nxg6  16.Qxg6!  hxg6  17.Rxh8+  Ke7  18.Rxa8  After some exchanges, it doesn't look like that the situation is so bad for Black. However, we're winning more material as Black can't do anything about Rh8-Rdh1-R1h7.  18...g5  19.Rh8  gxf4  20.Rdh1+-  Black couldn't avoid the loss of the queen in Ivanov,A - Crouch,C Netherlands 1992.   10...a6?  Black goes for c5, but the whole concept doesn't quite work.  11.O-O-O  Nf8  Is necessary, but Black's position is no fun after   11...c5?  Loses on the spot after  12.Nf4!  The threats of Ng6 and Nfxd5 are decisive - Black can't defend against both!  12...Nf8  And now  13.Ncxd5!  Wins after  13...exd5  14.Nxd5  Black's position falls apart.  14...Qd8  15.dxc5+-  It's safe to say that Black's opening has been a total disaster.  12.Nf4  Qf7  13.Be2+-  With ideas in mind such as Bh5 or Na4 followed by c4 @@StartBracket@@in particular if Black goes Nc6.@@EndBracket@@ }
11. Nf4 c6
{ Black adds extra protection on the pawn on d5 to avoid a potential knight sacrifice. }
12. O-O-O g5
{ It's always risky to launch the kingside pawn forward, but it's hard to tell what else Black is supposed to do. }
13. Nh5 Nbd7 14. Bd3
{ White had obtained a terrific position in Gromotka,H -Woodhouse,S ICCF email 2017. }
