[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter − Caro-Kann, French"]
[Black "French Winawer 5…Ba5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ We have finally arrived to the main bulk of our coverage on the French, and our very last topic to cover for Part 1! This is the Winawer Variation, named after Szymon Winawer and popularized later in the 1940s by the greats Nimzowitch and Botvinnik. After 3... Bb4, Black pins the knight and thus attacks the pawn on e4 so we're forced to make a decision in the center. }
4. e5
{ This is by far the most challenging move against the Winawer. We're gaining additional space while we're also limiting Black's knight on g8 as it can no longer jump to f6. }
4... c5
{ Black's main move challenges our center immediately, a necessary course of action to obtain the desired counterplay on the queenside. }
5. a3
{ By far the most played move as this is the only way to maintain the strong pawn chain. }
5... Ba5
{ Black keeps the bishop and maintains the pressure on our center. It's necessary to be aware of how to react to this sideline, since our center will quickly fall apart after cxd4. }
6. b4
{ We're interfering with Black's plans of attacking our center by sacrificing a pawn.  6.Qg4  is the alternative, when the position after  6...Ne7  7.dxc5  Bxc3+  8.bxc3  has been thoroughly discussed between strong GMs. I'm not convinced that White has much here. }
6... cxb4
{ Grabbing the pawn is subpar to  6...cxd4  , as we get a lot of compensation for the pawn. }
7. Nb5 Nc6 { Black should keep the tension. } 8. Bd2
{ The safest approach is to avoid Black's discovered checks. } 8... bxa3
{ 8...a6?  Looks dreadful after  9.Nd6+  Kf8  10.axb4  When we have the best wing gambit ever.  10...Bxb4  11.Bxb4  Nxb4  12.c3  Nc6  13.Bd3+-  Black is just busted as Qf3 is a move which makes it really hard to develop the knight. In a practical game, this position is unplayable. Note that f6 can be met by f4. }
9. Rxa3 Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2
{ With the dark-squared bishop gone the pressure is less powerful, but we still have a very big edge as Nd6+ will keep Black's king from safety. }
10... Nh6
{ Is better than  10...Nge7  , as Black leaves the e7-square for the other knight. }
11. Nd6+ Kf8 12. Be2
{ A deep move with the point of meeting  12...Ne7  with  13.g4! } 12... Nf5 13.
Nxf5 exf5 14. Nh3
{ Similarly to what we've seen earlier, we intend to battle Black's center with Nf4. This time though it will be tougher to win the pawn, so instead we intend to prepare the breakthrough c2-c4, which can be done with for example Rd1 and Bf3. Our powerful center and Black's weak king are factors that strongly outweigh Black's pawns on a7 and b7. Tleptsok, R-Florian,J ICCF email 2013. }
*

