[White "Quickstarter − Caro-Kann, French"]
[Black "French Winawer 5…Ba5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ This is the Winawer Variation, named after Szymon Winawer and popularized later in the 1940s by the greats Nimzowitch and Botvinnik. After 3... Bb4, Black pins the knight and thus attacks the pawn on e4 so we're forced to make a decision in the center. }
4. e5
{ This is by far the most challenging move against the Winawer. We're gaining additional space while we're also limiting Black's knight on g8 as it can no longer jump to f6. }
4... c5
{ Black's main move challenges our center immediately, a necessary course of action to obtain the desired counterplay on the queenside. }
5. a3
{ By far the most played move as this is the only way to maintain the strong pawn chain. }
5... Ba5
{ Black keeps the bishop and maintains the pressure on our center. It's necessary to be aware of how to react to this sideline, since our center will quickly fall apart after cxd4. }
6. b4
{ We're interfering with Black's plans of attacking our center by sacrificing a pawn. }
6... cxd4
{ Black's best try for counterplay, as our center is less powerful without the pawn on d4. }
7. Nb5 Bc7 8. f4
{ This is the main tabiya of the 5... Ba5-variation, when Black needs to make a decision on which set-up he should go for. Our set-up usually consists of Bd3-Bb2-Nf3-Qe2-O-O in some order. }
8... Bd7
{ Is a pretty interesting move, with several ideas. If we don't capture on c7 right away, Black can take our knight on b5 when the bad bishop is gone, while the strong bishop remains. If we do decide to capture on c7 @@StartBracket@@which we will@@EndBracket@@, Black can place the light-squared bishop on a4 where it's pretty decent placed. From there, Black pressures the pawn on c2, but more importantly, he can trade bishops with Bb5 at some point, usually prepared with a6. }
9. Nxc7+ Qxc7 10. Nf3 Ba4 { 10...Ne7  reaches the main line,  8...Ne7  . } 11.
Bd3
{ And now, instead of transposing to 8... Ne7 with 11... Ne7, there's an extra alternative in }
11... Qc3+
{ That forces the game into an endgame. Unfortunately for Black, this endgame is pretty bad for him. }
12. Bd2 Qxd3 13. cxd3 Bxd1 14. Kxd1
{ Black is struggling due to his very passive position and little space. }
14... Ne7
{ 14...a6?  gives Black problems after  15.a4!  with the idea of playing Ke2-b5. Indeed, after  15...Ne7  16.Ke2  Kd7  17.b5  , White's advantage was already decisive in Neubauer, M - Testor, S Oberwart 2004. }
15. Ke2 Na6 { Is apparently best, which speaks for itself! } 16. Rhc1 Kd7 17.
b5 Nc7 18. a4
{ Black was close to lost in Korneev,O - Jerez Perez,A Sitges 2004, and resigned nine moves later. An engine might find defensive resources, but for a human being it's impossible to play such a position. }
