[White "Quickstarter − Caro-Kann, French"]
[Black "French Winawer 5…Bxc3+ and …Qc7	"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ We have finally arrived to the main bulk of our coverage on the French, and our very last topic to cover for Part 1! This is the Winawer Variation, named after Szymon Winawer and popularized later in the 1940s by the greats Nimzowitch and Botvinnik. Black pins the knight and thus attacks the pawn on e4 so we're forced to make a decision in the center. }
4. e5
{ This is by far the most challenging move against the Winawer. We're gaining additional space while we're also limiting Black's knight on g8 as it can no longer jump to f6. }
4... c5
{ Black's main move challenges our center immediately, a necessary course of action to obtain the desired counterplay on the queenside. }
5. a3
{ By far the most played move as this is the only way to maintain the strong pawn chain. }
5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Qc7
{ Black usually starts with  6...Ne7  , but  6...Qc7  is a possible move-order as well. The queen is well placed on  c7  where it's eyeing our pawn on  c3  , making  cxd4  a move to watch out for. }
7. h4 cxd4
{ The critical test, and usually what Black opts for when going for this move order as he wins a pawn. }
8. cxd4 Qc3+
{ Black's queen chimes in and wins the pawn on d4, as we must protect our rook. }
9. Bd2 Qxd4 10. Nf3
{ Our compensation for the pawn lies in rapid development. Black has to make a decision on where to place the queen: }
10... Qe4+ { Black gains some time by giving a check. } 11. Be3
{ The right piece to place in between as Bd3 is a useful resource to have.   11.Be2  has been played just as many times in my base, when Black has the annoying  11...b6  with the idea of trading bishops with  Ba6  . }
11... Ne7
{ Black intends to make use of Be3 by going for a quick knight jump to f5. }
12. Bd3 Qa4 { Is not very challenging, as we can play } 13. h5
{ Followed by h6 or Rh4, depending on what Black does. } 13... Nbc6
{ 13...Nf5  is met by  14.Bxf5  exf5  15.h6  , when we're just winning. The text is Black's best, when we should respond with }
14. h6 gxh6 15. Rxh6
{ With a promising position due to Black's weaknesses on the dark squares. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter − Caro-Kann, French"]
[Black "French Winawer 5…Bxc3+ – Main Line #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ We have finally arrived to the main bulk of our coverage on the French, and our very last topic to cover for Part 1! This is the Winawer Variation, named after Szymon Winawer and popularized later in the 1940s by the greats Nimzowitch and Botvinnik. Black pins the knight and thus attacks the pawn on e4 so we're forced to make a decision in the center. }
4. e5
{ This is by far the most challenging move against the Winawer. We're gaining additional space while we're also limiting Black's knight on g8 as it can no longer jump to f6. }
4... c5
{ Black's main move challenges our center immediately, a necessary course of action to obtain the desired counterplay on the queenside. }
5. a3
{ By far the most played move as this is the only way to maintain the strong pawn chain. }
5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Ne7 7. h4 Qa5 8. Bd2 Qa4 9. Rb1
{ I settled for this move on chess24 in 'Destroy the French,' and it seems like it has stood the test of time! Our rook controls a lot of squares in the b-file so it makes sense to place it there. }
9... c4 10. h5 h6 11. Qc1
{ This novelty is not necessary by any means, but I think it's best to play it sooner than later as we must defend the pawn at some point. }
11... Nbc6 12. Rh3
{ Not the only approach we can take, but I think we should clamp down on f7 to force Black to play Rf8. This is good for us, as Black's 'queenside' rook will lack a purpose. }
12... b6 13. Rf3 Bd7 14. g4
{ Our g-pawn marches forward! I took a calmer approach to the position on chess24 with 14. Nh3, but the text is an improvement as the position is surprisingly concrete! }
14... Rf8 15. Bh3 { We're ready for the pawn break g4-g5. } 15... O-O-O 16. g5
{ Concrete. We could also consider the slower 16. Ne2, with the idea of playing Rg3-f4-Be3-Kd2. }
16... hxg5 17. Bxg5 Kb7 18. Ne2
{ The open g-file and the pressure on f7 gives us a really good position. Black has to be accurate in order to avoid being totally lost as we're intending the simple idea of going Kd2 followed by Ra1 and Qg1, with an invasion in the g-file. Bxe7 followed by Qg5 is in the air too. }
18... Rde8 19. Kd2 Rh8
{ Another 'only-move.' Black needs a purpose for the rook on  e8  . It's also worth mentioning that this move works as  Kd2  leaves our bishop on  g5  unprotected, forcing us to capture on  e7  after  20.Rxf7  Rxh5  . }
20. Bg4 Ref8 21. Ra1 Nf5 22. Qh1
{ Our queen on h1 is powerful where it can head to f3 and even target Black's d5-pawn with Bxf5, followed by Re3 and Nf4. }
22... Nce7 { Looks forced, when } 23. Bxe7 Nxe7 24. Qh4
{ Looks very promising for us. Qg5 will follow, followed by some shuffling with Rg3-Bh3. We may target Black's pawn on g7 with Rag1, or even play for the f5-break. Black is under a lot of pressure. }
