[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. Rare Moves (1...h6, 1...g5 & 1...a6)"]
[Black "1...h6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 h6
{ This move is the Carr Defense, and certainly better than  1...g5  . } 2. d4
{ Throughout the course when we have the opportunity to take the center, we take the center! }
2... a6
{ 2...g5  takes us back to the Borg Defense.  2...e6  should lead to the French after  3.Nc3  d5  , which I believe is Black's best bet, as  h6  in the French is a useful move. This is dealt with in our French coverage. }
3. c4 { I like this move, eliminating the possibility of playing b5. } 3... c5
{ Going for a different pawn structure. A move like  3...d6  should simply be met by  4.Nc3  . A set-up I like is Be3-Nge2-f3-Qd2, similar to what we saw in the g5-line. }
4. d5 d6 5. Nc3 g5 6. f4
{ I really like this move. We challenge Black's speculative g5-move, while we also take control of the center. The English super-GM David Howell played the legend himself, Michael Basman in 2018. While he got a great position, things turned far too messy for my taste. The game went:  6.Nge2  Bg7  7.Ng3  Nd7  8.h4  gxh4  9.Nh5  Bxc3+  10.bxc3  Qa5  11.Rxh4  Ngf6  12.Bd2  Nxh5  13.Qxh5  Ne5  14.f4  Ng6  15.e5  Nxh4  16.e6  , when Black should have played:  16...Rf8!  17.Qxh4  fxe6  , with a winning position. Howell complicated things and prevailed, but his opening play wasn't convincing. }
6... Bg7 7. Be2
{ If we play  7.Nf3  , Black can take on  f4  , followed by  Bg4  .  We want to avoid this, because this allows him to get a grip on the e5 square, which is what he is aiming for. Be2 leaves Black in a weird Zugzwang, as it is not easy to come up with a move. }
7... Nd7
{ 7...Qa5  is met by  8.Qd3!  Not only do we defend the knight on  c3  , but we are also not interfering with our bishop on  c1  so we can recapture on  f4  . Our next moves are simple. We will play  Nf3  and  O-O  , when Black's position will be in dire straits.   7...Nf6  is no fun either, as we simply play  8.Nf3  with  e5  coming next. }
8. Nf3 gxf4 9. Bxf4 Ne5 { Is a common plan, which we can meet with: } 10. Nxe5
Bxe5 11. Bxe5 dxe5 12. O-O Nf6 13. Qd2
{ Black's king is weak. The plan forward is to play Qe3 followed up by a4-a5-Na4 opening up the queenside and playing for a c5-break. We don't have to worry about any attack on our king either, as we can always put our king on h1 if Black plays Rg8. }
