[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. Rare Moves (1...h6, 1...g5 & 1...a6)"]
[Black "1...g5 (2...h6)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 g5
{ This speculative pawn launch, known as the Borg Defense, can't objectively be good, but I will take a deep dive into it for the sake of completion and satisfying Basman and all his fans @@StartBracket@@Michael Basman is an IM from England who is known for playing very rare lines, giving him a sort of legendary status@@EndBracket@@. The reason for the name 'Borg,' is the fact that this is a reversed Grob. 'Borg' is 'Grob' spelled backwards. This took me several weeks to realize. }
2. d4 { As usual, we will seize control of the center. } 2... h6 3. Nc3
{ As per usual, simple development is the way to go. } 3... Bg7 4. h4
{ Taking advantage of the pawn launch. } 4... c5
{ Attempting to wreak some havoc down the g7-a1 diagonal.   4...gxh4  is not an ideal situation for Black. We'll simply play  5.Nf3  , and continue with normal developing moves like Be3-Qd2. Black has only weakened himself, while there is no hurry to recapture the pawn on  h4  .   4...g4  The 'Vovk-' approach has been tried in a few games, but it does not change the evaluation.  5.Be3  d6  6.Nge2  Once again we will put our knight on g3 with a very nice position.  6...c6  7.Ng3+-  The knight will one day jump to h5. If Black tries to play h5 himself, the square on g5 is left severely weakened. }
5. Be3
{ The strong prodigy Esipenko took on c5 here, but I prefer this approach. }
5... Qa5 6. Ne2 Nf6 7. Qd2
{ 7.f3  is also possible, like in Klein, F-Perrenet, J Maastricht 2013.  However, Ng4 is not anything to worry about as we shall see. }
7... Ng4 8. Nd5 { Heading to a very nice endgame. } 8... Qxd2+ 9. Bxd2 Na6
{ Guarding the c7-square as we were threatening a knight-fork. } 10. dxc5 e6
{ Chasing away the knight before grabbing the c5-pawn. } 11. Ndc3 Nxc5 12. f3
Ne5 13. Ng3
{ The evaluation might seem a tad exaggerated, but it is justified by the fact that Black has tons of weaknesses to deal with. We are threatening to take on g5, which alone is a very hard threat to meet. Besides, moves like Nh5 and Nb5 are looming in the air, exploiting the weak squares on f6 and d6. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
