[White "1. Rare Moves (1...h6, 1...g5 & 1...a6)"]
[Black "1...g5 (2...g4)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 g5
{ This speculative pawn launch, known as the Borg Defense, can't objectively be good, but I will take a deep dive into it for the sake of completion and satisfying Basman and all his fans @@StartBracket@@Michael Basman is an IM from England who is known for playing very rare lines, giving him a sort of legendary status@@EndBracket@@. The reason for the name 'Borg,' is the fact that this is a reversed Grob. 'Borg' is 'Grob' spelled backwards. This took me several weeks to realize. }
2. d4 { As usual, we will seize control of the center. } 2... g4
{ I was quite surprised when I saw this move in the database, played numerous times in blitz games online by the Ukrainian Fide Master, Orest Vovk. }
3. Nc3 { It never fails to play natural developing moves! } 3... Bg7 4. Be3 h5
{ Vovk has had this position three times, with a score of 2/3. However, it is hard to believe that this set-up can work out for Black. }
5. h3 { Challenging the pawn on g4. } 5... d6 6. hxg4 hxg4 7. Rxh8 Bxh8 8. Nge2
{ White has a nice outpost on g3. Next, he will play Ng3, Be2, Qd2 and O-O-O given the chance. Moves like f4 are also in the air, opening up the g-file if Black takes en passant with gxf3. There is no need to analyze any further, as our position is simple to play while g5-g4 has only cost Black valuable time. It is instructive to see how the Brazilian GM Supi handled White's position in an online game against Vovk.   8...c6  9.Ng3  Qb6  10.a3!  Nf6  11.Be2  Qa5  12.Qd2  b5  13.f4  gxf3  14.gxf3  Nbd7  15.Kf2  Kd8  16.Rh1  Bg7  17.Nf5  Bf8  18.Rh8  Ne8  19.Bh6  Bxh6  20.Nxh6+-  Black was in a world of hurt in Supi, L-Vovk, O Chess.com INT 2020, as  Nxf7  followed by  Rxe8  comes }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. Rare Moves (1...h6, 1...g5 & 1...a6)"]
[Black "1...a6 (5...c5 6...Nf6)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 a6
{ This opening has been given several names, but it is perhaps best known as the St. George's Defense. This odd-looking move was first seen in a simul game between Wilhelm Steinitz and the English amateur, J. Baker. The move had its 'breakthrough' in the game Karpov-Miles from the European Team Chess Championship held in Sweden, 1980, when Miles prevailed. However, this had little to do with the opening, as White got in trouble later in the game. That being said, this is not such a bad move! Some GMs have played it repeatedly, however, this is mostly in games with short time control. Black's idea is to play b5, followed up by Bb7, applying pressure against our e4-pawn. The next moves will be e6-Nf6-c5. We can compare this to 1... b6, with the difference being that Black has gained more space on the queenside with 1... b5. However, this tends to backfire since we can target the b5-pawn with a4, as we shall soon see. }
2. d4
{ You know the drill! We always place this move, seizing the center, when given the chance. }
2... b5
{ 2...e6  3.Nf3  will either transpose to the Main Line after  3...b5  , or the French after  3...d5  4.Nc3  2...h6  is the Carr Defense. }
3. Nf3
{ If you have seen our b6 coverage, you will see that we go for a set-up with the knight on c3. However, we want to avoid that here, as our knight on c3 can be harassed with b4 in tons of lines, which is rather annoying, because we will lose protection of the pawn on e4. In general, we want to avoid playing Nc3 if Black has played b5, because of this very reason. In the Modern Defenses, we will notice that Black only plays b5 when our knight is placed on c3, so he can play b4 at some point. When our knight is placed on d2, which is what we will go for, we can target the weak pawn on b5 with moves like a4, which we will see rather frequently. }
3... Bb7 { 3...e6  should also transpose, after  4.Bd3  c5  5.c3  Bb7  6.O-O }
4. Bd3 e6 { 4...Nf6  should lead to  5...Nf6  after  5.Nbd2  . } 5. O-O
{ Simple chess, getting our king to safety. Now moves like e5 and d5 are on the table, as our king is no longer vulnerable. }
5... c5
{ The main line and the best move, because it forces us to play c3. If we take on c5, Black can simply recapture, when we no longer have the e5-resource, as the knight is still placed on g8. }
6. c3 { Supporting our center. } 6... Nf6 7. e5
{ 7. Re1 is more popular, but I think this is even more testing. } 7... Nd5 8.
dxc5
{ This is strong as we will soon be able to follow up with Nbd2-Ne4, with a strong attack. }
8... Bxc5 9. Nbd2 { The knight is headed to e4. } 9... Nc6 10. a4 O-O
{ The most logical approach, } 11. axb5 axb5 12. Rxa8 Bxa8 13. Bxh7+
{ We're sacrificing the bishop for a very dangerous attack. } 13... Kxh7 14.
Ne4 Be7 { This is the most natural move in the world, but it loses to } 15.
Nfg5+
{ Our pieces are well placed to carry out a brutal attack against the enemy forces. }
15... Bxg5 16. Nxg5+ Kg6
{ 16...Kg8  leads to mate after  17.Qh5  Re8  18.Qxf7+  Kh8  19.Qh5+  Kg8  20.Qh7+  Kf8  21.Qh8+  Ke7  22.Qxg7 }
17. Qg4
{ We are threatening a deadly discovery, so Black is forced to remove the pawn on e5, giving him an escape route to f6. }
17... Nxe5 18. Qg3 Kf6 19. Nh7+ Ke7 20. Nxf8
{ The extra material and attack leads to a winning position. } *

