{ The main line and the best move, because it forces us to play c3. If we take on c5, Black can simply recapture, when we no longer have the e5-resource, as the knight is still placed on g8. }
6. c3 { Supporting our center. } 6... Nf6 7. e5
{ 7.Re1  is more popular, but I think this is even more testing. } 7... Nd5 8.
dxc5
{ This is strong as we will soon be able to follow up with Nbd2-Ne4, with a strong attack. }
8... Bxc5 9. Nbd2 { The knight is headed to e4. } 9... Nc6 10. a4 O-O
{ The most logical approach, } 11. axb5 axb5 12. Rxa8 Bxa8 13. Bxh7+
{ We're sacrificing the bishop for a very dangerous attack. } 13... Kxh7 14.
Ne4 Nxe5 { This amazing move is the only way for Black to stay in the game. }
15. Nfg5+ { It's worth noting that we have nothing after  15.Nxe5  Be7  . }
15... Kg8 { loses once again to } 16. Qh5
{ As we are playing for an attack, there is no time to waste. Grabbing the bishop with 16. Nxc5 would give Black valuable time to defend himself with moves like 16... Ng6, 16... Qc7 or 16... f6. }
16... Re8 17. Qh7+ Kf8 18. Qh8+ Ke7 19. Qxg7 d6
{ It might look like that Black has everything under control, but... } 20. Nxf7
{ A decisive blow! } 20... Nf3+
{ The knight on f7 is untouchable due to Bg5, winning the queen as the knight on f7 is pinned. }
21. gxf3 Rg8 22. Bg5+ Kd7 23. Nxc5+ dxc5 24. Qh7
{ Ra1 will follow, with a winning position. We never have to worry about Rxg5 either, since we will recapture with check. }
