{ 7.Re1  is more popular, but I think this is even more testing. } 7... Nd5 8.
dxc5
{ This is strong as we will soon be able to follow up with Nbd2-Ne4, with a strong attack. }
8... Bxc5 9. Nbd2 { The knight is headed to e4. } 9... Nc6 10. a4 Qc7
{ Looks interesting to me, attacking the e5-pawn. } 11. axb5
{ There's no reason why we shouldn't target the b5-pawn. } 11... axb5 12. Rxa8+
Bxa8 13. Re1 Ba7
{ Black's best bet is to give away the b5 pawn and try to gain compensation with a quick f6-break. }
14. Bxb5 O-O
{ 14...Bxf2+??  15.Kxf2  Qb6+  16.Nd4  Nxd4  17.Nc4  Qxb5  18.Nd6++-  Is quite a cunning tactic.   14...Qb6?  15.Ne4+-  The bishop is untouchable due to Nd6+. }
15. Qa4
{ The queen plays a good role here, protecting the bishop on b5 while also preventing the Black knight from jumping to g4 in the near future, as Black will respond with f6, taking with the knight. }
15... f6 16. exf6 Nxf6 17. Nf1
{ Black has some compensation, as his bishops are quite strong. However, it is far from enough for the pawn. Black should prevent us from playing Bf4 with Nd5, when I think Ng3, followed by Bd3-Qh4, and maybe Be4 next, is a good plan. }
