4. Bd3 e6 { 4...Nf6  should lead to 5... Nf6 after  5.Nbd2  . } 5. O-O
{ Simple chess, getting our king to safety. Now moves like e5 and d5 are on the table, as our king is no longer vulnerable. }
5... Nf6
{ I believe that this move order is inaccurate, due to the fact that we have a concrete way of dealing with the main move, 6. c5. If Black can't play this, he will be left with a passive position, giving us a very nice edge. }
6. Nbd2 c5
{ This is played often, but it is an inaccurate move order due to the fact that we can start harassing the knight with e5, followed by c4. }
7. e5
{ This is the strongest move, because we can follow up with c4! next, giving us a massive development advantage, while also aiming for the weak d6-square in Black's camp, as we shall soon see. }
7... Nd5 8. c4
{ This move is the key to success. We will get our knight to c4 by tempo, when our development advantage gives us a winning position. }
8... bxc4 9. Nxc4 cxd4 10. Bg5 { Gaining a tempo on the queen. } 10... Qc7 11.
Rc1 { Once again we gain a tempo, threatening to win the queen with Nf6+. }
11... Nc6 12. Be4
{ We are planning to take on d5, followed by Nd6. This will give us a devastating initiative, as the Black pieces are too passive and the king is too weak. }
12... Bc5 { This looks more human to me. } 13. Bxd5
{ The point of the knight capture is that we open up the e-file. } 13... exd5
14. Nd6+ Bxd6 15. exd6 Qxd6 16. Re1+ Kf8 17. Nxd4
{ There are many moves, but this is the easiest. Our attack is too powerful, with ideas like Nf5 followed by Qd5. }
17... h6 18. Nf5 Qg6 19. Be7+ { Setting a cunning trap. } 19... Nxe7
{ Black has to take, as his queen will be out of the game after  19...Kg8  20.Nh4! }
20. Nxe7 Qf6 21. Qb3
{ Gaining a tempo on the bishop, but more importantly, White reaches the a3-square when Black won't escape a devastating discovered attack. }
21... Bc6 22. Qa3 { White's next move will hurt! } *

