7. Bc2 d5 8. Nbd2
{ 8.e5  is definitely good, but I prefer to play it with a tempo  if Black plays Nf6. I feel like Black will be 'happy' after e5, as this is the type of position he is looking for. }
8... Nf6
{ Four games have been played with this move, while I also think this is the most natural continuation.   8...dxe4  9.Bxe4!  The capture with the Bishop might seem odd, but it is a huge advantage for us to have the b7-monster gone. It becomes a lot easier to attack Black's pawn chain with a4 and b3, while the white squares will be very weak.  9...Bxe4  10.Nxe4+-  With a4 coming next, Black is essentially busted. }
9. e5 { Finally! } 9... Nfd7 10. h4 { We want to put our knight on g5. } 10...
h6 11. h5
{ This destroys every option of playing g6 or g5 in the future for Black. }
11... Nc6 12. Re1
{ The engine loves this position and gives White an edge of 2 pawns, however I think that the human evaluation is 'only' close to winning. A logical plan here for White is to play Nh2, followed by f4-f5, which can also be supported by the knight on d2 with Nf1-Ne3. Black will surely suffer here, but there still is a glimpse of hope. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. Rare Moves (1...h6, 1...g5 & 1...a6)"]
[Black "1...a6 (5...c5 6...d6)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 a6
{ This opening has been given several names, but it is perhaps best known as the St. George's Defense. This odd-looking move was first seen in a simul game between Wilhelm Steinitz and the English amateur, J. Baker. The move had its 'breakthrough' in the game Karpov-Miles from the European Team Chess Championship held in Sweden, 1980, when Miles prevailed. However, this had little to do with the opening, as White got in trouble later in the game. That being said, this is not such a bad move! Some GMs have played it repeatedly, however, this is mostly in games with short time control. Black's idea is to play b5, followed up by Bb7, applying pressure against our e4-pawn. The next moves will be e6-Nf6-c5. We can compare this to 1... b6, with the difference being that Black has gained more space on the queenside with 1... b5. However, this tends to backfire since we can target the b5-pawn with a4, as we shall soon see. }
2. d4
{ You know the drill! We always place this move, seizing the center, when given the chance. }
2... b5
{ 2...e6  3.Nf3  will either transpose to the Main Line after  3...b5  , or the French after  3...d5  4.Nc3  2...h6  is the Carr Defense. }
3. Nf3
{ If you have seen our b6 coverage, you will see that we go for a set-up with the knight on c3. However, we want to avoid that here, as our knight on c3 can be harassed with b4 in tons of lines, which is rather annoying, because we will lose protection of the pawn on e4. In general, we want to avoid playing Nc3 if Black has played b5, because of this very reason. In the Modern Defenses, we will notice that Black only plays b5 when our knight is placed on c3, so he can play b4 at some point. When our knight is placed on d2, which is what we will go for, we can target the weak pawn on b5 with moves like a4, which we will see rather frequently. }
3... Bb7 { 3...e6  should also transpose, after  4.Bd3  c5  5.c3  Bb7  6.O-O }
4. Bd3 e6 { 4...Nf6  should lead to 5... Nf6 after  5.Nbd2  . } 5. O-O
{ Simple chess, getting our king to safety. Now moves like e5 and d5 are on the table, as our king is no longer vulnerable. }
5... c5
{ The main line and the best move, because it forces us to play c3. If we take on c5, Black can simply recapture, when we no longer have the e5-resource, as the knight is still placed on g8. }
6. c3 { Supporting our center. } 6... d6
{ Is a logical move, as it takes control of the e5-square. } 7. a4
{ This is always in the air as we force Black to make really unpleasant decisions on the queenside. }
7... c4
{ Is by far the most played move, since it closes the position. Black is struggling with his development, so he can't afford to open up the positions like we have seen in earlier lines. }
8. Bc2 Nd7
{ Believe it or not, this leads to a forced sequence that gives us a winning endgame. }
9. axb5 axb5 10. Rxa8 Qxa8 11. Na3 Ba6 12. d5
{ Black needs to keep the position closed. } 12... e5 13. Be3 Ngf6 14. Qa1
{ Utilizing the a-file by threatening to take on b5. } 14... Qb7 15. h3 Be7 16.
Qa2
{ We want to play Ra1 next, winning the pawn on c4, as the bishop on a6 will hang. }
16... O-O 17. Ra1 Ra8 18. Nxb5 { This still works! } 18... Qxb5 19. Ba4 Qb8
{ 19...Qa5  is met by  20.Bc6  when Black can't save the bishop on  a6  without losing the rook on  a8  . }
20. Bc6 Bb7 21. Qxa8 Bxa8 22. Rxa8 Qxa8 23. Bxa8 Nxe4 24. Bc6
{ We have reached a very interesting endgame where we have acquired the bishop pair. Black has a very weak pawn on  c4  which should fall somehow, although Black does have control over the d2-square, while the bishop on  c6  needs to guard the pawn on  d5  . Play may continue  24...Ndf6  25.Bb6  Kf8  26.Kf1  h5  27.Ke2  g5  Creating a pawn storm seems like the only way to create counterplay.  28.g3  Planning to thrust the h-pawn forward next, with the idea of Ne1-Ng2-Ne3-Nxc4.  28...g4  29.hxg4  hxg4  30.Nh4+-  White will win the  c4  pawn, as the white knight on  h4  will reach  e3  soon. }
*

