[Result "*"]

1. e4 a6
{ This opening has been given several names, but it is perhaps best known as the St. George's Defense. This odd-looking move was first seen in a simul game between Wilhelm Steinitz and the English amateur, J. Baker. The move had its 'breakthrough' in the game Karpov-Miles from the European Team Chess Championship held in Sweden, 1980, when Miles prevailed. However, this had little to do with the opening, as White got in trouble later in the game. That being said, this is not such a bad move! Some GMs have played it repeatedly, however, this is mostly in games with short time control. Black's idea is to play b5, followed up by Bb7, applying pressure against our e4-pawn. The next moves will be e6-Nf6-c5. We can compare this to 1... b6, with the difference being that Black has gained more space on the queenside with 1... b5. However, this tends to backfire since we can target the b5-pawn with a4, as we shall soon see. }
2. d4
{ You know the drill! We always place this move, seizing the center, when given the chance. }
2... b5
{ 2...e6  3.Nf3  will either transpose to the Main Line after  3...b5  , or the French after  3...d5  4.Nc3  2...h6  is the Carr Defense. }
3. Nf3
{ If you have seen our b6 coverage, you will see that we go for a set-up with the knight on c3. However, we want to avoid that here, as our knight on c3 can be harassed with b4 in tons of lines, which is rather annoying, because we will lose protection of the pawn on e4. In general, we want to avoid playing Nc3 if Black has played b5, because of this very reason. In the Modern Defenses, we will notice that Black only plays b5 when our knight is placed on c3, so he can play b4 at some point. When our knight is placed on d2, which is what we will go for, we can target the weak pawn on b5 with moves like a4, which we will see rather frequently. }
3... Bb7 { 3...e6  should also transpose, after  4.Bd3  c5  5.c3  Bb7  6.O-O }
4. Bd3 e6 { 4...Nf6  should lead to 5... Nf6 after  5.Nbd2  . } 5. O-O
{ Simple chess, getting our king to safety. Now moves like e5 and d5 are on the table, as our king is no longer vulnerable. }
5... c5
{ The main line and the best move, because it forces us to play c3. If we take on c5, Black can simply recapture, when we no longer have the e5-resource, as the knight is still placed on g8. }
6. c3 { Supporting our center. } 6... cxd4
{ This move has been played by the Russian super-GM, Dubov. This means that we must take it seriously. }
7. cxd4 Nf6 8. Re1 Be7 9. Nc3 { Active and strong. } 9... b4 10. Na4 d5
{ Black is heading for a French Defense type of structure, but it seems like it is far too passive. }
11. e5 Ne4 12. Nd2
{ 12.Be3  is also good, but I like this move as we get rid of the only active black piece in the position. }
12... Nxd2 13. Bxd2 Bc6 14. Nc5
{ Our knight has found a home on c5, however there was nothing wrong with 14. Rc1 either. }
14... Qb6 15. Qg4 { Provoking Black into weakening himself even further. }
15... g6
{ 15...O-O ?  Loses in 'x' amount of ways, with the nicest winning move being  16.Bxh7+!  Kxh7  17.Re3  Rh8  18.Nxe6!  Demolishing the last piece of Black's wall, as mate follows after  18...fxe6  19.Rh3+  Kg8  20.Qxe6+  Kf8  21.Rxh8 }
16. Rac1
{ Black had a terrible French Defense in Hebden, M-Flear, G London 1985. After the natural  16...Nd7  , taking on  d7  followed by  Bh6  looks crushing. We will play  Bg7  next, forcing the rook to move all hopes of castling will be gone. The bishop will find a nice home on  f6  , when Black will be overloaded with weaknesses on the dark squares, as we will exchange the dark-squared bishop.  Conclusion: We started our e4-journey with some of the most unusual openings out there.  1...g5  might produce some shock value unless you are playing against Vovk or Basman.  Sacrificing the pawn on  g5  does not work, while the mainline weakens Black's position immensely after the move 4. h4, followed by a knight maneuver from g1-e2-g3.   1...h6  is very likely to transpose to  1...g5  , but other options do exist. Going for the h6/  a6  isn't impressive, as an easy solution is to meet it with  3.c4  , eliminating any hope for  b5  .  In our mainline, the f4-move, in particular, gives Black massive problems to solve, as we get a grip on the center.   1...a6  was the biggest topic of the chapter, as it has been employed by numerous GMs, even in Classical Games. Black has a coherent plan of playing  b5  ,  Bb7  ,  c5  ,  Nf6  , and  e6  in some order, but it is clear that our space advantage tends to be too much to handle for Black. The set-up with Nbd2-c3-e5-Re1-Ne4 is simple when also  a4  is very often a key idea that I want to highlight. Along with that, we have a great central space advantage, which is close to being fatal in almost every line. Objectively, Black's best bet is to transpose to a French, where both  a6  and  h6  have a function. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. Owen's Defense (1...b6)"]
[Black "Making Choices 1...b6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 b6
{ This defense is perhaps most well-known as Owen's Defense, or the Greek Defense. Black's idea is rather similar to the St' George's Defense, as he plans a Bb7-e6-Nf6-Bb4-c5 set-up, applying pressure against our center. When compared to the St. George's Defense, the major advantage is that the pawn stands on b6 instead of being a target on b5. The downside is that unlike   1...g6  for example, b6 does not prepare to castle, leaving Black's king rather vulnerable, especially due to the fact that 1... b6 gives up the center. The opening does have a dubious reputation, and rightfully so. However, the appeal with this opening, and other rare lines, is the limited amount of theory to learn making them easy to play. It is obviously highly unlikely that a player with the white pieces has studied this line in great depth, and that makes it an excellent surprise weapon and a fun tool in games with a short time control. }
2. d4
{ I've said it before, and I'll say it again. Whenever we have the chance, we'll take full control of the center. }
2... Bb7 3. Nc3 e6
{ 3...g6  is possible, which is covered in the Modern chapter. } 4. Bd3 Bb4
{ Pinning the knight is a logical way for Black to fight against our center, with Nf6 and c5/ d5 coming. This set-up is not so easy to play against, and I even remember struggling with White against a lower-rated player in a rapid game. }
5. Nf3
{ This move is the other Main Line, which has been seen over 2000 times. Therefore, it made sense for me to consider it, but I was quite surprised when I discovered that it was far from easy to get an advantage in several lines. I will give some of my analysis, as I think it is insightful to see some of Black's resources. However, I will refrain from doing detailed explanations, as this is not my recommendation. }
5... Nf6 6. Qe2
{ Has been by far the most popular move, but I think Black just equalizes. 6. Nd2! is the best way to go, but things aren't so easy here either.   6.e5  Negi gave this move in a recent book, but I found several ways to equalize for Black.  6...Ne4  7.O-O  Nxc3  8.bxc3  Bxc3  White sacrifices a pawn for initiative, but it is not enough to claim an edge.  9.Bg5  Qc8  Looks also fine after   9...Bxf3  Leads to a rather complex middlegame, since Black sacrifices an exchange for a couple of pawns.  10.Qxf3  Qxg5  11.Qxa8  Qd8  12.Rad1  Bxd4  Black has now two pawns for the missing exchange, a deal he can be happy with.  13.Rfe1  a5  There's no need to give away the pawn on a7.  14.Qe4  Bc5  15.g3  g6  Preparing to castle kingside.  16.Bb5  Forcing Black to play c6, but it isn't a big deal.  16...c6  17.Bd3  O-O  18.Kg2  d5  Black untangles.  19.exd6  Qxd6  =∞ Black's pawns compensate for the exchange. White's rooks do not have any clear targets, as Black has no weaknesses in the position, while the only open file is the d-file.  10.Rb1  d5   10...c5  Also leads to a rather acceptable position for Black, with a simple line being:  11.Nd2  Bxd2  12.Bxd2  Nc6  13.Qg4  Kf8  Black can't weaken himself with 14... g6, so he is forced to defend the pawn with the king. This is nothing to weep about though.  14.c3  h5  15.Qf4  Ne7  Opening up the light-squared diagonal which now targets g2.  16.dxc5  Qc6  ! Clever, because Black will be able to take the pawn on c5 with check.  17.f3  Qxc5+  18.Kh1  Nd5  19.Qh4  Ne3  20.Rfe1  Nf5  = The position is unclear. Black will follow up with h4 next, when ideas like Ng3 are on the table. Therefore, taking the knight is a likely continuation, when the opposite-colored bishops lead to a balanced game.  11.Rb3  Ba5  12.Be3  Giving the g5-square to the knight.  12...h6  Black do not want to allow Ng5, when Qh5 becomes really unpleasant.  13.Nh4  White now goes for the typical plan of opening up Black's kingside with f4-f5.  13...Ba6  Black gets rid of the strong bishop on d3.  14.f4  Bxd3  15.Qxd3  Qa6  ∞ Black will play Nc6 with O-O-O coming if White avoids the queen exchange. Black is the only one that can stand better, as the initiative for the pawn is dying out. }
6... d5 7. O-O
{ Is given as an alternative by Negi, but once again I am not convinced.   7.exd5  Leads to an endgame where White has a very slight upper hand, but it is not what you're hoping for when facing 1... b6.  7...Qxd5  8.O-O  Bxc3  9.bxc3  White has grabbed the bishop pair, but it doesn't add to much.  9...O-O  10.c4  Qh5  And now White goes for the endgame after  11.Ne5  Qxe2  12.Bxe2  Rd8  13.Rd1  Nbd7  = White has the bishop pair, but Black is extremely solid with a great bishop on b7. }
7... Bxc3 8. e5 Bb4 9. exf6 gxf6 10. c3 Bd6
{ Is a great move with a hidden function as we will see in a few moves. } 11.
Nh4 h5 { This is very clever, avoiding moves like Qh5 and Bh6. } 12. Re1 Nc6
13. b4
{ 13.Bd2  Qd7  ⩱ Black will go for O-O-O next, when I think White does not have enough for the missing pawn.   13.a4  Kd7  ! Black's king finds an unusual safe spot.  14.Ng6  Rg8  ∞ The position is unclear, but I would pick Black if I had to choose. f5 followed by Qf6, is one good plan. }
13... a5 14. b5 Ne5
{ This is a fantastic sacrifice, which shows the point of Bd6. After this, the position becomes amazingly complex. Black's horde of central pawns give excellent compensation for the missing piece. Alright, I am not writing a course for Black here, but it is important to point out that Black will be left with a fine position if he can cope with our initiative. In Negi's lines, White sacrificed material, but it wasn't enough. Let's return to my recommendation. }
*

