[White "2. Owen's Defense (1...b6)"]
[Black "2...Bb7 (3...e6 4...Bb4 5...d5)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 b6
{ This defense is perhaps most well-known as Owen's Defense, or the Greek Defense. Black's idea is rather similar to the St' George's Defense, as he plans a Bb7-e6-Nf6-Bb4-c5 set-up, applying pressure against our center. When compared to the St. George's Defense, the major advantage is that the pawn stands on b6 instead of being a target on b5. The downside is that unlike   1...g6  for example, b6 does not prepare to castle, leaving Black's king rather vulnerable, especially due to the fact that 1... b6 gives up the center. The opening does have a dubious reputation, and rightfully so. However, the appeal with this opening, and other rare lines, is the limited amount of theory to learn making them easy to play. It is obviously highly unlikely that a player with the white pieces has studied this line in great depth, and that makes it an excellent surprise weapon and a fun tool in games with a short time control. }
2. d4
{ I've said it before, and I'll say it again. Whenever we have the chance, we'll take full control of the center. }
2... Bb7 3. Nc3
{ We have arrived at our first major crossroad. My biggest reason for choosing this move was when I discovered that the Main Lines are very bad for Black, for reasons we'll get to shortly. The other main move,   3.Bd3  , is also good of course. }
3... e6 { 3...g6  is possible, which is covered in the Modern chapter. } 4. Bd3
Bb4
{ Pinning the knight is a logical way for Black to fight against our center, with Nf6 and c5/ d5 coming. This set-up is not so easy to play against, and I even remember struggling with White against a lower-rated player in a rapid game. }
5. Ne2
{ When diving deeply into this line, it became clear to me that this move was the best. One of the huge advantages with Nge2 is that we can recapture back on c3 with our knight, avoiding a bad pawn structure. We can gain an attack rather quickly with Nf4, followed by Qg4 and Nh5. Another plan, especially if Black weakens the c6-square by playing d6, is to play d5 and put the knight on d4.   5.Nh3!?  is a very interesting move here as well, just not as good as our move. }
5... d5
{ I personally think this is Black's best bet, gaining at least some sort of control in the center. However, the resulting position is a bad French. }
6. e5
{ Taking away the f6 square for the knight, while also closing the diagonal for the bishop on b7. }
6... Ne7
{ A FIDE-master has played this twice against two 2500-rated opponents, but without any luck. }
7. a3 Bxc3+ 8. Nxc3 a6 { Black wants to gain space with c5. } 9. Ne2
{ Preparing c3, supporting the center. } 9... c5 10. c3
{ We can stop here really, as Black's position is a French-gone-wrong. Black has no pressure on d4, and our plan of playing Ng3-Nh5, or putting our bishop on g5 if Black plays g6, is rather simple to execute. White played a nice game, and I will leave you to click through it.   10...Nbc6  11.O-O  c4  12.Bc2  Na5  13.Ng3  Qc7  14.Nh5  O-O-O  15.Nxg7  Ng6  16.Nh5  Kb8  17.Bg5  Rc8  18.Qe2  Ka7  19.f4  f5  20.exf6  h6  21.Bxg6  hxg5  22.fxg5  Rcg8  23.f7  Rxg6  24.f8Q  Rxf8  25.Rxf8  Rxg5  26.Raf1  Nb3  27.R1f7  Qd6  28.Nf4  e5  29.Nh3  Rg6  30.Qxe5  Qxe5  31.dxe5  d4  32.Nf4  dxc3  33.bxc3  Rg5  34.e6  Re5  35.e7  Nd2  36.e8Q  Rxe8  37.Rxe8  a5  38.h4  Ka6  39.Rxb7  Kxb7  40.h5  Nb3  41.h6  Nc5  42.h7  Ka6  43.h8Q  Kb5  44.Qd4  Ka4  45.Qxc4+  1–0  (45)  (Ivic,V)  (2581)  (-Al Tarbosh,W)  (2230)  (Chess.com INT 2020) }
