{ Pinning the knight is a logical way for Black to fight against our center, with Nf6 and c5/ d5 coming. This set-up is not so easy to play against, and I even remember struggling with White against a lower-rated player in a rapid game. }
5. Ne2
{ When diving deeply into this line, it became clear to me that this move was the best. One of the huge advantages with Nge2 is that we can recapture back on c3 with our knight, avoiding a bad pawn structure. We can gain an attack rather quickly with Nf4, followed by Qg4 and Nh5.   5.Nh3!?  is a very interesting move here as well, just not as good as our move. }
5... d5
{ I personally think this is Black's best bet, gaining at least some sort of control in the center. However, the resulting position is a bad French. }
6. e5
{ Taking away the f6 square for the knight, while also closing the diagonal for the bishop on b7. }
6... c5
{ Is a natural way to continue, gaining more activity and pressure against our center. }
7. a3
{ There is no time to waste. We can't allow Black to take our pawn on d4, followed by Bxc3, when our pawns will be very weak. }
7... Ba5 { Was seen in a game, but it loses. } 8. b4 cxb4 9. Nb5
{ This is the point! Black can't prevent a jump to d6. } 9... Ba6
{ Was tried, but there were many good ways to continue. In Polovchenya,V -Purygin,A Dagomys 2009, White won material after }
10. axb4 Bxb4+ 11. c3 Be7 12. Rxa6 { A tactical trick that wins material. }
12... Nxa6 13. Qa4
{ Black loses material, as it is impossible to defend the knight and Nc7+. } *

