1. e4 b6 2. d4
{ I've said it before, and I'll say it again. Whenever we have the chance, we'll take full control of the center. }
2... Bb7 3. Nc3 e6
{ 3...g6  is possible, which is covered in the Modern chapter. } 4. Bd3 Bb4
{ Pinning the knight is a logical way for Black to fight against our center, with Nf6 and c5/ d5 coming. This set-up is not so easy to play against, and I even remember struggling with White against a lower-rated player in a rapid game. }
5. Ne2
{ When diving deeply into this line, it became clear to me that this move was the best. One of the huge advantages with Nge2 is that we can recapture back on c3 with our knight, avoiding a bad pawn structure. We can gain an attack rather quickly with Nf4, followed by Qg4 and Nh5.   5.Nh3!?  is a very interesting move here as well, just not as good as our move. }
5... Ne7
{ This move has been played a decent amount of times, but it seems to go against the concept of the variation. Black wants to apply pressure in the center, but it is a lot harder with a knight on e7 instead of f6. }
6. O-O O-O
{ Getting the king to safety before it is too late. Unfortunately for Black though, the king isn't really safe on g8 either. }
7. Ng3
{ We are on our way towards the Black king. The plan forward is to launch an attack with f4-f5-Qg4, which looks very hard to stop, as Black's pieces are far from the kingside. A high-rated game continued }
7... Bxc3 8. bxc3 d6 9. Qg4 Kh8
{ GM Benjamin Joel went for Nh5 here, but I prefer having the knight on g3 , supporting a f5-break. }
10. f4
{ Is the simple move, when f5 will follow with a very dangerous attack. Once we have accomplished f5, we can consider Nh5, or Bd2 followed by Rae1. Black's pieces are too passive, so they will struggle against the forces of the white pieces. }
