[White "2. Owen's Defense (1...b6)"]
[Black "2...Bb7 (3...e6 4...Bb4 5...Nf6 3)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 b6 2. d4
{ I've said it before, and I'll say it again. Whenever we have the chance, we'll take full control of the center. }
2... Bb7 3. Nc3 e6
{ 3...g6  is possible, which is covered in the Modern chapter. } 4. Bd3 Bb4
{ Pinning the knight is a logical way for Black to fight against our center, with Nf6 and c5/ d5 coming. This set-up is not so easy to play against, and I even remember struggling with White against a lower-rated player in a rapid game. }
5. Ne2
{ When diving deeply into this line, it became clear to me that this move was the best. One of the huge advantages with Nge2 is that we can recapture back on c3 with our knight, avoiding a bad pawn structure. We can gain an attack rather quickly with Nf4, followed by Qg4 and Nh5. Another plan, especially if Black weakens the c6-square by playing d6, is to play d5 and put the knight on d4.   5.Nh3!?  is a very interesting move here as well, just not as good as our move. }
5... Nf6
{ Has been played in the far majority of games. Nevertheless, it is not good due to }
6. a3
{ Kicking away the bishop, showing once again why our knight is so well placed on e2. }
6... Be7
{ This is a very sad move to make. Black has lost all pressure against our center. }
7. e5
{ Playing as direct as possible is the right approach, as Black is very passive. The knight on b8 is out of the game for now, while playing d6-Nd7 takes too much time. I was very surprised by the fact that Karjakin played   7.O-O  here against Nakamura, until I discovered it was a Bullet game. }
7... Nd5 8. Nxd5 Bxd5 9. Nf4
{ This move is really strong. We're opening up the possibility of sending our queen to g4 or h5, while gaining a tempo on the bishop. Black has lost far too many tempos, making the position objectively lost already after just nine moves. }
9... Bb7 10. Qh5
{ This is a very strong move, and a novelty. The move prevents d6, which is met by Nxe6, while Nc6 is met by d5. O-O is also not on the table, because of the mate on h7. }
10... c5 11. d5
{ This works out well for us tactically. Black is in huge trouble as we are attacking the pawn on e6. Neither of the pawn captures are good, either. }
11... Bxd5
{ This is a better capture compared to the following line but it also gives Black a miserable position.   11...exd5  12.e6  dxe6  13.Nxe6  Once again showing how useful the queen is on h5 .  13...g6  14.Bb5+  Nd7  15.Nxd8  gxh5  16.Nxb7  Rb8  17.Bf4  The rook will be trapped if it captures the knight after Bc6 , so a resignation here is appropriate. }
12. Nxd5 exd5 13. Qf3 Qc7 14. Bf4
{ 14.Qxd5  is also good, but I dislike that Black can trade queens after  14...Qc6 }
14... Nc6
{ Defending the pawn with  14...Qc6  would have been met by  15.c4!  , when Black can't take on c4 due to Be4 , winning the rook on a8 . }
15. Qxd5
{ Black's position is terrible. We have an incredible space advantage and full control of the center. If Black decides to castle short, we can go for queenside castling, followed by Qe4 and a quick h4-h5. c3 is also a nice resource, removing the d4 square for the knight on c6. Another good plan is to play Bg3, followed up by e6, or f4-f5. }
