[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. Owen's Defense (1...b6)"]
[Black "2...Bb7 (3...e6 4...Nf6 5...d5 1)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 b6 2. d4
{ I've said it before, and I'll say it again. Whenever we have the chance, we'll take full control of the center. }
2... Bb7 3. Nc3 e6
{ 3...g6  is possible, which is covered in the Modern chapter. } 4. Bd3 Nf6
{ This is a better move order. As we have seen,   4...Bb4  is met by  5.Nge2  ruining Black's fun rendering the attempt rather pointless. Therefore, it is better to develop the knight, followed by a quick d5  , aiming for a French-type of structure. }
5. Nge2
{ We once again go for this move. We have seen that the knight is rather flexible on e2 , when we also bait Black into playing Bb4 , which we know is rather terrible. }
5... d5
{ This move makes sense, grabbing the center, when Black is headed into a French-type of structure.   5...Bb4  is met by  6.a3!  was really good for White. }
6. e5 { From here Black needs to choose between three knight moves. } 6... Ng8
{ This backward move has been played by some players, including one of the Chessbrah starts, IM Aman Hambleton. Now Black will play c5 next, since Nf4-Nxe6 no longer is an issue. }
7. Nb1
{ It seems like both colors are setting up the pieces, but we saw this idea after Ne4 too. Strengthening the center gives us a perfect pawn structure, when the knight on b1 will soon find a new home on f3. }
7... c5 8. c3
{ We've actually transposed to a different line in the Owen's Defense. } 8...
Nc6 9. Nd2 { The knight is headed to f3. } 9... Nge7 10. Nf3 Ng6
{ Black is trying to get his pieces out with Be7-O-O and potentially Nh4, but we can spoil this idea rather easily. }
11. h4 { We'll harass the knight with h5 next. } 11... Be7 12. h5 Nh4 13. Nxh4
Bxh4 14. Nf4 { This typical move again, preparing for Qg4. } 14... Bg5 15. Qg4
h6
{ Black is trying to withstand the pressure, but one day we'll play Nh3, removing the defender on g5. }
16. O-O Qe7 17. Be3
{ Every piece has been developed, and we can now start considering Nh3. } 17...
cxd4 18. cxd4 O-O 19. Rac1
{ Nb4 would make us having to put the bishop on b1, when our rook on a1 would have been out of the game. }
19... Qd7
{ Happened in a correspondence game from 2014, when the improved engine likes }
20. Nh3 Bxe3 21. fxe3
{ The rook is headed to f6, when ideas like Qf4-Rxh6 are in the air. If Black tries to play Rac8, with the idea of playing Nb4, aiming at our c1-rook while attacking our bishop on d3, we can simply play Rcd1. Rf3-Rg3 is another neat idea, when we have a really nice attack. Black doesn't have any way to withstand the upcoming slaughter, with the engine giving an edge of +5. }
