{ This might look odd, but the plan is to support the center with c3, and potentially trapping the knight on e4. }
7... c5
{ This typical move is always possible.   7...f6  I think this is a decent way to fight for the center. If we decide to take, Black may get some activity after Qxf6, when the knight will have an extra square on d6.  8.f3  Simply removing the knight is best.  8...Ng5  9.O-O  c5  10.c3  As per usual, we support d4 with this move.  10...Nc6  11.Bxg5  fxg5  12.f4  We'll open up the f-file followed by Nf4 next, when we'll have tons of pressure.   7...h6  was seen in a game, where I like  8.c3  , followed by Be3 & f3, pushing away the knight on e4. We can later transpose our knight from b1 to f3, where it will be supporting our center perfectly. }
8. Bb5+
{ It's important not to get tempted with  8.f3  , when  Nd6!  is not so bad for Black,  the point being that he will trap our bishop with c4 when we take the knight. }
8... Bc6 9. Bxc6+ Nxc6 10. f3
{ We have trapped Black's knight, but he will get some pawns for it after }
10... Qh4+ 11. g3 Nxg3 12. Nxg3 cxd4
{ I don't think the pawns justify the piece, with the pawn on d4 in particular, being quite weak. }
13. O-O f6 14. f4
{ We do not want to take, because Black can strengthen his center further with gxf6! }
14... Bc5 15. Kg2
{ The knight will go from d2 to f3 next, while we can place our queen on e2. Slowly, but steadily we will get our pieces into the game, when Black will miss his knight. }
