[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. Owen's Defense (1...b6)"]
[Black "2...Bb7 (3...e6 4...Nf6 5...d5 3)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 b6 2. d4
{ I've said it before, and I'll say it again. Whenever we have the chance, we'll take full control of the center. }
2... Bb7 3. Nc3 e6
{ 3...g6  is possible, which is covered in the Modern chapter. } 4. Bd3 Nf6
{ This is a better move order. As we have seen,   4...Bb4  is met by  5.Nge2  ruining Black's fun rendering the attempt rather pointless. Therefore, it is better to develop the knight, followed by a quick d5  , aiming for a French-type of structure. }
5. Nge2
{ We once again go for this move. We have seen that the knight is rather flexible on e2 , when we also bait Black into playing Bb4 , which we know is rather terrible. }
5... d5
{ This move makes sense, grabbing the center, when Black is headed into a French-type of structure.   5...Bb4  is met by  6.a3!  was really good for White. }
6. e5 { From here Black needs to choose between three knight moves. } 6... Nfd7
{ This move has been twice as popular as the other two, which makes sense. Black always opts for this in the french, following up with c5 next, aiming at the d4 and e5-pawns. The knight targets the e5 pawn nicely from d7, making it sort of 'intuitive.' I do believe this to be the worst alternative due to tactical reasons, as Black is very vulnerable on the kingside. }
7. Nf4
{ The threats are coming in already as Nxe6 will win if Black is not careful. }
7... c5 { Black fell for the trick in a couple of games. } 8. Nxe6
{ A strong tactical shot! } 8... fxe6 9. Qh5+
{ Now that the King is wide open we continue to aggression. } 9... Ke7 10. Bg5+
Nf6 11. exf6+ gxf6 12. Bxf6+
{ The tone of the final nail in the coffin can be heard. } 12... Kxf6 13. Qh4+
{ Black loses the queen and resigned in 1-0 Bodnar, N -Pastar,S Chess.com INT 2021. }
