[Result "*"]

1. e4 b6 2. d4
{ I've said it before, and I'll say it again. Whenever we have the chance, we'll take full control of the center. }
2... Bb7 3. Nc3 e6
{ 3...g6  is possible, which is covered in the Modern chapter. } 4. Bd3 Nf6
{ This is a better move order. As we have seen,   4...Bb4  is met by  5.Nge2  ruining Black's fun rendering the attempt rather pointless. Therefore, it is better to develop the knight, followed by a quick d5  , aiming for a French-type of structure. }
5. Nge2
{ We once again go for this move. We have seen that the knight is rather flexible on e2 , when we also bait Black into playing Bb4 , which we know is rather terrible. }
5... d5
{ This move makes sense, grabbing the center, when Black is headed into a French-type of structure.   5...Bb4  is met by  6.a3!  was really good for White. }
6. e5 { From here Black needs to choose between three knight moves. } 6... Nfd7
{ This move has been twice as popular as the other two, which makes sense. Black always opts for this in the french, following up with c5 next, aiming at the d4 and e5-pawns. The knight targets the e5 pawn nicely from d7, making it sort of 'intuitive.' I do believe this to be the worst alternative due to tactical reasons, as Black is very vulnerable on the kingside. }
7. Nf4
{ The threats are coming in already as Nxe6 will win if Black is not careful. }
7... g6 { Prevents Nxe6, but the attack is very dangerous for Black after } 8.
Qg4
{ White has a 100% score from this position, meaning that it is really difficult to be Black here. We are threatening to take on e6, followed by Bxg6 and Bg5, making }
8... Qe7 { The most played move. } 9. Nb5 Na6
{ Developing the knight while defending c7 has been played 3/3 times.  The other move   9...Kd8  is better, but still awful after  10.O-O  a6  11.Na3  c5  12.c3  +-. We have full control and we may even support our center with Nc2 if needed. Black's king is highly vulnerable on d8. There's a reason all games have proceeded with Na6. Black has been highly rated too in all three games with two of them being around 2400. }
10. c3 { Solidifying our center. } 10... Bg7 11. h4 { Going for h5. } 11... h5
12. Qg3 O-O 13. O-O
{ Black would love to move the pawn on c7, but that's always met by Nd6. We will prepare for the sacrifice on g6 which seems inevitable. }
13... Rfb8 14. Nxg6 fxg6 15. Qxg6 Nf8 16. Qxh5
{ We have three pawns and a very powerful attack. Black's pieces are so badly placed that the engines gives a stunning advantage of +6. }
16... Qf7 17. Qg4
{ We have several plans up our sleeve. Placing the bishop on g5, followed up by f4-f5 seems really reasonable. We can also push up our h-pawn with h5-h6. The rook on f1 will also join the fight at some point by Re1-Re3-Rf3/Rg3. Black won't survive here, as his pieces are horribly placed. We're technically not even down material, as we do have three pawns after all. }
