1. e4 b6 2. d4
{ I've said it before, and I'll say it again. Whenever we have the chance, we'll take full control of the center. }
2... Bb7 3. Nc3 e6
{ 3...g6  is possible, which is covered in the Modern chapter. } 4. Bd3 Nf6
{ This is a better move order. As we have seen,   4...Bb4  is met by  5.Nge2  ruining Black's fun rendering the attempt rather pointless. Therefore, it is better to develop the knight, followed by a quick  5...d5  , aiming for a French-type of structure. }
5. Nge2
{ We once again go for this move. We have seen that the knight is rather flexible on e2 , when we also bait Black into playing Bb4 , which we know is rather terrible. }
5... c5 { Has been the most popular move here, but it once again allows... } 6.
d5 { We close the diagonal, making Black's pieces rather passive. } 6... Na6
{ Has been played by a strong French GM, along with 4 correspondence games. That being said, it is subpar compared to the Main Line, and White has won every single correspondence game, confirming that this is not ideal. We will take a look, though. The solution is to play actively and aggressively, because after all we have an advantage in central-control and development. }
7. O-O Nb4
{ This is the point, applying more pressure on d5 while attacking our bishop. The engine prefers   7...Nc7  , but it looks awful to me after  8.Nf4  a6  9.a4  . Black has achieved absolutely nothing by playing Na6-Nc7, and would have been better off grabbing the pawn. }
8. Bc4 { Defending the pawn while preventing Nxd3. } 8... b5 9. Bxb5 exd5 10.
a3 d4 11. axb4 dxc3 12. Nxc3 cxb4 13. e5
{ The most direct, although   13.Nd5  which won for White in Cook, D - R, Picken ICCF email 2015, is also good. Black lost the correspondence game which continued:  13...Bc6  14.Bf4  Rc8  15.Ba6  Be7  16.Nxe7  Kxe7  17.Bd6+  Ke8  18.Qd4  and Black decided to resign. As stated above, the text move is stronger as it is even more concrete. }
13... Ne4 14. Nxe4 Bxe4 15. Re1
{ Black can't prevent the move e6, when Black's king will have no shelter. }
15... Bc6 16. e6 { White is finally breaking through. } 16... fxe6 17. Bxc6
dxc6 18. Qh5+ g6 19. Qe5
{ Black resigned in Jefferson,N 2055 - Picken,R ICCF email 2015, due to the fact that the rook on h8 will fall. }
