{ 4...Bb4  Pinning the knight is a logical way for Black to fight against our center, with Nf6 and c5/ d5 coming. This set-up is not so easy to play against, and I even remember struggling with White against a lower-rated player in a rapid game.  5.Nge2!  ruining Black's fun rendering the attempt rather pointless. Therefore, it is better to develop the knight, followed by a quick...d5, aiming for a French-type of structure. }
5. Nge2
{ We once again go for this move. We have seen that the knight is rather flexible on e2 , when we also bait Black into playing Bb4 , which we know is rather terrible. }
5... c5 { Has been the most popular move here, but it once again allows... } 6.
d5 { We close the diagonal, making Black's pieces rather passive. } 6... Na6
{ Has been played by a strong French GM, along with 4 correspondence games. That being said, it is subpar compared to the Main Line, and White has won every single correspondence game, confirming that this is not ideal. We will take a look, though. The solution is to play actively and aggressively, because after all we have an advantage in central-control and development. }
7. O-O Nb4
{ This is the point, applying more pressure on d5 while attacking our bishop.   The engine prefers  7...Nc7  , but it looks awful to me after  8.Nf4  a6  a4  . Black has achieved absolutely nothing by playing Na6-Nc7, and would have been better off grabbing the pawn. }
8. Bc4 { Defending the pawn while preventing Nxd3. } 8... Nxe4
{ This is perhaps the trickiest move, aiming to win the piece back with exd5. }
9. Nxe4 exd5 10. Bg5
{ Attacking the queen while preventing Be7, which is met by Nd6+. } 10... f6
{ The most testing move, since any queen move can be met by a3. } 11. Nf4
{ Going for Qh5+. } 11... dxe4
{ Loses also to   11...dxc4  Was quickly hopeless for Black after  12.Re1  Bxe4  13.Qh5+  Ke7  Note that 13... g6 fails to 14. Nxg6!  14.Rad1  d5  15.Nxd5++-  Black kept it going some more moves, but was dead lost in Howard,J @@StartBracket@@1863@@EndBracket@@-Ott,P ICCF email 2015. }
12. Qh5+ Ke7 13. Qf7+ Kd6 14. Rad1+ Kc6 15. Be6
{ Black has to part with his queen or play } 15... d6 { But here, the move }
16. Nd5 { is crushing. White will take on b4 followed by Bd5+. } *

