1. e4 b6 2. d4
{ I've said it before, and I'll say it again. Whenever we have the chance, we'll take full control of the center. }
2... Bb7 3. Nc3 e6
{ 3...g6  is possible, which is covered in the Modern chapter. } 4. Bd3 Nf6
{ This is a better move order. As we have seen,   4...Bb4  is met by  5.Nge2  ruining Black's fun rendering the attempt rather pointless. Therefore, it is better to develop the knight, followed by a quick  5...d5  , aiming for a French-type of structure. }
5. Nge2
{ We once again go for this move. We have seen that the knight is rather flexible on e2 , when we also bait Black into playing Bb4 , which we know is rather terrible. }
5... d6
{ This is a rare move, but I think it is objectively best to take further control of the center, preventing moves like e5. Black will follow up with Be7-O-O-Nd7, when the development is completed at least. }
6. d5
{ We're already making Black to make an unpleasant choice, while giving the d4-square to our knight. }
6... exd5 7. exd5
{ It is better to take the pawn, when the e5-square is available for the knight on b8. }
7... Nbd7 { can be met by  Note that   7...Nxd5  loses to  8.Bb5+  c6  9.Qxd5 }
8. Nd4 { aiming to occupy the c6-square with Bb5-Bc6. If Black grabs the pawn }
8... Nxd5 9. Nxd5 Bxd5 10. O-O
{ We should once again get a fantastic initiative for the pawn, } 10... Be7 11.
Re1 Kf8 { Black's best try. } 12. Bc4
{ A clever decoy so we can place our knight on c6. The issue for Black is that the f7-pawn will be under a heavy attack if the decoy isn't captured, with Qh5. }
12... Bxc4 13. Nc6 Qc8 14. Nxe7
{ Black's king is very weak, but we need to play very accurately to keep a winning advantage. After all, Black has an extra pawn. }
14... Qb7 15. Qg4
{ The queen joins the attack, targeting the knight and bishop simultaneously. It also opens up the possibility of targeting the g7-pawn with Nf5. }
15... Be6 { It seems like Black has saved himself, but it is not the case. }
16. Rxe6 fxe6 17. Bh6
{ Black's king is opened, and he doesn't have enough defenders to defend against the slaughter coming his way. }
17... gxh6 18. Qxe6
{ White has sacrificed a whole rook, but Black is defenseless. Re1 or Nf5 will follow next. }
18... Nc5 { Is the engine's best defense, but } 19. Qf6+
{ Forces Black king to the center after } 19... Ke8 20. Nf5
{ The king now has to head to d7 because of the mate threat on e7. } 20... Kd7
21. Qg7+ Kc6 22. Nd4+ Kd5
{ Black's king is in the middle of the board, and should get mated sooner or later. }
23. Rc1
{ A sample line is:  23...b5  24.Qf7+  Kxd4  25.c3+  Kd3  26.Qf4  Nb3  27.Qe3+   27.axb3  is poor, as Black saves himself after  27...Qe4  27...Kc4  28.axb3+  Kxb3  29.c4+  Kxb2  30.Qc3+  Ka2  31.Ra1# }
