[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. Owen's Defense (1...b6)"]
[Black "1...b6 Conclusion"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ CONCLUSION: In the informational section, one can clearly see that 1. b6 has some potential. If one is not prepared, this move can be rather annoying to handle, as Black will attack our center quickly with Bb7-e6-Bb4-c5/ d5. However, the opening has its clear downsides like we've seen in several variations. Black is not preparing to castle, making his king always a target for us. Black is also more often than not getting passive positions due to the lack of central-control. }
1... b6 2. d4 Bb7 3. Nc3 e6 4. Bd3
{ This is the first major crossroads for Black. Putting the bishop on b4 seems rather pointless when we can defend the knight on c3 with Nge2, avoiding the double paws! Black has huge problems in this line, and I was far away from finding any satisfactory positions for him. As stated earlier, I really like that all the most popular moves in the position lead to awful positions. }
4... Nf6
{ is better than  4...Bb4  , but still not good enough to claim any sort of equality. }
5. Nge2
{ is once again good, when Black needs to tread with care.  5...c5  more or less fails due to the pawn sacrifice  6.d5  , when we saw how our initiative becomes rather overwhelming.   5...d6  might be objectively best, but it all looks like suffering to me, as the  c6  square becomes weak, while Black is also struggling to find any good squares for his pieces.   5...d5  is certainly possible, but it is a bad French as Black really has no pressure on the queenside.  The best way forward might be to follow in the footsteps of GM Aman Hambleton with Ng8, but even this isn't exactly satisfactory due to the passivity and vulnerable kingside. All in all, our set-up with Nge2 is strong and fairly simple to grasp. 1. b6 remains a fun surprise weapon that could wreak some havoc against unprepared players, but I believe that I have clearly demonstrated why this move is not seen often. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3. Alekhine's Defense (1...Nf6) Minor Lines"]
[Black "2...Ng8 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6
{ Alekhine's Defense is on the table, ready to be dissected. Black is provoking us into moving the pawn one more step forward, attacking the knight. This will allow White to get a decent pawn mass in the center, often on c4, d4, e5 & f4. However, this highly depends on which set-up White goes for of course. Having made these points, it does indeed seem very strange for Black to just give White central control 'for free,' so what is the idea behind the opening? Black aims to undermine and attack the pawns, with moves like Nc6, Bg4, d6, etc. The resulting position is highly unsymmetrical, making it a good choice for aggressive players, especially higher-rated players who want to beat their lower-rated opponents, avoiding symmetrical and dull positions. The opening isn't so popular nowadays, but played by strong players every now and then in shorter time controls, just like most rare lines. White has been proven to get a stable edge according to theory, but it is easier said than done. }
2. e5 Ng8
{ Going back to g8 looks really silly. However, we have played e5, so the pawn is an easy target for Black who will most likely play d6 next. I won't be spending too much time on it though, as it is more of a meme, attempting to troll the other player. }
3. d4 d6
{ 3...d5  has been seen a decent amount of times, but this makes no sense to me at all. Black is avoiding putting pressure on our center, playing something that looks like an advanced Caro-Kann or French with several tempos down. I simply suggest going for  4.c4  , applying pressure on d5 . }
4. f4
{ As we also go for this set-up in our Main Line, I felt like this was the most logical choice. The point is obvious, taking space while supporting our pawn on e5. }
4... dxe5
{ 4...Bf5  5.Nf3   5.g4  is objectively best, but there is no reason to complicate things.  5...e6  6.c3  Black has simply lost several tempos in an advanced Caro-Kann. }
5. fxe5 c5
{ This move has been seen the most amount of times, when we should simply advance.   5...e6  is met strongly by  6.Nc3!  and we can now meet Black's plan of  6...c5  with  7.d5 }
6. d5 e6 7. Nc3 exd5
{ This is forced, otherwise we'll play d6, locking Black down completely. } 8.
Qxd5 Nc6 { Heading into a really good endgame. } 9. Qxd8+ Nxd8 10. Nf3
{ Black is extremely passive. It will take a long time for his pieces to be fully developed. Our moves as quick and simple. Be3-O-O-O-Bb5, etc. Black also need to watch out for Nd5 and Nb5. }
*

