[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3. Alekhine's Defense (1...Nf6) Minor Lines"]
[Black "2...Ne4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Ne4
{ A further provocation, but very senseless. We can try to either trap the knight, or push it back to an inferior square. I prefer the latter due to how simple it is to play, but 3. d4 is also good, perhaps even objectively better. }
3. d3 Nc5 4. d4 Ne6 5. d5 Nc5
{ We have gained fantastic control of the center, so now it's time to develop our pieces. }
6. Nf3 e6 7. Nc3 d6 8. Be3
{ Our development is very quick, so Black probably needs to get rid of the tension as quick as possible in the center. }
8... dxe5 9. Nxe5 { Now Bb5+ is nasty, so the move } 9... exd5
{ Prevents that, further removing the tension. The drawback is how active pieces we get. }
10. Qxd5 Be6 11. Qf3 Nbd7 12. O-O-O
{ We have a massive lead in development when our pieces are also a lot more active.  12...Bd6  is the most logical continuation when  13.Nc4  or  13.Nxd7  followed by Nb5 makes sense, aiming to take the bishop. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3. Alekhine's Defense (1...Nf6) Minor Lines"]
[Black "2...Nd5 (5...dxe5 6...g6 1)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4
{ Around the time I started playing 1. e4, I consulted my good friend GM Aryan Tari about the Alekhine. He suggested me to play 4. Nf3, sharing some lines with me on how to obtain an edge. This is definitely a good move, but I somehow feel that it isn't the most critical one. The reason for this is that Black has a tendency to get slightly worse, but very playable positions. Black can play in numerous ways, and the outcome always seem to remain 'slightly worse, but that's it.' I mentioned this to Aryan recently, who agreed on my sentiment saying that he seldom acquired more than a slight edge. Having to study so many lines for a rare guest especially in Classical Chess, was not appealing to me at all, therefore I decided to investigate the other continuation that is known for being critical for Black, namely the Four Pawns Attack. }
4... Nb6 5. f4
{ Here we go. We keep our center intact, aiming for a massive space advantage. A massive pro with this system is that Black does not have many decent options at his disposal, as we soon shall see. }
5... dxe5 6. fxe5 g6
{ 6...Nc6  is the Main Line where the play continues  7.Be3  Bf5  8.Nc3  e6  9.Nf3  . This is the main tabiya in the Four Pawns Attack, and it will be examined thoroughly in the next chapter. }
7. Nc3 Bg7 8. c5
{ This is the only way to create problems for Black. If we don't do this we will get c5 slapped in our face when Black has succeeded well with his opening play. }
8... Nd5 9. Bc4 { We need to take control of this diagonal. } 9... Nxc3
{ 9...Be6  is met by  10.Qb3  With excellent chances. } 10. bxc3
{ 23 games have reached this position, but it simply looks too difficult for Black to play. It is extremely difficult for Black to fight against our center, so the position is more or less doomed to passiveness. }
10... O-O 11. Nf3 b6
{ The text move is an attempt to fight against our horde of pawns, but it fails to }
12. Ng5
{ The queen now gets a beautiful square on f3 while the knight is also creating lots of pressure against the weak pawn on f7. }
12... Bb7 13. e6 { We will now place our knight on f7. } 13... f5 14. Nf7 Qe8
15. O-O { Our knight on f7 gives us a really powerful attack. } 15... Nc6 16.
Bh6 Bxh6 17. Nxh6+ Kg7 18. Qd2
{ The knight will move back to f7, when Qh6+ followed by Ng5 is one deadly threat. We may also move our queen to g5 directly, aiming to win the f5-pawn. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3. Alekhine's Defense (1...Nf6) Minor Lines"]
[Black "2...Nd5 (5...dxe5 6...g6 2)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 Nb6 5. f4
{ Here we go. We keep our center intact, aiming for a massive space advantage. A massive pro with this system is that Black does not have many decent options at his disposal, as we soon shall see. }
5... dxe5 6. fxe5 g6 7. Nc3
{ Has been by far the most played move, but I won't put it as our Main Line due to the fact that I find }
7... c5
{ a much bigger challenge. My engine gives a massive advantage to us after this move, but don't be fooled. Things are exceptionally tricky in this line which we will soon see. }
8. d5 Bg7 9. Bf4 { Playing Nf3 would allow Bg4, so this is essential. } 9...
O-O 10. Qd2
{ This is a great move. Black is rather passive here, so we are aiming for a quick attack on the kingside. }
10... e6 { Black has to fight against our center. } 11. O-O-O exd5 12. cxd5 Re8
{ Has been seen a few times, but it loses more or less by force. } 13. Bg5
{ Attacking the queen. } 13... Qc7 14. Bb5
{ The threat here is to play d6, when Black's queen will have no available squares. If the knight on b8 moves to d7, we can play e6 followed by d6 when Black is busted. }
14... Bd7 15. e6 { 15. Nf3 also wins, but this is the most direct approach. }
15... fxe6 16. d6 Bxc3
{ Another line worthy of note:   16...Qc8  17.Bh6!  Nc6  18.Bxg7  Kxg7  19.h4  h5  20.g4  Nd4  21.gxh5 }
17. Qxc3 Qc8 18. Bh6 e5 { Black is almost out of the woods, but... } 19. Nf3
Bxb5 20. Nxe5
{ We are threatening to play d7, when the discovery on g7 decides the game. Black can't really do anything to stop it, as seen in the sample line }
20... Qe6 21. d7 Rd8 22. Nc6 Rxd7 23. Rxd7 Qxd7 24. Rd1
{ Black will soon be mated. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
