{ Has been by far the most played move, but I won't put it as our Main Line due to the fact that I find }
7... c5
{ a much bigger challenge. My engine gives a massive advantage to us after this move, but don't be fooled. Things are exceptionally tricky in this line which we will soon see. }
8. d5 Bg7 9. Bf4 { Playing Nf3 would allow Bg4, so this is essential. } 9...
O-O 10. Qd2
{ This is a great move. Black is rather passive here, so we are aiming for a quick attack on the kingside. }
10... e6 { Black has to fight against our center. } 11. O-O-O exd5 12. cxd5 Bg4
{ The engine might give a massive advantage for White here, but that doesn't mean that it's simple. The play becomes unbelievably complicated, giving Black great chances to achieve trickeries and swindles. }
13. Re1 c4
{ This is Black's best bet for counterplay. The point is that the bishop will maneuver from g4 to d3, opening up the c4-file. The c4-move also gives Black the c5-square for the knight. }
14. h3 Bf5 15. Nf3
{ This move has only been seen 5 times, but I think it's best not to give Black Bd3 with a tempo. }
15... Na6 16. d6
{ We are aiming to play Bh6 and exchanging the dark-squared bishop, followed up by Nd4 and a potential h4-h5. }
16... Nc5 17. Bh6 { We stick to our plan. } 17... Rc8
{ Putting the rook in the open file towards our king is very sensible. } 18.
Bxg7 Kxg7 19. Nd4 { Threatening to take on f5, while e6 is also in the air. }
19... Bd3
{ This move makes the most sense to me. Black wants to take on f1, followed by a Nd3 jump at some point. Nba4 may also come if we are not careful, making tactics like Nb3 possible due to the discovered check. }
20. h4
{ 20.e6  is equally good according to my engine, but it's a lot harder to play and filled to the brim with complications. Black can for instance sacrifice an exchange, etc. h4 is rather straightforward, aiming for h5 next with the attack we've talked about. }
20... Kh8
{ The exclam is there due to the fact that this is objectively best, but obviously not very critical as it is rather slow.   20...Bxf1  We always need to watch out for this option, but here it just doesn't work.  21.Rexf1  Nd3+  Grabbing the pawn seems like the critical option, otherwise we simply play h5.  22.Kb1  Nxe5  23.h5  g5  is met by  24.Nf5+  when Ne7+ comes next, threatening the rook on c8 and pawn on g5.   20...Nba4  Is an extremely tricky move. Black aims to take on c3 and play Na4 next, playing c3. This is a very dangerous idea, and in fact, there is only one way to counter it... Something concrete and direct...  21.e6!  We need to act quickly.  21...Qf6  Black is attacking our knight while dodging the fork on e7.  The engine wants to give the knight after   21...Nxe6  , but that obviously loses. Note also how Black loses the queen after  21...Qxd6  22.Nf5+!  gxf5  23.Qg5+!  Black is forced to move to h8 , when we will play Qf6+ , taking on f7 next and winning the queen on d6 .  22.d7!  We keep marching with our soldiers.  22...Qxd4  Black has to sacrifice an exchange due to e7 coming next.  23.dxc8=Q  Rxc8  24.exf7  I'd normally like to stop, but play from here is still slightly tricky.  24...Kxf7  25.Bxd3  This is a concrete move. We want to develop our pieces, while Black can't win the exchange back due to tactical reasons.  25...Nxd3+  26.Kb1  The knight on d3 is pinned.  26...Nxc3+  27.bxc3!  Qb6+  28.Ka1   20...h5  Is the human reaction, but it won't stop our attack.  21.g4!  Black can't stop our attack. For example:  21...hxg4  22.h5  Rh8  There is an 'x' amount of winning moves here, but the best one is  23.Kd1!  Prophylaxis at it's finest. The point is to take on d3 followed by hxg6, when there no longer will be a recapture with check.  23...Bf5  An alternative for Black:   23...Nba4  24.Nxa4  Nxa4  25.Bxd3  cxd3  26.hxg6  Black's king is blasted open. The engine gives an edge of 20+ pawns, which is rather accurate.  24.hxg6  Bxg6  25.Bg2  White will simply take on h8 followed by Rh1, when Black will be forced to give his queen. }
21. h5 g5
{ This is the entire point. Black closes down the h-file making it harder for us to attack. }
22. e6
{ There might be better moves, but I like this concreate approach forcing the matter. }
22... fxe6 23. Nxe6 Nxe6 24. Rxe6 { Black's dangerous initiative is all gone. }
24... Qd7 25. Qe3 { Otherwise we lose the pawn on d6. } 25... Bf5 26. Qd4+ Qg7
{ Only move. } 27. Qxg7+ Kxg7 28. h6+
{ This is an important move, destroying Black's king safety. } 28... Kh8 29.
Re7
{ The material might be equal, but White is winning. Black has incredibly problems with his king due to the constant worries of back-rank mates. This makes it rather difficult to stay active, which is a key factor in endgames. Without active pieces, you're doomed. }
