[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 Nb6 5. f4
{ Here we go. We keep our center intact, aiming for a massive space advantage. A massive pro with this system is that Black does not have many decent options at his disposal, as we soon shall see. }
5... dxe5 6. fxe5 g6 7. Nc3
{ Has been by far the most played move, but I won't put it as our Main Line due to the fact that I find }
7... c5
{ a much bigger challenge. My engine gives a massive advantage to us after this move, but don't be fooled. Things are exceptionally tricky in this line which we will soon see. }
8. d5 Bg7 9. Bf4 { Playing Nf3 would allow Bg4, so this is essential. } 9...
O-O 10. Qd2
{ This is a great move. Black is rather passive here, so we are aiming for a quick attack on the kingside. }
10... e6 { Black has to fight against our center. } 11. O-O-O exd5 12. cxd5 Bg4
{ The engine might give a massive advantage for White here, but that doesn't mean that it's simple. The play becomes unbelievably complicated, giving Black great chances to achieve trickeries and swindles. }
13. Re1 c4
{ This is Black's best bet for counterplay. The point is that the bishop will maneuver from g4 to d3, opening up the c4-file. The c4-move also gives Black the c5-square for the knight. }
14. h3 Bf5 15. Nf3
{ This move has only been seen 5 times, but I think it's best not to give Black Bd3 with a tempo. }
15... Na6 16. d6
{ We are aiming to play Bh6 and exchanging the dark-squared bishop, followed up by Nd4 and a potential h4-h5. }
16... Nb4
{ The other knight jump seems slightly trickier to me, as Black does have some more flexibility. First of all, the knight is closer to our king, which is slightly uncomfortable. One clear advantage of having the knight on b4 is that the c5 square is vacant, making a jump from b6-d7-c5 a very tempting maneuver. It should also be pointed out that the knight is hard to remove, due to a5 being a constant resource against a3. The knight may also attempt to jump to d5, trying to remove our control of the c3-square. }
17. Nd4 { I like this move, chasing the bishop on f5. } 17... Bd3
{ I believe this is a move a human would play every time. The engine prefers   17...Bd7  , but this makes no sense at all to me. I suggest continuing with our plan with  18.Bh6  .  18...Nd3+  is also nothing to worry about, as we can simply take and play Bh6 . }
18. a3
{ Is the typical reaction, but it works out well for us after  18...a5!?  19.Bh6!  Our plan remains the same. Get rid of the dark-squared bishops and start an attack.  19...Re8  20.Bxg7  Kxg7  21.Ncb5!  I like this move, aiming for Nc7 while also preparing to capture the b4 knight in the future.  21...Na2+  22.Kd1  Rc8  This is the most sensible way to play, attempting to play c3 at some point.  23.e6  Once again we see this concrete move.  23...c3  24.bxc3!   After  24.Qxd3  cxb2!  comes, when things have become extraordinarily complicated, with Rc1+ moves looming in the air.  24...Nxc3+  25.Nxc3  Nc4  Is the last attempt from Black to create some fireworks due to the fork on b2, when one winning continuation is  26.exf7!  Rxe1+  27.Kxe1  Now that we have moved our king, the d3-bishop is under attack.  27...Qh4+  28.Qf2  Qxf2+  29.Kxf2  The queens are off the board, erasing any hopes for a swindle. The extra piece gives White a winning position. }
18... Bxf1
{ This is certainly the most critical move, avoiding exchange and keeping the tension. Taking the knight will open the a-file, allowing a vicious attack. Note how  18...N4d5  loses a pawn after  19.Bg5  when we will take on d3 next. }
19. axb4 Bd3 20. e6
{ This move is very important, otherwise Black will play a5-a4-a3, with a very dangerous attack. }
20... Bxd4
{ Is the most critical move if you ask me, sacrificing an exchange. } 21. e7
Qd7 22. exf8=Q+ Rxf8 23. Re7 { Playing actively always works out. } 23... Qc6
24. b5 Qc5 25. Bh6 Bg7
{ Moving the rook is bet by Rhe1, when Black is struggling with back-rank mating threats. }
26. Bxg7 Kxg7 27. Ne4
{ We keep our pawn on d6, and it is clear that Black do not have enough for the material deficit. Qc3+ and Re1 may follow. }
