10... e6 { Black has to fight against our center. } 11. O-O-O exd5 12. cxd5 Bg4
{ The engine might give a massive advantage for White here, but that doesn't mean that it's simple. The play becomes unbelievably complicated, giving Black great chances to achieve trickeries and swindles. }
13. Re1 c4
{ This is Black's best bet for counterplay. The point is that the bishop will maneuver from g4 to d3, opening up the c4-file. The c4-move also gives Black the c5-square for the knight. }
14. h3 Bf5 15. g4
{ I analyzed this in great depth, and I was not happy at all with the resulting positions. It is extremely tricky making it simple to error. The strong GM Movsesian @@StartBracket@@2646@@EndBracket@@ won a game here, but even he struggled along the way. This is definitely a viable alternative though, so I will present some of my analysis to you.  15...Bd3  16.Bxd3  cxd3  17.Qxd3  Na6  18.d6!  Rc8   18...Nb4  19.Qd1  Qc8  20.Kb1  Qc4!  21.Re4  Qd3+  22.Qxd3  Nxd3  23.Bg3  f5  24.exf6  Rxf6  25.Nge2  Rf3  26.Re7  Bxc3  27.bxc3  Nc4  19.Kb1!  Nb4!   19...Nc4  20.Nf3  Qb6  21.Rh2!  Nb4  22.Qd1!   19...Nc5  20.Qe2  Ne6  21.Bc1  Nc4  22.Nf3  Qa5  23.h4!  Na3+  24.Ka1+–  20.Qd1  Nc4  21.Re4!  g5   21...Qa5  22.Qb3  b5  23.Nf3  Nd3  24.Nd5!  Nc5  25.Qc2  Nxe4  26.Qxe4+– }
