[Black "2...Nd5 (5...dxe5 6...c5 1)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 Nb6 5. f4
{ Here we go. We keep our center intact, aiming for a massive space advantage. A massive pro with this system is that Black does not have many decent options at his disposal, as we soon shall see. }
5... dxe5 6. fxe5 c5
{ Undermining the center with c5 is a typical and rather tricky way to play, so we must be prepared. }
7. d5 e6
{ Going for a Benoni-like structure doesn't work too well here. The better move is  7...g6  which will lead to 6...g6 . }
8. Nc3 Qh4+ { Has been seen in 30 games, but it just loses. } 9. g3 Qd4
{ Is the point, but it's just an awful endgame after } 10. Qxd4 cxd4 11. Nb5
Na6 12. d6
{ White will play Nf3 followed by Nbxd4 and Bf4. If Black is too slow, we might even play a3-b4-c5. One nice game continued }
12... f6 { This is the point of the line, aiming to win our weak pawn on d6. }
13. Nf3 Bd7 14. Nbxd4 fxe5 15. Nxe5 Bxd6
{ Black has succeeded in his aim, but at the cost of the bishop pair, passive pieces and a really weak pawn on e6. }
16. Nxd7 Kxd7 17. Bh3 { A great move, targeting the weak pawn on e6. } 17...
Rae8 18. b3
{ Black was lost in Kotronias,V - Karagiannis,A Salonica 2006. The plan forward is Bb2-Ke2-Rad1-Rhf1. Black is way too passive and struggling massively with the weak pawn on e6. }
