[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 Nb6 5. f4
{ Here we go. We keep our center intact, aiming for a massive space advantage. A massive pro with this system is that Black does not have many decent options at his disposal, as we soon shall see. }
5... dxe5 6. fxe5 c5
{ Undermining the center with c5 is a typical and rather tricky way to play, so we must be prepared. }
7. d5 e6
{ Going for a Benoni-like structure doesn't work too well here. The better move is  7...g6  which will lead to 6...g6 . }
8. Nc3 exd5 9. cxd5 Qh4+ { Is better in this line, but still pretty bad. } 10.
g3 Qd4
{ We can now longer take on d4, because Black will take on d5 and defend the c7-fork. However, we have another resource up our sleeve! }
11. Bb5+
{ Developing our bishop out with a check gives us a really valuable tempo. }
11... Bd7 12. Qe2
{ Black needs to watch out for e6 now, which is a deadly threat. We may also play Nf3 soon, gaining a tempo on the exposed queen on d4. }
12... Nxd5
{ This has been the most played move by quite a bit, and certainly the most critical one from a practical perspective.   12...a6  is met by  13.e6! }
13. e6
{ This is the only way to win, but the entire point behind our scheme with Bb5-Qe2. }
13... fxe6 14. Qxe6+ Ne7 15. Nf3 { Gaining a tempo on the queen. } 15... Qf6
{ 15...Qb4  has also been played, when  16.Ne5  wins!  Black may take the bishop, but we will play a3 followed by Bf4-O-O-O-Qf7 when Black will soon be mated. }
16. Qe2
{ We do not want to trade queens. Black will have a hard time fending off our idea of playing Bf4-Ne4-Nd6. }
16... Nc6 17. Ne4 Qg6 18. Bf4
{ Black can resign, as there is no way to defend against Nd6 when his position will be in shambles. }
