[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 Nb6 5. f4
{ Here we go. We keep our center intact, aiming for a massive space advantage. A massive pro with this system is that Black does not have many decent options at his disposal, as we soon shall see. }
5... dxe5 6. fxe5 c5
{ Undermining the center with c5 is a typical and rather tricky way to play, so we must be prepared. }
7. d5 e6
{ Going for a Benoni-like structure doesn't work too well here. The better move is  7...g6  which will lead to 6...g6 . }
8. Nc3 exd5 9. cxd5 c4
{ Has been by far the most popular move, and the only way to justify giving away the center. }
10. d6
{ Black's point is seen after   10.Nf3  Bb4!  when he gets some pressure against our center. This gives White a decent advantage too, but it is extremely unnecessary.  d6  takes away all of Black's fun, when the position is objectively lost already due to our massive space advantage. }
10... Nc6 11. Bf4 Be6
{ Normal play won't do Black any good. He is extremely passive, and our moves forward are quite simple. }
12. Nf3 { We're eyeing the square on g5. } 12... Nd7
{ Black wants to play g6-Bg7, applying a lot of pressure against e5. However, it's too late...   12...h6  Preventing Ng5, while also aiming to play g5 which can be quickly followed up by Bg7-g4, aiming for e5.  13.Nd4!  This is an excellent move, spoiling Black's plans.  13...Nxd4  14.Qxd4  g5  15.Bg3  Bg7  Black may have developed his bishop, but the pressure on e5 is non-existent.  16.Be2  O-O  17.O-O  We have an extremely powerful pawn on d6, and Black has no counterplay whatsoever. Black may attempt to move his knight some day, when Nd5 will always be strong. }
13. Ng5
{ Black has to give the strong bishop on e6, which is the piece that holds everything together. }
13... Ndxe5
{ This leads to a forced sequence, but I can't see what else Black is supposed to do. }
14. Nxe6 fxe6 15. Bxe5 Nxe5 16. Qh5+ Nf7 17. Bxc4
{ Black is struggling massively due to the pin on the f7-knight. Black also needs to watch out for Qb5 ideas, capturing on b7. }
17... Bxd6 18. Bxe6 Qe7 19. O-O O-O 20. Rae1
{ The queen has no squares to move to without losing the knight, and } 20... g6
21. Qd5 { Black loses a piece. } *

