1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 Nb6 5. f4
{ Here we go. We keep our center intact, aiming for a massive space advantage. A massive pro with this system is that Black does not have many decent options at his disposal, as we soon shall see. }
5... g6 { Is the most popular sideline. } 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. Be3
{ Black has a critical decision to make here, since the main move loses almost on the spot. }
7... Be6
{ Black was to provoke us even more into playing d5, also dxe5 followed by c5 could occur in some lines, undermining our e5-pawn. }
8. Rc1
{ Originally I wanted to play  8.d5  but it became too messy for my taste.   8.b3  is another good alternative, which should transpose to our Main Line. }
8... dxe5 9. fxe5 Nxc4
{ The engine wants to grab the pawn, but this makes little sense for a human. }
10. Bxc4 Bxc4 11. Qa4+
{ Black is now forced to give the b-pawn which will create a weak pawn on c7 and a7. }
11... b5 12. Nxb5 Bxb5 13. Qxb5+ Nd7 14. Nf3 O-O 15. b3
{ Black is left with weak pawns and fairly passive pieces. I like the thought of playing Qc6 next, putting pressure on c7. We may also double the rooks on the c-file, and prevent a5 and c5 with b4 in the future. }
