[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 Nb6 5. f4
{ Here we go. We keep our center intact, aiming for a massive space advantage. A massive pro with this system is that Black does not have many decent options at his disposal, as we soon shall see. }
5... g6 { Is the most popular sideline. } 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. Be3
{ Black has a critical decision to make here, since the main move loses almost on the spot. }
7... Be6
{ Black was to provoke us even more into playing d5, also dxe5 followed by c5 could occur in some lines, undermining our e5-pawn. }
8. Rc1
{ Originally I wanted to play  8.d5  but it became too messy for my taste. }
8... O-O { All the games in my database have seen this move on the board. } 9.
b3 dxe5 10. fxe5 c5
{ Is a standard reaction for Black, undermining our pawn on e5. } 11. d5
{ We won't let Black ruin our beautiful pawn structure. } 11... Bc8
{ This is the other alternative. } 12. Nf3 Bg4
{ Black is finally able to put the bishop on g4, targeting our pawn on e5. }
13. Bxc5 N8d7 14. Bf2
{ This looks rather curious at first, since the move has a hidden point to it. }
14... Nxe5 15. Be2 Bxf3 16. gxf3
{ 16.Bxf3  isn't as strong, because Black gets some compensation after  16...e6  , followed by a quick exd5 . After that he will play f5, when all of a sudden Ng4-jumps are quite annoying. After the text move we may play f4, chasing away the knight on e5. The bishop is also better placed on f2, because it can move to g3, supporting f4 if necessary. }
16... Bh6
{ Preventing the f4-move is more or less the only way to stay in the game. }
17. O-O
{ We're prepared to sacrifice the exchange, because we will have excellent control on the dark squares. }
17... e6 { Black should challenge our center. } 18. Bg3 Bxc1 19. Qxc1
{ We'll have a really powerful initiative for the exchange, due to our really strong bishop pair and central pawns. }
19... Qf6 20. Ne4 Qg7 21. Qc3
{ We're soon heading into an endgame, where White will have all the fun. }
21... Ned7 22. Qxg7+ Kxg7 23. dxe6 fxe6 24. a4
{ We are aiming to play a5 next, chasing away the knight on b6. If Black decides to prevent this and play a5 himself, he will have to always watch out for Be1, targeting the pawn. The reason for my evaluation is the fact that Black has really passive pieces. In order for the rooks to be superior to the minor pieces, they have to have open files, giving them control of tons of squares. In our camp, we are more or less no weaknesses. We can't say the same for Black, who needs to watch out for Nd6, Nc5, etc. }
