{ Here we go. We keep our center intact, aiming for a massive space advantage. A massive pro with this system is that Black does not have many decent options at his disposal, as we soon shall see. }
5... Nc6
{ is a pretty good attempt to provoke us into playing d5, when e6 followed by Bb4 will create decent counterplay against our center. Therefore, I think we simply should go for the move }
6. Nc3 dxe5
{ Is a natural move, but it should have been played a move earlier. } 7. d5 Nb8
8. c5 { Now Black doesn't have time for the counterplay with e6-Bb4. } 8...
N6d7 9. Nf3
{ We do not care about the pawn on c5. Black is free to take it, but our development advantage is far more important than a mere pawn. }
9... Nxc5
{ Is a better move, but Black is still suffering from underdevelopment.   9...exf4  10.Bxf4  Nxc5  11.Bc4  Black is too undeveloped.  11...e6  is met by   11...g6  12.Qd4  Hits the Knight and Rook.  12.b4 }
10. fxe5 e6 11. Bg5 { Attacking the queen with a tempo. } 11... Be7 12. Bxe7
Qxe7 13. Qd4 { Threatening to play d6 and win the knight, so it has to move. }
13... Nba6 14. Bxa6 Nxa6 15. d6
{ We have created a deadly passed pawn on d6 which is highly likely to decide the game. }
15... cxd6 16. exd6 Qf6 17. Qxf6
{ Going for the endgame wins, but it requires some accuracy. } 17... gxf6 18.
Ne4 f5 19. Nf6+ Kf8
{ Black will be fine if he is able to play Kg7 and Rd8 rather quickly. One trap he has here is that d7 is met by Ke7! We may win a piece, but Black will have excellent compensation after Rc2 . }
20. g4
{ This is a fantastic move. We aim to open up the g-file in several lines, Ne5 becomes a very serious threat. }
20... Kg7 21. Nh5+
{ This is another point of g4. If Black moves the king to h6, we no longer need to worry about the knight on h5. }
21... Kf8 22. Rc1
{ Nb8 is not a possible move any longer, due to the fact that the bishop on c8 will be hanging. White will play Ne5 followed by d7 next, winning a piece. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4. Alekhine's Defense (1...Nf6) Mainlines"]
[Black "2....Nd5 (5...dxe5 6...Bf5)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6
{ Alekhine's Defense is on the table, ready to be dissected. Black is provoking us into moving the pawn one more step forward, attacking the knight. This will allow White to get a decent pawn mass in the center, often on c4, d4, e5 & f4. However, this highly depends on which set-up White goes for of course. Having made these points, it does indeed seem very strange for Black to just give White central control 'for free,' so what is the idea behind the opening? Black aims to undermine and attack the pawns, with moves like Nc6, Bg4, d6, etc. The resulting position is highly unsymmetrical, making it a good choice for aggressive players, especially higher-rated players who want to beat their lower-rated opponents, avoiding symmetrical and dull positions. The opening isn't so popular nowadays, but played by strong players every now and then in shorter time controls, just like most rare lines. White has been proven to get a stable edge according to theory, but it is easier said than done. }
2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4
{ Around the time I started playing 1. e4, I consulted my good friend GM Aryan Tari about the Alekhine. He suggested me to play 4. Nf3, sharing some lines with me on how to obtain an edge. This is definitely a good move, but I somehow feel that it isn't the most critical one. The reason for this is that Black has a tendency to get slightly worse, but very playable positions. Black can play in numerous ways, and the outcome always seem to remain 'slightly worse, but that's it.' I mentioned this to Aryan recently, who agreed on my sentiment saying that he seldom acquired more than a slight edge. Having to study so many lines for a rare guest @@StartBracket@@especially in Classical Chess@@EndBracket@@, was not appealing to me at all, therefore I decided to investigate the other continuation that is known for being critical for Black, namely the Four Pawns Attack. }
4... Nb6 5. f4
{ Here we go. We keep our center intact, aiming for a massive space advantage. A massive pro with this system is that Black does not have many decent options at his disposal, as we soon shall see. }
5... dxe5 6. fxe5
{ Before we move to the Main tabiya of the Four Pawn Attack, I just want to quickly highlight what happens if Black chooses to go for a set-up without Nc6, or delays e6. }
6... Bf5 7. Nc3 e6
{ 7...Nc6  takes us back to Main Line territory. A massive advantage of delaying the knight to  c6  is the fact that Black can often opt for Bb4-c5 rather quickly, which will be a great version of the Bb4-line in the Main Line. }
8. Nf3
{ We do not need to develop our bishop to  e3  yet, and it is important that we manage to castle as quickly as possible.  8.Be3  Bb4  9.Nf3  c5  looks quite equal if you ask me. }
8... Bb4
{ This is really the only independent option, as  8...Nc6  leads to the Main Line, while after  8...Be7  it really doesn't make any sense to delay the jump to  c6  for too long. }
9. Bd3
{ In the Final of The Tour, GM Nakamura played  9.Be2  against Magnus, but this is much stronger, aiming to trade bishops. }
9... Bg4 { Has been played by two strong GMs, but it is flawed. } 10. O-O Nc6
{ Black has some pressure against d4, but it is easy to dodge the threat. } 11.
c5 Nd5 12. Ne2 Bxf3 13. Rxf3
{ Black's bishop on b4 is struggling, so Black tried } 13... Nxd4 14. Nxd4 Bxc5
15. Kh1
{ A resignation would be appropriate in Xiong,J -Bortnyk,O chess.com INT 2020. The knight is protected due to Qa4+, when White is simply up a piece. }
