1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 Nb6 5. f4
{ Here we go. We keep our center intact, aiming for a massive space advantage. A massive pro with this system is that Black does not have many decent options at his disposal, as we soon shall see. }
5... dxe5 6. fxe5
{ Before we move to the Main tabiya of the Four Pawn Attack, I just want to quickly highlight what happens if Black chooses to go for a set-up without Nc6, or delays e6. }
6... Nc6 7. Be3 Bf5 8. Nc3 e6 9. Nf3
{ We have arrived at the Main Position in the Four Pawns Attack. Black has a wide arsenal of options here, and all of them have been played 200+ times. }
9... Be7
{ As we have seen, none of the sidelines have been particularly impressive, so it is not surprising to see that this is by far the most played move. }
10. Be2
{ It seems to be that we get a highly comfortable middlegame after this move, making it a rather simple choice.  10.Bf2!?  is another move I looked at, but I didn't find anything convincing. }
10... O-O
{ 10...f6  has been played, but it really shouldn't make a difference after O-O. Other moves have been seen here before, but the text move is by far the most popular and logical. I've had this position in around 10 blitz games online, and indeed, Black always goes for this. }
11. O-O Qd7
{ Has been played before, but it seems like Black just loses a tempo when we compare the position to the Main Line. }
12. Qd2 Rad8 13. Rad1
{ We have achieved excellent control over our center. Sooner or later Black has to play }
13... f6 14. exf6 Bxf6 15. Bf2
{ Black's queen just stands in the way of the rook, when it's clear that 11...Qd7   was nothing but a waste of time. }
