{ Before we move to the Main tabiya of the Four Pawn Attack, I just want to quickly highlight what happens if Black chooses to go for a set-up without Nc6, or delays e6. }
6... Nc6 7. Be3 Bf5 8. Nc3 e6 9. Nf3
{ We have arrived at the Main Position in the Four Pawns Attack. Black has a wide arsenal of options here, and all of them have been played 200+ times. }
9... Be7
{ As we have seen, none of the sidelines have been particularly impressive, so it is not surprising to see that this is by far the most played move. }
10. Be2
{ It seems to be that we get a highly comfortable middlegame after this move, making it a rather simple choice.  10.Bf2!?  is another move I looked at, but I didn't find anything convincing. }
10... O-O
{ 10...f6  has been played, but it really shouldn't make a difference after O-O. Other moves have been seen here before, but the text move is by far the most popular and logical. I've had this position in around 10 blitz games online, and indeed, Black always goes for this. }
11. O-O f6
{ More or less the point of the set-up. Black aims to put the bishop on f6, adding pressure on our d4-pawn. The clear drawback though, is the fact that the e6-pawn will be left rather weak. }
12. exf6 Bxf6 13. Qd2
{ We go for this set-up again. Putting the rook on  d1  , defending the targeted pawn on  d4  . From here, our queen may maneuver to e1-g3. Other than that, we will play b3-Kh1-h3, simply strengthening our position.  13.b3!?  has been tried recently by strong players, and certainly worth a look, but there is no need to give alternatives to such an uncommon variation. Besides, I think  13.Qd2  is stronger. }
13... Rf7 { Has been played, but it's not a great move due to a neat trick. }
14. g4
{ Black's pieces will be kicked back giving him a very passive position. }
14... Bg6 15. g5 { The point, making Black's position even more passive. }
15... Be7 16. Nh4
{ Removing Black's bishop on g6, gaining full control of the light squares. }
16... Qe8 17. Nxg6 Rxf1+ 18. Rxf1 Qxg6 19. Bd3 Qh5 20. c5
{ Taking space, while giving us the square on c4 for the bishop, attacking e6. }
20... Nd7 21. Qe2 Qxe2 22. Bxe2
{ Our active pieces and bishop pair grants us a massive advantage in the endgame. a3-b4-Bc4-h4 is a logical plan. }
*

