[Round "?"]
[White "4. Alekhine's Defense (1...Nf6) Mainlines"]
[Black "2...Nd5 (5...dxe5 6...Nc6 9...Be7 9)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 Nb6 5. f4
{ Here we go. We keep our center intact, aiming for a massive space advantage. A massive pro with this system is that Black does not have many decent options at his disposal, as we soon shall see. }
5... dxe5 6. fxe5
{ Before we move to the Main tabiya of the Four Pawn Attack, I just want to quickly highlight what happens if Black chooses to go for a set-up without Nc6, or delays e6. }
6... Nc6 7. Be3 Bf5 8. Nc3 e6 9. Nf3
{ We have arrived at the Main Position in the Four Pawns Attack. Black has a wide arsenal of options here, and all of them have been played 200+ times. }
9... Be7
{ As we have seen, none of the sidelines have been particularly impressive, so it is not surprising to see that this is by far the most played move. }
10. Be2
{ It seems to be that we get a highly comfortable middlegame after this move, making it a rather simple choice.  10.Bf2!?  is another move I looked at, but I didn't find anything convincing. }
10... O-O
{ 10...f6  has been played, but it really shouldn't make a difference after O-O. Other moves have been seen here before, but the text move is by far the most popular and logical. I've had this position in around 10 blitz games online, and indeed, Black always goes for this. }
11. O-O f6
{ More or less the point of the set-up. Black aims to put the bishop on f6, adding pressure on our d4-pawn. The clear drawback though, is the fact that the e6-pawn will be left rather weak. }
12. exf6 Bxf6 13. Qd2
{ We go for this set-up again. Putting the rook on  d1  , defending the targeted pawn on  d4  . From here, our queen may maneuver to e1-g3. Other than that, we will play b3-Kh1-h3, simply strengthening our position.  13.b3!?  has been tried recently by strong players, and certainly worth a look, but there is no need to give alternatives to such an uncommon variation. Besides, I think  13.Qd2  is stronger. }
13... Qe7 14. Rad1 Rad8
{ As usual, Black puts the rook in the d4-applying pressure against our soldier on d4. }
15. Kh1
{ This prophylactic move is rather clever. We are prepared against the tricky idea of playing e5-Nd4, when h3 may soon follow too, preventing Bg4.   15.Qc1  is the natural instinct, removing the queen from the d-file. However, I think Black has decent counterplay after  15...e5  16.d5  Nd4  17.Nxd4  exd4  18.Bxd4  Bg5  , when things are not clear. The game Perunovic, M-Berkes, F 2019 is a nice reference. }
15... Bg4
{ 15...h6  will transpose to  13...h6  after  16.h3  . The  15...e5  trick is also no longer good now that we can move our queen to  e1  instead of  a1  . A move like  15...Rfe8  or  15...Kh8  is met by Qc1-h3-b3 when we keep improving our position. We may also put our bishop on  g1  , leaving the e-file open for our rook on  e1  . It really is rather difficult for Black to find a good plan here. The text move is kind of a direct approach, aiming to go for  Bxf3  when the pawn on  d4  will fall if we don't act accordingly. }
16. Ne4
{ Once again we have this resource, capturing on f6 if Black goes for Bxf3. }
16... Bxf3 17. Nxf6+ Rxf6 18. gxf3
{ We shouldn't allow Black to trade off the rooks. The g-file may now be used for attacking purposes, giving us a rather big advantage. We can end the theory section here, but I want to let you click through a sample way the game may proceed.   18...Qf7  19.Bd3!  The bishop will be well placed on  e4  .  19...Rxf3  Taking the pawn is critical of course.  20.Qg2  Rxf1+  21.Rxf1  with the strong Bishop Pair white has the edge.   20...Rf8  Doesn't work after  21.d5  exd5  22.Bc5  Rxd3  Black's ultimate trick, but it fails to  23.Rde1!  Re8  24.Rxe8+  Qxe8  25.Qe2!  A fantastic line. }
