[White "4. Alekhine's Defense (1...Nf6) Mainlines"]
[Black "2...Nd5 (5...dxe5 6...Nc6 9...Qd7 4)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 Nb6 5. f4
{ Here we go. We keep our center intact, aiming for a massive space advantage. A massive pro with this system is that Black does not have many decent options at his disposal, as we soon shall see. }
5... dxe5 6. fxe5
{ Before we move to the Main tabiya of the Four Pawn Attack, I just want to quickly highlight what happens if Black chooses to go for a set-up without Nc6, or delays e6. }
6... Nc6 7. Be3 Bf5 8. Nc3 e6 9. Nf3
{ We have arrived at the Main Position in the Four Pawns Attack. Black has a wide arsenal of options here, and all of them have been played 200+ times. }
9... Qd7
{ This move aims to add additional pressure on d4, sort of similar to the Bg4-line. }
10. Be2 O-O-O { The sharpest and most popular try. } 11. O-O Bg4
{ It's not a surprise that this move has been the most popular move, due to the added pressure on d4. }
12. c5 { Kicking the knight while going for a queenside pawn storm. } 12... Nd5
13. Nxd5 Qxd5 14. b4
{ There are other good moves, but this pawn-launching move is best. } 14... f6
{ It makes sense to fight against our center. } 15. h3 Bh5 16. Qc1
{ Protecting the bishop on e3 while vacating the square on d1 for the rook. We may also play Rb1, protecting the pawn on b4. }
16... Nxb4 { The only 'critical move,' but it's just too dangerous. } 17. Rb1
Nc6 18. Bc4 Qd7 19. Qb2
{ We will breakthrough sooner or later.  19...b6  is for instance met by  20.cxb6  ,  when we will follow up with d5 and Bxb6, blasting up Black's entire fortress. }
