[White "4. Alekhine's Defense (1...Nf6) Mainlines"]
[Black "2...Nd5 (5...dxe5 6...Nc6 9...Bb4 2)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 Nb6 5. f4
{ Here we go. We keep our center intact, aiming for a massive space advantage. A massive pro with this system is that Black does not have many decent options at his disposal, as we soon shall see. }
5... dxe5 6. fxe5
{ Before we move to the Main tabiya of the Four Pawn Attack, I just want to quickly highlight what happens if Black chooses to go for a set-up without Nc6, or delays e6. }
6... Nc6 7. Be3 Bf5 8. Nc3 e6 9. Nf3
{ We have arrived at the Main Position in the Four Pawns Attack. Black has a wide arsenal of options here, and all of them have been played 200+ times. }
9... Bb4
{ This is once again a possible move, and not a half-bad way to play. Black aims to capture on c3 in the future followed by Na5, getting excellent control of the light squares. }
10. Be2
{ The difference here is that Black has a knight on c6 that puts pressure on our pawn on d4. Therefore, Bd3 isn't so good here, because of Bg4 when it's not easy to defend the pawn. }
10... O-O 11. O-O Na5
{ It's better to play this at once. If we try Nd2 now, Black can play c5! when d5 is nowhere near as effective when Black still has the dark-squared bishop.   Alternatively,  11...Bxc3  12.bxc3  Na5  13.Nd2  c5  transposes to other variations. }
12. c5 Bxc3 { Black has to take, otherwise the bishop will be in trouble. } 13.
bxc3 Nbc4 { Has been seen before, but it loses more or less on the spot after }
14. Bg5 Qd5 15. Nh4 Be4 16. Qc1
{ We will place our Queen on f4 followed by Rae1, when Black will either lose material, or be under a vicious attack. }
