[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 Nb6 5. f4
{ Here we go. We keep our center intact, aiming for a massive space advantage. A massive pro with this system is that Black does not have many decent options at his disposal, as we soon shall see. }
5... dxe5 6. fxe5
{ Before we move to the Main tabiya of the Four Pawn Attack, I just want to quickly highlight what happens if Black chooses to go for a set-up without Nc6, or delays e6. }
6... Nc6 7. Be3 Bf5 8. Nc3 e6 9. Nf3
{ We have arrived at the Main Position in the Four Pawns Attack. Black has a wide arsenal of options here, and all of them have been played 200+ times. }
9... Bb4
{ This is once again a possible move, and not a half-bad way to play. Black aims to capture on c3 in the future followed by Na5, getting excellent control of the light squares. }
10. Be2
{ The difference here is that Black has a knight on c6 that puts pressure on our pawn on d4. Therefore, Bd3 isn't so good here, because of Bg4 when it's not easy to defend the pawn. }
10... O-O
{ This is not the most accurate move order for reasons we will see soon. } 11.
O-O Na5
{ It's better to play this at once. If we try Nd2 now, Black can play c5! when d5 is nowhere near as effective when Black still has the dark-squared bishop. }
12. c5 Bxc3 { Black has to take, otherwise the bishop will be in trouble. } 13.
bxc3 Nd5 14. Bd2 Nc6
{ The knight returns, as c4 was a rather annoying threat. } 15. Rc1
{ 15.c4  Nde7  16.Bc3  was played by GM Fier, but I don't see why we should hurry. It's best to give room for the bishop on  h7  . }
15... h6 16. Qe1
{ This move is a typical plan, aiming to create an attack on the kingside. }
16... Kh8 17. Qg3
{ Our plan is simple. We will play Rf2-Rcf1-Nh4 with excellent pressure against f7. We may also put our bishop on b5 in order to prevent Black from breaking up our center with b6. }
17... Nde7 18. Nh4 Bh7 19. Rf2 { We have the idea of Rcf1 coming next. } 19...
Nf5 { Putting the knight in the way doesn't help Black. } 20. Nxf5 Bxf5 21.
Rcf1
{ Black has to be careful of a potential exchange sacrifice on f5. We may also go for g4 at some point, removing the bishop on f5. }
