[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4. Alekhine's Defense (1...Nf6) Mainlines"]
[Black "2...Nd5 (5...dxe5 6...Nc6 9...Bg4)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 Nb6 5. f4
{ Here we go. We keep our center intact, aiming for a massive space advantage. A massive pro with this system is that Black does not have many decent options at his disposal, as we soon shall see. }
5... dxe5 6. fxe5
{ Before we move to the Main tabiya of the Four Pawn Attack, I just want to quickly highlight what happens if Black chooses to go for a set-up without Nc6, or delays e6. }
6... Nc6 7. Be3 Bf5 8. Nc3 e6 9. Nf3
{ We have arrived at the Main Position in the Four Pawns Attack. Black has a wide arsenal of options here, and all of them have been played 200+ times. }
9... Bg4
{ This move has been the second most popular move in the position, with the idea of taking on f3 next. We will be forced to take with the g-pawn because our pawn on d4 will be hanging. }
10. Be2 { It's best to keep it simple. } 10... Qd7
{ Is a rather interesting continuation. The point being that Black wants to expand his pressure on b4 with Rd8. }
11. O-O Rd8 12. b3
{ I analyzed this position deeply, and things were much harder than I had expected. First of all, I wanted to go for  12.Ng5  , but the game gets rather complicated after  12...Nxc4!  Then, I decided to analyze  12.c5  , but I honestly feel that Black's light-square control is solidified in the position. See for instance the game Hoeppenstein, M - Mulde, R GER email 2009. }
12... Be7 { Developing the bishop is sensible. } 13. Qe1
{ This move is important. First of all we give the d1-square to our rook. Second of all we make Qg3 and Nh4 available to us. }
13... Bxf3 14. Bxf3 Nxd4
{ Black's every move has had this in mind, so he can't allow us to play Rd1. }
15. Bxb7 c6
{ This might be objectively best, but I still think we're doing very well after }
16. Rd1 Qxb7 17. Rxd4 Rxd4 18. Bxd4 c5 19. Be3 O-O 20. Qg3
{ We have a terrific pawn structure, and Black's pawn on c5 is weak. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4. Alekhine's Defense (1...Nf6) Mainlines"]
[Black "2...Nd5 (5...dxe5 6...Nc6 9...Bg4 2)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 Nb6 5. f4
{ Here we go. We keep our center intact, aiming for a massive space advantage. A massive pro with this system is that Black does not have many decent options at his disposal, as we soon shall see. }
5... dxe5 6. fxe5
{ Before we move to the Main tabiya of the Four Pawn Attack, I just want to quickly highlight what happens if Black chooses to go for a set-up without Nc6, or delays e6. }
6... Nc6 7. Be3 Bf5 8. Nc3 e6 9. Nf3
{ We have arrived at the Main Position in the Four Pawns Attack. Black has a wide arsenal of options here, and all of them have been played 200+ times. }
9... Bg4
{ This move has been the second most popular move in the position, with the idea of taking on f3 next. We will be forced to take with the g-pawn, due to our pawn on d4 will be hanging. }
10. Be2 { It's best to keep it simple. } 10... Qd7
{ Is a rather interesting continuation. The point being that Black wants to expand his pressure on b4 with Rd8. }
11. O-O Rd8 12. b3
{ I analyzed this position deeply, and things were much harder than I had expected. First of all, I wanted to go for  12.Ng5  , but the game gets rather complicated after  12...Nxc4!  Then, I decided to analyze  12.c5  , but I honestly feel that Black's light-square control is solidified in the position. See for instance the game Hoeppenstein, M - Mulde, R GER email 2009. }
12... Be7 { Developing the bishop is sensible. } 13. Qe1
{ This move is important. First of all we give the d1-square to our rook. Second of all we make Qg3 and Nh4 available to us. }
13... Bxf3 14. Bxf3 Nxd4
{ Black's every move has had this in mind, so he can't allow us to play Rd1. }
15. Bxb7 Bb4
{ 15...Nc2  loses after  16.Qf2  Bb4  17.Bc6  . I believe the text move to be the most critical, threatening to take on  c3  followed by a fork on  e2  . }
16. Kh1 { Defending against the threat. } 16... O-O 17. Be4
{ Making sure that we protect the fork, while also putting the bishop on a better square. }
17... Qe7 18. a3 { Is a fantastic move, giving us a winning edge. } 18... Bxc3
19. Qxc3 c5 20. Rad1
{ Black has to go for this line, but it's not very good. Our bishop pair is very strong here while Black is likely to lose the c5-pawn due to Bxd4. }
