[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 Nb6 5. f4
{ Here we go. We keep our center intact, aiming for a massive space advantage. A massive pro with this system is that Black does not have many decent options at his disposal, as we soon shall see. }
5... dxe5 6. fxe5
{ Before we move to the Main tabiya of the Four Pawn Attack, I just want to quickly highlight what happens if Black chooses to go for a set-up without Nc6, or delays e6. }
6... Nc6 7. Be3 Bf5 8. Nc3 e6 9. Nf3
{ We have arrived at the Main Position in the Four Pawns Attack. Black has a wide arsenal of options here, and all of them have been played 200+ times. }
9... Bg4
{ This move has been the second most popular move in the position, with the idea of taking on f3 next. We will be forced to take with the g-pawn, due to our pawn on d4 will be hanging. }
10. Be2 { It's best to keep it simple. } 10... Qd7
{ Is a rather interesting continuation. The point being that Black wants to expand his pressure on b4 with Rd8. }
11. O-O Rd8 12. b3
{ I analyzed this position deeply, and things were much harder than I had expected. First of all, I wanted to go for  12.Ng5  , but the game gets rather complicated after  12...Nxc4!  Then, I decided to analyze  12.c5  , but I honestly feel that Black's light-square control is solidified the position. See for instance the game Hoeppenstein, M - Mulde, R GER email 2009. }
12... Bb4 { It's best to develop the bishop to b4, harassing the knight. } 13.
Ne4 O-O { Black should get the king to safety before taking the pawn on d4. }
14. Kh1 { Placing the king on h1 is clever, preventing any annoying checks. }
14... Bxf3 15. Rxf3 Nxd4 { Black has to go for it. } 16. Rh3
{ Bd3 might follow if Black is not careful, with a decisive attack. } 16... Nf5
17. Qc2 { We should obviously not trade queens. } 17... h6
{ The bishop on e3 can't be taken due to Nf6+, followed by a mate on h7. } 18.
Bg1 { We don't want to allow Black to take our bishop. } 18... Be7
{ Black goes for f6 to get rid of some of our initiative. } 19. Rf1 f6 20. exf6
Bxf6 21. Nc5 { We have found a new target, the pawn on b7. } 21... Qc6 22. Bf3
Nd4 { Is pretty much the last trick in the position. } 23. Bxc6
{ 23.Bxd4??  would give up all our advantage after  23...Bxd4!  when our bishop on  f3  can't move due to the hanging rook on  f1  . }
23... Nxc2 24. Bf3
{ With a winning endgame. Black is losing one pawn, while we also have a fantastic pawn structure along with the bishop pair. }
