{ Before we move to the Main tabiya of the Four Pawn Attack, I just want to quickly highlight what happens if Black chooses to go for a set-up without Nc6, or delays e6. }
6... Nc6 7. Be3 Bf5 8. Nc3 e6 9. Nf3
{ We have arrived at the Main Position in the Four Pawns Attack. Black has a wide arsenal of options here, and all of them have been played 200+ times. }
9... Bg4
{ This move has been the second most popular move in the position, with the idea of taking on f3 next. We will be forced to take with the g-pawn, due to our pawn on d4 will be hanging. }
10. Be2 { It's best to keep it simple. } 10... Bxf3
{ This is why Black played Bg4, so it is not surprising that it is the most popular continuation. }
11. gxf3 Qh4+
{ Has been seen in over 250 games, when we have a pleasant choice between an attack or a better endgame. Alternatives exist, but they are not impressive.  11...Be7  can simply be met by  O-O  , when our pawn on  f3  is an addition to our position as  f4  is possible, strengthening our center.  11...Qd7  can be met by  Qd2  , when we will castle long.  11...Bb4  is an attempt to play similar to the  9. Bb4-lines, but again I think our f-pawn just helps our center. Remember that the light-squared bishop is absent, making our bishop pair rather strong. We may also put our king onh1  when we can utilize the f-file for attacking purposes. }
12. Bf2 Qf4 13. c5 Nd7
{ Moving the knight to d7 has been the most popular way to play. } 14. O-O
{ Once again we are not afraid of white's attack. I initially wanted to walk down the safe path with the move  14.Qc1  , achieving a very pleasant endgame. However,  O-O  is so much stronger that I had to recommend it. }
14... O-O-O { Going for queenside castling is the most direct approach. } 15.
Qa4 { Ndxe5 was a threat, so moving the queen is necessary. } 15... f6
{ Black doesn't have much time, so going for counterplay is essential. } 16.
Bb5 Ndb8 { The only way to defend the fort. } 17. Bc4
{ Attacking the Achilles heel in Black's position, the pawn on e6. } 17... Qf5
{ Is a way to defend the pawn. } 18. Ne4 { We want to play Ng3 next, so } 18...
fxe5 { is more or less forced. } 19. b4
{ b5 is now in the air, while it's important that the pawn on c5 is defended in several lines. Next we may follow up with Ng3-Qb3, when the pawn on e6 will fall. }
19... Nxd4
{ 19...exd4  20.Rae1  e5  21.b5  Ne7  22.Qxa7  White is breaking through with Rb1 followed by c6. }
20. Bxd4 exd4 21. Rae1
{ Black will either lose the pawn on e6 or the pawn on a7. } *

