[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4. Alekhine's Defense (1...Nf6) Mainlines"]
[Black "2...Nd5 (5...dxe5 6...Nc6 9...Nb4 1)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 Nb6 5. f4
{ Here we go. We keep our center intact, aiming for a massive space advantage. A massive pro with this system is that Black does not have many decent options at his disposal, as we soon shall see. }
5... dxe5 6. fxe5
{ Before we move to the Main tabiya of the Four Pawn Attack, I just want to quickly highlight what happens if Black chooses to go for a set-up without Nc6, or delays e6. }
6... Nc6 7. Be3 Bf5 8. Nc3 e6 9. Nf3
{ We have arrived at the Main Position in the Four Pawns Attack. Black has a wide arsenal of options here, and all of them have been played 200+ times. }
9... Nb4
{ This is the least popular move of the bunch. However, it has been played over 200 times and it is rather tricky. Black is threatening to play Nc2+, forcing our rook to c1. He will soon play c5, gaining the desired counterplay against our center. }
10. Rc1 c5
{ This is almost always played. Otherwise we can simply remove the knight by playing a3. }
11. Qb3
{ This is a fantastic novelty which wins by force. Even the engines fail to spot the win until they've been thinking for a while, due to a forced sequence with 'only-moves' from the white side. The point of Qb3 is that we are threatening to play dxc5, forcing Black to play cxd4 when our knights may soon jump to b5 and d6. }
11... cxd4 12. Nxd4 Bd3
{ This is a tricky move when our path to victory is extremely narrow. I certainly think that this is the human move, making Nxf5 impossible while aiming to capture our bishop on f1. }
13. Rd1
{ Taking the d-file is the only way to achieve a winning position, in particular due to our discoveries against the black queen. }
13... Bxf1 14. Rxf1 Qc7 { Aiming for the e5 pawn. } 15. Ndb5
{ This is the simplest way to continue if you ask me, due to a forcing continuation. a3 followed by Ke2 was apparently best, but it seems to me that Black gets practical chances there. }
15... Qxe5 16. Ne4
{ This wonderful move is the point. We are aiming to play Nd6, when f7 will fall. Keep in mind that the knight can't be taken due to Nc7+ followed by Qxb4. }
16... Rd8 { The only way to stop Nd6. } 17. Rxd8+ Kxd8 18. Ng5
{ f7 is massively under attack, forcing Black to trade queens after } 18...
Nc2+ 19. Ke2 { The only safe spot for the white king. } 19... Qxe3+ 20. Qxe3
Nxe3 21. Nxf7+ Ke8 22. Kxe3 Rg8 23. b3
{ I can't see how Black will survive the ending. We are threatening to play Nd6 and win the pawn on b7, while Black's pieces are also incredibly passive. The engine gives an edge of close to 3 pawns here which is not surprising due to the superiority of our pieces. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4. Alekhine's Defense (1...Nf6) Mainlines"]
[Black "2...Nd5 (5...dxe5 6...Nc6 9...Nb4 2)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 Nb6 5. f4
{ Here we go. We keep our center intact, aiming for a massive space advantage. A massive pro with this system is that Black does not have many decent options at his disposal, as we soon shall see. }
5... dxe5 6. fxe5
{ Before we move to the Main tabiya of the Four Pawn Attack, I just want to quickly highlight what happens if Black chooses to go for a set-up without Nc6, or delays e6. }
6... Nc6 7. Be3 Bf5 8. Nc3 e6 9. Nf3
{ We have arrived at the Main Position in the Four Pawns Attack. Black has a wide arsenal of options here, and all of them have been played 200+ times. }
9... Nb4
{ This is the least popular move of the bunch. However, it has been played over 200 times and it is rather tricky. Black is threatening to play Nc2+, forcing our rook to c1. He will soon play c5, gaining the desired counterplay against our center. }
10. Rc1 c5
{ This is almost always played. Otherwise we can simply remove the knight by playing a3. }
11. Qb3
{ This is a fantastic novelty which wins by force. Even the engines fail to spot the win until they've been thinking for a while, due to a forced sequence with 'only-moves' from the white side. The point of Qb3 is that we are threatening to play dxc5, forcing Black to play cxd4 when our knights may soon jump to b5 and d6. }
11... cxd4 12. Nxd4 Nd3+
{ This is the other sensible continuation, but it fails after a long tactical sequence. }
13. Bxd3 Bxd3 14. Ncb5
{ Attacking the bishop. If the bishop moves, we'll simply castle with a domination position, so Black is forced to play }
14... a6 15. Rd1
{ Taking the bishop immediately would give Black decent counterplay after axb5, where we have a very tiny edge. }
15... Bxc4 { The critical move. } 16. Nxe6
{ This fantastic blow is the reason why our line works. } 16... axb5
{ This is forced. Taking the queen would leave to a picturesque mate after Nbc7 followed by Bc5. Black sacrifices the queen in this line, when we need to play accurately to neutralize the ensuing counterplay. }
17. Rxd8+ Rxd8 18. Nc7+ Kd7 19. Qc3
{ This is the only move that wins because it is important that we can win the knight on b6 if Black takes on c7. This is now possible due to Qa5. }
19... Na4 20. Qa5 { Protecting the knight. } 20... Nxb2 21. Kf2
{ I like this move, hiding on g3 when it will be difficult for Black to check our king. }
21... Nd3+ 22. Kg3 Bb4 23. Qb6
{ Qxb7 or Nxb5 will follow, giving us a winning position.  CONCLUSION: The Alekhine Defense can be tricky to meet, due to the fact that Black has a lot of different set-ups and the positions tend to become quite dynamic. The huge appeal of the Four Pawns Attack is the fact that avoiding the main lines will cause major harm to the black position as we saw in the previous chapter. In this chapter we took a look at the main tabiya of the Four Pawns Attack, when Black has five different options.   9... Nb4 loses by force if we know what we're doing in the arising complications after 10. Qb3!   9... Bb4 is an interesting move, aiming to gain decent control of the light squares. Unfortunately for Black, giving us the bishop pair isn't such a great idea, and it seems to me that we simply get a very comfortable position.   9... Qd7 followed by O-O-O is a dynamic continuation, but our attack is far too powerful for Black. A very instructive game here was Kotronias-Short, when the Greek GM played more or less flawlessly.   9... Bg4 is the most popular alternative with the simple idea of taking on f3. After the further 10. Be2, Black has an important choice. I believe I have clearly shown that our attack is very powerful after the moves 10... Bxf3 11. gxf3, so Black should probably opt for 10... Qd7.11. O-O Rd8 will likely follow, when the move 12. b3 is a key move, removing the possible counterplay on the light squares. Taking on f3 and on d4 doesn't really work in any line, which we saw.   The main move is 9... Be7, and the most logical approach. Theory has established that 10. d5 results in a draw, but 10. Be2 is strong. Black will castle and play f6, attacking our center. The clear drawback is that the pawn on e6 becomes weak, along with the square on e5. Remembering everything in this line can be rather confusing, so I highly suggest that you simply keep the ideas in mind. We almost always go for a set-up that consists of Qd2-Rad1-h3-Kh1-b3-Bg1-Rfe1. In the resulting positions, Black ends up getting very passive due to our excellent central control. Having to make tons of waiting moves might be objectively the best way to play. Although the engines have no problems with this, I think the task is incredibly tough for a human. The Four Pawns Attack remains a highly critical way to battle this opening, and the more I analyze it, the more I am convinced that it is superior to the Classical mainline. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. Scandinavian (1...d5) Minor Sidelines"]
[Black "2...c6 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5
{ This move marks the Scandinavian Defense, one of the oldest openings in the history of chess! The opening was played in the game Francesc de Castellvi - Narcis Vinyoles, Valencia 1475!. It has been tried by tons of Grandmasters throughout the years, most notably the World Champion Magnus Carlsen who thoroughly enjoys going for this system in short time controls, sticking to his Norwegian roots. The opening has always been considered fairly dubious, but it has stood the test of time. The huge advantage with rare defenses is that the opening theory moves at a relatively slow pace. One could say that there's a couple of new discoveries every year in the Scandinavian Defense. Najdorf, on the other hand, probably has a novelty every week! }
2. exd5
{ This is obviously the critical way to go. Black has two major moves here, Nf6 and Qxd5 , but I will first handle a gambit known as the Blackburne-Kloosterboer Gambit, c6 . }
2... c6
{ Black wants to gain a lead in development by sacrificing a pawn, but objectively it is quite unsound. It should be mentioned that it's not so easy to find the refutation on the board, though. }
3. dxc6
{ We'll take Black's offer.   3.d4  is a hilarious transposition to the Caro-Kann if you're interested in that sort of thing. }
3... e5
{ My good friend GM David Lariño has played this against me in a couple of blitz games, but the sacrifice is too much. }
4. cxb7 Bxb7 5. Bb5+ { Developing the bishop with check. } 5... Nd7 6. Nf3 Bd6
7. d4
{ Black does not have sufficient compensation for the two pawns. I suppose I can also mention that I won both blitz games against GM Lariño if you don't believe me... }
*

