[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. Scandinavian (1...d5) Minor Sidelines"]
[Black "2...c6 2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5 2. exd5
{ This is obviously the critical way to go. Black has two major moves here, Nf6 and Qxd5 , but I will first handle a gambit known as the Blackburne-Kloosterboer Gambit, c6. }
2... c6
{ Black wants to gain a lead in development by sacrificing a pawn, but objectively it is quite unsound. It should be mentioned that it's not so easy to find the refutation on the board, though. }
3. dxc6
{ We'll take Black's offer.   3.d4  is a hilarious transposition to the Caro-Kann if you're interested in that sort of thing. }
3... Nxc6
{ 3...e5  My good friend GM David Lariño has played this against me in a couple of blitz games, but the sacrifice is too much.  4.cxb7  Bxb7  5.Bb5+  Developing the bishop with check.  5...Nd7  6.Nf3  Bd6  7.d4  Black does not have sufficient compensation for the two pawns. I suppose I can also mention that I won both blitz games against GM Lariño if you don't believe me... }
4. Nf3 { Natural developing moves is the way to go. } 4... e5
{ Taking control of the center with e5 is the only way to prove some compensation. Black may now kick away our knight with e4, which can be rather annoying. }
5. Nc3 { Moving the knight to c3, controlling the e4-square. } 5... Nf6 6. Bb5
{ It's very natural to develop the bishop while threatening to take the pawn on e5. }
6... Bd6 7. d4
{ Playing actively. Remember, we are a pawn up, so trading off pieces will be very beneficial to us. }
7... e4 { Has been played twice, and the only critical move if you ask me. } 8.
Ne5
{ This is the way to go, adding some pressure against c6. Next we will play Bg5, pinning the knight on f6. }
8... O-O
{ Playing in the fashion of the gambit, not caring about the pawn on c6.8...   8...Qc7  is natural, but no fun for Black after  9.Bg5!  Bxe5  10.dxe5  Qxe5  11.Qd2  O-O  12.Bxc6  bxc6  13.O-O-O  . Black has won back the pawn, at the cost of an awful pawn structure. The pawn on e4 won't last for long either, as Bxf6 will come next. }
9. Bxc6 bxc6 10. Bg5 { We should keep playing active moves. } 10... h6
{ Is always a sort of 'automatic reaction' when one meets Bg5. } 11. Bxf6 gxf6
{ Taking with the queen would be met by Nxe4. } 12. Nc4 Bc7 13. d5
{ Further trading pieces. } 13... cxd5 14. Nxd5 Be6 15. Nce3
{ We have a pawn up and Black has a terrible pawn structure. The bishop pair makes up for the pawn structure, but not for the missing pawn. }
