[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. Scandinavian (1...d5) Minor Sidelines"]
[Black "2...c6 4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5 2. exd5
{ This is obviously the critical way to go. Black has two major moves here, Nf6 and Qxd5 , but I will first handle a gambit known as the Blackburne-Kloosterboer Gambit, c6. }
2... c6
{ Black wants to gain a lead in development by sacrificing a pawn, but objectively it is quite unsound. It should be mentioned that it's not so easy to find the refutation on the board, though. }
3. dxc6
{ We'll take Black's offer.   3.d4  is a hilarious transposition to the Caro-Kann if you're interested in that sort of thing. }
3... Nxc6
{ 3...e5  My good friend GM David Lariño has played this against me in a couple of blitz games, but the sacrifice is too much.  4.cxb7  Bxb7  5.Bb5+  Developing the bishop with check.  5...Nd7  6.Nf3  Bd6  7.d4  Black does not have sufficient compensation for the two pawns. I suppose I can also mention that I won both blitz games against GM Lariño if you don't believe me... }
4. Nf3 { Natural developing moves is the way to go. } 4... e5
{ Taking control of the center with e5 is the only way to prove some compensation. Black may now kick away our knight with e4, which can be rather annoying. }
5. Nc3 { Moving the knight to c3, controlling the e4-square. } 5... Nf6 6. Bb5
{ It's very natural to develop the bishop while threatening to take the pawn on e5. }
6... Bd6 7. d4
{ Playing actively. Remember, we are a pawn up, so trading off pieces will be very beneficial to us. }
7... e4 { Has been played twice, and the only critical move if you ask me. } 8.
Ne5
{ This is the way to go, adding some pressure against c6. Next we will play Bg5, pinning the knight on f6. }
8... O-O
{ Playing in the fashion of the gambit, not caring about the pawn on c6.8...   8...Qc7  is natural, but no fun for Black after  9.Bg5!  Bxe5  10.dxe5  Qxe5  11.Qd2  O-O  12.Bxc6  bxc6  13.O-O-O  . Black has won back the pawn, at the cost of an awful pawn structure. The pawn on e4 won't last for long either, as Bxf6 will come next. }
9. Bxc6 bxc6 10. Bg5 { We should keep playing active moves. } 10... Re8
{ Aiming to win back the pawn, or play c5. } 11. Qd2 Bxe5
{ Grabbing the pawn leads to an inferior endgame. } 12. dxe5 Qxd2+ 13. Bxd2
Rxe5 14. Bf4
{ The endgame includes opposite colored-bishops, increasing the drawing chances. Unfortunately for Black, we are more active and have a much better pawn structure in the sense that we have enormous potential of creating a passed pawn on the queenside. }
14... Rh5
{ Keeping the rook on the fifth rank is another way to play, making Nd5 possible.   14...Re8  Retreating with the rook certainly makes sense.  15.O-O-O  Taking the d-file, when Rd6 may come next, attacking c6.  15...Be6  16.Rd6  Nd5  Is a natural way to defend, but it doesn't help too much.  17.Bd2  Nxc3  18.Bxc3  Bd5  19.Bd2  We have a clear path forward. We'll play b3, followed by c4, removing the bishop on d5. If Black tries to trade the rooks with Rd8, we will take and play Rd1.  19...e3  Is a logical try with the idea of maintaining control of the diagonal.  20.Bxe3  Bxg2  21.Rg1  Be4  22.b3  a6  23.a4  Our pieces are more active while our pawn structure is much better, controlling a decent amount of light squares. Black should probably try to trade rooks, but that will give us the d-file with Rgd1. }
15. O-O-O Nd5 { Blocking our rook. } 16. Rd4 Bb7 17. Nxd5
{ This may look strange, but we will have fantastic control of the dark squares. Another factor is that Black's bishop is hitting its own pawns, making it rather passive. }
17... cxd5 18. Rb4 Bc6 19. Be3
{ White is close to winning. Our rook on b4 is a nuisance for Black, while the black rooks do not contribute much.   CONCLUSION: Our first dive into the Scandinavian waters is the unsound Blackburne Gambit, 2. c6. However, it is not the worst gambit in the world. It may even be rather unpleasant to play against if we do not know where to place our pieces. However, I believe our set-up with Nf3-Nc3-Bb5-d4 to be rather simple to understand since our idea is to trade pieces with active play. Black should more or less meet this with 7... e4, otherwise we get rather simple play, remaining a pawn up for little compensation. Going further down the line, Black has the choice of heading into a position with a pawn down with a weak pawn structure, when the bishop pair keeps the position alive. The other way to play is the opposite-colored bishops ending which looks close to losing both objectively and practically. A nice summary is that this move may be fun to play in blitz, but I don't think the player with the white pieces will have any trouble figuring it out over a classical game. Angering your opponent with the move 3. d4 is possible if you want to gain some psychological points. }
