[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. Scandinavian (1...d5) Minor Sidelines"]
[Black "3...Qe5+ 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3
{ This is the most natural way to fight for an advantage against the Scandinavian, gaining a tempo on the queen. From here Black has a lot of squares to choose from, but three of them remain a lot more popular than the rest. That comes later though, because first we need to deal with the two checks. }
3... Qe5+ 4. Be2 c6
{ Black's going into hiding on c7.  Alternatively,   4...Bg4  is met by  5.d4  Bxe2  6.Ngxe2  Black has no minor pieces developed, while we have two knights. We could investigate deeper of course, but I don't think we need to spend more time on this line. }
5. Nf3 Qc7 6. d4 Bf5
{ This has been the most played move. The alternative,   6...Nf6  is likely to transpose after  7.O-O  Bf5  e6 has been played here too, but this closes the door on developing the bishop on c8 . }
7. O-O Nf6
{ We can meet this set-up with the typical idea . e6 has been played here too, but this closes the door on developing the bishop on c8 . }
8. Ne5
{ Not only will the bishop on f5 be in danger after e6, we can also gain another tempo on the queen with Bf4. }
8... Nbd7
{ 8...e6  9.g4!  Bg6  10.f4  Black doesn't have a good way to defend against our threat of trapping the bishop with f5.  10...Bd6  Moving the h-pawn would lead to the destruction of the kingside pawns after Nxg6, so Black should try to gain some counterplay instead.  11.f5  exf5  12.gxf5  Nbd7  Black will win the pawn on e5, but it won't be enough to compensate for the piece.  13.fxg6  hxg6  14.Bf4  Nxe5  15.dxe5  Bxe5  16.Qd2  Black's missing piece will decide the game. }
9. Bf4 { The other advantage of putting the knight on e5. } 9... Qd8
{ The engine's suggestion when I like } 10. g4 Be6
{ 10...Bg6  11.h4  would be too passive. } 11. g5
{ It's really hard for Black to untangle. } 11... Nxe5 12. Bxe5 Nd7 13. Bg3
{ Black now needs to worry about the typical pawn break d5, opening up the position. }
13... Bf5 14. Bg4 Bxg4 15. Qxg4
{ We are very active, but Black does finally get his pieces out after } 15...
e6 { Here I like reinforcing our space advantage with } 16. Ne4 Be7 17. c4 O-O
18. Rad1 { Black is extremely passive, giving us a clearly better position. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. Scandinavian (1...d5) Minor Sidelines"]
[Black "3...Qe5+ 2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3
{ This is the most natural way to fight for an advantage against the Scandinavian, gaining a tempo on the queen. From here Black has a lot of squares to choose from, but three of them remain a lot more popular than the rest. That comes later though, because first we need to deal with the two checks. }
3... Qe5+ 4. Be2 c6
{ Black's going into hiding on c7.  Alternatively,   4...Bg4  is met by  5.d4  Bxe2  6.Ngxe2  Black has no minor pieces developed, while we have two knights. We could investigate deeper of course, but I don't think we need to spend more time on this line. }
5. Nf3 Qc7 6. d4 Bf5
{ This has been the most played move. The alternative,   6...Nf6  is likely to transpose after  7.O-O  Bf5  e6 has been played here too, but this closes the door on developing the bishop on c8 . }
7. O-O e6
{ I'll name this the Krsnik Cohar-variation, since the Fide Master has played this position in a lot of blitz games with Black. If Black is allowed to get his pieces out on the board in quick fashion, his position will be extremely solid as there are no weaknesses in the position. }
8. d5
{ Much to my dismay, I realized that this move is by far the best move in the position. I wanted to give   8.Nh4  , grabbing the bishop pair. However, Black is still incredibly solid. The text move is a very engine-type of move, aiming to get an insane amount of counterplay after Black takes the pawn. What I disliked here was that we are forced to look at this variation in such a great depth, a variation that you see once in a blue moon. The good thing though, is that Black needs to play extremely accurately in order to have a chance of surviving, something that is very unlikely. }
8... cxd5 { Has been played twice, but it loses. } 9. Nb5
{ Black will have to worry about Nc7+ ideas soon. } 9... Qb6 10. Bf4 Na6 11. c4
{ Opening up the position even more. } 11... Nf6 12. cxd5 Nxd5 13. Qa4
{ Black's king is about to be left in grave danger after Nbd4+ or Nd6+ next, grabbing the bishop on f5.  After for example Bc5 , we should take the bishop on f5 , rather than the rook on a8 . Nc5 is met by   13.Nd6+  followed by capturing the Bishop. }
