{ I'll name this the Krsnik Cohar-variation, since the Fide Master has played this position in a lot of blitz games with Black. If Black is allowed to get his pieces out on the board in quick fashion, his position will be extremely solid as there are no weaknesses in the position. }
8. d5
{ Much to my dismay, I realized that this move is by far the best move in the position. I wanted to give   8.Nh4  , grabbing the bishop pair. However, Black is still incredibly solid. The text move is a very engine-type of move, aiming to get an insane amount of counterplay after Black takes the pawn. What I disliked here was that we are forced to look at this variation in such a great depth, a variation that you see once in a blue moon. The good thing though, is that Black needs to play extremely accurately in order to have a chance of surviving, something that is very unlikely. }
8... exd5 { Taking the pawn with the e-pawn is necessary. } 9. Nd4
{ Grabbing a tempo on the bishop. The knight on d4 is also incredibly strong as it can go to either f5 or b5 in the future. Yes indeed, we do sacrifice our knight in several lines so we can open up Black's camp. }
9... Bg6 { Black's best defense. } 10. h4 { Playing against the bishop on g6. }
10... Nd7
{ Black doesn't mind sacrificing the bishop on g6.  Preventing   10...h5  is of course logical, when I suggest getting rid of the light-squared bishops in order to take control of the important f5-square. We can achieve this with  11.Bd3  . }
11. Ndb5
{ This thematic sacrifice is once again on the table.   11.h5  would give Black the annoying counterplay after  11...Be4  12.f3  Bg6  13.hxg6  hxg6  14.f4  Ngf6  , when I think the resulting position is rather unclear. After the text move, Black needs to proceed with care. }
11... cxb5 12. Nxd5 Qa5 { Black is hoping to survive by playing O-O-O next. }
13. Bxb5 O-O-O 14. Qe2 { Bd2 is now a threat, trapping the queen. } 14... a6
15. a4 axb5 16. axb5 { The complications works out for us. } 16... Qxa1 17.
Qc4+ Bc5 18. Nb6+
{ Black is forced to play Kc7, when Bf4+ will win the queen on a1. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. Scandinavian (1...d5) Minor Sidelines"]
[Black "3...Qe5+ 8"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3
{ This is the most natural way to fight for an advantage against the Scandinavian, gaining a tempo on the queen. From here Black has a lot of squares to choose from, but three of them remain a lot more popular than the rest. That comes later though, because first we need to deal with the two checks. }
3... Qe5+ 4. Be2 c6
{ Black's going into hiding on c7.  Alternatively,   4...Bg4  is met by  5.d4  Bxe2  6.Ngxe2  Black has no minor pieces developed, while we have two knights. We could investigate deeper of course, but I don't think we need to spend more time on this line. }
5. Nf3 Qc7 6. d4 Bf5
{ This has been the most played move. The alternative,   6...Nf6  is likely to transpose after  7.O-O  Bf5  e6 has been played here too, but this closes the door on developing the bishop on c8 . }
7. O-O e6
{ I'll name this the Krsnik Cohar-variation, since the Fide Master has played this position in a lot of blitz games with Black. If Black is allowed to get his pieces out on the board in quick fashion, his position will be extremely solid as there are no weaknesses in the position. }
8. d5
{ Much to my dismay, I realized that this move is by far the best move in the position. I wanted to give   8.Nh4  , grabbing the bishop pair. However, Black is still incredibly solid. The text move is a very engine-type of move, aiming to get an insane amount of counterplay after Black takes the pawn. What I disliked here was that we are forced to look at this variation in such a great depth, a variation that you see once in a blue moon. The good thing though, is that Black needs to play extremely accurately in order to have a chance of surviving, something that is very unlikely. }
8... exd5 { Taking the pawn with the e-pawn is necessary. } 9. Nd4
{ Grabbing a tempo on the bishop. The knight on d4 is also incredibly strong as it can go to either f5 or b5 in the future. Yes indeed, we do sacrifice our knight in several lines so we can open up Black's camp. }
9... Bg6 { Black's best defense. } 10. h4 { Playing against the bishop on g6. }
10... Nd7
{ Black doesn't mind sacrificing the bishop on g6.  Preventing   10...h5  is of course logical, when I suggest getting rid of the light-squared bishops in order to take control of the important f5-square. We can achieve this with  11.Bd3  . }
11. Ndb5
{ This thematic sacrifice is once again on the table.   11.h5  would give Black the annoying counterplay after  11...Be4  12.f3  Bg6  13.hxg6  hxg6  14.f4  Ngf6  , when I think the resulting position is rather unclear. After the text move, Black needs to proceed with care. }
11... Qb8 { Black needs to control the b8-h2 diagonal, avoiding Bf4. } 12. Re1
Be7 13. g3 { Opening up the possibility of playing Bf4 again. } 13... f6
{ A great multi-purpose move. Black gets an escape route for the bishop on g6, while the pawn on f6 also makes Ne5 possible after Bf4.   13...Ne5!?  Black wants to block the diagonal with f6 next.  14.h5  Bf5  15.Bf4  f6  Black's plan is extremely close to working, but it doesn't due to  16.Nxd5!  Opening up Black's camp.  16...cxd5  17.Qxd5  Bc4 is now a deadly threat.  17...g5  18.Bxe5  Qxe5  19.Qxb7  Be4  Black keeps resisting, but it isn't enough.  20.Nd6+  Bxd6  21.Bb5+  Kf8  22.Rxe4  From here, Black is forced to give his queen for a rook and two minor pieces. This would normally be more than enough, but Black doesn't have good enough coordination.  22...Rb8  23.Qd7  Qxb5  24.Re8+  Rxe8  25.Qxb5  Nh6  26.Rd1  Black won't be able to handle our strong passed pawns along with his weak king.   13...Kf8  , removing the king from the e-file, can be met by  14.Bf4  . After  14...Qd8  ,  15.h5  is excellent for us, as Black can't play  15...Bf5  due to  16.Nd4  . Therefore, cxb5 must come when we'll take on g6 and then d5 . }
14. Nd4
{ Black has created a new weakness in his camp, the square on e6, so it's time to make use of it. }
14... Bf7 15. Bg4 Ne5 16. Bh3
{ This is a really difficult position to defend for Black in practice. Our ideas are rather simple. We can improve our position with simple moves like Kg2-b3-Bb2. Pushing the knight away by the means of f4 is also on the table, even pushing the pawn to f5 in the future. Nce2-Nf4 is another idea, doubling down on the weak e6-square. }
16... h5
{ This move is strong, giving Black the option of meeting f4 with Ng4!   16...Kf8  is less impressive due to  17.f4  , getting rid of the strong e5-stallion. }
17. Kg2 Kf8
{ Black should step out of all the potential discoveries in the e-file. } 18.
Nce2 Nh6
{ Black has finally developed his pieces, but I do believe the knight should be placed on e7 instead. Alternatively,   18...Bd6  19.Ne6+  Forcing Black to give up the control of the light squares in his camp.  19...Bxe6  20.Bxe6  Ne7  21.b3  We have fantastic counterplay for the pawn. I can't imagine that a human will survive a practical game here with the black pieces, as there is no viable path forward. }
19. Bxh6 Rxh6 20. Nf5 { Is quite annoying due to } 20... Rh8 21. Ned4
{ White will play f4 next, followed by Ne6, when we'll have fantastic play in the e-file.   CONCLUSION: We started our coverage on 2... Qxd5 with looking at two rare checks. 3... Qe6+ is the worst option here, as Black can't afford to waste so many tempos with the queen. We saw how quickly our lead in development becomes a decisive factor for Black in this line, a highly instructive way of showing how important piece development is in chess.   3... Qe5+ is much better, wanting to put the queen on c7. If we don't act fast, Black will get all his pieces out, giving him an extremely solid position as there are no major weaknesses to exploit. In the Main Line we saw how we can exploit the bishop on f5 with Ne5, followed by g4, and potentially f4 or h4. Bf4 may also come, forcing Black to move the queen once more.   The Croatian FM Krsnik Cohar knows his stuff in this system, which is why he has gone for 7... e6, a rather clever move. The point is that if we would play 8. Ne5, Black can play Nd7. Now Bf4 no longer works for us, as Black has time to play Bd6. 8. Nh4 is definitely an option, grabbing the bishop pair. I wasn't so satisfied though, as Black's position is extremely solid.   Having these things in mind, one can certainly see the appeal of playing 3... Qe5+. The refutation of Black's concept is 8. d5!, a fantastic move that I doubt a human would find over the board, reinforcing the argument of this opening choice. After our fantastic move, Black has to be careful of not capturing with the wrong pawn, since 8... cxd5 is already completely losing. The one and only FM Krsnik Cohar is well aware of the refutation, as he had a wonderful game where he played with the white pieces. After 8... exd5 9. Nd4, Black needs to make a choice of where to place the bishop. One important idea in these lines is the sacrifice of playing Ndb5 followed by Bf4.   In practice, a human will certainly step on one of the many landmines places on the board. In case Black figures everything out, he is still stuck with a rather miserable position as we saw at the end of the Main Line. I certainly could have expanded on my analysis here, but I don't think we need to look at the variation so extensively as you will face it once in a blue moon. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. Scandinavian (1...d5) Minor Sidelines"]
[Black "3...Qe6+ 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3
{ This is the most natural way to fight for an advantage against the Scandinavian, gaining a tempo on the queen. From here Black has a lot of squares to choose from, but three of them remain a lot more popular than the rest. That comes later though, because first we need to deal with the two checks. }
3... Qe6+
{ This check has a fancy idea in mind, making it a typical 'blitz' approach. World Champion Magnus Carlsen has even played it, meaning that we should take it seriously. }
4. Be2 Qg6
{ Black's concept is this, attacking our vulnerable pawn on g2. Other moves have been played of course, but they make very little sense as the queen stands in the way on e6. }
5. Nf3
{ Sacrificing the pawn for a massive lead in development.   5.Bf3  is certainly logical, but I think Black is not doing badly after  5...e5  . }
5... Qxg2 { The critical response is grabbing the pawn. } 6. Rg1 Qh3 7. d4
{ Four pieces are already out on the board, while Black has NONE. Stopping here is certainly possible, but I would like to showcase how White elaborates on the development advantage. }
7... Nf6 8. Rg3 { The queen is forced to make yet another move. } 8... Qe6
{ Has been seen a few times, when I like  Getting the queen as far away from the action as possible makes a lot of sense to me.   8...Qf5  has never been seen before, when we can continue with  9.Ne5  . The queen is really exposed on f5 and is likely to move soon in the future. Soon we will play moves like Be3-Qd2-O-O-O, with a fantastic development advantage. }
9. Ne5 { Bc4 is now a threat, so Black has to move the queen once again. } 9...
Qb6 10. Nc4 Qe6 11. d5 { The queen is not having a good time... } 11... Qf5 12.
Bg5
{ White's massive lead in development was decisive in Houpt,W - Walker,J ICCF email 2016. }
*

