1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3
{ This is the most natural way to fight for an advantage against the Scandinavian, gaining a tempo on the queen. From here Black has a lot of squares to choose from, but three of them remain a lot more popular than the rest. That comes later though, because first we need to deal with the two checks. }
3... Qe6+
{ This check has a fancy idea in mind, making it a typical 'blitz' approach. World Champion Magnus Carlsen has even played it, meaning that we should take it seriously. }
4. Be2 Qg6
{ Black's concept is this, attacking our vulnerable pawn on g2. Other moves have been played of course, but they make very little sense as the queen stands in the way on e6. }
5. Nf3
{ Sacrificing the pawn for a massive lead in development.   5.Bf3  is certainly logical, but I think Black is not doing badly after  5...e5  . }
5... Qxg2 { The critical response is grabbing the pawn. } 6. Rg1 Qh3 7. d4
{ Four pieces are already out on the board, while Black has NONE. Stopping here is certainly possible, but I would like to showcase how White elaborates on the development advantage. }
7... Nf6 8. Rg3 { The queen is forced to make yet another move. } 8... Qd7
{ Getting the queen as far away from the action as possible makes a lot of sense to me.   8...Qf5  has never been seen before, when we can continue with  9.Ne5  . The queen is really exposed on f5 and is likely to move soon in the future. Soon we will play moves like Be3-Qd2-O-O-O, with a fantastic development advantage. }
9. Ne5 { We shouldn't miss an extra tempo on the queen if we have the chance. }
9... Qd8 10. Bc4 e6 11. Bg5 { Logical developing moves. } 11... h6
{ The human move which has been played in the two games played in this position.   11...Be7  might be objectively better, but we should simply proceed with our development. For example:  12.Qe2  c6  13.O-O-O  . }
12. Bxf6 gxf6 13. Nxf7 { This blow is fantastic. } 13... Kxf7 14. Qh5+
{ Black's king will be placed in the center, when we will have all our pieces on the board already. }
14... Ke7 15. O-O-O { I think this is the simplest way to continue. } 15... Qe8
{ After this move, we will material after a very beautiful sequence.   15...Qd6  16.d5  Qe5  The best defensive try.  17.Qh4  h5  An important defensive move, aiming to meet f4 with Bh6.  18.dxe6  Bh6+  19.Kb1  Black's king is incredibly vulnerable to ideas like Nd5+.  19...Bg5  Is the best defensive move, when I think the forcing  20.f4!  is the way we should proceed.  20...Bxh4  21.Rg7+  Kf8  22.Rf7+  Ke8  23.fxe5  Nb5 will come next.  23...fxe5  24.Nb5  Otherwise Black survives.  24...Na6  It looks like Black is off the hook, but  25.Nd6+  cxd6  26.Bb5+  We have finally broken through Black's defense. }
16. Nd5+ { The knight can't be taken, of course. } 16... Kd8 17. Qxe8+ Kxe8 18.
Nxc7+ Kd8 19. Nxa8 { d5 will come next. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. Scandinavian (1...d5) Minor Sidelines"]
[Black "2...Nf6 (3...Bg4 1)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Nf6
{ This is the first branch of the Scandinavian Defense. Black's idea is to avoid the time loss of capturing the pawn with the queen. }
3. d4 Bg4 4. f3
{ We choose to go for objectively the best move, a move that pretty much kills the entire variation. However, 'objectively' means obviously that an engine will have no problems winning with the white pieces in the ensuing chaos. It's a different story when humans are playing, as swindles and tactical blunders are always in the air. This is the main reason why White has chosen moves like   4.Nf3  and Be2 in around 2000 games each. Bb5!?+ has been suggested in some books as well. However, I don't think we should be afraid to go for the kill since there is a ton of logic behind our play, and obviously, we want to win! }
4... Bd7
{ Looks extremely strange, but it is actually a very decent alternative. Even the engine is convinced that this is objectively the best move, but it has only been tried 6 times. The main line, on the other hand, has been seen 2275 times. ..  By far the most popular move, played almost exclusively.   4...Bh5  is another alternative when I suggest transposing to the Main Line after  5.g4  . }
5. c4 c6 6. Nc3
{ It's important to get our pieces out as quickly as possible.   6.dxc6  Nxc6  is very unclear, which is not a good sign when we are a pawn up. }
6... cxd5 7. cxd5 Na6
{ Was seen in a Correspondence game, but it is a bit unnatural. Here is another attempt:   7...e6  8.dxe6  Bxe6  9.Bd3  Nc6  10.Nge2  We're getting our pieces out on the board, when the extra pawn gives us a clearly better position. Note that Nxd4 does not work due to the discovery check on b5 in the end. We'll put our bishop on e3 next, where it can go to f2 if it is chased by a move like Nd5. }
8. Bxa6 bxa6 9. Nge2 { Black has a damaged pawn structure and is a pawn down. }
9... g6 10. Bf4 Bg7 11. d6 { Getting rid of the doubled pawns in the center. }
11... O-O 12. dxe7 Qxe7 13. Qd2 Rfe8 14. O-O
{ White has done everything right in Beveridge,C - O'Brien,P ICCF email 2015. The extra pawn is significant and White eventually prevailed. }
