[White "5. Scandinavian (1...d5) Minor Sidelines"]
[Black "2...Nf6 (3...Bg4 2)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Nf6
{ This is the first branch of the Scandinavian Defense. Black's idea is to avoid the time loss of capturing the pawn with the queen. }
3. d4 Bg4 4. f3 Bc8 { Going all the way back does not make a lot of sense. } 5.
c4 { We'll protect our pawn. } 5... e6 6. dxe6 Bxe6 7. Nc3
{ Black needs to prove that there is enough compensation for the piece. Our main 'weakness' is that it's not so easy to develop our pieces on the kingside, but our king may find a nice home on f2. }
7... Qe7
{ Is a pretty good attempt to trick us. Another attempt in the position:   7...Bb4  I think this move makes the most amount of sense from a human perspective, which is the reason why I'm covering it.  8.d5  Bd7  9.Qe2+  Be7  10.Bf4  Black can't prevent us from castling to the queenside, when our king will be safe and Black will have no compensation for the pawn. }
8. Kf2
{ Our king is surprisingly safe on f2 when Black does not have enough for the missing pawn. I think this Correspondence game played in this position is instructive, so I will leave them as clickable.   8...Nbd7  9.Bd3  O-O-O  10.Nge2  Nc5  11.Be3  Nxd3+  12.Qxd3  h5  13.Rhe1  Re8  14.d5  Bd7  15.Bd4  b6  16.Rab1  h4  17.b4  Qd8  18.c5  Kb8  19.a4  g6  20.a5  Bf5  21.Qb5  Bxb1  22.Bxf6  Bxc5+  23.bxc5  Qxf6  24.Rxb1  Qe7  25.Ne4  f5  26.Nd4  Qf7  27.cxb6  cxb6  28.axb6  a6  29.Nc6+  Black resigned in Sinnett, G-Lewyk, I ICCF email 2017. }
