1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Nf6
{ This is the first branch of the Scandinavian Defense. Black's idea is to avoid the time loss of capturing the pawn with the queen. }
3. d4 Bg4 4. f3 Bf5 5. g4
{ This is when all the fun begins. We want to cling to the extra pawn and follow up with c4-Nc3. The pawn on g4 will often go to g5, chasing away the knight on f6. It's important to distinguish between the text move and the move 5. c4.  After the move   5.c4  e6  will be played. After the further  6.Nc3  exd5  7.g4  , Black can play  7...Be6! }
5... Bd7
{ Is yet again rather strange, but this time it isn't objectively good. } 6. c4
{ As usual we will defend our extra pawn. } 6... e6 7. dxe6 Bxe6 8. Nc3 Qe7
{ This looks like the only 'tricky' option to me, which Black won a game with in 2015.   8...Bb4  has been played thrice, when we can reply with  9.d5  Bd7  10.Qe2+  Kf8  11.Bd2  White will castle queenside next with a dominating position. }
9. Kf2 { Yet again it's good to place the king here. } 9... Na6 10. g5 Nh5 11.
c5 { The idea of Bxa6 is really powerful. } 11... Rd8 12. Bxa6 bxa6 13. Qa4+
Qd7 { After  13...Bd7  the pawn on  a6  hangs. } 14. Qxd7+ Rxd7 15. Nge2
{ White is up a pawn and completely winning. } *

