[Black "2...Nf6 (3...Bg4 4)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Nf6
{ This is the first branch of the Scandinavian Defense. Black's idea is to avoid the time loss of capturing the pawn with the queen. }
3. d4 Bg4 4. f3 Bf5 5. g4
{ This is when all the fun begins. We want to cling to the extra pawn and follow up with c4-Nc3. The pawn on g4 will often go to g5, chasing away the knight on f6. It's important to distinguish between the text move and the move 5. c4.  After the move   5.c4  e6  will be played. After the further  6.Nc3  exd5  7.g4  , Black can play  7...Be6! }
5... Bc8 { This doesn't look playable for Black. } 6. c4 c6
{ GM Anna Muzychuk played this in an internet blitz game, when we can go for   6...b5  Is a rather crazy move, but it doesn't work out for Black.  7.Nc3  bxc4  8.Bxc4  Nbd7  Black wants to attack the pawn with Nb6 in the future, which we can prevent.  9.Qa4!  g6  10.Bf4  Qc6 is now a threat, followed by Bxc7.  10...a6  11.h4!  Our attack is very powerful.  11...Bg7  12.h5!  O-O  13.hxg6  hxg6  14.Qc2  The queen will make its way to h2, when our attack gives us a winning position. }
7. dxc6 Nxc6 8. d5 { Chasing the knight while grabbing space. } 8... Ne5 9. Qe2
Ng6 10. h4 { We keep playing against the knight. } 10... h5 11. g5 Nd7 12. Nc3
{ Black has massive problems developing his pieces. Furthermore, with a pawn down, saving this will require a miracle. }
