1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Nf6
{ This is the first branch of the Scandinavian Defense. Black's idea is to avoid the time loss of capturing the pawn with the queen. }
3. d4 Bg4 4. f3 Bf5 5. g4
{ This is when all the fun begins. We want to cling to the extra pawn and follow up with c4-Nc3. The pawn on g4 will often go to g5, chasing away the knight on f6. It's important to distinguish between the text move and the move 5. c4.  After the move   5.c4  e6  will be played. After the further  6.Nc3  exd5  7.g4  , Black can play  7...Be6! }
5... Bg6 { The most popular move by a decent amount. } 6. c4
{ From here, Black can challenge the center in different ways, but I will only spend my time on two of them. 180 games have seen this move. }
6... c6
{ Once again Black has this move at his disposal. , while others have been seen twice or once. This move makes the most sense if you ask me as Black can soon develop the bishop and castle. }
7. Nc3 cxd5 8. g5 Nfd7
{ 8...Nh5  is met by the thematic  9.f4!  when Be2 is a powerful threat. } 9.
cxd5 Na6 { This position has been reached in some games, when I like the move }
10. Qb3
{ Okay, okay if you looked at an engine this won't be the top choice. The moves   10.h4  and  10.Kf2  are objectively stronger, but I think this is the easiest practical choice as we force Black into a miserable endgame with zero counterplay. }
10... Qb6 11. Qxb6 Nxb6 12. Bb5+ Kd8 13. Bxa6
{ Without this move we don't have a shred of an advantage. } 13... bxa6 14. h4
Ke8 { Is a pretty logical plan with the idea of playing Rd8-Nxd5. } 15. Nge2
Rd8 16. Bf4 { We keep playing active moves while our pieces get developed. }
16... Nxd5 17. Nxd5 Rxd5 18. Rc1
{ Black is suffering due to the undeveloped pieces and the endgame is objectively winning for White. }
