[Black "2...Nf6 (3...Bg4 8)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Nf6
{ This is the first branch of the Scandinavian Defense. Black's idea is to avoid the time loss of capturing the pawn with the queen. }
3. d4 Bg4 4. f3 Bf5 5. g4
{ This is when all the fun begins. We want to cling to the extra pawn and follow up with c4-Nc3. The pawn on g4 will often go to g5, chasing away the knight on f6. It's important to distinguish between the text move and the move 5. c4.  After the move   5.c4  e6  will be played. After the further  6.Nc3  exd5  7.g4  , Black can play  7...Be6! }
5... Bg6 { The most popular move by a decent amount. } 6. c4
{ From here, Black can challenge the center in different ways, but I will only spend my time on two of them. }
6... e6
{ 180 games have seen this move, 22 have seen 6... c6, while others have been seen twice or once. This move makes the most sense if you ask me as Black can soon develop the bishop and castle. }
7. Nc3 { Be careful not to give Black counterplay by taking on e6. } 7... exd5
8. g5 { Removing Black's protection on d5 so we can keep our extra pawn. } 8...
Nfd7 9. Nxd5 Nc6 10. h4
{ We keep pushing our pawns, grabbing a lot of space while having h5 in mind at some point. }
10... Bd6
{ Is a fairly logical move that prevents Bf4 and aims to play Bg3+ if we're not careful. }
11. Ne2
{ Highly logical as it is a developing move that defends against Bg3+. } 11...
O-O 12. c5 Nxc5
{ Sacrificing a piece is the only way to get some counterplay.   12...Be7  would be met by  13.Bf4  , for instance. }
13. dxc5 Bxc5 14. Be3
{ Gaining the option of putting our king on f2 while wanting to trade some more pieces. }
14... Nb4 15. Nxb4 Bxe3 16. Nd5 Bc2
{ 16...Bc5  isn't anything to worry about, since we can keep chasing the bishop away from the diagonal with the move  17.Rc1  . }
17. Nf6+ gxf6 18. Qxc2
{ The bishop on e3 is annoying, but Black does not have enough. } 18... Qd5 19.
Nc3 { Making use of the fact that Qxf3 allows a queen trade after Qg2! } 19...
Qe5 { Qg3+ is something we should prevent with } 20. Qh2 Bf4+ 21. Qe2 Qd4
{ It does look slightly dangerous, but we have everything under control after }
22. Ne4 Rfe8 23. Bh3
{ White had consolidated and eventually won in Krakovsky,P - Tleptsok,R ICCF email 2009. The king will find a safe space on g2, while we can also chase away the queen with Rd1. }
