[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. Scandinavian (1...d5) Minor Sidelines"]
[Black "2...Nf6 (3...Nxd5 4...Nf6 1)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Nf6
{ This is the first branch of the Scandinavian Defense. Black's idea is to avoid the time loss of capturing the pawn with the queen. }
3. d4 Nxd5 4. c4
{ We will keep occupying the center. This is Black's most active response which has seen the light of day over 7500 times! }
4... Nf6
{ This retreat is slightly unusual compared to the main move, but definitely playable. GM Savielly Tartakower described this as 'the soundest move'. Modern engines suggest that he might be correct in his statement. }
5. Nf3
{ From here, Black has numerous set-ups. This challenges our center more than the move }
5... c5
{ Black invites us to take the game into a Benoni-like pawn structure, an invite which I think we should politely decline. }
6. Nc3 cxd4 7. Qxd4 Qxd4 8. Nxd4 a6
{ I think the only sensible move is to prevent the knight jump to b5. } 9. Na4
{ This surprising move is the best move in the position. We're forcing Black to play Nbd7, while the knight is in general very well placed on a4. From here it supports our pawn majority on the queenside. }
9... Nbd7 10. Be3 e5
{ It makes sense to remove our knight from the d4-square. Pushing the pawn only one square with   10...e6  seems too passive to me when a simply continuation would be  11.a3  . }
11. Nc2 Rb8
{ Black can now harass our knight with b5.  If Black attempts simple development we have a straightforward plan:   11...Be7  12.a3  O-O  13.Nc3  b6  14.Be2  Bb7  15.f3  Blocking the diagonal while preventing a knight jump to e4, with a clearly better position. O-O-O may come soon when our pawn majority on the queenside is very powerful. A b5-break is also easily deal with by the move c5. }
12. b4 b5 { Is the most direct approach, but it is too early. } 13. cxb5 axb5
14. Nc3 Bb7
{ Black attacks g2 . If we choose to defend it, Bc6 is an option when Black is not doing too badly.   14...Ba6  might defend the pawn, but it is incredibly passive. A great move here is just to simply play  15.O-O-O  with the nasty threat of a4 . }
15. Bxb5 Bxg2 16. Rg1 Bf3
{ This retreat prevents us from long castling, but this is of little concern. An alternative line worthy of not:   16...Be4  17.O-O-O  Bxc2  18.Kxc2  Bxb4  19.Nd5  Rxb5  20.Nc7+  Ke7  21.Nxb5  The extra material should lead to a full point for the white side. }
17. Rg3 e4 18. Rxf3 { 18.a4  is also good. } 18... exf3 19. O-O-O
{ The pin on b5 is extremely strong, allowing us to march with our pawn with ease. }
