1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Nf6
{ This is the first branch of the Scandinavian Defense. Black's idea is to avoid the time loss of capturing the pawn with the queen. }
3. d4 Nxd5 4. c4
{ We will keep occupying the center. This is Black's most active response which has seen the light of day over 7500 times! }
4... Nf6
{ This retreat is slightly unusual compared to the main move, but definitely playable. GM Savielly Tartakower described this as 'the soundest move'. Modern engines suggest that he might be correct in his statement. has been seen around 2000, just to compare. }
5. Nf3
{ From here, Black has numerous set-ups. This challenges our center more than the move }
5... e6 6. Nc3 Be7
{ Is the most seen move in the position, but it looks awfully passive to me.   6...c5!?  Black aims to remove our iron fist on the center. leads to 5... e6.  7.Be3  cxd4  8.Nxd4  a6  Ndb5 is very often a rather annoying move to meet, so I think this prophylactic move makes some sense.  9.a3!?  We make a little prophylactic move on our own with preventing Bb4 and aiming for b4 in the near future.  9...Bd7  After   9...Bc5  we have the nice trick  10.Nxe6!  Black wants to play  10...Nc6  with this move, before it's too late.  10.g3  Nc6  11.Bg2  Rc8  12.b4  Grabbing more space while intending to meet a jump to e5 with c5.  12...Be7  13.O-O  With more active pieces and great central control we can be satisfied with the outcome of the opening. We'll meet Nxd4 with Qxd4, defending the pawn on c4. }
7. Bd3 O-O 8. O-O { Our path forward is simple. } 8... b6 9. Bf4 Bb7 10. Qe2
Nc6
{ This was played in a blitz game between Carlsen and Nakamura, and it is a mistake. However, Black's position was rather unpleasant to play anyway. }
11. Rad1 { Indirectly defending the pawn on d4. } 11... Bd6 12. Bg5 h6 13. Bh4
Be7
{ The pawn on the f6-knight was very annoying of course, so Black went for this move. Unfortunately, it only make matters worse. }
14. d5 exd5 15. cxd5 Nb4 16. Bc4
{ Simply guarding the pawn would be best when Black is more or less busted.   16.Rfe1  was seen in Carlsen, M - Nakamura, H chess.com INT 2018, when Naka got decent counterplay after  16...Nxd3  . }
