[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. Scandinavian (1...d5) Minor Sidelines"]
[Black "2...Nf6 (3...Nxd5 4...Nb6 1)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Nf6
{ This is the first branch of the Scandinavian Defense. Black's idea is to avoid the time loss of capturing the pawn with the queen. }
3. d4 Nxd5 4. c4 { We will keep occupying the center. } 4... Nb6
{ This is Black's most active response which has seen the light of day over 7500 times!  4...Nf6  has been seen around 2000, just to compare. }
5. Nf3
{ We have reached the Main Position in the 2... Nf6 variation. From here Black has played a lot of moves, but the main moves are g6 and Bg4 . Other moves are possible, but extremely seldom played. }
5... Nc6
{ Is one alternative worth mentioning.   5...Bf5  Has also been tried.  6.Bd3  A simple move that give a great position!  6...Bxd3  7.Qxd3  e6  8.Nc3  Be7  9.O-O  O-O  10.Bf4  We have made simple developing moves and gained a wonderful position due to Black's passivity. }
6. Nc3 Bf5
{ 6...Bg4  is the most popular move, but it makes little sense after  7.d5! }
7. c5 { This is a novelty, and a very strong move here. } 7... Nd5 8. Bb5
{ We're getting our pieces out. Black needs to seriously worry about Ne5 ideas, while we could also destroy the structure with Bxc6. }
8... g6
{ This is the engine choice, and by far the best move apparently. We can meet other moves with the simple O-O and eventually Re1, Ne5, etc. }
9. Ne5 Nb4 10. Qb3 Nc2+ { Forced, as f7 and b4 was under attack. } 11. Qxc2
Bxc2 12. Nxc6 bxc6
{ No other moves would have saved the queen.  12...Qc8  for instance, was countered by  13.Nxa7  . }
13. Bxc6+ Qd7 14. Bxd7+ Kxd7 15. g4
{ Threatening to trap the bishop. Bf4 and O-O-O will follow soon, with a winning endgame. Our extra pawn should decide the game. }
