[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. Scandinavian (1...d5) Minor Sidelines"]
[Black "2...Nf6 (3...Nxd5 4...Nb6 4)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Nf6
{ This is the first branch of the Scandinavian Defense. Black's idea is to avoid the time loss of capturing the pawn with the queen. }
3. d4 Nxd5 4. c4 { We will keep occupying the center. } 4... Nb6
{ This is Black's most active response which has seen the light of day over 7500 times!  4...Nf6  has been seen around 2000, just to compare. }
5. Nf3 Bg4
{ Pinning the knight is certainly logical, but that doesn't make it a great move. However, this is due to concrete reasons as we soon shall see. }
6. c5
{ Attacking the knight on c5 is the most concrete approach to the position. }
6... N6d7 7. Be2
{ Removing the pin while developing our pieces. Black has two main moves here, but the position remains very uncomfortable to play in practice. White has a very good score from here, while neither Stockfish or Leela survived with the black pieces when this opening was given in the Top Computer Chess Championship TCEC. }
7... e6 { Is the main move here, but Black is far from achieving equality. } 8.
h3
{ Leela played h3 here, so I trust that she made the right call. Is the human move, but objectively inferior to }
8... Bh5 9. Nc3 Be7 10. Qb3
{ This move is always thematic. There certainly was nothing wrong with   10.Be3  , though. }
10... Qc8 11. g4 Bg6 12. Be3
{ Black is struggling with the passive pieces and lack of space. } 12... Nc6
13. O-O-O
{ This may look risky, but Black is not prepared to handle White's attack. }
13... a5 { Black needs to somehow get some counterplay. } 14. d5
{ Not necessary, but still good. } 14... a4
{ Is an inaccuracy. It was important to take the pawn, but I doubt Black would have been satisfied after the recapture with the queen. }
15. dxc6 axb3 16. cxd7+ Qxd7 17. Rxd7
{ The resulting endgame is hopeless for Black. } 17... bxa2 18. Nxa2 Kxd7 19.
Ne5+ { Snagging the bishop on g6. } 19... Ke8 20. Nxg6 hxg6
{ 20...Rxa2  is met by  21.Kb1!  , preventing  (21...Ra1+)  . } 21. Kb1
{ In a game between two very strong Correspondence players, White eventually prevailed in Jandek,S - Van Leeuwen,E ICCF email 2011. }
