{ This is Black's most active response which has seen the light of day over 7500 times!  4...Nf6  has been seen around 2000, just to compare. }
5. Nf3 Bg4
{ Pinning the knight is certainly logical, but that doesn't make it a great move. However, this is due to concrete reasons as we soon shall see. }
6. c5
{ Attacking the knight on c5 is the most concrete approach to the position. As we have seen, }
6... Nd5
{ This move loses by force, provided that we play precisely. loses, so this has to be played. }
7. Qb3
{ Defending the pawn on b7 is now a very tough task. is now no longer an issue, because Black can play }
7... Nc6
{ with ideas like Bxf3 and Nxd4 .  Trying to complicate things. The move   7...Bc8  has been the most popular, but it is obvious that if Black needs to resort to a move like that, his opening strategy has failed spectacularly. b6 fails for many reasons, in particular  8.Ne5  . }
8. Qxb7 { Once you've said A, B must be investigated. .. } 8... Bd7
{ 8...Ndb4  doesn't make a difference. } 9. Bb5
{ Qxc6 is a threat now, so Black has to play } 9... Ndb4 10. d5
{ The refutation is beautiful.   10.Bxc6  should also win, though. } 10... a6
{ Is the engine move.   10...Rb8  is nothing to worry about, as we can take the knight due to the fact that cxd7 will win back the queen in the end.   10...Nc2+  Is tricky, when we should play  11.Kd1  Rb8  12.dxc6  It looks outrageous to walk into the discovered attack, but Black has nothing. Also do keep in mind that our queen is untouchable, as Black has to defend the check with his queen.   11...Bf5  12.Ke2  e5  13.Rd1  Qc8  14.Nc3  White had done everything right in Priasmoro, N - Cuhendi, S Yogyakarta 2019. Black might take the rook, but the black king is too weak. }
11. Bxc6 { This looks like the simplest way to proceed. } 11... Rb8 12. Bxd7+
Kxd7 13. c6+ Ke8 14. Qa7 { Our queen escapes. } 14... Ra8 15. d6
{ The only move, as all the other moves are countered by knight forks on d3 or c2. }
15... Nc2+
