[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. Scandinavian (1...d5) Minor Sidelines"]
[Black "2... Nf6 (3...Nxd5 4...Nb6 5...g6 1)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Nf6
{ This is the first branch of the Scandinavian Defense. Black's idea is to avoid the time loss of capturing the pawn with the queen. }
3. d4 Nxd5 4. c4 { We will keep occupying the center. } 4... Nb6
{ This is Black's most active response which has seen the light of day over 7500 times! }
5. Nf3 g6
{ The most popular move, for good reason. The bishop will be better placed on g7 than on e7 as it attacks our pawn on d4. Besides, the pawn on g6 blocks the b1-h7 diagonal, so the king won't be vulnerable. This may sound appealing, but I think Black is biting the bullet with this line. The arising positions tend to lean towards a rather passive and sad game, much due to our fantastic central control and active pieces. }
6. a4
{ I really like this move. a5 is our plan, pushing away the knight on b6. The point here is that the knight can't move to d5, due to the fact that our c-pawn still stands on c4.   That being said,  6.Nc3  Bg7  7.c5  is also decent. }
6... Bg7 { Black ignores our plan completely. } 7. a5 N6d7 8. Be2
{ 8.Nc3  should more or less lead to the same thing. } 8... e5
{ Has been tried before, but I think the endgame is rather unpleasant for Black. }
9. dxe5 Nxe5 10. Qxd8+ Kxd8 11. Bg5+ { Gaining a valuable tempo. } 11... Ke8
12. Nc3 Be6 13. O-O-O
{ We keep playing active moves. Nb5/ Nd5 is rather annoying for Black. } 13...
Na6 14. Nxe5 Bxe5 15. Nd5
{ Black's king is stuck in the center, making it rather difficult to coordinate the pieces. Our rook may soon come to e1, followed by Bf3. Black has to play extremely accurate in order to stay in the game. }
