[White "5. Scandinavian (1...d5) Minor Sidelines"]
[Black "2... Nf6 (3...Nxd5 4...Nb6 5...g6 3)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Nf6
{ This is the first branch of the Scandinavian Defense. Black's idea is to avoid the time loss of capturing the pawn with the queen. }
3. d4 Nxd5 4. c4 { We will keep occupying the center. } 4... Nb6
{ This is Black's most active response which has seen the light of day over 7500 times! }
5. Nf3 g6
{ The most popular move, for good reason. The bishop will be better placed on g7 than on e7 as it attacks our pawn on d4. Besides, the pawn on g6 blocks the b1-h7 diagonal, so the king won't be vulnerable. This may sound appealing, but I think Black is biting the bullet with this line. The arising positions tend to lean towards a rather passive and sad game, much due to our fantastic central control and active pieces. }
6. a4 { I really like this move. } 6... Bg7
{ Black ignores our plan completely. } 7. a5 N6d7 8. Be2 O-O 9. Nc3
{ Black's knight on d7 is a huge annoyance for him. } 9... e5
{ The one way to make use of the bad knight placement. } 10. Bg5 Bf6
{ Might be best, but that doesn't mean too much. } 11. Bxf6 Qxf6 12. dxe5 Nxe5
13. O-O
{ We have already finished our development, when Black has two minor pieces in the starting position. }
13... Be6 14. Nxe5 Qxe5 15. Re1
{ The absence of the dark-squared bishops has weakened Black's king, meaning that Ne4 is a move we will play very soon. The queen will be moved to b3, followed up by Rad1, grabbing the d-file. The h-pawn may even advance in the future, aiming to weaken Black's kingside even further. }
15... Qf4 16. Bf3
{ Black now needs to play accurately in order to stay in the game. } 16... Na6
{ 16...c6?  Is extremely natural, but a mistake.  17.g3  Qc7  18.Bg4  Bxg4  19.Qxg4  White is already winning according to the engine. The reason is quite clear, Black is simply put, too exposed on the kingside.  19...Na6  20.Qh4+-  Ne4 will soon come, but Qh4 also opens up the possibility of putting a rook on e7, which certainly will be a thorn in Black's side. }
17. Ne4
{ This is important.  17.Bxb7  would allow give Black to almost equalize after  17...Rad8  when c4 hangs next, guarding the knight on a6. }
17... Qe5
{ The queen needs to control the diagonal.   17...Rad8?  Is another extremely logical move, but it's not a good one.  18.Qb3+-  There is no good way to protect the pawn on b7. If Black tries to go for 18... Bc8, we can respond with 19. Qc3, when Black will be forced to weaken his position even further with f6. }
18. Qb3 Rab8 19. Qb5
{ Giving Black the option of getting into a bad endgame or placing the queen on an inferior square. }
19... Qf5
{ 19...Qxb5  Gives us a very nice endgame.  20.cxb5  Nb4  21.Rec1  21...c6  Black is so close to being fine, but...  22.a6!  keeps our advantage.  22...Nd3  Is the trickiest defense.  23.Rd1  Nxb2  24.axb7!  Not an easy move to find on the board.  24...Rxb7  Black has to remove the pawn on b7.  25.bxc6  Rc7  26.Rdb1  Rb8  27.Nc5+-  The passed pawn on c6 will is likely to decide the game. }
20. h4 { Going for the h5-break. } 20... Rfd8 21. h5
{ The pawn on h5 is extremely annoying, as Black needs to make sure he is always prepared for a h6-thrust. }
21... c6 22. Qb3 { We will of course keep the queens on the board. } 22... Nc5
{ Black has to get rid of the knight on e4 before it is too late. } 23. Qa3
Nxe4 24. Rxe4
{ We'll double our rooks on the e-file with a great initiative. Black is still in the game, but by the skin of his teeth. }
