{ This is Black's most active response which has seen the light of day over 7500 times! }
5. Nf3 g6
{ The most popular move, for good reason. The bishop will be better placed on g7 than on e7 as it attacks our pawn on d4. Besides, the pawn on g6 blocks the b1-h7 diagonal, so the king won't be vulnerable. This may sound appealing, but I think Black is biting the bullet with this line. The arising positions tend to lean towards a rather passive and sad game, much due to our fantastic central control and active pieces. }
6. a4 { I really like this move. } 6... Bg7
{ Black ignores our plan completely. } 7. a5 N6d7 8. Be2 O-O 9. Nc3
{ Black's knight on d7 is a huge annoyance for him. } 9... e5
{ The one way to make use of the bad knight placement. } 10. Bg5 f6
{ Isn't a great idea, as we shall soon see. } 11. Be3 Nc6 12. O-O
{ Black has different options at his disposal, but none of them are satisfactory. }
12... exd4
{ Was played in the only game I found in the base.   12...f5  Is a thematic move, but it doesn't work.  13.Bg5!  Black doesn't have a good way of parrying the threat of taking the queen.  13...Bf6  14.Bxf6  Qxf6  15.Nd5  Qd8  Black's pieces are pushed back. Now that we have developed our pieces, it's time to open up Black's position.  16.dxe5  Ndxe5  17.Nxe5  Nxe5  18.Qd4+-  We have a dominating position. Qc3-Rad1 will come next, when Black won't be able to defend all the threats.   12...Re8  Black wants to play e4-f5, with typical King's Indian play.  13.d5  Is a nice way to dodge that plan.  13...Ne7  14.c5  Our pawns are much faster.  14...Nf5  15.b4  Nxe3  16.fxe3  Our queenside pawns are extremely powerful.  16...a6  Preventing a6, but it doesn't help.  17.e4  Black can't prevent us from launching our pawns even further with the move d6.  17...f5  18.d6  c6  19.Bc4+  Kh8  20.Qc2+-  Our position is simply put, gorgeous. }
13. Nxd4 Nxd4 14. Bxd4 c6
{ Black has gotten rid of some of the pressure. So far we have been following Kozel,R - Palkovich,D Geller Memorial 2007, when White should have played }
15. c5 { Opening up the diagonal while grabbing space. } 15... Ne5 16. Qb3+ Kh8
17. Rfd1 Qe7 18. Ne4 { The knight is headed to d6. } 18... Be6 19. Qe3 Bd5 20.
Nd6 { I doubt that Black can withstand our pressure for long. } *

