1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Nf6
{ This is the first branch of the Scandinavian Defense. Black's idea is to avoid the time loss of capturing the pawn with the queen. }
3. d4 Nxd5 4. c4 { We will keep occupying the center. } 4... Nb6
{ This is Black's most active response which has seen the light of day over 7500 times! }
5. Nf3 g6
{ The most popular move, for good reason. The bishop will be better placed on g7 than on e7 as it attacks our pawn on d4. Besides, the pawn on g6 blocks the b1-h7 diagonal, so the king won't be vulnerable. This may sound appealing, but I think Black is biting the bullet with this line. The arising positions tend to lean towards a rather passive and sad game, much due to our fantastic central control and active pieces. }
6. a4 { I really like this move. } 6... a5
{ Preventing us from playing a5 is the most logical way to play. } 7. c5
{ It looks like to me that we get a good version of the Main Line. The pawn on a5 weakens the square on b6 which is an advantage in several lines. }
7... Nd5 8. Bc4
{ Black needs to proceed with care now that Qb3 is in the air. } 8... Bg7
{ 8...Nc6  Is an attempt to make use of the fact that our pawn is on a4.  9.Nc3  Ncb4  Black has an outpost on b4, but it won't last long.  10.Nxd5  Nxd5  11.Qb3  Locking down the knight on d5.  11...c6  12.O-O  Bg7  13.Re1  O-O  14.Bd2±  We are clearly better according to the engines, but I'd argue that we are close to winning. The reason for this, is that Black has no satisfactory plan. For an engine that's not the end of the world, but for a human being it is psychologically extremely difficult to just sit and wait. An easy way forward for us is to play Re2 followed by Rae1, doubling on the e-file. }
9. Qb3 { Black can defend the knight in two ways. } 9... e6 10. Bg5
{ This is an excellent move, gaining a tempo on the queen. Black can dodge the threat in many ways, but only one move leads to a playable position. }
10... Ne7
{ This move has been played once and it is objectively the strongest move.   10...f6  This ugly move has been played twice.  11.Bd2  Nc6  12.Nc3  'Play logical developing moves, chess is a logical game' as my old coach used to say.  12...Nce7  13.O-O  O-O  14.Rfe1  Every cloud has a silver lining is a saying, but I can't see anything positive about Black's position. Indeed, White eventually prevailed in Real de Azua,E - Luconi,C Mendoza 2008. }
11. Nc3 h6 { Black should get rid of the bishop on g5 as soon as possible. }
12. Bxe7 { Taking the knight gives us easy play. } 12... Qxe7 13. O-O O-O 14.
Rfe1 Na6 15. Rad1
{ We're fully developed, while Black is far behind. Black's bishop is stuck on c8 due to the hanging b-pawn, but Rb8 isn't possible due to Bxa6. If Black moves the knight to b4, the d5-break becomes possible! 15... b6 might be necessary, when we should play 16. c6. }
