{ This is Black's most active response which has seen the light of day over 7500 times! }
5. Nf3 g6
{ The most popular move, for good reason. The bishop will be better placed on g7 than on e7 as it attacks our pawn on d4. Besides, the pawn on g6 blocks the b1-h7 diagonal, so the king won't be vulnerable. This may sound appealing, but I think Black is biting the bullet with this line. The arising positions tend to lean towards a rather passive and sad game, much due to our fantastic central control and active pieces. }
6. a4 { I really like this move. } 6... a5
{ Preventing us from playing a5 is the most logical way to play. } 7. c5
{ It looks like to me that we get a good version of the Main Line. The pawn on a5 weakens the square on b6 which is an advantage in several lines. }
7... Nd5 8. Bc4
{ Black needs to proceed with care now that Qb3 is in the air. } 8... Bg7 9.
Qb3 { Black can defend the knight in two ways. } 9... c6
{ This is better as we don't get Bg5 with a tempo. } 10. Nc3 O-O 11. O-O
{ Black can approach this position in different ways. } 11... Nb4
{ The knight looks nice on b4, but it doesn't do much there.   11...e6  Blocking the diagonal has been played by two 2500-players, among others.  12.Bg5  Once again we gain a developing tempo on the queen.  12...Qc7  13.Rfe1  Nd7   This makes more sense than  13...Na6  . Here we can play  14.Bxa6  Rxa6  15.Bh4  , when the bishop will head to  g3  next.  14.Bh4  14...b6  Fighting our c5-pawn is best.  15.Bxd5!  exd5  Black is forced to give an exchange in this line, but it is the best way to fight for equality.  16.cxb6  Nxb6  17.Be7±  We will win an exchange as  17...Re8  is met by  18.Bc5+-  Black is lost. If he saves the material with Rxe1+, we will enter on e8 followed by Qa3. }
12. Ne5
{ We want to provoke Black into playing e6, when we would soon get the d6-square for our knight. }
12... Qe8
{ Was played by a polish GM.   12...Bxe5  13.dxe5  Bf5  Bc2 can be rather annoying, so we should play  14.Ne2!  Not only do we get more squares for our queen, the knight may also jump to f4 in the future.  14...e6  15.Bh6  Re8  In Cornette,D - Raeva,E Bucharest 2017, White should have played  16.Qg3!  When Bg5 will give Black a headache.  16...Nd7  17.Rfd1+-  Our initiative is extremely powerful. If Black attacks our pawn on e5 with Qc7, we can respond with Rd6. Other moves can be met by Nd4 when we aim to get rid of the defender on f5. }
13. Bg5 { Applying pressure on the pawn on e7. } 13... h6 14. Bd2 Bf5
{ We can now make use of the fact that Black doesn't guard b7 with the move }
15. Na2 { Black will now lose material, for example } 15... Nxa2 16. Bxf7+ Rxf7
17. Nxf7 Qxf7 18. Qxb7
{ Black loses the rook on a8 or the knight on b8, including the game. } *

