[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. Scandinavian (1...d5) Minor Sidelines"]
[Black "2...Nf6 Conclusion"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Nf6
{ CONCLUSION: a popular alternative to the mainstream  2...Qxd5  . Black wants to take with the knight instead, avoiding a time loss. }
3. d4 Nxd5 { The most common way is to capture the pawn. } 4. c4
{ Hitting the Knight again picking up time. } 4... Nb6
{ is the main move, when Black has two options after   4...Nb4  has a nice trap in mind, but the simple  5.a3  takes care of Black's shenanigans.   4...Nf6  is suggested by the engines and GM Tartakower, but I find the resulting positions awfully passive for Black. Heading to the endgame with  5...c5  is the engine's suggestion when I believe our plan of playing 9. Na4, followed by an expansion on the queenside is rather effective. }
5. Nf3
{ Black has a few responses in review:  5...Bg4  is one of them when  6.c5!  is strong.   6...Nd5  loses by force after 7... Qb3, so   6...N6d7  should be played. From this position, we discovered a mini-match between Stockfish and Leela, when neither engine was able to survive with the black pieces. This certainly paints an ugly picture of the variation, when human games have also seen a vastly negative trend for Black.   5...g6  is more common, but it seems like to me that Black is on thin ice in this line. My suggestion is the slightly uncommon move  6.a4  , intending to chase away the knight on  b6  . The most likely reply will be  6...a5  , when  7.c5!  followed by  Bc4  gives us an excellent position where Black is more or less doomed to passivity - a very common trend for the entire 2... Nf6 variation. I think Black's barking up the wrong tree with the 2... Nf6 line, as the concept looks like a bad version of 3...  Qd8  ,  giving us  c4  with a tempo, reinforcing our control of the center. I find absolutely zero appeal with this line, as none of the arising positions after 3... Nxd5 are particularly tricky to handle from the white side. At least Alekhine Defense can be rather difficult to play if you don't know what you're doing, but here simple moves do the trick. Sure, 3... Bg4 is somewhat tricky, but the refutation is crystal clear for a prepared player. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6. Scandinavian (1...d5) 3...Qd8 Retreat"]
[Black "3...Qd8 (5...g6 1)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qd8
{ This retreat was depicted in the ancient game Castellvi-Vinyoles. Back in the good old days it used to be the Main Line, but 3... Qa5 eventually replaced it. Nowadays, it is the pet line of some strong players, in particular my fellow Chessable author, IM John Bartholomew. He describes the line as 'Rock-Solid,' saying that the black player gets a 'flawless structure, easy development and good chances to play for a win.' I will agree with John in the sense that the plans are always the same for Black, meaning that you can play the opening without knowing huge amounts of theory. I can also back the 'flawless structure' argument, as Black does not have any weaknesses that we can target in the position.   I think this line is a decent surprise weapon as few players have spent their time studying this line in great depth. However, I think we can give Black a run for his money. Black may be solid, but the resulting positions tend to become extremely passive, making the objective evaluation certainly point in White's favor. }
4. d4 { Grabbing the center as we always do. } 4... Nf6
{ Other moves have been played here, but this logical move is by far the most popular in the position. Black has to play Nf6 at some point anyway, so other options are likely to transpose. }
5. Nf3 g6
{ This move has been played by a lot of World Class players in shorter time controls, and the reason for this is that Black's moves are sort of 'automatic, ' while the line is rather unknown on the theoretical spectrum. However, Black does weaken himself with the move, namely the h6-square. This is something we will exploit to the fullest, as we will choose a set-up involving Bf4, followed by Qd2 and O-O-O, launching an attack. }
6. Bf4 Bg7 7. Qd2 { Our plan is set in motion. } 7... a6
{ This looks like the only alternative to  7...O-O  really, as Black has to castle sooner or later. }
8. O-O-O
{ I don't see why we shouldn't castle here. Firouzja went for  8.Bc4  but I think it is rather subpar compared to our choice. }
8... b5
{ Two games have had 9. Ne5 on the table in this position, but I prefer Two games have had Ne5 on the table in this position, but I prefer }
9. Bh6 { Forcing Black to make an unpleasant decision. } 9... Bxh6 10. Qxh6
{ Black is biting the bullet as it will take long before it will be possible to castle. }
10... Bb7 11. Be2
{ Our path forward is rather simple. We want to jump to e5 at some point with our knight, and grab the e-file by the means of Rhe1. }
11... Qd6
{ Black gets the queen out to open up the possibility of castling to the other side. }
12. Rhe1 Nbd7 13. Ne5
{ Our knight jumps into Black's position, making queenside castling impossible at the moment. }
13... e6 14. f4
{ I think this move makes a lot of sense, reinforcing our control over e5. That being said, there were a lot of decent moves in the position. }
14... Rf8
{ Is the most desired move in the position, but it fails to a rather stunning tactic.  Black needs to find an optimal way of defending the pawn on f7 , so it's possible to castle queenside.   14...Qe7  is a move I like less due to  15.Bf3!  After  15...Bxf3  16.gxf3  , Black has to deal with threats of Nc6 , f5 and potentially d5 , and they're all rather irritating. }
15. d5
{ Utilizing the fact that Black's king is in the same file as our took on e1. }
15... Bxd5 16. Nxd5 Nxd5 17. Rxd5 exd5
{ 17...Qxd5  would lose to  18.Bf3  , winning the rook. } 18. Nc6
{ The only move that grants a decisive edge. The point is that it's not possible for Black to castle, while the knight can't be taken due to Bxb5+. }
18... Nc5
{ Stockfish thinks that this is the best try, aiming to meet Bxb5+ with Ne6. }
19. Bxb5+ Ne6 20. Ba4
{ We might be an exchange down, but our attack is extremely strong. } 20... Kd7
21. Re5 { Attacking the pawn on d5. } 21... Kc8 22. a3
{ Strengthening the position around our king. We are not in a hurry, so we might as well spend some time improving our position before striking. }
22... Qc5 23. Kb1
{ Black's pieces lack coordination, while the king is also very vulnerable. One very strong plan is to sacrifice a pawn with f5 followed by Qd2, winning the d5-pawn. }
*

