4. d4 { Grabbing the center as we always do. } 4... Nf6
{ Other moves have been played here, but this logical move is by far the most popular in the position. Black has to play Nf6 at some point anyway, so other options are likely to transpose. }
5. Nf3 g6
{ This move has been played by a lot of World Class players in shorter time controls, and the reason for this is that Black's moves are sort of 'automatic, ' while the line is rather unknown on the theoretical spectrum. However, Black does weaken himself with the move, namely the h6-square. This is something we will exploit to the fullest, as we will choose a set-up involving Bf4, followed by Qd2 and O-O-O, launching an attack. }
6. Bf4 Bg7 7. Qd2 { Our plan is set in motion. } 7... a6
{ This looks like the only alternative to   7...O-O  really, as Black has to castle sooner or later. }
8. O-O-O
{ I don't see why we shouldn't castle here. Firouzja went for   8.Bc4  but I think it is rather subpar compared to our choice. }
8... b5
{ Two games have had 9. Ne5 on the table in this position, but I prefer Two games have had Ne5 on the table in this position, but I prefer }
9. Bh6 { Forcing Black to make an unpleasant decision. } 9... O-O 10. Bxg7 Kxg7
11. h4
{ A type of position where a human player would be terrified with the black pieces. Positions like these are always so easy to play for the attacking side - open up the h-file and deliver checkmate. }
11... b4
{ 11...h5  12.Ne5  Black's definitely not out of the woods yet. Now that Black has played h5, the pawn on g6 is a new target. We can exploit this by playing Bd3 followed by Qg5 at some point. One day we will also play f3-g4, opening up the g-file. It's logical to block the h-file break.   11...Bg4  for instance, could be met by  12.h5  , when our attack should grant us victory. }
12. Ne2 Qd5 13. Kb1
{ We're threatening to play Nf4 followed b4 h5, while we can grab the pawn on b4 if Black decides to go for h5. Be6 can always be countered by b3. }
