1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qd8 4. d4 { Grabbing the center as we always do. }
4... Nf6
{ Other moves have been played here, but this logical move is by far the most popular in the position. Black has to play Nf6 at some point anyway, so other options are likely to transpose. }
5. Nf3 g6
{ This move has been played by a lot of World Class players in shorter time controls, and the reason for this is that Black's moves are sort of 'automatic, ' while the line is rather unknown on the theoretical spectrum. However, Black does weaken himself with the move, namely the h6-square. This is something we will exploit to the fullest, as we will choose a set-up involving Bf4, followed by Qd2 and O-O-O, launching an attack. }
6. Bf4 Bg7 7. Qd2
{ Our plan is set in motion. This looks like the only alternative to } 7... O-O
{ really, as Black has to castle sooner or later. } 8. O-O-O
{ Few games have been tried here, but a lot of different moves have been played, showing that the path forward is rather unclear. }
8... c5
{ Is a novelty and a computer-ish move. Black wants to gain counterplay with Qa5 in case we decide to go pawn-grabbing. }
9. d5 a6
{ Black is preparing for a queenside assault with b5, which can become extremely dangerous if we're not careful. }
10. h4
{ I originally wanted to suggest  10.d6  but I eventually discovered that it was best to continue with our attack. }
10... Bg4 { Is the best way to stop our attack. } 11. Bh6 Nbd7
{ Black has quickly finished his development. The knight on d7 may also assist the knight on f6 in controlling the h5-square, as the typical pawn sacrifice of h5 is always looming in the air. }
12. Be2 b5
{ Now Black starts attacking on his own, but as usual, we're faster. } 13. Bxg7
Kxg7 14. h5 { Once again we go for the typical sacrifice. } 14... Bxh5
{ 14...Nxh5  is met by  15.Ng5  , when our attack is decisive. } 15. g4
{ A fantastic move with a tactical idea. } 15... Nxg4
{ This is forced, of course. } 16. Ng5
{ The point. Now h7 could hang in the end. } 16... Ndf6
{ Defending the knight on g4.   16...Rh8  Loses to the stunning  17.Rxh5!  gxh5  18.Bxg4  hxg4  19.Ne6+!  Opening up Black's king.  19...fxe6  20.Qg5+  Kf8  21.dxe6  Nf6  Black needs to part with the queen.  22.Rxd8+  Rxd8  And here  23.Qh6+!  Ke8  24.Ne4!  Threatening to take on f6.  24...Rf8  25.Nxc5  Black does have two rooks for the queen, but his weak king is a massive liability. The queen remains supreme for that very reason. }
17. Nce4
{ Black's will have difficulties fending off our powerful attack. I prefer it over the mess after   17.Bxg4  Bxg4  18.Nxh7  Nh5  19.Nxf8  Bxd1  20.Nxg6  fxg6  21.Rxd1  , but this is probably good too. }
17... h6 { Is the best defense, and indeed very logical. } 18. Bxg4
{ The point, as Black is forced to take on g5. } 18... hxg5
{ 18...Bxg4  loses to  19.Ne6+  followed by Qxh6+ . } 19. Nxf6 exf6 20. Bxh5
gxh5 21. f4
{ Black's pawns will soon be dismantled, while we have a fantastic passed pawn on d5. }
