[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6. Scandinavian (1...d5) 3...Qd8 Retreat"]
[Black "3...Qd8 (5...Bf5 1)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qd8
{ This retreat was depicted in the ancient game Castellvi-Vinyoles. Back in the good old days, it used to be the Main Line, but 3... Qa5 eventually replaced it. Nowadays, it is the pet line of some strong players, in particular my fellow Chessable author, IM John Bartholomew. He describes the line as 'Rock-Solid,' saying that the black player gets a 'flawless structure, easy development and good chances to play for a win.' I will agree with John in the sense that the plans are always the same for Black, meaning that you can play the opening without knowing huge amounts of theory. I can also back the 'flawless structure' argument, as Black does not have any weaknesses that we can target in the position. Certainly, I think it is a decent surprise weapon as few players have spent their time studying this line in great depth. However, I think we can give Black a run for his money. Black may be solid, but the resulting positions tend to become extremely passive, making the objective evaluation point in White's favor. }
4. d4 { Grabbing the center as we always do. } 4... Nf6
{ Other moves have been played here, but this logical move is by far the most popular in the position. Black has to play Nf6 at some point anyway, so other options are likely to transpose. }
5. Nf3 Bf5 6. Ne5
{ This reaction is extremely typical and a crucial idea to remember in the Scandinavian. Just like in the 3... Qe5+ line, we're aiming to harass the bishop with a subsequent g4-h4. }
6... Nbd7 { Would be a huge mistake, due to } 7. Qf3
{ Black has to part with the b7-pawn. } 7... e6 8. Qxb7 Rb8 9. Qxa7
{ We have now won two pawns, for no compensation at all. } 9... Ra8 10. Qb7
{ Our queen escapes, for example } 10... Rb8 11. Qa6 Ra8 12. Qc6
{ The extra material gives us a winning position. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6. Scandinavian (1...d5) 3...Qd8 Retreat"]
[Black "3...Qd8 (5...Bf5 2)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qd8 4. d4 { Grabbing the center as we always do. }
4... Nf6
{ Other moves have been played here, but this logical move is by far the most popular in the position. Black has to play Nf6 at some point anyway, so other options are likely to transpose. }
5. Nf3 Bf5 6. Ne5
{ This reaction is extremely typical and a crucial idea to remember in the Scandinavian. Just like in the 3... Qe5+ line, we're aiming to harass the bishop with a subsequent g4-h4. }
6... e6 { Would be another error. } 7. g4
{ Chasing the bishop while giving the g2-square for our f1-bishop, putting pressure on b7. }
7... Be4 { Doesn't help Black, after } 8. Nxe4 Nxe4 9. Bg2 Nd6
{ Black has lost the bishop-pair and is left with an extremely passive position. }
10. Bf4 c6 11. Qe2
{ As our development advantage is massive, I suggest going for queenside castling and a pawn storm on the kingside. }
11... Be7 12. h4
{ We prevented Black from playing Bg5 after O-O-O. If Black grabs the pawn, we can play Qe3 with O-O-O next. Black is far behind in development, so the extra pawn won't matter much. }
*

