Qe2
{ I like gaining a valuable tempo on the knight, so we can soon proceed with Bd2-O-O-O, with a powerful attack.  The forcing   10.Nxf7  is also decent after  10...Kxf7  11.Qf3+  Nf6  12.g5  , but I prefer our continuation. }
10... Nd6 11. Bd3 Nd7 12. Bd2 { Preparing to castle queenside. } 12... Be7 13.
O-O-O
{ Black did not last long in Karthik,V 2457-Jyothsna, L Bhubaneswar 2018. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6. Scandinavian (1...d5) 3...Qd8 Retreat"]
[Black "3...Qd8 (5...Bf5 5)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qd8 4. d4 { Grabbing the center as we always do. }
4... Nf6
{ Other moves have been played here, but this logical move is by far the most popular in the position. Black has to play Nf6 at some point anyway, so other options are likely to transpose. }
5. Nf3 Bf5 6. Ne5
{ This reaction is extremely typical and a crucial idea to remember in the Scandinavian. Just like in the 3... Qe5+ line, we're aiming to harass the bishop with a subsequent g4-h4. }
6... c6 { Black hasn't closed the door on playing Be6 after g4. } 7. Bc4
{ We proceed by forcing Black to play e6. } 7... e6 8. g4
{ We strike while the iron is hot. If Black has time for a Nbd7, the position will be bullet-proof. }
8... Bg6
{ Black has a better version than in the line with 6... e6. The difference here is that we don't have a bishop on g2 that covers the e4 escape route for Black's bishop on g6. }
9. h4
{ Our play of harassing the bishop is still extremely effective here, even though we have less control of the square on e4. }
9... Nbd7
{ Has been played by the super GM Michael Adams, among others, but it loses. }
10. f3 { The nail in the coffin. The bishop on g6 has nowhere to go! } 10...
Qc7
{ Is a decent try to complicate things, as there is only one refutation.   10...Nxe5  Doesn't help Black either.  11.dxe5  Qxd1+  12.Kxd1  O-O-O+  13.Bd2!  Close, but no cigar! Black's bishop will now be lost.  13...Nd7  14.h5  Nxe5  15.Be2  The only move, as f3 had to be protected.  15...Bc5  16.Kc1  There are no tricks left, so Black loses a piece. We can even delay the capture unless Black plays f5 or f6. }
11. Qe2
{ It's important to guard e5 . After   11.Bf4  , the bishop escapes after  11...Nxe5  12.Bxe5  Qb6  , as white needs to defend the b2-pawn, giving Black time to play h5 or h6. }
11... Nxe5
{ Was an attempt to gain some counterplay for the piece, but it is far from enough.   11...h6  Black's only hope of saving the bishop.  12.h5  Bh7  13.Nxf7!  Qg3+  14.Kd1  Black could resign in Wei, Y-Wang,R China 2014. }
12. dxe5 Nd7 13. h5 Bxc2 14. Qxc2 Nxe5
{ Black as two pawns, but it doesn't help much. } 15. Be2
{ Black played on for ten more moves, but the position was too far gone in Kovchan,A -Plaskett,H Palma de Mallorca 2015. }
*

