9... Bb4 10. f3
{ Once again this is strong, removing Black's control of the e4-square. } 10...
Nd5 { Is the best attempt to fight for survival. } 11. Bd2
{ 11.Bxd5  is also strong  as we will play h5 next, forcing Black to play f6. After our main move, four moves have been played. }
11... Nb6 { Attacking our pawn on d4. } 12. Bb3 Qxd4 13. Qe2
{ Defending the knight and opening up for the possibility of O-O-O. } 13... Bd6
14. Nxg6 Bg3+ 15. Kf1
{ It doesn't matter that we can't castle. Our king will be very safe on g2. }
15... hxg6 16. Ne4 Rxh4 17. Kg2
{ This is objectively best, but  17.Nxg3  is winning as well of course. } 17...
Rxh1 18. Rxh1
{ Black resigned in Gongora Reyes,M - Monell Camarasa,D Mislata 2007, as Bc3 followed by Rh8+ comes once the bishop moves. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6. Scandinavian (1...d5) 3...Qd8 Retreat"]
[Black "3...Qd8 (5...Bf5 10)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qd8 4. d4 { Grabbing the center as we always do. }
4... Nf6
{ Other moves have been played here, but this logical move is by far the most popular in the position. Black has to play Nf6 at some point anyway, so other options are likely to transpose. }
5. Nf3 Bf5 6. Ne5
{ This reaction is extremely typical and a crucial idea to remember in the Scandinavian. Just like in the 3... Qe5+ line, we're aiming to harass the bishop with a subsequent g4-h4. }
6... c6 { Black hasn't closed the door on playing Be6 after g4. } 7. Bc4
{ We proceed by forcing Black to play e6. } 7... e6 8. g4
{ We strike while the iron is hot. If Black has time for a Nbd7, the position will be bullet-proof. }
8... Bg6
{ Black has a better version than in the line with 6... e6. The difference here is that we don't have a bishop on g2 that covers the e4 escape route for Black's bishop on g6. }
9. h4
{ Our play of harassing the bishop is still extremely effective here, even though we have less control of the square on e4. }
9... Bb4 10. f3
{ Once again this is strong, removing Black's control of the e4-square. } 10...
Nd5 { Is the best attempt to fight for survival. } 11. Bd2 Bxc3
{ The strong GM Laznicka won a game here against GM Ragger with the Black pieces, but that doesn't change the evaluation of the line. }
12. Bxc3 { I prefer the bishop capture. } 12... Ne3
{ Looks scary, but it doesn't work.   12...f6  Is the way to save the bishop.  13.Nxg6  hxg6  14.Qd3  Black is once again left with an awful structure that we can target in the near future. }
13. Qe2 Nxc2+ 14. Kf2 Nxa1 15. h5
{ Black will lose the bishop on g6, along with the knight on a1. } 15... Bxh5
16. gxh5 { The knight on a1 falls. Nxf7 followed by Qxe6 is also a threat. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6. Scandinavian (1...d5) 3...Qd8 Retreat"]
[Black "3...Qd8 (5...Bg4 1)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qd8 4. d4 { Grabbing the center as we always do. }
4... Nf6
{ Other moves have been played here, but this logical move is by far the most popular in the position. Black has to play Nf6 at some point anyway, so other options are likely to transpose. }
5. Nf3 Bg4
{ The most played move by a decent amount, and the main move of the 3... Qd8-line. This has been the choice of IM John Bartholomew, while World Champion Magnus Carlsen defeated GM Fabiano Caruana with it in the Tromsø Olympiad, 2014. The idea is rather simplistic, really. Black wants to take the knight on f3, followed by a set-up that consists of c6, e6, Nbd7 and Bd6/Bb4. Black will then have gotten rid of the bad light-squared bishops, with a pretty rock-solid position. }
6. h3 { More or less forcing Black to give up the bishop pair, as } 6... Bh5
{ more or less loses, to the typical } 7. g4 Bg6 8. Ne5
{ We are likely to transpose to the 5... Bf5-line. } 8... Nbd7 9. Qe2
{ Now Qb5+ will follow if Black decides to take the knight and play Nd5. } 9...
e6 10. Bg2 c6 11. h4
{ Black had to part with the g6-bishop due to the threat of h5, or get an awful pawn structure after   11...h6  12.Nxg6  in Millette, F-Saba, N ICCF email 2014. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6. Scandinavian (1...d5) 3...Qd8 Retreat"]
[Black "3...Qd8 (5...Bg4 2)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qd8 4. d4 { Grabbing the center as we always do. }
4... Nf6
{ Other moves have been played here, but this logical move is by far the most popular in the position. Black has to play Nf6 at some point anyway, so other options are likely to transpose. }
5. Nf3 Bg4 6. h3 { More or less forcing Black to give up the bishop pair, as }
6... Bxf3 7. Qxf3 c6 8. Be3 e6
{ GM Wesley So points out that White is scoring really well in the Correspondence database here, with a whopping 83%. He explains further that this opening is mostly played as an opening surprise, while ideas are rather easy to remember. I certainly agree with all of his points. The other side of the coin, as Welsey also points out, is that it seems that White gets a risk-free advantage with the bishop pair. One must remember that the Correspondence games are a decent indicator of how good a line objectively is. If White has such a decent score, the line can't be sound. }
9. Bd3
{ We now have the option of castling to either side. Black is doing fairly okay after   9.O-O-O  Bb4  10.Ne4  Nxe4  11.Qxe4  Qd5  allows Black to equalize. }
9... Qa5
{ Is an interesting move. Black is more or less preventing us from castling to the left side, but that's not a problem. }
10. O-O
{ Castling kingside is also good for us. Now that Black won't be under attack anytime soon, we must change our strategy. I like the idea of strengthening the center with Ne2 where it can potentially jump to g3, followed by c4, seizing control of the center. }
10... Nbd7
{ 10...Bd6?  Would allow a fun trick.  11.Nb5!  Be7  The bishop is forced to move back to e7, as the knight couldn't be captured due to Qxb7.  12.Bf4  Na6  Was played in the game Vrban,M - Perez Prieto,G Calvia 2006, when I think the move  13.a3  Would have been best.  13...Qd8  14.Nc3  O-O  15.Ne2  Protecting g4, while we can go for c4 next, followed by Be3-Rad1-Nc3 and eventually d5. }
11. a3
{ This move is always sensible, going for a potential b4 in the near future, while occupying the b4-square. }
11... Bd6 12. Rfe1 O-O 13. Rad1
{ Just simple logical moves, bringing our rooks into the game. } 13... Rfe8 14.
g4
{ Now that all of our pieces are in ideal places we can start expanding on the kingside. }
