1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qd8 4. d4 { Grabbing the center as we always do. }
4... Nf6
{ Other moves have been played here, but this logical move is by far the most popular in the position. Black has to play Nf6 at some point anyway, so other options are likely to transpose. }
5. Nf3 Bg4 6. h3 { More or less forcing Black to give up the bishop pair, as }
6... Bxf3 7. Qxf3 c6 8. Be3 e6
{ GM Wesley So points out that White is scoring really well in the Correspondence database here, with a whopping 83%. He explains further that this opening is mostly played as an opening surprise, while ideas are rather easy to remember. I certainly agree with all of his points. The other side of the coin, as Welsey also points out, is that it seems that White gets a risk-free advantage with the bishop pair. One must remember that the Correspondence games are a decent indicator of how good a line objectively is. If White has such a decent score, the line can't be sound. }
9. Bd3
{ We now have the option of castling to either side. Black is doing fairly okay after   9.O-O-O  Bb4  10.Ne4  Nxe4  11.Qxe4  Qd5  allows Black to equalize. }
9... Nbd7 10. O-O-O
{ Once again, queenside castling is on the table. This is the way to punish Black for his rather passive play in the opening, as it's rather difficult to get counterplay when one's pieces are inactive. }
10... Nb6
{ Played in most of the games, for good reason as it is rather logical. Black develops the bishop and is 'threatening' to destroy our pawn structure, forcing us to move our knight.   10...Qa5  is too late now, as we can simply play  11.Kb1  , when our initiative will be really strong. }
11. Kb1
{ This side-step is almost always a good idea, as the pawn on a2 is no longer hanging. }
11... Bd6 12. Bc1 { Preparing to start an attack with h4-g4-g5. } 12... Nbd5
13. Nxd5 Nxd5 14. c4 Nb4 15. Be2
{ Black's incredibly passive here, and probably has to castle queenside. In the game Moreto Quintana - Saevich,Y ICCF email 2016, Black decided to go for a miserable endgame with }
15... Qf6 16. Qxf6 gxf6 17. Bh5 Rg8 18. Rhe1 Ke7 19. Bf3
{ Black was incredibly passive and objectively lost. It's instructive to see how White takes his point home, so I'll leave the game as a Clickable.  19...Rad8  20.Re4  Kd7  21.Rh4  Rh8  22.Rh6  Be7  23.a3  Na6  24.Be3  Kc7  25.Bh5  Rdf8  26.Ka2  b6  27.b4  Nb8  28.d5  cxd5  29.cxd5  exd5  30.Bf4+  Bd6  31.Rc1+  Kd7  32.Bg4+  Ke7  33.Re1+  Be5  34.Bg3  Kd8  35.Bh4  Nd7  36.Rxe5  Nxe5  37.Bxf6+  Ke8  38.Bxe5  Rhg8  39.Bd6  Rxg4  40.hxg4  Rg8  41.Bb8  Black had had enough and resigned. }
