[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6. Scandinavian (1...d5) 3...Qd8 Retreat"]
[Black "3...Qd8 (5...Bg4 9)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qd8 4. d4 { Grabbing the center as we always do. }
4... Nf6
{ Other moves have been played here, but this logical move is by far the most popular in the position. Black has to play Nf6 at some point anyway, so other options are likely to transpose. }
5. Nf3 Bg4 6. h3 { More or less forcing Black to give up the bishop pair, as }
6... Bxf3 7. Qxf3 c6 8. Be3 e6
{ GM Wesley So points out that White is scoring really well in the Correspondence database here, with a whopping 83%. He explains further that this opening is mostly played as an opening surprise, while ideas are rather easy to remember. I certainly agree with all of his points. The other side of the coin, as Welsey also points out, is that it seems that White gets a risk-free advantage with the bishop pair. One must remember that the Correspondence games are a decent indicator of how good a line objectively is. If White has such a decent score, the line can't be sound. }
9. Bd3
{ We now have the option of castling to either side. Black is doing fairly okay after   9.O-O-O  Bb4  10.Ne4  Nxe4  11.Qxe4  Qd5  allows Black to equalize. }
9... Nbd7 10. O-O-O
{ Once again, queenside castling is on the table. This is the way to punish Black for his rather passive play in the opening, as it's rather difficult to get counterplay when one's pieces are inactive. }
10... Bb4 11. Ne2
{ It's better to keep the knights on the board as we're going for an attack.  11...O-O  is really risky, as our attack is really strong after g4  , followed by g5-h4. }
11... Nd5
{ I think getting rid of our bishop pair is the best thing Black can come up with in the position. }
12. Kb1 { Once again we will play this prophylactic move. } 12... Nxe3
{ 12...Bd6  13.Bd2  b5  Black can try to start an attack himself, but as we do not have any weaknesses, the chance of it succeeding is very slim.  14.g4  a5  15.g5  a4  16.h4  b4  17.Rde1  I don't see Black getting through, as a3 can always be countered by b3, and vise-versa. }
13. fxe3 Qe7 { Black is going for queenside castling. } 14. Rhf1 Rf8 15. e4
O-O-O
{ This position occurred in an e-mail game between Landers Rodriguez, J - Tedesco, M 2018. }
16. c3 Bd6
{ 16...Ba5  is met my the double attack  17.Qh5  , when the bishop and pawn on h7 are under attack. }
17. e5 Bc7 { We need to be prepared against Black's f6-break. } 18. Nf4
{ Our knight here is flexible as it attacks e6, while it also can jump to h5 in some instances but Black would have to lose control of the f6-square first. }
18... f6
{ I don't think Black should delay the break, as we can often put our bishop on c4, when f6 will no longer be available. }
19. Qg4 { This is the reason why our scheme works. } 19... Rde8
{ This is rather cunning from Black, but stepping into the 'trap' with   19...fxe5?  This doesn't work well for Black after  20.Nxe6  Rxf1  21.Rxf1  Not only is Black losing a pawn, but our active pieces should be decisive in the endgame. }
20. Bxh7 { This is still the best way to go. } 20... g5
{ Is Black's point as our bishop and knight are both under attack. } 21. Nxe6
Qxh7+
{ 21...Qxe6  would lose after  22.Bf5  , when we will play d5 next, opening up the d-file. We will win the knight on d7 , with a winning position. }
22. Ka1 Rxe6
{ Black is more or less forced to do this as for example   22...Rf7  is met by  23.Nxc7  followed by e6 . If Black removes the rook from the f-file, we will grab the pawn on f6 with a completely winning position. }
23. Qxe6
{ Our two pawns and extra rook are stronger than Black's minor pieces. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6. Scandinavian (1...d5) 3...Qd8 Retreat"]
[Black "3...Qd8 (5...Bg4 10)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qd8 4. d4 { Grabbing the center as we always do. }
4... Nf6
{ Other moves have been played here, but this logical move is by far the most popular in the position. Black has to play Nf6 at some point anyway, so other options are likely to transpose. }
5. Nf3 Bg4 6. h3 { More or less forcing Black to give up the bishop pair, as }
6... Bxf3 7. Qxf3 c6 8. Be3 e6
{ GM Wesley So points out that White is scoring really well in the Correspondence database here, with a whopping 83%. He explains further that this opening is mostly played as an opening surprise, while ideas are rather easy to remember. I certainly agree with all of his points. The other side of the coin, as Welsey also points out, is that it seems that White gets a risk-free advantage with the bishop pair. One must remember that the Correspondence games are a decent indicator of how good a line objectively is. If White has such a decent score, the line can't be sound. }
9. Bd3
{ We now have the option of castling to either side. Black is doing fairly okay after   9.O-O-O  Bb4  10.Ne4  Nxe4  11.Qxe4  Qd5  allows Black to equalize. }
9... Nbd7 10. O-O-O
{ Once again, queenside castling is on the table. This is the way to punish Black for his rather passive play in the opening, as it's rather difficult to get counterplay when one's pieces are inactive. }
10... Bb4 11. Ne2
{ It's better to keep the knights on the board as we're going for an attack.  11...O-O  is really risky, as our attack is really strong after g4  , followed by g5-h4. }
11... Nd5
{ I think getting rid of our bishop pair is the best thing Black can come up with in the position. }
12. Kb1 { Once again we will play this prophylactic move. } 12... Nxe3
{ 12...Bd6  13.Bd2  b5  Black can try to start an attack himself, but as we do not have any weaknesses, the chance of it succeeding is very slim.  14.g4  a5  15.g5  a4  16.h4  b4  17.Rde1  I don't see Black getting through, as a3 can always be countered by b3, and vise-versa. }
13. fxe3 Qe7 { Black is going for queenside castling. } 14. Rhf1 Rf8 15. e4
O-O-O
{ This position occurred in an e-mail game between Landers Rodriguez, J - Tedesco, M 2018. }
16. c3 Bd6
{ 16...Ba5  is met my the double attack  17.Qh5  , when the bishop and pawn on h7 are under attack. }
17. e5 Bc7 { We need to be prepared against Black's f6-break. } 18. Nf4
{ Our knight here is flexible as it attacks e6, while it also can jump to h5 in some instances but Black would have to lose control of the f6-square first. }
18... f6
{ I don't think Black should delay the break, as we can often put our bishop on c4, when f6 will no longer be available. }
19. Qg4 { This is the reason why our scheme works. } 19... f5
{ This move is not what Black intended, but it looks like it's the best move. }
20. Qe2 g5 { Black should chase away our knight on f4. } 21. Nh5 c5
{ Makes the most amount of sense to me, since it applies some pressure against our beautiful pawn chain.   21...Nb6  22.g4  f4  23.Be4  White is in full control. Whenever Black plays Nd5, we will respond by taking the knight. One plan forward is to play h4 to open up the h-file. We will certainly jump to f6 in the future with our knight as well. }
22. Bc2
{ I like the idea of putting the bishop on b3 where it will be a thorn in Black's side. }
22... Kb8 23. Bb3
{ Recapture with the bishop, intending to put it on f3 next.   CONCLUSION: Qd8 is a move that has existed forever, but it doesn't look like that it has stood the test of time. IM John Bartholomew has made this line his pet line, having an excellent score with the black pieces. The appeal is the lack of theory, simple plans, and excellent pawn structure, meaning that if White does not play critically, Black will get a rather comfortable game. Let's get to the different lines:   After the move of Bf5, it's important to remember the idea of playing Ne5, followed by g4, and a subsequent h4/f4, harassing the bishop. This idea pops up CONSTANTLY in the Scandinavian. Black is doing rather terribly here, and could quite possibly be objectively lost already.   The new move 5...g6 has been played by a lot of super-GMs, as it is not well-known and the moves for Black are rather simple. After our plan of attack with Bf4-Qd2-O-O-O, I think Black is struggling, as clearly indicated by our coverage. One massive pro is that we almost always play the same attacking moves, with the major goal of opening up the h-file, delivering checkmate. I suggest that you do study this line carefully though, as my gut feeling is that this line will take over from the standard Bg4, in the future.   It's not surprising that Bg4 is the most popular move. Black gets rid of the bad light-squared bishop, leaving him with an extremely solid pawn structure. On the surface, this looks appealing, but the resulting positions tell a different story. I suggest going for Be3, but the interesting pawn sacrifice primarily in shorter time controls 2.g4!? is also worth looking at. As we proceed through the line, I like leaving our options open with Bd3, when we can castle to both sides, depending on what Black does. There are many different ways to continue for Black, but most of them can be met by a rather unpleasant pawn storm on the kingside. The most popular path forward has been to play Nbd7, followed by Bb4, gaining a tempo on our knight. Black really needs to play actively, otherwise, our initiative takes over quite rapidly. Grabbing our bishop pair is the best way to fight for equality, but I would definitely not be satisfied with the black pieces. White's position is objectively much better and rather simple to play if you ask me. Black is simply too passive, which is the reason why the Correspondence score is that low. Therefore, like most rare lines, Qd8 remains a good surprise weapon, but against a prepared player, Black will have a hard time. }
*

