1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qd6 4. d4
{ We will once again take control of the center. } 4... c6 5. Nf3 Bf5
{ Tiviakov has played this twice, so we should take a look. } 6. Nh4
{ Chasing the bishop away. } 6... Be6
{ Does not make so much sense to me, but it was played by a strong GM among others. }
7. Be2 Nf6 8. O-O g6
{ Now that Black has a bishop on e6, the bishop on f8 has to be developed by this means. }
9. f4
{ Is a great move, utilizing the knight on h4. f5 followed by Bf4 is now a really annoying idea to meet. }
9... Bg7 10. f5 Bd5 11. Bf4 { Gaining a tempo on the queen. } 11... Qd8 12. Bd3
{ Is an improvement over the Correspondence Game Schieferdecker,M - Schaffarth,P GER email 2017. }
12... Qb6 { Is the most critical move, which we can meet with } 13. Qe1 Qxd4+
{ And now we have to play } 14. Kh1
{ Black's queen is rather exposed and he needs to be prepared for a possible Na4 followed by c4, when the bishop on d5 will be trapped. }
14... Nbd7 15. Rd1 { Forcing the queen to move away. } 15... Qb4
{ Otherwise Na4 followed by c4 will come. } 16. fxg6 fxg6 17. Nxg6
{ Wins for White after } 17... hxg6 18. Nxd5
{ Getting rid of the defender on d5. } 18... Nxd5 19. Bxg6+ Kd8 20. Qe6
{ Black's busted. Our initiative is far too strong with ideas like Bf5, Rd3/ Rf3-Rb3, b3-c4, etc. We may also move our bishop to g3 so we can play Rf7 or Rf3-b3. }
