1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qd6 4. d4
{ We will once again take control of the center. } 4... Nf6 5. Nf3 Bg4 6. h3
{ Hitting the bishop is once again the best. } 6... Bxf3 7. Qxf3 Nc6
{ 7...c6  Should hopefully give you deja vu after  8.Bf4!   8...Qxd4  will now transpose to previously covered lines. Not grabbing the pawn by playing something like  8...Qd8  is just extremely passive. If the reader is interested in complications check out Horvath, R - Fauland, P Deutschlandsberg 2018. }
8. Bf4 { The complications work out for us. } 8... Qe6+ 9. Be3
{ It's important to protect d4. } 9... O-O-O 10. O-O-O Nb4
{ And here, we have the great resource } 11. d5 Nfxd5
{ 11...Nbxd5  is simply met by  12.Bc4  , when we can take on 12...a6 next. }
12. a3
{ Forcing Black to open up the position when his king will be in peril.   12.Bc4?  would be an error, as Black has the move  12...Qg6! }
12... Nxe3
{ Is the most critical move, when we should play   12...Nxc3  13.Rxd8+  Kxd8  14.axb4  Now we are attacking b7, so Black has to play  14...Ne4  15.Bd3  f5  16.Rd1  Kc8  17.Kb1  Preventing any kind of Qa2-nonsense in the future. Black is more or less completely lost due to his passive pieces and weak king. }
13. Rxd8+ Kxd8 14. Qxb7 { We're in no hurry to take any of the knights. } 14...
Nxf1
{ 14...Qf5  may look scary, but we have  15.Qa8+  followed by Bb5+ and Ba4 , guarding the mate threat on c2 . }
15. Rxf1
{ Black has to give up the knight on b4 with Nd3+, otherwise he will suffer decisive loss of material or get mated, after Rd1+. }
