1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qd6 4. d4
{ We will once again take control of the center. } 4... Nf6 5. Nf3 c6 6. h3
Nbd7 { Is another alternative, but again, I think it's awfully passive. } 7.
Bd3 { From here, Black can complete the development in two days. } 7... g6
{ The advantage with this move is that it blocks our bishop on d3, meaning that Black's king will be safe for now. This doesn't mean that the set-up is good, though. }
8. O-O Bg7 9. Re1 O-O 10. Be3
{ This time I like placing the bishop on e3 as it makes it harder for Black to carry out the move c5. }
10... Nb6
{ Has been played twice, but it doesn't look good to me.   10...e5  Black sacrifices a pawn with this break in the center.  11.dxe5  Nxe5  12.Nxe5  I think the simplest way to proceed is to grab the pawn. 12. Bf4 is also strong, though.  12...Qxe5  13.Bxa7  Looks like a clean pawn up to me. }
11. Qd2 Be6
{ Black wants to play Nc4 and may finish the development with moves like Rad8 and Rfe8.   11...Nbd5  12.Nxd5  Nxd5  13.Bg5  Black's position is a sad sight. }
12. Bf4 Qd8 13. b3
{ Preventing Black's idea. Another pro is that we support the move of c4, which we will surely play whenever we get the chance. }
13... Nbd5 14. Nxd5 Bxd5 15. Ne5 { The knight is well placed on e5. } 15... Be6
16. Bf1 { A good way of defending the pawn on d4. } 16... Rc8 17. c4
{ Kosintseva had done everything right so far, and she went on to win a really nice game in Kosintseva,T - Khairullin,I Kazan 2001. Black's position was really passive, so it's not surprising that he collapsed rather quickly. }
