[Black "3...Qd6 (5...c6 5)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qd6 4. d4
{ We will once again take control of the center. } 4... Nf6 5. Nf3 c6 6. h3 Bf5
{ Now that the bishop can't be placed on g4, it has to be placed on f5. If Black doesn't do it now, we will play Bd3 when Black will have problems with the c8-bishop, as we saw in the alternative variations. Therefore, it's not surprising that this is the best and most played response. After this move, White has many good options up his sleeve... }
7. g3
{ This move has not been tested much in practice. The idea is simple enough. We want to develop our bishop to g2, and grab the bishop pair with a knight jump to h4. Having the bishop pair and slightly more space gives us a comfortable edge that seems rather risk-free to me, meaning that it's a great practical weapon. 7. Ne5 is a more direct and perhaps the most testing option, but I was unable to find a convincing edge, making it pointless to give it as an alternative. }
7... Nbd7
{ Black keeps the e6-square available to the bishop if he decides to wait with e6. In addition, he also keeps the option open of playing e5 in one go. }
8. Nh4 Be6
{ Black wants to play Bc4 whenever we decide to play Bg2, to prevent us from castling. }
9. Bg2 Bc4
{ The only move that makes sense. Otherwise, we will simply castle and Black would have wasted a lot of time. }
10. b3 Ba6 11. Ne2 Qb4+
{ 11...Bxe2  is simply met by  12.Kxe2  , when we will play Re1 and Kf1 next. }
12. c3 Bxe2 13. Qc2
{ We must protect the pawn on c3 before we capture the bishop. } 13... Qb5
{ 13...Bd1  is met by  14.Kxd1  , when we can once again place our king on f1 in the near future with moves like c4-Ke2-Rd1-Kf1. }
14. Qxe2 Qxe2+ 15. Kxe2
{ We have reached a comfortable endgame where the bishop pair plays a huge role in White's clear advantage. }
