1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qd6 4. d4
{ We will once again take control of the center. } 4... Nf6 5. Nf3 c6 6. h3 Bf5
{ Now that the bishop can't be placed on g4, it has to be placed on f5. If Black doesn't do it now, we will play Bd3 when Black will have problems with the c8-bishop, as we saw in the alternative variations. Therefore, it's not surprising that this is the best and most played response. After this move, White has many good options up his sleeve... }
7. g3 Nbd7
{ Black keeps the e6-square available to the bishop if he decides to wait with e6. In addition, he also keeps the option open of playing e5 in one go.   7...h6  Definitely makes sense, because the bishop now gets a square on h7.  8.Bf4  There is no reason not to play this move, as we get an extra tempo on the queen while developing a piece.  8...Qd8  9.g4  As Black has lost valuable time, we should aim for an attack.  9...Bh7  10.Bd3  Bxd3  11.Qxd3  e6  12.O-O-O  Black is soon going to be under a dangerous attack. }
8. Nh4 Qe6+
{ Is the engine's favorite move it should be noted that  9.Be2  loses the h3-pawn. }
9. Be3 Nb6
{ Blacks wants to castle long and get a decent grip on the d5-square. } 10.
Nxf5 Qxf5 11. Bd3
{ We have obtained the bishop pair, but Black has a really sold position. }
11... Qe6 12. Qe2
{ Making sure that we can meet a knight jump to d5 with Bd2, while also preparing to castle queenside. }
12... g6
{ Black has to develop the bishop to g7 now that the queen stands in the way on e6. }
13. O-O-O Bg7 14. Bd2 { Avoiding Nfd5 with a tempo. } 14... Qxe2
{ Black should head into the endgame. } 15. Nxe2 O-O-O 16. Rhe1
{ Our bishop pair yields us a slight edge, but Black is incredibly solid. } *

