[White "7. Scandinavian (1...d5) 3...Qd6"]
[Black "3...Qd6 (5...g6 1)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qd6 4. d4
{ We will once again take control of the center. } 4... Nf6 5. Nf3 g6
{ This move was not played very much until GM Vladimir Kramnik picked it up in top-level play in 2009. Since then, it has been played by tons of world-class players, including GM Fabiano Caruana and World Champion Magnus Carlsen. I suspect it has become popular due to the fact that it isn't so well-known, meaning that the theory doesn't run deep. Black's moves are also simple. He plans to castle kingside and later on he will place the pieces in positions entirely dependent on White's set-up. These points are rather appealing to higher-rated players who want to 'get a position' and outplay the opponent from there. }
6. Bg5
{ The downside to 5... g6 is that Black weakens his kingside. Therefore, similar to the g6-line in 3... Qd8, I suggest going for an attack. 6. Nb5 has been the most common response, which is more of a positional approach. }
6... Bf5 { Is Black's only attempt to spoil our plan as Ne4 might soon come. }
7. Qd2 Ne4 8. Nxe4 Bxe4
{ Now that Black is threatening to destroy our pawn structure with Bxf3, O-O-O is not so appealing any longer. I suggest going for }
9. Bf4 Qb6 10. Be2
{ We've changed our plan of castling queenside, but this is still very effective. }
10... Bg7
{ Black doesn't have time for  10...Qxb2  We will simply castle with a fantastic initiative. }
11. O-O O-O { Is probably best, but can be countered with } 12. Ng5 Bf5 13. c3
{ Defending two pawns at the same time. The pawn on d4 and the pawn on b2. }
13... Nc6
{ 13...c5  Is an attempt to fight against our center, when we have the move  14.g4!  Putting Black in a position of passivity.  14...Bc8  15.d5  It won't be easy for Black to finish his development, giving us a massive edge. }
14. g4 { Once again removing Black's active bishop on f5. } 14... Bc8 15. Be3
{ Not only is d5 now a threat, we're also going to expand our central control by the likes of Rfe1/ Rae1 and f4. The knight can always move to e4 if Black plays h6. Black's position is really unpleasant due to the passive pieces and lack of control in the center. }
