{ We've changed our plan of castling queenside, but this is still very effective. }
10... Bg7 11. O-O Qxb2
{ I originally intended to barely mention this move, but it turned out to be a lot trickier than what I expected. }
12. Qe3 Bc6
{ The engine likes a lot of moves here, but I think the best option is } 13.
Bg5 { Threatening mate, but also intending to meet O-O with Bxe7. } 13... O-O
{ 13...e6  This move is objectively worse than O-O, but it requires us to play with precision.  14.Rab1  Qxa2  Is no better, when our refutation is  15.d5!  The point is that Qxd5 fails to Rbd1/Rfd1, since the queen can't move due to the mating threat on d8 .  15...Bxd5  16.Qc5  The mating threat on e7 is deadly.  16...Nc6   16...f6  is slightly better, but it allows  17.Ra1  which will trap Black's queen.  17.Rxb7  White is completely winning due to the fact that   17...Bf8  is refuted by the simple  18.Qc3  . }
14. Bxe7 Re8 { This would have worked for Black if it wasn't for } 15. Bc4
{ We're now threatening to take on f7 followed by Ng5. The threat of Bf6 is also parried due to the fact that we can play Qf4. }
15... Bxf3 16. Qxf3 { Sacrificing the bishop on e7 for a brief moment. } 16...
Rxe7 17. Rab1
{ White wins material, as  17...Qxc2  18.Qxb7  comes next followed by Qxa8 . It doesn't help Black that the bishop on c4 is hanging as the knight on b8 falls after Qxa8 . }
