Bf5 { Is Black's only attempt to spoil our plan as Ne4 might soon come. } 7.
Qd2 Ne4 8. Nxe4 Bxe4
{ Now that Black is threatening to destroy our pawn structure with Bxf3, O-O-O is not so appealing any longer. I suggest going for }
9. Bf4 Qb6 10. Be2
{ We've changed our plan of castling queenside, but this is still very effective. }
10... Bg7
{ Black doesn't have time for  10...Qxb2  . We will simply castle with a fantastic initiative.  Qe3, Rab1 and c4 might come. }
11. O-O Qxb2
{ I originally intended to barely mention this move, but it turned out to be a lot trickier than what I expected. }
12. Qe3 Bc6
{ The engine likes a lot of moves here, but I think the best option is } 13.
Bg5 { Threatening mate, but also intending to meet O-O with Bxe7. } 13... e6
{ This move is objectively worse than O-O, but it requires us to play with precision. }
14. Rab1 Qxc2 15. Rfc1 Qe4
{ 15...Qxa2  is met by  16.d5!  similar to 14...Qxa2. } 16. Qa3 Bf8
{ Black's best bet.  16...f6  is lost after  17.Bc4  when  Re1  will come and Black's king will be blasted open. }
17. Qb3
{ This might not look so dangerous for Black, but our plan of Bd3-Bc4- followed by d5 is so dangerous that the position is just lost. }
17... Bg7
{ Black is not in time to castle as we can respond with   17...Qxe2  This move loses to a fantastic sequence:  18.Re1  Once the queen moves, we can take on e6.  18...Qb5  19.Rxe6+  Kd7  Otherwise Black gets mated.  20.Re8  A mind-blowing move, threatening Rd8#. If Black takes the rook, we can play Qe3+, followed by Rxb5 and Ne5+. If Black takes our queen he is mated after Rd8+ and Re1+ next. Therefore, a resignation is appropriate. }
18. Bd3 Qd5 19. Bc4 Qd7
{ This is the best way to counter our d5-idea, but it still leads to a hopeless position after }
20. Ne5 { 20.d5  is still good, but the text move is a lot stronger. } 20...
Qd6 21. Re1 { Now Nxf7 is a decisive blow. } 21... O-O 22. Nxf7
{ A beautiful blow which is tactically justified. } 22... Rxf7 23. Bxe6
{ Black loses decisive material.  23...Qf8  is met by  d5  , when the pawn on  b7  falls if the bishop moves.   23...Be8  is met by  24.Bd5  , followed by  Rxe8  and  Bxf7  . }
