1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qd6 4. d4
{ We will once again take control of the center. } 4... Nf6 5. Nf3 g6 6. Bg5
Bg7 7. Qd2 a6
{ Has been played a few times, which is not surprising as Black wants to create an attack himself against our king.   7...O-O  8.O-O-O  Black now needs to make an important decision, as indeed, there are many different ways to proceed.  8...c6  9.Bf4  Qd8  In an interesting twist of fate, we've transposed to 3... Qd8. We saw that Giri played 10. Bh6, but my suggestion was  10.Kb1!  You can find this position analyzed in the 3... Qd8 chapter, under 8... c6 in the 5... g6 section. }
8. Bf4 { I like this move, posing Black's queen a question. } 8... Qb6
{ Was played by the strong GM Kurajica, who has been an avid Scandinavian player. }
9. Bc4
{ I like this active developing move, but other moves like O-O-O and Ne5 were also good. }
9... O-O 10. O-O Bg4 11. Ne5 Nc6
{ In Kovalevskaya, E - Kurajica, B Solin 2005, White prevailed with the move Nxg4 , but she should have played }
12. h3 { which is a useful move that gains a tempo on the bishop. } 12... Bf5
13. Rad1
{ Protecting d4 while also threatening to play Na4 followed by Nc6, when Black's pawn structure will be completely destroyed. }
13... Nxe5
{ 13...Rad8  allows us to carry out our plan with  14.Na4  , as the pawn on d4 can't be captured due to Nxc6 . }
14. dxe5 Ne4 15. Nxe4 Bxe4
{ Black has managed to trade off some pieces, meaning that our pressure has been slightly diminished. However, we have control of the d-file which gives us an edge. }
16. Rfe1 Qc6 17. Bf1
{ If Black lets us, we will play c4 followed by b3 next, which will quickly lead to a dominating position. }
