{ Black is awfully passive with a weak pawn on h4 , which will fall sooner or later. a6 is likely to come, when we can choose between putting our bishop on d3 or f1 .  Black's only hope is to get counterplay against our pawn on d5, but it won't be easy to achieve. }
1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qd6 4. d4
{ We will once again take control of the center. } 4... Nf6 5. Nf3 g6 6. Bg5
Bg7 7. Qd2 O-O 8. O-O-O
{ Black now needs to make an important decision, as indeed, there are many different ways to proceed. }
8... Bf5
{ Just like in the 3... Qd8-line, this developing move makes some sense. } 9.
Bf4
{ This move is once again logical, putting the queen in an inferior position. }
9... Qb6 10. Ne5
{ This active move is clearly the best way forward. Otherwise Black will be doing fairly well after Nc6, with decent activity. }
10... Nc6
{ 10...c5  Is possible, but nothing to worry about.  11.d5  Taking away the c6-square for the knight.  11...Nbd7  12.Nc4  Forcing the queen back to d8.  12...Qd8  13.Bh6  We have a rather dangerous attack which looks difficult to stop. Another intention is to take on g7 followed by Ne3, which is really annoying for Black. }
11. Nxc6
{ 11.Nc4  Qa6  wasn't so clear in Davidavicius, R - Fels, B ICCF email 2013. }
11... bxc6
{ My engine prefers to open up the d-file, while also taking control of the d5-square.   11...Qxc6  12.d5  This move is important, grabbing space while pushing the queen to an inferior square.  12...Qd7  13.f3  We shouldn't give Black the option of playing Ne4. In addition, we are now threatening to trap the bishop with g4, meaning that the move  13...h5  14.h3  Is a good response, forcing the pawn advance.  14...h4  And now, we can maintain pressure.  15.Bb5  Qc8  16.Rhe1 }
12. Na4 { Black's weak pawn structure has given us a nice square on c5. } 12...
Qb7 13. Nc5 { There's no reason not to play this move. } 13... Qb6 14. Bc4
{ Our bishop is well placed on c4, as we can easily block Black's counterplay on the queenside by the means of Bb3-a4. }
14... Rab8 15. Bb3
{ Black's counterplay is nonexistent. Our plan forward is rather simple as we will continue our attack with Bh6. Rhe1 is also a logical way forward, when f3-g4 may follow suit.  The engine thinks that   15....Nd7  is the only way to avoid a lost position, when we can take and play  16.Bh6 }
