{ 9.Bd3  was played in Gashimov, V - Kramnik, V Moscow 2009, when Kramnik had already equalized after  9...Bg4  . The game continued  10.Ne4  Nxe4  11.Bxe4  Qe6  12.Qf4  , when  12...f6  already would have been a decisive. Still, GM Gashimov soon resigned as he blundered two moves later.  13.Bh6  , and White resigned. }
9... Qd8
{ I somehow forgot to cover this in the 3... Qd8-line, as I found no games from that move order. }
10. Ne5
{ I really like this knight jump as it prevents Bg4 and gives us the option of a quick h5-launch by the means of Be2. }
10... b5
{ Black should go for counterplay as soon as possible.   10...Nbd7  is met by  11.Be2  , when we can soon carry out our plan of playing h4-h5. }
11. h4 { We have no time to lose. } 11... h5
{ Is always a typical 'human response,' whenever h4 is on the board. } 12. Bh6
Bb7
{ Is the most logical response if you ask me.   My engine likes  12...c5  but we can simply take on g7 and then take the pawn, followed by Qe3, with a clean pawn up. }
13. Bxg7 Kxg7 14. Bd3
{ Black has problems with the pawn on g6, as Qg5 soon will come. } 14... Nbd7
15. Qg5
{ The knight will soon come to f4, when I doubt Black will survive for long. }
