1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qd6 4. d4
{ We will once again take control of the center. } 4... Nf6 5. Nf3 g6 6. Bg5
Bg7 7. Qd2 O-O 8. O-O-O
{ Black now needs to make an important decision, as indeed, there are many different ways to proceed. }
8... a6 { Has been the most popular move, and played by GM Kramnik in 2009. }
9. Bf4
{ 9.Bd3  was played in Gashimov, V - Kramnik, V Moscow 2009, when Kramnik had already equalized after  9...Bg4  . The game continued  10.Ne4  Nxe4  11.Bxe4  Qe6  12.Qf4  , when  12...f6  already would have been a decisive. Still, GM Gashimov soon resigned as he blundered two moves later.  13.Bh6  , and White resigned. }
9... Qb6
{ The upside is that the queen is more active on b6, making moves like c5 possible. The downside is that it's harder to get the desired counterplay on the queenside with b5. }
10. Ne5
{ This is definitely a sensible move. Our knight stands firm on the e5-square, while we now can play f3-g4, Be2-Bf3, or chase away the queen with Nc4. In addition, we do apply pressure on f7 so Black can't really play Rd8 now due to Bc4. }
10... Nc6 11. Nc4
{ I like that we push back Black's pieces. That being said,  11.f3  was also decent. }
11... Qa7 12. d5 Nd8
{ The only move that doesn't lead to a lost position.  12...b5  was played in a blitz game, but it looks awful after  13.dxc6  bxc4  14.Be3!  It's important to insert this move before we take the pawn on c4 , as we prevent Qc5 }
13. Be3 Qb8 14. Be2 b5 { Black is finally able to play b5. } 15. Ne5 b4
{ I don't think this move achieves so much. Also worth considering:   15...c5  16.f4  Nb7  17.Bf3  White can't complain after the opening. }
16. Na4 Ne4 17. Qd4 Nd6 18. f4
{ We must reinforce our control on the e5-square. } 18... Nf5
{ I don't think Black should wait with grabbing the bishop pair. } 19. Qe4 Nxe3
20. Qxe3 Qa7 { I don't really see what else Black can do here. } 21. Qxa7 Rxa7
22. Bf3
{ The resulting endgame doesn't look fun for Black with passive pieces and a silly rook on a7. }
