8... a6 { Has been the most popular move, and played by GM Kramnik in 2009. }
9. Bf4
{ 9.Bd3  was played in Gashimov, V - Kramnik, V Moscow 2009, when Kramnik had already equalized after  9...Bg4  . The game continued  10.Ne4  Nxe4  11.Bxe4  Qe6  12.Qf4  , when  12...f6  already would have been a decisive. Still, GM Gashimov soon resigned as he blundered two moves later.  13.Bh6  , and White resigned. }
9... Qb6
{ The upside is that the queen is more active on b6, making moves like c5 possible. The downside is that it's harder to get the desired counterplay on the queenside with b5. }
10. Ne5
{ This is definitely a sensible move. Our knight stands firm on the e5-square, while we now can play f3-g4, Be2-Bf3, or chase away the queen with Nc4. In addition, we do apply pressure on f7 so Black can't really play Rd8 now due to Bc4. }
10... Nbd7
{ The knight is better placed here since it supports the c5-break, while it can no longer be attacked with d5. }
11. Be2 { We continue with our attacking plan of playing h4-h5. } 11... c5
{ Black needs to play actively. } 12. Nc4 Qa7 13. Bf3
{ Making sure that b5 is not possible. } 13... cxd4 14. Qxd4 Qxd4 15. Rxd4
{ The course of the game has changed now that we have reached an endgame. If we are allowed to play Rhd1 next, we will soon get an overwhelming initiative as Black is incredibly passive. Black needs to act fast. }
15... Nh5
{ I think every human would play this move.   15...e5!?  Is an interesting pawn sacrifice to create counterplay.  16.Nxe5  Nh5  Is Black's point.  17.Bxh5  Nxe5  18.Be2  Black has gotten some activity, but I don't think it justifies the missing pawn.  18...Nc6  19.Rd2  Bxc3  Black has to take the knight, otherwise Nd5 will come when Black will be dead lost.  20.bxc3  Be6  21.a4  Rac8  Black has some counterplay against our double pawns.  22.Bd6  Rfe8  23.Rhd1  Na5  And now it's important that we play  24.Bb4  Protecting the pawn.  24...Nc4  25.Rd4  Black is not lost yet, but needs to fight tooth and nail in order to save the game. }
16. Be3
{ We are forced to give away the exchange, but we get a fantastic initiative in return. }
16... Bxd4 17. Bxd4 Nhf6 { The knight has fulfilled its duty and heads back. }
18. a4 { Preventing b5. } 18... h5
{ Black doesn't have many moves here, as the knight is forced to stay on d7 due to Nb6. }
19. a5 { Fixing the pawn structure. } 19... Re8
{ Black's only plan is to play e5-e4, blocking the bishop on f3. } 20. Rd1
{ We don't really need to worry about Black's plan. } 20... e5 21. Be3 e4 22.
Be2
{ Black doesn't have anything to do. The engine thinks Black needs to give the exchange back with  22...Nf8  23.Nb6  Rb8  24.Bf4  , but I don't think it will be enough to save the game. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7. Scandinavian (1...d5) 3...Qd6"]
[Black "3...Qd6 (5...a6 1)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qd6 4. d4
{ We will once again take control of the center. } 4... Nf6
{ 4...g6  is likely to transpose to the Main Line as I don't think Black can do without Nf6 . }
5. Nf3
{ This is the main position of the 3... Qd6 line. Black has a choice between a lot of different set-ups. c6 and g6 will be dealt with in the next chapter. }
5... a6
{ This has been the most common move, which is not surprising. Black's idea is clear. Now that Nb5 is not a problem, he can easily start to apply pressure in the center. a6 also opens up the possibility of b5-Bb7, but Black has to be careful with that pawn launch as the pawn on b5 can be easily targeted by a4, as we've seen earlier. Black's plans are crystal clear and not easily dealt with by the unprepared player, so pay attention! }
6. g3
{ This move is rather effective, since it makes it possible to get a tempo on Black's queen with Bf4, while giving the f1-bishop a nice square on g2 where it will be rather effective. }
6... g6 { Has been tried by the 3... Qd6 pioneer GM Tiviakov. } 7. Bg2 Bg7 8.
Bf4 { Kicking the queen back to d8. } 8... Qd8 9. O-O O-O 10. Qd2
{ Normal development moves will give White a decent position due to our space and development advantage. }
10... c6
{ A move like   10...Nbd7  can be met by  11.d5  , when e6/c6 is suddenly a lot harder to achieve. }
11. Rfe1 Bg4
{ 11...Re8  was played in Arakhamia Grant, K - Tiviakov, S Birmingham 2005, when White had many good responses like  12.Rad1  White will sooner or later kick back the bishop with g4 , when Black will have a hard time developing his pieces. }
12. Ne5 Be6 13. Rad1
{ All of white's forces are in ideal places, so it's time to consider a d5-break soon. }
13... Nbd7 14. Nxd7
{ An improvement over  14.Qc1  like in Asrian, K - Kurajica, B Istanbul 2003. }
14... Bxd7 { Forced, as  14...Qxd7  is met by  15.Na4 } 15. d5
{ Time to open up the position. } 15... cxd5 16. Nxd5 Nxd5 17. Qxd5 Bg4 18. Rb1
{ Black will have to fight for a draw in the upcoming endgame, as there's no way to prevent the loss of a pawn. }
*

