1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qd6 4. d4
{ We will once again take control of the center. } 4... Nf6 5. Nf3 a6
{ This has been the most common move, which is not surprising. Black's idea is clear. Now that Nb5 is not a problem, he can easily start to apply pressure in the center. a6 also opens up the possibility of b5-Bb7, but Black has to be careful with that pawn launch as the pawn on b5 can be easily targeted by a4, as we've seen earlier. Black's plans are crystal clear and not easily dealt with by the unprepared player, so pay attention! }
6. g3
{ This move is rather effective, since it makes it possible to get a tempo on Black's queen with Bf4, while giving the f1-bishop a nice square on g2 where it will be rather effective. }
6... Nc6 { Trying to achieve the desired set-up. } 7. Bf4
{ There's no reason why this move shouldn't be played. } 7... Qd8
{ 7...Qb4  Is refuted by the thematic  8.a3  And Black can't take the pawn as Na4 traps the queen.  8...Qb6  9.d5  Ng4  10.Qd2  e5  Is Black's 'idea,' which fails in numerous ways. One way is  11.dxc6  exf4  12.O-O-O  Bd6  In Kasparov, S-Ramon Perez, J Balaguer 2008, White went for Re1+ , but  13.Qe2+!  was much stronger!  13...Kf8  And White wins after the nice trick  14.Rxd6!  cxd6  15.Nd5  Qd8  16.c7  With Nb6 next. }
8. Bg2 { Now that Bg2 is on the board, Black needs to prevent our d5-break. }
8... e6 9. O-O Be7 10. Qe2 { We keep developing our pieces. } 10... O-O 11.
Rad1 { This not exactly what Black had hoped for. } 11... Nd5 12. Bc1 b5 13.
Ne4 { It's rather typical to move the knight, making way for our c-pawn. }
13... Bb7 14. c3 Qd7 15. Rfe1 Rae8
{ Black ended up winning in Spasov,V-Kurajica,B La Laguna 2007, but this was certainly not thanks to the opening. One logical way to proceed with White is }
16. h4
{ with the neat idea of playing Nfg5 followed by Qh5, provoking the weakening move h6. }
