{ 9...Ne5?  Would have worked without the inclusion of h3-Bh5, but here it loses.  10.g4!  We're now out of the annoying pin.  10...Bg6  11.O-O  Nxf3+  12.Qxf3  Black was way too passive in Klek,H -Repkova, E Balatonszarszo 2017. }
10. Bf4 Qc5 { 10...Qb6?  has been played twice, but  11.a3  wins a piece. } 11.
Be3 { Pushing the queen away to a worse square. } 11... Qa5 12. O-O
{ Our initiative will outweigh the missing pawn. } 12... Nbxd5 13. Nxd5
{ It's important to play concretely, so Black is not able to consolidate. }
13... Nxd5 14. Bd2
{ We attack with each move, not allowing Black to consolidate, as mentioned in the previous note. }
14... Qc5 15. g4 Bg6 16. Ne5 { White wants to play c4, followed by b4. } 16...
O-O-O 17. c4 Ne3
{ Is the engine's attempt to escape, but it loses to   17...Nb6  18.Re1  Black's development is so bad that the engine gives us an advantage of +5 here!  18...c6  19.b4  Soon we will open up Black's king with b5, with devastating effect.  19...Qd6  20.b5!  axb5  21.cxb5  The bishop on d2 hangs, but it doesn't save Black.  21...Qxd2  22.bxc6  Qxd1  23.cxb7+  Kb8  24.Raxd1  Black resigned in Llorente, J -Wittal, IECC email 2017. The passed pawn on b7 is the real MVP. }
18. Bxe3 Qxe5 19. Bxb7+ { Winning the rook on d8. } 19... Kxb7 20. Qxd8
{ White's extra material should lead to glory. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7. Scandinavian (1...d5) 3...Qd6"]
[Black "3...Qd6 (5...a6 11)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qd6 4. d4
{ We will once again take control of the center. } 4... Nf6 5. Nf3 a6
{ This has been the most common move, which is not surprising. Black's idea is clear. Now that Nb5 is not a problem, he can easily start to apply pressure in the center. a6 also opens up the possibility of b5-Bb7, but Black has to be careful with that pawn launch as the pawn on b5 can be easily targeted by a4, as we've seen earlier. Black's plans are crystal clear and not easily dealt with by the unprepared player, so pay attention! }
6. g3
{ This move is rather effective, since it makes it possible to get a tempo on Black's queen with Bf4, while giving the f1-bishop a nice square on g2 where it will be rather effective. }
6... Bg4
{ The fact that this move has been played the most is not surprising, considering the fact that Black's plan is Nc6-O-O-O, when the pawn on d4 will be under pressure. }
7. h3 { I think the inclusion of h3-Bh5 favors White. } 7... Bh5
{ A common scenario in the Scandinavian is that this move is less accurate than Bxf3 due to concrete reasons, but played a lot more as it is 'trickier.' }
8. Bg2
{ We should get our pieces out before we start playing g4 followed by Ne5.   8.g4?!  Bg6  9.Ne5  would now allow  9...Nc6!  when Black gets a decent amount of activity with O-O-O next. }
8... Nc6
{ This is not the best move, but almost always played as it has been Black's idea all along. A move like   8...c6  gives us easy play with  9.Bf4  etc, similar to what we've already seen. }
9. d5
{ This straightforward response is the refutation to Black's shenanigans. }
9... Nb4
{ 9...Ne5?  Would have worked without the inclusion of h3-Bh5, but here it loses.  10.g4!  We're now out of the annoying pin.  10...Bg6  11.O-O  Nxf3+  12.Qxf3  Black was way too passive in Klek,H -Repkova, E Balatonszarszo 2017. }
10. Bf4 Qc5 { 10...Qb6?  has been played twice, but  11.a3  wins a piece. } 11.
Be3 { Pushing the queen away to a worse square. } 11... Qa5 12. O-O
{ Our initiative will outweigh the missing pawn. } 12... Rd8 13. Qe2
{ Getting out of the pin. } 13... Nbxd5 14. Nxd5 Nxd5 15. Bd2 Qb6
{ 15...Qc5  is no better.  16.c4  Nb6  17.Rac1  was seen in Putman, M - Semmelroth, H ICCF email 2017, when White will soon push away Black's pieces with g4 and b4 . }
16. c4 Nf6 17. Be3 c5
{ Alternatively:   17...Qa5  18.b4  Qf5  19.Rfd1  e5  20.Rxd8+  Kxd8  21.g4  White won a piece and prevailed in James, A - Vachtfeidl, P ICCF email 2017. }
18. Rfd1 { Removing the active rook on d8. } 18... e6 19. Rxd8+ Qxd8 20. Rd1
{ We have gotten full control of the d-file, so now it's time to target the bishop on h5 next. }
20... Qb6 21. g4 Bg6 22. g5 Nd7 23. Bf4
{ 23...Be7  24.Ne5  is strong as  24...Nxe5  25.Qxe5  O-O  26.Rd7  winning the pawn on  b7  following the correspondence game Ozols, A - Owens, J ICCF email 2016. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7. Scandinavian (1...d5) 3...Qd6"]
[Black "3...Qd6 Conclusion"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qd6
{ CONCLUSION: This chapter concluded our analysis on the  3...Qd6  variation. }
4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 c6
{ This move has replaced the  5...a6  as the Main Line, and for good reason.   Black is solid here, so it isn't easy for us to take this bad boy down. I suggest playing the modern  6.h3  , preventing  Bg4  . Here Black will surely pay the price in case he decides to avoid the main move  6...Bf5  . From here, I initially intended to give two options, but it turned out that the complications after  7.Ne5  leads nowhere. Therefore, my main suggestion is  7.g3  , when we intended to grab the bishop pair with a slight edge. The funky idea of 12. Nb5! is an important one to remember. In these positions we will surely have the better position, due to our bishop pair. As stated though, Black is solid, but our position contains a really low risk of losing. I most honestly admit that Black's best bet may be to play the curious  7...Nbd7  followed by  8.Nh4  Qe6+  , but even here our bishop pair should give us a comfortable edge, although it isn't big.  3...Qd6  is all in all a possible option, but it seems to me that White gets all the fun, making the line questionable.   5...g6  We started with this modern move when I suggest going for an attack with  6.Bg5!?  6...Bf5  is a rather interesting alternative, but it doesn't look too good. The complications after Black's pawn grab were fun to dive into when we will be granted victory if we know what we're doing. In the Main Lines we often push the queen away with the bishop to  f4  , meaning that there is a huge chance we transpose to our coverage on 3... Qd8. The story has a tendency to repeat itself here. Black becomes rather passive, yielding us a clearly better game. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8. Scandinavian (1...d5) 3...Qa5"]
[Black "3...Qa5 (4...Nf6 1)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5
{ Here we go. The last branch of the Scandinavian Defense, and also the most popular. The queen on a5 is harder to attack, while it is also more useful there since it controls some important squares. Now that the queen is out, Black may soon go for queenside castling by the means of Nc6-Bg4. The queen can also easily return to c7, b6 or d8 from the a5-square, if Black plays the typical Scandinavian move c6. I think this is Black's best bet, for the simple reason that it's more active than its predecessors. }
4. d4
{ The normal procedure. We grab control of the center, while opening up the diagonal for our bishop on c1. }
4... Nf6 5. Nf3
{ This is the main position in 3... Qa5, when Black has a bunch of different ways to play. }
5... Ne4
{ Is a rather ambitious move, but it doesn't look like it works. Black's point is that he wants us to defend the knight on c3 with Bd2, when he will obtain the bishop pair. Instead, we will just sacrifice the pawn with }
6. Bd3 Nxc3 7. bxc3 g6
{ Black usually opts for this move, and rightfully so, as he needs to develop his pieces.   7...Qxc3+?  Black will be really far behind in development if he decides to grab the pawn.  8.Bd2  Qa3   8...Qc6  Is slightly better, but still not good enough after  9.O-O  Bg4  10.Rb1  Nd7  11.Re1  The open b and e-file are really effective.  11...Bxf3  12.gxf3  e6  13.Be4  White wins the pawn on b7, when d5 will soon follow.  9.O-O  We have developed all our minor pieces and gotten our king to safety, so it's not surprising that Black is already objectively lost. }
8. O-O Bg7 9. Re1 { Applying pressure in the e-file. } 9... O-O 10. Rb1
{ The rook is very well placed in the open b-file where it targets Black's pawn on b7. It could also harass Black's queen with Rb5. }
10... Nc6
{ 10...Qxc3  is met by  11.Rxe7  , when the c7-pawn is likely to fall too, as Bf4 comes soon. }
11. Rb5 { White's initiative is really powerful. } 11... Qxa2 12. h4
{ Now our rook on b5 may soon be used as an attacking force, since it can swing to the kingside. }
12... b6 { With this move, Black wants to play Ba6. } 13. Rg5
{ The rook will be placed on g3, where it will play a huge role in our attack. }
13... h6 14. Rg3 h5 15. Ng5
{ With a powerful attack. Keep in mind that one way we can eventually break through is to take on f7 followed by Bxg6. }
*

