1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4
{ The normal procedure. We grab control of the center, while opening up the diagonal for our bishop on c1. }
4... Nf6 5. Nf3 Nc6
{ This is an active move, but Black may struggle with the queen as it is not possible to play c6. }
6. Bd2 Bg4
{ Is the most popular move, but it seems to me that it loses by force. } 7. d5
{ A pawn sacrifice which refutes Black's entire concept. } 7... Nxd5 8. Nb5
{ Black has severe problems with protecting the hanging pawn on c7. } 8... Qb6
{ 8...Bxf3  9.gxf3!  The right capture! Black is still in the game after   9.Qxf3  Ndb4  , but this doesn't work after gxf3 due to 10.a3 .  Qb6  10.c4  Black once again loses material, due to the threat of c5. }
9. c4
{ Black loses material as c5 is a threat, removing the queen from covering the square on c7. }
9... O-O-O 10. cxd5 Rxd5
{ It may look like that Black has something, but it isn't the case. } 11. Nc3
Bxf3 12. gxf3 { 12.Qxf3?  would lose to  12...Rxd2! } 12... Rd7
{ And now, in Sadykov,R - Rasulov,V chess.com INT 2020, White should have played }
13. Bb5 { When Black doesn't have enough for the missing piece. } *

