1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4
{ The normal procedure. We grab control of the center, while opening up the diagonal for our bishop on c1. }
4... Nf6 5. Nf3 Nc6
{ This is an active move, but Black may struggle with the queen as it is not possible to play c6. }
6. Bd2 a6 { Defending the b5-square is necessary. } 7. Bc4
{ Aiming to trap the queen with Nd5, or pushing the knight on c6 away with d5. }
7... Qh5
{ 7...Nxd4  8.Nxd4  Qc5  Is a creative way to play, which we should meet with  9.Bxf7+  Kxf7  10.Nf3  White has regained the pawn with a much better pawn structure and a safer king.  10...e5  11.Qe2  Aiming to castle queenside.  11...Bd6  12.Ng5+  Kg8  13.Nge4  White has a beautiful knight on e4 and the clearly better game due to the superior pawn structure and safer king. }
8. h3
{ 8.Be2  should lead to the same. The Main Move,  8...Ne5  reaches a clearly better endgame, and it's not a bad move either. }
8... Bg4 9. Be2 O-O-O { Is aggressive, but it doesn't really work. } 10. O-O
Bxh3
{ Requires a couple of precise moves, but they're not hard to find.   10...Bxf3  11.Bxf3  Black's pawn structure around the king will now be in ruins.  11...Qf5  12.Bxc6  bxc6  13.Qe2  Kb7  14.Rab1  White will soon get a decisive attack. }
11. gxh3 Qxh3 12. Ng5 { It's important to prevent Qg4+. } 12... Qh4 13. Kg2
{ Now Rh1 is a nice defensive resource. } 13... Qxd4 14. Nxf7
{ Black loses decisive material. } *

