1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4
{ The normal procedure. We grab control of the center, while opening up the diagonal for our bishop on c1. }
4... Nf6 5. Nf3 Bf5
{ This is a highly interesting move-order, as there are advantages of delaying c6. If we continue like in the main line with Bc4 & Bd2, Black can play a quick Bb4 followed by Bxc3 with a fairly solid position. GM Mamedyarov is one of several top players who has utilized this weapon in practice. }
6. Ne5
{ I like this typical knight jump of harassing Black's pieces with g4 and Nc4. }
6... c6 { Black should give the queen an escape route to c7. } 7. Bc4 e6 8. g4
{ Is the best way to challenge Black's set-up. } 8... Be4
{ Has been played over 250 times, which is rather surprising to me. } 9. O-O
Bd5
{ Is Black's point is that the bishop is better placed here than on g6, but it looks more vulnerable to me. }
10. Bd3 Bd6
{ 10...Nbd7  11.f4  Qb6  Is now met by  12.Nxd5  Nxd5  13.c3  When White has an excellent pawn structure, a space advantage and a powerful bishop pair. }
11. f4 Qb6
{ We don't need to worry about the pawn on b2, as brilliantly shown in a game }
12. Be3 Qxb2 13. Qe1
{ It's important to keep the d2-square available for the bishop. } 13... Bxe5
14. Rb1 Qa3 15. fxe5 Nxg4 16. Nxd5 cxd5 17. Rxb7
{ White was dominating in Kokkila, - Syvalahti,H Finland 2018. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8. Scandinavian (1...d5) 3...Qa5"]
[Black "3...Qa5 (4...Nf6 7)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4
{ The normal procedure. We grab control of the center, while opening up the diagonal for our bishop on c1. }
4... Nf6 5. Nf3 Bf5
{ This is a highly interesting move-order, as there are advantages of delaying c6. If we continue like in the main line with Bc4 & Bd2, Black can play a quick Bb4 followed by Bxc3 with a fairly solid position. GM Mamedyarov is one of several top players who has utilized this weapon in practice. }
6. Ne5
{ I like this typical knight jump of harassing Black's pieces with g4 and Nc4. }
6... c6 { Black should give the queen an escape route to c7. } 7. Bc4 e6 8. g4
{ Is the best way to challenge Black's set-up. } 8... Bg6 9. h4
{ Maintaining the pressure. } 9... Nbd7 10. Nxd7 Nxd7 11. h5
{ We should play h5 before Black does so. } 11... Be4 12. O-O
{ Our kingside is safer than what it looks. Black also needs to spend yet another tempo on his bishop. }
12... Bd5 13. Nxd5 cxd5 14. Bd3 Bd6
{ We have been following the Main Line so far. Our light-squared bishop in particular is rather strong here, and Black could quickly find himself under a powerful attack if he's not careful. }
15. Bd2 { Posing a question to Black's queen. } 15... Qd8
{ Black aims to put the queen on h4, which we should meet with   15...Qc7  16.Qf3!  We shouldn't allow Black to play Bf4, when we are in danger of getting rather weak on the dark squares.  16...O-O  17.Rae1  Rae8  Black's only plan is to find a suitable time to play e5.  18.h6  The pawn on h6 will be a thorn in Black's side.  18...g6  19.Bb5!  A strong move, forcing Black's bishop to a worse square.  19...Be7  Black can't allow Bxd7 followed by Qf6.  20.Bf4  Qd8  21.Be5  Wins an exchange after  21...Nxe5  22.dxe5  Black is not objectively lost, but it looks incredibly difficult to defend this position as c4 comes next. }
16. Kg2
{ This move dodges Black's threat, as we unlock the h1-square for our rook. }
16... Qh4 17. Rh1 Qf6
{ Black has moved our rook from f1 to h1, meaning that he has taken control of the f4-square. I don't think it justifies the tempi spent on this plan, though. }
18. Qf3
{ An improvement over  18.c3  Bf4  which was seen in Fedorov, A - Nisipeanu, L Batumi 1999. After  19.Qf3  , Black is unable to trade bishops. }
18... Qxf3+ 19. Kxf3 { Black will suffer in the endgame. } *

