[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4
{ The normal procedure. We grab control of the center, while opening up the diagonal for our bishop on c1. }
4... Nf6 5. Nf3 c6 6. Bd2 Qb6 7. Bc4
{ We don't care about the hanging pawn on b2. } 7... Qxb2
{ Taking the pawn loses. Black's best way forward is to play   7...Bf5  , which transposes to 7...Qb6 in the Main Line of 6...Bf5 . It's definitely logical to move out of the diagonal.  8.Qe2  Let's carry out our usual plan.  8...e6  9.O-O-O  Nbd7  10.Nh4  There are many good moves. I like to grab the bishop pair.  10...Bg6  11.Nxg6  hxg6  12.h4!  A great move, grabbing control of the g5-square.  12...O-O-O  13.Bg5  The bishop is really well placed here.  13...Bb4  14.Ne4  White was clearly better in Kurnosov,I - Varga,Z Austria 2010 and went to win a nice game. Sure, Black is solid, but he doesn't have any straightforward plans to carry out. White, on the other hand, can slowly and steadily improve his position with moves like Kb1-c3 etc. }
8. Rb1 Qa3 9. O-O
{ Black's suffering from the lack of development and will soon be under a vicious attack. }
9... e6 10. Re1
{ White has surprisingly enough lost every single game from this position, but it's not anything we should worry about. }
10... Be7 11. Ng5
{ This move is strong, with the intention of placing a knight on e4, where it will be very powerful. }
11... O-O 12. Rb3 Qd6 13. Nce4
{ White's attack is too powerful. Note how the rook on b3 is participating as it can swing to the kingside. }
13... Nxe4 14. Nxe4 Qxd4 15. Rg3 { An important move, threatening Bc3. } 15...
g6 16. Qe2 { g6 has weakened the a1-h8 diagonal tremendously. } 16... b5
{ Note that   16...Nd7  17.Bc3  Qb6  18.Qh5  loses for Black, due to the decisive threat of Qxh7+ followed by Rh3+ and Rh8 mate. }
17. Bc3 { White wins by force. } 17... Qxc4 18. Qh5
{ The threat of Qxh7+ followed by Rh3+ and Rh8 mate can't be parried in a satisfactory way. }
18... f6 { 18...Qd5  loses to  19.Be5  . And now, the typical blow. } 19. Rxg6+
hxg6 20. Qxg6+ Kh8 21. Re3 { Black will soon get mated. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8. Scandinavian (1...d5) 3...Qa5"]
[Black "3...Qa5 (4...Nf6 10)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4
{ The normal procedure. We grab control of the center, while opening up the diagonal for our bishop on c1. }
4... Nf6 5. Nf3 c6 6. Bd2 Bg4
{ As usual it's possible to play this move, and as usual, it's not advisable. }
7. h3 { As we always do, posing a question to the bishop. } 7... Bh5 8. g4 Bg6
9. Bc4
{ This active developing move is the best option we have in our arsenal. We intend to sacrifice a pawn with h4-h5, followed by Qe2-O-O-O-Nh4, when our initiative will be incredibly strong. }
9... e6
{ Is probably the most logical move, and also the lesser evil.   9...Qc7?  Has been the most popular move, but it looks like it loses by force.  10.h4!  Almost never played, but very effective.  10...Nxg4  Taking the pawn is the critical move, of course.  11.Ng5!  Black has to deal with an obnoxious amount of pressure on the f7-pawn.  11...h5  Is pretty much forced, when  12.Qe2  Nd7  13.O-O-O  Is completely dominating for White.   9...Nbd7  Is another way Black can play, when we should go for  10.h4!  It's once again very strong to sacrifice the pawn.  10...Nxg4  11.h5  Bf5  12.Qe2  Our development advantage is significant. Besides, I think we will win back the pawn soon anyway, as Black can't hold on to the pawn on  f7  for very long.  12...O-O-O  for instance, is met by  13.Nh4  e6  14.Nxf5  exf5   14...Qxf5?  loses a piece to  15.Bd3  15.Bxf7  Black's position has seen better days, as the light squares are incredibly weak, and the pieces poorly placed. }
10. Qe2
{ This looks like the easiest path forward if you ask me. It's worth mentioning that  10.h4  was yet again, strong. }
10... Nbd7 11. O-O-O Bb4 12. a3 { The most straightforward move. } 12... Bxc3
13. Bxc3 Qc7
{ We have reached a rather typical scenario. We have the bishop pair and more space, while Black is solid. Therefore, it's important that we maintain the pressure. }
14. Ne5 Nd5
{ 14...Ne4  has been played by two strong GMs. It's important that we face this knight jump with  15.Be1!  , not giving away our strong dark-squared bishop. }
15. Bd2 Nxe5 16. dxe5 O-O-O
{ Black has always castled queenside, which is not surprising. Our attack on the kingside would soon be overwhelming if Black decided to go short. }
17. f4 { We keep playing against Black's light-squared bishop. } 17... h5 18.
Rhf1
{ An improvement over   18.Qf2  Qb6!  when Black was fine in Adams, M Rogers, I Groningen 1990. }
18... hxg4 19. hxg4
{ f5 was looming in the air in Ippolito, M-Hauchard,A Cappelle-la-Grande 2000. }
