[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8. Scandinavian (1...d5) 3...Qa5"]
[Black "3...Qa5 (4...Nf6 11)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4
{ The normal procedure. We grab control of the center, while opening up the diagonal for our bishop on c1. }
4... Nf6 5. Nf3 c6 6. Bd2
{ Moving the queen to c7 should transpose to the Main Line as well, since Black doesn't have anything better than }
6... Qc7 7. Bc4 Bf5 8. Ne5 e6 9. g4
{ When we get our usual play against Black's light-squared bishop. } 9... Bg6
{ 9...Be4  is possible, but certainly not what Black aims for when playing the Scandinavian. A logical response is  10.Nxe4  Nxe4  11.Be3  We should obviously not let Black grab the bishop on d2.  11...Nd7  12.Nxd7  Qxd7  13.Qf3  Nf6  14.O-O-O  White is definitely in the driving seat with the bishop pair and better pieces. }
10. Qe2
{ Grabbing the control of the e4-square, while placing the queen in the same file as the black king, making f4-f5 possible. }
10... Nbd7 11. f4 O-O-O 12. h4
{ This looks like everything Black is NOT hoping for when playing the Scandinavian. }
12... b5 { Is the best attempt of survival, when we should play } 13. h5
{ This is essential as Black gets some counterplay after  13.Bb3  b4  . } 13...
Bxc2 14. Bxb5 cxb5 15. Rh3
{ Threatening to play  15.Nxb5  followed by Rc3 . It's also worth noting that the pawn on f7 is hanging after for example  15...Kb8  . }
15... b4 16. Rc1 { Regaining the piece. The engine suggests } 16... Nxe5 17.
fxe5 Nd5 18. Nxd5 Rxd5 19. Be3
{ When White's pressure in the endgame is close to decisive after } 19... Kb8
20. Qxc2 Qxc2 21. Rxc2 Be7 22. Rf3
{ I don't see how Black can survive this. Our king will move to d3, while we can dismantle Black's pawn structure with h6 at some point. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8. Scandinavian (1...d5) 3...Qa5"]
[Black "3...Qa5 (4...Nf6 12)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4
{ The normal procedure. We grab control of the center, while opening up the diagonal for our bishop on c1. }
4... Nf6 5. Nf3 c6 6. Bd2 Bf5 7. Bc4
{ The best square to place the f1-bishop. } 7... Nbd7
{ This move is rare when we compare it to the Main Move 7... e6, but it's Black's best bet. The idea is to prevent Nd5, as a knight jump to d5 now doesn't do anything for White, as Black simply recaptures the knight on f6 with the knight. }
8. Qe2 e6
{ This has been played a surprising amount of times, but it loses on the spot.   8...Qc7  9.O-O-O  e6  10.Nh4  Simply grabbing the bishop pair.  10...Bg6  11.Nxg6  hxg6  12.h4!  We have seen this move before, and it's good yet again as we grab control of the g5-square and limit Black's fun in the h-file.  12...Nb6  13.Bb3  Black is solid, but White's position is easier to handle. The plan is to eventually expand on the kingside.  13...Bb4  14.Kb1  O-O-O  Black needs to put the king on the queenside, as it would be far too vulnerable on the kingside.  15.a3  Be7  16.Bc1  Nbd5  17.Na2  White is calling the shots. Black can't do much else than making waiting moves. }
9. d5 cxd5 10. Nxd5 Qd8 11. Nxf6+ gxf6
{ 11...Qxf6  is met by  12.Bb5  , with a really nasty pin. } 12. Nd4
{ Applying pressure against the pawn on e6. } 12... Bg6 13. O-O-O
{ White's initiative is too powerful, as demonstrated in the following lines }
13... Qb6
{ 13...Bc5  Was seen in Quesada Perez,Y - Esipenko,A Lichess.org INT 2020, when the Cuban GM missed a forced win after  14.Nxe6!!  BAM! A beautiful blow.  14...fxe6  15.Ba5!  Opening up the d-file for the rook.  15...Qe7  16.Bb5  Bd6  Black loses decisive material, as  17.Bc7  deflects the Bishop which will lose by force. }
14. Nxe6 fxe6 15. Ba5
{ Black soon resigned in Schnur,E-Henke,S DESC email 2007. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8. Scandinavian (1...d5) 3...Qa5"]
[Black "3...Qa5 (4...Nf6 13)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4
{ The normal procedure. We grab control of the center, while opening up the diagonal for our bishop on c1. }
4... Nf6 5. Nf3 c6 6. Bd2 Bf5 7. Bc4
{ The best square to place the f1-bishop. This move is rare when we compare it to the Main Move. }
7... e6
{ This is Black's best bet which has been the Main Line of the 3... Qa5-variation for a while, but the resulting positions for Black do not look satisfactory. }
8. Nd5
{ A knight jump to d5 now doesn't do anything for White as Black simply recaptures the knight on f6 with the knight. We're forcing the queen all the way back to d8, while we get a favorable exchange on f6. }
8... Qd8 9. Nxf6+ { Black has now an important choice to make. } 9... Qxf6
{ Black keeps his pawn structure in tact with this capture, but the queen is left slightly exposed on f6. }
10. Qe2
{ The plan of castling queenside is still good. Keep in mind also that the queen on d2 helps out greatly in our quest of one day opening up the position with d5. }
10... Nd7 11. O-O-O Nb6
{ Note that   11...Bg4  transposes to 10...Bg4 after  12.d5! } 12. Bg5
{ This is the downside of placing the queen on f6. } 12... Qg6 13. h4
{ Threatening h5 or Ne5, trapping Black's queen. } 13... h6
{ Loses to a fantastic computer line:   13...Be7!  Black has to give up the ability of castling.  14.Bxe7  Kxe7  15.Bd3  Rhd8  16.Kb1  White had the much safer king and excellent initiative in the game Repp,H - Koch,H ICCF email 2014. }
14. Ne5 Qh7 15. d5
{ This move has only been found in email-games, which is not surprising. }
15... hxg5 16. dxc6 bxc6 { Otherwise we get a fantastic passed pawn on b7. }
17. Bb5 { The only road that leads to Rome. } 17... Be4 18. hxg5 Qxh1 19. Qxe4
{ And now Black must give the queen } 19... Qxd1+ 20. Kxd1 Rd8+ 21. Bd3
{ We should obviously keep the bishop. Two Correspondence games reached this position and White won both games as Black's king is far too vulnerable. }
*

