[Round "?"]
[White "8. Scandinavian (1...d5) 3...Qa5"]
[Black "3...Qa5 (4...Nf6 16)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4
{ The normal procedure. We grab control of the center, while opening up the diagonal for our bishop on c1. }
4... Nf6 5. Nf3 c6 6. Bd2 Bf5 7. Bc4
{ The best square to place the f1-bishop. This move is rare when we compare it to the Main Move. }
7... e6
{ This is Black's best bet which has been the Main Line of the 3... Qa5-variation for a while, but the resulting positions for Black do not look satisfactory. }
8. Nd5
{ A knight jump to d5 now doesn't do anything for White as Black simply recaptures the knight on f6 with the knight. We're forcing the queen all the way back to d8, while we get a favorable exchange on f6. }
8... Qd8 9. Nxf6+ { Black has now an important choice to make. } 9... Qxf6
{ Black keeps his pawn structure in tact with this capture, but the queen is left slightly exposed on f6. }
10. Qe2
{ The plan of castling queenside is still good. Keep in mind also that the queen on d2 helps out greatly in our quest of one day opening up the position with d5. }
10... Bg4
{ We must consider this move which aims to ruin our pawn structure with Bxf3. }
11. d5 { We must turn to concrete play in order to get an edge. } 11... Bxf3
{ This is always played, for good reason, as it was Black's idea with Bg4. }
12. gxf3 { This is forced of course. } 12... cxd5 13. Bxd5 Nd7
{ An important difference in this position is that the b7 pawn is poisonous due to Qxb2, therefore we must protect it first. }
14. O-O-O
{ I love moves with several functions. With O-O-O we protect the pawn on b2, while we get our king to safety! }
14... O-O-O 15. Be4
{ This has position has been seen in games among GMs and in Correspondence games, where White is generally scoring really well. This not surprising at all due to our bishop pair advantage and safer king. }
15... Qe5
{ Has been the most popular in recent times.   15...Bd6  A rare continuation tested less than 20 times.  16.Bc3  Looks like the most logical move to me.  16...Qf4+  Has been played four times. The best move seems to be to sac a pawn with   16...Qe7  17.Bxg7  Qg5+  18.Kb1  Qxg7  19.Rxd6  , when Black has to fight for a draw.  17.Kb1  Nf6  18.Rd4  18. Bxf6 was also promising.  18...Nxe4  19.Rxe4  Qf5  20.Bxg7  Rhg8  21.Bd4  White was a clean pawn up and eventually won in Potrata,J - Novak,A ICCF email 2010. }
16. Bc3
{ The bishop is well placed on c3 so there is no reason why we shouldn't do it now. }
16... Qc7 17. Kb1 { This is always a good prophylactic move. } 17... f6
{ Fighting against our annoying bishop on c3. } 18. Rhg1
{ The rook puts a great deal of pressure on Black on g1. } 18... Nc5
{ Black should try to get rid of some of the pressure, until it's too late. }
19. Rxd8+ Kxd8
{ The Scandinavian advocates GM Prie and IM Bartholomew both played this move, which is why I'm considering it. }
20. f4
{ White aims to put the bishop on g2 and later the queen in the diagonal to apply maximum pressure against Black's king. }
20... Bd6 21. Rd1 Kc8 22. Bg2
{ White has a powerful initiative that the engine evaluates as decisive. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8. Scandinavian (1...d5) 3...Qa5"]
[Black "3...Qa5 (4...Nf6 17)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4
{ The normal procedure. We grab control of the center, while opening up the diagonal for our bishop on c1. }
4... Nf6 5. Nf3 c6 6. Bd2 Bf5 7. Bc4
{ The best square to place the f1-bishop. This move is rare when we compare it to the Main Move. }
7... e6
{ This is Black's best bet which has been the Main Line of the 3... Qa5-variation for a while, but the resulting positions for Black do not look satisfactory. }
8. Nd5
{ A knight jump to d5 now doesn't do anything for White as Black simply recaptures the knight on f6 with the knight. We're forcing the queen all the way back to d8, while we get a favorable exchange on f6. }
8... Qd8 9. Nxf6+ { Black has now an important choice to make. } 9... gxf6
{ Black bites the bullet and accepts that he will get a subpar pawn structure. The pro is that the pawn on f6 controls some important squares, though. }
10. O-O
{ Now that   10.Qe2  is met by  10...Bxc2!  we will castle on the kingside instead. }
10... Nd7
{ 10...Bg7  Was played by two GMs, when I think we should expand on the queenside with  11.a4  O-O  12.a5  Nd7  13.Re1  Re8  14.b4  Our more spacious position and better pawn structure yields us a clearly better game. }
11. a4 { I think this move is interesting. However,   11.Re1  is also decent. }
11... Qc7
{ Is another way to play, when we can respond with   11...Nb6  Black usually does this in these positions, but here I think it just helps us.  12.Be2  We always desire to move the bishop anyway so we can reinforce our central control with c4.  12...a5  13.c4  The game may continue  13...Be7  14.Bc3  O-O  15.Re1  Black's position looks absolutely terrible as he has a bad pawn structure and central control.   11...h5?!  This attacking move has been played thrice, but it's not anything to worry about.  12.a5  h4  13.Re1  Is the easiest way to deal with the attack. We can always meet h3 with g3 and send the bishop to f1 to defend and allow us to play c4. I honestly think we can stop here, as I think a4-a5 has done a lot more good than h5-h4. }
12. Nh4 Bg6 13. Re1 { Black's position is rather passive. } 13... Nb6 14. Bb3
{ It was just as good to place the bishop on f1. } 14... Be7 15. a5 Nd5 16. Qf3
{ Simple and active moves from the white side. } 16... O-O 17. c4
{ Black is losing control of the center, meaning that he will have to worry about a d5-breakthrough rather soon. }
17... Nb4 18. Bc3
{ d5 is a powerful threat so Black should try to diminish our control of the d5-square. }
18... b5 19. c5
{ This is an improvement over the Correspodence game Karachurin, S - Wallinger, M which went   19.axb6  , although that was also good enough for a decisive advantage. }
19... Nd5 20. Bxd5 cxd5 21. Bd2 Rfe8 22. b4
{ White can do whatever he wants on the kingside as Black has absolutely zilch amount of counterplay. }
