{ Grabbing space on the queenside. As we've seen, the rook is well placed on e1. }
12... Qc7
{ 12...Bd6  13.g3  Our bishop will get a nice home on g2.  13...Bg4  14.Bf1  f5  Black's hope of creating something, but it won't lead anywhere.  15.c4  f4  16.Bg2  Everything is under control.  16...fxg3  17.hxg3  h5  Black's attempt of opening up our kingside.  18.c5  Bc7  19.Qb3!  We need the queen on the queenside to supports our queenside expansion.  19...Rb8  20.Ra3  Black's attack has lead nowhere, so we can finally start a queenside expansion. }
13. b4
{ We proceed with expanding on the queenside, as we've done in the other lines as well. }
13... Bg4
{ 13...Bd6  We can meet this move with the calm  14.Kh1  We might as well move out of the pin. Moving out of the pin.  14...O-O-O  15.h3  Our attack looks more threatening.   15.a5  a6  16.h3  Black's hopes of getting an attack are slowly fading away.  16...Kb8  17.Bf1  Black has to prevent c4-b5 with the move  17...e5  18.c3  exd4  19.Nxd4  Bg6  20.Qf3  We have full control and the clearly better game as Black is struggling with his double pawns. If Black tries c5 we will play Nb3, when a capture on c5 will follow. }
14. Be2
{ We are no longer pinned and again we open up the possibility of playing c4. }
14... f5 15. b5 { Dismantling Black's queenside pawns. } 15... Bd6 16. bxc6
bxc6 17. a5 Bxf3
{ Grabbing the pawn loses the pressure after   17...Bh3  Is nothing to worry about, since we have  18.Bf1  Bg4  19.g3  This is the way forward, placing the bishop on a better square. }
18. Bxf3 Bxh2+ 19. Kf1 { The king is safer on f1 than h1. } 19... Bf4
{ More or less forced, as   19...Bd6  is met by  20.c4  with a deadly initiative. }
20. Bc3 Nf6 21. Rb1 Kf8 22. Qd3
{ Black's extra pawn doesn't mean much in this position. His king is vulnerable and his pieces aren't that well coordinated. Placing the king on g7 also makes Black vulnerable to a move like d5, opening up the diagonal. }
