1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4
{ The normal procedure. We grab control of the center, while opening up the diagonal for our bishop on c1. }
4... Nf6 5. Nf3 Bg4 { I hope that your intuitive reaction is to play } 6. h3
{ As we did in the other Scandinavian lines when Black played Bg4. } 6... Bh5
{ 6...Bxf3  Usually the case in the Bg4-lines. Giving up the bishop pair is objectively better, but yields White a really comfortable edge.  7.Qxf3  c6  8.Bd2  Nbd7  9.O-O-O  White's position is more spacious, and the path forward is simple.  9...e6  There are many good moves here, one of them is  10.Kb1  Protecting the pawn on a2.  10...Bb4  11.a3  Bxc3  12.Bxc3  Qc7   12...Qd5  has been more popular, when  13.Qg3  is strong.  13.Bd2  O-O  14.g4  White will simply advance the kingside pawns and create a vicious attack, while prevent Black from doing the same on the queenside. }
7. g4 { The same procedure! } 7... Bg6 8. Nd2
{ I suggest to confuse Black with this move, but it really makes little difference to the main move   8.Ne5  . This move has only been played once ! while Ne5 has been seen around 1800 times. }
8... c6
{ 8...Nd5  Leads to a terrible endgame for Black after  9.Nc4  Nxc3  10.Nxa5  Nxd1  And now, we should play  11.Bg2!  Otherwise, Black will be fine after Be4.  11...Nxf2  12.Kxf2  Nd7  13.Bf4  White's bishops were incredibly strong in Moza, M - Held,B GER email 2008. }
9. h4 { We keep playing against the bishop on g6. } 9... Nbd7
{ 9...e6  10.h5  Be4  11.Nb3  Qc7  12.Nxe4  Nxe4  13.Qd3  Nd6  14.Bf4  is awful for Black. }
10. h5 Be4 { Now we get an overwhelming initiative. } 11. Nc4 Qc7 12. Nxe4 Nxe4
13. Qf3 Nd6 14. Bf4
{ Funnily enough, this position has occurred 50+ times, and the engine gives an advantage close to 4 pawns for White! }
14... Nb6 15. Ne3
{ Black soon has to deal with the pawn launch c4-c5, which contains a lot of venom. }
15... Na4 16. O-O-O Qb6 17. b3 Nc3 18. Bxd6 Nxd1 19. Bc5
{ Black lost material and was dead lost in Tseshkovsky,V -Savic,M Herceg Novi 2005. }
