1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4
{ The normal procedure. We grab control of the center, while opening up the diagonal for our bishop on c1. }
4... Bf5 { Is an uncommon move order, but one that we still must consider. } 5.
Bd2
{ The bishop is well-placed on d2 as it opens up the possibility of discovery attacks like Nb5/ Nd5. }
5... e6
{ Has been played as little as three times, but it is my engine's favorite option. Keep in mind that   5...Nf6  is not good here, due to  6.Qf3!  , which forces the bishop back to c8 since Nb5 is a threat. }
6. Bc4
{ Threatening Nd5, which is something Black has fallen for as much as 12 times. By a different move-order. }
6... c6
{ We have reached a position which has arisen a decent amount of times, but by a different move-order. }
7. g4
{ This ultra-aggressive move is the best.   7.Nf3  heads into our Main Line after  7...Nf6  . }
7... Bg6 8. Qe2 Bb4 { Is the most played move by a long shot, but it loses. }
9. f4 { f5 is not a threat, winning a piece. } 9... Ne7 10. O-O-O
{ Our initiative is incredibly powerful with ideas like h4-h5 and even f5. }
10... Nd7 11. a3 { Getting rid of the annoying bishop on b4. } 11... Bxc3
{ 11...Bxa3!?  Is an interesting attempt to complicate the game.  12.f5  exf5  13.Na2!  A really subtle way of winning material.  13...Bxb2+  14.Kxb2  Qb6+  And here, I like  15.Bb4!  The knight on e7 is falling.  15...O-O-O  16.Ka1  I think the safest way forward is to move out of the pin. 16. Qxe7 is also good of course.  16...Nd5  17.Bxd5  cxd5  18.gxf5  Bxf5  19.Nf3  Our extra piece should decide the game. }
12. Bxc3 Qc7
{ The pawn on f4 is under attack, which should be defended by the developing move }
13. Nh3 Nb6 { Black wants to plant a knight on d5. } 14. d5
{ Just in time, opening up the position. } 14... exd5
{ 14...Nxc4  is refuted by  15.dxe6  . So far, we have been following Hector, J - Nakamura, H Malmo/ Copenhagen 2005, when White had been playing flawlessly. However, White soon started giving Black counterplay with the move Bxg7 and Naka eventually prevailed. }
15. Bb3 { Now f5 is still a threat. } 15... Be4
{ 15...f6  Gives the bishop a square on f7, but it isn't good enough.  16.f5  Bf7  17.Rhe1  Our forces are too strong.  17...h6  Black has to prevent g5.  18.Ba5  Black is completely dominated. }
16. Bxg7 { Now it's time! } 16... Rg8 17. Be5 Qd7 18. Rhg1
{ Protecting the pawn on g4. } 18... O-O-O 19. Ng5
{ Black's position is resignable, as there is no way to avoid a major loss of material. }
