1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4
{ The normal procedure. We grab control of the center, while opening up the diagonal for our bishop on c1. }
4... Bf5 { Is an uncommon move order, but one that we still must consider. } 5.
Bd2
{ The bishop is well-placed on d2 as it opens up the possibility of discovery attacks like Nb5/ Nd5. }
5... c6
{ Has been overwhelmingly the most popular way to continue, but the move-order is inaccurate. Nf3 is likely to transpose to the Main Line, but we can punish Black's inaccurate move-order. }
6. g4 { This move is once again really effective. } 6... Be6
{ The only logical alternative to the Main Line. Other bishop moves are simply met with Bc4. }
7. Bg2
{ Keeping control of the d5-square seems like the simplest continuation. The plan forward is simple, really. We will play h3-Nge2, when the knight may eventually jump to f4. Moves like d5 are also looming in air. We will also play g5 in case of Nf6 or h5. }
7... h6
{ The engine thinks that the move of g5 is so annoying that it's worth to spend time preventing it. We have many good ways of battling the move, though.   7...Qc7  It makes sense to move out of the diagonal.  8.h3!  Nf6  9.Nge2  Black is objectively lost as he is massively behind in development. The bishop on e6 looks incredibly silly, as it blocks Black's bishop on f8 from getting out on the board. }
8. Nd5
{ Is a nice maneuver to keep in mind, which is my reason for suggesting this jump. Moves like 8. f4 or 8. d5 were also really good. }
8... Qd8 9. Nf4 Bc8
{ Is the human way to play. The engine wants   9...Bd5  , but after  10.Nxd5  cxd5  11.c4!  our position looks fantastic. }
10. c3 { Let's keep it simple. } 10... Nf6 11. h3 Nbd7 12. Nf3
{ Logical, developing moves is always the way to go. } 12... e6 13. Qe2
{ Black is far behind in development and will soon be a victim to a slaughter on the kingside. }
