6. g4 { This move is once again really effective. } 6... Bg6 7. f4
{ It's important to remember this typical plan of trapping Black's bishop. }
7... e6 8. Qe2 { Maintaining the threat of f5. } 8... Ne7 9. d5
{ Is the most direct way to proceed. } 9... cxd5 10. f5
{ The point with our sacrifice. } 10... exf5
{ 10...Nxf5  Black could certainly give a piece for three pawns, but I think our forces are too powerful.  11.gxf5  Bxf5  12.Bh3!  A great move, forcing Black to give away the strong bishop on f5 as a sac on e6 would sting.  12...Bxh3  13.Nxh3  Nc6  14.O-O  Black's pawn chain is strong, but the extra piece is worth more.  14...Be7  15.Kh1!  Making way for the rook on f1.  15...O-O  16.Rg1  With an attack against the Black king. }
11. Bg2 { Now Nxd5 is a nasty threat. } 11... Qa6 { Requires us to play } 12.
Nb5 { Black has to deal with a rather unpleasant check on c7 with the move }
12... Kd8 { when the king will be rather exposed. } 13. Bf4
{ It seems like Black has to give the exchange, as } 13... Nd7
{ Make things worse due to } 14. Bc7+
{ Forcing the king to c8, so we can grab the pawn on d5. } 14... Kc8 15. Bxd5
{ White is winning, as O-O-O comes with a deadly attack. Note how the bishop on d5 protects the pawn on a2. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8. Scandinavian (1...d5) 3...Qa5"]
[Black "3...Qa5 (4...Bf5 9)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4
{ The normal procedure. We grab control of the center, while opening up the diagonal for our bishop on c1. }
4... Bf5 { Is an uncommon move order, but one that we still must consider. } 5.
Bd2
{ The bishop is well-placed on d2 as it opens up the possibility of discovery attacks like Nb5/ Nd5. }
5... c6
{ Has been overwhelmingly the most popular way to continue, but the move-order is inaccurate. Nf3 is likely to transpose to the Main Line, but we can punish Black's inaccurate move-order. }
6. g4 { This move is once again really effective. } 6... Bg6 7. f4
{ It's important to remember this typical plan of trapping Black's bishop. }
7... e6 8. Qe2 { Maintaining the threat of f5. } 8... Ne7 9. d5
{ Is the most direct way to proceed. } 9... cxd5 10. f5
{ The point with our sacrifice. } 10... exf5 11. Bg2
{ Now Nxd5 is a nasty threat. } 11... Na6
{ Was Black's try in an e-mail game. } 12. Nxd5 Qc5
{ Black can't afford to play passively with   12...Qd8  , as White gets too much play after  13.O-O-O  . }
13. b4 Qc8 14. Nf3 { Finally getting our knight on the board. } 14... Qe6 15.
Ne5 { We should not trade queens of course. } 15... O-O-O 16. Nf4
{ With O-O-O coming, Black is forced to play } 16... Rxd2 { And now } 17. Bxb7+
{ Wins by force. } 17... Kxb7
{ Black should take, otherwise we can simply capture Black's rook with the king. }
18. Qf3+ Nd5 19. Nxe6 Bxb4
{ Is Black's best bet of counterplay, when the only winning move is } 20. Nc5+
Nxc5
{ White's point is shown after   20...Kc8  After this, Black regains the queen but still ends up with less material after the forced sequence  21.Nxa6  Rd3+  22.Nxb4  Rxf3  23.Nxf3  White is up an exchange.  23...Nxb4  24.gxf5  Nxc2+  25.Kf2  Bxf5  26.Rac1  White eventually realized his material advantage in Agachi,L - Houston Smith,D ICCF email 2018. }
21. Rb1 { When White is threatening to take on b4 followed by Kxd2. } 21... Ne4
{ Defends the rook on d2, when } 22. gxf5 { wins. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8. Scandinavian (1...d5) 3...Qa5"]
[Black "3...Qa5 (4...e5 1)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4
{ The normal procedure. We grab control of the center, while opening up the diagonal for our bishop on c1. }
4... e5
{ Is a speculative pawn launch, where Black wants to play rather concretely. We should deal with it by the simple means of }
5. Nf3 { Developing our pieces. } 5... exd4 6. Qxd4
{ I like taking with the queen, as it controls a lot of squares. } 6... Nc6 7.
Bb5
{ Other moves would allow Black to get a huge amount of counterplay as we would lose time moving our queen. }
7... Ne7
{ Has been played in every game I found. After   7...Bd7  we should eliminate the enemy knight with  8.Bxc6  , followed by Bf4 . }
8. Qf4 { Threatening to win the queen with b4 followed by Be3. } 8... Bd7 9.
Rb1 { Once again b4 is a threat. } 9... Nd5
{ The most active continuation. If Black had played   9...Qb4  , we could simply take the pawn on c7 . }
10. Qe4+ Be6 11. O-O { Getting our king to safety. } 11... O-O-O 12. Bg5
{ Keeping up the active play. } 12... Nxc3 13. bxc3
{ The open b-file yields us a powerful attack. } 13... Bd5 14. Qd3 Rd6
{ One nice detail is that   14...f6  loses to  15.Qf5+  . After  15...Kb8  16.Bxc6  is a double pin.   15...Rd7  doesn't help either, when  16.Rfd1  is decisive. }
15. c4
{ Was good enough for a winning advantage, but my engine thinks that  15.Nd4!  is even stronger. }
15... Be6 16. Qe4
{ White had a powerful attack as Black had to deal with annoying ideas like Bxc6 followed by Nd4 or Ne5, and Bf4/Bd2. From here, White won two e-mail games: Piacenti,L - Cosentino,A ICCF email 2016 & Danzanvilliers,P - Cosentino,A ICCF email 2015. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8. Scandinavian (1...d5) 3...Qa5"]
[Black "3...Qa5 (4...e5 2)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5
{ Here we go. The last branch of the Scandinavian Defense, and also the most popular. The queen on a5 is harder to attack, while it is also more useful there since it controls some important squares. Now that the queen is out, Black may soon go for queenside castling by the means of Nc6-Bg4. The queen can also easily return to c7, b6 or d8 from the a5-square, if Black plays the typical Scandinavian move c6. I think this is Black's best bet, for the simple reason that it's more active than its predecessors. }
4. d4
{ The normal procedure. We grab control of the center, while opening up the diagonal for our bishop on c1. }
4... e5
{ Is a speculative pawn launch, where Black wants to play rather concretely. We should deal with it by the simple means of }
5. Nf3 { Developing our pieces. } 5... Bb4 { Is the trickiest way to proceed. }
6. Bd2 { As simple as defending the knight on c3. } 6... exd4
{ Leads to a forced endgame after } 7. Nxd4 Qe5+ 8. Qe2 Qxe2+ 9. Bxe2 Nf6 10.
O-O-O
{ Our development advantage grants us an endgame which is close to objectively lost for Black. Indeed, White's score from this position is as high as 8/9 two draws, seven wins. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8. Scandinavian (1...d5) 3...Qa5"]
[Black "3...Qa5 (4...e5 3)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4
{ The normal procedure. We grab control of the center, while opening up the diagonal for our bishop on c1. }
4... e5
{ Is a speculative pawn launch, where Black wants to play rather concretely. We should deal with it by the simple means of }
5. Nf3 { Developing our pieces. } 5... e4
{ This move only makes matters worse.   5...Bb4  Is the trickiest way to proceed.  6.Bd2  As simple as defending the knight on c3.  6...Bg4  7.a3  Pushing away the bishop on b4.  7...Bxf3  Has been the most played move, but it loses in several ways.  8.Qxf3  Nc6  9.Rd1   9.O-O-O  or Bc4 was also winning. With Rd1 we are threatening to take the bishop on b4 , while we will place a deadly pin on the knight on c6 if the bishop moves.  Nxd4  Is the most critical move.  10.Qxb7  Nxc2+  11.Ke2  The rook and bishop is under attack.  11...Nd4+  12.Kd3  Rd8  13.axb4  There is no discovered check to worry about, and Black can't avoid the trade of queens, when he will be down a piece.  13...Qb6  14.Qxb6  axb6  15.Kc4  A fun king march which has lead to an endgame with a piece up. }
6. Ng5 { 6.Ne5  is also good. } 6... Bb4
{ 6...Nf6  Allows  7.Bc4  When the pawn on f7 can't be defended.  7...Bb4  This is Black's best attempt, when the winning continuation is  8.Bxf7+  Ke7  9.Bb3  Black's king is on thin ice.  9...Bxc3+  10.bxc3  Qxc3+  11.Qd2  There is no need to give the pawn on d4 with Bd2.  11...Qxd2+   11...Qxa1  is met by  12.O-O  , when Ba3 comes next, trapping the queen.  12.Kxd2  Nc6  13.Ba3+  White was on his way to victory in Coleman,P-Saunders,M CServe email 1995. }
7. Nxe4 { Black has no counterplay for the missing pawn. } 7... Bf5 8. Ng3
{ Is the easiest way to proceed. 8. a3 is the engine's first try, but I like keeping things as simple as possible. }
8... Bxc3+ 9. bxc3 Qxc3+
{ If Black moves the bishop we will simply play Bd2 with a clean pawn up. The text move isn't good, but it's the most critical option. }
10. Bd2 Qxc2 11. Qe2+ { One of many good moves. } 11... Ne7 12. Rc1 Qd3 13. Qe5
{ And Black loses material. } *

