[White "8. Scandinavian (1...d5) 3...Qa5"]
[Black "3...Qa5 Conclusion"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5
{ CONCLUSION: In this chapter, we took a look at the last branch of the Scandinavian tree, 3... Qa5. This move has for long been regarded as the most principled move, and for good reason. Black's queen is more active on a5 where it controls some key squares, while it's also less vulnerable to attacks. Black has several alternatives to the main move, but they all look shaky to me. }
4. d4 Nf6
{ Moving on, Black has many options at his disposal, but it's clear that he will pay the price if he opts for something else other than 5... Bf5 or 5... c6. }
5. Nf3 c6
{ is the main move.   5...Bf5  is interesting when we arrive at a crossroads.  6.Bd2   or  6.Bc4  should lead us back to our lines with 5...c6 via transposition but Black does have some extra options, like a quick Bb4. }
6. Bd2 { The objective evaluation of this move is best compared to 6.Bc4. }
6... Bf5 7. Bc4 e6 8. Nd5
{ The positions resulting after this move seem rather sad for Black.  8...Qd8  9.Nxf6  Black must choose how to capture the knight. After  9...Qxf6  , the queen on  f6  is rather exposed,   but after  9...gxf6  , Black is left with an inferior pawn structure. Black's best bet from there is to try to create counterplay down the g-file, but it really doesn't look like much to me as we can often place our bishop on  f1  , and even play g3-Bg2. The expansion on the queenside also moves in rapid speed, while it never seems like Black gets anything significant on the kingside.  At the end of the day, the Scandinavian Defense is an opening where its usage comes as a surprise weapon, but like all rare openings, it is no match for the prepared player. After this chapter, I still believe that Black's best move is 3... Qa5 though, when I }
*

