1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 c6
{ Before we get started with more mainstream stuff, we should knock this system out. This move is not as dumb as it looks as Black can develop his queen to a5, applying pressure on our pawn on e4. If we decide to defend the e4 pawn with a move like Bd3, Black can pressure the pawn on d4 with e5. All other options will be covered in future chapters: Philidor Defense, Pirc Defense and Nbd7 which is what GM Simon Williams called 'The Risky Lion'. }
4. f4 g6
{ This leads to a rather poor version of the Austrian Attack in the Pirc Defense. }
5. Nf3
{ Is the best way to proceed.  5.h3  would have transposed to our Pirc coverage, if it wasn't for the annoying  5...Nh5! }
5... Bg7 6. h3 { Preventing Bg4. } 6... O-O 7. Bd3
{ The position is similar to the one we get in the c6-Pirc Chapter. I do think it's an improvement though, because we get an early e5-break which is quite annoying for Black. }
7... b5
{ 7...Nbd7  allows  8.e5!  when Be3-Qe2 will follow. We may even play a quickly h4-h5, with a dangerous attack. }
8. e5 { Is once again rather strong. } 8... Nd5
{ Black has to bite the bullet with this move.  8...Nfd7  could be met by the pawn break I mentioned:  9.h4  ,  when the pawn will soon go to h5 with a dangerous attack. }
9. Nxd5
{ My engine wants to castle, but this move looks better to me. Black will have less counterplay against our center, because c5 is no longer possible. }
9... cxd5 10. O-O Qb6 11. Kh1 { Moving out of the pin. } 11... Nc6 12. exd6
{ Is an improvement over Hendriks, R - Luberti, W Haarlem 1999 which continued with  12.c3  . }
12... exd6 13. c3 b4 14. f5 { Black will get slaughtered on the kingside. } *

