[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 c6
{ Before we get started with more mainstream stuff, we should knock this system out. This move is not as dumb as it looks as Black can develop his queen to a5, applying pressure on our pawn on e4. If we decide to defend the e4 pawn with a move like Bd3, Black can pressure the pawn on d4 with e5. All other options will be covered in future chapters: Philidor Defense, Pirc Defense and Nbd7 which is what GM Simon Williams called 'The Risky Lion'. }
4. f4
{ This is the best way to punish Black's third move, as e5 is already a rather annoying threat. After the text move, Black has many different options in his arsenal. }
4... Qa5 { The main move which should be no surprise. } 5. Bd3
{ This is objectively the best way to proceed, but it does contain an annoying amount of theory. My colleague and very slightly better chess player GM Wesley So advocates for  5.e5  as it is more concrete and trickier. Not a bad choice either, so feel free to investigate it. It is not as strong as the text move, though. }
5... d5
{ GM Robert Hess among others has played this move with some success, so let's take a look. }
6. Bd2 Qb6
{ This move is slightly more challenging, but that doesn't mean that the resulting position is satisfactory for Black.   6...dxe4  Does not accomplish anything.  7.Nxe4  Qd5  8.Qe2  We will sacrifice a pawn for an insane initiative.  8...Nxe4  9.Bxe4!  Not 9. Qxe4 which gives Black a rather comfortable endgame.  9...Qxd4  10.O-O-O  If you paid attention in the coverage of the Scandinavian Defense, it should be clear to you that we have magnificent compensation for the missing pawn. }
7. e5 Ne4 8. Nf3 { Let's defend the d4-pawn. } 8... Bf5
{ Three strong players have played this move, but it can be refuted. } 9. Ng5
{ Increasing our pressure on e4, while utilizing the pin on the knight. Black has different moves, but none are good enough for a satisfactory game: }
9... Na6
{ Can be met by the simple   9...e6  Now we must play  10.Bxe4!  If we capture with the knight, Black is able to grab the pawn on d4 when things are not as clear as they should be.  10...dxe4  11.g4!  Once again we will play against the bishop.  11...Bg6  12.Qe2  O-O-O will come next, along with a nasty f5-break and a potential capture on e4. I doubt that Black will survive for long.   9...Qxd4  Looks like the most critical move.  10.Bxe4!  Taking with the knight would just give Black a tempo on our bishop on d3, so we must take with the bishop.  10...dxe4  11.Qe2  Our initiative will be overwhelming very soon. }
10. Ncxe4 dxe4 11. Bc4 e6 { And now, the beautiful refutation is } 12. g4 Bg6
{ 12...Qxd4  loses a piece after  13.Bxa6  . } 13. f5
{ Black can kiss this game goodbye. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9. Czech Pirc"]
[Black "4...Qa5 (5...e5 6...Nbd7)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 c6 4. f4
{ This is the best way to punish Black's third move, as e5 is already a rather annoying threat. 4. Nf3 isn't as challenging, as Black can transpose into the Pirc or Philidor. After the text move, Black has many different options in his arsenal: }
4... Qa5 { The main move which should be no surprise. } 5. Bd3
{ This is objectively the best way to proceed, but it does contain an annoying amount of theory. My colleague and very slightly better chess player GM Wesley So advocates for  5.e5  as it is more concrete and trickier. Not a bad choice either, so feel free to investigate it. It is not as strong as the text move, though. }
5... e5 { Black's idea, and by far the most popular move. } 6. Nf3
{ Black now has three different ways of defending the pawn on d4. } 6... Nbd7
{ Is a natural move when Black keeps his control over the center. } 7. O-O Be7
8. Kh1
{ It's always good to make this prophylactic move, getting out of harm's way. }
8... O-O 9. Qe1
{ Not only does this move contribute to our attack, it also aims to meet exd4 with Nd5, when we grab the bishop pair. }
9... Qc7
{ The most popular move in the position, but it's close to losing....   9...Re8  Gives us a vicious attack after  10.dxe5  dxe5  11.f5  b5  12.g4→  I don't really see how Black will survive the onslaught. Our attack plays itself.  12...Nxg4  A human would probably take the pawn, which we can meet with  13.Rg1  Ngf6  14.Bh6  g6  15.Qh4+-  Our knight is going to g5 and our rook to f1. The knight on c3 will also be re-routed to e3. Black has no counterplay at all. In case you find b4 annoying you can always play a3. }
10. g4
{ This aggressive pawn launch is a real stinger, and in fact, a novelty. The idea is clear - ATTACK! }
10... exd4
{ 10...Nxg4  Taking the pawn immediately allows  11.dxe5  dxe5  12.f5→  The fixed structure is a huge advantage for us. Black won't survive for long. }
11. Nxd4 Nc5
{ An engine type of defense, Black wants to meet g5 with Nxd3 and perhaps also counterstrike in the center with d5. }
12. f5 d5 { Black is striking back. } 13. e5 { We can't allow Nfxe4. } 13...
Nxg4 14. Qg3
{ 14.Bf4  might look tempting, but it doesn't lead anywhere after  14...Nxd3  15.cxd3  Qb6  . }
14... f6
{ A very interesting sacrifice.   14...Nf6  A funny-looking defense. If we take the knight, Black will get some strong pawns in the center when things are less clear.  15.Qg1+-  The refutation. If Black moves the knight he loses a piece after f6. The pawn on e5 can't be touched either due to Bf4. }
15. Qxg4 fxe5 16. Ne6 { The most concrete. } 16... Bxe6 17. fxe6 e4 18. Bh6 Bf6
19. Be3 { A great move, aiming to capture the annoying knight on c5. } 19...
Qe7 20. Bxc5 { Just in time, otherwise we're losing the pawn on e6. } 20...
Qxc5
{ And now, I think the best practical option is to give back the piece with }
21. Bxe4 dxe4 22. Nxe4 Qe7 23. Rad1
{ Black has an extremely unpleasant position in front of him, considering that a rook will arrive to d7 any time. }
