{ The main move which should be no surprise. } 5. Bd3
{ This is objectively the best way to proceed, but it does contain an annoying amount of theory. My colleague and very slightly better chess player GM Wesley So advocates for  5.e5  as it is more concrete and trickier. Not a bad choice either, so feel free to investigate it. It is not as strong as the text move, though. }
5... e5 { Black's idea, and by far the most popular move. } 6. Nf3
{ Black now has three different ways of defending the pawn on d4. } 6... exd4
{ The capture is one way to avoid the loss of the pawn on e5. } 7. Nxd4 Be7 8.
Be3 Ng4
{ One always dreads this knight jump, but it's nothing to worry about.   8...O-O  9.h3  h3 is always a useful move as it prevents Black from placing a piece on g4.  9...Na6  10.O-O  Qc7  Black prepares Nc5. Playing it right away would have allowed Nb3.  11.Qf3  The queen is well placed here.  11...Nc5  12.Be2  White has more space and a rather comfortable position. We will chase away the knight on c5 next with b4. If Black plays a5, we can play Rad1 followed by Rfe1 and trade knights with Nb3 at some point. }
9. Bg1
{ The bishop is nicely placed on g1, although our castling will be delayed. }
9... O-O 10. Qf3 Na6 11. O-O-O
{ Change of plans! However, a move like Nb3 or h3 was also strong. } 11... Nc5
{ This position was on the table in Galdunts,S -Holvason,J Germany 2016, when White should have kept it simple with }
12. h3 Nf6 13. Kb1
{ White's kingside attack plays itself. Black has little counterplay, and moves like b5 will weaken c6 tremendously. Black's hanging in there, but barely. }
