1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 c6 4. f4 Qa5
{ The main move which should be no surprise. } 5. Bd3
{ This is objectively the best way to proceed, but it does contain an annoying amount of theory. My colleague and very slightly better chess player GM Wesley So advocates for  5.e5  as it is more concrete and trickier. Not a bad choice either, so feel free to investigate it. It is not as strong as the text move, though. }
5... e5 { Black's idea, and by far the most popular move. } 6. Nf3
{ Black now has three different ways of defending the pawn on d4. } 6... exd4
{ The capture is one way to avoid the loss of the pawn on e5. } 7. Nxd4 g6
{ This move was played by The Komodo Dragon, a chess player that far surpasses any human in strength, meaning we must take a look at the move. }
8. O-O Bg7 { After 8... Qb6 we should move the bishop to e2 or c4. } 9. Kh1
{ Let's move out of the pin. } 9... O-O 10. Qe1
{ The queen is headed to h4 along with a f5 pawn push which will put Black under a powerful attack. }
10... Nbd7 11. f5
{ This move opens up the bishop's diagonal and prevents Black from putting the queen on h5 as seen after   11.Qh4  Qh5! }
11... Ng4 { Gaining additional control over e5 while attacking the knight. }
12. Qh4 Nge5 13. Be2 Qd8 { Bringing the queen to the defence is logical. } 14.
Bg5 Bf6 15. Bxf6
{ Black now has a choice, but the computers think Black is struggling. } 15...
Nxf6
{ Komodo tried this capture, but it seems to me that the engine underestimated White's attack.   15...Qxf6  16.Qg3  We shouldn't trade queens.  16...Qg7  17.a4  Grabbing space while preventing a futuristic b5.  17...Nf6  Black now wants to play gxf5 and trade queens, which we should prevent with  18.Qh4  A correspondence game proceeded with  18...Bd7  19.Rad1  Black is struggling with the weak pawn on d6.  19...Rae8  20.Nf3!  Now Black loses the d6-pawn.  20...d5  21.Nxe5  Rxe5  22.Qf4  Now Black's best bet is to sacrifice a piece with  22...Nxe4  23.f6  Qxf6  24.Qxf6  Nxf6  25.Rxf6  But I doubt it's enough for survival. Indeed, White eventually prevailed in Vliet,E -Pastor Alonso De Prado,A ICCF email 2018. }
16. Nf3
{ White wants to get rid of the knight on e5 and then start an attack with g4-g5. }
16... Qe7 17. Nxe5
{ My upgraded Stockfish thinks that 17. g4 could be even better, but it does look rather complex. The text move is simpler. }
17... Qxe5 18. Rf3
{ Not only can White double the rook in the f-file, but he can also place the rook on h3. }
18... b5 { Trying to create some counterplay. } 19. Raf1 Kg7 20. Rh3
{ White's attack is becoming incredibly dangerous. } 20... b4 21. Qh6+ Kg8 22.
Nb1
{ It's even hard for the engine to initially spot that White's winning here, as the position requires precision. The computer game continued: }
22... Bxf5 23. Rh4 Rfe8 24. Nd2 Qxb2 25. Bd3 Bd7 26. Nf3
{ 26.e5  is also good as it wins a piece, but the engine thinks this move is even better. }
26... Nh5 27. e5 { Threatening Rxh5. } 27... Rxe5 28. g4
{ White wins material.  28...Nf6  is met by  29.g5!  so Black's position is in ruins. I leave the engine game as a clickable, as it's a pleasure to see how the game ended.   28...Rd5  29.gxh5  Qg7  30.Qf4  Be6  31.Ng5  Re5  32.Nxe6  Rxe6  33.Qf3  d5  34.Rf4  Re7  35.Rf6  Rae8  36.Rxc6  Qe5  37.hxg6  fxg6  38.Bxg6  hxg6  39.Rxg6+  Kh8  40.Rg2  Rd7  41.Rfg1  Qe4  42.Qf6+  Kh7  43.Qg5  Komodo would be mate in short notice, so the resignation was a factor in Stockfish 20200701- Komodo 2566.00 TCEC 2020. }
