{ Black now has three different ways of defending the pawn on d4. } 6... exd4
{ The capture is one way to avoid the loss of the pawn on e5. } 7. Nxd4 Qb6
{ Black has achieved nothing after  7...Bg4  8.Qd2  . The text move is very interesting and Black's best bet according to my engine. }
8. Be2 { The best way to defend the knight. } 8... d5
{ A very interesting move because of. . . } 9. e5 Bc5
{ I was shocked and rather annoyed when I discovered how extremely complicated the game becomes after this move. The complications do show nicely the art of chess, although it's a whole lot to memorize!  9...Ne4  has been seen twice, but our game is simple after a knight capture followed by  c3  . }
10. Be3
{ The way forward.  10.Na4  Was seen in the only game with this line, but White lost her advantage quickly.  10...Qa5+  11.c3  Bxd4  12.Qxd4  Ne4  13.Be3  Na6  14.Bf3  f5  Black's position was now only slightly worse.  15.exf6  Nxf6  16.Nc5  Qxc5  17.Qxc5  Nxc5  18.Bxc5  Bf5  19.Bd4  Kf7  20.O-O  White offered a draw which Black accepted in Milliet, S -Koch, J Brest 2018. A fair result as White's advantage was all gone. }
10... Qxb2 { And now the forced sequence } 11. Na4 Bb4+ 12. Kf1 Qa3 13. c3
{ Threatening to trap the queen with Bc1. } 13... Bxc3 14. Bc1
{ An important move, as taking on c3 right away leaves our bishop on e3 hanging. }
14... Qb4 15. Nxc3 Qxc3 16. exf6
{ Everything in the line has been forced so far. We're sacrificing an exchange, but Black will get an army of pieces against his king. }
16... Qxa1 17. fxg7 Rg8 18. Kf2
{ We must get our rook to e1 asap, otherwise Black will have time for Nd7-Nc5/ Nf6-Ne4. }
18... Nd7
{ This move deserves an exclam as it is Black's best defense.   18...Rxg7  19.Qd2!  Getting ready to trap Black's queen with Re1 followed by a bishop move.  19...Qb1  Black's best bet to avoid a queen loss.  20.Re1  Qb6   20...Kd8  21.Ba3  Qg6  Is another way to try to escape our attack, but it also fails.  22.Be7+  Kc7  23.Bf3  f5 is now a threat, followed by Qf4. Black can parry it with f5 or Bf5, but both moves will be met by Qc3 when our attack decides the game.  21.Qe3+  Kd8  22.Ba3  Black won't survive the attack.  22...f6  23.Bf8  Black loses material.  23...Rf7   23...c5  is met by  24.Bxc5!  24.Bh5  All our pieces collaborate. A beautiful position.   18...c5  A decent practical attempt, but nothing else.  19.Re1!  The nail on the coffin. Black has lost control of b5 and d5, so he is dead lost here.  19...Qxd4+  20.Qxd4  cxd4  21.Bb5+  Kd8  22.Re8+  Rxe8  23.Bxe8  Our pawn promotes after this beautiful sequence. Amazing stuff.   18...Qxa2  19.Qd3!  Is the most effective antidote.  19...Rxg7  20.Qe3+  Kd8  21.Ba3  f6  22.Qc3  The queen on a2 will be trapped. }
19. Re1 Qxa2
{ Now loses to the deep   19...Nc5!  The knight on c5 is a strong defensive piece as it can interfere on e4.  20.Kg1!   The only move.  20.Bf3?  Be6  21.f5  Qxc1!!  is equal, according to the engine.  20...Ne4  21.Bf3!  We must act before Black plays Bd7 and O-O-O.  21...Rxg7  22.f5!   It's essential to prevent Black from playing  Be6  .  22.Bxe4  dxe4  23.Rxe4+  would allow  Be6  when Black survives. Too lazy to go into details ;  22...Qxa2  23.Re2!  Preventing any sorts of nonsense on g2.  23...Qc4  24.Bxe4  dxe4  25.Rxe4+  Be6  26.fxe6  O-O-O  The job is still not done!  27.e7  Re8  28.Nf5  A beautiful move, making use of the knight fork on d6.  28...Rxg2+  29.Kh1  Rd2  A funny defense, aiming to take on e4 with check.  30.Qe1  Qd3   30...Rd1  loses to  31.Nd6!  31.Bxd2  Qf3+  32.Kg1  Qxf5  33.h4  Our extra piece and strong passed pawn decide the game. A fantastic variation has come to an end. Phew! }
20. Kf1 { Not  20.Qd3?  which allows  20...Nf6!! } 20... Kd8 21. Qd3 Rxg7 22.
Qh3
{ f5 will soon come, opening up for our bishop when Black's king doesn't have sufficient shelter. }
