1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 c6 4. f4 Qa5
{ The main move which should be no surprise. } 5. Bd3
{ This is objectively the best way to proceed, but it does contain an annoying amount of theory. My colleague and very slightly better chess player GM Wesley So advocates for  5.e5  as it is more concrete and trickier. Not a bad choice either, so feel free to investigate it. It is not as strong as the text move, though. }
5... e5 { Black's idea, and by far the most popular move. } 6. Nf3
{ Black now has three different ways of defending the pawn on d4. } 6... Bg4
{ Defending the e5 pawn with a pin is the most common way to proceed. } 7. Be3
{ This developing move is natural, defending the pawn on d4. } 7... d5
{ This tricky move has been played by some strong players, but it doesn't work for Black. }
8. fxe5 Nxe4 9. O-O
{ Black is too undeveloped and may soon be in trouble down the f-file. } 9...
Nxc3 10. bxc3 Be7 { Preventing a nasty knight jump to g5. } 11. Rb1 Qc7 12. Qe1
{ The queen is heading to g3 where it will create nasty threats. } 12... Be6
13. Qg3
{ My good friend Haldorsen, B had done everything correctly against Lazic, M in Novi Sad 2021, and was already completely winning.  13...g6  should follow when we will jump to  g5  . Black's busted, as taking the knight makes the dark squares in his camp far too weak. }
