1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 c6 4. f4 Qa5
{ The main move which should be no surprise. } 5. Bd3
{ This is objectively the best way to proceed, but it does contain an annoying amount of theory. My colleague and very slightly better chess player GM Wesley So advocates for  5.e5  as it is more concrete and trickier. Not a bad choice either, so feel free to investigate it. It is not as strong as the text move, though. }
5... e5 { Black's idea, and by far the most popular move. } 6. Nf3
{ Black now has three different ways of defending the pawn on d4. } 6... Bg4
{ Defending the e5 pawn with a pin is the most common way to proceed. } 7. Be3
{ This developing move is natural, defending the pawn on d4. } 7... exd4
{ Another attempt played by many 2500+ players, but this is also subpar. } 8.
Bxd4 Qb4
{ This move is always played. Other moves are met by h3 when Black has a terrible position. }
9. Be2
{ The only move that wins. Black's doing fairly okay after 9. Bxf6, and moving the bishop back will simply allow a queen capture on b2. }
9... Nxe4 { The critical try, but it's incredibly greedy. } 10. O-O d5 11. a3
{ Chasing away the queen. } 11... Qe7
{ 11...Qd6  Is a defense that prevents Nxe4, but instead we can play:  12.Ng5!  The strongest resource. We're getting rid of the knight on e4 which will greatly benefit us due to Black's unsafe king.  12...Nxg5  13.Bxg4  Black's king is too exposed.  13...Ne6  14.Bxe6  fxe6  15.Qh5+  I don't think Black will survive for long. }
12. Nxe4 dxe4 13. Ng5
{ Black will soon pay the price for his lack of development. } 13... Bxe2 14.
Qxe2 f5
{ It's too risky to protect the pawn. Other moves can be met by Rad1 followed by b4, for example. }
15. Qh5+ g6 16. Qh3 Bg7 { If  16...Rg8  ,  17.Qb3  wins. } 17. Bxg7 Qxg7 18.
Ne6 { The engine wants a rook to d1 first, but this is more than good enough. }
18... Qe7 19. Qc3 Rg8 20. Qb3
{ Black can't avoid the loss of an exchange as  20...Rh8  is met by  21.Rad1  and a doubling on the d-file, which will soon be fatal. White won a long game in Brodsky, M - Rakhmangulov, A Nikolaev 1995. }
