[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9. Czech Pirc"]
[Black "Czech-Pirc Conclusion"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 c6
{ CONCLUSION: The Czech Pirc is a rare breed that we should make extinct if we know what we are doing. }
4. f4 Qa5 5. Bd3
{ After this move there is an annoying amount of theory to learn, but the hard work will pay off. Sure, I didn't want to make this 'sideline' into an entire chapter, but sometimes you just need to bite the bullet. }
5... e5 6. Nf3 { Black now has three different ways to defend the pawn. } 6...
Bg4
{ I think Black's positions after the main line are rather sad. It's not difficult to handle the position from the white side, as Black is just terribly passive.   6...Nbd7  is the worst move, as Black tends to become awfully passive in these positions.   6...exd4  is interesting, but those positions also tend to become very comfortable for us as there are great opportunities for a powerful attack.  7.Nxd4  Qb6  The line Komodo played against Stockfish.  8.Be2  d5  where the game suddenly takes a highly complicated turn. Sure, Black loses by force, but White needs to play extremely accurately. }
7. Be3 Nbd7 8. O-O Be7 9. h3
{ Perhaps Black should play the move  9...Bh5  and try to survive these resulting positions, but if that's the case, he might as well play a different opening!  After  9...Bxf3  , Black is even worse, where I think we're already winning! I will repeat myself and remind you that rare lines remain rare for a reason. Against unprepared opponents, Black might be 'living the dream' but against prepared opponents, Black will surely regret the unorthodox opening choice. }
