[Black "2...Bg7 (4...c6 1)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 g6 2. d4
{ As always we will take full control of the center if we get the chance. }
2... Bg7 { I'd say this move will be played against you 99/100 times... } 3.
Nc3
{ There are a bunch of different set-ups we can go for, but I think the knight move is the most critical option. The Main Line gives Black a plethora of options, which will all be covered in this chapter. }
3... d6 4. Be3 c6
{ A rather typical move in g6-systems. In comparison to a6, Black takes control of the d5-square. However, Black doesn't get the nice diagonal for his bishop on b7 as the c6-pawn blocks it. The system has been played a decent amount and it's likely to transpose to the Pirc as Black can play Nf6 anytime. }
5. f4
{ This space-grabbing move is highly common against Pirc/Modern, and I discovered that it was the most practical move when considering the repertoire. There are many good moves of course, but Black can always transpose to the Pirc with Nf6 when we are at risk of getting move-ordered. Therefore, this move made sense due to transpositions. }
5... Qb6
{ This move is the most popular try behind 5... Nf6, and indeed a thematic move. }
6. a3
{ I'm honestly baffled that this move hasn't been played in more games. It's a very typical way to face Qb6 as we've already seen, because the pawn on b2 can't be touched. }
6... Nf6
{ 6...e5  The Qb6-advocate GM Victor Bologan played this move and beat a strong GM.  7.Nf3  Bg4  7... Nd7 is what my engine suggests, but Black is still in trouble after 8. Nd2 when the knight is headed to c4.  8.Qd2  Now Black is forced to head into a terrible ending due to the threat of dxe5.  8...exf4  9.Bxf4  Bxf3  If not, we'll simply castle long with a dominating position.  10.gxf3  Qxd4  11.Qxd4  Bxd4  12.Bxd6  Nd7  13.O-O-O  This move was better than 13. Bh3, when Black got some counterplay with 13... Ne5 in Palac,M - Bologan,V Cannes 2006. White was still much better, but Victor did prevail in the end. After the text move is incredibly passive as Bh3 will come soon. Black will probably play Bc5/Be5 to trade bishops, when we will then be able to double our rooks. }
7. Nf3 Bg4
{ Black plays actively and may soon think about an e5-break, or even a capture on f3. }
8. Rb1
{ It's best to keep the pawn on b2 defended, so Black won't be able to pull off any tricks. }
8... d5
{ Two strong GMs played this dubious move, so we will take a look. Other moves could be met by h3 for example, when we get a rather comfortable game. Black's queen on b6 looks rather silly. }
9. e5 Ne4 10. Nxe4 { Accurately calculated by GM Vishy. } 10... dxe4 11. h3 Be6
{ 11... Bxf3 isn't impressive either as we can simply take, followed by an expansion on the queenside with b4/c4. }
12. Nd2 Nd7 13. b4
{ I think this move is better than  13.Qc1  , which is what GM Vishy did in Anand, V - Lobron, E Munich 1991. However, Vishy won convincingly. }
13... f5 14. c4 { Our powerful center gives us a huge advantage. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10. Modern (1...g6) Minor Sidelines"]
[Black "2...Bg7 (4...c6 2)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 d6 4. Be3 c6 5. f4
{ This space-grabbing move is highly common against Pirc/Modern, and I discovered that it was the most practical move when considering the repertoire. There are many good moves of course, but Black can always transpose to the Pirc with Nf6 when we are at risk of getting move-ordered. Therefore, this move made sense due to transpositions. }
5... Nd7 6. Nf3 Ngf6
{ 6...e5?!  Another typical move, but it's not so strong here.  7.Bc4  Aiming on the f7-square.  7...Ngf6  Played three times, but it's inaccurate. Black has to bite the bullet with 7... exf4, but then it's clear that we are much better after 8. Bxf4 because of our activity.  8.fxe5  dxe5  9.dxe5  Ng4  Black's concept would have worked if it wasn't for:  10.Bxf7+!  A nice tactical shot.  10...Kxf7  11.Ng5+  Ke8  12.Qxg4  Nxe5  13.Qg3  Black's king is stuck in the center, so his position is essentially hopeless. Dominguez Perez,L - Galaktionov,A Chess.com INT 2020. }
7. h3 { I want to play h3 before we strike in the center with e5. } 7... Nh5
{ Is Black's attempt to punish our early h3-push as the square on g3 is suddenly weak. }
8. Rg1
{ Moving the rook out of the way is best, because we can castle queenside. Black has to watch out for a g4-push, so it's logical to play }
8... e5 9. fxe5 dxe5 10. d5
{ We shouldn't allow Black to open the position, when our king could be in jeopardy. }
10... cxd5
{ Black avoids a weak pawn on c6, but the price to pay is too high.   10...O-O  11.dxc6  bxc6  12.Qd6  Black has castled, but his pawn structure has suffered in the process.  12...Nb6  13.O-O-O  It's better to castle and complete the development, than giving Black counterplay after 13... Qxc6 Be6.  13...Qxd6  14.Rxd6  Black is still holding on, but it won't take many inaccuracies before the position is dead lost. }
11. Qxd5
{ Gaining an important tempo in development as we are aiming to castle queenside. }
11... Nhf6 12. Qd6 { Is strong, preventing Black from castling. } 12... Qe7 13.
Nb5 Qxd6 { Black has nothing better. } 14. Nxd6+ Ke7 15. O-O-O
{ Black has gotten himself into a rather gloomy situation. } *

