1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 d6 4. Be3 c6 5. f4
{ This space-grabbing move is highly common against Pirc/Modern, and I discovered that it was the most practical move when considering the repertoire. There are many good moves of course, but Black can always transpose to the Pirc with Nf6 when we are at risk of getting move-ordered. Therefore, this move made sense due to transpositions. }
5... Nd7 6. Nf3 Ngf6
{ 6...e5?!  Another typical move, but it's not so strong here.  7.Bc4  Aiming on the f7-square.  7...Ngf6  Played three times, but it's inaccurate. Black has to bite the bullet with 7... exf4, but then it's clear that we are much better after 8. Bxf4 because of our activity.  8.fxe5  dxe5  9.dxe5  Ng4  Black's concept would have worked if it wasn't for:  10.Bxf7+!  A nice tactical shot.  10...Kxf7  11.Ng5+  Ke8  12.Qxg4  Nxe5  13.Qg3  Black's king is stuck in the center, so his position is essentially hopeless. Dominguez Perez,L - Galaktionov,A Chess.com INT 2020. }
7. h3 { I want to play h3 before we strike in the center with e5. } 7... O-O 8.
e5 Nd5
{ 8...dxe5  9.dxe5  Nd5   Black has to play actively. After  9...Nh5  , we can play  10.Kf2!  when  g4  will follow suit. Black will get smashed on the kingside.  10.Nxd5  cxd5  11.g4!?  This attacking move is something we will play sooner or later.  11...Nb6   Black has to play actively.  11...e6  is very human, but it's terrible due to  12.g5!  Black will get slaughtered on the kingside, with zero counterplay.  12...Qc7  13.h4  White was well on his way to victory in Garcia Rodriguez, I - Bonoldi, F ICCF email 2006.  12.Qe2  Qc7  13.O-O-O  Nc4  14.Kb1  Black's attack is getting nowhere. He might have to fight our space with the weakening f6, when we can defend with Bc1. Note that a capture on e5 is met by a rook capture on d5. }
9. Nxd5 cxd5 10. Qd2 Nb6
{ Black may soon get decent play with Bf5-Rc8-Nc4, so we must stay put. } 11.
b3 { We should prevent Black from playing Nc4. } 11... dxe5
{ Was seen in a couple of email-games. } 12. dxe5 f6
{ Black aims to open the diagonal, thus gaining counterplay against our center. }
13. exf6 Bxf6 14. O-O-O
{ White is better, but Black does have a decent amount of counterplay. } 14...
Bf5 15. Bd3 { Neutralizing some of Black's activity. } 15... Bxd3 16. Qxd3
{ Black has some weaknesses in his cap, giving us a clearly better game. A logical continuation is: }
16... Rc8 17. Kb1 e6 18. Rhe1
{ The evaluation is justified by Black's backward pawn on e6. } *

