1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 d6 4. Be3 c6 5. f4
{ This space-grabbing move is highly common against Pirc/Modern, and I discovered that it was the most practical move when considering the repertoire. There are many good moves of course, but Black can always transpose to the Pirc with Nf6 when we are at risk of getting move-ordered. Therefore, this move made sense due to transpositions. }
5... Nd7 6. Nf3 Ngf6
{ 6...e5?!  Another typical move, but it's not so strong here.  7.Bc4  Aiming on the f7-square.  7...Ngf6  Played three times, but it's inaccurate. Black has to bite the bullet with 7... exf4, but then it's clear that we are much better after 8. Bxf4 because of our activity.  8.fxe5  dxe5  9.dxe5  Ng4  Black's concept would have worked if it wasn't for:  10.Bxf7+!  A nice tactical shot.  10...Kxf7  11.Ng5+  Ke8  12.Qxg4  Nxe5  13.Qg3  Black's king is stuck in the center, so his position is essentially hopeless. Dominguez Perez,L - Galaktionov,A Chess.com INT 2020. }
7. h3 { I want to play h3 before we strike in the center with e5. } 7... O-O 8.
e5 Nd5 9. Nxd5 cxd5 10. Qd2 Nb6
{ Black may soon get decent play with Bf5-Rc8-Nc4, so we must stay put. } 11.
b3 { We should prevent Black from playing Nc4. } 11... Bf5
{ 8 games have been played in this position, when White's result has been rather decent with 4 wins and 4 draws. }
12. Bd3 Bxd3 13. Qxd3 { White has more space which gives him a slight edge. }
13... Qc7
{ Black aims to put pressure in the c-file.   13...Qd7  Makes some sense, when I suggest that we change our plans and castle kingside with  14.O-O  Rfc8  15.Rac1  Rc6  16.a4  White had a nice position in Greig,S - Vajas,S ICCF email 2017 and eventually prevailed. }
14. h4 { Going for an attack. } 14... Rfc8 15. O-O-O
{ A strong move.  15.Rc1  would allow a queen trade, when I doubt we have much. }
15... a5 16. Kb1 a4 17. h5
{ With an attack in Rogos, J - Williamson, H ICCF email 2018. Note that  17. ..axb3  is met by  18.cxb3!  as we can't afford to open the a-file.  CONCLUSION: With the c6-Modern, Black aims for Pirc-like play. The result of the opening is a good version of the Austrian Attack, since Black normally would have time for a quick O-O followed by c5, but this isn't possible when Black has played c6 and the knight is on g8! The positions are easier to handle and very comfortable for us. A nice and easy branch of The Modern, really. }
*

