1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 d6 4. Be3 c6 5. f4
{ This space-grabbing move is highly common against Pirc/Modern, and I discovered that it was the most practical move when considering the repertoire. There are many good moves of course, but Black can always transpose to the Pirc with Nf6 when we are at risk of getting move-ordered. Therefore, this move made sense due to transpositions. }
5... b5
{ A highly thematic move. Black expands on the queenside and may soon play b4 and chase away our knight on c3. }
6. a3 { I like to prevent Black from playing b4. } 6... a6
{ Black protects the b5-pawn so he can play c5 in the future. } 7. Nf3 Nd7
{ Protecting the pawn on b5 is sensible, as the c5-break is desirable.   7...Nf6  8.h3  And we're back in the Pirc Defense. }
8. Bd3
{ We have now transposed to the 6... b5-note in 5... Nd7. We keep developing our pieces. The bishop on d3 is also strong as it can eventually move to e4 and trade the bishops. }
8... c5 9. e5 Bb7 10. Be4
{ I like this move, trading the bishops and increasing the pressure. } 10...
Bxe4 11. Nxe4 cxd4
{ 11...Nh6  Is Black's best move as the knight can head to f5 or g4.  12.dxc5  Ng4  13.Qe2  dxe5  14.O-O-O  White has some initiative thanks to his active pieces. We will probably take on e5 next followed by Bd4, or even Nc3 to provoke Black to weak the d6-square with e6. }
12. Bxd4 { We must keep the pawn on e5 protected. } 12... dxe5 13. fxe5
{ e6 is now a deadly threat. } 13... Nf8 14. Nfg5
{ Black is in huge trouble. An instructive line is: } 14... h6 15. Nxf7
{ Black's king won't be able to survive the upcoming battle. } 15... Kxf7 16.
Qf3+ Ke8 17. O-O-O
{ Now that a rook will swing to f1 next, Black won't survive for long. } *

