1. e4 g6
{ With this move, Black aims to fianchetto his bishop on f8. The move is rather flexible as it can transpose to several different openings. The downside is clear though, as Black doesn't take control of the center. }
2. d4
{ As always we will take full control of the center if we get the chance. }
2... Bg7 { I'd say this move will be played against you 99/100 times... } 3.
Nc3
{ There are a bunch of different set-ups we can go for, but I think the knight move is the most critical option. If you're comfortable in King's Indian territory, you could certainly consider 3. c4, but that's another story. The Main Line gives Black a plethora of options, which will all be covered in this chapter. }
3... b6
{ Double-fianchettoing the bishops has been played by a decent amount of high-rated players, in particular GM Gata Kamsky. This is a typical move used in short time controls or against lower-rated opponents, but it has a clear downside. The problem is the fact that Black gives up the center completely, giving us a large space advantage. }
4. Be3 Bb7 5. Qd2 { We will see this set-up frequently throughout the course. }
5... d6 6. O-O-O
{ The usual antidote when Black has little central control is to create an attack. We will continue down the path here too, as Black's passivity will give us an overwhelming initiative on the kingside. }
6... e6 { Kamsky tried this, but it doesn't end well for Black. } 7. h4
{ Aiming to play h5 next.   If Black plays  7...Nf6  we will get our usual attack with f3-g4.   7...h5  isn't ideal either, as we can meet it with  8.Nh3  when we will have a fantastic outpost on g5. }
7... h6 8. h5 g5 { Was Black's idea, but GM Guseinov broke through with } 9. f4
gxf4 10. Bxf4 { Black's position is simply put, terrible. } 10... Nd7 11. Nf3
{ White's moves are very straightforward. } 11... a6 12. Kb1 b5
{ Now, in Guseinov,G - Kamsky,G Khanty-Mansiysk 2013, White should have played }
13. e5
{ when Black's position is extremely passive and already lost according to the engine. }
*

