1. e4 g6 2. d4
{ As always we will take full control of the center if we get the chance. }
2... Bg7 { I'd say this move will be played against you 99/100 times... } 3.
Nc3
{ There are a bunch of different set-ups we can go for, but I think the knight move is the most critical option. The Main Line gives Black a plethora of options, which will all be covered in this chapter. }
3... c5
{ This move is not good objectively, but we must be prepared against it. } 4.
dxc5 { Taking the bait is the most critical move. } 4... Bxc3+
{ The other alternative. Black hopes to make the game unbalanced with giving away this strong bishop for a damaged pawn structure.   4...Na6?  Was once played by GM Nakamura, but it doesn't work.  5.Bxa6  This move is logical and good.  5...bxa6  6.Nge2  Nf6  7.f3  All I see for Black is a destroyed pawn structure and a pawn down. The engine gives +3 already, and I believe him. }
5. bxc3 Nc6
{ Has been played by a couple of GMs among other strong players, so we should take a look. }
6. Bd3 { A natural developing move. } 6... Qa5
{ Always played and the best move, so we won't consider anything else. } 7. Ne2
Qxc5 8. O-O
{ Black has regained the pawn, but the undeveloped pieces and the exposed queen make the position miserable. }
8... Nf6 9. Rb1 { A strong move, playing against the queen. } 9... O-O 10. Rb5
Qd6 11. f4
{ I think this move is an improvement over the game Weil, T - Bowen, F ICCF email 2018, where White had played  11.c4  .  11.e5  is even more concrete. It's winning by force, but it requires us to play extremely accurately, something I don't think is necessary. The text move is easier. }
11... Qc7 12. Rg5 d6 13. Qe1
{ Black will be under a massive attack. Ideas like Qh4-Nd4 are strong. I don't see what Black is doing... }
*

