1. e4 g6 2. d4
{ As always we will take full control of the center if we get the chance. }
2... Bg7 { I'd say this move will be played against you 99/100 times... } 3.
Nc3
{ There are a bunch of different set-ups we can go for, but I think the knight move is the most critical option. The Main Line gives Black a plethora of options, which will all be covered in this chapter. }
3... c5
{ This move is not good objectively, but we must be prepared against it. } 4.
dxc5 { Taking the bait is the most critical move. } 4... Bxc3+
{ The other alternative. Black hopes to make the game unbalanced with giving away this strong bishop for a damaged pawn structure. }
5. bxc3 Nf6
{ An interesting try, played particularly in online games by FM Storey,C and IM Barria Zuniga,D. }
6. e5 Ne4 7. Bc4
{ The only move that leads to more than just a small advantage. The point is that we create a counterattack, as Black's f7-pawn in particular, is vulnerable. }
7... Qa5
{ Was seen in a recent email-game, but it doesn't work either.   7...e6?  Doesn't work, due to  8.Qd4  Qa5  9.Ne2!  Black will be extremely vulnerable on the dark squares.  9...Nxc5  10.O-O  Nc6  11.Qh4  Na4  12.Bg5  My Play Magnus Colleague ended up winning an online game here with Black, but her position would have been in major trouble after the text move in Gara, A -Dolzhikova,O Chess.com INT 2020. }
8. Ne2 { Simple, but efficient. } 8... Nxc5
{ 8...Qxc5  is dealt with  9.Qd4  , when White's edge in the endgame hits over +3, due to for instance the vulnerable knight on  e4  . }
9. Qd5
{ This is the only reason why our edge is decisive. The point is that we practically force Black to make the weakening move  9...e6  , when we will get fantastic dark-square control. }
9... e6 10. Qf3 Nc6 11. O-O
{ Black may soon find himself in major trouble if our bishop gets to g5, so he tried the desperate }
11... f5 12. exf6 O-O { But it doesn't help. } 13. Bh6 Rf7 14. Rfe1
{ The pawn on f6 is simply too strong. A game continued } 14... Ne5 15. Qf4
Nxc4 16. Qxc4 b6
{ Note that Black couldn't capture on f6 due to the threat of Qh4, when he can resign. }
17. Qf4 Bb7 18. Nd4 Qxc3 19. Rad1
{ White had a decisive attack in Wharrier,J - Knoeppel, B ICCF email 2017. } *

