8. Qd5 Ne6 9. Nf3
{ An important move. The natural move  9.Be3  lead nowhere for White in Taylor, A - Storey, C Torquay 2019, when Black even became slightly better after the further moves  9...Nc6  10.Nf3  b6  11.O-O  Bb7  . }
9... Nc6 10. Qe4
{ This move is clever, because we are now well prepared to meet Black's b6-Bb7 with Bd5 if needed. }
10... b6
{ 10...b5!?  The computer way to create counterplay.  11.Bd5  Bb7  12.a4  A strong move as we want to play c4 to reinforce our control over the d5-square.  12...bxa4  13.O-O  Qc7  14.c4  Sticking to the plan.  14...O-O  15.Re1  Black's position is rather passive due to our effective Bd5-plan.  15...Ng7  16.Qh4  Nf5  17.Qf4  Nd8  18.Ba3!  Maintaining the pressure.  18...Ne6  19.Qe4!  Gaining a tempo. Black has to take on d5 or lose the pawn on e7 as we are now prepared to play g4.  19...Bxd5  20.cxd5  Nc5  21.Qf4  White's advantage was already decisive in Lovakovic,F - Burmeister,F ICCF email 2017. }
11. O-O Bb7 12. Bd5
{ Black doesn't get the counterplay he got in the game Taylor,A - Storey,C. }
12... Nc7
{ Is not the best move in the position, but it is extremely natural from a human perspective. }
13. c4 { We got everything under control. } 13... e6 14. Bxc6
{ The simple way.  14.Bg5  is a rather beautiful piece sacrifice, after  14...exd5  15.cxd5  Ne7  16.c4  . The engine thinks it's dead lost, but it's not really necessary. }
14... Bxc6 15. Qe2
{ e6 is a move Black will surely regret due to the weak dark squares as we've seen earlier. }
