[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10. Modern (1...g6) Minor Sidelines"]
[Black "2...Bg7 (3...c5 6)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 g6 2. d4
{ As always we will take full control of the center if we get the chance. }
2... Bg7 { I'd say this move will be played against you 99/100 times... } 3.
Nc3
{ There are a bunch of different set-ups we can go for, but I think the knight move is the most critical option. The Main Line gives Black a plethora of options, which will all be covered in this chapter. }
3... c5
{ This move is not good objectively, but we must be prepared against it. } 4.
dxc5 { Taking the bait is the most critical move. } 4... Qa5
{ Is the most popular way to play for Black. } 5. Bd2 Qxc5
{ 5...Na6?  I'm only covering this move because of GM Guseinov, who played it once with Black.  6.Nb5!  The refutation.  6...Qd8  7.Bc3  Black won't be able to regain the pawn on c5 due to Qd4, attacking the knight and rook on h8.  7...Nf6  8.Qd4  A really strong move, guarding the two pawns.  8...O-O  9.e5  Black's knight will now be kicked back to e8.  9...Ne8  10.Nf3  My engine prefers 10. h4, but this natural move is also good.  10...Nec7  11.Nxc7  Qxc7  12.Bxa6  bxa6  13.O-O-O  White's extra pawn and active pieces gave him a decisive advantage in Bersamina, P - Cueto Chajtur,J Tromsoe 2014. }
6. Nd5 { The only way to test Black is to play against the vulnerable queen. }
6... b6
{ Is the second most popular move, but it's not good.   6...e6?  Has been played 14 times, and it loses to this beauty:  7.Bb4  Qc6  8.Bb5  The bishop can't be taken due to the fork on c7, so Black loses the queen. }
7. Bb4 Qc6 8. Bb5
{ We once again see this neat trick. Black does have a square on b7, so the queen escapes. }
8... Qb7 9. Qf3
{ A clever move, aiming to play Qg3 or Bc3. We may even play Bc4, pressuring f7. }
9... Nc6
{ 9...Bxb2  loses to  10.Bc3!  Bxa1  11.Bxa1  f6  And now, we must strike while the iron is hot with the move  12.e5!  Our bishop on a1 is a monster.  12...e6  13.exf6  Nh6  14.Qa3  Nc6  15.Nf3  After 15. Ba6 Black somehow pulled a Houdini and escaped in Zelesco,K - Chau,B Wahroonga 2014. The text move is a really simple move as we're planning to move the knight to d4. It's also worth noting that exd5 is met by Qe3+.  15...Nf7  16.Nd4  with a huge attack wich looks impossible to dodge. }
10. Bc3
{ Our plan all along, and the nail in the coffin. The engine hits more than +3 here! }
10... f6 { It makes sense to block the diagonal. } 11. Qg3
{ Threatening Nc7+. } 11... d6 12. h4 { A strong move, aiming to play h5. }
12... a6 13. Bxc6+ Qxc6 14. h5 g5 15. O-O-O
{ Black is extremely undeveloped, so he can't afford the opening of the position. }
15... e5 16. f4 { White will break through. } 16... h6 17. Nf3
{ Black has to worry about Nh4 or a sacrifice on e5. } 17... Be6 18. fxe5 fxe5
19. Bxe5
{ Black resigned in Kosic, B - Attard,I ICCF email 2010 as Black's pieces won't be able to handle all the upcoming threats. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10. Modern (1...g6) Minor Sidelines"]
[Black "2...Bg7 (3...c5 7)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 g6 2. d4
{ As always we will take full control of the center if we get the chance. }
2... Bg7 { I'd say this move will be played against you 99/100 times... } 3.
Nc3
{ There are a bunch of different set-ups we can go for, but I think the knight move is the most critical option. The Main Line gives Black a plethora of options, which will all be covered in this chapter. }
3... c5
{ This move is not good objectively, but we must be prepared against it. } 4.
dxc5 { Taking the bait is the most critical move. } 4... Qa5
{ Is the most popular way to play for Black. } 5. Bd2 Qxc5 6. Nd5
{ The only way to test Black is to play against the vulnerable queen. } 6...
Na6 { Black guards the c7-square and b4-square. } 7. Nf3 e6
{ The best move in the position. Black has to get rid of our monster-knight on d5.   7...Nf6?  Loses, after  8.b4!  Chasing away the queen while the pawn may advance to the b5-square as well.  8...Qd6  9.Bf4  We keep harassing the queen.  9...Qe6  10.Ng5!  Qc6  11.Be5!  Not many people are aware that this move is significantly stronger than 11. b5. Now the threat of b5 wins material.  11...h6  12.b5!  Just in time!  12...Qc5  13.Bd4  Nxd5  This attempt to complicate the game is the best try for survival.  14.Bxc5  Bc3+  15.Ke2  Nf4+  16.Ke3  Nxc5  17.Nxf7!  Without this resource, we have nothing.  17...O-O  18.Kxf4  Our king may look rather vulnerable, but we got it under control.  18...e5+  19.Ke3  Bd4+  20.Kd2  Stronger than 20. Ke2 which was seen in Belyakov,B - Boiarintsev,V Moscow 2018. That being said, 20. Ke2 also wins.  20...Nxe4+  21.Kc1  Our king escapes the enemy pieces.  21...Kxf7  The best try, but it doesn't save the game.  22.Qf3+  Nf6  23.Bc4+  Kg7  24.Rb1  Black's initiative has faded away, so he is left with a lost position. }
8. b4 Qf8
{ 8...Qd6?  Black steps into another landmine with this move.  9.Bf4  Qf8  We've now gotten Bf4 for free compared to the 8... Qf8-line.  10.Bxa6  exd5  11.O-O !  The refutation! We must get our king out of harm's way first!  11...Bxa1  12.Qxa1  A puny exchange doesn't make up for the lack of development.  12...f6  13.Bd3  With a bad king and undeveloped pieces Black didn't last long in Steingrimsson,H - Braun,C Germany 2009. The game continued:  13...Qxb4  14.Rb1  Qa4  15.Bb5  Qa3  16.e5  a6  17.exf6  Black resigned as he gets mated in short notice. }
9. Nc3
{ Now that we haven't gotten Bf4 for free, we can't afford to sac material. }
9... Qe7
{ Has also been tried, when we should play   9...Qxb4  My chess24 colleague, Alboredo,J faced this against Amura,C in Villa Martelli 2017. She played 10. Rb1 which was good, but  10.e5  was stronger! It's going to be difficult to stop a knight from coming to d6 in the foreseeable future. }
10. e5
{ We will once again make our way towards the d6-square. If Black takes on b4 with the knight we can also maneuever the bishop from d2 to a3 by the means of d2-c1-a3. }
10... f6 { A logical way to fight back. } 11. Ne4
{ A strong move.  11.Bxa6  followed by  Ne4  was good, too. } 11... fxe5 12.
Bg5 Qxb4+ 13. Nfd2
{ A knight was well on it's way to c4-d6 in Motta,P - Owens,J ICCF email 2014. One nice detail is that }
13... d5 { can be met by } 14. Bb5+ { when Black loses decisive material. } *

