Na6 { Black guards the c7-square and b4-square. } 7. Nf3 e6
{ The best move in the position. Black has to get rid of our monster-knight on d5.   7...Nf6?  Loses, after  8.b4!  Chasing away the queen while the pawn may advance to the b5-square as well.  8...Qd6  9.Bf4  We keep harassing the queen.  9...Qe6  10.Ng5!  Qc6  11.Be5!  Not many people are aware that this move is significantly stronger than 11. b5. Now the threat of b5 wins material.  11...h6  12.b5!  Just in time!  12...Qc5  13.Bd4  Nxd5  This attempt to complicate the game is the best try for survival.  14.Bxc5  Bc3+  15.Ke2  Nf4+  16.Ke3  Nxc5  17.Nxf7!  Without this resource, we have nothing.  17...O-O  18.Kxf4  Our king may look rather vulnerable, but we got it under control.  18...e5+  19.Ke3  Bd4+  20.Kd2  Stronger than 20. Ke2 which was seen in Belyakov,B - Boiarintsev,V Moscow 2018. That being said, 20. Ke2 also wins.  20...Nxe4+  21.Kc1  Our king escapes the enemy pieces.  21...Kxf7  The best try, but it doesn't save the game.  22.Qf3+  Nf6  23.Bc4+  Kg7  24.Rb1  Black's initiative has faded away, so he is left with a lost position. }
8. b4 Qf8
{ 8...Qd6?  Black steps into another landmine with this move.  9.Bf4  Qf8  We've now gotten Bf4 for free compared to the 8... Qf8-line.  10.Bxa6  exd5  11.O-O !  The refutation! We must get our king out of harm's way first!  11...Bxa1  12.Qxa1  A puny exchange doesn't make up for the lack of development.  12...f6  13.Bd3  With a bad king and undeveloped pieces Black didn't last long in Steingrimsson,H - Braun,C Germany 2009. The game continued:  13...Qxb4  14.Rb1  Qa4  15.Bb5  Qa3  16.e5  a6  17.exf6  Black resigned as he gets mated in short notice. }
9. Nc3
{ Now that we haven't gotten Bf4 for free, we can't afford to sac material. }
9... Nc7
{ Is the best way to try to consolidate the pieces.   9...Qxb4  My chess24 colleague, Alboredo,J faced this against Amura,C in Villa Martelli 2017. She played 10. Rb1 which was good, but  10.e5  was stronger! It's going to be difficult to stop a knight from coming to d6 in the foreseeable future. }
10. Rb1 { Moving out of the pin and protecting the pawn on b4. } 10... Qe7 11.
e5
{ A plan we saw in the other lines as well, taking control of the juicy d6-square. }
11... d5
{ Black has won both games here, but the wins are certainly not due to the opening. }
12. exd6 Qxd6
{ Black has eased off some of the pressure, but his position is still in jeopardy after }
13. Ne4 { Active play! } 13... Qc6 14. Bd3 f5
{ Black tries to get some activity, but it looks like it will only backfire. }
15. b5 Qd5 16. Nc3 Qd8 17. O-O
{ Black's pawn on e6 has become rather weak, while he is also struggling with poor development. }
17... Nh6 18. Bc4 Nf7 19. Qe2 { All eyes on the target on e6. } 19... O-O 20.
Rfd1 Bd7 21. a4 Re8 22. a5
{ Na4 will come next, when h4 may follow suit, controlling the g5-square. Black's position is really passive. If we're able to, we would also like to play Bb3 followed by c4 in the future.   22.Bb3  which happened in Gonzalez Sanchez, F - Heini, H ICCF email 2018 was also strong. Black ended up winning the game due to something that I suspect was a typo as White blundered his rook in one move. However, Black had fought well, so the objective evaluation was only clearly better which should lead to a draw before the unfortunate incident. }
