[Black "2...Bg7 (3...d5 3)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 g6 2. d4
{ As always we will take full control of the center if we get the chance. }
2... Bg7 { I'd say this move will be played against you 99/100 times... } 3.
Nc3
{ There are a bunch of different set-ups we can go for, but I think the knight move is the most critical option. The Main Line gives Black a plethora of options, which will all be covered in this chapter. }
3... d5
{ Is a highly interesting pawn sacrifice which could even be the best move in the position. Black's scheme is to develop quickly and regain the pawn at a later stage with Nbd7-Nb6. }
4. exd5 { Taking the pawn is the best way to fight for an edge. } 4... Nf6 5.
Bc4 Nbd7 { Black should try to regain the pawn as fast as possible. } 6. Nf3
Nb6 7. Bb3 O-O { The most accurate move is to castle. } 8. O-O Nbxd5 9. Nxd5
Nxd5 10. Ne5 { Gives White a better game. } 10... c6 11. Re1 Be6
{ Having a4-a5 included would lead to the main line. However, let's see how lethal it is for Black not having it included!   11...Bf5!?  Black has drawn twice with this move.  12.c3  Supporting our center.  12...a5  13.h3  Logical prophylactic moves to improve the position.  13...Qb6  14.g4  Bc8  We have followed Stephaniec,L - Brzoza,M ICCF email 2015, when I think White should have played  15.Nd3  White has a clearly better position due to the better pieces and central control. }
12. h4 { Launching an attack. } 12... h5
{ This works in the main line, but not here. Other moves give us easy play with h5 and c3. }
13. Nxg6 Bg4 14. f3 Bxf3 15. Qxf3 fxg6 16. Qd3 Kh7
{ A major problem for Black is that the bishop on  b3  no longer hangs after  16...Qb6  17.c3  . }
17. c3
{ Black's king is extremely vulnerable, so vulnerable that I think the position might be lost already. }
