{ There are a bunch of different set-ups we can go for, but I think the knight move is the most critical option. The Main Line gives Black a plethora of options, which will all be covered in this chapter. }
3... d5
{ Is a highly interesting pawn sacrifice which could even be the best move in the position. Black's scheme is to develop quickly and regain the pawn at a later stage with Nbd7-Nb6. }
4. exd5 { Taking the pawn is the best way to fight for an edge. } 4... Nf6 5.
Bc4 Nbd7 { Black should try to regain the pawn as fast as possible. } 6. Nf3
Nb6 7. Bb3 O-O { The most accurate move is to castle. } 8. O-O a5
{ The exclam might seem exaggerated, but it's advantageous for Black to have a5-a4 included. }
9. a4 Nbxd5 10. Nxd5 Nxd5 11. Ne5
{ Seems like the most testing continuation for Black's concept. } 11... Be6 12.
Re1 c6 13. h4
{ Aiming for the h5-break is a rather uncomfortable plan for Black to face. In Libiszewski, F - Remolar Gallen, J Barbera del Valles 2012, Black was fine after  13.c3  Qb6  14.Ra3  Rad8  . }
13... h5
{ This defensive move works tactically, making it by far the best move. } 14.
Nxg6
{ Is the trickiest move.  14.c4!?  Is another testing option for Black.  14...Nf6  15.Nxg6  This leads to a force line:  15...Bg4  16.Nxe7+  Kh8  17.f3  And now, the only move for Black is to play  17...Re8!  18.Bg5  Rxe7!  This is also the only move.  19.Rxe7  Qxe7  20.fxg4  Qd7!  Another clever move for Black aiming to play  Ng4  .  21.gxh5  Ng4  Black gets enough counterplay and will survive.  22.d5  c5!=  Black has played perfectly and obtained equality. }
14... Bg4 { Now, a forced continuation. } 15. f3 Bxf3 16. Qxf3 fxg6 17. Qd3 Qb6
{ Now, as we saw, it changes the game completely that we're unable to play c3. }
18. Re4
{ This is the only way to defend the d4-pawn for now. Black should now get out of the pin, when both king-moves seem to be fine. }
18... Kh8 19. Bg5
{ Now Black has to play precisely in order to avoid a rather depressing position. }
19... Rf5
{ A strong defensive move as Black blocks our queen's diagonal, supports e5 and aims to double the rooks.   19...Rad8?!  Is also inaccurate as seen after  20.Rae1  Nb4  The most critical move as there is only one antidote.  21.Qg3!  Now the point is that the queen protects the queen on e1. This is seen after  21...Rxd4  22.Be3  Rxe4  23.Bxb6  White wins.   19...Rae8?  Isn't precise due to  20.Rae1  c4 is now a threat when the e7-pawn also could be in trouble.  20...e5  21.c4  Nb4  22.Qd2  Our pieces are too strong.  22...Kh7  23.Bd1  Black will have to watch after we create a massacre on the kingside by the means of g4. }
20. c4
{ Arguably a more dangerous move, but we are also marginally better after the strange line  20.Rae1  Raf8  21.Kh2  R8f7  22.Kh3  . }
20... Nf6
{ An accurate defense.  20...Nb4?  is more natural, but after  21.Qe3  we are clearly better as c5 will soon follow. }
21. Rxe7 c5 { Black can't allow us to play c5. } 22. Rae1 Ng4
{ Black has to gain counterplay, otherwise our strong pieces become a force too tough to stop. }
23. R1e6 Qa7 24. Rxg7
{ 24.Bh6  Is a rather funny drawing line.  24...Bxd4+  25.Qxd4+  cxd4  26.Bg7+  Kg8  27.c5  Rf7  28.Rf6  Nxf6  29.Rxf7  Qxc5  30.Rd7+  Nd5  31.Bxd5+  Qxd5  32.Rxd5  Kxg7  33.Rxd4=  The resulting endgame is a draw. }
24... Qb8
{ The only move!  24...Kxg7  is a losing battle after  25.d5!  when  Qc3+  will follow. }
25. g3 Kxg7
{ Now this works as the queen has time to join the defense with Qf8 if we decide to play d5. }
26. Bf4
{ White has some initiative, but there is no objective advantage as Black has defended himself fantastically. }
*

