18. Re4
{ This is the only way to defend the d4-pawn for now. Black should now get out of the pin, when both king-moves seem to be fine. }
18... Kh7 19. Bd2
{ The best move, but I did analyze two other testing moves which I will show as clickables.  19.Bg5  Rf5!  Once again this defense is effective.  20.Bxd5  cxd5  21.Rxe7  Qxb2  22.Rae1  Raf8!  Black has to play actively in order to survive.  23.R1e6  Threatening  Bh6  which is a fantastic move.  23...Kh8!  Moving out of the pin, so now our pawn in  d4  is under attack.  24.c3  Qf2+  25.Kh2  Rf3!  Black saves himself due to a perpetual.  26.Re3  Qg3+  27.Kg1  Qf2+=  A fun line to take a look at, but I was annoyed when I didn't find an edge;   19.g4!?  Is another very testing option, when I found a highly entertaining line.  19...Kh8  20.Bg5  hxg4  21.Rxg4  Rf5  This defense is a constant throughout this entire line.  22.Kh1  Moving the king out of harm's way, preparing h5 and placing something in the g-file.  22...Raf8  The engine shows 0.00, but it's really difficult.  23.h5  gxh5  24.Qh3  Kg8  25.Qxh5  White's attack is extremely powerful, so Black has to play accurately in order to save the day.  25...Qa6!  26.Rgg1  The position is incredibly unclear. My analysis continued:  26...c5  27.Qh2  c4!  28.Bh6  Kf7!  A fantastic move by Black as the king escapes and our king is all of a sudden vulnerable. What a twist of events!  29.Bxg7  Nf6!  30.Bxf6  Rxf6  31.Qh5+  Ke6  32.Rg7  Kd7  Black's king is finally safe.  33.Qd5+  Rd6  34.Bxc4  Rxd5  35.Bxa6  bxa6=  The complex middlegame has faded into a drawn endgame. }
19... e5
{ A highly interesting move as Black attacks our d4-pawn.   19...Rf5?  Funnily enough, this move is now terrible.  20.Rae1  Raf8  21.Bxd5  cxd5  22.Rxe7  An exact copy of the 19. Bg5-line, but this time it doesn't work for Black!  22...Qxb2  23.R1e6!  Kh8  24.c3  The difference of the bishop placement is decisive, as Black no longer saves the game with a queen check on f2. }
20. Rae1 { This typical move is always good. } 20... Nf4
{ The best defense!   20...Rad8?  loses to  21.Rxe5!  White breaks through with this fantastic exchange sacrifice.  21...Bxe5  22.Rxe5  Kh8  23.Bxa5  Qxa5  24.Qxg6  Black will soon get mated.   20...Rf5?  This typical defense move is now refuted with  21.g4!  Utilizing that the king and rook are in the same diagonal.  21...hxg4  22.h5!  Our attack is too dangerous.  22...Rxh5  23.Rxg4  Rf5  24.Rh4+  Kg8  25.c4  Now Black has to play 25... Qd8 in order to avoid the loss of material.  25...Qd8  26.Qh3!  Increasing the pressure down the h-file, forcing the sequence  26...Nb6  27.c5+  Nd5  28.Bc2  Black is lost as he has to give the exchange. }
21. Qg3 Rf5 22. Kh2 { Moving the king out of the pin. } 22... Rd8
{ Pinning our bishop is very logical. } 23. Bc3 Nd5 24. dxe5 Nxc3 25. bxc3
{ Our pawn on e5 is very strong, but not strong enough to claim more than a slight edge. }
