18. Re4
{ This is the only way to defend the d4-pawn for now. Black should now get out of the pin, when both king-moves seem to be fine. }
18... Kh7 19. Bd2 e6 { This was Black's best defense according to my engine. }
20. c4 { Chasing away the knight. } 20... Nb4 21. Qe3 Rad8
{ The rook is best placed on d8 where it attacks our pawn on d4.   21...Rae8  is met by  22.Rd1  when a nice plan is to play Be1-Bg3-Be5. }
22. Bc3 { Getting ready for Re1 or c5. } 22... Nd5
{ Is a move that looks crazy, but it's actually pretty good.   22...Rde8!  Now my engine prefers this move, which is extremely illogical from a human perspective.  23.Re1  Qc7!  A strong move, preventing our queen from heading to desirable g3-square.  24.Rd1  We are marginally better, threatening to play d5. From here, both sides are going to maneuver the pieces back and forth. I'd choose White, but Black is objectively close to equality. This is not really anything to worry about, as the moves are too engine-like. White also has several alternatives along the way, making it rather difficult to remember everything.   22...Rfe8?  Is natural, but not good as we can play  23.Rf1  The rook is headed to f7 while also the e6 pawn will most likely fall as we can soon play c5. }
23. cxd5 exd5
{ This capture is insanely natural, but it gives us Re7 with a tempo which is lethal.   23...cxd5!  The right way to capture.  24.Rxe6  Qxb3  25.Re7  Kh8  A major difference is that Black has time for this, meaning that we can no longer play Qe5.  26.Kh2  The control over the e-file gives us some advantage, but Black is still in the game. }
24. Re7 Qxb3 25. Qe5
{ This is the simplest road to Rome. My engine prefers  25.g4  , but I prefer dodging complications when the text move is more than good enough. }
25... Rg8 26. Rf1 Kh8 27. Qg5
{ The pawn on g6 falls. If Black tries to defend it we can double our rooks on the 7th rank, where a mate will be hard to avoid. }
