{ As always we will take full control of the center if we get the chance. }
2... Bg7 { I'd say this move will be played against you 99/100 times... } 3.
Nc3
{ There are a bunch of different set-ups we can go for, but I think the knight move is the most critical option. The Main Line gives Black a plethora of options, which will all be covered in this chapter. }
3... c6 4. Be3
{ This is the easiest for our repertoire as Black can still change his mind with d6 next. }
4... d5
{ 4...Qb6  Applying pressure on b2 and d4, but it's nothing to worry about.  5.a3  A thematic way to meet an attack on the b2-pawn as the queen will be trapped after Na4.  5...d6  6.f4  Where we have transposed to previously covered variations. }
5. e5 { Advancing the pawn is the critical move. } 5... Qb6
{ 5...h5  6.Qd2  Black doesn't have anything better than transposing to 5... Nh6 with  6...Nh6  7.O-O-O  Nf5  8.Bf4  . }
6. a3 { Is once again the right response. } 6... Nh6
{ Happened in Xu,X - Wen,Y Tianjin 2018, when I like continuing in the spirit of the Main Line. }
7. Qd2 Nf5 8. Na4
{ We must chase away the queen before we can move the bishop. } 8... Qd8 9. Bf4
h5 10. Nf3
{ White is clearly better due to the space advantage. Black is forced to play }
10... Nd7
{ 10...O-O?  is too dangerous when Black will get slaughtered on the kingside in a heartbeat. }
11. Bd3 Nf8 12. O-O { When White has a very comfortable game. } *

