[White "10. Modern (1...g6) Minor Sidelines"]
[Black "2...Bg7 (3...c6 4)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 g6 2. d4
{ As always we will take full control of the center if we get the chance. }
2... Bg7 { I'd say this move will be played against you 99/100 times... } 3.
Nc3
{ There are a bunch of different set-ups we can go for, but I think the knight move is the most critical option. The Main Line gives Black a plethora of options, which will all be covered in this chapter. }
3... c6 4. Be3
{ This is the easiest for our repertoire as Black can still change his mind with d6 next. }
4... d5 5. e5 { Advancing the pawn is the critical move. } 5... f6
{ Black's most common move is to attack our center with this move. } 6. f4
{ In order to keep an edge we must keep the center intact. } 6... Nh6
{ Almost always played, so I won't check other moves. } 7. Qd2
{ I like the plan of castling queenside as Black is weak on the kingside. }
7... O-O
{ 7...Ng4  Has been tried before.  8.O-O-O  fxe5  8... O-O transposes to the Main Line.  9.fxe5  Nxe3  10.Qxe3  Black has obtained the bishop pair, but this is nothing to brag about.  10...O-O  11.Kb1  It's always clever to make this prophylactic move.  11...Bg4  In Sun Chin,R - Hemmat,A Montevideo 2016, White should have played fun fact, this was played in the WYCC in Uruguay where I also played, my last year  12.Be2  Hitting the bishop on e2. It's extremely desirable for us to get Ncxe2 with a tempo, so Black's best move is  12...Qd7  Which we can respond to with  13.h4  Our attack looks very dangerous.  13...h5  14.Nf3  Black has a weak kingside and problem with his development. Biting the bullet with  14...Na6  is best, although it doesn't help much as we can take it and place our knight on  c5  via  a4  . }
8. O-O-O Ng4
{ 8...e6?  Lead to a disaster for Black.  9.Nf3  c5  An attempt to create counterplay.  10.dxc5  Nc6  11.Bb5  A good move, aiming to take on c6 when Black won't be able to regain the pawn.  11...Ng4  12.Bxc6  bxc6  13.h3  Nxe3  14.Qxe3  The famous streamer was in a hopeless situation in Skripchenko,A -Rudolf,A Kishinev 2005. }
9. Kb1 { This prophylactic move is once again the way to go. } 9... b5
{ Black's best bet to create an attack.  9...Bh6  can always be answered by  10.g3  . }
10. Nf3 Nd7 11. Bg1 { Preparing to chase away the knight on g4. } 11... Nb6 12.
Bd3 { There's no need to be hasty with h3. } 12... a5 13. h3 Nh6 14. Re1
{ Giving the knight a square on d1. } 14... b4 15. Nd1 Nc4 16. Qe2 fxe5 17.
fxe5 { Black's attack hasn't lead anywhere, so we're in the driving seat. } *

