1. e4 g6 2. d4
{ As always we will take full control of the center if we get the chance. }
2... Bg7 { I'd say this move will be played against you 99/100 times... } 3.
Nc3
{ There are a bunch of different set-ups we can go for, but I think the knight move is the most critical option. The Main Line gives Black a plethora of options, which will all be covered in this chapter. }
3... a6
{ This cute little move gave me a serious headache as Black wants to move-order us out of our repertoire. }
4. h4
{ I eventually discovered that this move was the best to avoid any move-order nonsense. }
4... d5
{ The only alternative to the main move.   4...h5  A move a human makes from pure instinct, and in this case the instinct is correct.  5.Be3  We are now likely to transpose to different main lines. Which will be dealt with in a later chapter. }
5. Nxd5 { Black has two ways to chase away the knight. } 5... e6
{ This is better as Black will be able to use the c6-square for his knight. }
6. Nc3 { This time it's better to jump back to c3. } 6... Qxd4
{ Leads to a very depressing endgame for Black after   6...Bxd4  is the lesser evil, although  7.h5  there is nothing wrong with keeping the tension here if you really want to avoid an endgame.  7...Bxc3+  8.bxc3  Qxd1+  9.Kxd1  Nf6  10.hxg6  fxg6  11.f3  Isn't an endgame where Black has anything to smile about. Black is in for a hard time, but the drawing chances are still existent... }
7. Qxd4 Bxd4 8. Nf3 Bxc3+ 9. bxc3
{ Black is incredibly weak on the dark squares. Taking control of the dark squares by the means of  9...f6  10.Bf4  e5?  loses to  Nxe5  , when the rook on  h8  will fall if Black takes the knight. Stevic, H - Loncar, R Zagreb 2016. }
