1. e4 g6
{ With this move, Black aims to fianchetto his bishop on f8. The move is rather flexible as it can transpose to several different openings. The downside is clear though, as Black doesn't take control of the center. }
2. d4
{ As always we will take full control of the center if we get the chance. }
2... d6 { Shouldn't make a difference. } 3. Be3
{ This move is the most precise when it comes to our repertoire. If we play  3.Nc3  , we are at risk of getting move-ordered after  3.. .b5  . }
3... a6
{ The only independent try, but almost never played.  3...Nf6  is the Pirc after  4.Nc3   while  3...Bg7  transposes to the main line after  4.Nc3  . }
4. c4
{ This is an additional option when there is no knight placed on c3, making a6 a waste of time. I don't think we need to look any further, as we have a great version of the KID. From here, I suggest a Sämisch set-up with Nc3-f3-Bd3-Nge2-Qd2. }
