[Black "2... Nf6 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 g6
{ With this move, Black aims to fianchetto his bishop on f8. The move is rather flexible as it can transpose to several different openings. The downside is clear though, as Black doesn't take control of the center. }
2. d4
{ As always we will take full control of the center if we get the chance. }
2... Nf6
{ This move is called 'Norwegian Defence,' used by World Champion Magnus Carlsen on several occasions. It's extremely provocative, in Alekhine-style. }
3. Nc3 { Things aren't so easy as I'd like them to be after  3.e5  Nh5 } 3...
d5
{ The point of the variation.  3...d6  is the Pirc, arguably what Black should do. }
4. e5 Nh5
{ Leads to a worse version of 3. e5, as Black gets no counterplay against the center with d6. }
5. Be3
{ As my coach said, 'chess is a logical game,' so indeed, we will play natural moves. }
5... Ng7
{ The most played move. Black wants to move the knight to a better square. } 6.
Qd2 c6 7. h3 { A typical prophylactic move. } 7... Nf5
{ Is suggested by the engine. } 8. Bf4 Ng7
{ It's strange, but the engine wants to play Ne6 'with a tempo.' Black doesn't have anything better though, as the knight on f5 is extremely vulnerable to a g4 pawn push after Nf3. }
9. Nf3 Ne6 10. Be3 Bg7 11. Be2
{ Black's unusual play had led to nothing but agony in Chadwick,N - Martyniuk,C Buenos Aires 2012. h4 and Bh6 will soon come, with a rather powerful attack. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10. Modern (1...g6) Minor Sidelines"]
[Black "2... Nf6 2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 g6
{ With this move, Black aims to fianchetto his bishop on f8. The move is rather flexible as it can transpose to several different openings. The downside is clear though, as Black doesn't take control of the center. }
2. d4
{ As always we will take full control of the center if we get the chance. }
2... Nf6
{ This move is called 'Norwegian Defence,' used by World Champion Magnus Carlsen on several occasions. It's extremely provocative, in Alekhine-style. }
3. Nc3 { Things aren't so easy as I'd like them to be after  3.e5  Nh5 } 3...
d5
{ The point of the variation.  3...d6  is the Pirc, arguably what Black should do. }
4. e5 Ne4
{ The best place to place the knight, due to it's active spot. However, the knight is in danger of getting trapped on e4, which is something we can utilize. }
5. Nce2 f6 { The only move that avoids the loss of a piece. } 6. Be3
{ I spent an annoying amount of time analysing this position, but after a while it became clear that this move was best. }
6... Bg7 7. f3
{ Chasing away the knight has to be played sooner or later, as Black is attacking our center. }
7... Ng5 8. Bxg5
{ I think this move is the best as we keep our strong center.  8.Qd2  has been played twice, but Black was doing pretty okay in Campos Moreno, J - Romero Holmes, A San Sebastian 2015 after  8...Nf7  9.f4  c5  , and even ended up victorious. }
8... fxg5 9. h4 { A great move that allows us to play f4. } 9... gxh4
{ 9...g4  allows  10.h5! } 10. f4 c5 11. Rxh4
{ Our pawns in the center are really strong. } 11... Nc6 12. Nf3
{ Our plan is simple. } 12... h5
{ Certainly not necessary, but very human as Black wants to place the bishop on the juicy g4-square. }
13. dxc5 Bg4 { And now } 14. Rxg4 { A very strong exchange sacrifice. } 14...
hxg4 15. Nfd4
{ Black has serious problems on the light squares. His pieces aren't particularly great either due to our very strong center. Besides, we are up an extra pawn. I'd surely pick White every day of the week. }
