[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10. Modern (1...g6) Minor Sidelines"]
[Black "Modern Conclusion"]
[Result "*"]

{ CONCLUSION: This was our first dive into the ocean of The Modern Defense. As we have seen in this chapter, Black has A TON of different moves up his sleeve... And we haven't even handled the main lines yet! We started our coverage with the Norwegian Defense, a defense that has been used by World Champion Magnus Carlsen with some success in short time controls. Knowing the man, I am sure that the name of the opening has inspired him to pick it up once in a while. The opening looks corny, but it's not so bad. However, with precise play we should certainly be sure of an advantage. }
1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 { This move is almost always played. } 3. Nc3
{ Black has so many different ways to proceed that it's easy to get a headache. }
3... d6
{ is the main move, and indeed a very flexible one. Black can now decide whether or not he wants to take the game into a c6-structure, a6-structure or straight to the Pirc with Nf6. There were so many factors for me to consider and I really tore my hair out!   3...b6  is probably the worst move as Black becomes incredibly passive.   3...c5  isn't impressive either, but it requires us to memorize some theory. If we do our work, Black will surely regret his unorthodox opening choice.   3...Nc6  followed by d5 sure is fancy, but not good as the resulting endgame is extremely unpleasant for Black.   3...c6  is a typical GM-type of move, who might be interested in changing the game's direction more commonly through a Caro-Kann move-order. However, our plan of attack is very powerful when I suspect that Black is suffering tremendously. The lines with h5-Nh6 were also very good for us, as the queen sac is very effective. Once again it looks like Black becomes too passive...   3...a6  was a move that made me slightly nervous at first, but I was thankfully able to find a way to sneak the game into our repertoire.   3...d5  This move was far from easy to take down. We witnessed tons of analysis which contained a plethora of landmines for Black to step on. I think the position is almost impossible to handle from the black side, so you should not be too worried about the fact that Stockfish was able to defend it to the bitter end. Practically, it's a lot easier to play White, which is something we should be thrilled about. }
4. Be3 Nd7
{ is an interesting way to trick us from our repertoire, but I did find the solution in the end! The first batch of the Modern is now complete, so 10 points to Gryffindor for getting through it all! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11. Modern (1...g6) Mainlines"]
[Black "4...a6 (5...Nf6 1)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 d6 4. Be3 a6
{ The main tabiya of the Modern. Black aims to get quick play on the queenside, when the moves b5-Bb7-Nbd7-c5 will follow in some order. }
5. h4
{ After analyzing this line in great depth, I came to the conclusion that this was the most accurate move order that aligns with all our set-ups in the Pirc/ Modern coverage. The text move aims for a quick h5-h6, which is something Black has to prevent. }
5... Nf6
{ Is a natural move, but it's not very good. However, many strong GMs have failed to find the refutation here... }
6. h5 { The exchange sacrifice will lead to a fantastic initiative. } 6... Ng4
{ Is a very interesting move, suggested by my engine. Black's point is that he wants to achieve e5, and even f5, gaining some play.   6...gxh5?  Is very ugly.  7.f3  Nc6  8.Nge2  No fancy moves are required. We will simply complete our development when it will be clear that Black's inferior pawn structure on the kingside will make him suffer.  8...e5  9.Qd2!  There is no need to give Black activity by playing 9. dxe5, like in Prie,E - Frick,C Sables d'Olonne 2019.  9...exd4  10.Nxd4  Black's position looks incredibly passive.  10...Nxd4  11.Qxd4  The best move, because we would rather like to place the bishop on the g5-square.  11...Be6  12.Bg5!  The pin is very unpleasant.  12...Qe7  13.O-O-O  White's position is superior in every single way. Ne2-Ng3 will soon come, winning the pawn on h5. Black also needs to watch out for f4-e5, when the knight will fall. }
7. Qd2
{ Looks like the best way to fight against Black's plan. It doesn't matter so much that we give up the bishop pair, as Black has spent valuable time on Ng4-Nxe3. }
7... c5 { 7...Nxe3  first won't make a difference. } 8. dxc5 Nxe3 9. Qxe3 dxc5
{ Black has managed to open the position slightly, making the bishop on g7 quite strong. I suggest that we play }
10. e5 { Closing the bishop's diagonal and threatening to play h6 next. } 10...
Qd4 { Is Black's best move, when we get a pleasant endgame after } 11. Qxd4
cxd4 12. Nd5 Ra7
{ The best way to avoid the loss of material.   12...Kd8?  Gives Black a terrible game after  13.Nb6  Ra7  14.Nxc8  Kxc8  15.f4  Black is in dire straits. }
13. f4 { Protecting the pawn on e5 and keeping the bishop on g7 closed. } 13...
b5
{ Is logical, but punishable as we can play   13...Nd7  Black needs to wait with the queenside expansion, but the endgame is still very bad after  14.h6  Pushing the bishop back to the sad square on f8.  14...Bf8  15.Nf3  b5  Black has to play for compensation, as it's clear that he has to part with the pawn on d4.  16.Nxd4  e6  17.Nf6+  Nxf6  18.exf6  White is close to winning the endgame, but some technique is required to score the decisive goal. }
14. a4
{ Black will soon have to take on a4 in order to avoid the loss of a pawn, which is really not ideal. }
14... Be6 15. Nb4 bxa4 16. Rxa4
{ Black pawns are incredibly weak. Play may continue: } 16... Bd7 17. Ra5
{ Black has gotten himself into a terrible endgame due to the vulnerable queenside pawns, so the defensive task will be incredibly tough. }
