[Result "*"]

1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 d6 4. Be3 a6
{ The main tabiya of the Modern. Black aims to get quick play on the queenside, when the moves b5-Bb7-Nbd7-c5 will follow in some order. }
5. h4
{ After analyzing this line in great depth, I came to the conclusion that this was the most accurate move order that aligns with all our set-ups in the Pirc/ Modern coverage. }
5... h6 { Is another way for Black to defend against our h5-thrust. } 6. Qd2
{ Now h5 followed by f4 is a nice plan for us which is something Black has to be prepared for anytime. }
6... Nd7 7. O-O-O b5
{ Black has to gain counterplay somehow, and the way to do so is to expand on the queenside. }
8. Nh3
{ The knight is well placed here, as we want to play f3, defending the pawn on e4. From h3 it can also jump to f4 in some lines as we will see. Another factor is that the e2-square remains available to our knight on c3 in case Black plays b4, while our bishop on f1 can also be developed. }
8... Bb7 9. f3
{ Protecting the pawn on e4. Black has different tries in this position, and we will take a detailed look at all of them: }
9... Ngf6
{ The knight is better placed on f6, as our h5-f4 plan is much harder to execute than with the knight on e7. }
10. g4
{ Grabbing space on the kingside and preparing to kick away the knight on f6 by playing g5. }
10... Nb6
{ Freeing the d7-square for the knight on f6, so the g5-launch won't be as effective. }
11. a3
{ We should prevent Black from getting his usual activity on the queenside with b4.   That being said,  11.d5  was also a strong alternative. None of these alternatives are mentioned by Vjeko in his Modern-course. But then again, the man is planning a major update, so it will be fun to see what he comes up with! }
11... e6 { Black wants to calmly place his queen on e7 and castle queenside. }
12. h5 { Now that our pieces are well placed, it's time to strike! } 12... gxh5
{ The critical move is to grab the pawn.  12...g5  is thematic, but one day we will surely get to play f4 after some preparation with Bd3-Rhg1. }
13. gxh5 Nxh5 14. Rg1 { Placing the rook in the open g-file. } 14... Qe7 15.
Be2
{ Black has some problems to solve here, as f4 is coming. The best one seems to be }
15... Nc4
{ Getting rid of our light-squared bishop. The reason is that Black has problems after  15...Rg8  due to  16.Bf2!  when the bishop is heading to  h4  next after we have played  f4  and Black has responded with Nf6. }
16. Bxc4 bxc4 17. Qe2
{ We will win the pawn on c4 next with an excellent position. } *

