[Black "4...a6 (5...h6 4)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 d6 4. Be3 a6
{ The main tabiya of the Modern. Black aims to get quick play on the queenside, when the moves b5-Bb7-Nbd7-c5 will follow in some order. }
5. h4
{ After analyzing this line in great depth, I came to the conclusion that this was the most accurate move order that aligns with all our set-ups in the Pirc/ Modern coverage. }
5... h6 { Is another way for Black to defend against our h5-thrust. } 6. Qd2
{ Now h5 followed by f4 is a nice plan for us which is something Black has to be prepared for anytime. }
6... Nd7 7. O-O-O b5
{ Black has to gain counterplay somehow, and the way to do so is to expand on the queenside. }
8. Nh3
{ The knight is well placed here, as we want to play f3, defending the pawn on e4. From h3 it can also jump to f4 in some lines as we will see. Another factor is that the e2-square remains available to our knight on c3 in case Black plays b4, while our bishop on f1 can also be developed. }
8... Bb7 9. f3 { Protecting the pawn on e4. } 9... Ngf6
{ The knight is better placed on f6, as our h5-f4 plan is much harder to execute than with the knight on e7. }
10. g4
{ Grabbing space on the kingside and preparing to kick away the knight on f6 by playing g5. }
10... Nb6
{ Freeing the d7-square for the knight on f6, so the g5-launch won't be as effective. }
11. a3 h5
{ Was played by the Modern guru - GM Tiger Hillarp who is an expert on the field. }
12. gxh5 { Is the way to create problems for Black. } 12... Nxh5 13. Rg1
{ Our plan from here is to play f4, and it is a lot easier to achieve now that we have gotten rid of the g-pawn. Our knight could also jump to g5 in several lines. }
13... Bc8
{ I am thrilled to say that Vjeko has finally brought his major update to the table, and after a long and tedious search, he found this move which points towards our knight and therefore aims to play Nc4, eliminating our light-squared bishop. I'm also really thrilled about receiving compliments from the dude, saying: 'I think this is the closest you'll get to refuting the Modern' Means a lot, buddy. He is not wrong, though! :@@EndBracket@@   13...e6  Looks very natural to me, as Black wants to complete his development by placing the queen on e7 and castling queenside.  14.Ng5  Qe7  15.Kb1  Nf6  The knight doesn't do much on h5 so Black moves it back to f6.  16.Qe1  O-O-O  17.Bd3±  Black has a solid pawn structure, but his pieces remain very passive. From here it will become a game of maneuvering and playing f4 at the right time, which is something Black will have to meet in the best manner as possible. }
14. b3
{ There's not more to this move than the fact that it prevents Black from carrying out his idea. }
14... Bxh3
{ Black's best try is to eliminate our dangerous knight. Vjeko points out how dangerous our plan is in the line  14...c6  15.f4  a5  16.f5  b4  17.fxg6  f5  18.Ng5  , when Black is pretty much busted... }
15. Bxh3 a5
{ Vjeko goes for gold and sacrifices a pawn in order to obtain counterplay on the queenside. A very nice idea, but unfortunately, the concept doesn't work. }
16. Nd5
{ Unfortunately for Vjeko, we can simply ignore the pawn sacrifice... The point is to grab Black's knight and play Bf1, when Black will lose all hope for counterplay on the queenside. }
16... Nxd5 17. exd5 Nf6
{ For a human being, this looks like the most natural way to proceed. It's also quite challenging, as we're required to find 'only moves' to maintain our edge. }
18. Qd3
{ A very strong move, targeting both b5 and g6. Be6 is now a nasty threat. }
18... Kf8 { The best defense, as it allows Black to defend with Qe8. } 19. Bg5
{ Defending the h4-pawn. } 19... Nxd5 20. f4
{ 20.Qxb5?  would run into  20...Nc3! } 20... Nf6 21. f5 gxf5 22. Bxf5
{ Black's position is hopeless as our initiative is far too strong. Black lacks the necessary counterplay on the queenside. I applaud Vjeko for his excellent work! Unfortunately he's bringing a knife to a gunfight, as The Modern is simply put an unsound opening objectively. However, chess is a game for humans and the chances for anyone knowing the refutation is extremely low... Still, you, the readers, do now have a nasty surprise up your sleeve in case any of you run into any of Vjeko's fans, or perhaps Vjeko himself! :@@EndBracket@@ }
