[White "11. Modern (1...g6) Mainlines"]
[Black "4...a6 (5...h6 5)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 d6 4. Be3 a6
{ The main tabiya of the Modern. Black aims to get quick play on the queenside, when the moves b5-Bb7-Nbd7-c5 will follow in some order. }
5. h4
{ After analyzing this line in great depth, I came to the conclusion that this was the most accurate move order that aligns with all our set-ups in the Pirc/ Modern coverage. }
5... h6 { Is another way for Black to defend against our h5-thrust. } 6. Qd2
{ Now h5 followed by f4 is a nice plan for us which is something Black has to be prepared for anytime. }
6... Nd7 7. O-O-O b5
{ Black has to gain counterplay somehow, and the way to do so is to expand on the queenside. }
8. Nh3
{ The knight is well placed here, as we want to play f3, defending the pawn on e4. From h3 it can also jump to f4 in some lines as we will see. Another factor is that the e2-square remains available to our knight on c3 in case Black plays b4, while our bishop on f1 can also be developed. }
8... Bb7 9. f3
{ Protecting the pawn on e4. Black has different tries in this position, and we will take a detailed look at all of them: }
9... e6
{ Some strong GMs have tried this move here, developing the knight to e7. } 10.
Nf2
{ The knight supports the e4-pawn, making a f4 possible in the future. However, it's worth noting that we want to play h5 before an eventual f4, making Black open his kingside. }
10... Ne7 11. g3
{ Let's not be too hasty, and prepare h5-f4 a little bit first.  11.h5  was too quick in Sidhant, M - Salgado Lopez, I Dubai 2017 which continued  11...g5  12.f4  Here, the strong Spanish GM missed the strong move  12...g4!  when the play is complicated after  13.Nxg4  b4  14.Ne2  Bxe4  . }
11... d5
{ Black draw an email game with this move, so let's take a look. Black wants to gain counterplay by potentially playing c5, while he also grabs space and stops us from playing d5 ourselves in the near future. }
12. Kb1
{ A typical prophylactic move which we always want to play at some point. }
12... Nb6 13. a3
{ White prevents Black from playing b4 followed by Nc4.   13.Qe1  was played in Rogos, J - Piersig, K ICCF email 2017, but Black had some play after  13...b4  14.Ne2  dxe4  15.fxe4  a5  . }
13... Qd7 14. h5 { Even though Black has played d5, our plan is strong. } 14...
g5 15. f4 gxf4 16. gxf4 Nc4
{ 16...O-O-O  can be met by  17. when our extra space grants us a clear edge.  16...dxe4  is met by  17.Nfxe4  when we can soon jump to the c5-square. }
17. Bxc4 dxc4 18. Rhg1 Rh7
{ 18...Rg8  was met by  19.f5!  followed by  Bxh6  next. } 19. d5 O-O-O 20. Bc5
{ Our play here is just too strong. } 20... exd5 21. f5
{ Black is now objectively lost as he has to worry about threats like Rxg7 followed by f6, or Ng4.   A nice line is:  21...dxe4  22.Qxd7+  Rxd7  23.Bxe7  Rxe7  24.f6  , winning material. }
