{ After analyzing this line in great depth, I came to the conclusion that this was the most accurate move order that aligns with all our set-ups in the Pirc/ Modern coverage. }
5... h6 { Is another way for Black to defend against our h5-thrust. } 6. Qd2
{ Now h5 followed by f4 is a nice plan for us which is something Black has to be prepared for anytime. }
6... Nd7 7. O-O-O b5
{ Black has to gain counterplay somehow, and the way to do so is to expand on the queenside. }
8. Nh3
{ The knight is well placed here, as we want to play f3, defending the pawn on e4. From h3 it can also jump to f4 in some lines as we will see. Another factor is that the e2-square remains available to our knight on c3 in case Black plays b4, while our bishop on f1 can also be developed. }
8... Bb7 9. f3
{ Protecting the pawn on e4. Black has different tries in this position, and we will take a detailed look at all of them: }
9... Rc8
{ Black places the rook in the c-file and is now well prepared to carry out the desired c5-break. }
10. g4 { Grabbing space on the kingside. } 10... c5 11. Kb1
{ A prophylactic move, moving the king out of the c-file, while protecting the pawn on a2. }
11... Qc7
{ It does make sense for Black to create a battery down the c-file.   11...Ngf6  is met by  12.g5!  Removing the knight on f6.  12...hxg5  13.hxg5  Nh5  14.Nf2  Black's position looks grim, as we have full control over both sides of the board. Black has problems down the h-file, as we will soon play Bh3-Bg4. It's also difficult for him to achieve something on the queenside, as Nb6 can be met by b3. }
12. dxc5
{ A strong move, limiting Black's counterplay on the queenside as Black won't be able to carry out Nb6-Nc4, as he is forced to take the pawn with the knight. }
12... Nxc5 13. a3
{ It's important that we prevent Black from advancing on the queenside with b4. }
13... Nf6
{ Black needs to complete his development, when we will once again play } 14.
g5 hxg5 15. Nxg5
{ This time we will take with the knight, since Black had  15...Nfd7  if we took with the pawn.  Bh3-Bg4 and Bd4 will follow, preparing the h5-break in the future. f4-f5 can also be played, in case Black loosens the grip on the e4-pawn. Black's play on the queenside is on a standstill, as control all the important squares. }
