{ Black's best way forward is to get rid of our pawns on the kingside.   14...b4?!  Doesn't work out for Black due to  15.Na2!  Maintaining the control over the b4-square, while the knight could also head to b3 via c1 if necessary.  15...cxd4  Black doesn't have anything better.  16.Bxd4  16. Bf2 is also strong, but I like getting rid of the bishop on g7.  16...Bxd4  17.Qxd4  bxa3!  Black has to sac the rook in order to have a chance to survive.  18.b3  18. Qxh8 gives Black a lot of compensation after 18... Rxb2+ 19. Ka1 Rxc2, when the play becomes very complex.  18...Qe5  19.hxg6  Creating a weak pawn on g6.  19...fxg6  20.Nf4  A strong move, utilizing that the knight can't be taken.  20...Qxd4  21.Rxd4  Ne5  22.Nb4  Black loses the pawn on a6.  22...Bb7  23.Nxa6  Bxa6  24.Bxa6  Nxf3  25.Rd5  Black's pieces are terribly placed, so the endgame is simply lost. }
15. Nxg5 Rxh5 { The only move. } 16. Rxh5 gxh5 17. e5
{ A very strong move. Not only do we block Black's bishop on g7, e6 is also looming in the air. }
17... cxd4
{ Grabbing the bull by the horns.   17...b4  is once again met by  18.Na2  Maintaining the control over the b4-square while keeping the b-file closed as Black can't take on a3.  18...cxd4  Black grabs the pawn on e5.  19.Bxd4  Bxe5  20.Nxb4  Bxd4  21.Qxd4  Our knight on g5 is hanging, but so is Black's bishop on c6.  21...Rxb4  22.Qg7!  Otherwise we lose material. Now Black has to force a queen trade after  22...Rxb2+!  23.Kxb2  Qe5+  24.Qxe5  Nxe5  We are up an exchange, but we don't have many pawns left to promote.  25.Bxa6  Nxf3  26.Nxf3  Bxf3  27.Rd4  Maybe the endgame can be saved, but it looks incredibly tough as our a-pawn runs fast! }
18. e6 { Otherwise we lose the pawn on e5! The tactics work out for us. } 18...
fxe6 19. Nxe6 dxe3 { 19...dxc3  loses to  20.Qg2! } 20. Nxg7+ Kf7
{ Leaves Black's king in jeopardy after   20...Kd8  The king is safer on the queenside.  21.Qxe3  b4  A logical move, opening the b-file.  22.Ne6+  Kc8  Black is busted if he moves to e8 due to 23. Nd5 when the tactics work out in our favor as 23... Bxd5 can be met by 24. Rxd5, due to the fork on c7.  23.Qa7!  The best move, threatening Bxa6.  23...Qb6  Black needs to take a worse ending with a pawn less.  24.Bxa6+  Bb7  25.Bxb7+  Rxb7  26.Qxb6  Nxb6  27.axb4  Black has to fight for a draw. }
21. Qg2 Ngf6 22. Nf5
{ Preventing Black from defending himself with Rg8. Unfortunately for Black, he has to do so anyway, otherwise our attack is too strong. }
22... Rg8 { And now we win an exchange after } 23. Nh6+
{ White wins material. } *

