1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 d6 4. Be3 a6
{ The main tabiya of the Modern. Black aims to get quick play on the queenside, when the moves b5-Bb7-Nbd7-c5 will follow in some order. }
5. h4
{ After analyzing this line in great depth, I came to the conclusion that this was the most accurate move order that aligns with all our set-ups in the Pirc/ Modern coverage. }
5... h6 { Is another way for Black to defend against our h5-thrust. } 6. Qd2
{ Now h5 followed by f4 is a nice plan for us which is something Black has to be prepared for anytime. }
6... Nd7 7. O-O-O b5
{ Black has to gain counterplay somehow, and the way to do so is to expand on the queenside. }
8. Nh3
{ The knight is well placed here, as we want to play f3, defending the pawn on e4. From h3 it can also jump to f4 in some lines as we will see. Another factor is that the e2-square remains available to our knight on c3 in case Black plays b4, while our bishop on f1 can also be developed. }
8... Bb7 9. f3
{ Protecting the pawn on e4. Black has different tries in this position, and we will take a detailed look at all of them: }
9... Rc8
{ Black places the rook in the c-file and is now well prepared to carry out the desired c5-break. }
10. g4 { Grabbing space on the kingside. } 10... c5 11. Kb1
{ A prophylactic move, moving the king out of the c-file, while protecting the pawn on a2. }
11... b4 { The most played move in the position is to chase our knight to e2. }
12. Ne2 Qc7 13. dxc5
{ I like this move, opening up the d-file and limiting Black's play in the c-file. }
13... dxc5
{ Black's best try for an attack is to take with the d-pawn.   13...Nxc5  Is met by  14.Nd4!  Now we have everything under control, as we can see after  14...e6  15.Nb3  Nxb3  16.cxb3  Black's attack is all gone, so our position is superior. }
14. g5 { We proceed with our play on the kingside. } 14... Nb6
{ 14...hxg5?  is bad due to  15.Nxg5  We break through as h5-Nf4-Bc4 comes. }
15. Nef4
{ Playing actively while preventing Nc4. Now Black needs to worry about h5. }
15... h5
{ prevents us from playing h5, but it makes it harder for Black to complete his development after }
16. Nd5 Bxd5
{ 16...Nxd5  Black's attack loses much of its force without the knight.  17.exd5  Qe5  18.Qc1  It doesn't matter that the pawn on d5 hangs, as initiative is more important.  18...Bxd5  19.Nf4  Our pieces get out quickly as Bh3 and Rhe1 comes soon. If Black tries  19...Bxf3  We can just play  20.Bxa6  When Black won't win any material as  20...Rb8  Is refuted by  21.Nd3  Black has no good squares to place the queen and is thus hopelessly lost. }
17. exd5 { Black can win a pawn after } 17... Qe5 18. Qc1 Nxd5
{ But he will surely pay a heavy price for the pawn, as our initiative is incredibly strong after }
19. Bf4 Nxf4 20. Nxf4
{ Bc4 followed by Rhe1 comes quickly, when our forces are too strong. } *

