12. Kb1
{ The most precise move is to play Kb1, which prophylaxes against Qa5 as we protect the pawn on a2. }
12... Qc7
{ Black places the queen on c7 and is ready to place a rook on c8 and a knight on b6.   12...b4?  Makes things easier for us, since the c3-knight will join the kingside.  13.Ne2  a5  14.Ng3  White breaks through. }
13. dxc5
{ I think this move is the best, making it harder for Black to carry out his plan as he has to take with the knight, slowing down his attack. }
13... Nxc5 14. Bh6 { The natural move, getting rid of Black's defender on g7. }
14... hxg4
{ loses to   14...Na4  Is an interesting try.  15.Nxa4  I think this is the simplest, which wins the a4-pawn by force. That being said, there was nothing wrong with 15. Ne2, when play is complicated, but in our favor after 15... d5.  15...bxa4  16.Bxg7  Kxg7  17.gxh5  Nxh5  18.Qd4+  Kg8  19.Qxa4  We have won the pawn, but our attack is no longer as dangerous.  19...Qb6  20.Rh2  The rook on h2 joins the defense. Black doesn't have enough for the material deficit, so he has to fight for a draw in the endgame that occurs after we have played Qd4.   14...Rac8?  Black doesn't have time for this move.  15.Bxg7  Kxg7  16.gxh5  Nxh5  17.Bh3  With Bg4 coming, followed by Ne2-Ng3, Black won't be able to stop us from breaking through with h5. Meanwhile, his attack on the queenside is on a standstill. }
15. h5 b4 16. Nd5
{ 16.Ne2  would be met by  16...gxf3  when play becomes more complex as  e4  is hanging. }
16... Bxd5 17. exd5
{ Black can't prevent the opening of the h-file, when the black monarch will be wondering where his defenses went. }
