{ The main tabiya of the Modern. Black aims to get quick play on the queenside, when the moves b5-Bb7-Nbd7-c5 will follow in some order. }
5. h4
{ After analyzing this line in great depth, I came to the conclusion that this was the most accurate move order that aligns with all our set-ups in the Pirc/ Modern coverage. The text move aims for a quick h5-h6, which is something Black has to prevent. }
5... h5 { The main way of stopping h5, and also the best way to do so. } 6. Nh3
{ I spent a long time in this position, wondering which move order to go for. My conclusion became to develop the knight to h3 at once, where it will quickly reach g5. From the g5-square, the knight targets f7 which opens many tactical possibilities and traps for Black to step in! Let's see how the game can proceed. }
6... Nf6 7. f3
{ It's important that we prevent Black from jumping to g4 with the knight. }
7... Nbd7
{ Black opted for this move in most of the games I found in my base, so I will make it my main line.   7...b5  8.Ng5  And we have transposed to 6... b5. }
8. Ng5
{ The knight has reached g5, meaning that Black has to be careful in order to avoid some nasty tactics. }
8... O-O
{ Is possible, but even riskier this time for Black as our knight is better placed on g5 than f2.   8...b5?  Was played twice, when  9.e5!  wins tactically!  9...dxe5  10.dxe5  Nxe5  11.Qxd8+  Kxd8  And now, the move  12.Bd4  wins material, as the knight on e5 can't move because of the hanging f7-pawn.  12...Nfd7  13.f4  And White had won a piece in Horvath,A - Pflug,M Austria 2003, a game where Black resigned 6 moves later. }
9. Qd2 b5 10. O-O-O
{ The usual aggressive moves are made. Our goal is to massacre Black on the kingside with g4 and h5 as soon as possible. The question remains, who will win the race? }
10... Nb6
{ Funnily enough,  10...Bb7  11.g4  transposes to a position which we covered in the a6-Pirc chapter. }
11. Qf2
{ The point of this mysterious move is that we have moved the queen away in the event of b4 followed by Nc4. }
11... b4
{ The most direct and best fighting move.  11...Rb8  for example is too slow, as we can see in this line:  12.g4!  b4  13.Ne2  Nc4  14.Nf4  Nxe3  15.Qxe3  . White's breaking through on the kingside. }
12. Ne2
{ The knight has to move here, as it has no function on the b1-square. } 12...
Qe8
{ The queen moves out of the d-file making e5 possible, while it could also head to a4.   12...Nc4  is met by  13.Nf4  when g4 will follow suit. Our attack is incredibly fast, leaving Black's position incredibly difficult to defend. }
13. g4 { Going for glory! } 13... hxg4 14. Kb1
{ It's funny but my engine wants to play this prophylactic move before advancing on the kingside. }
14... Rb8 15. h5 { It's finally time. } 15... Nxh5 16. Qg1
{ A strong move, attacking the g4-pawn. } 16... f5
{ The best defensive try. Note that  16...Nc4  should be met by  17.Nf4!   16...gxf3  Doesn't work due to  17.Nf4!  f5  18.e5  White's attack is decisive. }
17. exf5 Bxf5 18. Ng3
{ We're getting ready to remove the defensive forces around Black's king. }
18... gxf3 19. Nxf5 Rxf5 20. Bd3
{ A very tricky position to play for Black, but it's not objectively winning yet! }
20... Rf6
{ Loses for several reasons, but most precise is the move   20...e6!  21.Bxf5  exf5  22.Nxf3  Black has enough compensation to claim a position that is 'only' clearly worse due to the material deficit. }
21. Nh7
{ Attacking the rook on f6, but more importantly, the g6-pawn hangs if Black moves the rook. }
21... Kxh7 22. Rxh5+ Kg8 23. Rg5 { White breaks through with Bxg6 next. } *

