{ Has been played by some strong players as it is a typical reaction from Black, but it doesn't seem good due to concrete reasons.   7...Nf6  Is possible here as well.  8.f3  Bb7?!  This move is inaccurate. Instead Black should play 8... Nbd7 which will transpose to the main line. It's also worth mentioning that 8... O-O could be played, when we have also transposed after 9. Qd2 Nbd7.  9.e5  I think this move is the simplest approach. That being said though, 9. a4 is also strong, but it leads to a long line which you would have to memorize. The text move gives us a highly pleasant endgame, something we can be thrilled about.  9...dxe5  10.dxe5  Qxd1+  11.Rxd1  Nh7  Black can't let us play e6.  12.f4  Nxg5  13.hxg5  e6  14.Kf2  Protecting the pawn on g2, so we are now getting ready to develop the bishop on f1. The plan is to trade Black's strong bishop on b7, where Black will then be left with a weak bishop on g7. Black's position will become rather cramped, so we will indeed be pulling in all the strings. }
8. d5
{ Giving Black a pretty undesirable pawn structure.  8.Qd2  is possible as well, when play is likely to transpose to our coverage later on. }
8... Nf6
{ Black has to ignore the fact that we are taking on  e6  . If  8...e5  was played instead,  9.b4!  is dreadful for Black as  a4  comes next. }
9. dxe6 Bxe6 10. Nxe6 fxe6 { And here, the strike } 11. e5
{ is excellent, opening the position even further. } 11... Ng4
{ Black can't take the pawn on e5 due to Bd3, when everything crumbles. } 12.
Bg5 Qd7 13. exd6 O-O
{ Black's best move to fight is to prevent us from playing Be2 and taking the knight on g4. }
14. f3 Ne5 15. Ne4 { We maintain a healthy extra pawn. } *

