[Black "4...a6 (5...h5 6...b5 2)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 d6 4. Be3 a6
{ The main tabiya of the Modern. Black aims to get quick play on the queenside, when the moves b5-Bb7-Nbd7-c5 will follow in some order. }
5. h4
{ After analyzing this line in great depth, I came to the conclusion that this was the most accurate move order that aligns with all our set-ups in the Pirc/ Modern coverage. The text move aims for a quick h5-h6, which is something Black has to prevent. }
5... h5 { The main way of stopping h5, and also the best way to do so. } 6. Nh3
{ I spent a long time in this position, wondering which move order to go for. My conclusion became to develop the knight to h3 at once, where it will quickly reach g5. From the g5-square, the knight targets f7 which opens many tactical possibilities and traps for Black to step in! Let's see how the game can proceed. }
6... b5
{ Black's usual response in the a6-Modern is to make this expansion rather quickly. }
7. Ng5 Bb7 8. Qd2
{ For the sake of our coverage, I want to suggest this move as Black can reach the main line in more ways than just this one. However, the alternatives in  8.g4!?  and  8.a4!?  are extremely interesting.  8.g4!?  is the engine's favorite and certainly worth investigating. }
8... Nd7 { 8...Nf6  transposes to the a6-Pirc after  9.f3  Nbd7  10.O-O-O  . }
9. O-O-O
{ Now, Black has tried a decent amount of moves. I would like to mention that  9...Ngf6?  won't work now due to  10.e5!  when we win material after all the exchanges due to  f4  in the end.   Thus, in order to reach the a6-Pirc line, Black has to play  9...e6  first. We will take a look at it and the alternatives: }
9... Nb6
{ Has been tried by Black, and a common move in these positions as Black is aiming to play b4 followed by Nc4. }
10. f3 Nf6
{ 10...d5?  Was played by the strong GM Bologan, but it looks really bad due to  11.e5!  Aiming to play e6, while also preventing Black from developing the knight on g8.  11...e6  Black can't allow us to play e6, but now the game has turned into one of the ugliest French Defenses that I have ever seen.  12.b3  Preventing Nc4.  12...Ne7  13.g4  Black is really struggling, as he has no activity, while we will soon open the position with gxh5.   10...e6?!  Isn't good here, due to  11.d5!  Black has to make a rather unpleasant decision. Opening the position or closing it with 11... e5 when he will be left with no counterplay on the queenside?  11...exd5  Is the lesser evil, but still very good for us as we can see  12.exd5  Ne7  13.Bd4  The dark squared bishops will be traded, when Black's king will be weak.  13...Bxd4  14.Qxd4  O-O  15.Bd3  We don't need to worry about the d5-pawn.  15...Nbxd5  16.Nxd5  Nxd5  16... Bxd5 is met by 17. g4, when Black's kingside will be blasted open.  17.Be4  We must get rid of the knight on d5 before Black is able to defend himself with Qf6.  17...c6  18.Bxd5  cxd5  19.g4  The files around Black's king are about to be opened, when our consecutive attack gives us a winning position. }
11. Bd3 { Completing our development. } 11... e6 12. Kb1 Qe7
{ Suddenly we are back in the a6-Pirc after } 13. Qf2
{ That being said, there are good alternatives in  13.a3  and  13.Rhe1  . } *

