1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 d6 4. Be3 a6
{ The main tabiya of the Modern. Black aims to get quick play on the queenside, when the moves b5-Bb7-Nbd7-c5 will follow in some order. }
5. h4
{ After analyzing this line in great depth, I came to the conclusion that this was the most accurate move order that aligns with all our set-ups in the Pirc/ Modern coverage. The text move aims for a quick h5-h6, which is something Black has to prevent. }
5... h5 { The main way of stopping h5, and also the best way to do so. } 6. Nh3
{ I spent a long time in this position, wondering which move order to go for. My conclusion became to develop the knight to h3 at once, where it will quickly reach g5. From the g5-square, the knight targets f7 which opens many tactical possibilities and traps for Black to step in! Let's see how the game can proceed. }
6... b5
{ Black's usual response in the a6-Modern is to make this expansion rather quickly. }
7. Ng5 Bb7 8. Qd2
{ For the sake of our coverage, I want to suggest this move as Black can reach the main line in more ways than just this one. }
8... Nd7 9. O-O-O { Now, Black has tried a decent amount of moves. } 9... Qc8
{ This is an engine-move, only played in correspondence chess. Black's idea is similar to  9...Rc8  , since Black intends to play  c5  which we have seen that it didn't work, so Black has to go for this move instead.   9...Ngf6  won't work now due to  10.e5  when we win material after all the exchanges due to f4 in the end. Thus, in order to reach the a6-Pirc line, Black has to play e6 first.  10...dxe5  11.dxe5  Nxe5  12.Qxd8+  Rxd8  13.Rxd8+  Kxd8  14.f4  Where the f-pawn is taking a last gasp. }
10. Kb1 { The typical prophylactic move, moving out of the c-file. } 10... Ngf6
{ Is suggested by the engine and highly logical of course as Black develops the knight.   10...c5  We should meet Black's c5-thrust with  11.dxc5  Nxc5  12.Nd5  Black hasn't completed his development yet, so opening the position is beneficial to us.  12...Nf6!?  Black has to complete his development before we play Bd4, trading the g7-bishop. This move does sacrifice an exchange, but Black gets far too much compensation if we grab it.  13.Nxe7  13. Nb6 gives Black great compensation after 13... Ncxe4. The text move forces an endgame, as 13... Qd8 fails to 14. e5!  13...Ncxe4  14.Nxe4  Nxe4  15.Nxc8  Nxd2+  16.Rxd2  Rxc8  17.Rxd6  Tons of pieces have been traded, and we've ended up with an extra pawn.  17...O-O  18.f3  Blocking Black's bishop on b7 so we can develop the f1-bishop.  18...Rfe8  19.Bf2  White consolidates. Black has tons of suffering ahead due to our extra pawn. }
11. f3 c5
{ 11...O-O ?  Two correspondence games proceeded with this natural move, but it just loses instantly.  12.g4!  Our attack is way too dangerous. The email game continued:  12...Qe8  13.Ne2  The knight is heading to g3.  13...c5  14.Ng3  hxg4  15.h5  Opening the h-file.  15...Nxh5  16.Qh2  The most precise move, placing the queen in the soon-to-be-opened-lane.  16...f5  Now we get to see the point behind Qe8, but it doesn't help due to  17.exf5  Black won't survive as the h-file will be opened. Black lasted only a few more moves in Koelewijn,A - Van Vliet,E ICCF email 2017. }
12. dxc5 { We want to open the position. } 12... Nxc5 13. Bd4
{ The bishop is well placed in this diagonal. } 13... O-O
{ We have somehow transposed into the human game Sesar,I - Cappelletto,J Tarvisio 2017, when White should have started the attack with }
14. g4 hxg4 15. Nd5
{ The best move, as we want to get rid of the knight on f6 so we can open the h-file with h5. }
15... Nxd5 16. Bxg7 Kxg7 17. exd5
{ We are ready to open the h-file with h5 so Black has to react fast. } 17...
e5
{ The reason why this works is that it prepares Black to play Qf5-Qf4, which is now possible as the e5-pawn controls the f4-square. }
18. h5 Qf5 { Is the only defense, with as mentioned, the idea of Qf4. } 19.
hxg6 Rh8 { The best shot for counterplay. } 20. Rg1 Qf4
{ Seems to me the best try for survival, forcing an endgame. } 21. gxf7 Qxd2
22. Rxd2 Kf6 23. f4 exf4 24. Rxg4
{ This is now possible, as Rh1 doesn't work anymore for Black due to Rf4+. }
24... Raf8 25. Rdg2
{ Preparing to take on f4 next, when it seems like Black is simply busted. } *

