1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 d6 4. Be3 a6
{ The main tabiya of the Modern. Black aims to get quick play on the queenside, when the moves b5-Bb7-Nbd7-c5 will follow in some order. }
5. h4
{ After analyzing this line in great depth, I came to the conclusion that this was the most accurate move order that aligns with all our set-ups in the Pirc/ Modern coverage. The text move aims for a quick h5-h6, which is something Black has to prevent. }
5... h5 { The main way of stopping h5, and also the best way to do so. } 6. Nh3
{ I spent a long time in this position, wondering which move order to go for. My conclusion became to develop the knight to h3 at once, where it will quickly reach g5. From the g5-square, the knight targets f7 which opens many tactical possibilities and traps for Black to step in! Let's see how the game can proceed. }
6... b5
{ Black's usual response in the a6-Modern is to make this expansion rather quickly. }
7. Ng5 Bb7 8. Qd2
{ For the sake of our coverage, I want to suggest this move as Black can reach the main line in more ways than just this one. }
8... Nd7 9. O-O-O { Now, Black has tried a decent amount of moves. } 9... Rc8
{ Is the second most popular move here played by many 2300+ players, but it just doesn't work! The reasons are concrete:   9...Ngf6  won't work now due to  10.e5  when we win material after all the exchanges due to f4 in the end. Thus, in order to reach the a6-Pirc line, Black has to play e6 first.  10...dxe5  11.dxe5  Nxe5  12.Qxd8+  Rxd8  13.Rxd8+  Kxd8  14.f4  Where the f-pawn is taking a last gasp. }
10. e5 { White's threat is e6, leaving Black with little choices. } 10... dxe5
{ 10...c5?  Was seen in a game, when our response is  11.e6  fxe6  12.Nxe6  Qa5  Black's position is completely lost due to his weak king. I choose to show the game as Adair who is rated 2480 managed to complicate things tremendously, so maybe it's not so easy from a practical standpoint.  13.Nxg7+  Kf7  Black will win our knight, so opening the position is the way to cause problems.  14.dxc5  b4  15.Bc4+  Kxg7  16.Nd5  Nxc5  Black has 'some activity, ' but it doesn't justify the poor king. Now, a nice blow is  17.Nxe7  Nxe7  This is the critical moment.  18.Qd4  The way to win, improving on Adair, J - Ackley, P Harrogate 2018, when Black missed  18...Kh7  19.Qf6+-  White breaks through Black's defenses. A sample line is:  19...Nf5  20.Qf7+  Ng7  21.Rxd6  Be4  22.Qf4!  The only move that wins, but it wins!  Qh6  is the threat, a beautiful mate.  22...Nf5  23.Rxg6  Black's king has no defenses, and taking the rook leads to mate:  23...Kxg6  24.Qg5+  Kh7  25.Qxh5+  Kg7  26.Qf7#  Nice! }
11. dxe5 Bxe5
{ 11...Nxe5  loses material after the trades on  d8  followed by  f4  . } 12.
Bd3 Nf8
{ Allowed the beautiful   12...Ngf6  Doesn't work for Black due to  13.f4  Bd6  14.Bxg6  Black's queen will be trapped with  Ne6  if the takes the bishop, so the position is hopeless.   12...Rb8  Was played in an e-mail game I discovered. The point is simply to give the queen an escape route to c8.  13.Rhe1  White is already completely winning as f4-f5 gives him a dangerous attack. I leave the nice e-mail game as a clickable, but you don't need to know more than this...  13...Bd6  14.Ba7  Ra8  15.Bd4  Ngf6  16.f4  The pawn is well on its way to f5 where it will create major damage.  16...O-O  17.f5  gxf5  18.Nge4!  An engine move which gives the g5-square for the queen.  18...Nxe4  19.Nxe4  e5  Preventing the nasty Queen check.  20.Nxd6  cxd6  21.Bxf5!  Taking the pawn works as Black will be mated in short order if he takes the d4-bishop.  21...Qf6  22.Bxd7  exd4  23.Rf1  Qg6  24.g4+-  The g-file will finally be opened.  24...Be4  25.gxh5  Qxh5  26.Rg1+  Bg6  27.Rg5  Qxh4  28.Qg2+-  Black resigned, as White breaks through his defenses in Johnson, B - Efanov, N ICCF email 2014. }
13. Bxb5+ axb5 14. Qxd8+ Rxd8 15. Rxd8+ Kxd8 16. Nxf7+ Kc8 17. Nxe5
{ When White had a completely winning endgame in Zeller,F- Schulz,K Wunsiedel 2016. }
