[Black "4...a6 (5...e6)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6
{ Here we have arrived at the opening sequence that defines the Pirc Defense. The opening tends to lead to exciting and complicated games, which is why the opening is often utilized by higher-rated players who badly needs a win with the black pieces. On top level you won't see this opening occur often, as White has numerous dangerous ways of fighting it, making the opening a risky choice. Just like most openings, White needs to know what he's doing in order to fight for an edge, so we must be prepared! }
4. Be3 { We will play in similar fashion to the Modern Defense. } 4... a6
{ Black can choose to delay Bg7 and play a6 already here. It's suggested by IM Christof Sielecki in his Pirc Course, as he is not a fan of the fact that Bh6 often comes when Black has played Bg7, which makes sense. }
5. h3 { I think this is the best way to fight against Black's set-up. } 5... e6
{ Has only been played twice, but one of the players has been the great GM Ian Nepo, so we must consider it. The move sure looks strange, but the idea behind it is to play b5 as Black now controls the d5-square. }
6. Qf3
{ Not only can we now meet b5 with e5, we can also castle queenside next. }
6... Bg7
{ 6...b5  is refuted by  7.Bg5!  with e5 to follow, so this move looks best. }
7. O-O-O O-O
{ The players have now castled on opposite sides, when the resulting play will become sharp. Black is still lacking pieces on the queenside though. With limited space control as well, we certainly have the upper hand. }
8. g4 Nbd7 9. e5 { This direct pawn launch looks strongest. } 9... Nd5
{ Black's best bet is to sac a pawn, as the position after  9...dxe5  10.dxe5  Ne8  11.Qg3  Qe7  12.f4  is far from satisfactory. }
10. Nxd5 exd5 11. exd6 b5 { Black tempts us into taking yet another pawn. } 12.
Bd3 { We humbly decline, as  12.Qxd5  is not clear at all after  12...Nb6! }
12... Nf6 13. dxc7
{ I think it's best to take the extra pawn, but there's still nothing wrong with  13.Ne2  . }
13... Qxc7 14. Qf4 Qb7 15. Nf3
{ Black does not have sufficient counterplay for the missing pawn. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
