[Round "?"]
[White "12. Pirc (1...d6) a6 lines"]
[Black "4...a6 (5...b5)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6
{ Here we have arrived at the opening sequence that defines the Pirc Defense. The opening tends to lead to exciting and complicated games, which is why the opening is often utilized by higher-rated players who badly needs a win with the black pieces. On top level you won't see this opening occur often, as White has numerous dangerous ways of fighting it, making the opening a risky choice. Just like most openings, White needs to know what he's doing in order to fight for an edge, so we must be prepared! }
4. Be3 { We will play in similar fashion to the Modern Defense. } 4... a6
{ Black can choose to delay Bg7 and play a6 already here. It's suggested by IM Christof Sielecki in his Pirc Course, as he is not a fan of the fact that Bh6 often comes when Black has played Bg7, which makes sense. }
5. h3 { I think this is the best way to fight against Black's set-up. } 5... b5
{ Has been played by many strong players, but it's already a huge error due to }
6. e5
{ The reason why this concrete move works is that Black no longer has the knight jump to g4. }
6... Nfd7 7. Qf3
{ Another strong move, developing the queen while attacking the rook. } 7...
Nb6
{ Is the lesser evil, but Black is still in huge problems after   7...Ra7  8.O-O-O  A natural move. White's score here is 3/3, which is good news for us, of course.  8...Bb7  9.Qg3  b4  Both GMs tried this move for Black, and I also think it's the most logical way to create some counterplay.  10.Na4  This move is my favorite, but according to my engine, 10. Nce2 which was seen in Raznikov,D - Onischuk,V Zalakaros 2015, was equally strong.  10...Ra8  Black moves the rook out of harm's way.  11.h4  Much stronger than 11. Bc4 which was seen in Jones, G - Tukhaev,A St. Petersburg 2018. White aims to play h5 which is really unpleasant and difficult to meet, since  11...h5  is refuted by  12.e6+-  Black's kingside is about to get destroyed, so White is completely winning. }
8. a4 { A strong move, attacking b5 and threatening to play a5. } 8... bxa4 9.
Nxa4 N8d7
{ Black is defending the knight that guards the rook, and at first sight he is holding up. However, there is a second weakness we can attack, namely the pawn on g6. }
10. h4
{ Every time Black has played g6, ideas with h4-h5 are always in the air. }
10... Rb8
{ Was played twice by the Correspondence player Dominique Conterno, so let's take a brief look. The idea is simple, Black can play Bb7 and the rook is finally gone from the vulnerable spot on the a8-square.   10...dxe5  Is nothing to be scared of, when our response should be  11.Nxb6  Nxb6  12.dxe5  Qd5  13.h5!  Executing our idea.  13...Rg8  Black can't really allow us to take on h6, where he would have had to take with the extremely ugly fxg6.  14.Bxb6  Forcing the game into a really horrendous ending for Black.  14...Qxf3  15.Nxf3  cxb6  16.h6!  The h-pawn remains very strong on g6 while it also limits Black's forces.  16...e6  17.Ng5!  A strong move, targeting the h7-pawn, so Black has to play  17...Rh8  18.O-O-O  Be7   18...Bb7  is met by the neat trick  19.Nxf7  , with  Rd7+  being the reason why the trick works.  19.Ne4+-  Nd6+ comes next, when Black is simply left with one of the worst endings I have ever seen. }
11. h5 { Our plan all along, so there's no reason not to play it. } 11... g5
{ The best chance for counterplay. } 12. Nxb6 Rxb6
{ Defending the hanging pawn on a6. } 13. Qg3
{ A clear improvement over the confusing  13.O-O-O  which was seen in Holec, M - Conterno, D ICCF email 2013. }
13... h6 14. Bd3 e6 15. Nf3
{ Simple development. There is no reason to worry about the hanging pawn on b2 as our initiative outweighs the missing pawn. }
15... Rxb2 16. O-O Be7 17. Nh2
{ The knight is headed to g4 with ideas like f4 lingering in the air. The pawn on a6 is also hanging, so it's worth considering to play c3 at some point. Black's position is filled with weaknesses, making it close to impossible to handle over the board. }
*

