{ Here we have arrived at the opening sequence that defines the Pirc Defense. The opening tends to lead to exciting and complicated games, which is why the opening is often utilized by higher-rated players who badly needs a win with the black pieces. On top level you won't see this opening occur often, as White has numerous dangerous ways of fighting it, making the opening a risky choice. Just like most openings, White needs to know what he's doing in order to fight for an edge, so we must be prepared! }
4. Be3 { We will play in similar fashion to the Modern Defense. } 4... a6
{ Black can choose to delay Bg7 and play a6 already here. It's suggested by IM Christof Sielecki in his Pirc Course, as he is not a fan of the fact that Bh6 often comes when Black has played Bg7, which makes sense. }
5. h3 { I think this is the best way to fight against Black's set-up. } 5...
Nbd7
{ With the knight out of the way, Black is preparing to launch the b-pawn two squares. Unfortunately for him, it's our move. }
6. Nf3
{ This developing move controls the square on e5, which is something Black has to keep in mind. }
6... e5 { The most played move in the position. } 7. g4
{ This aggressive pawn launch is an engine-move, aiming to attack the black king with Qe2 followed by O-O-O. }
7... Bg7 { Was played twice, with a score of 0/2 for Black! } 8. dxe5
{ Removing the tension in the center. } 8... dxe5 9. Qd2 c6 10. O-O-O
{ It's time to attack! } 10... Qe7
{ 10...O-O  was met by the tactical blow  11.Nxe5!  so Black defends the pawn first. }
11. Ne1 { The knight is on its way to the d3-square. } 11... O-O 12. f3
{ Defending the pawns on e4 and g4.   My engine shows that  12.Nd3  right away is even stronger though... }
12... Re8 13. Nd3 b5 14. Kb1
{ Is always a prophylactic move you want to make once you have castled queenside. }
14... Nf8 15. h4 { It's time for our pawns to start rolling! } 15... h5 16. Bh3
{ Is a strong move, as White aims to take on h5 followed by Bg4 next. } 16...
Be6 17. gxh5 Nxh5
{ 17...Bxh3  was met by  18.hxg6!  when White's pawns are much stronger than the piece. }
18. Bg4
{ White had a very powerful attack, which eventually led to glory in Blake,M - Pyrich,G ICCF email 2017. }
