5. h3 { I think this is the best way to fight against Black's set-up. } 5...
Nbd7
{ With the knight out of the way, Black is preparing to launch the b-pawn two squares. Unfortunately for him, it's our move. }
6. Nf3
{ This developing move controls the square on e5, which is something Black has to keep in mind. }
6... e5 { The most played move in the position. } 7. g4
{ This aggressive pawn launch is an engine-move, aiming to attack the black king with Qe2 followed by O-O-O. }
7... exd4
{ The best try according to the engine and played in one email game where Black achieved a draw. }
8. Nxd4 Bg7 9. g5
{ It's always nice to have this move in stock, as Black loses pressure on the e4-pawn. }
9... Nh5 10. Qd2 O-O 11. Be2 { Targeting the vulnerable knight on h5. } 11...
Ne5 12. O-O-O b5 13. Bxh5
{ We should take the knight before Black can play Nc4. } 13... Nc4 14. Qe2
{ A clear improvement over  14.Qe1  which happened in Dunlop, G - Conterno, D ICCF email 2017. }
14... c5
{ Black's only try.  14...gxh5  is met by  15.Qxh5  of course, when Black can pretty much resign due to  Nf5  and Rg1-Rg4-Rh4 ideas. }
15. Nc6
{ This move works tactically. I suspect that the engines in 2017 missed this opportunity. }
15... Qe8 16. Nd5 { Defending the c6-knight with tactics. } 16... Bxb2+ 17. Kb1
{ There are a lot of pieces hanging, but it all works out! } 17... Kh8 18. Nce7
{ We shouldn't give Black the option of taking our precious knight on c6. }
18... Be6 19. f4
{ A strong move, with the powerful threat of e5.   Note that  19.Bf3?  is a bad move as Black will have tremendous compensation after  19...Ra7!  due to our exposed king @@StartBracket@@Rxe7 will follow@@EndBracket@@. }
19... gxh5 20. Bc1
{ Giving our king some protection while aiming to rid ourselves with Black's guardian on the dark squares. }
20... Bg7 21. Rhg1
{ White has Black's initiative under control, so Black is objectively lost here. }
21... Ra7 { Would now fail to } 22. Qxh5 Rxe7 23. Nf6 { We break through. }
23... Bxf6 24. gxf6 { Black is soon mated. } *

