1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6
{ Here we have arrived at the opening sequence that defines the Pirc Defense. The opening tends to lead to exciting and complicated games, which is why the opening is often utilized by higher-rated players who badly needs a win with the black pieces. On top level you won't see this opening occur often, as White has numerous dangerous ways of fighting it, making the opening a risky choice. Just like most openings, White needs to know what he's doing in order to fight for an edge, so we must be prepared! }
4. Be3 { We will play in similar fashion to the Modern Defense. } 4... a6
{ Black can choose to delay Bg7 and play a6 already here. It's suggested by IM Christof Sielecki in his Pirc Course, as he is not a fan of the fact that Bh6 often comes when Black has played Bg7, which makes sense. }
5. h3 { I think this is the best way to fight against Black's set-up. } 5...
Nbd7
{ With the knight out of the way, Black is preparing to launch the b-pawn two squares. Unfortunately for him, it's our move. }
6. Nf3
{ This developing move controls the square on e5, which is something Black has to keep in mind. }
6... e5 { The most played move in the position. } 7. g4
{ This aggressive pawn launch is an engine-move, aiming to attack the black king with Qe2 followed by O-O-O. }
7... h6
{ Was played four times, so it seems like the move appealed a lot to the engines a few years ago. }
8. Qe2
{ A strong move, as we aim to castle queenside and launch our forces at the black king. }
8... b5 9. O-O-O { Taking on e5 right away won't make any difference. } 9...
Qe7 { Defending the pawn on e5. } 10. dxe5 dxe5 11. h4
{ A very strong move as we aim to remove the knight on f6 by playing g5. }
11... Nb6 { Is met by } 12. Bxb6 cxb6 13. Bh3
{ This move is required in order to carry out the desired g5-move. } 13... Bg7
14. a3
{ This looks strange, but it's essential that we prevent Black from playing b4.   14.g5  is too hasty, as Black is fine in the sequence  14...hxg5  15.Bxc8  Rxc8  16.hxg5  Rxh1  17.Rxh1  Nh5  18.Nd5  Nf4! }
14... Kf8
{ Was played instead in Sommerbauer,N - Nyvylt,Z ICCF email 2016, but Black is passive and his king remains in jeopardy.   14...O-O ?  Is horrible after  15.g5+-  Black won't last for long. }
15. Qe3 { White agrees to an exchange of pawns. } 15... Bxg4 16. Bxg4 Nxg4 17.
Qxb6
{ The black pieces look slightly liberated, but in return we have obtained full access to the square on d5. }
17... h5 18. Nd5 Bh6+ 19. Kb1 Qa7 20. Qc6 Kg7
{ It looks like Black has escaped and is in perfect shape, but everything works in our favor after }
21. Nc7 Rhc8 22. Rd7 { The queen on a7 has to move. } 22... Qxf2 23. Qc3
{ Not only does the queen defend the knight on this square, it can also move to b3 where it will attack the pawn on f7. }
23... Rab8 24. Qb3 Rf8 25. Ne6+
{ White will be up an exchange and eventually prevailed. Sommerbauer,N - Nyvlt,Z ICCF email 2016. }
