5. h3 { I think this is the best way to fight against Black's set-up. } 5...
Nbd7
{ With the knight out of the way, Black is preparing to launch the b-pawn two squares. Unfortunately for him, it's our move. }
6. Nf3
{ This developing move controls the square on e5, which is something Black has to keep in mind. }
6... e5 { The most played move in the position. } 7. g4
{ This aggressive pawn launch is an engine-move, aiming to attack the black king with Qe2 followed by O-O-O. }
7... h6
{ Was played four times, so it seems like the move appealed a lot to the engines a few years ago. }
8. Qe2
{ A strong move, as we aim to castle queenside and launch our forces at the black king. }
8... b5 9. O-O-O { Taking on e5 right away won't make any difference. } 9...
Qe7 { Defending the pawn on e5. } 10. dxe5 dxe5 11. h4
{ A very strong move as we aim to remove the knight on f6 by playing g5. }
11... Nc5 { This active jump looks like Black's best try. } 12. g5
{ It takes great depth for the engine to realize that this move is superior to the alternative  12. Bh3... The reason for this is that we sacrifice an exchange, but in return our initiative is overwhelming. If you don't like the arising complications, there is in an alternative in  12.Bh3  . The game continues  12...Ncxe4  13.Nxe4  Nxe4  14.Nd2  Nxd2  15.Bg2!  e4!  16.Bxd2  , when White has some initiative with  Bc3  to come. }
12... hxg5 13. hxg5 Rxh1 14. gxf6 Qe6
{ The only move.  14...Qxf6  loses to  15.Nd5  Qd6  16.Ng5  when Black is overwhelmed by our threats, one of them being  Qf3  . }
15. Nd5 Qd6
{ Once again the only move.  15...Qc6  16.Nxe5  Qd6  17.Nxg6  fxg6  18.f7+  is a beautiful finish. }
16. Nb4 Qb6
{ The best attempt.  16...Qxf6  fails to  17.Nd5  Qd6  18.Ng5!  The fact that Black has taken the f6-pawn and left the f6-square available to our knight secures his doom, as  18...Bb7  is no longer possible. }
17. Qd2 c6 { Preventing Qd8. } 18. Nxe5 Qc7 { Black moves out of the pin. } 19.
f4 Nxe4 { Black has to give the exchange back. } 20. Qg2 Rxf1 21. Rxf1 Bf5
{ 21...Bc5  22.Bxc5  was a bizarre end to Steiger, W - Nyvlt, Z ICCF email 2016, when I suspected Black's move was a typo. The reason this loses is that  Rh1  will follow. }
22. Nbxc6 Qd6 23. Nd4
{ White's initiative is decisive, due to Black's terrible king. However, the game is still slightly complex, there's no doubt about that. }
