5. h3 { I think this is the best way to fight against Black's set-up. } 5...
Bg7
{ This move is the most popular move, and the suggested approach by IM Sielecki. He refrained from playing this one move earlier, but justifies the move now as we now longer can use the 'caveman approach' with Bh6 against it. An accurate summation. }
6. g4
{ A very interesting move where White aims to develop the bishop to g2 and the knight to e2. Black also needs to be careful of a potential g5-thrust. The more common 6. f4 is definitely worth investigating, and GM Wesley So goes through it in great depth in his excellent 1. e4 course. }
6... O-O 7. Nge2 { As planned, we place the knight on e2. } 7... b5
{ Has been played in all human games, when we should respond with the typical   7...e5  Has never been played in any human games, but it is suggested by my engine.  8.dxe5  Seems like the best way to respond.  8...dxe5  9.g5  Forcing the knight to an inferior square.  9...Nfd7   Forced, as  9...Nh5?  10.Qxd8  Rxd8  11.Nd5  is simply winning for White.  10.h4  An attack is coming Black's way!  10...Nc6  11.Bh3  The bishop is better placed in this diagonal.  11...Re8  12.f3  Nf8  Is a very thematic move in these positions, as Black wants to place a knight on d4 at some point.  13.Qxd8  Rxd8  14.Bxc8  Raxc8  15.Nd5  Blocking the black rook so we can castle queenside.  15...Ne6  16.O-O-O  ±  White has the upper hand due to his active pieces. }
8. e5 { Opening the diagonal again, making Bb7 impossible for Black. } 8...
Nfd7
{ Should be played, when   8...dxe5?!  Leads once again to an atrocious endgame for Black after  9.dxe5  Qxd1+  10.Rxd1  Nfd7   And now, White made a massive mistake in Van der Wiel, J - Vandenbussche, T Brasschaat 2010, by playing  11.Nd5?  which allowed  11...Bb7!  when Black was suddenly better! Instead, the simple  11.Bg2  Gives us a massive advantage.  11...c6  12.f4  g5  Is an attempt to dismantle our pawns, but we can simply play  13.e6!  fxe6  14.fxg5+-  Black's position is just awful due to the terrible pawn structure and pieces. }
9. Bg2 c6 10. f4
{ Gives us a great center, similar to what we've already seen. } *

