1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6
{ Here we have arrived at the opening sequence that defines the Pirc Defense. The opening tends to lead to exciting and complicated games, which is why the opening is often utilized by higher-rated players who badly needs a win with the black pieces. On top level you won't see this opening occur often, as White has numerous dangerous ways of fighting it, making the opening a risky choice. Just like most openings, White needs to know what he's doing in order to fight for an edge, so we must be prepared! }
4. Be3 { We will play in similar fashion to the Modern Defense. } 4... a6
{ Black can choose to delay Bg7 and play a6 already here. It's suggested by IM Christof Sielecki in his Pirc Course, as he is not a fan of the fact that Bh6 often comes when Black has played Bg7, which makes sense. }
5. h3 { I think this is the best way to fight against Black's set-up. } 5...
Bg7
{ This move is the most popular move, and the suggested approach by IM Sielecki. He refrained from playing this one move earlier, but justifies the move now as we now longer can use the 'caveman approach' with Bh6 against it. An accurate summation. }
6. g4
{ A very interesting move where White aims to develop the bishop to g2 and the knight to e2. Black also needs to be careful of a potential g5-thrust. The more common 6. f4 is definitely worth investigating, and GM Wesley So goes through it in great depth in his excellent 1. e4 course. }
6... h5
{ Advocated by IM Sielecki and utilized by the strong French GM Fressinet, so we must take a look. Black uses the fact that he hasn't castled yet. His desire is to fix the pawn structure on the kingside, forcing us to make an important decision on which direction we should take the game. }
7. g5 Nfd7 8. Bg2
{ The usual continuation and the most logical approach. However,  8.f4!?  is another alternative, when the play will be 'razor-sharp, ' as Christof describes it, something I agree with. Our expansion has its downsides after all. }
8... b5
{ Is what Fress decided to play.   8...e6  Is suggested by IM Sielecki. The idea is to take control of the d5 and f5 squares. Black's strategy, as IM Sielecki greatly puts it, is that he is hoping that we overextend ourselves.  9.Nge2±  Looks more accurate than playing f4 directly. White's position looks much easier to handle in my opinion, as Black is quite cramped. A strategic fight will definitely ensue, but there's no doubt that we are in the driving seat. }
9. f4
{ The most accurate way to proceed.  9.e5  is insanely logical, but not the best as Black has the stunning resource:  9...Nb6!  10.Bxa8  Nxa8  11.Qf3  Nb6  . The play remains unclear, as we are incredibly weak on the light squares due to the fact that our light-squared bishop is absent. That being said, this is a really tough move to find for Black OTB.   The strong GM encounter continued with  9...Ra7  10.e6!  fxe6  11.Qd3  Nf8  12.Be4  Kf7  13.d5  c5  14.dxc6  Rc7  15.Bb6  , when Black was completely busted in Bauer, C - Fressinet, L Caen 2011. }
9... Bb7 { Black prevents f5. } 10. Nf3 b4
{ Is the critical move, as Black wins the e4-pawn. } 11. Ne2 Bxe4 12. Ng3 Bd5
{ Is Black's best attempt to defend.   12...Bb7  Leads to a horrible position for Black after  13.f5  13...e6  Black's best attempt to avoid being overrun on the kingside.  14.fxe6  fxe6  15.Qe2+-  Black's pawns are easy targets for our pieces. }
13. f5 e6
{ One important difference is that the black bishop defends the e6-pawn.   13...h4  Is met by the cute  14.Nxh4  Nb6  A necessary move, otherwise we get Qf3 quickly.  15.Bxd5  Nxd5  16.Ng2  Sweet harmony!  16...Nxe3  17.Nxe3  Nc6  18.c3±  We have everything under control and some very powerful pawns. fxg6 followed by Qd3 is one idea to keep in mind, so Black probably has to force matters with e6 at some point, when our response should be f6. }
14. f6 { Is now what we should play, when } 14... Bf8 15. O-O
{ Gives us a clearly better game due to Black's pieces struggling to get out on the board. }
*

