5. h3 { I think this is the best way to fight against Black's set-up. } 5...
Bg7
{ This move is the most popular move, and the suggested approach by IM Sielecki. He refrained from playing this one move earlier, but justifies the move now as we now longer can use the 'caveman approach' with Bh6 against it. An accurate summation. }
6. g4
{ A very interesting move where White aims to develop the bishop to g2 and the knight to e2. Black also needs to be careful of a potential g5-thrust. The more common 6. f4 is definitely worth investigating, and GM Wesley So goes through it in great depth in his excellent 1. e4 course. }
6... h5
{ @@StartSquare@@Alternative@@EndSquare@@ I really want to mention this novelty which looks really strong. The idea is that we sacrifice a pawn for a strong initiative. }
7. e5 dxe5
{ There are alternatives, but I am certain that a human player would grab the pawn. }
8. dxe5 Qxd1+ 9. Rxd1 Nfd7
{ Black is threatening two pawns at once - the pawn on e5 and the pawn on g4. }
10. f4
{ We must keep the e5-pawn in order to keep our advantage.  10.gxh5  keeps the pawn, but Black has no issues after  10...Bxe5  . }
10... hxg4 { Black can't allow us to play g5, when Black has no counterplay. }
11. Bg2 gxh3
{ Keeping the extra pawn is greedy, when we have the strong resource   11...c6  Looks logical to me, as Black closes the diagonal.  12.hxg4  Rxh1  13.Bxh1±  Our strong center and better pieces give us a clear edge. }
12. Nd5 { Attacking the pawn on c7. } 12... Kd8 13. Nxh3
{ Black has to worry about Ng5 now, when there will be too many things to defend at the same time. }
13... e6
{ Black has to drive the knight away, but he is still badly suffering after }
14. Nf6 Ke7 15. Ng4
{ Our pieces are so strong that I think Black is objectively lost. Overall a great alternative, so feel free to analyze it deeper with the engine if you prefer it over the text move. It's not mentioned by IM Sielecki, so it most certainly will be an obnoxious surprise for his fans :@@EndBracket@@ }
*

