1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6
{ Here we have arrived at the opening sequence that defines the Pirc Defense. The opening tends to lead to exciting and complicated games, which is why the opening is often utilized by higher-rated players who badly needs a win with the black pieces. On top level you won't see this opening occur often, as White has numerous dangerous ways of fighting it, making the opening a risky choice. Just like most openings, White needs to know what he's doing in order to fight for an edge, so we must be prepared! }
4. Be3 { We will play in similar fashion to the Modern Defense. } 4... Bg7
{ Black keeps us guessing with this move as he can play O-O, a6 or c6! It was not easy for me to come up with something that battles all of these set-ups, but I eventually came to the conclusion that the text move is best. }
5. f3
{ We go for the set-up we saw in the Modern Defense, f3-Be3-Qd2-O-O-O etc. I had a tough time deciding which move to go for. White has so many good options against Pirc/Modern so I felt like a kid in a candy store. I was however, very happy with what I came up with in the end. Here are some of my findings:  5.h3  demonstrates perfectly the advantage of Black's move order as he can now play,  5...O-O  6.f4  c5!  with pretty decent counterattack.   5.Qd2  is more dangerous and the reason why IM Sielecki wanted to avoid  Bg7  . The line I analyzed was:  5...c6  6.Nf3  b5  7.Bd3  O-O  8.Bh6  Bg4  9.h4  Bxf3  10.gxf3  Nh5  11.Bxg7  Kxg7  12.f4  Nd7  13.O-O-O  Qb6  14.Be2  b4  15.Na4  Qa5  16.b3  Nb6  with a mess. Black survives, but he needs to play insanely accurately as many moves along the way have been 'only moves.' IM Sielecki argues that White's play is very easy to carry out, as he simply needs to play 'natural moves only.' I agree, but that's the prize you're paying for choosing the Pirc Defense as your opening. You are at risk of getting smashed in some lines, so a decent amount of knowledge is required. }
5... O-O { Black can even castle before playing a6. } 6. Qd2 a6
{ This has been played in many games, but our attack on the kingside is much faster than Black's attack on the queenside. In fact, my engine tells me we're already winning after }
7. O-O-O { The most natural move, when a powerful attack soon ensues. } 7... b5
8. h4
{ The same plan as always. The h-file will get opened, followed by Bh6, when Black gets mated shortly afterwards. }
8... h5
{ Is the natural response whenever h4 is pushed on the board.   8...Nbd7  Is met by  9.h5  Nxh5  10.Bh6  Ng3  Is nothing to worry about, as we can simply play  11.Bxg7  Nxh1  12.Bxf8  Nxf8  13.Qg5+-  Black can't prevent us from playing Qh4, when the knight on h1 falls.   8...b4  Is natural, but not impressive as seen after  9.Nce2  a5  10.h5  Our attack plays itself.  10...Nc6  11.hxg6  fxg6  12.Nf4  Now Black needs to worry about Bc4+ followed by Nxg6.  12...Qe8  13.Bb5  Another strong move, pinning Black's knight on c6.  13...Rb8  14.Ba4  d5 is now a really annoying threat, so Black placed the bishop in the pin with  14...Bd7  which now allowed  15.Bxc6  Bxc6  16.Ne6  Rf7  17.Nh3+-  Black was completely busted in Bachmann,W - Pino Munoz,F ICCF email 2010. Nxg7 comes next followed by Bh6 and Ng5, when Black has to give an exchange. }
9. Bh6 { We keep playing in similar fashion. } 9... Nc6 10. g4
{ Black's blockade on h5 is only temporary. } 10... e5
{ 10...hxg4  is met by  11.h5!  of course. } 11. Bg5
{ Pinning the knight so it can no longer recapture on h5. } 11... Nxd4 12. gxh5
{ Our attack gives us a decisive advantage. } *

