1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6
{ Here we have arrived at the opening sequence that defines the Pirc Defense. The opening tends to lead to exciting and complicated games, which is why the opening is often utilized by higher-rated players who badly needs a win with the black pieces. On top level you won't see this opening occur often, as White has numerous dangerous ways of fighting it, making the opening a risky choice. Just like most openings, White needs to know what he's doing in order to fight for an edge, so we must be prepared! }
4. Be3 { We will play in similar fashion to the Modern Defense. } 4... Bg7
{ Black keeps us guessing with this move as he can play O-O, a6 or c6! It was not easy for me to come up with something that battles all of these set-ups, but I eventually came to the conclusion that the text move is best. }
5. f3
{ We go for the set-up we saw in the Modern Defense, f3-Be3-Qd2-O-O-O etc. I had a tough time deciding which move to go for. White has so many good options against Pirc/Modern so I felt like a kid in a candy store. }
5... a6
{ Black should play a6 before castling. Black's play is similar to the Modern Defense. He plans to place a bishop on b7, a knight on d7 and will eventually follow up with c5 or b4-a5. }
6. Qd2 b5
{ Is the most played move in the position, but I won't put it as the main line as I analyzed through the move-order that occurs after  6...Nbd7  . }
7. O-O-O
{ Black should transpose to the main line from this position, but I will include one alternative. }
7... b4
{ 7...Nbd7  , along with  7...Bb7  8.h4  h5  9.Nh3  Nbd7  lead to the main tabiya of the chapter. }
8. Nce2 a5
{ Some strong players have played like this against lower-rated opponents, which is the reason why Black's score is that great. @@StartBracket@@5 wins, 1 loss and 2 draws@@EndBracket@@. }
9. Kb1
{ This side-stepping move is a move we've seen consistently whenever we have castled queenside, and it's once again a nice prophylactic move. }
9... Ba6 10. Bh6 { Looks like the most accurate way to fight Black's set-up. }
10... Bxh6
{ Black can't castle due to our powerful attack, so he is pretty much forced to take. }
11. Qxh6 a4
{ Black has some play on the queenside, so we must play accurately. } 12. Nh3
{ We should finish our development.  12.Nc1  was too passive in Tologontegin, S - Adly, A Sharjah 2014, when Black would have gotten nice play after  12...Bxf1  13.Rxf1  c5  . }
12... Nbd7
{ 12...e6  13.Nf2±  Looks really nice for us, as we soon will continue with g4-h4-h5. Black's play on the queenside isn't fast enough. We can even consider playing d5 at some point, making c5 for Black difficult to achieve. }
13. Nc1 Qc8
{ Black moves out of the pin and aims to play c5, while the queen can also recapture on a6. }
14. Nf4
{ The knight is well placed on f4 where it can head to d3 if necessary. It also gives us the option of playing h4-h5 as well. }
14... c5 15. Bxa6
{ Taking the bishop on a6 is something we should do sooner or later so we can place a rook on e1 and play e5. }
15... Qxa6 16. dxc5 Nxc5 17. Rhe1
{ We are preparing to play e5 next, so Black has to try to get some counterplay. }
17... Qc4
{ Black is preparing to play a3 when we are vulnerable on the dark squares.   Note that  17...b3  is met by  18.a3!  , when  18...bxc2+  is nothing to fear, although our king looks exposed on  c2  . It will go back to  b1  next when we have everything under control. }
18. Rd2
{ Defending against Black's b3-advance, as the c2-pawn is now defended. } 18...
a3 19. b3 Qc3 20. Nfd3
{ We have everything under control, when it seems like Black's queenside pawn advances harms him in the end as the pawns are quite weak. A nice plan is to play Ne2 followed by Rc1 and c3. Black of course needs to avoid his Queen getting trapped on c3 with the initial move of the plan. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12. Pirc (1...d6) a6 lines"]
[Black "4...Bg7 (5...a6 3)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6
{ Here we have arrived at the opening sequence that defines the Pirc Defense. The opening tends to lead to exciting and complicated games, which is why the opening is often utilized by higher-rated players who badly needs a win with the black pieces. On top level you won't see this opening occur often, as White has numerous dangerous ways of fighting it, making the opening a risky choice. Just like most openings, White needs to know what he's doing in order to fight for an edge, so we must be prepared! }
4. Be3 { We will play in similar fashion to the Modern Defense. } 4... Bg7
{ Black keeps us guessing with this move as he can play O-O, a6 or c6! It was not easy for me to come up with something that battles all of these set-ups, but I eventually came to the conclusion that the text move is best. }
5. f3
{ We go for the set-up we saw in the Modern Defense, f3-Be3-Qd2-O-O-O etc. I had a tough time deciding which move to go for. White has so many good options against Pirc/Modern so I felt like a kid in a candy store. }
5... a6
{ Black should play a6 before castling. Black's play is similar to the Modern Defense. He plans to place a bishop on b7, a knight on d7 and will eventually follow up with c5 or b4-a5. }
6. Qd2 Nbd7 7. O-O-O
{ Black does have some alternatives to the usual 7... b5, but none of them look good. Let's take a look before we head to the main move: }
7... b5
{ The exclam might be a tad exaggerated, but as we have seen Black doesn't really have alternatives.   7...e6?  Was played once by the strong English GM Gawain Jones, but Black's position is hopeless after  8.e5  The pawn isn't hanging, since Black's queen on d8 will fall in the end.  8...Ng8  A very painful move to make, but the best.  9.h4  As you are well aware of by now, the pawn-launch h4-h5 is a powerful plan in these positions. There was nothing wrong with 9. f4 like in Poulsen,M - Thomsen,T Torshavn 2000, but the text move is much stronger.  9...dxe5  The critical move and the human response. Other moves just allow us to carry out our plan, when Black is in major trouble.  10.dxe5  Bxe5  Otherwise we'll defend the pawn with f4.  11.f4  Bg7  12.g4  Taking more space on the kingside. Black now has to worry about f5 when we will open all the lines against Black's king.  12...Ngf6  13.g5  Nh5  14.Nge2  Black can't do anything about our plan of playing Bg2-Bf3-Bxh5.  14...O-O  15.Bg2  c6  16.Bf3+-  Black is completely lost as we will take on h5 followed by Ng3 next.   7...O-O ?  Surprisingly enough, over 50 players have had the guts to play this move. It loses due to concrete reasons:  8.e5  Ne8  9.h4  With our usual devastating attack.  9...dxe5  10.dxe5  Bxe5  11.h5+-  White's attack was decisive in Offenborn,H - Wagner,K GER email 2011, so Black resigned four moves later.   7...e5?  Is another poor move, when we will proceed by playing  8.g4  It's easy to play with the white pieces as all we have to do is launching a pawn storm on the kingside.  8...b5  Black has tried this move in most of the games, when the refutation is  9.dxe5  Nxe5  10.g5  We will push away Black's knights.  10...Nfd7  11.f4  Nc6  12.h4  Black can't stop the massacre on the kingside.  12...h5  13.gxh6  Bxh6  14.h5+-  White is completely winning. I want to show the end of the Correspondence game, but I leave the theory section here.  14...gxh5  15.e5  The diagonal is opened!  15...Bf8  16.Bg2  Bb7  17.Nf3  Rg8  18.Rhe1  Black's king on e8 is in huge trouble.  18...dxe5  19.fxe5  Rxg2  This obviously loses, but Black had no defense.  20.Qxg2  Ncxe5  21.Nd5  Bxd5  22.Rxd5  Black called it a day and resigned in Shchemelev,P- Larsen,N ICCF email 2017. }
8. h4
{ It's time to start launching the pawns on the kingside. Checking IM Chessexplained's course, I realize that we have almost transposed to his f3-coverage. The difference is that Black has a bishop placed on f8 in the course which is to his advantage since Bh6 no longer comes with a tempo. }
8... Bb7 9. Kb1
{ I always approve of this prophylactic move. That being said, White's most popular choice has been  9.g4  which is also very interesting to analyze. }
9... c5
{ An interesting alternative, when we should respond with   9...h5  Is very likely to transpose to the mainline after  10.Nh3  Play should lead to the main line one way or another, for example:  10...O-O  11.Ng5  c5  12.g4  And indeed, the transposition is a fact. }
10. g4 { This is the prize Black pays when not playing h5. } 10... h6
{ Makes sense, as Black can meet h5 with g5, and g5 with hxg5. } 11. Nh3
{ We just develop our stallion as Black has stopped our pawns for now. } 11...
Qc7
{ Was played in Duzhakov,I - Shomoev,A Voronezh 2016, when White's best response would have been   11...b4  Was tried in an e-mail game.  12.Ne2  Qa5  Again we can see how useful it is to have played Kb1.  13.g5  hxg5  14.Nxg5±  White is very active and eventually won a very nice e-mail game that I suggest you look up in the database. Medina,M - Burmeister,F ICCF email 2017. }
12. dxc5 Nxc5 { 12...dxc5  is met by  13.g5  hxg5  14.hxg5  . } 13. g5 hxg5 14.
Nxg5
{ Our activity and safer king grants us a clearly better position. The bishop on e3 will head to d4 and the bishop on f1 will find a nice home on h3. White can also further open the position by playing Nd5. }
*

