[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12. Pirc (1...d6) a6 lines"]
[Black "4...Bg7 (5...a6 4)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6
{ Here we have arrived at the opening sequence that defines the Pirc Defense. The opening tends to lead to exciting and complicated games, which is why the opening is often utilized by higher-rated players who badly needs a win with the black pieces. On top level you won't see this opening occur often, as White has numerous dangerous ways of fighting it, making the opening a risky choice. Just like most openings, White needs to know what he's doing in order to fight for an edge, so we must be prepared! }
4. Be3 { We will play in similar fashion to the Modern Defense. } 4... Bg7
{ Black keeps us guessing with this move as he can play O-O, a6 or c6! It was not easy for me to come up with something that battles all of these set-ups, but I eventually came to the conclusion that the text move is best. }
5. f3
{ We go for the set-up we saw in the Modern Defense, f3-Be3-Qd2-O-O-O etc. I had a tough time deciding which move to go for. White has so many good options against Pirc/Modern so I felt like a kid in a candy store. }
5... a6
{ Black should play a6 before castling. Black's play is similar to the Modern Defense. He plans to place a bishop on b7, a knight on d7 and will eventually follow up with c5 or b4-a5. }
6. Qd2 Nbd7 7. O-O-O
{ Black does have some alternative to the usual  7...b5  , but none of them look good. Let's take a look before we head to the main move: }
7... b5
{ The exclam might be a tad exaggerated, but as we have seen Black doesn't really have alternatives. }
8. h4
{ It's time to start launching the pawns on the kingside. Checking IM Chessexplained's course, I realize that we have almost transposed to his f3-coverage. The difference is that Black has a bishop placed on f8 in the course which is to his advantage since Bh6 no longer comes with a tempo. }
8... h5 { Black slows down our play on the kingside. } 9. Nh3
{ The downside of playing h5 is that Black leaves a nice outpost on g5 for our knight. At this point you might be getting deja vu if you have already looked through our coverage in the Modern Defense, with good reasons as we have almost transposed. }
9... Nb6
{ This move is not the most played move, but it's the most accurate way to play. Black wants to capture the knight on h3. If we decide to move the knight to g5, Black can play b4 followed by Nc4 which is quite annoying. }
10. Bd3
{ I suggest that we simply develop our bishop. The alternative  10.Qe1!?  is also worth investigating. }
10... Bxh3 { Black's best move is to get rid of the annoying knight. } 11. Rxh3
Nfd7
{ A logical move since Black wants to carry out the c5-break. Black also prevents us from playing e5 which is a thematic move in some lines. }
12. f4 { Critical, but not the only move.  12.g4!?  is another decent try. }
12... c5 13. dxc5
{ My engine prefers  13.Be2  which leads to very complicated positions after  13...c4  , which is the reason why I avoided it. }
13... b4
{ Was a huge mistake by the strong Russian GM, but the game was played with short time control. ljiushenok,I -Dubov, D Moscow 2019.   13...Nxc5  14.Be2!  This is a strong move that allows us to play Nd5 when we can take with the queen, or play the thematic Bd4.  14...O-O !  By far the best move in the position.  15.f5!  Creating an attack.   You may consider throwing in  15.Bd4  first, when Black has to play  15...Bh6  . Our best bet is then to play  16.Be3  when the position transposes after  16...Bg7  .  15...b4  Black needs to act fast.  16.Nd5  Nxd5  17.Qxd5  e6  Black has to push our queen away.  18.Qc4  18...Qc7  The position on the board is complicated and probably fine for Black objectively with accurate play. There are several ways we could test Black here, one example is:  19.Rf3  The point of this rook move is to play f6, so Black's best move is to move the bishop out of harm's way.  19...Be5  20.Kb1  Rac8  21.fxg6  fxg6  Black has to be very careful, but it seems like he is holding on after  22.Rxf8+  Kxf8!  Black has to be able to meet g4 with Na4.  23.g4  Na4!  Black has to create some counterplay, otherwise our play on the kingside will be too powerful.  24.Bh6+  Kg8  25.Qxc7  Rxc7  26.gxh5  Nxb2  27.Rg1  The complications have turned into an endgame which Black should hold with accurate play. This might be discouraging, but it's extremely tough for Black to memorize everything as there are many alternatives along the way. 13. Be2 is worth looking into, when as far as I can tell, leads to very complicated positions. }
14. cxb6 { Is the refutation which White missed. } 14... bxc3 15. Qf2 cxb2+ 16.
Kb1 { It's funny, but the pawn on b2 isn't dangerous at all. } 16... Rb8
{ And here, we must strike with } 17. e5
{ The point is that we want to play e6 and destroy Black's pawn structure. }
17... Nxb6 18. e6 Na4
{ 18...O-O  Is met by  19.exf7+  Rxf7  20.Bxg6  Rf6  21.Bd3+-  White has everything under control and the advantage is as high as +4. This might seem crazy, but it's justified by Black's poor king safety. Na4 is met by Bd4 or Bd2, which is something to keep in mind. }
19. Bd4 Qb6 { Is a really funny line, when the move } 20. Bxg6
{ wins the game. We can take on b6 next since the rook on h3 guards the c3-square! }
*

