1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6
{ Here we have arrived at the opening sequence that defines the Pirc Defense. The opening tends to lead to exciting and complicated games, which is why the opening is often utilized by higher-rated players who badly needs a win with the black pieces. On top level you won't see this opening occur often, as White has numerous dangerous ways of fighting it, making the opening a risky choice. Just like most openings, White needs to know what he's doing in order to fight for an edge, so we must be prepared! }
4. Be3 { We will play in similar fashion to the Modern Defense. } 4... Bg7
{ Black keeps us guessing with this move as he can play O-O, a6 or c6! It was not easy for me to come up with something that battles all of these set-ups, but I eventually came to the conclusion that the text move is best. }
5. f3
{ We go for the set-up we saw in the Modern Defense, f3-Be3-Qd2-O-O-O etc. I had a tough time deciding which move to go for. White has so many good options against Pirc/Modern so I felt like a kid in a candy store. }
5... a6
{ Black should play a6 before castling. Black's play is similar to the Modern Defense. He plans to place a bishop on b7, a knight on d7 and will eventually follow up with c5 or b4-a5. }
6. Qd2 Nbd7 7. O-O-O
{ Black does have some alternative to the usual 7... b5, but none of them look good. Let's take a look before we head to the main move: }
7... b5
{ The exclam might be a tad exaggerated, but as we have seen Black doesn't really have alternatives. }
8. h4
{ It's time to start launching the pawns on the kingside. Checking IM Chessexplained's course, I realize that we have almost transposed to his f3-coverage. The difference is that Black has a bishop placed on f8 in the course which is to his advantage since Bh6 no longer comes with a tempo. }
8... h5 { Black slows down our play on the kingside. } 9. Nh3
{ The downside of playing h5 is that Black leaves a nice outpost on g5 for our knight. At this point you might be getting deja vu if you have already looked through our coverage in the Modern Defense, with good reasons as we have almost transposed. }
9... Nb6
{ This move is not the most played move, but it's the most accurate way to play. Black wants to capture the knight on h3. If we decide to move the knight to g5, Black can play b4 followed by Nc4 which is quite annoying. }
10. Bd3
{ I suggest that we simply develop our bishop. The alternative  10.Qe1!?  is also worth investigating. }
10... c6
{ Black has also tried this move, when we should move the knight out of the way as Black no longer has b4 followed by Nc4. }
11. Ng5 Qc7 12. Kb1
{ Once again this is strong. What I like about the move here is that it's useful while we wait for Black to decide in which direction he wants to take the game. Shall he castle kingside? Play b4 followed by c5? }
12... O-O { Black has to castle in order to make progress on the queenside. }
13. Qf2 { A typical move which fights against Black's desired c5-break. } 13...
Nc4
{ Black's best try is to jump towards our king as he will get decent counterplay in the b-file in case we decide to capture the knight. }
14. Bc1 { We shouldn't give Black his desired counterplay. } 14... a5
{ The race has begun. Black needs to run as fast as possible towards our king in order to create counterplay. }
15. g4
{ Our pawn break has finally been carried out, which can be supported by our knight with the maneuver Ne2-Ng3/Nf4. }
15... a4
{ Black goes for the throat.  15...hxg4  is met by  16.h5  as always. } 16. a3
{ We shouldn't allow Black to play a3 which could be really unpleasant since the knight will jump to b2 after b3. }
16... Qb6 { Black will play b4 next, but we are one step ahead. } 17. Bxc4 bxc4
18. Qd2
{ Allowing Black to play e5 wouldn't be ideal, so we are moving the queen out of the way. It also supports our king. }
18... Rb8 19. Ka1 { Moving out of harm's way, with a powerful attack. } *

