1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6
{ Here we have arrived at the opening sequence that defines the Pirc Defense. The opening tends to lead to exciting and complicated games, which is why the opening is often utilized by higher-rated players who badly needs a win with the black pieces. On top level you won't see this opening occur often, as White has numerous dangerous ways of fighting it, making the opening a risky choice. Just like most openings, White needs to know what he's doing in order to fight for an edge, so we must be prepared! }
4. Be3 { We will play in similar fashion to the Modern Defense. } 4... Bg7
{ Black keeps us guessing with this move as he can play O-O, a6 or c6! It was not easy for me to come up with something that battles all of these set-ups, but I eventually came to the conclusion that the text move is best. }
5. f3
{ We go for the set-up we saw in the Modern Defense, f3-Be3-Qd2-O-O-O etc. I had a tough time deciding which move to go for. White has so many good options against Pirc/Modern so I felt like a kid in a candy store. }
5... a6
{ Black should play a6 before castling. Black's play is similar to the Modern Defense. He plans to place a bishop on b7, a knight on d7 and will eventually follow up with c5 or b4-a5. }
6. Qd2 Nbd7 7. O-O-O
{ Black does have some alternative to the usual 7... b5, but none of them look good. Let's take a look before we head to the main move: }
7... b5
{ The exclam might be a tad exaggerated, but as we have seen Black doesn't really have alternatives. }
8. h4
{ It's time to start launching the pawns on the kingside. Checking IM Chessexplained's course, I realize that we have almost transposed to his f3-coverage. The difference is that Black has a bishop placed on f8 in the course which is to his advantage since Bh6 no longer comes with a tempo. }
8... h5 { Black slows down our play on the kingside. } 9. Nh3
{ The downside of playing h5 is that Black leaves a nice outpost on g5 for our knight. At this point you might be getting deja vu if you have already looked through our coverage in the Modern Defense, with good reasons as we have almost transposed. }
9... Bb7 10. Ng5 { The knight finally reaches the beautiful square on g5. }
10... O-O
{ Is almost as popular as the text move  10...e6  , but it looks extremely risky. }
11. g4 { We are not wasting any time! } 11... c5
{ The most played move and a very logical try.   11...e5  Has been tried, when I suggest going for  12.dxe5   12.d5  is the engine move and a good one of course, but I think the text move is easier practically. However, White did win a beautiful game in Nekhaev, A - Conterno, D ICCF email 2017. In case you check out the game, I want you to pay attention when White plays the brilliant  Be6  move. Fantastic stuff. Now, back to the main line:  12...Nxe5  13.gxh5  Nxh5  14.f4  Simple play from White. We just want to open everything with f5 at some point and break through. The knight on h5 can also be removed with the help of Be2.  14...Ng4  15.Be2  Ngf6  16.Bxh5  Is the simplest.   Playing  16.f5  works out well too, but it leads to a mess that I would like to avoid if I can.  16...Nxh5  17.f5→  Black is under a very powerful attack. I doubt that he will make it through the storm. Note that a3 is often a nice move to make, preventing Black from playing b4.   11...hxg4  We must always consider this move, but I am sure you know our response...  12.h5!  Indeed, we open the h-file right away.  12...Nxh5  13.fxg4  Nhf6  14.Qh2  The h-file has been successfully taken over by our forces.  14...e5  15.Bg2  Re8  16.Rdf1  Moving the rook gave the black king shelter on the f8-square, but it no longer defends f7. Therefore, we should place pressure down the f-file.  16...exd4  17.Bxd4  Ne5  18.Nd5!  The most accurate move, which forces  18...Bxd5  As Nxf6+ was a nasty threat.  19.exd5  Nexg4  20.Qh4  Ne5  It seems like Black has survived the worst, but  21.Rxf6  Qxf6  22.Rf1  Black now has to give the queen.  22...Qxf1+  23.Bxf1+-  With extra material, White had a decisive advantage in Bennett,P - Cumming,D ICCF email 2015. }
12. Kb1
{ You already know that I am a huge fan of this move. The reason why it works so well here is that we are well prepared to face Qa5, which is rather important. }
12... hxg4 { Is now best met by } 13. dxc5 Nxc5
{ 13...gxf3  Leads to a remarkable line after  14.h5!  The standard procedure.  14...Nxh5  15.Rxh5!  We are sacrificing our way through!  15...gxh5  16.Qh2  f5  The engine suggest to defend with this ugly move, but it's obvious that it can't possibly work out for Black.  17.Qxh5  Nf6  18.Qxf3  Black has too many weaknesses around his king.  18...Qe8  19.Bh3  Qh5  20.Qg3  Ng4  21.Ne6+-  Black won't survive the onslaught. }
14. h5 { Of course! } 14... gxh5 15. Qh2
{ It's important not to play  15.fxg4  , since Black has  15...b4  when Black is suddenly in the game. }
15... Qc7 16. Nd5 Bxd5 17. exd5
{ Black's initiative on the queenside pales in comparison to our attack on the kingside. }
*

