{ Is almost as popular as the text move, but it looks extremely risky. } 11. g4
{ We are not wasting any time! } 11... c5
{ The most played move and a very logical try.   11...e5  Has been tried, when I suggest going for  12.dxe5  12. d5 is the engine-move and a good one of course, but I think the text move is easier practically. However, White did win a beautiful game in Nekhaev,A - Conterno,D ICCF email 2017. In case you check out the game, I want you to pay attention when White plays the brilliant Be6 move. Fantastic stuff. Now, back to the main line:  12...Nxe5  13.gxh5  Nxh5  14.f4  Simple play from White. We just want to open everything with f5 at some point and break through. The knight on h5 can also be removed with the help of Be2.  14...Ng4  15.Be2  Ngf6  16.Bxh5  Is the simplest. Playing 16. f5 works out well too, but it leads to a mess that I would like to avoid if I can.  16...Nxh5  17.f5→  Black is under a very powerful attack. I doubt that he will make it through the storm. Note that a3 is often a nice move to make, preventing Black from playing b4.   11...hxg4  We must always consider this move, but I am sure you know our response...  12.h5!  Indeed, we open the h-file right away.  12...Nxh5  12... gxh5 13. fxg4 is even worse for Black.  13.fxg4  Nhf6  14.Qh2  The h-file has been successfully taken over by our forces.  14...e5  15.Bg2  15. d5 might be even stronger...  15...Re8  16.Rdf1  Moving the rook gave the black king shelter on the f8-square, but it no longer defends f7. Therefore, we should place pressure down the f-file.  16...exd4  17.Bxd4  Ne5  18.Nd5!  The most accurate move, which forces  18...Bxd5  As Nxf6+ was a nasty threat.  19.exd5  Nexg4  20.Qh4  Ne5  It seems like Black has survived the worst, but  21.Rxf6  21... Bxf6 is met by 22. Kb1! with Qh7+, Ne6 & Rf1 to come. In that order!  21...Qxf6  22.Rf1  Black now has to give the queen.  22...Qxf1+  23.Bxf1+-  With extra material, White had a decisive advantage in Bennett,P - Cumming,D ICCF email 2015. }
12. Kb1
{ You already know that I am a huge fan of this move. The reason why it works so well here is that we are well prepared to face Qa5, which is rather important. }
12... cxd4 13. Bxd4 hxg4 { Black can also take this way. } 14. fxg4
{ The most precise way to take. } 14... e5 15. Bg1
{ A strong move, as the bishop is more vulnerable on the other squares. } 15...
Nc5
{ 15...Nxg4  Is easily refuted by  16.Be2  Ndf6  17.h5+-  With a decisive attack. }
16. Bxc5 { The easiest is to get rid of the knight on c5. } 16... dxc5 17. Qc1
Qe7 18. h5 { Black's king is in severe danger. The best defense is: } 18...
Rfd8 19. hxg6 fxg6 20. a4 { Freeing the c4-square for our bishop. } 20... c4
21. Be2 Bc6
{ Black has control of the queenside, so it's time to switch gears with } 22.
Rdf1 { The plan is to maneuver our queen from c1 to h3. } 22... Rd4 23. Qe3
Rad8 24. Qh3 { The threat is now Nh7. } 24... R8d6 25. Rf3
{ Finally breaching Black's defense, as Qh2-Rh3 is a deadly maneuver. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12. Pirc (1...d6) a6 lines"]
[Black "4...Bg7 (5...a6 8)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6
{ Here we have arrived at the opening sequence that defines the Pirc Defense. The opening tends to lead to exciting and complicated games, which is why the opening is often utilized by higher-rated players who badly needs a win with the black pieces. On top level you won't see this opening occur often, as White has numerous dangerous ways of fighting it, making the opening a risky choice. Just like most openings, White needs to know what he's doing in order to fight for an edge, so we must be prepared! }
4. Be3 { We will play in similar fashion to the Modern Defense. } 4... Bg7
{ Black keeps us guessing with this move as he can play O-O, a6 or c6! It was not easy for me to come up with something that battles all of these set-ups, but I eventually came to the conclusion that the text move is best. }
5. f3
{ We go for the set-up we saw in the Modern Defense, f3-Be3-Qd2-O-O-O etc. I had a tough time deciding which move to go for. White has so many good options against Pirc/Modern so I felt like a kid in a candy store. }
5... a6
{ Black should play a6 before castling. Black's play is similar to the Modern Defense. He plans to place a bishop on b7, a knight on d7 and will eventually follow up with c5 or b4-a5. }
6. Qd2 Nbd7 7. O-O-O
{ Black does have some alternative to the usual  7...b5  , but none of them look good. Let's take a look before we head to the main move: }
7... b5
{ The exclam might be a tad exaggerated, but as we have seen Black doesn't really have alternatives. }
8. h4
{ It's time to start launching the pawns on the kingside. Checking IM Chessexplained's course, I realize that we have almost transposed to his f3-coverage. The difference is that Black has a bishop placed on f8 in the course which is to his advantage since Bh6 no longer comes with a tempo. }
8... h5 { Black slows down our play on the kingside. } 9. Nh3
{ The downside of playing h5 is that Black leaves a nice outpost on g5 for our knight. At this point you might be getting deja vu if you have already looked through our coverage in the Modern Defense, with good reasons as we have almost transposed. }
9... Bb7 10. Ng5 { The knight finally reaches the beautiful square on g5. }
10... e6
{ I remember laughing when I realized that I had somehow transposed to Modern-theory when I first analyzed this. You may say that it makes sense to put it in the modern-chapter, but I decided to analyze it here as I hadn't analyzed the Modern yet when I did my analysis. Black's play is natural as he wants to put the queen on e7, knight on b6, f6-knight on d7. The king could head to either direction, but it does look safer to castle queenside. }
11. Kb1 { Our usual prophylactic move. } 11... Qe7 12. Qf2
{ We have seen this maneuver before. The queen is well placed in this diagonal. Additionally, it makes way for the rook on d1. }
12... Rc8
{ Is an interesting move, when I suggest playing   12...Nh7  Was tried in a recent game. Black's so sick of the knight on g5 that he thinks it's worth to rid himself of it.  13.Nxh7  Rxh7  14.Ne2  Nb6  We have been following Seul,G - Escobar Medina,A Barcelona 2019, when I suggest the improvement  15.Nc1!  The knight is headed for the b3-square, where it will be very useful.  15...O-O-O  16.Nb3±  There is no doubt that White is much better. White's position is very spacious, while it also seems rather difficult for Black to come up with something clever to do. The knight on b3 can also head to a5 where it will be a major annoyance for Black, when ideas like d5 are suddenly in the air. }
13. Bc1
{ The point of this sneaky move is to give a clear path to the rook on d1 which will head to e1 next. }
13... Nb6
{ 13...c5  Is natural, and met by  14.d5  e5  15.Ne2+-  Black has nothing on the queenside and will soon be in major trouble on the kingside as we will play g4 and Ng3 with great velocity. }
14. Re1 { As previously discussed, we will move the rook to e1. } 14... c5 15.
d5 Nh7 { Black has to get rid of the knight. } 16. Nd1 Nxg5 17. hxg5 Kd7
{ The king is safer on the queenside. } 18. dxe6+ fxe6 19. Bd3
{ We are clearly better and ready to launch our pawns on the kingside. Black's pieces are quite cramped. }
*

