[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12. Pirc (1...d6) a6 lines"]
[Black "Pirc Conclusion"]
[Result "*"]

{ Conclusion: In the first branch of the Pirc tree, we focused on a6-systems. Black aims for modern-type of play with a6, often accompanied with b5, Nbd7, Bb7 and c5. Black can play a6 during several stages of the game. }
1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Be3 Bg7
{ is better in my opinion, since we are not aware of how Black will proceed.   4...a6  is suggested by IM Chessexplained, since he dislikes playing with Black against the quick Bh6-setups in the 4... Bg7 line. This is a valid point, but not without its downsides. Playing a6 immediately, Black has already shown us his hand, making it possible for us to plan accordingly.  5.h3  My suggestion, which controls the square on g4. In these positions, Black needs to tread with care, since e5 is a nasty blow in several lines. Now that the pawn has moved to h3, the Bh6-lines are less dangerous so IM Chessexplained suggests going for  5...Bg7  . Now I like  6.g4!?  which is an unusual, but a rather tricky line where we want the harmonious set-up with Nge2-Bg2. I think Black is under intense pressure which the analysis showed. }
5. f3 { is a testing option against Black's scheme. } 5... a6
{ is what Black should do if he's interested in going for this type of set-up.   5...O-O  Isn't the best as in most positions where Black castles, our attack remains superior with accurate play. }
6. Qd2
{ when  6...b5  or  6...Nbd7  should lead to the main line. There are possibilities along the way, but our analysis proved that it is indeed unwise for Black to avoid standard play.  7.O-O-O  b5  8.h4  h5  9.Nh3  is the main tabiya of the opening, when Black can choose between  9...Nb6  or  9...Bb7  .  10.Bd3  follows   after  9...Nb6  , when the play remains quite unexplored as there are alternatives for both sides in the positions that arise after  10...Bxh3  . The positions are really interesting and quite complicated when I believe White has the easier position to handle from a practical point of view. But indeed, at the end of the line we looked at the end result was heading towards a draw with great speed...  9...Bb7  is the main move here, when we head to the beautiful outpost on  g5  with  10.Ng5  . Black should proceed with  10...e6  , when I think the positions that arise after  11.Kb1  Qe7  12.Qf2!  are much easier to play for White due to our wonderful space advantage. Black's problem is that he is cramped with limited things to do. A difficult situation to be in as a human player, since it's very easy to get impatient - when the mistakes will surely come. Black should be playing in a Modern move-order instead if he wants to pick up this system, as it is more flexible since the knight still stands on the g8-square. }
