[Black "4...c6 (5...Qb6 1)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Be3 c6
{ Black can delay Bg7 and play c6 already here,   similarly to the  4...a6  line. GM Mihail Marin, a well-known Pirc expert advocated for this set-up in 'The Pirc Defense, ' which is a book that he published in 2017. He also dislikes the positions that occur in the Bh6-lines after  4...Bg7  , just like IM Chessexplained. }
5. h3
{ We are taking control over the g4-square. From here, we plan to carry out the move f4 which will give us a better version of the Austrian Attack. Additionally, the possibility of playing g4 is there, although this occurs less frequently. }
5... Qb6
{ Attacking the b2-pawn is very uncommon, but it ranks high on the engine's list. }
6. Qc1
{ The most popular way to defend the b2-pawn, and also the most accurate. }
6... Bg7 7. f4 O-O 8. Nf3 Qc7
{ The queen has fulfilled its role on b6, so it heads to c7.   8...Nh5!?  Attempts to make use of the fact that the g3-square is not under surveillance, thus our plans of castling will be disturbed.  9.Kf2  This is one way to dodge Black's plan. Our king is not unsafe on f2.  9...Qc7  10.e5  Taking control of the f6-square, so now the h5-knight is in danger of getting trapped.  10...Bh8  Giving the g7-square for the knight.  11.g4  Ng7  12.Bd3  Our center is incredibly powerful. One game continued:  12...Nd7  13.h4  13...dxe5  14.dxe5  Ne6  15.Ne4+-  Black will be under a massive pawn storm and is essentially busted. Chytilek,R -Nyvlt,Z Czechia 2003. }
9. Bd3 { We simply develop our pieces. } 9... b5 10. a3
{ The usual, but there was nothing wrong with striking immediately with  10.e5  . }
10... a6 { Black supports the b5-pawn so he can play c5. } 11. O-O
{ There was nothing wrong with  11.e5  . } 11... Nbd7
{ 11...c5  can be met by  12.dxc5  ,  followed by e5. } 12. e5 Nd5 13. Nxd5
cxd5 14. Qe1
{ A small improvement over  14.Qd2  which occurred in Serazeev, A - Mercadal Benejam, J ICCF email 2013.  The queen is headed to h4 where it will greatly aid us in an attack against the black king. Black has no counterplay as we can always meet a knight jump to b6 with b3, preventing it to jump to c4. Plans of action include f5 or h4-h5. Black's essentially busted. }
*

