[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Be3 c6 5. h3
{ We are taking control over the g4-square. From here, we plan to carry out the move f4 which will give us a better version of the Austrian Attack. Additionally, the possibility of playing g4 is there, although this occurs less frequently. }
5... b5
{ Can be played already here, and has been by a decent squad of 2400+ players. }
6. a3 { The best way to meet b5 is to stop the plan of playing b4! } 6... a5
{ Black has to develop some pieces before he should take action on the queenside.  6...Nbd7  will transpose to the mainline after  7.f4  ,   And  6...Bg7  7.f4  is also something we covered earlier in the chapter. }
7. e5 { This forces Black into a really unpleasant endgame. } 7... Nfd7
{ Bad things will happen if Black refuses to take the endgame, but it requires us to be precise.   7...dxe5  8.dxe5  Qxd1+  9.Rxd1  Nfd7  10.f4±  White is in the driving seat due to his strong center and lead in development. Black's pawns on the queenside are also quite vulnerable. }
8. exd6
{ This wins due to a nice follow-up.  8.f4  was 'only' clearly better after  8...Nb6  in Schoene, M - Bade, J Germany 2018. }
8... exd6 9. d5
{ Black's pawns on the queenside are about to get destroyed. A nice thematic trick to remember. }
