[Black "4...c6 (5...Bg7 2)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Be3 c6 5. h3
{ We are taking control over the g4-square. From here, we plan to carry out the move f4 which will give us a better version of the Austrian Attack. Additionally, the possibility of playing g4 is there, although this occurs less frequently. }
5... Bg7 6. f4
{ Black has now gotten himself into a worse edition of the Austrian Attack, as a set-up with c6 is undesirable. Black usually wants to castle and play c5, gaining quick counterplay against the expansion of our pawns. Now Black has limited play against our pawns, so we will be able to enjoy a comfortable space advantage. }
6... b5
{ A very natural launch by Black where the goal is to push the pawn to b4, removing the c3-guardian of the e4-pawn. }
7. a3 { a3 is very often a good way to meet b5. } 7... O-O
{ This natural move is also Black's best.   7...a6  Is a typical move and played by the great GM Timman, but it's too slow.  8.Nf3  Nbd7  9.e5!  A strong move, striking in the center and forcing Black to get an inferior pawn structure.  9...Nd5  10.Nxd5  cxd5  This was Jackova, J - Timman,J Prague 2007, when White should have played the simple  11.Bd3  developing our bishop  11...Nb6  12.b3+-  There is no need to allow Black to jump to c4. Black's opening has gone horribly wrong and he is left with a cramped position with zero counterplay against our center.   7...Nfd7  Black aims to jump quickly to b6, but it's also way too slow.  8.Nf3  Nb6  9.Bd3  Natural developing moves all the way.  9...a5  10.O-O  +-  White had already obtained a massive edge in Erenburg,S - Blit,J chess.com INT 2018, and it did not take long until Black pressed the resign button. }
8. Nf3
{ Black has now tried different moves, let's take a look at some of them: }
8... a5
{ The engine disapproves, but this thematic move was played by two strong GMs, so we should take a look. }
9. Bd3 Ba6 { Black blocks the a-file and is now ready to play b4. } 10. e5
{ We have the first say and strike before Black is able to do so. } 10... Nd5
{ And now we should just take   10...Nfd7  11.h4!   Is the simplest way to proceed, with the goal of opening the h-file.  11.e6  is thematic and good too, but looks more complex.  11...b4  12.Na4+-  With h5 next, Black will soon be under a very powerful attack. }
11. Nxd5 cxd5 12. h4 { And carry on with our naughty kingside plans. } 12... b4
13. h5 { The opening of the h-file will cause harm to Black's monarch. } *

