7. a3 { a3 is very often a good way to meet b5. } 7... O-O
{ This natural move is also Black's best.   7...a6  Is a typical move and played by the great GM Timman, but it's too slow.  8.Nf3  Nbd7  9.e5!  A strong move, striking in the center and forcing Black to get an inferior pawn structure.  9...Nd5  10.Nxd5  cxd5  This was Jackova, J - Timman,J Prague 2007, when White should have played the simple  11.Bd3  developing our bishop  11...Nb6  12.b3+-  There is no need to allow Black to jump to c4. Black's opening has gone horribly wrong and he is left with a cramped position with zero counterplay against our center.   7...Nfd7  Black aims to jump quickly to b6, but it's also way too slow.  8.Nf3  Nb6  9.Bd3  Natural developing moves all the way.  9...a5  10.O-O  +-  White had already obtained a massive edge in Erenburg,S - Blit,J chess.com INT 2018, and it did not take long until Black pressed the resign button. }
8. Nf3
{ Black has now tried different moves, let's take a look at some of them: }
8... Bb7
{ The most played in the move in the position is to place the bishop in the diagonal where it will target e4 after c5.   8...Nbd7  9.e5  It's time to strike before Black is able to play e5 himself!  9...Ne8  10.Bd3   There no need to be fancy like White was when he played  10.d5  in the game Liew, C - Torre, E Dubai 1986.  10...Nb6  11.O-O  Nc7  It looks like Black is not doing too shabby, but  12.Qe1→  causes problems. The queen is on its way to h4 where it will put Black under an unpleasant attack. }
9. Bd3 a5
{ And indeed, the way we should meet Black's queenside scheme is to play   9...Nbd7  Is met by the typical  10.e5  Ne8  11.h4→  The plan of attacking by opening the h-file is an effective strategy in these positions, which is why it keeps showing up. }
10. e5 Ne8 11. h4
{ I'm sure you expected this move, with the thematic plan of attack! I had some fun analyzing  11.Ng5!?  with the idea of playing e6, but it turns out that Black saves the position!  11...c5  is the way to do so when the complications continue:  12.Nxh7  Kxh7  13.f5  dxe5  14.O-O  gxf5!  15.Qh5+  Kg8  16.dxe5  e6!  17.Rxf5  c4!  18.Rxf7  cxd3!  19.Raf1  Rxf7  20.Qxf7+  with a perpetual. }
11... c5 { Black's best bet is to complicate the game by sacrificing a pawn. }
12. Bxb5 cxd4 13. Qxd4 Nc7
{ Black wants to take on b5, and we should in fact just let him! } 14. O-O-O
Nxb5 15. Nxb5 Qd7
{ 15...Nc6  was met by  16.Qa4!  when Black is in big trouble. } 16. Nc3
{ Black has very limited counterplay. If he decides to go for the e5-pawn, he quickly has to deal with the opening of the h-file as we plan to play h5 if possible. The alternative is to be a clean pawn down. }
