1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Be3 c6 5. h3
{ We are taking control over the g4-square. From here, we plan to carry out the move f4 which will give us a better version of the Austrian Attack. Additionally, the possibility of playing g4 is there, although this occurs less frequently. }
5... Nbd7 { Suggested by GM Marin and also the most played move. } 6. f4
{ The same plan like in the other lines. In order to punish Black's passive play, we must take full control of the center. }
6... e5
{ It's better for Black to play this move right away, as there is no way to 'dismantle' the pawn structure since b5 isn't played yet. }
7. Nf3 { The most principled approach, increasing pressure on Black's center. }
7... Qe7
{ This is the suggest way to proceed by GM Marin - defending the pawn on e5. }
8. Qd2
{ This move is not mentioned by GM Marin. The plan is simple as we are preparing to castle queenside. }
8... exf4
{ 8...Bg7  9.O-O-O  O-O  Black's position looks fine, but  10.fxe5  dxe5  11.d5  Is quite unpleasant for Black because our d-pawn is very strong.  11...cxd5  12.exd5  a6  Black has to create counterplay by playing b5.  13.g4  b5  14.g5  Removing the knight from the f6-square.  14...Nh5  Black wants to prevent us from playing h4-h5 which is a likely scenario after 14... Ne8.  15.Bg2  Rb8  16.Rhe1±  White had a lot of pressure in Herman,T - Scott,P ICCF email 2018, and eventually won a nice game. }
9. Bxf4 Nxe4 { Grabbing the pawn is risky, but of course critical. } 10. Nxe4
d5
{ Is the best move when play continues   10...Qxe4+??  This loses to  11.Kf2+-  When the queen will be trapped as Re1 is coming.   11...Kd8  helps nothing due to  12.Re1  Qd5  13.c4  Qf5  14.g4  when the queen has no squares as the f6-square is poisoned due to  Bg5  . }
11. O-O-O dxe4 12. Ng5
{ We will win the pawn as we can play  Nxe4  next due to the resulting pin on the queen if Black takes the knight.  12...Nf6  is not recommended, due to  13.Bc4  . }
