1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Be3 Bg7
{ As already discussed, I believe that Black should accept the challenge and go for this move. }
5. f3 O-O
{ Just like in the a6-Pirc, Black can choose a set-up that involves O-O with c6. However, I must stress that it's not recommended to play in this fashion, due to our enormous potential on the kingside as we soon shall see. }
6. Qd2 c6 7. O-O-O { The race begins! } 7... b5
{ Black's most logical move and the most popular choice by a long shot since Black must try to create something too. }
8. h4
{ It's was not so easy to decide which move to go for as White has scored well with several moves, but the choice fell in the end on this natural attacking move.  8.g4  is more popular, but less convincing after  8...b4  followed by  c5  , although it's still reasonable for White.  8.Bh6  was the other main alternative which has given White some decent wins in Correspondence chess. Some sample games are: Potrata, J - Milde, L ICCF email 2018, Burmeister, F - Salzmann, S ICCF email 2017 & Tornow, M - Mehlhorn, U GER email 2017. }
8... b4
{ Can be played already here, when Black aims to go directly for our throat. }
9. Nce2 Qa5 10. Kb1 h5
{ Is the strongest move and a highly natural way to proceed as Black stops our h5-thrust.   10...c5?  Our attack is faster than Black's, which is why I put a question mark behind the move.  11.h5  c4  And now the most precise way forward is  12.hxg6  fxg6   12...hxg6  was met by  13.Bh6  , when Black is toast.  13.Nf4  c3  14.Qe1  Black's attack is completely harmless, as we can play b3 and close everything. There is no need to worry about a queen invasion on b2, as our bishop on e3 can head to c1 if necessary.  14...Ba6  15.b3+-  Black's attack is all gone, so his position is dreadful as our attack is very powerful. Our knight will also find a nice home on e6.   10...Be6  Was tried in an email game, when the easiest response is to play  11.Nc1!  Our knight is very well placed on the c1-square.  11...Nbd7  12.Bh6  Now that Black's attack has been taken care of, it's time that we launch our forces towards the black king.  12...Nb6  13.h5  Bxh6  14.Qxh6+-  White was breaking through in Nettles,E - Phillips, P ICCF email 2017. }
11. g4 { Going for the kill right away. } 11... c5
{ Is Black's best fighting attempt.   11...hxg4?  Loses immediately due to  12.h5  The opening of the h-file is too much to bear for the black king.  12...Nxh5   12...gxf3  can be met by  13.Ng3  , defending the pawn on  e4  .  13.Bh6  Bf6  We have so far followed the struggle between Lumachi,G - Moroni,L Bassano del Grappa 2021 where the Italian GM somehow survived the massacre on the kingside and ended up winning the game. However, after the improvement  14.fxg4  Bxg4  15.Bh3+-  I doubt even he would be able to pull off a save, as White is breaking through on the kingside.   11...Be6  12.Nc1  hxg4  Having Be6 & Nc1 included doesn't mean that the pawn grab works.  13.h5!  This is once again the response, opening the h-file.  13...Nxh5  14.Qg2!  Forcing matters on the kingside.  14...Nf6  15.fxg4  Nxg4  16.Bf4+-  The open h-file will be an important asset to White's attack. }
12. Bg5
{ Is a move I like as the plan is simple, but effective. We will take the one piece that guards the h5-pawn. }
12... cxd4
{ Is the engine move, but it doesn't save Black after   12...c4   12...hxg4  is met by  13.h5  of course. After the text move, we are allowed to carry out our plan.  13.Bxf6!  And the important defender has been vanquished!  13...Bxf6  14.gxh5  c3  Black's pawns look impressive, but they are completely harmless.  15.Qe3  Qxh5  16.Ng3  Qa5  17.Bc4+-  With a decisive attack. }
13. Nxd4 hxg4 14. Bc4 { This move is even stronger than  14.h5  . } 14... Ba6
15. Bb3
{ A simple improvement over the correspondence game Castello Benavent, J - Ramos Verdu, J ICCF email 2012, where  15.Bxa6  was played. That being said,  15.Bxa6  was also good enough for a decisive advantage. After  15.Bb3  ,  h5  comes next with a devastating attack. }
