1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Be3 Bg7
{ As already discussed, I believe that Black should accept the challenge and go for this move. }
5. f3 O-O
{ Just like in the a6-Pirc, Black can choose a set-up that involves O-O with c6. However, I must stress that it's not recommended to play in this fashion, due to our enormous potential on the kingside as we soon shall see.   5...Nbd7  Black has tried this move in over 800 games, so I would like to quickly mention it since we could get move-order tricked.  6.g4  Is how we will respond, similarly to the Main Line.  6...c6  7.h4  As usual, this is our follow-up.  7...h5  8.g5  Nh7  Now, we have a very pleasant choice.  9.Nge2  Will transpose to the game Rodriguez,L - Larsen,A email 2017, after  9...b5  10.a3  That being said, 9. a4 is a very good alternative since we stop Black's b5-thrust, making it difficult for him to create counterplay. The choice is yours! }
6. Qd2 c6
{ This is significantly more popular than  6...a6  , and the second most played move in the position after  6...e5  which is the main road Black can take. This will be discussed in the upcoming chapter. }
7. O-O-O { The race begins! } 7... b5
{ Black's most logical move and the most popular choice by a long shot since Black must try to create something too.   7...h5  Is a prophylactic move that is likely to transpose to the main line.  8.h4!?  I think this is the easiest way to play.  8...Nbd7  Better than 8... b5, which is the most played move and reaches the main line.  9. Bh6± With our usual attack on the kingside.  9.e5!?  is also an alternative which aims to utilize the fact that Black can't take the pawn due to the hanging queen on  d8  . This takes the game in a different direction, which is also good for us after  9...dxe5  10.dxe5  Nd5  11.Nxd5  cxd5  12.f4  Nb6  13.b3  . }
8. h4
{ It's was not so easy to decide which move to go for as White has scored well with several moves, but the choice fell in the end on this natural attacking move.  8.g4  is more popular, but less convincing after  8...b4  followed by  c5  , although it's still reasonable for White.   8.Bh6  was the other main alternative which has given White some decent wins in Correspondence chess. Some sample games are: Potrata, J - Milde, L ICCF email 2018, Burmeister, F - Salzmann, S ICCF email 2017 & Tornow, M - Mehlhorn, U GER email 2017. }
8... h5 { Playing h5 directly is the main move. } 9. Nce2
{ A very strong move. We are aiming to play g4-Ng3, when the knight will be a very useful force in our attack. It also doesn't give Black b4 with a tempo which can sometimes be annoying. }
9... Nbd7
{ 9...b4  10.Kb1  Qa5  is a funny transposition to the other line we took a look at. }
10. g4 { There's no time to waste! } 10... hxg4
{ 10...b4!?  Was an interesting try by the Italian GM Luca Moroni.  11.Ng3  It's best to simply ignore what Black is doing on the queenside.  11...Qa5   And now, I find it very strange that White decided to give the a2-pawn by playing  12.gxh5  in Bellahcene, B - Moroni, L Bassano del Grappa 2021. Instead, the natural  12.Kb1+-  Is the natural way to proceed, when White's attack is decisive. The path forward is to take twice on h5, followed by Nh3-Ng5. }
11. Ng3
{ As discussed, the knight is very well placed on g3 where it covers the important squares on e4 and h5. }
11... gxf3 12. h5 { It's time to blast open the kingside. } 12... Ng4
{ The best try for Black, covering the h6-square. } 13. Nxf3 Nb6 14. Bf4
{ The bishop on f4 supports a potential e5, while it also allows the queen to join the attack with a move like Qg2. }
14... c5 15. Bxb5 { Strong enough, but  15.Qg2  is even more accurate! } 15...
cxd4 16. Rdg1
{ Placing the rook in the g-file where a move like Nf5 is suddenly very problematic for Black. }
16... Qc7 17. Nf5 { A very strong move which opens the g-file. } 17... gxf5 18.
Bh6
{ Without this move, Nf5 wouldn't have worked. We must eliminate Black's defenders in order to make progress. }
18... Bf6 19. exf5 Bxf5 20. Bd3
{ We must prevent Black from taking on c2 followed by a rook to c8. Now Black can't do much about a knight jump to h2 which will regain the piece. }
20... Kh8 { Was tried, but obviously hopeless. The game continued: } 21. Bxf5
Nc4 22. Qf4 Rg8 23. Bg5
{ Black has to give material, so he decided that it was time to resign in Jordan Rodriguez, M-Schelberg,M ICCF email 2019. }
