[Black "4...Bg7 (5..O-O 3)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Be3 Bg7
{ As already discussed, I believe that Black should accept the challenge and go for this move. }
5. f3 O-O
{ Just like in the a6-Pirc, Black can choose a set-up that involves O-O with c6. However, I must stress that it's not recommended to play in this fashion, due to our enormous potential on the kingside as we soon shall see.   5...Nbd7  Black has tried this move in over 800 games, so I would like to quickly mention it since we could get move-order tricked.  6.g4  Is how we will respond, similarly to the Main Line.  6...c6  7.h4  As usual, this is our follow-up.  7...h5  8.g5  Nh7  Now, we have a very pleasant choice.  9.Nge2  Will transpose to the game Rodriguez,L - Larsen,A email 2017, after  9...b5  10.a3  That being said, 9. a4 is a very good alternative since we stop Black's b5-thrust, making it difficult for him to create counterplay. The choice is yours! }
6. Qd2 c6 7. O-O-O { The race begins! } 7... Qa5 8. Kb1
{ Defending the pawn on a2. } 8... b5
{ Some games have carried on like this, when I suggest to go for the concrete   8...Be6  Looks a bit unpleasant as Black is aiming for the a2-pawn with b5-b4 to come, but it's nothing to worry about.  9.Nge2  b5  10.Nc1+-  Black's attack was stalled in Belov,V-Matthiesen,M Aarhus 1997. Black can't do much about the upcoming pawn storm White is about to launch on the kingside, which is why my engine gives over +2.   8...e5  Black can try this move as well, but it's not very challenging.  9.Nge2  b5  And now, the most accurate way to proceed is to play  10.dxe5  dxe5  11.Nc1+-  Black's attack is under control. The knight could jump to b3, when we can even follow up by playing a4, damaging Black's pawn structure. We're also set to launch our kingside pawns towards the black king. }
9. Nd5 Qd8
{ This move loses, but almost played every single time as no player with the black pieces wants to head into an endgame with a pawn down after  9...Qxd2  10.Nxe7+  . }
10. Nxf6+ Bxf6 11. h4
{ White has won 7/7 games from this position which is not surprising as the attack plays itself. }
11... Nd7 12. h5 e6
{ The strongest player that had played with the black pieces tried to defend with this move, but as a matter of fact, there are no defensive moves that can stop the attack. }
13. Nh3
{ There are a plethora of good moves here for White, this is one of them. }
13... Re8 14. hxg6 fxg6 15. f4 { The pawns keep marching. } 15... Bg7 16. e5 d5
17. Ng5 { Targeting the h7-pawn. } 17... Nf8 18. Bd3
{ Black's king can't defend itself against the attack. Matsuura,E - Jatoba de Oliveira Reis,P Rio de Janeiro 2017. }
