[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "13. Pirc (1...d6) c6 lines"]
[Black "4...Bg7 (5...c6) 6.Qd2 Informational"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Be3 Bg7
{ As already discussed, I believe that Black should accept the challenge and go for this move. }
5. f3 c6
{ The exclamation mark might be a tad exaggerated, but this was the first time in the course that I was truly stuck and puzzled about which line to go for. Black's play is simple as he is ready to play on the queenside with b5 and Nbd7, while avoiding to castle kingside for now. The engine isn't so excited here either which is an important thing to highlight, and certainly an oddity in the lines with g6. Before we move on to the move I suggest, I want to showcase some sample lines here, as I believe it's worth to go through some of the problems I faced when analyzing this line. }
6. Qd2
{ This move is by far the most played move, which is not surprising as it is incredibly natural. }
6... b5 7. O-O-O
{ Slightly less common than 7. g4, but a better try.   7.g4  Is a line White can try, but I am not convinced.  7...h5  A strong move, forcing us to make a decision on the kingside.  8.g5  Nfd7  9.f4  Is how the main line goes. Now I figured out that Black can play  9...b4  10.Nce2  10. Nd1 gives the same verdict.  10...c5∞  The position remains highly unclear, but I prefer Black to be honest as it's hard for us to find a safe spot for our king. Black can safely castle kingside, since we don't have a clear cut way to open any lines there. }
7... Nbd7
{ Black can also develop the knight right away to d7.   7...Qa5  Can be played here, when the main line goes:  8.Kb1  Nbd7  9.Bh6  Bxh6  10.Qxh6  b4  11.Nce2  c5∞  An exciting position is on the board as Black has excellent prospects on the queenside. The engine thinks it's equal, but I honestly think 'unclear,' is a better word, since this game could go either way. }
8. g4
{ White starts launching the pawns on the kingside.  8.Bh6  is the alternative, but rather harmless as Black can play  8...Bxh6  followed by b4 and a5, with excellent play. Remember that Black's king hasn't castled yet, which is a huge advantage. }
8... Nb6
{ There are many viable options for Black here, including  8...h5  or  8...Qa5  . }
9. Bd3
{ Is a natural way to proceed, but it gives Black the option of playing   9.Bh6!  This was the necessary way to test Black.  9...Bxh6  10.Qxh6  Kd7  N  Is a funny novelty which looks very interesting to me. Black switches gears completely, and surprisingly enough, the king will be quite safe on c7. There were other moves Black could try as well of course, but I won't cover them since this is purely a way to demonstrate some different lines.  11.h4  11. e5 has to be countered with 11... b4! when Black is fine. The text move aims to play h5 which is a good plan.  11...Kc7⩲  It would be wrong not to give White an edge here, but the position remains complicated. }
9... h5 { When Bh6 becomes a move of the past. } 10. g5 Nfd7 11. f4 b4 12. Nce2
c5
{ And suddenly, Black was close to winning in the battle of the Norwegian youngsters @@StartBracket@@both are really good friends of mine, particularly GM Tari who I went to the same high school with for three years@@EndBracket@@. Tari,A - Holm, K Larvik 2019. }
