1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Be3 Bg7
{ As already discussed, I believe that Black should accept the challenge and go for this move. }
5. f3 c6
{ The exclamation mark might be a tad exaggerated, but this was the first time in the course that I was truly stuck and puzzled about which line to go for. Black's play is simple as he is ready to play on the queenside with b5 and Nbd7, while avoiding to castle kingside for now. The engine isn't so excited here either which is an important thing to highlight, and certainly an oddity in the lines with g6. }
6. g4
{ This move has only been played 60 times, so it's extremely uncommon.  6.Qd2  on the other hand has been seen over 4500 times, but as I showed in the informational, Black is fine. The plan behind  g4  is simple enough, as we want to launch a pawn storm towards the black king as quickly as possible.  6.a4  is a move the engine really likes which stops Black from playing b5. Definitely worth a look.  6.Nge2  is interesting too, with similar play as the text move. }
6... Qa5 7. Ne2
{ The most accurate response. We simply proceed with our development. } 7...
O-O
{ Black's king is slightly safer here than in the positions we saw earlier in the chapter as our king is still stuck in the center. }
8. g5 Nh5
{ Black should keep some control over the h5-square, otherwise h4-h5 might be quite obnoxious as it could come quite quickly. }
9. Ng3 d5
{ Black needs to get counterplay, and this is the best way to get some. This is usually a nice rule of thumb as well - if you're getting attacked, try striking in the center. @@StartBracket@@Especially if your opponent hasn't castled yet@@EndBracket@@. }
10. Nxh5 gxh5 11. Bd3 { We need to get the rest of our pieces on the board. }
11... c5
{ Black strikes in the center and has actually a decent amount of counterplay. }
12. Qd2
{ The knight is now unpinned, so we are ready to meet  12...cxd4  with  13.Nxd5  . }
12... dxe4 13. Nxe4
{ We will head into an endgame where we've sacrificed a pawn for a dangerous initiative. }
13... Qxd2+ 14. Bxd2 cxd4
{ 14...Bxd4?!  Is now inaccurate, since we win the pawn back after  15.c3  c4  Is the best move. After other bishop moves we can simply take on c5.  16.Bxc4±  We keep a strong initiative in the endgame due to our active pieces. Black also has problems with the pawn on h5 which is quite weak. }
15. O-O-O
{ Black's kingside is a little unsafe which is where we will place our pieces. }
15... Nc6 16. Ng3 { The knight is headed to h5. } 16... h4 17. Nh5 Be5 18. Rhg1
{ We keep a strong initiative with f4-f5 in the air. The knight could even head to f6 in some lines which is unpleasant to meet for Black. }
