5. f3 c6
{ The exclamation mark might be a tad exaggerated, but this was the first time in the course that I was truly stuck and puzzled about which line to go for. Black's play is simple as he is ready to play on the queenside with b5 and Nbd7, while avoiding to castle kingside for now. The engine isn't so excited here either which is an important thing to highlight, and certainly an oddity in the lines with g6. }
6. g4 b5
{ The typical response by Pirc-players is to launch the b-pawn immediately. }
7. a3
{ Allowing Black to play b4 gives him a relatively easy game, so it's crucial that we prevent it. }
7... h5
{ Is always a move Black can try, when the game continues in similar fashion to 6... h5. }
8. g5 Nfd7 9. f4
{ The plan remains the same, we want to create a strong center and develop our g1-knight to f3. }
9... Nb6
{ Black's plan also remains the same. He needs to play d5 in order to prevent us from playing f5 which could cause tremendous damage. }
10. Nf3 d5
{ 10...O-O ?  Allows us to play  11.f5±  When it looks like that White is close to objectively winning already due to Nh4 coming when Black's pawn chain is in severe danger. }
11. e5
{ It looks hard to break through, but Nh4 followed by Ne2-Ng3-Nxh5 is a very dangerous plan that makes Black's defensive task tough - especially because of his limited counterplay. }
11... Bg4
{ I think it makes sense to rid himself of the light-squared bishop and capture our knight. }
12. h3 Bxf3 13. Qxf3 e6 14. Bd3
{ Black has a nice wall of pawns, but it doesn't mean that it's impossible to break through. Our advantage isn't massive, but from a practical point of view, we are only playing for two results. Let's check how the game can proceed from here: }
14... N8d7 15. Ne2
{ The knight stands in the way of our c-pawn, so it makes sense to move it. If Black is not careful, Ng3-Nxh5 may come as well... }
15... a5
{ Black grabs some space on the queenside and delays castling - a clever strategy.   15...O-O ?  Is the most natural move in the world, but a decisive mistake.  16.Ng3!  The knight is ready to sacrifice itself on the h-pawn.  16...Re8  17.Nxh5  gxh5  18.Qxh5  White has 'only' two pawns for the piece, but the attack is very dangerous. Also, it helps us that the position is quite closed which makes it tough for Black to utilize his extra piece.  18...Nf8  19.b3  We should prevent Black from gaining counterplay with Nc4.  19...Nbd7  20.Qf3+-  We are ready to launch our h-pawn up the board, and there is nothing Black can do about it. }
16. O-O Nc8
{ A strong defensive move, as the knight is headed to f5 where it will greatly support Black's defenses. }
17. Kh2
{ There are numerous ways to proceed of course, but I like this prophylactic move the most. }
17... Ne7 18. a4 { In order to make progress, we must open the c-file. } 18...
b4 19. Ng3
{ The knight on g3 prevents Black from castling, which is quite annoying for him. }
19... Nf5
{ Black's knight has reached f5 so he can finally castle.   19...O-O ?  Is once again a poor move due to  20.Nxh5→  When our attack is far too dangerous. }
20. c4 { A slightly tricky move.  20.Nxf5  is also good. } 20... Nxg3
{ Falls into our 'trap.'  20...bxc3  is necessary, when we should play  21.Nxf5  before we take on  c3  . We are playing for two results, although it won't be easy to break through. }
21. Kxg3
{ It's essential that Black can not play dxc4 followed by Nb6. Now that our queen stays on f3, this is not a resource Black has! Ah those small details... }
21... O-O 22. c5
{ The position remains completely closed after we will play b3 next. From there we will have all the time in the world to prepare a potential sacrifice on h5. All Black can do is wait... }
