[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "13. Pirc (1...d6) c6 lines"]
[Black "4...Bg7 (5...c6 8)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Be3 Bg7
{ As already discussed, I believe that Black should accept the challenge and go for this move. }
5. f3 c6
{ The exclamation mark might be a tad exaggerated, but this was the first time in the course that I was truly stuck and puzzled about which line to go for. Black's play is simple as he is ready to play on the queenside with b5 and Nbd7, while avoiding to castle kingside for now. The engine isn't so excited here either which is an important thing to highlight, and certainly an oddity in the lines with g6. }
6. g4 b5
{ The typical response by Pirc-players is to launch the b-pawn immediately. }
7. a3
{ Allowing Black to play b4 gives him a relatively easy game, so it's crucial that we prevent it. }
7... Nbd7 { Was played in the only game I found with this line. } 8. h4 h5 9.
g5 Nh7
{ We have reached a position similar to the one we get after 7... h5. The plan forward is to play f4-f5, and of course a potential sacrifice on h5 if possible. }
10. Nge2
{ This time we develop the knight directly to e2 where it can reach g3 and attack h5, while supporting f4-f5. }
10... O-O 11. Bg2 Nb6 12. b3
{ Preventing the annoying knight jump to c4 - a move we've seen several times already. }
12... a5 13. O-O
{ There is no doubt that White has the upper hand as Black's position is tough to handle. Our plan is straightforward... f4-f5 and a knight sac on h5. Meanwhile what should Black do? Even for an engine this situation is not ideal, which this game clearly shows... }
13... d5
{ Black goes for the usual compensation on the light squares.  13...Qc7  is suggested by my engine, but we have a very comfortable position after for example  14.Ng3  . }
14. e5 Re8 15. Ng3 e6 16. f4
{ The engine evaluation keeps climbing, as the knight sac will cause major damage. The game continued: }
16... a4 17. b4
{ Blocks Black's counterplay on the queenside. Black now can't do much else than watch as we sacrifice our way through on h5, which was achieved in a few moves: }
17... Ba6 18. Nce2 Re7 19. Nxh5
{ It's time! Although White could have waited even longer since Black has no counterplay. }
19... gxh5 20. Ng3 Nc4 21. Bc1 Kh8 22. Qxh5
{ White was breaking through and eventually won in Rodriguez,L - Larsen,A ICCF email 2017. }
