1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Be3 Bg7
{ As already discussed, I believe that Black should accept the challenge and go for this move. }
5. f3 c6
{ The exclamation mark might be a tad exaggerated, but this was the first time in the course that I was truly stuck and puzzled about which line to go for. Black's play is simple as he is ready to play on the queenside with b5 and Nbd7, while avoiding to castle kingside for now. The engine isn't so excited here either which is an important thing to highlight, and certainly an oddity in the lines with g6. }
6. g4 b5
{ The typical response by Pirc-players is to launch the b-pawn immediately. }
7. a3
{ Allowing Black to play b4 gives him a relatively easy game, so it's crucial that we prevent it. }
7... O-O
{ This is Black's best version of the lines with O-O, as having b5 and a3 included can only benefit Black. It's still not good enough to equalize though... }
8. h4 h5
{ It seems like Black has everything under control, but we can force a nice endgame with the move }
9. e5 { Getting rid of the knight on f6 that protects the pawn on h5. } 9...
dxe5 10. dxe5 Qxd1+ 11. Rxd1 Ne8
{ Is the lesser evil, but still great for us after   11...Nfd7  Is now met by  12.f4!  It's important that we defend the e5-pawn.  12...hxg4  There are many good moves here, but the tactical shot  13.Nxb5+-   Is the simplest. Black has to give an exchange after  13...cxb5  14.Bg2  , when we are pretty much completely winning. }
12. gxh5 Bxe5 13. hxg6 fxg6 14. Nge2
{ We do not need to worry about the pawn on f3 since Black will open the diagonal if he decides to take it. If he doesn't take it, we can proceed with Nd4, Bg2-f4 or even h5. }
14... Rxf3
{ It's a bit greedy to go pawn-grabbing, but I will still consider it. A move like  14...Nf6  is a bit better, when we should play  15.Bg2  followed by f4. }
15. Bd4 Bxd4 16. Nxd4 Rf4 17. Bg2
{ With excellent play in the diagonal. We are winning back the pawn, since the pawn on b5 can be taken due to the hanging rook on a8. }
