[Black "4...Bg7 (5...c6 10)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Be3 Bg7
{ As already discussed, I believe that Black should accept the challenge and go for this move. }
5. f3 c6
{ The exclamation mark might be a tad exaggerated, but this was the first time in the course that I was truly stuck and puzzled about which line to go for. Black's play is simple as he is ready to play on the queenside with b5 and Nbd7, while avoiding to castle kingside for now. The engine isn't so excited here either which is an important thing to highlight, and certainly an oddity in the lines with g6. }
6. g4 b5
{ The typical response by Pirc-players is to launch the b-pawn immediately. }
7. a3
{ Allowing Black to play b4 gives him a relatively easy game, so it's crucial that we prevent it. }
7... a5
{ Black's best bet is to grab space on the queenside and aim to play b4 as soon as possible. }
8. Nge2 Ba6
{ With this move, Black is preparing to play b4 since the rook no longer hangs on a8. The bishop is also well placed on a6 after Black has played b4.   8...O-O ?!  Is a very risky move, as we get our usual powerful attack after  9.h4  9...h5  10.Ng3!  When we are opening the h-file.  10...hxg4  11.h5  gxf3  12.Qxf3→  I doubt that Black can survive our deadly attack. }
9. e5
{ I had completed my analysis and reviewed the chapter until I had an epiphany and realized that what I initially recommended,  9.h4  , wasn't the way to go. The reason why I changed my mind was the fact that the line is complicated while we don't even end up with an edge once the dust has settled. Black even has several good tries along the way, which just makes everything even worse. The main tabiya is:  9...b4  10.Na4  h5  11.g5  Nfd7  12.f4  O-O  13.f5  , with some pressure. However, Black has the tricky  13...Qe8!  when we have to watch out for  c5  followed by  Nc6  when we are at risk of getting a terrible position. The analysis kept going with  14.Bg2  when Black has more than one good move in the position. The forcing sequence is  14...c5  15.e5  cxd4  16.Nxd4  Nxe5  17.Bxa8  leads to a position where Black has sacrificed an exchange, but with sufficient compensation. It's a minefield for both sides really as precise play is required.  17...Ng4!?  is tricky, when the game continues  18.Rh3  Qxa4  19.Bd5  Bxd4!  20.Bxd4  Qb5  21.Qf3  e6  22.fxe6  fxe6  23.Bxe6+  Kh7  24.O-O-O  Rxf3  25.Rxf3  Ne5  26.Bxe5  Qxe5  27.Rf7+  with a perpetual. Once I discovered that we actually get an edge after the text move, while it is much easier to learn, it wasn't difficult to change my mind. }
9... Nd5 { Black places the knight on the most active square. } 10. Nxd5 cxd5
11. f4
{ I think we should keep our center intact.  11.e6  leads to tricky play where Black has to play accurately, so it's a decent alternative. However, in the end we won't get any advantage here, so it's inferior to the text move. It's worth checking out nonetheless though, as the lines are rad. }
11... O-O 12. h4 { It's time to launch the h-pawn towards the black king. }
12... Nc6 13. h5
{ It might seem premature to end the analysis already here, but our path forward is simple. We will lock Black down completely on the kingside with h6 followed by g5. Then, we will proceed developing our bishop to g2 @@StartBracket@@or h3 if we attack the queen with a tempo@@EndBracket@@ and castle kingside, or place the king on f2. That's right, our king will be perfectly safe on the kingside! Afterwards, we will solidify the queenside with moves like Qd2, b3 @@StartBracket@@or b4 if we're allowed to@@EndBracket@@ and c3. Black's bishop will be stuck on h8 where it will greatly suffer, especially in endgames. }
