[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "13. Pirc (1...d6) c6 lines"]
[Black "Pirc 5...c6 Conclusion"]
[Result "*"]

{ CONCLUSION: Playing the Pirc with a c6-system is a standard way of playing, as the pawn on c6 supports the typical b5-b4 launch, while it also controls the center. Just like in the a6-Pirc, I want you to notice these subtle differences as they are vastly different. Playing c6 in the 4th move is what GM Mihail Marin recommends, but I must admit that I am not too impressed. Black's idea is that he wants to avoid the trickery with Bh6 which leads to complications where Black is required to memorize some lines. The prize of playing c6 already here is that we are now well-aware of Black's set-up so we have time to act accordingly. }
1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Be3 Bg7
{ The other alternative to Marin’s line which is referenced below is to play and delay the c6-advance. }
5. f3
{ controlling the g4 square and aiming for f4 next in many variations which will grant us a better version of the Austrian Attack. }
5... c6
{ is clearly the way to go as Black avoids O-O and aims for a queenside expansion with b5 etc.   5...Nbd7  GM Marin’s suggestion when we should carry out our plan with  6.f4  . Indeed, the downside of Black's opening choice is that he gets little space and less control of the center, so the way we punish him is by taking maximum control of it.  6...e5  is how GM Marin wants to proceed but after  7.Nf3  Qe7  8.Qd2!  Black's position is incredibly unpleasant which the correspondence game Herman, T - Scott, P ICCF email 2018 clearly showed.   5...O-O  is extremely risky, because our attack is clearly superior to Black's as our analysis showed along with White's victories in Correspondence chess. One idea I want you to keep in mind is how we often meet h5 with g4 and play h5 in the event Black decides to take the pawn on g4. Once we have the pawn on g4, we usually place a knight on g3 or f4 to break through, often via e2. I will emphasize again how powerful our attack is, so Black should avoid this line at all costs - or at least choose a different set-up than with c6. We will cover those set-ups in the next Pirc chapter. }
6. g4
{ which I believe creates some problems for Black. Against this set-up. Black can play h5 on several occasions, aiming to block our pawns and place a blockade on the light squares. These positions are solid enough, but tough for humans to defend as Black has very limited things to do. Our plan is simple as we often prepare a deadly sacrifice on the pawn on h5. }
6... b5
{ is Black's most sensible response, when it's essential that we respond with }
7. a3
{ On several occasions in the chapter we face the standard b5-move with this answer, preventing the pawn from advancing even further to the b4-square. Black should push for this plan with  7...a5  8.Nge2  Ba6  . I initially suggested  9.h4  which lead to extremely tricky positions, but later discovered that  9.e5!  was much better as we get a massive space advantage on the kingside. 6. g4!? is a rare move, but I am sure it will be played more frequently when people realize that 6. Qd2 is nothing special. I am more certain than ever that Black should opt for 5... c6, as the alternatives aren't viable. Still, our 6. g4!? poses some questions to Black which won't be easy for him to answer. }
