[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "14. Pirc (1...d6) e5 & Sidelines"]
[Black "4...Bg7 (6...c5)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Be3 Bg7 5. f3 O-O 6. Qd2
{ The last remaining branch of Pirc is to consider the rest of the systems Black can play besides a6 & c6. }
6... c5
{ This move deserves an exclam since it's much better than the alternatives. }
7. dxc5
{ We should accept Black's pawn offer.   7.Nge2  was the alternative, when  7...cxd4  8.Nxd4  Nc6  is a surprising transposition to the Dragon.   However, Black can do better with  8...Qa5!  After  9.O-O-O  b5  the game is complicated and Black has terrific counterplay on the queenside. The game Bolk, M - Schou Moldt, T Berlin 2013 was the only game I found in my base which resulted in a crushing victory for Black... }
7... dxc5 8. Qxd8 Rxd8 9. Bxc5
{ Here is the reason why I suspect Black refrains from playing this line. When Black plays the Pirc he is interested in a fighting game, he's interested in tricky positions. The position we have on the table is the exact opposite. Black has excellent compensation for the missing pawn, but with very limited winning chances - a scenario that Pirc-players are not very interested in. }
9... Nc6 10. Nge2
{ The most precise way to continue.   10.Bb5  was played in a recent correspondence game where Black held a draw without too much trouble. The game continued:  10...Nd7  11.Ba3  Nde5  12.Nge2  Be6  13.b3  a6  14.Bxc6  Nxc6  15.Rd1  Rxd1+  16.Nxd1  when White's edge was relatively tiny. Indeed, with computer help there was never any doubt how the game would end in Jensen, K - Torgersen, T ICCF email 2019. }
10... b6 11. Be3 Bb7 { Black played this move twice, but it's too passive. }
12. h4
{ Is the way we increase our edge. The point is to grab space and provoke Black to play h5 which will weaken the square on g5. If Black avoids h5 we could play h5 ourselves with h6 next. }
12... Rac8 13. Rd1
{ Since we are up material it's a good strategy to try to trade some pieces. The rook is also well placed on d1 where it could move to d2 and defend the pawn on c2. if necessary. }
13... Nb4
{ 13...h5  14.Nf4  Opening the diagonal for our bishop.  14...Ne8  It's not so easy for Black to find good moves. With Ne8 Black wants to take on c3 and destroy our pawn structure. We should respond with  15.Rxd8  Rxd8  16.Bd3  Black does not have sufficient compensation for the pawn and can look forward to suffer in the endgame. }
14. Rd2
{ We are now ready to push the black knight back to c6. It's also worth noting that our king can sneak towards the safer c1-square via d1. }
