[Black "4...Bg7 (6...c5 2)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Be3 Bg7 5. f3 O-O 6. Qd2
{ The last remaining branch of Pirc is to consider the rest of the systems Black can play besides a6 & c6. }
6... c5
{ This move deserves an exclam since it's much better than the alternatives. }
7. dxc5
{ We should accept Black's pawn offer.   7.Nge2  was the alternative, when  7...cxd4  8.Nxd4  Nc6  is a surprising transposition to the Dragon.   However, Black can do better with  8...Qa5!  After  9.O-O-O  b5  the game is complicated and Black has terrific counterplay on the queenside. The game Bolk, M - Schou Moldt, T Berlin 2013 was the only game I found in my base which resulted in a crushing victory for Black. }
7... dxc5 8. Qxd8 Rxd8 9. Bxc5
{ Here is the reason why I suspect Black refrains from playing this line. When Black plays the Pirc he is interested in a fighting game, he's interested in tricky positions. The position we have on the table is the exact opposite. Black has excellent compensation for the missing pawn, but with very limited winning chances - a scenario that Pirc-players are not very interested in. }
9... Nc6 10. Nge2
{ The most precise way to continue.   10.Bb5  was played in a recent correspondence game where Black held a draw without too much trouble. The game continued:  10...Nd7  11.Ba3  Nde5  12.Nge2  Be6  13.b3  a6  14.Bxc6  Nxc6  15.Rd1  Rxd1+  16.Nxd1  when White's edge was relatively tiny. Indeed, with computer help there was never any doubt how the game would end in Jensen, K - Torgersen, T ICCF email 2019. }
10... b6 11. Be3 Ba6
{ The bishop is more active on a6 than on b7, making this move the right way to proceed. }
12. Bd2 { We are now blocking Black's rook which allows us to O-O-O next. }
12... Rxd2
{ The best try for compensation is to sac an exchange. This leads to a forced sequence where Black has some counterplay due to our vulnerable king and undeveloped pieces. }
13. Kxd2 Bh6+ { Black needs to start with this move. } 14. Kd1
{ This move is very illogical since we are allowing Black to get another tempo with Rd8+ . The point is that   14.Ke1  allows  14...Nb4  which gives Black more than enough compensation for the material deficit. Having Rd8 included actually harms Black which we will see. }
14... Rd8+ 15. Ke1 Nb4
{ Funnily enough, Black is better off having the rook on a8 than d8! } 16. Rd1
{ The difference is that we get a tempo with Rd1, since we are 'threatening' the rook on d8. }
16... Nxc2+
{ Black has to take the pawn. Moving the rook would allow us to give the exchange back with Rd2 when our extra pawn in the endgame should decide yes, we are still up a pawn! }
17. Kf2 Be3+ 18. Kg3
{ In the 14. Ke1-line Black would have been able to play Bc5 in this position, but now that's not possible. If Black moves the rook, we will simply play Nf4 when Black's pressure is pretty much gone. Hence Black has to play }
18... Rxd1 19. Nxd1 Bc5 20. Nc1
{ With the rooks gone Black's pressure has been significantly decreased, but we don't have a winning position yet. I still believe that Black is struggling in a practical game though, since he needs to play extremely accurately as we will surely be winning if we are allowed to untangle. }
