[White "14. Pirc (1...d6) e5 & Sidelines"]
[Black "4...Bg7 (6...Nbd7)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Be3 Bg7 5. f3 O-O 6. Qd2
{ The last remaining branch of Pirc is to consider the rest of the systems Black can play besides a6 & c6. }
6... Nbd7
{ Is a popular alternative to the main moves 6... e5 & 6... c6, but it's not good. }
7. O-O-O
{ Just like against a6 & c6, our path forward is to create a powerful attack. }
7... e5 8. g4 { I prefer launching the g-pawn first. } 8... exd4
{ Black has to play concretely in order to create something, otherwise he will get smashed on the kingside. }
9. Bxd4 c5
{ Black's best shot for counterplay is to play actively.   9...a6?  Some players have tried this typical move, but it's too slow.  10.g5  The simplest way to proceed is to kick away the knight so we can rid ourselves of the defender on g7.  10...Nh5  11.Bxg7  Nxg7  12.h4  Now it's time to play for the h5-break!  12...b5  13.Nh3  The knight is headed for the f4-square where it will greatly aid us in playing h5.  13...Bb7  14.Nf4  White's attack is easy to carry out. We will develop our bishop and then place a rook on g1 in order to support the g5-pawn. Along with that we can make the typical prophylactic moves on the queenside, Kb1 & a3. Black can't do much else than watch as we break through. }
10. Be3 d5 { A strong pawn sacrifice. } 11. exd5 b5
{ And yet another pawn sacrifice! Black has sacrificed two pawns, but in return he gets activity which is crucial in order to avoid being smashed on the kingside. }
12. Bxb5 Rb8 { Can be met by } 13. Bf4
{ Threatening the rook. Now Black has to sacrifice even more material with }
13... Nxd5 14. Qxd5 Rxb5 15. Nxb5 Qf6
{ Black attacks b2 and f4 simultaneously, so he will win a piece back. } 16.
Nc3 Qxf4+ 17. Kb1
{ Black has regained some material, but is still an exchange down. It doesn't look like he has enough, although he has the bishop pair. }
17... Ba6 { A clever trap. } 18. Nge2
{ Not  18.Qxd7?  when Black is suddenly much better after  18...Bxc3!  The reason why this works is that we must give back material after  19.bxc3  Rb8+  20.Ka1  Qf6  , when the queen attacks c3 while fatal mate threats after a queen swing to b6 are in the air.  21.Ne2  is the move followed by Qd2 , when we are lucky if we manage to escape with a draw in the endgame. }
18... Qb4 19. a3 Qb8 20. Qd6 { Forcing a trade of queens. } 20... Bxe2
{ Wins a pawn, but it still isn't enough. } 21. Qxb8 Rxb8 22. Nxe2 Rxb2+ 23.
Kc1 { With a clean exchange down, Black has no chances to save the game. } *

