{ Black has to play concretely in order to create something, otherwise he will get smashed on the kingside. }
9. Bxd4 c5
{ Black's best shot for counterplay is to play actively.   9...a6?  Some players have tried this typical move, but it's too slow.  10.g5  The simplest way to proceed is to kick away the knight so we can rid ourselves of the defender on g7.  10...Nh5  11.Bxg7  Nxg7  12.h4  Now it's time to play for the h5-break!  12...b5  13.Nh3  The knight is headed for the f4-square where it will greatly aid us in playing h5.  13...Bb7  14.Nf4  White's attack is easy to carry out. We will develop our bishop and then place a rook on g1 in order to support the g5-pawn. Along with that we can make the typical prophylactic moves on the queenside, Kb1 & a3. Black can't do much else than watch as we break through. }
10. Be3 d5 { A strong pawn sacrifice. } 11. exd5 b5
{ And yet another pawn sacrifice! Black has sacrificed two pawns, but in return he gets activity which is crucial in order to avoid being smashed on the kingside. }
12. Bxb5 Qa5 { Is a better try. } 13. Bh6
{ Once again we want to trade the dark-squared bishops since the bishop on g7 has a potential of becoming a monster down that diagonal. }
13... Bxh6 14. Qxh6 Rb8
{ Funnily enough, all other moves gives more than +5 for White! It's not surprising as we are two pawns up, so Black is required to play as active as possible. }
15. Bxd7 Nxd7
{ Taking with the knight is the only move. The knight is heading to f8 where it will defend against our attack. Simultaneously, the bishop on c8 is much better placed on a6 than on d7. }
16. Nge2 Ba6
{ Black is playing actively and has ideas of playing Bxe2 when the pawn on a2 will hang in the end. }
17. h4 { Going for the kill! } 17... Rfe8
{ 17...Bxe2  is something we can ignore with  18.h5!  when we are just winning. }
18. h5 Nf8 19. hxg6 fxg6
{ Black has fended off our forces on the kingside. For now... } 20. Rh2
{ We must defend the knight and give the pawn on a2, but we have everything under control. }
20... Bxe2 21. Rxe2 Rxe2 22. Nxe2 Qxa2 23. Qe3
{ The only move that secures an edge as we need the queen in the defense. }
23... Qxb2+ 24. Kd2
{ We will play Nc3 next when the strong d5-pawn gives us a clearly better game. Our king will find a safe place on e2. }
