1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Be3 Bg7 5. f3 O-O 6. Qd2
{ The last remaining branch of Pirc is to consider the rest of the systems Black can play besides a6 & c6. }
6... Nc6 { Placing the knight on c6 doesn't do the job either. } 7. O-O-O e5 8.
d5
{ 8.Nge2  is the Main Line, but this is the way to punish Black's inaccurate move order. }
8... Nd4
{ Is met by   8...Ne7  Black plays in typical King's Indian fashion, but it allows us to do whatever we want on the kingside.  9.g4  Ne8  Black aims for the typical f5 to create some space.  10.h4!  We proceed with our plan.  10...f5  11.exf5  gxf5  12.h5  The pawn will soon reach h6 when Black will be suffocated.  12...f4  Is logical, but it gives away the control of the e4-square.  13.Bf2  h6  14.Nh3  Black has zero counterplay and will sooner or later get obliterated on the kingside. }
9. Nge2 c5 { Necessary, as  9...Nxe2+  gives us a really easy game. } 10. dxc6
bxc6 11. Nxd4 exd4 12. Bxd4
{ Black has sacrificed one pawn, but he has opened the b-file and gotten some central control for it. It's still not enough though. }
12... Be6 13. Na4
{ A strong move since the bishop can now contribute well in defense on the c3-square. }
13... c5 14. Bc3 Qe7 { 14...Bd7  is met by  15.Nxc5!  and e5 next. } 15. g4
{ It's time to play g5 so we can trade off the dark-squared bishops. } 15...
Rfd8 16. g5 Nh5 17. Bxg7 Nxg7 18. c4
{ A great move, preventing Black's potential counterplay with d5. } 18... Rab8
19. h4 Qc7 20. Nc3 a6 21. f4
{ White had perfectly neutralized Black's counterplay, and had obtained a completely winning position in Zelbel, P - Hoi, C Germany 2019. }
