[White "14. Pirc (1...d6) e5 & Sidelines"]
[Black "4...Bg7 (6...e5)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Be3 Bg7 5. f3 O-O 6. Qd2
{ The last remaining branch of Pirc is to consider the rest of the systems Black can play besides a6 & c6. }
6... e5
{ Black's most popular move in the position. The idea is simple as Black wants to get counterplay against our center. In the event of  7.d5  , Black has  7...c6  when he will take on  d5  next with active play. Black's concept is interesting, but the engines are not impressed. }
7. Nge2
{ The natural continuation since we want to take with the knight in case Black decides to capture on d4. }
7... c6
{ Black has tried this move in some games, but the usual theme in these positions still stands - our attack is more dangerous.   7...Nc6  This move is inaccurate as it gives us an extra option.  8.O-O-O   As the alternative  8.d5  leads to the same evaluation, I simply suggest that you play this and transpose to the mainline as Black has nothing better than  8...exd4  . You can of course look into  8.d5  if you want to. The choice is yours! }
8. h4 h5
{ Black should stop us from playing h5. It's worth noting that if Black allows us to do so, we can often respond with Nf5 when Black takes the h-pawn with the knight. }
9. O-O-O Nbd7
{ 9...Qa5?  Black doesn't have time to play Qa5.  10.Bh6  It's best to ignore whatever stew Black is trying to stir up on the queenside.  10...b5  And now, we can improve on the three games I found by playing  11.dxe5!  Which releases the tension in the center.  11...dxe5  12.g4!  As usual, the way we break through when Black has played h5 is to play g4-Ng3.  12...Be6  13.Ng3  b4  14.Nb1+-  Black's queenside attack is nonexistent which means that he is essentially busted as we're breaking through on the kingside. }
10. Bg5
{ The best move in the position as we aim to take on e5 and then on d6. The reason why we move the bishop first is to prevent Black from playing Nc4 which will win material if we take on d6 right away. }
10... Qa5
{ 10...b5  Is now met by  11.dxe5  Nxe5   This is necessary as our attack reaches decisive heights after  11...dxe5  12.g4  .  12.Qxd6  Qxd6  13.Rxd6±  Black is down a pawn and will have to fight for a draw. }
11. dxe5 { Is once again our response. } 11... Nxe5
{ Black has to do this for the very same reason like in the  10... b5-line.  11...dxe5  allows us to play  12.g4  , with the same deadly attack. }
12. Nd4
{ Black's position has problems to solve. First of all we are threatening to play Nb3 and grab the pawn on d6. g4 followed by f4 is also a neat idea which will chase Black's knight away from e5-square. The queen can also head to f4 in case Black decides to strike in the center with d5. }
