[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Be3 Bg7 5. f3 O-O 6. Qd2
{ The last remaining branch of Pirc is to consider the rest of the systems Black can play besides a6 & c6. }
6... e5 7. Nge2
{ The natural continuation since we want to take with the knight in case Black decides to capture on d4. }
7... exd4
{ Since our attack is faster and more dangerous than Black's, Black's best strategy is to fight against our center instead of launching a queenside attack.   7...Nc6  This move is inaccurate as it gives us an extra option.  8.O-O-O   As the alternative  8.d5  leads to the same evaluation, I simply suggest that you play this and transpose to the main line as Black has nothing better than  8...exd4  . You can of course look into  8.d5  if you want to. The choice is yours! }
8. Nxd4 Re8
{ Black is preparing d5 with this move, so it's essential that we get our king out of the way. }
9. O-O-O a6
{ 9...d5?  Now that our king is safe, Black can't play d5 although GM Mamedyarov did it.  10.exd5  I am a bit surprised that only one player has captured the pawn on d5. Deviates from Vachier Lagrave,M - Mamedyarov,S chess24. com INT 2021 lead to a clearly better position for the Frenchman, but the text move is much better.  10...Nxd5  11.Bg5!  We once again see this move, attacking Black's queen.  11...Bf6   11...Qd7  is met by  12.Ne4  when  Nc5  will follow suit.  12.Bxf6  Nxf6  13.Qf4+-  Black has to move the queen out of harm's way with  13...Qe7  ,  when Bd3 and Rhe1 comes quickly. Black's pieces can't deal with our pressure.   9...Nbd7?  As I stated earlier, Black needs to play against our center in order to have a chance for counterplay.  10.Bh6!  The moves should come naturally to you at this point!  10...Bh8  11.h4  The h-pawn march starts its march to the h5-square.  11...Ne5   11...Nb6  can be met with  12.Bg5  when h5 comes next.  12.h5  a6   12...Nxh5  is met by  13.Bg5  when  Qf2  and  Qh4  comes.  13.Bg5  b5  14.f4  Removing the knight from the active e5-square.  14...Neg4  15.hxg6  fxg6  16.Be2  White is preparing to play e5 at the right moment.  16...Qd7  17.Bxf6  Nxf6   17...Bxf6  is met by  18.Bxg4  and  Nd5  when Black recaptures.  18.e5  It's time to strike!  18...dxe5  19.fxe5  Rxe5  20.Bf3+-  Black couldn't avoid the loss of material in Rau - Schubert,W GER email 2009. }
10. h4
{ I will repeat myself once more. Black doesn't have time to attack on the queenside. }
10... b5 11. Bh6 { 11.h5  is also strong. } 11... Bh8 12. Bg5
{ I like this thematic move, pinning the knight on f6. That being said, playing h5 right away was strong too. }
12... Bb7 13. h5 { It did not take long until we achieved our kingside goal. }
13... Nbd7 { And here we have the concrete } 14. hxg6 fxg6 15. Nb3
{ The knight will jump to a5 where it will be a huge annoyance for Black. It's also worth nothing that a4 is a move that lies in the air, particularly if Black has moved the rook to b8 or c8. It's tough for Black to find a good move here! }
