1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Be3 Bg7 5. f3 O-O 6. Qd2
{ The last remaining branch of Pirc is to consider the rest of the systems Black can play besides a6 & c6. }
6... e5 7. Nge2
{ The natural continuation since we want to take with the knight in case Black decides to capture on d4. }
7... exd4
{ Since our attack is faster and more dangerous than Black's, Black's best strategy is to fight against our center instead of launching a queenside attack. }
8. Nxd4 d5
{ Many strong GMs have played this move which strikes immediately in the center, and it's certainly an interesting try as we need to react precisely. }
9. e5
{ The obvious choice.  9.exd5?  would give Black a great position after  9...Nxd5  due to his active pieces. The knight can now move to three different squares. }
9... Nfd7
{ I personally think this is Black's most logical choice since he aims to capture the pawn with the knight while keeping the e8-square available for the queen.  10.e6  is the extra option Black gives us with this move, but it achieves nothing after  10...Ne5  .   9...Nh5!?  Is an interesting try.  10.Bg5  Our reaction remains the same as against the other knight moves.  10...Qe8  11.O-O-O  It's essential that we castle and get our king to safety.  11...Qxe5  12.g4  The concrete way to play as Bf4-Ncb5 would lead to devastation for Black.  12...h6   Black's only move as  12...Nf6  allows our idea of playing  13.Bf4  and  Ncb5  .  13.Be3  c5!  Black's point.  14.f4!  A strong move, removing the queen from the diagonal.  14...Nxf4  Black has to sacrifice the piece. Play continues:  15.Nf3!  Otherwise we won't win the piece.  15...Qf6  16.Bxf4  Bxg4  17.Bg2+-  Black's three extra pawns do not give enough compensation for the missing piece.  17...d4  is Black's best move, when  18.Nd5  followed by c4 is very strong. }
10. Bg5 { The same response and the only way we can pose any problems. } 10...
Qe8
{ This time Black doesn't have  10...f6  available, as  11.Ne6  wins material. }
11. O-O-O
{ I am sure you saw this coming - it's essential that our king is safe. } 11...
c6
{ 11...Qxe5  Is met by  12.Ncb5  Black's queen is now in major trouble with f4 or Re1 to come.  12...a6  Black is pretty much forced to play this and give material.  13.f4  Black has to give the queen.  13...Qxg5  14.fxg5  axb5  15.Kb1  It's important to keep the a2-pawn under protection.  15...c6  Happened in Jarmula, L - Lobejko,R Szklarska Poreba 2013 a game where Black quickly obtained excellent compensation. I suggest to play  16.h4  N  With the simple plan of playing h5-Qf4-Qh4 or h5-h6-Bd3-Rhf1. Black's two extra minor pieces do create some practical play, but they will be no match for our queen if we place the pieces on the correct squares. }
12. f4 { We should protect the pawn on e5. } 12... Nc5 13. h4
{ Our usual plan of creating an attack stands strong. } 13... h5
{ 13...h6  is met by  14.Bf6  when h5 will follow suit. } 14. Re1
{ Supporting the pawn on e5, so we are now ready to blast through with f5. }
14... b5 15. f5 { The pawn is heading to f6. } 15... b4 16. f6
{ A strong move, ignoring Black's play on the queenside as our attack triumphs. }
16... bxc3 17. Qxc3 Ne4 18. Rxe4 { A strong exchange sacrifice. } 18... dxe4
19. fxg7 Kxg7 20. e6 f6 21. Bc4
{ Black was completely busted in Manninen, H-Thiel, K ICCF email 2017. The finale was fantastic, so I leave you to click through the game as it is a delight.  21...Ba6  22.Bf4  Bxc4  23.Qxc4  Qe7  24.g4  White is breaking through.  24...c5  25.gxh5  cxd4  26.Rg1  White's attack is so powerful that he is allowed to sacrifice a rook!  26...Kh8  27.hxg6  Re8  28.Qd5  The queen is headed to  h5  with  g7  to come.  28...Kg8  29.g7  f5  30.Rg6  Protecting the e6-pawn.  30...Nc6  31.Qxf5  Nd8  32.Bd6  Removing the queen from protecting the g7-pawn so we can play  Rh6  and mate.  32...Nxe6  33.Bxe7  Rxe7  34.h5  Nxg7  35.Qg5+-  Black finally resigned. }
