[White "15. Philidor"]
[Black "3...Nbd7 (4...c5)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 Nbd7
{ Before we dive into the main tabiya of the Philidor, we must take a look at GM Simon William's 'The Risky Lion,' because it dodges our weapon against the Main Line. 'The Risky Lion' is an accurate label, as it turns out that this line isn't very playable from an objective point of view as Black tends to lose in Correspondence Chess. Ginger GM argues that Black gets some practical chances, but I beg to differ. Of course, it requires us to be prepared, but that's the case with pretty much every line out there. Black is much better off playing 3... e5, which we will take a look at after we've knocked this one out of the way. }
4. f4
{ Just like in the Czech Pirc, we will take full control of the center. Now we are already threatening e5 which could lead to a disaster for Black. }
4... c5 { This move isn't very good as it allows us to strike in the center. }
5. e5 { Black is usually lost whenever we're allowed to do this... } 5... cxd4
6. Qxd4 Ng4
{ 6...dxe5  7.fxe5  Ng8  Is a catastrophe for Black for a lot of reasons. I like the sadistic  8.e6  When Black will have a hard time developing his pieces. }
7. Nf3 { We are sacrificing a pawn for a lot of play. } 7... dxe5 8. fxe5 Ndxe5
9. Qxd8+ Kxd8 10. Bf4
{ It's important that we maintain the pressure because of the material deficit. }
10... f6
{ Black's best bet. Against other moves we can play h3 followed by O-O-O, Bc4 and potentially Ng5/ Nb5. The moves come by themselves. }
11. Rd1+ { The most precise continuation. } 11... Nd7
{ Now Black wants to play e5 next, so we must keep attacking. } 12. h3
{ And now, a forced sequence is: } 12... e5 13. Bc1 Nh6 14. Bxh6 gxh6 15. Nd5
{ Not allowing Black a moment to rest. } 15... f5 16. Nh4 f4 17. Bb5
{ Active moves all the way, maintaining the pressure. Now Black has to watch out for Bxd7, when we will win material. }
17... Rg8 { The only defense, aiming to play Rg7. } 18. Nf6 Rg7 19. Nf3
{ Black's defense is starting to crumble. } 19... Re7
{ The only move that didn't lose material. } 20. O-O
{ Our initiative is overwhelming. } 20... Bg7 21. Nd5 Re6 22. Rfe1
{ All of our pieces are perfectly placed. } 22... Rd6
{ 22...a6  doesn't help either as we can play  23.Bd3  , when the pawn on  h7  will fall. }
23. c4
{ Aiming to play Nh4 and c5, when Black will lose all the defense against our battery in the d-file. }
23... b6 24. Nh4
{ Nf5 comes next, when Black will lose material one way or another. } *

