1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 Nbd7
{ Before we dive into the main tabiya of the Philidor, we must take a look at GM Simon William's 'The Risky Lion,' because it dodges our weapon against the Main Line. 'The Risky Lion' is an accurate label, as it turns out that this line isn't very playable from an objective point of view as Black tends to lose in Correspondence Chess. Ginger GM argues that Black gets some practical chances, but I beg to differ. Of course, it requires us to be prepared, but that's the case with pretty much every line out there. Black is much better off playing 3. .. e5, which we will take a look at after we've knocked this one out of the way. }
4. f4
{ Just like in the Czech Pirc, we will take full control of the center. Now we are already threatening e5 which could lead to a disaster for Black. }
4... c6 { GM Christian Bauer, famous for his rare openings, tried this once. }
5. e5 Nd5 6. Nxd5 cxd5 7. Nf3
{ Black has only achieved a position where he will be doomed to passivity. }
7... g6 8. Bd3 Qb6
{ Now instead of playing  9.h4  like in Siebrecht, S - Bauer, C Switzerland 2014, I suggest to target the queen on  b6  . }
9. a4 Bg7 10. a5 Qc7
{ We have a huge amount of space. Black's position is just trash. } 11. c3 O-O
12. O-O
{ Now that we have full control of the board, it's time to launch an attack with h4-h5 and Ng5. }
