[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "15. Philidor"]
[Black "3...Nbd7 (4...e5)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 Nbd7 4. f4
{ Just like in the Czech Pirc, we will take full control of the center. Now we are already threatening e5 which could lead to a disaster for Black. }
4... e5
{ Played almost every game, and for good reason. Black takes some central control and stops our e5-thrust. }
5. Nf3 c6
{ The only 'serious' alternative to the main move.  5...Be7  has been played sometimes, but it just loses the pawn on  e5  . Black doesn't gain anything from playing  5...Qe7  either. The pawn on  e4  isn't even under attack.  6.Be2  can be played, as we can capture on  d4  with the queen when Black takes on  d4  , protecting the pawn on  e4  . }
6. dxe5 dxe5 7. fxe5 Ng4
{ This is Black's scheme. If we now play  8.Bf4  , Black gets fantastic compensation after  8...Bc5  followed by a swift  Qe7  . }
8. e6 { This thrust is the refutation. } 8... fxe6 9. Ng5
{ Attacking g4 and e6 simultaneously. } 9... Nde5
{ The only way to protect both targets. } 10. Qxd8+ Kxd8 11. h3
{ Black has avoided loss of material, but the endgame that has occurred is not ideal. }
11... Nh6 { Black has to guard the f7-square. } 12. Bf4
{ White's initiative looks very dangerous. } 12... Nhf7
{ 12...Ng6  13.O-O-O+  Black's score from this position isn't very good, but it's not surprising. His pieces are quite passive and his king is in jeopardy.  13...Ke8  14.Be3  Be7  Black has to get rid of the knight before we play Bc4 and take the e6-pawn.  15.Be2  Bxg5  I somehow thought that Black could castle here, but his king has already moved... This move was played in every game as Black gets rid of some of our pressure. It's a common strategy when the other side has the initiative to trade pieces.  16.Bxg5  Nf7  17.Be3  White has the bishop pair, better pieces and a safe king. Black has scored 1/8 here, 6 losses and 2 draws which is not surprising as the position looks incredibly difficult to handle. We can stop the theory section here, but I want to show off a game as a clickable since it was quite instructive.  17...b6  18.a4  Ke7  19.a5  Rb8?  20.Na4  c5  21.axb6  axb6  22.Nxb6!  This trick works tactically.  22...Rxb6  23.Bxc5+  Rd6  24.Rhf1  White wins back the material with a nice profit.  24...Nge5  doesn't work either due to  25.Rxf7  Nxf7  26.e5  White is completely winning. Black decided to fight a bit more, but the position wasn't possible to save following Volke, K - Anistratov, D Germany 2019. }
13. Be2
{ Is the most accurate move in the position, as it's sometimes ideal to castle kingside instead of queenside. }
13... Be7 14. O-O-O+ Ke8 15. Nxf7 Nxf7 16. e5
{ Taking control of the f6 square and d6 square. Black will soon have to deal with a knight on d6 when our initiative will become too much to bear. }
16... Bd7 { Note that  16...Bg5  is met by  17.g3  . } 17. Bh5 g6
{ So far, we have been following Shahaliyev,I - Davidov,S Baku 2019, when I suggest }
18. Bf3
{ Black will suffer when our knight reaches the destination on  d6  .  18...Ng5  is nothing to worry about as we can play  19.Be2  followed by g3-h4 and then Ne4. }
