1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 Nbd7 4. f4
{ Just like in the Czech Pirc, we will take full control of the center. Now we are already threatening e5 which could lead to a disaster for Black. }
4... e5
{ Played almost every game, and for good reason. Black takes some central control and stops our e5-thrust. }
5. Nf3 exd4 6. Qxd4
{ Taking with the queen has been overwhelmingly the most common response, and indeed, it's the best move in the position as we want to castle queenside. }
6... c6
{ This is a good way to fight against our e5-break in the center as Black has taken control of the d5-square and he can respond with Bc5 if we play e5. }
7. Bd2
{ My analysis concluded that this move was the strongest approach. The advantage of having the bishop on d2 is that it's harder for Black to attack it. }
7... Qb6
{ Black should neutralize our initiative by trading queens. However, this is probably the least 'Ginger-GM' move out there, as the man lives for the chaos : Therefore he suggest the center-strike  7...d5  which is more complex, but subpar objectively. _ }
8. O-O-O Be7 { Black has to complete his development first. } 9. g3
{ It seems to be that White gets a better endgame, but it's not more than slightly better if Black plays his card right. Moves like  9.Re1  or  9.Bc4  also give us a slight edge. }
9... O-O 10. Kb1 Qxd4 { It's time for Black to trade queens. } 11. Nxd4 Re8 12.
Bg2 Nc5
{ The set-up for Black that makes the most amount of sense is to apply pressure on the pawn on e4. }
13. Rhe1
{ This move is an improvement over the game Mary, P - Glinz, G ICCF email 2015, when Black equalized after  13.Nb3  Nxb3  14.axb3  . }
13... Ng4 { Is the trickiest move in the position. } 14. b4
{ We must chase away the strong knight on c5. } 14... Na6
{ 14...Ne6  was better, when  15.Nf5  gives us a slightly better game. } 15. h3
{ Concrete and strong. } 15... Nf2
{ Surely the only critical approach.  15...Nf6  is met by  16.b5  and  e5  . }
16. Rc1 Nxb4
{ 16...Nxh3  17.Be3  White will trap Black's knight, but Black will get some compensation.  17...Nc7  18.Rh1  d5  Black wins the b4-pawn, but it isn't enough.  19.Nde2  Bxb4  20.Bxh3  Bxh3  21.Rxh3  Nb5  22.Nxb5  Rxe4  Black has won some pawns, but our extra piece is stronger.  23.g4  cxb5  24.Rd1  Rae8  25.Rd3  White had a winning endgame in Jerkovic,L - Lagergren,H ICCF email 2015. In case you decide to check out the game, let me mention that 31. Bd2 was much better than Bxc5 when Black could save himself. However, he errored later on and White prevailed. }
17. Rf1 Bf6
{ The best fighting move as  17...Nxh3  is met by  18.Nf5  when Black loses the knight on  h3  . }
18. Be3 c5 19. Ndb5 a6 { The only move that doesn't lose decisive material. }
20. Nxd6 Bxc3 21. a3
{ 21.Nxe8??  loses to  21...Be6  when Black's pieces are too strong. A funny twist of events. }
21... Bxh3
{ There are so many hanging pieces that it's easy to get confused, but trust me when I say that this is Black's best try. After a move like  21...Rd8  , I suggest to play  22.e5  when we'll capture one of the knights next. }
22. Rxf2
{ 22.Bxh3?  looks tempting, but Black saves the game after the amazing line  22...Nxe4  with the point  23.Nxe8  Nd5!! }
22... Bxg2 23. Nxe8 Rxe8 24. Rxg2 Rxe4 25. Bxc5 Nc6 26. Rd1
{ The complications have faded away and Black is in a lost endgame with an exchange down. }
