1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 Nbd7 4. f4
{ Just like in the Czech Pirc, we will take full control of the center. Now we are already threatening e5 which could lead to a disaster for Black. }
4... e5
{ Played almost every game, and for good reason. Black takes some central control and stops our e5-thrust. }
5. Nf3 exd4 6. Qxd4
{ Taking with the queen has been overwhelmingly the most common response, and indeed, it's the best move in the position as we want to castle queenside. }
6... c6
{ This is a good way to fight against our e5-break in the center as Black has taken control of the d5-square and he can respond with Bc5 if we play e5. }
7. Bd2
{ My analysis concluded that this move was the strongest approach. The advantage of having the bishop on d2 is that it's harder for Black to attack it. }
7... d5
{ Ginger-GM stays true to his style - sacrificing a pawn for initiative. } 8.
O-O-O { We must get our king to safety before we grab the offered material. }
8... Bc5 9. Qd3 O-O
{ Other moves have been tried, but this is the only critical variation as Black stays true to the spirit of the variation. The drawback though is that Black has to sacrifice the pawn on d5 in the process. }
10. exd5 cxd5
{ For some reason my engine puts this move at the top of its list, but from a practical point of view I think it makes our job easier as we trade pieces. }
11. Nxd5 Nxd5 12. Qxd5
{ In order to get some compensation, Black has to try to get active as soon as possible. He can do so with a queen move to c7 or b6, protecting the bishop, so the knight can go to f6, bishop to e6 and rook to d8. Unfortunately for Black, it's not good enough for sufficient compensation as the following lines demonstrate. }
12... Qc7
{ 12...Qb6  Is the most played move here, when I think a decent move is  13.Bc4  Nf6  14.Qd3  Bg4  Black has completed his development, but it doesn't justify the missing soldier.  15.Rhe1  Rad8  16.Qb3  Black has to head into an endgame with a pawn less, a scenario where the most likely outcome will be 1-0. }
13. Bc3 { I think this move is the simplest approach. } 13... Qxf4+ 14. Kb1
{ We have given back the pawn, but in return we have obtained a nice initiative. }
14... Be3
{ 14...Be7!  The reason why this move is the strongest is that it prevents the Qxf7-idea after Bc4, so Black is able to carry out Nb6. Another pro is that Black can also trade off our strong bishop on c3 by playing Bf6.  15.Qc4!  Forcing a clearly better endgame.  15...Qxc4  16.Bxc4  Nb6  17.Rhe1  Gaining a tempo on the bishop.  17...Bf6!  The most accurate defense.  18.Bb3  Our active pieces grants us a clearly better endgame. }
15. g3 { Chasing the queen away. } 15... Qh6 16. Bc4
{ White's initiative was overwhelming in Sharapov, E - Nesterets, A Alushta 2010. A cute detail is that Black is mated after  16...Nb6  17.Qxf7+  Rxf7  18.Rd8#  . }
