[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 Nbd7 4. f4
{ Just like in the Czech Pirc, we will take full control of the center. Now we are already threatening e5 which could lead to a disaster for Black. }
4... e5
{ Played almost every game, and for good reason. Black takes some central control and stops our e5-thrust. }
5. Nf3 exd4 6. Qxd4
{ Taking with the queen has been overwhelmingly the most common response, and indeed, it's the best move in the position as we want to castle queenside. }
6... c6
{ This is a good way to fight against our e5-break in the center as Black has taken control of the d5-square and he can respond with Bc5 if we play e5. }
7. Bd2
{ My analysis concluded that this move was the strongest approach. The advantage of having the bishop on d2 is that it's harder for Black to attack it. }
7... d5
{ Ginger-GM stays true to his style - sacrificing a pawn for initiative. } 8.
O-O-O { We must get our king to safety before we grab the offered material. }
8... Bc5 9. Qd3 O-O
{ Other moves have been tried, but this is the only critical variation as Black stays true to the spirit of the variation. The drawback though is that Black has to sacrifice the pawn on d5 in the process. }
10. exd5 Qc7
{ This move is the main try where Black aims to apply pressure on d5 with Nb6 followed by Rd8. }
11. Ng5
{ Is a strong move with the idea of placing the knight on the ideal e4-square. Another advantage to this move is that it applies pressure on h7 which leaves the knight on f6 stuck for the time being. }
11... Bd6
{ Played in every game I found and also suggested by Ginger-GM. It's very logical because it attacks the pawn on f4 and frees the c5-square for the black knight on d7. }
12. dxc6 { We should hold on to the extra pawn. } 12... bxc6
{ 12...Nc5  The strong correspondence player Burmeister tried this twice, but he lost both games.  13.Qd4  bxc6  14.Bc4  Completing our development and applying pressure on the pawn on f7.  14...h6  15.Nce4  Trading the strong knight on c5.  15...Ncxe4  16.Nxe4  Be7  17.Rhf1  17. Rde1 was also strong and played in Hameister,R - Burmeister,F ICCF email 2018, when White prevailed after 66 moves.  17...Rd8  18.Qe3  Bf5  19.Ng3  Bg4  20.Rde1  White is simply a pawn up. The game continued:  20...Re8  21.h3  Bb4  22.Qf2  Bxd2+  23.Qxd2  Another piece has been traded, which is obviously a huge advantage for us. Black's compensation is nowhere to be found, so the position is objectively lost. Indeed, White won after 20 additional moves in the e-mail game Martynov, A -Burmeister, F ICCF email 2018. }
13. Qf3
{ Is the best move, allowing the bishop on f1 to get on the board and protects the pawn on f4. }
13... Rb8 { Utilizing the open b-file. } 14. Nge4
{ Our knight has finally arrived to the strong post in the center. } 14... Bb4
{ Tried in two e-mail games, but I can't really see what Black accomplishes after }
15. a3 Be7
{ Compared to the main line, we have gotten a3 for free. It might look like a weakness at first sight, but Black's attack is rather harmless if we place our bishop on b3. }
16. Bc4 Kh8 17. Rde1 Nb6 18. Bb3 Bg4 19. Qe3 Nbd5 20. Qf2
{ Black doesn't have enough for the material deficit. The game Pundak,M -Burmeister,F ICCF email 2018 ended in a draw, but that was because White's engine hadn't calculated deeply enough and evaluated one position as winning when it was in reality a draw. My engine gives several improvements along the way, but I digress. }
