[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 Nbd7 4. f4
{ Just like in the Czech Pirc, we will take full control of the center. Now we are already threatening e5 which could lead to a disaster for Black. }
4... Nb6
{ This corny move has been a favorite of GM Kunin, who has beaten some 2400 players with it. The point is that Black can jump to d5 if we decide to go for the usual strike in the center. Black may also play d5, when the e4 square will be available to his knight on f6, gaining some control on the light squares. }
5. Nf3 { As always, simple development does the trick. } 5... d5
{ Black's idea was this little break in the center. He doesn't have time for other moves. Black played  5...Bg4  in 10 games, but  6.h3  does the trick when Black's position is terrible after  6...Bxf3  7.Qxf3  . }
6. e5
{ 6.Bd3  is even easier when our central control gives us a nice edge too. The text move is the concrete refutation, but it is slightly more complex. }
6... Ne4 7. Nxe4
{ White didn't find this move in the three games that were played. White went for  7.Bd3  , but I don't think things are so clear any longer after  7...Bf5  . }
7... dxe4 8. Ng5 f5 { This move is refuted by } 9. e6
{ Obviously we are threatening Nf7, but we are also aiming to play c4-c5. }
9... Qd5 10. g4
{ With the simple plan of taking on f5 followed by Bh3 or Bg2. Note also that c4 is a threat as the pawn on f5 will hang in the end. }
10... Bxe6 { The critical move. } 11. c4
{ The key move, as it provides us with a very strong center. } 11... Nxc4
{ Loses a piece after   11...Qd7  12.d5!  Black can't withstand the pressure.  12...Bg8  13.gxf5  Qxf5  14.Bh3  Qf6  15.O-O  Black is completely busted. If you don't believe me I urge you to flip the board and see the position for yourself : }
12. Nxe6 Qxe6 13. Qb3 { The knight falls so Black can resign. } *

