[Black "3...e5 (6...Be6)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5
{ This is the best and most common way to reach the Philidor Defense, named after the famous 18th century player Francois-André Danican Philidor. Black's position is surprisingly solid, and correspondence games show that the defense is a tough nut to crack. The use of the opening doesn't occur frequently on top level, but it has been considered a fairly good opening for amateur players who want something that's easy to understand with less complex positions than those that occur in mainstream theory. Black usually makes the same type of moves here: Nbd7-Be7-O-O-c6-a5-Re8-Qc7 etc, but it all depends on the set-up of the white player. It's also a fairly good practical weapon against lower-rated players, who may not be used to play these kind of positions. The drawback is rather typical for uncommon openings, the fact that Black's position becomes quite passive. }
4. dxe5
{ This move might be surprising to you, considering the aggressive stance we have taken so far in the repertoire. Before I walked in the land of Philidor, I was well aware of all the critical responses from the white side. This was one of them, so it made sense to me to investigate it even further. When my analysis was complete, I intended to at least have this weapon as a backup plan. Perhaps as an alternative? Unfortunately, I was unable to come up with something more convincing, as it turns out that Black is doing surprisingly okay against other moves as well. The enormous amounts of theory to learn did not appeal to me as much when the end result was only a slightly better game and a fairly playable one for the black side too. }
4... dxe5 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8 6. Bc4
{ The game has barely started, and an endgame is already here. Black's biggest pro is that the pawn structure is perfect, so he only needs to develope his pieces in order to obtain a fine position. The con is that it's impossible to castle, making the task more difficult. Black now has to make a decision on how to defend the pawn on f7: }
6... Be6
{ I must admit that it's baffling to me that this move is the most played move in the position. Black willingly gives himself an inferior pawn structure, resulting in a position where only White can play for a win. }
7. Bxe6 fxe6 8. f3
{ Defending the pawn is the first matter of business. From here, Black has a wide range of different set-ups: }
8... Bb4
{ My engine prefers this move, but it's played very seldom.   8...Bd6  Is the most played move, when  9.Nh3  We are likely to transpose to lines in the chapter. }
9. Ne2
{ This time our knight will be placed on e2 instead, preventing Black from giving us doubled pawns after Bxc3. }
9... Nc6 10. Be3 Ke7 11. O-O-O a6
{ Black usually plays this move, like in the early variation we have taken a look at.   11...Rad8  12.Rxd8  Rxd8  The game Sebestyen,B - Solomons,D Budapest 2006 was soon drawn here, but White would have been better after  13.Nd1  Our knights aren't ideally placed, so we should place them on better squares. We will slowly improve our position, by moves like c3-Kc2-Nc1-Nd3-b3-Bd2-Ne3-Nc4, etc. Black will suffer as he can't do much, but I can't deny that the drawing chances obviously exist but in chess, they always do : }
12. Na4
{ Looks like the strongest move, eyeing the c5-square, and making way for the pawn on c2. }
12... b6 { The human move is to prevent the knight jump to c5. } 13. Kb1
{ Looks odd, but it allows us to maneuver the e2 knight to c1, where it can reach the d3-square. }
13... Rhd8 14. Rxd8 Rxd8 15. c3
{ The position is easy to play for us, and again, due to Black's doubled pawns, clearly better. }
15... Bd6 16. b3
{ The theory section can stop here. Black has to suffer in an endgame with pretty much zero chances of winning, while we can freely maneuver our pieces. }
