[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "15. Philidor"]
[Black "3...e5 (4.Nge2 Informational)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nge2
{ Here are some of my findings of the alternate moves: the text move is a weapon I considered, as the positions aren't too difficult to play for White. The plan is to develop by the means of g3-Bg2-O-O-h3-Be3 and maybe someday create a kingside attack. The engine assured me that Black had no problems after a quick d5-break in the main tabiya of this line.   4.Nf3  is obviously the most common move, and I did indeed take a look. After  4...Nbd7  , White needs to decide which direction he wants to take the game.  5.g4!?  has been known for a long time to be dangerous, but theory has well established that all the complications end in a draw.  5.Rg1  is a fairly new move, aiming to get the kingside attack without the loss of a pawn. I originally intended to go for the line. Unfortunately, Black has too many playable options up his sleeve.  5...g6  ,  5...h6  ,  5...c6  and even  5.. .h5  , are viable tries. The tricky positions and the overwhelming amount of theory were not worth it to me, so I decided to ditch that ambitious project.  A black player will surely be well prepared here as it is White's most common way to proceed, and arguably what he wants as he gets the type of position he is asking for out of the opening. Sure, the space advantage gives us a slight edge, but that's it. Engine games and correspondence games showed me that Black's position is in a pretty okay shape, so I was dissatisfied. The text move also gives us a slight edge, but our position is easier to handle and a lot less complex. I should also mention the psychological damage this line has on the black player, as this is the last thing Black is hoping for when playing the Philidor - defending a worse endgame with limited winning chances. Having all these thoughts considered - the decision seemed like a no-brainer to me! In case you are interested in investigating something else, I encourage you to take a look at  5.Rg1  with its complex and fascinating positions. Anyways, I digress, so let's get back to the theory! }
