[White "15. Philidor"]
[Black "3...e5 (6...Be6 4)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5
{ This is the best and most common way to reach the Philidor Defense, named after the famous 18th century player Francois-André Danican Philidor. }
4. dxe5 dxe5 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8 6. Bc4
{ The game has barely started, and an endgame is already here. } 6... Be6
{ I must admit that it's baffling to me that this move is the most played move in the position. Black willingly gives himself an inferior pawn structure, resulting in a position where only White can play for a win. }
7. Bxe6 fxe6 8. f3
{ Defending the pawn is the first matter of business. From here, Black has a wide range of different set-ups: }
8... Nc6 9. Be3
{ Similar to the 8... Bc5-line, our bishop belongs on the e3-square. } 9... Bd6
{ Overwhelmingly the most played move in the position, also because play can transpose if Black plays 8... Bd6 first. }
10. Nh3 { Once again the knight maneuver f2-d3 is strong. } 10... Ke7
{ This is the usual way for Black to coordinate his pieces. } 11. Nf2 a6
{ A common plan for Black is to expand on the queenside. } 12. Nb1
{ A highly sophisticated move as White aims to place the knight on the improved d2-square. Another important fact is that c3 will soon be playable, preventing Black from jumping into d4 or b4. }
12... h6
{ A prophylactic move, preventing Bg5 in some lines. Note that a knight jump to b4 or d4 is easily dealt with by the means of Kd1. When Black puts a rook on d8, we will move our knight to d2 where it shields everything. c3 comes next, chasing Black's knight away. }
13. c3 { Taking control of the d4-square. } 13... Nd7
{ The knight doesn't do much on f6, so maneuvering it to c5 makes some sense. }
14. Nd2 b5 15. Ke2 { White's position is easy to handle and very comfortable. }
15... Na5
{ Happened in one game where Black aimed to grab more queenside space with c5.   15...Bc5  Trading the poor bishop makes some sense.  16.Bxc5+  Nxc5  17.Nb3  Chasing away the knight on c5 so we can place our knight on the ideal d3-square.  17...Nxb3   17...Na4  is met by  18.Nd3  .  18.axb3  a5  19.Rhd1  We have a clearly better endgame. }
16. g3
{ A subtle move taking control over the majority of key squares on the 4th rank. }
16... c5 17. Rhc1 c4 { And now, the thematic } 18. b4
{ The point is that we're fixing the pawn structure. If Black captures the pawn, we have managed to open the a-file. He will have to move the knight, when we can play a4 and apply pressure down the a-file. Playing a4 right away gives Black the possibility of playing b4 in some cases, hence why we play b4 first. }
18... Nb7
{ Was a massive error.  18...Nc6  was better, but Black is still worse after  19.a4  . }
19. a4
{ A rook maneuver to a2 will hurt for Black. Valenzuela Gomez,F - Llopis de Aysa,M Sitges 2020. }
