1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5
{ This is the best and most common way to reach the Philidor Defense, named after the famous 18th century player Francois-André Danican Philidor. }
4. dxe5 dxe5 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8 6. Bc4
{ The game has barely started, and an endgame is already here. } 6... Ke8
{ This side-step is a logical way to defend the pawn, and the suggested reaction by Ginger-GM in 'The Black Lion.' }
7. f4
{ This looks like the best way to aim for an advantage, and not considered by Simon in 'The Black Lion.' It's not so surprising that he doesn't mention it, because the move has been seen in a few number of games. }
7... Bd6
{ It's important to note that  7...Nc6  and  7...Nbd7  will most likely transpose to this line after  8.Nf3  , as Black doesn't have any decent alternatives to  8...Bd6  .   7...Bc5?  Doesn't work.  8.fxe5  Ng4  9.Nf3  Nc6  10.Nd5  Black will lose material.  10...Ncxe5  11.Nxc7+  The accurate response.  11...Kd7  12.Bf4  Is a very strong move, because we get O-O-O with a tempo.  12...Nxc4  13.O-O-O+  Ke7  14.Nxa8  Nf2  Black wins back the exchange, but he will be a clean pawn down.  15.Nc7  Nxh1  16.Nd5+  Ke8  17.Rxh1  White is a clear pawn up and Black has no compensation. }
8. Nf3 Nc6 { Less popular than  8...Nbd7  , but it's a stronger move. } 9. Bb5
{ It takes the engine a depth of 52 to realize that this is better than the pawn-sacrifice  9.Nb5  . The text move threatens to win a piece with  fxe5  , so Black has to play }
9... Nd7 10. g3 { It's important that we keep our center intact. } 10... a6
{ I must admit that I for one second thought Black could castle, but the king has already moved! The text move is a logical try. Other alternatives are simply met by Be3 followed by long castle. }
11. Bxc6 bxc6 12. Be3
{ The engine thinks that Black is doing okay, but practically it looks a lot easier to handle the white pieces. }
12... a5
{ I think this move makes a lot of sense, as Black gets a nice place for the bishop on a6. }
13. O-O-O f6
{ Black has to guard the pawn on  e5  in order to make progress. Note that  13...Ba6  is met by a capture on  e5  followed by  Bd4  , when Black will suffer in the endgame. The bishop pair is all gone and our knight will find a nice home on  c5  . }
14. a3
{ A prophylactic move, preventing Black from playing Bb4. The plan forward is to create a pawn storm on the kingside with f5-g4-g5. }
14... Ke7 15. f5 { We proceed with our kingside plan. } 15... Ba6 16. g4
{ Our breakthrough will be to play g5 and double our rook on the g-file. }
16... h6 17. h4 Nb6
{ Black has to do something, so it makes sense to place the knight on c4. } 18.
Nd2 Nc4 19. Nxc4 Bxc4 20. Rh2
{ White is in the driving seat and is essentially playing a game where the risk of losing is close to zero. White will prepare the g5-break to the best of his ability, for instance by doubling in the h or g-file. The knight could also move to a4 and from there to c5. Black is only tiny worse according to the engine, but luckily for us, a human being will defend the position: }
