[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "15. Philidor"]
[Black "3...e5 (6...Ke8 3)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5
{ This is the best and most common way to reach the Philidor Defense, named after the famous 18th century player Francois-André Danican Philidor. }
4. dxe5 dxe5 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8 6. Bc4
{ The game has barely started, and an endgame is already here. } 6... Ke8
{ This side-step is a logical way to defend the pawn, and the suggested reaction by Ginger-GM in 'The Black Lion.' }
7. f4
{ This looks like the best way to aim for an advantage, and not considered by Simon in 'The Black Lion.' It's not so surprising that he doesn't mention it, because the move has been seen in a few number of games. }
7... Bd6 8. Nf3 Nbd7
{ Black has gone for this move in most of the games I found in my base, but it's clear that the knight is better placed on c6. }
9. g3 { The best way forward is once again to support the center. } 9... a6
{ Controlling the b5-square. } 10. a4
{ It's clear that our advantage is gone if we allow Black to play b5. } 10...
b6 11. Bd2
{ White has only castled kingside in the games I found, but castling queenside is even better! }
11... Bb7 12. O-O-O b5
{ I discovered this line which was rather spectacular. Black's point is that if we grab the pawn on b5, the a-file will be opened and the pawn on e4 can be captured.   12...Nxe4  Is met by the trick  13.Nxe4  Bxe4  14.Bxf7+  Kf8?   14...Kxf7  is best, when we are clearly better after  15.Ng5+  Ke7  16.Nxe4  , when  Rhe1  will follow suit. The text move is only mentioned because I just want to show that our tactic is justified.  15.Rhf1  Bxf3  16.Rxf3   16...Kxf7  is met by  17.fxe5+  , when the bishop on  d6  falls.  16...e4  17.Bd5  Everything has worked out and White has obtained a winning advantage. }
13. Bb3 b4 { The critical move. } 14. fxe5
{ The path for survival for Black is narrow as the following sequence shows: }
14... bxc3 15. Bf4 { Protecting the pawn on e5. } 15... cxb2+ 16. Kxb2 g5
{ A fantastic move.   16...Nxe5  Gives us a good game after  17.Bxe5  Nxe4  18.Bxg7  Rg8  19.Bd4  Nxg3!  Being greedy is the way to go for Black.  20.Rhe1+  Ne4  Otherwise the trick fails as any king move is met by Ne5 when White is completely winning.  21.Re2  White has a powerful initiative, so Black has to play very accurately in order to save the game. }
17. Bxg5 Nxe4 18. exd6 Nxg5
{ Now, a nice detail is that if we check Black's king he can place the knight in between on e6. }
19. Nxg5 Bxh1 20. Nxf7 Rg8
{ The only move as  20...Rf8  is met by  21.Re1+  of course. } 21. Rxh1
{ White is now threatening to take on c7 followed by Nd6. Note also that Black can't take our pawn on d6 because the rook on g8 will hang. }
21... Nc5
{ is refuted by   21...Rg7?  Loses as well, after  22.Re1+  Kf8  23.Rf1  Ke8  24.dxc7  Nb6  Is one way to defend, when there is a lot of ways to win.  25.Rd1  Is one way, when one continuation could be:  25...Rxf7  26.Rd8+  Rxd8  27.Bxf7+  Kd7  28.cxd8=Q+  The resulting endgame is dead lost.  28...Kxd8  29.a5  Black is dead lost.   21...Rg6!!  A fantastic resource. The point is that Black guards the crucial d6-square.  22.dxc7  Rc8  Black has to hurry up and grab the pawn. All other moves lose after Nd8-Ne6.  23.Nd8  Rxc7  24.Ne6  Ra7!  Another accurate move.  25.Re1  Black still needs to be accurate, but he has survived the worst with superb play. }
22. Re1+ Kf8 23. dxc7 { Black can't stop the pawn from queening. } 23... Nxb3
24. Nd6
{ The pawn will promote, when the resulting endgame is completely lost for Black. }
