1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5
{ This is the best and most common way to reach the Philidor Defense, named after the famous 18th century player Francois-André Danican Philidor. }
4. dxe5 dxe5 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8 6. Bc4
{ The game has barely started, and an endgame is already here. } 6... Ke8
{ This side-step is a logical way to defend the pawn, and the suggested reaction by Ginger-GM in "The Black Lion." }
7. f4
{ This looks like the best way to aim for an advantage, and not considered by Simon in "The Black Lion." It's not so surprising that he doesn't mention it, because the move has been seen in a few number of games. }
7... Bb4
{ A very logical move so it's not surprising its on top of the list in popularity. }
8. Bd3
{ We must defend the e4-pawn. The exclam is there because it's the only testing move. }
8... Nc6 9. Nf3 Bg4
{ Is the lesser evil, but I still think Black has nothing to jump for joy about after   9...Bxc3+  10.bxc3  Be6  GM Bosiocic won a game here, but this is not very fun for Black.  11.O-O  a6  12.a4  Black's position is simply put, TERRIBLE.   9...Be6  Is met by  10.a3!  Forcing Black to hand over the bishop pair.  10...Bxc3+  11.bxc3  Our bishop pair, central control and Black's vulnerable king are all factors that justify the evaluation. }
10. fxe5 Nd7 11. Bf4 Bxf3 12. gxf3 Ncxe5 13. Be2
{ Some strong encounters have had this position and the score is 50% I definitely believe that having the White pieces is much easier, though. }
13... Ke7 { Black's only victory was with this move when I suggest } 14. Bd2
{ Keeping it simple, avoiding the double pawns. Black is clearly worse. } 14...
Bxc3 15. Bxc3
{ Our bishop pair will be a thorn in Black's side. Black's position looks lost if you ask me, but I can't get myself to give more than a clear edge. }
