[White "15. Philidor"]
[Black "3...e5 (6...Bb4 2)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5
{ This is the best and most common way to reach the Philidor Defense, named after the famous 18th century player Francois-André Danican Philidor. }
4. dxe5 dxe5 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8 6. Bc4
{ The game has barely started, and an endgame is already here. } 6... Bb4
{ The most active way of defending the pawn is to attack our pawn on e4. } 7.
Bxf7 Nxe4
{ Leela's choice and the most accurate way of playing. Therefore I have rewarded the move with an exclam. }
8. Ne2 Bf5
{ Black should once again stick to this active approach.   8...Ke7?!  Became quickly uncomfortable for Black.  9.Bd5  Nf6  10.Bd2  c6  11.Bf3  Bf5  12.O-O-O  Black was under immense pressure in Firouzja,A - Bortnyk,O Lichess.org INT 2020. The rook is headed to e1 along with a knight to g3, when it seems like the pawn on e5 is in huge trouble. We can also play a3, attacking the bishop. The strong prodigy did indeed prevail in the end. }
9. Be3
{ One major difference here is that our bishop isn't on b3, protecting the c-pawn. Thus, Black can play }
9... Nxc3
{ If we take with the knight, the c2-pawn is hanging, so we have to take with the pawn. }
10. bxc3 Ba3 { A natural move, preventing us from castling queenside. } 11.
Rd1+ Nd7 12. Bb3
{ Protecting the targeted pawn on c2. We don't have much, but the fact that Stockfish defeated Leela in this position means that we are definitely in the driving seat. Our plan forward is to harass the strong f5-bishop by playing Ng3-h4-h5. }
12... Bd6
{ I found this move in two correspondence games, where Black drew both games. }
13. Ng3 Bg6 14. h4
{ As I stated, we want to chase the bishop away by playing h5. If we are allowed to jump to f5 with the knight, Black would be in major trouble. }
14... h6 15. h5 Bh7
{ Now is a critical moment. White was unable to create anything with  16.Bd5  in Grigoryev, V - Malnar, A ICCF email 2017 & Schulz, G ICCF email 2018 respectively, but the improved engines have found an improvement. }
16. Rh4
{ The rook can now use the 4th rank to target Black's pawns, while it also controls the e4-square, making Bd5-Be4 a pretty viable maneuver. If the light-squared bishops are off, we get the typical pressure in the ending. }
16... Nf6 { Is Black's best try, preventing our Bd5-Be4 idea. } 17. c4
{ Change of plans. c5 is now a threat which can best be defended by playing }
17... b6 18. c5 bxc5 19. Bxc5 Ke7 20. Rc4
{ White maintains the pressure in the endgame. } *

