{ One major difference here is that our bishop isn't on b3, protecting the c-pawn. Thus, Black can play }
9... Nxc3
{ If we take with the knight, the c2-pawn is hanging, so we have to take with the pawn. }
10. bxc3 Ba3 { A natural move, preventing us from castling queenside. } 11.
Rd1+ Nd7 12. Bb3
{ Protecting the targeted pawn on c2. We don't have much, but the fact that Stockfish defeated Leela in this position means that we are definitely in the driving seat. Our plan forward is to harass the strong f5-bishop by playing Ng3-h4-h5. }
12... Re8 { Leela's choice was this rook swing to e8. } 13. h4 Be6
{ The point of Re8 is now revealed, but it does weaken the control of the e4-square. }
14. h5 h6 15. Ng3 Ke7 16. Rh4
{ The h4-square is a useful post for the h1-rook. Here, it's biggest job is that it covers the square on e4. }
16... Nf6 17. Ke2 { Improving our pieces. } 17... Rh8
{ A bizarre move, but I am sure Leela had a reason for placing the rook there. }
18. Bxe6 Kxe6 19. Ne4
{ The main strategy for White will be to dominate on the light-squares, a strategy that ultimately succeeds as we shall see. }
19... Be7 20. c4
{ Placing the pawns on the opposite color of the bishop is a nice strategy to remember. }
20... b6 21. a4 Rab8
{ Black doesn't have too much to do, so she simply makes waiting moves. } 22.
Rdh1 Rhg8 23. g3 Kf5
{ I have a feeling Leela missed the following continuation when calculating moves earlier. It's biggest weakness is that it has a tendency to miss tactics. }
24. Nxf6 Bxf6 25. Re4
{ A wonderful move. White maintains the control of the light-squares, meaning that the strategy is one step further in succeeding. The rook can't be taken as Black's king won't avoid a mate after g4 followed by f3. }
25... Rge8 26. g4+ Ke6 27. Rb1 { White's pressure is getting stronger. } 27...
a6 { Leela prevents Stockfish from playing a5. } 28. f4 Kd7 29. f5
{ White has obtained full control on the light squares, so I suspect the position is close to objectively lost. I will end the theory section here, but I will leave the rest of the game as a clickable as it is incredibly instructive to see how Stockfish prevails.  29...Kc6  30.Bd2  Rbd8  31.Bc3  Rd7  32.Kf3  Stockfish is maneuvering his pieces to ideal squares, but it takes some triangulation to make it happen. Watch and enjoy.  32...Kc5  33.Rbe1  Ree7  34.Kg2  Re8  35.Kg3  a5  36.R1e3  Kd6  37.Bb2  Kc5  38.Kf3  Kd6  39.Rb3  Kc6  40.Rd3  My engine's advantage has increased and its close to decisive levels.  40...Ree7  41.Rxd7  Kxd7  One rook is off the board and from here it's easy. White will grab control of the d-file and place the king on the beautiful e4-square.  42.Ba3  Re8  43.Re3  The only move that wins, as it is important that White can take control of the d-file  43...Kc6  44.Ke4  Rd8  45.Rd3  Rb8  46.Rd5  White has full control, so from here it's easy.  46. ..Re8  47.Bc1  Rh8  48.Be3  Ra8  49.Rb5  Kd7  50.c5  bxc5  51.Bxc5  Ke8  52.Be3  Ke7  53.c4  Kd6  54.Bd2  c6  55.c5+  Kc7  56.Rb1  Kd7  57.Rb7+  Ke8  58.Rc7  Rd8  59.Bc3  Rd1  60.Rxc6  Rc1  61.Bxa5  Ra1  62.Kd5  Rxa4  63.Bb6  Kf7  64.Rc7+  Be7  65.c6  Kf6  66.Ra7  Rxg4  67.c7  Rb4  68.c8Q  Kg5  69.Rxe7  Kf4  70.Qc1+  Kf3  71.Qf1+  Kg3  72.Rxg7+  Rg4  Leela finally resigned in Stockfish Latest - LCZeroCPU Latest TCEC-chess 2020. About time if you ask me! A terrific display by Stockfish, showing that  4.dxe5  is a serious attempt for a win. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "15. Philidor"]
[Black "Phillidor Conclusion"]
[Result "*"]

{ CONCLUSION: Our Philidor started with the line that Ginger-GM labels as 'The Risky Lion' in 'The Black Lion' course. A very accurate description, as it turns out that the engines do not approve Black's position at all. }
1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5
{ The best approach for Black from a theoretical standpoint. As I stated in my description of the line, this is by no means a bad opening! Black is solid and scores very acceptably in engine games. The downside is that Black becomes passive, but it's not the end of the world for players who enjoy those types of positions.   3...Nbd7  4.f4  e5  5.Nf3  exd4  6.Qxd4  c6  7.Bd2  Qb6  heading into an endgame that is at least slightly better for us.   7...d5  Simon William's 7... d5 is a cool line, but objectively unsound as Black is not doing well in the correspondence chess games. It seems like we can fairly easily neutralize Black's initiative when we will be a clean pawn up for nothing. Overall, a wonderful scenario for us, }
4. dxe5
{ As our edge is minimal anyway, I suggest this psychologically damaging move. Black will obviously be unhappy when seeing this move on the board, while our analysis show it's a very viable choice! }
4... dxe5 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8 6. Bc4 Be6
{ has been the most common response, but the double-pawns give Black a serious headache. In these positions it's more important that you remember the ideas more than anything else, as you will more often than not make the same type of moves, like Nh3-f2-Nd3 and Nb1-Nd2. Black's position is not very fun to handle, and it also seems like the objective evaluation is quite high, making the 6... Be6 concept seems quite poor.   6...Ke8  is much better and more concrete.  7.f4  Black has to be careful as we gain some initiative towards the black king. In this case, you should try to memorize some lines as you are required to play accurately in order to test Black. There were lots of fun stuff here, especially the line with a6-b5. Black's probably alright, but he has to know what he's doing, otherwise, he could obtain a losing position in a nick of time. I must emphasize that the resulting positions are often at least slightly better for us, but more importantly, Black has pretty much zero chances of winning as he is forced to defend, defend and defend. Not a fun scenario to be in when opting for the Philidor!   6...Bb4  Last but not least, we have the engine line. Once again we remain slightly better in most cases, at least from a practical point of view. Black's problem is often the poor pawn on e5, which we can target. It's clear that things aren't so simple here, although the engines aren't so optimistic at first glance. After all, Stockfish brilliantly defeated Leela in this line! Do your homework and study 6... Bb4 & 6... Ke8 carefully. They will certainly become more popular than 6.. . Be6. The Philidor remains a highly playable opening, but the endgame takes a lot of fun from it for Black. }
