[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "16. Nimzowitch's Defense (1...Nc6)"]
[Black "2...d6 (3...Nb8)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nc6
{ This opening is called the 'Nimzowitch Defence,' a very rare breed. That being said, it is by far the best opening out of the rare openings out there. In fact, it remains highly playable, something that frustrated me immensely when I dealt with it. Black invites us to take the center, but will later on undermine our center with moves like c5 or f6 @@StartBracket@@especially in the 2... d5 line, which is Black's best bet@@EndBracket@@. Although the opening is surprisingly good, it is incredibly rare with only 36,000 games in my database. In comparison, the Alekhine Defence has over 115,000. Indeed, I have never faced this opening in my entire career, so you are not very likely to face it either. }
2. d4
{ Grabbing the center is the most principled approach. 2. Nf3 has been suggested by numerous authors, something I suspect they decided to do when they realized that Black's position in the 2... d5-lines is pretty acceptable.  2.Nf3  is a lazy approach, as this obviously can't be the way to take advantage of Black's concept, as  2...e5  transposes to mainstream theory. We should try to punish Black for his unusual first move, and our main move is the only way we can do so. }
2... d6
{ Might seem like a mouse-slip to you, but it's not. Black is provoking us into playing d5, when he has gotten a pawn structure that he desires. The price he has to pay for this is to be several tempos down a King's Indian, which can't be sound. }
3. d5 Nb8 { Black's better off by returning with the knight. } 4. c4 e5
{ Black can try this move already here and later on go for a f5-break. } 5. Nc3
g6
{ 5...f5  Has been played already here, but it looks like it's played too early.  6.exf5  The easiest is to grab the pawn and play on the light squares.  6...Bxf5  7.Nge2  The knight is headed to g3 and the bishop on d3 when our light-square control will be excellent.  7...Nf6  8.Ng3  Bg4  9.Qc2  Be7  10.Bd3  O-O  11.Nce4+-  White is in full control, so our coverage can end here. }
6. Bd3 Bg7 7. Nge2
{ I think the Sämisch set-up is the most effective, especially since the positions are easy to handle for White. }
7... Ne7 { Black can try to go for f5, when our best response is } 8. h4 h5 9.
Bg5 { Black has gotten a rough start to the game. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "16. Nimzowitch's Defense (1...Nc6)"]
[Black "2...d6 (3...Nb8 2)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nc6
{ The 'Nimzowitch Defence,' a very rare breed. That being said, it is by far the best opening out of the rare openings out there. }
2. d4 d6
{ Might seem like a mouse-slip to you, but it's not. Black is provoking us into playing d5, when he has gotten a pawn structure that he desires. The price he has to pay for this is to be several tempos down a King's Indian, which can't be sound. }
3. d5 Nb8 { Black's better off by returning with the knight. } 4. c4 Nf6 5. Nc3
g6
{ Black goes for a King's Indian with two tempos down. The d4-pawn would have been better placed on d4 at the moment, but that doesn't make Black's play sound. Logical moves will maintain our control. }
6. h3
{ Preventing Black from playing Bg4 and trading his bishop for our knight. Bg4 is a normal strategy for Black who then could be getting some control on the dark squares, the e5-square in particular, so let's prevent it. }
6... Bg7 7. Nf3 a5
{ A typical King's Indian move. Black controls the b4-square and will soon place a knight on c5, when we won't be able to chase it away with b4. }
8. Bd3 Na6 9. Be3
{ As I stated, no fancy moves are required from us. Just simple development moves. }
9... e6 { A logical move, fighting against our center. } 10. O-O O-O 11. Re1
Re8 12. Rc1 { White puts his rook in the half open files. } 12... b6
{ Black has fairly decent control of the dark squares in the position, but our advantage is stable due to our extra space. }
13. Bc2 { Prophylaxis against Nc5. } 13... exd5
{ A bit early, but extremely natural.  13...Nc5  is better, when we should respond with  14.Qd2  and take with the e-pawn if Black takes on  d5  . }
14. cxd5 { 14.exd5  was equally strong. } 14... Nc5 15. Bd4 Bb7
{ Black has completed his development, but we can now remove the strong knight on c5 with the typical }
16. a3 c6 17. b4 { We are faster than Black. } 17... axb4 18. axb4 Ncd7 19.
dxc6 Bxc6 20. Bb3 { Targeting the pawns on f7 and d6. } 20... h6 21. Qd3 Re7
{ So far, we have been following Prizant,J - Stukalov, A Pushchino 2013 when the most precise way forward would have been to play }
22. Be3 Rc8 { Note that  22...Nxe4  doesn't work due to  23.Nd5  . } 23. Qxd6
Bxe4 24. Nxe4 Rxe4 25. Qd2 { Our initiative gives us a decisive advantage. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "16. Nimzowitch's Defense (1...Nc6)"]
[Black "2...d6 (3...Nb8 3)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nc6
{ The 'Nimzowitch Defence,' a very rare breed. That being said, it is by far the best opening out of the rare openings out there. }
2. d4 d6
{ Might seem like a mouse-slip to you, but it's not. Black is provoking us into playing d5, when he has gotten a pawn structure that he desires. The price he has to pay for this is to be several tempos down a King's Indian, which can't be sound. }
3. d5 Nb8 { Black's better off by returning with the knight. } 4. c4 Nf6 5. Nc3
g6
{ Black goes for a King's Indian with two tempos down. The d4-pawn would have been better placed on d4 at the moment, but that doesn't make Black's play sound. Logical moves will maintain our control. }
6. h3
{ Preventing Black from playing Bg4 and trading his bishop for our knight. Bg4 is a normal strategy for Black who then could be getting some control on the dark squares, the e5-square in particular, so let's prevent it. }
6... Bg7 7. Nf3 O-O 8. Bd3 e5
{ Leads to the Makogonov Variation in the King's Indian, but Black is down two tempos.   8...e6  9.O-O  exd5  Is definitely natural, but our position remains clearly better after  10.cxd5  Re8  11.Re1  Nbd7  12.Bg5±  Due to our extra space and better central control. }
9. g4
{ A highly aggressive push, taking away the h5-square for Black's knight on f6. This is the most testing option in the Makogonov, so it's not surprising that we go for it here as well. Note also that it's much harder for Black now to carry out the desired f5-break. }
9... a5 { The usual way to play for Black is to place a knight on c5. } 10. Be3
Na6 11. Nd2
{ The knight is well placed on d2 where it controls the e4-square. We also support the g4-pawn with the queen, so we can soon think of advancing on the kingside with h4-g5. }
11... Nd7
{ Black can also place this knight on c5 when the f5-break becomes more available.   11...Nc5  12.Be2  c6  13.h4  It's time to advance on the kingside!  13...cxd5  14.cxd5  Bd7  Black's only hope for counterplay is to launch his pawns on the queenside.  15.h5  a4  And now, instead of playing 16. f3, Naka should have played  16.h6  in Nakamura,H - Amin,B St. Petersburg 2018. Black's position is hopeless as we can see after  16...Bh8  17.g5  Ne8  18.b4!  Preventing Black from getting counterplay with Qa5.  18...axb3  19.axb3  19...Rc8  20.Ra7+-  White has excellent control on both sides of the board. }
12. a3 { Controlling the b4-square and maybe one day we can play b4 too. }
12... c6 13. h4 { The kingside launch begins. } 13... Ndc5 14. Bc2
{ This time we want to place the bishop here, so we can keep an eye out on Black's f5-break. }
14... Bd7
{ 14...f5?  Doesn't work due to  15.exf5  gxf5  16.gxf5  Bxf5  17.Bxf5  Rxf5  18.Nde4+-  Black is essentially busted as his king is too weak. Besides, our knight on e4 is fantastic. }
15. h5 cxd5 16. exd5 { This is important as  16.cxd5  allows  b5! } 16... Rc8
17. Qe2 { White has a powerful attack. } *

