1. e4 Nc6
{ The 'Nimzowitch Defence,' a very rare breed. That being said, it is by far the best opening out of the rare openings out there. }
2. d4 d6
{ Might seem like a mouse-slip to you, but it's not. Black is provoking us into playing d5, when he has gotten a pawn structure that he desires. The price he has to pay for this is to be several tempos down a King's Indian, which can't be sound. }
3. d5 Nb8 { Black's better off by returning with the knight. } 4. c4 Nf6 5. Nc3
g6
{ Black goes for a King's Indian with two tempos down. The d4-pawn would have been better placed on d4 at the moment, but that doesn't make Black's play sound. Logical moves will maintain our control. }
6. h3
{ Preventing Black from playing Bg4 and trading his bishop for our knight. Bg4 is a normal strategy for Black who then could be getting some control on the dark squares, the e5-square in particular, so let's prevent it. }
6... Bg7 7. Nf3 O-O 8. Bd3 c6
{ 8...e6  9.O-O  exd5  Is definitely natural, but our position remains clearly better after  10.cxd5  Re8  11.Re1  Nbd7  12.Bg5±  Due to our extra space and better central control. }
9. O-O a6
{ 9...e6  10.Re1  We are well prepared for the opening of the position.  10...cxd5  11.cxd5  exd5  12.exd5  Nbd7  13.Bf4  Nc5  14.Bf1±  Our position is easy to handle with moves like Qd2-Rc1-b4. We can also consider maneuvering the knight from f3-d2-c4. }
10. Be3
{ It's not magic - by simply placing our pieces on natural squares we are well prepared to meet whatever soup Black is stirring at us. }
10... b5
{ Unfortunately for Black, the desired break doesn't really work out. } 11.
cxb5 axb5
{ 11...cxb5  isn't much better as we have complete control with  12.Nd4  . }
12. dxc6 b4 13. Nd5 { And now, we win by force due to the cute line } 13...
Nxc6 14. Bb6 Qd7 15. Bb5 { Pinning the knight. } 15... Bb7
{ 15...Qb7  doesn't protect the knight, as Black loses the queen if he recaptures. }
16. Ne5
{ Was Moranda, W - Bartnicki, P Gorzow Wielkopolski 2008, when Black loses material. The nice point is that  16...dxe5  loses the queen after  17.Nxf6+  .  16...Qc8  fails to  17.Nxc6  when the fork on  e7  ensures Black's doom. }
