1. e4 Nc6
{ The 'Nimzowitch Defence,' a very rare breed. That being said, it is by far the best opening out of the rare openings out there. }
2. d4 d6
{ Might seem like a mouse-slip to you, but it's not. Black is provoking us into playing d5, when he has gotten a pawn structure that he desires. The price he has to pay for this is to be several tempos down a King's Indian, which can't be sound. }
3. d5 Ne5 4. f4
{ Gaining yet another tempo on the knight and increased central control. } 4...
Nd7 { Is the lesser evil, but that doesn't make the line good. } 5. Nf3 c6 6.
c4 { Our center is too strong. } 6... Nc5
{ Black's knight has had a pretty fascinating journey. Nc6-e5-d7-c5. It's obvious that this concept can't possibly work. }
7. Nc3 Nf6 8. Qd4
{ This move is never played before, which is slightly surprising. The queen covers everything, while she supports the e5-break. }
8... cxd5
{ 8...Qa5  Is an interesting way to trick us, threatening Ncxe4 and Nb3.  9.e5!  Nb3 is nothing to be concerned about.  9...Nb3  10.Qd1  Nxa1  11.exf6+-  Black's extra exchange won't last long, as there is no way the knight on a1 leaves unscorched. }
9. cxd5 e6
{ The engine suggests that Black tries to decrease the strength of our center. }
10. b4 { Black's knight is forced to move yet again... } 10... Na6 11. dxe6
fxe6 12. Bb2 { White is way too active. } 12... Be7 13. a3
{ Supporting the pawn on b4. } 13... O-O 14. Bc4 { Pressuring the pawn on e6. }
14... Nc7 15. Rd1 d5
{ Trying to fight off our forces, but our power is too strong. } 16. exd5 exd5
17. Nxd5 Ncxd5 18. Qe5
{ The point is that we want to take the knight with the rook, not the bishop! Black can't recapture due to the mate on g7. }
18... Kh8 19. Rxd5
{ 19.Bxd5  gives Black an insane amount of counterplay after  19...Bd6  . }
19... Qb6 20. Bb5
{ The last accuracy. Preventing Black from causing havoc in the e-file. The queen on b6 is also in trouble as Bd4 comes next. }
