[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "16. Nimzowitch's Defense (1...Nc6)"]
[Black "2...e5 (4...h5 2)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nc6
{ The 'Nimzowitch Defence,' a very rare breed. That being said, it is by far the best opening out of the rare openings out there. }
2. d4 e5
{ Is one move Black can try in this position, but it seems like his position will become rather passive. }
3. d5
{ I think this is the best shot for an edge.  3.Nf3  is the Scotch of course, if you fancy that instead. }
3... Nce7 4. h4
{ This move makes it harder for Black to develop his pieces, as we can often meet g6 or Ng6 by h5. If Black plays h5 himself, the square on g5 will become rather weak. }
4... Nf6 5. f3
{ I like playing this move right away as we are going to do so anyway at some point. I want to avoid placing the knight on c3 for now, so we can further reinforce our center with c4 first. }
5... h5
{ Black should do this if he wants to complete his development.   5...g6?!  Is a weak move, because of  6.Bg5  Bg7  7.d6!  Making use of the fact that Black hasn't played d6.  7...cxd6  8.Qxd6  Qb6  And now the endgame is very good for us after  9.Qxb6  axb6  10.Bb5  O-O  11.c4+-  We have full control. The engine gives a decisive advantage already, and I agree as Black has absolutely no counterplay. }
6. Be3 d6 { Not as common as the text move, but highly logical of course. } 7.
c4 g6 8. Nc3 Neg8
{ Black's best bet is to place the bishop on  f8  on the active h6-square.  8...Bg7?  is far too passive, when we will continue with business as usual with  9.Qd2  . }
9. Bg5
{ I think it's best to face Black's plan by placing the bishop here, where Black has to play Bh6 and take in order to get rid of it. }
9... Bh6 10. g3
{ First of all, we can play Bh3 and trade off the 'weak' light-squared bishop, but more importantly we can play f4 in order to defend the pawn on g5 when Black takes on g5. }
10... Bxg5 { Black has to play concretely. } 11. hxg5 Nh7 12. f4 f6
{ Black has to fight back asap, otherwise his position will fall apart. } 13.
Be2 { A good move, threatening to take on h5. } 13... fxg5
{ Taking immediately is possible too. } 14. fxe5
{ Necessary, as  14.Bxh5  is met by  14...Nf8! } 14... dxe5 15. Nf3 Ngf6
{ Our center becomes too powerful after  15...Qe7  16.c5!  Qxc5  17.Nxe5  . }
16. Qa4+
{ A strong move when our queen can move to the a3-f8 diagonal, preventing Black from castling. }
16... Bd7 17. Qa3 { Preventing Black from castling. } 17... Ng4
{ Black has to defend the pawn on e5 and this is the only way to do so. } 18.
O-O-O { Black's position is on the verge of collapse. } 18... Kf7
{ A pretty clever resource, the king seeks shelter on g7.   18...Qe7  can be met by  19.d6!  when White is breaking through. }
19. c5
{ The only way to get an edge is to advance the pawn to this square, when it will reach c6-next. Also, Nb5 is also in the air along with Qb3. }
19... Kg7 20. c6 Bc8 21. cxb7 Bxb7 22. Na4
{ The knight will be very strong on the c5-square. } 22... Nf2
{ Leads to a very interesting position. } 23. Nc5 Bc8 24. Nxe5
{ We sacrifice the exchange for a very powerful initiative. } 24... Nxd1 25.
Rxd1 Qf6 { Black has to place the queen in this diagonal. } 26. Ncd7 Qd6 27.
Qc3 { It looks like our initiative is too powerful for Black. } 27... Bxd7 28.
Nxd7+ Nf6 29. Bb5
{ Rf1 will come when we will win back the exchange with an objectively winning position. }
