{ Is one move Black can try in this position, but it seems like his position will become rather passive. }
3. d5
{ I think this is the best shot for an edge.  3.Nf3  is the Scotch of course, if you fancy that instead. }
3... Nce7 4. h4
{ This move makes it harder for Black to develop his pieces, as we can often meet g6 or Ng6 by h5. If Black plays h5 himself, the square on g5 will become rather weak. }
4... Nf6 5. f3
{ I like playing this move right away as we are going to do so anyway at some point. I want to avoid placing the knight on c3 for now, so we can further reinforce our center with c4 first. }
5... h5 { Black should do this if he wants to complete his development. } 6.
Be3 d6 { Not as common as the text move, but highly logical of course. } 7. c4
g6 8. Nc3 Neg8
{ Black's best bet is to place the bishop on  f8  on the active h6-square.  8...Bg7?  is far too passive, when we will continue with business as usual with  9.Qd2  . }
9. Bg5
{ I think it's best to face Black's plan by placing the bishop here, where Black has to play Bh6 and take in order to get rid of it. }
9... Bh6 10. g3
{ First of all, we can play Bh3 and trade off the 'weak' light-squared bishop, but more importantly we can play f4 in order to defend the pawn on g5 when Black takes on g5. }
10... Bxg5 { Black has to play concretely. } 11. hxg5 Nh7 12. f4 f6
{ Black has to fight back asap, otherwise his position will fall apart. } 13.
Be2 { A good move, threatening to take on h5. } 13... exf4 14. gxf4 fxg5
{ Leads to a piece sacrifice for Black, but it's good for us. } 15. Qd4 Qf6 16.
Qxf6 Ngxf6 17. e5
{ We are down a pawn for the time being, but our center is incredibly strong. }
17... Ng4 { A more humane move if you ask me. } 18. e6 O-O
{ 18...gxf4?  Fails to  19.Nb5!  The c7-move is a target which is difficult to defend.  19...Kd8  20.Bxg4  Now Black has massive problems in the h-file.  20...hxg4  21.Ne2  g5  22.Kf2+-  Black is completely destroyed. A beautiful position. }
19. Bd3 { A strong move, targeting g6. } 19... Rf6
{ And now   19...Kg7  The most logical way to defend the g6-pawn.  20.Nh3  Targeting g5 while developing the knight.  20...gxf4  21.Nb5!  Once again we can target the solider on c7.  21...c6  22.Nxd6  Ne5  23.Bc2+-  Black's position is in dire straits. Our advantage just keeps climbing on my engine. }
20. f5 { Breaking through Black's little army of pawns. } 20... Ne5 21. Bc2
{ We obviously can't allow Black to grab our precious bishop. } 21... h4
{ Making sure that the pawn on h5 no longer hangs.   21...Nxc4  22.fxg6  Nf8  23.Rxh5+-  White's pawns are incredibly strong, so I think Black will have to sac a piece sooner or later. Then our extra material should decide. }
22. Nb5 { Once again targeting the pawn on c7. } 22... c6
{ There are many ways to win from here. } 23. fxg6
{ Is one of them, when a logical continuation is } 23... Nf8 24. Nc7 Rb8 25.
Ne8
{ A pretty sweet move to make. Note that  25.e7?  ruins everything after  25...Bd7!  when Black gets great compensation. }
25... Rf4 26. Nxd6 { Black's position is falling apart like a house of cards. }
