[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "16. Nimzowitch's Defense (1...Nc6)"]
[Black "2...d5 (2...e6)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nc6
{ The 'Nimzowitch Defence,' a very rare breed. That being said, it is by far the best opening out of the rare openings out there. }
2. d4 d5
{ The exclam is well-deserved because this is Black's best bet and only path to 'equality.' Black's aim is to get decent control on the light squares and later attack our center with a move like f6. The engines are surprisingly optimistic on Black's behalf, which was quite sensational to me when I took a look.   2...e6  Should transpose to the 2... d5-line.  3.Nf3  d5  Here, we have the luxury of transposing to either the French with 4. Nc3, or the coverage in the 2... d5-line with 4. e5.  4.e5  Looks best, as the resulting positions are better than the ones in the 3... Nc6-line in the French. }
3. e5
{ Advancing the pawn is the most testing continuation. We are gaining space and limiting Black's pieces @@StartBracket@@the knight for instance can't move to f6@@EndBracket@@.  3.exd5  is a good version for Black of the Scandinavian. }
3... e6
{ Is inaccurate, because we get a fantastic version of the Advanced French. }
4. Nf3 f6
{ The strong Serbian GM Indjic has played this move in blitz games. The move is not bad and extremely typical, attacking our center.   4...Nge7  5.c3  We will once again play c3-Bd3-Qe2. The moves come by themselves!  5...Nf5   The knight has to be placed here, because  5...Ng6  is met by  6.h4!  when Black has major problems.  6.Bd3  6...Be7  7.h4!?  This move looks strong to me.  7...h5  Played in all the human games I found, and for good reason. If we are allowed to play h5, we can soon follow up with g4, when Black's pieces will be pushed back.  8.Bg5  b6  Black tries to complete his development and castle to the queenside. 8... f6 is nothing to worry about as we can simply play 9. Bf4, when Black's kingside is weak.  9.Nbd2  Bb7  10.Qe2  Keeping options open. If Black castles kingside we will castle queenside, and vise versa.  10...Qd7  11.a4  Preparing an attack on the queenside.  11...O-O-O  Black goes for it anyway, as he has to castle somewhere.  12.a5  A strong move, but not the only road to Rome.  12...f6  13.Bf4  fxe5  And now, in Jansa,V - Markos,J Czech Republic 2011, the easiest way forward would have been to play  14.axb6!  Opening the a-file.  14...cxb6  15.Nxe5  Nxe5  16.Bxe5+-  Black's king will soon be surrounded by enemy pieces. The engine gives an advantage as high as +6 which may be surprising to you, but Black can't do anything about our upcoming assault. One strong plan is to play Nf3, followed by Bh2 and Ne5. }
5. c3
{ I suggest to play this move, taking control of the b4 square and protecting the d4-pawn. }
5... Nge7
{ A Bulgarian GM won a game with this move, so let's take a look.   5...fxe5  Black's most common move is to take right away, when I suggest to play  6.Nxe5!   I like this move more than  6.dxe5  , when Black can play  6...Nh6  .  6...Nxe5  7.dxe5±  The play from here is simple. We will play Nd2 and place the knight on f3. The bishop will be placed on d3 and the queen on e2. We can play f4 as well if we so desire. Later on we will castle queenside and start expanding on the queenside with a4-b4. }
6. Bd3 fxe5 { Black can't do much else. } 7. dxe5
{ The best way to capture although I will admit,  7.Nxe5  is also strong as in Freeman, D - Primrose, J ICCF email 2017. }
7... g6
{ Black tries to desperately develop his pieces, but it's easier said than done. }
8. h4
{ A strong move, White is going to play h5 and create weaknesses in Black's camp if he gets the chance. }
8... Bg7 9. Qe2 h6 { The idea behind this move is to meet h5 with g5. } 10. Na3
{ Is more accurate than  10.Bf4  , which happened in Dimitrov, P - Drenchev, P Plovdiv 2007. White's knight is headed to  c2  where it can support the queenside pawns or jump to  d4  . }
10... Bd7 11. Bd2 O-O 12. O-O-O
{ Our attack is more dangerous than Black's attack on the queenside, as demonstrated in the following variation: }
12... a6 13. Kb1 b5 14. Nc2
{ A strong move, preventing Black from playing b4 with a tempo. } 14... a5 15.
h5 g5 { And now, we break through with } 16. Bxg5 hxg5 17. h6 Bh8 18. h7+ Kg7
19. Nxg5 { Black's king won't survive for long. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "16. Nimzowitch's Defense (1...Nc6)"]
[Black "2...d5 (3...f6)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nc6
{ The 'Nimzowitch Defence,' a very rare breed. That being said, it is by far the best opening out of the rare openings out there. }
2. d4 d5
{ The exclam is well-deserved because this is Black's best bet and only path to 'equality.' Black's aim is to get decent control on the light squares and later attack our center with a move like f6. The engines are surprisingly optimistic on Black's behalf, which was quite sensational to me when I took a look. }
3. e5 f6
{ Can be played as early as in the third move, when I think we should respond by going for }
4. f4
{ 4.Bb5  was the move I intended to suggest, but I was unable to find a clear-cut way to a convincing edge. There was a lot of things to remember, so I simply didn't think it was worth it in the end, as the text move is likely to transpose to the mainline. }
4... Nh6 5. c3 Bg4
{ This is Black's attempt to steer the game towards another route than the main line, but I don't think it's such a good idea. }
6. Be2 Bxe2 7. Qxe2 e6
{ 7...Qd7?  is a mistake, because it allows  8.e6!  , when  g4  will follow suit. Black has major issues. }
8. Nh3
{ This looks strange to the eyes, but our plan is to place the b1-knight on f3 instead. }
8... Qd7 9. Nd2 Be7 10. Nf3 O-O
{ The safest bet for Black is to castle kingside. Placing the king on the queenside is riskier as our initiative could quickly become very powerful with moves like a4-b4. }
11. O-O f5
{ It's not so fun to make this move, but I think Black has to do it someday as the pawn on e6 could become very weak after exf6 at some point. }
12. Nf2 { White's space advantage grants him a clearly better position. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "16. Nimzowitch's Defense (1...Nc6)"]
[Black "2...d5 (3...Bf5)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nc6
{ The 'Nimzowitch Defence,' a very rare breed. That being said, it is by far the best opening out of the rare openings out there. }
2. d4 d5
{ The exclam is well-deserved because this is Black's best bet and only path to 'equality.' Black's aim is to get decent control on the light squares and later attack our center with a move like f6. The engines are surprisingly optimistic on Black's behalf, which was quite sensational to me when I took a look. }
3. e5 Bf5
{ Surprisingly enough, the position now resembles an advanced Caro-Kann. One of the key differences is that Black's f6-break is more effective because of the knight on c6. The downside to having the knight on c6 is that the c5 pawn break can't happen yet as the knight stands in the way. }
4. c3
{ Like in the other lines, we will play this move solidifying our pawn structure. }
4... h5
{ Looks very bizarre, but Black aims to create a potential attack on the kingside after he has castled long. }
5. Be2 Qd7 { Is a subtle trick, as the pawn on h5 is poisonous. } 6. Nf3
{ 6.Bxh5?  is refuted by  Bxb1!  when  Qf5  follows and we lose a piece. } 6...
h4
{ Black stops a potential knight jump to h4, while advancing with his pawns. Unfortunately for him, it doesn't seem like it's dangerous for us at all. }
7. h3 { Not necessary, but I like to fix the pawn structure. } 7... f6 8. Nbd2
e6 9. b4
{ Our attack is much stronger than Black's attack as demonstrated in the following e-mail games. }
9... Nge7
{ Black could attack e5 with a quick Ng6, but it is the same story here. Our play is much faster.   9...O-O-O  Black tried this in Cvak,,R - Kuusik,J ICCF email 2016, but was soon toast after  10.b5  Nb8  11.c4  Ne7  12.O-O  Qe8  13.c5+-  Black resigned already here, as the engine was showing an overwhelming advantage. White will some day play c6 with devastating consequences. It's worth mentioning that Black has no play on his own on the kingside, so no wonder why the evaluation is that high... }
10. Nb3 Ng6 11. O-O
{ Before we launch our forces at the black king, we should put our king to safety. }
11... O-O-O 12. a4 { ATTACK! } 12... Re8 13. b5
{ It's funny, the engine already gives more than +4... } 13... Nd8 14. c4 dxc4
15. Bxc4
{ White's position is totally dooming as you probably can tell. I leave the theory section here, but I will leave the rest of the e-mail game as a clickable, since Black did not last long.  15...fxe5  16.Qe2  exd4  17.Nfxd4  e5  18.b6!  A beautiful move!  18...cxb6  19.Bb5  Nc6  20.Nxf5  Qxf5  21.a5  Re6  22.a6  Kb8  23.axb7+-  White was breaking through, so Black threw in the towel in Bissmann, S - Morin, S ICCF email 2010. }
*

