1. e4 Nc6
{ The 'Nimzowitch Defence,' a very rare breed. That being said, it is by far the best opening out of the rare openings out there. }
2. d4 d5
{ The exclam is well-deserved because this is Black's best bet and only path to 'equality.' Black's aim is to get decent control on the light squares and later attack our center with a move like f6. The engines are surprisingly optimistic on Black's behalf, which was quite sensational to me when I took a look. }
3. e5 Bf5
{ Surprisingly enough, the position now resembles an advanced Caro-Kann. One of the key differences is that Black's f6-break is more effective because of the knight on c6. The downside to having the knight on c6 is that the c5 pawn break can't happen yet as the knight stands in the way. }
4. c3
{ Like in the other lines, we will play this move solidifying our pawn structure. }
4... f6
{ 4...Qd7  Can be played by Black, when we should respond with  5.Be2±  The play is likely to transpose to the 4... f6-line. }
5. f4 { Maintaining a strong center. } 5... e6 6. Nf3 Be7
{ Black's best bet is to try to castle as soon as possible, not wasting anytime with Qd7. }
7. Be2
{ Our moves remain the same. Develop our pieces, then expand on the queenside. }
7... Nh6 8. O-O O-O 9. exf6
{ Is an interesting way to proceed. There was nothing wrong with  9.Nbd2  of course. After the text move, we may attack the pawn on  e6  in the future, while we could also someday jump to the e5-square. }
9... Bxf6 10. Nbd2 a5
{ Makes more sense if you ask me, preventing our thematic pawn launch, while grabbing space.   10...Qe8!?  Was seen in a couple of Correspondence games, where Black managed to score half a point in both.  11.Ne1  White re-routes the knight from f3 to d3, and aims to put the d2-knight on the now vacant f3 square.  11...b6  Black would like to play c5 at some point. He also stops our knight from jumping to c5.  12.Nd3  Nd8  Black's best bet. The knight doesn't do much on c6, so it will have a better function on the b7-square, where it supports the c5-break. It can also move to d6 when it can eventually move to e4.   Note also that  12...Nf7  was poor do to  13.g4!  followed by  f5  .  13.Nf3  Be7  Black prepares for c5.  14.h3  Our way to make progress is to grab space with g4.  14...Nhf7  15.g4  Bg6  So far, we have followed Cleto,D - Latypov,M ICCF email 2017, when my engine shows me that  16.a4!  Is the most precise way to continue.  16...a5  17.Be3⩲  White has better prospects in the dynamic middlegame. }
11. a4 b6 { Black plays similarly to the previous note. } 12. h3
{ Again, if we want to achieve something we should limit Black's pieces by playing g4 at some point. }
12... Be7 13. g4 Bg6 14. Qe1 { The queen will be well placed on g3. } 14... Bd6
{ 14...Rxf4  was met by  15.Bb5  , when the pawn on  e6  falls. } 15. Ne5
{ White has a comfortable spacious position. } 15... Nxe5 16. dxe5
{ The right way to capture.  16.fxe5  allows  Rxf1!  when our initiative is fading away like merchandise on Black Friday. }
16... Bc5+ 17. Kh2 Nf7 18. Qg3
{ White's pawn majority on the kingside gives him a promising position. Black's pieces aren't ideally placed either, especially the poor knight on f7. White's ideas contain a potential f5-break or h4-h5 break or Nb3 followed by Be3 to trade the dark squared bishops. Indeed, White eventually won in the strong correspondence battle Romm,M - Stoeckert,M ICCF email 2019, a game I highly suggest that you check out. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "16. Nimzowitch's Defense (1...Nc6)"]
[Black "2...d5 (3...Bf5 3)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nc6
{ The 'Nimzowitch Defence,' a very rare breed. That being said, it is by far the best opening out of the rare openings out there. }
2. d4 d5
{ The exclam is well-deserved because this is Black's best bet and only path to 'equality.' Black's aim is to get decent control on the light squares and later attack our center with a move like f6. The engines are surprisingly optimistic on Black's behalf, which was quite sensational to me when I took a look. }
3. e5 Bf5
{ Surprisingly enough, the position now resembles an advanced Caro-Kann. One of the key differences is that Black's f6-break is more effective because of the knight on c6. The downside to having the knight on c6 is that the c5 pawn break can't happen yet as the knight stands in the way. }
4. c3
{ Like in the other lines, we will play this move solidifying our pawn structure. }
4... f6
{ 4...Qd7  Can be played by Black, when we should respond with  5.Be2±  The play is likely to transpose to the 4... f6-line. }
5. f4 { Maintaining a strong center. } 5... Qd7
{ Black has also tried this move here, when the option of castling queenside appears. }
6. Nf3 e6
{ 6...O-O-O?  is too dangerous. After  7.b4  , our attack on the queenside is much faster when a4-Nd2-Nb3-b5 will follow suit, similar to other positions in the chapter. }
7. Be2 Nh6 8. b4
{ Making O-O-O even less tempting for Black. Also, b4 grabs queenside space, which is essentially where we will place our pieces if Black castles kingside as well.   8.a4!?  with the same idea, was also strong as seen in the instructive game Kowalczyk, R - Wyzga Rybicki, W ICCF email 2018. }
8... Be7 9. O-O { Our play from here is straightforward. a4-Nbd2-Nb3-b4. } 9...
Bg6
{ Was tried by a 2300-player.  9...O-O  is met by  10.Nbd2  , with the mentioned plan. }
10. a4 O-O 11. Nbd2 { We continue with the same plan. } 11... a6
{ Black's best bet is to slow down our queenside initiative.   11...fxe5?  Was now a major error, due to  12.b5  Chasing away the knight, so we can soon capture on e5 with our stallion on f3.  12...Nd8  13.Nxe5  Qe8  14.Nxg6  Grabbing the strong bishop on g6 was a strong way to proceed, but not the only strong way.  14...hxg6  15.Nf3  Bd6  16.g3  Nf5  17.Bd3+-  Black's position had seen better days in the game Frolov,A - Ozenir,E Lvov 2018. }
12. Nb3 b6 13. a5
{ Black has gained some control, but it's still very unpleasant. } 13... Qc8
{ 13...b5?  is met by  14.Ne1!  when the knight is headed to  d3  and  c5  . On the board Black is highly passive, so we don't need to do anything fancy. }
14. h3 Nf5 15. Qe1
{ White is soon ready to carry out g4 on the kingside. Black is struggling to find moves. }
