[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "16. Nimzowitch's Defense (1...Nc6)"]
[Black "2...d5 (3...Bf5 4)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nc6
{ The 'Nimzowitch Defence,' a very rare breed. That being said, it is by far the best opening out of the rare openings out there. }
2. d4 d5
{ The exclam is well-deserved because this is Black's best bet and only path to 'equality.' Black's aim is to get decent control on the light squares and later attack our center with a move like f6. The engines are surprisingly optimistic on Black's behalf, which was quite sensational to me when I took a look. }
3. e5 Bf5
{ Surprisingly enough, the position now resembles an advanced Caro-Kann. One of the key differences is that Black's f6-break is more effective because of the knight on c6. The downside to having the knight on c6 is that the c5 pawn break can't happen yet as the knight stands in the way. }
4. c3
{ Like in the other lines, we will play this move solidifying our pawn structure. }
4... e6 5. Be2
{ This move is played very seldom. The point is that we aim to play similarly to lines we've already seen. f4-Nf3-Nbd2 etc. }
5... Nge7 { Has been played before, but it's inaccurate. } 6. Nd2
{ The best continuation.  6.f4?!  is too hasty, as Black can play  6...Bg6  , among other moves when  Nf5  will follow suit - justifying  Nge7  . }
6... f6 { Will of course be met by } 7. f4
{ As it is vital that we maintain our strong center. } 7... Ng6 8. g3
{ Guarding the pawn on f4. } 8... fxe5 9. fxe5 Be7 10. h4
{ A strong move as we want to remove Black's knight on g6. } 10... O-O 11. Ndf3
{ The best move by a long shot. We want to open the diagonal for our bishop on c1, while we also want to trade Black's strong bishop on f5 with Bd3. The knight on g1 can head to h3 instead, where it can potentially jump to f4. }
11... Qd7 12. Nh3 Nd8
{ Black can't do much about our plan so he also tries to improve his pieces. Removing the knight from the c6-square gives Black the opportunity of playing c5, fighting our center. }
13. h5 { It's time! } 13... Nh8 14. Bd3
{ We keep going with our plan of trading bishops.   If Black carries on with  14...c5  for example,  we can take on f5 followed by g4 and O-O. Our king will be perfectly safe although we have expanded a lot on the kingside. }
14... a6
{ Is an engine move, when Black aims for capturing on d3 followed by Qb5. Very subtle, indeed.   14...Bxd3?  Leaves Black's king very vulnerable after  15.Qxd3  15...h6  16.g4+-  White's attack is already decisive according to Stockfish 13. }
15. g4 { A funky move. } 15... Bxd3
{ 15...Bxg4  is met by  16.Bxh7!  of course. } 16. Qxd3 Qb5
{ Black has achieved his goal, but the resulting endgame looks pretty bad. }
17. Qxb5 axb5 18. Ke2
{ White's extra space makes the position clearly better. } *

