[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "16. Nimzowitch's Defense (1...Nc6)"]
[Black "2...d5 (3...Bf5 7)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nc6
{ The 'Nimzowitch Defence,' a very rare breed. That being said, it is by far the best opening out of the rare openings out there. }
2. d4 d5
{ The exclam is well-deserved because this is Black's best bet and only path to 'equality.' Black's aim is to get decent control on the light squares and later attack our center with a move like f6. The engines are surprisingly optimistic on Black's behalf, which was quite sensational to me when I took a look. }
3. e5 Bf5
{ Surprisingly enough, the position now resembles an advanced Caro-Kann. One of the key differences is that Black's f6-break is more effective because of the knight on c6. The downside to having the knight on c6 is that the c5 pawn break can't happen yet as the knight stands in the way. }
4. c3
{ Like in the other lines, we will play this move solidifying our pawn structure. }
4... e6 5. Be2
{ This move is played very seldom. The point is that we aim to play similarly to lines we've already seen. f4-Nf3-Nbd2 etc. }
5... f6 6. f4 g5
{ I found only one game with this move, and it's not surprising that it was a correspondence game. Black goes for direct counterplay and dismantles our center. The lines that occur from here are unbelievably complicated. Black is constantly on the verge of losing, but somehow someway there are an absurd amount of resources for Black. Although I was left rather irritated when I discovered that the game fizzles into a draw in the end, it doesn't really matter. For a human player there is just too much to remember, making the task for Black practically impossible. Buckle up, the positions coming up are wild! }
7. Bh5+
{ The most venomous move is to give this check.  7.Nf3  leads nowhere, although the play remains complicated. Here,  7...gxf4  8.Bxf4  is enough for equality.   7...g4!?  is trickier, when the line continues  8.Nh4  Be4!  Black's point is that the knight on  h4  hangs after  9.Bxg4  fxe5  . From here, the game continues  10.Nf3  exd4  11.O-O  Bc5  12.Kh1  , when the position is rather unclear.  7.exf6  happened in the only game I found in the database following Sanchez Carol, J - Sedlacek, T ICCF email game 2017. }
7... Bg6
{ This move is inaccurate, but the resulting positions are still tricky. } 8.
Nh3 gxf4 9. Nxf4
{ Black is in huge trouble here, unless he finds the pawn sacrifice } 9... fxe5
10. Bxg6+ hxg6 11. Nxg6 Rh7 12. dxe5
{ We should grab the pawn. Note that  12.Nxf8?  loses to  12...Qh4!  when Black all of a sudden takes over. }
12... Rf7
{ The strongest continuation for Black.   12...Kd7!?  Is a fancy move, with the idea of capturing with the queen on f8 if we take the bishop. However, we can utilize the poor placement of the king with the move  13.c4!  We should open the position as much as possible.  13...Nge7  14.cxd5!  Striking while the iron is hot. We can't allow Black to consolidate.  14...Nxg6  15.dxc6+  Ke8  16.Qxd8+  Rxd8  17.cxb7+-  Black has reached an endgame which is lost.   12...Bc5!?  Is a dangerous move that requires us to play accurately.  13.b4!  The reason why this move is strong is that Black has to move the bishop to b6, where he will lose control of the f8-square.  13...Bb6  14.Rf1!  Kd7  The only way to dodge the threat of Rf8.  15.Qd3   Don't get greedy with  15.Nf8?  as Black's compensation is incredible after the queen sacrifice when our position has turned from winning to losing.  15...Rg7  16.b5  Another good move, removing the knight from the c6-square.  16...Na5   16...Nce7  is met by  17.Nf4  , when Black has lost a lot of activity.  17.g3  Taking control of the important f4 and h4 squares, and preparing to grab material with Rf8.  17...Qe8  Black couldn't prevent us from playing Rf8 anyway.  18.Rf8  Qxf8  19.Nxf8+  Rxf8  20.Nd2!  It's crucial to prevent Nc4.  20...Rf5  21.c4!  Opening the diagonal for the bishop.  21...Rxe5+  22.Kd1  Re3  23.Qf1  Ne7  And here,  24.c5  Wins material.  24...Bxc5  25.Nb3+-  Black has some pawns, but White will win with correct play.   12...Nge7?!  Doesn't seem like a challenging move, as we get a nice initiative after  13.Nxf8  Kxf8  14.O-O+  ↑  We are a pawn up and Black's king is weak. }
13. Bf4 { Blocking the f-file and preparing to castle. } 13... Bc5
{ Black's best bet is to keep the bishop. If we are allowed to grab the bishop, our play is rather simple. }
14. Qh5 Kd7 { The only way to escape the pin. } 15. g3
{ We must keep the f4-square under control, like in the previous lines. } 15...
Nge7 16. Nd2
{ We have managed to consolidate fairly well. I will end the theory section here, but I will allow you to click you through a sample line.  16...Rf5  17.Qh7  Pinning the knight on  e7  and preventing Black from untangling.  17...Qe8  18.Nh4  Rh5  19.Qg7  We shouldn't allow Black to play Qf7 and get the rook into the game. Black can't do much here, as he is pretty much forced to offer the exchange of queens.  19...Qf8  20.Qg4  Gaining a valuable tempo.  20...Qh8  21.O-O-O  Nxe5  Black has won this pawn, but our king is safe. Still, Black's active pieces give him compensation for the exchange.  22.Bxe5  Rxe5  23.Nhf3  Rf5  24.Rhe1  Black has to be very careful here. The line continues  24...Rg8  25.Qa4+  c6!  25...Nc6  would allow  26.g4  followed by Ne4, when Black is in trouble. Now Black has the option of playing b5 in case we play g4, so it's not effective. Instead,  26.Kb1  Should be played, when the game is heading towards a complicated struggle where Black has decent compensation for a missing exchange. Still, we do have an advantage, and practically, it's also easier to handle White. }
*

