7. Bh5+ Bg6
{ This move is inaccurate, but the resulting positions are still tricky. } 8.
Nh3 gxf4 9. Nxf4
{ Black is in huge trouble here, unless he finds the pawn sacrifice } 9... fxe5
10. Bxg6+ hxg6 11. Nxg6 Rh7 12. dxe5
{ We should grab the pawn. Note that  12.Nxf8?  loses to  12...Qh4!  when Black all of a sudden takes over. }
12... Rg7
{ 12...Kd7!?  Is a fancy move, with the idea of capturing with the queen on f8 if we take the bishop. However, we can utilize the poor placement of the king with the move  13.c4!  We should open the position as much as possible.  13...Nge7  14.cxd5!  Striking while the iron is hot. We can't allow Black to consolidate.  14...Nxg6  15.dxc6+  Ke8  16.Qxd8+  Rxd8  17.cxb7+-  Black has reached an endgame which is lost.   12...Bc5!?  Is a dangerous move which requires us to play accurately.  13.b4!  The reason why this move is strong is that Black has to move the bishop to b6, where he will lose control of the f8-square.  13...Bb6  14.Rf1!  Kd7  The only way to dodge the threat of Rf8.  15.Qd3  Rg7  16.b5  Another good move, removing the knight from the c6-square.  16...Na5  17.g3  Taking control of the important f4 and h4 squares, and preparing to grab material with Rf8.  17...Qe8  Black couldn't prevent us from playing Rf8 anyway.  18.Rf8  Qxf8  19.Nxf8+  Rxf8  20.Nd2!  It's crucial to prevent Nc4.  20...Rf5  21.c4!  Opening the diagonal for the bishop.  21...Rxe5+  22.Kd1  Re3  23.Qf1  Ne7  And here,  24.c5  Wins material.  24...Bxc5  25.Nb3+-  Black has some pawns, but White will win with correct play.   12...Nge7?!  Doesn't seem like a challenging move, as we get a nice initiative after  13.Nxf8  Kxf8  14.O-O+  ↑  We are a pawn up and Black's king is weak. }
13. Qd3 { The best way to defend the knight. } 13... Kd7
{ Once again we see this king move, allowing a queen capture on f8. } 14. g3
{ A great consolidating move as we can place the bishop on f4. } 14... Nge7
{ Black aims to sacrifice an exchange for a dangerous initiative. We must tread carefully.   14...Qe8?  Allows us to carry out our plan after  15.Nxf8+  Qxf8  16.Bf4  Nge7  17.Nd2+-  Black has no compensation for the missing pawn. }
15. Nxf8+ Qxf8 16. Bh6 { We must grab the material. } 16... Nxe5 17. Qb5+
{ Every tempo is vital, so we should give this check. } 17... N7c6 18. Nd2
{ We need some pieces around our king before we take the rook.  18.Bxg7?  would have allowed  18...Qf3!  when my engine shows me that the position is a draw. }
18... Nf3+ 19. Kd1 { The best square for the king. } 19... Ne5
{ Is the best move according to the engine, when our queen should join the defense.   19...Nxd2  Leads to a fun line where our king ends up on a4.  20.Bxg7  Qxg7  21.Kxd2  Qg5+  22.Kc2  Qf5+  23.Kb3  We escape Black's checks.  23...a6  24.Qe2!  The only move, but good enough to win.  24...Na5+  25.Ka4!  It's hilarious that Black has nothing against our king on a4.  25...b6   25...d4  looks scary, but we have everything under control after  26.Rad1  .  26.Rhf1  Qg6  27.Rf4  Planning to double the rook in the f-file.  27...Qe8  Is one last attempt to create something, when the refutation is  28.Re1!  Now, things works out as  28...Kc8+  29.Ka3  Nc4+  Is met by  30.Rxc4+-  Black doesn't have enough pawns left to save the game. }
20. Qe2 Qf6 21. Bxg7 Qxg7 22. Rf1
{ Black has compensation due to our lack of coordination, but our extra material yields us the upper hand. One plan forward to secure our king is to play Rc1-Rc2-Kc1-Kb1. }
