[Round "?"]
[White "16. Nimzowitch's Defense (1...Nc6)"]
[Black "2...d5 (3...Bf5 11)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nc6
{ The 'Nimzowitch Defence,' a very rare breed. That being said, it is by far the best opening out of the rare openings out there. }
2. d4 d5
{ The exclam is well-deserved because this is Black's best bet and only path to 'equality.' Black's aim is to get decent control on the light squares and later attack our center with a move like f6. The engines are surprisingly optimistic on Black's behalf, which was quite sensational to me when I took a look. }
3. e5 Bf5
{ Surprisingly enough, the position now resembles an advanced Caro-Kann. One of the key differences is that Black's f6-break is more effective because of the knight on c6. The downside to having the knight on c6 is that the c5 pawn break can't happen yet as the knight stands in the way. }
4. c3
{ Like in the other lines, we will play this move solidifying our pawn structure. }
4... e6 5. Be2
{ This move is played very seldom. The point is that we aim to play similarly to lines we've already seen. f4-Nf3-Nbd2 etc. }
5... f6 6. f4 g5
{ I found only one game with this move, and it's not surprising that it was a correspondence game. Black goes for direct counterplay and dismantles our center. The lines that occur from here are unbelievably complicated. Black is constantly on the verge of losing, but somehow someway there are an absurd amount of resources for Black. Although I was left rather irritated when I discovered that the game fizzles into a draw in the end, it doesn't really matter. For a human player there is just too much to remember, making the task for Black practically impossible. Buckle up, the positions coming up are wild! }
7. Bh5+ Kd7
{ Black's best bet is to simply move the king away. It's indeed true that the king could become a target on d7, but it's not so easy for us to attack it yet. If Black has time, he will take on f4 and e5 when our initiative disappears. }
8. fxg5 { The best move is to play concretely and grab the pawn. } 8... fxe5 9.
Nf3
{ Not giving Black any time to rest, attacking the pawn on e5. Here Black has to be careful, as we can often play Nh4 and get rid of the defending piece on f5. c4 is also an idea in the air, opening up the file against Black's monarch. }
9... Nge7
{ Black forgets about the pawn on e5 and goes for straightforward counterplay instead. Not a bad strategy! }
10. O-O { Safety first. } 10... Ng6
{ Defending e5 and getting ready to develop the f8-bishop.   10...h6!?  This move is once again strong, just not as strong as in the main line.  11.c4!  We need to attack with great velocity, otherwise Black's counterplay will be very strong.  11...dxc4   The best move is to take immediately. Note that  11...hxg5  is met by  12.g4!  12.Nxe5+  Nxe5  13.dxe5+  Bd3  In the spirit of the variation, avoiding a trade of queens for the time being.   13...Kc8  14.Qxd8+  Kxd8  15.Be2⩲  White keeps the upper hand in the endgame due to the better coordination and safer king.  14.Be2  Black will lose the pawn on d3 as seen in the variation  14...Kc8  15.Bxd3  cxd3  16.Rf3  Black will win the pawn on e5 in return, but opening the position is just to our advantage.  16...Qd4+  17.Kh1  Nc6  18.Rxd3  Qxe5  19.gxh6  Bxh6  20.Bxh6  Rxh6  21.h3±  This position looks close to lost for Black, as his king is in severe danger. It doesn't help either that the rook on a8 is out of the game for the time being, and that the pawn on e6 is rather weak. }
11. dxe5
{ The strategy remains the same - let's open the position as much as possible. }
11... Ngxe5 12. Nxe5+ Nxe5 13. Rxf5
{ The exchange sac is the most dangerous reply. } 13... exf5 14. Qxd5+ Bd6 15.
Bf4 { White has a powerful initiative. } 15... c6 16. Qd4 Qe7
{ Defending the knight on e5, the only way to do so. } 17. Na3
{ The knight is making way for our rook on a1, which can either go to d1 or e1. }
17... Kc8
{ The best defense is to place the h8-rook on d8 instead.   17...Rad8?  Is a very natural move, but it fails to the beautiful  18.Kf1!  Moving the king allows us to play Re1 as it prevents the trick of Nf3+. The king is also better placed on f1 than h1, as there are no back-rank mates.  18...Kc8  19.Re1  Black now loses the extra material, so he is forced to give the exchange back by playing  19...Bxa3  20.Qxe5  Qxe5  21.Bxe5  Bxb2  And here, we have the brilliant  22.Bf7!  The point is that we are gaining a valuable tempo as we are threatening Be6+.  22...b5  Black gives the b7-square for his king.  23.Bxh8  Rxh8  24.Re7+-  Black won't hold the endgame as our kingside pawns are faster and more furious. Black's pawns on the queenside can also be easily targeted by our R+B, for example by playing Be4 once we have captured the pawn on f5. }
18. Kh1 { This time, we can place the king on the h1-square. } 18... Rd8 19.
Re1
{ We do once again head into a great endgame, but this time it's only 'close-to-winning.' }
19... Bxa3 20. Qxe5 Qxe5 21. Rxe5
{ Our bishops are stronger than Black's extra exchange. } 21... Bd6
{ Black has to get rid of one of our bishops in order to stand a chance in drawing.   21...Bxb2?  Loses to  22.Rxf5  Now Bg4 is a powerful threat, so Black has to play  22...Kd7  23.Rf7+  Ke6  24.Rxh7  Black's problem is that our kingside pawns are so much faster.  24...Bxc3  25.g3+-  Black is completely lost, so it's appropriate to stop here. }
22. Rxf5 Bxf4 23. Rxf4 Kc7 24. h4
{ Our extra two pawns on the kingside are worth a lot. Black needs to get counterplay by playing active moves. }
24... Rf8 25. Re4
{ Trading a rook would make the defensive task for Black significantly easier, so we should avoid that if possible. }
25... Rad8 26. Re2
{ Preventing a rook to d2. Black certainly has chances of saving the game, but the road towards the half point remains long. }
