{ The most critical move, but Black has many moves to watch out for. I analyzed a lot here, but the chapter will never come to an end if I show all my analysis. Alternatives are:  10.g4!?  10.O-O!?  10.c4!?  The best alternative, but Black pulls a Houdini here as well... }
10... Nxe5 11. dxe5 hxg5 12. g4
{ Stopping Black's play in the h-file, and preventing Black from playing g4 himself, which could be very dangerous. }
12... Rxh5 { A fantastic rook sacrifice, which... } 13. gxf5 g4
{ Another brilliancy, opening up the queen's diagonal. } 14. fxe6+ Kc8
{ The most accurate move.  14...Ke8  is also possible, but it looks unnatural to me as the king looks weaker there than on  c8  . The game becomes rather complicated though, so feel free to investigate if you're curious! }
15. Bf4 Qh4+ 16. Ke2
{ The only move that doesn't lose, as  16.Bg3  loses to  16...Qxg3!  , winning a piece. The game from here is extremely complicated, but I feel like it's a crime to ask you to memorize everything. Still, I can't stop all the curious souls, but I want to emphasize that the chances for this to occur in a game is around 0%. It's just too difficult for a human being to find the most accurate moves, even for super-GMs... }
16... g3
{ A very dangerous move. Now Qg4+ check is in the air when we can quickly lose. }
17. Qxd5 { It looks like that we're winning, but no! } 17... Nf6
{ Defends the square on d7 while developing a piece. } 18. Qf3 g2
{ Black can't allow us to take on g3. } 19. Rg1 Rf5
{ Another only move. Black can't allow us to consolidate. } 20. Bg3 Qh3
{ Leads to a wild draw after  20...Qg5  21.h4!  Is the most accurate way to proceed.  21...Qg6  22.Qxg2  Qg4+  23.Ke1  23...Bc5  Black has to keep threatening stuff.  24.exf6  Bxg1  25.Qxg1  Rxf6  26.Kd2  Rxe6  We have gained two pieces for a rook, but Black has decent counterplay due to our vulnerable king. Further, I analyzed  27.Qf2  Re8  28.Kc1  Qf7 is a nice threat.  28...b6  29.Qf7  Kb7  30.Qxc7+  Ka6  Black's king survives on a6, believe it or not.  31.b4  31...Rac8  32.b5+  Kxb5!  Black can take, as we have nothing.  33.Qf4  Qxf4+  34.Bxf4  Re2  The last required precise move in order to draw the game.  35.a4+  Ka6  36.h5=  White can try for a little longer, but the game is objectively drawn.   20...Qc4+  Leads to a marginally better endgame after  21.Qd3  Qxe6  22.Nd2  We are close to consolidating, so Black should hurry up and grab the e5-pawn.  22...Nh5  23.Nf3  23...c6!  Stopping Rad1, as the king can move to c7.  24.Nd4  We can't do much else as Black's rook comes quickly with Rd8.  24...Nxg3+  25.Qxg3  Rxe5+  26.Kd3  Our king is safe on d3.  26...Rd5  27.Qxg2  Qf5+  28.Qe4  Qxe4+  29.Kxe4⩲  The extra pawn gives us a mini-edge, but Black should of course draw. }
21. Qxg2 Qg4+
{ There are two king moves here, but none of them lead anywhere on my engine. }
22. Kd2
{ The exclam is there as I think it's the best attempt.  22.Ke1  is a draw after  22...Bc5!  23.exf6  Bxg1  Black's point is that we can't take due to  Re5!  with a perpetual.  24.e7  is the best move, when the kame ends in a draw after  24...Kd7  25.Nd2  Rxf6  26.Ne4  Rg6  27.Kd2  Re6!  28.Nf6+  Rxf6  29.Rxg1  Kxe7  30.Qxb7  Rd8+  31.Kc1  Qg5+  32.Kb1  Qf5+  , with a threefold. }
22... Bh6+
{ Another strong move, and the only one  @@StartBracket@@again...@@EndBracket@@.   22...Bc5?  Loses now, after  23.exf6  Bxg1  24.e7  Kd7  25.f7!  The reason this works is that our king is much safer on d2 than e1.  25...Rxf7  26.Qxg1+-   In  22.Ke1  ,  Rxe7+  would have happened now, but our king is on d2 instead. Thus, we have time to consolidate and our extra material will decide the game. }
23. Kc2 Rf3 { Threatening a perpetual with Qf5+ and Qxe6+. } 24. Nd2 Qf5+ 25.
Kb3
{ 25.Kc1  doesn't win either as we can see after  25...Ne4  26.Bf4!?   26.Be1  is the other line, when  26...b6!  27.h4  Kb7  28.Qg4  Rh8!  29.Qxf5  Rxf5  should lead to a draw  26...Rxf4  27.Qg8+  Bf8  28.e7  Kd7  29.exf8=Q  Rxf8  30.e6+  Kd6  31.Qg7  Nxd2  32.Qd7+  Ke5  33.Qxd2  Kxe6=  with an equal position. The game does continue though, as it's still possible to error. }
25... Qxe6+ 26. Nc4 Ne4
{ Once again the only move. It was really frustrating to me that Black's tactics always worked! }
27. Be1 { We must prevent Nd2+. } 27... Nc5+ 28. Kc2 Qf5+ 29. Kd1 Rd3+ 30. Ke2
{ Now Qg4 is a threat that leads to a terrible endgame, but Black has the amazing }
30... Rd4 { Preventing Qg4! } 31. Nd2 Qh5+
{ Another accuracy, taking h2 with check, then e5. } 32. Qf3
{ 32.Kf1  is a draw after  32...Rf4+  33.Bf2  Nd3  34.Ne4  Qf5  35.Rd1  Nxf2  36.Nxf2  c6  37.Rd2  Qb1+  38.Ke2  Qf5  39.Kf1  . }
32... Qxh2+ 33. Rg2 Qxe5+ 34. Kd1 Rd8
{ Covering any sorts of tricks on the last rank. } 35. Qh3+
{ Pulling the emergency break. } 35... Qe6 36. Qxe6+ Nxe6 37. Kc2
{ With a drawn endgame... What else can I say? Chess is a fantastic game. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "16. Nimzowitch's Defense (1...Nc6)"]
[Black "Nimzowitch Defence Conclusion"]
[Result "*"]

{ CONCLUSION: Nimzowitch Defence remains an opening choice Black goes for very seldom. I am not entirely sure why the appeal is not there, as it is much less popular than other rare opening like Alekhine's Defence - despite being an objectively superior choice! }
1. e4 Nc6 2. d4 d5
{ It's clear though that Black has to go for this move, as the positions after  2...d6  and  2...e5  become quite passive, as thoroughly explained in our analysis section. This is indeed Black's best shot, grabbing control over the light squares. }
3. e5 Bf5 4. c3
{ , when Black has an important choice to make.  4...f6  is definitely possible, but the resulting positions are undoubtedly more pleasant for us, as our play is simple: f4-Be2-Nf3-Nbd2, and eventually an expansion on the queenside with a4-b4. Black can try to castle queenside in several lines, but our attack is too fast and significantly more dangerous, meaning that the aggressive play is very likely to backfire. Black should castle kingside when our space advantage gives us a pleasant edge.   Instead, Black should proceed with  4...e6  . My suggestion is to play  5.Be2!  keeping the option of playing  f4  . From here,  5...Nge7  looks natural when  6.Nd2!  gives us a great position.  5...f6  best, as Black should fight against our central pawns. We will of course respond with the move  6.f4  , when I think a human being is likely to respond with  6...Nge7  or  6...Qd7  . Those positions are similar to the ones we have seen earlier, where our plans are pretty much always the same. f4-Nf3-Nbd2-b4-a4 etc. Anyway, the engine shows that  6...g5!  is best, leading to extremely complicated positions, where Black is on the verge of losing in every line. Don't let the fact that Black gets an equal game discourage you, as the path towards equality is almost impossible for a human being to find. There's just too much for Black to memorize! We even have numerous alternatives along the way, while many of the moves make no sense for a human. I also want to highlight that most of our ideas are logical and not too difficult to find over the board.  5.Be2  is also a rather uncommon response to Black's concept. Going through all the complex lines that occur after  6...g5  was great fun, but I don't recommend you to spend the most of your energy here as 1... Nc6 remains a highly uncommon move - a move I have yet to face over the board myself! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "17. Caro-Kann (1...c6) Minor Sidelines"]
[Black "Caro-Kann Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6
{ So, here it is. Caro-Kann, perhaps my least favorite opening against 1. e4. I have for long tried to wrap my head around why so many people choose this little move as their weapon against 1. e4. When I was a coach in the World Youth Chess Championship, pretty much every single one of my students played it. The results weren't what I had hoped for, so I was determined to make them pick a weapon that gave greater chances to score goals. In the end, I straight up forbid one of my best friends @@StartBracket@@FM Lucas Ranaldi@@EndBracket@@ to play the opening, but he didn't listen... Ah, good times! I'm always upset when I see young players play this move since I think it is a move you should play when you are 40+ and waaaay past your prime! Let's take a look at the history of this move, brilliantly written by GM Erwin L'Ami who has created a fantastic course on the topic @@StartBracket@@much to my dismay :@@EndBracket@@@@EndBracket@@: 'Named after the Englishman Horatio Caro and Austrian Markus Kann, the Caro-Kann is one of those timeless openings. A significant moment for its history was the year 1886, when Caro published an article in the Magazine 'Bruderschaft' featuring what is now known as the Caro-Kann Defence. Before the article was published, Markus Kann had played the opening successfully in Viennese chess circles and so the Chess World had to find a compromise: binding the two names gave birth to the Caro-Kann!' As much as I love to make fun of this opening, it is undeniable that it's one of Black's most reliable choices against 1. e4. It's utilized by World-Class GMs and amateur players alike, due to its rock-solid foundation. Black's strategy is usually 'neutralize White's pressure and head to a favorable endgame.' This strategy works well due to Black's excellent pawn structure. A strategy that's typical for 'older' players, hence my mockery :@@EndBracket@@ Things are not so simple though, due to White's vast choices. In some lines, the play will lead to extremely complex strategical battles, and in others, not much will be going on. Trust me, if White could only play 3. e5, my opinion would have been completely different! Before we start, I will once again point out how amazing GM L'Ami's guide is on the topic. One of the finest courses on the platform! }
2. d4 d5 3. exd5
{ After lots of thinking and consulting with some good friends of mine, I decided to head for the Exchange Variation. Before I explain why, let me briefly explain the alternatives:   3.f3!?  is the Fantasy Variation and a very unpleasant surprise for the unprepared player. For a prepared player on the other hand, this won't pose a serious threat.   3.Nc3  is the Classical Variation, when the mainline goes  3...dxe4  4.Nxe4  4...Bf5  had for many years been Black's most reliable choice, but recently  4...Nf6  has been in the wind, played with success by the super GM David Howell, among others. I did not consider this for long, due to the huge amounts of theory. GM L'Ami even covers both of these moves in his course!   3.e5  is the Advanced Variation, arguably the most challenging response. White maintains excellent central control and space, but Black doesn't have any serious weaknesses. The battle that ensues is extremely rich strategically and dynamically, which is why I believe the move is favored by the top players when they try to take down this line. Indeed, GM Wesley So gives this in his course for this very reason. A very tricky line, so Black has to watch his step carefully here. Once again, GM L'Ami covers two options for Black  3...c5  and  3...Bf5  , but I must admit that I believe the latter is better than  3...c5  . I also checked a line played by my good friend GM Christiansen,  3...Bf5  4.Nc3  e6  5.g4!?  Bg6  6.Nge2  , but I threw in the towel when I discovered how complicated the lines were and the number of decent tries Black has. It just wasn't worth it!  Let's now return to my recommendation. I believe the move to be good for many reasons:   1. It's a simple task to handle the positions from the white side.   2. The moves are very logical and easy to understand. Compare that to the extremely complex positions that arise after some of the examples above. It's objectively a great attempt for an edge.   3. It's very solid for White and contains little risk.   4. There's not much theory to learn, as Black doesn't have so many different set-ups. A huge advantage, of course.   5. It's an annoying move for Black, similar to our exchange Philidor, which gives us psychological points.  The positions that occur for Black are rather dull with greatly diminished winning chances. I am yet to hear a player who is happy to see this move with Black. It's hard to be creative here without creating serious concessions. A higher-rated player will at some point take risks to win the game, which you can utilize. If your opponent is lower-rated, you have excellent chances of outplaying him as the line requires precision from Black. And the list goes on... }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "17. Caro-Kann (1...c6) Minor Sidelines"]
[Black "4...g6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4
{ Our strategy during this course has always been to grab the center while we can, and this time is no different! That being said, I had some alternatives in mind already here!  2.Nf3  is played frequently at top level. After  2...d5  ,  3.Nc3  is the Two Knights Variation. I took a brief look, but I was not satisfied with our chances after  3...Bg4  . We do grab the bishop pair, but Black remains rock-solid...   3.d3  is the trendy move on top level, but far too sophisticated for my taste! I also discovered that Black could take a completely different direction with  2...g6  , when we transpose to a line I do not give against the Modern/ Pirc! }
2... d5
{ Black takes control of the center and poses an important question to our e4-pawn. We can defend it with Nc3/Nd2, move forward, defend it with f3 or capture on d5.2... g6 will most likely head to a sideline we covered in our Modern coverage. }
3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3
{ The main tabiya of the variation, developing our bishop to the active d3-square. Very logical indeed. I have played  4.Nf3  myself too, with the idea of playing a quick  Ne5  . Definitely worth a look. Black has different ways of playing against  4.Bd3  , and our coverage will be extensive. }
4... g6
{ Some players have chosen to play this move already here, with the idea of fianchettoing the f8-bishop. With this set-up the play becomes less symmetrical, which is a typical way for a higher-rated opponent to act. The downside is that Black gets less control of the center, something that can make his position rather passive. }
5. Nf3 Bg7 6. c3
{ A move which we always play, as it's essential to support the d4-pawn. } 6...
Bg4
{ Some players have tried this move, but it's doesn't make sense to play it now that Black has chosen a set-up with g6.   6...Nf6  This move will be covered in great depth in the next chapter.  7.O-O  O-O  8.Bf4  Nc6  And we have transposed. There's no need to worry about getting move-ordered here, since it makes no sense for Black to avoid the knight-move. }
7. Nbd2
{ We're making sure that we can capture on f3 when Black takes the knight. }
7... Nf6 8. h3 Bxf3 9. Nxf3 O-O 10. O-O
{ The absence of the light-squared bishops creates problems for Black. The position is also worsened by the fact that the bishop stands on g7, where it does absolutely nothing. }
10... Qc7 11. Re1
{ There's no need to be fancy.  11.Ne5  Nc6  12.f4  e6=  This is normally a good plan when it's possible to create an attack, but here it's the wrong direction. White had lost his advantage in Santarius, E - Norowitz, Y Nassau 2012, and the game was eventually drawn. }
11... Nc6 12. g3
{ A strong move, as we will be able to place the bishop on f4 with a tempo next. g3 also frees the g2-square for our king, which will create attacking possibilities with Rh1-h4-h5. }
12... e6 13. Bf4 Qd7 14. a4 a6 15. Kg2 Rfe8 16. h4
{ Our excellent bishop pair give us a very nice edge. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "17. Caro-Kann (1...c6) Minor Sidelines"]
[Black "4...g6 (9...Qc7)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4
{ Our strategy during this course has always been to grab the center while we can, and this time is no different! }
2... d5
{ Black takes control of the center and poses an important question to our e4-pawn. }
3. exd5
{ After lots of thinking and consulting with some good friends of mine, I decided to head for the Exchange Variation. }
3... cxd5 4. Bd3
{ The main tabiya of the variation, developing our bishop to the active d3-square. }
4... g6
{ Some players have chosen to play this move already here, with the idea of fianchettoing the f8-bishop. With this set-up the play becomes less symmetrical, which is a typical way for a higher-rated opponent to act. The downside is that Black gets less control of the center, something that can make his position rather passive. }
5. Nf3 Bg7 6. c3
{ A move which we always play, as it's essential to support the d4-pawn. } 6...
Nh6
{ Black has this extra alternative at his disposal. It looks very odd indeed, but it's not as bad as it looks. The knight can head to f5 and from there to d6. Black can also attempt to change the light-squared bishops by playing Bf5, and he may even attempt an e5-break with the support of f6-Nf7. Once again, this approach is a typical one from someone who searches to make the game unbalanced, as the winning chances will obviously increase. }
7. O-O O-O { 7...Nc6  is the same. } 8. Re1
{ A move we constantly see in these positions, as it takes control of the open e-file. }
8... Nc6 9. h3
{ A strong move which limits the bishop on c8 and the knight on h6, since it controls the g4-square. }
9... Qc7
{ A standard move from Black in the Exchange Caro-Kann, as our bishop is prevented from moving to the f4-square. }
10. a4
{ A very strong move, with the standard plan of expanding on the queenside.  10.Na3  has been played by some GMs, when I think GM Dreev responded well both times. In one game he played  10...Bf5  , when White chose to make some trades with  11.Bxh6  Bxh6  12.Bxf5  gxf5  . Black's king looks exposed, but the dark-squared bishop does a good job of defending it. The game went:  13.Nh4  e6  14.Qh5  Qf4  15.Re3  , and here it was important to play 15... Bg7! or 15... Ne7! The bishop move is subtle, as Black wants to quickly trade queens with  Qh6  . Instead, GM Dreev was inaccurate with  15...Kh8?!  , and was indeed punished for it, as White's forces looked very strong after  16.Nf3  in Artemiev, V - Dreev, A Sochi 2016.   The other game went  10...a6  11.Nc2  Bf5  12.Ne3  Bxd3  13.Qxd3  . GM Dreev lost a long game, but had a satisfactory position after the opening in Jumabayev, R - Dreev, A St Petersburg 2018. }
10... Bf5
{ The typical move. And once again I remind you that  10. ..f6?  is bad due to  11.c4!  An important idea to keep in mind! }
11. Bf1
{ As you can see, our play very often remains the same. KEEP THE BISHOPS! }
11... Rfe8 12. Na3 a6 13. Bd2
{ 13.Be3  is also strong, but I like having the e-file open.  Qc1  is now a rather annoying idea to meet for Black. }
13... f6
{ The natural choice is to give the knight some shelter on f7, while it also supports e7-e5. }
14. b4
{ The strongest move. Normally, we would have liked to play  14.c4  , but Black has the move  14...Be4  which is kind of annoying. Black's bishop can take on  f3  in several lines, when the d4-pawn all of a sudden hangs. }
14... Nf7 15. Rc1 { While Black prepares e7-e5, we prepare c3-c4! } 15... e5
16. c4 { What else? } 16... Nxd4 { Black should get rid of the tension. } 17.
Nxd4 exd4 18. cxd5 Qd7 { And now, we have the important move } 19. Nc4
{ A great move. The d5-pawn is covered to the fork on b6. If Black allows it, we will secure the d5-pawn with Nb6-a5 with a dominating position, as we get complete control over the c-file. Black's best move is }
19... Rac8 { And here, we should play } 20. Rxe8+
{ Our plan of playing  20.Nb6  is not effective without any rooks on the board!  20...Rxc1  21.Qxc1  Rxe1  22.Qxe1  Qd6  is sadly just equal. }
20... Qxe8 { The right way to capture, otherwise Nb6-a5 comes of course! } 21.
Na5
{ We have excellent pressure. It seems to me that Black has to part with either the b7-pawn or the d4-pawn. In order to achieve a draw, Black would have to play pixel perfect - a tough task! }
*

