[White "17. Caro-Kann (1...c6) Minor Sidelines"]
[Black "4...g6 (9...Bf5)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4
{ Our strategy during this course has always been to grab the center while we can, and this time is no different! }
2... d5
{ Black takes control of the center and poses an important question to our e4-pawn. }
3. exd5
{ After lots of thinking and consulting with some good friends of mine, I decided to head for the Exchange Variation. }
3... cxd5 4. Bd3
{ The main tabiya of the variation, developing our bishop to the active d3-square. }
4... g6
{ Some players have chosen to play this move already here, with the idea of fianchettoing the f8-bishop. With this set-up the play becomes less symmetrical, which is a typical way for a higher-rated opponent to act. The downside is that Black gets less control of the center, something that can make his position rather passive. }
5. Nf3 Bg7 6. c3
{ A move which we always play, as it's essential to support the d4-pawn. } 6...
Nh6
{ Black has this extra alternative at his disposal. It looks very odd indeed, but it's not as bad as it looks. The knight can head to f5 and from there to d6. Black can also attempt to change the light-squared bishops by playing Bf5, and he may even attempt an e5-break with the support of f6-Nf7. Once again, this approach is a typical one from someone who searches to make the game unbalanced, as the winning chances will obviously increase. }
7. O-O O-O 8. Re1
{ A move we constantly see in these positions, as it takes control of the open e-file. }
8... Nc6 9. h3
{ A strong move which limits the bishop on c8 and the knight on h6, since it controls the g4-square. }
9... Bf5
{ An interesting move with the simple goal of trading the light-squared bishops. }
10. Bf1
{ In order to maintain control of the light squares, it's important that we keep the bishop. }
10... Rc8
{ This move makes more sense than capturing the knight on b1. The rook on c8 plays a good role in achieving the plan f6-e5, as it's aiming towards the c4-square. As we have seen, c4 is the typical response when dealing with that plan.   10...Bxb1  In both of the games I found, Black proceeded with taking our knight on b1. I find it hard to believe that Black achieves anything significant with this, as our bishop will control a lot of squares.  11.Rxb1  Nf5  12.h4  A good move which intends to open the h-file with h5-hxg6.  12...h5  It makes sense for Black to keep things blocked.  13.Bd3  e6  14.g3±  We have excellent control of the board. Black has a solid position, but is clearly worse as he has no straightforward plan due to the lack of targets and space. We can, on the other hand, improve our position bit by bit. One plan that can be used to cause great damage is the preparation of opening the kingside with g4. }
11. Ne5
{ An intriguing move. It's not necessary by any means, but it has a nice subtle point as we want to capture on c6. With the c6-knight gone, it's harder for Black to achieve e5. If Black takes with the b-pawn, we could also think of placing our b1-knight on the outpost on c5. }
11... f6
{ The most logical move if you ask me, as Black is trying to go for e5 anyway.   11...Bxb1  Black can still capture the knight, but remain unimpressed.  12.Rxb1  Nf5  13.Nd3±  We have tons of ideas available like g3-h4. Once that is achieved, moves like Qf3-Nf4 could follow suit. Meanwhile I question what Black should do. The advantage is not incredibly high here, but I certainly would have felt rather miserable with the black pieces. }
12. Nxc6 bxc6
{ This move looks more sensible since it supports Black's pawn on d5, diminishing the effect of our c4-resource.   12...Rxc6  13.Na3  It's time to get our knight out... One advantage of having the knight placed on c3 is that it supports our desired c4-break.  13...Nf7   Black moves the knight before playing  e5  , as  13...e5  directly loses a pawn to  14.dxe5  fxe5  15.Bxh6  Bxh6  16.Rxe5  .  14.c4!  I'm sure you saw it coming! We're once again just in time!  14...dxc4  14... e5 can be played, when our position looks good after the logical 15. Be3.  15.Bxc4  Kh8  Black gets out of the annoying pin on the knight.  16.Be3±  We have a very comfortable position due to our space advantage and better pieces. If Black tries 16... e5, we can respond with 17. d5 when our d-pawn looks strong. }
13. Nd2
{ We can't do much about Black's plan, so we choose to ignore it and get our pieces out. }
13... e5 14. b4
{ It's time to switch our attention to the kingside. b4 gives us a better grip on the beautiful c5-square, while it also creates more space. We may soon expand even further, with moves like a4-b5. }
14... Nf7 15. Nb3 { The knight has a bright future on c5. } 15... Nd6 16. a4
Re8 17. Nc5
{ White is in the driving seat. Black has achieved to play e5, but without the knight on c6 and knight on f3 it has lost a lot of its venom. Black is solid, but we can create weaknesses with a move like b5. We can also start playing on the kingside with the typical idea Be3-Qd2-Bh6, and even f3-g4 when the timing is right. }
