{ Our strategy during this course has always been to grab the center while we can, and this time is no different! }
2... d5
{ Black takes control of the center and poses an important question to our e4-pawn. }
3. exd5
{ After lots of thinking and consulting with some good friends of mine, I decided to head for the Exchange Variation. }
3... cxd5 4. Bd3
{ The main tabiya of the variation, developing our bishop to the active d3-square. }
4... g6
{ Some players have chosen to play this move already here, with the idea of fianchettoing the f8-bishop. With this set-up the play becomes less symmetrical, which is a typical way for a higher-rated opponent to act. The downside is that Black gets less control of the center, something that can make his position rather passive. }
5. Nf3 Bg7 6. c3
{ A move which we always play, as it's essential to support the d4-pawn. } 6...
Nh6
{ Black has this extra alternative at his disposal. It looks very odd indeed, but it's not as bad as it looks. The knight can head to f5 and from there to d6. Black can also attempt to change the light-squared bishops by playing Bf5, and he may even attempt an e5-break with the support of f6-Nf7. Once again, this approach is a typical one from someone who searches to make the game unbalanced, as the winning chances will obviously increase. }
7. O-O O-O 8. Re1
{ A move we constantly see in these positions, as it takes control of the open e-file. }
8... Nc6 9. h3
{ A strong move which limits the bishop on c8 and the knight on h6, since it controls the g4-square. }
9... Kh8
{ A very subtle way of preparing to play e5. The king on h8 is out of the a2-g8 diagonal, so c4 no longer creates problems. }
10. b4
{ A strong move which prepares to get rid of Black's knight on  c6  , an avid supporter of the e5-break.  10.Bf4  allows Black to carry out his idea.  10...f6  11.c4  dxc4  12.Bxc4  e5  gave Black an equal game in Goryachkina, A - Kuzubov, Y Chess.com INT, a game Black eventually won. }
10... a6
{ Necessary, as  10...f6  11.b5  Na5  12.Nbd2  gives us a clearly better position. }
11. a4 f6 12. Ba3 Re8
{ The rook has moved out of harm's way, so Black is ready to finally play e5. Unfortunately for him, we are one step ahead! }
13. c4 { Just in time! } 13... dxc4
{ 13...e5?  Doesn't work well for Black after  14.cxd5!  The right pawn to take. Black has no problems after 14. dxe5 Nxe5!  14...Qxd5  15.Nc3  Qd8  16.dxe5  The fact that our knight is placed on c3 makes a huge difference of course.  16...Nxe5  17.Nxe5  fxe5  18.Be4+-  I find it hard to believe that Black will make it out of this mess. }
14. Bxc4 Nf5
{ Black forces our pawn to take a step forward. A request we will humbly accept! }
15. d5 Ne5 16. Nxe5 fxe5
{ Black now has a weak pawn on e5 which we can target. } 17. Bb2 Qd6
{ The most precise move in the position, hence the exclam.   17...Nd4  18.Na3  Our knight is heading to c2 so we can get rid of the knight on d4.  18...e6  19.Bxd4!  19. dxe6 allows Black to get out after 19... Bxe6.  19...exd4  20.dxe6±  Our e6-pawn is incredibly strong so we are well on our way to victory. }
18. Nd2 { The knight is heading to f3 where it will target e5. } 18... Nd4 19.
Bb3
{ A fantastic prophylactic move. The problem with  19.Nf3  right away was  19. ..Qxb4  was that Black attacks both of our bishops. }
19... Bf5 { 19...Qxb4  is met by  20.Re3  , when Nf3 will follow. } 20. Nf3
Nxf3+ 21. Qxf3 Rac8 22. Qe3 { Targeting the e5-pawn. } 22... e4 23. Qd2
{ The most precise move and the only move that keeps a serious advantage! }
23... Bxb2 24. Qxb2+ Qf6
{ Black has to take the endgame, otherwise g4 comes when Black loses the e4-pawn. }
25. Qxf6+ exf6 26. Rac1 { Black is under a lot of pressure in the endgame. } *

