1. e4 c6 2. d4
{ Our strategy during this course has always been to grab the center while we can, and this time is no different! }
2... d5
{ Black takes control of the center and poses an important question to our e4-pawn. }
3. exd5
{ After lots of thinking and consulting with some good friends of mine, I decided to head for the Exchange Variation. }
3... cxd5 4. Bd3
{ The main tabiya of the variation, developing our bishop to the active d3-square. }
4... g6
{ Some players have chosen to play this move already here, with the idea of fianchettoing the f8-bishop. With this set-up the play becomes less symmetrical, which is a typical way for a higher-rated opponent to act. The downside is that Black gets less control of the center, something that can make his position rather passive. }
5. Nf3 Bg7 6. c3
{ A move which we always play, as it's essential to support the d4-pawn. } 6...
Nh6
{ Black has this extra alternative at his disposal. It looks very odd indeed, but it's not as bad as it looks. The knight can head to f5 and from there to d6. Black can also attempt to change the light-squared bishops by playing Bf5, and he may even attempt an e5-break with the support of f6-Nf7. Once again, this approach is a typical one from someone who searches to make the game unbalanced, as the winning chances will obviously increase. }
7. O-O O-O 8. Re1
{ A move we constantly see in these positions, as it takes control of the open e-file. }
8... Nc6 9. h3
{ A strong move which limits the bishop on c8 and the knight on h6, since it controls the g4-square. }
9... Nf5
{ A natural move which should be played sooner or later. After all, the knight plays a very little part on h6. }
10. Bf4 f6
{ Black can play this move at different times, and this is one of them. } 11.
Nbd2 Re8 { Black wastes no time. } 12. Bh2
{ A prophylactic move which avoids Black playing e5 with a tempo. } 12... e5
{ And now, we should play } 13. dxe5 fxe5 14. c4
{ We can't allow Black to maintain his strong center. } 14... Nb4
{ Black's best shot.  14...d4  allows  15.Be4  when the e5-pawn will fall due to  Bxc6  or  Bxf5  coming next. }
15. Bf1 e4
{ Things are looking scary for us, but we do have everything under control. }
16. cxd5 exf3 17. Qa4
{ We're attacking e8 and b4 simultaneously, so Black is unable to keep the extra material. }
17... Rf8 18. Qxb4 fxg2 19. Bxg2
{ We have an extra pawn, but our king is slightly vulnerable. } 19... Nh4 20.
d6 { We should of course try our best to keep our d-pawn. } 20... Qg5 21. Bg3
{ We have everything under control. } 21... Nxg2 22. Kxg2 Qd5+ 23. Ne4
{ Our pawn on d6 remains very dangerous. Black does have some practical compensation as the queens are still on the board, but we have neutralized most of it. }
