1. e4 c6 2. d4
{ Our strategy during this course has always been to grab the center while we can, and this time is no different! }
2... d5
{ Black takes control of the center and poses an important question to our e4-pawn. }
3. exd5
{ After lots of thinking and consulting with some good friends of mine, I decided to head for the Exchange Variation. }
3... cxd5 4. Bd3
{ The main tabiya of the variation, developing our bishop to the active d3-square. }
4... g6
{ Some players have chosen to play this move already here, with the idea of fianchettoing the f8-bishop. With this set-up the play becomes less symmetrical, which is a typical way for a higher-rated opponent to act. The downside is that Black gets less control of the center, something that can make his position rather passive. }
5. Nf3 Bg7 6. c3
{ A move which we always play, as it's essential to support the d4-pawn. } 6...
Nh6
{ Black has this extra alternative at his disposal. It looks very odd indeed, but it's not as bad as it looks. The knight can head to f5 and from there to d6. Black can also attempt to change the light-squared bishops by playing Bf5, and he may even attempt an e5-break with the support of f6-Nf7. Once again, this approach is a typical one from someone who searches to make the game unbalanced, as the winning chances will obviously increase. }
7. O-O O-O 8. Re1
{ A move we constantly see in these positions, as it takes control of the open e-file. }
8... Nc6 9. h3
{ A strong move which limits the bishop on c8 and the knight on h6, since it controls the g4-square. }
9... Nf5
{ A natural move which should be played sooner or later. After all, the knight plays a very little part on h6. }
10. Bf4 e6
{ A strong Peruvian GM played this move, but it looks a bit questionable. I can't see the purpose of it, although it solidifies Black's position. What's Black's plan from here? Black can play for the e5-break once again, but then e6 seems like a waste of tempo. }
11. Nbd2 a5
{ A space-grabbing move which also prevents White from playing b4. } 12. a4
{ We answer the same way. } 12... f6
{ The cat's out of the bag! To be fair, did Black have any other choice? } 13.
Qb3 g5
{ An interesting route to take the game.  13...Re8  prepares  e5  , when  14.Re2  is a simple response with  Rae1  coming next. }
14. Bh2 h5
{ Black complicates the game, but this type of expansion will only backfire. }
15. Nf1 Nh6
{ GM Cordova prepares to launch the f-pawn forward as well, but this will create a weakness on g5. To be fair, there weren't any better alternatives. }
16. Re2
{ A strong idea to cause problems for Black's attack is to occupy the e-file.  16.Qc2  was not bad, but it was the beginning of a negative trend. The game continued  16...f5  17.Ne5  Nxe5  18.Bxe5  Bxe5  19.Rxe5  Nf7  20.Ree1  Qf6  21.Qe2  g4  , and White's advantage was pretty much all gone in Aguero Jimenez, L - Cordova, E Merida 2015. }
16... f5 17. h4
{ With this move we spoil everything Black is trying to accomplish. } 17...
gxh4 { 17...g4  allows  18.Ng5  . } 18. Rae1
{ Without the possibility of playing g4, Black has nothing. } 18... Ng4 19. Bf4
{ Black is strategically completely busted. A thematic idea is even to sac an exchange on e6, but this is of course not necessary. }
