[White "17. Caro-Kann (1...c6) Minor Sidelines"]
[Black "4...g6 (9...Nf5 3)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4
{ Our strategy during this course has always been to grab the center while we can, and this time is no different! }
2... d5
{ Black takes control of the center and poses an important question to our e4-pawn. }
3. exd5
{ After lots of thinking and consulting with some good friends of mine, I decided to head for the Exchange Variation. }
3... cxd5 4. Bd3
{ The main tabiya of the variation, developing our bishop to the active d3-square. }
4... g6
{ Some players have chosen to play this move already here, with the idea of fianchettoing the f8-bishop. With this set-up the play becomes less symmetrical, which is a typical way for a higher-rated opponent to act. The downside is that Black gets less control of the center, something that can make his position rather passive. }
5. Nf3 Bg7 6. c3
{ A move which we always play, as it's essential to support the d4-pawn. } 6...
Nh6
{ Black has this extra alternative at his disposal. It looks very odd indeed, but it's not as bad as it looks. The knight can head to f5 and from there to d6. Black can also attempt to change the light-squared bishops by playing Bf5, and he may even attempt an e5-break with the support of f6-Nf7. Once again, this approach is a typical one from someone who searches to make the game unbalanced, as the winning chances will obviously increase. }
7. O-O O-O 8. Re1
{ A move we constantly see in these positions, as it takes control of the open e-file. }
8... Nc6 9. h3
{ A strong move which limits the bishop on c8 and the knight on h6, since it controls the g4-square. }
9... Nf5
{ A natural move which should be played sooner or later. After all, the knight plays a very little part on h6. }
10. Bf4 a6
{ Black has played this move in some games, but I really don't think the move makes a lot of sense. Normally Black goes for a quick b5-b4 which will create a weakness on c3, but here it would only severely weaken the c5-square. }
11. Nbd2 Re8
{ Now that the b5-b4 plan achieves very little, the only logical plan for Black is to push for e5. }
12. Nb3
{ Protecting the d4-pawn which means that we can meet 12... f6 with the standard 13. c4! }
12... Nd6 13. Ne5
{ A strong positional move with the idea of capturing on c6. We will then get a strong outpost on the c5-square. }
13... f6
{ It looks like e5 will be achieved and that everything will be solved, until... }
14. Nxg6
{ All of a sudden there's problems towards Black's king!  14.Ng4  was played in Pham, L - Bui, T Bac Giang 2016, but Black is totally fine after  14...e5  . }
14... hxg6 15. Bxg6
{ Qh5 followed by Bh6 could be mate very soon, so Black has to act fast. }
15... Bf5
{ Black has to get rid of our g6-bishop as soon as possible.   15...e5  A logical way to defend, but it's not the right way.  16.Qh5!  We increase our pressure against the e8-rook while threatening Qh7 followed by Bh6.  16...exf4  17.Qxd5+  Another upside to this move is the hanging pawn on d5.  17...Kh8  18.Bxe8  We have regained some material with a very powerful attack  18...Ne7  19.Qh5+  Kg8  20.Ba4  With the logical plan of moving the knight to c5 and bishop to b3.  20...b5  It's almost for Black, but we have a beautiful tactic:  21.Nc5  bxa4  22.Rxe7!  Freeing the d5-square.  22...Qxe7  23.Qd5+  Kh7  24.Qxa8+-  Black remains three pawns down, and the pawns he has left are all scattered. The extra minor pieces don't compensate. }
16. Bxe8 Nxe8
{ This if course necessary, otherwise the knight will hang on d6. } 17. Qh5 Bh7
18. Nc5 { We're creating tons of pressure. Black has to play } 18... e5 19.
Nxb7 Qc7 20. Nc5
{ The knight is hanging on e8, so Black can't take our bishop on f4. } 20...
Qf7
{ Black has a lot more chances to survive without the queens on the board. }
21. Qxf7+ Kxf7 22. dxe5 fxe5 23. Bg3
{ The endgame is far from satisfactory though, and the position remains close to winning for White as three pawns are a bit too much, even for the strong bishop pair. }
