10. Bf4 Nd6
{ In most games I found in my base, Black played this move. The knight takes control of c4 and e4, but it really doesn't do too much on d6. }
11. Qb3 { Nd6 has left the e6-pawn vulnerable, so this move makes sense. }
11... e6 12. Qa3
{ Black's d6-knight is under attack, making all the maneuvering a failed mission. }
12... Nf5
{ The knight heads back.   12...Nc4?  This loses a pawn after  13.Bxc4  dxc4  14.Qa4  Qd5  15.Na3  Na5  16.Ne5+-  Black loses the c4-pawn with nothing to show for it. }
13. Nbd2 b6
{ Black tries developing the bishop to b7.   13...f6  can be played once more, when my favorite response is  14.Re2  with  Rae1  coming. Black won't be able to play  e5  . }
14. Qa4 Bb7 15. Re2
{ We're preparing the usual doubling in the e-file which will make the desired e5-break impossible for Black to achieve. }
15... Nd6 16. Rae1
{ Our pieces are well placed, so it's time to think of a kingside attack towards Black's king with moves like Ng5-h4-h5. }
