{ Black has this extra alternative at his disposal. It looks very odd indeed, but it's not as bad as it looks. The knight can head to f5 and from there to d6. Black can also attempt to change the light-squared bishops by playing Bf5, and he may even attempt an e5-break with the support of f6-Nf7. Once again, this approach is a typical one from someone who searches to make the game unbalanced, as the winning chances will obviously increase. }
7. O-O O-O 8. Re1
{ A move we constantly see in these positions, as it takes control of the open e-file. }
8... Nc6 9. h3
{ A strong move which limits the bishop on c8 and the knight on h6, since it controls the g4-square. }
9... f6
{ On most occasions Black has played this thematic move, but it turns out it's too rushed. If you have been paying attention, I am sure you now the answer that is...   9...Re8  Black can start with this move, but it should transpose to other variations.  10.Bf4  f6  Is a terrible move here due to the standard response  11.c4+-  Which was played in Wist, A -Goetz, A Bayern 2013.   10...Nf5  11.Nbd2  will surely transpose, unless Black does something outrageous. If that ends up being the case, I trust that you will be able to handle it! }
10. c4
{ YES! c4 attacks the pawn on d5 which will damage Black's center, making e5 a lot less potent. Black has tried different moves from this position: }
10... Nf7 { Some players have tried this move, covering the a2-g8 diagonal. }
11. cxd5 Qxd5
{ Probably the best attempt, but that doesn't say much.   11...Nb4  A knight jump is still possible, but it provides only misery to Black's position. To be fair, this can be blamed on 9... f6?...  12.Bc4!  12. Nc3 was not bad in Velkovski,K - Ivanova,K Skopje 2019, but the text move is more precise as it creates the typical pressure in the diagonal.  12...Nxd5  13.Nc3  Nb6  14.Bb3  Black's position really is a sad scheme...  14...Kh8  Black moves out of the diagonal so the pinned knight can move.  15.Bf4  15. Bxf7 achieves nothing, as our light-squared bishop is much stronger than the f7-knight.  15...Nd6  16.a4  a5  17.Qe2  Nf5  18.Nb5+-  As you might have guessed by looking at Black's horrible pieces, we are completely winning. }
12. Nc3 Qd8 13. Bc4 { One of many good moves in the position. } 13... Kh8 14.
Bxf7
{ A strong positional move, but there was nothing wrong with a move like  14.Bf4  . }
14... Rxf7 15. d5
{ The point. Black is getting pushed back and won't achieve e7-e5. } 15... Ne5
{ The lesser evil is to accept the double pawns and 'kill' the bishop on g7. }
16. Nxe5 fxe5 17. Be3
{ Black is pretty much lost strategically. Soon we will target the e5-pawn, which won't survive for long. Qb3-Rad1-f3-Bf2-Bg3 is one way to do so. The bishop can also get to g3 via g5-h4. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "17. Caro-Kann (1...c6) Minor Sidelines"]
[Black "4...g6 (9...f6 3)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4
{ Our strategy during this course has always been to grab the center while we can, and this time is no different! }
2... d5
{ Black takes control of the center and poses an important question to our e4-pawn. }
3. exd5
{ After lots of thinking and consulting with some good friends of mine, I decided to head for the Exchange Variation. }
3... cxd5 4. Bd3
{ The main tabiya of the variation, developing our bishop to the active d3-square. }
4... g6
{ Some players have chosen to play this move already here, with the idea of fianchettoing the f8-bishop. With this set-up the play becomes less symmetrical, which is a typical way for a higher-rated opponent to act. The downside is that Black gets less control of the center, something that can make his position rather passive. }
5. Nf3 Bg7 6. c3
{ A move which we always play, as it's essential to support the d4-pawn. } 6...
Nh6
{ Black has this extra alternative at his disposal. It looks very odd indeed, but it's not as bad as it looks. The knight can head to f5 and from there to d6. Black can also attempt to change the light-squared bishops by playing Bf5, and he may even attempt an e5-break with the support of f6-Nf7. Once again, this approach is a typical one from someone who searches to make the game unbalanced, as the winning chances will obviously increase. }
7. O-O O-O 8. Re1
{ A move we constantly see in these positions, as it takes control of the open e-file. }
8... Nc6 9. h3
{ A strong move which limits the bishop on c8 and the knight on h6, since it controls the g4-square. }
9... f6
{ On most occasions Black has played this thematic move, but it turns out it's too rushed. If you have been paying attention, I am sure you now the answer that is...   9...Re8  Black can start with this move, but it should transpose to other variations.  10.Bf4  f6  Is a terrible move here due to the standard response  11.c4+-  Which was played in Wist, A -Goetz, A Bayern 2013.   10...Nf5  11.Nbd2  will surely transpose, unless Black does something outrageous. If that ends up being the case, I trust that you will be able to handle it! }
10. c4
{ YES! c4 attacks the pawn on d5 which will damage Black's center, making e5 a lot less potent. Black has tried different moves from this position: }
10... Nb4 { Black goes for the counterattack, a typical reaction. } 11. Bf1
{ The strongest way to proceed. The knight on  b4  can now be pushed back unless Black goes for  11...Bf5  which creates the threat of  Nc2  . }
11... Bf5
{ The exclam is perhaps exaggerated, but it's Black's only chance.   11...e6  The famous streamer 'GothamChess,' is an experienced Caro-Kann player, but was in this game no match for the rising star GM Gukesh.  12.Nc3  Nf7  13.Qb3  Levy is getting pushed back and is already dead lost according to the machine. Some more moves:  13...a5  14.a3  dxc4  15.Bxc4  And Black the e6-pawn.  15...Nc6  16.Bxe6  Nxd4  Black's desperate attempt for counterplay loses by force, but there were no alternatives.  17.Nxd4  Qxd4  18.Bxf7+  Rxf7  19.Re8+  Bf8  20.Bh6  One can't help but feel a wonderful feeling of satisfaction when seeing the position on the board. The American streamer threw in the towel in Gukesh,D -Rozman,L chess.com INT 2020. }
12. Nh4
{ A fantastic move and the refutation of Black's concept.  12.Na3  is the human move and it has been seen twice. The position is clearly better for White, but pales in comparison to the text move. }
12... Be4 13. Nc3 { We will now be able to capture Black's strong bishop. }
13... e6
{ The trickiest move as Black aims to open the d8-h4 diagonal and target our h4-knight. }
14. cxd5
{ 14.a3  was my initial plan, but the play after  14...Nc6  15.Nxe4  dxe4  16.d5  Ne5  17.Rxe4  f5  was annoyingly complex. That being said, White is pretty much completely winning as Black has too many weaknesses.  18.Rxe5!  is a wonderful exchange sac, with the point  18...Bxe5  19.Nf3!  Bg7  20.Ng5  and Black has problems on  e6  . White is winning of course, but the text move looked much cleaner if you ask me. }
14... Bxd5
{ Is the necessary reaction, when our play is very simple.   14...f5  And now we have the beautiful move  15.dxe6  Our passed pawns are simply too strong, so Black won't be able to keep the extra piece.  15...Qxh4  16.d5+-  The pawns are rolling down the board and Black will get pushed back with for example a3 or g3.  16...Bxc3  17.bxc3  Nxd5  is met by  18.g3  , when Black loses control of the h6-knight. Simply put, Black is busted. }
15. Nxd5 Qxd5 16. Bd2
{ We are pushing back Black's pieces and creating pressure on the e6-pawn via the a2-e6 diagonal. }
16... Nc6 17. Rc1 Nxd4 18. Bc4 Qd8 19. Be3
{ We will regain the lost pawn on d4 with interest. When the knight moves to c6, we will capture on e6 followed by something like Qa4 with Red1 to follow. We are completely dominating, just look at Black's horrible pieces! }
