[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "17. Caro-Kann (1...c6) Minor Sidelines"]
[Black "4...Nf6 (5...e6)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4
{ Our strategy during this course has always been to grab the center while we can, and this time is no different! }
2... d5
{ Black takes control of the center and poses an important question to our e4-pawn. }
3. exd5
{ After lots of thinking and consulting with some good friends of mine, I decided to head for the Exchange Variation. }
3... cxd5 4. Bd3
{ The main tabiya of the variation, developing our bishop to the active d3-square. }
4... Nf6
{ Black can choose to develop the g8-knight first, although it's somewhat rare compared to the main move  4...Nc6  . }
5. c3
{ We invite Black into a transposition to the Main Line with  5...Nc6  . } 5...
e6
{ A question mark might be too strict, but this move goes against all chess principles as it 'kills' the bishop on c8. Karpov would surely shake his head. Black achieves absolutely nothing playing this way, as the positions often turn into a rather poor version of the main lines. As we will see in the main tabiya, the c8-bishop @@StartBracket@@which is moved to g4@@EndBracket@@ is often a useful piece for defense, but that's completely ruled out here. Lean back and enjoy the lines I will guide you through, as it is very instructive to see how we deal with this horrible set-up. }
6. Nf3 { Let's now take a look at Black's two bishop moves - Be7 and Bd6. }
6... Nc6 7. O-O Bd6 { It's more sensible for Black to place the bishop on d6. }
8. Re1
{ Our plan is no different. We aim to place our knight on the beautiful e5-square, with a dangerous attack. }
8... h6
{ This move makes some sense as well, since it prevents us from playing Bg5. The con to this approach is that h6 can become a liability when defending, as it is a target for our forces. }
9. Ne5 O-O 10. Bf4
{ The same procedure as we've seen so far. Just like I said, the positions are very easy to handle from the white side! }
10... Qc7 11. Nd2
{ Next, we will actually follow up with Qf3 instead of Nf3, as we can target the pawn on h6. }
11... Nd7
{ It seems like Black has to do this.  11...a6  12.Qf3  Ne7  13.Bxh6  was a disaster for Black in Khalezov, A - Korolev, A Nizhnij Novgorod 1999. }
12. Qh5 { We are now threatening to play Bxh6, so Black should play } 12... f5
13. Nxd7 Bxd7 14. Bxd6 Qxd6 15. Qe2
{ Our queen has done its job, so it now returns to the e2-square where it maintains control over the e5-outpost. }
15... Rae8 16. Nf3
{ Obviously we must prevent e5. Black has pretty much gotten himself into a poor version of the Stonewall Dutch, as he severely lacks control over the dark squares. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "17. Caro-Kann (1...c6) Minor Sidelines"]
[Black "4...Nf6 (5...e6 2)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4
{ Our strategy during this course has always been to grab the center while we can, and this time is no different! }
2... d5
{ Black takes control of the center and poses an important question to our e4-pawn. }
3. exd5
{ After lots of thinking and consulting with some good friends of mine, I decided to head for the Exchange Variation. }
3... cxd5 4. Bd3
{ The main tabiya of the variation, developing our bishop to the active d3-square. }
4... Nf6
{ Black can choose to develop the g8-knight first, although it's somewhat rare compared to the main move 4... Nc6. }
5. c3 e6
{ A question mark might be too strict, but this move goes against all chess principles as it 'kills' the bishop on c8. Karpov would surely shake his head. Black achieves absolutely nothing playing this way, as the positions often turn into a rather poor version of the main lines. As we will see in the main tabiya, the c8-bishop @@StartBracket@@which is moved to g4@@EndBracket@@ is often a useful piece for defense, but that's completely ruled out here. Lean back and enjoy the lines I will guide you through, as it is very instructive to see how we deal with this horrible set-up. }
6. Nf3 { Let's now take a look at Black's two bishop moves - Be7 and Bd6. }
6... Nc6 7. O-O Bd6 { It's more sensible for Black to place the bishop on d6. }
8. Re1
{ Our plan is no different. We aim to place our knight on the beautiful e5-square, with a dangerous attack. }
8... Qc7
{ The queen move has been played by Black in a decent amount of games. It's certainly logical, as Black reinforces his control of the e5-post. }
9. Qe2
{ We quickly regain our control of the e5-square, as we are determined to place our f3-knight there. }
9... O-O 10. Ne5 Nd7
{ Played twice, and also objectively the strongest. Black wants to get rid of our beast on  e5  . If we decide to play  11.f4  , Black can play in Dutch-fashion with  11...f5  , when Black will soon get a knight on  e4  with equal play! }
11. Bf4
{ The right way to proceed, as 11. f4 wasn't satisfactory as mentioned in the note above. }
11... Bxe5 { Black gets rid of the beast. } 12. dxe5 Nc5
{ Black has given up the bishop pair, but he will be able to take care of the kingside with f5 next, as we can't go en passant. }
13. Bc2
{ I don't want to give away the light-squared bishop unless we have no choice. In an old e-mail game, Kratochvil, V - Svrsek, R ICCF email 2007, White played  13.Nd2  , but after  13...Nxd3  14.Qxd3  f5  , White's advantage is very tiny. }
13... f5 { A strong defensive move, keeping the kingside blocked. } 14. Be3
{ Our bishop plays no role on f4, so it's better that we move it away so we can defend the e5-pawn with f2-f4. }
14... b6 15. b4
{ An essential move!  15.f4?  would be a huge positional mistake, as Black gets a very powerful knight on the e4-square. }
15... f4
{ Black's best chance is to sacrifice a pawn. In the event of  15...Nd7  , we are dominating after  16.f4! }
16. bxc5 fxe3 17. Qxe3
{ Black has to defend a clearly worse endgame with a pawn down. } *

