[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "17. Caro-Kann (1...c6) Minor Sidelines"]
[Black "4...Nf6 (5...e6 6)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4
{ Our strategy during this course has always been to grab the center while we can, and this time is no different! }
2... d5
{ Black takes control of the center and poses an important question to our e4-pawn. }
3. exd5
{ After lots of thinking and consulting with some good friends of mine, I decided to head for the Exchange Variation. }
3... cxd5 4. Bd3
{ The main tabiya of the variation, developing our bishop to the active d3-square. }
4... Nf6 5. c3 e6
{ A question mark might be too strict, but this move goes against all chess principles as it 'kills' the bishop on c8. Karpov would surely shake his head. Black achieves absolutely nothing playing this way, as the positions often turn into a rather poor version of the main lines. As we will see in the main tabiya, the c8-bishop @@StartBracket@@which is moved to g4@@EndBracket@@ is often a useful piece for defense, but that's completely ruled out here. Lean back and enjoy the lines I will guide you through, as it is very instructive to see how we deal with this horrible set-up. }
6. Nf3 { Let's now take a look at Black's two bishop moves - Be7 and Bd6. }
6... Be7
{ This move is very passive, but it's somehow the most played move in my base. I suspect this is to avoid the annoying Bg5-pin. }
7. O-O O-O 8. Nbd2
{ All natural moves. We are planning to place a knight on e5, support with Ndf3-Bf4, and launch an attack. Note that Bf4 can often be met by Nh5, which is quite annoying as Black gets Bd6 and the h5-knight could jump to f4. }
8... Nc6 9. Re1
{ White has a great score from this position, which is not surprising. Our moves are so simple! The best combination in chess - simple & dangerous. }
9... a6
{ Black has very little to do, so here he attempts to play b7-b5. This plan does nothing about our attack, so we can simply ignore it. }
10. Ne5 Qc7 { Black prepares b7-b5 by supporting the knight. } 11. Ndf3 b5
{ Black has managed to grab some space, but our attack is already decisive. }
12. Nxc6 Qxc6 13. Ne5 Qb6 14. Re3
{ 14. a3 was played in Witte,M - Langer,G Berlin 2014, but there's no need to make prophylactic moves. Our rook is swinging towards the kingside. Where's Black's defense? }
14... Bd6 15. Rg3 g6
{ Black defends against the Bh6-threat, but g6 weakens the dark squares around the king. }
16. Bh6 Re8 17. Qf3
{ We're forcing Black to take the bishop, which will remove one defender around Black's king. }
17... Bxe5 18. dxe5 Nd7 19. Qh5 { With the lethal threat of Bxg6. } 19... Kh8
20. Qh4
{ Black can resign as he can't do anything about Rh3-Bg5, Bg5-Bf6 etc. } *

