{ The main tabiya of the variation, developing our bishop to the active d3-square. }
4... Nf6 5. c3 e6
{ A question mark might be too strict, but this move goes against all chess principles as it 'kills' the bishop on c8. Karpov would surely shake his head. Black achieves absolutely nothing playing this way, as the positions often turn into a rather poor version of the main lines. As we will see in the main tabiya, the c8-bishop @@StartBracket@@which is moved to g4@@EndBracket@@ is often a useful piece for defense, but that's completely ruled out here. Lean back and enjoy the lines I will guide you through, as it is very instructive to see how we deal with this horrible set-up. }
6. Nf3 { Let's now take a look at Black's two bishop moves - Be7 and Bd6. }
6... Be7
{ This move is very passive, but it's somehow the most played move in my base. I suspect this is to avoid the annoying Bg5-pin. }
7. O-O O-O 8. Nbd2
{ All natural moves. We are planning to place a knight on e5, support with Ndf3-Bf4, and launch an attack. Note that Bf4 can often be met by Nh5, which is quite annoying as Black gets Bd6 and the h5-knight could jump to f4. }
8... Nc6 9. Re1
{ White has a great score from this position, which is not surprising. Our moves are so simple! The best combination in chess - simple & dangerous. }
9... Qc7
{ Black's usual way of playing. The queen on c7 prevents a potential Bf4, while it also keeps an eye on the e5-square. Therefore, Black can sometimes capture our knight on e5, followed by a swift Nd7 and f7-f6 with some 'counterplay.' }
10. Ne5 { We stick to our plan. } 10... Nxe5
{ As I mentioned, Black has the option of capturing our knight, followed by pressure on e5 with Nd7 and f7-f6. }
11. dxe5 Nd7 12. Nf3
{ 12.Qh5?!  is inaccurate, when Black has  12...f5  with only a slightly worse position. }
12... Nc5 13. Bc2
{ We have plenty of dangerous ideas like Bf4-Nd4-Qh5. It's hard to come up with moves for Black. Therefore, Black tried the move }
13... f5
{ In Mitrovic,M - Plamenac,A Cetinje 2016, as it aims to close the diagonal of our powerful c2-bishop. Black who was 300 points lower rated than his opponent actually managed to win the game. White's plan was completely wrong as he allowed Black to stay blockaded with 14. Nd4, when things were less clear. It didn't take long until Black's advantage was decisive. Instead, it was vital open the position with }
14. exf6 Bxf6 15. Ng5 { When Black has too many weaknesses. } 15... Bxg5
{ 15...h6  is met by  16.Nh7  , while   15...g6  is met by  16.h4  and later Be3-Qd2-Rad1 etc. }
16. Bxg5
{ Black is incredibly weak on the dark squares, a factor that puts our advantage to decisive heights. }
