1. e4 c6 2. d4
{ Our strategy during this course has always been to grab the center while we can, and this time is no different! }
2... d5
{ Black takes control of the center and poses an important question to our e4-pawn. }
3. exd5
{ After lots of thinking and consulting with some good friends of mine, I decided to head for the Exchange Variation. }
3... cxd5 4. Bd3
{ The main tabiya of the variation, developing our bishop to the active d3-square. }
4... Nf6 5. c3 Bg4
{ As I mentioned earlier, this is an extra attempt Black has in his arsenal with the  4...Nf6  move-order. The differences aren't huge, but they are there!  5...Nc6  is the main move of course, when we respond with  6.Bf4  . I will however use the move-order with  4...Nc6  , as this is by far the most common way to play. Many strong players have tried this move, in particular the Caro-Kann expert GM Alireza Firouzja. GM Maxime Vachier-Lagrave has also played it, but his domain is the Najdorf - a topic for Part 2! }
6. Qb3
{ The most challenging move. Black gets the bishop out on the board, but the downside is that the b7-pawn can be targeted, hence the text move. }
6... b6 { Is just as bad as it looks, so I will only mention it briefly. } 7.
Bf4 e6 8. Qa4+ { The best move which wins an exchange by force. } 8... Nbd7 9.
Ba6 { All of a sudden, there's no good answer to Bb7! } 9... Be7 10. h3 Bf5 11.
Bb7
{ White won the exchange and eventually the game in Kapferer,R Schenker,L ICCF email 2017. }
