[Black "4...Nf6 (5...Bg4 2)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4
{ Our strategy during this course has always been to grab the center while we can, and this time is no different! }
2... d5
{ Black takes control of the center and poses an important question to our e4-pawn. }
3. exd5
{ After lots of thinking and consulting with some good friends of mine, I decided to head for the Exchange Variation. }
3... cxd5 4. Bd3
{ The main tabiya of the variation, developing our bishop to the active d3-square. }
4... Nf6 5. c3 Bg4 6. Qb3
{ The most challenging move. Black gets the bishop out on the board, but the downside is that the b7-pawn can be targeted, hence the text move. }
6... Qb6
{ The super-GM Maxime Vachier-Lagrave has played this move in many blitz games, but the engine is not impressed.   6...Qd7  A typical move, but not the most common one.  7.Bf4  after  7...Nc6  , we have reached the main tabiya of the final Caro-Kann chapter. }
7. Qxb6 { The simplest approach is often the best. } 7... axb6 8. Na3
{ The knight is headed towards the beautiful outpost on b5. } 8... e6 9. Nb5
Kd7
{ The best move, as it allows Black to develop the b8-knight to the improved c6-square.   9...Na6?!  Has been tried, but Black's knight is rather poor on a6.  10.Ne2  Bxe2  The bishop does very little on g4, so it makes sense for Black to take the knight.  11.Kxe2  We have an excellent endgame. A sample line is:  11...Be7  12.a4  Kd7  13.Bf4  It's not easy to come up with something to do for Black. I think it makes sense to attempt getting the a6-knight into the game.  13...Ne8  14.g4  Grabbing some space on the kingside.  14...Nac7  15.b3±  We are playing for two results as Black can't do more than shuffling his pieces around. We should expand on the kingside and eventually push for c3-c4 at the right moment. Black is in for a tough fight. }
10. f3
{ The strongest move due to concrete reasons.  10.h3  was rather unimpressive in Kobalia, M - Vachier-Lagrave, M chess. com INT 2020, when the game proceeded  10...Bh5  11.Bf4  Nc6  , and here White played the very strange  12.Be2?!  There and back again, a tale by Bilbo Baggins? Perhaps the inspiration behind the curious move...  12. ..Be7  and here  13.Bxh5?  was rather poor as the knight on  b5  was suddenly in huge danger! After the further  13...Nxh5  14.Bh2?  was a decisive mistake as Black was totally winning after  14...Ra5  15.b4  Rxb5  16.a4  Nxb4  . A nice display by the French super-GM. }
10... Bh5 11. Nh3 { We are heading to f4 to grab Black's bishop. } 11... Nc6
{ 11...Bg6?  Is a natural reaction, but it gives Black issues after  12.Bxg6  Because he is forced to take with the f-pawn, as  12...hxg6?  13.Ng5  Ke7  14.Nd6+-  Is a catastrophe. }
12. Nf4 Bg6 13. Nxg6 hxg6
{ We do have the bishop pair and more space, but it's undeniable that Black's position is solid. }
14. a4 Be7 15. Kf2
{ We have excellent prospects in the endgame. It won't be easy to break through, but it won't be easy for Black to defend the entire game either. We will slowly, but steadily, improve our position with moves like b3, g3, h4 etc. }
