[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "17. Caro-Kann (1...c6) Minor Sidelines"]
[Black "4...Nf6 (5...Bg4 3)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4
{ Our strategy during this course has always been to grab the center while we can, and this time is no different! }
2... d5
{ Black takes control of the center and poses an important question to our e4-pawn. }
3. exd5
{ After lots of thinking and consulting with some good friends of mine, I decided to head for the Exchange Variation. }
3... cxd5 4. Bd3
{ The main tabiya of the variation, developing our bishop to the active d3-square. }
4... Nf6 5. c3 Bg4 6. Qb3
{ The most challenging move. Black gets the bishop out on the board, but the downside is that the b7-pawn can be targeted, hence the text move. }
6... Qc8
{ Black has tried this move in a lot of games, but it's not very good. } 7. h3
{ Kicking Black's bishop away. } 7... Bh5
{ And now, we should have no fear and grab the pawn on d5 with   7...Bd7  Will give us a very comfortable game after  8.Bf4  e6  9.Nd2  Nc6  10.Ngf3±  It's safe to say that Black's opening play has been far from a success. }
8. g4 Bg6 9. Bxg6 hxg6 10. g5 Nfd7 11. Qxd5
{ We will see something similar in the 6... Qc7-variation, with the only difference being the placement of the queens. }
11... Nc6
{ Black has to do something quick in order to gain compensation for the pawn. Nc6 prepares e5 which will give Black some activity. }
12. Be3 e5 { Black's only decent try to shake things up. } 13. Ne2 Nb6 14. Qe4
{ The most accurate move. It doesn't matter that the h3-pawn is hanging, as we can capture on e5. }
14... Rxh3 15. Rxh3 Qxh3 16. dxe5 O-O-O
{ Black has some compensation as we are undeveloped and our e5-pawn can be targeted, but we have everything under control. }
17. Nd2
{ The knight blocks the d-file so O-O-O is now on the table. It can also move to c4 where it will guard the e5-pawn. }
17... Nd5 18. Nc4
{ The strongest. 18. O-O-O is tempting, but Black has 18... Nxe3 when our e5-pawn falls after 19. fxe3 Qf5. }
18... Nxe3 19. fxe3
{ Another excellent move. The pawn on e3 reinforces our control of the d4-square, where we would really like to place our knight. }
19... Qe6
{ 19...Be7?!  Makes some sense, but it's inaccurate.  20.Nd4!  Qg3+  21.Ke2  Our king is perfectly safe on e2.  21...Bxg5  22.Rf1!  Our initiative is close to decisive. Remarkable! }
20. b3 { Protecting our knight, so we can play Nd4. } 20... Qd5
{ Black has nothing better than taking the endgame. } 21. Qxd5 Rxd5 22. Nf4 Rc5
{ We must now play } 23. e6 { Otherwise we lose the e5-pawn. } 23... b5
{ Is Black's best attempt to hold the draw, when the line goes } 24. exf7 bxc4
25. Nxg6 Rf5 26. Nxf8 Rxf7 27. Ng6
{ Although there are few pawns left, Black is far away from achieving the draw. I suppose it's holdable, but very precise play is required. It's finally time to stop our analysis! }
