[Round "?"]
[White "17. Caro-Kann (1...c6) Minor Sidelines"]
[Black "4...Nf6 (5...Bg4 4)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4
{ Our strategy during this course has always been to grab the center while we can, and this time is no different! }
2... d5
{ Black takes control of the center and poses an important question to our e4-pawn. }
3. exd5
{ After lots of thinking and consulting with some good friends of mine, I decided to head for the Exchange Variation. }
3... cxd5 4. Bd3
{ The main tabiya of the variation, developing our bishop to the active d3-square. }
4... Nf6 5. c3 Bg4 6. Qb3
{ The most challenging move. Black gets the bishop out on the board, but the downside is that the b7-pawn can be targeted, hence the text move. }
6... Qc7
{ The main move in the position showcases a key difference between the main line as we can't play Bf4. }
7. h3
{ The best attempt for an advantage. I'm much less impressed by  7.Ne2  , when Black usually plays  7...Bxe2  8.Bxe2  e6  . }
7... Bh5
{ Black has the queen on c7 this time, which is an improved version of what we saw after 6... Qc8. }
8. g4
{ Once again, the critical approach is the courageous approach - grabbing the pawn. }
8... Bg6 9. Bxg6 hxg6 10. g5 Nfd7
{ The right place for the knight, as Black has to go for something quick in order to get enough compensation.   10...Nh5  Black needs the knight to support the e5-thrust in the center. On h5 it's out of the game.  11.Qxd5  Nc6  12.Nf3  As you can see, Black is unable to carry out e7-e5. Hence, Black won't have enough compensation for the pawn.  12...e6  13.Qe4  Bd6  14.Be3  Ne7  15.Nbd2±  White was ready to castle long with a clean pawn up in Abdusattorov, N -Sadhwani,R Lichess.org INT 2020. }
11. Qxd5 e5
{ White has a terrible score here - only 0.5/4. We should take this with a grain of salt though, as White blundered the queen in a completely winning position in one game. That being said, the resulting positions are tricky, so it's important that we play accurately. }
12. Ne2 Nc6 13. Be3
{ As usual, if we are allowed to consolidate, our pawn will grant us a huge advantage. Therefore, it's vital that we get our pieces out on the board as fast as we can. }
13... Nb6
{ Played in all the games I found in my base, but not covered in Sopiko's course on chess24. Her course is from 2018 while these games are fairly recent, so it makes sense. I believe that Nb6 right away is the most dangerous approach, as Black doesn't allow us to place our knight on the active c3-square.   13...exd4  Black can release the tension in the center, but it makes things easier for us.  14.cxd4!  Not only does this move free the c3-square for our knight, it also covers the key squares e5 and c5.  14...Bb4+  It makes some sense to give a check.   14...Nb6  15.Qe4+  Be7  16.Nbc3±  Black's compensation has faded away, so our extra pawn grants us a massive edge.  15.Nbc3  Nb6  16.Qb3⩲  Qe4+ is less effective now that the bishop stands on b4, so here I prefer the b3-square. Black does have a decent amount of activity, but with O-O-O coming next, the worst has passed. }
14. Qf3
{ The right square for the queen!  14.Qe4  gives Black excellent play after  14...O-O-O  , with  f5  coming with a tempo @@StartBracket@@hence why we place the queen on f3@@EndBracket@@. A clash between two strong GMs continued:  15.Nd2  f5  16.gxf6  gxf6  17.Qxg6  exd4  18.cxd4  Nd5  19.Rc1  Kb8  20.Qg3  Bd6  , when Black had fantastic compensation in Tukhaev, A - Mchedlishvili, M Ankara 2018. Black played a very good game, and found a really beautiful mate at the end. }
14... exd4 { 14...O-O-O  15.Nd2  should transpose. The text move is bet by }
15. Nxd4 { 15.cxd4  would now be met by  15...Nb4  , which is unpleasant. }
15... Nxd4 16. Bxd4 O-O-O
{ Black has castled while we are still slightly undeveloped. Luckily, our king will be rather safe on f1/d1. }
17. Nd2 Rh4
{ A very strong move with the idea of playing Rf4, or even sac an exchange with Rhxd4! Note also that we will lose the bishop if we castle queenside, as the pawn is pinned.   17...Re8+  Black can give a check, but he doesn't achieve much by doing so.  18.Be3  Bc5!  Black has to shatter our pawns, otherwise there won't be any compensation.  19.O-O-O  Bxe3  20.fxe3  Qe7  21.h4±  Black's weak pawn on f7 makes it tough for him to regain the pawn. That being said, it will require decent technique to win this endgame, but we have excellent chances. }
18. Qg3 Re8+ 19. Kf1
{ 19.Be3  loses a piece, so this time our majesty has to move. } 19... Rf4
{ Black's play is scary with ideas like Qc6 and Bd6. We must neutralize the pressure with }
20. Re1 Rxe1+ 21. Kxe1
{ With one rook less to attack with, Black's play is a lot less dangerous. I analyzed:  21...Bd6  22.Qe3  Qc6  23.Rg1  Nd5  Black has to do keep creating threats.  24.Qd3  Now we may even trade queens if Black allows it. Furthermore, our queen on  c4  will attack the f7-pawn which is quite significant.  24...Bc7  25.Qc4  Qd7  26.Kd1  A prophylactic move, moving the king out of any nasty checks.  26...Ne7  And here I found the excellent move  27.Rg4!  This move looks crazy, but Black can't defend the  g7  and  f7  pawn at the same time.  27...Rxg4  28.hxg4  Qxg4+  29.f3  Qf5  30.Bxg7  Our extra pawn gives us excellent winning chances. }
21... Bd6 22. Qe3 { An important move which prevents Bc5. } 22... Qc6 23. Rg1
{ In order to neutralize Black's pressure even further, we should play Rg4, trading the rooks. }
23... Nd5 { Black has to do keep creating threats. } 24. Qd3
{ Now we may even trade queens if Black allows it. Furthermore, our queen on c4 will attack the f7-pawn which is quite significant. We will finish off this variation as a clickable:   24...Bc7  25.Qc4  Qd7  26.Kd1  A prophylactic move, moving the king out of any nasty checks.  26...Ne7  And here I found the excellent move  27.Rg4!  This move looks crazy, but Black can't defend the g7 and f7 pawn at the same time.  27...Rxg4  28.hxg4  Qxg4+  29.f3  Qf5  30.Bxg7  Our extra pawn gives us excellent winning chances. }
