[White "17. Caro-Kann (1...c6) Minor Sidelines"]
[Black "4...Nf6 (5...Bg4 5)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4
{ Our strategy during this course has always been to grab the center while we can, and this time is no different! }
2... d5
{ Black takes control of the center and poses an important question to our e4-pawn. }
3. exd5
{ After lots of thinking and consulting with some good friends of mine, I decided to head for the Exchange Variation. }
3... cxd5 4. Bd3
{ The main tabiya of the variation, developing our bishop to the active d3-square. }
4... Nf6 5. c3 Bg4 6. Qb3
{ The most challenging move. Black gets the bishop out on the board, but the downside is that the b7-pawn can be targeted, hence the text move. }
6... Qc7
{ The main move in the position showcases a key difference between the main line as we can't play Bf4. }
7. h3
{ The best attempt for an advantage. I'm much less impressed by  7.Ne2  , when Black usually plays  7...Bxe2  8.Bxe2  e6  . }
7... Bd7
{ 'A loss of tempo,' is how Sopiko describes this line, and I do agree with her statement as we wanted to play h3 anyway. That being said, it's important to highlight that we are unable to play Bf4 for the time being, which is kind of annoying. That begs the question - how do we place our pieces? }
8. Nf3
{ The knight belongs on the f3-square where it hits e5.   8.Ne2  prepares  Bf4  , but after  8...Nc6  9.Bf4  e5  , Black has equalized. }
8... e6
{ Should lead to the same play as the Main Line, but Black has an extra option in }
9. O-O Bd6 10. Re1 Bc6
{ A very interesting move with the simple intention of placing a knight on e4. This is a very sophisticated way to play, which explains why it has only been played by players rated above 2450. }
11. Qc2
{ I like the idea of maneuvering the queen to the improved e2-square.  11.Ne5  is the alternative. After  11...Nbd7  ,  12.Bf4  Black can play  12...Ne4!  which is a rather annoying move. I analyzed  13.Na3  Nxe5  14.dxe5  Bc5  15.Bxe4  dxe4  16.Nc4  O-O  17.Nd6  Bxd6  18.exd6  Qd7  19.c4  , with a minimal edge.   12.f4  can also be considered, which takes the game towards a complicated struggle. }
11... Nbd7 12. Qe2 O-O 13. Nbd2
{ 13.Ne5  is met by  13...Bxe5  14.dxe5  Ne4!  15.f3  And here, Black has the fantastic piece sacrifice  15...Nxe5!  After the further  16.fxe4  Nxd3  17.Qxd3  dxe4  , Black's pawns are so dangerous that we should give away some material with  18.Rxe4  . }
13... Nh5
{ A very nice move. Black's knight is headed to the nice square on f4. } 14.
Nf1
{ 14.Bxh7!?  leads to a long forced line which is drawn by force. Fun stuff to look at, but I think Black is the one with the chances here as White has to be precise. }
14... Nf4 15. Bxf4 { We can't allow Black to capture our strong bishop on d3. }
15... Bxf4 16. g3 Bd6 17. N1h2
{ We have a double-edged fight ahead of us. I think it's significantly easier to play White with nice attacking ideas like h4-h5, Nh2-Ng4 followed by Nf3-Ng5. Black's bishop pair is strong, albeit slightly passive. Note that Qc2 is a thematic way to meet a potential f7-f6, as e6-e5 is a logical plan for Black. }
