[White "17. Caro-Kann (1...c6) Minor Sidelines"]
[Black "4...Nf6 (5...Bg4) Informational"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4
{ Our strategy during this course has always been to grab the center while we can, and this time is no different! }
2... d5
{ Black takes control of the center and poses an important question to our e4-pawn. }
3. exd5
{ After lots of thinking and consulting with some good friends of mine, I decided to head for the Exchange Variation. }
3... cxd5 4. Bd3
{ The main tabiya of the variation, developing our bishop to the active d3-square. }
4... Nf6 5. c3 Bg4 6. Qb3
{ The most challenging move. Black gets the bishop out on the board, but the downside is that the b7-pawn can be targeted, hence the text move. }
6... Qc7
{ The main move in the position showcases a key difference between the main line as we can't play Bf4. }
7. h3 Bd7
{ 'A loss of tempo,' is how Sopiko describes this line, and I do agree with her statement as we wanted to play h3 anyway. That being said, it's important to highlight that we are unable to play Bf4 for the time being, which is kind of annoying. That begs the question - how do we place our pieces? }
8. Nf3 Nc6
{ The 'automatic' move in the position is to develop the knight to the c6-square. The 'automatic' move in the position is to develop the knight to the c6-square. }
9. O-O e6 10. Re1 Bd6
{ We have now arrived at a critical moment. There are several ways to proceed, but only one way to create problems for Black. }
11. Bg5
{ As an informational, I want to showcase a game my good friend GM Aryan Tari played against GM Alireza Firouzja in Norway Chess. We have seen this move before, and indeed it's very logical, but it turns out that White doesn't accomplish much after the precise }
11... O-O
{ An accurate move! Black doesn't care about a potential capture on f6, as the dark squared bishop will provide decent defense. }
12. Nbd2 Nh5
{ We saw this idea in the previous note, and comes back yet again. The knight will jump to the beautiful f4-square, when we will be forced to part with our bishop. It's becoming noticeable that 11. Bg5 didn't do much. }
13. Qd1
{ Aryan's queen doesn't do much on the b3-square, so it makes sense that he's going back. With the queen gone, he can start expanding on the queenside with b2-b4, Nd2-b3 and even c3-c4. }
13... f6
{ Not a necessary move by any means, as the simple 13. Nf4 equalizes. Firouzja is ambitious so he wants to complicate the game. A necessary cause of action, as I doubt Aryan would have too much trouble holding the fort otherwise. Not a necessary move by any means, as the simple 13. Nf4 equalizes. Firouzja is ambitious so he wants to complicate the game. A necessary cause of action, as I doubt Aryan would have too much trouble holding the fort otherwise. }
14. Be3 Nf4 15. Bf1 g5
{ This is not a fun move to face when you're dealing with the player GM Alireza Firouzja, who's well-known for his dynamic style. 15... Rad8 is safer, with approximately equal play. }
16. c4
{ Aryan chooses the correct plan, but the execution isn't the best. Instead,  16.b4!  was the way to go.  White's plan is to play b5 and push away the c6-knight before he plays c3-c4. The pawns will be quite strong, distracting Black from his attack.  I analyzed:  16...Kh8  17.b5  Na5   17...Ne7  is met by  18.c4!  when I like White's prospects.  18.Rc1  Rg8  19.c4  Qd8  20.Nh2  Qf8  21.c5  Be7  22.Nb3  Nc4  23.Bxf4  White has Black's initiative under control and maintains strong pressure. }
16... Kh8 { Black is getting ready to place the rook on g8. } 17. Rc1
{ We see the difference between this line and 16. b4! Aryan's counterplay is less powerful here, so it's easier for Firouzja to execute his evil plans on the kingside. }
17... Rg8 18. Bxf4 Bxf4 19. b4
{ I like the way Aryan is trying to create counterplay. The engine move is 19. Rc3, a strange move to put it mildly. }
19... Qd6 20. b5 Ne7 21. c5
{ This is when it begins going downhill for Aryan. 21. Rc3 is essential, as it prepares the move g3 which neutralizes some of Black's pressure. }
21... Qc7 22. g3
{ Unfortunately, this move requires the support of the rook in order to succeed. }
22... g4
{ Firouzja is not someone who hesitates. g4 opens the g-file, with deadly threats incoming at White's king at great speed. }
23. hxg4 Rxg4 24. Bh3 Rg7
{ The engine claims that Black is winning, showing how dangerous Firouzja is when he gets the initiative. It's kind of baffling to be honest, as Aryan has made logical moves every step of the way. }
25. Kh1 e5
{ This move is not precise.  25...Bxg3!  wins, as Black's attack is lethal after  26.fxg3  Qxg3  27.Ng1  Nf5  . }
26. Bxd7
{ White needs to maintain control of the light squares. 26. dxe5! keeps some hope after 26... fxe5 27. Ng1! }
26... Qxd7 27. Nh2 Qh3
{ All of Black's pieces are approaching. Nf5-Rag8 will come soon, when Black will sooner or later break through with a sacrifice on g3. }
28. Rg1 Rag8 29. Qe2 e4 30. Rc3 Nf5
{ Firouzja plays excellent attacking chess, bringing every single force into the attack. He's not just threatening Nxd4, e3 is the decisive threat as Aryan won't be able to guard the g3-pawn. Aryan sacs a piece, but the position can't be saved. }
31. Nxe4 dxe4 32. Qxe4 Bxg3 33. Rg2 Re7 34. Qb1 Rge8
{ White finally resigned in Tari,A - Firouzja,A Stavanger 2020.11. Bg5!? is an interesting approach, but if Black knows about O-O followed by Nh5 we won't be able to cause him any problems. Aryan learned his lesson, and as we shall see, he was able to get revenge in the Champions Chess Tour. }
