1. e4 c6 2. d4
{ Our strategy during this course has always been to grab the center while we can, and this time is no different! }
2... d5
{ Black takes control of the center and poses an important question to our e4-pawn. }
3. exd5
{ After lots of thinking and consulting with some good friends of mine, I decided to head for the Exchange Variation. }
3... cxd5 4. Bd3
{ The main tabiya of the variation, developing our bishop to the active d3-square. }
4... Nf6 5. c3 Bg4 6. Qb3
{ The most challenging move. Black gets the bishop out on the board, but the downside is that the b7-pawn can be targeted, hence the text move. }
6... Qc7
{ The main move in the position showcases a key difference between the main line as we can't play Bf4. }
7. h3
{ The best attempt for an advantage. I'm much less impressed by  7.Ne2  , when Black usually plays  7...Bxe2  8.Bxe2  e6  . }
7... Bd7
{ 'A loss of tempo,' is how Sopiko describes this line, and I do agree with her statement as we wanted to play h3 anyway. That being said, it's important to highlight that we are unable to play Bf4 for the time being, which is kind of annoying. That begs the question - how do we place our pieces? }
8. Nf3
{ The knight belongs on the f3-square where it hits e5.8.  Ne2  prepares  Bf4  , but after  8...Nc6  9.Bf4  e5  , Black has equalized. }
8... Nc6
{ The 'automatic' move in the position is to develop the knight to the c6-square. The 'automatic' move in the position is to develop the knight to the c6-square. }
9. O-O e6 10. Re1 Bd6
{ We have now arrived at a critical moment. There are several ways to proceed, but only one way to create problems for Black. }
11. Qd1
{ The killer move! The queen has done its job on b3, so it's on its way to the e2-square where it will have excellent control over the e5-square. }
11... O-O
{ 11...h6  Black aimed for O-O-O in an online game I found, but this approach is not good.  12.Qe2  O-O-O ?  Was soon harshly punished by the strong Iranian GM after  13.b4  Kb8  14.a4  White's attack is incredibly fast. Where's Black's attack?  14...Rhe8  15.Ne5  Re7  16.Nd2+-  16. Na3 was better, but it doesn't matter as Black is busted anyway. Black did not last long, so I allow you to enjoy the rest of the game.  16...Bxe5  17.dxe5  Ne8  18.Nb3  Bc8  19.a5  Ka8  20.b5  Nb8  21.Ba3  Red7  22.Bc5  f5  23.b6  And Black resigned in Tabatabaei,M -Lou,Y Lichess.org INT 2020. }
12. Qe2
{ Now we are ready to play Ne5. This is quite significant, as Black won't be able to play the desired Nh5-Nf4 for this reason. }
12... Be8
{ Firouzja's move, a move which the engine also likes. The idea is to meet Ne5 with Nd7. If we avoid Ne5, Black can continue with his usual scheme of playing Nh5.   12...a6  Is a typical move, when we respond with the standard  13.Ne5  Just like before, we are planning to play Bf4, followed by a swift Nd2-Ndf3. The engine suggests the interesting  13...Ne4!?  Which is a clever pawn sacrifice. Black gets rid of our beast on e5, so we have to grab the pawn.  14.Bxe4  dxe4  15.Nxd7  Qxd7  16.Qxe4  And now, Black's point is shown after  16...e5  17.dxe5  Nxe5  Black has a decent amount of activity while our minor pieces are still in their starting positions.  18.Be3⩲  However, a pawn is a pawn so we maintain a slight edge.   12...Rad8  Is another way the game can proceed. We continue the same way with  13.Ne5  And yet again, Black should go for  13...Ne4!  Otherwise we will get easy play with our standard Bf4-Nd2-Ndf3 set-up.  14.Nxd7  Qxd7  15.Nd2!  An important move. 15. Bxe4 dxe4 16. Qxe5 e5 is a better version than what we saw in the 12... a6-line.  15...f5  Black keeps the e4-knight locked on e4.  16.f3  Nxd2  17.Bxd2⩲  With a slightly better position due to Black's weak pawns. }
13. Nbd2
{ I don't think you need to memorize more than this. Generally speaking, it's more pleasant to play White as our moves are very simple. Black on the other hand has limited things to do. An annoying situation to be in if one is aiming for a win! The idea of playing Nh5-f4 is still there, which I will discuss in the clickable. The engine evaluation isn't too impressive, but remember that you're not playing an engine during the game. After all, one will be able to equalize in most openings with 100% correct play. What matters is that it's unpleasant to be Black here! Let's now take a look at another clash between GM Aryan Tari & GM Alireza Firouzja, this time from the Champions Chess Tour!   13...Nh5  14.Nb3  Nf4  15.Bxf4  Bxf4  16.Ne5!?  g6  Firouzja prevents a potential tactic in the b1-h7 diagonal, while the bishop could also be placed on g7 one day.  17.a4  Aryan decides to expand on the queenside, but I prefer the calmer 17. g3. Black's queenside play is nothing to worry about, so I think we should focus our attention on the kingside.  17...a6  18.a5  Rc8  19.h4?!  Slightly inaccurate, but correct plan. 19. g3! is the accurate way to proceed, which could potentially transpose to the game.  19...Qe7?!  20.g3  Bh6?!  21.h5  Aryan has now obtained a clearly better position with a very dangerous initiative.  21...Nxe5  22.dxe5  g5  Firouzja is desperate and tries to keep the position blocked.  23.Nd4  It's beautiful to look at White's position here. Firouzja is famous for his tricks, but can he get out of this one?  23...Bd7  24.Nf3  The most logical plan in the world. However, the move 24. Ra3! was much better. The idea is Rb3-Rb6, when ideas like Nf5 show up suddenly. Of course, it's not realistic for a human to find such a move, especially in a game with a short time control.  24...Bg7  25.h6  Bh8?  Firouzja doesn't dare to take the pawn, but it was the necessary approach.  26.Nh2  Very logical, but it gives Black some hope. 26. Nd4 was better, with ideas like f4.  26...f5  27.exf6  Bxf6  28.Ng4  It really doesn't look fun to play Black here!  28...Rce8  29.Ne5?!  There's no need to be hasty. A move like 29. Rad1 with the intention of playing Bc2-Qd3 etc was stronger.  29...Bxe5  30.Qxe5  Black is quite solid, so a potential endgame won't be easy to win.  30...Rf3?!  30... Qf6 is the way to go, with a slightly worse endgame.  31.Re3  Ref8?  Believe it or not, this is Firouzja's decisive mistake. Black needs both of the rooks to cope with all of White's threats. With one rook gone, it's impossible to defend. 31... Rf7 was the way. There are few margins in chess!  32.Rxf3  Rxf3  33.Bc2  Aryan's technique from here is pretty much as flawless as it gets with little time on the clock.  33...Rf8  34.Rf1  Bc8  35.f4  g4  36.Re1  Rf7  37.Qh5  Bd7  38.Qxg4+  Kf8  39.Re5  Qc5+  40.Kg2  Qb5  41.Qg5  Qxb2  42.Qd8+  Be8  43.Qd6+  Re7  44.Re2  Qxc3  45.Bxh7  Qc6  46.Qa3  Qa4  47.Qxa4  Bxa4  48.Bb1  d4  49.g4  Bb5  50.Rd2  d3  51.Kf3  e5  52.fxe5  Rxe5  53.Bxd3  Bxd3  54.Rxd3  Rxa5  55.Rd8+  And Aryan had finally earned his revenge in Tari,A -Firouzja,A chess24. com INT 2021. }
