[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "17. Caro-Kann (1...c6) Minor Sidelines"]
[Black "Caro-Kann Conclusion"]
[Result "*"]

{ CONCLUSION: Our first chapter dealing with the Caro-Kann was an interesting affair. }
1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6
{ 4...g6  Playing this with Nh6 looks very suspicious to me, but it's definitely an interesting way for Black to take the game in a different direction. The clue here is to prevent Black from achieving the break e7 or e6-e5 in the center. If we are able to do just that, we will get an excellent edge due to our better-placed pieces and space advantage. A KEY idea is to remember that c3-c4 is a thematic way to meet f7-f6, as it applies pressure against Black's d5-pawn, making e5 way less dangerous. This theme occurs frequently throughout, so you must remember it. After our extensive analysis, it's fair to say that Black's unorthodox attempt to create a more complex position won't go unpunished. }
5. c3 Nf6
{ 5...e6  is a move that can be described by the five letters T R A S H. It locks the bishop on  c8  , so Black will be passive and vulnerable to an attack on the kingside. Why do this? I think Black's 'only' chance is to place the bishop on  d6  , and play  8...O-O  . With the resource  Ne4  , we must change our strategy and put Black under a pin with  9.Bg5  . Black's most accurate response is probably  10...Qb6!?  , which is a clever move. We can also be clever and play  11.Na3  when the resulting positions are unsatisfactory for Black. That being said, I doubt a human would play  11.Na3  without knowing about it beforehand, so this is a decent practical attempt from Black. But I repeat myself. Why put yourself in the situation in the first place with 5... e6? }
6. Bf4 Bg4 { is the big sideline here, played by Firouzja. } 7. Qb3
{ Black has different choices to defend the pawn.  6...Qc8?  looks poor to me. Why place the queen on c8 instead of c7? I will briefly mention that the complications that occur after  7.h3  Bh5  are not THAT simple to handle, but if we know what we're doing we'll definitely be doing well.   6...Qd7  transposes to the Main Line,   while  6...b6?  looks bad.  6...Qb6?!  heads into a very comfortable ending for us. Although winning will require decent technique, we are most definitely in the driving seat as we can slowly, but steadily improve our position. Black has to shuffle around in the meantime.   6...Qc7  is the logical way to proceed, and the main move. Black prevents us from playing  Bf4  , which is kind of annoying.  7.h3  is our response, when  7...Bh5  has been the most played move. I suggest that you take a detailed look at what happens here, as you are required to be precise. If you are precise, you will be rewarded with a nice position with a pawn up.  7...Bd7  is the alternative, which looks like a poor version of other similar lines. However, things are not so simple. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "18. Caro-Kann (1...c6) Major Sidelines"]
[Black "5...e6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6
{ With the first section of the Caro-Kann out of the way, it's time to look at número dos. We will examine some interesting sidelines by Black, before we move on to the main tabiya with 6... Bg4 which is covered in the next chapter. You may notice that I have chosen a different move-order here. The reason is that this move is what Black usually does, as it attacks our pawn. Also, the absence of the g8-knight on f6 gives Black some additional tries. }
5. c3 e6
{ You may remember that I was quite harsh with this move in the previous chapter. The move remains very uncommon, but it's a lot stronger here. The reason why is that Black can choose to go for the set-up Bd6-Nge7-O-O, which is a lot better. Now Black can cover the e5-square with moves like Ne7-g6 or f7-f6. These two moves also make it harder to create a powerful attack. }
6. Bf4 { I prefer placing my bishop on the f4-square before Black plays Bd6. }
6... Bd6
{ The most common move, as Black should get the bishop out before playing Nge7. }
7. Bxd6 Qxd6 8. Nf3 Nge7
{ As discussed earlier, this is the right square for the knight. } 9. O-O O-O
10. Re1
{ It's true that our advantage is far from extraordinary. Black has a very solid position which will be far from easy to take down. However, our bishop is better than Black's bishop, which is a factor that gives us a slightly better game. Practically especially, as it's a lot easier and more pleasant to play White. }
10... f6
{ Playing for e5 is a standard plan in these positions, hence why this move was played by a strong GM in 2019. }
11. c4
{ Another thematic idea I hope that you remember! c3-c4 puts pressure on the d5-pawn, so it's going to be tougher for Black to play e6-e5 at good circumstances. }
11... Nb4 12. c5
{ The right approach is to take additional control of the dark squares.  12.Nc3  Nxd3  13.Qxd3  b6  was very comfortable for Black in Babiy, O - Popov, I Chennai 2019, where the strong GM eventually got the full point. }
12... Qc7 13. Bf1
{ The knight on b4 is looking quite silly. Now we are threatening to attack it with a2-a3, and expand our strong queenside majority with b2-b4. Therefore, Black should get rid of the pawn on c5. }
13... b6 14. cxb6 axb6 15. Nc3 Bd7 16. Rc1
{ Black is under some pressure here, primarily due to the backward pawn on e6. The pawn will also be a target for us the day Black decides to play e6-e5. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "18. Caro-Kann (1...c6) Major Sidelines"]
[Black "5...e6 2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 e6
{ You may remember that I was quite harsh with this move in the previous chapter. The move remains very uncommon, but it's a lot stronger here. The reason why is that Black can choose to go for the set-up Bd6-Nge7-O-O, which is a lot better. Now Black can cover the e5-square with moves like Ne7-g6 or f7-f6. These two moves also make it harder to create a powerful attack. }
6. Bf4 { I prefer placing my bishop on the f4-square before Black plays Bd6. }
6... Nge7
{ The GMs Jobava and Hammer are among the players who have tried this move. Black will play Ng6 with a tempo, before playing Bd6. }
7. Nd2 Ng6
{ The right approach. Black focuses on development first.   7...f6?!  Jobava-style! Black decides to go for an early strike in the center. Or maybe even g5...?  8.Qe2!   The correct reaction!  8.Ngf3  is the natural response, but after  8...g5  followed by a quick Ne7-f5, I think Black is fine! After the queen-move, it's no longer possible to play Ne7-f5 due to the pin.  8...Bd7  This move looks slightly strange, but it's not easy at all for Black to find a good move.  9.Nb3  b6  Jobava stops a potential nasty jump to c5.  10.h4  Another excellent move! A strong idea is to play h5-h6, dismantling Black's kingside.  10...a5  11.a4±  There were many strong moves in this position, seen in Tari,A - Jobava, B Batumi 2019, and in Ganguly,S - Jobava,B Douglas 2019. I prefer the text move due to its simplicity. It blocks Black's counterplay on the queenside. It won't be easy for Black to develop his pieces. I doubt that he will ever be able to achieve e6-e5. The whole concept in the opening has simply put been a huge failure. }
8. Bg3 Bd6 9. Ne2
{ 9.Ngf3  is what we usually want, but here  9...Nf4  is kind of annoying. }
9... e5
{ Black can of course play this move right away.   9...O-O  10.Nf3  We're making it as hard as possible for Black to play e6-e5 at good circumstances.  10...Re8  11.O-O  e5  Black neutralizes our pressure for the prize of an isolated pawn.  12.dxe5  Ngxe5  13.Nxe5  Bxe5  14.Re1  Qd6  15.Qd2⩲  With a slightly better game due to Black's isolated pawn on d5. }
10. dxe5
{ The best attempt for an edge.  10.Bxg6  hxg6  11.dxe5  Bxe5  12.Bxe5  Nxe5  13.Qa4+  Bd7  14.Qd4  was Harikrishna, P - Ganguly, S Kolkata 2018, but it looks completely equal to me. At best, a minimal advantage for White. This time Ganguly was Black, so it seems like he knows what he's doing in this line. }
10... Ngxe5
{ The most natural way to capture the pawn.  10...Ncxe5  is rather similar, while  10...Bxe5?!  is poor due to  11.Nf3! }
11. Bc2 O-O 12. O-O Bg4
{ An important move. If Black does not get activity, the isolated pawn is going to make him suffer. }
13. Re1 Re8 { Black maintains the pressure down the e-file. } 14. Nf1
{ A nice attempt to maintain some pressure. } 14... Bc5
{ Black prevents the knight from jumping to e3. } 15. Qd2 Qd7 16. h3
{ Pushing the bishop. Black now needs to make the correct decision. } 16... Bf5
{ The correct square for the bishop.   16...Bh5  Allows  17.Nf4±  When Black loses the pawn on d5.   16...Bxh3?  Looks like a cunning trick at first, but it loses.  17.b4!  The added tempo on the bishop is important:  17...Bb6  18.b5  Black's knight on c6 will have to move, which means that Black's trick won't work.  18...Na5  19.Bxe5  Rxe5  20.gxh3  Qxh3  21.Neg3+-  Black has far from enough for the piece. }
17. b4 Bb6 18. b5 Na5
{ Now that Black's knight is moved from the c6-square, we can make a jump to d4. }
19. Bxf5 Qxf5 20. Nd4 { We have slight pressure in the endgame. } 20... Qf6 21.
Rxe5 Rxe5 22. Bxe5 Qxe5 23. Re1
{ Black has to be careful, but it turns out that } 23... Qf6 24. Ne3 Nc4
{ Gives him an endgame with excellent drawing chances. } 25. Nxc4 dxc4 26. Qe2
g6 27. Qxc4
{ We have a pawn up and we will keep pressing, but Black has sufficient compensation which provides him great chances to save the game. }
