[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "18. Caro-Kann (1...c6) Major Sidelines"]
[Black "5...e5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6
{ With the first section of the Caro-Kann out of the way, it's time to look at número dos. We will examine some interesting sidelines by Black, before we move on to the main tabiya with 6... Bg4 which is covered in the next chapter. You may notice that I have chosen a different move-order here. The reason is that this move is what Black usually does, as it attacks our pawn. Also, the absence of the g8-knight on f6 gives Black some additional tries. }
5. c3 e5
{ Has been a fairly rare try from Black, but it is possible. The reason why Black seldom plays this move is that it gives him an isolated pawn in the center for very little activity. White's advantage isn't HUGE by any means, but we get a very comfortable position with very little risk. }
6. dxe5 Nxe5 7. Qe2
{ This is the best try for an edge.  7.Nf3  Nxd3  8.Qxd3  Nf6  9.O-O  Be7  10.Bg5  O-O  11.Nbd2  is probably a bit better too, but I think it's less promising. }
7... Qe7 8. Be3
{ 8.Bb5+  has been the main move, but after  8...Bd7  I don't think Black has any problems. The text move is slightly annoying for Black, as he will have to spend a move moving the queen as it stands in the way for the f8-bishop. Meanwhile, we will be able to get Black's isolated pawn under control. }
8... Nxd3+ 9. Qxd3 Qc7
{ Black leaves the d5-hanging, but taking it will give him a ton of activity. }
10. Nd2
{ I prefer to develop the knight. The knight on d2 covers the c4-square, so we can take the pawn in the event that Black once again leaves it unprotected. }
10... Nf6 11. Ngf3 Be7 12. O-O O-O 13. Rfe1
{ Black has very little activity for the isolated pawn, meaning that we get a very comfortable game. I think Black's poor results in Correspondence Chess speak for themselves. }
13... h6
{ Is a better move, but our position is very comfortable after   13...Be6  14.Ng5  I like this move, as it will give Black a weak backward pawn on e6.  14...Qd7  15.Nxe6  fxe6  16.Bd4  The plan from here is simple. We will double on the e-file to ensure that Black is unable to play e6-e5.  16...Bd6  17.Re2  b6  Is a strange move, but it is what it is.  18.Rae1  Rac8  This loses, but Black's position was poor. 18... Rae8 was better, but Black is clearly worse after 19. g3, with the intent of playing Kg2 and f2-f4.  19.Rxe6  Ne4  Was Black's idea, but White is winning after  20.Nxe4!  If Black takes on e4, we will be up two pawns.  Taking the rook is met by  21.Nf6!+  , when the queen is left hanging on  e6  . Pacholsky, M -Bystricky, K ICCF email 2011. }
14. Bd4 Be6 15. Re2 Rfe8 16. Rae1 Rad8 17. h3
{ We have Black's play under control. These positions with isolated pawns are highly unpleasant to play without any activity. The machine isn't as optimistic as it defends very well, but it still thinks that White is slightly better. Be5-Nd4 is a plan I really like. }
