1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 e5
{ Has been a fairly rare try from Black, but it is possible. The reason why Black seldom plays this move is that it gives him an isolated pawn in the center for very little activity. White's advantage isn't HUGE by any means, but we get a very comfortable position with very little risk. }
6. dxe5 Nxe5 7. Qe2
{ This is the best try for an edge.  7.Nf3  Nxd3  8.Qxd3  Nf6  9.O-O  Be7  10.Bg5  O-O  11.Nbd2  is probably a bit better too, but I think it's less promising. }
7... Qe7 8. Be3
{ 8.Bb5+  has been the main move, but after  8...Bd7  I don't think Black has any problems. The text move is slightly annoying for Black, as he will have to spend a move moving the queen as it stands in the way for the f8-bishop. Meanwhile, we will be able to get Black's isolated pawn under control. }
8... Nxd3+ 9. Qxd3 Qc7
{ Black leaves the d5-hanging, but taking it will give him a ton of activity. }
10. Nd2
{ I prefer to develop the knight. The knight on d2 covers the c4-square, so we can take the pawn in the event that Black once again leaves it unprotected. }
10... Bd6
{ Black played this move in a recent Correspondence game, but I highly doubt that a human ever would play it. }
11. Qxd5 Ne7 12. Qc4
{ The addition of Nd2 allows us to place the queen on c4, so Black doesn't get the same desired activity as we will trade queens. }
12... O-O 13. Ne2
{ The knight on e2 is flexible as it can jump to d4, or allow us to trade bishops with Bf4. }
13... Re8 14. Nd4 Bd7 15. Qxc7 Bxc7 16. O-O
{ White was better in Voveris,S - Lagergren,H ICCF email 2016 due to the additional pawn. One can't deny that the bishop pair provides some sort of compensation, but the addition of engines was not enough for Black to hold as he lost after 73 moves. }
