[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "18. Caro-Kann (1...c6) Major Sidelines"]
[Black "5...g6 (6...Nh6)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6
{ With the first section of the Caro-Kann out of the way, it's time to look at número dos. We will examine some interesting sidelines by Black, before we move on to the main tabiya with 6... Bg4 which is covered in the next chapter. You may notice that I have chosen a different move-order here. The reason is that this move is what Black usually does, as it attacks our pawn. Also, the absence of the g8-knight on f6 gives Black some additional tries. }
5. c3 g6
{ Playing g6 without the knight on f6 or h6 is possible as well, as it allows Black to place the bishop on f5 as an additional option. }
6. Nf3
{ 6.Bf4  has been slightly more common, but I discovered that  6...Bh6!  is a rather annoying move to face. }
6... Nh6
{ A fancy move. Black places the knight on h6 in order to capture with the knight when we grab the bishop on f5.   6...Bg7  Has been the most common move, which should lead to a transposition to either the previous chapter or 5... Nf6 in this chapter.  7.O-O   And here one possible transposition is  7...Nf6  8.Bf4  O-O  9.Nbd2  . }
7. O-O Bf5
{ 7...Bg7  will head to the previous chapter after  8.Re1  O-O  9.h3  . } 8.
Re1 { We're minding our own business. } 8... Bxd3
{ 8...Bg7?  Has been tried by some players, but it's a terrible move as White is winning after  9.Bxh6  Bxh6  10.Bxf5  gxf5  11.Nh4+-  The pawn on f5 falls as 11... e6 doesn't defend it due to the pin. Spornberger,M -Napoli,N Fermo 2010. }
9. Qxd3
{ Black has traded the light-squared bishops, but he is slightly worse as we have better control of the center and better placed pieces. A top GM-encounter continued }
9... Bg7 10. Bf4 O-O 11. Nbd2 Nf5 12. Re2
{ I approve of this idea by GM Nisipeanu. He's going to take complete control of the e-file before acting on the kingside. That being said, there were many different approaches to the position, for example 12. a4. }
12... Re8 13. Rae1 e6 14. g4
{ There's no reason not to play this move right away! White wasted time with  14.h3  in Nisipeanu, L - Piorun, K Skopje 2019. The game went  14...Rc8  15.g4  Nd6  16.h4  h6  17.Qe3  until Black accepted White's draw offer. I suspect that White is slightly better, but a draw was a decent result for both players as they were one step closer to qualify to the prestigious World Cup. }
14... Nh4
{ I think this knight jump is what stopped Nisipeanu from playing  14.g4  right away.  14...Nd6  15.h4  is an extra tempo for White when we compare to Nisipeanu's game. }
15. Ng5
{ This is a pretty cool move that intends to trap the knight on  h4  with Qg3/Qh3. Other alternatives exist like  15.g5  with the intent of playing h4-h5 quickly, along with  15.Bg3  or even  15.Nxh4  .  The knight on g5 will also jump to h3 where it supports the pawn launch f2-f4 which is a move that will greatly aid us in our attack. }
15... h6 16. Nh3 { According to plan! } 16... g5 { The best try from Black. }
17. Bg3
{ We are threatening to take on h4 followed by f2-f4 which would give us a dominating position. }
17... e5
{ The only move! Black needs to get counterplay until it's too late!   17...Ng6  Is a natural move, but we are faster than Black!  18.f4!  Just in time!  18...gxf4  19.Nxf4  Nxf4  20.Bxf4+-  Black's kingside is so weak that our advantage is already decisive. We also have e6-e5 under control which means that the counterplay is all gone. }
18. Bxh4
{ The simplest reaction.  18.dxe5  is natural, but Black has counterplay after  18. ..d4!  Apparently, it's not sufficient, however I deem it as highly unnecessary to venture into complications. }
18... gxh4 19. f4 e4 20. Qe3 f5
{ If Black allows us to play f4-f5, he will lose quickly. } 21. g5
{ Important. We do not want to give the f5-square to the Black knight on c6. }
21... Kf7 22. Kh1
{ White maintains a strong initiative after this prophylactic move. Ideas involve Qf2-Qxh4, Qf2-Nf3-Nxh4 and placing a rook or two in the g-file. }
