1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 g6
{ Playing g6 without the knight on f6 or h6 is possible as well, as it allows Black to place the bishop on f5 as an additional option. }
6. Nf3
{ 6.Bf4  has been slightly more common, but I discovered that  6...Bh6!  is a rather annoying move to face. }
6... Bf5
{ Whenever Black has played g6, this move is a possibility. It's a very common idea, as Black wants to rid himself of the poor light-squared bishop.   6...Bg7  Has been the most common move, which should lead to a transposition to either the previous chapter or 5... Nf6 in this chapter.  7.O-O   And here one possible transposition is  7...Nf6  8.Bf4  O-O  9.Nbd2  . }
7. Bxf5 { Damaging Black's pawn structure is the way to go. } 7... gxf5 8. Bg5
{ The most critical move. We develop our bishop, while we also prevent Black from playing e7-e6. }
8... Qc7
{ Has been Black's most played move here, which I think makes sense.   8...Qb6  Black moves out of the pin and targets the pawn on b2.  9.O-O !  We don't have to worry about the capture on b2.  9...Qxb2  The entire point behind 8... Qb6, so I find it hard to believe that Black would try something else.  10.Nbd2  Qxc3  The greedy path is risky, but we must act correctly. Note that 10... Qb6 is met by 11. c4! when we are already winning!  11.Rb1!  Black can't do anything about the pawn on b7.  11...Bg7  12.Rxb7±  I would be incredibly scared as Black, as the king is extremely open. 12... Nf6 13. Ne5 for instance looks already winning for White.   8...Qd7  A logical reaction.  9.O-O  e6  10.Qe2  A logical square to place the queen.  10...Bg7  11.Nbd2  Nge7  The knight looks better placed on the e7-square than on f6.  12.Nb3  b6  Black should prevent us from jumping to the beautiful square on c5.  13.Rfe1  O-O  14.Bxe7  It's not necessary to get rid of the knight, but I like this positional approach. Feel free to play 14. Bd2 though if you prefer keeping more pieces on the board.  14...Nxe7  15.Nc1  Ng6  16.Nd3⩲  Black is solid, but we remain slightly better as we got control over the e5-square and Black does have a pair of double pawns. }
9. O-O e6 { A critical moment. } 10. c4
{ A very strong move which opens the position.  10.Re1  Be7  11.c4  dxc4  was already equal, when White blundered with  12.d5?  12...O-O-O!  13.Nc3  Nf6  14.Qa4  Nxd5  and Black was already winning in Dominguez Perez, L - Kobalia, M Moscow 2019. }
10... Nge7
{ 10...dxc4  is met by  11.d5!  when we break through. Note how our g5-bishop covers the d8-square. }
11. Bf6 Rg8 12. Bxe7
{ The reason why we don't do this right away is that we want to prevent Black from castling short. }
12... Nxe7
{ This makes sense, as Black keeps his pawns intact.   12...Bxe7  Is met by  13.cxd5  exd5  14.Nc3  Black pawns are pretty bad.  14...O-O-O  15.Qd2±  With a clearly better game for us. Black is lacking a knight on e4. }
13. c5 { Change of plans! We are now expanding on the queenside! } 13... Ng6
{ 13...b6  14.b4  accomplishes nothing for Black. } 14. Nc3
{ Black has an open g-file, but our play on the queenside is faster than Black's on the kingside. }
14... Be7 15. b4 h5 16. a4 Nf4 17. Ne1
{ Is the simplest. Where's Black's attack? } *

