1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6
{ With the first section of the Caro-Kann out of the way, it's time to look at número dos. We will examine some interesting sidelines by Black, before we move on to the main tabiya with 6... Bg4 which is covered in the next chapter. You may notice that I have chosen a different move-order here. The reason is that this move is what Black usually does, as it attacks our pawn. Also, the absence of the g8-knight on f6 gives Black some additional tries. }
5. c3 Qc7
{ The first sideline we will take a look at is this popular move that prevents our bishop from developing to the f4-square. }
6. h3
{ I believe that this is the most challenging move, although there is a very interesting alternative in 6. Na3!? The point behind the text move is to prevent Black's bishop from heading to g4, which is Black's standard reaction after the immediate 6. Ne2. Black has several different reactions here, which we will take a look at in turn and order. }
6... e5
{ This is the least popular move. The engine might approve, but for a human being it's usually suffering as Black has to defend an unpleasant position with an isolated pawn. }
7. dxe5 Nxe5
{ 7...Qxe5+?  I'll give this move a question mark as it makes no sense to capture with the queen. Black wastes time as we get Bf4 for free.  8.Ne2  Bc5  8... Bd6 is met by 9. Nd2 followed by Nf3.  9.O-O  Nf6  10.Bf4  Natural moves all along.  10...Qe7  11.Re1  O-O  12.Ng3  Be6  13.Nd2±  With natural play we have obtained a very comfortable position. }
8. Bc2
{ There is an interesting option in  8.Bb5!?  , but the text move is better.  8.Nf3  has been played more frequently, but I think we should keep our bishop pair. }
8... Nf6
{ 8...Bd6  baits us into taking the d5-pawn, but we should just play naturally and play  9.Nf3  . The game transposes to the Main Line. }
9. Nf3 Bd6
{ No fancy moves are required.   9...Be7  It makes little sense to place the bishop on e7 instead of the more active d6-square. Perhaps Black was afraid of Bg5.  10.O-O  O-O  We have been following Paszewski,M - Dzierzak,R Krakow 2019, when I suggest the improvement  11.Nxe5  Qxe5  12.Re1  Qc7  13.Nd2±  The knight heads to the f3-square, with Black's isolated pawn completely under control. In the event of  13...h6  , we can play  14.Qf3  , intending Nf1-Be3-Bd4-Ne3. }
10. Nxe5 Bxe5 11. Nd2 O-O 12. Nf3 Bd6 13. O-O
{ With a typical isolated pawn position which is better for us as Black lacks sufficient activity. }
