[White "18. Caro-Kann (1...c6) Major Sidelines"]
[Black "5...Qc7 (6...e6)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 Qc7 6. h3
{ I believe that this is the most challenging move, although there is a very interesting alternative in 6. Na3!? The point behind the text move is to prevent Black's bishop from heading to g4, which is Black's standard reaction after the immediate 6. Ne2. Black has several different reactions here, which we will take a look at in turn and order. }
6... e6
{ Black has the option of going for the system with Bd6/ Nge7 here as well, similar to 5... e6. }
7. Nf3 Bd6
{ Black has complete control of the f4-square, so we must live with the fact that we are unable to play Bf4. The downside for Black is the c8-bishop which is currently locked behind the e6-pawn. }
8. O-O Nge7 9. Re1 { Black has tried different moves in this position: } 9...
Ng6
{ Has also been tried, but our reaction is no different.   9...f6?!  A typical idea for Black, when it's important that you remember our reaction...  10.c4!  This is the antidote!  10...O-O  11.Nc3  It's pretty much impossible for Black to play e6-e5 at the moment.  11...a6  12.c5  White played 12. a3 first in Sergeev,V - Hofer,E Bregenz 2016, but there was no reason to wait.  12...Bf4  13.Na4  Our knight is headed to the fantastic square on b6.  13...Bxc1  14.Rxc1  Bd7  14... e5 fails tactically due to 15. Nb6.  15.Nb6  Rad8  16.Qe2+-  Black loses the pawn on e6 as we will take on d7 next. }
10. b3 { As we saw earlier, this is how we should develop. } 10... Nce7
{ Slightly strange by the 2400-player.  10...O-O  makes more sense when we respond with c3-c4 with  Nc3  . }
11. c4 dxc4 12. bxc4 O-O 13. Nc3
{ The Russian GM had obtained a fantastic center in Antipov,M - Taher,Y Tornelo INT 2021. }
