[Black "5...Qc7 (6...e6 2)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 Qc7 6. h3
{ I believe that this is the most challenging move, although there is a very interesting alternative in 6. Na3!? The point behind the text move is to prevent Black's bishop from heading to g4, which is Black's standard reaction after the immediate 6. Ne2. Black has several different reactions here, which we will take a look at in turn and order. }
6... e6
{ Black has the option of going for the system with Bd6/ Nge7 here as well, similar to 5... e6. }
7. Nf3 Bd6
{ Black has complete control of the f4-square, so we must live with the fact that we are unable to play Bf4. The downside for Black is the c8-bishop which is currently locked behind the e6-pawn. }
8. O-O Nge7 9. Re1 { Black has tried different moves in this position: } 9...
Bd7 10. b3
{ As we will see in the main option, this is a strong move. We are preparing c3-c4 while we could develop the bishop to the square on b2. }
10... O-O 11. c4
{ Black has to be careful with allowing us to play c4-c5 which could potentially have drastic positional consequences. }
11... dxc4
{ 11...b6  Is a logical reaction, but we get a great game after  12.Nc3  a6  13.Bb2  Qb7  14.Qd2±  We have a strong center with a comfortable space advantage. }
12. bxc4 Nb4 { Makes more sense for Black as he gets some activity. } 13. Bf1
Bc6 { Black is now threatening to play Bxf3 so we must defend the knight. } 14.
Nbd2 Qd7 { A sophisticated move, the bishop is headed to the a4-square. } 15.
Bb2 Ba4 16. Nb3
{ Of course, otherwise Black would win an exchange after Nc2. d5 followed by c5 @@StartBracket@@after exd5@@EndBracket@@ is now a very powerful resource, so Black has to prevent it. }
16... b6 17. Qd2 Nxa2
{ So far we have been following the correspondence game Koronowski, H - Khokhlov, I ICCF email 2012, and here I found the improvement }
18. Rxa2 Bxb3 19. Ra6
{ Black has to be careful of ideas like c5/d5 followed by Qc3 which would drop material. Black's only move is: }
19... Qc8 20. c5 { Black can't take the pawn, as the bishop will hang on d6. }
20... Bb8
{ 20...Bc7  doesn't help, as  21.cxb6  wins material. Black can't recapture due to  Qb4  . }
21. cxb6 Bd5
{ Black moves the bishop out of harm's way. We must find a way to maintain the pressure. }
22. Ba3 Qd7 23. Ra1
{ We keep having tactics that prevents Black from grabbing the pawn on b6. This time it's Rxa8 followed by Bxe7. }
23... Bb7 24. Ra5 Rc8
{ Black has some activity, but is still struggling with the lack of coordination. }
25. Bxe7 Qxe7 26. Qb2
{ A deep prophylactic move that defends the b2-pawn. We maintain a ton of pressure. A logical continuation is  26...h6  when we can respond with  27.Ne1  with the clever idea of playing Be2-Bf3-Nd3. Perhaps Black's best bet is to give some material away with  27...axb6  with  Bh2+  in the end. }
