[Black "5...Qc7 (6...e6 3)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 Qc7 6. h3
{ I believe that this is the most challenging move, although there is a very interesting alternative in  6.Na3!?  The point behind the text move is to prevent Black's bishop from heading to  g4  , which is Black's standard reaction after the immediate  6.Ne2  . Black has several different reactions here, which we will take a look at in turn and order. }
6... e6
{ Black has the option of going for the system with Bd6/ Nge7 here as well, similar to 5... e6. }
7. Nf3 Bd6
{ Black has complete control of the f4-square, so we must live with the fact that we are unable to play Bf4. The downside for Black is the c8-bishop which is currently locked behind the e6-pawn. }
8. O-O Nge7 9. Re1 { Black has tried different moves in this position: } 9...
O-O 10. b3
{ Some correspondence games introduced this plan of playing b3-Bb2/ Ba3-Na3-c4, and it's indeed a very testing move like we've also seen earlier. GM Aryan Tari, who knows his stuff very well in these lines, is as always well prepared. }
10... Rd8
{ GM Fedoseev shows that he's also well prepared, as this is the top suggestion from the engine. }
11. Na3
{ I like Aryan's way of playing, although  11.Bb2  was a success for White in Pospisil, L - Marbourg, D ICCF email 2016. }
11... a6 12. Nc2
{ The point. The knight is on its way to the improved e3-square where it could aid us in a kingside attack. It's also worth noting that the c2-knight protects the b4-square, making c5-b4 a possibility. }
12... b5 { Fedoseev decides to grab some space. } 13. Bd2 Bd7 14. Rc1
{ Aryan continues to play very well. The rook is well placed on c1 where it reinforces the effect of a c3-c4 break. }
14... f6
{ The first inaccuracy comes from the strong GM Fedoseev. A proof that it's not easy to handle this position from the black side!   14...Ng6!  The engine's suggestion is to place the knight on g6 where it can eventually jump to f4.  15.Ne3  Nf4  16.Bc2↑  We are not much better, but we have a strong initiative. g2-g3 will soon follow suit which will push the knight on f4 away. A potential Ng5-Qh5 could suddenly become very dangerous. We can also maneuver our knight to e5, for example Ng4-Nfe5. Don't forget about the c3-c4 break which Black has to calculate every single move, as it is a constant possibility we have up our sleeve. I'd take White any day! }
15. c4
{ Aryan is well-aware of the fact that this is the standard way to meet f7-f6. }
15... Qb8
{ Fedoseev moves the queen out of harm's way, while leaving the c7-square available for the bishop if needed. }
16. Ne3 Kh8 17. Qe2 Be8
{ Up to this point, Aryan has played incredibly well and has pretty much outplayed the super-strong GM Vladimir Fedoseev. }
18. cxd5
{ This move looks strange, but Black is badly coordinated!  18.Ng4  was Aryan's choice, but it lets Black of the hook with  18...Ba3  . However, Black played  18...Bf7  when Aryan once again had the option of taking on  d5  . Instead he chose the wrong direction with  19.cxb5?!  when the game was complicated after  19...Nb4  20.Bxb4  Bxb4  21.Red1  @@StartBracket@@21.  bxa6  was a strong exchange sac!@@EndBracket@@  21...axb5  22.Bxb5  Ba3  . The game went back and forth until Aryan made a decisive blunder later on in a complicated position. Very unfortunate for Aryan, who had obtained a fine position with excellent play. We will see more to Aryan, as he has many instructive games in the Exchange Caro-Kann. Tari, A - Fedoseev, V Germany 2020. }
18... exd5
{ 18...Nxd5?  Loses to the brilliant  19.Nxd5  exd5  20.Ng5!!  The knight opens the path for the queen on e2.  20...fxg5  21.Rxc6!!  Another brilliancy. We must lure the bishop away from the e8-square.  21...Bxc6  This is of course the critical move.  22.Qh5  g6  23.Bxg6  Ra7  24.Bxg5+-  Black's king is too weak so White wins. }
19. Nf5
{ We have managed to open the e-file which gives us a nice amount of pressure. Look at Black's terrible coordination! }
19... Nxf5 20. Bxf5 Ne7 21. Nh4
{ We are making sure that we keep Black under pressure. This move prevents Bh5 also. }
21... Qb6 22. Qg4 { Defending the d4-pawn. } 22... Nxf5
{ It's hard to see what else Black should do. } 23. Nxf5 Bg6 24. Nxd6 Qxd6 25.
Rc5 { We have excellent chances to win in the endgame. } *

