1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 Qc7 6. h3
{ I believe that this is the most challenging move, although there is a very interesting alternative in  6.Na3!?  The point behind the text move is to prevent Black's bishop from heading to  g4  , which is Black's standard reaction after the immediate  6.Ne2  . Black has several different reactions here, which we will take a look at in turn and order. }
6... e6
{ Black has the option of going for the system with Bd6/ Nge7 here as well, similar to 5... e6. }
7. Nf3 Bd6
{ Black has complete control of the f4-square, so we must live with the fact that we are unable to play Bf4. The downside for Black is the c8-bishop which is currently locked behind the e6-pawn. }
8. O-O Nge7 9. Re1 { Black has tried different moves in this position: } 9...
O-O 10. b3
{ Some correspondence games introduced this plan of playing b3-Bb2/ Ba3-Na3-c4, and it's indeed a very testing move like we've also seen earlier. GM Aryan Tari, who knows his stuff very well in these lines, is as always well prepared. }
10... b6
{ Black played this move in two Correspondence games from 2018, so let's take a look. }
11. Na3 { We stick to the same plan. } 11... a6 12. Nc2 Ng6 13. Ba3
{ After analyzing this position for a long time, I decided to stick with simplicity.  13.Bb2  was seen in Azevedo, P - Filin, E ICCF email 2018, when the game continued  13...Bb7  14.Rc1  @@StartBracket@@14.  Ne3  is also possible@@EndBracket@@  14...Rac8  15.Ne3  Nf4  16.Bf1  b5  17.h4  Ne7  and apparently Black has almost equalized. I guess it's not too difficult in these positions with computer assistance...   13.Ne3  like in Hablizel, F - Filin, E ICCF email 2018 makes sense as well, but  13.a5!  is an annoying move. There are many moves here like  14.h4  ,  14.a3  etc. This is just a position where the play is not concrete at all, it's all about finding the right plan. As stated above, the text move makes the play super easy for us. We trade bishops and will later place a knight on e5. }
13... Bxa3 14. Nxa3 Nf4 15. Bf1 Bb7 16. Rc1 Rac8 17. Nc2
{ Simple, but logical moves. The knight is on its way to the e5-square. Our edge is not massive, but we have a very comfortable position. }
