[Black "5...Qc7 (6...g6)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 Qc7 6. h3
{ I believe that this is the most challenging move, although there is a very interesting alternative in  6.Na3!?  The point behind the text move is to prevent Black's bishop from heading to  g4  , which is Black's standard reaction after the immediate  6.Ne2  . Black has several different reactions here, which we will take a look at in turn and order. }
6... g6
{ Black can usually opt for this move, and this position is no exception. } 7.
Ne2 { The right approach as we want to punish Black's 5... Qc7 with a tempo. }
7... Bg7
{ Can be played, but it looks like an inferior version of the usual system with g6. What does Black gain by giving us a tempo with Bf4? }
8. O-O
{ The easiest. I also took a look at  8.Bf4  which I discovered was also strong, but I disliked how complicated the game became after  8...e5  9.dxe5  Nxe5  10.Bb5+  Bd7  11.Qxd5  O-O-O  12.O-O!  Bxh3  13.Qe4  Bf5  14.Qa4  a6  15.Nd4!  Ne7  . White might be doing well, but it's far from easy. When we have a cleaner and just as good option on the table, why pick the complicated one? }
8... Nf6
{ 8...e5?!  Is now rather poor as we can see after  9.dxe5  Nxe5  10.Bb5+±  Black is struggling with his development. After  10...Nc6  , we should ignore the pawn with  11.Bf4  , we pick up more time and have an excellent position. }
9. Bf4
{ Black's Qc7-move has now wasted valuable time as we've managed to play Bf4 anyway. }
9... Qb6 10. Qb3 { A potential endgame would be excellent for us. } 10... Bf5
11. Bxf5
{ I prefer grabbing Black's bishop right away instead of trading queens like in Oyama,A - Batchelor,P Torquay 2013. }
11... gxf5 12. Na3
{ A good move. The trade of queens will give us a nice square on b5 for the knight. }
12... O-O 13. Qxb6 axb6 14. f3
{ We take the f3-square away for Black's knight. Black's weak pawns and lack of a decent plan give us a clear advantage. Black has to shuffle his pieces around while we will slowly improve our pieces.   If Black plays  14...Ra5  , it's a good idea to respond with  15.Nc2  to prevent our knight from being stuck on  a3  after  Rfa8  . }
