[Black "5...Qc7 (6...g6 2)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 Qc7 6. h3
{ I believe that this is the most challenging move, although there is a very interesting alternative in  6.Na3!?  The point behind the text move is to prevent Black's bishop from heading to  g4  , which is Black's standard reaction after the immediate  6.Ne2  . Black has several different reactions here, which we will take a look at in turn and order. }
6... g6
{ Black can usually opt for this move, and this position is no exception. } 7.
Ne2 Bf5 { Black's usual response, utilized by countless strong players. } 8.
Bf4
{ It's unusual to go for this move right off the bat, but it seems to be the most precise as we are planning a cunning switch of plans if Black plays  8...Qd7  9.Bxf5  is not a bad try for an edge though. Black suffered a defeat in the game Eljanov, P - Rodshtein, M Israel 2020. }
8... Qd7
{ 8...Qb6  Can be played, when I like the approach  9.Bxf5  gxf5  10.Nd2!  There's no need to worry about the b2-pawn! 10. Qb3 was played by the '3. exd5-guru' GM Lucas Van Foreest, but his Polish opponent managed to equalize comfortably. Despite that fact, the Dutch prevailed in the end but it was not due to superior opening play!  10...e6  11.O-O  Nf6  We have been following the game Eljanov,P - Balakrishnan,P Chess.com INT 2020, when White has an improvement over the move 12. Rc1.  12.a4  It makes sense to start playing on the queenside.  12...Bg7  13.Nb3  O-O  14.Nc5±  White is much better. Black has achieved nothing with the queen moves. }
9. Bb5
{ A strong change of plans. We are planning to trade our bishop for the knight on c6, instead of the light squared bishops. }
9... Nf6 10. Nd2 a6 11. Bxc6
{ More accurate than  11.Ba4  which was seen in Warmerdam, M - Arutinian, D Amsterdam 2019. Max is always very well prepared, but I suspect he mixed variations here! Anyway, it didn't matter much as he prevailed in the end! And of course,  11.Ba4  is by no means 'a bad move, ' but just slightly inaccurate. }
11... Qxc6 12. O-O Bg7 13. Ng3 Be6
{ It always looks wrong to place the bishop in front of a pawn like this, but it's important that Black has a potential resource in Ne4.   13...Bd7  Gives us a pretty easy time after  14.Re1  e6  15.Nf3  O-O  16.Qd2±  Black has some issues on the dark squares. }
14. Re1 O-O 15. Re2 { A fancy move with a neat idea. } 15... Rac8 16. Qe1
{ We maintain some pressure in the e-file with ideas like Nf3-Ng5 or Nf3-Ne5-Nd3-Nc5.   If Black plays  16...Qb6  which aims to answer  17.Nf3  with  Ne4!  , we should change course with  17.Nb3  with the intention of placing the knight on  c5  and later expand on the queenside with a4-b4. }
