1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 Qc7 6. h3
{ I believe that this is the most challenging move, although there is a very interesting alternative in  6.Na3!?  The point behind the text move is to prevent Black's bishop from heading to  g4  , which is Black's standard reaction after the immediate  6.Ne2  . Black has several different reactions here, which we will take a look at in turn and order. }
6... Nf6 { It's not surprising that this is Black's most common move. } 7. Nf3
{ The right square for the knight.  7.Ne2  allows  7...e5  when it seems like Black has already equalized due to these active pieces. From this position the path is split in two: }
7... e6
{ Black can still go for a set-up with e6, but I am not a fan when the knight is placed on the f6-square. }
8. O-O Bd6 9. Re1 { Different moves have been tried by Black: } 9... b6
{ Black's idea with this move is to play Bb7 and place the f6-knight rather quickly on the e4-square.   9...Bd7?!  Is the wrong plan for Black.  10.Qe2  O-O-O ?  Our attack is extremely fast, making this move already a massive error. 10. .. O-O is better of course, when Black has a poor version of similar lines as Bd7 is not desirable.  11.a4  Be8  12.Na3  The knight is approaching the b5-square.  12...Na5  12... a6 is no better after 13. b4, when b4-b5 will be a decisive break at some point.  13.Nb5  Bxb5  14.axb5+-  White's attack was decisive in Peng,D - Ghatti,S Irving 2017.   9...h6!?  A prophylactic move, but it should transpose to the Main Line after  10.Qe2  There is an interesting alternative in 10. Na3!?, but of course it's simpler to transpose. }
10. Qe2 Bb7 11. Ne5
{ The standard reaction when Black has the knight placed on f6. } 11... O-O 12.
Bf4
{ The best way to play is to start by developing the bishop to f4.   12.Nd2  Rac8  13.Ndf3  is met by the annoying  13...Ne4  , when Black is fine. }
12... Ne4 { Black takes the leap of faith, a correct decision. } 13. Nd2
{ And now, Black's best bet is to trade some pieces: } 13... Bxe5 14. Bxe5 Nxe5
15. dxe5 Nxd2 16. Qxd2
{ White's e5-pawn is rather strong and allows a potential kingside attack which the polish GM perfectly demonstrates. I leave the game as a clickable as it is gorgeous to see how White does this, but the theory section ends here!   16...a5  17.Re3  A very standard plan is to use the third rank.  17...Ba6  18.Bc2  Correct, as we need the bishop for the attack.  18...Rfd8  19.Rae1  Rac8  20.Rg3  Qe7  21.Qd4  Rc5  22.h4!  A strong move, the pawn is headed to h5 when it will be harder for Black to defend himself. White's advantage is already huge.  22...Rb8  23.b3!+-  Preventing Rc4 which could be an annoying defensive resource.  23...Rbc8  24.h5  h6  25.Ree3  The other rook joins the attack.  25...Kh8  26.Ref3  Be2  27.Rf6  A brilliant and thematic move. The rook on f6 can't be captured while it contributes to the attack as it targets the pawn on h6.  27...Bxh5  28.Qh4  g6?  After this Black is mated by force, but the position was lost anyway.  29.Qxh5!  Rxc3  30.Qxh6+  Kg8  31.Rfxg6+  fxg6  32.Qxg6+  Kf8  33.Qg8#  A beautiful game! Swiercz, D - Shimanov, A chess.com INT 2020 }
