6... Nf6 { It's not surprising that this is Black's most common move. } 7. Nf3
{ The right square for the knight.  7.Ne2  allows  7...e5  when it seems like Black has already equalized due to these active pieces. From this position the path is split in two: }
7... e6
{ Black can still go for a set-up with e6, but I am not a fan when the knight is placed on the f6-square. }
8. O-O Bd6 9. Re1 { Different moves have been tried by Black: } 9... O-O 10.
Qe2
{ The simplest path is to stick to our usual scheme.  10.Bg5  is a decent alternative, but Black has the annoying  10...Nh5  . After  11.Ne5  g6  it looks like Black is okay.  12.Ng4?  f5!?  was clearly better for Black in Kuosmanen, K - Crabb, N ICCF email 2014,   but perhaps White can maintain a slight edge after  12.Nf3  f6  13.Bh6  . }
10... h6
{ h6 is always a useful move for Black.   10...Bd7  Gives us easy play after the thematic  11.Ne5±  We have gotten everything we wanted.   10...Re8  This move is on top in my database, but not on my engine's recommendations!  11.Ne5  There's no need to refrain from playing this standard move.  11...Ne7  The highest rated player tried this move, maneuvering the knight to g6.  12.Nd2  Ng6  13.Nxg6  hxg6  14.Nf3  Nd7  And now  15.Ne5+-   Looks dreadful for Black.  15.Bd2?  was a mistake in Shuvalova, P - Garcia Ramos, D Chess.com INT 2020, as it allowed  15...e5! }
11. Ne5
{ The direct approach.  11.Nbd2  is a move you may also consider, which looks 'easier' to play for White than the text move. Black's best try is to play  11...Nh5  which is kind of tricky. It's important not to fall in Black's trap with  12.g3?  as Black has the fantastic  12...Bxg3!  13.fxg3  Qxg3+  14.Kh1  Nf4  15.Qf1  e5  And Black was already completely winning in an encounter between two Norwegian buddies of mine. Kaasen, T - Risting, E Stockholm 2017. I remember this well, as I participated in the same tournament and stayed with Eivind.   White should play  12.Nf1  . I claim that White has a slightly better game after  12...Nf4  13.Bxf4  Bxf4  14.Bc2  . }
11... Bxe5
{ Black should grab the knight right away, otherwise we will have an easy time. There is an alternative in  11...Nd7  I guess, when I like our prospects after  12.f4  . }
12. dxe5 Nd7 13. f4 Nc5 14. Bc2
{ Our attack has the potential of becoming incredibly dangerous, so Black has to be careful. }
14... b6
{ A strong move, Black needs to get activity somehow.   14...a5?  Is not a good idea, as Black severely weakens the b5-square.  15.Na3  b6  16.Nb5  Qd7  17.a4  The knight is looking fantastic on b5.  17...Ba6  18.Be3±  We have everything under control and an excellent position.  18...Na7  looks annoying, but  19.c4  takes care of it, as we can play  Bxc5  followed by  Red1  and  Nd6  in case Black goes  19...dxc4  . }
15. b4 Ne4
{ Black has to get rid of our strong bishop on c2.   15...Nd7?  Gives Black huge problems after  16.Qd3  f5  Samu,F played 17. g4 against Gyurkovics, B in Hungary 2005, but I think  17.a4  Is much easier.  17...a5  18.Ba3+-  Black is is positionally dead lost. Our plan of playing Nd2 followed by b5 and Bd6 is extremely powerful. }
16. Bxe4 { 16.Nd2  would normally be desirable, but here Black has  16...Nd4! }
16... dxe4 17. Na3 a6 18. Be3 { We maintain a nice amount of pressure. } *

