{ The right square for the knight.  7.Ne2  allows  7...e5  when it seems like Black has already equalized due to this active pieces. From this position the path is split in two: }
7... g6 { The most popular move by a long shot. } 8. Qc2
{ There's nothing wrong with  8.O-O  , but I prefer to avoid  8...Bf5  . } 8...
Bg7 9. O-O O-O
{ We have arrived at the main place of this variation. This is one of the rare instances where I provide you with an alternative, but it's because the two moves sort of intertwine in several places. }
10. Be3
{ It's not so common for White to play this move right away, which could confuse your opponent. However, it transposes to the main move  10.Re1  on several occasions. }
10... Nd7
{ Black aims for a quick e7-e5, which is a clever plan.   10...b6  Black aims to place the c8-bishop on the b7-square, but it doesn't look like a good plan.  11.Re1  I prefer this reaction, although Aryan got a fantastic position rather quickly with 11. Na3 in Tari,A - Rasmussen,A Helsingor 2019.  11...Bb7  12.Qc1!  I really like this move which will place the bishop on f4.  12...Rfe8  13.Bf4  Qd7  14.Nbd2⩲  We have a very comfortable position as we have complete control of the e5-square.   10...Bd7  In my base, this has been Black's most popular move. I can't deny that I find it slightly strange, as it looks a bit slow.  11.Re1  We proceed the same way.  11...Rfe8  12.Nbd2  a6  13.Nb3  The knight is headed to the c5-square.  13...Rad8  14.Qc1  This is always a possibility and it seems like a correct moment to play it.  14...Qc8  14... e5 is the lesser evil, but the downside is Black's isolated pawn on e5. So far we have been following Pham,L -Hoang,T Makati 2018, and here I suggest the improvement  15.Ne5±  This is my favorite move of the options White has here. We have a decent amount of activity and a clearly better game.   10...Nh5  Is one way to transpose, as we have nothing better than  11.Re1  Which is covered through the move order 10. Re1. }
11. Nbd2 e5 12. dxe5 Ndxe5
{ Black has an isolated pawn on d5, but objectively a rather solid position. The scenario with these types of positions is that Black has to defend for the entire game and hope it's enough for a draw. Objectively it's fine, but practically it's not fun to be left with such slim winning chances. }
13. Rfe1 Re8
{ 13...Nxd3  14.Qxd3  Bf5?!  Looks scary, but we can safely grab the pawn.  15.Qxd5±  We are a clean pawn up.   13...Be6  14.Nxe5  Trading pieces is a standard strategy against an isolated pawn.  14...Nxe5  15.Bd4⩲  White had the isolated pawn under control in Wei,Y-Le, Q Chess.com INT 2020. }
14. Rad1 Be6 15. Nxe5 { Same strategy. } 15... Nxe5 16. Bb5
{ Gaining a tempo on the rook. } 16... Bf5 17. Qc1
{ Black has some activity, but we have everything under control. } 17... Bd7
{ 17...Nd3  Is nothing to worry about. Trading pieces will only benefit us.  18.Bxd3  Bxd3  19.Nf3  Bc4   19...Be4  is met by  20.Nd4  .  20.Qc2⩲  With a solid edge for us. Black is not much worse, but he will have to suffer. }
18. Bf1 Bc6 19. Nb3 { With a stable advantage. } *

