10. Re1
{ The main move and my recommendation, although the play is likely to transpose to 10. Be3. }
10... Re8
{ Black has tried this natural rook move in some games too.   10...Nd7  Black can play this move again with the intention of playing a quick e7-e5.  11.Be3   There are alternatives but none are superior to this move. Therefore, it makes sense to transpose. And indeed, after  11...e5  12.dxe5  Ndxe5  13.Nbd2  we reach a position covered under  10.Be3  .   10...Bd7  Black has this move in his arsenal.  11.Be3  The simple route is to transpose to a position covered under 10. Be3. I analyzed 10. Ne5 for a long time which is an interesting alternative, but let's keep it simple!   10...a6  A standard move to play in these positions.  11.Be3  b5?!  The strong GM picks the wrong plan.  12.a4  b4  13.Nbd2  bxc3  And here, in Kleinman,M - Nyzhnyk,I Burlingame 2018 I think the right capture is  14.Qxc3⩲  With a nice position for White as we are planning to expand on the queenside b2-b4, and Nb3-Nc5. }
11. Be3
{ We usually make the same moves with White as you can see. Re1-Be3-Nbd2. }
11... Nh5
{ A natural idea for Black is to jump to h5 in order to get to the f4-square which will chase our d3-bishop away. This will allow Black to develop the c8-bishop to the improved square on f5. }
12. Nbd2 Nf4 13. Bf1 { We won't allow Black to capture our precious bishop. }
13... Bf5 14. Qb3
{ We are now threatening to take on f4 when a pawn on b7 or on d5 will be hanging. We also have Ne5 in the air which can be quite annoying for Black. Black is in trouble here and decides to sac the pawn on d5. }
14... h5 15. Bxf4 Qxf4 16. Qxd5 { There's no reason not to! } 16... e5
{ This is what Pragg was hoping for. } 17. g3 Qh6 18. Bc4
{ 18.h4  worked out well for White in Aronian, L - Praggnanandhaa, R Kolkata 2018, but it made the game more complex than necessary. After this move it looks like Black is in huge trouble. }
18... Be6 19. Qb5 Bxc4 20. Nxc4 { There's no counterplay to be found, as }
20... exd4 21. Nd6 Rxe1+ 22. Rxe1
{ Is just winning for White due to the hanging pawns on b7 and f7. } *

