1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 Nf6
{ After a ton of analysis, we have reached Black's main continuation in the position. This is also the approach GM Erwin L'Ami suggests in his course. }
6. Bf4
{ 'The best scheme' - GM Erwin L'Ami.  6.h3  was suggested to me a while back by my buddy GM Lucas Van Foreest, until recently where he pointed out that  6...e5  for Black should equalize.  7.dxe5  Nxe5  8.Nf3  Nxd3+  9.Qxd3  Bd6  is how the game continues. Erwin points out that Black's lead in development justifies the isolated pawn. I wholeheartedly trust the Dutch GMs here, so I did not attempt to find an edge for White here on my own.   As  6.Nd2  blocks our bishop and  6.Nf3  allows  6...Bg4  , I firmly believe that this is our best shot for an edge.   Black's main response is  6...Bg4  , which I have saved for the final chapter. Black has a significant amount of options to battle  6.Bf4  , which is covered extensively below. }
6... Qb6
{ We must consider this move which makes use of the fact that our bishop no longer stands on the c1-square. }
7. Qb3
{ The right way to defend the b2-square.  7.Na3!?  is a cool alternative, when I think  7...e5!  gives Black decent chances. }
7... Qxb3
{ The usual response. 6... Bg4 is also played a lot, which is a fancy way of reaching a position covered in our final Caro-Kann chapter.   7...Qa5?!  Is a rather poor move. What does Black achieve by going Qb6-Qa5? Our queen is also well placed on b3. Perhaps the move could be used as a trick since it targets the pawn on d4, but the chance for White to fall into it is close to zero as all the natural moves in the position defend the pawn.  8.Nd2  e6  9.h3  It's always nice to have the option of placing the bishop on h2 in the event of Nh5.  9...Be7  10.Ngf3  O-O  11.O-O  ±  With a clearly better position in Lopez Silva,H - Cuevas Araya,W Santiago de Chile 2009. Not a shock when you look at Black's passive pieces compared to ours. }
8. axb3 Bd7
{ Another logical move by Black, with a rather unsatisfying result as the position will remain passive. }
9. b4 { The same plan, removing the knight from the c6-square! } 9... e6 10. h4
{ Yet again, I like to prevent Black's Nh5-Bd6 idea. } 10... Be7 11. Nf3 O-O
12. b5 Nd8 13. O-O
{ The position is very similar to the one we saw after 8... e6, and the evaluation hasn't changed. }
