{ The right way to defend the b2-square.  7.Na3!?  is a cool alternative, when I think  7...e5!  gives Black decent chances. }
7... Qxb3
{ The usual response.  6...Bg4  is also played a lot, which is a fancy way of reaching a position covered in our final Caro-Kann chapter. }
8. axb3 g6
{ Black could try this plan as well, intending fianchettoing the bishop and developing the light-squared bishop to f5. }
9. b4 Bg7 10. Nf3
{ 10. b5 is tempting, but Black has the excellent move 10... e5 when things are not as clear. }
10... Bf5
{ Black should try to trade bishops. Other moves are of course possible, but they are not very challenging. }
11. Bxf5
{ Destroying Black's pawn structure. Alternatives like  11.Bb5  and  11.Be2  are good, too. }
11... gxf5 12. g3
{ A prophylactic move that prevents Black from playing Nh5-f4 in some lines. }
12... e6 13. Nbd2
{ With a clearly better game thanks to our superior pieces and open file on the queenside. }
