[White "18. Caro-Kann (1...c6) Major Sidelines"]
[Black "5...Nf6 (6...Qb6 5)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 Nf6
{ After a ton of analysis, we have reached Black's main continuation in the position. This is also the approach GM Erwin L'Ami suggests in his course. }
6. Bf4 { 'The best scheme' - GM Erwin L'Ami. } 6... Qb6
{ We must consider this move which makes use of the fact that our bishop no longer stands on the c1-square. }
7. Qb3
{ The right way to defend the b2-square.  7.Na3!?  is a cool alternative, when I think  7...e5!  gives Black decent chances. }
7... Qxb3 8. axb3 Nh5
{ I choose to give this move an exclam, as Black should play it at once. Now he'll be able to place his bishop on d6. }
9. Be3 e6
{ 9...e5  I don't think Black should go for this move, as the pawn on d5 becomes rather weak.  10.dxe5  Nxe5  11.Be2  Nf6  The pawn on a7 can be grabbed right now, but instead of taking it I think we should focus on developing our pieces.  12.Na3  Bd6  13.Nf3  a6  Black defends the pawn, but he will be left with a rather uncomfortable isolani position.  14.Bd4  Nxf3+  15.Bxf3  O-O  16.O-O  ±  Black's pawn on d5 has a very grim future. Black will have to rely on getting sufficient compensation for it, which will be far from easy. }
10. b4 { The b4-b5 idea once again looks very strong. } 10... Bd6 11. b5 Nd8
12. Ne2 { We shouldn't allow Black to place the knight on f4. } 12... O-O 13.
O-O f5
{ Black has to do something in order to get some play. In Stojanovski,D - Brzovski,T Struga 2007, White continued with 14. f3, but I think }
14. f4 { Is stronger, as we get a strong grip on the e5-square. } 14... Nf6 15.
b3 { We are preparing to strengthen our queenside pawn majority. } 15... Bd7
16. Nd2 Nf7 17. Ra2
{ Black is gonna have a hard time as we're planning to double our rooks in the a-file when a pawn is very likely to fall. }
