[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "18. Caro-Kann (1...c6) Major Sidelines"]
[Black "5...Nf6 (6...e6)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 Nf6
{ After a ton of analysis, we have reached Black's main continuation in the position. This is also the approach GM Erwin L'Ami suggests in his course. }
6. Bf4 { 'The best scheme' - GM Erwin L'Ami. } 6... e6
{ GM Erwin L'Ami calls this 'admitting defeat' in his notes, and I will certainly agree @@StartBracket@@you guys should know my stance on e6 by now if you've been paying attention!@@EndBracket@@. The dutch GM says that Black gets problems with the c8-bishop which is true. Play should become fairly similar to what we've seen, unless Black goes for a quick e6-e5 which changes things a bit - hence my coverage on this move. }
7. Nd2 Bd6 8. Bxd6 Qxd6 9. Ngf3 O-O 10. O-O
{ And we have reached the key position where Black should grab his chance to liberate his pieces by playing e6-e5. Otherwise, we will get control of the e5-square which gives us a rather easy game like we've seen in other instances where Black has played e6. }
10... e5
{ Black opens the diagonal for the bishop on c8, when the prize to pay is an isolated pawn. }
11. dxe5 Nxe5 12. Nxe5 Qxe5 13. Re1
{ White has scored well from here which is not surprising as it's very easy to play White. Black has to defend an unpleasant position with almost zero chances of winning - a notion we've talked about before. }
13... Qf4
{ The queen goes to the active f4-square.   13...Qd6  And here, a strong move is to play  14.Qa4!  The queen is on its way to the d4-square where it will perfectly block the d5-pawn.  14...Bd7  15.Qd4⩲  Black has an unpleasant journey ahead.   13...Qc7  14.Qa4  Same strong idea!  14...Bd7  15.Qd4  Qb6  Black tried this move in a game, but the resulting endgame is very comfortable for us.  16.Qxb6  axb6  17.f3  We're taking control of the e4-square, while also making room for our king in the future.  17...Rfe8  18.Rxe8+  Nxe8  19.Nf1  The knight heads to e3 where it will increase the pressure against Black's pawn.  19...Nd6  20.Ne3  Be6  21.a3±  With a very promising endgame which White eventually won in Soldano,G - Beck,G ICCF email 2011. The game continued with 21... Nc4, when 22. Bxc4 dxc4 23. Rd1 looks completely winning for White. }
14. g3 { Pushing the queen away. } 14... Qh6
{ By far the best try to complicate the game due to our slightly exposed king. }
15. Qc1
{ A weird-looking move, with the intent of playing Nb3 which will trade queens.   15.Nb3  was what I initially considered, but  15...Ng4  was slightly annoying to me. However, White is apparently doing well after  16.h4  Qf6  17.Qe2  Bd7  18.Nc5  . }
15... Qh5
{ It's important to note that  15...Ng4  is now met by  16.Nf3  , when  16...Qf6  is answered by  17.Kg2  . }
16. Nb3 Bf5
{ Black should try to trade bishops, as we are slightly exposed on the light squares.   16...Ng4  Is not as scary as it looks.  17.h4  Ne5  18.Be2  We have everything under control.  18...Bg4  19.Bxg4  Nxg4  20.Nd4±  As Black's kingside initiative has vanished, the position is rather poor due to the isolated d5-pawn. }
17. Bf1 Rfe8 18. Nd4 Bh3
{ There's no problems for us to avoid the trade of bishops. } 19. Bb5 Rxe1+ 20.
Qxe1 a6 21. Ba4
{ Maintaining our control over the e8-square. Some plans forward for us include Qe3-Qf4, Qe3-Ne2-Nf4 or the more sophisticated f2-f3 followed by Kf2 or Qf2. }
21... b5 22. Bc2 Re8 23. Qd2
{ We maintain an excellent position, as Black doesn't have justifiable play for the isolated pawn. }
