1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 Nf6
{ After a ton of analysis, we have reached Black's main continuation in the position. This is also the approach GM Erwin L'Ami suggests in his course. }
6. Bf4 { 'The best scheme' - GM Erwin L'Ami. } 6... g6
{ Just like we saw with 5... Qc7, Black can fianchetto his bishop or play the thematic move Bf5. Black can even play an early Nh5, which is actually fairly interesting. }
7. Nd2 Nh5
{ Black has an interesting option in jumping to the rim right away - removing our bishop from the square on f4.   7...Qb6  Black can once again attack the b2-pawn, but it doesn't do much.  8.Nb3⩲  Is a very simple reaction, when Black's queen should return to c7 one day as it does very little on b6. Nb3 on the other hand, is a useful move. }
8. Be3 { The right square, as we do want to keep our bishop. } 8... Qd6 9. Ne2
{ The usual response is to prevent Black's idea. The machine also mentions  9.Ngf3  Nf4  10.Bf1  , with the intention of kicking Black's f4-knight away with Nb3-Qd2 eventually. Definitively a possible approach, but I prefer the text way of handling the position. }
9... Bg7 10. h3 { Always a useful move in these positions. } 10... Nf6
{ The strong GM Michael Roiz played this move, but it looks rather poor. } 11.
Bf4 Qd8
{ And now, I am a bit puzzled by the fact that White didn't play the supernatural }
12. Nf3
{ Which gives him a pleasant version of the Main Line. 12. Ng3 was the move in Jakubowski,K - Roiz, M Germany 2010 when White still had a nice advantage, but there was no need to jump to g3 just yet. }
12... O-O 13. O-O Ne4
{ Happened in Shevchenko,K - Rodrigue Lemieux,S Chess.com INT 2020, when I think the right approach is to play }
14. Ng3 f5 15. h4
{ We're in control, with a nice plan being Ne2-Be3-g3-Kg2-Qc1-Bh6. We could also consider placing our g3-knight on f4 via e2. }
