[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 Nf6
{ After a ton of analysis, we have reached Black's main continuation in the position. This is also the approach GM Erwin L'Ami suggests in his course. }
6. Bf4 { 'The best scheme' - GM Erwin L'Ami. } 6... g6
{ Just like we saw with 5... Qc7, Black can fianchetto his bishop or play the thematic move Bf5. Black can even play an early Nh5, which is actually fairly interesting. }
7. Nd2 Nh5
{ Black has an interesting option in jumping to the rim right away - removing our bishop from the square on f4. }
8. Be3 { The right square, as we do want to keep our bishop. } 8... Qd6 9. Ne2
{ The usual response is to prevent Black's idea. The machine also mentions  9.Ngf3  Nf4  10.Bf1  , with the intention of kicking Black's f4-knight away with Nb3-Qd2 eventually. Definitively a possible approach, but I prefer the text way of handling the position. }
9... Bg7 10. h3 { Always a useful move in these positions. } 10... O-O
{ A much better move as Black's  10...Nf6?!  only helped us as we saw. } 11.
Nf3 f5
{ A typical idea when Black has moved the knight to h5. Now, he can get some nice space with f5-f4 followed by e7-e5 if we don't act correctly. }
12. g3
{ We should prevent Black from playing f5-f4. It's also worth nothing that we're planning to jump to the f4-square with our knight, unless Black goes for the central break right away. }
12... e5 { Black shouldn't waste time. } 13. dxe5 Nxe5 14. Nxe5 Bxe5 15. Bh6
{ A strong move, as we move the bishop out of harm's way. The bishop is a nice asset on h6, while it avoids f5-f4 with a tempo. }
15... Re8
{ With a pretty interesting position in Broadway, D-Hrzina,B ICCF email 2017. }
16. Qd2
{ I discovered that this was the most challenging response. We're simply going to castle queenside and apply pressure against Black's pawn on d5.   16.Qc2!?  was played in the email game, when Black eventually managed to hold. }
16... Rb8
{ An interesting move, as Black is trying to launch the b-pawn up the board with b5-b4.   16...Bd7?!  Gives us an easy time after  17.O-O-O  Rad8  18.Bc2±  With excellent pressure against Black's d5-pawn. Black's position looks rather terrible. }
17. Bb5 { The correct reaction. } 17... Bd7 18. Bxd7 Qxd7 19. O-O-O
{ We're faster than Black. } 19... Nf6 20. f3
{ It's essential to prevent Black from jumping to e4. } 20... b5 21. Bf4
{ Black's attack will be far less venomous without the bishop on e5. } 21... a5
22. Bxe5 Rxe5 23. Kb1 { Black has nothing, as } 23... b4 24. cxb4 Rxb4 25. Nd4
{ Demonstrates. Black is almost busted here, as the advantage is reaching close to +2.00. The reasons for this is Black's poor coordination, Black's vulnerable king and loose pawns on a5 and d5. }
