{ Black counter attacks.   18...Re4?  Is just terrible for Black after  19.O-O-O  +-   Black has huge problems with his exposed king. I analyzed:  19...Qc5+  20.Kb1  Qxb5  21.Nxd4  Qb6  22.f3  Re8  23.g4  when White's attack is decisive.   18...Rd8?  Doesn't impress either. A nice line I found was  19.Nxd4!  Qxd4  20.Bc4+!  Forcing Black's king to the corner.  20...Kh8  21.Qxd4+  Rxd4  22.Rd1  Look at the amazing job our bishop on h6 is doing!  22...Rxd1+  23.Kxd1  Bd7  Necessary, otherwise Black loses quickly after Re1-Re7.  24.Re1  Re8  25.Rxe8+  Bxe8  26.Be3  The pawn on a7 is under attack, but more importantly, We are also going to play Bd4 when Black will be completely pinned down.  26...a6  27.Bd4+  Ng7  28.Bd5+-  A beautiful picture of how strong the bishop pair can become.   18...Qd5!?  Black forces the trade of some pieces.  19.O-O-O  Qxb5  20.Nxd4  Black has to be careful due to the absence of the dark-squared bishop. However, if the right measures are taken, our advantage won't climb over slightly better.  20...Qb6  21.Rhe1  Bd7  22.Kb1  Nf6  23.f3⩲  Our strong dark-squared bishop applies some pressure on Black's position, but it's not more than slightly better. Practically it's another story, as the bishop on h6 is very scary. }
19. O-O-O { And now, some pieces will get traded after } 19... Rxb5 20. Qxd4
Qxd4 21. Rxd4 Be6 22. Rhd1 { We have the upper hand in the ending. } *

