{ After a ton of analysis, we have reached Black's main continuation in the position. This is also the approach GM Erwin L'Ami suggests in his course. }
6. Bf4 { 'The best scheme' - GM Erwin L'Ami. } 6... g6
{ Just like we saw with 5... Qc7, Black can fianchetto his bishop or play the thematic move Bf5. Black can even play an early Nh5, which is actually fairly interesting. }
7. Nd2 Bf5 8. Bxf5 { We'll accept the challenge. } 8... gxf5 9. Nh3
{ A very strong move, as the knight can eventually move to the f4-square where it will be excellently placed. It also allows f2-f3, which can be very useful in some instances. }
9... e6 10. O-O Bd6 11. Bg5 { Pinning Black's knight. } 11... h6 12. Bh4 Be7
{ It makes sense for Black to block the pin.   12...Qe7?  Is rather poor, due to the concrete  13.c4!  Black has problems with the pawn on d5.  13...dxc4  14.Nxc4  O-O-O  And here  15.Nxd6+!   The right approach.  15.d5  is tempting, but Black will regain the piece after  15...Bc7  16.d6  Bxd6  17.Bxf6  Qxf6  18.Nxd6+  Kb8  , as the knight is pinned.  15...Rxd6  16.Rc1  A strong move, pinning Black's knight on c6.  16...Kb8?   A poor move.  16...Qd8  is the lesser evil, but I think Black is also busted after  17.Qa4  with ideas like  Qxa7  ,  Bg3  and  d5  in the air.  17.Rxc6!  A beautiful tactic. Black's knight on f6 is a lost cause, due to the powerful pin.  17...Rxc6  18.Qe1+-  Qe5 comes, when we win material. }
13. Nf4 Qc7 { Black is preparing to castle queenside. } 14. g3 O-O-O 15. Qe2
{ We're threatening to take on e6, a pretty nice tactic. } 15... Ne4 16. Bxe7
Nxe7 17. Nf3
