{ After a ton of analysis, we have reached Black's main continuation in the position. This is also the approach GM Erwin L'Ami suggests in his course. }
6. Bf4 { 'The best scheme' - GM Erwin L'Ami. } 6... g6
{ Just like we saw with 5... Qc7, Black can fianchetto his bishop or play the thematic move Bf5. Black can even play an early Nh5, which is actually fairly interesting. }
7. Nd2 Bg7 8. Ngf3 Nh5 { Black can jump to the rim in this position as well. }
9. Be3 Qd6
{ We see this move once again. A big difference here is that our knight stands on f3 so we're able to castle.   9...f5  is an option as well, when  10.Nb3  f4  11.Bd2  O-O  12.O-O  transposes to a position covered a bit later in the chapter.   9...e5?  This might look natural, but Black needs to castle first before thinking about moves like these.  10.Nxe5  Nxe5  11.dxe5  Bxe5  12.Nf3  Black has problems with his king, which can be seen after  12...Bg7  13.Bc5+-  Black is in dire straits as castling is impossible. }
