1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 Nf6
{ After a ton of analysis, we have reached Black's main continuation in the position. This is also the approach GM Erwin L'Ami suggests in his course. }
6. Bf4 { 'The best scheme' - GM Erwin L'Ami. } 6... g6 7. Nd2 Bg7 8. Ngf3 O-O
9. O-O
{ The main tabiya of this line. Black has tried a large number of different continuations, as the game is not very concrete - a common theme for this opening. Usually it's all about finding the right ideas and placing the pieces in the correct positions. Let's take a look at how the game could continue: }
9... Bg4
{ Black gives away the bishop pair with this move, but in return he's hoping that the solid pawn structure makes up for it.   9...a6  A standard idea by Black, but it doesn't look too strong.  10.Re1  b5  Black grabs space on the queenside, but it doesn't really help too much. We can target the b5-pawn with a2-a4 some day, while we have a nice square on c5 for our knight.  11.Ne5  Nxe5  12.Bxe5  Qb6  13.Nb3±  Everything has gone right for us in the opening as we're placing our knight on the wonderful c5-square next. It's hard to come up with a great plan for Black. }
10. h3 Bxf3 11. Nxf3 e6
{ Black is solid, but it's not a difficult task to play with the white pieces here. }
12. Re1 Rc8 13. g3
{ This is a move I like a lot. We are preparing Kg2 when it we could eventually push for h4-h5! }
13... Na5
{ A logical plan way for Black to continue - placing the knight on c4. It looks nice, but it really doesn't do much there. }
14. Qe2 Nc4 15. Kg2 { It's time to set our plan in motion. } 15... a6 16. h4
Qe7 17. a4
{ It's not necessary to play this move, but I like making it even more difficult for Black to create any sorts of counterplay. }
17... h5 { It makes sense for Black to slow our play down on the kingside. }
18. a5
{ We're now switching gears completely with the plan of playing b3-c4. The position is difficult to handle for Black, as pointed out in the sample line: }
18... Qd8 19. Ra4 Nxa5 { The pawn grab fails to the spectacular } 20. Bxg6 fxg6
21. Qxe6+ Kh8 22. Ne5 { Black has major problems around the king. } 22... Kh7
23. Nf7 { Otherwise we don't have much. } 23... Rxf7 24. Qxf7 Nc6 25. Qxb7
{ 25.Re6  also wins the game, but this is the easiest. } 25... a5 26. Re6 Qd7
27. Qxd7 Nxd7 28. Ra3 { White is completely winning. } *

