9... Bf5 10. Bxf5 gxf5 11. Ne5
{ A large amount of games have proceeded this way, but it seems like White gets a pretty easy time. }
11... Ne4
{ Won't challenge us very much.   11...Nxe5  We must consider what happens in case Black decides to capture the knight.  12.dxe5!  The strongest capture.  12...Nd7  13.Re1  Nc5  14.Nf3  We can't allow Black to head to d3.  14...Rc8  15.Qe2  15. Qd2 was Kulpruethanon,T - Suelo,R Penang 2019, but I prefer to place the queen on e2 as we can pressure Black down the d-file with Rad1.  15...e6  16.Rad1  Simple chess. Black is slightly exposed on the kingside, so we will focus our attention on that side of the board. For example:  16...Qe7  17.Kh1  Ne4  18.Nd4+-  With a promising attack. The deeper I go with the engine, the higher the evaluation is climbing. A sign that our attack is incredibly dangerous. }
12. Nxc6 bxc6 13. Qh5 { Gives us a pretty comfortable game. } 13... e6
{ We have reached Shehzad,S - Abdrlauf,E Kragero 2019, with the latter being one of former teammates. A self-proclaimed expert in the Caro-Kann, he wouldn't have had an easy time if White had found }
14. Rae1
{ Which is a really nice move as we take control of the e-file and make sure that a potential rook swing to the kingside is available to us via e3.14. f3? happened in the game, when Black had no problems after a capture on d2. }
14... f6
{ 14...Qf6  Makes some sense, and here I suggest keeping the knights on the board with  15.Nb3  Qg6  16.Qe2±  We have a very nice game as Black has some issues to solve on the queenside, while the queen is slightly misplaced on g6. }
15. f3
{ This time it's correct to play f3, as Black's e6-pawn has become weak. }
15... Nxd2 16. Bxd2 Qd7 17. Bh6
{ I like the idea of trading the bishops, making it difficult for Black to achieve e6-e5. }
17... Rab8 18. Rf2
{ The rook is heading to the e2-square where it will create unpleasant pressure against Black's pawn on e6. }
