10. Be3 Qd6 { Black's standard set-up. } 11. Re1 Nf4
{ This is a typical move, but I can't really see what Black has achieved after   11...Bd7  12.Nb3  Nothing fancy here as we stick to our plan of placing the knight on c5. As usual, we can also maneuver the knight to d3 via c1 in case Black takes control over the c5-square.  12...b6  13.a4  Expanding on the queenside.  13...Nf4  14.Bf1  Ne6  And now, in Persson,A - Lundin,J Stockholm 2013, White should have played  15.Nc1±  We're heading to the d3-square which can be followed up by b2-b4 or b3-c4.   11...b6!?  This is a very interesting way for Black to play with the intention of fianchettoing the bishop on b7. Several strong players have tried this approach, including GM Wang Hao.  12.a4  Bb7  13.Nb3  a5  Black prevents us from pushing the pawn to a5.  14.Qd2  Rfe8  15.Bh6   I like how the IM is handling White's position. There's a pretty decent alternative in  15.h3!?  Ba6  16.Nc1  Bxd3  17.Nxd3  , when White had a very nice position in Tari, A - Prohaszka, P Gallipoli 2017. As usual, Aryan knows what he's doing.  15...Bh8?!  Wang Hao wants to avoid trading pieces in order to play for a win. Objectively, 15... Ba6 is better, but I still like White after 16. Bxg7.  16.Bb5  Pinning Black's knight, while also making the d3-square available for the knight on b3.  16...Nf6  Wang Hao heads back.  17.Bf4  Qd8  18.Ne5  Rc8  19.f3±  An improvement over 19. Qd3 which was Fenil,S - Wang,H Douglas 2018. After 19. f3 Black loses the option of playing Ne4. It looks pretty difficult to come up with something for Black to do. }
12. Bf1
{ The knight has to go back at some point, since it really doesn't do anything on f4. }
12... h6
{ Black played this move in Esipenko,A - Sakaev, K St Petersburg 2018.   12...Ne6  Has been tried twice, when I think a simple reply is to go for  13.Nb3  b6  14.Nc1±  Our play is rather straightforward. We're planning to expand on the queenside with a4 and b4, and our knight will head to d3. Black's knight will probably move from e6, which will allow Bf4. }
13. Ne5 { A very powerful move which the strong prodigy missed. } 13... Nh5
{ 13...Bxe5  Taking the piece doesn't work due to  14.dxe5  Qxe5  15.g3!  Black loses an exchange as seen after  15...Nh3+  16.Bxh3  Bxh3  17.Bxh6+-  Black doesn't have enough for the material deficit. }
14. Ndf3
{ The word 'terrible' is an accurate way to describe Black's position. } *

