{ CONCLUSION: The second part of our Caro-Kann coverage has finally come to its end! This was definitely one of the lengthiest chapters of the course, as Black has a bunch of different ways to avoid the main tabiya with 6... Bg4. }
1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5
{ Anyway, there are a lot of different lines here and I can imagine that it can get overwhelming for the reader at times. The story repeats itself in most of these positions - our advantage isn't too high objectively, but practically our position remains easy to play with little risk. }
4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3
{ The thing that I really like about these positions is the fact that the ideas have a tendency to remain the same. This makes everything easier to remember. }
5... Nf6
{ Study this move in great detail.   5...Qc7  Pay close attention to this move, as this is a very popular sideline since Black avoids 6. Bf4. If you do your homework, you can be sure that you'll get a very comfortable position after the opening. Also keep in mind Black has the option of playing e5 on many occasions throughout the chapter, but the result is always an unpleasant isolated pawn position - though not much better on paper. }
6. Bf4 g6
{ It's not easy to distinguish the differences after this move of Black playing Bf5 in move 7, 8 etc, but the differences are there! Our analysis shows that we get a pleasant position if we know what we're doing, so again PAY ATTENTION IN CLASS! Hard work pays off!! }
*

