[Black "6...Bg4 (7...e5)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 Nf6 6. Bf4 Bg4
{ The most critical variation, Black develops the bishop with a tempo. L'Ami emphasizes on how essential it is for Black to get the bishop out on the board before playing e7-e6. Positions we have seen earlier clearly shows that the Dutchman is 100% correct in his statement. Therefore, it really isn't very surprising that this is Black's most played move in the position. }
7. Qb3
{ The obvious choice as Black's bishop no longer covers the pawn on b7. } 7...
e5
{ I remember discovering this fancy move in a rapid game played by Stockfish with Black. I was @@StartBracket@@and still am@@EndBracket@@ an avid fan of computer chess back then, and was frequently a witness to fancy stuff in the opening. This move has been discussed by strong grandmasters, but I am surprised by the fact that it hasn't seen a bigger spike in popularity. Perhaps Black prefers to keep it simple by playing  7...Qd7  where there's not really much theory to learn.  7...e5!?  changes that, as Black must be aware of how to react to our different moves in the position. }
8. h3
{ The most testing reaction is to kick Black's bishop away. For the sake of being very instructive, allow me to present to you what happens in the scenario of other reactions too.  8.Qxb7  is the obvious move on everyone's mind. Why on earth isn't this pawn just hanging? Well the truth is that Black gets a lot of compensation.  8...exf4  9.Qxc6+  Bd7  10.Qa6  Qb8  11.b4  Qc7  12.Ne2  f3  13.gxf3  Bd6  14.Na3  with an unclear position in Legrand, S - Tommasi, G FICGS email 2011.   11...Bd6  is easier in my opinion, when Black has nice compensation after  12.Nf3  O-O  13.O-O  Rc8  .   8.dxe5  is the most human reaction. Black's point is  8...Nh5!  when he will take back on  e5  later with the knight. Black has gotten an isolated pawn, but is objectively fine due to his activity. I played a game that went:  9.Be3  Nxe5  10.Bb5+  Nc6  11.Nd2  Be6  12.Qa4  Qc7  13.Ngf3  Bd6  O-O  a6  15.Bd3  Nf4  16.Bxf4  Bxf4  and I had successfully equalized in Lund, G - Mihajlov, S Fagernes 2018.   White's last option is  8.Bxe5!?  . After  8...Qe7  , the game goes  9.Ne2  Nxe5  10.dxe5  Qxe5  11.Bb5!   not  11.Qxb7?  , when White is just lost after  11...Rb8  12.Qxa7  Bxe2!  13.Bxe2  Rxb2  11...Kd8  12.Nd2  Bd6  13.f3  with an exciting position that is unclear. I hope this has been enlightening, so let's return to the text. }
8... exf4 9. hxg4 Bd6
{ Getting the bishop out is logically enough, but in this position it's rather poor as the pawn on b7 is just hanging. }
10. Qxb7 { I found no reason to avoid the pawn grab. } 10... Na5
{ I think this move looks the most human.  10...Ne7  can also be played, when the line goes  11.g5  Rb8  12.Qxa7!  Another pawn that it doesn't hurt to grab.  12...Ne4  , and now the queen returns:  13.Qa4+  Kf8  14.Qc2  Nxg5  15.Nd2  . White's extra material is decisive. Our king is perfectly safe on  f1  . }
11. Qb5+
{ The check is important.  11.Qa6?  would give Black unnecessary compensation after  11...O-O  . }
11... Kf8 12. b4
{ A great move that keeps up the momentum. Black may be a pawn down, but if he gets Rb8 quickly then he could definitely get an acceptable amount of compensation. }
12... Nc4 13. Bxc4 dxc4 14. Nd2
{ The simplest.  14.g5  is decent too, but I think our life is a little bit harder than it should be after  14...Qe7+  15.Kd1  Ng4  16.Nh3  , although the engine gives more than +1.5. }
14... Nxg4 15. Nxc4 { Black has far from enough compensation. } *

