1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 Nf6 6. Bf4 Bg4
{ The most critical variation, Black develops the bishop with a tempo. L'Ami emphasizes on how essential it is for Black to get the bishop out on the board before playing e7-e6. Positions we have seen earlier clearly shows that the Dutchman is 100% correct in his statement. Therefore, it really isn't very surprising that this is Black's most played move in the position. }
7. Qb3
{ The obvious choice as Black's bishop no longer covers the pawn on b7. } 7...
e5
{ I remember discovering this fancy move in a rapid game played by Stockfish with Black. I was @@StartBracket@@and still am@@EndBracket@@ an avid fan of computer chess back then, and was frequently a witness to fancy stuff in the opening. This move has been discussed by strong grandmasters, but I am surprised by the fact that it hasn't seen a bigger spike in popularity. Perhaps Black prefers to keep it simple by playing  7...Qd7  where there's not really much theory to learn.  7...e5!?  changes that, as Black must be aware of how to react to our different moves in the position. }
8. h3 { The most testing reaction is to kick Black's bishop away. } 8... exf4
9. hxg4 Nxg4
{ Going for the pawn grab is possible, but then I must ask why Black didn't go 9... Qe7+ first which is just a better version as we can't take on b7.   9...Qd7?  Was tried in Giesen,D - Prueske,W Hamburg 2018, but it doesn't look very fun for Black after the simple  10.Bf5±  Black has gained nothing from playing Qd7. After Bf5, we're ready to go g5-g6 next. The reason why we avoid g5 immediately is because of Ng4, when Black has some activity.   9...Rb8?  Is way too slow for this type of position.  10.g5  Ne4  11.Nh3  f3   11...Nxg5  12.Nxf4  gives us a rather easy game as our king will be very safe on  f1  .  12.Bxe4  dxe4  13.g3+-  Black's pawns are very weak. After Nd2 and O-O-O, they'll fall quickly. }
10. Qxb7 Rc8
{ Gives Black a slightly better version of 10... Qe7 after   10...Qe7+  Played in both of the games I found in my online database.  11.Qxe7+  Bxe7  12.Nd2  White has obtained a clearly better ending as Black pawns on f4 and d5 are rather weak. We also have a beautiful pawn majority on the queenside which could very quickly become a decisive factor.  12...Rb8  13.b4!  Simple and strong.  13...g6  14.Ngf3  White played a nice game in Choisy,M - Zpevakova,J Le Castella 2018 with 14. Ne2 @@StartBracket@@although she blundered in the end@@EndBracket@@, but I do think the knight is better placed on f3 as Black can easily defend the pawn on f4 by playing Bd6.  14...O-O  15.O-O  ±  A long night of suffering is in sight for Black, as the endgame is rather terrible. }
11. Bb5 Qe7+ 12. Qxe7+ Bxe7 { Due to Black's increased activity. } 13. Ne2 O-O
{ Not  13...Bd6?  when Black is in trouble after  14.c4! } 14. Nd2
{ Being greedy with  14.Nxf4?  gives Black a lot of play after the shot  14...Nxd4! }
14... Bd6 15. Rh4 f5 16. a4
{ Black definitely has more play in this version of the endgame, but the poor pawns are still a major problem. }
