e5
{ I remember discovering this fancy move in a rapid game played by Stockfish with Black. I was @@StartBracket@@and still am@@EndBracket@@ an avid fan of computer chess back then, and was frequently a witness to fancy stuff in the opening. This move has been discussed by strong grandmasters, but I am surprised by the fact that it hasn't seen a bigger spike in popularity. Perhaps Black prefers to keep it simple by playing  7...Qd7  where there's not really much theory to learn.  7...e5!?  changes that, as Black must be aware of how to react to our different moves in the position. }
8. h3 { The most testing reaction is to kick Black's bishop away. } 8... exf4
{ 8...Qe7  is a transposition after  9.hxg4  exf4+  . } 9. hxg4 Qe7+
{ 9...Rb8?  Is way too slow for this type of position.  10.g5  Ne4  11.Nh3   I initially intended to go for  11.g6  when the force sequence goes  11...fxg6  12.Nf3  Be7  13.Nbd2  Nxd2  14.Bxg6+  Kd7  15.Bf5+  Kc7  16.Kxd2  . This is really good for us, but after  16...Na5  the game is still going. The text move makes our life much easier, so it was a logical choice.  11...f3   11...Nxg5  12.Nxf4  gives us a rather easy game as our king will be very safe on  f1  .  12.Bxe4  dxe4  13.g3+-  Black's pawns are very weak. After Nd2 and O-O-O, they'll fall quickly. }
10. Kf1
{ Black has prevented us from castling, but it doesn't matter too much as the king is quite safe on f1. }
10... O-O-O
{ Black's best choice is to play actively.   10...Nxg4  Doesn't look very challenging, although it's the best moment for Black to take this pawn.  11.Nd2  Qd7   11...O-O-O?  loses to  12.Bf5  of course.  12.Re1+  Be7  13.Nh3  O-O-O  14.Nf3⩲  Black's pawn on f4 won't make it, so we can claim an edge due to our superior pawn structure. }
11. Nd2
{ It quite crazy, but this position has only been seen TWICE in my base! That goes to show how unexplored this line really is... }
11... g5
{ Is a fantastic novelty. This move does make sense as Black utilizes his kingside majority. It's also worth pointing out that Black stops our usual pawn push g4-g5. The kingside pawns can quickly become very scary if Black is able to play h5 and g4 @@StartBracket@@when we take on h5@@EndBracket@@ without resistance.   11...Kb8?  Was played by the prodigy IM Yoo in a blitz game, but it's a bad move.  12.Re1  Qd6  13.g5  Black's pieces are getting pushed back.  13...Nd7  14.Ndf3  14. Ngf3 like in Kostenko,P - Yoo,C Chess.com INT 2020 is definitely good, but I prefer the text due to the strong idea of going Rh4 followed by Nh3. It's also worth mentioning that Black has to watch out for g6 followed by Ng5 as well.  14...Be7   Black prevents our idea, now that  15.Rh4?  could be met by  15...h6!  15.Ba6  Nb6  16.Bb5  16...Na5  It makes sense for Black to keep the knight.  17.Qc2  Suddenly Black has problems with the pawn on h7.  17...a6  18.Qe2  Bf8  19.Bd3  Nc6  Black prevents Ne5, but he is in dire straits after  20.g6  fxg6  21.Ng5  Qf6  22.Rxh7+-  White is simply dominating the board.   11...g6?!  Played in the U.S Championship between Sam Shankland and Awonder Liang. Sam is as usual, very well prepared.  12.Re1  Qc7  13.g5  The problem for Black in these positions is that it's very difficult to find decent squares for the pieces. It really is significantly easier to play White, as our moves come very naturally.  13...Nh5  Black is ready to neutralize our pressure with h6, but Sam is observant and prevents it.  14.Be2  Ng7  15.Ngf3  Ne6  16.Bb5  Sam keeps playing well and aims to reinforce the pressure on Black's position with Qa4, and potentially Bxc6.  16...Bg7?!   Black has finally coordinated his forces, but it's slightly inaccurate.  16...Ne7  is best, so  17.Qa4  can be dodged with  17...Kb8  . It's essential that we can't take on  c6  in this position.  17.Bd3  is apparently best with a very interesting position. We are in the driving seat as we have some initiative on both sides of the board, but the advantage isn't more than slightly better.  17.Qa4  Rd6  18.Nb3  b6?   Awonder makes an error in a tough position.  18...a6  is best, but Black's position is still incredibly shaky after  19.Bxc6  Rxc6  20.Nc5  Nxc5  21.dxc5  .  19.Nc1  The knight gets ready for a journey to the juicy square on b4.  19...Nb8  20.Nd3  Kb7  21.Nb4+-  Sam had played very well so far and converted his advantage smoothly in Shankland,S -Liang,A Saint Louis 2018. }
12. Ndf3 h5
{ The only move, otherwise Black is in major trouble.  12...Rg8?  for example, is just terrible after  13.Bxh7  . }
13. Qc2
{ The queen joins the action and also takes control of the h7-square. @@StartBracket@@yeah, this is actually important...@@EndBracket@@ Note also that Black can't take on  g4  in any manner, for example  13...Nxg4?  14.Bf5+  and Black loses material. }
13... Bh6
{ Black has completed his development and is thus finally ready to grab on g4.   13...Kb8?  Is one way things could go very wrong for Black.  14.Nxg5   Works, as  14...Bh6  can be met by  15.Nh7!  now that  h7  is under control!  14...Nxg4  Is just met by  15.Nh7+-  Black's kingside adventure has clearly failed. }
14. Re1 Qc7
{ 14...Qd6?  would give Black huge problems after  15.Ne5!  followed by gxh5. }
15. Bb5 Kb8 { 15...Nxg4  is met by  16.Rxh5  - an important resource to have. }
16. Qf5 hxg4
{ Is the line given by my engine.   16...Ne4?!  Would now be inaccurate due to  17.Rxh5  A hanging pawn!  17...f6  Black must control the square on e5. Here, we have a pleasant choice:  18.Bxc6   18.Rxe4  is a strong exchange sac when we get terrific play on the light squares, for example  18...dxe4  19.Qxe4  Rhe8  20.Qc2  Bg7  21.Bd3  .  18...Qxc6  19.Ne2  Our king can now head to g1.  19...Bg7  20.Kg1±  Black has compensation due to the strong knight on e4. This won't last forever though, as we plan to drive it away by playing Nb3 and Nfd2. Black needs to find a way to meet this plan - not an easy task! }
17. Qxf6 Bg7 { Black's point, otherwise it's just lost. } 18. Qxg7 Rxh1 19.
Nxg5 f3
{ Black's kingside attack gives him compensation for the material deficit, but we do keep an edge with accurate play. }
20. g3 Rdh8 { The other rook joins the attack. } 21. Bd3
{ A prophylactic move against Qb6 which can be rather annoying. Now we're going to play either Nh7 or Qf6-followed by Qf5-Qxg4, so Black needs to keep attacking. }
21... R8h2 22. Qf6
{ We're getting ready to give the exchange, as Black's pawns are incredibly strong. }
22... a6 23. Nxf3 gxf3 24. Qxf3
{ We have two pawns for the exchange. Black is also not so well coordinated as the rooks in the h-file look strange now that the attack is coming to an end. }
