{ The best try. The king simply hides from annoying checks.   18...Nxh5?  Is not a good idea due to  19.Qe2  gxf2   19...Nf6  is no better, when White is winning after  20.Rxh8  Rxh8  21.fxg3  fxg3  22.Qe5  .  20.Qg4+  Kb8  21.Kxf2  Qh6  22.Nf3+-  White is just winning due to Black's problem with his minor pieces.   18...gxf2?  Is also not very challenging.  19.Qxf2  Black has to make the attack succeed somehow, otherwise he will be in major trouble due to our superior pawn structure. But there really isn't a way to make the attack work!  19...Qd6   19...Nxh5  is met by  20.Qf3  , when after  20...Ng3+  we have  21.Rxg3  fxg3  22.Qg4+  , when Black loses the bishop on  g7  .  20.Re5  A nice square for the rook where it perfectly protects the pawn on h5.  20...Kb8  21.Rf5+-  Black is just dominated. A sample line is:  21...Bh6  22.Qh4  Ne4  23.Bxe4  dxe4  24.Qf6  Qd7  25.Qe5+  Ka8  26.Qxe4  Rde8  27.Qc2  Qe6  28.Nf3+-  It truly is beautiful how harmoniously our pieces work together! }
