1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 Nf6 6. Bf4 Bg4
{ The most critical variation, Black develops the bishop with a tempo. L'Ami emphasizes on how essential it is for Black to get the bishop out on the board before playing e7-e6. Positions we have seen earlier clearly shows that the Dutchman is 100% correct in his statement. Therefore, it really isn't very surprising that this is Black's most played move in the position. }
7. Qb3
{ The obvious choice as Black's bishop no longer covers the pawn on b7. } 7...
e5
{ I remember discovering this fancy move in a rapid game played by Stockfish with Black. I was @@StartBracket@@and still am@@EndBracket@@ an avid fan of computer chess back then, and was frequently a witness to fancy stuff in the opening. This move has been discussed by strong grandmasters, but I am surprised by the fact that it hasn't seen a bigger spike in popularity. Perhaps Black prefers to keep it simple by playing  7...Qd7  where there's not really much theory to learn.  7...e5!?  changes that, as Black must be aware of how to react to our different moves in the position. }
8. h3 { The most testing reaction is to kick Black's bishop away. } 8... Na5
{ Black's best choice is to jump to the rim with the knight. The point is simply to keep the b7-pawn under protection. }
9. Qc2 Bd1
{ This is a funky-looking move, but I doubt that Black benefits from having avoided hxg4. }
10. Qxd1 exf4
{ Black has gained our dark-squared bishop, but other than that I don't see how this can be better than, let's say, the main tabiya with 7... Qd7. Black's pawns are scattered and fairly easy targets for our forces. It's indeed quite easy to play with the white pieces. However, I will give Black the benefit of a doubt, as the objective evaluation is 'only' around 0.40. }
11. Nf3 Bd6 12. Nbd2 O-O 13. O-O
{ Before we do anything insane, we should simply get our pieces on the board. }
13... Re8 14. b4
{ Now that our pieces are out, it's time to improve our position by conquering on the queenside. }
14... Nc6 15. Qb3 Rc8 16. Rfe1
{ White's moves have been incredibly simple, yet effective. It's very difficult to play Black as the annotated game clearly shows. }
16... Rc7
{ Black's idea is to fight for control of the e-file by playing Re7. } 17.
Rxe8+ Qxe8 18. a3
{ I think this little move deserves an exclam. In order to make progress, we must play c4 at some point. Additionally, I like how we have abandoned fighting for the e-file. Black may play Re7, but there's no place to intrude! }
18... Re7 19. Rd1
{ 19. c4 right away was possible, but I like White's approach of making Black wait for the strike. It's rather annoying for Black having to calculate what happens after c4 after every move. There's really no need to rush! }
19... Bc7 20. Qc2 { White maintains the same strategy. } 20... g6 21. Nb3 Ne4
{ Black is desperate after having something to do, but this move puts him in serious trouble. The waiting move 21... Bd6 was the way to go, when White can decide between playing c4 or even retreat with the knight. }
22. c4
{ It's finally time! Having the knight on e4 is a disadvantage for Black, as the knight should keep the d5-square covered in order to make d5 tougher for us to achieve. }
22... dxc4 23. Bxc4 Nd6 24. Bf1
{ With d5 or Nc5 coming, White had an excellent position and soon obtained a decisive advantage after   24...a5  25.d5  Nb8  26.Nxa5  Bxa5  27.bxa5  Qd8  28.Qc5  in Vaibhav, S - Ravi, T Majitar 2019. }
