[Round "?"]
[White "19. Caro-Kann (1...c6) Mainline"]
[Black "6...Bg4 (7...e5 9)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 Nf6 6. Bf4 Bg4
{ The most critical variation, Black develops the bishop with a tempo. L'Ami emphasizes on how essential it is for Black to get the bishop out on the board before playing e7-e6. Positions we have seen earlier clearly shows that the Dutchman is 100% correct in his statement. Therefore, it really isn't very surprising that this is Black's most played move in the position. }
7. Qb3
{ The obvious choice as Black's bishop no longer covers the pawn on b7. } 7...
e5
{ I remember discovering this fancy move in a rapid game played by Stockfish with Black. I was @@StartBracket@@and still am@@EndBracket@@ an avid fan of computer chess back then, and was frequently a witness to fancy stuff in the opening. This move has been discussed by strong grandmasters, but I am surprised by the fact that it hasn't seen a bigger spike in popularity. Perhaps Black prefers to keep it simple by playing  7...Qd7  where there's not really much theory to learn.  7...e5!?  changes that, as Black must be aware of how to react to our different moves in the position. }
8. h3 { The most testing reaction is to kick Black's bishop away. } 8... Na5
{ Black's best choice is to jump to the rim with the knight. The point is simply to keep the b7-pawn under protection. }
9. Qc2 exf4 10. hxg4 Nxg4 { Black should go for glory and take the pawn. } 11.
Qe2+
{ Now that we can't exploit Black's poor queen placement on e7, or take the hanging pawn on b7, we must go for an endgame. }
11... Qe7 12. Nh3
{ Black won't keep the extra pawn for long. Now he has to make a decision on whether to ignore our knight jump or destroy our pawn structure with f3. }
12... f3 13. gxf3 Qxe2+ 14. Kxe2
{ The obvious choice. Taking with the bishop would be way too passive. } 14...
Nf6 15. Nd2 Bd6
{ 15...g6  Let's see how we should react if Black chooses a fianchetto set-up.  16.f4  This move is pretty much always played, as it frees the f3-square for our king, while grabbing additional control of the central square on e5. Also, we may be looking into playing f5 at some point in the future.  16...Bg7  17.Bb5+  Another very subtle move. The point is to actually make sure Black can't play b5 which is at times rather annoying.  17...Nc6  18.f5!?  An interesting plan. The other way is to go Nf3-Ne5 which is slightly better for us.  18...O-O  19.Nf4⩲  The same plan applies. Nf1-Ne3 & Kf3. Note that we can consider moving our bishop back to d3 if Black decides to play 19... a6. }
16. f4
{ Seems to be the most critical test.  16.Rag1!?  is an interesting alternative, when I think White was slightly better after  16...g6  17.f4  Rb8  18.Nf3  b5  19.Ne5  Nh5  20.b4  Nc4  21.a4  Bxe5  22.fxe5  bxa4  23.Ra1  in Pospisil, L - Aberg, L ICCF email 2017. The game was drawn after 61 moves, not a very surprising outcome when you have aid from engines. }
16... Nh5
{ An interesting approach by the strong Israelian GM Postny. Black wants us to play Kf3 which will make a knight jump to e5 impossible to achieve for the time being.   16...O-O  Was recently played in a Russian GM-encounter. Instead of playing 17. a4 like in Savchenko,B - Bocharov,I Khanty-Mansiysk 2020, I suggest the simple  17.Nf3  h6  18.Ne5⩲  I think our position is rather pleasant with ideas like Ng1-Ngf3-Rag1-Nh4-Nf5. }
17. Kf3 g6
{ There's no need for Black to play this weakening move yet. Instead, he should bring the knight back with  17...Nc6  , when we maintain some pressure after  18.f5  Ne7  19.Nf1  with  Ne3  next. }
18. f5 O-O-O 19. Nf1
{ Black is suddenly on deep waters here with moves like Ne3 and Ng5 lurking around the corner. }
19... Nc6 20. Ne3 Ne7
{ A logical defense, but it makes things even worse. The stubborn 20... Be7 was necessary, but Black is still clearly worse as he's very passive. }
21. Ng5 Rdf8
{ I think this is what Postny had in mind. Things don't look so bad, do they? h6 comes next and the beast from g5 has to move... Unfortunately for Postny, Demchenko is wide awake. .. }
22. Rxh5
{ A fantastic exchange for every book about positional chess. This destroys Black's position entirely. }
22... gxh5 23. f6 Ng6 24. Nxd5
{ White was completely dominating in Demchenko, A - Postny, E Fagernes 2019. I leave the rest of the game as a clickable, as it's simply pure art.  24...h6  25.Ne4  Rd8  26.Rh1  h4  27.Bc4  Bb8  28.Ne3  Rdf8  29.Nf5  Kd7  30.b4  b6  31.Bb5+  Kd8  32.c4  h5  33.c5  h3  34.Ned6  Bxd6  35.cxd6  Kc8  36.Ne7+  Kb7  37.Rc1  Postny threw in the towel. A magnificent display by Demchenko! }
