[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 Nf6 6. Bf4 Bg4
{ The most critical variation, Black develops the bishop with a tempo. L'Ami emphasizes on how essential it is for Black to get the bishop out on the board before playing e7-e6. Positions we have seen earlier clearly shows that the Dutchman is 100% correct in his statement. Therefore, it really isn't very surprising that this is Black's most played move in the position. }
7. Qb3
{ The obvious choice as Black's bishop no longer covers the pawn on b7. } 7...
Qb6
{ Black seldom chooses to guard the pawn in this way, but we should still take a look at what happens. Similarly to what we saw in the first chapter with an early Bg4, the endgames that occur after Qb6 tend to be very good for us. }
8. Nd2
{ There's no need to hurry. Let's let Black decide whether he wants to head for an endgame or not. }
8... e6 9. Ngf3
{ The same strategy applies - let Black take the queen if he wants to! } 9...
Nd7
{ Is a pretty interesting move. Black gains the option of taking with the knight in case we one day decide to take Black's queen, while it's also harder for us to jump to the central square on e5 with our knight. }
10. O-O Be7 11. Rfe1 Bh5
{ Black goes for the standard plan of trading bishops.  11...O-O  can be played, when I think  12.Qc2  gives us a great version of the Main Line as Black's queen looks quite strange on  b6  . }
12. Qc2
{ 12.Qxb6  is the other direction we can take, with a more pleasant endgame. I analyzed  12...axb6  13.a4  Rd8  14.Bb5  O-O  15.h3  Na7  16.Be2  Nc6  17.g4  Bg6  18.Bg3  , when I think we're doing well. After some consideration however, I did settle on choosing  12.Qc2  as our approach. The reason for this is the fact that Black's queen looks misplaced on  b6  . }
12... Rc8
{ There's no reason why Black shouldn't throw in this move, with the threat of playing Nb4. }
13. a3 Bg6 14. Bxg6 hxg6 15. Qd3 O-O 16. h4
{ As stated above, Black's queen looks misplaced on b6. Qxb2 is never a threat as the queen will get trapped, while it also stands in the way of the standard pawn storm on the queenside. Our way of proceeding is playing g3-Kg2 with h5 coming some day. The knight can also join the attack by jumping to g5. If you feel annoyed by the fact that Black's queen is aiming towards b2, you can always play Rab1. }
