{ There's no need to hurry. Let's let Black decide whether he wants to head for an endgame or not. }
8... e6 9. Ngf3
{ The same strategy applies - let Black take the queen if he wants to! } 9...
Be7 10. Ne5
{ I spent a long time in this position, simply because there were so many ways of playing that looked good!  10.O-O  is what I intended to do, but I discovered that  10...Bh5!?  was clever. After  11.Qxb6  axb6  12.a3  Bg6  13.Bb5  O-O  14.Ne5  Nxe5  15.dxe5  Ne4  16.Nxe4  Bxe4  17.Rad1  , there’s no doubt that White is better, but Black is quite solid. The endgame after   10.Qxb6  axb6  11.Ne5  Nxe5  12.dxe5  looks good too.  12.Bxe5  should transpose to the text. }
10... Nxe5 11. Bxe5 O-O 12. Qxb6
{ We're taking the game into a comfortable endgame. } 12... axb6 13. a3
{ Is always a nice move to make, as our rook on a1 is liberated. } 13... Ne8
{ And now, instead of playing  14.f3  like in Huber, M - Seelig, J GER email 2018, I suggest }
14. Nf1
{ With the plan of playing Ng3 or Ne3, as our knight doesn't do so much on d2 at the moment. }
14... Bh5 15. h4
{ I like this space-grabbing move, as it allows us to push Black's bishop away from g6. }
15... Bg6 16. Be2
{ We should keep the bishop on the board since we'll knock back Black's bishop on g6 next. }
16... f6 17. Bf4 Nd6 18. h5 Be8 19. Ne3
{ With a very pleasant endgame for White. Black's only plan will be to play e5 in the future, but this will make the pawn on d5 quite weak. It's also not to difficult to prevent, as we can place a rook on e1 and a knight on g4. Our plan should be to improve our pieces with O-O-O, Rde1, f3, Bd3, g4 etc. }
