[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 Nf6 6. Bf4 Bg4
{ The most critical variation, Black develops the bishop with a tempo. L'Ami emphasizes on how essential it is for Black to get the bishop out on the board before playing e7-e6. Positions we have seen earlier clearly shows that the Dutchman is 100% correct in his statement. Therefore, it really isn't very surprising that this is Black's most played move in the position. }
7. Qb3
{ The obvious choice as Black's bishop no longer covers the pawn on b7. } 7...
Na5
{ Has been played by a bunch of strong GMs, so we should know how to react. }
8. Qc2 e6 9. Nd2 Bd6 10. Bxd6 Qxd6 11. Ngf3 Nc6
{ Black retreats the knight so we can't access the e5-square. The position we have on the board is exactly the same as the main line, with the difference being our queen placement. This looks like a better version to me, since we do usually want to maneuver our queen to another square as it doesn't do too much on b3. }
12. O-O O-O 13. Rfe1 Rac8 14. a3
{ Obviously we must prevent Black from playing Nb4. } 14... Bh5
{ Black proceeds with the same plan as always - Bg6. } 15. h3 Rfe8
{ There's no harm in playing Bg6 right away either, but Black decides to develop the rook first. }
16. Re3 { A thematic plan for White is to double the rooks on the e-file. }
16... Bg6 17. Bxg6 hxg6 18. Rae1
{ It doesn't matter that the objective advantage isn't too high here. Our position is more pleasant and easier to handle. Look how quickly Black collapses in the annotated game! }
18... Ne7 19. R3e2 { Played so Black doesn't get Nf5 with a tempo. } 19... Rc7
{ 19...Nf5  is logical, but it can be met by  20.g4!  when the knight is pushed back. }
20. Ne5
{ Ideas like Ndf3-Ng5 are in the air, along with Nxf7. Black has to be very careful. }
20... Nd7 21. Ndf3 Qa6
{ A very surprising blunder. Maybe a typo?  21...Nxe5  is Black's best move, when we get a slightly better game after  22.Nxe5  Nf5  23.Qd3  due to our strong knight on  e5  . }
22. Nxf7
{ Black resigned in Beavan, R -Clancey, J ICCF email 2015 due to the line  22...Kxf7  23.Rxe6  Rc6  24.Ng5+  Kf8  25.Qxg6!!  when Black is mated. Obviously this is not the best objectively, but without the extra piece Black doesn't stand a practical chance. }
