{ A very thematic plan in these positions. Black prepares to play Bg6 and trade our strong light-squared bishop. }
11. Rfe1 Bg6 12. Bxg6
{ Although our strong bishop disappears, it's the right choice. Keeping it with  12.Bf1  is possible, but Black's bishop is quite strong on  g6  . Black has achieved his goal, but that doesn't mean it's flawless. After  hxg6  the h-file is opened which can be utilized by our forces to start an attack @@StartBracket@@imagine for example a queen on  h4  and a knight on g5@@EndBracket@@. This is indeed our standard procedure in these positions as we will see constantly throughout the chapter. }
12... hxg6 13. h4
{ After placing the engine on a high depth, it came up with this excellent move. There are several points here. First of all, we take control over the g5-square. Secondly, we plan to open Black's kingside by playing h5 in the future. Additionally, we can place our bishop on the h2-b8 diagonal in case Black plays Nh5. }
13... a6 { A logical response. Black plans a queenside expansion with b5. } 14.
a3
{ A neat prophylactic move. The idea is just to prevent Black from playing b5-b4. We want to prevent this because b4 will create a weak pawn on c3 which Black can eventually target by placing his heavy pieces in the c-file. This is another plan you will see often, as Black can't do much else. }
14... O-O 15. Qc2
{ The queen has fulfilled its duty on b3, so it's time to bring it somewhere else. Our destination is the d3-square where it can swing to the kingside. }
15... b5 16. Qd3
{ There's no doubt that we are in the driving seat. Black is still far away from creating something on the queenside. On the other hand, we are ready to stop Black's queenside play by playing b4 and later a4-a5, so we can later proceed to the kingside in peace. }
16... Na5 { Is a very logical way for Black to continue. } 17. Ne5
{ Now that Black gets a knight to c4, we can't afford to waste any time on the kingside. }
17... Nc4 18. Ndxc4
{ The best.  18.Rab1  is too slow, when I think Black is fine after  18...Nxd2  followed by  Ne4  for example. }
18... bxc4 19. Qh3
{ The queen heads to the kingside so we can start an attack. } 19... Rb8 20. g4
{ There's no time to waste!  20.Re2  looks natural, but after  20...Rb6  Black comes fast in the b-file. }
20... Rxb2
{ Being greedy will cause Black major problems.  20...Rb6  is the computer-defense. The forced sequence goes  21.h5  gxh5  22.g5  Nh7  23.Qxh5  Bxg5  24.Bxg5  Nxg5  25.Kg2  f6  26.Ng6  Re8  27.Re2  . Black is on the edge as our attack is quite dangerous, but is still in the game. }
21. h5 { Our attack is incredibly fast. } 21... gxh5 22. g5 Ne4
{ Black's best practical try. This time, Black can't play  22...Nh7  , as we win after  23.Qxh5  Bxg5  24.Bxg5  Nxg5  and now  25.Qxg5!  with the point  25...f6  26.Qc1!  Black's rook is now hanging on b2, a huge difference between having the rook on b6! }
23. Qxh5
{ There are many nasty threats in the air. Nxf7 followed by g6 is one of them. Rxe4 followed by Kg2 is another one. Black can't do anything. }
23... Qb7
{ Is also met by   23...Qb8!?  A decent try to trick us.  24.g6!   The refutation!  24.Rxe4  dxe4  25.Kg2  doesn't work this time, as Black has  25...Rxf2!  24...fxg6  25.Nxg6+-   And White wins decisive material, as the line  25...Rxf4  26.Nxe7+  Kf8  27.Ng6+  Kg8  28.Qh8+  Kf7  29.Qxb8  Rg4+  30.Kh1  Nxf2+  31.Kh2  Rxb8  32.Ne5+  Ke8  33.Nxg4  Nxg4+  34.Kg3  demonstrates.   23...Qe8  Loses for several reasons, for example  24.Rxe4!  dxe4  25.Kg2+-  When Rh1 comes with a decisive attack. }
24. Nxf7 Nxg5 25. Nxg5 Bxg5 26. Qxg5 Qf7
{ It might look slightly scary, but Black doesn't have anything in the f-file. }
27. Bg3 Rxf2 { And now the blow } 28. Rxe6
{ Wins, with  Rae1  coming.  28.Bxf2??  would actually lose the game, as Black takes the rook and plays  Rf4  with a decisive attack. Be careful out there! }
*

