[Black "6...Bg4 (7...Qc8 2)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 Nf6 6. Bf4 Bg4
{ The most critical variation, Black develops the bishop with a tempo. L'Ami emphasizes on how essential it is for Black to get the bishop out on the board before playing e7-e6. Positions we have seen earlier clearly shows that the Dutchman is 100% correct in his statement. Therefore, it really isn't very surprising that this is Black's most played move in the position. }
7. Qb3
{ The obvious choice as Black's bishop no longer covers the pawn on b7. } 7...
Qc8 8. Nd2
{ A necessary move to make so we can play Ngf3 and avoid a terrible pawn structure after Bxf3. }
8... e6 9. Ngf3 Be7
{ Now that Black placed the queen on c8, Bd6 is no longer possible. } 10. O-O
O-O 11. Rfe1
{ 11.Ne5  has been slightly more common, but I prefer taking things slower. Why rush things? After  11.Ne5  ,  11.. .Nxe5  looks pretty decent.  12.dxe5  Nd7  13.Qc2  h6  14.h3  Bh5  15.g4!?  Bg6  16.Bxg6  fxg6  17.Bxh6  Nxe5  18.Be3  g5  and Black had a fine position in Novitzkij, D - Stupak, K Minsk 2014. }
11... a6
{ The thematic move can be played anytime. In this case, I think we should simply transpose to the Main Line by going }
12. h3 Bh5 13. Qc2 Bg6
{ I can't imagine that a human would play something else.  13...b5  can obviously be tried, but after  14.b4  Black's play on the queenside is stopped. }
14. Bxg6 hxg6 15. Qd3 { And we have transposed to  11...Bh5  . } *

