[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 Nf6 6. Bf4 Bg4
{ The most critical variation, Black develops the bishop with a tempo. L'Ami emphasizes on how essential it is for Black to get the bishop out on the board before playing e7-e6. Positions we have seen earlier clearly shows that the Dutchman is 100% correct in his statement. Therefore, it really isn't very surprising that this is Black's most played move in the position. }
7. Qb3
{ The obvious choice as Black's bishop no longer covers the pawn on b7. } 7...
Qc8
{ Is almost as popular as  7...Qd7  , but I struggle to wrap my head around why on earth Black would place the queen here instead of  d7?  After all, the queen is better placed on  d7  . }
8. Nd2
{ A necessary move to make so we can play Ngf3 and avoid a terrible pawn structure after Bxf3. }
8... e6 9. Ngf3 Be7
{ Now that Black placed the queen on c8, Bd6 is no longer possible. } 10. O-O
O-O 11. Rfe1 Nh5
{ It's always annoying when Black plays Nh5 and removes our bishop from the beautiful h2-b8 diagonal. However, Black's knight on h5 looks silly and will have to move back. }
12. Be3 Nf6
{ Is a draw offer, but objectively best.   12...Bd6  A typical reaction now that our bishop is gone from the diagonal.  13.h3  Bxf3  14.Nxf3  Nf4  Was played in Krapivin,A - Medvegy,Z Budapest 2003, and here I think we should just play  15.Bxf4  As we get a very dangerous attack after  15...Bxf4  16.g3  Bd6  17.h4±  With Kg2, h5, Bb1 and Qc2 coming quickly. Black hasn't created anything on the queenside.   12...Qc7  Is another way Black can obtain control over the diagonal, when our reaction remains no different  13.h3  Bxf3  14.Nxf3  And we have obtained the bishop pair.  14...Bd6  And now I think  15.Qc2  g6  16.g3±  Looks excellent for us. Black has weakened his kingside with g6, while it's also rather hard to see the queenside plan a6-b5-b4 working out. The pawn break e6-e5 is thematic, but would only leave Black with an isolated pawn. }
13. h3
{ You can take a day off with  13.Bf4  if you want, but I urge you to be more ambitious! }
13... Bh5 14. Bf4 { And we have once again transposed. } *

