[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 Nf6 6. Bf4 Bg4
{ The most critical variation, Black develops the bishop with a tempo. L'Ami emphasizes on how essential it is for Black to get the bishop out on the board before playing e7-e6. Positions we have seen earlier clearly shows that the Dutchman is 100% correct in his statement. Therefore, it really isn't very surprising that this is Black's most played move in the position. }
7. Qb3
{ The obvious choice as Black's bishop no longer covers the pawn on b7. } 7...
Qc8 8. Nd2
{ A necessary move to make so we can play Ngf3 and avoid a terrible pawn structure after Bxf3. }
8... e6 9. Ngf3 Be7
{ Now that Black placed the queen on c8, Bd6 is no longer possible. } 10. O-O
O-O 11. Rfe1 Bh5
{ As I already mentioned, Black's plan of trading bishops with Bh5-Bg6 is incredibly common. }
12. h3
{ There's nothing more to this move than the fact that it slightly improves our position. There a ton of different ways to play, with good candidate choices being  12.a3  ,  12.Qc2  or  12.Ng5  like in Guramishvili, S - Leutwyler, M Douglas 2018. }
12... Bg6 13. Bxg6 hxg6 14. Qb5
{ I am a huge fan of this provocative way of getting our queen to  d3  . Normally we would play  14.Qc2  , but here Black gets quick play on the queenside with  14...b5  15.a3  Na5  . }
14... a6 15. Qd3 Na5
{ If Black wants to play b5 he should play this move first to avoid b2-b4.   15...b5  Is of course extremely natural. Black's problem is just that we can prevent the queenside play with the thematic  16.b4!  With a4 or Nb3-Nc5 coming, it's hard to imagine that Black will be able to create anything.  16...Qb7  17.Nb3!  Is the right way to go! The knight will cause major discomfort to Black's camp when it reaches c5.   17.a4  gives Black no problems this time due to  17...bxa4  18.Rxa4  Qb5  19.Qc2  a5  .  17...Nd7?!   Is not good, but the position is really tough to play anyway after for example  17...Qb6  18.Nc5  , with  a4  coming.  18.Nc5  Nxc5  19.bxc5+-  White had a fantastic position in the Norwegian encounter Holand,P -Leonhardsen,V Skien 2019. It's hard to tell what Black is supposed to do as he's dominated on both sides of the board. The thematic plan h4-g3-Kg2-Rh1-h5 looks very strong here. It's also worth mentioning that we can often double our rooks in the e-file with Re2-Rae1 as well. a3 is also worth considering in case you're worried about b4. }
16. Ne5 { A standard reaction when Black no longer controls this square. }
16... Nd7
{ A pretty clever reaction, as getting rid of the knight will ease off some of the pressure.   16...b5  17.h4  Nc4  Was on the board in Nihal,S - Checa,N Chess.com INT 2021. But instead of the tame 18. Rab1, I prefer  18.Ndxc4!  The same reaction as a similar position we had earlier in the chapter. It's worth giving Black the b-file for the pesky knight on c4.  18...bxc4  19.Qh3→  With a promising attack. }
17. Qg3
{ 17.Ndf3  is more natural, but after  17...Nxe5  18.Nxe5  Nc4  , Black trades another knight. }
17... Nxe5 18. Bxe5 b5 19. h4
{ We have a strong attacking potential as h5 is looming in the air. Our rook can also contribute via e3 where it will defend the c3-pawn while also potentially swing to either g3 or h3. }
