[White "19. Caro-Kann (1...c6) Mainline"]
[Black "6...Bg4 (7...Qd7 9)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 Nf6 6. Bf4 Bg4
{ The most critical variation, Black develops the bishop with a tempo. L'Ami emphasizes on how essential it is for Black to get the bishop out on the board before playing e7-e6. Positions we have seen earlier clearly shows that the Dutchman is 100% correct in his statement. Therefore, it really isn't very surprising that this is Black's most played move in the position. }
7. Qb3
{ The obvious choice as Black's bishop no longer covers the pawn on b7. } 7...
Qd7
{ Is the most natural way to guard the pawn on b7, so it's not surprising that this is the most played move and also L'Ami's choice in his course. }
8. Nd2 { Pretty much always played, intending Ngf3. } 8... e6 9. Ngf3 Bd6 10.
Bxd6 Qxd6 11. O-O
{ Don't be tempted to grab the pawn. After  11.Qxb7  Rb8  12.Qa6  O-O  13.O-O  Rb6  14.Qa3  Qxa3  15.bxa3  Bxf3  16.Nxf3  Rc8  and Black has excellent compensation as our horrible pawn structure makes our extra pawn insignificant. The pawn on  c3  is also a weakness Black can exploit as well. The objective evaluation is not surprising, the typical 0.00. Practically, I'd pick Black though... }
11... O-O 12. Rfe1 Rab8
{ Black prepares the standard queenside plan and intends to play b5 in one go. This is beneficial, because with b5 on the board, Black can play a5 right away instead of having wasted a tempo with a6. }
13. Ne5
{ With no knight on d7, we're free to jump to the beautiful e5-square. } 13...
Bh5 14. Qc2
{ It makes sense to move the queen now that it doesn't do much on b3.  14.Re3  can also be considered. After  14...Qc7  15.Rae1  b5  16.a3  Na5?!  17.Qc2  Nc4  18.Rh3  Bg6  19.Bxg6  hxg6  20.Ndf3  , Black was in huge trouble in Praggnanandhaa, R - Tari, A chess24.com 2019.   The improvement is to play the slightly strange-looking  16...Nxe5!  when Black is completely fine after  17.dxe5  Ng4  18.Rh3  Bg6  19.Bxg6  fxg6!  A surprising capture that gives Black some initiative. }
14... Rfc8
{ 14...b5  is not so tempting, as it gives us a nice square on  c5  for our knight via  b3  . }
15. Nxc6
{ It's going to be difficult for Black to achieve anything significant on the queenside without the knight. }
15... Rxc6 { 15...bxc6  is met by  16.b4  , an important detail! } 16. g3 Bg6
{ 16...b5  is typical, but nothing to worry about after  17.a3  . If Black follows up with  17.. .a5  , we have  18.Nb3  when we'll place a knight on  c5  .  Black can't stop this, as the knight must stay on f6 to prevent Bxh7. }
17. Bxg6 hxg6 18. Nf3
{ White has a pleasant edge. It's not easy for Black to do much as we can easily stop the play on the queenside and then proceed on the kingside. A sample line is:  18...b5  19.a3  a5  20.Ne5  Rc7  21.Nd3  Ne4  22.Qe2  , when Kg2-h4-Rh1-h5 will follow. }
