1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 Nf6 6. Bf4 Bg4
{ The most critical variation, Black develops the bishop with a tempo. L'Ami emphasizes on how essential it is for Black to get the bishop out on the board before playing e7-e6. Positions we have seen earlier clearly shows that the Dutchman is 100% correct in his statement. Therefore, it really isn't very surprising that this is Black's most played move in the position. }
7. Qb3
{ The obvious choice as Black's bishop no longer covers the pawn on b7. } 7...
Qd7
{ Is the most natural way to guard the pawn on b7, so it's not surprising that this is the most played move and also L'Ami's choice in his course. }
8. Nd2 { Pretty much always played, intending Ngf3. } 8... e6 9. Ngf3 Bd6 10.
Bxd6 Qxd6 11. O-O
{ Don't be tempted to grab the pawn. After  11.Qxb7  Rb8  12.Qa6  O-O  13.O-O  Rb6  14.Qa3  Qxa3  15.bxa3  Bxf3  16.Nxf3  Rc8  and Black has excellent compensation as our horrible pawn structure makes our extra pawn insignificant. The pawn on  c3  is also a weakness Black can exploit as well. The objective evaluation is not surprising, the typical 0.00. Practically, I'd pick Black though... }
11... O-O 12. Rfe1 Ne7
{ Is the move L'Ami suggests, initially introduced at the highest level by Mamedyarov. Black's point is quite creative, as he simply wants to avoid the double pawns after Bg6 by playing Bf5 directly. Black doesn't have to worry about the hanging pawn on b7 either, as he gets sufficient counterplay as L'Ami greatly demonstrates. }
13. Nh4
{ Is a step in the wrong direction according to L'Ami, with a single purpose of stopping Black's plan. He's certainly right about the fact that e5 is the square for the piece, but I didn't find anything special after   13.Ne5  Bf5  . I analyzed a few moves here, but I think Black is fine:  14.a4  Bxd3  15.Nxd3  Rab8  16.a5  Ng6  17.g3  Rfc8  18.Qb4  Qxb4  19.Nxb4  was just equal in Carlsen, M - Firouzja, A Lichess.org INT 2020.   14.Bxf5  Nxf5  15.Qxb7  is very well analyzed by L'Ami, with an important detail being  15...Rab8  16.Qxa7  Rxb2  17.Nb3  h5!  intending Ng4.  After  18.h3  Rc2  19.Nc5  Ne4  , Black has enough counterplay and the game should end in a draw in most lines. Nice work by my colleague.   Perhaps we have a very small plus after  14.a3  a6  15.Qd1  Rac8  16.Bxf5  Nxf5  17.Qf3  , but I was hungry for more... }
13... Ng6 { Black gets rid of the knight in order to play Bf5. } 14. Bxg6
{ It definitely looks rather strange to take with the bishop, which is why I think the Dutch GM didn't check this move. The plan is not too deep, however. We're heading back to f3 next, when we have obtained the desired pawn structure. Having the knight gone makes it tougher for Black to achieve the queenside plans, as we've seen earlier! }
14... hxg6 15. h3 Qf4
{ Seems best, intending to get rid of the bishop.   15...Bf5  I don't think Black benefits much from having the bishop on the board, as the doubled pawns makes it vulnerable to g4-thrusts.  16.Nhf3  Our knight has fulfilled its duty and heads back to f3 where it can reach e5 and g5. This position looks really difficult to play for Black. A sample line is:  16...Rab8  17.Qd1!  This is a nice prophylactic way to meet Black's queenside plans, as it allows us to jump to b3 in case Black plays c5.  17...b5  18.a3  a5  And here, a really nice thematic idea is  19.Nb3  b4  20.cxb4!  We take in this fashion to create a powerful passed pawn!  20...axb4  21.a4  The passer is incredibly dangerous.  21...Rfc8  The open c-file can't be used by Black either, as we can just go  22.Rc1  And after  22...Rxc1  23.Qxc1+-  The endgame looks lost to me due to our powerful passer. }
16. Nhf3 Bxf3 17. Nxf3
{ I'll admit that White doesn't have much, but there is some small plus due to our better pawn structure, while Black's queen is also slightly misplaced. We'll proceed similarly to what we've seen earlier, by doubling our rooks in the e-file, play Ne5 and eventually g3-Kg2-h4-h5. We can also stop Black's queenside play with a3 and Nd3. Your move, Erwin! :@@EndBracket@@ }
