{ It looks best to play this move first, intending to play Ne5 in the next move. The difference will be that Black can't recapture, as the h7-pawn will hang in the end.   13.Ne5!?  looks more natural, which was played against me recently by Bluebaum. I had a bad day at work and blundered in a drawn rook endgame @@StartBracket@@however, I was worse the entire game@@EndBracket@@ The game proceeded with the surprising  13...Nxe5  , which looks pretty decent. I somehow did not play  14.dxe5  , as I didn't like  14...Nd7  15.Qa4  Bh5  16.Qh4  Bg6  17.Bxg6  fxg6  18.Nf3  , like in Blomqvist, E - Prohaszka, P Batumi 2019.   14.Rxe5  , my move, was not bad by any means, but Bluebaum was able to get the queenside play relatively easily, when I quickly found myself defending a worse position. Mihajlov, S - Bluebaum, M Tornelo INT 2021.  I suppose that  13...Bh5  is more natural, when we can transpose to our line after  14.Qc2  .  14.f4  was played by my good friend and expert in the Exchange Caro-Kann, Lucas Van Foreest in Van Foreest, L - Bareev, E Wijk aan Zee 2019, a game I urge you to check out as it demonstrates how dangerous our attack can get.  14.f4  is objectively worse than our move though, but the positions that arise are complex and rather tough to play for an unprepared player, as the aforementioned game clearly shows. }
13... Bh5 14. Ne5 a6
{ 14...Rac8  Was played in Shubin,K - Svane,R Tornelo INT 2020, and here I suggest to play  15.Nxc6!  With a slight edge after  15...Qxc6  After 15... bxc6, Black will struggle to achieve anything on the queenside after 16. b4.  16.a4  We're once again stopping Black's play on the queenside. We can follow with the typical rook doubling by playing Re1-Rae1, and even play a5 in case Black plays a6. White is in the driving seat.   14...Nxe5  Looks risky for Black after  15.dxe5  It's even possible to take with the rook, but this is the most critical of course.  15...Nd7  16.Bxh7+  Kh8  17.Bd3  Nxe5  18.Re3→  And we have the a dangerous attack with the open h-file. }
15. Re3 { The typical plan is still strong. } 15... Rac8 16. Nxc6 Qxc6 17. Nf3
{ Other thematic moves like  17.a3  or  17.Rae1  were perfectly fine here as well. }
17... Bg6 18. Bxg6 hxg6
{ We have been following the blitz game Zhigalko, S - Rakhmanov, A Moscow 2019. White went  19.Ng5  , but all the edge was gone after  19...b5  20.a3  a5  21.Qd3  b4  . Instead, I think the thematic }
19. Ne5 { Is just excellent after } 19... Qc7 20. Qe2
{ When Black has no counterplay on the queenside. We have a very dangerous-looking attack with h4-h5 coming at great velocity. }
