[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "20. French Defense (1...e6)  Minor Sidelines"]
[Black "French Defense Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6
{ This move is what defines the opening called 'French Defense,' which is by far the biggest topic of this course! }
2. d4 { Keeping with our common theme throughout the course. } 2... d5
{ This is where my life as an author begun for me around 9 months ago when I started creating the video series called 'Destroy the French. ' French Defense is an opening I have played for years with Black, but I had always struggled to face it with the white pieces. For pure selfish reasons I pursued to investigate it, as I was sick of my poor results in OTB chess. Here is a breakdown of some alternatives White has and my experiences with them: I had tried the funky 3. Bd3 earlier, when Black has like 4-5 different ways to equalize. GM Jon Ludvig Hammer slowly but very convincingly outplayed me with the move 3... c5 in the Norwegian Championship. 3. e5 is known as the Advanced Variation where White gets pressure on the kingside, while Black gets a significant amount of pressure on the queenside, particularly against the pawns on d4 and b2. The theoretical verdict is that Black is doing well here, as long as he knows what he's doing. 3. exd5 is not a serious attempt to achieve any advantage, and I would call it the worst exchange variation out there much less critical than for example Exchange Slav and Exchange Caro-Kann. The play is symmetrical of course, but there are lots of pieces left and Black will have decent possibilities to outplay his lower rated opponent. 3. Nd2 is known as the most solid choice and indeed a move which usually suits positional players. Here 3... c5 has proven to be a very tough nut to crack. Black has a lot of other tries as well here similarly to 3. Nc3. 3... a6 for instance, was and still is, my pet line. A nice summary is that White can hope for a long-term positional advantage at best, but we won't win right out of the opening unlike in the 3. Nc3-lines. 3. Nc3 is by far the most critical test for Black, something I was well-aware of before the course as I am an avid French-player myself. I was positively surprised once I discovered how venomous it was! }
3. Nc3
{ So it begins! This is the critical test for Black, developing the knight to c3 where it defends the e4-pawn and applies pressure against the pawn on d5. In this chapter I will only examine all of Black's oddities, but I still want to highlight Black's other options: 3... Bb4 is the Winawer Variation which is advocated by GM Anish Giri in his Chessable Course. These positions that arise from this bad boy are some of the wildest and most fascinating in the game of chess! 3... dxe4 is the Rubinstein Variation when the game changes entirely, because Black chooses to open the position. It's known for being a rather solid choice since Black has a good pawn structure with no weaknesses, much like the 3... Qd8-Scandinavian. 3... Nf6 is the Classical Variation which is what I have played numerous times with Black. These three are the main options, but there are a couple more: 3... Be7 & 3... Nc6 are less common sidelines which both deserve a chapter each. Before we start our analysis, I want to highlight some themes throughout our French coverage and the typical positions that arise: Black has more space on the queenside and tends to focus most of his attention on that side of the board. c5 is a move Black almost always plays which attacks the base of our pawn chain, especially if we have committed to e5. This is seen in the Winawer Variation for example. It's not unusual to be loved by anyone... for Black to apply additional pressure on d4 with the help of Nc6/Qb6 too, and he may also further expand on the queenside with the a and b-pawns, for example with a6/b5. Our strong center is often very annoying for Black to deal with, so you can be certain that he will play against it. c5 is not always enough to create sufficient pressure, so Black often includes f6 as well. We can often support our e5-pawn with the help of f4, but we must be careful that Black can't utilize the opening of the a7/ g1-diagonal. This is yet another reason why Black's queen is often placed on b6. Our play revolves around the kingside as we have extra space there. This is for example seen in the Alekhine-Chatard Attack where we even sacrifice a pawn for the initiative. The Greek Gift: the typical Bxh7+ sac is a theme that shows up every now and then in these positions so stay on the lookout for it! Our space advantage on the kingside is also rather prominent in the endgame which we try to expand on with the likes of f4-f5, g4-g5 and even h4-h5. Placing the pawn on f5 is a common plan since it attacks the base of Black's pawn chain the pawn on e6. Another positional struggle Black has is the bishop on c8 which is known as 'the French-bishop.' It's not surprising that this piece is bad, as Black puts the pawns on light squares. A dream scenario is to have a knight against this bishop in the endgame. There are countless model games on this topic out there as it serves as a very instructive positional theme. For this reason, Black tends to try to exchange it with moves like b6/Ba6 or Bd7-Qb6-Bb5. These rules are by no means 'absolute,' as they depend on which approach Black takes. As you can see there are many paths forward, but few lead to Rome... Let's now check out Black's different possibilities! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "20. French Defense (1...e6)  Minor Sidelines"]
[Black "3...c5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6
{ This move is what defines the opening called 'French Defense,' which is by far the biggest topic of this course! }
2. d4 { Keeping with our common theme throughout the course. } 2... d5 3. Nc3
c5
{ This move is a great move against the moves 3. Nd2 and 3. e5, but here it loses a pawn. The move has been seen as much as 1800 times, primarily by lower-rated players. I have even encountered it myself several times in some banter blitz sessions! }
4. exd5 exd5 5. Bb5+
{ I prefer developing the bishop with a check before grabbing the pawn, but there's nothing wrong with taking it immediately. }
5... Nc6
{ 5...Bd7  Is now met by  6.Qe2+  The subtle point is that we defend the bishop, so we can take the pawn on d5 next.  6...Qe7  7.Be3  The most precise. White is attacking c5 and d5 simultaneously and has a completely winning position after just 7 moves. Chen, F - Blackmore,M ICCF email 2018. }
6. dxc5
{ The advantage of having placed the knight on c3 is now clear, because the d5-pawn is now under fire. }
6... Nf6 { If Black chooses to defend the d5-pawn, we should respond with } 7.
Be3 { Which develops a piece while it prevents Black from capturing on c5. }
7... Be7 8. Nge2
{ The best spot for the knight, as Nf3 makes Bg4 an unnecessary annoyance. }
8... O-O 9. h3 { Let's prevent a knight jump to g4 before we castle! } 9... a6
10. Bxc6 bxc6 11. O-O
{ White was a clean pawn up in Simeoni, M-Farina, S Italy 1997. A simple plan is to play b4-Nd4-Na4-c3. }
