1. e4 e6
{ This move is what defines the opening called 'French Defense,' which is by far the biggest topic of this course! }
2. d4 { Keeping with our common theme throughout the course. } 2... d5 3. Nc3
c5
{ This move is a great move against the moves 3. Nd2 and 3. e5, but here it loses a pawn. The move has been seen as much as 1800 times, primarily by lower-rated players. I have even encountered it myself several times in some banter blitz sessions! }
4. exd5 exd5 5. Bb5+
{ I prefer developing the bishop with a check before grabbing the pawn, but there's nothing wrong with taking it immediately. }
5... Nc6
{ 5...Bd7  Is now met by  6.Qe2+  The subtle point is that we defend the bishop, so we can take the pawn on d5 next.  6...Qe7  7.Be3  The most precise. White is attacking c5 and d5 simultaneously and has a completely winning position after just 7 moves. Chen, F - Blackmore,M ICCF email 2018. }
6. dxc5
{ The advantage of having placed the knight on c3 is now clear, because the d5-pawn is now under fire. }
6... Bxc5
{ Black can capture on c5 right away with some hopes of getting some counterplay with quick development. }
7. Qxd5
{ We should of course take with the queen which attacks the bishop on c5 while gaining a tempo on Black's queen. }
7... Qb6 { The logical move which defends c5 & c6 and attacks f2. } 8. Ne4
{ A strong move. White is not only defending the f2-pawn, he is also attacking Black's bishop on c5 so Black is forced to spend a move moving it. }
8... Be7 9. Be3 { Gaining a very valuable tempo on the queen. } 9... Qc7 10.
Nf3 a6 11. Ne5
{ This move is very strong due to tactical reasons, but it was by no means necessary. The simple  11.Bxc6  followed by  Qd2  gives White as much as +3 due to the better development and extra material. }
11... Bb4+ 12. c3
{ Forced, since the check allowed Black's queen to defend the pawn on f7. }
12... axb5 13. cxb4 Qxe5
{ Black has won a piece, but the extra material didn't last long. } 14. Nd6+
Kd7 15. Qxf7+ Nge7
{ 15...Qe7  is met by  16.O-O-O  , when Black has to take on  f7  which will lose the rook on  h8  . }
16. Nc4 { Another beautiful move! } 16... bxc4 17. O-O-O+ Kc7 18. Bf4
{ White won the queen in Matei,C -Darvas,I ICCF email 2011. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "20. French Defense (1...e6)  Minor Sidelines"]
[Black "3...g6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6
{ 1... e6 is what defines the opening called "French Defense," which is by far the biggest topic of this course as it spans through more than 20 chapters! }
2. d4
{ The common theme throughout the course is that we take full control of the center whenever we are able to! }
2... d5 3. Nc3 g6
{ Black has tried this move in some games, but it's a mean thing to do to the dark squares. }
4. Nf3 Bg7 5. h4
{ I am sure you're not surprised by seeing this move if you've taken a look at my coverage on the Pirc & Modern. Whenever Black plays g6, he is extremely vulnerable to h4-h5 ideas as the g6-pawn works as a hook to open the h-file. The pawn can also go to h6 where it will push Black's bishop to the sad f8-square. }
5... h6
{ A natural response where the idea is to meet h5 with g5.   5...h5  Is more sensible, but weakens the g5-square.  6.Bd3  Ne7  7.O-O  Just natural moves all around.  7...O-O  8.Bg5  The bishop is finally headed to the beautiful g5-square.  8...f6  Is not a nice move to make, but Black has nothing better.  9.Bf4  Nbc6  10.Re1  Taking control of the e-file.  10...Nb4  11.Bf1  dxe4  12.Nxe4  Black's position is terrible due to his passive pieces and backward pawn on e6. }
6. Bf4
{ Now that Black has placed the pawn on h6, we can apply pressure on it. } 6...
Ne7 7. Qd2 { It's not easy for Black to castle. } 7... dxe4 8. Nxe4 Nbc6 9.
O-O-O { A developing move which defends the d4-square. Simple chess! } 9... Nd5
{ Black tries to get rid of our bishop so he can castle without losing the h6-pawn. }
10. g4
{ One of many good moves in the position - grabbing space on the kingside. }
10... Nxf4 11. Qxf4 O-O
{ Black has castled, but the position is beyond salvation after } 12. g5 h5 13.
Ne5
{ Black's position won't survive our kingside attack as a bishop sacrifice on h5 will come as soon as we've placed a knight on f6. }
