[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "20. French Defense (1...e6)  Minor Sidelines"]
[Black "3...b6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6
{ 1... e6 is what defines the opening called 'French Defense,' which is by far the biggest topic of this course as it spans through more than 20 chapters! }
2. d4
{ The common theme throughout the course is that we take full control of the center whenever we are able to! }
2... d5 3. Nc3 b6
{ This sideline gave me an annoying amount of trouble. Not because it's good by any means, but because we have so many good options! On chess24 I gave a line that lead to fun complications and some really beautiful tactics. The lines were long and there was an annoying amount to memorize. All that for a line you will 'never' see OTB! Why should we bother? Your time is better spent elsewhere, especially in the Winawer & Classical Variation. }
4. exd5
{ I know what you're thinking. From aggressive play to THIS? The thing is that b6 is often a useful move for Black as it supports a potential break with c5 and opens the possibility of trading the light-squared bishops with Ba6.  I simply want to give Black a poor version of the Exchange French, which is the last thing he desires when playing 3... b6. Many options here are possible. }
4... exd5 5. Nf3 Nf6
{ Black doesn't want to place the bishop on b7 in the Exchange French, as it just hits the d5-pawn. }
6. Ne5
{ A strong knight jump with the threat of Bb5+. Black should prevent this, when our moves will be Qf3 followed by Bf4 and O-O-O, with a ton of initiative. }
6... Bb7
{ This logical move prevents Bb5+, but it's not the most accurate move in the position.   6...Bd6  &  6...Be7  are both met by  7.Bb5+  . }
7. Qf3 { A strong move, creating pressure against Black's position. } 7... Be7
{ 7...Bd6?  is not good due to  8.Bg5  , when the bishop will have to return to the e7-square due to the annoying pin. }
8. Bf4 O-O 9. O-O-O
{ White's active position gives him a massive edge. One plan I really like is to play h4-h5, then start creating threats with Qg3. Qg3 immediately would be met by Nh5 which is why we play h4-h5 first. The light-squared bishop will be placed on d3 where it takes control over the e4-square and aids us in the attack. If Black plays c5, we can just take and play Bc4 when the pawn on d5 falls. White's already close to winning... }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "20. French Defense (1...e6)  Minor Sidelines"]
[Black "3...b6 2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6
{ 1... e6 is what defines the opening called 'French Defense,' which is by far the biggest topic of this course as it spans through more than 20 chapters! }
2. d4
{ The common theme throughout the course is that we take full control of the center whenever we are able to! }
2... d5 3. Nc3 b6
{ This sideline gave me an annoying amount of trouble. Not because it's good by any means, but because we have so many good options! On chess24 I gave a line that lead to fun complications and some really beautiful tactics. The lines were long and there was an annoying amount to memorize. All that for a line you will 'never' see OTB! Why should we bother? Your time is better spent elsewhere, especially in the Winawer & Classical Variation. }
4. exd5 exd5 5. Nf3
{ Black doesn't want to place the bishop on b7 in the Exchange French, as it just hits the d5-pawn. }
5... Nf6 6. Ne5
{ A strong knight jump with the threat of Bb5+. Black should prevent this, when our moves will be Qf3 followed by Bf4 and O-O-O, with a ton of initiative. }
6... c6
{ This move doesn't make much sense from a human perspective when b6 has been played, but it's a strong move. Black can now decide what he wants to do with his bishop. It can be placed on e6 when it will no longer hit the pawn, or it can be placed on a6 where it will achieve the favorable trade. }
7. Bd3 Be7
{ Black should place the bishop on the diagonal right away.   7...Bd6?  A move that looks super natural, but essentially a waste of time as it has to return to e7 when we place Black under the annoying pin.  8.O-O  O-O  9.Bg5  The pin creates massive problems for Black who will have to play Be7 in order to untangle.  9...h6  10.Bh4  Be7  11.f4  Grabbing additional space.  11...Nfd7  The only way to untangle is to get rid of our e5-knight which has placed the pawn on c6 under an annoying amount of pressure.  12.Bxe7  Qxe7  13.Qf3  We keep playing actively.  13...Nxe5  14.fxe5  Both captures are good but I prefer to open the f-file. White has an outstanding position here due to our development advantage and activity. We have a ton of ideas like Nd1-Ne3-Nf5 or Ne2-Nf4 when c3-Bc2-Qd3 will follow suit. }
8. O-O O-O 9. Bg5
{ We are a tempo down, but we still have a much better position. } 9... Nfd7
10. Bxe7 Qxe7 11. f4 Nxe5 12. fxe5
{ Black has gotten rid of our knight, but our space advantage and development advantage gives him a clearly worse game. }
12... Na6 { Black should place the knight on the e6 square. } 13. Qh5
{ Creating direct pressure towards Black's king. } 13... h6 14. Rf6
{ A very strong move, with the plan of doubling on the f-file, and break through with a sacrifice on h6 if allowed. }
14... Nb4
{ Black has to get rid of the d3-bishop. Taking the rook with  14...gxf6?  fails to  15.Qxh6  , followed by Rf1-Rf3. }
15. Raf1 Nxd3 16. cxd3 Qb4
{ Black needs direct counterplay.   16...Be6?  Loses to  17.Rxh6!  White is breaking through.  17...gxh6  18.Rf6  Black can't do much about the threat of Rxh6, so he is forced to give the queen.  18...Qxf6  19.exf6  Kh7  20.Ne2  White is completely winning although Black has two rooks. The queen and knight is much better, much due to the strong f6-pawn.  20...Rg8  21.Qe5  Rg5  22.Qc7  With Nf4 coming next, Black is doomed. Black's rook will be trapped if taking the f6-pawn after Nf4-h3-g4-Qe5! }
17. Ne2 { Defending the d4-pawn but also potentially heading to f4. } 17... Qd2
{ Black needs to maintain the pressure at the cost of the f7-pawn. } 18. Rxf7
Be6 19. R7f6 { An excellent way of maintaining the pressure. } 19... Qxd3
{ 19...gxf6?  Doesn't work due to  20.Qg6+  Kh8  21.Nf4  Blocking the queen's protection on the h6-pawn.  21...Qe3+  22.Kh1  fxe5  Black tries to open the position, but it doesn't save it.  23.Qxh6+  Kg8  24.Qxe6+  Kh7  25.Qg6+  Kh8  26.dxe5  We are down an exchange, but Black's poor king gives us a winning position.  26...Qxe5  27.Qxc6  Grabbing pawns while we can.  27...Qf6  28.Qxd5  Rae8  29.g3  Securing our king. We are now up three pawns so even an endgame will be winning for us. After almost 30 moves, we can stop the line! Phew. }
20. Qg6
{ Forcing a queen trade which will give us a good endgame.  20.Rxe6??  would lose to  20...Qe3+  . }
20... Qxg6 21. Rxg6 Rxf1+ 22. Kxf1
{ Our active pieces give us a fantastic endgame. } 22... Re8 23. Nf4 Rf8
{ Black's best defense.  23...Kf7  doesn't do anything, so we can just continue with  24.Kf2  with  Ke3  coming. Black is tied down. }
24. g3 Bf7 25. Rd6
{ 25.Rxc6?  allows  25...g5  when we will be forced to play Rf6 after we've moved the knight due to the discovery check. The trade of the rooks leads to a drawn endgame. }
25... g5 26. Nd3 { White is close to winning due to Black's passivity. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "20. French Defense (1...e6)  Minor Sidelines"]
[Black "3...a6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6
{ 1... e6 is what defines the opening called 'French Defense,' which is by far the biggest topic of this course! }
2. d4
{ The common theme throughout the course is that we take full control of the center whenever we are able to! }
2... d5 3. Nc3 a6
{ This sideline is not very common, but it has been utilized by a lot of strong GMs. With this move Black avoids a bunch of theory, forcing the opponent to think for themselves. As I stated in the beginning, a6 is a typical move in the French Defense as Black's play revolves around the queenside. a6 is very useful, because it defends the b5-square. White will usually move the pawn to e5 at some point, when Black will respond with c5. This weakens the d6-square which is a strong destination for our knight on c3 that can jump to b5. a6 also supports a potential b5-launch, a common way for Black to expand on the queenside. I suspect that this is objectively Black's best sideline, as it took some doing to find the best way to punish it. }
4. Nf3
{ In chess, you can never really go wrong with natural developing moves. } 4...
Nf6 5. Bd3
{ The easiest approach.  5.e5  might be more dangerous on paper, but it takes the game into a direction that's different from our coverage. Play continues  5...Nfd7  6.Ne2  c5  7.c3  Nc6  , with an interesting version of the Ne2-variations in the Classical Variation. }
5... c5
{ Black can't afford to lose any more valuable time, so it's time for this thematic advance in the center.  5...Be7?  has been seen a surprising amount of times, when  6.e5  Nfd7  7.Ne2  c5  8.c3  Nc6  9.O-O  gives White a dream version of the Ne2-lines. Notice the massive difference of having the bishop on  d3  instead of  f1  like in the  5. e5-line! }
6. exd5
{ The best try for an advantage is to release the tension, as Black is likely to be stuck with an isolated pawn in the center that we can easily target. }
6... exd5 7. Bg5
{ We will reinforce our pressure in the center with a pin on the f6-knight. }
7... Be6 8. Qe2
{ On chess24 I claimed that  8.O-O  Be7  9.dxc5  Bxc5  10.Bxf6  Qxf6  11.Be2  Qd8  12.Qd2  Nc6  13.Rad1  is better for White which is true, but the advantage is really miniscule after  13...Ne7  . The text move is more direct and puts Black under an annoying pin. }
8... Nc6 { Allows us to play } 9. Bf5 { Utilizing our pin on the e6-bishop. }
9... cxd4
{ Black doesn't have anything better.  9...Qd7  is met by  10.O-O-O  when the line goes  10...O-O-O  11.Na4  ,  when the fork on b6 and the pawn on c5 are nice targets for our knight.  9...Qe7  is met by  10.Bxe6  , when  10...Qxe6  11.Qxe6  fxe6  12.Bxf6  gxf6  12.Nxc5  wins a pawn. }
10. Bxe6 fxe6 11. Qxe6+ Qe7 12. Qxe7+ Bxe7 13. Bxf6 Bxf6 14. Nxd5
{ After a long sequence of exchanges, we are a pawn up in the endgame. The advantage is dangerously close to decisive as Black has another weakness in the pawn on d4. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "20. French Defense (1...e6)  Minor Sidelines"]
[Black "3...a6 (7...Be6 Informational)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6
{ 1... e6 is what defines the opening called 'French Defense,' which is by far the biggest topic of this course! }
2. d4
{ The common theme throughout the course is that we take full control of the center whenever we are able to! }
2... d5 3. Nc3 a6
{ This sideline is not very common, but it has been utilized by a lot of strong GMs. With this move Black avoids a bunch of theory, forcing the opponent to think for themselves. As I stated in the beginning, a6 is a typical move in the French Defense as Black's play revolves around the queenside. a6 is very useful, because it defends the b5-square. White will usually move the pawn to e5 at some point, when Black will respond with c5. This weakens the d6-square which is a strong destination for our knight on c3 that can jump to b5. a6 also supports a potential b5-launch, a common way for Black to expand on the queenside. I suspect that this is objectively Black's best sideline, as it took some doing to find the best way to punish it. }
4. Nf3
{ In chess, you can never really go wrong with natural developing moves. } 4...
Nf6 5. Bd3
{ The easiest approach.  5.e5  might be more dangerous on paper, but it takes the game into a direction that's different from our coverage. Play continues  5...Nfd7  6.Ne2  c5  7.c3  Nc6  , with an interesting version of the Ne2-variations in the Classical Variation. }
5... c5
{ Black can't afford to lose any more valuable time, so it's time for this thematic advance in the center.  5...Be7?  has been seen a surprising amount of times, when  6.e5  Nfd7  7.Ne2  c5  8.c3  Nc6  9.O-O  gives White a dream version of the Ne2-lines. Notice the massive difference of having the bishop on  d3  instead of  f1  like in the  5. e5-line! }
6. exd5
{ The best try for an advantage is to release the tension, as Black is likely to be stuck with an isolated pawn in the center that we can easily target. }
6... exd5 7. Bg5 Be6
{ An automatic response by most humans.   7...Qe7+?!  Black's check on e7 wastes valuable time.  8.Be2   8.Qe2  c4  9.Bxc4  is a crazy sacrifice, my engine advocates, but it's pointless to enter such crazy complications when the text move is so simple.  8...Be6  Black has to guard the d5-pawn.  9.O-O  Nc6  10.Re1  Black has to deal with some tactics involving the e-file and Nxd5, hence my stance on this variation. The check hasn't achieved anything.  10...Qd6  Black keeps d5 defended as dxc5 followed by Bxf6 was in the air.  11.Bf1  cxd4   Black is not in time to play  11...Be7  due to  12.dxc5  Qxc5  13.Bxf6  Bxf6  14.Qxd5  , when White wins a pawn due to the pin on Black's bishop.  12.Nxd4  Nxd4  13.Qxd4  Be7  14.Qa4+   A strong move for tactical reasons.  14.Bxf6  is not as strong now that the knight is no longer present. After  14...Bxf6  15.Qxd5  Qc7  16.Qf3  O-O  Black has excellent compensation.  14...Bd7?   A decisive mistake due to a beautiful tactical fitness. The sad  14...Kf8  is Black's best, when both  15.Ne2  heading to  d4  or  15.Rad1  secure White a clearly better game due to the isolated pawn on  d5  and unsafe king.  15.Bb5  Black can't take the bishop due to the hanging rook.  15...O-O-O  16.Bf4  Qb4  17.Rxe7  I'm sure you've seen the theme that's about to pop up when you're noticing how vulnerable Black's king is...  17...Qxe7  18.Qxa6!!  The justification of the variation, the famous Boden's Mate theme. I'm sure most of you have seen it before. Very beautiful indeed. Black has to take the bishop, but the loss of the queenside pawns and exposed king makes the fight very tough:  18...Bxb5  19.Qa8+  Kd7  20.Qxb7+  Ke8  21.Qxb5+  Kf8  The king hides in the corner, but Black's position is still hopeless after  22.Rd1  White will play h3 next to avoid any back-rank tricks. Black's d-pawn won't survive long, when there will only be a matter of time until White's queenside pawns roll up the board and decide the game. }
*

