[White "20. French Defense (1...e6)  Minor Sidelines"]
[Black "3...a6 3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4
{ The common theme throughout the course is that we take full control of the center whenever we are able to! }
2... d5 3. Nc3 a6
{ This sideline is not very common, but it has been utilized by a lot of strong GMs. With this move Black avoids a bunch of theory, forcing the opponent to think for themselves. As I stated in the beginning, a6 is a typical move in the French Defense as Black's play revolves around the queenside. a6 is very useful, because it defends the b5-square. White will usually move the pawn to e5 at some point, when Black will respond with c5. This weakens the d6-square which is a strong destination for our knight on c3 that can jump to b5. a6 also supports a potential b5-launch, a common way for Black to expand on the queenside. I suspect that this is objectively Black's best sideline, as it took some doing to find the best way to punish it. }
4. Nf3
{ In chess, you can never really go wrong with natural developing moves. } 4...
Nf6 5. Bd3
{ The easiest approach.  5.e5  might be more dangerous on paper, but it takes the game into a direction that's different from our coverage. Play continues  5...Nfd7  6.Ne2  c5  7.c3  Nc6  , with an interesting version of the Ne2-variations in the Classical Variation. }
5... c5
{ Black can't afford to lose any more valuable time, so it's time for this thematic advance in the center.  5...Be7?  has been seen a surprising amount of times, when  6.e5  Nfd7  7.Ne2  c5  8.c3  Nc6  9.O-O  gives White a dream version of the Ne2-lines. Notice the massive difference of having the bishop on  d3  instead of  f1  like in the  5. e5-line! }
6. exd5
{ The best try for an advantage is to release the tension, as Black is likely to be stuck with an isolated pawn in the center that we can easily target. }
6... exd5 7. Bg5
{ We will reinforce our pressure in the center with a pin on the f6-knight. }
7... c4 { Black's strongest move in the position, hence the exclam. } 8. Bxf6
{ The drawback of c4 is that Black's pawn structure will be completely destroyed. The engine thinks that it's not such a big deal due to the fact that our dark-squared bishop is gone, making it easier for Black to control the dark squares. However, practically it really doesn't seem fun for Black. }
8... gxf6 9. Be2 Bh6
{ Black can go for a set-up where he placed the bishop on the active h6-c1 diagonal. It was even played in a game I found. }
10. O-O O-O 11. Nh4
{ We're playing for the f5-square with Bg4 coming next. This is slightly harder to prevent than what it initially looks like due to a nice trick. }
11... f5
{ Black has to prevent us from playing Bg4.   11...Bg5?  This would have been sensible if it wasn't for:  12.Bg4!  The trading of the pieces will give Black serious holes in his camp.  12...Bxh4  The missing piece is only temporary.  13.Bxc8  Qxc8  14.Qh5  Nc6   14...Bg5  was met by  15.f4!  when Black loses.  15.Qxh4  Qf5  Black's only hope for counterplay is to stay active.  16.Rae1  Taking control of the open file.  16...Kh8   16...Rae8  looks good until you spot that  17.Re3!  gives Black severe problems due to our powerful attack. The computer gives  17...Kh8  18.Nxd5  , which works as the knight can't be trapped due to the following mate.  17.Nd1!  Another very strong move. The knight is headed to e3 where it will target the pawn on d5. We can also secure our d4-pawn with c3 if necessary.  17...Qg5  Black's best fighting choice is a depressing endgame due to Black's major weaknesses.  18.Qxg5  fxg5  19.c3  White had a fantastic endgame and won eventually in Bruzon Batista,L -Borges Matos,J Santa Clara 2004. }
12. g3 Be6 13. Bf3
{ White's position looks promising with the knight maneuver Ng2-Ne3 coming. Black will have to give away the dark-squared bishop for the knight, when we will have great control on the dark squares. Black has a nice little stonewall so it's not easy to break the defense down, however it is pure suffering for Black as he has to defend for the rest of the game.   Note also that  13...Nc6?  loses to  14.Bxd5!  Bxd5  15.Nxf5  when Black won't be able to defend the bishop on  d5  and the mate threats simultaneously. }
