[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "20. French Defense (1...e6)  Minor Sidelines"]
[Black "3...c6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4
{ The common theme throughout the course is that we take full control of the center whenever we are able to! }
2... d5 3. Nc3 c6
{ Is one of the more sensible sidelines in the position which is more commonly played through a Caro-Kann move order: 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 e6. It's not awful by any means, but certainly not dangerous due to how passive Black becomes. }
4. Be3 { Normal developing moves should do the trick as usual. } 4... Nf6
{ 4...Bb4  is met by  5.e5! } 5. Bd3
{ Because of our repertoire I thought it was best to keep it simple with this move. 5. e5 is the other move here which should give us one extra tempo in the line 1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. e5 Nfd7 5. f4 c5. This is good obviously, but the fact that I don't recommend 4. e5 made it less appealing to me. }
5... dxe4 { Gives Black a poor version of the 3... dxe4-line. } 6. Nxe4 Nxe4 7.
Bxe4 Nd7 8. Qe2
{ Once we get to the coverage on the Rubinstein Variation you will see that we usually go for a set-up which involves queenside castling. Black may be solid, but he is passive so playing aggressively is an ideal approach to this type of play. }
8... Nf6 9. Bd3 Bd6 10. Nf3 O-O 11. Bg5
{ I am a bigger fan of attacking than castling kingside. Still,  11.O-O  was also clearly better for White in the game Laux, G - Lohmann, W Bruchkoebel 2002. }
11... h6 { And here, we have the thematic } 12. h4
{ This move prevents Black from taking the bishop as he can't afford to open the h-file. }
12... Qa5+ 13. Bd2 Qc7 14. O-O-O c5 15. Rhg1
{ Our attack is incredibly strong with g4-g5 being a killer plan. My engine points out that Black's only move is  15...Ng4  which can be countered with  16.Rde1  with Ne5 to follow. }
