[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "20. French Defense (1...e6)  Minor Sidelines"]
[Black "3...c6 2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4
{ The common theme throughout the course is that we take full control of the center whenever we are able to! }
2... d5 3. Nc3 c6 4. Be3
{ Normal developing moves should do the trick as usual. } 4... Nf6
{ 4...Bb4  is met by  5.e5! } 5. Bd3 Qb6
{ The exclam is well-deserved as this a decent try. Black is simply targeting the pawn on b2 with the queen while it supports c5. }
6. Rb1 c5 { This is the only way to make use of the queen on b6. } 7. Nf3
{ In my video series on chess24, 'Destroy the French, ' I gave  7.exd5  but I was never really too thrilled about it. The line continued:  7...exd5  8.Bb5+  Nc6  9.Nge2  a6  10.Bxc6+  Qxc6  11.O-O  Bd6  12.dxc5  Bxc5  13.Bxc5  Qxc5  14.Qd4  . Sure White is better due to Black's isolated pawn, but it's not by that much! Why on earth does Black get a fairly okay position after the silly move  3...c6?  I was baffled to say the least, so I was happy when I discovered the text move which does improve on the line I gave earlier. }
7... c4
{ Black has to keep the position as closed as possible. After  7...Nc6  we can play  8.O-O  with an already massive advantage as we are about to open the position. Black remains undeveloped. }
8. Be2 Bb4
{ Another important move. Other alternatives would allow us to get rid of Black's pawn chain with b3. Black will now take on c3 next when his pawn chain will look pretty nice. }
9. O-O Bxc3 10. bxc3 Qa5
{ Black has destroyed our pawn structure and is now attacking the c3 pawn and the pawn on e4 at the same time! }
11. Nd2
{ A very strong move which defends the pawn on e4, while it tactically prevents Black from taking on c3.   11.e5?  would give Black a great French after  11...Ne4  , when I believe he could even be slightly better due to our weak pawns on the queenside. }
11... O-O
{ Black should get the king out of the way before we're able to play e5 followed by Bxc4. }
12. e5 Nfd7 13. Qc1
{ Sets up a neat trap while it also can provide some protection for the bishop on e3 once we play f4. }
13... Nc6
{ 13...Qxc3?  is bad due to  14.Rb5!  when the queen is out of the game after a subsequent  Nb1  . }
14. f4
{ We should just accept that we're losing the c3-pawn.   14.Qb2?  would be a huge mistake due to  14...Nb6!  when Black wins the pawn anyway. }
14... Qxc3 15. Nf3 { Showing the usefulness of Qc1. } 15... Qa5 16. g4
{ Black has an extra pawn, but it will take a long time before it's possible to make good use of it. }
16... f5
{ Black's best defense is to try to block our pawns on the kingside straight away.   16...f6  As I also mentioned in the beginning of this chapter, this is a common way for Black to fight against our center.  17.h4  It looks best to keep launching our pawns towards the Black king with the simple plan of h5-h6-Nh4. The position looks really tough for Black to defend.  17...Ne7  Makes sense, bringing a piece to the defense.  18.h5  f5!  Black's best way to fight for survival. Against other moves we will play h6 and then start improving our pieces. The maneuver Bd2-Bb4-Bd6 is really strong.  19.h6!   We will play this move anyway!  19.g5  would allow Black to equalize completely, because we need the g5-square for our knight in the future.  19...gxh6   Black's best. The more human  19...g6  looks dreadful after  20.Bd2  , when this idea is yet again very powerful.  20.Nh4  It's time to prepare a capture on f5.  20...Kh8  21.gxf5  exf5  22.Kf2  The king makes way for our rook which can now move to the g-file or h-file where it will create lots of pressure against Black's king. Note also that Bd2 is often a strong move, as we can move to the a3 square with the queen when Black moves the queen. On a3 the queen increases the pressure on the a3-f8 diagonal, while it can also swing to h3. }
17. Nh4
{ Preparing to take on f5 next, when Kh1 and Rg1 will follow suit with dangerous play on the g-file. }
17... Qd8
{ A very natural move of course, but it just helps us.   17...Ne7  A logical attempt for Black to defend.  18.gxf5  I suggest grabbing the pawn straight away.  18...Nxf5  19.Nxf5  exf5   19...Rxf5  sacrifices an exchange after  20.Bg4  . It's not much worse than the text move, but Black has far from enough for the exchange.  20.Bd2  The bishop is best placed on the a3-f8 diagonal.  20...Qd8  21.Bb4  Re8  22.Bf3  Nf6 would have been a cold shower, so we must move the bishop out of the way.  22...Nb6  23.Kh1  It's time to place a rook on the g-file.  23...Re6!  Black needs to be able to control the g6-square. A move like 23... Be6 looked more natural, but it will be tough for Black to defend in the g-file. The text move plans Bd7-Be8, when it's not so easy for us to break through.  24.Rg1  Bd7  25.Qd2  Planning to double the rooks on the g-file with Rg2-Rbg1.  25...Kh8  26.Rg5  Attacking the f5-pawn while preparing for Rbg1.  26...Rh6  27.Qg2  g6  28.Be1!  I don't see how Black is supposed to survive due to our deadly plan of playing h4-h5-Bh4. Yeah, all in all I don't think Black can really survive here, even with very accurate play. Especially in a practical game. I can't stress enough how essential it is to have counterplay. The 3... c6 line lasted way too long for my taste, but I am very happy with what I came up within the end. }
18. Qe1
{ There are different advantages with this queen move. Not only does the queen defend the knight, it can now join the attack on the g-file with Qg3. It also frees the c1-square for the bishop on e3 which will find an excellent spot on the a3-square. }
18... Nb6 19. Kh1 { The king side-steps so we can place a rook on the g-file. }
19... Ne7
{ Black can't do much about our attack. There's just no counterplay. The extra pawn is pretty much worthless unless we reach an endgame... }
20. Rg1 Bd7 21. Qg3 { Our moves come by themselves. } 21... g6 22. Qh3
{ Black's position is dreadful. One mere pawn helps little when there's no counterplay. We will take on f5 on the next move, followed by ideas like Nf3-Ng5 or more subtle Nf3-Bf2-Bh4-Bf6. The bishop can also head to b4 via f2-e1. }
