1. e4 e6 2. d4
{ The common theme throughout the course is that we take full control of the center whenever we are able to! }
2... d5 3. Nc3 c6 4. Be3
{ Normal developing moves should do the trick as usual. } 4... Nf6
{ 4...Bb4  is met by  5.e5! } 5. Bd3 Qb6
{ The exclam is well-deserved as this a decent try. Black is simply targeting the pawn on b2 with the queen while it supports c5. }
6. Rb1 c5 { This is the only way to make use of the queen on b6. } 7. Nf3
{ In my video series on chess24, 'Destroy the French, ' I gave  7.exd5  but I was never really too thrilled about it. The line continued:  7...exd5  8.Bb5+  Nc6  9.Nge2  a6  10.Bxc6+  Qxc6  11.O-O  Bd6  12.dxc5  Bxc5  13.Bxc5  Qxc5  14.Qd4  . Sure White is better due to Black's isolated pawn, but it's not by that much! Why on earth does Black get a fairly okay position after the silly move  3...c6?  I was baffled to say the least, so I was happy when I discovered the text move which does improve on the line I gave earlier. }
7... c4
{ Black has to keep the position as closed as possible. After  7...Nc6  we can play  8.O-O  with an already massive advantage as we are about to open the position. Black remains undeveloped. }
8. Be2 Bb4
{ Another important move. Other alternatives would allow us to get rid of Black's pawn chain with b3. Black will now take on c3 next when his pawn chain will look pretty nice. }
9. O-O Bxc3 10. bxc3 Qa5
{ Black has destroyed our pawn structure and is now attacking the c3 pawn and the pawn on e4 at the same time! }
11. Nd2
{ A very strong move which defends the pawn on e4, while it tactically prevents Black from taking on c3.   11.e5?  would give Black a great French after  11...Ne4  , when I believe he could even be slightly better due to our weak pawns on the queenside. }
11... Nc6
{ Black can play this move when we have the stunning sequence   11...Qxc3?  Black can't take the pawn for concrete reasons.  12.e5  Nfd7   12...Ne4  is objectively best, but still awful for Black after  13.Nxe4  dxe4  14.Bc1!  when the bishop is heading to b2 to remove Black's protection of the pawn on c4. If Black plays Qb4 we can play Qc1 when the bishop heads to a3 next.  13.Bxc4!  A fantastic tactical shot.  13...dxc4  Practically this is obviously Black's best bet. If Black ignores the bishop, we can follow up with Rb3 and Bd3, with a completely dominating position.  14.Ne4  The tactical point is that we get our stallion to d6 where Black simply won't have enough defenses to deal with our attack.  14...Qa5  15.Nd6+  Ke7  16.Qh5  Black can resign as Qxf7+ or Qg5+ comes next. }
12. e5 Ng8 { This gives Black the best prospects to defend. } 13. Bxc4 dxc4 14.
Nxc4 { The piece sacrifice gives us a deadly attack. } 14... Qc7
{ Black's advantage of having placed the knight on g8 is that the queen on c7 defends the f7-pawn. }
15. Nd6+ Kf8 16. Qh5 { Applying more pressure on Black's f7-pawn. } 16... Nd8
{ Black defends the f7-square so he can develop the g8-knight to e7. } 17. c4
{ c4 is another strong move which supports a potential d5 break in the center. Another subtle idea is to play Rb3 and swing the rook over to f3! }
17... Ne7 18. g4
{ It's important that Black is not allowed to play Nf5. A clear idea for us is to play f4-f5, which doesn't seem possible for Black to avoid. The engine tries: }
18... h6 19. f4 Kg8
{ 19...g6  Is the natural human response, but it still fails to  20.Qh4  h5  21.Rb3  Black is paralyzed. One annoying detail for Black is that the king can't be moved due to the fancy-looking Ne8. Our plan forward is placing the bishop on a3 with devastating effect. }
20. f5 { The f-pawn is breaking through! } 20... exf5 21. gxf5 g6
{ And here we have the sophisticated } 22. Ne8 { Which wins on the spot: }
22... gxh5
{ 22...Qc6  23.Nf6+  Kg7  24.fxg6  fxg6  25.Qe2  It was important to keep the c4 pawn defended. Now Black is doomed due to d5 followed by e6 and Bd4. }
23. Nxc7 Rb8 24. d5 { Attacking the pawn on a7 while marching forward. } 24...
b6 25. e6
{ Our pawns are far too strong. If Black attacks our c7-knight we can move it to e8 and from there to d6. }
