1. e4 e6 2. d4
{ The common theme throughout the course is that we take full control of the center whenever we are able to! }
2... d5 3. Nc3 c6 4. Be3
{ Normal developing moves should do the trick as usual. } 4... Nf6
{ 4...Bb4  is met by  5.e5! } 5. Bd3 Bb4
{ Black has played this move twice, but it leads to a terrible Winawer after }
6. e5 Nfd7 7. Qg4
{ The queen almost always heads to g4 whenever Black has moved the bishop in these positions, so keep this idea in mind. Black is down some tempos in the Winawer as he still hasn't been able to carry out the desired c5-break yet. }
7... g6 8. Nf3 c5
{ Black finally achieves to play c5, but will soon suffer the consequences of the tempos lost. }
9. a3 Bxc3+ 10. bxc3 c4
{ A thematic move in the Winawer which stops us from opening the position with c4 while it also pushes our bishop to the inferior e2-square. You will see that this move appears frequently in the Winawer chapters! }
11. Be2 Nc6 12. h4 { Always a thematic move when Black has played g6! } 12...
h6
{ 12...h5  would allow us to easily open the position with  g4  a few moves later. }
13. Bd2 { A prophylactic move which defends the c3-pawn. } 13... Ne7 14. Qf4
{ Black has none of the desired Winawer-counterplay and will sooner or later get infiltrated on the kingside. Our ideas are Nh2-Ng4-Nf6, and potentially a pawn push to h5 which will provoke Black into playing g5. Once Black has played g5 we can prepare the f4-break which is how we'll break through. }
