[Black "3...h6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4
{ The common theme throughout the course is that we take full control of the center whenever we are able to! }
2... d5 3. Nc3 h6
{ This move makes more sense against 3... Nd2 when Black gets some pressure against the center with c5-Nc6 and usually follows up with a g5-launch with g4 in mind, removing the knight on f3 which defends the d4-pawn. Here that idea doesn't work because our knight stands more active on the c3-square. Still, it's not completely useless as the move controls the g5-square. }
4. Bd3 { I suggest simple play with Bd3. } 4... c5
{ This move is suggested by my engine, which is surprising to me as Black simply gives away the pawn. It is much better than 3... c5, but Black is still far away from an equal game. }
5. exd5 exd5 6. dxc5 { We will take the pawn of course. } 6... Bxc5
{ Black aims for active play for the pawn.  6...Nf6  would be bad due to  7.Be3!  when we maintain the pawn on  c5  , with Bb5-Nge2 next.   6...Nc6  is possible too when I suggest  7.Na4  , winning the bishop pair after  7...Bxc5  8.Nxc5  Qa5+  9.c3  . }
7. Bb5+ Bd7 8. Qxd5 Qe7+
{ Black has to force an endgame in order to have chances for compensation. } 9.
Qe4
{ Due to our extra material, there is no need to avoid the trade of queens. }
9... Bxb5 10. Qxe7+ Nxe7 11. Nxb5 Nd5
{ The right way to defend the fork.  11...Na6  is worse as Black's position becomes much more passive since the knight stands on the rim instead of  c6  . }
12. Nf3 Nc6 13. c4 { Forcing some more trades. } 13... Ndb4
{ The only move that doesn't lose decisive material. Now the sequence goes: }
14. Nc7+ Kd7 15. Nxa8 Nc2+ 16. Ke2 Nxa1 17. Nc7 Kxc7 18. Bf4+ Kc8 19. Rxa1
{ Black is a pawn down and has to hold the endgame. Not an impossible task by any means, but it will require very accurate play. }
