[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4
{ The common theme throughout the course is that we take full control of the center whenever we are able to! }
2... d5 3. Nc3 h6 4. Bd3 { I suggest simple play with Bd3. } 4... Nc6
{ This move looks strange, but it is Black's most popular try by a lot. The point is that Black can annoy our d3-bishop with a jump to b4.   4...Nf6?!  Is poor here as it gives us a dream set-up.  5.e5  Nfd7  c5 is Black's next move which will create some pressure against our center. Therefore, the move  6.Nce2!  Is very strong, because we can maintain our powerful center with c3. Now Black will struggle immensely to get the much needed queenside counterplay. This is an idea I certainly want you to keep in mind, as it shows up all the time in the French.  6...c5  7.c3  With the desired set-up. We are now ready to expand our central control with f4-Nf3 next. After that, we will prepare for a kingside attack. White won a nice game in Morozov,D - Kochan,I ICCF email 2017, a game I urge you to check out! }
5. Nf3 Nb4 6. Be2
{ We obviously want to keep the strong light-squared bishop. } 6... Nf6
{ Now that we no longer control the e4-square, Black aims to place a knight there. }
7. e5 Ne4 8. Be3
{ Taking control of the d4-square, so now Nxe4 is a threat. White has usually tried   8.a3  Nxc3  9.bxc3  Nc6  10.O-O  Na5  , when I think Black is doing pretty well considering the unorthodox opening choice. }
8... c5
{ Black switches gears. 8... Nxc3 is possible of course, but worse here as Be3 is much more useful than a3. }
9. dxc5 Nxc5
{ This contradicts what Black initially intended, but it is the best move in the position. }
10. Nd4
{ A logical move which intends to reinforce the center with f4 in the near future. }
10... Be7 11. O-O O-O 12. f4 Nc6
{ We have been following Sebag,M -Legky,N France 2007, when I suggest the improvement }
13. Qd2
{ White is clearly better due to the extra space. Black hasn't achieved anything special on the queenside and will sooner or later get pushed back with a3-b4. }
