1. e4 e6 2. d4
{ The common theme throughout the course is that we take full control of the center whenever we are able to! }
2... d5 3. Nc3 h6 4. Bd3 { I suggest simple play with Bd3. } 4... Nc6
{ This move looks strange, but it is Black's most popular try by a lot. The point is that Black can annoy our d3-bishop with a jump to b4. }
5. Nf3 Nb4 6. Be2
{ We obviously want to keep the strong light-squared bishop. } 6... Nf6
{ Now that we no longer control the e4-square, Black aims to place a knight there. }
7. e5 Ne4 8. Be3
{ Taking control of the d4-square, so now Nxe4 is a threat. White has usually tried   8.a3  Nxc3  9.bxc3  Nc6  10.O-O  Na5  , when I think Black is doing pretty well considering the unorthodox opening choice. }
8... c5
{ Black switches gears.  8...Nxc3  is possible of course, but worse here as  Be3  is much more useful than  a3  . }
9. dxc5 Nxc3 10. bxc3 Nc6
{ Black has managed to ruin our pawn structure, but it turns out that the b-file is a highly useful asset for us. }
11. O-O Qa5
{ Black has tried twice to regain the pawn, but it loses. This doesn't change much though, as the line suggested by the computer looks terrible for Black:   11...Be7  12.Rb1  O-O  13.Re1  Qc7  14.Bd3  . Black has no compensation at all for the pawn. }
12. Nd4
{ This move destroys Black's concept completely due to tactical reasons. }
12... Nxe5
{ 12...Qxc3  gives Black huge problems after  13.Rb1  . Both captures on  c5  lose material. }
13. Bf4 { This move is important, removing the e5-knight from its post. } 13...
Ng6
{ 13...Nc6  14.Nb5  e5  It looks like Black is out of the woods, but...  15.Bxe5!!  BAM! We're breaking through anyway. Black has no soldiers around the king.  15...Nxe5  16.Qxd5  Nc6  17.Bh5  Black will soon get mated. }
14. Bb5+
{ The knight can no longer access the c6-square, so the king will be stuck in the center. }
14... Kd8
{ 14...Bd7  Is met by  15.Bxd7+  Kxd7  16.Rb1  With a really strong attack as c6 comes if Black plays 16... b6.  16...Qa6  Doesn't help, as the pawn hangs anyway.  17.Rxb7+ }
15. Bg3 Bxc5
{ Black is up a pawn, but the exposed king makes sure that the position is lost despite that fact. }
16. Bd3
{ A strong move, freeing the b5-square for the knight while aiming to destroy Black's pawn structure with Bxg6. }
16... Ne7 17. Nb5 { I like being straightforward. Now Bc7+ is a threat. } 17...
b6 18. Nc7 Rb8 19. Nxe6+ Bxe6 20. Bxb8
{ With Black's exposed king and material deficit, I don't see Black getting out of this one.   CONCLUSION: Our adventure in the French Defense began with some unusual lines by Black. 3... c5 and 3... g6 won't challenge you in any way, as the first move loses a pawn while the latter doesn't fit Black's set-up. 3... c6 is possible, when the game has turned into a strange version of the Caro-Kann. It took some doing to take down this move due to the fact that Black's excellent 5... Qb6 proved to be quite a challenge! Indeed, the line almost concluded with 30 moves of analysis. Pretty wild for such a peculiar move like 3... c6! The final verdict is that Black's position is very tough to handle from a practical perspective. The GM-move 3... a6 is Black's best sideline, as the move is a tough nut to crack. a6 is a highly useful move in the French as it covers the b5-square and supports a b5-thrust. The game could head into a version of the Classical Variation, but that's outside of our repertoire! I therefore suggest to play Bd3 followed by exd5, giving Black a hanging pawn on d5. Black has an important decision to make after we've played Bg5. 7... Qe7+?! doesn't do much as Black can't afford to waste time. 7... c4! is what the engine suggests, but the resulting positions look much easier to handle from the white side. Black has two different set-ups here. Against Bg7, an important idea to remember is Re1-Bf1-g3-Bg2 and a potential Ne2-Nd4 or even Nh4-Ng2-Ne3. These positions are not very concrete, so there are many different set-ups White can go for. Bh6, on the other hand, is more concrete when it's important to play 11. Nh4 with the idea of settling on the light squares. 11... f5 is forced, when we will place the knight on e3 via g2. I like White's prospects a lot here, as it looks like pure misery from a practical perspective for Black. 7... Be6 is not an easy move to face either, as I had to change my recommendation from my video series on chess24 when I discovered that 8. O-O wasn't anything special. The new move is 8. Qe2! which gives Black some problems to solve due to the annoying pin on the bishop on e6. I'm quite happy with what I came up with against 3... a6, but I will point out that it remains a highly respectable sideline which is why it has been played by numerous strong GMs. 3... b6?! is not as bad as it looks as the move is useful in the French. It took me 3-4 hours to take this move down, as I kept going back and forth on what system to recommend! In the end I discovered that 4. exd5 gives Black a poor version of the Exchange French. With a quick knight jump to e5 followed by Qf3, Black is under a lot of pressure. 3... h6?! was the last topic of the chapter. Our response should be 4. Bd3, a natural developing move that covers the e4-square. The machine wants Black to play 4... c5, but that simply gives away a pawn. Black has a lot more compensation than in the 3... c5-line, but a pawn is a pawn. Why would you go into an endgame where you'll have no winning chances as Black? Doesn't make sense! : 4... Nc6 is the common move here, when Black's idea is to jump to b4 in order to get rid of our bishop which covers the e4-square. Black will follow up with a knight jump to e4, when my analysis showed that 8. Be3! destroys Black's fun in this variation. Last thing I want to mention is that you should not be spending so much time here, as you are very unlikely to face these lines over the board. }
*

