1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Be7
{ The last sideline we must consider is this move which looks very peculiar indeed. To me it looks like a way for Black to avoid the most dangerous lines in the Classical Variation I am indeed talking about our move 4. Bg5 while confusing the opponent. However, the move has a major flaw which is clearly seen after our response. }
4. e5
{ This is the only way to punish Black's set-up as the knight is locked in place on g8. }
4... c5 5. Qg4
{ This is a typical reaction when Black has no protection over the pawn on g7 as we are forcing him to make a concession. }
5... g5
{ This move is Black's best bet to create some problems for us as the positions that occur are quite tricky. Black will soon follow with up with h5 which will give him some space on the kingside. The aggressive approach has its downside though, as it does make Black more vulnerable on the kingside. }
6. dxc5 h5 { Black gets some space on the kingside and pushes our queen away. }
7. Qg3 Nc6 8. Nf3
{ I think this move is the simplest which transposes to  6...Nc6  . Black's most accurate way of playing is to start with  6...Nc6  though, since this move-order allows the extra move  8.Nb5!?  . In the end I didn't find anything special in that line, so I decided to choose the simple path and transpose... I analyzed:  8...h4  9.Qc3  d4  10.Qa3  Nxe5  11.f4  gxf4  12.Bxf4  Rh5!  13.Nd6+  Bxd6  14.cxd6  Nc6  15.O-O-O  with some initiative for White, but Black is hanging in there and the fight remains complex. }
8... g4
{ It does look like that Black has a lot of play, until you discover that the knight isn't really under attack! }
9. h3 { A strong move which removes Black's annoying pawn on g4. } 9... d4
{ Loses the game, but it requires some precision! } 10. Nb5 a6
{ And now we are winning after the fantastic } 11. hxg4
{ We are giving away the knight as we are blasting through.  11.Na3  is the alternative, when the edge has gone down from +3 to  +1. }
11... h4
{ The critical move of course, since Black closes the h-file and attacks our queen at the same time. Luckily, we have more brilliancies up our sleeve.   11...axb5  Is not a good fighting attempt, as we regain the piece quickly.  12.Rxh5  Rxh5  13.gxh5  The h-pawn is rolling up the board.  13...Kd7  14.h6  Black has to give the knight back when he will be left with a dead lost position.  14...Nxh6  15.Bxh6  Black's king is stuck in the center and his pawns are weak. Nothing more to say here. }
12. Nd6+ { We are sacrificing our queen for an insane amount of compensation. }
12... Bxd6 13. cxd6 { The right way to capture. } 13... hxg3 14. Rxh8 Kd7
{ Black won't be able to save the knight in the long run.   14...Qa5+  Doesn't achieve much either, as Black won't be able to win our strong e5-pawn.  15.Bd2  Qd5  16.Rxg8+  Kd7  17.Rg5  We have everything under control and thus, a completely winning position. }
15. Bd3 { Black is paralyzed. A truly amazing position. } *

[Event "?"]
