[Black "3...Be7 (4...c5 4)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Be7
{ The last sideline we must consider is this move which looks very peculiar indeed. To me it looks like a way for Black to avoid the most dangerous lines in the Classical Variation I am indeed talking about our move 4. Bg5 while confusing the opponent. However, the move has a major flaw which is clearly seen after our response. }
4. e5
{ This is the only way to punish Black's set-up as the knight is locked in place on g8. }
4... c5 5. Qg4
{ This is a typical reaction when Black has no protection over the pawn on g7 as we are forcing him to make a concession. }
5... g6
{ A move we will see over and over again in the Winawer-chapters. The problem with this move is the weakening of the dark-squares, in particular the f6-square, around Black's camp. }
6. dxc5 { In similar fashion to the previous note. } 6... Nc6 7. Nf3 Bxc5 8.
Bd3
{ Achieving the usual f6-break will be significantly harder for Black due to the pawn on g6. }
8... Nb4
{ In most games I found Black tried this with the intent of grabbing our d3-bishop.   8...f6?!  Will only cause problems after the precise  9.Qh3!  Attacking the g6-pawn.  9...f5  Is pretty much forced, when  10.O-O  Gives us a fantastic game as Black is struggling on the kingside and on the dark squares. The knight has to stay in its place on g8, otherwise we will infiltrate with Bg5-Bf6. Next, we can start to open the position with the likes of Ne2-c4. Black's position is simply put in dire straits. }
9. O-O
{ We will ignore Black's shenanigans. Black may gain the bishop pair, but he loses valuable time in the process. }
9... Nxd3 10. cxd3 Bd7
{ The factor that  10...Ne7  allows  11.Bg5  is extremely annoying for Black, so he can't develop the knight on  g8  yet. }
11. Be3 h5 12. Qf4 Be7
{ Since Black is very exposed on the dark squares, he should keep the bishop. }
13. Rfc1 { We will take control of the open c-file. } 13... Nh6 14. Ne2
{ The trade of the dark-squared bishops will benefit us greatly. Black doesn't have a good way to prevent it. }
14... Nf5 15. Bc5 O-O { Black has finally castled, but it helps little. } 16.
Ng3 Nxg3 17. hxg3 Bxc5 18. Rxc5
{ We have achieved a dream position against the French Defense. Karpov would be proud. }
