[Black "3...Be7 (4...b6 )"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Be7 4. e5
{ This is the only way to punish Black's set-up as the knight is locked in place on g8. }
4... b6 5. Nf3
{ After I went back and re-checked this line, I came to the conclusion that it was best to switch gears from my course on chess24. On chess24 I gave a fun line, but at the end of the day the advantage was close to non-existent.   It went:  5.h4  c5  6.Qg4  ,  and my point here was that h4 forces Black to place the king on f8 due to h5.  It turns out that  6...Kf8!  is pretty okay for Black! The game continues:  7.h5!?  Nc6  8.Nf3  Nh6  9.Qf4  f6  10.exf6  Bxf6  11.g4!?  The game has become rather chaotic, and my analysis concluded that Black's position survives the complications. Thus, I was inclined to come up with something new and that I did! }
5... c5 { Some players have decided to play this natural move right away. } 6.
Ne2
{ If you have been paying close attention, this move should not be a huge surprise to you. When we move the knight, it's possible to support our center with c3. Additionally, we can place it on the beautiful f4-square where it could even move to h5 in the near future. }
6... Nc6 7. c3 Ba6
{ Black's idea in this variation is to place the bishop on this diagonal, so this makes a lot of sense. }
8. h4
{ A recurring move in our arsenal in these types of position. We grab space and control the g5-square. Our pawn could also move to h5, making Black's f6-advance a lot less desirable. It does also prevent Black from playing g5, but this is usually when our knight stands on f4. }
8... Qd7
{ Our e5-pawn makes it hard for Black to finish his development. Qd7 makes some sense as it takes further control of the light-squares, while it prepares the idea of playing Bd8-Nge7-O-O. }
9. g3
{ This might look strange to you, but our idea is to play Nf4 and Kg2 as Black will surely respond with Bxf1 after Nf4. }
9... Rc8 10. Nf4 Bxf1 11. Kxf1
{ Our king will be very well placed on the g2-square. } 11... Bd8 12. Kg2 Nge7
{ The dark knight rises! Black is now ready to castle kingside. } 13. Nh5
{ Our knight starts creating obnoxious threats against Black's king. } 13...
O-O 14. Bg5
{ Black has to be careful of ideas like Nxg7-Bf6-Qh6, when he will be mated instantly. The only move is to play }
14... Ng6 { When I like our prospects after } 15. Qe2
{ White is doing well due to the cramped nature of Black's position. Black should probably play f6 at some point, but that will create weaknesses in the position. }
