[White "20. French Defense (1...e6)  Minor Sidelines"]
[Black "3...Be7 (4...b6 2)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Be7 4. e5
{ This is the only way to punish Black's set-up as the knight is locked in place on g8. }
4... b6 5. Nf3
{ After I went back and re-checked this line, I came to the conclusion that it was best to switch gears from my course on chess24. On chess24 I gave a fun line, but at the end of the day the advantage was close to non-existent. }
5... Ba6
{ Most players have played this move right away with the black pieces, trading the light-squared bishops. }
6. Bxa6 Nxa6 7. Ne2 { The plan remains the same as in the previous note. } 7...
Qd7 8. O-O c5 9. Nf4
{ I was less convinced of  9.Be3  which happened in Gross, M - Brown, K ICCF email 2017, and indeed, Black had equalized comfortably after:  9...Rc8  10.c3  Bd8  11.Qd3  cxd4  12.Nfxd4  Nc5  13.Qc2  Ne7  . }
9... h5 { A logical move to play, preventing Nh5. } 10. Qe2 Nc7
{ 10...c4  gives us easy play as long as remember to give an additional square for the knight with  11.g3  . Our next moves could be for example h4-Kg2-a3-Bd2. Black's position looks impossible to manage... }
11. dxc5
{ I like this straightforward way of playing. Remember, opening the position is usually a clever way to proceed when the opposite side is undeveloped. }
11... bxc5
{ 11...Bxc5  won't help Black in any way, as we can respond with the simple move  12.c3  which prevents Black from playing Ne7 due to b4.   12...a5  is met by  13.Bd2  , with the same idea. }
12. c4
{ Our position looks extremely strong with pressure against d5 coming Black's way. What is Black supposed to do? }
12... g5 { The trickiest move in the position. } 13. cxd5
{ The right path forward. It doesn't matter if Black takes our knight, because of d6 which forks Black's minor pieces. }
13... exd5 14. e6
{ An excellent move, further opening the position.  14.Nd3?  would give Black a great position after  14...Ne6!  when Black has everything under control. }
14... Nxe6
{ Necessary.  14...fxe6?  allows  15.Ng6  when Black is just busted. } 15. Nxe6
Qxe6 { 15...fxe6  blunders the pawn on  g5  . } 16. Qd3
{ The opening of the e-file has given us a very powerful attack. We will play Re1 next, especially if Black plays g4. A way to increase our pressure is to play b3-Bb2 or Bd2/Bc3. Of course, it depends entirely on what Black does. }
