[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "20. French Defense (1...e6)  Minor Sidelines"]
[Black "3...Nc6 (4...Bb4)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3
{ We spent the last section covering some of the most unusual stuff Black has at his disposal. There are two additional moves that fit in the category of 'unusual species,' namely 3... Nc6 & 3... Be7. There's more to these moves than what meets the eye, so they have earned their own unique chapters. }
3... Nc6
{ This eccentric move is found over 4.000 times in my database, making it the most popular sideline. It does seem curious to place the knight in front of the c-pawn, making c5 rather difficult to achieve. However, this is not the only way to fight the center as Black can attack it with f6 in the case we decide to push our e-pawn one step forward. Black's other plan is similar to what we saw when Black played 3... h6, placing a knight on f6 which will move to e4 if we push the e-pawn to e5. The play may looks similar to what we saw in 1... Nc6, but there are some differences. In particular, the knight on c3 gives us an inferior version as we can't reinforce our center with the help of c3. Black's drawback is that the bishop stands on the c8-square instead of the active post on f5. }
4. Nf3
{ There are essentially two decent tries here for White - 4. e5 & 4. Nf3. I prefer the text move as the positions are easier to understand and easier to handle. It's all a matter of taste of course, but I do prefer limiting time on lines that pop up on very rare occasions. }
4... Bb4
{ Black can try to play Bb4 here which looks like an interesting hybrid of the Winawer. }
5. e5
{ Now that e4 was under attack, we push the pawn and prevent Black from developing the knight to f6. Therefore, it heads to e7. }
5... Nge7 6. Bd3
{ The position we have right here is pretty much a poor Winawer as Black lacks the counterplay on the queenside. }
6... Nf5
{ Other moves are possible like always in the game of chess, but this has consistently been Black's move in the position. }
7. a3 { Kicking away the bishop. } 7... Be7
{ 7...Bxc3  gives us a comfortable game after  8.bxc3  with a4-Ba3 coming next. White won quickly in Eckhardt, A - Tortoza, C Remote email 2013. }
8. Ne2 h5
{ Black's usual response when placing a knight on f5 is to make sure we can't remove it with a pawn storm by the likes of g4-h4 etc. Black may also even consider a pawn storm with g5. }
9. b4 { Grabbing some queenside space. } 9... g5
{ Black's only way to put a spanner in the works is to create something on the kingside. }
10. h3 { It's important to stop Black from playing g4. } 10... b6
{ Black's only sensible plan is to go for Bb7-Qd7-O-O-O. } 11. c3
{ Defending the d4-pawn. } 11... Bb7 12. Bd2 Rg8
{ Black has to defend the g-pawn in order to finish his development. } 13. g4
{ The easiest approach. } 13... hxg4 14. hxg4 Nh4 15. Nxh4 gxh4 16. Nf4
{ White is pretty much completely winning with the simple plan of playing Qe2-Nh5-f4-g5- in the near future. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "20. French Defense (1...e6)  Minor Sidelines"]
[Black "3...Nc6 (4...Nf6 6...Na5)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3
{ We have spent this chapter covering some of the most unusual stuff Black has at his disposal. There are two moves that fit in this category of 'unusual species,' namely 3... Nc6 & 3... Be7. There's more to these moves than what meets the eye, be prepared! }
3... Nc6 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. e5 Ne4 6. Ne2
{ Our strategy should be to play around the knight on e4. } 6... Na5
{ Black switches plans and opts for the c5-break. } 7. Ng3
{ In order to create an attack against Black's king, we should get rid of the e4-knight. }
7... c5 8. Bd3 Nxg3 9. fxg3
{ It's always strange to take with the f-pawn instead of the h-pawn, but in this case the open file is a highly useful asset to our attack. }
9... cxd4 10. O-O
{ Black already needs to stay alert on the dangers looming in the f-file. }
10... Be7
{ Black has to control the g5-square without making serious concessions.  10...h6?  weakens the g6-square significantly, so White is completely winning after  11.Nxd4  due to Black's weaknesses on the kingside. Now,  Qh5  followed by  Rxf7  and  Bg6  is a typical theme.   10...Nc6?  Black doesn't have time to keep the extra pawn on d4.  11.Ng5!  Straight for the kill.  11...Nxe5  12.Bf4  Black is too weak down the f-file.  12...h6  13.Nxf7!  A beautiful move.  13...Nxf7  14.Bg6+-  We will regain the piece with interest as Black's king has no shelter. }
11. Nh4
{ A fantastic move which improves on  11.Nxd4  which I suggested on chess24.The point is that we want to play  Qg4  or  Qh5  , creating decisive threats against Black's king. The knight on  h4  contributes more than the knight on  d4  , hence the evaluation difference. }
11... h6
{ Doesn't save the day either.   11...Bxh4  Black may take the knight, but it weakens the dark squares significantly.  12.gxh4  Qxh4  13.Qf3  We are down two pawns, but our attack gives us a completely winning position.  13...Qe7  14.Qg4  Black can't defend. For example:  14...f5  15.exf6  gxf6  16.Bg5  The cruelest way to secure the full point.  16...fxg5  17.Qh5+  Kd8  18.Rf7+-  Black loses the queen and the game.   11...Nc6  Is met by  12.Qh5  g6  When we break through with  13.Bxg6  fxg6  14.Nxg6  hxg6  15.Qxh8+  Kd7  16.Qg7+-  Black's inactive pieces make his position a lost cause. }
12. Qg4 g5
{ 12...Bg5  Black can also try this move which fails to another beautiful sequence.  13.Qh5  O-O  14.Ng6!  A beautiful move which destroys Black's defence.  14...fxg6  15.Rxf8+  Qxf8  16.Qxg6+-  Bxg5,Qh7 and Rf1 comes in some order, when Black has to give the queen on f8 to avoid getting mated. }
13. Rxf7 { A fantastic move which wins the game. } 13... h5
{ 13...gxh4  is met by  14.Qg7  when White wins. Black is also doomed after  13...Kxf7  14.Qh5+  . After the text move there are many ways to win. }
14. Rxe7+ Qxe7 15. Bxg5 hxg4 16. Bxe7
{ We are down an exchange, but we are a pawn up. Black is likely to lose the exchange, or get completely dominated by our minor pieces. }
16... Bd7 17. Rf1 { 17...Kxe7  is met by the fork on  g6  of course. } 17...
Nc6 18. Ng6 Rg8 19. Bd6 O-O-O
{ Black's king gets out of the way, but our pieces dominate. } 20. Rf7
{ Our pieces are all collaborating in a fantastic way. Black can't do anything about h4-h5-h6-h7-h8 without losing material. }
