1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3
{ We have spent this chapter covering some of the most unusual stuff Black has at his disposal. There are two moves that fit in this category of 'unusual species,' namely 3... Nc6 & 3... Be7. There's more to these moves than what meets the eye, be prepared! }
3... Nc6 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. e5 Ne4 6. Ne2
{ Our strategy should be to play around the knight on e4. } 6... Bd7
{ Looks strange, but I will cover it as it has been played by many strong players. The move is kinda prophylactic, as Black will eventually maneuver the bishop via e8 to g6 where it stands much better than on c8. }
7. Ng3 { As usual, we will kick the knight on e4 away. } 7... f5 8. exf6 Nxf6
{ The difference here is that the bishop can go directly to d6. } 9. Be2
{ The play is not very different from what we've already seen. We will arrange our pieces around Black's e5-break, as our advantage lies on the backward pawn on e6. }
9... Bd6 10. c4
{ We once again see this move which makes it significantly harder for Black to play e5. }
10... O-O 11. O-O Be8 12. Re1
{ The rook belongs in the e-file, as we've already seen. } 12... Bg6 13. c5
{ A nasty move for Black to face as he loses control of the dark squares. }
13... Be7 14. Bb5
{ The idea of taking on c6 followed by Ne5 gives White a fantastic position, so much so that Black may already be objectively lost - at least strategically. }
