1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3
{ We have spent this chapter covering some of the most unusual stuff Black has at his disposal. There are two moves that fit in this category of 'unusual species,' namely 3... Nc6 & 3... Be7. There's more to these moves than what meets the eye, be prepared! }
3... Nc6 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. e5 Ne4 6. Ne2
{ Our strategy should be to play around the knight on e4. } 6... f6
{ Black's best move is to fight our center immediately. } 7. Nf4
{ This time we are taking the game in a different direction! Our move is not very well-known, but it was played by a strong polish GM in 2018. The knight is very flexible on f4 as it targets the e6-pawn, while it can reach the d3, h5 and h3-squares. An important thing to remember, as we will see in the upcoming lines.   7.Ng3  fxe5  is played a lot here, but I remain unconvinced. White's most dangerous option is  8.Bb5  , when Black is required to memorize some theory. I analysed  8...exd4  9.Nxe4  dxe4  10.Nxd4  Qd5  11.Nxc6  a6  , but it seems to me that White is not even remotely close to getting an edge as the following endgame after  12.Ba4  Bd7  13.c4  Qxd1+  14.Kxd1  Bxc6  15.Bxc6  bxc6=  looks completely equal.  8.dxe5  is perhaps a better try due to the forced play that occurs after  8.Bb5  , but we can't hope for more than a slight edge.  7.exf6  has also been played, but the difference here is that Black can take with the queen. Hell, it's even possible to take with the g-pawn! Anyway, with some accurate moves Black is totally fine:  7...Qxf6  8.Ng3  e5!  9.Bb5  exd4  10.Nxe4  dxe4  11.Nxd4  Bb4+!  12.c3  O-O!  13.Be3  Bc5  14.Bxc6  bxc6=  . The position on the board is easier to handle for White, hence the two victories, but the objective evaluation is equality. }
7... Qe7
{ The swedish GM Tikkanen played this move with the idea of Bd7 and queenside castling. }
8. Nd3 { I like this move which controls the e5-square. } 8... Bd7 9. Be2
{ We can safely castle kingside, as Black's attack is not dangerous at all. }
9... O-O-O 10. c3 g5
{ Black goes for an attack, but as stated above it really is nothing to worry about. One problem for Black is that we can soon take on f6 followed by a knight jump to e5 when we'll have everything under control. }
11. O-O h5
{ And before Black's pawns start rolling for real, we will go for   11...f5?  Black can't stop our plan of taking on f6.  12.Nfe1!  We are threatening to trap the knight with f3.  12...g4  13.f3!  Black will lose a lot of his initiative when the knight is gone from e4.  13...gxf3  14.gxf3  Rg8+  15.Kh1  Ng5  All it takes now is to neutralize Black's play on the kingside. After that, it's our turn to launch our pawns forward.  16.Rg1  Bh6  17.Ng2  The knight is headed to f4 where it can jump to h5 and eventually f6.  17...Nf7  18.Bxh6  Nxh6  19.Ndf4  We have everything under control. Black can't do anything on the g-file as our knights block everything. The knight on f4 can also move to h5, when we will be able to bring the g2-knight to f4. Additionally, we will push the queenside pawns. The e2-bishop doesn't do that much, so we can trade it for the knight on c6. Black's pretty much busted. }
12. exf6 Qxf6 13. Nfe5 Nxe5 14. Nxe5
{ We have everything under control with a subsequent f3, removing the annoying knight on e4. }
