1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3
{ We have spent this chapter covering some of the most unusual stuff Black has at his disposal. There are two moves that fit in this category of 'unusual species,' namely 3... Nc6 & 3... Be7. There's more to these moves than what meets the eye, be prepared! }
3... Nc6 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. e5 Ne4 6. Ne2
{ Our strategy should be to play around the knight on e4. } 6... f6
{ Black's best move is to fight our center immediately. } 7. Nf4 fxe5
{ This is arguably the first move that pops in one's head when seeing this position. Out of my curiosity I checked the lichess database here, and it was overwhelmingly Black's most popular move. Considering the vast difference between online chess and classical chess I will take this with a grain of salt, but it's still an interesting observation. }
8. Nxe5
{ It's important that we capture with the knight so we can remove Black's monster on e4 with a pawn push to f3. }
8... Nxe5 9. dxe5 g6
{ Black prevents the Qh5-check.   9...Qh4  Happened in an old email game, when the game continues:  10.g3  Qg5  11.Nd3   I prefer this over the mess that happens after  11.f3  Bb4+  12.c3  Nxc3  13.Qc2!  Qxe5+  14.Kf2  . White wins the piece, but Black will get practical compensation.  11...Qf5  12.Be2  Nc5?!  This move only harms Black.  13.O-O  I wonder what the strong correspondence player @@StartBracket@@who was rated above 2500@@EndBracket@@ was thinking here, as Nc5 seems extremely pointless. Taking the pawn on e5 would be suicidal.  13...Bd7  14.Bh5+  Provoking Black into playing g6.  14...g6  15.Bg4  Qf7  16.Be3  Black is now forced to trade knights, when we will be able to utilize the open c-file.  16...Nxd3  17.cxd3±  White had an excellent position and realized his advantage after 62 moves. De Souza,O - Gonzalez,J ICCF email 2005. }
10. Qg4
{ The queen joins the action. Black has to do something about h4-h5-f3, which will come very quickly. }
10... Qe7
{ Black is threatening Qb4+ while opting for the standard plan of castling queenside with Bd7.   10...c6  Black wants to stir up some trouble against our pawn on f2 with Qb6 & Bc5.  11.c3  Qb6  We finally get to demonstrate the usefulness of having the knight on f4.  12.Nh3!  We are defending the f2-pawn while not intefering with a potential Bd3.  12...Bc5  13.Qe2  It's possible to sacrifice the f2-pawn with 13. Bd3!?, but I prefer the text move. We are now getting ready to play f3 which will finally remove the knight that has been bothering us for a while. Note also that the queen defends the b2-pawn which allows us to develope our c1-bishop.  13...Be7  Black needs to give the c5-square to the knight.  14.f3  Nc5  15.Be3⩲  Black's position is solid enough, but it is slightly cramped. The bishop on c8 is bad, although it will provide protection to the pawns. Our position can be improved in numerous ways. One way is to place our queen on c2 so we can develope our f1-bishop and castle kingside. A h4-h5 break is looming in the air, and even a potential knight maneuver from h3-f2-g4-f6. }
11. Nd3
{ A strong move! The knight covers the b4-square while it gives our bishop a great square on g5. }
11... Bd7 12. f3 { It's time to remove the knight. } 12... Nc5 13. Bg5
{ Spoiling Black's plans of castling queenside. } 13... Nxd3+ 14. Bxd3 Qf7 15.
O-O Bc5+ 16. Kh1
{ A common trend in these positions is that Black has no particularly weaknesses, but he has a cramped position which yields us a clearly better position. }
