1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3
{ We have spent this chapter covering some of the most unusual stuff Black has at his disposal. There are two moves that fit in this category of 'unusual species,' namely 3... Nc6 & 3... Be7. There's more to these moves than what meets the eye, be prepared! }
3... Nc6 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. e5 Ne4 6. Ne2
{ Our strategy should be to play around the knight on e4. } 6... f6
{ Black's best move is to fight our center immediately. } 7. Nf4 Be7
{ The French GM Christian Bauer played this move with Black, a well-known expert of unusual openings. }
8. exf6
{ It's time to take the pawn now that Black can't recapture with the queen. }
8... Bxf6 9. c3 O-O 10. Be2
{ The bishop needs to be placed here since it's important that our Queen aims towards d5 after dxe5. }
10... Be7 { Black decides to maneuver the bishop to the d6-square. } 11. O-O
{ 11.Bb5  was played in the strong GM encounter Tomczak, J - Bauer, C Batumi 2018, but this move makes no sense to me. If you wanted to play  Bb5  , why didn't you do it right away? White eventually won, but the advantage had decreased substantially after  11.Bb5  . }
11... Bd6 12. Nh5
{ Yet another advantage with having the knight on f4! We can return to the old plan of removing the e4-knight. This will allow us to play against the e6-pawn in the e-file. }
12... Qe7 13. Ng3 { We stick to the plan. } 13... Nf6
{ 13...Nxg3  14.hxg3  is excellent for us. A quick  c4  will make Black's position rather miserable. }
14. Re1 e5
{ Black is finally able to play e5 and is pretty much forced to do so, although the resulting position isn't anything to brag about. }
15. dxe5 Nxe5 16. Bf4 { We have obtained excellent pressure on the e-file. }
16... Nf7 { Black needs to get out of the pin. } 17. Bd3 Qd8 18. Bxd6 Qxd6 19.
h3
{ We don't want to allow Black to play Bg4. In this position our pieces are better placed than Black's, so we have obtained a clearly better game. We will create pressure against Black's d-pawn next with the help of Qc2-c4-Rad1.   CONCLUSION: 3... Nc6 is a strange-looking sideline which seems to be going against the principles of The French Defence as the knight blocks the c-pawn. Black's point with this eccentric idea is to battle e5 with f6 and place a knight on e4 in case we refrain from playing e5 immediately. My suggestion is to play 4. Nf3, as I am not so convinced by the main move 4. e5 After 4... Nf6 5. e5 Ne4, my suggestion is to play around the e4-knight with the move 6. Ne2! as we are planning to head to g3 and play Bd3. 6... Na5 sticks to classic principles in the French as Black heads for a quick c5. The downside to this idea is that we are able to create a powerful attack in the meantime which my improvement 11. Nh4 clearly shows. This section was incredibly fun to analyze due to the mindblowing tactics I found. 6... Be7 & 6. .. Bd7 lead to fairly similar positions. We will play Ng3 and remove the knight from its post on e4. Black has to answer with f6/f5, when we will capture and leave Black with a backward pawn on e6. Black will then try to get rid of the weakness by preparing e5, which we should do our best to prevent. c4 is one key move here that will often force Black to take due to the threat of c5 which would give us amazing dark-square control and a strategically winning position. Black should fight the center immediately with 6... f6, which has been the most common move. It turns out that Black's position is pretty acceptable after the main moves 7. Ng3 or 7. exf6, but 7. Nf4! gives us excellent chances to obtain an edge. The knight is very flexible on the f4-square which is seen in the lines we covered. After 7... fxe5 it's important to remember to recapture with the knight, otherwise Black will keep the monster on e4. 7... Be7 will lead to similar positions like we saw in the line with 6... Be7, when Black will do his best to achieve e5. A key idea here is to play Nh5-Ng3 to remove the e4-knight which will grant us control of the e-file. 3... Nc6 is definitely one of the better sidelines out there, as it is pretty solid. The downside for Black is the e6-pawn which makes the position rather cramped. Therefore, it's essential that we don't allow Black to play e5 at favorable circumstances and place our pieces accordingly. If we play our cards right, we will have a comfortable spacious position after the opening. }
