1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3
{ We have completed our work against Black's sidelines, so it's time to take a look at Black's main tries in the position. }
3... dxe4
{ Black captures our pawn and changes the position completely. Now the position is open, so we won't get the standard French pawn structures we have seen in earlier lines. This move can be compared to the 3... Qd8-line in the Scandinavian. Black is solid as there are no weaknesses in the pawn structure, but he does lack some space. Black intends to play c7-c5 at a later stage, which will neutralize our center. The line has been played by countless GMs, perhaps in particular by the strong German GM Georg Meier. I jokingly regard this line as a 'draw offer,' as it is used primarily as a drawing weapon. }
4. Nxe4 Bd7
{ Black has a wide range of alternatives which will be examined in the next chapter.  4...Nd7  is the main tabiya, labeled the Rubinstein Variation, and also examined at a later stage. The text move is a corny-looking move. Black wants to activate the poor French bishop by placing it on the c6-square. 'Fort Knox' is what this line is called, named after the U.S army installation in Kentucky. I suspect that the reason for this given name is the solid reputation of the line. }
5. Nf3 Bc6
{ Black's point. Other moves make no sense which the online database clearly demonstrates as the second most popular move has only been seen a bit over 20 times. The text move has been seen over 9600 times in comparison! }
6. Neg5
{ Before we head to the line I'm suggesting, I want to showcase this variation right here which is quite tricky. }
6... Nd7 7. Nxf7
{ We sacrifice a piece for the initiative. Although I tried hard to make it work, the objective evaluation is 0.00 as Black is able to neutralize our attack. }
7... Kxf7 8. Ng5+ Ke8
{ Black has to head to  e8  , as our attack is too strong after  8...Ke7  9.Qe2  . }
9. Bc4
{ The best attempt. I analyzed the other bishop moves as well, but Black is doing well:  9.Bd3  is met by  9...Qf6  . After  10.Qe2  Nb6  11.O-O  Kd7  the game is unclear, but we have no advantage.  9.Be2  can also be played. I found a couple of ways for Black to continue:  9...Qf6  10.O-O  Rd8  looks fine. Same can be said about  9...Ndf6  10.O-O  Qd5  11.Bf3  Qf5  12.Bxc6+  bxc6  13.Re1  Bd6  . }
9... Bxg2 { Black should grab the pawn. } 10. Rg1 Bd5
{ A strong defensive resource. } 11. Nxe6 Bxe6 12. Bxe6
{ We have excellent compensation for the missing piece, but it's not enough to get an advantage. The play could continue: }
12... Qe7 13. Qe2 Ngf6 14. Bf4 Kd8 15. O-O-O
{ The position is unclear. We are down a piece for a pawn, but Black's king is very exposed in the center. }
15... a5
{ A very strong defensive resource. This move allows the a8-rook to participate in the game which will help a lot. I also discovered that  15...Qe8  is possible, when we reach an exciting position after  16.d5  Bd6  17.Bxd6  cxd6  18.Rxg7  Rg8! }
16. Rg3 Ra6 17. Re3 Rb6 18. c4
{ 18.Re1  Qe8  19.Bc4  Qg6  20.Bd3  Qf7  21.Bc4  is a draw. } 18... Rxe6
{ Black has to take. } 19. Rxe6 Qf7 20. a3 Bd6 21. Bxd6 cxd6 22. c5 Re8 23.
Rxe8+ Nxe8
{ The dust has settled and the position we have on the board is equal. Fun stuff to examine, but unfortunately it's not enough to take down the Fort Knox! }
