1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3
{ We have completed our work against Black's sidelines, so it's time to take a look at Black's main tries in the position. }
3... dxe4
{ Black captures our pawn and changes the position completely. Now the position is open, so we won't get the standard French pawn structures we have seen in earlier lines. This move can be compared to the 3... Qd8-line in the Scandinavian. Black is solid as there are no weaknesses in the pawn structure, but he does lack some space. Black intends to play c7-c5 at a later stage, which will neutralize our center. The line has been played by countless GMs, perhaps in particular by the strong German GM Georg Meier. I jokingly regard this line as a 'draw offer,' as it is used primarily as a drawing weapon. }
4. Nxe4 Bd7
{ Black has a wide range of alternatives which will be examined in the next chapter.  4...Nd7  is the main tabiya, labeled the Rubinstein Variation, and also examined at a later stage. The text move is a corny-looking move. Black wants to activate the poor French bishop by placing it on the c6-square. 'Fort Knox' is what this line is called, named after the U.S army installation in Kentucky. I suspect that the reason for this given name is the solid reputation of the line. }
5. Nf3 Bc6
{ Black's point. Other moves make no sense which the online base clearly demonstrates as the second most popular move has only been seen a bit over 20 times. The text move has been seen over 9600 times in comparison! }
6. Bd3
{ As the complications after  6...Neg5  lead nowhere, we should stick with this logical developing move. Black has tried different moves here, but the clear main move is  6...Nd7  . }
6... Nd7
{ Black usually plays this move since  6...Nf6  right away is rather poor as we saw. }
7. c3 Ngf6 8. Nxf6+ Nxf6
{ Black's position has no weaknesses, but our extra space gives us a clearly better game. }
9. O-O
{ We decide to rely on our positional advantage by abandoning a plan of queenside castling.  9.Qe2  allows the typical idea  9...Bxf3  10.Qxf3  Qd5  when it will be really difficult for us to attack.  9.Bf4  is also possible. The engine comes up with  9...Nd7  here which avoids  Ne5  in some lines. After  10.O-O  Bd6  White was slightly better in Gharamian, T - Miton, K Germany 2018, but I think we get better chances after the text move.  9.a4!?  is also interesting, seen in the game Ivec, I - Bredenhof, B ICCF email 2017. A sophisticated approach, but I don't think there's any need to avoid  O-O  . }
9... Bxf3
{ The standard way to play this line. Black gives away the bishop pair, but hopes that the solid pawn structure will hold the fort. }
10. Qxf3 c6 11. Re1 { The usual square for our rook. } 11... Be7
{ Black has continued in this manner in most games in the base.   11...Qd5  Can be played once again.  12.Qe2  Again, we do not trade queens.  12...Bd6  13.g3  I'm once again fond of this move that prepares h2-h4.  13...O-O  14.h4  We have now obtained a square on g5 for our bishop.  14...Rad8  Black should be careful with 14... h6, as we can play 15. g4! followed by g5 with a powerful attack.  15.Bg5  Be7  16.Rad1±  The same story - the bishop pair and extra space give us a clearly better game, although Black is solid as there are no weaknesses. }
12. Qg3 { A cunning move, targeting the pawn on g7. } 12... O-O
{ The most logical approach. } 13. Bh6 Ne8 14. Bc2
{ We can be very happy with what we've achieved out of the opening. The bishop pair and a nice space advantage. }
14... Qc7 15. Bf4
{ I'm a bit surprised that White didn't play this natural move in Smola,M - Bobula,M Sroda Wielkopolska 2008. }
15... Bd6 16. Qh4 { Forcing Black to make a concession on the kingside. } 16...
g6 17. Bg5 Ng7 18. Rad1
{ We maintain a decent amount of pressure. The next moves are all about improving our position, for example a3-g3-h4,Qg4 etc.   CONCLUSION: The Fort Knox has a solid reputation, as many GMs have used it as a drawing weapon. Black's idea is to activate the bishop on c8, which is usually quite poor. We decide to keep it simple with 6. Bd3, when Black should prepare Nf6 with the move 6... Nd7. Playing Nf6 immediately is poor, as we can simply capture when Black's queen will be trapped if he goes Qx. A nice trick to remember. The play will probably go 7. c3 Ngf6 8. Nxf6+ Nxf6 9. O-O, when Black should play 9... Bxf3. Avoiding the capture is going to make matters even worse, as we can often jump to e5 with the knight when Black's bishop on c6 will look silly. After Black grabs the knight, we obtain the bishop pair. Black is hoping that the solid pawn structure is going to make up for the passive position, but I must admit that I remain quite skeptical as the positions are very pleasant for us and easy to handle. Fort Knox has a solid reputation, but in my opinion the concept seems abhorrent. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
