[Round "?"]
[White "21. French Defense (1...e6) Rubinstein Sidelines"]
[Black "4...Be7 (7...b6)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3
{ We have completed our work against Black's sidelines, so it's time to take a look at Black's main tries in the position. }
3... dxe4
{ Black captures our pawn and changes the position completely. Now the position is open, so we won't get the standard French pawn structures we have seen in earlier lines. }
4. Nxe4 Be7
{ This is a very sneaky move - Black prevents our usual set-up as we can no longer place the bishop on g5! }
5. Nf3 Nf6 6. Nxf6+ Bxf6 7. c3 b6 { This approach looks too slow. } 8. Bd3 Bb7
9. Qe2
{ Once again, it's a lot easier for us to play for an attack when Black has little to no counterplay. }
9... Nd7 10. Bf4 O-O 11. O-O-O { En garde! } 11... Re8
{ The two strongest players tried this move that provides the knight on d7 a square on f8 where it protects the king. }
12. h4 { It's time to march forward with our soldiers. } 12... Nf8 13. Kb1
{ This move is always very thematic. Here it protects the pawn on a2 which is a potential target for Black. The king is also safer on b1, as it's likely that the c-file will be opened. }
13... Qe7 14. Ne5
{ An improvement over  14.g4  which happened in Leal, P - Ignatov, B ICCF email 2006 and Kreiman, B - Blatny, P New York 1998. The issue with this move is that Black gets sufficient counterplay with  14...Ng6  followed by  e5  . With the knight on  e5  this is no longer possible, so Black's pieces will remain passive. }
14... Rad8 15. h5
{ I doubt that a human player will survive with the black pieces. } 15... Bxe5
16. dxe5
{ The right capture. After  16.Bxe5  , Black can answer with  16...f6  which is a useful defensive resource. It's still much better for White, but why allow it? }
16... h6 17. Rh3
{ Our rook moves out of the target zone of the sniper on b7. We can now launch our g-pawn forward or place the rook on g3. With the rook on g3, ideas like Qe3-Bxh6 are in the air, along with Qg4. It's worth nothing that Black could have some Rxd3 tactics followed by Be4 in some lines, so do consider moving the majesty to a1 at some point. }
*

[Event "?"]
