[White "21. French Defense (1...e6) Rubinstein Sidelines"]
[Black "4...Be7 (7...Nd7)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3
{ We have completed our work against Black's sidelines, so it's time to take a look at Black's main tries in the position. }
3... dxe4
{ Black captures our pawn and changes the position completely. Now the position is open, so we won't get the standard French pawn structures we have seen in earlier lines. }
4. Nxe4 Be7
{ This is a very sneaky move - Black prevents our usual set-up as we can no longer place the bishop on g5! }
5. Nf3 Nf6 6. Nxf6+ Bxf6 7. c3 Nd7
{ The right approach. With c7-c5 coming very quickly, Black will be able to create sufficient counterplay. }
8. Bd3 O-O 9. h4
{ With h2-h4 on the board, Black has to be very careful of Bxh7-ideas. Black has to spend time on defending against our attack, making it difficult to obtain the desired counterplay. As we've seen, without counterplay Black is in big trouble. }
9... e5
{ Leads to the same story, as pointed out by the user 'KitGallagher' on chess24.   9...h6  Is a logical way to defend, as there is no longer a sacrifice on h7.  10.Qe2  h6 has opened the gates to Black's king, as Qe4 can no longer be defended by g7-g6 due to h5.  10...Re8   The only move.  10...Be7?  makes  Nf6  possible, but it's too passive. A simple response is  11.Be3  followed by  O-O-O  with a decisive attack.   10...e5?  requires more precision to take down.  11.Qe4  g6  and now  12.Bc4  is the killer move. The g6-pawn is not so easy to defend.  12...Kg7  defends it, but then we can simply play  13.dxe5  . Black can't take back, as we will take with check.  11.O-O  Nf8  Black won't get mated, but will play with a passive position.  12.Bf4±  We have obtained a dream position after the opening.   9...c5?  Black doesn't have time for counterplay.  10.Bxh7+!  White missed this blast in both of the games I found in the database.  10...Kxh7  11.Ng5+  Kg8  12.Qh5  Re8  The only way to avoid mate.  13.Qxf7+  Kh8  14.Qh5+  Kg8  15.Qh7+  Kf8  Black's king has escaped, but it doesn't mean that the position is playable.  16.O-O  Our attack remains too powerful. Black's extra piece helps little, as he has terrible coordination.  16...cxd4  Black prevents Bf4, but our bishop can enter the game from another angle!  17.b3!  With the deadly threat of Ba3!  17...Bxg5  Seems like the only move.  18.hxg5  Qa5  19.Re1+-  Black has prolonged the game with accurate defense. However, our attacking forces are impossible to stop.  19...Qf5  allows  20.Ba3+  Kf7  21.Qxf5+  exf5  22.g6+  , when the rook on  e8  falls. }
10. Bxh7+ Kxh7 11. Ng5+ Kg8 12. Qh5 Re8 13. Qxf7+ Kh8 14. Qh5+ Kg8 15. Qh7+ Kf8
16. O-O { We must get our king to safety before we can continue attacking. }
16... Bxg5
{ We will be able to open the position after  16...e4  as well, after  17.Be3  when f2-f3 comes. After the text move, the brilliancy }
17. f4
{ Wins the game, as the opening of the f-file is fatal for Black. Note that  17...Bxf4  is met by  18.dxe5!  , which is somehow the only winning move. }
