1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3
{ We have completed our work against Black's sidelines, so it's time to take a look at Black's main tries in the position. }
3... dxe4
{ Black captures our pawn and changes the position completely. Now the position is open, so we won't get the standard French pawn structures we have seen in earlier lines. }
4. Nxe4 Be7
{ This is a very sneaky move - Black prevents our usual set-up as we can no longer place the bishop on g5! }
5. Nf3 Nf6 6. Nxf6+ Bxf6 7. c3 Nd7
{ The right approach. With c7-c5 coming very quickly, Black will be able to create sufficient counterplay. }
8. Bd3 O-O 9. h4
{ With h2-h4 on the board, Black has to be very careful of Bxh7-ideas. Black has to spend time on defending against our attack, making it difficult to obtain the desired counterplay. As we've seen, without counterplay Black is in big trouble. }
9... Re8 { Black can also move the rook out of the way immediately. } 10. Ng5
{ We must strike immediately, otherwise e6-e5 hits us in the face. } 10... g6
11. Ne4
{ We need to move the knight out of the way before we can proceed with h4-h5. }
11... e5 12. d5 { We must keep the e-file closed. } 12... Be7
{ Black intends to meet h5 with g5.   12...Bxh4  It looks incredibly risky to grab the pawn.  13.Qd2  The queen is heading to h6.  13...Nf8  And now I think the simplest is to regain the pawn with  14.Bb5  c6  15.dxc6  We have regained the pawn, but we are about to collect even more profit as Black can't avoid the loss of an exchange.  15...Be7  16.Qc2±  cxb7 comes, when we will win on e8. Black won't have enough compensation. }
13. h5 g5 14. h6
{ This looks horrendous for Black, but it's the best practical choice according to the machine. }
14... Nc5
{ 14...f5?  allows  15.d6!  which wins for White due to  Bc4+  followed by  Nxd6  if Black takes the pawn. }
15. Nxc5 Bxc5 16. Qe2
{ Simple play. We will move our bishop to e3 and castle queenside. } 16... e4
17. Bc4 Bf5 18. Be3
{ Apparently it's not over yet, but I doubt Black will be able to survive in the long run with such an exposed kingside. }
