1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3
{ We have completed our work against Black's sidelines, so it's time to take a look at Black's main tries in the position. }
3... dxe4
{ Black captures our pawn and changes the position completely. Now the position is open, so we won't get the standard French pawn structures we have seen in earlier lines. }
4. Nxe4 Be7
{ This is a very sneaky move - Black prevents our usual set-up as we can no longer place the bishop on g5! }
5. Nf3 Nf6 6. Nxf6+ Bxf6 7. c3 Nd7
{ The right approach. With c7-c5 coming very quickly, Black will be able to create sufficient counterplay. }
8. Bd3 c5 { There's no time to waste for Black! } 9. O-O cxd4 10. Nxd4
{ 10.cxd4  is also possible of course, but it's just a matter of taste. } 10...
Bxd4 { 10...O-O  transposes to  9...O-O  . } 11. cxd4 Nf6
{ We have an isolani pawn, but in return we have the bishop pair. Not the best scenario for an endgame, but strong for attacking purposes. }
12. a4 { This move has a very cunning idea to it... } 12... O-O 13. Ra3
{ A beautiful move! Moving the bishop on d3 will allow the rook to head to h3 where it will play a crucial role in our attack! }
13... Bd7 14. Bc2 Bc6
{ A very natural move, but a decisive error.   14...Nd5!  Black should block our powerful bishop on b1.  15.Rh3  f5  16.Bb3  Switching targets now that Black has weakened the a2-g8 diagonal significantly.  16...Be8  17.Re1  Qd7  18.Re5±  With a promising position. The plan is to capture on d5 in favorable circumstances. The capture can be prepared with moves like Rg3 and Qe1. }
15. Bg5 h6 { And now the point is that } 16. Bxh6 { Wins for us. } 16... gxh6
17. Qd2
{ Rg3+ followed with Qxh6 is mate. The only antidote is to give back the piece. }
17... Ng4 18. Rg3 Qg5 19. Qxg5+ hxg5 20. Rxg4
{ The dust has settled, but White is winning after } 20... Rad8 21. Rxg5+ Kh8
22. Rd1 { Due to the extra pawns. } *

