[White "21. French Defense (1...e6) Rubinstein Sidelines"]
[Black "4...b6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3
{ We have completed our work against Black's sidelines, so it's time to take a look at Black's main tries in the position. }
3... dxe4
{ Black captures our pawn and changes the position completely. Now the position is open, so we won't get the standard French pawn structures we have seen in earlier lines. }
4. Nxe4 b6
{ Although this was played by the World Champion in 2017, I think the move is too weakening.   4...Nf6  5.Bg5  We have transposed to 3... Nf6 4. Bg5 dxe4. That being said, you can certainly consider 5. Nxf6+ Qxf6 6. Nf3 h6 7. Bd3 which is a very comfortable position for White. }
5. Nf3 Bb7 6. Bb5+
{ We're provoking Black into playing c7-c6 which will block the bishop. } 6...
c6 7. Bd3 Be7
{ Black's most popular try, but it's incredibly passive.   7...Nd7?!  Is a mistake due to  8.Ne5!  Our strong knights create huge problems for Black.  8...Ngf6  9.Ng5  We will now get a favorable trade.  9...Nxe5  10.dxe5  Nd7  Black will be fine if he's able to place the knight on c5, but we're one step ahead...  11.Nxe6!  A nice tactical trick which works due to the nasty check on h5.  11...Bb4+  Is Black's best chance, when the forced line goes:  12.c3  fxe6  13.Qh5+  Kf8  14.cxb4  Nxe5  A nice move which works as the d3-bishop is attacked by the queen, but it doesn't save Black.  15.Qxe5  Qxd3  16.Bh6  It's always great to develope with a tempo.  16...Qg6  17.Be3+-  Black will be under a heavy attack as the king is very exposed. }
8. Bf4 Nf6 9. Nxf6+ Bxf6 10. Qe2
{ Intending to create a powerful attack by castling queenside. It's going to be incredibly difficult for Black to create counterplay with his passive pieces. }
10... Nd7 11. O-O-O Qe7
{ Black should also go for queenside castling, as it's suicidal to castle kingside due to the enormous speed of our attack. }
12. g4 { Grabbing space while threatening to trap Black's bishop with g4-g5. }
12... g6 13. Bh6 { Maintaining the threat. } 13... Qd6 14. Be4 O-O-O 15. Qe3
{ With Rhe1 and Bf4 coming, Black's position looks awful. The h2-b8 diagonal can be exploited to the fullest by creating a battery with Bg3-Qf4. I don't think Black will be able to make it. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "21. French Defense (1...e6) Rubinstein Sidelines"]
[Black "4...Qd5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3
{ We have completed our work against Black's sidelines, so it's time to take a look at Black's main tries in the position. }
3... dxe4
{ Black captures our pawn and changes the position completely. Now the position is open, so we won't get the standard French pawn structures we have seen in earlier lines. }
4. Nxe4 Qd5
{ Black attacks our knight on e4, while the queen aims towards g2 in case we decide to move it. }
5. Bd3
{ The correct reaction is to develope our bishop. The pawn on d4 is untouchable due to the discovered check on b5. A thematic trick for the French Defense. At first glance it might look scary to leave g2 unprotected, but as we shall see Black shouldn't get greedy and grab the pawn. }
5... Nc6
{ Black wants to jump to b4 where the bishop on d3 can be grabbed. However, Black can't really afford to spend such a huge amount of time.   5...f5?  A poor decision. Let's see how we react!  6.Ng3  It's important to place the knight on g3 where it protects the rook on h1.  6...Qxg2?  Taking the pawn loses, however I won't spend time on other moves since f7-f5 is a terrible concession.  7.Nf3  We're threatening to play Bf1, trapping the queen.  7...Qh3  8.Bf1  Qg4  The queen almost escapes to g6, but...  9.Bg5+-  Black can't avoid h2-h3 which will trap the queen. Leotard, C-Martenot,J France 1990. }
6. Nf3 Nb4 7. O-O
{ We don't need to pay attention to what Black is doing, as our development advantage is more significant than Black's bishop pair. }
7... Nxd3 8. Qxd3 Be7
{ Black has also played 8... Nf6, when my suggested response will be to take and play c4. We have a very easy game. }
9. Bf4 { Another developing move with a tempo! } 9... Qd8 10. Ne5
{ It's time to strike! } 10... Nf6 11. Ng5 O-O 12. Ng4
{ A beautiful move. Black has difficulties guarding the mate threat on h7. }
12... g6 { And here, I found the beautiful line } 13. Nh6+ Kg7 14. Be5
{ A fantastic move which wins on the spot. Qh3 comes next, when Black gets mated or loses decisive material.   Note that after  14...Kxh6  ,  15.Bxf6  decides.  14...Bd6  is the engine move, when  15.f4  kills the game as we'll take with the f-pawn if Black takes our bishop. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
