[White "21. French Defense (1...e6) Rubinstein Sidelines"]
[Black "4...Qd5 2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3
{ We have completed our work against Black's sidelines, so it's time to take a look at Black's main tries in the position. }
3... dxe4
{ Black captures our pawn and changes the position completely. Now the position is open, so we won't get the standard French pawn structures we have seen in earlier lines. }
4. Nxe4 Qd5
{ Black attacks our knight on e4, while the queen aims towards g2 in case we decide to move it. }
5. Bd3
{ The correct reaction is to develope our bishop. The pawn on d4 is untouchable due to the discovered check on b5. A thematic trick for the French Defense. At first glance it might look scary to leave g2 unprotected, but as we shall see Black shouldn't get greedy and grab the pawn. }
5... Nf6 { Black's best bet. } 6. Nxf6+ gxf6
{ Black has doubled pawns in the f-file, but he is hoping that the open g-file can provide him with some counter chances. The active queen has also opened the possibilties of castling queenside in the future. }
7. Nf3 Rg8
{ Although Black's rook looks powerful down the g-file, Black is lacking attacking power for it to pack a serious punch.   7...Nc6  8.O-O  There's no need to worry about Black's play on the kingside.  8...Bd7  8... Rg8 transposes to 7... Rg8.  9.c4  One of the disadvantages of having the queen right in the middle of the board! With c2-c4 we get a nice grip on the center with a tempo!  9...Qh5  10.Be2!  We keep harassing the queen.  10...Qg6  11.Be3  O-O-O  12.Qb3+-  Our attack is significantly more harmful as we're going for a quick d5 which will create huge problems for Black. Rg8 can be dodged easily with g2-g3. }
8. O-O Nc6 9. Re1 { Our rook is well placed on the e-file. } 9... Bd6
{ Black brings the bishop into the attack, but it's easy for us to handle the threats. }
10. c4 { We play in similar manner to the previous note. } 10... Qh5 11. Re4
{ A strong move, aiming to place the rook on h4 where it will neutralize Black's attack. }
11... f5
{ 11...Qh3  is nothing to worry about. After  12.Bf1  , Black has nothing. }
12. Rh4 Qg6 13. g3 { Black's attack is gone in the blink of an eye. } 13... Bd7
14. Bg5 { With a dominating position. } *

