1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3
{ We have completed our work against Black's sidelines, so it's time to take a look at Black's main tries in the position. }
3... dxe4
{ Black captures our pawn and changes the position completely. Now the position is open, so we won't get the standard French pawn structures we have seen in earlier lines. }
4. Nxe4 Nd7 5. Nf3 Be7
{ 5...Ngf6  is the most played move by far, but it doesn't fit in this chapter as it is no sideline!  5...Be7  looks incredibly strange, but I felt that I had to consider it as it avoids the system I am recommending against the Rubinstein. }
6. Bd3 { We proceed with natural piece development. } 6... Ngf6 7. Nxf6+ Bxf6
{ 7...Nxf6  is the topic of the next chapter. } 8. c3
{ Hilariously enough, I did not notice that I had transposed to the Main Line of this chapter, 4... Be7 when I saw this position.   I analyzed  8.Qe2  extensively, but as we have transposed this was only a massive waste of time! I could obviously include it as an alternative, but there's absolutely no point to do so.  So, this position is covered under the move order 4... Be7 5. Nf3 Nf6 6. Nxf6+ Bxf6 7. c3 Nd7. }
