[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "22. French Defense (1...e6) Rubinstein & Burn Variation"]
[Black "4...Nbd7 (5...Be7)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3
{ We have completed our work against Black's sidelines, so it's time to take a look at Black's main tries in the position, starting with the move  3...dxe4  . }
3... dxe4
{ Black captures our pawn and changes the position completely. Now the position is open, so we won't get the standard French pawn structures we have seen in earlier lines. This move can be compared to the 3... Qd8-line in the Scandinavian. Black is solid as there are no weaknesses in the pawn structure, but he does lack some space. Black intends to play c7-c5 at a later stage, which will neutralize our center. The line has been played by countless GMs, perhaps in particular by the strong German GM Georg Meier. I jokingly regard this line as a 'draw offer,' as it is used primarily as a drawing weapon. }
4. Nxe4
{ Before we can head to the main tabiya in the Rubinstein Variation, we must take a look at what happens if Black decides to capture on f6 with the knight. }
4... Nd7 5. Nf3 Be7 6. Bd3 Ngf6 7. Nxf6+ Nxf6
{ This move makes more sense to the human eye, but I dare to say that  7...Bxf6  is better! The problem with  7...Nxf6  is that it's essentially a bad version of  1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nd7 5. Nf3 Ngf6 6. Nxf6+ Nxf6 7. Bd3, as Black usually goes for 7... c5 in this position with the intent of a quick cxd4. 7... Be7, on the other hand, is rather passive. }
8. Qe2
{ And how do we fight against passive set-ups? You guessed it, it's by starting an attack! }
8... b6 { Another logical move. Our reaction is the same: } 9. Bf4 Bb7 10.
O-O-O O-O
{ Black has refrained from playing c5, but in return the bishop looks quite active on b7. }
11. h4
{ We're launching the h-pawn forward! This move is useful as we can potentially place our rook on h3 which is a thematic idea. We can certainly push the pawn even further down the board as well. }
11... Qd5
{ Black activates the queen.  11...Qc8  12.Be5  c5  was Sermek, D - Luther, T Ptuj 1995, but this approach looks rather slow in my opinion. I discovered that  13.Rh3  was strong, when we have a powerful attack after  13...cxd4  14.Ng5  with  Rg3  coming. }
12. Kb1 c5
{ This is possible as Black can capture with the queen in case we go for 13. dxc5.   12...Qh5  Halts our attack, but it gives up a pawn.  13.Bxc7  Rac8  14.Be5  Rfd8  This was Semasev, K - Secula,V Grieskirchen 1998, when I suggest the simple  15.c3+-  I see approximately zilch compensation for Black. }
13. c4 { Is our response, with the nice idea } 13... Qh5 14. d5
{ Our pawn on d5 is untouchable due to the hanging bishop on e7. } 14... Rfe8
15. dxe6 fxe6 16. Bc2
{ We have created a huge weakness on e6 which looks tough to defend as we can target the pawn with Rhe1 and Ng5. Black is in huge trouble. }
*

