[White "22. French Defense (1...e6) Rubinstein & Burn Variation"]
[Black "4...Nbd7 (5...Be7 2)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4
{ Black captures our pawn and changes the position completely. Now the position is open, so we won't get the standard French pawn structures we have seen in earlier lines. This move can be compared to the 3... Qd8-line in the Scandinavian. Black is solid as there are no weaknesses in the pawn structure, but he does lack some space. Black intends to play c7-c5 at a later stage, which will neutralize our center. The line has been played by countless GMs, perhaps in particular by the strong German GM Georg Meier. I jokingly regard this line as a 'draw offer,' as it is used primarily as a drawing weapon. }
4. Nxe4
{ Before we can head to the main tabiya in the Rubinstein Variation, we must take a look at what happens if Black decides to capture on f6 with the knight. }
4... Nd7 5. Nf3 Be7 6. Bd3 Ngf6 7. Nxf6+ Nxf6
{ This move makes more sense to the human eye, but I dare to say that  7...Bxf6  is better! }
8. Qe2
{ And how do we fight against passive set-ups? You guessed it, it's by starting an attack! }
8... c5
{ Some strong players have tried this move here, so we must take a look. I must ask though... If c7-c5 was your plan all along, why on earth did you play 7... Be7 first? }
9. dxc5 Bxc5
{ Black has wasted time by playing Be7, meaning that we're one tempo up. } 10.
Bf4
{ The standard move has been  10.Bg5  ,  but I don't see why I should give Black h6 for free. The pin is no problem for Black either, as he can give a check on a5 if he desires. }
10... O-O 11. O-O-O { The race has begun! } 11... Qa5
{ Black moves the queen out of harm's way towards our king. In order to create difficulties for us though, a lot more firearms will be required! }
12. Kb1
{ It's always a good feeling when we have played Kb1. Our path forward is now incredibly simple. The pawn storm with h4-g4 will come, while we could place the knight or bishop on e5. }
12... Bd7 13. Be5
{ Our dark-squared bishop joins the attack as we're planning to play Ng5, and then capture the defender on f6 with deadly consequences for Black. }
13... Be7
{ This is not a nice move to make for Black as he has to part with a pawn, but it's the best try.   13...Nd5?  Moving the knight is fatal for Black after the beautiful  14.Bxh7+  Kxh7  15.Qe4+  Kg8  16.Ng5  There are no defenders.  16...f5  17.Qh4+-  Black can prevent mate with 17... Rf7, but it won't change the result as we win decisive material. }
14. Bxf6
{ We must remove the defender of the bishop on d7 in order for our trick to work. }
14... Bxf6 15. Bxh7+ Kxh7 16. Rxd7
{ With a pawn up in Panagiotakos,N - Sfougatakis,N Heraklion 2009. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "22. French Defense (1...e6) Rubinstein & Burn Variation"]
[Black "4...Nbd7 (5...Be7 3)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4
{ Black captures our pawn and changes the position completely. Now the position is open, so we won't get the standard French pawn structures we have seen in earlier lines. This move can be compared to the 3... Qd8-line in the Scandinavian. Black is solid as there are no weaknesses in the pawn structure, but he does lack some space. Black intends to play c7-c5 at a later stage, which will neutralize our center. The line has been played by countless GMs, perhaps in particular by the strong German GM Georg Meier. I jokingly regard this line as a 'draw offer,' as it is used primarily as a drawing weapon. }
4. Nxe4
{ Before we can head to the main tabiya in the Rubinstein Variation, we must take a look at what happens if Black decides to capture on f6 with the knight. }
4... Nd7 5. Nf3 Be7 6. Bd3 Ngf6 7. Nxf6+ Nxf6
{ This move makes more sense to the human eye, but I dare to say that  7...Bxf6  is better! }
8. Qe2
{ And how do we fight against passive set-ups? You guessed it, it's by starting an attack! }
8... c5
{ Some strong players have tried this move here, so we must take a look. I must ask though... If c7-c5 was your plan all along, why on earth did you play 7... Be7 first? }
9. dxc5 Qa5+
{ This approach looks better as Black becomes slightly more active. } 10. Bd2
Qxc5 11. O-O-O { We will stick to our strategy. } 11... O-O 12. Ne5
{ It's really simple to play White as the only thing we need to do is kicking our kingside pawns forward. And that begs the question... How is Black supposed to stop us? }
12... Rd8
{ The strong Peruvian GM Cordova played this logical move that places the rook in the open d-file.   12...b6  It's logical to place the bishop on the a8-h1 diagonal.  13.g4  Bb7  14.g5  We don't have to worry about our rook just yet.  14...Bd6   The best try to defend.  14...Nd5  is the human move. I found a beautiful game by the legend Keres who showed his brilliancy after  15.Rhg1  Qc7  16.Rg4!  and won in style in 32 moves. I definitely suggest checking out this jewel! Keres, P - Petrovs, V Riga 1939.  15.Nc4  Nd5  16.Qe4  g6  17.h4+-  With a very dangerous attack as  h5  followed by  Qh4  is incredibly hard to stop. I suppose  17...Rab8  is a logical reaction, and here I think  18.Nxd6  Qxd6  19.Qg4  should deliver the goods. }
13. Kb1
{ As I've pointed out before, I'm fond of this prophylactic move. I'm more skeptical of the approach  13.a3  Qc7  14.Bg5  which was Macieja, B - Cordova, E Leon 2017. There's no need to spend time on moving the bishop to  g5  . }
13... Bd7 14. g4 { Let's GO! } 14... Bd6 15. f4
{ It's already looking incredibly dangerous for Black. } 15... Bc6 16. Nxc6
{ I prefer grabbing Black's bishop, but there was nothing wrong with  16.Rhf1  either. }
16... bxc6 17. c4
{ An important move. Let's not give Black counterplay with Nd5! It's also worth mentioning that this move makes it easier for us to defend on the queenside. }
17... Rab8 18. Bc1
{ After some precaution, it's time to continue our assault on Black's king! } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "22. French Defense (1...e6) Rubinstein & Burn Variation"]
[Black "4...Nbd7 (5...Be7 4)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4
{ Black captures our pawn and changes the position completely. Now the position is open, so we won't get the standard French pawn structures we have seen in earlier lines. This move can be compared to the 3... Qd8-line in the Scandinavian. Black is solid as there are no weaknesses in the pawn structure, but he does lack some space. Black intends to play c7-c5 at a later stage, which will neutralize our center. The line has been played by countless GMs, perhaps in particular by the strong German GM Georg Meier. I jokingly regard this line as a 'draw offer,' as it is used primarily as a drawing weapon. }
4. Nxe4
{ Before we can head to the main tabiya in the Rubinstein Variation, we must take a look at what happens if Black decides to capture on f6 with the knight. }
4... Nd7 5. Nf3 Be7 6. Bd3 Ngf6 7. Nxf6+ Nxf6
{ This move makes more sense to the human eye, but I dare to say that  7...Bxf6  is better! }
8. Qe2
{ And how do we fight against passive set-ups? You guessed it, it's by starting an attack! }
8... O-O 9. Bg5
{ This time I prefer placing the bishop on  g5  , as Black can play  9.Bf4  Nd5  with tempo which is kind of annoying. }
9... h6
{ A human instinct is to play h6 whenever a piece stands on g5.   9...Nd5  Is always met by  10.h4  And if  10...h6  11.Bd2±  Is a typical reaction. Black hasn't achieved anything of playing h6 & Nd5 in this fashion, while we have already played the attacking move h4. }
10. h4
{ We're wasting no time! Black can't take the bishop, as the open h-file will lead to mate one way or another. }
10... c5 11. O-O-O Nd5
{ The trickiest approach by Black. Other moves allow us to proceed with our attack. }
12. c4
{ An important move. The standard  12.Bd2  gives Black counterplay after  12...cxd4  , when  Qb6  and  Bf6  could follow suit. }
12... hxg5
{ Let's take a look at what happens if Black grabs the hanging piece. In my opinion it looks like the best practical attempt, as it requires precise play from us. }
13. hxg5 { 13.cxd5  g4  gives Black compensation. } 13... Bxg5+ 14. Kb1 Nf4
{ The engine jumps to +5 after this move, but it's the best practical chance.  14. ..Bh6  is better, but after  15.cxd5  it's easy for us. I don’t know about you, but I prefer a simple +2.50 over a complicated +5.00... }
15. Bh7+ Kh8 { It's not easy to tell how we should proceed... but } 16. Qe4
{ Wins! On e4 the queen targets the knight on f4 while it also sets up the beauty Bg8+. }
16... f5
{ 16...Bh6  Black would have held the fort if it wasn't for...  17.Rxh6!  Which wins the game.  17...gxh6  18.Qxf4  Kg7   Black is mated after  18...Kxh7  19.Rh1  .  19.Bc2  Qf6  20.Qg3+  Kh8  21.Ne5+-  Black's extra exchange pales in comparison to our lethal attack. }
17. Qe5
{ The pin on the g7-pawn makes sure that Black doesn't have the defensive resource Bh6! }
17... Qf6 { Is Black's best choice, when we must play } 18. Nxg5 Qxg5 19. Bxf5+
{ In order to win the game. } 19... Nh5 20. g4 { And White wins. } *

