{ We must stop Black from playing a4-a3 which would dismantle our pawns. }
14... Qc7
{ Black moves the queen to a better square, making way for the bishop on e7. }
15. Bc2 Ra5
{ A very nice move which prevents Ne5, while it also prepares e6-e5. } 16. Rd4
{ A very good move. Our rook allows us to play Bf4, it targets the pawn on a4, it allows us to double in the d-file... }
16... e5 17. Rc4
{ Don't fall for  17.Rxa4  Rxa4  18.Bxa4  Bxa3!  when Black has almost equalized. }
17... Qd6 18. Re1 { Targeting e5. } 18... h6 19. Bf4 exf4 20. Qxe7
{ Black's pieces are scattered across the board, while our pieces work harmoniously together. The queens will get traded, and the resulting endgame is winning for us. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "22. French Defense (1...e6) Rubinstein & Burn Variation"]
[Black "4...Nbd7 (5...Be7 7)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4
{ Black captures our pawn and changes the position completely. Now the position is open, so we won't get the standard French pawn structures we have seen in earlier lines. This move can be compared to the 3... Qd8-line in the Scandinavian. Black is solid as there are no weaknesses in the pawn structure, but he does lack some space. Black intends to play c7-c5 at a later stage, which will neutralize our center. The line has been played by countless GMs, perhaps in particular by the strong German GM Georg Meier. I jokingly regard this line as a 'draw offer,' as it is used primarily as a drawing weapon. }
4. Nxe4
{ Before we can head to the main tabiya in the Rubinstein Variation, we must take a look at what happens if Black decides to capture on f6 with the knight. }
4... Nd7 5. Nf3 Be7 6. Bd3 Ngf6 7. Nxf6+ Nxf6
{ This move makes more sense to the human eye, but I dare to say that  7...Bxf6  is better! }
8. Qe2
{ And how do we fight against passive set-ups? You guessed it, it's by starting an attack! }
8... O-O 9. Bg5
{ This time I prefer placing the bishop on  g5  , as Black can play  9.Bf4  Nd5  with tempo which is kind of annoying. }
9... c5 10. dxc5 Qa5+
{ Black's best attempt for counterplay, played almost exclusively. } 11. c3
Qxc5 12. O-O-O { Our plan hasn't changed! } 12... h6
{ 12...Rd8?!  Allows the nice tactic  13.Bxf6  Bxf6  14.Bxh7+  Kxh7  15.Rxd8  Bxd8  16.Qd3++-  Which wins a pawn. Black's position looks already lost if you ask me. White has 9.5/10 from this position, so apparently my theory is kind of accurate. }
13. Be3
{ This move is strong, gaining a tempo on the queen. More importantly though, our bishop will be better placed on the a1-h8 diagonal! }
13... Qa5
{ A very logical move. Black targets the pawn on a2 while preparing for e6-e5.   13...Qc7  Looks very passive.  14.Bd4  Look at our strong pair of bishops!  14...Rd8  15.Bc2  Bd7  16.Kb1  It's business as usual! Some preparation before the attack is unleashed.  16...Rac8  17.h4  Bc6  18.Ne5→  With a very dangerous attack. }
14. Bd4
{ A fantastic move, let's not care about the pawn! It's more important that Black can't achieve e6-e5 which would give him decent compensation. }
14... Qxa2 15. g4
{ A fantastic move! The idea is simple, but incredibly effective - g4-g5, capture with the rook, then double in the g-file! When I first encountered this position, I analyzed 15. Bb1 to an insane extent, but much to my annoyance, I was unable to find a win! I leave my analysis with you here, as it's incredibly beautiful. I will refrain from comments though, as it's unbelievably complicated and not the suggested approach. Click through the lines and enjoy!!   15.Bb1  Qa5!  16.g4!  Rd8!  17.Rhg1  e5!  18.Nxe5  Be6  19.g5  hxg5  20.Rxg5  Qa1!  Here, I took a look at as much as 4 different moves, but Black barely saves himself in every single line!! It was mind-blowing!  21.Qc2!?  Kf8  22.Rxg7  Kxg7  23.Nd7  Qxb1!!  24.Qxb1  Rxd7  25.Qe4  with an unclear position. The engine gives 0.00. As usual...  21.Nxf7  Rxd4!!  22.Rxd4  Ba2!!  And here we must take the draw with  23.Nh6+  Kh8  24.Nf7+  Kg8   21.Ng6  Ba3!!  22.Qc2  @@StartBracket@@22.  bxa3  Rxd4!!  23.cxd4  Rc8+!!  also leads nowhere@@EndBracket@@  22...fxg6  23.bxa3  Bf5  24.Qb3+  Kh7  25.Rxf5!?  gxf5  26.Bxf6  Rxd1+  27.Kxd1  gxf6  28.Qf7+  Kh8  29.Qxf6+  Kg8  30.Qg5+  Kh8  31.Qxf5  . The position is drawn, but further precision is required from Black. Can you believe it?  21.Rdg1  was the last move I looked at, but this is also a draw after  21...Rxd4  22.Rxg7+  Kf8  23.Qh5!  Ke8  24.Rxf7  Rd1+!!  25.Qxd1  Bxf7  26.Nxf7  Kxf7  27.Qb3+  Kf8  28.Kc2  . The game is still going, but it is a draw. Phew! Fun stuff, let's go back to the  15.g4! }
15... Rd8
{ Black takes over the d-file and is ready to play Bd7-Bc6 or even Ba4. } 16.
Rhg1 { We have no time to waste! } 16... Bd7
{ 16...e5  was Black's magic in the 15. Bb1-line, but here it doesn't work due  to  17.Bc4!  The line goes  17...Qa1+  18.Kc2  Qa4+  19.Bb3  A big difference from last time!  19...Qe8  20.Qxe5  . White's close to winning. }
17. g5 { We are faster than Black! } 17... hxg5 18. Rxg5 Be8
{ Black's only move, as he can't allow us to sacrifice our way through on g6. }
19. Rdg1 g6
{ Black's survives in the g-file for now, but that doesn't mean that we can't create more threats. }
20. Bc4 Qa1+ 21. Kc2 Qa4+ 22. Kb1
{ I find it hard to believe that Black will survive the attack. One deadly plan is to play Rxg6+ followed by Qxe6+. h4-h5 is looming in the air as well. }
