1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3
{ It's time to examine the main tabiya of the Rubinstein Variation. } 3... Nf6
4. Bg5
{ I am not going to head into details in this chapter, but this is my chosen weapon against the Classical Variation. }
4... dxe4 5. Nxe4 Nbd7 6. Nxf6+ Nxf6 7. Nf3
{ We have arrived at the main position of the Rubinstein. } 7... h6 8. Be3
{ The best square for the bishop, as we're preventing Black from playing c5. }
8... Bd6
{ We can see a huge improvement from the 7... Be7-line now that Black is able to place the bishop on the better square on d6. }
9. Bd3 Nd5
{ In the standard game of the match, Moroni decided to go for this knight jump here. }
10. Bd2 Nf4
{ An extra option as Black has developed the bishop to d6. It's not a challenge for us, though. }
11. Bxf4 Bxf4 12. Qe2 Qf6
{ And now I became too fancy with  13.Ne5  . After  13...Bd7  , my opponent offered me a draw, an offer I pondered for over 40 minutes but accepted as I was unable to find anything concrete. Mihajlov, S - Moroni, L Tornelo INT 2021. Instead, I should have just gone for: }
13. O-O O-O 14. c4
{ With a very comfortable position as Black is quite passive. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "22. French Defense (1...e6) Rubinstein & Burn Variation"]
[Black "4...Nbd7 (5...Ngf6 7...h6 2)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3
{ It's time to examine the main tabiya of the Rubinstein Variation. } 3... Nf6
{ Yes yes, I am well-aware that the standard way to head into the Rubinstein is with  3...dxe4  . However, it's important to highlight the reasoning behind my chosen system against Black's scheme.  3...dxe4  4.Nxe4  Nd7  5.Nf3  Ngf6  6.Nxf6+  Nxf6  7.Bg5  is the most common move-order. }
4. Bg5
{ I am not going to head into details in this chapter, but this is my chosen weapon against the Classical Variation. }
4... dxe4 5. Nxe4 Nbd7 6. Nxf6+ Nxf6 7. Nf3
{ We have arrived at the main position of the Rubinstein. } 7... h6 8. Be3
{ The best square for the bishop, as we're preventing Black from playing c5. }
8... Bd6
{ We can see a huge improvement from the  7... Be7-line now that Black is able to place the bishop on the better square ond6  . }
9. Bd3 b6
{ I must admit that it looks slightly strange to play this move before castling first. However, as it has been tried by many strong players we should take a look. }
10. Ne5 Bb7
{ Black can obviously play  10...O-O  here, but then why didn't he play it in the previous move. In most games the play has proceeded with  11.Qf3  Nd5  12.Bd2  Bb7  13.O-O-O  c5  14.Nc4  Rb8  15.Nxd6  Qxd6  16.dxc5  bxc5  17.Qg4  . White had a promising position and won a nice game in Popov, I - Baklan, V Denizili 2013. }
11. Bb5+ { The way to punish Black's move-order. } 11... Kf8 12. Qe2
{ We should avoid the trade of queens.  12.O-O  is met by  12...Bxe5  followed by  Qd5  . The endgame is slightly better for us I suppose, but I want more. }
12... a6 13. Bd3 c5
{ 13...Bxg2?  We must consider what happens if Black is greedy and grabs the hanging pawn.  14.Rg1  Bd5  15.f4  The f-pawn will eventually head to f5 where it will create even more weaknesses inside Black's camp.  15...b5  16.O-O-O  c6  And now we can improve on Kaczmarczyk,D - Kosic,D Porto Carras 2018 by going straight for the throat with  17.f5  Opening the position. I suspect White was afraid of  17...Qa5  But it's nothing to fear as our attack is much stronger.  18.fxe6  Qxa2  19.Bf4!  A fantastic move with several functions. The most important one is that we make the e3-square available to our king. Another function is that discoveries like Ng6+ are on the table.  19...Qa1+   19...Bxe6  is met by  20.Ng6+  fxg6  21.Bxd6+  Kg8  22.Rxg6  . Black is busted.  20.Kd2  Bb4+  21.Ke3  Our king escapes!  21...Qxb2  22.exf7  Bxf7  23.Nxf7  Kxf7  24.Bg6+  Kf8  25.Kf2  Black's attack has vanished completely and he is now completely dominated. What a fantastic line! }
14. O-O-O b5
{ Was Svidler,P - Gurevich,M Gibraltar 2009, and here I found the beautiful move }
15. Bg6 { Black is forced to give his queen: } 15... fxg6 16. dxc5 Bxe5 17.
Rxd8+ Rxd8
{ Black has obtained two minor pieces and a rook for the queen which is usually quite enough. However, after }
18. c6
{ We break through with our queen so we can target Black's queenside pawns. }
18... Bxc6 19. Bc5+ Bd6 20. Qxe6 Bxc5 21. Qxc6 Bxf2 22. Rf1
{ It's not possible for Black to defend the pawns on the queenside. When a6 and b5 falls, everything is set for us to create a very powerful passed pawn. }
22... Be3+ 23. Kb1 Re8
{ By far the best defense according to the engine.  23...Bf4  is fancy, when we should answer with  24.a3  . A sample line is:  24...Bd6  25.Qxa6  Kf7  26.Rd1  Bxh2  27.Qb7+  Ke6  28.Qb6+  Rd6  29.Qe3+  Kf7  30.Rxd6  Bxd6  31.Qb3+  Ke7  32.Qxb5  . I don't think Black can survive the endgame, especially in a practical game. }
24. a3 Kf7 25. Qxa6 Re6 26. Qxb5 Rhe8 27. Qd3
{ Black has coordinated his forces well, but again I can't stress enough how difficult it is to defend an endgame like this in practice. }
