1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3
{ It's time to examine the main tabiya of the Rubinstein Variation. } 3... Nf6
4. Bg5
{ I am not going to head into details in this chapter, but this is my chosen weapon against the Classical Variation. }
4... dxe4 5. Nxe4 Nbd7 6. Nxf6+ Nxf6 7. Nf3
{ We have arrived at the main position of the Rubinstein. } 7... h6 8. Be3
{ The best square for the bishop, as we're preventing Black from playing c5. }
8... Bd6
{ We can see a huge improvement from the 7... Be7-line now that Black is able to place the bishop on the better square on d6. }
9. Bd3 O-O 10. Qe2 b6 11. O-O-O Bb7 12. Ne5 c5
{ Is much better. Here I suggest   12...Qe7?  Some strong players have tried this natural move, but it's just too slow!  13.Rhg1!  The g-pawn goes fast.  13...c5  14.g4  cxd4  15.Bxd4→  Our attack looks lethal already. How is Black going to stop it? }
13. Nc4 { With the intention of grabbing the bishop pair. } 13... Nd5 14. Nxd6
Qxd6 15. dxc5 bxc5
{ 15...Qe5?  was played in Adams, M - Speelman, J Daventry 2019, but it just loses. I suspect that Black had missed that he has  Nf4  which we will see in just a moment. The game went:  16.Bd2  Qxe2  17.Bxe2  bxc5  18.c4  Ne7  19.Be3  with a decisive advantage for White. }
16. c4 Nf4
{ Otherwise Black loses material, the detail I suspect Speelman missed. } 17.
Bh7+ Kh8 { The only move, as  17...Kxh7?  loses to  18.Qc2+! } 18. Qg4 Nd5
{ Is a fantastic move and the only way to get a position Black can live with.   18...Qc6?  Doesn't do the trick for Black.  19.Qxf4  Kxh7  Was Sulskis,S - Kotsur,P Nakhchivan 2013, and here I found the nice move  20.b3  Which solidifies our pawn chain.  20...f6  And now  21.Qd6+-  Black has severe problems with the pawn on c5.   18...Qa6?  Has also been tried, but it loses to the beautiful  19.Bc2!  Black is struggling with the knight on f4.  19...Nxg2  20.Bxh6  Well spotted by the strong GM.  20...gxh6  21.Qh5  Kg7  22.Rd7+-  Black was dead lost and resigned a few moves later in Gharamian,T -Michiels,B Belgium 2010. }
19. cxd5 Kxh7 20. dxe6 Qxe6 21. Qxe6 fxe6
{ This is sort of an anti-climax, but it was forced. } 22. Rd7 Bd5 23. Kb1
{ We're playing for two results here, although there's no doubt that Black will draw with correct play. }
