{ It's time to examine the main tabiya of the Rubinstein Variation. } 3... Nf6
4. Bg5
{ I am not going to head into details in this chapter, but this is my chosen weapon against the Classical Variation. }
4... dxe4 5. Nxe4 Nbd7 6. Nxf6+ Nxf6 7. Nf3
{ We have arrived at the main position of the Rubinstein. } 7... h6 8. Be3
{ The best square for the bishop, as we're preventing Black from playing c5. }
8... Nd5
{ In my database, this is Black's most played move. The idea is very simple. Black gets rid of our bishop so he can play c7-c5. What's the problem with this? Well, Black's minor pieces on c5 @@StartBracket@@we're going to take on c5 some day@@EndBracket@@ and d5 can be pushed back by our queenside pawns @@StartBracket@@b2-b4 & c2-c4@@EndBracket@@. }
9. Bd2
{ 9. Bd3 is quite popular as well, but there's no reason to give the bishop on e3. }
9... c5 10. Bb5+ Bd7 11. Bxd7+ Qxd7 12. c4
{ An important resource that shows the downside of Black's Nd5-scheme. } 12...
Nb6 { Essential, as Black looks almost lost after  12...Nf6  13.Ne5! } 13. Rc1
Rc8
{ Black prepares to take on d4 now that the c5-square is covered.   13...cxd4?  Loses for Black due to  14.c5  And Black loses control of the a4-square.  14...Nd5  15.Ne5+-  Black is in dire straits following Szabo,G -Stanciu,A Arad 2010. }
14. dxc5 Bxc5
{ 14...Rxc5  Can be easily dealt with by the means of  15.Qe2  Be7  16.O-O  O-O  17.b3±  White's queenside majority played a huge role in White's advantage in Bacrot,E -Vaisser,A Evry 2008. Black's pieces are also rather poorly placed. }
15. b4
{ As previously mentioned, the downside with Black's play is how we can push back his minor pieces. }
15... Be7 16. c5
{ We keep pushing! Black's knight is forced to leave, which means that the a4-square will be vacant for our queen. }
16... Nd5 17. Ne5 Qc7
{ Not 17... Qb5?? as it allows 18. a4 when Black's queen will be trapped. } 18.
Qa4+ Kf8 19. Nc4
{ With a clearly better game due to our strong queenside majority and Black's exposed king. }
