[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "22. French Defense (1...e6) Rubinstein & Burn Variation"]
[Black "4...Nbd7 (5...Ngf6 7...c5)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3
{ It's time to examine the main tabiya of the Rubinstein Variation. } 3... Nf6
{ Yes, I am well-aware that the standard way to head into the Rubinstein is with 3... dxe4. However, it's important to highlight the reasoning behind my chosen system against Black's scheme.   3...dxe4  4.Nxe4  Nd7  5.Nf3  Ngf6  6.Nxf6+  Nxf6  7.Bg5  is the most common move-order. }
4. Bg5
{ I am not going to head into details in this chapter, but this is my chosen weapon against the Classical Variation. }
4... dxe4 5. Nxe4 Nbd7
{ Black's most common move has been  5...Be7  which takes the game into a pretty interesting direction. However, Black can play this move which transposes directly to the Rubinstein Variation! I was therefore forced into recommending  Bg5  as our weapon against the Rubinstein. }
6. Nxf6+ Nxf6 7. Nf3
{ We have arrived at the main position of the Rubinstein. Black has to deal with the pin on the knight somehow... This can be done with  7...h6  , which targets the bishop immediately,  7...c5  can be played which challenges our center, or  7...Be7  which simply puts an end to the pin. }
7... c5
{ Is a very interesting move that the strong Italian GM, Luca Moroni Jr, played against me in a recent game. With this move, Black wants to clear the situation in the center. The resulting positions usually follow a pattern - Black is incredibly solid, but slightly passive. If we're not able to create anything, Black will equalize easily. }
8. Bc4
{ After analyzing this position for over 2 hours, I came up with this bishop move. I analyzed a plethora of alternatives, but I was never satisfied with what I came up with.   8.dxc5  makes sense, but after  8...Qxd1+  9.Rxd1  Bxc5  , I honestly doubt we have much. It's definitely easier to play White, but objectively quite even.   8.Ne5  is adventurous, but it lead nowhere. I found a pretty nice threefold after  8...Qa5+  9.Bd2  Qb6  10.Bc3  a6  11.Bd3  cxd4  12.Bxd4  Bc5  13.Nc4  Bb4+  14.c3  Qxd4  15.Qa4+  Bd7  16.Qxb4  Qxd3  17.Nd6+  Kd8  18.Rd1  Qg6  19.O-O  Bc6  20.Nf5+  Kc7  21.Qf4+  Kb6  22.Qb4+  .   8.c3  looks interesting, but after  8...cxd4  9.Nxd4  Be7  , I think Black was okay in Abasov, N - Cernousek, L Prague 2020.   In my game I tried  8.Bb5+  which has been the most played move. The game went:  8...Bd7  9.Bxd7+  Qxd7  10.O-O   10.Qe2  is more testing, but after  10...Be7  11.O-O-O  O-O  12.dxc5  Qc7  I think Black is doing well  10...cxd4  11.Nxd4  Be7  and Black had equalized. The game was drawn after  12.c4  a6  13.Nf3  Qc7  14.Qe2  O-O  15.h3  Rfd8  16.Rfd1  h6  . Mihajlov, S - Moroni, L Tornelo INT 2021. Fun fact, we were both more interested in playing Armageddon :@@EndBracket@@ }
8... cxd4 9. O-O
{ Black has to make a decision on where to place the bishop on f8. } 9... Bc5
10. Qe2 { Our reaction is the same. We will grab the pawn with Rad1. } 10...
O-O 11. Rad1 h6
{ Other moves are possible, but this is the most sensible move. } 12. Bh4
{ The pin on Black's knight on f6 is quite annoying for Black to deal with. This is why Black usually gets out of the pin with }
12... Qb6 { At the cost of the doubled pawns on the kingside. } 13. Bxf6 gxf6
14. Rd3
{ Our rook is strong on d3 where it can potentially swing to the kingside via g3, making moves like Ne5 appear. It also allows a doubling of the rooks in the d-file. }
14... Kh7 { Black has to get the king to a safe place. } 15. Rfd1 Rg8 16. Nxd4
{ We have finally regained the pawn. } 16... Bd7
{ This appeared in the game Peinz,G - Owens,J ICCF email 2016. Here I found a nice improvement: }
17. Rb3 { Maintaining the pressure on Black. } 17... Qc7 18. Qf3
{ Targeting the pawns on b7 and f6. } 18... Bb6 19. Bf1 Rg6 20. Rc3
{ Forcing Black's queen to the passive square on b8. } 20... Qb8 21. h4
{ With a very strong initiative. It's tough for Black to defend all of the weak pawns in his camp. It's worth noting that the natural  21...Kg7  is met by  22.Nf5!+ }
