4. Bg5
{ I am not going to head into details in this chapter, but this is my chosen weapon against the Classical Variation. }
4... dxe4 5. Nxe4 Nbd7
{ Black's most common move has been  5...Be7  which takes the game into a pretty interesting direction. However, Black can play this move which transposes directly to the Rubinstein Variation! I was therefore forced into recommending  Bg5  as our weapon against the Rubinstein. }
6. Nxf6+ Nxf6 7. Nf3
{ We have arrived at the main position of the Rubinstein. } 7... c5
{ Is a very interesting move that the strong Italian GM, Luca Moroni Jr, played against me in a recent game. With this move, Black wants to clear the situation in the center. The resulting positions usually follow a pattern - Black is incredibly solid, but slightly passive. If we're not able to create anything, Black will equalize easily. }
8. Bc4 cxd4 9. O-O
{ Black has to make a decision on where to place the bishop on f8. } 9... Be7
10. Qe2
{ The right approach. We want to play Rad1 and then capture the pawn, when the pressure in the d-file will give us some play. }
10... O-O 11. Rad1 { We're now ready to capture the pawn on d4. } 11... Qb6
{ The b6-square is a more active post for the queen.   11...Qc7  GM Tiviakov's move from 2012, and it does indeed look like a good one.  12.Rxd4  Bd7  Black's pieces are now out on the board. He's soon ready to place a rook on d8 and then trade rooks. Where's our initiative?  13.Rh4!  I am a big fan of this move as we're planning to create a decent amount of pressure against Black's king. These types of moves are really unpleasant to face. That being said, it's also good to start with 13. Ne5 like in G,A - Tiviakov,S Kolkata 2012.  13...Bc6  14.Ne5  Rad8  15.Rh3!  A strong prophylactic move, as the rook on h4 can be targeted in some lines by the black forces. Our attack looks tough to meet, as Black will have to weaken his position with g7-g6 when we play Bd3. The best defense I found was:  15...Rd4  Intending  16.Bd3  Be4  Our attack will fade into nothing without our light-squared bishop. The forced line goes:  17.Bxf6  Bxd3  18.Rxd3  Rxd3  19.Bxe7  Rd5  20.Bxf8  Rxe5  The tactics have worked out for Black, but he has to part with a pawn after  21.Qd3  Kxf8  22.Qxh7±  Black has to fight for a draw with a pawn down. }
12. Nxd4 { Nf5 has all of a sudden shown up as a pretty unpleasant trick. }
12... Qxb2 { Black's critical move is to grab the hanging pawn. } 13. Nf5
{ Black's pieces are now quite loose. } 13... exf5
{ Black's best chance is to grab the hanging piece.   13...Qb4  Allowed the forced beautiful sequence  14.Rb1  Qc5  15.Rb5  Qc7  16.Nxe7+  Qxe7  17.Rf5!  Brilliant, Black can't avoid the doubled pawns on the kingside which will give us excellent attacking potential.  17...Qc7  18.Rxf6!  A very powerful exchange sacrifice which destroys Black's kingside. Behold, our magnificent bishop pair!  18...gxf6  19.Bxf6  Qf4  The only way to avoid mate.  20.Be5  Qh6  21.Rd1  The rook is ready to join the attack.  21...b5  22.Bd3!  22. Bxb5 Bb7 is less clear.  22...f6  It's almost for Black, but...  23.Be4+-  Maintains a winning position as we're regaining the exchange. White had played a magnificent game and prevailed after 45 moves in Copie,J - Lepikhov,A Poland corr 2000 Corr 2002. }
14. Qxe7 { We're now threatening Qxf7+ with a back-rank mate. } 14... h6 15.
Bxf7+ { 15. Rd8 is also possible. } 15... Rxf7 16. Rd8+ Kh7 17. Qxf7 Be6
{ Necessary, as 17... hxg5 loses after 18. Qc7. } 18. Qxe6 Rxd8 19. Qxf5+ Kh8
20. Be3
{ We're a pawn up with a much safer king, but Black's active pieces give him some hope to save the game. }
*

