1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3
{ It's time to examine the main tabiya of the Rubinstein Variation. } 3... Nf6
4. Bg5
{ I am not going to head into details in this chapter, but this is my chosen weapon against the Classical Variation. }
4... dxe4 5. Nxe4 Nbd7 6. Nxf6+ Nxf6 7. Nf3
{ We have arrived at the main position of the Rubinstein. } 7... Be7
{ Certainly a logical approach, but it does look slightly passive if you ask me. }
8. Bd3 { Natural development. } 8... Nd5
{ Is an interesting try, as Black can get rid of some of our pressure by targeting our bishop with Nb4 in case we refrain from trading dark-squared bishops. }
9. h4
{ The usual way to respond to  Nd5  . There's no doubt that we're better after  9.Bxe7  followed by  O-O  as Black is quite passive, however he remains rather solid. }
9... h6 10. Bd2 { I prefer to keep the bishop. } 10... Nb4
{ Looks best, although it loses valuable time after } 11. Bxb4 Bxb4+ 12. c3 Bd6
{ Black has obtained the bishop pair, but it has been a time-consuming affair. }
13. Qe2 Qe7
{ Black should try to go queenside castling as well, as our attack is incredibly fast if he goes to the kingside. }
14. Ne5 { A nice jump into the center. Black's bishops are not doing much. }
14... Bd7 15. Qf3 c6 { 15... O-O-O hangs the pawn on f7. } 16. O-O-O Qf6 17.
Qe3 { We will keep the queens on the board. } 17... O-O-O 18. f4
{ Our space advantage gives us a clearly better game. } *

