1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3
{ It's time to examine the main tabiya of the Rubinstein Variation. } 3... Nf6
4. Bg5
{ I am not going to head into details in this chapter, but this is my chosen weapon against the Classical Variation. }
4... dxe4 5. Nxe4 Nbd7 6. Nxf6+ Nxf6 7. Nf3
{ We have arrived at the main position of the Rubinstein. } 7... Be7
{ Certainly a logical approach, but it does look slightly passive if you ask me. }
8. Bd3 { Natural development. } 8... h6
{ Honestly, I think that this move is slightly strange as Black can play it right away. Why waste time on playing Be7 first? Still, this has been played in over 300 games, so let's take a look. }
9. Be3
{ I prefer placing the bishop on the e3-square where it can potentially target the h6-pawn with the help of Qd2, or get placed on the improved square on d4 in case Black plays c5. }
9... O-O 10. Qd2
{ An excellent move! Black has to worry about a sacrifice on h6 now. } 10... c5
{ Black's best try is to challenge our center right away.   10...Nd5?  Allows us to take the pawn  11.Bxh6  gxh6  Black can't recapture, but it's obviously not ideal to play with a pawn down with no compensation.  12.Qxh6  f5  At first sight, it looks like there's no way through!  13.Qg6+  Kh8  14.g4!!  The only move that wins! In order for our attack to succeed, we must open the g-file.  14...Bf6  15.gxf5  With the open g-file for our rook, Black's task of defending becomes impossible.  15...Qe7  16.Qh6+  Kg8  17.Rg1+  Bg7  18.O-O-O  +-  Black won't survive the attack. }
11. dxc5 Qc7 12. Bd4
{ A strong improvement over  12.O-O-O  which was played in Rudolf, A - Den Hartog, M Hoogeveen 2014. Black looks fine after  12...e5  . Our bishop is very well placed on  d4  where it targets the knight on  f6  , making  Bxc5  unavailable for Black at the moment. }
12... Nd5 13. a3 { We're preparing to keep our c5-pawn with b2-b4. } 13... f6
{ Black's best try. He now occupies the e5-square, which means that we can no longer meet Bxc5 with Be5. Additionally, e6-e5 could be possible in the future. }
14. g3
{ The most precise, as Black has some compensation after  14.b4  b6  15.cxb6  axb6  16.O-O  Rd8  . With  g3  , Black can no longer jump to the square on  f4  . This practically forces Black to recapture on  c5  , since  14...e5  fails to  15.Be4!  when  Bxe5  comes next. }
14... Bxc5 15. O-O-O
{ Black's f7-f6 has weakened the b1-h7 diagonal along with the pawn on e6. Our position is clearly better after we will force the move f6-f5 by placing our queen on e4. f6-f5 will leave a nasty hole on e5 which we can fully exploit with moves like Rhe1. }
