1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3
{ It's time to examine the main tabiya of the Rubinstein Variation. } 3... Nf6
4. Bg5
{ I am not going to head into details in this chapter, but this is my chosen weapon against the Classical Variation. }
4... dxe4 5. Nxe4 Nbd7 6. Nxf6+ Nxf6 7. Nf3
{ We have arrived at the main position of the Rubinstein. } 7... Be7
{ Certainly a logical approach, but it does look slightly passive if you ask me. }
8. Bd3 { Natural development. } 8... c5
{ It makes a lot of sense for Black to challenge our center immediately.   8...O-O  Has been by far the most common way to proceed here. If you have been observant, you might notice that  9.Qe2  Takes us back to the previous chapter. }
9. dxc5 Qa5+
{ Black's idea is to recapture with the queen. Otherwise Be7 is a complete waste of time. }
10. c3 Qxc5 11. Qe2 Bd7
{ A very interesting move which was surprisingly difficult to take down. Black aims to disturb our coordination with  Ba4  in case we castle queenside.  11...O-O  looks more natural. After  12.O-O-O  we have once again reached the previous chapter. Fun twist of events! }
12. Ne5
{ A very interesting try for an edge. Perhaps White is slightly better after  12.O-O-O  Ba4  13.Rd2  Rd8  14.Re1  with  Ne5  coming, but it's minuscule at best. }
12... Rd8
{ Has also been tried.   12...Bd6!?  The engine suggests Black not to care about the bishop on d7.  13.Bxf6  gxf6  14.Nxd7  Kxd7  15.O-O-O  Black's king is rather safe behind the army of pawns and the strong dark-squared bishop, but we're playing for two results here.  15...Ke7  16.g3  We're going for a potential f4-f5 which will weaken Black's king while taking control of some dark squares. Play may continue:  16...h5  17.Rhe1  Kf8  18.Bc2  Rd8  19.Rd4⩲  We have the upper hand in the endgame. Black needs to worry about his slightly exposed king. As I already stated, we're playing for two results. A nice place to be in! }
13. O-O
{ We're setting up a nice little trap a dozen players have fallen into! } 13...
Bd6
{ Black's best bet is to target our knight. Note also that  14.Nxd7  is met by  14...Qxg5  , a crucial resource Black has.   13...O-O ?  This move falls right into our trap:  14.Bxf6  Bxf6  15.Bxh7+  Kxh7  16.Qd3+  Kg8  17.Nxd7+-  Since we're taking on f6 with a check, Black will be a pawn down for absolutely no counterplay. The engine goes crazy and gives a decisive advantage. Rellstab, L-Richter,K Berlin 1932. }
14. Rfe1
{ I found nothing better than allowing Black to head into an endgame. } 14...
Qxe5 15. Qxe5 Bxe5 16. Rxe5 { Our bishop pair grants us a tiny edge. } *

