{ I am not going to head into details in this chapter, but this is my chosen weapon against the Classical Variation. }
4... dxe4 5. Nxe4 Nbd7 6. Nxf6+ Nxf6 7. Nf3
{ We have arrived at the main position of the Rubinstein. } 7... Be7
{ Certainly a logical approach, but it does look slightly passive if you ask me. }
8. Bd3 { Natural development. } 8... c5
{ It makes a lot of sense for Black to challenge our center immediately.   8...O-O  Has been by far the most common way to proceed here. If you have been observant, you might notice that  9.Qe2  Takes us back to the previous chapter. }
9. dxc5 Qa5+
{ Black's idea is to recapture with the queen. Otherwise Be7 is a complete waste of time. }
10. c3 Qxc5 11. Qe2 Bd7
{ A very interesting move which was surprisingly difficult to take down. Black aims to disturb our coordination with  Ba4  in case we castle queenside.  11...O-O  looks more natural. After  12.O-O-O  we have once again reached the previous chapter. Fun twist of events! }
12. Ne5 { A very interesting try for an edge. } 12... Bc6
{ Black's most popular try does not impress after } 13. h4
{ After checking this position again I discovered that this move is more accurate than  13.O-O-O  which I gave in 'Destroy the French.' The reason is Black's annoying  13...Nd7  . After  14.Bxe7  Qxe5  15.Ba3  , I only considered  15.. .O-O-O  when I thought that we have a better endgame after  16.f3  . This is indeed true, but it turns out that Black can simply grab the hanging pawn with  15...Bxg2!  After  16.Rhg1  Bc6  , Black has apparently equalized. Bummer! After the text move,  Nd7  is no good as we can simply grab the bishop on  c6  because our bishop on  g5  is no longer hanging. Very subtle! }
13... Bxg2 { It's natural to consider what happens if Black grabs our pawn. }
14. Rg1 Bc6 15. O-O-O
{ Black is a pawn up, but the open g-file only helps us out. } 15... Rd8 16.
Kb1
{ We maintain a clearly better game with ideas like Nxc6 followed by Be3 and Rxg7, or Rde1 followed by a quick f4-f5 or even a knight capture on f7. The engine suggests a quick Rd5 followed by Rxe5 for Black, which should give you an idea of how difficult it is to play for our opponent. Good stuff! }
