4. Bg5
{ I am not going to head into details in this chapter, but this is my chosen weapon against the Classical Variation. }
4... dxe4 5. Nxe4 Nbd7 6. Nxf6+ Nxf6 7. Nf3
{ We have arrived at the main position of the Rubinstein. } 7... Be7
{ Certainly a logical approach, but it does look slightly passive if you ask me. }
8. Bd3 { Natural development. } 8... c5
{ It makes a lot of sense for Black to challenge our center immediately.   8...O-O  Has been by far the most common way to proceed here. If you have been observant, you might notice that  9.Qe2  Takes us back to the previous chapter. }
9. dxc5 Qa5+
{ Black's idea is to recapture with the queen. Otherwise Be7 is a complete waste of time. }
10. c3 Qxc5 11. Qe2 Bd7
{ A very interesting move which was surprisingly difficult to take down. Black aims to disturb our coordination with  Ba4  in case we castle queenside.  11...O-O  looks more natural. After  12.O-O-O  we have once again reached the previous chapter. Fun twist of events! }
