{ After checking this position again I discovered that this move is more accurate than  13.O-O-O  which I gave in 'Destroy the French.' The reason is Black's annoying  13...Nd7  . After  14.Bxe7  Qxe5  15.Ba3  , I only considered  15...O-O-O  when I thought that we have a better endgame after  16.f3  . This is indeed true, but it turns out that Black can simply grab the hanging pawn with  15...Bxg2!  After  16.Rhg1  Bc6  ,  Black has apparently equalized. Bummer! After the text move, Nd7 is no good as we can simply grab the bishop on c6 because our bishop on g5 is no longer hanging. Very subtle! }
13... O-O 14. O-O-O
{ We're now back in the analysis I gave on chess24. The play from here is rather simple really, we're planning to throw our pieces at Black's king as fast as we can. }
14... Rfd8 15. Kb1 Bxg2
{ Greedy, but it's the most critical practical attempt Black has.   15...Rab8  It looks natural for Black to start an attack on his own, but he's not fast enough!  16.Rhe1  Be8   Black protects the vulnerable pawn on  f7  .  16...b5  immediately is met by the fantastic  17.b4!!  with the intention  17...Qb6  18.Nxf7  . If Black goes for  17...Qxc3  , we have  18.Bd2  which wins material.  17.g4  It's time to start rolling our pawns up the board!  17...b5  18.Bc1  b4  And here, it's important that we have  19.c4→  Which keeps the b-file closed. Black's attack has been stopped for now, so we can continue attacking. Black's position looks really tough to defend. }
16. Rhg1 Bc6 17. Rde1
{ Our rook is always well placed on e1 as it opens the possibility of a knight sac on f7. It's also worth mentioning that we can improve our bishop with Bc2, as Black is no longer able to trade rooks. }
17... Rd5
{ The engine approach is to sac an exchange for our knight on e5.   17...Rac8?  Fails to a fantastic tactical sequence.  18.Bh6!   Simple enough, targeting the g7-pawn. But it's just the beginning, which is why most engines won't see pick this move immediately as it's required to look very deep in the subsequent lines.  18.Bc2  was my move on chess24 which is definitely decent, but nowhere near as strong as the text move.  18...Bf8   18...g6  fails due to the forced line:  19.Nxg6!  hxg6  20.Rxg6+!  fxg6  21.Qxe6+  Kh8  22.Qf7  Rg8  23.Rxe7  .  19.Nxf7  Black can't take the knight due to the mate in one, but things are still tricky after  19...Rxd3  20.Qxe6  There's no defense for Black...  20...Rd7   20...Bd7  is met by  21.Bxg7!  which wins on the spot. There's a nice mate on  h6  .   20...Qd5  is met with the same idea.  21.Bxg7  gives us the win, as seen after  21...Bxg7  22.Nh6+  Kg8  23.Qxc8+  .  21.Rxg7+!  This time we take with the rook!  21...Bxg7  22.Nd6+  Kh8  23.Bxg7+  Rxg7  24.Qxf6  We're winning back the missing rook as Black can't defend both the rook on c8 and the threat of Re7.  24...Rcc7  Almost works, but we have the nice trick  25.Qf8+  Rg8  26.Nf7+  Rxf7  27.Qxc5+-  With a winning position. Amazing lines! }
18. Bh6 Bf8 19. h5 { With the threat of Bxg7 followed by h6. } 19... Rxe5
{ Is Black's best defense, but things are still very grim after } 20. Qxe5 Qxe5
21. Rxe5 g6 22. Bxf8 Kxf8 23. hxg6 hxg6 24. Bf1
{ An engine may hold, but for a human being it will be incredibly tough. We will trade the strong bishop on c6 with Bg2 next. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "22. French Defense (1...e6) Rubinstein & Burn Variation"]
[Black "4...h6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6
{ Now that we have knocked out the Rubinstein. Let's take a look at its distant cousin the Burn Variation, a favorite of French-gurus GM Bluebaum and GM Christiansen. I have also utilized this move a lot in practice, but I am by no means a French-guru :@@EndBracket@@ }
4. Bg5
{ My weapon of choice is pinning the knight.  4.e5  is the other path White can take when the arising positions are rich both dynamically and strategically, depending on the system played. After  4.Bg5  we are threatening to play  e5  , attacking the pinned knight. Black can respond to this threat in three different ways:  4...Be7  is the most logical way to do so, and indeed a very popular choice. My suggestion is the aggressive Alekhine-Chatard Attack which creates very exciting positions and it is regarded as a highly critical test for Black. The line goes:  5.e5  Nfd7  6.h4!?  and now Black needs to make a decision of whether or not he should grab the pawn.  4...Bb4!?  is a counterattacking weapon I have utilized in practice with various results. Theory goes:  5.e5  h6  6.Bd2  Bxc3  7.bxc3  Ne4  , and instead of the mainstream  8.Qg4  , my choice is the unusual  8.Bc1!  which is an extremely dangerous move - in fact I think it refutes the entire system! The Burn Variation,  4...dxe4  , the topic of today's chapter, is the most popular try at top level. The reason for this is simple since the road to equality is significantly tougher in the  4...Be7  &  4... Bb4-systems. }
4... h6
{ Before we start covering The Burn Variation, we should take a brief look at what happens in case Black plays this strange-looking pawn sacrifice. I only discovered this rarity recently, as it has been tried by a lot of GMs. }
5. Bxf6 Qxf6 6. exd5 { And now Black's point is } 6... Bb4
{ When he gets some activity for the missing pawn. } 7. dxe6 Bxe6 8. a3
{ This looks like the easiest way to obtain a slight edge. } 8... Ba5
{ This was GM Jorden Van Foreest's choice in the Champions Chess Tour.   8...Bxc3+  9.bxc3  O-O  Black does have some compensation due to White's doubled pawns, but it still doesn't justify the missing pawn.  10.Bd3  c5  And here we can improve on the game Nakamura,H - Guevara,R Long Island 1998, played by a young Hikaru Nakamura, by playing  11.Qf3!   An excellent move! Black has to make the unpleasant decision of whether to trade queens or give us  Qf3  for free.  11...Nd7  seems best, when we have excellent winning chances after  12.Qxf6  Nxf6  13.f3  . }
9. Nf3 Nc6 10. Bb5
{ Pinning the knight makes it tougher for Black to create something against the d4-pawn. }
10... O-O-O 11. Bxc6 bxc6
{ And now, an important improvement over  12.O-O  which Karjakin played in Karjakin, S - Van Foreest, J chess24.com INT 2021 is to play }
12. Qd3
{ After the text move we can castle queenside if needed. Black also has to watch out for a queen check on a6. Let's now return to the topic of the day! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "22. French Defense (1...e6) Rubinstein & Burn Variation"]
[Black "4...dxe4 (8...c5)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6
{ Now that we have knocked out the Rubinstein. Let's take a look at its distant cousin the Burn Variation, a favorite of French-gurus GM Bluebaum and GM Christiansen. I have also utilized this move a lot in practice, but I am by no means a French-guru :@@EndBracket@@ }
4. Bg5 dxe4 5. Nxe4 Be7 6. Nxf6+
{ I prefer capturing with the knight.  6.Bxf6  is by far the most popular alternative, but I was uninterested in venturing into a territory where there's a lot of theory and where Black is doing very well. Black has a choice here.  6...Bxf6  is an improved version of the Rubinstein Variation in my opinion, due to the fact that he has obtained the bishop pair.  6...gxf6!?  is an incredibly interesting alternative that leads to very complicated and double-edged positions, making it a decent weapon to play for a win. Apparently, Black is fine after  7.Nf3  f5  8.Nc3  a6  . This is just the tip of the iceberg as there's a lot of theory of course, but the stubborn engine gives 0.00. The text move is an easy-to-learn weapon suggested to me by my good friend and opening expert GM Johan-Sebastian Christiansen, so it wasn't difficult for me to make up my mind on which move to recommend. }
6... Bxf6 7. Bxf6 Qxf6 8. Nf3 c5
{ Before we dive into the main tabiya of  8...O-O  , we should take a look at the alternative that challenges our center right away. }
9. Bb5+
{ There's nothing wrong with  9.c3  either, but the bishop check is our best bet for an edge. }
9... Bd7 10. Qe2
{ A strong move, as we're preparing to castle long.  10.Bxd7+  Nxd7  11.O-O  cxd4  looks completely equal. }
10... O-O
{ 10...cxd4  Is a typical reaction, when our response is  11.Bxd7+  Nxd7  12.O-O-O  We will capture the pawn with the rook and take control of the d-file.  12...O-O  13.Rxd4  We have transposed to 10... O-O. }
11. O-O-O { We should not take on d7 until Black decides to take on d4! } 11...
cxd4 12. Bxd7 { It's now time to take! } 12... Nxd7 13. Rxd4 Nb6
{ b6 is not an ideal square for Black's knight. } 14. Rhd1
{ Our play is simple. We can jump to the center with Ne5 and later reinforce the knight with the help of f2-f4 and g2-g3, or we can take additional control on the queenside with b2-b3 and c2-c4. }
14... Rad8 15. Qe4 Rxd4 16. Rxd4
{ We have a reached a position which is very comfortable for White as we have control of the d-file. Black also has to worry about the hanging pawn on b7. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "22. French Defense (1...e6) Rubinstein & Burn Variation"]
[Black "4...dxe4 (8...c5 2)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6
{ Now that we have knocked out the Rubinstein. Let's take a look at its distant cousin the Burn Variation, a favorite of French-gurus GM Bluebaum and GM Christiansen. I have also utilized this move a lot in practice, but I am by no means a French-guru :@@EndBracket@@ }
4. Bg5 dxe4 5. Nxe4 Be7 6. Nxf6+ Bxf6 7. Bxf6 Qxf6 8. Nf3 c5
{ Before we dive into the main tabiya of  8...O-O  , we should take a look at the alternative that challenges our center right away. }
9. Bb5+
{ There's nothing wrong with  9.c3  either, but the bishop check is our best bet for an edge. }
9... Bd7 10. Qe2
{ A strong move, as we're preparing to castle long.  10.Bxd7+  Nxd7  11.O-O  cxd4  looks completely equal. }
10... a6 { Black can also force us to take on d7. } 11. Bxd7+ Nxd7 12. O-O-O
{ Our reaction is no different. We castle queenside and aim to take complete control over the d-file. }
12... O-O
{ 12...O-O-O ?!  Might look tempting, but it's the wrong approach.  13.Rhe1  Kb8  14.dxc5!  A strong move. Black's knight is forced to the c5-square where it no longer guards the square on e5.  14...Nxc5  15.Qe3!  Black will be badly coordinated as he is forced to protect the knight.  15...Rc8   15...Nd7  is met by  16.Rd4  , followed by another rook to  d1  .  16.Ne5±  Black is in big trouble here as he can't maintain control over the d-file while keeping the f7-pawn under protection.  b4  is now a threat due to the fork on  d7  , so Black should play  16...Ka8  which is a logical way to dodge the threat. I suggest to go  17.Rd2  then and double in the d-file when we will be in control. }
13. dxc5
{ 13.d5  has been played in all games I found, but Black has an excellent game after  13...exd5!  14.Rxd5  and instead of  14...Rfe8  which was seen in Naiditsch, A - Skoberne, J Bled 2016, Black can play  14...Qc6!  Black is clearly better, for example:  15.Qd3  Nf6  16.Rd6  Qa4  17.Kb1  Ne4  18.b3  Qb4  19.a3  c4  20.axb4  cxd3  . }
13... Nxc5 14. Rd4 { The same plan - control over the d-file! } 14... Rfd8 15.
Rhd1 Rac8 { And now I like } 16. Qe3 Rxd4 17. Rxd4
{ We have some pressure in the endgame due to our control over the d-file. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "22. French Defense (1...e6) Rubinstein & Burn Variation"]
[Black "4...dxe4 (8...O-O)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6
{ Now that we have knocked out the Rubinstein. Let's take a look at its distant cousin the Burn Variation, a favorite of French-gurus GM Bluebaum and GM Christiansen. I have also utilized this move a lot in practice, but I am by no means a French-guru :@@EndBracket@@ }
4. Bg5 { My weapon of choice is pinning the knight. } 4... dxe4 5. Nxe4 Be7 6.
Nxf6+ Bxf6 7. Bxf6 Qxf6 8. Nf3 O-O 9. Qd3
{ This is the point behind our entire scheme. We're going to start an attack by playing Qe4 and O-O-O. Later on we will play Bd3 when Black will be forced to make a concession in his camp. h2-h4-g2-g4-g5 will follow suit as well. It really is simple to play White, hence why I like this system so much. }
9... Bd7 { Can also be tried, with the plan of placing the bishop on c6. } 10.
Qe3
{ Looks best, intending to meet Bc6 with Ne5. Our queen also gives the d3-square for our bishop.   10.O-O-O  was played by my buddy Benjamin, but Black reacted well with  10...Bc6  11.h4  Bxf3  . After the dubious  gxf3?!  Black was already better in Haldorsen, B - Ghosh, D Riga 2017. However, there's an excellent alternative in  10.h4!?  The point is  10...Bc6  11.Rh3  , when we can capture on  f3  with the rook. I'd say White is slightly better here. }
10... Rd8
{ Was seen in Matusek,J - Fremmegaard,J ICCF email 2018. I don't think the move does so much here though, as we can always defend the pawn on d4 with c3. I suggest to simply develop our pieces.   10...Nc6  I doubt that a human will play such a strange-looking move, but it has a nice idea of maneuvering the knight to d5 via b4.  11.c3  Rad8  12.Bd3  Ne7   12...Rfe8  makes sense as well, when we can respond with  13.O-O-O  . A detail here is that if Black plays  e5  we can always play  d5  .  13.O-O   White changes his mind and castles kingside, a reaction I applaud.  13.O-O-O  is met by  Bc6  when I must admit that I prefer Black.  13...Nd5  14.Qe4  g6  15.Ne5  It looks rather difficult for Black to get his pieces out in decent positions.  15...Bc8  16.Rad1  White had a very comfortable position in Rhodes,J -Blake,M ICCF email 2019, but was unable to win. }
11. Bd3 Bc6 { 11...Nc6  is met by  12.c3  . } 12. Ne5
{ We shouldn't let Black take on f3. } 12... Nd7 13. Nxc6 bxc6 14. O-O-O Rab8
15. c3 { With a very comfortable position for White. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
