[Round "?"]
[White "22. French Defense (1...e6) Rubinstein & Burn Variation"]
[Black "4...dxe4 (8...O-O 2)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6
{ Now that we have knocked out the Rubinstein. Let's take a look at its distant cousin the Burn Variation, a favorite of French-gurus GM Bluebaum and GM Christiansen. I have also utilized this move a lot in practice, but I am by no means a French-guru :@@EndBracket@@ }
4. Bg5 { My weapon of choice is pinning the knight. } 4... dxe4 5. Nxe4 Be7 6.
Nxf6+ Bxf6 7. Bxf6 Qxf6 8. Nf3 O-O 9. Qd3
{ This is the point behind our entire scheme. We're going to start an attack by playing Qe4 and O-O-O. Later on we will play Bd3 when Black will be forced to make a concession in his camp. h2-h4-g2-g4-g5 will follow suit as well. It really is simple to play White, hence why I like this system so much. }
9... Rd8 10. O-O-O c5
{ It's logical for Black to apply pressure against our pawn on d4. } 11. Qe4
{ We follow our plan of attack. } 11... cxd4
{ 11...Nc6  has been played in most games which transposes to the Main Line. }
12. Bd3
{ We're ignoring the pawn on d4. Black has to make a concession in his camp now. }
12... g6
{ 12...h6  Can be met by  13.h4  Nc6  14.g4→  With a powerful attack. It's quite unpleasant to defend this from the black side. }
13. h4 { In order for us to create something, we must open the h-file. } 13...
Nc6 { Doesn't stop us from carrying out our plan. } 14. h5 e5
{ Black's only viable attempt to create counterplay. } 15. hxg6 fxg6
{ Black is ready to play Bf5 with a fine game. This can be prevented with the strong   15...hxg6  Our attack looks completely gone, but we have the nice  16.g4!  We prevent Bf5 and we're also intending to play g5 followed by Qh4.  16...Qf4+  As Black is a pawn up, it makes sense to head into an endgame.  17.Qxf4  exf4  18.Rh4  Be6  19.g5±  We will regain the pawn with profit as our rook on f4 will be quite strong. Black is headed for a tough endgame as the pawn on d4 is likely to fall as well. }
16. Rh6 Bf5
{ This is still Black's best move, otherwise he will met by an unpleasant rook-doubling in the h-file. }
17. Qxf5 { The point behind Rh6! } 17... Qxf5 18. Bxf5 gxf5 19. Rdh1 Rd7 20.
Ng5 { Black has to part with the pawn on h7. } 20... Rg7 21. Rxh7 Rxg5
{ Black's only chance as  21...Rxh7  22.Rxh7  gives us a winning endgame. Black's pawns are too loose. }
22. Rh8+ Kg7 23. Rxa8 Rxg2
{ Black's active rook and strong clash of pawns in the center justifies the exchange sac. }
24. b4 Nxb4 25. Rxa7
{ Black has to be very precise in order to avoid a defeat. I guess it's appropriate to stop here! }
