10. O-O-O Rd8
{ The same strategy as  9...Rd8  , Black applies pressure on our pawn in the center. }
11. Qe4 Nc6
{ We have already taken a look at  11...cxd4  , through the move-order  9...Rd8  . }
12. Bd3 Qh6+
{ The logical choice. Black protects the pawn on h7 with a tempo, and will then get an excellent version of both 12. .. Nxd4 and 12... cxd4.   12...g6?  Is now a terrible blunder as the pawn on c5 is left hanging.  13.dxc5  e5  Was played by the expert himself, GM Bluebaum. Instead of 13. a3 which was played in Paravyan,D - Bluebaum,M Chess. com INT 2020, I suggest  14.Qe3  Which doesn't give Black Bf5 with a tempo.  14...Bg4  15.Be4+-  Black has a hopeless position as there's no compensation for the missing pawn.   12...cxd4?  Looks bad.  13.Qxh7+  Kf8  14.Be4!  A strong move that makes it difficult for Black to get his pieces out with e5 followed by Bg4, as there will be a capture on c6.  14...Bd7  15.Rhe1  Rac8   Note that if Black plays  15...Ke7  , our queen gets out after  16.Qh5  .  16.Kb1  It's always a good feeling to dodge potential checks and nastiness down the c-file.  16...Ke7  17.Qh3  Our queen is heading to g3. We can also launch the g-pawn forward in order to remove Black's queen from f6.  17...Qf4  18.g3  Qf6  19.g4  Qf4  Black prevents us from placing our queen on the juicy square on g3.  20.Qh4+  f6  21.Qh7  We're forcing an ending which looks close to winning.  21...Qh6  22.Qxh6  gxh6  23.Bxc6  Bxc6  24.Nxd4+-  Black has to fight teeth and nail in order to save the game. I'd say it's too late, but never say never...   12...Nxd4?!  Better, but still bad.  13.Qxh7+  Kf8  14.Be4  This move is yet again quite important. In this case, it makes sure Black can't meet Qh5 with a rook lift to d5.  14...Ke7  15.Qh5  Qf4+  16.Nd2  e5  Bg4 looks like a very nasty threat, but we have everything under control after  17.g3  Bg4  18.Qh4+  g5  19.Qh6  And yet again the queens are traded.  19...Qf6  20.Qxf6+  Kxf6  21.f3  We're pushing Black's active pieces back.  21...Be6  22.c3  Nc6  And here, we should create a passed pawn with  23.h4  gxh4  24.gxh4±  With excellent winning chances as our h-pawn is very dangerous. Black also needs to be on the lookout for a capture on c6, followed by Ne4 which can be quite obnoxious. }
13. Kb1
{ I prefer sacrificing the pawn for initiative. The calm  13.Qe3  gives us a very tiny edge, but I don't think Black will have any problems here. An email-game went  13...Qxe3+  14.fxe3  cxd4  15.Be4  Bd7  16.exd4  which was drawn 17 moves later. Nilsson, N - Berthelot, P ICCF email 2018. }
13... Nxd4
{ It goes against my intuition to capture with the knight, but as a matter of fact it could be the best choice. }
14. Rhe1
{ The best try for an edge. I also looked at  14.Ne5!?  , but apparently Black is doing fine after  14...f6  15.Nc4  Nc6  , intending  Rd4  . After the text move, it's not so simple for Black to come up with something to do. }
14... Rb8
{ Black defends the pawn on b7 so he can develop the bishop.   14...Bd7  Gives away the extra pawn after  15.Nxd4  cxd4  16.Qxb7±  The right pawn to capture as the pawn on d4 can be targeted in the future. Black's open b-file is also nothing to worry about, because we have b3 which will eliminate most threats. }
15. Nxd4 { Is how we should react! } 15... cxd4 16. Qe5
{ We're now going to play Be4 next, when the pawn on d4 won't last long. }
16... Ra8
{ Is the top suggestion by the machine, and here I suggest launching the kingside pawns forward. }
17. g4 Bd7 18. Qg3 { Our queen provides support behind our soldiers. } 18...
Bc6 19. f4 Rac8 20. h4 { White has a lot of play for the pawn. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "22. French Defense (1...e6) Rubinstein & Burn Variation"]
[Black "4...dxe4 (8...O-O 8)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6
{ Now that we have knocked out the Rubinstein. Let's take a look at its distant cousin the Burn Variation, a favorite of French-gurus GM Bluebaum and GM Christiansen. I have also utilized this move a lot in practice, but I am by no means a French-guru :@@EndBracket@@ }
4. Bg5 { My weapon of choice is pinning the knight. } 4... dxe4 5. Nxe4 Be7 6.
Nxf6+ Bxf6 7. Bxf6 Qxf6 8. Nf3 O-O 9. Qd3
{ This is the point behind our entire scheme. We're going to start an attack by playing Qe4 and O-O-O. Later on we will play Bd3 when Black will be forced to make a concession in his camp. h2-h4-g2-g4-g5 will follow suit as well. It really is simple to play White, hence why I like this system so much. }
9... c5
{ c5 right away is the most logical move in my opinion, hence why I have decided to put it as the Main Line. }
10. O-O-O Rd8
{ The same strategy as  9...Rd8  , Black applies pressure on our pawn in the center. }
11. Qe4 Nc6
{ We have already taken a look at  11...cxd4  , through the move-order  9...Rd8  . }
12. Bd3 Qh6+ 13. Kb1
{ I prefer sacrificing the pawn for the initiative. The calm  13.Qe3  gives us a very tiny edge, but I don't think Black will have any problems here. An email game went  13...Qxe3+  14.fxe3  cxd4  15.Be4  Bd7  16.exd4  which was drawn 17 moves later. Nilsson, N - Berthelot, P ICCF email 2018. }
13... Nxd4
{ It goes against my intuition to capture with the knight, but as a matter of fact it could be the best choice. }
14. Rhe1
{ The best try for an edge. I also looked at  14.Ne5!?  , but apparently Black is doing fine after  14...f6  15.Nc4  Nc6  , intending  Rd4  . After the text move, it's not so simple for Black to come up with something to do. }
14... Nxf3
{ Is the most sensible approach, since Black avoids the potential captures on d4 which will more often than not give him a pawn we can easily target. }
15. Qxf3 { Bxh7+ is now a threat. Black has different ways to dodge it: } 15...
Qh4
{ This move looks strange, but it's the best way to dodge our discovered check.   15...Qg5?!  Allows  16.h4!  Which speeds up our shenanigans on the kingside.  16...Qe7  17.h5!  A strong follow-up. The point is that we want to go Qe4 and open the h-file when Black answers with g6.  17...Qg5  18.h6!  Forcing Black to play the unpleasant g7-g6.  18...g6  19.Bc4  The strong pawn on h6 gives Black a serious headache, as there's a lot of tactics involving an infiltration on the 8th rank, or mate threats on g7.  19...Rxd1+?  It hurts to give away the d-file, and in fact it's a losing move, but I think it's instructive to see the refutation. Other moves are met by Rh1 which makes sure that our precious pawn stays.  20.Rxd1  Qxh6  21.Rd8+   Don't fall for  21.Qf6?  as Black has the fantastic  21...Bd7!!  which wins.  21...Kg7  22.Qc3++-  Black has a hopeless position due to the pieces on the 8th Rank being pinned down. A nice sample line is:  22...f6  23.Be2  b6  24.Qf3  Rb8  25.g3  Qh5  26.Rxc8  Qxf3  27.Rc7+  Kh6  28.Bxf3  with a piece up.   15...g6  16.Be4!  Targeting Black's pawn on b7 while grabbing the d-file.  16...Qg5   16...Bd7  is not what Black wants to do because of the hanging pawn on  b7  , but it's the lesser evil. After the text move we will infiltrate Black down the d-file and on the 8th rank.  17.Rxd8+  Qxd8  18.Rd1  Qe7  19.Qd3  f5  20.Bf3  Kf7  21.Qd8  Qxd8  22.Rxd8±  Black is completely pinned down. Positions like these tend to be lost in the long run, but I will give Black the benefit of a doubt and 'only' give White a clearly better game since it's not objectively lost yet. The way to win is to grab Black's pawns at the right timing... }
16. Be4 Re8
{ Black steps away from the d-file, so it's time to occupy it with our forces. }
17. Rd6 Qe7 18. Qd3 h6 19. Rd1
{ With ideas like Qb5, Qe3 & Rd8, Black has to be very careful. } *

