[White "22. French Defense (1...e6) Rubinstein & Burn Variation"]
[Black "4...dxe4 (8...O-O 9)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6
{ Now that we have knocked out the Rubinstein. Let's take a look at its distant cousin the Burn Variation, a favorite of French-gurus GM Bluebaum and GM Christiansen. I have also utilized this move a lot in practice, but I am by no means a French-guru :@@EndBracket@@ }
4. Bg5 { My weapon of choice is pinning the knight. } 4... dxe4 5. Nxe4 Be7 6.
Nxf6+ Bxf6 7. Bxf6 Qxf6 8. Nf3 O-O 9. Qd3
{ This is the point behind our entire scheme. We're going to start an attack by playing Qe4 and O-O-O. Later on we will play Bd3 when Black will be forced to make a concession in his camp. h2-h4-g2-g4-g5 will follow suit as well. It really is simple to play White, hence why I like this system so much. }
9... c5
{ c5 right away is the most logical move in my opinion, hence why I have decided to put it as the Main Line. }
10. O-O-O Rd8
{ The same strategy as  9...Rd8  , Black applies pressure on our pawn in the center. }
11. Qe4 Nc6
{ We have already taken a look at  11...cxd4  , through the move-order  9...Rd8  . }
12. Bd3 Qh6+ 13. Kb1
{ I prefer sacrificing the pawn for the initiative. The calm  13.Qe3  gives us a very tiny edge, but I don't think Black will have any problems here. An email game went  13...Qxe3+  14.fxe3  cxd4  15.Be4  Bd7  16.exd4  which was drawn 17 moves later. Nilsson, N - Berthelot, P ICCF email 2018. }
13... cxd4 14. h4
{ We proceed with our attack. I found a decent alternative in  14.Rhe1  which looks promising for White after for example  14...Bd7  15.g4  . }
14... f5
{ Black puts an end to our pawn storm, but weakens the e5-square in the process. }
15. Qe2 Qf6
{ The queen has finished its role on h6, so it makes sense to move it to the improved square on f6.   15...Bd7  Allows us to proceed with our pawns with  16.g4!  Since Black can't take due to  16...fxg4  17.Ng5+-  When everything falls apart for Black.   15...a6  Was played in Portela Peleteiro, A - Christiansen,J Prague 2016, the game I suspect inspired 'J.S' to dive into this variation from the white side. Instead of the game's 16. Bc4, I am a fan of  16.g4  b5  17.Ng5  Ra7  18.Rhe1  White has a very powerful initiative. Black's best try is  18...Re7  Which should be answered with  19.Qf3  Attacking the knight and the pawn.  19...Qxh4  And now a forced line is:  20.Nxh7  Bb7  21.Rh1  Qxg4  22.Nf6+  gxf6  23.Rhg1±  Black will have some compensation for the queen, but is still far from equality. }
16. Rhe1
{ We alter our plans now that Black is better suited to deal with a kingside attack. }
16... h6 17. Bc4 Kh7
{ Black doesn't have too much to do, despite being up a pawn. } 18. g3 Bd7 19.
Ne5 Nxe5 20. Qxe5 Qxe5 21. Rxe5
{ We will regain the pawn as Black's pawns on e6 and d4 are both very weak. Black has to fight for a draw in the ending that ensues. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "23. French Defense (1...e6) Mainlines"]
[Black "4...Bb4 (8...Qh4)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5 Bb4
{ It's time to start looking at the McCutcheon Variation, named after John Lindsay McCutcheon of Philadelphia who used it to defeat World Champion Wilhelm Steinitz in a simul in Manhattan 1886. Black goes for a counterattack and ignores our threat of playing e5. This line is extremely complicated and filled to the brim with theoretical nuances. The line has always been quite popular due to its complexity, but nowadays I think it's almost unplayable due to a very fancy computer idea which poses a serious threat to Black's scheme. }
5. e5 h6 { Black's idea, otherwise he will lose a piece. } 6. Bd2
{ White can place the bishop anywhere in this position, but Bd2 has been the main move for a long time as it forces Black to capture on c3. }
6... Bxc3 7. bxc3 Ne4 8. Bc1
{ The refutation is not well known at all, as I only found approximately 100 games in my base!  8.Qg4  is by far the most popular move, and here the game becomes rather double-edged after  8...g6  9.Bd3  Nxd2  10.Kxd2  c5  11.h4  . The position we have is incredibly exciting, but Black is fine. You may wonder why we choose to play  Bc1  now, instead of right away? The point is that Black doesn't have to capture on  c3  after  6.Bc1  . This is very important detail. Our idea behind the strange-looking  8.Bc1  is to play against Black's knight on  e4  .  If Black allows us to, we will push it back with f2-f3, h2-h4 and then later create a powerful attack on Black's kingside. In this position, Black needs to make a decision of whether to grab the pawn on c3 or play c7-c5. A recurring theme to stumble across in the Universe of McCutcheon. }
8... Qh4
{ Before we take the two main moves into concern, I quickly want to show off what happens if Black attempts a little trick. }
9. g3 { And now the tactic } 9... Nxg3 { Fails to } 10. fxg3 Qe4+ 11. Kf2 Qxh1
12. Nf3 { Because Black can't avoid the loss of the queen after Qd2 and Bg2. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "23. French Defense (1...e6) Mainlines"]
[Black "4...Bb4 (8...c5)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5 Bb4
{ It's time to start looking at the McCutcheon Variation, named after John Lindsay McCutcheon of Philadelphia who used it to defeat World Champion Wilhelm Steinitz in a simul in Manhattan 1886. Black goes for a counterattack and ignores our threat of playing e5. This line is extremely complicated and filled to the brim with theoretical nuances. The line has always been quite popular due to its complexity, but nowadays I think it's almost unplayable due to a very fancy computer idea which poses a serious threat to Black's scheme. }
5. e5 h6 { Black's idea, otherwise he will lose a piece. } 6. Bd2
{ White can place the bishop anywhere in this position, but Bd2 has been the main move for a long time as it forces Black to capture on c3. }
6... Bxc3 7. bxc3 Ne4 8. Bc1 c5
{ It's always a good feeling to play this move when playing the French, but it turns out that it's quite inaccurate and it leads to a position which is almost lost! Being by far the most common response by Black, it's great news for us! I can also confirm this statement myself, as I have never faced 8... Nxc3 online. }
9. Ne2
{ We're defending our hanging pawn, and thus ready to start kicking Black's knight from e4. }
9... O-O
{ Black makes things easy for us by castling, as he allows us to easily carry out our plan. }
10. f3 Ng5 11. h4 { From e4 all the way back to h7! } 11... Nh7 12. g4
{ Our attack begins! } 12... b6
{ Placing the bishop on a6 where it can target our knight makes logical sense, but we're one step ahead! }
13. Nf4 { g5 comes next, blasting the files around Black's king open. } 13...
cxd4
{ 13...Nc6  And now  14.g5!  Black can't stop our forces.  14...hxg5  15.hxg5  Nxg5  16.Nh5+-  Black won't survive the onslaught. }
14. cxd4 Qc7
{ Is a typical reaction by Black, searching for counterplay towards our king. }
15. Kf2 { The simplest reaction. We can now meet  15...Qc3  with  16.Rb1  . }
15... Ba6 { Black's counterplay is too slow. } 16. Bxa6 Nxa6 17. Bd2
{ An important move that stops Black's hope for counterplay. } 17... Rac8 18.
c3
{ Black's play has been completely neutralized, so it's our time to shine with g5 coming next! }
*

