[White "23. French Defense (1...e6) Mainlines"]
[Black "4...Bb4 (8...c5 2)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5 Bb4
{ It's time to start looking at the McCutcheon Variation, named after John Lindsay McCutcheon of Philadelphia who used it to defeat World Champion Wilhelm Steinitz in a simul in Manhattan 1886. Black goes for a counterattack and ignores our threat of playing e5. This line is extremely complicated and filled to the brim with theoretical nuances. The line has always been quite popular due to its complexity, but nowadays I think it's almost unplayable due to a very fancy computer idea which poses a serious threat to Black's scheme. }
5. e5 h6 { Black's idea, otherwise he will lose a piece. } 6. Bd2
{ White can place the bishop anywhere in this position, but Bd2 has been the main move for a long time as it forces Black to capture on c3. }
6... Bxc3 7. bxc3 Ne4 8. Bc1 c5
{ It's always a good feeling to play this move when playing the French, but it turns out that it's quite inaccurate and it leads to a position which is almost lost! Being by far the most common response by Black, it's great news for us! I can also confirm this statement myself, as I have never faced  8...Nxc3  online. }
9. Ne2
{ We're defending our hanging pawn, and thus ready to start kicking Black's knight from e4. }
9... Nc6
{ This approach is similar to  9...O-O  , but it's an important factor here that Black still hasn't castled. This makes our kingside pawn launch less effective, so another strategy is required. }
10. f3 Ng5 11. Ba3
{ In the event of  11.h4  , Black benefits from having his king on  e8  . After  11...Nh7  12.g4  Qa5  13.Kf2  f6  I think Black has decent counterplay. }
11... cxd4
{ Suddenly it looks like we have made a grand error due to the queen check on a5 in the event of   12.cxd4  . }
12. h4
{ It's important that we remove Black's protection on the f7-pawn which the game Orfini,N - Di Benedetto,E Premium Chess Arena INT 2020 demonstrates.   The game went  12.Nxd4  Qa5  13.Nb5  a6  14.Nd6  Kd7  when the game was highly unclear. It would have made a big difference if the pawn on  f7  was hanging as we soon shall see... }
12... Nh7
{ And here the game becomes rather complicated, but the tactics favor us.   12...Qa5  We have two decent choices here:  13.Bb4   Wins a piece. The alternative is  13.Bd6  which aims to dominate Black completely. The line goes:  13...Nh7  14.Rb1  Nf8  15.Kf2  dxc3  16.Nd4  we're just in time!  16...Ng6  17.Nxc6  bxc6  18.Qd4  with a dominating position.  13...Nxb4  14.cxb4  Qxb4+  15.c3  Nxf3+  16.gxf3  dxc3  Black has gained as much as four pawns for the piece. The pawn on c3 will fall, when Black will have three pawns. This usually justifies being a piece down, but Black's pieces are not that well placed in this case, making our extra piece more significant.  17.Qb3  Qe7  I think most players would keep the queens on the board.  18.Qxc3  Bd7  19.Nd4  Our knight is well placed on d4.  19...O-O  20.Qe3  Rac8  21.Kf2±  Black's three pawns do not justify the missing minor piece. }
13. Nxd4 Qa5
{ Our position is similar to Orfini,N - Di Benedetto,E, but with a knight on h7 Black's position is significantly worse. }
14. Nb5 a6 15. Nd6+ Kd7 16. Qc1
{ The most accurate move is to defend the bishop on a3 and simply ignore the fact that we have a hanging pawn on c3. }
16... Qxc3+ 17. Kd1 f6
{ Black's best bet.  17...Nxe5  loses to  18.Bb2  , while  17...Qxe5  gives Black major problems after  18.Nxf7  Qd4+  19.Bd3  Rf8  20.Bb2!!  @@StartBracket@@grabbing the rook would give Black a lot of compensation@@EndBracket@@  20...Qc5  21.Ne5+  Nxe5  22.Bxe5  , when we are dominating on the dark squares. }
18. Rb1
{ Our rook steps into the b-file, while also aiming to go Rb3 followed by c2-c4 at some point. }
18... Nxe5 19. Be2
{ Preparing f3-f4, now that we're covering g4 with our bishop. } 19... Kc7 20.
Rb3 Qd4+ 21. Ke1
{ c2-c4 is going to come next which will hurt for Black.  21...b5  is met by  22.Rxb5!  due to the fork. Beautiful stuff! }
*

