1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5 Bb4
{ It's time to start looking at the McCutcheon Variation, named after John Lindsay McCutcheon of Philadelphia who used it to defeat World Champion Wilhelm Steinitz in a simul in Manhattan 1886. Black goes for a counterattack and ignores our threat of playing e5. This line is extremely complicated and filled to the brim with theoretical nuances. The line has always been quite popular due to its complexity, but nowadays I think it's almost unplayable due to a very fancy computer idea which poses a serious threat to Black's scheme. }
5. e5 h6 { Black's idea, otherwise he will lose a piece. } 6. Bd2
{ White can place the bishop anywhere in this position, but Bd2 has been the main move for a long time as it forces Black to capture on c3. }
6... Bxc3 7. bxc3 Ne4 8. Bc1 c5
{ It's always a good feeling to play this move when playing the French, but it turns out that it's quite inaccurate and it leads to a position which is almost lost! Being by far the most common response by Black, it's great news for us! I can also confirm this statement myself, as I have never faced  8...Nxc3  online. }
9. Ne2
{ We're defending our hanging pawn, and thus ready to start kicking Black's knight from e4. }
9... cxd4 { Is a very logical approach by Black. } 10. cxd4 Qa5+ 11. c3
{ Our point! Black can't take the pawn due to the pin on the queen after Qd2. }
11... Bd7
{ Is a pretty interesting try by Black, intending Ba4. However, we can refute the plan with   11...Nc6  Black defends the queen and is now ready to go pawn-grabbing.  12.Qb3!  There's no need to be fancy! 12. Qb3 defends the pawn, and Black is already lost according to my engine. Next, we will proceed with our standard plan of kicking Black's knight all the way back.  12...O-O  Black's best bet. Other moves are met by f3 followed by h4 and Ba3.  13.h4!   The most precise move is to trap Black's knight, however  13.f3  is almost as strong. Up to you!  13...f6  And now  14.f3  fxe5  15.fxe4  exd4  Looks like a mess, but I can assure you that we have everything under control.  16.Ba3  Rd8  17.O-O-O  +-  Black does not have enough for the piece and is objectively completely lost. }
12. f3 Ba4 { 12...Ng5  gives us our standard fantastic play after  13.h4  . }
