1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5 Bb4
{ It's time to start looking at the McCutcheon Variation, named after John Lindsay McCutcheon of Philadelphia who used it to defeat World Champion Wilhelm Steinitz in a simul in Manhattan 1886. Black goes for a counterattack and ignores our threat of playing e5. This line is extremely complicated and filled to the brim with theoretical nuances. The line has always been quite popular due to its complexity, but nowadays I think it's almost unplayable due to a very fancy computer idea which poses a serious threat to Black's scheme. }
5. e5 h6 { Black's idea, otherwise he will lose a piece. } 6. Bd2
{ White can place the bishop anywhere in this position, but Bd2 has been the main move for a long time as it forces Black to capture on c3. }
6... Bxc3 7. bxc3 Ne4 8. Bc1 c5
{ It's always a good feeling to play this move when playing the French, but it turns out that it's quite inaccurate and it leads to a position which is almost lost! Being by far the most common response by Black, it's great news for us! I can also confirm this statement myself, as I have never faced  8...Nxc3  online. }
9. Ne2
{ We're defending our hanging pawn, and thus ready to start kicking Black's knight from e4. }
9... Qa5
{ Black's most played move in the position is to attack our pawn on c3 without capturing on d4. This means that we can now longer play c3, but instead we're forced to play }
10. f3 Ng5
{ A sad retreat.   10...Nxc3?  White's score is as high as 96% after the pawn capture, and for good reason as it loses on the spot!  11.Qd2  cxd4  12.Nxd4  Bb2 is now a lethal threat, winning the knight.  12...Qc7   Other moves don't help either.  12...Nc6  loses the knight after  13.Nb3  Qb4  14.a3  Qh4+  15.g3  . A recent game went  15...Qh5  16.Qxc3  Nxe5  17.f4  Nc6  18.Qxg7  . Black resigned in Gilevich, A - Luebsen, K Karlsruhe 2019.   12...Qc5  fails to  13.a4!  It's essential that we make sure that Black's knight can't escape. Gilevich played a game again here that went  13...Bd7  14.Ba3  Qc8  15.Bb4  Nxa4  16.Nb5  Bxb5  17.Bxb5+  Nc6  18.Bxa4  And White was completely winning in Gilevich, A - Di Benedetto, E Chianciano Terme 2018. Black miraculously escaped due to White blundering in the end. Such is the cruel game of chess!  13.Bb2  Qxe5+   13...Na4  loses to  14.Nb5  , like in Zarubitski, V - Favaloro, A Tarvisio 2017.  14.Kf2  Na4  And now, a forced line goes  15.Bb5+  Bd7  16.Bxa4  Bxa4  17.Qb4!  Protecting our bishop on b2, while attacking Black's bishop. Now, Nxe6 is coming.  17...Bd7  18.Nxe6!  Qxe6  19.Rhe1+-  A fantastic display. Christiansen,J -Vovk,I Sweden 2019 & Novotny,J -Laznicka,V Nachod 2000. @@StartBracket@@A very young Laznicka!@@EndBracket@@ }
11. Bd2 { We don't have to play h4 yet. } 11... Nc6 12. Ng3
{ We're getting ready to jump to h5! } 12... O-O 13. Bd3 c4
{ And here, we have the intermezzo } 14. h4 Nh7 15. Bxh7+
{ The point! Black's king has very little shelter, while the queenside initiative is all gone due to  13...c4  . }
15... Kxh7 16. Nh5 { Otherwise Black has no problems after f6. } 16... Bd7 17.
Qe2
{ Our queen is headed to e3 where it will threaten tactics like Nxg7 followed by Qxh6+. We're also going to launch our g-pawn up the board. }
17... Be8 { And now } 18. Nf6+ { Leaves Black completely paralyzed. } 18... Kh8
{ 18...gxf6  Gives us a winning attack after  19.Qe3  Rh8  20.exf6   Not  20.Qxh6?  as it's important that we can capture on  f6  with the pawn!  20...Kg8  21.Rh3  The threat of Rg3 followed by Qxh6+ is deadly.  21...Rh7  Black almost defends, but...  22.Rg3+  Kh8  23.Rg7  Mates. A beautiful attacking line! }
19. Kf2 { Black is doomed, as there's no counterplay. } *

