{ It's time to start looking at the McCutcheon Variation, named after John Lindsay McCutcheon of Philadelphia who used it to defeat World Champion Wilhelm Steinitz in a simul in Manhattan 1886. Black goes for a counterattack and ignores our threat of playing e5. This line is extremely complicated and filled to the brim with theoretical nuances. The line has always been quite popular due to its complexity, but nowadays I think it's almost unplayable due to a very fancy computer idea which poses a serious threat to Black's scheme. }
5. e5 h6 { Black's idea, otherwise he will lose a piece. } 6. Bd2
{ White can place the bishop anywhere in this position, but Bd2 has been the main move for a long time as it forces Black to capture on c3. }
6... Bxc3 7. bxc3 Ne4 8. Bc1 c5
{ It's always a good feeling to play this move when playing the French, but it turns out that it's quite inaccurate and it leads to a position which is almost lost! Being by far the most common response by Black, it's great news for us! I can also confirm this statement myself, as I have never faced  8...Nxc3  online. }
9. Ne2
{ We're defending our hanging pawn, and thus ready to start kicking Black's knight from e4. }
9... Qa5
{ Black's most played move in the position is to attack our pawn on c3 without capturing on d4. This means that we can now longer play c3, but instead we're forced to play }
10. f3 Ng5 { A sad retreat. } 11. Bd2 { We don't have to play h4 yet. } 11...
Nc6 12. Ng3 { We're getting ready to jump to h5! } 12... Bd7
{ Black opens the possibility of castling queenside. } 13. Nh5 Rg8
{ The best attempt. Black's king is too unsafe on the kingside, as we've seen.   13...O-O ?  14.Bd3   The safe alternative.  14.f4  is best objectively, but I disliked the mess after  14...Ne4  15.Qg4  g6  16.Nf6+  Kg7  17.Nxd7  Rfd8  18.Nxc5  Nxd4  19.Bd3  .  The text move is rather simple, but do certainly feel free to head for 14. f4 if you dare!  14...cxd4  15.cxd4  Qa4  16.c3  Qxd1+  17.Kxd1+-  A dreadful endgame is ahead. }
14. Rb1 Qc7 { 14...O-O-O  is met by  15.Rb5  . } 15. Bb5 O-O-O 16. O-O
{ We have a position that resembles a Winawer, but Black's knight on g5 is completely out of the game. }
16... Na5
{ A standard way of playing for Black, taking control of the c4-square. } 17.
a4 Bxb5
{ 17...a6  can be met by  18.Bxd7+  Rxd7  19.Nf4  , when are knight is headed to  d3  . In case Black tries  19...c4  , we can play  Bc1  , similar to the text variation. }
18. Rxb5 c4 19. Bc1 { Our bishop has a bright future on d6. } *

