1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5 Bb4
{ It's time to start looking at the McCutcheon Variation, named after John Lindsay McCutcheon of Philadelphia who used it to defeat World Champion Wilhelm Steinitz in a simul in Manhattan 1886. Black goes for a counterattack and ignores our threat of playing e5. This line is extremely complicated and filled to the brim with theoretical nuances. The line has always been quite popular due to its complexity, but nowadays I think it's almost unplayable due to a very fancy computer idea which poses a serious threat to Black's scheme. }
5. e5 h6 { Black's idea, otherwise he will lose a piece. } 6. Bd2
{ White can place the bishop anywhere in this position, but Bd2 has been the main move for a long time as it forces Black to capture on c3. }
6... Bxc3 7. bxc3 Ne4 8. Bc1 Nxc3 { Grabbing the pawn is the right way to go! }
9. Qg4 { Black has to make a crucial decision. How to defend the pawn? } 9...
Kf8 { Is inaccurate due to a pretty sweet queen maneuver. } 10. Qg3
{ 10.Qf3  or  10.Qh3  won't make a difference. } 10... Ne4 11. Qa3+
{ The point with the check is to gain a tempo. The same strategy we saw earlier applies here as well. We're going to play against Black's knight. }
11... Qe7 12. f3 { It's time to kick the knight back. } 12... Ng5 13. h4 Nh7
{ One important difference from earlier is the fact that we're a pawn down. However, we have excellent pressure after }
14. c4 Nc6
{ Can be met by the cunning   14...dxc4  15.Bxc4±  Gives us an easy game.   14...Qxa3  Black heads into an ending with a pawn up, but his pieces are very badly placed.  15.Bxa3+  Ke8  16.cxd5  exd5  17.Ne2!  Our knight is headed to f4 where it will apply strong pressure on Black's pawn on d5.  17...Nc6  18.Nf4  Be6  19.Bb5  We're getting ready to trade our bishop for the knight on c6.  19...Kd8  20.Bxc6  bxc6  21.Nxe6+  fxe6  22.Rc1  Kd7  23.g4±  Black's position is close to lost. Look at the harmony of our pieces. It's incredibly difficult for Black to find anything to do, as our pieces coordinate beautifully. }
15. cxd5 exd5 16. Qc3
{ Intending Ba3 which is incredibly unpleasant. Black can try } 16... a5
{ To take control of the b4-square. } 17. Bb5
{ Looks very strong. We'll capture the knight when Ba3 will follow suit. }
17... Kg8 18. Bxc6 bxc6 19. Ba3 { With a fantastic position for White. } *

