1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5 Bb4
{ It's time to start looking at the McCutcheon Variation, named after John Lindsay McCutcheon of Philadelphia who used it to defeat World Champion Wilhelm Steinitz in a simul in Manhattan 1886. Black goes for a counterattack and ignores our threat of playing e5. This line is extremely complicated and filled to the brim with theoretical nuances. The line has always been quite popular due to its complexity, but nowadays I think it's almost unplayable due to a very fancy computer idea which poses a serious threat to Black's scheme. }
5. e5 h6 { Black's idea, otherwise he will lose a piece. } 6. Bd2
{ White can place the bishop anywhere in this position, but Bd2 has been the main move for a long time as it forces Black to capture on c3. }
6... Bxc3 7. bxc3 Ne4 8. Bc1 Nxc3 { Grabbing the pawn is the right way to go! }
9. Qg4 { Black has to make a crucial decision. How to defend the pawn? } 9...
Kf8 { Is inaccurate due to a pretty sweet queen maneuver. } 10. Qg3 Ne4 11.
Qa3+
{ The point with the check is to gain a tempo. The same strategy we saw earlier applies here as well. We're going to play against Black's knight. }
11... Kg8
{ 11...c5?  Loses after  12.f3  Qh4+  The trickiest approach.  13.g3  Nxg3  14.Qxc5+  Kg8  15.hxg3  Qxh1  16.Qxc8+  Kh7  17.Qxb7  Qxg1  It seems like Black has sufficient counterplay, but  18.Bf4!!  Wins on the spot. The plan is to castle queenside, when the threat of Bd3 decides the game.  18...Nc6  19.O-O-O  +-  Black loses, as there are no good ways to meet Bd3+. }
12. Ne2
{ In order to play f3 and get rid of Black's knight, we must make sure that we have g3-covered. Otherwise Qh4+ will be a cold shower. }
12... b6
{ 12...c5  gives away a pawn after  13.f3  Ng5  14.Qxc5  .  The text move was played by a Spanish prodigy, with the intent to place the bishop on the f1-a6 diagonal, followed by a bishop capture on e2. The move is kind of tricky to meet, but my Norwegian buddy reacted well. }
13. h4 { Black has severe problems with the knight on e4. } 13... Ba6
{ Black's only move.  14.f3  no longer works due to  14...Bxe2  ,  when the knight suddenly can jump to g3. }
14. Rh3
{ Another excellent move! g3 is covered, so f3 remains a very deadly threat. }
14... c5
{ Is a typical human reaction when one is unaware that 14... Bxe2 somehow bails out the knight.   14...Bxe2!  Is the only way to save the knight, but it's extremely difficult to find OTB.  15.Bxe2  Nc6!  Black keeps threatening stuff.  16.Bb2  And now, the only move is the brilliant  16...g5!   Intending to meet  17.f3  with  17...g4!  This line looks impossible to find.  17.c4!  Is the best try. We'll take on d5 and then place a rook down the c-file.  17...gxh4  18.cxd5  exd5  19.Rc1±  The knight is saved miraculously, but the game is far from it. }
15. f3 cxd4 16. fxe4 dxe4
{ Black is down a piece, but it's not incredibly easy for us yet... } 17. Qa4
{ The most accurate. White gave Black a lot of compensation when he played  17.Ng3?  in Risting, E - Henderson de la Fuente, L London 2017. After  17...Bxf1  , White became too fancy with  18.Nxe4??  . Instead,  18.Kxf1  would have been clearly better, but a major step down compared to the text. }
17... d3 { We can play any move really here. The easiest is perhaps } 18. cxd3
exd3 19. Nf4
{ When Black has no compensation. A beautiful sample line is:  19...d2+  20.Bxd2  Bxf1  21.Kxf1  Qxd2  22.Rd3  Qb2  23.Rd8+  Kh7  24.Qe4+  g6  25.Rad1  , when White wins decisive material. }
*

