{ It's time to start looking at the McCutcheon Variation, named after John Lindsay McCutcheon of Philadelphia who used it to defeat World Champion Wilhelm Steinitz in a simul in Manhattan 1886. Black goes for a counterattack and ignores our threat of playing e5. This line is extremely complicated and filled to the brim with theoretical nuances. The line has always been quite popular due to its complexity, but nowadays I think it's almost unplayable due to a very fancy computer idea which poses a serious threat to Black's scheme. }
5. e5 h6 { Black's idea, otherwise he will lose a piece. } 6. Bd2
{ White can place the bishop anywhere in this position, but Bd2 has been the main move for a long time as it forces Black to capture on c3. }
6... Bxc3 7. bxc3 Ne4 8. Bc1 Nxc3 { Grabbing the pawn is the right way to go! }
9. Qg4 { Black has to make a crucial decision. How to defend the pawn? } 9...
g6
{ As we saw,  9...Kf8  didn't work out so well for Black due to the extra tempo we gained by checking on  a3  .   9...g6  is the correct way to play, although it's not a fun move to make as the weakening of the dark-squared diagonal could become very problematic. }
10. Bd3
{ It's time to develop our pieces. However, there's a very interesting alternative in  10.Ne2  which certainly could be worth investigating. The line goes  10...Nxe2  11.Bxe2  when our point is that we will capture on c5 in case Black goes c5. The engine is optimistic, so it seems like an excellent alternative. }
10... Na4
{ Is a thematic move for the McCutcheon, but right here it's very poor. } 11.
h4
{ This move is a very common reaction, whenever Black has played g6. The point is simple, we're trying to break through with h5. In case Black decides to block with g5, we can play f4. When Black goes }
11... h5
{ We have achieved something major, as Black is incredibly weak on the dark squares, in particular f6 and g5. }
12. Qf4 c5 13. Nf3 { The knight is headed to the beautiful outpost on g5. }
13... Nc6 14. Ng5
{ It's hilarious, but Black is already dead lost. Here are some beautiful sample lines: }
14... Qc7
{ Is a better attempt to defend, but it also loses.   14...Qe7  Is met by  15.Bb5  We're getting rid of Black's protection of the c5-pawn so we can play Ba3.  15...Nb6  16.Ba3  Nd7  17.Rd1  It's difficult for Black to find any moves.  17...a6  18.Bxc6  bxc6  19.O-O  O-O  20.Rd3+-  Black's position is in shambles. Our rook heads to f3, and later on we'll blast Black's kingside open with g4. There's no defense. }
15. Qf6 O-O { And here we have the fantastic } 16. Ne4
{ With the deadly threat of Bh6. } 16... Nxd4
{ Black grabs a pawn and defends with Nf5, but it doesn't help. } 17. Bh6 Nf5
18. Bxf8 Kxf8 { And now, the easiest way to win is } 19. g4 dxe4 20. gxf5 exf5
21. Bc4 { Black can resign due to O-O-O with the decisive threat of Rd8+. } *

