{ It's time to start looking at the McCutcheon Variation, named after John Lindsay McCutcheon of Philadelphia who used it to defeat World Champion Wilhelm Steinitz in a simul in Manhattan 1886. Black goes for a counterattack and ignores our threat of playing e5. This line is extremely complicated and filled to the brim with theoretical nuances. The line has always been quite popular due to its complexity, but nowadays I think it's almost unplayable due to a very fancy computer idea which poses a serious threat to Black's scheme. }
5. e5 h6 { Black's idea, otherwise he will lose a piece. } 6. Bd2
{ White can place the bishop anywhere in this position, but Bd2 has been the main move for a long time as it forces Black to capture on c3. }
6... Bxc3 7. bxc3 Ne4 8. Bc1 Nxc3 { Grabbing the pawn is the right way to go! }
9. Qg4 { Black has to make a crucial decision. How to defend the pawn? } 9...
g6 10. Bd3 Qe7
{ Black develops the queen and aims to castle queenside in the near future. }
11. Bd2 Na4
{ 11...Ne4  has also been tried, but that just gives away the extra pawn.  The knight on a4 is quite flexible as it can meet Bd3 with Nb2, and it also supports c5. }
12. h4 { The same plan applies! We're forcing a concession in Black's camp. }
12... Nb2
{ Black wants our d3-bishop.   12...Bd7  13.h5  g5  14.Rb1  Targeting Black's b-pawn.  14...Nc6  Black is getting ready to castle queenside.  15.f4   15.Ne2  O-O-O  16.f4  gxf4  17.Qxf4  Rdg8  was not so clear in Christiansen, J - David, A Paleochora 2020.  15...gxf4  16.Rxb7  Nb6  I assume that this is what Johan-Sebastian was afraid of, but in fact we can give the exchange!  17.Rxc7  Kd8  18.Rxc6  Bxc6  19.Nf3↑  With a very strong initiative for the missing exchange. }
13. h5 g5 14. f4
{ It looks best to simply ignore what Black is doing, as he has wasted a lot of tempos with the knight. }
14... Nxd3+ 15. cxd3 gxf4 16. Nf3
{ We don't need to hurry with capturing the pawn on f4. } 16... Nc6
{ And now, it's important that we play } 17. Qg7
{ To prevent Black from castling kingside. } 17... Qf8
{ Black is forced into a very unpleasant ending. } 18. Qxf8+ Kxf8 19. Rc1 Bd7
20. Bxf4
{ Black's position looks objectively lost due to his incredibly passive pieces. Our plan is very simple. g4-g5 and then place our bishop on f6 and run with the h-pawn. }
