14... Bd7 15. Bd2
{ 15.Qf6  is also strong, but I don't think there's any need to hurry. } 15...
Ne7
{ 'Backward moves are always bad' is a nice rule to remember in chess, and this is certainly no exception.   15...d4  Makes some sense as well. Our response is to simply improve our pieces.  16.Rfe1  Nd5  17.Rab1  b6  18.Re4  We'll simply capture on d4 next.  18...Nc3  Saves the pawn, but not the game.  19.Bxc3  dxc3  20.Qf6  Rg8  21.Rc4+-  We're breaking through. Black is far too passive.   15...Ne4  Has been played twice, when the solution for us isn't too difficult as Black gives away a pawn for free.  16.Bxe4  dxe4  17.Qxe4  O-O-O  Was the point behind Black's play in Ashton,A - Horton,J Port Erin 2004, but as it turns out, our attack is incredibly dangerous.  18.Rab1  Qd5  19.Qe2+-  A doubling in the b-file is going to be incredibly dangerous. I don't see how Black will survive. }
16. Rab1
{ A very strong move, using the fact that the rook is untouchable due to Bb4. }
16... Bc6 { Two moves are winning here, with the simplest being } 17. Rb3
{ As it forces a winning endgame.  17.Nd4  is a sophisticated approach. The idea is that Black has pretty much no moves, but we got to stay alert tactically. One line is  17...Ne4  18.Be3  Qa5  19.Bxe4  dxe4  20.Nxc6  Nxc6  21.Bg5  with a dominating position.  17...Nxb1  is always in the air, but the tactics work out.  18.Nxe6!  is the refutation with  Bb4  coming. }
17... Ne4 18. Bxe4 dxe4 19. Bb4 { Black's best defense is } 19... g5
{ And now } 20. Nxg5 Ng6 21. Nxe4
{ Gives us a completely winning endgame, as we can see after } 21... Nxh4 22.
Nf6+ Kd8 23. Bxc5 b6 24. Rd1+ Kc8 25. Bd6
{ We're up a pawn, but more importantly, Black's pieces are totally dominated. Karpov would be proud. }
