1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5 Bb4
{ It's time to start looking at the McCutcheon Variation, named after John Lindsay McCutcheon of Philadelphia who used it to defeat World Champion Wilhelm Steinitz in a simul in Manhattan 1886. Black goes for a counterattack and ignores our threat of playing e5. This line is extremely complicated and filled to the brim with theoretical nuances. The line has always been quite popular due to its complexity, but nowadays I think it's almost unplayable due to a very fancy computer idea which poses a serious threat to Black's scheme. }
5. e5 h6 { Black's idea, otherwise he will lose a piece. } 6. Bd2
{ White can place the bishop anywhere in this position, but Bd2 has been the main move for a long time as it forces Black to capture on c3. }
6... Bxc3 7. bxc3 Ne4 8. Bc1 Nxc3 { Grabbing the pawn is the right way to go! }
9. Qg4 { Black has to make a crucial decision. How to defend the pawn? } 9...
g6 10. Bd3 c5 { Black should go for quick counterplay. } 11. dxc5 Qa5
{ Another strong move. Black develops the queen and halts our development on the kingside for a bit. }
12. Bd2 Qa4
{ Another strong move. We must waste a move with our queen which Black can utilize by jumping to the e4-square with the knight. }
13. Qf3 Ne4 14. Bxe4 dxe4
{ As we just saw, Black's position after  14...Qxe4+  isn't very fun. Therefore, the right capture is with the pawn! }
15. Qb3 { Again, there's a crucial decision for Black to make! } 15... Bd7
{ The most precise, seen only one time in my database! The point is simply to get the pieces out as fast as possible. Black doesn't waste any time with the queen.   15...Qc6?!  Black wants to go Nd7-Nxc5, but it's quite slow.  16.Ne2  Nd7  17.O-O  Nxc5  18.Qe3±  Black was very weak on the dark squares in Hoffmann,F - Bell,I ICCF email 2014. White eventually won a very well played game, so I leave it as a clickable for you to enjoy!  18...Qc7  19.Rfd1  b6  20.Bb4  Ba6  21.Ng3  Bb7  22.Rd6  Bd5  23.Qf4  Nd7  24.Nxe4  Bxe4  25.Qxe4  O-O  26.Rad1  Nc5  27.Qe3  h5  28.h3  Rad8  29.Qh6  Qe7  30.Qf4  Qc7  31.g4  Nb7  32.Qf6  hxg4  33.Kh2  Rfe8  34.hxg4  Nxd6  35.Bxd6  Rxd6  36.exd6  Qd7  37.Kg3  Rc8  38.g5  Rxc2  39.f3  Rc8  40.Rh1  Qxd6+  41.Kg4+-  Black finally resigned.   15...Qa6  Has been Black's usual response.  16.Ne2  16...Bd7  Necessary, as Black will have a hopeless position if we're allowed to play Ng3-Nxe4.  17.c4!  We're preventing Black from placing the bishop on b5.  17...Ba4  17... Bc6 is too slow. Black's position looks quite bad after 18. Nc3, followed by Nb5.  18.Qc3  Nd7  19.O-O  Nxc5  20.Be3  b6  21.Ng3  Bc6  Black keeps everything together for now, but it doesn't last long.  22.Rad1±  Black was under pressure in Hofer,R -Goreczny,G ICCF email 2018. This Correspondence game is yet another jewel I found, so I will leave this one as well!  22...Nb7  23.Qc1  Qa5  24.h3  h5  25.c5  Nxc5  26.Rd6  Bd5  27.Bg5  Kf8  28.Bf6  Rh7  29.Ne2  Kg8  30.Nf4  Qxa2  31.Nxd5  exd5  32.e6  Nxe6  33.Rxe6  fxe6  34.Qg5  Kf8  35.Qxg6  Rf7  36.Qh6+  Ke8  37.Qh8+  Kd7  38.Qxa8  Rxf6  39.Rc1  Qxf2+  40.Kh1  Qf1+  41.Rxf1  Rxf1+  42.Kh2  Ra1  43.Qh8  Ra4  44.Qxh5  e3  45.Qe2  Re4  46.g4  Kd6  47.Kg1  d4  48.g5  Re5  49.h4  Ke7  50.Kf1  a5  51.Qc4  Rd5  52.Qc7+  Rd7  53.Qf4  Rd5  54.Ke1  a4  55.Qc7+  Rd7  56.Qxb6  a3  57.Qa5  d3  58.Qxa3+  Kf7  59.Kd1  e2+  60.Kd2  e5  61.Qc3+-  A stunning game from White! }
16. Ne2 Bc6 17. Rb1
{ We could also play  17.O-O  , when I think White has a tiny edge after  17...Nd7  18.Rfb1  Nxc5  19.Qc3  Na6  20.Nd4  . }
17... Na6 18. Be3
{ 18.Qxa4!?  is a tricky attempt. I analyzed  18...Bxa4  19.Rxb7  Bxc2  20.c6  Nc5  21.Nd4  Bd3  22.Rc7  Ba6  23.Be3  Nd3+  24.Kd2  O-O  25.Rb1  Nxe5  26.Rbb7!  Rfd8  27.Kc3  , which is apparently 0.00. The game is not over yet, though... }
18... O-O-O
{ Precise.  18...Qxb3  19.axb3  Nb4  20.Kd2  O-O-O  21.Kc1  is better for White. }
19. O-O Qxb3 20. axb3 Nb4 21. Nd4
{ White had some pressure in Gonzalez Sanchez,F -Deneuville,C ICCF email 2018, but ended up losing the game as he overplayed. }
