[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "23. French Defense (1...e6) Mainlines"]
[Black "4...Be7 (6...Nc6)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5 Be7
{ The last branch of the 3... Nf6-line! Black gets out of the pin by simply moving the bishop in between. This has been the most popular response by Black, and is thus the main tabiya of the 4. Bg5-line. }
5. e5
{ Black targets our pawn, so we must advance. 5. Bxf6 is possible, but harmless for Black. }
5... Nfd7 6. h4 { This pawn sacrifice known as the Alekhine-Chatard Attack. }
6... Nc6
{ Is a pretty interesting sideline. Black will someday play f6, when the knight on c6 contributes by controlling the e5-square. This will make the desired pawn-break e6-e5 easier to achieve. Another detail is that Black has an additional option in Nxe7 if we decide to capture Black's bishop. }
7. Qd2 { The right square for the queen. } 7... a6
{ Black's plans the typical expansion on the queenside with b7-b5.   7...h6  We respond the same way as the trainable variation.  8.Bxe7  Nxe7  9.f4  c5  10.Nf3  a6  11.g4±  Our plan remains no different. We're going to play Ne2, and follow up with dxc5 and Ned4 at some point so we can support the pawn break f4-f5. }
8. Bxe7
{ I think we should play in the same style as against the 7... h6-variation. }
8... Nxe7 9. h5 { Grabbing some space and provoking h6. } 9... h6 10. f4
{ It's time to start our wonderful pawn storm on the kingside. } 10... c5 11.
Nf3 b5 12. g4 { We're faster than Black. } 12... Rb8 13. Rg1 b4 14. Ne2
{ We plan to play f5 whenever we get the chance. This can be supported in different ways, for example by playing dxc5 followed by Ned4 which is a standard idea in these positions. }
*

