[Round "?"]
[White "23. French Defense (1...e6) Mainlines"]
[Black "4...Be7 (6...Nc6 2)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5 Be7
{ The last branch of the 3... Nf6-line! Black gets out of the pin by simply moving the bishop in between. This has been the most popular response by Black, and is thus the main tabiya of the 4. Bg5-line. }
5. e5
{ Black targets our pawn, so we must advance. 5. Bxf6 is possible, but harmless for Black. }
5... Nfd7 6. h4 { This pawn sacrifice known as the Alekhine-Chatard Attack. }
6... Nc6
{ Is a pretty interesting sideline. Black will someday play f6, when the knight on c6 contributes by controlling the e5-square. This will make the desired pawn-break e6-e5 easier to achieve. Another detail is that Black has an additional option in Nxe7 if we decide to capture Black's bishop. }
7. Qd2 { The right square for the queen. } 7... Nb6
{ Black plans to play Bd7 and later castle queenside. } 8. Bxe7 Qxe7 9. b3
{ This little move is a pretty nice novelty. We're going to play against Black's knight by going a4-a5 in the future. }
9... Bd7 10. f4 { It's also strong to play 10. a4 right away. } 10... O-O-O 11.
a4 { We stick to our plan. } 11... Qb4
{ 11...a5  could be played, but it is slightly risky as it's quite easy for us to target the pawn. White's position looks promising after  12.Nf3  Kb8  13.Bb5  . }
12. Nf3 Kb8 { And now it's time to head into an ending with } 13. Nd1 Qxd2+ 14.
Kxd2
{ White has reached a very pleasant endgame as Black's minor pieces are badly placed. We're also enjoying a nice space advantage. }
