[White "23. French Defense (1...e6) Mainlines"]
[Black "4...Be7 (6...O-O)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5 Be7
{ The last branch of the 3... Nf6-line! Black gets out of the pin by simply moving the bishop in between. This has been the most popular response by Black, and is thus the main tabiya of the 4. Bg5-line. }
5. e5
{ Black targets our pawn, so we must advance. 5. Bxf6 is possible, but harmless for Black. }
5... Nfd7 6. h4 { This pawn sacrifice known as the Alekhine-Chatard Attack. }
6... O-O
{ Was used by a 10-years younger Wesley So to defeat Jonny Hector in a fun game where the king ended up on f2 in the end, but it looks incredibly risky. }
7. Qg4 { Our queen joins the attack. } 7... f5
{ Has been Black's most popular choice in the position. } 8. Bxe7
{ I'm not a fan of 8. Qg3, as Black gets quick counterplay on the queenside with 8... c5 followed by Nc6. }
8... Qxe7 9. Qg5 { We're gaining an important tempo. } 9... Qb4
{ 9...Qxg5  was the engine's top choice, but it's a nightmarish endgame for Black from a positional perspective.  10.hxg5  a6  11.f4  c5  12.Nf3  is how Lockwood, A - Cooper, R ICCF email 2011 proceeded when White quickly obtained a completely winning position. }
10. O-O-O c5
{ Black gets the desired counterplay against our center. However, it turns out that the absence of Black's queen is a serious problem. }
11. Qe7 { Attacking the pawns on c5 and e6 simultaneously! } 11... Qb6
{ Is the only way to defend both targets. } 12. Nf3 cxd4 { And now } 13. Na4
{ Is very powerful! Capturing the pawn on d4 would be too slow, as Black only needs to play Nc5  @@StartBracket@@so Nc6 is possible@@EndBracket@@ in order to be completely fine. }
13... Qc6 14. Nxd4 { A fantastic piece sacrifice. } 14... Qxa4 15. Nxe6 Qg4
{ The only move.  15...Rf7  fails to  16.Qe8+  , due to the hanging queen on  a4  when Black moves the knight on  d7  . }
16. Nxf8 Nxf8
{ Black's position looks pretty decent with Nc6 and Be6 coming really fast. After all, Black has two pieces for our rook. Unfortunately for him, we're one step ahead @@StartBracket@@as always!@@EndBracket@@ }
17. e6
{ We keep having annoying threats! The pawn can't be taken.  17...Bxe6  loses to  18.Qxb7  , and  17...Nxe6+  loses to  18.Qe8+  . Black has to bring the queen into defense. }
17... Qg6 18. Qc7
{ Another 'only move' to maintain an edge, but it's more than enough. Black still can't capture the pawn with the bishop, as it needs to guard the hanging pawn on b7. Black is forced to take with the queen. }
18... Qh6+ 19. Rd2 { Necessary, as we must have the trick } 19... Qxe6 20. Rxd5
{ The open files give us a decisive advantage, as our initiative is too powerful for Black to handle. Black's minor pieces would normally be quite strong, but in this case they lack coordination. They're all stuck on the 8th rank! Recasens Sanchez,J -Morley,P ICCF email 2012. }
*

