[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "23. French Defense (1...e6) Mainlines"]
[Black "4...Be7 (6...O-O 2)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5 Be7
{ The last branch of the 3... Nf6-line! Black gets out of the pin by simply moving the bishop in between. This has been the most popular response by Black, and is thus the main tabiya of the 4. Bg5-line. }
5. e5
{ Black targets our pawn, so we must advance. 5. Bxf6 is possible, but harmless for Black. }
5... Nfd7 6. h4 { This pawn sacrifice known as the Alekhine-Chatard Attack. }
6... O-O
{ Was used by a 10-years younger Wesley So to defeat Jonny Hector in a fun game where the king ended up on f2 in the end, but it looks incredibly risky. }
7. Qg4 { Our queen joins the attack. } 7... Kh8
{ Moving the king dodges our threat of Bh6, but it looks a little bit slow. }
8. Nf3 c5 9. Bd3
{ We're already threatening the deadly threat of Bxh7, which will give us a decisive attack. }
9... f5
{ Has to be played, when I suggest   9...cxd4??  Walks right into our evil plans.  10.Bxh7  And Black is toast, as we can see after  10...Kxh7  11.Bxe7  Qxe7  12.Qh5++-  When Ng5 comes and Black is mated. }
10. Qh5 Nc6 11. Nb5
{ We have a very strong initiative with ideas such as Nd6 and Bf4 followed by Ng5.   Note that after  11...cxd4  ,  12.Bf4  is forced because we must defend our pawn on  e5  . }
