[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "23. French Defense (1...e6) Mainlines"]
[Black "4...Be7 (6...O-O 3)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5 Be7
{ The last branch of the 3... Nf6-line! Black gets out of the pin by simply moving the bishop in between. This has been the most popular response by Black, and is thus the main tabiya of the 4. Bg5-line. }
5. e5
{ Black targets our pawn, so we must advance.  5.Bxf6  is possible, but harmless for Black. }
5... Nfd7 6. h4 { This pawn sacrifice known as the Alekhine-Chatard Attack. }
6... O-O
{ Was used by a 10-years younger Wesley So to defeat Jonny Hector in a fun game where the king ended up on f2 in the end, but it looks incredibly risky. }
7. Qg4 { Our queen joins the attack. } 7... f6
{ f6 is always on the table for a French-player, so it must be considered. } 8.
Bd3
{ An important move order! After 8. Nf3, Black can actually capture the hanging bishop. This is not the case now of course, due to 'The Greek Gift' on h7. }
8... Rf7
{ Black makes sure that we can no longer capture on e6 with a check, meaning that our pawn on e5 is under attack. Rf7 is also helpful in a defending manner too, as it frees the f8-square for the knight.   8...f5  This is an engine-move, as it makes absolutely no sense for a human being to go f7-f6 and then f6-f5 one move later.  9.Bxe7  The same reaction as against 7... f5.  9...Qxe7  10.Qg5  Qb4  Believe it or not, we have actually gotten a worse version! Our bishop on d3 blocks the rook, so we no longer protect the pawn on d4 when playing O-O-O. This is Black's point!  11.Nf3  Qxb2   11...c5  is met by  12.Qe7  .  12.Kd2+-  Our king looks exposed on d2, but it's actually quite safe. Black is underdeveloped and will soon face a brutal attack. }
9. Nf3
{ The logical way to defend the pawn.  9.exf6?  gives away most of our edge after  9...Nxf6  . Our pressure is greatly diminished. }
9... Nc6
{ Black accepts that c7-c5 won't be possible for a little while.   9...c5  Our center looks quite shaky, but we have the beautiful  10.Nxd5!  Which makes use of the awkward placement of Black's pieces.  10...exd5  11.e6±  And Black had to give the exchange in Matinian, N - Fedotov, N Moscow 2020, as  11...Rf8  loses to  12.Bh6  . }
10. exf6
{ Black's set-up with  Nc6  is not ideal, so here  exf6  is much stronger. I also looked at  10.Bg6!?  which is a hilarious move to make, but it turned out that the text was much better. }
10... Nxf6 11. Qg3
{ The character of the position has changed, so we're now playing against Black's hole on e5. }
11... Bd6 12. Ne5 Qf8 13. f4
{ White had a powerful initiative in the game Auryn - Ibermax Playchess.com INT 2007. I'm not sure whether or not it was played by humans or engines... }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "23. French Defense (1...e6) Mainlines"]
[Black "4...Be7 (6...c5)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5 Be7
{ The last branch of the 3... Nf6-line! Black gets out of the pin by simply moving the bishop in between. This has been the most popular response by Black, and is thus the main tabiya of the 4. Bg5-line. }
5. e5
{ Black targets our pawn, so we must advance. 5. Bxf6 is possible, but harmless for Black. }
5... Nfd7 6. h4 { This pawn sacrifice known as the Alekhine-Chatard Attack. }
6... c5 { Can be played, but I think it's too early due to the hole on d6. } 7.
Bxe7 Qxe7
{ Is a pretty interesting exchange sac which is not so easy to meet over the board if one doesn't know how to react. The objective evaluation says that it doesn't work, which isn't surprising. Let's see what happens if Black goes for this approach. }
8. Nb5
{ This is the obvious downside to playing c5 this early. Otherwise Black would have been completely fine. We're planning a knight jump to either c7 or d6. }
8... O-O
{ The only challenging approach is to give the exchange.  8...Kd8  is objectively stronger, but that doesn't mean much. Our reaction should be  9.c3!  Here, Black's best bet is to head into a terrible ending after  9...cxd4  10.cxd4  Qb4+  11.Qd2  Qxd2+  12.Kxd2  Nc6  13.f4  Ke7  14.Nf3  Piccolo, A - Cezario, M Brasil corr 1995. }
9. Nc7 cxd4
{ Black can also start with  9...Nc6  , when a transposition is reached after  10.Nxa8  cxd4  .   9...Nxe5  Has been tried, but I think it's not particularly challenging as it allows us to grab on d4 with the queen.  10.Nxa8  cxd4  11.Qxd4  Nbc6  12.Qd2+-  The fact that Black doesn't have such a big chunk of pawns in the center makes it easier to play White. Black has far from enough to justify the missing rook/exchange. White scores 75% from here, a decent sign. }
10. Nxa8 f6
{ Is one of those tricky-looking moves that do not work. It's quite easy to see ghosts with White, but the fact is that Black has nothing. }
11. Qxd4
{ As I pointed out under  9...Nxe5  , Black's counterplay won't pose a serious threat if we're allowed to take on  d4  . }
11... Nc6
{ 11...fxe5  12.Qe3  Where's the counterplay?  12...Nc6  13.O-O-O  Nf6  14.Nh3+-  We have consolidated and obtained a completely winning position. }
12. Qd2 { There's nothing wrong with other queen moves such as  12.Qe3  . }
12... fxe5 13. O-O-O
{ Black needs to achieve something quickly. We'll be completely winning if we're able to consolidate. }
13... Nf6 14. f3
{ Not a necessary move to make, but there's no reason to allow Black to play Ne4. }
14... Qd6 { Black covers c7 and gets ready to capture our knight with Bd7. }
15. h5
{ While Black is busy hunting for our knight, we should play on the kingside. }
15... Bd7 16. h6 { We have now obtained a nice outpost on g5. } 16... g6
{ So far we have been following Sax,G - Bilek,I Budapest 1973, and here I think the easiest path forward is to play }
17. Nh3 Rxa8 18. Bd3
{ Our material advantage is decisive as Black has far from sufficient counterplay. Our queen is headed to g5 and our rook to e1. Eventually we'll pressure Black's center with c4. }
*

