[White "23. French Defense (1...e6) Mainlines"]
[Black "4...Be7 (6...c5 2)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5 Be7
{ The last branch of the 3... Nf6-line! Black gets out of the pin by simply moving the bishop in between. This has been the most popular response by Black, and is thus the main tabiya of the 4. Bg5-line. }
5. e5
{ Black targets our pawn, so we must advance. 5. Bxf6 is possible, but harmless for Black. }
5... Nfd7 6. h4 { This pawn sacrifice known as the Alekhine-Chatard Attack. }
6... c5 { Can be played, but I think it's too early due to the hole on d6. } 7.
Bxe7 Qxe7
{ Is a pretty interesting exchange sac which is not so easy to meet over the board if one doesn't know how to react. The objective evaluation says that it doesn't work, which isn't surprising. Let's see what happens if Black goes for this approach. }
8. Nb5
{ This is the obvious downside to playing c5 this early. Otherwise Black would have been completely fine. We're planning a knight jump to either c7 or d6. }
8... O-O
{ The only challenging approach is to give the exchange.  8...Kd8  is objectively stronger, but that doesn't mean much. Our reaction should be  9.c3!  Here, Black's best bet is to head into a terrible ending after  9...cxd4  10.cxd4  Qb4+  11.Qd2  Qxd2+  12.Kxd2  Nc6  13.f4  Ke7  14.Nf3  Piccolo, A - Cezario, M Brasil corr 1995. }
9. Nc7 cxd4
{ Black can also start with  9...Nc6  , when a transposition is reached after  10.Nxa8  cxd4  .   9...Nxe5  Has been tried, but I think it's not particularly challenging as it allows us to grab on d4 with the queen.  10.Nxa8  cxd4  11.Qxd4  Nbc6  12.Qd2+-  The fact that Black doesn't have such a big chunk of pawns in the center makes it easier to play White. Black has far from enough to justify the missing rook/exchange. White scores 75% from here, a decent sign. }
10. Nxa8 Nc6 11. Nf3 Qb4+
{ Black's trickiest approach is to grab the pawn on b2. } 12. Qd2 Qxb2 13. Rc1
{ The right square for the rook! The reason why we shouldn't go  13.Rd1  like in Hunt, A - Short, N Bunratty 2011, is that we want to play  c3  which will either win the pawn on  d4  or trade queens. }
13... Nc5
{ 13...Ndxe5  makes things easy for us. A correspondence game went  14.Nxe5  Nxe5  15.c3  dxc3  16.Qxc3  Qxc3+  17.Rxc3  a6  18.Nb6  Nc6  19.Bxa6  bxa6  20.Rxc6  Bb7  21.Rc7  Ba8  22.Rh3  and Black resigned in Auzins, M - Unger, M ICCF corr 1990. }
14. c3 Qa3
{ The endgame after  14...Qxd2+  is winning for us. For example:  15.Nxd2  Nxe5  and now  16.Rh3!  d3  17.c4  . }
15. Nc7 { Our knight comes back to life, so Black is currently one rook down! }
15... a6 { Black prevents Nb5, like in the line   15...Ne4  16.Nb5  . } 16.
cxd4 { The pawn is finally ours! } 16... Ne4
{ Wins back the exchange, but Black has no counterplay. } 17. Qe3 Qa5+ 18. Nd2
Nxd2 19. Qxd2 Qxc7 20. Rh3
{ White had neutralized Black's play in Stubbs,M - Sisak,R ICCF email 2018. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "23. French Defense (1...e6) Mainlines"]
[Black "4...Be7 (6...c5 3)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5 Be7
{ The last branch of the 3... Nf6-line! Black gets out of the pin by simply moving the bishop in between. This has been the most popular response by Black, and is thus the main tabiya of the 4. Bg5-line. }
5. e5
{ Black targets our pawn, so we must advance. 5. Bxf6 is possible, but harmless for Black. }
5... Nfd7 6. h4 { This pawn sacrifice known as the Alekhine-Chatard Attack. }
6... c5 { Can be played, but I think it's too early due to the hole on d6. } 7.
Bxe7 Kxe7
{ Now that we saw that  7...Qxe7  doesn't really work, Black should take with the king! As strange as it looks, it might surprise you that Black's king is safer than what it looks on  e7  . }
8. Qd2
{ I am bit surprised by the fact that this natural move hasn't been played more often. Most games have continued with  8.f4  , and here I honestly think Black is okay after  8...cxd4  9.Qxd4  Qb6  10.Qxb6  Nxb6  like in Nunn, J - Seirawan, Y Cannes 1992. }
8... Nc6
{ Black protects the queen, so he can now answer 9. Qg5+ with 9... Kf8.   8...cxd4?  Is a blunder due to  9.Qg5+  And Black loses the valuable pawn on g7.  9...Ke8  10.Qxg7  Rf8  Things wouldn't have been so bad, if it wasn't for  11.Nb5+-  And the knight heads to d6. }
9. dxc5 { Black has to decide which pawn to take. } 9... Ndxe5
{ The right pawn to grab, as the e5-pawn contributed well to our attack.   9...Nxc5?  Is not the right pawn to take.  10.O-O-O  h6  Black takes control over the square on g5.  11.h5  Has a pretty neat idea to it. We're planning to use the 4h rank for our rook on h1 via h4.  11...a6  12.Nf3  b5  13.Rh4+-  Black's position is in dire straits due to the exposed king. }
10. O-O-O Qa5
{ Most games I found continued with this move, but it's not particularly challenging as we're allowed to carry out our plan. }
11. f4 Nd7 12. Bb5
{ Black has to spend time guarding our threat of playing Bxc6 followed by Nxd5+, winning the queen.   12.f5  was too early in Gusain, H - Kamble, V Tirupati 2012, as Black has time to 'castle' with  12...Rd8  followed by  Kf8  . }
12... Kf8 13. f5 Nxc5 14. Nf3
{ Black's terrible lack of king safety makes the position hopeless. } *

