[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "23. French Defense (1...e6) Mainlines"]
[Black "4...Be7 (6...h6)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5 Be7
{ The last branch of the 3... Nf6-line! Black gets out of the pin by simply moving the bishop in between. This has been the most popular response by Black, and is thus the main tabiya of the 4. Bg5-line. }
5. e5
{ Black targets our pawn, so we must advance. 5. Bxf6 is possible, but harmless for Black. }
5... Nfd7 6. h4 { This pawn sacrifice known as the Alekhine-Chatard Attack. }
6... h6
{ Black forces us to take the bishop on e7. Having h4 and h6 included gives us a favorable version of 5. Bxe7. }
7. Bxe7 Qxe7 8. f4
{ A thematic move. The point is to protect the pawn on e5, as Black can easily remove our pawn from d4 by playing c5. By playing f4, we are also hoping to some day break through with f5, but certain circumstances are required in order for this to work. }
8... a6
{ Black must play a6 before playing c5, otherwise we will play Nb5 and jump to d6. a6 is also useful in the sense that it prepares a queenside expansion with b5. }
9. Nf3 c5 10. Qd2 Nc6 { 10...b5  doesn't make a difference. } 11. Ne2
{ Our knight does little on c3 now that Black controls e4 and b5, so it makes to move it to another square. The knight has several functions on e2. First of all, it allows us to support our pawn chain with c3. Secondly, a thematic idea is to play dxc5 followed by Ned4, when the knight will support our plan of playing f5. The knight can also head to the kingside via g3. }
11... b5
{ Black needs counterplay on the queenside so this is a sensible approach.  11...cxd4  has also been tried, but it's not very challenging. Remember what I said about  dxc5  being a thematic idea! After  12.Nexd4  O-O  13.O-O-O  Nc5  14.Qe3  Bd7  15.g4  Ne4  16.Bd3  White already had a decisive advantage in Perez Candelario, M - Domingo Nunez, R Linares 2018. }
12. g4
{ This position has been discussed quite a lot, so I feel it's appropriate to call it the main tabiya of the 6... h6-variation. My verdict is that it looks very dangerous for Black @@StartBracket@@but I'm obviously biased@@EndBracket@@. }
12... h5
{ Black sometimes tries to stop our play on the kingside. It's important that we always react with }
13. gxh5
{ Opening the g-file. Black has stopped our pawn breaks for now, but we can easily achieve h4-h5 by playing Bh3-Bg4 later. }
13... Rxh5 14. O-O-O Bb7
{ Was a position that was reached in Ojeda,J - Pisani,C ICCF email 2016. The engines have improved a lot, so here I was able to find an excellent improvement in }
15. Bh3
{ As I already mentioned, we're planning to play Bg4 followed by h5. However, there's more to this move than what meets the eye... }
15... O-O-O { And now we have the fantastic } 16. f5
{ Nf4 is now coming with devastating effect. Black's pawn chain is falling apart. }
16... cxd4 17. Nf4 Rh6
{ Defends the pawn on e6, but the rook on h6 can be targeted by our queen. }
18. f6 Qf8 { 18...gxf6  loses to  19.Nxe6  . } 19. Bxe6
{ We're breaking through. } 19... gxf6 20. Bxd7+ Kxd7
{ 20...Rxd7  is even worse after  21.e6  . } 21. Nd3
{ Black has a hopeless position. } *

