{ The last branch of the 3... Nf6-line! Black gets out of the pin by simply moving the bishop in between. This has been the most popular response by Black, and is thus the main tabiya of the 4. Bg5-line. }
5. e5
{ Black targets our pawn, so we must advance. 5. Bxf6 is possible, but harmless for Black. }
5... Nfd7 6. h4 { This pawn sacrifice known as the Alekhine-Chatard Attack. }
6... h6
{ Black forces us to take the bishop on e7. Having h4 and h6 included gives us a favorable version of 5. Bxe7. }
7. Bxe7 Qxe7 8. f4
{ A thematic move. The point is to protect the pawn on e5, as Black can easily remove our pawn from d4 by playing c5. By playing f4, we are also hoping to some day break through with f5, but certain circumstances are required in order for this to work. }
