{ This position has been discussed quite a lot, so I feel it's appropriate to call it the main tabiya of the 6... h6-variation. My verdict is that it looks very dangerous for Black @@StartBracket@@but I'm obviously biased@@EndBracket@@. }
12... Bb7
{ A common plan Black chooses is to castle queenside due to our advanced kingside pawns. }
13. O-O-O
{ Our kingside plans do not change, despite the fact that Black will castle queenside. }
13... O-O-O
{ I am bit surprised by the fact that this is a novelty @@StartBracket@@at least in my online database@@EndBracket@@. The reason is that Black should castle until our initiative on the kingside becomes too much to handle. I found two very nice examples in my base that greatly showed how quickly things can go wrong for Black.   13...Rc8  was tried in a clash between two youngsters, but all it does is to prevent Black from castling and give us additional time. After  14.Kb1  f6  15.h5  cxd4  16.Nh4  Qc5  17.Ng6  Rg8  18.Bh3  Rc7  19.Rhe1  White was already well on his way to victory in Quirhuayo Chumbe, G - Nakada, A Montevideo 2016.13...  c4  is a badly executed plan of attack @@StartBracket@@compare it to the Main Line@@EndBracket@@. After  14.f5  b4  15.Nf4  Rg8  16.g5  Nb6  17.fxe6  fxe6  18.Bh3  White was completely winning in Popov, I - Rathnakaran, K Taleigao 2018. }
14. Kb1 Kb8 15. dxc5 { Our idea of placing the knight on d4 kicks in. } 15...
Nxc5 16. Ned4 Nxd4 17. Nxd4 Ne4 18. Qe1
{ This is a standard scenario in these positions. We get the square on d4 while Black gets the square on e4. Black plans to later battle our center with f6 to purge some of our pressure. }
18... Rc8
{ 18...f6?  right away would be an error due to  19.a4!  The neat point is that after  19...bxa4  ,  20.Bxa6!  comes. }
19. Bd3 f6 20. exf6 Qxf6 21. Qe3
{ We're slightly better due to our space advantage and Black's hanging pawn on e6. Black will get an isolated pawn the day he decides to go for e5. Black's bishop is also not the best, although it watches over the pawns. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "23. French Defense (1...e6) Mainlines"]
[Black "4...Be7 (6...h6 3)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5 Be7
{ The last branch of the 3... Nf6-line! Black gets out of the pin by simply moving the bishop in between. This has been the most popular response by Black, and is thus the main tabiya of the 4. Bg5-line. }
5. e5
{ Black targets our pawn, so we must advance. 5. Bxf6 is possible, but harmless for Black. }
5... Nfd7 6. h4 { This pawn sacrifice known as the Alekhine-Chatard Attack. }
6... h6
{ Black forces us to take the bishop on e7. Having h4 and h6 included gives us a favorable version of 5. Bxe7. }
7. Bxe7 Qxe7 8. f4
{ A thematic move. The point is to protect the pawn on e5, as Black can easily remove our pawn from d4 by playing c5. By playing f4, we are also hoping to some day break through with f5, but certain circumstances are required in order for this to work. }
8... a6
{ Black must play a6 before playing c5, otherwise we will play Nb5 and jump to d6. a6 is also useful in the sense that it prepares a queenside expansion with b5. }
9. Nf3 c5 10. Qd2 Nc6 11. Ne2
{ Our knight does little on c3 now that Black controls e4 and b5, so it makes to move it to another square. The knight has several functions on e2. First of all, it allows us to support our pawn chain with c3. Secondly, a thematic idea is to play dxc5 followed by Ned4, when the knight will support our plan of playing f5. The knight can also head to the kingside via g3. }
11... b5 12. g4
{ This position has been discussed quite a lot, so I feel it's appropriate to call it the main tabiya of the 6... h6-variation. My verdict is that it looks very dangerous for Black @@StartBracket@@but I'm obviously biased@@EndBracket@@. }
12... b4
{ I think Black's best try is to start an attack. The reason why  12...c4  is less accurate as we can't counterattack with f5 as Black still has cxd4 followed by capturing on e5. }
13. O-O-O
{ I discovered eventually that castling queenside was the way to go, intending f5 next. 13. dxc5 The engine is initially quite optimistic about   13.dxc5  , hence why it's played in almost every single Correspondence game I found. Apparently Black is doing okay, but for a human being it's going to be very tough. I want to share with you the most recent Correspondence game, as it was a really fun ride.  13...Nxc5  14.Ned4  Nxd4  15.Nxd4  a5  16.O-O-O  O-O  The race begins! Black attacks on the queenside and we attack on the kingside. Who's first? Well as a matter of fact, both! Take a look at what happens next!  Apparently, 16... Ne4 is decent as well, played in Gomila Marti,S - Cros Goma, A ICCF email 2016. White won the game on time, but the final positional was even.  17.Qe3  Qc7  18.Nb5  Qc6  19.Nd4  Qc7  20.h5  a4  Both sides are attacking at great velocity. The objective evaluation is dead even - 0.00!  21.Nb5  Qb6  22.Kb1  a3  23.g5  hxg5  24.h6  g6  25.fxg5  axb2  26.Qf2  It looks like White is very close to breaking through, as there's an entry on f6.  26...f5!  A fantastic way to dodge the threat.  27.gxf6  Qa5  28.a3  bxa3  29.Ka2  Close, but no cigar for Black either!  29...Ne4  30.Qg2  Kh7  31.Bd3  Qb4  32.Rhg1  Rg8  33.f7  White wins a rook, but not the game!  33...Ba6  34.fxg8Q+  Rxg8  35.Bxe4  Bxb5  36.Bxg6+  Kh8  Black has sufficient counterplay and the following line is forced:  37.Rd3  Bxd3  38.cxd3  Qc5  39.h7  Rxg6!  40.Qxg6  b1Q+ The players agreed to a draw in Komarica, B -Bussom, A ICCF email 2019, due to the imminent threefold. It's not obvious to me to be completely honest, but with an engine it won't be difficult to find the right way to check the white king. What a game! }
13... c4
{ Attack is the best defense!   13...O-O ?  Would obviously be suicidal due to our advanced pawns.  14.f5  cxd4  15.f6  Black's walls will break.  15...gxf6  16.exf6  Qxf6  17.Nexd4+-  Black is about to get smoked on the kingside. }
14. f5 c3
{ The most challenging move.   14...Nb6  Let's see what happens if Black's knight joins the attack.  15.Qf4  In order for us to make progress on the kingside, we must play f6.  15...a5  16.f6  Qf8   We have been following Kuosmanen, K - Cubides, A ICCF email 2015. Instead of  17.fxg7  , I suggest  17.g5  We're opening Black's camp with g6.  17...a4  18.g6!  There's no time to lose!  18...fxg6  19.Rg1  c3  20.Rxg6  cxb2+  21.Kb1±  The position is still quite complicated, but for now our attack looks much stronger than Black's. }
15. Qf4
{ I am not such a big fan of  15.bxc3  Nb6  16.Qf4  bxc3  17.Nxc3  Qa3+  18.Kd2  although the engine assures me that we're doing well. }
15... a5
{ Black's pawns are running quickly towards our king.   15...Nb6?  Is a logical way to continue the attack, but it just loses.  16.f6  Qf8  17.b3  Black is not getting through, as we can meet  17...a5  With  18.a4+-  Black is stopped from playing a4 due to the hanging pawn on c3 if Black goes bxa3.   15...cxb2+  Is nothing to fear  16.Kxb2±  Our king looks a bit exposed on b2, but Black's forces are too far away to cause any trouble. Our attack on the other hand is coming very quickly. }
16. g5 { We can't just sit there and wait! } 16... exf5
{ Is not Black's best move, but the refutation is not so easy to find.  16...hxg5  is a better try, when the play is rather tricky. I analyzed:  17.Nxg5  cxb2+  18.Kxb2  a4  19.Ka1  It looks dangerous, but our king is fully protected at the moment on  a1  . The line continues:  19...Rb8  20.fxe6  fxe6  21.Qc1  Na5  22.Nf4  b3  23.cxb3  axb3  24.Ng6  Qb4  25.Qd2  Qxd2  26.Rxd2  bxa2  27.Kxa2  Rh6  28.h5  . The storm has settled and we are left with an ending which looks very promising for us! A really fun line to analyze! }
17. gxh6
{ We must open the position in order to create something.  17.Ng3  is super natural, but after Black's  17...Nf8  , we don't have anything. }
17... gxh6 { 17...Rxh6  is met by  18.Rg1  . } 18. Ng3 Nf8
{ A huge difference compared to  17.Ng3  , as the g-file is completely open. }
19. Bb5 Qb7 { And now we have a fantastic way to break through with } 20. e6
{ Black's king is naked. } 20... Nxe6
{ Is met by   20...fxe6  There are many ways to win, perhaps the cleanest way is to play  21.Nxf5  exf5  22.Bxc6+  Qxc6  23.Qe5+  As we win material.   20...Qxb5  Loses to  21.exf7+  Kxf7  22.Nxf5+-  With every file being open there's no way Black will make it out alive. }
21. Qe5
{ I can't get over the small margins in chess. It really is crucial that the pawn stands on h6 instead of g7 @@StartBracket@@yeah this is actually why 17. Ng3 doesn't work@@EndBracket@@. }
21... Qxb5 { Black has to give the exchange. } 22. Qxh8+ Kd7 23. Ne5+ Nxe5 24.
Qxe5 { Our extra material gives us a decisive advantage. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "23. French Defense (1...e6) Mainlines"]
[Black "4...Be7 (6...h6 4)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5 Be7
{ The last branch of the 3... Nf6-line! Black gets out of the pin by simply moving the bishop in between. This has been the most popular response by Black, and is thus the main tabiya of the 4. Bg5-line. }
5. e5
{ Black targets our pawn, so we must advance. 5. Bxf6 is possible, but harmless for Black. }
5... Nfd7 6. h4 { This pawn sacrifice known as the Alekhine-Chatard Attack. }
6... h6
{ Black forces us to take the bishop on e7. Having h4 and h6 included gives us a favorable version of 5. Bxe7. }
7. Bxe7 Qxe7 8. f4
{ A thematic move. The point is to protect the pawn on e5, as Black can easily remove our pawn from d4 by playing c5. By playing f4, we are also hoping to some day break through with f5, but certain circumstances are required in order for this to work. }
8... a6
{ Black must play a6 before playing c5, otherwise we will play Nb5 and jump to d6. a6 is also useful in the sense that it prepares a queenside expansion with b5. }
9. Nf3 c5 10. Qd2 Nc6 11. Ne2
{ Our knight does little on c3 now that Black controls e4 and b5, so it makes to move it to another square. The knight has several functions on e2. First of all, it allows us to support our pawn chain with c3. Secondly, a thematic idea is to play dxc5 followed by Ned4, when the knight will support our plan of playing f5. The knight can also head to the kingside via g3. }
11... b5 12. g4
{ This position has been discussed quite a lot, so I feel it's appropriate to call it the main tabiya of the 6... h6-variation. My verdict is that it looks very dangerous for Black @@StartBracket@@but I'm obviously biased@@EndBracket@@. }
12... Nb6
{ It's not surprising that this is the move seen in human games. Black's knight jumps to a better square and may even jump further to c4, depending on how we react. }
13. a3
{ This move was played in a couple of extremely instructive Correspondence games I found. What a3 does is that it limits Black's queenside play by taking control over b4.   13.Ng3  has been the chosen approach, but Black is doing okay after  13...Bb7  14.O-O-O  O-O-O  15.Kb1  Kb8  16.Nh5  Rhg8  . This position has appeared in Razumikhin, A - Sodomski, A ICCF email 2018, Roehl Montes, J - Cubides, A ICCF email 2017 & Postupa, P - Dorer, M ICCF email 2018. My claim that Black is doing fine is backed by the fact that all games were drawn. }
13... Bb7
{ 13...Nc4!?  Is nothing to worry about, because we will push that annoying knight back sooner or later with b3.  14.Qc1  14...cxd4  Is the most logical way for Black to play.  15.Nexd4  Bb7  It's time to put the horse back in the stable!  16.b3  Nb6  17.Qe3  Black has achieved nothing by the jump to c4.  17...Nd7  18.h5±  We have a fantastic position as we control both sides of the board. }
14. b3
{ White's play is simple - let's control the entire board! It's going to be incredibly difficult for Black to find something to do, as we will see in the Correspondence games. }
14... Nd7
{ The point behind this move is to meet dxc5 with Nxc5.   14...Rc8  Black hopes to achieve something on the queenside.  15.dxc5  Qxc5  16.Ned4  This thematic plan occurs over and over, so remember it! Note how we defend everything with the knight on d4. What exactly can Black do in the c-file?  16...Qe7  17.Qe3  Nd7  The knight has found a new destination, namely the e4-square via c5.  18.b4!  There's no need to allow Black to carry out that plan, despite the fact that Black gets a square on c4 for the knight.  18...Nb6  Black's problem is that we are much faster.  19.f5!  Na4   A strange move, but  19...Nc4  is no better. After  20.Bxc4  dxc4  21.O-O-O  , our strong initiative on the kingside gives us a winning position.  20.Bd3  Kd8  21.O-O-O  White was completely dominating in Yeo, G - Merkuriev, V ICCF email 2019. I leave you to enjoy the rest of the game, but the trainables stop here.  21...Kc7  22.f6  gxf6  23.Nxc6  Bxc6  24.exf6  Qd6  25.Qa7+  Bb7  26.Qd4  Rcf8  27.Ne5  Nb6  28.g5  Nd7  29.Nxd7  Kxd7  30.g6  fxg6  31.Bxg6  Kc7  32.f7  e5  33.Qc3+  Bc6  34.Rhg1  d4  35.Qg3  Rd8  36.Rde1  Rhf8  37.Qxe5+-  A stunning victory by White! }
15. h5 { White fixes the pawn structure and prevents Black from playing h5. }
15... O-O-O 16. c3
{ A clever move. Black will no longer get the c5-square, because we can answer with cxd4. }
16... Kb8 17. Bg2 Rhg8 18. g5
{ White is dominating both sides of the board! Black can't do much. Yeo, G -Loeschnauer, R ICCF email 2018. I have attached the game, so you can click your way through it.  18...Rdf8  19.Rh3  Na5  20.Rb1  Rc8  21.Kf2  Rh8  22.gxh6  gxh6  23.f5  cxd4  24.cxd4  Qxa3  25.Rg3  Rc7  26.Bh3  exf5  27.Bxf5  Bc8  28.Qf4  Qf8  29.Rc1  Rxc1  30.Nxc1  Kb7  31.Nh4  Nc6  32.Bh3  Nb6  33.Bxc8+  Nxc8  34.Nd3  N8e7  35.Nc5+  Ka7  36.b4  a5  37.bxa5  Qd8  38.Nf5  Nxf5  39.Qxf5  Ka8  40.Qf4+-  @@StartSquare@@The resignation might look premature, but the engine shows an evaluation as high as  +3. }
