[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "23. French Defense (1...e6) Mainlines"]
[Black "4...Be7 (6...a6)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5 Be7
{ The last branch of the 3... Nf6-line! Black gets out of the pin by simply moving the bishop in between. This has been the most popular response by Black, and is thus the main tabiya of the 4. Bg5-line. }
5. e5
{ Black targets our pawn, so we must advance. 5. Bxf6 is possible, but harmless for Black. }
5... Nfd7 6. h4 { This pawn sacrifice known as the Alekhine-Chatard Attack. }
6... a6
{ We have finally arrived to the last sideline Black has in his arsenal. This is a very standard way of playing. Black covers the b5-square and is thus set to attack our center with c5 next. }
7. Qg4
{ The only way to disturb Black's plans as we're threatening Qxg7. Black has tried to dodge this threat in a number of ways: }
7... g6
{ Weakens the dark squares too much.   7...c5?  Ignoring our threat is a bad idea.  8.Bxe7  Qxe7  9.Qxg7  Rf8  9... Qf8 is the lesser evil, but that is an endgame with a clean pawn down!  10.dxc5  Black has absolutely no compensation for the pawn, for example:  10...Nc6  11.Nf3  Qxc5  12.Bd3  Qb4  13.O-O-O  Ndxe5  Black regains the pawn, but the open file leaves the king extremely vulnerable. 13... Nc5 was no better in Sengupta, D - Rathnakaran,K Panaji 2012, when White's advantage was sky high after 14. h5 Bd7 15. Rh4 Qa5 16. Bxh7.  14.Nxe5  Qf4+  15.Kb1  Qxe5  16.Qh6+-  Black has to worry about a rook coming to e1 followed by a capture on d5. We can also take on h7 whenever we want, when our h-pawn will become a monster.   7...Rg8?  Played by a strong Indian GM, but it's doesn't impress at all.  8.Bd3  g6  And now White achieved a very nice set-up with  9.Nce2  Always a thematic idea in these positions!  9...c5  10.c3  Nc6  GM Erigaisi has played this twice.  11.Nf3+-  Somehow did neither of his opponents play this natural move. This is the very definition of a French-gone-wrong. }
8. Qf4 { Our queen is well placed on f4 where it protects our pawn on e5. }
8... c5 9. dxc5 Nc6 10. Nf3
{ h5 is now an unpleasant threat, so Black should play h5 himself. } 10... h5
{ Not a fun move to make as it gives us an outpost on g5. } 11. Bxe7 Qxe7 12.
Na4 { Looks very strong, since after } 12... Nxc5 13. Nxc5 Qxc5 14. c3
{ Black is positionally lost due to the horrendous weaknesses on the dark squares. }
*

