1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5 Be7
{ The last branch of the 3... Nf6-line! Black gets out of the pin by simply moving the bishop in between. This has been the most popular response by Black, and is thus the main tabiya of the 4. Bg5-line. }
5. e5
{ Black targets our pawn, so we must advance. 5. Bxf6 is possible, but harmless for Black. }
5... Nfd7 6. h4 { This pawn sacrifice known as the Alekhine-Chatard Attack. }
6... a6
{ We have finally arrived to the last sideline Black has in his arsenal. This is a very standard way of playing. Black covers the b5-square and is thus set to attack our center with c5 next. }
7. Qg4
{ The only way to disturb Black's plans as we're threatening Qxg7. Black has tried to dodge this threat in a number of ways: }
7... f5
{ Has been tried by some strong players, but it's not a good move due to   7...f6?!  This is not too different from 6... f6.  8.Qh5+  8... g6 gives us the same fantastic ending we saw in the line with 6... f6.  8...Kf8  9.exf6  Nxf6  10.Qf3  Black has gotten rid of our strong center, but pays with a heavy prize. The king on f8 is very vulnerable.  10...c5  11.dxc5  Nc6  12.O-O-O  ±  White had a very promising position in Fernandez Barrera,V - Larino Nieto,D La Roda 2008. There are ideas in the air such as Nh3-Nf4, Na4-Nb6 and Ne4. }
8. Qh5+ { When Black gets huge problems with his king. } 8... g6 9. Qh6 Bxg5
10. hxg5
{ Nge2-Nf4 is coming very quickly, Black doesn't have a good way to meet this idea. }
10... Qe7 11. Nge2 c5
{ Unfortunately for Black, this standard plan in the French fails tactically.   11...Nf8  Black defends for the time being, but sooner or later we'll crash through.  12.Nf4  c6  13.O-O-O  +-  Black is busted as he can't do anything about our plan of opening the position with g4. }
12. Nf4 { The knight sac on d5 is crushing. } 12... Nf8 13. Ncxd5
{ Black can resign as there's no way to avoid a decisive loss of material. } *

