[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "23. French Defense (1...e6) Mainlines"]
[Black "4...Be7 (6...a6 6)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5 Be7
{ The last branch of the 3... Nf6-line! Black gets out of the pin by simply moving the bishop in between. This has been the most popular response by Black, and is thus the main tabiya of the 4. Bg5-line. }
5. e5
{ Black targets our pawn, so we must advance. 5. Bxf6 is possible, but harmless for Black. }
5... Nfd7 6. h4 { This pawn sacrifice known as the Alekhine-Chatard Attack. }
6... a6
{ We have finally arrived to the last sideline Black has in his arsenal. This is a very standard way of playing. Black covers the b5-square and is thus set to attack our center with c5 next. }
7. Qg4
{ The only way to disturb Black's plans as we're threatening Qxg7. Black has tried to dodge this threat in a number of ways: }
7... Bxg5
{ After a plethora of options, we have arrived to Black's most played move. }
8. hxg5 c5
{ Black has achieved c5 right away, while we have obtained an open h-file. } 9.
dxc5
{ Hopefully you're not surprised that this is our reaction! Black can now take on e5 right away or develop the knight to c6 first. }
9... Nxe5 10. Qg3 Nbc6 11. O-O-O
{ Now that our king is safe, we're all set to start an attack. My engine gives more than +2 here! Quite crazy... White scores almost 80% here, so I guess it could be true... }
11... Qa5 12. f4 { What else? } 12... Ng6
{ 12...Nd7  You remember how I said that a certain tactic tends to appear in these positions? Well...  13.g6!  Is now very strong with the same point  13...fxg6  14.Rxh7+-  Black is in dire straits. }
13. f5 { Keeping the momentum! } 13... Nge7
{ 13...Nge5  loses in many different ways, for example,  14.g6  fxg6  15.fxg6  h6  16.Rh5!  Nd7  17.Qe3  Nf6  18.Rhxd5  . }
14. f6 { Black has given us f4-f5-f6 with a tempo! } 14... gxf6 15. gxf6 Nf5
{ And here we must play } 16. Qe1 { The point is that we can play } 16... d4
17. Nd5 { As the queen on e1 pins the e6-pawn. } 17... Qxa2
{ The only practical chance.  17...Rb8  18.Qxa5  Nxa5  19.Nb6  is just dreadful for Black. }
18. Nc7+ Kd8 19. Nxa8 Qa1+
{ Black has some 'blitz-compensation' for the missing rook, but by being cautious we should easily handle it. }
20. Kd2 Qa5+
{ 20...Qxb2  is met by the neat  21.Rh3  , when Black's checks disappear. } 21.
c3
{ 21.Ke2?  makes our king too vulnerable after  21...Qxc5  , so in that position things are far from clear. }
21... e5
{ 21...Ne3  Looks scary, but we have  22.Qg3!  Which puts an end to Black's play rather quickly.  22...Bd7   22...Nxd1  loses to  23.Qd6+  Bd7  24.Nb6  .  23.Nf3  Black has nothing.  23...Nxd1  And here the easiest way to win is  24.Nxd4!  When  24...Nxd4  Loses to  25.Qb8+  Bc8  26.Qd6+  Bd7  27.Nb6+-  And Black is mated. }
22. Nf3 Qa2 23. Rb1
{ We have everything under control. There's not enough punch in Black's attack. }
23... dxc3+ 24. Kxc3 Be6 25. Qd1+ Nfd4 26. Ra1 Qd5 27. b4
{ Black's attack has faded into nothing, so we're completely winning. } *

