1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5 Be7 5. e5 Nfd7 6. h4 Bxg5
{ This time on the menu of our 1. e4 restaurant is the Alekhine- Chatard Attack Accepted. A courageous choice, but objectively the right one. That being said, the path forward is very narrow for Black... One has to be incredibly well prepared, hence why 4... dxe4 has taken more and more over. }
7. hxg5 Qxg5 8. Nh3
{ Black has to make an incredibly important decision on where to place the queen. }
8... Qd8
{ Is just a bad version of  8...Qe7  . Why would you go to  d8  instead of  e7?  It doesn't make sense... Anyway, our reaction is }
9. Qg4 { The standard reaction, targeting the pawn on g7 with a tempo. } 9...
g6 10. Ng5 h5
{ Black dodges out threats for now, but g6 and h5 are serious concessions. The h5-pawn can eventually be targeted by g4, while we could also attack the pawn on f7 by playing for example O-O-O-Rd3-Rf3. }
11. Qg3 Nf8 12. O-O-O { We're ready to bring our rook to the party! } 12... c6
{ This makes things even easier, but there's seriously no defense. For example:  12...Qe7  13.Rd3  Nh7  14.Rxh5!!  A beautiful tactic.  14...gxh5  15.Nxh7  Nd7  16.Qg7  and White is winning. }
13. Rd3 { The rook swing to f3 decides the game. } 13... Nh7 14. Rxh5 { BOOM! }
14... gxh5 15. Nxf7
{ Black had enough and resigned in Alberny, M - McLaughlin, E ICCF email 2018, because of  15...Kxf7  16.Rf3+  Ke8  17.Qg6+  Kd7  18.Rf7  . }
