[White "23. French Defense (1...e6) Mainlines"]
[Black "4...Be7 (6...Bxg5 8...Qh6)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5 Be7 5. e5 Nfd7 6. h4 Bxg5
{ This time on the menu of our 1. e4 restaurant is the Alekhine- Chatard Attack Accepted. A courageous choice, but objectively the right one. That being said, the path forward is very narrow for Black... One has to be incredibly well prepared, hence why 4... dxe4 has taken more and more over. }
7. hxg5 Qxg5 8. Nh3
{ Black has to make an incredibly important decision on where to place the queen. }
8... Qh6
{ This move is objectively quite poor, but OTB I don't think it's so bad due to the fact that there's only one path that gives White a huge advantage. }
9. Nb5
{ We're making use of the fact that Black's queen is completely absent from the queenside.  9.Qg4  is the second best move, but less strong here because Black protects the g7-pawn with the queen.  9.g3  is White's most common move. It's not inaccurate as it allows  9...a6  , and now there are no longer jumps to  b5  . After  10.f4  g6  11.Qf3  Qf8  Black is fine, like in Simmelink, J - Alfredo ICCF email 2010. }
9... Na6
{ Black's knight is forced on the rim. It's also worth mentioning that c5 will be a lot less effective here as there's no knight on c6 that pressures the pawn on d4, while we can also easily keep our pawn chain intact with c3. }
10. g3
{ It's now time to play g3! The idea is to play Qf3 or Bg2 followed by moving our knight so we can castle queenside. }
10... f6
{ Black applies some pressure on our center, while leaving some room for the vulnerable lady on h6. }
11. Qe2
{ It's important that we maintain our powerful center.   Ignoring the pawn with  11.Bg2?  gave Black a great game in Szava, M - Peterka, J LSS email 2010, after  11...fxe5  12.Nf4  Qf6  .   11.exf6  Nxf6  is also perfectly fine for Black. }
11... fxe5
{ 11...O-O  Has been tried in three games, when Black has scored 0/3...  12.Bg2  Qg6  13.Nf4  Qf7  14.O-O-O  +-  This must be one of the worst French-positions I have seen for Black. I will leave a fantastic Correspondence game I found, but the trainables stop here!  14...Nb6  15.Rxh7!  A fantastic shot that's justified tactically.  15...Kxh7  16.Rh1+  Kg8  17.Qg4  A knight is heading to g6.  17...Qe8  18.Ng6  Bd7  19.Nc3  There's no need to make a check on h8, yet. White has a lot of time.  19...Bc6  20.Ne2  fxe5  21.Rh8+  It's finally time.  21...Kf7  22.Rh7  The engine move, but obviously 22. Rxf8+ wins too.  22...Rg8  23.Bh3  Black has no good way to meet the threat Nxe5 followed by Qxe6.  23...Nc4  24.b3  Qd7  25.bxc4  White regains some of the missing material, so from here it's incredibly easy:  25...Ke8  26.Nxe5  Qe7  27.Nf4  Kd8  28.Nxe6+  Kc8  29.Nf8+  Kd8  30.Nfg6  Bd7  31.Qf3  Qb4  32.a3  Qe1+  33.Kb2  c6  34.Qf7  Kc7  35.Nxd7  Black resigned in Sherwood,R -Gallimore,C ICCF email 2018, but in all honesty he could have resigned 20 moves ago. }
12. dxe5 Ndc5 { Is another approach Black can take. } 13. Bg2 g6
{ Black's queen can now escape to g7 if necessary. } 14. b4
{ Black's knight is now pushed to the unattractive square on e4 now that our bishop controls e4.   14.O-O?  is logical, but Black's position is playable after  14...Bd7  . }
14... Na4 15. c4 { Attacking Black's center. } 15... dxc4 16. Qxc4
{ My engine prefers to stay calm with  16.a3  , but this move is more than good enough. }
16... Qg7 17. f4
{ White is completely dominating. Black didn't last long and resigned after  17...Nb6  18.Qb3  h6  19.Nd4  Qe7  20.a3  O-O  21.f5  in Van Tricht, M - Bolignano, G ICCF email 2014. }
