[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5 Be7 5. e5 Nfd7 6. h4 Bxg5
{ This time on the menu of our 1. e4 restaurant is the Alekhine- Chatard Attack Accepted. A courageous choice, but objectively the right one. That being said, the path forward is very narrow for Black... One has to be incredibly well prepared, hence why 4... dxe4 has taken more and more over. }
7. hxg5 Qxg5 8. Nh3
{ Black has to make an incredibly important decision on where to place the queen. }
8... Qe7
{ This is by far the most logical and popular move. Unfortunately for Black, it is a bad one. }
9. Qg4
{ There's no reason why we shouldn't play this move as we gain a tempo on Black's g7-pawn while developing the queen.  9.Nf4  has been more common, but it doesn't seem very dangerous for Black. The unusual  9...c5!?  seems to be quite good, with exciting play after  10.Nb5  Kd8!  The standard  9...Nc6  is also decent, when the game can continue  10.Qd2  Nf8  like in Engelhard, C - Gaujens, A ICCF email 2015.  10.Qg4  has been more common, but apparently Black can just grab the pawn on  d4  . The game heads from there in a long forced sequence which is a draw. Tropf, P - Snowden, E ICCF email 2010. }
9... Kf8 { Can be played, but it's not very challenging. } 10. f4
{ We'll keep it simple and reinforce our powerful center. } 10... a6
{ 10...c5?!  Is seldom a good idea without a6.  11.Ng5  h6  12.Nb5+-  The knight heads to d6/c7 next, with a crushing position. }
11. Bd3 c5
{ Is a logical way for Black to play, but I found a beautiful way to refute it. }
12. Ng5 h6 { Otherwise we can just take the pawn on h7. } 13. Nxf7
{ The point! This tactic is justified tactically, as Black's king is insanely vulnerable. }
13... Qxf7 14. Bg6
{ An important move. We're forcing Black's queen away, so we can open the f-file with f5. }
14... Qe7 15. f5 Nc6 16. O-O
{ We need to be fast in our attack. After  16.fxe6?  Black is suddenly fine after  16...Ndxe5  17.dxe5  Bxe6  , when our play has suddenly vanished. }
16... Kg8 { It looks like Black is out of the woods, but we have } 17. f6
{ Which breaks down Black's defense. } 17... gxf6 18. Bh5+ Qg7
{ 18...Kf8  loses to  19.exf6  followed by  Qg6  . } 19. Qxe6+ Kh7 20. Qf5+ Kg8
21. exf6
{ Black has to give away the piece, so the hope of saving the game is all gone. }
