1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5 Be7 5. e5 Nfd7 6. h4 Bxg5
{ This time on the menu of our 1. e4 restaurant is the Alekhine- Chatard Attack Accepted. A courageous choice, but objectively the right one. That being said, the path forward is very narrow for Black... One has to be incredibly well prepared, hence why 4... dxe4 has taken more and more over. }
7. hxg5 Qxg5 8. Nh3
{ Black has to make an incredibly important decision on where to place the queen. }
8... Qe7
{ This is by far the most logical and popular move. Unfortunately for Black, it is a bad one. }
9. Qg4 g6 { The most natural way to face the threat of Qxg7. } 10. Ng5
{ We're provoking additional concessions in Black's camp. } 10... h6
{ 10...f5  And now we should just take  11.exf6  Nxf6  12.Qh4±  White was clearly better in Milde,L-Peroutik,J LSS email 2007. Black's extra pawn matter little as he is quite passive. We have excellent pressure down the h-file, while we soon can pressure in the e-file after we have played O-O-O. }
11. Bd3
{ Suddenly Nxf7 pops up, a move which is incredibly unpleasant to meet. } 11...
Nc6
{ Black's only defense with a subtle point. Moves like  11...Nb6  and  11...a6  are both met by  12.Nxf7!  when White is just winning.  11...Nf8  fails to  12.Nxd5!  a trick we have seen appear rather frequently. }
12. Nxf7 { The capture still works out for us, although it's not so easy. }
12... Kxf7
{ 12...h5  Black doesn't have to take the knight right away.  13.Qg3  h4  14.Qg4  Kxf7  The difference isn't huge when we compare to 12... Kf7. Black's h-pawn makes it slightly more difficult for our rook to join the attack, but that's pretty much it.  15.Bxg6+  Kf8!   Necessary, as  15...Kg7  fails to  16.Bh5+  Kf8  17.Qf4+  Kg8  18.Rxh4  when Black's defense crumbles.  16.Rd1   We must bring the rook to the party this way, since Black defends after  16.Rh3  Nxd4  17.Qxd4  Qg5  . In this line, it's quite significant that the pawn stands on  h4  instead of h6...  16...Qg7?   Natural, but it loses rather spectacularly.  16...Nf6  is what Black needs to do, when I analyzed a sequence that looks pretty forced.  17.exf6  Qxf6  18.Rd3  e5  19.Nxd5  Qxf2+  20.Kxf2  Bxg4  21.Ne3  Bd7  22.dxe5  Nxe5  23.Rd5  Kg7  24.Bf5  Bxf5  25.Nxf5+  Kf6  26.Nxh4  . Black has to fight for a draw with a pawn down.  17.Rxh4!  Simply stunning! We'll sacrifice another piece!  17...Rxh4  18.Qxh4  Qxg6  19.Rd3  Black is up two pieces, but our attack is too powerful.  19...Ndxe5   19...Ne7  looks more human, when the only move that wins is  20.Rg3!  Black loses the queen.  20.dxe5  Qg7  21.f4+-  White is completely winning due to the strength of the attack. Let's check some more moves:  21...Ke8  22.Rg3  Qf8  23.Nb5  Kd7  And now, a fantastic trick  24.f5  Which is the nail in the coffin.  24...exf5  25.e6+  And Black loses the rook on a8.  25...Kxe6  26.Nxc7+  Kd7  27.Nxa8+-  Black fought for 30 more moves in Heydt, H -Maylott, P ICCF email 2018, but perished in the end. }
13. Bxg6+
{ The point of  11...Nc6  is seen after  13.Qxg6+  Kf8  14.Rh3  Nxd4! } 13...
Kg7
{ This time Black can move to g7, as the pawn on g6 allows the defensive resource Qg5. }
14. Rh5 { A very strong move that stops Black's aforementioned resource. }
14... Kg8 15. Bd3+ Kf8
{ Black won't get mated, so we must try to create additional weaknesses in his camp. }
16. Nb5 { Now Black has to worry about the pawn on c7. } 16... Qg7 17. Qf4+ Qf7
18. Qh4 { Two pawns are under attack! } 18... Rb8 19. O-O-O
{ It's essential that we finish our development before grabbing pawns. Black is completely fine after  19.Rxh6  Rxh6  20.Qxh6+  Qg7  21.Qh4  a6  . }
19... Qe7 20. Qf4+ Qf7 21. Qh2
{ Rodriguez,L - Gaujens,A ICCF email 2018. Black loses the pawn on h6. Sooner or later, everything will fall apart.   The game continued  21...Ke8  22.Rxh6  Rxh6  23.Qxh6  Nf8  24.Rh1  Bd7  25.Rh3  Ne7  26.Rf3  Nf5  27.Bxf5  exf5  28.Nxc7+  Kd8  29.Qd6  Rc8  30.Rc3  Qe7  31.Qxe7+  Kxe7  32.Nxd5+  , and White eventually prevailed in the ending due to the extra pawns. }
