1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5 Be7 5. e5 Nfd7 6. h4 Bxg5
{ This time on the menu of our 1. e4 restaurant is the Alekhine- Chatard Attack Accepted. A courageous choice, but objectively the right one. That being said, the path forward is very narrow for Black... One has to be incredibly well prepared, hence why 4... dxe4 has taken more and more over. }
7. hxg5 Qxg5 8. Nh3
{ Black has to make an incredibly important decision on where to place the queen. }
8... Qe7
{ This is by far the most logical and popular move. Unfortunately for Black, it is a bad one. }
9. Qg4 g6 { The most natural way to face the threat of Qxg7. } 10. Ng5
{ We're provoking additional concessions in Black's camp. } 10... h5
{ Now that we've seen that  10...h6  doesn't work out for Black due to the Nxf7-tactics, Black has no choice but to go for this move.  h5 has other downsides as it gives us a fantastic outpost on g5, while the pawn on h5 can easily be targeted by the means of g4. }
11. Qf4 a6 { Black's usual way of playing these positions. } 12. O-O-O
{ We're getting ready to strike with g4, a rather annoying threat. } 12... b5
{ 12...c5?  Fails tactically for Black due to the fantastic  13.dxc5  Nc6   13...Nxc5  14.Rxd5!!  And White just wins  14...exd5  15.Nxd5+-  The Black queen can't defend against Qxf7 and Nxc7.  14.Rxd5!!  Having the knight on c6 makes no difference.  14...O-O  Everything wins here, but I wanted to share the beautiful line  15.Rxd7!  Bxd7  16.Nce4!  With you, as it's incredibly instructive. Black has no counterplay at all!  16...Kg7  17.g4+-  Black won't survive the attack without giving back material, for example:  17...Rh8  18.gxh5  Rxh5  19.Rxh5  gxh5  20.Nh7  Kxh7  21.Nf6+  . }
13. g4
{ Now that there's no sacrifice, we should proceed with our initial plan. }
13... b4
{ Can be met by   13...h4  Is objectively best, but that doesn't mean much. After the cunning idea  14.Rd3  Nc6  15.Rdh3±  White was doing really well in Schulz,G -Gatto,C ICCF email 2008 as Black loses the pawn. After we have captured the pawn, we will have the open h-file to our disposal. }
14. gxh5 Rxh5
{ 14...bxc3  Fails to the nice trick  15.hxg6  Rxh1  16.g7+-  And White queens. }
15. Rxh5 gxh5 16. Nb1
{ Simple chess.  16.Nxd5  is the engine line and objectively best, but harder to play. I analyzed  16...exd5  17.Bh3  Nc6  and here we must play  18.Nh7!!  with the point of going  Rg1  .  17...Nb6  is met by  18.e6  f6  19.Nh7  Bxe6  20.Nxf6+  Kd8  21.Re1  . }
16... Nc6 17. Be2
{ Black loses the pawn on h5. Once the bishop is on h5 the pawn on f7 falls to.   A sample line is:  17...Bb7  18.Bxh5  O-O-O  19.Nxf7  Rf8  , and here we must go  20.Rg1  so we can play  20...Nd8  21.Rg7  . }
