[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "23. French Defense (1...e6) Mainlines"]
[Black "4...Be7 (6...Bxg5 8...Qh4) 9.g3 Alternative"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5 Be7 5. e5 Nfd7 6. h4 Bxg5
{ This time on the menu of our 1. e4 restaurant is the Alekhine- Chatard Attack Accepted. A courageous choice, but objectively the right one. That being said, the path forward is very narrow for Black... One has to be incredibly well prepared, hence why 4... dxe4 has taken more and more over. }
7. hxg5 Qxg5 8. Nh3
{ Black has to make an incredibly important decision on where to place the queen. }
8... Qh4
{ This move receives two exclams, because it's the only way for Black to obtain an objectively fine position. The idea behind the move, is quite incredible. Black provokes us into playing g3, which will give us a worse version of 8... Qe7 as we soon shall see. The move is very unknown, so in my base I was only able to find 23 games! Compare that to 8... Qe7 with 1111 games! This is not surprising, because for a human it makes no sense to give us g3 for free. The queen has to head back, and Black has given us an extra move! Before we start with our coverage, I want to highlight that this is very unknown territory. There are a plethora of different ways we can challenge Black, when Black will be required to play extremely accurately in order to avoid defeat. Interesting alternatives worth investigating are for example 9. Qd2!? and 9. Qd3!?, but for this alternative line, 9. g3!? is our move. }
9. g3 Qe7 10. Qg4
{ 10.Nf4!?  is another path worth checking out, with the dangerous idea of capturing on  d5  at some point. I looked at  10...a6  11.Qd3  c5  12.Ncxd5  exd5  13.Nxd5  Qd8  14.O-O-O  , a huge mess where Black must play very accurately in order to go unscathed. The line went:  14...Nc6  15.Bg2  cxd4  16.Rxh7  Rxh7  17.Qxh7  Ndxe5  18.Qg8+  Kd7  19.Qxg7  Kd6!!  @@StartBracket@@only move@@EndBracket@@  20.f4  Ng6  21.Qxf7  Nge7!!  @@StartBracket@@another only move@@EndBracket@@  22.Rh1  Nxd5  23.Qxd5+  Kc7  24.Rh7+  Kb8  , and Black has escaped the worst. }
10... g6
{ The best move by far. Obviously, g2-g3 won't make a significant difference after the move 10... Kf8. }
11. O-O-O
{ The best attempt for an edge. Hopefully, you can recall that  11.Ng5  was our choice in  8...Qe7  . Unfortunately, having  g3  included means that this no longer works for us! Pretty wild!  11...h6  12.Bd3  Nc6!  and here, we can no longer play  13.Nxf7  , because after  13...h5  , we don't have the g3-square available for our queen! My jaw dropped when I saw this for the very first time! }
11... Nc6
{ 11...a6?!  Black played this move in some online games I found, but it's too slow.  12.Ng5  h5  13.Qf4  c5?   This move was played almost exclusively in the lichess base, but it loses.  13...Nc6  is best, but White has an excellent position after the thematic  14.g4  .  14.dxc5  Nc6  And here we have the blow  15.Rxd5+-  White was completely winning in the 10+0 game between the user 'Cranguejo' and 'legendabove'   11...h5  Was Black's choice in a recent Correspondence game.  12.Qf4  Nb6  13.Ng5  Bd7  And now, instead of 14. a3 which was White's choice in Ovcharenko,L - Gnilka,T ICCF email 2018, I found a neat improvement in  14.g4!  Which puts Black under pressure.  14...Nc6  15.Qf6!  Is a neat point, when we get a better ending after  15...Qxf6  16.exf6  a6  17.f4⩲  Despite being a pawn down, we are in the driving seat as we have a nice space advantage and a powerful knight on g5. }
12. Ng5 h6
{ 12...h5  gives us an easy game after  13.Qh4  , with thematic ideas such as  g4  and Rd3-Rf3. }
13. Nb5
{ A really interesting try. We will pressure Black's center with c4.   13.Kb1!?  can also be played, with a very exciting position after  13...Nf8  14.f4  Bd7  15.Qf3  . Black's extra pawn makes the position objectively even, but there's no doubt that it's easier to handle White. }
13... Nf8 14. c4 a6 15. Nc3 Bd7
{ Black has to castle queenside before it's too late.  15...dxc4?  would be a huge error due to  16.Nce4  , when White has a dominating position after for example  16...Nd7  17.Qf4  . }
16. f4 O-O-O 17. Qe2
{ The position is objectively unclear, but it's a lot easier to play White as Black is rather cramped. }
