[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5 Be7 5. e5 Nfd7 6. h4 Bxg5
{ This time on the menu of our 1. e4 restaurant is the Alekhine- Chatard Attack Accepted. A courageous choice, but objectively the right one. That being said, the path forward is very narrow for Black... One has to be incredibly well prepared, hence why 4... dxe4 has taken more and more over. }
7. hxg5 Qxg5 8. Nh3
{ Black has to make an incredibly important decision on where to place the queen. }
8... Qh4
{ This move receives two exclams, because it's the only way for Black to obtain an objectively fine position. The idea behind the move, is quite incredible. Black provokes us into playing g3, which will give us a worse version of 8... Qe7 as we soon shall see. The move is very unknown, so in my base I was only able to find 23 games! Compare that to 8... Qe7 with 1111 games! This is not surprising, because for a human it makes no sense to give us g3 for free. The queen has to head back, and Black has given us an extra move! }
9. Nb5
{ Our knight attacks c7 and practically forces Black to give up the rights to castle. In return however, Black will get a6 with a tempo, meaning that it's easier to carry out the desired a6-c5 plan. }
9... Kd8
{ Necessary. I spotted that  9...Na6?  was almost always played online. This looks terrible after  10.Bd3  followed by Qd2/ Qf3 and O-O-O. }
10. Qd2
{ 10.Qf3!?  leads to a rather interesting position after  10...a6  11.Qxf7  Rf8  12.Qxg7  axb5  13.Qg5+  Qxg5  14.Nxg5  Nb6  15.Bxb5  . White has sacrificed a piece, but will have three pawns for it as the pawn on  h7  falls. Objectively it's 0.00, but the game goes on! }
10... a6 11. Nc3 c5
{ There are many possible moves here, but I think this is what most humans would play.  11...b5  was tried in the strong Correspondence clash Elyoseph, H - Talpak, T ICCF email 2019, but it looks risky if you ask me. White went  12.O-O-O  , but after the important  12...Qe7  Black is apparently fine. The game went  13.f4  Nb6  14.Kb1  Bd7  15.Qe1  Kc8  16.Ne2  a5  17.Nf2  Nc4  18.Nd3  , with a pretty strange position.   Instead of  12.O-O-O  , I prefer  12.g3  with the simple point of developing the bishop to  g2  . After  12...Qe7  13.Be2  Bb7  14.f4  c5  15.dxc5  Nxc5  16.Nf2  , things look scary for Black due to the king in the center. However, the objective evaluation is 0.00. Such is the game of chess! }
12. dxc5 Nc6 13. O-O-O
{ Black has dismantled our center, but with a king on d8 he has to tread very carefully. }
13... Kc7
{ Black's king should get out of the way before grabbing pawns. There are a number of ways Black could simply just lose. For example:  13...Qe7?  is met by  14.Nf4  Qxc5  15.Ncxd5  exd5  16.Nxd5  when White's attack is decisive.   13...Ndxe5?  loses as well, to  14.f4  Nd7  15.Bc4  intending Ng5.  After  15...Qe7  White wins after  16.Bxd5  exd5  17.Nxd5  Qxc5  18.Ng5  .   13...Nxc5  14.Be2  is a semi-forced sequence that heads to an ending which is very good for White.  14...Kc7  15.Ng5  Qxf2  16.Rdf1  Qd4  17.Rxf7+  Bd7  18.Qxd4  Nxd4  19.b4  h6  20.Nf3  Nxe2+  21.Nxe2  Ne4  22.Nf4  and White is close to winning. }
14. Be2
{ I analyzed this position in great depth. After  14.Be2  , we're ready to play  Ng5  which will win the pawn on  f7  . Black has an important decision to make. }
14... h6 { Is also a bad idea. } 15. Nf4 Qxf2
{ Black's best try. After  15...Qd8  , Black has problems after  16.Nd3  . }
16. Ne4
{ This incredible sacrifice works tactically due to Black's vulnerable king. }
16... dxe4 17. Qd6+ Kd8 18. Rhf1 Qh4
{ Black has to try to bring the queen back to the defense.  18...Qg3?  would lose after  19.Bh5  , as Black no longer has the important move  19...Qe7  to protect the pawn. }
19. Nxe6+ { Another piece bites the dust. } 19... fxe6 20. Rf7 { The point. }
20... Nxe5 21. Qb6+
{ Not  21...Qxe5??  when Black wins after  Qg5+  as he trades queens. } 21...
Ke8 22. Qxe6+ Kd8 23. Bg4 { The pressure on d7 increases. } 23... Qg5+
{ This is an essential check to make for a very deep reason. If Black takes on  g4  right away with  23...Qxg4  , we win after  24.Qe7+  Kc7  25.Qxe5+  Kd8  26.Qe7+  Kc7  27.Qd6+  Kd8  28.b4  e3  And here we have  29.Qe7+  Kc7  30.Rxg7  .  The difference of having the king on b1 and c1 is clearly shown here, as our rook on d1 remains protected with the king on c1. Truly amazing! }
24. Kb1 Qxg4
{ We have forced the queen away from the e7-h4 diagonal, so we can now take the knight with check. }
25. Qe7+ Kc7 26. Qxe5+ Kd8 27. Qe7+
{ We make this check so we can play Qd6 with a tempo. } 27... Kc7 28. Qd6+ Kd8
{ It looks like there's no way to proceed from here, but as a matter of fact, there is! }
29. Rd4
{ Believe it or not, the sole purpose of this move is to stop Black from playing e3! With Rd4 on the board, our way forward is to simply play b4-a4-b5 and b6, when Black is mated!! }
29... a5
{ Prevents our brilliant plan, while Black also has a defensive resource in Ra6. }
30. Qe7+ { Is now forced } 30... Kc7 31. Qe5+ Kd8 32. Rxg7
{ Black has to give the queen and fight for a draw. } *

