{ Black has dismantled our center, but with a king on d8 he has to tread very carefully. }
13... Kc7 14. Be2
{ I analyzed this position in great depth. After  14.Be2  , we're ready to play  Ng5  which will win the pawn on  f7  . Black has an important decision to make. }
14... Kb8
{ A very decent move. Black gets the king out of harm's way before grabbing pawns. }
15. Ng5
{ I gave  15.a3!?  in great depth in my video series on chess24, but this move looks even stronger. That being said,  15.a3  is also an excellent choice. If you're premium on chess24 you can check out my analysis there. }
15... Qxf2
{ Black has to grab the pawn, otherwise we simply take on f7 with a crushing position. }
16. Na4
{ Our knight on a4 is strong as it protects the pawn on c5 and opens the door to Nb6-ideas. }
16... Ndxe5
{ Black's only move. Taking with the other knight is a bad version, because Black no longer keeps the pawn on  e6  protected. This is quite significant, seen in the line  16...Ncxe5  17.Rhf1  Qh4  18.b3  f6  19.Nxe6  .   16...f6  is also not ideal for Black as we get a fantastic endgame after  17.exf6  Nxf6  18.Bf3!  Qxd2  19.Rxd2  . We can now clearly see the role our knight on  a4  plays as it's heading to  b6  next. After  19...Ka7  20.Nb6  Rb8  21.Re1  Nd8  22.b4  , we're ready to take on  c8  followed by a capture on  e6  . }
17. Rhf1 Qh4
{ Is necessary. Black prevents us from capturing the pawn on f7 as he's attacking our knight. }
18. Nb6 f6
{ The best move. Black needs to keep the pawn on  f7  . Keeping the exchange with  18...Ra7?  is just awful after we capture on  f7  .   18...Rf8?!  Is inaccurate.  19.g3!  Gives us a fantastic initiative after  19...Qxg3  20.Ne4!  Black can't take the knight due to the check on d6.  20...Qh4  21.Nd6±  We are three pawns down, but it's incredibly difficult for Black to find any good moves. We're going Rg1 or Rh1 to apply pressure against Black's pawns. When the queen no longer covers the b4-square, we can play b4 and expand on the queenside. I find it highly amusing how we're casually playing on with three pawns down! }
19. Nxc8 { Our best chance is to go for an ending. } 19... Qxg5
{ 19...Rxc8  is met by  20.Nxe6  , hence why we took on  c8  . } 20. Qxg5 fxg5
21. Nb6 { We are two pawns down, but Black's pawns are very fragile. } 21...
Kc7
{ Black should give the exchange.   21...Ra7?  Keeping the rook would be a huge error due to  22.a3  Kc7  23.b4±  We are down two pawns, but we are completely dominating. }
22. Nxa8+ Rxa8 23. a3
{ We're planning to expand on the queenside with c4 followed by b4. With correct play the game should obviously end in a draw @@StartBracket@@the usual scenario in chess@@EndBracket@@, but it looks rather difficult to get there in a practical game. Our rooks are strong. }
