18... Rd8 19. Nb6 d4 { 19...Rb8  is also met by  20.Qa3  with similar play. }
20. Qa3 Rb8
{ I analyzed the crazy line  20...d3  on chess24 as well. It goes  21.Bxd3  Rd4  22.Be2  Re4  23.b5  Rxe2  24.bxc6  Rb8  25.Nf4  Re4  26.Rxh7  Nxc6  27.Rh8  Rxf4  28.Nxc8+  Rxc8  29.Rxc8  29...Rxf2??  30.Rxc6!!  bxc6  31.Qa5  Qb7  32.Qd8  and White wins.  29...Qg5  is Black's only move.  30.Kb1  Qg4  31.f3  Rb4+  32.Ka1  Qc4  33.Qd3  Qxc5  34.c3  Rb6  35.Qd2  .  Black has compensation, but not enough to claim equality as we're playing Qc1-Rdd8-Ra8 next. I obviously could have given more lines and explained everything in great depth, but it's just a waste of time for both of us, as we're way out of 'important lines to remember.' After all, I found two games with 9. Nb5 in my base!! }
21. Bb5
{ Is now very strong, intending f4 and Bxc6 when the knight moves.   21.b5  would have been crushing, if it wasn't for  21...d3  which saves the day as Black gets the d4-square for the knight. }
21... Bd7
{ Is bad, due to   21...d3  Can once again be played, when our response is  22.f4  Nd4!  Otherwise we'll simply take on c6 and on d3.  23.fxe5  Nxb5  24.Qb2  d2+!   Necessary. If  24...dxc2  , we get the d-file after  25.Kxc2  when  a4  and  Rd6  follows.  25.Rxd2  Rxd2  26.Kxd2↑  We have regained the pawn and maintain a nice initiative with c4 coming. Our king looks vulnerable on d2, but it's nothing to worry about as we can play Kc1 in the next move. }
22. f4 Ng4 23. Bd3 { We'll play b5 next with a decisive advantage. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "23. French Defense (1...e6) Mainlines"]
[Black "4...Be7 (6...Bxg5 8...Qh4 5)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5 Be7 5. e5 Nfd7 6. h4 Bxg5
{ This time on the menu of our 1. e4 restaurant is the Alekhine- Chatard Attack Accepted. A courageous choice, but objectively the right one. That being said, the path forward is very narrow for Black... One has to be incredibly well prepared, hence why 4... dxe4 has taken more and more over. }
7. hxg5 Qxg5 8. Nh3
{ Black has to make an incredibly important decision on where to place the queen. }
8... Qh4
{ This move receives two exclams, because it's the only way for Black to obtain an objectively fine position. The idea behind the move, is quite incredible. Black provokes us into playing g3, which will give us a worse version of 8... Qe7 as we soon shall see. The move is very unknown, so in my base I was only able to find 23 games! Compare that to 8... Qe7 with 1111 games! This is not surprising, because for a human it makes no sense to give us g3 for free. The queen has to head back, and Black has given us an extra move! }
9. Nb5
{ Our knight attacks c7 and practically forces Black to give up the rights to castle. In return however, Black will get a6 with a tempo, meaning that it's easier to carry out the desired a6-c5 plan. }
9... Kd8 10. Qd2 a6 11. Nc3 c5 12. dxc5 Nc6 13. O-O-O
{ Black has dismantled our center, but with a king on d8 he has to tread very carefully. }
13... Kc7 14. Be2
{ I analyzed this position in great depth. After  14.Be2  , we're ready to play  Ng5  which will win the pawn on  f7  . Black has an important decision to make. }
14... Qe7
{ Our main line is this move that prevents all our shenanigans with Ng5. } 15.
Qf4
{ A very strong move that prevents Black from grabbing any of the hanging pawns.  15...Ndxe5?  is met by  16.Rxd5!  , while  15...Qxc5?  is met by  16.Qxf7  . }
15... Kb8 { Black prevents our trick Rxd5. } 16. Na4
{ In order to maintain an edge, we must keep the pawn on c5 protected. We have also seen earlier how flexible the knight is on a4 where it can jump to b6. }
16... Ndxe5 17. Qg3
{ On chess24 I gave  17.Qe3  which is also strong. However, I found a new resource for Black in  17...Rd8  18.Nb6  Nd7!  when things are not as clear as I'd like them to be.  Black will have tons of compensation in case we take the exchange. After the text move, we're attacking Black's pawn on g7, while f4, Rhe1 and Nb6 are in the air. }
17... Ka7
{ 17...Rg8  Can be met by  18.Rhe1  Ka7  19.Qa3  When the game is rather similar to what we saw in 16... Ka7, with b4-Nb6 coming. }
18. Rhe1 h5
{ Is interesting, Black wants to expand on the kingside with h4 followed by g5 at some point. }
19. f4 Ng6
{ The right square. After  19...Nd7  , we can take the pawn on  g7  . } 20. Qa3
{ The same plan! } 20... Qc7 21. b4 Kb8
{ 21...Nxf4?  would lose immediately to  22.b5  , so Black moves the king out of the way first. }
22. Nb6 Ra7 23. f5 { A strong move as Black will get a weak pawn on e6. } 23...
Nh4 24. fxe6 Nxg2 25. Rf1 fxe6
{ 25...Bxe6  is worse due to  26.Rf2!  which removes Black's knight from covering the important f4-square. After  26...Nh4  ,  27.Nf4  looks close to winning. }
26. Ng5
{ White's position is fantastic with the strong idea of Nf7-Nd6.   Black's best attempt is to play  26...Qe5  , when an endgame occurs after  27.Nf7  Qa1+  28.Kd2  Qd4+  29.Qd3  Qxb4+  30.Qc3  Qxc3+  31.Kxc3  . After the further  31...Rg8  32.Rf2  Ne3  33.Rg1  , there's no doubt that White is calling the shots. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "24. French Defense (1...e6) Winawer Sidelines"]
[Black "3...Bb4 (4...Qd7)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ We have finally arrived to the main bulk of our coverage on the French, and our very last topic to cover for Part 1! This is the Winawer Variation, named after Szymon Winawer and popularized later in the 1940s by the greats Nimzowitch and Botvinnik. After 3... Bb4, Black pins the knight and thus attacks the pawn on e4 so we're forced to make a decision in the center. }
4. e5
{ This is by far the most challenging move against the Winawer. We're gaining additional space while we're also limiting Black's knight on g8 as it can no longer jump to f6.   Black's standard way of playing is to challenge our center right away with the standard French-move  4...c5  , but the topic for this chapter is to take a look at what happens in case Black refrains from the usual procedure. }
4... Qd7
{ Looks incredibly strange. Black's idea is to meet 5. Qg4 with 5... f5, when the g7-pawn is under protection. }
5. h4
{ This is a move you will see constantly throughout the entire coverage of Winawer. With h4 our rook can join the game by swinging to h3-g3, while we also aim to get a very nice pawn structure with h5 later on. Note that Qg4 is more dangerous with h4 included, as g6 is met by the very unpleasant h5. }
5... c5
{ The only sensible alternative to  5...b6  , which is covered via the  4...b6  move order. }
6. a3 Bxc3+ 7. bxc3
{ This is just a bad version of the Main Line with 4... c5, as h4 is significantly more useful than Black's Qd7. }
7... Qa4
{ A thematic plan in the Winawer. Black is blocking the queenside entirely so he can later safely castle on that side of the board.   7...Nc6  And here I like  8.a4!  This move allows us to bring our c1-bishop to life via a3.  8...Qc7  A better square for the queen where it targets the c3-pawn.  9.Rh3!  A very nice and thematic resource. Our pawn is perfectly covered.  9...Nge7  10.Ba3  b6  Black should keep the diagonal closed.  11.Bd3  Bb7  12.Nf3  Na5   12...O-O-O  right away is met by  13.dxc5  , when White is just winning.  13.h5±  White has a dominating position as Black lacks the necessary counterplay on the queenside. }
8. Rb1
{ The open b-file is often a useful asset. After this move, we're pretty much forcing Black to close the queenside with  8...c4  . This is desirable for us, as it makes it easier to focus on the kingside now that we no longer have to worry about  cxd4  . }
8... c4
{ Other moves are worse.   8...a6  can be met by  9.dxc5  , while   8...Nc6  runs into  9.Bb5  Qa5  10.Bd2  , when Black has major problems. For example:  10...c4  11.Bxc6+  bxc6  12.Qg4  Kf8  13.h5  h6  14.Rh3  . Our rook stands firm in the open b-file, while our Q+R collaborate excellently on the kingside. Black has no counterplay. }
9. Qg4 { It's time to switch our attention to the kingside. } 9... Kf8
{ 9...g6  can be dealt with by  10.Kd1  , when we're free to do whatever we want on the kingside.   9...Qxc2?  Doesn't work, due to  10.Qxg7  Qxb1  And now, there's no haste to take the hanging rook!  11.Ne2!  This works as Black's rook can't be defended.  11...Nc6  12.Qxh8  Nce7  Doesn't look so bad for Black considering that he will quickly castle long, but in fact it's hopeless as he has problems with his kingside pawns.  13.g4  Bd7  14.f4  O-O-O  15.h5+-  We're ready to play Qg7 and capture on f7. Our king will be perfectly safe on f2. }
10. Kd1 Nc6 11. h5 { Fixing the pawn structure. } 11... h6 12. Rh3
{ The standard rook swing. Remember this idea! } 12... Nge7 13. Rf3
{ With ideas such as Qf4-g4-g5, or Nh3-Nf4, Black has major problems. The position looks hopeless in a practical game. Once again, Black lacks the necessary counterplay on the queenside, as our pieces have all the targets covered. }
*

