[White "24. French Defense (1...e6) Winawer Sidelines"]
[Black "3...Bb4 (4...Ne7)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ We have finally arrived to the main bulk of our coverage on the French, and our very last topic to cover for Part 1! This is the Winawer Variation, named after Szymon Winawer and popularized later in the 1940s by the greats Nimzowitch and Botvinnik. After 3... Bb4, Black pins the knight and thus attacks the pawn on e4 so we're forced to make a decision in the center. }
4. e5
{ This is by far the most challenging move against the Winawer. We're gaining additional space while we're also limiting Black's knight on g8 as it can no longer jump to f6.   Black's standard way of playing is to challenge our center right away with the standard French-move  4...c5  , but the topic for this chapter is to take a look at what happens in case Black refrains from the usual procedure. }
4... Ne7
{ This is by far the most popular alternative to the main move,  4...c5  . Although the reason for this is simply because it's a different way to reach the main line. }
5. a3 Bxc3+
{ 5...Ba5?  is a disaster after  6.b4  , when Black won't be able to play  c5  . }
6. bxc3 b6
{ This move is not played often compared to  6...c5  , when we have reached the main position of the Winawer. Black's idea with this move is trading bishops with  Ba6  , similarly to  4...b6  . }
7. Qg4
{ If Black is able to carry out his idea in peace, he will be completely fine. An example is  7.Nf3  Ba6  . After  7.Qg4  , Black needs to find a way to protect the g7-pawn. Unfortunately for him, there are no good ways to do so! }
7... O-O { Is not for the faint-hearted! } 8. Bd3
{ We're starting a powerful attack on Black's monarch. } 8... f6
{ The best try.  8...c5  is met by  9.Bg5  when Black is in huge trouble.   Most games have proceeded with  8...Ba6  , but this move is also awful after  9.Bh6  . A nice game went:  9...Ng6  10.Bg5  Qe8  11.Bxa6  Nxa6  12.h4  h6  13.Bxh6  gxh6  14.h5  and Black was just busted in Ghvamberia, N - Moosavian, S Poti 2013. }
9. exf6 Rxf6 10. Qh5 { Black is forced to make a concession. } 10... h6
{ 10...g6  weakens the dark squares too much after  11.Qg5  . } 11. g4
{ The two exclams are there as this is the only move that gives us an advantage! The threat of g5 is just crushing. }
11... Qf8 { And now the endgame after } 12. g5 g6 13. Qxh6 Nf5 14. Bxf5 Qxh6
15. gxh6 Rxf5 16. Nh3
{ Is just hopeless for Black, due to our passed pawn on h6. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "24. French Defense (1...e6) Winawer Sidelines"]
[Black "3...Bb4 (4...Ne7 2)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ We have finally arrived to the main bulk of our coverage on the French, and our very last topic to cover for Part 1! This is the Winawer Variation, named after Szymon Winawer and popularized later in the 1940s by the greats Nimzowitch and Botvinnik. After 3... Bb4, Black pins the knight and thus attacks the pawn on e4 so we're forced to make a decision in the center. }
4. e5
{ This is by far the most challenging move against the Winawer. We're gaining additional space while we're also limiting Black's knight on g8 as it can no longer jump to f6.   Black's standard way of playing is to challenge our center right away with the standard French-move  4...c5  , but the topic for this chapter is to take a look at what happens in case Black refrains from the usual procedure. }
4... Ne7 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 b6 7. Qg4 Kf8
{ Caruana defeated Giri with this move back in 2018, so let's check how we should react. }
8. Bg5
{ There are many good ways to play here, but this was my favorite move out of all of them. What this move is doing is that it prevents Black's knight from participating in the defense with Ng6/Nf5, while it also opens the possibility of capturing the knight. Giri played  8.a4  which is also strong.  8...Ba6  9.Bxa6  Nxa6  , but here Giri played two inaccurate moves in a row.  10.Qe2?!  gave Black useful time after  10...Nb8  , and after  11.a5?!  Nbc6  Black was fine in Giri,A - Caruana,F Leuven 2018. 10. Ne2 would have been better, followed by O-O and potentially Nf4-Nh5 or f4. }
8... c5
{ Black's best.  8...Ba6  9.Bxa6  Nxa6  was played recently in Shirov, A - Suarez Gomez, J Pontevedra 2019. Instead of playing  10.Qe2  , I found out that the move  10.f4  is just very powerful as Black has problems with stopping our f4-f5 advance. For example  10...c5  11.Ne2  h6  12.Qh3  Qd7  13.Bxe7+  Qxe7  14.f5  and Black's position looks very ugly. }
9. h4
{ This plan is once again quite strong, hence why it's important that you remember this thematic idea! }
9... Ba6 10. Bxa6 Nxa6 11. h5 h6 { Black can't allow us to advance to h6. } 12.
Bxe7+
{ With the knight on e7 gone, it will be easier for us to achieve the desirable pawn breakthrough with f4-f5. }
12... Qxe7 13. f4 Rc8
{ Black's best try to get counterplay, but we're faster. } 14. Nf3 cxd4 15.
cxd4
{ O-O followed by f5 is coming, when Black will be under a very serious pressure.   The desperate  15...f5?  fails to  16.exf6  , when Black is just dead lost after  16...Qxf6  17.Ne5  . }
