[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "24. French Defense (1...e6) Winawer Sidelines"]
[Black "3...Bb4 (4...Ne7 3)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ We have finally arrived to the main bulk of our coverage on the French, and our very last topic to cover for Part 1! This is the Winawer Variation, named after Szymon Winawer and popularized later in the 1940s by the greats Nimzowitch and Botvinnik. After 3... Bb4, Black pins the knight and thus attacks the pawn on e4 so we're forced to make a decision in the center. }
4. e5
{ This is by far the most challenging move against the Winawer. We're gaining additional space while we're also limiting Black's knight on g8 as it can no longer jump to f6.   Black's standard way of playing is to challenge our center right away with the standard French-move  4...c5  , but the topic for this chapter is to take a look at what happens in case Black refrains from the usual procedure. }
4... Ne7 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 b6 7. Qg4 Ng6
{ Black has played this move in most games, with the intention of stopping our powerful initiative with }
8. h4 h5
{ Black has halted our kingside play for now, but as we will see in the upcoming chapters, h5's weakness is that it gives us an outpost on g5. }
9. Qg3
{ The queen belongs on the queenside.  9.Qd1  has been played a decent amount, but I think  9...c5  is not too bad for Black, for example  10.Bb5+  Bd7  11.Bd3  Ba4  12.Nf3  Nc6  like in De Magalhaes, L - Rubinas, P ICCF email 2015. }
9... Ba6 10. Bxa6 Nxa6 11. Bg5
{ There's nothing wrong with  11.Ne2  right away, but I prefer developing the bishop with a tempo first. }
11... Qd7 12. Ne2 Nb8
{ Black has scored 50% with this strange-looking move, so let's see how we should react. Black's idea is to move the knight to the improved square on c6 where it can reach e7 or a5.   12...c5  I suggest meeting this advance with  13.O-O  When our pawn will quickly advance to f5, for example  13...Nb8  14.f4  Nc6  15.f5  exf5  16.Rf2+-  White looks just winning with  Rad1  coming next with deadly effect. In Giri, A - Ostrovskiy, A chess.com INT 2020, the super-GM went  16.Nf4?  , but after  16...Nxf4  17.Rxf4  c4  , Black would have had a nice blockade. }
13. Qf3 { Our queen targets the h5-pawn, so Ng3 is now a threat. } 13... Qc6
{ This engine-move is the only way to play for Black.  13...Ne7  has been played, but after  14.Nf4  g6  15.Bf6  Rg8  16.Bxe7  Kxe7  17.c4  c6  18.cxd5  cxd5  19.c4  , Black is toast.   13...Qa4  is also rather poor after  14.Ng3  Qxc2  15.Rc1  Qb2  16.Nxh5  , when White will follow with  O-O  and  g4  in the next moves. }
14. O-O
{ 14.Ng3  doesn't do anything as our queen on  f3  is forced to defend the c3-pawn, making  Nxh5  impossible. }
14... Nd7 15. Qg3
{ It might look strange to go back, but the only intent with Qf3 was to attack Black's h5-pawn. Our queen is better placed on g3 where it allows our f-pawn to run up the board. }
15... Ne7 16. Bxe7 { We shouldn't allow that knight to jump to f5. } 16... Kxe7
17. a4 { We're grabbing some space on the queenside. } 17... Qc4 18. Nf4 a5
{ This was Rolle,H - Skorna,U ICCF email 2018. The engines have gotten stronger, and here they found }
19. Qg5+ Kf8 20. Rad1
{ The rook is heading to f3 where it will cause terrors in Black's camp. } *

