1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ We have finally arrived to the main bulk of our coverage on the French, and our very last topic to cover for Part 1! This is the Winawer Variation, named after Szymon Winawer and popularized later in the 1940s by the greats Nimzowitch and Botvinnik. After 3... Bb4, Black pins the knight and thus attacks the pawn on e4 so we're forced to make a decision in the center. }
4. e5
{ This is by far the most challenging move against the Winawer. We're gaining additional space while we're also limiting Black's knight on g8 as it can no longer jump to f6.   Black's standard way of playing is to challenge our center right away with the standard French-move  4...c5  , but the topic for this chapter is to take a look at what happens in case Black refrains from the usual procedure. }
4... Ne7 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 b6 7. Qg4 Ng6
{ Black has played this move in most games, with the intention of stopping our powerful initiative with }
8. h4 h5
{ Black has halted our kingside play for now, but as we will see in the upcoming chapters, h5's weakness is that it gives us an outpost on g5. }
9. Qg3
{ The queen belongs on the queenside.  9.Qd1  has been played a decent amount, but I think  9...c5  is not too bad for Black, for example  10.Bb5+  Bd7  11.Bd3  Ba4  12.Nf3  Nc6  like in De Magalhaes, L - Rubinas, P ICCF email 2015. }
9... Ba6 10. Bxa6 Nxa6 11. Bg5
{ There's nothing wrong with  11.Ne2  right away, but I prefer developing the bishop with a tempo first. }
11... Qd7 12. Ne2 Qa4
{ Black's most played move in the position targets our c2-pawn. } 13. O-O
{ The best is to ignore Black's scheme entirely.  13.Qd3  has been more common, but I am unconvinced after  13...c5  . }
13... Qxc2 14. Qe3 Ne7
{ Was played in the only game I found in my base.   14...Qe4  15.Qd2  We should of course avoid the queen trade. Black's queen is now in danger of getting trapped, so  15...Ne7  Is practically forced  16.Bxe7  Kxe7  17.f4!  And there's no way for Black to stop f5 as  17...Qf5  Is met by  18.Rf3+-  When we will force Black's queen away from f5 by playing Rg3-Rg5. }
15. Rac1 Qe4
{ We react similarly to 14... Qe4.   15...Qa4  16.Bxe7  White could even play 16. Ng3 first which might be even stronger...  16...Kxe7  17.Qg5+  Kd7   17...Kf8  is hopeless after  18.f4  , when  f5  will be lethal.  18.Qxg7  Raf8  This was Fakhrutdinov,T - Yuferev,O Ekaterinburg 2018, and here I think  19.f4+-  Is just winning for White, as f5 comes followed by Qf6 and Nf4. }
16. Qd2 c5 { We have tons of good ways to play, with the simplest being } 17.
Bxe7 Kxe7 18. f4 { With the same plan as before, and just like last time }
18... Qf5 { Can be countered by } 19. Rf3
{ Intending either Ng3 or Rg3-Rg5, when White is breaking through. } *

