1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ We have finally arrived to the main bulk of our coverage on the French, and our very last topic to cover for Part 1! This is the Winawer Variation, named after Szymon Winawer and popularized later in the 1940s by the greats Nimzowitch and Botvinnik. After 3... Bb4, Black pins the knight and thus attacks the pawn on e4 so we're forced to make a decision in the center. }
4. e5
{ This is by far the most challenging move against the Winawer. We're gaining additional space while we're also limiting Black's knight on g8 as it can no longer jump to f6.   Black's standard way of playing is to challenge our center right away with the standard French-move  4...c5  , but the topic for this chapter is to take a look at what happens in case Black refrains from the usual procedure. }
4... b6
{ Black sometimes opts for this sideline to get us out of book. The intention behind the move is very clear, as Black aims to trade the 'French-bishop with Ba6. I don't think this line is particularly good if we know what we're doing. }
5. h4
{ The h4-thrust is the best weapon we have at our disposal. Lots of games have continued  5.Qg4  Bf8  when we're also doing fairly well.  5.a3  can also be played, when the game usually continues  5...Bxc3+  6.bxc3  Qd7  or  6...Ne7  , when we're also doing well. Despite our decent alternatives, I'm convinced that the text is the best. }
5... Ne7
{ Has been tried by a couple of GMs. Our way of playing is hopefully familiar to you now: }
6. h5 { Once again we're fixing the pawn structure. } 6... h6 7. Qg4 Kf8
{ 7...Nf5  is no better, for example  8.Bd3  O-O  9.a3  Be7  10.Nce2  c5  11.c3  Nc6  12.Nf3  and we have a dream set-up. }
8. Nf3 c5
{ Was seen in the GM duel Lu,S - Marin,M Roquetas de Mar 2020, and here I suggest we go for the thematic }
9. Rh3 { With the plan Nh4-Rg3 or Qf4-Nh4-g4-Rf3. } 9... Qc7 10. Bd3 cxd4 11.
Rg3 { The square on f5 is covered, so this intermezzo works well. } 11... Rg8
12. Kf1
{ A clever move, making use of the fact that Black's bishop on  b4  is hanging if Black goes  12...dxc3  . Black has to worry about  Nb5  now, so the best is to get rid of the knight }
12... dxc3 13. Qxb4 Ba6
{ The exclam is there as this is the only move that doesn't give us a decisive advantage, but still after   13...Na6  Gives us a dominating game after  14.Qf4!  The best square for the queen, as we can target Black's pawn on f7 with Rf3 soon.  14...Nc5  15.Nd4  Nxd3  16.cxd3  cxb2  17.Bxb2+-  With moves like Rf3, Rc1 and Ba3 coming Black's way, he won't survive for long. }
14. bxc3 Bxd3+ 15. cxd3 Nc6 16. Qf4
{ We're doing well, with a very dangerous plan in Ba3-Nh4/Nd4-Rf3-g4. It's worth mentioning that  16...Nf5  can be met by  17.Rh3  , when Black's knight will be chased with  g4  in the next move. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "24. French Defense (1...e6) Winawer Sidelines"]
[Black "3...Bb4 (4...b6 2)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ We have finally arrived to the main bulk of our coverage on the French, and our very last topic to cover for Part 1! This is the Winawer Variation, named after Szymon Winawer and popularized later in the 1940s by the greats Nimzowitch and Botvinnik. After 3... Bb4, Black pins the knight and thus attacks the pawn on e4 so we're forced to make a decision in the center. }
4. e5
{ This is by far the most challenging move against the Winawer. We're gaining additional space while we're also limiting Black's knight on g8 as it can no longer jump to f6.   Black's standard way of playing is to challenge our center right away with the standard French-move  4...c5  , but the topic for this chapter is to take a look at what happens in case Black refrains from the usual procedure. }
4... b6
{ Black sometimes opts for this sideline to get us out of book. The intention behind the move is very clear, as Black aims to trade the 'French-bishop with Ba6. I don't think this line is particularly good if we know what we're doing. }
5. h4
{ The h4-thrust is the best weapon we have at our disposal. Lots of games have continued  5.Qg4  Bf8  when we're also doing fairly well.  5.a3  can also be played, when the game usually continues  5...Bxc3+  6.bxc3  Qd7  or  6...Ne7  , when we're also doing well. Despite our decent alternatives, I'm convinced that the text is the best. }
5... Ba6 { Looks great for us after } 6. Bxa6 Nxa6 7. Qd3
{ Black has to choose between  7...Nb8  or  7...Qc8  , two sad moves to make. Our queen is also very flexible on  d3  as it can swing to the kingside and attack Black's vulnerable pawn on  g7  , forcing a concession. }
7... Qc8
{ The lesser evil.  7...Bxc3+  8.bxc3  Nb8  9.Qg3  looks fantastic for us. We have a vastly improved version of the Winawer. }
8. a3 Bxc3+ 9. Qxc3
{ 9. bxc3 is strong as well, but there's no need for us to damage our pawn structure. }
9... c5 10. Qg3
{ The queen finally swings to the kingside where it causes trouble for Black. }
10... Kf8 { Is necessary, when we have an excellent position after } 11. h5 h6
12. c3 Ne7 13. Ne2
{ Black's king is in the center while he lacks the necessary counterplay on the queenside to justify the bad placement of it. }
13... Nf5 { It's hard to find good moves for Black } 14. Qf4 cxd4 15. cxd4
{ The advantage is climbing as we will quickly take over the c-file and push Black's knight back with g4. Our rook will move to h3, where it can go to c3 or even f3 to target Black's pawn on f7. }
