[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "24. French Defense (1...e6) Winawer Sidelines"]
[Black "3...Bb4 (4...b6 6)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ We have finally arrived to the main bulk of our coverage on the French, and our very last topic to cover for Part 1! This is the Winawer Variation, named after Szymon Winawer and popularized later in the 1940s by the greats Nimzowitch and Botvinnik. After 3... Bb4, Black pins the knight and thus attacks the pawn on e4 so we're forced to make a decision in the center. }
4. e5
{ This is by far the most challenging move against the Winawer. We're gaining additional space while we're also limiting Black's knight on g8 as it can no longer jump to f6.   Black's standard way of playing is to challenge our center right away with the standard French-move  4...c5  , but the topic for this chapter is to take a look at what happens in case Black refrains from the usual procedure. }
4... b6
{ Black sometimes opts for this sideline to get us out of book. The intention behind the move is very clear, as Black aims to trade the 'French-bishop with Ba6. I don't think this line is particularly good if we know what we're doing. }
5. h4
{ The h4-thrust is the best weapon we have at our disposal. Lots of games have continued  5.Qg4  Bf8  when we're also doing fairly well.  5.a3  can also be played, when the game usually continues  5...Bxc3+  6.bxc3  Qd7  or  6...Ne7  , when we're also doing well. Despite our decent alternatives, I'm convinced that the text is the best. }
5... Qd7
{ This position can also be reached via the 4... Qd7 move-order, as explained earlier. }
6. h5 h6
{ Has been the main continuation, but due to a pretty outstanding move in move 8, the line is just trash. }
7. Qg4 Bf8 8. b4
{ A stunning move that was a novelty at the time I created 'Destroy the French.' The point of the move is to take complete control over both sides of the board. Black's position is already hopeless, but of course it will require precision from us. I analyzed a decent chunk of moves: }
8... f5
{ Black's best try is to force an endgame. The problem is that the endgame is also miserable...   8...c5  Another typical reaction that fails.  9.bxc5  bxc5  10.Nb5!  Is incredibly strong, with the threat of Nd6+ followed by Qxg7 @@StartBracket@@if Black takes@@EndBracket@@ .  10...f6  11.Nf3  Black is dead lost, as seen in the sample line  11...a6  12.Qg6+  Kd8   12...Qf7+  loses to  13.Nc7+  .  13.Nd6  Bxd6  14.exd6  Ra7  15.dxc5+-  Black can resign. A single glance at Black's position is enough to tell you why... }
9. Qg6+ Qf7 10. Qxf7+ Kxf7 11. a3
{ Once again, it's important that we keep our pawn chain intact.  11.b5  is met by  11...a6  , when a lot of the pressure has faded away in the blink of an eye. }
11... c5 { I can't imagine Black doing anything else. } 12. Nf3
{ A strong move as there's no need to worry about the pawn on b4 yet. } 12...
Nc6
{ 12...cxb4  Is refuted by  13.Nb5!  Black is actually dead here, amazingly enough.  13...Nc6   13...Na6  is met by the same continuation.  14.Nd6+  When Black captures our knight, we'll have a fantastic square on e5.  14...Bxd6  15.exd6  Nf6  16.Bb5  Black's guardian knight on c6 is removed, so we can freely take on b4 and jump to e5.  16...Na5  17.Ne5+  Kg8  18.axb4+-  And Black loses. }
13. Rh3
{ Looks strange, but it's a huge advantage to have the rook on the third rank in several lines. }
13... Bd7
{ It's not so easy to tell how we should proceed, but   13...cxb4  Is still met by  14.Nb5!  With the same plan of heading to d6.  14...Nge7  15.axb4  Opening the a-file for our rook.  15...Nxb4  16.Nd6+  Kg8  17.Kd1  Black is up a pawn, but my engine gives close to +4.00! The evaluation is justified by the fact that Black's pieces are horribly placed.  17...Bd7  18.Nh4  The knight is headed to g6 while our rook may head to g3, b3 or c3, depending on what Black does.  18...Kh7  19.Rg3+-  White's completely dominating. Our knight will head to g6. When Black moves the b-knight to c6, we can pin it by playing Bb5 and later follow up with c3 and Ba3. Black position falls apart. There are no moves!   13...Be7  14.Bd2  We proceed with our development.  14...c4   Note that  14...cxb4  is still met by  15.Nb5!  If Black closes the position, I suggest  15.Rh1!?  We're going back to g1 where the rook will support a thrust with the g-pawn.  15...Bd7  16.Rg1!  Black can't do more than watch as we breakthrough on the kingside with g4.  16...a6  17.g4  fxg4  18.Rxg4+-  Our kingside initiative is decisive. }
14. dxc5 { Looks really powerful with the idea } 14... bxc5 15. b5
{ We have created a passed pawn, while we also force the knight to an inferior square. }
15... Na5
{ 15...Nce7  Is met by  16.Na4  Rc8   16...c4  is met by  17.Nc5  , when our knights are dancing after  17...Bc8  18.Nd4  g5  19.f4  .  17.c4!  Black has problems getting his pieces out, for example  17...g5  18.Nd2!   A really important move.  18.hxg6+?  Nxg6  and Black is suddenly completely fine as the pieces are getting out.  18...g4  19.Rc3  Bg7  And now  20.f4+-  When Black's pieces are completely dominated. A beautiful sight. }
16. Nh4 Ne7 { Black should prevent us from jumping to g6. } 17. Bd2
{ And now Black's knight has to move back. } 17... Nb7 18. Be2 c4 19. Be3
{ I don't see how Black can coordinate his forces. He's almost in zugzwang! } *

