1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ We have finally arrived to the main bulk of our coverage on the French, and our very last topic to cover for Part 1! This is the Winawer Variation, named after Szymon Winawer and popularized later in the 1940s by the greats Nimzowitch and Botvinnik. After 3... Bb4, Black pins the knight and thus attacks the pawn on e4 so we're forced to make a decision in the center. }
4. e5
{ This is by far the most challenging move against the Winawer. We're gaining additional space while we're also limiting Black's knight on g8 as it can no longer jump to f6. }
4... c5
{ Black's main move challenges our center immediately, a necessary course of action to obtain the desired counterplay on the queenside. }
5. a3
{ By far the most played move as this is the only way to maintain the strong pawn chain. }
5... cxd4
{ This move looks rather dubious to me. The pawn on b4 is more of a strength than a weakness, while Black struggles on the dark squares and with obtaining a sufficient amount of counterplay on the queenside. }
6. axb4 dxc3 7. Qg4
{ This move gives Black huge problems as we get a tremendous amount of compensation for the sacrificed pawn. }
7... g6
{ Some players have tried playing g6 here, but I must admit that it looks strange to play it without the inclusion of cxb2. }
8. Nf3
{ We don't wanna play  8.bxc3  , as Black gets some play after  8...Qc7  . }
8... Qc7 { 8...cxb2  reaches 7... cxb2. } 9. Bd3
{ My engine prefers  9.Qd4  , but this is too sophisticated for my taste... }
9... Nc6 10. O-O
{ There's no need to worry about the pawn on  e5  , although the protecting  10.Qf4  is also strong. }
10... Nxe5 11. Nxe5 Qxe5 12. bxc3
{ Black will soon struggle on the a1-h8 diagonal, as it won't take long for us to get a bishop to d4. }
12... Qxc3
{ Greedy, but what else?  12...Nf6  is met by  Qh4  , followed by a swift Be3-Bd4. }
13. Be3 e5
{ A logical way to stop Bd4, but Black's position was still hopeless after }
14. Qh4 d4 15. Bg5
{ In Zlochevskij,A-Frog,I Moscow 1986 due to his poor development. Ra5 or Rfe1 comes next, when I doubt that the e5 pawn will make it. }
