[Black "3...Bb4 (5...cxd4 6)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ We have finally arrived to the main bulk of our coverage on the French, and our very last topic to cover for Part 1! This is the Winawer Variation, named after Szymon Winawer and popularized later in the 1940s by the greats Nimzowitch and Botvinnik. After 3... Bb4, Black pins the knight and thus attacks the pawn on e4 so we're forced to make a decision in the center. }
4. e5
{ This is by far the most challenging move against the Winawer. We're gaining additional space while we're also limiting Black's knight on g8 as it can no longer jump to f6. }
4... c5
{ Black's main move challenges our center immediately, a necessary course of action to obtain the desired counterplay on the queenside. }
5. a3
{ By far the most played move as this is the only way to maintain the strong pawn chain. }
5... cxd4
{ This move looks rather dubious to me. The pawn on b4 is more of a strength than a weakness, while Black struggles on the dark squares and with obtaining a sufficient amount of counterplay on the queenside. }
6. axb4 dxc3 7. Qg4
{ This move gives Black huge problems as we get a tremendous amount of compensation for the sacrificed pawn. }
7... cxb2
{ Black wins a pawn, but our strong pieces outweigh it on a large scale. In particular, our dark-squared bishop. }
8. Bxb2 Qe7 { Black fights our threat of Qxg7 with a counterattack. } 9. Bd3
{ The simplest is often the best. On chess24 I suggested  9.Bc3  with the idea of meeting  9...Qc7  with  10.Ra3  . The line is still good, but annoyingly complex after  9...f5  10.Qg3  Nh6!?  11.Bd2  Nc6  12.b5  f4  when the position is not so easy to navigate.  9.Ba3  is fancy as well, with the idea of  b5  . I encountered the same issue here. It's objectively strong, but unnecessary complex. After  9.Bd3  it's simple to play White, while our edge is very high. }
9... f5
{ The advantage of having the queen placed on e7.   9...Nh6  is nothing to worry about, as we can take the pawn on  g7  .  10.Qxg7  Qxb4+  is dodged by  11.Ke2  . Our king looks exposed, but it's surprisingly secure as we're able to defend the pawn on  e5  in time with  Nf3  .  11...Rg8  12.Qxh6  Qxb2  13.Nf3  Nc6  14.Rhb1  Qc3  15.Qxh7  was Kasper, M - Van der Moot, H ICCF email 2010, when the h-pawn eventually ran up the board and promoted. }
10. Qf4 Nh6 11. Nf3 O-O 12. O-O
{ Was really good for White in Davletov,J - Wiacek,K ICCF email 2006, with b5-Ba3-c4 coming in short order. Black is suffering a lot on the dark squares. The extra pawn remains insignificant. }
