[White "24. French Defense (1...e6) Winawer Sidelines"]
[Black "3...Bb4 (5...cxd4 5)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ We have finally arrived to the main bulk of our coverage on the French, and our very last topic to cover for Part 1! This is the Winawer Variation, named after Szymon Winawer and popularized later in the 1940s by the greats Nimzowitch and Botvinnik. After 3... Bb4, Black pins the knight and thus attacks the pawn on e4 so we're forced to make a decision in the center. }
4. e5
{ This is by far the most challenging move against the Winawer. We're gaining additional space while we're also limiting Black's knight on g8 as it can no longer jump to f6. }
4... c5
{ Black's main move challenges our center immediately, a necessary course of action to obtain the desired counterplay on the queenside. }
5. a3
{ By far the most played move as this is the only way to maintain the strong pawn chain. }
5... cxd4
{ This move looks rather dubious to me. The pawn on b4 is more of a strength than a weakness, while Black struggles on the dark squares and with obtaining a sufficient amount of counterplay on the queenside. }
6. axb4 dxc3 7. Qg4
{ This move gives Black huge problems as we get a tremendous amount of compensation for the sacrificed pawn. }
7... Ne7
{ Black plays in the style of the 7... Qg4-line, the main tabiya of the Winawer by sacrificing two pawns on the kingside. }
8. Qxg7 { We should accept the challenge. } 8... Rg8 9. Qxh7 Qc7
{ In my series on chess24 I forgot to mention the move  9...cxb2  , but after  10.Bxb2  Qb6  11.c3  Black's compensation looks nonexistent. Duduev, V - Sousa, C ICCF email 2018.   9...Nbc6  10.bxc3!  Strong, as we keep the pawn on b4 protected.  10...Nxe5   I don't see any compensation after  10...Qc7  11.Bf4  Nxe5  12.Ne2  .  11.h4!  A really strong move with the familiar idea of defending the pawn on c3 by placing our rook on h3. Additionally, h4 allows us to play Bg5 which is certainly useful in some lines.  11...Qc7  12.Rh3  Ng4   The trickiest move.  12...Bd7  13.Ne2  O-O-O  14.Bg5  was seen in another email game, when Black was forced to give the exchange.   14...Nf5  15.Bxd8  Qxd8  16.Qh5  Ng4  17.Nd4  is how the game proceeded when Black was lost in Beresford, A - Thurstan, A ICCF email 2017.  13.Bg5  Qe5+  14.Ne2  Nf6  15.Qh6  Ne4  Things still look slightly chaotic, but we have everything under control after  16.Bf4+-  when Black was forced to head into a lost endgame which White converted comfortably in Wuerschner,M Skorna,U ICCF email 2017. }
10. Nf3 Nbc6 { And here, we have another powerful rook swing } 11. Ra3
{ That forces Black to capture the pawn on b2. } 11... cxb2 12. Bxb2 Nxb4
{ This pawn hangs, but it doesn't matter as we are able to finish the development of our pieces. }
13. Bb5+ Bd7 14. Rc3 { Gaining a tempo on the queen. } 14... Qb6 15. Bxd7+ Kxd7
16. O-O { Our king is safe, while Black's king is stuck on d7. } 16... Raf8 17.
Rb3
{ Black had huge problems in the b-file in Rimkus,B -Oppermann,P ICCF email 2011. }
