[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "24. French Defense (1...e6) Winawer Sidelines"]
[Black "3...Bb4 (5...Ba5 6...cxb4 2)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ We have finally arrived to the main bulk of our coverage on the French, and our very last topic to cover for Part 1! This is the Winawer Variation, named after Szymon Winawer and popularized later in the 1940s by the greats Nimzowitch and Botvinnik. After 3... Bb4, Black pins the knight and thus attacks the pawn on e4 so we're forced to make a decision in the center. }
4. e5
{ This is by far the most challenging move against the Winawer. We're gaining additional space while we're also limiting Black's knight on g8 as it can no longer jump to f6. }
4... c5
{ Black's main move challenges our center immediately, a necessary course of action to obtain the desired counterplay on the queenside. }
5. a3
{ By far the most played move as this is the only way to maintain the strong pawn chain. }
5... Ba5
{ Black keeps the bishop and maintains the pressure on our center. It's necessary to be aware of how to react to this sideline, since our center will quickly fall apart after cxd4. }
6. b4
{ We're interfering with Black's plans of attacking our center by sacrificing a pawn.  6.Qg4  is the alternative, when the position after  6...Ne7  7.dxc5  Bxc3+  8.bxc3  has been thoroughly discussed between strong GMs. I'm not convinced that White has much here. }
6... cxb4
{ Grabbing the pawn is subpar to  6...cxd4  , as we get a lot of compensation for the pawn. }
7. Nb5 bxa3+
{ Black retains the extra pawn, but for a heavy price as our bishop will be a monster on a3. }
8. c3 Ne7
{ 8...Bc7?  Is the most played move in my online database, but I think it just loses.  9.Qg4  Black is now forced to make a concession.  9...g6   9...Kf8  is no better, when  10.Bxa3+  is strong, followed by  Nh3  and  Bxe7  . Black needs to watch out for ideas such as  Nxd5  and Nh5-Nf6.  10.Rxa3!   Is somehow even stronger than  10.Bxa3  . The point is to make use of Black's poor development, in the sense that  10...a6  will no longer be a threat due to the hanging rook on  a8  .  10...Nc6  And now I like provoking yet another concession with  11.h4  When we will have a very nice outpost on g5 after  11...h5  12.Qf3  Nge7  13.Bg5+-  White's initiative is overwhelming, as Black is far too passive and weak on the dark squares. }
9. Nd6+
{ 9.Bxa3  , the move I suggested on chess24, is also quite strong here, but it turns out that this move is even more convincing. }
9... Kf8 10. Qf3
{ Black is forced to play  10...Nf5  which will create a very weak pawn on  d5  . A very good practical decision as white's play is easy to grasp. I suspect that  10.Qh5  might be even better, as Black has to find  10...g6  11.Qh6+  Kg8  12.Rxa3  Bc7!  . This position leads to a massive edge, but it's not THAT easy. In the games I found online Black had played  10.. .Ng6  which leads to complete domination as Black has major problems with his king safety.  11.Qf3  Qc7  12.Rxa3  Nc6  13.Rxa5!  Nxa5  14.h4  h5  15.Bd3  Kg8  16.Bxf5  gxf5  17.Nh3  Nc6  18.O-O  a5  19.Ng5  a4  20.Ba3  and I was left in awe. There are no words that can describe Black's position. Perhaps abominable fits! }
10... Nf5 11. Nxf5 exf5 12. Bb5
{ We can always capture the pawn, so there's no need to do so right away. With  12.Bb5  we aim to eventually target Black's pawn by placing the bishop on  b3  , while we also don't take the e2-square from our knight. }
12... Nc6 13. Bxa3+ Kg8 14. Ne2 { We won't fall for Nxd4! } 14... a6
{ It's hard to tell what Black is supposed to do. Our plan of playing Ba4-Bb3-Nf4 is incredibly straightforward and tough to do anything about. }
15. Ba4 Be6 16. O-O
{ The king is safe so we're completely ready to attack Black's pawn. } 16... b5
{ 16...Qd7  doesn't help, as the move  17.Bd6  kills Black's hopes of defending the pawn. }
17. Bb3 Qd7 18. Bd6 { The pawn on d5 falls. } 18... Bc7 19. Bxc7 Qxc7 20. Bxd5
Bxd5 21. Qxd5
{ White regained the pawn and thus had a completely winning position in Townsend,W-Katz,A Parsipanny 2009. }
