9. Nd6+
{ 9.Bxa3  , the move I suggested on chess24, is also quite strong here, but it turns out that this move is even more convincing. }
9... Kf8 10. Qf3
{ Black is forced to play  10...Nf5  which will create a very weak pawn on  d5  . A very good practical decision as white's play is easy to grasp. I suspect that  10.Qh5  might be even better, as Black has to find  10...g6  11.Qh6+  Kg8  12.Rxa3  Bc7!  . This position leads to a massive edge, but it's not THAT easy. In the games I found online Black had played  10...Ng6  which leads to complete domination as Black has major problems with his king safety.  11.Qf3  Qc7  12.Rxa3  Nc6  13.Rxa5!  Nxa5  14.h4  h5  15.Bd3  Kg8  16.Bxg6  fxg6  17.Nh3  Nc6  18.O-O  a5  19.Ng5  a4  20.Ba3  and I was left in awe. There are no words that can describe Black's position. Perhaps abominable fits! }
10... Nf5 11. Nxf5 exf5 12. Bb5
{ We can always capture the pawn, so there's no need to do so right away. With  12.Bb5  we aim to eventually target Black's pawn by placing the bishop on  b3  , while we also don't take the e2-square from our knight. }
12... Qb6 { Is trickier, as Black attacks targets two pieces. } 13. Qd3
{ Double attack is met by double defense!  13.Bxa3+  should lead to the same. }
13... a6 14. Bxa3+ Kg8 15. Ba4
{ Similarly to  12...Nc6  , we'll target Black's weak pawn. } 15... Qg6
{ Played in 3/3 games, so let's take a look.  15...Nc6  16.Ne2  Be6  17.O-O  leads to similar play to  12...Nc6  . }
16. Ne2 { There's no reason to be worried about the pawn on g2. } 16... f4
{ Black tempts us into trading queens, an offer we will of course decline.   16...Qxg2  17.Rg1  Qe4  Is met by  18.Qh3  When Black's queen on e4 will be trapped.  18...Nd7   18...h5  is objectively best, when  19.Kd2  Bd8  20.f4  traps the queen, as  Bc2  comes.  19.Bc2  A fancy way to win the game as  19...Qxc2  Leads to mate after  20.Rxg7+!  20...Kxg7  21.Qg3+  Kh6  22.Qh4+  Kg6  23.Nf4+  Kg7  24.Qg5#  . }
17. Qd2 Qxg2
{ The best practical chance. After something like  17...Nc6  , the pawn on  f4  hangs and Black is left with zero counterplay. }
18. Rg1 Qf3 19. Bb2
{ With the pawn on c3 protected, we can happily take on f4 with the queen in the next move when Black's position is hopeless. }
