[White "24. French Defense (1...e6) Winawer Sidelines"]
[Black "3...Bb4 (5...Ba5 6...cxd4)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ We have finally arrived to the main bulk of our coverage on the French, and our very last topic to cover for Part 1! This is the Winawer Variation, named after Szymon Winawer and popularized later in the 1940s by the greats Nimzowitch and Botvinnik. After 3... Bb4, Black pins the knight and thus attacks the pawn on e4 so we're forced to make a decision in the center. }
4. e5
{ This is by far the most challenging move against the Winawer. We're gaining additional space while we're also limiting Black's knight on g8 as it can no longer jump to f6. }
4... c5
{ Black's main move challenges our center immediately, a necessary course of action to obtain the desired counterplay on the queenside. }
5. a3
{ By far the most played move as this is the only way to maintain the strong pawn chain. }
5... Ba5
{ Black keeps the bishop and maintains the pressure on our center. It's necessary to be aware of how to react to this sideline, since our center will quickly fall apart after cxd4. }
6. b4
{ We're interfering with Black's plans of attacking our center by sacrificing a pawn.  6.Qg4  is the alternative, when the position after  6...Ne7  7.dxc5  Bxc3+  8.bxc3  has been thoroughly discussed between strong GMs. I'm not convinced that White has much here. }
6... cxd4
{ Black's best try for counterplay, as our center is less powerful without the pawn on d4. }
7. Nb5
{ 7.Qg4  might be more dangerous on paper, but there's a lot to learn here while the positions remain complicated. This is slightly unattractive to me, as  5...Ba5  is a sideline you will face very seldom. Black has two main alternatives.  7...Ne7  is considered very good for White,  8.bxa5  dxc3  9.Qxg7  Rg8  10.Qxh7  Nbc6  11.Nf3  . Black has several ways of playing, and the positions are tricky, despite our big advantage.  7...Kf8  is the modern way played by the World Champion Magnus Carlsen and Mamedyarov among others, as the engines dislike  7...Ne7  . }
7... Bb6
{ This is almost never played, as it allows us to jump onto the square on d6. However, some strong GMs have tried the move, so we should check it. }
8. Nd6+ { There's no reason not to make use of the opportunity. } 8... Kf8 9.
f4
{ It's necessary to play this move before placing the knight on f3, in order to protect the vulnerable pawn on e5. }
9... Nc6
{ There's no need to worry about the move  9...a6  as we can ignore Black's plan completely of grabbing the knight on  d6  , similarly to what we'll see in this sample line. After  10.Nf3  Bc7  11.Qxd4  is strong, as  11...Bxd6  12.exd6  Qxd6  13.Bb2  gives us an enormous amount of play for the missing pawn. }
10. Nf3 Nh6
{ Played in both of the games I found online.  10...Bc7  looks better here now that we can't take on  d4  with the queen. I would suggest meeting it with  11.Nb5  followed by  Bd3  or  Bb2  if Black plays  11...Bb6  . }
11. Bd3 a6
{ Black goes for the plan of getting rid of the annoying knight, but it's too slow. }
12. Bb2 Bc7 13. Nxd4 Bxd6
{ We have been following the French-GM encounter Bacrot,E - Baucer,C Nimes 2014, when I think the simplest solution is to play }
14. Nxc6 bxc6 15. exd6 Qxd6 16. O-O
{ When our dark-squared bishop is a monster. Black's extra pawn is insignificant. The game could continue  16...Nf5  17.Bxf5  exf5  18.Be5  Qe7  19.Bd4  Kg8  20.Qh5  Be6  21.Rf3  when Black is under a deadly attack. }
