[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ This is the Winawer Variation, named after Szymon Winawer and popularized later in the 1940s by the greats Nimzowitch and Botvinnik. After 3... Bb4, Black pins the knight and thus attacks the pawn on e4 so we're forced to make a decision in the center. }
4. e5
{ This is by far the most challenging move against the Winawer. We're gaining additional space while we're also limiting Black's knight on g8 as it can no longer jump to f6. }
4... c5
{ Black's main move challenges our center immediately, a necessary course of action to obtain the desired counterplay on the queenside. }
5. a3
{ By far the most played move as this is the only way to maintain the strong pawn chain. }
5... Ba5
{ Black keeps the bishop and maintains the pressure on our center. It's necessary to be aware of how to react to this sideline, since our center will quickly fall apart after cxd4. }
6. b4
{ We're interfering with Black's plans of attacking our center by sacrificing a pawn. }
6... cxd4
{ Black's best try for counterplay, as our center is less powerful without the pawn on d4. }
7. Nb5 Bc7 8. f4
{ This is the main tabiya of the 5... Ba5-variation, when Black needs to make a decision on which set-up he should go for. Our set-up usually consists of Bd3-Bb2-Nf3-Qe2-O-O in some order. }
8... a6
{ I don't think this move makes too much sense, as we're planning to take on c7 anyway at some point. }
9. Nxc7+ Qxc7 10. Bb2 Nc6 11. Nf3
{ The plan is to get all the pieces out before we choose to capture the hanging pawn. f4 strengthens our center, but don't forget that the e3-square is potentially available for the black knight via f5. }
11... Nge7 12. Bd3
{ Don't rush with the capture of the pawn!  12.Nxd4  is way too soon, when Black can make use of our bad development with  12...Nxd4  13.Bxd4  Nf5  . }
12... Bd7
{ 12... Nf5 can be answered the same way.   12...O-O ??  Would lose the game immediately due to the thematic tactical trick  13.Bxh7+!  When  13...Kxh7  14.Ng5+  Kg6  15.Qd3+  Nf5  16.g4  f6  17.Qh3+-  Is the end for Black, due to our powerful attack. }
13. Qe2
{ This might look slightly odd, but we're preparing against Black's knight jump to f5 when Ne3 will no longer come with a tempo. Besides that, our queen may target Black's pawn by moving to f2. }
13... Nf5 14. O-O O-O 15. Qf2
{ The queen targets the pawn on d4, while also g4 followed by Bxh7 is a trick Black needs to watch out for. }
15... f6 { Makes sense as it fights our center, when I think } 16. Bxf5 exf5
17. Bxd4 fxe5 18. Nxe5 Nxe5 19. Bxe5
{ Is excellent for us, due to our incredible bishop on e5. } *

