1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ This is the Winawer Variation, named after Szymon Winawer and popularized later in the 1940s by the greats Nimzowitch and Botvinnik. After 3... Bb4, Black pins the knight and thus attacks the pawn on e4 so we're forced to make a decision in the center. }
4. e5
{ This is by far the most challenging move against the Winawer. We're gaining additional space while we're also limiting Black's knight on g8 as it can no longer jump to f6. }
4... c5
{ Black's main move challenges our center immediately, a necessary course of action to obtain the desired counterplay on the queenside. }
5. a3
{ By far the most played move as this is the only way to maintain the strong pawn chain. }
5... Ba5
{ Black keeps the bishop and maintains the pressure on our center. It's necessary to be aware of how to react to this sideline, since our center will quickly fall apart after cxd4. }
6. b4
{ We're interfering with Black's plans of attacking our center by sacrificing a pawn. }
6... cxd4
{ Black's best try for counterplay, as our center is less powerful without the pawn on d4. }
7. Nb5 Bc7 8. f4
{ This is the main tabiya of the 5... Ba5-variation, when Black needs to make a decision on which set-up he should go for. Our set-up usually consists of Bd3-Bb2-Nf3-Qe2-O-O in some order. }
8... Nc6
{ Is likely to lead to similar play like we've already seen, for example: } 9.
Nf3 Nge7 10. Bd3
{ One difference is that Black's knight has moved from b8 early, making a retreat to b8 with the bishop an additional option.   A standard way of playing would be to play  10...Nf5  , preventing the capture on  h7  , when  11.Qe2  will be our response with the same ideas of  O-O  ,  Nxc7  ,  Bb2  etc. }
10... Bb8
{ Black keeps the bishop for the price of spending a lot of time. The bishop on b8 won't do anything, until Black has played a6 and placed it on a7. }
11. Nbxd4
{ We can play  11.O-O  first, but now that we can no longer grab the bishop, I prefer to get the knight out of there right away. }
11... a5
{ Is Black's best try.   11...Nxd4  12.Nxd4  a6  13.Be3  Ba7  14.Qe2±   White's space advantage gave him a very nice position in Westerinen, H-Dueckstein, A Lugano 1968. The Finnish GM played a very nice game and was soon completely winning after  14...Bd7  15.O-O  O-O  16.Rf3  g6  17.Rh3  Nc6  18.Nf3  f6  19.Rf1  Bxe3+  20.Qxe3  Rf7  21.c4  fxe5  22.Ng5  Rg7  23.fxe5  d4  24.Qg3  Ne7  25.Nxh7  . }
12. Bb2
{ 12.b5  looks tempting, but the problem is that it gives away our nice control of the dark squares. Black can trade some minor pieces with  12...Nxd4  13.Nxd4  Ba7  14.Be3  Nf5  , when I think he's not far away from equality. The point of the text is to give us the option of taking with the bishop on  d4  , which will give us the necessary control over the dark squares. }
12... axb4 { Is Black's best try. } 13. O-O
{ Securing our king before recapturing on b4. } 13... Ba7
{ 13...Nxd4  or  13...bxa3  is likely to lead to the same. } 14. axb4 Bxd4+
{ Is Black's best try as he's able to trade more pieces.   14...Nxb4  If Black takes like this, we should respond with  15.Ba3  With a lot of compensation after  15...Nbc6  16.c3⇆  We can consider ideas such as Rf2-Rfa2 or even Kh1-Qe2-g4-f5 with a powerful attack. }
15. Bxd4 Rxa1 16. Qxa1 Nxb4
{ When we maintain a strong amount of pressure after } 17. Qa4+ Nbc6
{ Not  17...Nec6?  when Black is in big trouble after  18.Bb5  followed by  Bc5  . }
18. Bc5 Qa5 { Black forces the trade of queens, but is still worse after } 19.
Qxa5 Nxa5 20. Kf2 { As our bishop pair outweighs the extra pawn. } *

