{ With this move, Black aims to play Bb5 at some point to trade the bishops. }
13. Rf2
{ A strong continuation, intending to play Nxd4 now that Black can't take the knight with check. }
13... Bb5
{ 13...Nbc6?  Would be a huge error due to  14.b5!  The pawn is untouchable due to Rb1 followed by a4, so Black faces a danger of getting the bishop trapped.  14...Na5  15.Rb1  Rb4 is an annoying threat that can only be prevented by playing  15...a6  Black saves the bishop, but is still in big trouble after  16.f5!  A strong attacking move  16...Nxf5   16...exf5  is also terrible after  17.Bg5  axb5  18.Bxe7  Kxe7  19.Bxb5  Bxb5  20.Nxd4  .  17.Bxf5  exf5  18.Nxd4+-  With an overwhelming initiative. Black's minor pieces on the queenside are completely out of the game. }
14. a4
{ Taking control of some light square while we still can.  14.Bxb5+  Qxb5  15.Nxd4  Qxc4  looks quite even to me. Bellegotti, G - Loeschnauer, E ICCF email 2014. }
14... Bxd3 15. cxd3
{ An important way to capture as we take control of the squares on e4 and c4, while opening the c-file. }
15... Nf5
{ 15...O-O  16.a5  Qd8  17.b5  looks extremely good for us due to our powerful pawns. }
16. h3
{ Preparing to one day play g4, while our king receives some shelter on h2. }
16... O-O 17. Bb2
{ 17.g4  was also strong, but this move is more than good enough. } 17... Ne7
{ A passive move with the idea of tempting us into taking the pawn on d4.   17...Nd7  isn't much better, when  18.g4  comes, followed by a quick a5-b5. Black is very passive. }
18. Rc2 Nd7 19. a5 Qb5
{ The best move objectively, but it loses material.  19...Qd8  20.Nxd4  gives us an overwhelming advantage as well. Black is too passive. }
20. Rc7 { Black can't prevent the threat of playing Nxd4, followed by Bc3. }
20... Rfc8 21. Nxd4 Qxb4 22. Bc3
{ White won material and eventually converted his advantage in Milde,L -Droessler,U ICCF email 2018. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "24. French Defense (1...e6) Winawer Sidelines"]
[Black "3...Bb4 (5...Ba5 6...cxd4 8)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ This is the Winawer Variation, named after Szymon Winawer and popularized later in the 1940s by the greats Nimzowitch and Botvinnik. After 3... Bb4, Black pins the knight and thus attacks the pawn on e4 so we're forced to make a decision in the center. }
4. e5
{ This is by far the most challenging move against the Winawer. We're gaining additional space while we're also limiting Black's knight on g8 as it can no longer jump to f6. }
4... c5
{ Black's main move challenges our center immediately, a necessary course of action to obtain the desired counterplay on the queenside. }
5. a3
{ By far the most played move as this is the only way to maintain the strong pawn chain. }
5... Ba5
{ Black keeps the bishop and maintains the pressure on our center. It's necessary to be aware of how to react to this sideline, since our center will quickly fall apart after cxd4. }
6. b4
{ We're interfering with Black's plans of attacking our center by sacrificing a pawn. }
6... cxd4
{ Black's best try for counterplay, as our center is less powerful without the pawn on d4. }
7. Nb5 Bc7 8. f4
{ This is the main tabiya of the 5... Ba5-variation, when Black needs to make a decision on which set-up he should go for. Our set-up usually consists of Bd3-Bb2-Nf3-Qe2-O-O in some order. }
8... Ne7 9. Nf3 Bd7
{ This line has the same intention as 8... Bd7 of capturing our knight, our placing the bishop on a4. }
10. Nxc7+ Qxc7 11. Bd3 Ba4 12. O-O
{ Black has mainly tried three different approaches from this position: } 12...
Nbc6 { Looks incredibly natural, but it's not good due to } 13. b5
{ We're attacking the knight with a tempo. Black's problem is the bishop on a4 which is suddenly in danger of getting trapped! }
13... Na5 { 13...Nd8  would be way too passive after  14.Nxd4  . } 14. Qe1
{ An excellent move! The queen is eyeing the square on b4. } 14... Qb6
{ Black defends with tactics, as  15.Qb4  is met by  15...Bxc2!  with  d3+  next.   14...a6  Doesn't work, due to the brilliant  15.b6!  And White won a piece after  15...Qxb6  16.Qb4  Bb5  17.a4  Nec6  18.Qb1+-  In Anton Guijarro,D -Kazhgaleyev,M chess.com INT 2020. }
15. f5
{ This crazy-looking engine move is incredibly strong.  15.Qf2  is more human, with a comfortable position after  15...Nc4  16.Nxd4  . Mickevicius, J - Schneider, K ICCF email 2017. }
15... exf5 16. Bg5 { Is a fantastic move, with the threat of Qb4. } 16... Ng6
17. Nh4
{ This move is also very strong with the intention of capturing the pawn and opening the f-file. }
17... Nxh4
{ 17...O-O  18.Nxf5  With the knight on f5, Qb4 is once again a threat as we have the option of parrying d3+ with Be3!  18...Nc4  And now we obtain a deadly attack after  19.Nxg7  Kxg7  20.Bf6+  The bishop on f6 causes deadly mating threats.  20...Kg8  21.Bxc4  dxc4  22.Qd2+-  Black can't stop Qh6. }
18. Bxh4
{ Black can't stop Qb4 next, winning a piece. The Bc2-trick can be parried by Bf2. }
*

