1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ This is the Winawer Variation, named after Szymon Winawer and popularized later in the 1940s by the greats Nimzowitch and Botvinnik. After 3... Bb4, Black pins the knight and thus attacks the pawn on e4 so we're forced to make a decision in the center. }
4. e5
{ This is by far the most challenging move against the Winawer. We're gaining additional space while we're also limiting Black's knight on g8 as it can no longer jump to f6. }
4... c5
{ Black's main move challenges our center immediately, a necessary course of action to obtain the desired counterplay on the queenside. }
5. a3
{ By far the most played move as this is the only way to maintain the strong pawn chain. }
5... Ba5
{ Black keeps the bishop and maintains the pressure on our center. It's necessary to be aware of how to react to this sideline, since our center will quickly fall apart after cxd4. }
6. b4
{ We're interfering with Black's plans of attacking our center by sacrificing a pawn. }
6... cxd4
{ Black's best try for counterplay, as our center is less powerful without the pawn on d4. }
7. Nb5 Bc7 8. f4
{ This is the main tabiya of the 5... Ba5-variation, when Black needs to make a decision on which set-up he should go for. Our set-up usually consists of Bd3-Bb2-Nf3-Qe2-O-O in some order. }
8... Ne7 9. Nf3 Bd7
{ This line has the same intention as 8... Bd7 of capturing our knight, our placing the bishop on a4. }
10. Nxc7+ Qxc7 11. Bd3 Ba4 12. O-O
{ Black has mainly tried three different approaches from this position: } 12...
a6
{ Black prepares to trade bishops with Bb5, and simultaneously evades all the b5-tactics we've seen earlier. }
13. Nxd4 { It's finally time to take the pawn. } 13... Nbc6
{ Not  13...O-O?  when our attack is already decisive after  14.Qh5  . } 14.
Nb3
{ A pretty interesting novelty I found, intending to one day jump to  c5  while also keeping an extra piece on the board.  14.Be3  has been the standard way, but I dislike the massive trading of pieces after  14...Nxd4  15.Bxd4  Bb5  . White has a very tiny edge here and I suppose it's also easier to play in practice, but I'm hungry for more! }
14... O-O 15. Be3 Rfc8
{ Black can also try placing the rook in the c-file.  15...Bb5  transposes to the previous note. }
16. Rf3
{ A strong rook swing. Black needs to be on the lookout for Bxh7+ ideas. }
16... h6
{ Seems like the most sensible move, as Rh3-ideas are no longer available.   16...Bb5?  Would lose due to  17.Bxh7+  Kxh7  18.Rh3+  Kg8  19.Qh5  When Black will either get mated or lose decisive material, for example  19...Kf8  20.Qh8+  Ng8  21.Rh7+-  And we break through. }
17. Bf2
{ This 'waiting' move is rather useful as Black no longer gets Nf5 with a tempo. It's not so easy for Black to find anything to do. I think }
