[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "24. French Defense (1...e6) Winawer Sidelines"]
[Black "3...Bb4 (6...cxd4)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ We have finally arrived to the main bulk of our coverage on the French, and our very last topic to cover for Part 1! This is the Winawer Variation, named after Szymon Winawer and popularized later in the 1940s by the greats Nimzowitch and Botvinnik. Black pins the knight and thus attacks the pawn on e4 so we're forced to make a decision in the center. }
4. e5
{ This is by far the most challenging move against the Winawer. We're gaining additional space while we're also limiting Black's knight on g8 as it can no longer jump to f6. }
4... c5
{ Black's main move challenges our center immediately, a necessary course of action to obtain the desired counterplay on the queenside. }
5. a3
{ By far the most played move as this is the only way to maintain the strong pawn chain. }
5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3
{ We have reached the main position of the Winawer. Let's establish the position at hand and the different plans for both sides of the aisle: Black has managed to double our pawns, and indeed this is going to be the main source of Black's counterplay. The typical plan of playing b6-Ba6, a plan we have seen frequently in our French coverage, is still on the cards. Besides that, a natural way to proceed is to finish the development on the queenside with Nc6, Bd7, Qc7/Qa5 and castle long. In order to stop a potential attack on the queenside, Black usually closes it with c4. When this is accomplished, Black can prepare the pawn break f6. Castling kingside is not for the faint-hearted, as it's almost always extremely risky due to our strong foot on that side of the board. As we have extra space on the kingside, it's not surprising that most of our play will revolve around creating an initiative there. With the dark-squared bishop gone, Black has to be cautious of how he chooses to defend. A move like g6 for example, could easily be fatal due to the severe weakening of the dark squares. There are different approaches we can take, but I prefer the h4-h5-approach, just like in the chapter with 4... b6. Although our doubled pawns favor Black long-term, it doesn't mean that they're only a weakness to our position. The pawn on c3 supports our center, while the open b-file is often a useful asset. Having the pawn gone from b2 also allows us to play a4-Ba3, which is a very nice diagonal for our bishop. In this position, Black usually plays 6... Ne7 or 6... Qc7. For this chapter though, we'll take a look at the alternative lines, with 6... Qa5!? being the main course on the menu. }
6... cxd4
{ Goes completely against Black's plans.   6...c4?  Before we dive into the main topic of the chapter,  6...Qa5  , we will quickly check what happens if Black plays  6...c4  &  6...cxd4  .  6...c4  is 'according to plan, ' but it releases the tension against our center too early.   7.Qg4  Is once again the way to proceed.  7...Kf8   If Black tries  7...g6  , we can respond with  8.h4  with similar play.  7...Qa5  can be met by  8.Ne2  which shows the disadvantage of having played 6...c4, as Black no longer has cxd4  8.Kd2  is even possible as well, when we will place our bishop on  a3  .  8.h4!  This plan is usually extra effective when Black's king is on f8, as a rook swing to f3 could hurt.  8...Qa5  9.Ne2  Nc6  10.h5   Fixing the pawn structure, but there's nothing wrong with  10.a4  or  10.Rh3  .  10...h6  11.a4  The right diagonal for our bishop.  11...Nge7  12.Ba3+-  Black's position looks dead lost if you ask me, as we're intending Rh3-Rf3-Qf4. If Black's knight moves to f5 we can easily push it away with g4. }
7. cxd4 { We can thank our opponent for correcting our pawn structure! } 7...
Nc6 8. Bd3
{ A nice move that makes use of the fact that we have Qg4 if Black captures the pawn. }
8... Qc7 9. Nf3 { Not  9.c3?  as Black has the thematic trick  9...Nxe5! } 9...
Nxd4
{ Black has played this losing move in most games I found online. Something like  9...Nge7  is necessary, when we have everything we can dream of in the French with the white pieces. }
10. Nxd4 Qc3+ 11. Qd2 Qxa1 12. c3
{ Is now the simplest, as Black can't prevent the queen from being trapped with Nb3 in the next move. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "24. French Defense (1...e6) Winawer Sidelines"]
[Black "3...Bb4 (6...Nc6)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ We have finally arrived to the main bulk of our coverage on the French, and our very last topic to cover for Part 1! This is the Winawer Variation, named after Szymon Winawer and popularized later in the 1940s by the greats Nimzowitch and Botvinnik. Black pins the knight and thus attacks the pawn on e4 so we're forced to make a decision in the center. }
4. e5
{ This is by far the most challenging move against the Winawer. We're gaining additional space while we're also limiting Black's knight on g8 as it can no longer jump to f6. }
4... c5
{ Black's main move challenges our center immediately, a necessary course of action to obtain the desired counterplay on the queenside. }
5. a3
{ By far the most played move as this is the only way to maintain the strong pawn chain. }
5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Nc6
{ This is the first alternative we will consider. Black develops the knight to the natural c6-square, where it targets our pawn on d4. The downside with this move is that it's a slower way to attack our center compared to Qc7 which is more direct. }
7. Qg4 { We're not wasting any time! } 7... Kf8
{ Black avoids a concession for the prize of abandoning the plan of castling queenside. }
8. a4
{ I like this response. We take control over the square on b5 while a3 is a potential home for our bishop on c1. }
8... Nge7 9. Nf3 Qa5
{ A very logical way to proceed as Black forces our bishop to d2.9...  cxd4  10.cxd4  Nb4  looks a bit scary, but the brilliant  11.Kd2!  gives us a decisive advantage. Our center is too powerful, Black doesn't have sufficient counterplay. For example  11...Nbc6  12.Bd3  Qa5+  13.Ke2  . You want to avoid playing  c3  , as it makes  b3  rather weak. }
10. Bd2 c4
{ Black closes the queenside.  10...Bd7  has also been tried, when I suggest playing  11.Be2  followed by  O-O  . We have a very simple game, as we're going to start playing against Black's king. Black's counterplay on the queenside is nonexistent.  10...Qb6  has also been tried, when  11.dxc5  Qxc5  12.Bd3  is simple and incredibly effective. Black experiences the same problem. His king is rather vulnerable while he doesn't have counterplay. }
11. h4 { A regular guest in these positions! } 11... b5
{ The only way Black can create something. } 12. h5 h6 13. Be2
{ We have obtained the pawn structure on the kingside that we desired, so it's time to complete our development and get our king to safety. }
13... bxa4 14. O-O Rb8 15. Ra2
{ We'll neutralize Black's play by doubling our rooks in the a-file. When that is accomplished, we will be free to do whatever we like on the kingside. }
15... Ba6
{ Black will keep the pawn defended, but how to make progress on the queenside? }
16. Rfa1 Bb5 17. Nh4
{ White is close to winning, with the very effective plan of playing Rd1-Qh3-Bc1-Ba3-f4-Bg4-f5. The problem for Black is that he has accomplished nothing on the queenside... Without counterplay, it's easy for us. }
