[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "24. French Defense (1...e6) Winawer Sidelines"]
[Black "3...Bb4 (6...Nc6 2)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ We have finally arrived to the main bulk of our coverage on the French, and our very last topic to cover for Part 1! This is the Winawer Variation, named after Szymon Winawer and popularized later in the 1940s by the greats Nimzowitch and Botvinnik. Black pins the knight and thus attacks the pawn on e4 so we're forced to make a decision in the center. }
4. e5
{ This is by far the most challenging move against the Winawer. We're gaining additional space while we're also limiting Black's knight on g8 as it can no longer jump to f6. }
4... c5
{ Black's main move challenges our center immediately, a necessary course of action to obtain the desired counterplay on the queenside. }
5. a3
{ By far the most played move as this is the only way to maintain the strong pawn chain. }
5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Nc6
{ This is the first alternative we will consider. Black develops the knight to the natural c6-square, where it targets our pawn on d4. The downside with this move is that it's a slower way to attack our center compared to Qc7 which is more direct. }
7. Qg4 { We're not wasting any time! } 7... Nge7
{ A standard reaction whenever we play Qg4. Black sacrifices the kingside pawns, but hopes that he will get sufficient counterplay on the queenside in return. Usually, Black's queen stands on c7 instead of Black's knight on c6. With the knight on c6, Black's play is slowed down. }
8. Qxg7 { We'll accept the challenge! } 8... Rg8 9. Qxh7 Qc7
{ If Black chooses to play Qc7 right away, I suggest going for } 10. Bf4
{ The bishop is well-placed on f4 where it guards the pawn on e5.   10.f4  is another way to proceed, but the text looks simpler to me. }
10... Qa5
{ The only alternative to  10...cxd4  , which will transpose to  9...cxd4  after  11.Nf3  . }
11. Bd2 Qa4
{ Black has only gotten himself a rather poor version of 6... Qa5 as he's left without the kingside pawns. Black has far from enough counterplay on the queenside to justify for this loss. }
12. h4
{ The h-pawn starts it's journey up the board. With h4 on the board, we can consider Rh3-Rf3-ideas and push the pawn even further. We have also taken complete control over the square on g5, so Ng5 is on the cards as well. }
12... cxd4 13. Nf3
{ Black has regained one pawn, but our play on the kingside is too powerful. }
13... Bd7 14. h5 { The h-pawn keeps going. } 14... dxc3
{ If  14...O-O-O  , we should respond with  15.Qd3  , when we will soon push the h-pawn even further. }
15. Bxc3 O-O-O 16. Rh4 { A neat advantage with having our pawn on h5. } 16...
Rg4 17. Bb5 { This move is the simplest as it forces the trade of queens. }
17... Qf4 18. Bd2 Qf5 19. Qxf5 exf5 20. Bg5
{ Our bishop pair and h-pawn is a deadly combination. Black is completely lost. }
