[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "24. French Defense (1...e6) Winawer Sidelines"]
[Black "3...Bb4 (6...Nc6 4)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ We have finally arrived to the main bulk of our coverage on the French, and our very last topic to cover for Part 1! This is the Winawer Variation, named after Szymon Winawer and popularized later in the 1940s by the greats Nimzowitch and Botvinnik. Black pins the knight and thus attacks the pawn on e4 so we're forced to make a decision in the center. }
4. e5
{ This is by far the most challenging move against the Winawer. We're gaining additional space while we're also limiting Black's knight on g8 as it can no longer jump to f6. }
4... c5
{ Black's main move challenges our center immediately, a necessary course of action to obtain the desired counterplay on the queenside. }
5. a3
{ By far the most played move as this is the only way to maintain the strong pawn chain. }
5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Nc6
{ This is the first alternative we will consider. Black develops the knight to the natural c6-square, where it targets our pawn on d4. The downside with this move is that it's a slower way to attack our center compared to Qc7 which is more direct. }
7. Qg4 { We're not wasting any time! } 7... Nge7
{ A standard reaction whenever we play Qg4. Black sacrifices the kingside pawns, but hopes that he will get sufficient counterplay on the queenside in return. Usually, Black's queen stands on c7 instead of Black's knight on c6. With the knight on c6, Black's play is slowed down. }
8. Qxg7 { We'll accept the challenge! } 8... Rg8 9. Qxh7 cxd4 10. Nf3 Qa5
{ Makes things worse for Black after   10...dxc3?  Doesn't work due to  11.Ng5  Our attack is incredibly fast. Black's pawn on c3 looks sweet, but our king is very safe on e1.  11...Rf8   11...Nxe5  loses the pawn on  f7  after  12.f4  .  12.Qh3!  Nh7 is a powerful threat. 12. f4 was also good enough in Gerhards,G - O'Neill Mc Aleenan,C ICCF email 2016.  12...Ng6   12...Nxe5  allows  13.Nh7  when Black loses an exchange.  13.f4  d4  14.Bd3+-  White has an overwhelming initiative. }
11. Rb1
{ A clever way to dodge the threat of Qxc3+ as we target Black's pawn on b7.   11.Bd2  would be inaccurate, since we don't want to give Black  dxc3  with a tempo! }
11... Bd7
{ The great Jan Timman played this against Short, but it turns out that the position is just hopeless after   11...Qxc3+  Black won a game from 1989 with this move, but it doesn't mean it's anything to worry about!  12.Bd2  Qxa3  13.Ng5  The most direct.  13...Rf8   13...Nxe5  can once again be answered by  14.f4  .  14.Bd3  We're preparing to castle. Simple chess!  14...Nxe5  And now  15.Bb4  Qa4  16.Qg7+-  Wins, as Nh7 will win decisive material. }
12. Rxb7 Qxc3+ 13. Kd1
{ Our king is perfectly placed on  d1!  13.Bd2??  allows  13...Qa1+  when Black wins after  14.Ke2  Bc8  . }
13... Na5 14. Rb4 Rc8
{ In Short, N - Timman, J Amsterdam 1988, the brit allowed Timman back into the game with the inaccurate  15.Ng5?  . Now,  15...Rg7!!  would have been a cold shower, when things are far from clear. Instead,  15...Rf8  was played when there was never any doubt about Short's win. My suggestion is }
15. Bd3 { When Black is completely busted. } *

