[White "24. French Defense (1...e6) Winawer Sidelines"]
[Black "3...Bb4 (6...Nc6 7)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ We have finally arrived to the main bulk of our coverage on the French, and our very last topic to cover for Part 1! This is the Winawer Variation, named after Szymon Winawer and popularized later in the 1940s by the greats Nimzowitch and Botvinnik. Black pins the knight and thus attacks the pawn on e4 so we're forced to make a decision in the center. }
4. e5
{ This is by far the most challenging move against the Winawer. We're gaining additional space while we're also limiting Black's knight on g8 as it can no longer jump to f6. }
4... c5
{ Black's main move challenges our center immediately, a necessary course of action to obtain the desired counterplay on the queenside. }
5. a3
{ By far the most played move as this is the only way to maintain the strong pawn chain. }
5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Nc6
{ This is the first alternative we will consider. Black develops the knight to the natural c6-square, where it targets our pawn on d4. The downside with this move is that it's a slower way to attack our center compared to Qc7 which is more direct. }
7. Qg4 { We're not wasting any time! } 7... g6
{ Weakens the dark squares, but Black does make sure that the pawn is protected and that castling queenside is still on the cards. }
8. a4
{ We react just like we did against 7... Kf8, preventing Qa5-Qa4 while Ba3 could be played in the future. }
8... f5
{ Tons of players have tried this speculative pawn launch. The point is that Black gains some space for his pieces, but I think it exposes Black too much on the dark squares. }
9. Qd1 { Our queen heads back, as we no longer need it on the kingside. } 9...
Qa5 { Almost exclusively played, so we won't consider other moves. } 10. Bd2 c4
{ Blocking the queenside immediately looks like Black's best try.   10...Nge7  To me it looks inaccurate to play this move before 10... c4, as it gives us an extra option in the move  11.Bb5  When our bishop is out on the board.  11...Bd7   11...a6  is even worse, when Black is completely destroyed on the dark squares after  12.Bxc6+  Nxc6  13.Ne2  c4  14.h4  Bd7  15.Bg5  .  12.Ne2  The right square for the knight, as it can reach the very nice square on f4. It also defends the pawn on c3.  12...O-O-O  13.O-O  c4  Black has blocked the queenside, but remains positionally lost as we're dominating on the dark squares.  14.Bg5  Rde8  15.Qd2  a6  16.Rfb1+-  Black is completely dominated. }
11. h4 { The most straightforward way to play. } 11... h6
{ Black intends to meet  12.h5  with  12...g5  .  Other moves are met by h5, when Black is just in big trouble. }
12. Ne2 Nge7
{ 12...Bd7  is apparently better, but after  13.Rh3  O-O-O  14.Rg3  Nge7  15.Qc1  Black is in serious trouble anyway, as  15...h5  16.Bg5  would leave Black positionally lost. }
13. Qc1 h5 { This is really ugly, but what else? } 14. f3
{ White prepares to place the king on f2 where it will be well placed. } 14...
Bd7 15. Kf2 Nd8 { 15...O-O-O  could be met by  16.Qa3  followed by  Bg5  . }
16. Bg5 Nf7 17. Bf6 { Our bishop is a monster! } 17... Rg8 18. Qa3 Nc6 19. Nf4
{ Black was completely outplayed in Timoshenko,G -Candura,S Siracusa 2006. A prime example of how things could go wrong for Black in the Winawer! }
*

