[White "24. French Defense (1...e6) Winawer Sidelines"]
[Black "3...Bb4 (6...Nc6 8)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ We have finally arrived to the main bulk of our coverage on the French, and our very last topic to cover for Part 1! This is the Winawer Variation, named after Szymon Winawer and popularized later in the 1940s by the greats Nimzowitch and Botvinnik. Black pins the knight and thus attacks the pawn on e4 so we're forced to make a decision in the center. }
4. e5
{ This is by far the most challenging move against the Winawer. We're gaining additional space while we're also limiting Black's knight on g8 as it can no longer jump to f6. }
4... c5
{ Black's main move challenges our center immediately, a necessary course of action to obtain the desired counterplay on the queenside. }
5. a3
{ By far the most played move as this is the only way to maintain the strong pawn chain. }
5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Nc6
{ This is the first alternative we will consider. Black develops the knight to the natural c6-square, where it targets our pawn on d4. The downside with this move is that it's a slower way to attack our center compared to Qc7 which is more direct. }
7. Qg4 { We're not wasting any time! } 7... g6
{ Weakens the dark squares, but Black does make sure that the pawn is protected and that castling queenside is still on the cards. }
8. a4
{ We react just like we did against 7... Kf8, preventing Qa5-Qa4 while Ba3 could be played in the future. }
8... Qa5 9. Bd2 c4 { Black proceeds with the same plan. } 10. h4
{ You know the drill by now! h4 intends the move h5 and practically forces Black to make a concession. }
10... h6
{ Black intends to meet h5 with g5. Allowing h5 with   10...Bd7  leads to pain and suffering for Black after  11.h5  O-O-O  12.Qf3  Nge7  13.Ne2  .   10...h5  Has been played, but it gives Black huge problems on the dark squares as we've seen earlier.  11.Qf4  Bd7  12.Nf3  The knight is on its way to the beautiful outpost on g5.  12...Nd8   Black's best chance.  12...Nge7  allows  13.Ng5  , when  13...Nf5  is met by  14.f3  and  g4  , and  13...Rf8  by  14. Nh7-Nf6+.  13.Ng5  Bxa4  Black has won a pawn and can only pray that he'll be able to withstand our pressure on the kingside.  14.g4  We should try to open the kingside before Black is able to consolidate.  14...hxg4  15.Qxg4  Qb5!   Black moves out of the pin and threatens thus  Bxc2  .  15...Ne7  is met by  16.Qf3  Nf5  17.h5  , when we break through.  16.Kd1  Ne7  17.Qf3  Nf5  Works this time, for a brilliant tactical reason.  18.Bh3   18.h5  is no longer the refutation, due to  18...Kd7!  If we play  19.hxg6+  , Black has the fantastic  19...Bxc2+  20.Kxc2  Qb3+  21.Kc1  Nxd4  , when the trades lead to an approximately equal game.  18...Nc6  Black regains some activity. The pawn on h4 couldn't be touched due to either Bxf5 or Qf6, depending on which piece Black takes with.  19.Bxf5   Not  19.Kc1??  when  19...Bxc2!  wins.  19...gxf5  20.h5  Ke7  21.Kc1+-  Our h-pawn is incredibly strong as it will get pushed to  h7  in the next moves. Black's extra pawn doesn't mean anything on the queenside. It's safe to say that Black is busted. Note that if Black plays  21...Na5  with the idea of  Nb3+  , we can easily dodge that by playing  22.Rb1  . }
11. Qg3
{ A really strong prophylactic move! The point can be seen after  11.h5?!  which gives Black a fine position after  11...g5  . Now, Black gets a really strong blockade after  12.f4?!  f5!  13.Qg3  g4!  when Black is clearly better. }
11... Nge7 12. Ne2 Bd7
{ The most sensible plan for Black is to complete the development and castle queenside. }
13. Qf3 { We target Black's pawn on f7 and make way for the g-pawn. } 13... Rh7
{ It's actually not necessary for Black to defend the pawn on  f7  , as we can't take it if Black plays  13...O-O-O  .  However, this move is useful because it allows Black to double the rook in the h-file or f-file if Black plays f6. }
14. g4 { It's time for us to take terrain on the kingside. } 14... O-O-O 15. h5
g5 { Black shouldn't allow us to play hxg6. } 16. Bg2 Ng8
{ Black's best try, aiming to play f6. } 17. Qg3 f6 18. O-O
{ We have a clear edge as we're planning the pawn break f2-f4 in the next move, with a nice space advantage. }
