[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "24. French Defense (1...e6) Winawer Sidelines"]
[Black "3...Bb4 (6...Qa5)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ We have finally arrived to the main bulk of our coverage on the French, and our very last topic to cover for Part 1! This is the Winawer Variation, named after Szymon Winawer and popularized later in the 1940s by the greats Nimzowitch and Botvinnik. Black pins the knight and thus attacks the pawn on e4 so we're forced to make a decision in the center. }
4. e5
{ This is by far the most challenging move against the Winawer. We're gaining additional space while we're also limiting Black's knight on g8 as it can no longer jump to f6. }
4... c5
{ Black's main move challenges our center immediately, a necessary course of action to obtain the desired counterplay on the queenside. }
5. a3
{ By far the most played move as this is the only way to maintain the strong pawn chain. }
5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Qa5
{ This move has always been a pretty popular sideline as not all players with Black are interested in venturing into the extreme complications that occur in the mainstream Winawer variations. Black is going to block the queenside entirely and later on castle long. }
7. Bd2 cxd4
{ Lots of players rated above 2000 have played this move, but that doesn't make it good! }
8. cxd4 Qa4
{ Black's idea is to apply pressure on the pawn on  d4  . If we play  9.c3  , the endgame after  9...Qxd1+  is not too bad. If we play  9.Nf3  , Black has  9...b6  followed by  Ba6  , when the queen on  a4  is very strong. Unfortunately for Black, these are not the only moves we can play... }
9. Rb1
{ After studying this position in great depth, I figured out that this is the best response. The idea is to sacrifice a pawn for a fantastic initiative. Black has to make a decision on which pawn to grab: }
9... Qxd4
{ Grabbing the central pawn makes more sense.   9...Nc6  10.Nf3  Qxa3  Taking the pawn on the rim doesn't look very testing to me, as we can greatly make use of the open files.  11.Bb5  Qe7   Black's queen escapes.  11...Bd7  is simply met by  12.O-O  with a lot of play for the pawn.  12.Bxc6+  Black has huge problems on the dark squares.  12...bxc6  13.Bb4  Qc7  14.Ra1  Our rook doesn't do anything special in the b-file now that Black's pawn stands on c6.  14...Ne7  15.Bd6   We throw in a tempo on the queen. Moves like  15.Qd2  or  15.O-O  were fine as well.  15...Qd8  16.Qd2  O-O  17.O-O  Re8  Black moves out of the pin in order to play Nf5.  18.Ra3  Nf5  19.Bc5+-  Black has an extra pawn but will pay the price for being so incredibly passive. }
10. Nf3 Qc5
{ 10...Qe4+  Is met by  11.Be2  Nc6  12.O-O  We gain too many tempos on Black's queen.  12...Nge7  13.Re1  Qg6  Black's queen has to move out of the way before we're able to trap it.  14.Ng5  Intending Bh5, so Black has to play  14...h5  And after  15.Bd3  Nf5  16.h4+-  Black is dominated. Rb3 followed by c4 or even Bxf5-Rg3 looks incredibly strong. }
11. Bb4 Qc7
{ Black's queen is safe for the time being, but we have gotten far too much play for the missing pawn. }
12. Bd6 Qc3+
{ 12...Qa5+  is met by the engine-move  13.Rb4  , with  Nd4  coming next. If Black tries  13...Nc6  , we can play  14.Bb5  when we'll have an overwhelming initiative on the dark squares after  14...Bd7  15.Bxc6  bxc6  O-O  . }
13. Nd2 { We will of course keep the queens on the board. } 13... Ne7 14. Rb3
Qa5 15. Bd3
{ Our bishop pair is incredibly strong. Note also that our rook on b3 may soon swing to the kingside. }
15... Nbc6 16. Qg4 Ng6
{ 16...O-O?  loses to  17.Qh4  when we win material. We have been following Zeller, F - Weiss, T Schwaebisch Gmuend 1999, when I suggest }
17. Qg3
{ With ideas such as h4-h5 and c3 followed by O-O. Black's greed has lead to an abysmal position. }
