[White "24. French Defense (1...e6) Winawer Sidelines"]
[Black "3...Bb4 (6...Qa5 2)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ We have finally arrived to the main bulk of our coverage on the French, and our very last topic to cover for Part 1! This is the Winawer Variation, named after Szymon Winawer and popularized later in the 1940s by the greats Nimzowitch and Botvinnik. Black pins the knight and thus attacks the pawn on e4 so we're forced to make a decision in the center. }
4. e5
{ This is by far the most challenging move against the Winawer. We're gaining additional space while we're also limiting Black's knight on g8 as it can no longer jump to f6. }
4... c5
{ Black's main move challenges our center immediately, a necessary course of action to obtain the desired counterplay on the queenside. }
5. a3
{ By far the most played move as this is the only way to maintain the strong pawn chain. }
5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Qa5
{ This move has always been a pretty popular sideline as not all players with Black are interested in venturing into the extreme complications that occur in the mainstream Winawer variations. Black is going to block the queenside entirely and later on castle long. }
7. Bd2 c4
{ The strong super-GM Yu from China has played this move twice in two blitz games, but it's an inaccurate move-order. }
8. Qg4 g6 9. h4
{ Our response is the same. Black is forced to make a pawn move he doesn't want to make. }
9... h6
{ Is still Black's best try, with the idea of playing  10...g5  after  10.h5  like we've seen so many times already.   9...h5  The problem with this move is the fact that we're handed a beautiful outpost on g5 for our knight.  10.Qf4  Bd7  11.a4+-  Black will suffer when we place a knight on  g5  .  11...Bxa4  could come, when we have somehow transposed to  10...h5  in the  6... Nc6-line after  12.Nh3  Nc6  13.Ng5  Nd8  14.g4  . }
10. Qg3
{ Our queen moves out of harm's way and opens the possibility of playing h5 followed by f4. }
10... Nc6 11. h5
{ If you're very observant, you might notice that  11.a4  transposes to  10...h6  in the  6... Nc6-line, but this is even better. }
11... g5 12. f4 f6 { Otherwise Black loses of course. } 13. Nf3
{ We don't want to take on f6 yet, as Black gets Nf6-Ne4 with an annoying amount of counterplay. We better get our pieces out first. }
13... Bd7
{ Black is ready to O-O-O and get his king to safety, so we should react with }
14. Nh4 { The knight is headed to g6. } 14... O-O-O
{ 14...gxh4?  loses to  15.Qg7  , while  14...Nge7  is still met by  15.Ng6  . }
15. Ng6 Rh7 16. Be2
{ Black is in big trouble as  16...fxe5  is always bet by  17.fxg5  which just wins for White.  It's tough for Black to find anything reasonable to do! Just make sure you don't castle yet, as Nxd4 is a nasty blow. Qe3 is a nice way to dodge this trick. }
