4... c5
{ Black's main move challenges our center immediately, a necessary course of action to obtain the desired counterplay on the queenside. }
5. a3
{ By far the most played move as this is the only way to maintain the strong pawn chain. }
5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Qa5
{ This move has always been a pretty popular sideline as not all players with Black are interested in venturing into the extreme complications that occur in the mainstream Winawer variations. Black is going to block the queenside entirely and later on castle long. }
7. Bd2 Ne7
{ Black develops the knight and waits a bit with the procedure on the queenside. }
8. Qg4 { A straightforward response. } 8... Kf8
{ I originally wanted to reward this move with an exclam, but I think the resulting positions are too difficult for Black to handle in practice.   8...Qa4?  Black has tried this move in some games, but it loses due to  9.Qxg7  Rg8  10.Qxh7  cxd4  11.Rb1  Nbc6   11...Bd7  is met by  12.cxd4  .  12.Bb5  Qxa3  13.Nf3  All of our minor pieces are out on the board, so we're ready to castle.  13...dxc3  14.Bg5  Bd7  15.O-O  +- Our initiative is so strong that we have a winning position. Ideas such as Bf6-Ng5 are incredibly dangerous, so  15...O-O-O  looks necessary. Here we have many good moves. I prefer  16.Bxc6  followed by  Ra1  and  Qxf7  .   8...Ng6?!  Is not very good due to  9.h4  h5  10.Qg3  c4  Black stops Bd3, but after  11.Be2±  Black has obtained nothing from playing Ne7-Ng6 followed by h5, instead of the standard 7... Qa4. With Qg5 coming next, Black will lose the pawn on h5 when we'll be close to winning. }
9. a4
{ We have seen this thematic move earlier in our coverage. It gives us a bit more space on the queenside, while we may also maneuver our bishop from d2 to a3 in the future. }
9... Nbc6 10. Be2
{ We don't want to move the bishop to d3, as Black would get c4 with a tempo. }
10... Qb6
{ I think this is the most difficult move to face over the board. Black can close the position with 10... c4 if he so desires, but we saw how to proceed. Develop and then launch an attack! }
11. Nf3 Qb2
{ Black's queen enters our camp, but we don't have to worry about the pawn on c2. }
12. O-O Qxc2
{ 12...c4  accomplishes nothing, as we can easily defend  c2  with  13.Rfc1  . }
13. dxc5 { We'll do this before Black is able to close the position. } 13...
Nxe5
{ Looks clever, but after   13...Qf5  Gives us a really nice endgame after  14.Qxf5  Nxf5  15.h4±  Black is incredibly passive. }
14. Nxe5 Qxd2 15. Qf3 f6 16. Nc4
{ Our knight will cause devastation to Black's position on d6.15... Nf5 was no better due to 16. Rab1, intending c4. Once again, 16... f6 could be answered with 17. Nc4. }
