[Round "?"]
[White "24. French Defense (1...e6) Winawer Sidelines"]
[Black "3...Bb4 (6...Qa5 5)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ We have finally arrived to the main bulk of our coverage on the French, and our very last topic to cover for Part 1! This is the Winawer Variation, named after Szymon Winawer and popularized later in the 1940s by the greats Nimzowitch and Botvinnik. Black pins the knight and thus attacks the pawn on e4 so we're forced to make a decision in the center. }
4. e5
{ This is by far the most challenging move against the Winawer. We're gaining additional space while we're also limiting Black's knight on g8 as it can no longer jump to f6. }
4... c5
{ Black's main move challenges our center immediately, a necessary course of action to obtain the desired counterplay on the queenside. }
5. a3
{ By far the most played move as this is the only way to maintain the strong pawn chain. }
5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Qa5
{ This move has always been a pretty popular sideline as not all players with Black are interested in venturing into the extreme complications that occur in the mainstream Winawer variations. Black is going to block the queenside entirely and later on castle long. }
7. Bd2 Ne7
{ Black develops the knight and waits a bit with the procedure on the queenside. }
8. Qg4 { A straightforward response. } 8... O-O
{ Black's top choice, but castling short is quite risky. } 9. Bd3 Nbc6
{ 9...c4?  Would now lose a pawn due to  10.Bxh7+  Kxh7  11.Qh4+  Kg8  12.Qxe7+-  When White is just winning. }
10. Nf3 { Bxh7+ is now a decisive threat, so Black usually plays } 10... f5
{ 10...f6  should lead to the same. } 11. exf6 Rxf6 12. Qh5
{ We don't want to allow Black to play e5 followed by e4. } 12... Nf5
{ 12...h6?  would lose to the nifty trick  13.Qe8+  Rf8  14.Bh7+  .  12...g6  is met by  13.Qg5  with  c4  coming next. }
13. c4
{ This move is very strong as Black is not allowed to play c4.   13.g4  c4  is less convincing, but also decent for White. Shirov, A - Khalifman, A Dos Hermanas 2003. }
13... Qa4
{ This variation was played by several GMs 15-20 years ago, but the modern engines show that it loses.   13...Qc7   Is apparently the lesser evil.  13...Qb6  is another alternative, when I suggest the simple approach  14.dxc5  Qxc5  15.cxd5  exd5  16.O-O  .  14.dxc5  Ne5  15.O-O !  It's important that we get our king to safety.  15...dxc4  16.Be4  Nxf3+  17.Qxf3±  White's pair of bishops gave him a very promising game in Hudak,D - Vecek,M ICCF email 2018 }
14. g4
{ The refutation!  14.cxd5  has been the most common move, when the line goes  14...Ncxd4  15.Ng5  h6  16.Ne4  Rf8  17.O-O  b6  18.Nc3  Qe8  19.Qxe8  Bxe8  and Black has equalized. A decent amount of games have been played here, for instance Sokolov, A - Rustemov, A Germany 2003. }
14... Ncxd4 { Black sacrifices a piece, as the knight on f5 can't move. } 15.
gxf5 dxc4 16. Be4
{ Black is a piece now, but the lingering question is... Can he create something in the gunfire? }
16... Nxc2+
{ 16...exf5  Almost works, but  17.Ng5!  Seals the victory for us.  17...h6  18.Bd5+  Kh8  19.Nf7+  Kh7?   This is even worse than  19...Kg8  , but who walks voluntarily into a discovered check just like that? White wins after  20.Nxh6+  Kf8  21.Bg5  . Komarica, B - Roehrig, U ICCF email 2017.  20.Nxh6  gxh6  21.Bxh6+-  Black either gets mated or loses decisive material. }
17. Kf1 { Very strong. Black has some counterplay after  17.Bxc2  Qxc2  . }
17... c3
{ The only way to prolong the game.  17...Nxa1  is met by  18.Bc3  when White wins. }
18. Bxc3 Qxe4
{ Some games also went  18...Qc4+  , but it doesn't make sense to me to give us  Kg2  for free. In case of  19.Kg2  Qxc3  , we win easily after  20.Rac1  . }
19. Bxf6 Bd7 20. Rg1 { The only move, but it's luckily a very logical one! }
20... Bb5+ 21. Kg2 Rf8 { 21...Nxa1  would lose to  22.Kh1  as  g7  falls. } 22.
Rad1
{ Another only move. The point is that we force an endgame in case Black takes our bishop. }
22... Rxf6
{ 22...Bc6  Is trickier, but Black loses after  23.Kh3!  Rxf6  24.Rd8+  Rf8  Black has almost made it out, but  25.f6!!  Is a killer move!  25...Rxd8  26.Rxg7+  Kh8  27.Ne5  And now the only way to avoid mate is  27...Rd3+  And now, Black runs out of checks after  28.f3  It's very close for Black, but not close enough...  28...Rxf3+  29.Nxf3  Qxf3+  30.Qxf3  Bxf3  And now the only move that wins is  31.Rg5+-  When Black resigned as the f-pawn is unstoppable in Wurschner,M -Walczak,P ICCF email 2007. }
23. Rd8+ Rf8 24. Rxf8+ Kxf8 25. fxe6
{ As Qxc5+ and Qf7# are threats, Black can't avoid an endgame with an exchange down. }
25... Qg6+ 26. Qxg6 hxg6 27. Kg3
{ White had played perfectly and converted his decisive advantage in Ruemmele,M -Szczepankiewicz, D ICCF email 2004. }
