[White "24. French Defense (1...e6) Winawer Sidelines"]
[Black "3...Bb4 (6...Qa5 8)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ We have finally arrived to the main bulk of our coverage on the French, and our very last topic to cover for Part 1! This is the Winawer Variation, named after Szymon Winawer and popularized later in the 1940s by the greats Nimzowitch and Botvinnik. Black pins the knight and thus attacks the pawn on e4 so we're forced to make a decision in the center. }
4. e5
{ This is by far the most challenging move against the Winawer. We're gaining additional space while we're also limiting Black's knight on g8 as it can no longer jump to f6. }
4... c5
{ Black's main move challenges our center immediately, a necessary course of action to obtain the desired counterplay on the queenside. }
5. a3
{ By far the most played move as this is the only way to maintain the strong pawn chain. }
5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Qa5
{ This move has always been a pretty popular sideline as not all players with Black are interested in venturing into the extreme complications that occur in the mainstream Winawer variations. Black is going to block the queenside entirely and later on castle long. }
7. Bd2 Qa4 { Black's main move and the main topic for the chapter. } 8. Qb1 a6
{ The strong polish GMs Socko and Bartel have played this move with an acceptable score, so let's check it to see how we should react. }
9. Nf3
{ On chess24 I gave  9.Qb3  Qxb3  10.cxb3  Nc6  11.dxc5  Nxe5  12.f4  Ng6  13.Nf3  Nf6  14.Be3  which is a very decent alternative. White gets a comfortable ending due to the bishop pair. However, I discovered that this move is even more dangerous for Black. }
9... Nc6 10. h4
{ Is a novelty in this very position, although if Black plays  10...Nge7  we have transposed to some other games. Our idea is to move the pawn up the board, and then swing the rook towards the black queen with Rh4.10.  Qb6!?  could be considered as well, when Black should play  10...c4  . Black has wasted time with  a6  , but we have also wasted time with our queen. }
10... Nge7
{ 10...cxd4  If Black grabs the pawn I suggest  11.h5  When we will have lots of compensation for the pawn after  11...dxc3  12.Bxc3  Black's queen is in danger so  12...Nce7  Looks necessary.  13.Bd3+-  With fantastic play for the missing pawn. }
11. h5 { Our pawn moves forward and paves a way for our rook on h1. } 11...
cxd4
{ Is met by   11...h6  Black stops our pawn and maintains the tension in the center.  12.Rh4  Other moves are possible too, for example 12. Qb2, but I think this is the simplest as we're forcing Black to make a decision in the center.  12...c4  Black plays thematically and closes the queenside.  13.Rf4  Our rook swings to f4 and prevents Black from playing O-O-O for now.  13...Bd7  14.Be2  Rf8  Black protects the f-pawn and gets ready to castle queenside.  15.Qb6  Our queen moves in and yet again prevents O-O-O.  15...Qb5   The best. Black doesn't have good alternatives, as a move such as  15...Nd8  can be met by  16.Qb2  when we've gotten this move for free. A the typical pawn break g4-g5 is a logical plan to play for.  16.Rb1  Qxb6  17.Rxb6  O-O-O  Black has been able to trade queens, but he is rather passive. The f7-f6 break is thematic, but it will often cause problems for the pawn on g6.  18.Nh4  Our knight swings to the rim and prepares g4-Rf3-Rg3-g5.  18...Kc7  19.Rb1  b5  Black plays on the queenside and tries to obtain some counterplay on that side of the board.  20.g4  a5  21.Be3  Our bishop on e3 protects the pawn on d4 which could be hanging the day Black pushes b4.  21...Rb8  22.Bd1  Another prophylactic move.  22...b4  Let's see what happens if Black goes for the pawn break right away. Against other moves we can proceed with our plan Rf3-Rg3-g5.  23.axb4  axb4  24.cxb4  Nxb4  And now  25.Ra1  Is an important move. Black has problems with his coordination as the pawn on f7 keeps hanging.  25...Nec6  26.Rf3+-  Our rook moves away from the fork on d3, so we're ready to push the knight away from b4 with a dominating position. It's hard for Black to find anything to do. }
12. Rh4 Nf5 13. Rf4
{ The right square.  13.Rg4?!  would be inaccurate due to  13...f6!  when Black has tricks with  e5  after  14.exf6  gxf6  15.cxd4  e5  . }
13... g6
{ Black targets our pawn on  h5  and also hopes that we'll fall for  14.g4?!  Nh4!  15.Nxh4  g5  when Black is fine. The best is to simply recapture on  d4  .   13...f6  Doesn't work as we can just play  14.exf6  e5?  Loses to the brilliant trick   14...gxf6  15.cxd4+-  Black is too exposed on the kingside.  15.Nxe5!  Nxe5  16.Rxf5!  Bxf5  17.Qxb7+-  With a double attack. }
14. Nxd4 Ncxd4 15. cxd4
{ The opening of the position has only benefited us as Black's king is very exposed. Our bishop pair is also very strong. }
