1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ We have finally arrived to the main bulk of our coverage on the French, and our very last topic to cover for Part 1! This is the Winawer Variation, named after Szymon Winawer and popularized later in the 1940s by the greats Nimzowitch and Botvinnik. Black pins the knight and thus attacks the pawn on e4 so we're forced to make a decision in the center. }
4. e5
{ This is by far the most challenging move against the Winawer. We're gaining additional space while we're also limiting Black's knight on g8 as it can no longer jump to f6. }
4... c5
{ Black's main move challenges our center immediately, a necessary course of action to obtain the desired counterplay on the queenside. }
5. a3
{ By far the most played move as this is the only way to maintain the strong pawn chain. }
5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Qa5
{ This move has always been a pretty popular sideline as not all players with Black are interested in venturing into the extreme complications that occur in the mainstream Winawer variations. Black is going to block the queenside entirely and later on castle long. }
7. Bd2 Qa4 { Black's main move and the main topic for the chapter. } 8. Qb1 c4
{ Black has managed to close down the queenside. From here, the arising positions are all about maneuvering due to the closed nature of the position. }
9. Be2
{ There are numerous ways for White to play against Black's set-up. My favorite move landed on 9. Be2 which intends to place the bishop on g4 or h5.   I also examined  9.Qd1!?  which is interesting enough as well. The queen heads back as we have managed to provoke  8...c4  . After  9...Nc6  10.Qg4  g6  11.Qd1!  White had managed to provoke another concession in Black's camp. The game proceeded  11...h6  12.Nh3  b6  13.Nf4  Ba6  14.g3  O-O-O  15.h4  , when White was really comfortable in Velilla Velasco, F - Loeschnauer, R ICCF email 2016.   9...Ne7  looks better, but I also like White after  10.Ne2  Nbc6  11.Nf4  Bd7  12.Nh5  Rg8  13.g3  O-O-O  14.Bh3  . Rada, H - Schabata, W ICCF email 2016. The general theme of these positions is that it's not easy for us to break through, but Black can't do much else than play for the pawn break f7-f6. The problem with this is that our forces are often very well prepared against it, so it's likely to backfire. }
9... Ne7
{ Let's check what happens in case Black decides to change plans completely by castling kingside! }
10. Bg4
{ Our bishop is well-placed on g4 where it targets the pawn on e6 and makes the desirable f7-f6 harder for Black to achieve.   I am less convinced by  10.Nf3  Nbc6  11.O-O  Bd7  12.Qb2  O-O-O  13.Rfb1  b6  14.Qc1  like in Firouzja, A - Livaic, L Chess.com INT 2021. However, White has scored 3/3 from this position which means that it's not easy to play Black over the board. Indeed, a common theme throughout this variation. }
10... O-O
{ This is the wrong set-up, but it's instructive to see how we battle it.  10...Nbc6  11.Ne2  Bd7  12.O-O  O-O-O  is very similar to the main line. }
11. Ne2 Nbc6 12. O-O
{ We have castled and plan to soon go for an attack with moves such as Re1-Nf4-Nh5. Black's only way to challenge our way of playing is to push f6 quickly, with the clear drawback that the pawn on e6 becomes weak. }
12... b6
{ Looks too slow, as our attack becomes dangerous really quickly.   12...Ng6  13.Qc1  f6  Was Black's attempt in an email game from 2014.  14.exf6  Rxf6  Black has diminished our chances to create a vicious attack, but in return he has gotten himself a weak pawn on e6.  15.Bg5  Rf7   15...Rf8  is met by a quick h4-h5.  16.Bh5  e5  Black has to do this, otherwise Nf4 comes.  17.dxe5  The engine move 17. f4 that was played in Schunck,F - Haumann,J GER email 2014 also wins, but it was trickier.  17...Ncxe5  18.h3  We're set to throw our pawns towards Black with f4 and g4.  18...Nc6  19.g4  Qa5  20.f4  Our pawns combined with our bishop pair is a devastating combination.  20...Qc5+  21.Kh2+-  With a decisive edge. }
13. Re1 Bd7 14. Nf4
{ Our forces are perfectly placed to meet f6, but more importantly, we're heading towards Black's king with great speed. }
14... Rae8 15. Nh5
{ Black is in dire straits, as the threat of Bg5-Bf6 is deadly. The only defense is }
15... Kh8
{ With the point of placing the knight on g8.   15...Ng6?  loses after  16.Bg5  , with a sample line being  16...h6  17.Bf6  gxf6  18.Qc1  Kh7  19.Nxf6+  Kg7  20.Nxd7  . }
16. Bg5 Ng8 { Black is barely hanging in there for now... } 17. Re3
{ Our rook joins the party. } 17... f5
{ Is a sad necessity.   17...Nce7  Intends f5/f6, when Black would 'only' be clearly worse, but it loses to the brilliant move  18.Nf6!!  Rh3 is coming and Black doesn't have a way to defend the onslaught.  18...gxf6  19.exf6  Ng6   19...Nf5  20.Rh3  e5  21.Qd1  is similar.  20.Rh3  e5  What else?  21.Qd1  Our queen joins in and gets ready to enter Black's camp on h5. Bxd7 followed by Rxh7+ is a threat now.  21...Nf4  22.Rh4!  The exclam is there as it's the only way to win. Black doesn't have any defense as dxe5 is coming when the knight on f4 will be hanging.  22...Ng6  Would allow  23.Rxh7+  Kxh7  24.Bxd7+-  When Black can resign. }
18. exf6 gxf6 19. Bf4 { A grim future is ahead for Black and his pawn on e6. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "24. French Defense (1...e6) Winawer Sidelines"]
[Black "3...Bb4 (6...Qa5 10)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ We have finally arrived to the main bulk of our coverage on the French, and our very last topic to cover for Part 1! This is the Winawer Variation, named after Szymon Winawer and popularized later in the 1940s by the greats Nimzowitch and Botvinnik. Black pins the knight and thus attacks the pawn on e4 so we're forced to make a decision in the center. }
4. e5
{ This is by far the most challenging move against the Winawer. We're gaining additional space while we're also limiting Black's knight on g8 as it can no longer jump to f6. }
4... c5
{ Black's main move challenges our center immediately, a necessary course of action to obtain the desired counterplay on the queenside. }
5. a3
{ By far the most played move as this is the only way to maintain the strong pawn chain. }
5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Qa5
{ This move has always been a pretty popular sideline as not all players with Black are interested in venturing into the extreme complications that occur in the mainstream Winawer variations. Black is going to block the queenside entirely and later on castle long. }
7. Bd2 Qa4 { Black's main move and the main topic for the chapter. } 8. Qb1 c4
{ Black has managed to close down the queenside. From here, the arising positions are all about maneuvering due to the closed nature of the position. }
9. Be2 Nc6 10. Bh5
{ A funky-looking move. Our bishop applies pressure against Black's pawn on f7, while it frees the e2-square for our knight.   10.Bg4  is possible, when Black has an extra option in  10...f6!? }
10... Nge7 11. Ne2 Bd7
{ Black played  11...Kd7!?  in Adair,J - Merry,A Harrogate 2018, a move that only looks like a time waste.  Black's idea is to trick us into taking the pawn on f7, as our bishop will be trapped with g6.  I suggest to play  12.O-O  and proceed with similar play as the main line. }
12. O-O b6 { Black played this move in an email game I came across. } 13. Qd1
{ The queen doesn't do anything in the b-file, so it makes sense to move it. }
13... Rf8
{ 13...O-O ?!  Is once again ill-advised.  14.Ng3  Looks good, with the plan of playing Bg4 and Nh5.  14...f6  Is Black's way of getting counterplay, but after  15.exf6  Rxf6  16.Bg5  Rff8  17.Qd2  h6  18.Bf4±  Black is clearly worse due to the backward pawn on e6 and our excellent control over the dark squares. }
14. Bg4
{ Now that Black has defended the pawn, our bishop moves to g4 where it gives the h5-square to our knight and presses e6. }
14... O-O-O 15. Ng3
{ White played  15.Nf4  in Talnis, A - Tauber, H ICCF email 2017, but quickly moved the knight back from  f4  to  g3  . I think it makes more sense to move the knight to  g3  right away. }
15... Kb7 16. Re1 Rde8
{ Black can't do much else than wait and hope that he'll be able to some day play f6 in good circumstances. }
17. Nh5 Rg8 18. Ra2
{ White's advantage is objectively 'only' slightly better, but over the board this is not very fun for Black. Practice has shown that positions such as these are difficult for humans to handle, as they feel the urge to do something at some point! Moving back and forth is no problem for an engine... I suggest playing for the pawn break f4-f5. We can prepare it by slowly improving our pieces, for example Qf3-h4-Kh2-g3-Bh3-Qg2-f4-Qf3-g4, etc. Our rook on a2 protects all the vulnerable spots in our camp. }
*

