[Black "3...Bb4 (6...Qa5 11)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ We have finally arrived to the main bulk of our coverage on the French, and our very last topic to cover for Part 1! This is the Winawer Variation, named after Szymon Winawer and popularized later in the 1940s by the greats Nimzowitch and Botvinnik. Black pins the knight and thus attacks the pawn on e4 so we're forced to make a decision in the center. }
4. e5
{ This is by far the most challenging move against the Winawer. We're gaining additional space while we're also limiting Black's knight on g8 as it can no longer jump to f6. }
4... c5
{ Black's main move challenges our center immediately, a necessary course of action to obtain the desired counterplay on the queenside. }
5. a3
{ By far the most played move as this is the only way to maintain the strong pawn chain. }
5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Qa5
{ This move has always been a pretty popular sideline as not all players with Black are interested in venturing into the extreme complications that occur in the mainstream Winawer variations. Black is going to block the queenside entirely and later on castle long. }
7. Bd2 Qa4 { Black's main move and the main topic for the chapter. } 8. Qb1 c4
{ Black has managed to close down the queenside. From here, the arising positions are all about maneuvering due to the closed nature of the position. }
9. Be2 Nc6 10. Bh5
{ A funky-looking move. Our bishop applies pressure against Black's pawn on f7, while it frees the e2-square for our knight.   10.Bg4  is possible, when Black has an extra option in  10...f6!? }
10... Nge7 11. Ne2 Bd7
{ Black played  11...Kd7!?  in Adair,J - Merry,A Harrogate 2018, a move that only looks like a time waste. Black's idea is to trick us into taking the pawn on f7, as our bishop will be trapped with g6.  I suggest to play  12.O-O  and proceed with similar play as the mainline. }
12. O-O Rf8
{ Black defends the pawn and prepares to castle queenside, as  12...O-O-O  would lose after  13.Bxf7  g6  14.Nf4  . }
13. Bg4 { Just like in the previous note, our bishop is better placed on g4. }
13... O-O-O 14. h4
{ For the sake of being instructive, I want to showcase another plan.  14.Re1  Kb8  15.Nf4  Ka8  16.Nh5  Rg8  17.Ra2  can also be played, with play similar to the previous note. }
14... Kb8 15. h5
{ We're fixing the pawn structure on the kingside so we can some day play g4-g5 or even attack g7 by swinging a rook to g3. }
15... h6
{ Black shouldn't allow h6 when he will get destroyed on the dark squares. }
16. f3 { This move prepares the bishop maneuver Be1-Bh4. } 16... Ka8
{ 16...f6  is nothing to worry about yet, as Black has only achieved to weaken his position after  17.exf6  Rxf6  18.Re1  . }
17. Be1 Rde8 18. Qb2 b6 19. Qc1
{ White's position looks promising with the straightforward idea of playing Bh3-g4-Bh4-f4-f5. }
