[White "25. French Defense (1...e6) Winawer Old Mainlines"]
[Black "6...Qc7 (7...Bd7)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ We have finally arrived to the main bulk of our coverage on the French, and our very last topic to cover for Part 1! This is the Winawer Variation, named after Szymon Winawer and popularized later in the 1940s by the greats Nimzowitch and Botvinnik. Black pins the knight and thus attacks the pawn on e4 so we're forced to make a decision in the center. }
4. e5
{ This is by far the most challenging move against the Winawer. We're gaining additional space while we're also limiting Black's knight on g8 as it can no longer jump to f6. }
4... c5
{ Black's main move challenges our center immediately, a necessary course of action to obtain the desired counterplay on the queenside. }
5. a3
{ By far the most played move as this is the only way to maintain the strong pawn chain. }
5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Qc7
{ Black usually starts with  6...Ne7  , but  6...Qc7  is a possible move-order as well. The queen is well placed on  c7  where it's eyeing our pawn on  c3  , making  cxd4  a move to watch out for. }
7. h4
{ Black has numerous ways to transpose to the mainline with  6...Ne7  , so I suggest to keep things simple by proceeding in the same manner. Black's early  Qc7  allows for some additional possibilities which we will examine in this chapter.  7.Qg4  is the other main move, when Black usually plays  7...f5  , an extra option when playing  6...Qc7  as the queen keeps the pawn on  g7  protected. }
7... Bd7
{ Is almost never played, but it's a very interesting sideline with the idea of placing the bishop on a4. }
8. h5 h6
{ Was tried by Black in Istratescu,A - Saiboulatov,D Novi Sad 2009, but it looks rather poor without the knight on e7.   8...Nc6   Has been tried before, when the game is extremely likely to transpose to the Giri Variation with  8...Nbc6  .  9.Nf3   I don't like  9.h6  , when Black looks good after  9...Nxh6  .  9...h6  10.Rb1   It makes no sense for Black to avoid playing  10...Nge7  , when the game has transposed to The Giri Variation. }
9. Qg4
{ With the knight on e7, Black would have been able to play Rg8, but this is not possible. }
9... Kf8 10. Rh3
{ White's attack with Rg3, or Rf3-Qf4 looks decisive already. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "25. French Defense (1...e6) Winawer Old Mainlines"]
[Black "6...Qc7 (7...Bd7 2)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ We have finally arrived to the main bulk of our coverage on the French, and our very last topic to cover for Part 1! This is the Winawer Variation, named after Szymon Winawer and popularized later in the 1940s by the greats Nimzowitch and Botvinnik. Black pins the knight and thus attacks the pawn on e4 so we're forced to make a decision in the center. }
4. e5
{ This is by far the most challenging move against the Winawer. We're gaining additional space while we're also limiting Black's knight on g8 as it can no longer jump to f6. }
4... c5
{ Black's main move challenges our center immediately, a necessary course of action to obtain the desired counterplay on the queenside. }
5. a3
{ By far the most played move as this is the only way to maintain the strong pawn chain. }
5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Qc7 7. h4 Bd7
{ Is almost never played, but it's a very interesting sideline with the idea of placing the bishop on a4. }
8. h5 Ba4 9. Bd2 { Our bishop develops to keep the c3-square protected. } 9...
Nc6
{ 9...cxd4  Black only helps us by correcting our pawn structure.  10.cxd4  Nc6  The pawn on c2 didn't hang due to Rc1.  11.Nf3  h6  Has to be played at some point.  12.Bd3  Nge7  13.Rh3±  The rook is heading to g3. When Black castles long, we should place our queen and rook in the b-file for increased pressure. Black is under a nasty pressure, for example:  13...O-O-O  14.Qc1  Kb8  15.Qb2  Nc8  16.Kf1  Nb6  17.Rg3  . }
10. Qg4 { The best way to proceed. } 10... cxd4
{ 10...O-O-O  Giving the pawn on g7 in this fashion is also possible.  11.Qxg7  Nge7  12.Bd3  Our bishop targets h7 and makes sure that c2 is protected.  12...cxd4  13.Ne2  Intending to recapture the pawn on c3 with the knight when the bishop on a4 will be in trouble.  13...Qxe5  14.h6!  A very strong move, keeping the queen protected.  14...Rhg8   14...dxc3  would be a blunder after  15.Bf4!  Qxg7  16.hxg7  , with  Nxc3  next.  15.cxd4  Qxg7  16.hxg7  Rxg7  17.g3±  Despite Black's extra pawn, we are clearly better as our bishop pair is very strong. }
11. cxd4
{ Our queen shows another useful side by having it on  g4  . I suggested  11.Qxg7  on chess24, when we are slightly better in the endgame after  11...Qxe5+  12.Qxe5  Nxe5  13.cxd4  Nc4  14.Bd3  Nxd2  15.Kxd2  Nf6  16.Rb1  b6  17.f3  , but I think the text is more promising. }
11... Nh6
{ By far Black's best, as it works tactically.  11...O-O-O  is met by  12.Bd3  when we have a really nice position. }
12. Bxh6
{ It's necessary to take! If we play  12.Qf4  , Black can suddenly change direction with  12...O-O  , followed by a quick  f6  .   12.Qxg7  is the critical, but after  12...Nxd4!  the tactics work for Black. For example:  13.Qxh8?  Kd7!  14.Qxa8  Nxc2+  15.Ke2  Qc4+  16.Kf3  Qg4#  is mate.  13.Rc1  has to be played, with a crazy position after  13...Nxc2+  14.Kd1  Nxa3+   14...Nd4+  is a draw  15.Ke2  Nc2  16.Bxh6  O-O-O  . The objective evaluation is 0.00, as expected! }
12... gxh6 13. Bd3 Nb4
{ Black keeps up the aggressive play.  Qc3+  is now a threat.  13...O-O-O  is too slow, when we consolidate, for example  14.Kf1  Rhg8  15.Qh4  Qb6  16.Ne2  Qb2  17.Rc1  , with an excellent position! g3-Kf2-Qf4 is coming next. }
14. Ne2 Nxc2+ { Black wins a pawn, but after } 15. Bxc2 Bxc2 16. O-O O-O-O 17.
Rfc1 Kb8 18. Rab1
{ I think we have excellent chances. Black has to tread very carefully. For example:  18...Bxb1?  would lose to  19.Rxc7  Kxc7  20.Qf4  , when Black can't defend the pawn on  f7  as  Qc1+  is also a threat. When the f7-pawn falls, Black is busted. }
