[White "25. French Defense (1...e6) Winawer Old Mainlines"]
[Black "6...Qc7 (7...f6)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ We have finally arrived to the main bulk of our coverage on the French, and our very last topic to cover for Part 1! This is the Winawer Variation, named after Szymon Winawer and popularized later in the 1940s by the greats Nimzowitch and Botvinnik. Black pins the knight and thus attacks the pawn on e4 so we're forced to make a decision in the center. }
4. e5
{ This is by far the most challenging move against the Winawer. We're gaining additional space while we're also limiting Black's knight on g8 as it can no longer jump to f6. }
4... c5
{ Black's main move challenges our center immediately, a necessary course of action to obtain the desired counterplay on the queenside. }
5. a3
{ By far the most played move as this is the only way to maintain the strong pawn chain. }
5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Qc7 7. h4 f6
{ Black's typical pawn break can be played already here. } 8. Rb1
{ This novelty is surprisingly strong, as the rook is very well placed in the b-file. }
8... Nc6
{ Black has three pieces that attack our pawn on e5, so we should play   8...fxe5  Is nothing to worry about, as we can regain the pawn with  9.Qh5+  g6  10.Qxe5  10. Qg5! is a strong alternative, but annoyingly complicated.  10...Qxe5+  11.dxe5  Our pair of bishops and strong control of the dark squares grant us a very nice endgame.  11...Nc6  12.Bb5  Bd7  13.h5±  Looks fantastic for us.   8...c4  This move looks awful to me, but it is surprisingly high on the list of moves suggested by the engine.  9.Qh5+  And now we get a really nice endgame after  9...Qf7  10.exf6  Nxf6  11.Qxf7+  Kxf7  12.f3±  It's important that we make sure that Black can't jump to e4. Our plans forward will be to expand on the kingside with h5 and g4, with excellent winning chances. }
9. Bb5 Bd7
{ 9...fxe5?  Is even worse than the endgame we saw after 8... fxe5.  10.Bxc6+  bxc6  11.Qh5+  g6  12.Qxe5  Qxe5+  13.dxe5+-  White is completely winning as Black lacks control of the dark squares. }
10. Nf3
{ 10. Qh5+ is objectively even better, but the text move is practically superior as it's really simple. There's no need to analyze complications in a line we are very unlikely to face anyway. }
10... fxe5 { And now our point is shown after } 11. Bxc6 Bxc6 12. Nxe5
{ We have regained the pawn with interest as Black is left with a backward pawn on e6. }
12... Nf6 13. Bf4 Qe7 { And now we should play } 14. dxc5
{ With the threat of Nxc6 followed by Bd6. } 14... Qxc5
{ Is necessary, as  14...Ne4  runs into  15.Qh5+! } 15. Qd4 Qxd4
{ 15... Qxa3 16. h5! showcases how strong our queen is on d4, when h6 will come next. }
16. cxd4 O-O { And now I think we should get rid of Black's bishop. } 17. Nxc6
bxc6 18. f3
{ Our strong bishop, Black's weaker pawns and our control of the b-file give us clearly better chances. }
