[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "25. French Defense (1...e6) Winawer Old Mainlines"]
[Black "6...Qc7 (7...cxd4)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ We have finally arrived to the main bulk of our coverage on the French, and our very last topic to cover for Part 1! This is the Winawer Variation, named after Szymon Winawer and popularized later in the 1940s by the greats Nimzowitch and Botvinnik. Black pins the knight and thus attacks the pawn on e4 so we're forced to make a decision in the center. }
4. e5
{ This is by far the most challenging move against the Winawer. We're gaining additional space while we're also limiting Black's knight on g8 as it can no longer jump to f6. }
4... c5
{ Black's main move challenges our center immediately, a necessary course of action to obtain the desired counterplay on the queenside. }
5. a3
{ By far the most played move as this is the only way to maintain the strong pawn chain. }
5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Qc7 7. h4 cxd4
{ The critical test, and usually what Black opts for when going for this move order as he wins a pawn.   7...Nc6  Can be tried by Black, when play should transpose to the main tabiya after  8.h5  h6  9.Nf3  Nge7  10.Rb1  And we have now reached The Giri Variation with 9... Nbc6. }
8. cxd4 Qc3+
{ Black's queen chimes in and wins the pawn on d4, as we must protect our rook. }
9. Bd2 Qxd4 10. Nf3
{ Our compensation for the pawn lies in rapid development. Black has to make a decision on where to place the queen: }
10... Qa4
{ Black intends to return to d7 with the queen, but why would you pick d7 instead of c7 like we saw in the 10... Qb6-line? Indeed, the move is rather poor. We can react in different ways with my favorite being }
11. h5
{ With the same thematic plan of fixing the pawn structure, while allowing a rook launch to h4. }
11... Qd7
{ The queen should head back at once.   11...h6  Black stops our pawn for now, but is still in huge trouble after  12.Rb1  a6  13.Rh4  Qd7  14.Bd3  As we have a massive lead in development.  14...Nc6  15.Rg4  Forcing Black to make a concession.  15...Kf8  16.Kf1  Nge7  17.Kg1+-  We're going to open the position next with c4 when we'll be completely dominating. Black struggles with his terrible coordination and passive position. }
12. Rh3
{ This time our rook moves to the third rank where it has the potential to eventually swing to the open c-file.  12.h6?  wouldn't be good here, as Black has  12...Nxh6  when he wins our very powerful bishop. }
12... Nc6 13. Bd3 Qc7
{ Black has wasted a move by playing Qa4-Qd7-Qc7 instead of Qb6-Qc7. That being said, the queen needs to move out of the way in order to complete the development. }
14. Kf1
{ The best way to defend against  14...Nxe5  , as we can play  15.Nxe5  Qxe5  16.Bc3  now that the king is out of the way. Besides, we have seen how our king always heads to the kingside so we kill two birds with one stone! }
14... Bd7 15. Rb1
{ Our rook is well placed in the b-file. In this very position it also allows a pretty nifty trick if Black castles long. }
15... O-O-O
{ 15...Nge7  is better, but still awful for Black after  16.Rg3  . } 16. Ba6
{ A fantastic move that wins material. } 16... bxa6 17. Qe2 Nb8
{ Black defends the pawn on a6. It's time for our rook on h3 to join the party after }
18. Nd4 { Rc3 is coming! } 18... Ne7 19. Rc3 Nec6
{ 19...Bc6  is no better.  20.Rc5  wins as  Ba5  comes. Black is pinned down. }
20. Qe3
{ White wins, with the plan of playing Rc5 followed by Ba5. The king should also move to g1 to avoid any checks on b5. A nice point with Qe3 is that the pawn on a7 usually hangs in the end, for example:   20...h6  21.Rc5  Rhg8  22.Kg1  Rde8  23.Ba5  Qxa5  24.Nxc6  Nxc6  25.Rxa5  Nxa5  26.Qxa7  . }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "25. French Defense (1...e6) Winawer Old Mainlines"]
[Black "6...Qc7 (7...cxd4 2)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ We have finally arrived to the main bulk of our coverage on the French, and our very last topic to cover for Part 1! This is the Winawer Variation, named after Szymon Winawer and popularized later in the 1940s by the greats Nimzowitch and Botvinnik. Black pins the knight and thus attacks the pawn on e4 so we're forced to make a decision in the center. }
4. e5
{ This is by far the most challenging move against the Winawer. We're gaining additional space while we're also limiting Black's knight on g8 as it can no longer jump to f6. }
4... c5
{ Black's main move challenges our center immediately, a necessary course of action to obtain the desired counterplay on the queenside. }
5. a3
{ By far the most played move as this is the only way to maintain the strong pawn chain. }
5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Qc7 7. h4 cxd4
{ The critical test, and usually what Black opts for when going for this move order as he wins a pawn.   7...Nc6  Can be tried by Black, when play should transpose to the main tabiya after  8.h5  h6  9.Nf3  Nge7  10.Rb1  And we have now reached The Giri Variation with 9... Nbc6. }
8. cxd4 Qc3+
{ Black's queen chimes in and wins the pawn on d4, as we must protect our rook. }
9. Bd2 Qxd4 10. Nf3
{ Our compensation for the pawn lies in rapid development. Black has to make a decision on where to place the queen: }
10... Qb6 { I suggest meeting this retreat with } 11. Bd3
{ The natural square for the bishop. } 11... Nc6 12. h5
{ Our pawn advances one step further and allows a potential rook swing via h4 to g4. }
12... h6
{ 12...f6  This thematic move was played by my old coach, Leif Erlend Johannessen, when he was just a teenager!  13.h6  We break up Black's kingside pawns and aim to take control over the dark squares.  13...g6   13...Qc7  is the lesser evil, but certainly not very fun for Black after  14.hxg7  Qxg7  15.exf6  Nxf6  16.Bh6  Qf7  17.Qe2  .  14.Bc3   This move refutes Black's concept completely.  14.exf6  was also good in Van Delft, M - Johannessen, L Guarapuava 1995. However, my former coach was already a decent player at the age of 16, and soon equalized after  14...Nxf6  15.Rb1  Qc7  16.Bb5  Ne4  17.Be3  O-O  , and later went on to win.  14...f5  Black closes the diagonal, but is completely lost positionally after  15.Rb1  Qc7  16.Qd2  Nge7  17.O-O  O-O  18.a4+-  Black is suffering tremendously on the dark squares. Our bishop will soon head to the a3-f8 diagonal via b2. }
13. Rh4 { Our rook swings to g4 to target Black's pawn on g7. } 13... Nge7 14.
Rg4 Nf5
{ 14...Kf8  looks even worse, when we should continue with calm moves that improve our position, such as Kf1-Kg1,  Bc3  ,  Rf4  , etc. }
15. Kf1 { We're preparing to 'fake-castle' by heading to g1. } 15... Qc7 16.
Qe2 Bd7 17. Rf4 { Our rook moves to f4 so g4 is now looming in the air. } 17...
O-O { Black castles short and prepares f6, so now we must play } 18. c4
{ In order to dismantle Black's center. } 18... dxc4 19. Rxc4
{ Qe4 followed by g4 is soon coming with a really devastating attack.   If Black tries  19...f6  , we can respond with  20.Bb4  when Black has to give the exchange as  20...Rf7  is met by  21.Bxf5  followed by  e6  . Moving the rook somewhere else allows  exf6  when our attack is too strong. }
*

