1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ We have finally arrived to the main bulk of our coverage on the French, and our very last topic to cover for Part 1! This is the Winawer Variation, named after Szymon Winawer and popularized later in the 1940s by the greats Nimzowitch and Botvinnik. Black pins the knight and thus attacks the pawn on e4 so we're forced to make a decision in the center. }
4. e5
{ This is by far the most challenging move against the Winawer. We're gaining additional space while we're also limiting Black's knight on g8 as it can no longer jump to f6. }
4... c5
{ Black's main move challenges our center immediately, a necessary course of action to obtain the desired counterplay on the queenside. }
5. a3
{ By far the most played move as this is the only way to maintain the strong pawn chain. }
5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Qc7 7. h4 cxd4
{ The critical test, and usually what Black opts for when going for this move order as he wins a pawn.   7...Nc6  Can be tried by Black, when play should transpose to the main tabiya after  8.h5  h6  9.Nf3  Nge7  10.Rb1  And we have now reached The Giri Variation with 9... Nbc6. }
8. cxd4 Qc3+
{ Black's queen chimes in and wins the pawn on d4, as we must protect our rook. }
9. Bd2 Qxd4 10. Nf3
{ Our compensation for the pawn lies in rapid development. Black has to make a decision on where to place the queen: }
10... Qe4+ { Black gains some time by giving a check. } 11. Be3
{ The right piece to place in between as Bd3 is a useful resource to have.   11.Be2  has been played just as many times in my base, when Black has the annoying  11...b6  with the idea of trading bishops with  Ba6  . }
11... Nc6 12. Bd3 { The lady has to move yet again. } 12... Qa4
{ 12...Qg4?  Is awful after  13.h5!  When we are threatening to win the queen with Rh4 followed by Bf1.  13...Qa4  Black has wasted another tempo, something he simply can't afford.  14.Bd2!   The logical  14.Rh4  is also decent, but this move is even better as it takes away the a5-square for the queen.  14...Nh6  Black plans to play Nf5, but is not on time as we have  15.Rh4  d4  Is forced, otherwise Black loses material.  16.Qb1  a6  17.Re4+-  Qb2 followed by g4 comes next, when the pawn on d4 falls. Black's position is hopeless. }
13. h5 { We need to play actively in order to justify the missing pawn. } 13...
Qa5+ 14. Kf1 Qc7 { Black's queen goes into hiding on c7. } 15. Rh3
{ 15.Rh4  is also strong. } 15... f6
{ Black hopes that we'll capture the pawn, but instead   15...h6  Is met by  16.Rg3  When Black has real problems with the pawn on g7, as  16...Kf8  17.Bc5+  Nge7  18.Bd6+-  Is just ghastly with Nh4-Qg4 coming next.   15...Nxe5?  Loses immediately to  16.Nxe5  Qxe5  17.Bd4+-  Black can't take the bishop due to the discovered check on b5, so the pawn on g7 falls along with the rook on h8. }
16. h6 { Is the road to Rome. Black is struggling on the a1-h8 diagonal. }
16... fxe5 17. hxg7 Qxg7 { And here we have the trick } 18. Bb5
{ With the plan of taking on c6 followed by Nxe5, which greatly shows how Black is struggling in the diagonal. }
18... e4 { Keeps the pawn, but Black is dead lost after } 19. Rg3 Qe7 20. Ne5
{ Due to the double attack of Nxc6+ and Qh5+. } *

