1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ We have finally arrived to the main bulk of our coverage on the French, and our very last topic to cover for Part 1! This is the Winawer Variation, named after Szymon Winawer and popularized later in the 1940s by the greats Nimzowitch and Botvinnik. Black pins the knight and thus attacks the pawn on e4 so we're forced to make a decision in the center. }
4. e5
{ This is by far the most challenging move against the Winawer. We're gaining additional space while we're also limiting Black's knight on g8 as it can no longer jump to f6. }
4... c5
{ Black's main move challenges our center immediately, a necessary course of action to obtain the desired counterplay on the queenside. }
5. a3
{ By far the most played move as this is the only way to maintain the strong pawn chain. }
5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Qc7
{ Black usually starts with  6...Ne7  , but  6...Qc7  is a possible move-order as well. The queen is well placed on  c7  where it's eyeing our pawn on  c3  , making  cxd4  a move to watch out for. }
7. h4 cxd4
{ The critical test, and usually what Black opts for when going for this move order as he wins a pawn. }
8. cxd4 Qc3+
{ Black's queen chimes in and wins the pawn on d4, as we must protect our rook. }
9. Bd2 Qxd4 10. Nf3
{ Our compensation for the pawn lies in rapid development. Black has to make a decision on where to place the queen: }
10... Qe4+ { Black gains some time by giving a check. } 11. Be3
{ The right piece to place in between as Bd3 is a useful resource to have.   11.Be2  has been played just as many times in my base, when Black has the annoying  11...b6  with the idea of trading bishops with  Ba6  . }
11... Ne7
{ Black intends to make use of Be3 by going for a quick knight jump to f5. }
12. Bd3 Qa4 { Is not very challenging, as we can play } 13. h5
{ Followed by h6 or Rh4, depending on what Black does. } 13... Nbc6
{ 13...Nf5  is met by  14.Bxf5  exf5  15.h6  , when we're just winning. The text is Black's best, when we should respond with }
14. h6 gxh6 15. Rxh6
{ With a promising position due to Black's weaknesses on the dark squares. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "25. French Defense (1...e6) Winawer Old Mainlines"]
[Black "6...Qc7 (7...cxd4 6)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ We have finally arrived to the main bulk of our coverage on the French, and our very last topic to cover for Part 1! This is the Winawer Variation, named after Szymon Winawer and popularized later in the 1940s by the greats Nimzowitch and Botvinnik. Black pins the knight and thus attacks the pawn on e4 so we're forced to make a decision in the center. }
4. e5
{ This is by far the most challenging move against the Winawer. We're gaining additional space while we're also limiting Black's knight on g8 as it can no longer jump to f6. }
4... c5
{ Black's main move challenges our center immediately, a necessary course of action to obtain the desired counterplay on the queenside. }
5. a3
{ By far the most played move as this is the only way to maintain the strong pawn chain. }
5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Qc7 7. h4 cxd4
{ The critical test, and usually what Black opts for when going for this move order as he wins a pawn. }
8. cxd4 Qc3+
{ Black's queen chimes in and wins the pawn on d4, as we must protect our rook. }
9. Bd2 Qxd4 10. Nf3
{ Our compensation for the pawn lies in rapid development. Black has to make a decision on where to place the queen: }
10... Qe4+ { Black gains some time by giving a check. } 11. Be3
{ The right piece to place in between as Bd3 is a useful resource to have.   11.Be2  has been played just as many times in my base, when Black has the annoying  11...b6  with the idea of trading bishops with  Ba6  . }
11... Ne7
{ Black intends to make use of Be3 by going for a quick knight jump to f5. }
12. Bd3 Qg4 13. h5 Nf5
{ Is now possible, as the queen defends the knight. This position was reached in Malakhov,I - Goganov,A St Petersburg 2011, and it's not so easy to tell what we're supposed to do here with White.   In the attached game, Black equalized easily after  14.Bxf5  Qxf5  15.Rh4  h6  and went on to win. Indeed, the best move is the unnatural }
14. Kf1
{ Which is a brilliant move. We will allow Black to capture our bishop on e3, as it will open the f-file which will be a useful asset in our position. It's also an important factor that the king guards the g2-pawn. }
14... Nxe3+
{ 14...Nc6  If Black delays the capture on e3, I suggest simply responding with  15.Qd2  The point is that we can play Bf4 next if Black keeps the queen on g4, while we can avoid the double pawns by capturing with the queen.  15...Qa4  Is the engine's suggestion, when we have a very nice game after  16.h6  gxh6  17.Bxh6  Due to Black's enormous problems on the dark squares. }
15. fxe3 Qa4
{ The exclam is there as Black's only chance is to get the queen out of the way.   15...Nc6?  Is just horrible after  16.Rh4  Qg3  17.Rh3  We have gotten Rh3 for free.  17...Qg4  18.Qe1  And the queen is forced back to a4, while we aim to play Qg3 to threaten Black's pawn on g7.  18...Qa4  19.Qg3+-  Black has to give the pawn on  g7  , and is thus lost after  19...Bd7  20.Rh4  Qa5  21.Qxg7  O-O-O  22.Bxh7  Qc3  23.Re1  Qxa3  24.h6  , as our h-pawn is too strong. }
16. Qe1
{ Our queen is heading to g3 and our rook to h4 to create a powerful attack. }
16... Qd7 { 16...O-O  17.Rh4  Qd7  18.Qg3  is the same. } 17. Qg3 O-O 18. Rh4
{ We prepare a rook swing to f4 followed by Kg1-Rf1, when our pressure in the f-file will be incredibly strong. }
18... h6 { Is another natural move that loses the game. } 19. Rf4
{ This is yet again our move, intending Rf6. } 19... b6
{ Black tries to respond to  20.Rf6  with  20...Ba6  and hopes that there will be some counterplay. Note that  19...Kh8  still loses to  20.Qg6!! }
20. Kg1 { The simplest, with the plan of doubling in the f-file. } 20... Ba6
{ Black is almost in time, but } 21. Rg4
{ Makes sure that the victory is ours after } 21... f5 22. exf6 Rxf6 23. Ne5
{ When Black is just busted after Rg6 or Ng6 next due to his exposed king. } *

