{ 14...Nc6  If Black delays the capture on e3, I suggest simply responding with  15.Qd2  The point is that we can play Bf4 next if Black keeps the queen on g4, while we can avoid the double pawns by capturing with the queen.  15...Qa4  Is the engine's suggestion, when we have a very nice game after  16.h6  gxh6  17.Bxh6  Due to Black's enormous problems on the dark squares. }
15. fxe3 Qa4
{ The exclam is there as Black's only chance is to get the queen out of the way.   15...Nc6?  Is just horrible after  16.Rh4  Qg3  17.Rh3  We have gotten Rh3 for free.  17...Qg4  18.Qe1  And the queen is forced back to a4, while we aim to play Qg3 to threaten Black's pawn on g7.  18...Qa4  19.Qg3+-  Black has to give the pawn on  g7  , and is thus lost after  19...Bd7  20.Rh4  Qa5  21.Qxg7  O-O-O  22.Bxh7  Qc3  23.Re1  Qxa3  24.h6  , as our h-pawn is too strong. }
16. Qe1
{ Our queen is heading to g3 and our rook to h4 to create a powerful attack. }
16... Qd7 { 16...O-O  17.Rh4  Qd7  18.Qg3  is the same. } 17. Qg3 O-O 18. Rh4
{ We prepare a rook swing to f4 followed by Kg1-Rf1, when our pressure in the f-file will be incredibly strong. }
18... Qe7
{ Black's only move, as the queen on f7 allows the knight to jump to d7 or a f7-f5 thrust. }
19. Rf4 { Our plan of wreaking havoc in the f-file still stands. } 19... f5
{ Is a decent fighting attempt. } 20. exf6 Rxf6 21. Rxf6 Qxf6 22. Rb1
{ The rook belongs in the open file! } 22... Nd7
{ The best defensive try, with the plan of playing e5 followed by Nc5.   22...Nc6  Should be met by  23.Kg1!  With the strong plan of playing Rf1.  23...e5  Black has no time to waste.  24.e4!  We must target Black's center.  24...dxe4   Is necessary, as  24...d4?  loses to  25.Ng5  .  25.Bxe4  h6  Black takes control over the g5-square and gives some air to the king.  26.Rf1↑  We're a pawn down but have an incredibly dangerous initiative. Black has to watch out for Bd5+ followed by Nh4.  I analyzed:  26...Qe6  27.c4  Qg4!  Taking the pawn would lose to  Qg6  .  28.Bd5+  Kh7   @28...  Kh8  loses to the brilliant  29.Nxe5!!  29.Qe1  Bf5  Otherwise  Qb1+  comes.  30.Nxe5  Qd4+  31.Qf2  Qxf2+  32.Rxf2  Nxe5  33.Rxf5  Re8  34.c5  . The complications are gone and we have an ending on the table where we're pressing for a victory. }
23. Qd6
{ The only way to stop Black's scheme.  23.Kg1  e5  24.e4  is no longer effective due to  24...Nc5! }
23... Nb6
{ Black protects the d5-pawn and gets ready to untangle by sacrificing a pawn with e5. }
24. Rb4
{ Our rook is swinging to f4 with deadly effect, so Black has to go for an endgame with }
24... e5 { 24...Bd7  25.Rf4  Qd8  26.h6  is the certain death for Black. } 25.
Qxe5 Qxe5 26. Nxe5 { With good winning chances in the endgame. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "25. French Defense (1...e6) Winawer Old Mainlines"]
[Black "6...Qc7 (7...cxd4 9)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ We have finally arrived to the main bulk of our coverage on the French, and our very last topic to cover for Part 1! This is the Winawer Variation, named after Szymon Winawer and popularized later in the 1940s by the greats Nimzowitch and Botvinnik. Black pins the knight and thus attacks the pawn on e4 so we're forced to make a decision in the center. }
4. e5
{ This is by far the most challenging move against the Winawer. We're gaining additional space while we're also limiting Black's knight on g8 as it can no longer jump to f6. }
4... c5
{ Black's main move challenges our center immediately, a necessary course of action to obtain the desired counterplay on the queenside. }
5. a3
{ By far the most played move as this is the only way to maintain the strong pawn chain. }
5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Qc7 7. h4 cxd4
{ The critical test, and usually what Black opts for when going for this move order as he wins a pawn. }
8. cxd4 Qc3+
{ Black's queen chimes in and wins the pawn on d4, as we must protect our rook. }
9. Bd2 Qxd4 10. Nf3
{ Our compensation for the pawn lies in rapid development. Black has to make a decision on where to place the queen: }
10... Qe4+ { Black gains some time by giving a check. } 11. Be3
{ The right piece to place in between as Bd3 is a useful resource to have.   11.Be2  has been played just as many times in my base, when Black has the annoying  11...b6  with the idea of trading bishops with  Ba6  . }
11... Ne7
{ Black intends to make use of Be3 by going for a quick knight jump to f5. }
12. Bd3 Qg4 13. h5 Nf5
{ Is now possible, as the queen defends the knight. This position was reached in Malakhov, I - Goganov, A St Petersburg 2011, and it's not so easy to tell what we're supposed to do here with White. In the attached game, Black equalized easily after  14.Bxf5  Qxf5  15.Rh4  h6  and went on to win. Indeed, the best move is the unnatural }
14. Kf1
{ Which is a brilliant move. We will allow Black to capture our bishop on e3, as it will open the f-file which will be a useful asset in our position. It's also an important factor that the king guards the g2-pawn. }
14... Nxe3+ 15. fxe3 Qa4
{ The exclam is there as Black's only chance is to get the queen out of the way. }
16. Qe1
{ Our queen is heading to g3 and our rook to h4 to create a powerful attack. }
16... Qd7 { 16...O-O  17.Rh4  Qd7  18.Qg3  is the same. } 17. Qg3 O-O 18. Rh4
{ We prepare a rook swing to f4 followed by Kg1-Rf1, when our pressure in the f-file will be incredibly strong. }
18... Qe7
{ Black's only move, as the queen on f7 allows the knight to jump to d7 or a f7-f5 thrust. }
19. Rf4 { Our plan of wreaking havoc in the f-file still stands. } 19... Nd7
20. h6 g6
{ Black has nothing else, as  20...f5  21.exf6  Rxf6  22.hxg7  Rxf4  23.Bxh7+  wins for us. }
21. Kg1 { Our king steps away so we can double our rooks in the f-file. } 21...
Nc5
{ Another only move. Rf1-Ng5 is coming really quickly. With Nc5 on the board, Black can defend the f7-pawn with Bd7-Be8. Deep stuff! }
22. Rf1 Bd7 { Black is just in time. } 23. Rf6
{ A strong attacking move with ideas such as Qh4.   23.Ng5  is pointless, since  23...Be8  keeps everything defended. Note also that the knight on  c5  defends  e6  . }
23... Be8
{ 23...Rac8?  Looks logical, but it loses to  24.Qh4!  With the threat of Rxg6+.  24...Kh8  25.Ng5  Be8  And now, the million-dollar move  26.e4!  Black's defense crumbles. The insane point behind 26. e4 is to prevent Black from playing Ne4, which was the only defense after 26. Bb5! These engines man...  26...d4   Other moves also fail:  26...Nxe4  loses to  27.Bxe4  dxe4  28.Nxe6  .   26...Rd8  loses to the beautiful  27.Rxf7  Bxf7  28.Rxf7  Rxf7  29.Nxf7+  Qxf7  30.Qxd8+  when Black is mated after  30...Qg8  31.Qf6+  Qg7  32.Qxg7#  .   27.Bb5+-  Black can resign as he loses the protection of the Achilles heel on f7. }
24. Qh4 Kh8 { Black dodges the threat of Rxg6+. } 25. Ng5
{ We have the perfect set-up, it's incredibly difficult for Black to keep everything together. }
25... Nd7
{ This move prolongs the game, but it turns out that the game can't be saved!   25...a6  26.R6f3  Black has no good way to meet the threat of Nxf7+.  26...Kg8  And now the deathblow  27.Bxg6!  Wins on the spot  27...hxg6  28.h7+  Kh8  29.Qh6+-  Black has no defense to Rf6 followed by Nxe6 when we win decisive material. If Black does nothing, it's mate after Rf6-Rxg6. }
26. Nxe6 Nxf6 27. Nxf8 Ng8
{ Is Black's deep defensive point.  27...Qxf8?  loses to  28.Qxf6+  Kg8  29.e6  . }
28. Qxe7 Nxe7 { Black has exchanged queens, but it's not enough! } 29. e6
{ This move wins by force as we're opening the f-file. I almost threw up when I discovered that  29.Ne6!?  fxe6  30.Rf8+  Ng8  31.Bb5  Rc8  32.Bxe8  a5  is just a draw. }
29... f5 30. g4 { We're forcing the opening of the f-file. } 30... fxg4
{ 30...Bc6  31.Nd7  The pawn on e6 gives us the square on d7 for our knight.  31...Bxd7  32.exd7  Black has serious problems with the weak king.  32...Rd8  Black gets rid of the pawn on d7, but he is busted after  33.gxf5  Rxd7  34.fxg6  Nxg6  35.Rf5+-  As the king is completely out of the game. }
31. Nd7 { The only winning move, but it's good enough. } 31... Bxd7 32. exd7
{ Everything works for us, but just barely... } 32... Rd8
{ 32...Ng8  Black wins the strong pawn on h6, but is it enough to save the game? No!!  33.c4!!  The only way as we need to make sure that our strong passed pawn on d7 stays protected.  33...Nxh6   33...dxc4  Is almost for Black, but he ends up in zugzwang in the line  34.Bxc4  Nxh6  35.e4  Rd8  36.Be6  Kg7  37.a4  Essential, we can't allow Black to create a passed pawn.  37...b6  38.Kg2  a6  39.Kg3  b5  40.a5  b4  41.Kh4  b3  42.Rf2  Black has no moves!  42...Rb8  43.Rb2+-  And Black can resign.  34.c5!!  Is the only winning move, with the deep plan of playing Rb1 followed by Rb7. This doesn't work after 34. cxd5 as Black easily dodges this with b6!  34...Rd8  35.Bb5  Nf5  36.Ba4  It's tough for Black to meet Rb1 followed by Rxb7.  36...Ng7  Is the best try, when  37.Rf6  Kg8  38.c6  bxc6  39.Bxc6+-  Wins. }
33. c4 { The only move again. } 33... Ng8
{ 33...Nc6  Wins the d7-pawn after  34.Rf7  Ne5  35.Re7  Nxd7  36.cxd5+-  But it doesn't help as our two moves in the center decide the game.   33...dxc4  34.Rf7  Is an important intermezzo.  34...Nc6  35.Bxc4  Ne5  36.Rf4  The h6-pawn is the real champion. Black can't take on d7! Re4 comes next and White wins. }
34. c5 Nxh6 35. Bb5
{ The e-pawn can't be stopped. A truly remarkable endgame! } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "25. French Defense (1...e6) Winawer Old Mainlines"]
[Black "6...Ne7 Informational 7.Qg4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ We have finally arrived to the main bulk of our coverage on the French, and our very last topic to cover for Part 1! This is the Winawer Variation, named after Szymon Winawer and popularized later in the 1940s by the greats Nimzowitch and Botvinnik. Black pins the knight and thus attacks the pawn on e4 so we're forced to make a decision in the center. }
4. e5
{ This is by far the most challenging move against the Winawer. We're gaining additional space while we're also limiting Black's knight on g8 as it can no longer jump to f6. }
4... c5
{ Black's main move challenges our center immediately, a necessary course of action to obtain the desired counterplay on the queenside. }
5. a3
{ By far the most played move as this is the only way to maintain the strong pawn chain. }
5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Ne7 7. Qg4
{ Has been the main move when we get some of the most exciting positions the game of chess has to offer. Black needs to watch his step very carefully as he's inches away from losing in the arising gunfire. I didn't choose this line as my recommendation because of the fact that Giri's analysis were top notch! I didn't find a way through! Indeed, as the flying dutchman himself points out, correspondence chess games show that this line is still very much playable in this modern age! That being said, that doesn't mean we can't make it difficult for Black... }
7... Qc7
{ Black decides to sacrifice the pawn on g7, as castling short is too risky. }
8. Qxg7
{ The obvious choice, but there is a dangerous alternative in  8.Bd3  as well. }
8... Rg8 9. Qxh7 cxd4 10. Ne2
{ White defends the pawn on  c3  . Some players have tried  10.Kd1!?  , a move that can be a very unpleasant surprise for the unprepared player. }
10... Nbc6
{ 10...dxc3  leads to the same thing, but this has been regarded as the most flexible path forward. }
11. f4 dxc3
{ We have reached the main position where White has numerous vicious alternatives. }
12. Qd3
{ 12.h4!?  is a very interesting line, intending to quickly push the h-pawn up the board. The line may go something like this:  12...d4  13.h5  Bd7  14.h6  O-O-O  15.Qd3  Kb8  16.h7  Rh8  17.g4  Bc8  18.Rb1  b6  19.Bg2  Bb7  20.Rh6  Nd5  21.Be4  Rd7  22.g5  , and here I found a remarkable correspondence game where White sacrificed the queen!  22...Qc8  23.f5  Ne3  24.Bxe3  Ba6  25.Qxa6!!  Qxa6  26.Rd1  , when it turns out that White is just winning. Szczepanski, Z - Serradimigni, R ICCF email 2015. }
12... d4
{ Is Giri's main suggestion which steers the game towards a very concrete terrain where Black needs to play pixel perfect in order to survive.  12...Bd7  is the alternative, and was considered the main move in the past. I analyzed:  13.Qxc3  Nf5  14.Ng3!?  Nxg3  15.hxg3  Rc8  16.Qb2!  This move isn't mentioned by Giri.  16...Rxg3  17.Rh8+  Ke7  18.Rxc8  Bxc8  19.Kf2  Rg8  20.Be3  Ke8  was Sgherri, M - Delizia, C ICCF email 2011, and here I believe White can press after  21.Be2  . }
13. Nxd4 Nxd4 14. Qxd4 Bd7
{ It's important that Black develops the bishop first, as  14...Nf5?  right away is awful after  15.Bb5+  . }
15. Rg1
{ White defends the pawn on g2 and prepares the pawn launch g2-g4 in the near future. }
15... Nf5 16. Qf2 Qc6 { Black prepares to meet  16.g4  with  16...Qe4+ } 17.
Bd3
{ 17.g4  Qe4+  18.Qe2  Qd5  19.Bg2  Qc5  20.Qf2  Nd4  21.Be4  Bc6  22.Be3  Bxe4  23.Bxd4  Qc4  Has been played in numerous correspondence games, for example Ljubicic, A - Serradimigni, R ICCF email 2015. }
17... Qd5
{ Is another necessary move. Black wants to play Bc6 and meet g4 with Nd4. }
18. Be3
{ This looks like White's scariest attempt.  18.a4  is also a decent try, with the idea of  Ra3  and  Rxc3  . The game goes  18...O-O-O  19.Ra3  Kb8  20.Rxc3  Bxa4  , and here White can choose between  21.Ra3  b5  22.Bb2  which was agreed draw in Podgursky, A - Serradimigni, R ICCF email 2015 @@StartBracket@@this guy again!@@EndBracket@@ or  21.Qc5  Qd7  22.Qb4  Bc6  23.Kf2  like in Hybl, V - Doren, D ICCF email 2016. Exciting stuff, but Black holds.  18.Rb1  is another scary move. For example:  18...Bc6  19.Rb3  O-O-O  20.Rxc3  Kb8  21.g4  Nd4  22.Rg3  Qh1+  23.Bf1  b6!!  An incredibly important move, also mentioned by Giri. Yes, I must once again praise Giri for his excellent work.  24.Bb2  Be4  and Caruana showed that he had done his homework already back in 2012 in Leko, P - Caruana, F Dortmund 2012. The line goes on, but it's equal. Lots of correspondence games from this position as well. }
18... Nxe3 { Necessary, otherwise we push g4. } 19. Qxe3 Rxg2 20. Rxg2 Qxg2 21.
Be4
{ 21.O-O-O  is the alternative, when the game was agreed drawn in Villaescusa Navalon, M - Vivante Sowter, J ICCF email 2019 after  21...Qd5  22.Rg1  O-O-O  23.Qxa7  Bc6  24.Rd1  Rd7  . }
21... Qxh2 22. O-O-O Bc6
{ Another only move. We've had a nice chunk of those in this variation! Some games have went  22...O-O-O?  but this leads to a losing endgame after  23.Qxc3+  Bc6  24.Bxc6  Rxd1+  25.Kxd1  . }
23. Bxc6+
{ 23.Kb1  is another critical try, when Black must find  23. ..Bxe4  24.Qxe4  Qf2!  in order to meet  Qxb7  with  Qb6+  and to avoid  Rh1  . Both  24.Qa4+  and  24.Qxb7  leads to a draw here, played for example in Savoca, A - Tauber, H ICCF email 2016. }
23... bxc6 24. Qd4
{ White attempts to place Black under Zugzwang. Black must be careful. } 24...
a5
{ Black waits. a5 is a move that doesn't hurt his position.   24...Kf8?  was a big mistake in Ivic, V - Livaic, L Chess.com INT 2020, when White wins after  25.Kb1!  Rb8+  26.Ka1  and the black king is in trouble.  26...Qxc2  loses to  27.Qd6+  Kg7  28.Rg1+  Kh7  29.Qxb8  , as the b2-square is guarded. Pointed out by Giri as well. In the online game Black tried  26...Kg8  , but was soon mated after  27.Rg1+  Kh8  28.Qd1  Rb3  29.Qd8+  . }
25. f5
{ A last attempt for tricks. Other moves:  25.Rg1  Qd2+  26.Qxd2  cxd2+  27.Kxd2  is a simple draw, played for instance in Sutton, A - Kruger, M ICCF email 2014.   25.Kb1  is a bit trickier, but soon agreed draw after  25...Qe2  26.Qd7+  Kf8  27.Qd3  Qxd3  in Jandek, S - Rook, D LSS email 2012. }
25... exf5 26. Kb1 Kf8
{ Giri points out the beautiful line  26...Qe2??  27.Qd7+  Kf8  28.Qd6+  Kg8  29.Rg1+  Kh7  30.Qxc6  , when Black can't avoid  Qh1  mate. }
27. Ka1
{ White was tired of pressing and went for a threefold with  27.Qd6+  in Titzhoff, F - Doren, D ICCF email 2017. }
27... Re8 28. Qc5+ Kg7 29. Rg1+ Kh7 30. e6 Rxe6 31. Qxf5+ Kh8 32. Qc5 Kh7 33.
Rf1 Kg7 34. Qg5+ Kf8 35. Qf5 Re7 36. Qc8+ Kg7 37. Qxc6 Re6 38. Qd7 Qh5 39. Qc7
Rh6
{ 39...Kf8  40.a4  Kg8  41.Qd7  was a draw in Kitson, K - Relyea, A ICCF email 2017. }
40. Qxc3+ Kf8 41. Rb1 Re6 42. Qc4 Qe5+ 43. Ka2 Qe4 44. Qc8+
{ Asquith,J -Owen,K ICCF email 2017. Our little trip through 7. Qg4 comes to an end! What a beautiful trip it was! I really loved analyzing these complications in such profound depth! As you can see, White has numerous dangerous alternatives along the way. There is so much to memorize for Black as there are so many mines to step on. Indeed, this is no problem in correspondence chess, but over the board is another story. This is surely why we seldom witness this line on top level. It's an incredibly risky choice. Even the French guru himself, Anish Giri, refrains from playing it. Certainly a warning sign! Let's now return to our move, 7. h4! }
*

