[Black "6...Ne7 (7...h5)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ We have finally arrived to the main bulk of our coverage on the French, and our very last topic to cover for Part 1! This is the Winawer Variation, named after Szymon Winawer and popularized later in the 1940s by the greats Nimzowitch and Botvinnik. Black pins the knight and thus attacks the pawn on e4 so we're forced to make a decision in the center. }
4. e5
{ This is by far the most challenging move against the Winawer. We're gaining additional space while we're also limiting Black's knight on g8 as it can no longer jump to f6. }
4... c5
{ Black's main move challenges our center immediately, a necessary course of action to obtain the desired counterplay on the queenside. }
5. a3
{ By far the most played move as this is the only way to maintain the strong pawn chain. }
5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Ne7 7. h4 h5
{ I will humbly accept my improved control over the dark squares and the outpost I get on g5! }
8. Nf3 Nbc6 9. Rb1 { We have the b-file so let's use it! } 9... Qc7 10. Be2
{ Easy does it! We'll complete our development and castle kingside. } 10... Bd7
11. O-O O-O-O 12. Bf4
{ Black's h5-advance has lead to a beautiful outpost for our knight and a weak pawn. We may also consider playing dxc5 next as well, followed by Nd4. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "25. French Defense (1...e6) Winawer Old Mainlines"]
[Black "6...Ne7 (7...Nd7)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ We have finally arrived to the main bulk of our coverage on the French, and our very last topic to cover for Part 1! This is the Winawer Variation, named after Szymon Winawer and popularized later in the 1940s by the greats Nimzowitch and Botvinnik. Black pins the knight and thus attacks the pawn on e4 so we're forced to make a decision in the center. }
4. e5
{ This is by far the most challenging move against the Winawer. We're gaining additional space while we're also limiting Black's knight on g8 as it can no longer jump to f6. }
4... c5
{ Black's main move challenges our center immediately, a necessary course of action to obtain the desired counterplay on the queenside. }
5. a3
{ By far the most played move as this is the only way to maintain the strong pawn chain. }
5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Ne7 7. h4 Nd7
{ Placing the knight on d7 looks wrong, but it has been played by a bunch of players rated above 2400. }
8. h5 { We resort to our same tactic. } 8... Qc7
{ Is Black's best move, played by a Hungarian GM back in 2014.   8...f6  Black has scored 5/6 with this move, but it's not very good.  9.h6  Of course!  9...g6  10.f4!   Much better than  10.exf6  , when Black gets what he wants. After  10.f4  we maintain our space advantage and leave Black rather cramped.  10...O-O  11.Nf3  Nf5  12.Rh3±  The engine is really excited and so am I, but I don't think I can give more than a clearly better game. We'll play a4-Ba3 next in case Black allows it.  In case Black tries  12...Qa5  , I think we should respond with  13.Bd2  , followed by  Bd3  and  Qe2  .  A capture on f5 might come in the future, when we can follow with the neat plan Kf1-Be1-Bh4. }
9. h6 cxd4 10. cxd4 Qc3+ 11. Bd2 Qxd4 12. Nf3
{ 12.Ne2  , the alternative I gave in 'Destroy the French' on chess24, is also very strong here, but I discovered that the text is an improvement. }
12... Qe4+
{ The logical way forward for Black is to give a check and capture the pawn on e5.   12...Qg4  Black can't afford to give us extra tempos on the queen.  13.Rh4  Qg6  14.Bd3  We give the pawn on g2, but after  14...Qxg2  15.Qe2+-  We'll castle queenside followed by a rook to g1 with a dominating position. }
13. Be2 Nxe5
{ We have now transposed to some games via a different move order. } 14. Bc3
{ We are currently two pawns down, so we must play actively and apply pressure on Black's position in order to justify for the material deficit. }
14... f6 15. hxg7 Rg8 16. Qd2
{ We'll castle queenside as fast as we can, followed by Rde1. } 16... Rxg7 17.
O-O-O N7c6
{ Is worse, but a tougher move to face as Black avoids the logical idea of taking on e5 followed by Bh5+.   17...Bd7  This move is objectively best, but it doesn't look very challenging to me.  18.Nxe5  fxe5  19.Bh5+  We have managed to open the e-file with a tempo, so we'll soon win the pawn on e5.  19...Kd8  20.Rde1!  The right rook, as our rook on h1 is very well placed in the open h-file where it can target the pawn on h7.  20...Qa4  21.Bxe5  Rxg2  22.Bd1!   This bizarre-looking move is the only way to target Black's pawn on  h7  , as  22.Bf3  fails to  22...Qxa3+  when our bishop on  f3  falls.  22...Nc6  23.Bd6+-  Black was under a lot of pressure in Koerber,B - Zylla,J ICCF email 2015, when Reg1 or Rxh7 comes next. Our dark-squared bishop makes the life of Black's king rather difficult.  23...Qd4  24.Qxd4  Nxd4  was how the game proceeded, when my engine suggests  25.Rxh7  when our bishop pair is incredibly strong. }
18. Nd4
{ Our knight jumps to the center and threatens  Bh5+  followed by  f3  when Black's queen is trapped.  18.Nxe5  was less clear in Maze, S - Goh, W Helsingor 2016, when White didn't have much after  18...fxe5  19.Qh6  Re7  20.Bh5+  Kd7  21.Rhe1  Qf4+  22.Qxf4  exf4  . }
18... Nxd4
{ Black should take.  18...Qxg2  for example would give us a completely winning position after  19.Nxc6  bxc6  20.Qf4  . Black's king is too exposed. }
19. Bxd4 Bd7 20. Rh6
{ A strong move that targets the pawn on f6, and once again threatens f3 followed by g4 as g6 is covered. }
20... Ba4
{ The best try. Black aims to meet  21.f3  with  21...Qxc2  and later take on  g2  with some pawns for the piece. }
21. Re1
{ Black's position falls apart, as seen in the following lines:  21...O-O-O  22.f3  is now a better version for us, due to  22...Qxc2+  23.Qxc2+  Bxc2  24.Kxc2  Rxg2  25.Rxf6  ,  when our bishop on e2 is protected by the inclusion of Re1.  21...Qf5  is the other move which should be met by  22.g4  Nxg4  23.Bd3  Qg5  . Here the simplest is to play  24.Qxg5  Rxg5  25.Rxh7  O-O-O  26.f3  Rgg8  27.Rxe6  , when our forces coordinate beautifully. }
