[Round "?"]
[White "25. French Defense (1...e6) Winawer Old Mainlines"]
[Black "6...Ne7 (7...O-O)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ We have finally arrived to the main bulk of our coverage on the French, and our very last topic to cover for Part 1! This is the Winawer Variation, named after Szymon Winawer and popularized later in the 1940s by the greats Nimzowitch and Botvinnik. Black pins the knight and thus attacks the pawn on e4 so we're forced to make a decision in the center. }
4. e5
{ This is by far the most challenging move against the Winawer. We're gaining additional space while we're also limiting Black's knight on g8 as it can no longer jump to f6. }
4... c5
{ Black's main move challenges our center immediately, a necessary course of action to obtain the desired counterplay on the queenside. }
5. a3
{ By far the most played move as this is the only way to maintain the strong pawn chain. }
5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Ne7 7. h4 O-O
{ Castling short is almost never played, and for good reason. It's incredibly risky as we get a powerful attack. f7-f6 is a typical way to get rid of some pressure, but Black will struggle immensely on the dark squares, in particular on the square on e5, after exf6. }
8. h5 { We'll keep pushing our precious pawn. } 8... h6
{ Makes sense, when   8...f6  Should be met by  9.h6  When Black gets severe trouble on the dark squares after  9...g6  10.exf6  Rxf6  11.Nf3  Black's 8... f6 has given us some nice squares on e5 and g5. Our h6-pawn also greatly contributes to our massive advantage.  11...Nbc6  12.Be2  Qd6  13.O-O  +-  White had gotten everything he could have dreamt of out of the opening in Delavekouras,S -Lindsalu,I ICCF email 2005. }
9. g4
{ Is incredibly strong. We're simply planning to break through with g5, with a decisive attack! }
9... Nbc6
{ Black tried this move in the only game I found in my base.   9...f6  Is horrible after  10.exf6  Rxf6  11.g5+-  When our attack decides the game. }
10. g5 Qa5
{ Looks like Black's best chance for counterplay.  10...hxg5?  can be met by  11.h6  , when Black can soon resign. }
11. gxh6 { 11. Bd2 is good too, but this is even better. } 11... Qxc3+ 12. Bd2
Qxd4 13. Nf3
{ Black has regained some pawns, but our kingside initiative is too strong. }
13... Qe4+ 14. Qe2 Bd7
{ We have so far been looking at the game Pehl,J - Nemeth,L LSS email 2008, and here the move }
15. Rg1 { Wins at once, for example } 15... g6 16. h7+ Kg7 17. Bg5
{ Bf6+ comes next, when Black has to give material in order to avoid mate. } *

