[Black "6...Ne7 (7...b6)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ We have finally arrived to the main bulk of our coverage on the French, and our very last topic to cover for Part 1! This is the Winawer Variation, named after Szymon Winawer and popularized later in the 1940s by the greats Nimzowitch and Botvinnik. Black pins the knight and thus attacks the pawn on e4 so we're forced to make a decision in the center. }
4. e5
{ This is by far the most challenging move against the Winawer. We're gaining additional space while we're also limiting Black's knight on g8 as it can no longer jump to f6. }
4... c5
{ Black's main move challenges our center immediately, a necessary course of action to obtain the desired counterplay on the queenside. }
5. a3
{ By far the most played move as this is the only way to maintain the strong pawn chain. }
5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Ne7 7. h4 b6
{ The typical plan of trading light-squared bishops is too slow. } 8. h5
{ As almost always, our pawn marches forward to fix the pawn structure. } 8...
h6
{ Played almost exclusively, for good reason. Black doesn't want to allow us to play h6. }
9. Qg4
{ Our usual follow-up. Black doesn't have any desirable ways to defend the hanging pawn. }
9... Kf8
{ The lesser evil.  9...Nf5  is the alternative, when we can play  10.Bb5+  and move back to  d3  after  10...Bd7  . Natural moves will follow suit when we'll have a very good game. }
10. a4
{ An excellent way to meet Black's idea of playing Ba6, as the bishop can move to b5. }
10... Ba6
{ 10...Qc7  has also been played, when it's important that we play the thematic  11.Rh3  to guard the pawn on  c3  . A 19-year old Nepo won a nice game after  11...Ba6  12.Rf3  Kg8  13.Qf4  Nec6  14.Bb5  Rh7  15.Ne2  Na5?  16.Be8  , and Black resigned in Nepomniachtchi, I - Shimanov, A St Petersburg 2009. }
11. Bb5 Bxb5 12. axb5
{ Black has managed to trade the poor bishop, but the pawn on b5 is quite annoying as it takes away the c6-square for the black knight and provides a nice open file for our rook. }
12... a5
{ The player rated around 2500 with Black played this move, but I don't see the point behind it.  12...Qd7  is better, but our edge remains really big after  13.Qe2  a6  14.dxc5  bxc5  15.Nf3  Qb7  16.Be3  c4  17.b6  Nd7  18.Kd2!?  when we'll push for g5. }
13. Ba3
{ I prefer this move over  13.Nf3  which was played in Vitiugov, N - Petrik, T Czech Republic 2016. }
13... Nd7 14. Ne2
{ Our knight is placed on e2 where it can jump to g3 and push a f4-f5 break. }
14... Rc8 15. f4 Kg8 16. Ng3
{ There's no need to worry about the hanging pawn on c2 as our initiative is decisive. }
16... cxd4 17. cxd4 Rxc2 18. O-O
{ f5 comes next when Black will get annihilated on the kingside. } *

