1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ We have finally arrived to the main bulk of our coverage on the French, and our very last topic to cover for Part 1! This is the Winawer Variation, named after Szymon Winawer and popularized later in the 1940s by the greats Nimzowitch and Botvinnik. Black pins the knight and thus attacks the pawn on e4 so we're forced to make a decision in the center. }
4. e5
{ This is by far the most challenging move against the Winawer. We're gaining additional space while we're also limiting Black's knight on g8 as it can no longer jump to f6. }
4... c5
{ Black's main move challenges our center immediately, a necessary course of action to obtain the desired counterplay on the queenside. }
5. a3
{ By far the most played move as this is the only way to maintain the strong pawn chain. }
5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Ne7 7. h4 Bd7
{ Black has tried this developing move in some games. } 8. h5
{ We keep pushing our pawn forward. } 8... h6
{ Black stops the annoying h5-h6. } 9. Qg4
{ It's time to target Black's weakest spot. } 9... Qa5
{ Black's best try.   9...Qc7?  Sacrificing the pawn on strong when we play Qg4 in the seventh move, but this time it just loses.  10.Qxg7  Rg8  11.Qxh6  cxd4  12.Ne2  Nbc6  And now the simplest is to play  13.Qf6+-  When our h-pawn grants us a decisive advantage.   9...Nf5  Doesn't look very challenging, as we can simply play  10.Bd3   When Black is more or less forced to play  10...Rg8  when we get an excellent game after  11.Bxf5  or  11.Ne2  . If Black tries  10...O-O ?!  A very strong response is  11.Qh3→  When g4-g5 comes really quickly with a deadly attack. }
10. Bd2 Kf8
{ This looks forced, as  10...Rg8  11.Bd3  Nf5  12.Ne2  is horrible for Black.   10...Nbc6  11.Qxg7  Transposing to future lines with 7... Nbc6. }
11. Rh3
{ Our rook heads to h3 and prepares to swing to f3 where it will create dangerous threats towards Black's king. }
11... Nbc6 12. Qf4 c4
{ Black attempts to create something on the queenside, but it looks slow. } 13.
g4
{ Grabbing more space on the kingside. Black has to be prepared for g4-g5 which can come any second. }
13... Qb6 14. Bc1 { Black's queenside intrusion is stopped. } 14... Kg8
{ The king gets out of the way. Moving to the other side with  14...Ke8?  is worse, when White is just winning after  15.Rf3  Nd8  16.a4  , when the bishop arrives to  a3  soon. }
15. a4 Rf8 { Black's only sensible plan is to play for f6. } 16. Qd2 f6 17. f4
{ Black's position is horrible. Our next moves are simple: Ba3-Nf3-Be2. Black doesn't have any counterplay. We will break through with g5 at the right circumstances. }
