1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ We have finally arrived to the main bulk of our coverage on the French, and our very last topic to cover for Part 1! This is the Winawer Variation, named after Szymon Winawer and popularized later in the 1940s by the greats Nimzowitch and Botvinnik. Black pins the knight and thus attacks the pawn on e4 so we're forced to make a decision in the center. }
4. e5
{ This is by far the most challenging move against the Winawer. We're gaining additional space while we're also limiting Black's knight on g8 as it can no longer jump to f6. }
4... c5
{ Black's main move challenges our center immediately, a necessary course of action to obtain the desired counterplay on the queenside. }
5. a3
{ By far the most played move as this is the only way to maintain the strong pawn chain. }
5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Ne7 7. h4 Qa5 8. Bd2 cxd4
{ Black has tried this move in some games, but I am remain unimpressed as it goes against Black's strategy in these positions. }
9. cxd4 Qa4
{ Black's point is this move, targeting the pawn on d4 when b6-Ba6 may come quickly. The problem for Black is that }
10. c3
{ Gives us a really comfortable endgame with the bishop pair and a sweet pawn chain. }
10... Qxd1+ 11. Rxd1
{ Black has scored 0/3 from this position in my base, an excellent sign. }
11... Nbc6 12. h5 h6 13. Rb1
{ It makes sense to place our rook in the open b-file. After all, it wasn't doing anything on d1. }
13... b6 14. Nf3 Bd7
{ Black's only plan here is to create something on the queenside with Rc8 and Nc4. The problem with that plan is that it's relatively easy for us to deal with, as the bishop on c1 will defend the hanging pawn on a3. Black's knight on c4 will look nice, but that's pretty much it. }
15. Nh4 Na5 16. Rh3
{ A nice placement for our rook, waking over the pawn on c3. } 16... Nc4 17.
Bc1 Rc8
{ Black's play on the queenside looks beautiful... But as we know, beauty alone is not enough! }
18. Be2 O-O 19. g4
{ It's time for us to start breaking through on the kingside. } 19... f6 20.
exf6 Rxf6 21. g5 Rf7
{ The only move. I examined  21.. .hxg5  on chess24, but this is just a hopeless ending after  22.Bxg5  Rf7  23.Bxe7  Rxe7  24.Ng6  Ree8  25.Bxc4  Rxc4  26.Rg3  , when  Kd2  followed by  Rbg1  and  Ne5  comes next with a decisive advantage. }
22. gxh6 gxh6 23. Bxh6 Nxa3
{ Black regains the pawn, but is still in major trouble after } 24. Rb3 Nc4 25.
Bd3
{ Rg3+ followed by Ng6 looks deadly.   The best defense is  25...Nf5  , but after  26.Nxf5  exf5  27.Rg3+  Kh7  28.Bf4  our bishop pair should take us to Rome. }
