[Round "?"]
[White "25. French Defense (1...e6) Winawer Old Mainlines"]
[Black "6...Ne7 (7...Qa5 2)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ We have finally arrived to the main bulk of our coverage on the French, and our very last topic to cover for Part 1! This is the Winawer Variation, named after Szymon Winawer and popularized later in the 1940s by the greats Nimzowitch and Botvinnik. Black pins the knight and thus attacks the pawn on e4 so we're forced to make a decision in the center. }
4. e5
{ This is by far the most challenging move against the Winawer. We're gaining additional space while we're also limiting Black's knight on g8 as it can no longer jump to f6. }
4... c5
{ Black's main move challenges our center immediately, a necessary course of action to obtain the desired counterplay on the queenside. }
5. a3
{ By far the most played move as this is the only way to maintain the strong pawn chain. }
5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Ne7 7. h4 Qa5 8. Bd2 Qa4 9. Rb1
{ I settled for this move on chess24 in 'Destroy the French,' and it seems like it has stood the test of time! Our rook controls a lot of squares in the b-file so it makes sense to place it there.   9.Qb1  c4   The standard reaction, but some players have also tried  9...Nbc6  which usually transposes after  10.h5  h6  11.Nf3  c4  .  10.h5  h6  11.Nf3  This time there's no bishop on h5 or g4, but our plan is still rather similar as we're planning to launch our pawns forward on the kingside.  11...Nbc6  12.g4!?  White goes for immediate action.  12...Bd7  13.Nh4  The knight moves to pave the way for the f-pawn.  13...O-O-O   Black went for the engine-looking  13...Kd8!?  and drew comfortably in Tobor, M - Dutra, A ICCF email 2018, but no human would every play such a move. On an objective note, it doesn't look that good to me either. I suggest a set-up for White with Be3-Be2-Kd2-Qb2 and eventually a f4-push, starting with  14.Be3  .  14.Qb2  We'll soon see the idea behind this move...  14...f6  15.f4  Kb8  16.O-O-O  A surprising move, but the king is very safe on the queenside as it's blocked.  16...Qa5  17.Bg2  Rhf8  18.exf6  White makes an interesting decision in releasing the tension.  18...Rxf6  19.Rde1  The rook goes to the open e-file and applies pressure on the vulnerable pawn on e6.  19...Rf7  20.Rhf1  Rdf8  21.Nf3  The knight doesn't do anything special on h4, so it's headed for e5.  21...Ka8  22.Ne5  Nxe5  23.dxe5  White has obtained a pawn majority on the kingside.  23...Nc6  24.Kb1  Bc8  25.Ka2  There's no need to hurry before striking. Black can't do much.  25...Re7  26.Re2  Ref7  27.f5!  At the right time!  27...Rg8   Looks strange, but Black didn't have anything better as  f6  comes.  27...exf5  is met by  28.e6!  , followed by  gxf5  .  28.Qb1  There was no need to wait with f6. As a matter of fact, the queen heads back to b2 soon!  28...Rh8  29.f6  a6  30.Qe1  Na7  31.Qa1  Qc7  32.Qb2  Told ya!  32...Nc6  Black presses our center, but after  33.fxg7  Rxg7  34.Bh3  Black is in deep trouble as the pawn on h6 is extremely weak and bound to fall at some point. Enjoy how White masterfully converts his advantage:  34...Re7  35.Rf6  Reh7  36.Bf4  Qd8  37.Rf2  Qc7  38.Bg2  Qa5  39.Bf3  Qc5  40.Rg2  Rg8  Black tries to gain counterplay as the pawn on e5 hangs after the capture on h6, but it's not enough.  41.Bxh6  Nxe5  42.Bd1  Qe7  43.g5  Nd7  44.Rg6  Rd8  45.Qb4  Qf7  46.Rf6  Qg8   Why not  46...Nxf6?  you may ask. Well, it fails to  47.g6  Qg8  48.gxh7  Qxg2  49.Qe7  Rh8  50.Qxf6  Rxh7  51.Qd8  Rxh6  52.Qxc8+  Ka7  53.Qc5+  Ka8  54.Qf8+  and the rook on  h6  falls!  47.Rff2  Ka7  48.Qb1  Qh8  49.Qc1  d4  50.Be2  Rg8  51.cxd4  Nb6  52.Bf3  c3  53.Qe3  Bd7  54.Be4  Nd5  55.Qe1  Bc6  56.Bxh7  Qxh7  57.Rh2  Nb6  58.Ka1+-  Black called it a day in Malashenkov,A Valli,L ICCF email 2018. A beautiful game and an extremely instructive one, too. }
9... Nbc6 { Should be met by } 10. h5 h6 11. Qc1
{ When Black has nothing better than transposing to the main line with  11...c4  , as  11...cxd4  is met by  12.Bb5  Qa5  13.cxd4  .   On chess24 I gave  11.Rh4!?  for some weird reason. I guess I didn't realize that I had transposed to the main line! Oops. I found some nifty tactics in the line  11...Nf5  12.Rf4  Bd7  13.dxc5  Qxa3  14.Nf3  Qxc5  15.Rxb7  Na5  16.Rxd7!!  when White wins in the arising complications. However,  11...c4  can be played, when Black has an improved version of the main line. }
