[White "25. French Defense (1...e6) Winawer Old Mainlines"]
[Black "6...Ne7 (7...Qa5 3)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ We have finally arrived to the main bulk of our coverage on the French, and our very last topic to cover for Part 1! This is the Winawer Variation, named after Szymon Winawer and popularized later in the 1940s by the greats Nimzowitch and Botvinnik. Black pins the knight and thus attacks the pawn on e4 so we're forced to make a decision in the center. }
4. e5
{ This is by far the most challenging move against the Winawer. We're gaining additional space while we're also limiting Black's knight on g8 as it can no longer jump to f6. }
4... c5
{ Black's main move challenges our center immediately, a necessary course of action to obtain the desired counterplay on the queenside. }
5. a3
{ By far the most played move as this is the only way to maintain the strong pawn chain. }
5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Ne7 7. h4 Qa5 8. Bd2 Qa4 9. Rb1
{ I settled for this move on chess24 in 'Destroy the French,' and it seems like it has stood the test of time! Our rook controls a lot of squares in the b-file so it makes sense to place it there. }
9... Qxa3
{ One automatically considers taking the pawn when there's no longer a rook that patrols it, but it doesn't work! }
10. Ra1 Qb2 11. h5
{ We proceed with our precious h-pawn, aiming to reach h6. That being said, there's a deeper point behind it... }
11... h6
{ 11...cxd4  Makes things even worse after  12.Rb1  Qa3  13.cxd4  When we have the best Wing-Gambit in the world.  13...Nec6  14.Rh3  Qe7  15.Rg3  Forcing Black to make a concession. There's no need to worry about the pawn on d4 yet, as we have Bb4, attacking the queen and knight.  15...f6  16.exf6  Qxf6  17.Nf3+-  Our forces outweigh the missing pawn by a long shot.   11...Nbc6  Can be met by  12.dxc5  Nxe5  13.Rh4!  And Black's queen is suddenly in trouble after  13...N5c6  14.Rha4+-  A really cool maneuver! }
12. dxc5 Nd7 13. Rh4 { The rook swing does the trick yet again! } 13... Nc6 14.
Rha4 Nxc5
{ Black wins the pawn and provides the queen with an escape route on b6, but... }
15. R4a2 Qb6 16. Be3 { Black's knight on c5 is in trouble! } 16... a6
{ 16...d4  is objectively best, but practically rather hopeless after  17.cxd4  Qb4+  18.Qd2  Qxd2+  19.Kxd2  Ne4+  20.Ke1  due to our powerful bishop pair and center. }
17. Rb1 Qa7 18. Bb5 { An important move, preventing b7-b5! } 18... Bd7 19. Qg4
{ The Russian GM plays perfectly here. Qg4 threatens Qxg7 and Bxc6 followed by Qb4. }
19... Qb6
{ The engine defense.  19...b6  20.Qxg7  Rf8  21.Bxc5  bxc5  22.Rxa6  was Antipov, M - Krishna, C Moscow 2020, when Black resigned a few moves later. }
20. Raa1 { Keeping the rook on b1 protected. } 20... Kf8 21. Ba4
{ White wins, in the view of  21...Qa5  22.Bxc6  Qxc3+  23.Kd1  Bxc6  24.Ne2  Qxe5  25.Bxc5+  Kg8  26.f4  Qc7  27.Bd4  . }
