1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ We have finally arrived to the main bulk of our coverage on the French, and our very last topic to cover for Part 1! This is the Winawer Variation, named after Szymon Winawer and popularized later in the 1940s by the greats Nimzowitch and Botvinnik. Black pins the knight and thus attacks the pawn on e4 so we're forced to make a decision in the center. }
4. e5
{ This is by far the most challenging move against the Winawer. We're gaining additional space while we're also limiting Black's knight on g8 as it can no longer jump to f6. }
4... c5
{ Black's main move challenges our center immediately, a necessary course of action to obtain the desired counterplay on the queenside. }
5. a3
{ By far the most played move as this is the only way to maintain the strong pawn chain. }
5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Ne7 7. h4 Nbc6
{ The old move, given as an alternative option by Giri. } 8. h5 h6
{ Black usually reacts with this move, but in this particular case it's not such a great idea due to }
9. Qg4 Nf5
{ 9...Qa5  Can be played, when  10.Bd2  Transposes to 9... h6 via the 8... Qa5 move order. }
10. Bd3
{ Giri mentions this line briefly and points out that Black is forced to either castle or play a clumsy move. A very accurate statement. }
10... O-O
{ Black's should go for quick development.  10...Nce7  is one of the clumsy moves Black can play, but after  11.dxc5  Qc7  12.Nf3  Qxc5  13.O-O  White was doing extremely well in Ayas Fernandez, A - Martinez, J Albacete 1995. }
11. Qh3
{ We have seen this idea earlier in a similar position. The point behind the move is to launch the g-pawn up the board and create a vicious attack. }
11... cxd4 12. g4 Nfe7
{ Black tried sacrificing the knight with  12...Nxe5  in Inarkiev, E - Shimanov, A Konya 2012, but I can't see any counterplay after  13.gxf5  dxc3  14.Ne2  . }
13. Qg3
{ A preparing move for the g5-break, as  13.g5  right away allows  13...Nxe5  . }
13... f6 { Black opens the position to neutralize our attack. } 14. exf6 Rxf6
15. g5
{ There's no time to waste as Black could become active very quickly with e5. }
15... Nf5 { Black's only move. } 16. Bxf5
{ We'll take the knight so we can capture on h6 next. } 16... Rxf5 17. gxh6 Qf6
18. Ne2 dxc3 { Is the critical position of this variation. } 19. Rg1
{ After analyzing for a long while, I decided to settle for the safe option.  19.hxg7  is more dangerous, but I think Black has a pretty decent blockade after  19...Bd7  20.h6  Kh7  21.Rg1  Rg8  . Apparently, the position is quite concrete, and the best play for both sides show the line  22.Be3  Ne5  23.f4  Nc4  24.Bd4  e5  25.Bxc3  d4  26.O-O-O  dxc3  27.Rxd7  exf4  28.Qd3  Ne5  29.Qd5  Nxd7  30.Qxg8+  Kxg8  31.h7+  Kxh7  32. g8/QKh6  when Black is still hanging on. Really fun stuff, but unnecessarily complicated.  19.Be3!?  might be worth considering, though. }
19... Rxh5
{ Black should grab the pawn.  19...e5  is met by  20.Nxc3!  when the complications go in our favor. I looked at  20...Be6  21.Rb1  b6  22.Nb5  Rf8  23.Rb3  Rxh5  24.Rc3  Nd8  25.hxg7  Rf7  26.Bg5  Qg6  27.Qxe5  , when White is completely dominating. }
20. Qxg7+ Qxg7 21. Rxg7+ Kh8 22. Ng3
{ Black needs to fight hard for a draw, as we have a very powerful initiative on the kingside. }
