[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "25. French Defense (1...e6) Winawer Old Mainlines"]
[Black "7...Nbc6 (8...Qa5 9...b6)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ We have finally arrived to the main bulk of our coverage on the French, and our very last topic to cover for Part 1! This is the Winawer Variation, named after Szymon Winawer and popularized later in the 1940s by the greats Nimzowitch and Botvinnik. Black pins the knight and thus attacks the pawn on e4 so we're forced to make a decision in the center. }
4. e5
{ This is by far the most challenging move against the Winawer. We're gaining additional space while we're also limiting Black's knight on g8 as it can no longer jump to f6. }
4... c5
{ Black's main move challenges our center immediately, a necessary course of action to obtain the desired counterplay on the queenside. }
5. a3
{ By far the most played move as this is the only way to maintain the strong pawn chain. }
5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Ne7 7. h4 Nbc6
{ The old move, given as an alternative option by Giri. } 8. h5 Qa5 9. Bd2 b6
{ Is a brand new idea, suggested by Giri. Black's idea isn't rocket science, it's simply to play Ba6 and trade bishops. Black allows us to weaken the dark squares with h6, but Giri justifies this by the fact that he will get decent play on the light squares. The king safety isn't such a big concern for him either, as d7 is actually a pretty good square for it. }
10. h6 gxh6
{ We have managed to destroy Black's pawn structure and gain additional control on the dark squares, but Black doesn't care as he'll soon trade bishops. }
11. Rxh6
{ 11.a4  would transpose to the line Giri gave, but we saw that Black holds with perfect play. }
11... Ba6 12. Nf3 Bxf1 13. Kxf1
{ This is the main position where I decided to analyze some different approaches by Black. Black has traded our bishop and has nice control of the light squares, but his camp is still rather exposed on the dark squares. Black's pawn on f7 is also a major weakness, as we'll see in the upcoming lines. I took a look at four approaches I thought looked natural, namely   13...O-O-O  ,  13...Qa6+  13...Nf5  and  13....cxd4  . }
13... Qa6+
{ Black gives a check and places the queen on an improved square.   13...Nf5  14.Rf6  Qa6+?!   Can be played as well, but it's not good. If Black plays  14...cxd4  , I was initially going to suggest  15.c4  which is an extra option we have. Black needs to play extremely accurately. A semi-forced line is:  15...Qa4!  16.Ng5  d3!  The point.  17.cxd3  Qxd1+  18.Rxd1  O-O  19.g4  Nfe7  20.Rh6  Rfd8  21.Nxh7  dxc4  22.Nf6+  Kg7  23.Kg2  Nxe5  24.Rdh1  N7g6  25.Bg5  Rh8!  The only move!  26.f4  Nxd3  27.Rh7+  Rxh7  28.Rxh7+  Kf8  29.f5  . White wins a piece, but it should be a draw. After all of that, I think the simplest is to transpose to the main move with  15.cxd4!  Still, Black's path to equality isn't exactly crystal clear after  15. c4...  15.Kg1  h6  Black has to stop Ng5.  16.Rxf5!  A really powerful exchange sac which causes problems for Black.  16...exf5  17.Nh4  Our point!  17...Qc8   By far the best defense.  17...Ne7  is not good as Black needs the knight for counterplay against our d4-pawn. After  18.Qh5  Qc8  , White wins after the beautiful  19.e6!  18.Qh5  Qe6  Black stops e6.  19.Nxf5  Kd7  20.Re1  Rag8  It seems like Black is starting to get the situation under control, but...  21.dxc5!  Is incredibly powerful with the idea  21...bxc5  22.c4  Opening the position.  22...dxc4   The most testing.  22...d4  leaves us dominating after  23.g3  Kc7  24.Bf4  , when  Nd6  will come next.  23.Be3  Kc7  24.Qf3   24.Bxc5?  would lose to  24...Rg5  , hence the queen move.  24...Nxe5  25.Bf4  f6  26.Ne3!  With a dominating game as we're playing  Qe4  followed by  Nxc4  or  Ng4  next. In case Black tries  26...Rd8  , we should play  Ng4  when we'll win on  e5  . Black's king is too exposed. }
14. Kg1 cxd4
{ In this position we can transpose to the main move,  13...cxd4  with  15.cxd4  , but I found a nice way to punish Black's inaccurate move order! }
15. Ng5
{ Suddenly Black needs to watch out for Qh5! There's also a neat point in that Black's king is stuck on e8 defending the f7-pawn. }
15... dxc3 { Is Black's best, but a very natural move for a human to make. }
16. Nxf7 { This nasty blow works! } 16... Kxf7 17. Qh5+ Ng6
{ The only move that doesn't lose at once. } 18. Rxh7+ Rxh7 19. Qxh7+ Ke8
{ 19...Kf8  would just give us  20.Bh6+  for free. } 20. Qxg6+ Kd7 21. Qh7+ Ne7
22. Bxc3
{ With a much safer king and pawn up, we can claim a clearly better game. Our bishop is heading to d6. a4-a5 may come at a later stage. }
*

