[White "25. French Defense (1...e6) Winawer Old Mainlines"]
[Black "7...Nbc6 (8...Qa5 9...b6 2)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ We have finally arrived to the main bulk of our coverage on the French, and our very last topic to cover for Part 1! This is the Winawer Variation, named after Szymon Winawer and popularized later in the 1940s by the greats Nimzowitch and Botvinnik. Black pins the knight and thus attacks the pawn on e4 so we're forced to make a decision in the center. }
4. e5
{ This is by far the most challenging move against the Winawer. We're gaining additional space while we're also limiting Black's knight on g8 as it can no longer jump to f6. }
4... c5
{ Black's main move challenges our center immediately, a necessary course of action to obtain the desired counterplay on the queenside. }
5. a3
{ By far the most played move as this is the only way to maintain the strong pawn chain. }
5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Ne7 7. h4 Nbc6
{ The old move, given as an alternative option by Giri. } 8. h5 Qa5 9. Bd2 b6
{ Is a brand new idea, suggested by Giri. Black's idea isn't rocket science, it's simply to play Ba6 and trade bishops. Black allows us to weaken the dark squares with h6, but Giri justifies this by the fact that he will get decent play on the light squares. The king safety isn't such a big concern for him either, as d7 is actually a pretty good square for it. }
10. h6 gxh6
{ We have managed to destroy Black's pawn structure and gain additional control on the dark squares, but Black doesn't care as he'll soon trade bishops. }
11. Rxh6
{ 11. a4 would transpose to the line Giri gave, but we saw that Black holds with perfect play. }
11... Ba6 12. Nf3 Bxf1 13. Kxf1
{ This is the main position where I decided to analyze some different approaches by Black. }
13... cxd4
{ Black's best move by a long shot, so it's worthy of an exclam.   13...O-O-O ?  It's very natural to castle queenside, but it gives Black problems after  14.Rf6  When Black has problems with the pawn on f7.  14...Rdf8  15.Kg1  Our king moves out of danger and avoids any annoying checks. Ng5 is now looming in the air.  15...h6!?  Black tempts us with a free pawn, as the capture would give him play in the h-file.  16.a4  We don't care about the pawn.  16...Rh7  It's hard for Black to find any sensible moves.  17.c4  Qa6  18.a5  We're breaking up Black's queenside.  18...dxc4  19.axb6  Qxb6  20.dxc5  Qxc5  21.Be3+-  Black is so exposed on the queenside that we're just winning. A really powerful plan is Qe2/Qf1 followed by Rf4 and a capture on c4. The other rook belongs in the b-file. }
14. cxd4 Qa6+ 15. Kg1 Nf5
{ Black attacks our rook and pawn on d4 simultaneously. } 16. Rf6 Ncxd4 17.
Nxd4
{ We must capture the knight, as something like  17.Ng5?  Ne2+  followed by  Qc4  would quickly be a disaster. }
17... Nxd4 18. Qg4 Qc4
{ The only move! The line is long enough as it is, but so I will leave what happens in case Black moves the knight as clickables:  18...Nf5  allows  19.Rxf5  exf5  20.Qxf5  with a deadly attack.  18...Ne2+  doesn't do much any longer. I looked at  19.Kh2  Qc4  20.Qh5  O-O-O  21.Re1  Nc3  22.Qxf7  and everything falls apart for Black. I checked  22...Ne4  23.Qxe6+  Kb7  24.Rf7+  Ka6  25.Be3  , when White wins due to Black's exposed king.  18...Nc6  fails to the beautiful  19.Rxf7!  when our attack is decisive after the forced sequence  19...Kxf7  20.Qh5+  Ke7  21.Bg5+  Kd7  22.Qf7+  Kc8  23.Qxe6+  Kb7  24.Qd7+  Kb8  25.Bf4  . Beautiful lines indeed! }
19. Qh5 { Our queen moves in the view of Ne2+. } 19... O-O-O 20. Re1
{ Preventing Ne2, so Black has to be careful of Rf4-ideas. } 20... Qc6 21. Qg4
{ Setting up the trap of  21...Nf5??  22.Qxf5!  The knight is thus forced to an inferior square. }
21... Nb5 22. Rxf7 Rd7 23. Rxd7 Qxd7 24. Qa4
{ Black's knight is almost in trouble, but... } 24... d4
{ Saves the day.  24...Kb7  25.Rb1  a6  would be hopeless for Black, as he needs to have  b6  protected. }
25. Rb1 Nc3 26. Qc4+ Kb7 27. Bxc3 dxc3 28. Qxc3
{ Giri's alternative finally concludes with us being a pawn up. Really cool line, but I think it's too risky for Black at the end of the day. }
