[White "25. French Defense (1...e6) Winawer Old Mainlines"]
[Black "7...Nbc6 (8...Qa5 9...h6)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ We have finally arrived to the main bulk of our coverage on the French, and our very last topic to cover for Part 1! This is the Winawer Variation, named after Szymon Winawer and popularized later in the 1940s by the greats Nimzowitch and Botvinnik. Black pins the knight and thus attacks the pawn on e4 so we're forced to make a decision in the center. }
4. e5
{ This is by far the most challenging move against the Winawer. We're gaining additional space while we're also limiting Black's knight on g8 as it can no longer jump to f6. }
4... c5
{ Black's main move challenges our center immediately, a necessary course of action to obtain the desired counterplay on the queenside. }
5. a3
{ By far the most played move as this is the only way to maintain the strong pawn chain. }
5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Ne7 7. h4 Nbc6
{ The old move, given as an alternative option by Giri. } 8. h5 Qa5 9. Bd2 h6
{ Is a possible choice, when we should respond in the same manner as against 8... h6. }
10. Qg4 { Black doesn't have a good way of defending the pawn on g7. } 10...
Bd7
{ Has been tried in a decent chunk of games, intending to sacrifice the pawn on g7. }
11. Qxg7 O-O-O { Black castles queenside and keeps the h6-pawn alive for now. }
12. Qf6
{ The queen gets out of harm's way and prevents ideas such as f5 followed by Rdg8. }
12... Qa4
{ Black moves out of the discovery and tries to obtain some counterplay. Issue is that it's not enough. }
13. Nf3 cxd4 { And now we have the thematic idea } 14. Rh4
{ 14.cxd4  Nxd4  15.Bd3  is also promising, but not AS promising... } 14... Nf5
{ 14....Qxc2  is met by  15.Nxd4  Qb2  16.Rc1  when Bxh6 will soon follow suit. Our bishop will move to d3 and our knight could even move to b5. }
15. Rf4 Qxc2 16. Rc1 Qb2 17. g4
{ Black's knight is removed from its post on f5. } 17... Nfe7
{ 17...dxc3  lost a piece after  18.Rxc3  Nfe7  19.Qxe7  in Seickel, R - Puschendorf, S Wiesbaden 2013, and Black resigned after  19...Qb1+  20.Bc1  Qa1  21.Qb4  . }
18. cxd4
{ Both captures are great, but I prefer the pawn capture. Black has serious problems with his kingside pawns. Next, I suggest securing our king by playing Be2-Kf1-Kg2. Then, we'll proceed with the hunting of Black's pawns, for instance by placing a rook on f6. }
