4. e5
{ This is by far the most challenging move against the Winawer. We're gaining additional space while we're also limiting Black's knight on g8 as it can no longer jump to f6. }
4... c5
{ Black's main move challenges our center immediately, a necessary course of action to obtain the desired counterplay on the queenside. }
5. a3
{ By far the most played move as this is the only way to maintain the strong pawn chain. }
5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Ne7 7. h4 Nbc6
{ The old move, given as an alternative option by Giri. } 8. h5 Qa5 9. Bd2 h6
{ Is a possible choice, when we should respond in the same manner as against 8... h6. }
10. Qg4 { Black doesn't have a good way of defending the pawn on g7. } 10...
Nf5 11. Bd3
{ The inclusion of Qa5 and Bd2 gives us a better version than the one we saw after 8... h6. }
11... Nce7
{ I suggest to take the same approach and play   11...O-O  Is once again met by the strong  12.Qh3!  When g4 is coming. It's clear why this version is worse, as Black doesn't have cxd4 as we target Black's queen when we recapture.  12...f6  Has been tried thrice, when the antidote is  13.g4  Nfe7  14.Nf3+-  With the strong idea of taking on f6, followed by Qg2 and the pawn break g4-g5. }
12. dxc5 Qxc5 13. Nf3 Qc7
{ Black would like to play  13...Nc6  , but can't do so yet as we have  14.Bxf5  when  g7  falls. }
14. Qf4
{ Black needs to be on the lookout for g4. Our queen on f4 also guards our pawn on e5. }
14... Nc6 15. O-O
{ Black is in big trouble as our bishop pair is incredibly strong, in particular our dark-squared bishop which can come to life after a4-Bc1-Ba3. }
15... Nfe7
{ 15...Bd7?  16.Bxf5  exf5  17.e6  was a nice trick in Martinez Gonzalez, A - Oliver Font, J Binissalem 2002. }
16. Qg3 { Forcing another concession from Black. } 16... Kf8 17. a4
{ The path has been opened for the bishop on d2 which will soon be a monster on the a3-f8 diagonal. Black lacks counterplay is pretty much lost. }
