[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ We have finally arrived to the main bulk of our coverage on the French, and our very last topic to cover for Part 1! This is the Winawer Variation, named after Szymon Winawer and popularized later in the 1940s by the greats Nimzowitch and Botvinnik. Black pins the knight and thus attacks the pawn on e4 so we're forced to make a decision in the center. }
4. e5
{ This is by far the most challenging move against the Winawer. We're gaining additional space while we're also limiting Black's knight on g8 as it can no longer jump to f6. }
4... c5
{ Black's main move challenges our center immediately, a necessary course of action to obtain the desired counterplay on the queenside. }
5. a3
{ By far the most played move as this is the only way to maintain the strong pawn chain. }
5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Ne7 7. h4 Nbc6
{ The old move, given as an alternative option by Giri. } 8. h5 Qa5 9. Bd2 Qa4
{ Should be met by   9...cxd4  This move has been tried from this move order as well, when we should transpose to the previous chapter after  10.cxd4  Qa4  11.c3  Qxd1+  12.Rxd1±  Black has to play 12... h6, when we saw that the resulting ending is very decent for us. }
10. Rb1
{ When Black has nothing better than transposing to the previous chapter with  10...h6  11.Qc1  . In case Black tries }
10... a6 { We can punish him with } 11. h6
{ When Black is in trouble on the dark squares. } 11... gxh6 12. Nf3
{ White has scored 7.5/8 from this position! } 12... cxd4 13. cxd4 Nxd4
{ Gives Black a pawn, but after } 14. Bd3
{ Our play far surpasses the extra pawn, with two model games being Van Assche,J -Trasciatti,M ICCF email 2017, and Linnichenko, M - Kurbasov,S ICCF email 2015. }
