[Black "7...Nbc6 (8...Qa5 9...Bd7)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ We have finally arrived to the main bulk of our coverage on the French, and our very last topic to cover for Part 1! This is the Winawer Variation, named after Szymon Winawer and popularized later in the 1940s by the greats Nimzowitch and Botvinnik. Black pins the knight and thus attacks the pawn on e4 so we're forced to make a decision in the center. }
4. e5
{ This is by far the most challenging move against the Winawer. We're gaining additional space while we're also limiting Black's knight on g8 as it can no longer jump to f6. }
4... c5
{ Black's main move challenges our center immediately, a necessary course of action to obtain the desired counterplay on the queenside. }
5. a3
{ By far the most played move as this is the only way to maintain the strong pawn chain. }
5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Ne7 7. h4 Nbc6
{ The old move, given as an alternative option by Giri. } 8. h5 Qa5 9. Bd2 Bd7
{ Has been Black's most popular move, with the intention of castling queenside as soon as possible.   9...cxd4  This move has been tried from this move order as well, when we should transpose to the previous chapter after  10.cxd4  Qa4  11.c3  Qxd1+  12.Rxd1±  Black has to play  12...h6  , when we saw that the resulting ending is very decent for us. }
10. h6 { Our pawn keeps marching, according to plan! } 10... gxh6
{ 10...g6?  Is more or less suicidal, with the cleanest refutation being  11.Rb1  Hitting b7 and threatening Rb5.  11...O-O-O  12.Rb5  Qxa3  13.Rxc5+-  Black is completely lost as the queen on  a3  is in big trouble.  13...a6  , attempting to trap our rook, can be met by  14.Qb1  . If Black maintains the threat of  b6  with  14...Kc7  , we have  15.c4  when our rook escapes. }
11. Rb1 { Is once again a very strong move, with Rxb7 and Rb5 in mind. } 11...
Qc7
{ The retreat with the queen is possible, but what has Black gained from allowing h6? In the Giri-variation Black did at least trade bishops. }
12. Nf3 O-O-O 13. Bxh6
{ Our bishops grabs the pawn and will soon find a home on f6 via g5. } 13...
cxd4 14. cxd4 Nf5 15. Bg5
{ Not  15.Bf4?  when Black had equalized after the blow  15...Ncxd4  16.Nxd4  Qc3+  in Alvir, A - Bachofner, A Austria 2001. A trick to watch out for! }
15... Rde8 16. g4 Ncxd4
{ The best practical attempt, as  16...Nfe7  17.Bf6  Rhg8  18.Ng5  is hopeless. }
17. Nxd4 Qc3+ 18. Qd2 Qxd2+ 19. Kxd2 Nxd4
{ Black has won a pawn, a consolation prize for the awful position. } 20. Bf6
Rhg8 21. c3 Nc6 22. g5 { DOMINATION! } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "25. French Defense (1...e6) Winawer Old Mainlines"]
[Black "7...Nbc6 (8...Qa5 9...Bd7 2)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ We have finally arrived to the main bulk of our coverage on the French, and our very last topic to cover for Part 1! This is the Winawer Variation, named after Szymon Winawer and popularized later in the 1940s by the greats Nimzowitch and Botvinnik. Black pins the knight and thus attacks the pawn on e4 so we're forced to make a decision in the center. }
4. e5
{ This is by far the most challenging move against the Winawer. We're gaining additional space while we're also limiting Black's knight on g8 as it can no longer jump to f6. }
4... c5
{ Black's main move challenges our center immediately, a necessary course of action to obtain the desired counterplay on the queenside. }
5. a3
{ By far the most played move as this is the only way to maintain the strong pawn chain. }
5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Ne7 7. h4 Nbc6
{ The old move, given as an alternative option by Giri. } 8. h5 Qa5 9. Bd2 Bd7
{ Has been Black's most popular move, with the intention of castling queenside as soon as possible. }
10. h6 { Our pawn keeps marching, according to plan! } 10... gxh6 11. Rb1
{ Is once again a very strong move, with Rxb7 and Rb5 in mind. } 11... O-O-O
12. Rb5
{ Black has to make an important decision on where to place the queen. } 12...
Qxa3
{ Was tried by the strong Swedish GM, Tiger Hillarp back in 2009.   12...Qc7  Looks pretty bad after  13.Rxc5  a6  14.Qb1!   A strong move, making sure that  14...Kb8  is met by  15.Bxa6  so Black can't trap our rook.  14...Rdg8  15.a4+-  Our rook stands firm on c5 as a5 is soon coming. We'll then proceed with Nf3 and c4, with a crushing advantage. }
13. Rxc5 a6
{ Tiger plays concretely and tries trapping White's rook. A natural way to proceed, but it doesn't hold up as White's initiative is too strong. }
14. Qb1 { An important move, making sure b6 can't be played. } 14... Kc7 15. c4
{ The Italian plays excellently. You may notice that the position resembles a lot the position in the 10... g6-line, with the only difference being that the pawn is on h6 here. }
15... b6 { White's rook is trapped, but Black's king is too weak after } 16.
cxd5 bxc5 17. d6+ Kc8 18. Rh3
{ Black is barely holding everything together, but it won't last. I'll show Tiger's game as it ended in a beautiful checkmate, but this is an appropriate stop to the trainable.  18...Qa4  19.Rb3  Nd5  20.dxc5  Rdg8  Black's rook is one move to slow... If it was Black to move in this very moment, Rg4 would have been winning. The nuances in chess!  21.c4  The knight perishes.  21...Nde7  22.Ne2  But White doesn't take it!  22...Qxc4  23.Nc3  Qxc5  24.Ne4  Qxe5  Black has regained some pawns, but it matters little as he's mated by force.  25.dxe7  Nxe7  26.Rb8+!  A sweet combination.  26...Qxb8  27.Bxa6+  Kc7  28.Ba5+  Kc6  29.Qc2+  Kd5  30.Qd3+  Ke5  31.Bc3+  Kf5  32.Nd6  Kg5  33.Qg3+  Kh5  34.Be2+  Rg4  35.Qxg4#  Mate was on the board in Vocaturo,D -Hillarp Persson,T Reykjavik 2009. A truly fantastic game by the Italian, who's now a strong GM rated above 2600. }
