[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "25. French Defense (1...e6) Winawer Old Mainlines"]
[Black "7...Nbc6 (8...Qa5 9...Bd7 3)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ We have finally arrived to the main bulk of our coverage on the French, and our very last topic to cover for Part 1! This is the Winawer Variation, named after Szymon Winawer and popularized later in the 1940s by the greats Nimzowitch and Botvinnik. Black pins the knight and thus attacks the pawn on e4 so we're forced to make a decision in the center. }
4. e5
{ This is by far the most challenging move against the Winawer. We're gaining additional space while we're also limiting Black's knight on g8 as it can no longer jump to f6. }
4... c5
{ Black's main move challenges our center immediately, a necessary course of action to obtain the desired counterplay on the queenside. }
5. a3
{ By far the most played move as this is the only way to maintain the strong pawn chain. }
5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Ne7 7. h4 Nbc6
{ The old move, given as an alternative option by Giri. } 8. h5 Qa5 9. Bd2 Bd7
{ Has been Black's most popular move, with the intention of castling queenside as soon as possible. }
10. h6 { Our pawn keeps marching, according to plan! } 10... gxh6 11. Rb1
{ Is once again a very strong move, with Rxb7 and Rb5 in mind. } 11... O-O-O
12. Rb5
{ Black has to make an important decision on where to place the queen. } 12...
Qa4 { Is Black's best move, with a pretty sneaky idea in mind. } 13. Qb1
{ Applying pressure on the b7-pawn, forcing the knight to move from  c6  so we can capture on  c5  with check.  13.Rxc5?  falls into Black's trap after  13...b6  14.Rb5  Nxd4  . }
13... Na5
{ 13...Nxd4?  Has lead to three draws in my base, but it looks like a very speculative sacrifice.  14.cxd4  Bxb5  15.Bxb5  Qxd4  16.Nf3  Black has currently three pawns extra, but our minor pieces work incredibly well together.  16...Qg4  17.Rh2  17. Kf1 is just as strong.  17...Nf5  18.Be2  With several discovery attacks in mind, the queen has to move again.  18...Qa4  And now I think  19.Qb3  Qxb3  20.cxb3+-  Is winning for us, as I don't think Black's rooks and pawns can match our minor pieces. Bd3 is coming soon, followed by a capture on f5 and h6. Black's pawns will fall like pears. }
14. Rxc5+ Kb8 15. Rxh6
{ The rook is headed to f6 in order to harass the pawn on f7.   I don't get  15.Rh3  which was Morozevich, A - Lputian, S Sochi 2007, when Black should have played  15...Nc4  when White probably loses the exchange. The game remains even, however. }
15... b6
{ Our rook is vulnerable on c5, but it's harder than what it looks to trap it.   15...Nc4  Wouldn't be so effective any longer, due to  16.Bxc4  dxc4  17.Bg5  When we'll be able to regain control over the d5-square by capturing the knight.  17...Rde8  18.Bxe7  Rxe7  19.Ne2  b6  And now we see the point with Bxe7 after  20.d5  As our rook on c5 is liberated after  20...Be8  21.d6  Rb7  22.Rc7  Rxc7  23.dxc7+  Kxc7  24.Qc1±  Our active pieces give us a clearly better game. }
16. Bg5 { Harassing Black's knight. } 16... Ka8
{ Our rook is now under attack, but there's an extra square on c7!   16...Rde8  Is met by the pretty  17.Rb5!  When the rook escapes. The game may continue  17...Nf5  18.Rb4  Qc6   18...Qxa3  is met by the same idea,  19.Rh3  .  19.Rh3!  Otherwise c3 falls.  19...Rhg8  20.Qc1+-  We have everything under control with a healthy pawn up.   16...Nb7  17.Bxe7   The same resource as in the previous note,  17.Rb5  , was also strong. I think this is a tad simpler, though.  17...bxc5  18.Bxd8  Rxd8  19.Ne2  Black hasn't achieved anything with the rook-hunting. We have managed to neutralize Black's counterplay by trading some pieces. Remember that we have a pawn up!  19...Qxa3  20.Rxh7  Rf8  And now we should start taking terrain on the kingside with  21.f4  Ka8  22.g4+-  When our extra pawn gives us an overwhelming advantage. }
17. Rc7 Rde8 18. g4 { Our pawn makes sure that Black can't jump to f5. } 18...
Kb8 { Black succeeds in winning the exchange, but for a heavy prize. } 19. Rxd7
Qxd7 20. Bb5 Nac6
{ Black has an extremely passive position and can't really make use of the extra rook. }
21. Qd1 Rc8 22. Ne2 Rhg8 23. f4
{ Our minor pieces are a lot stronger than Black's rooks. The pawn on h7 will fall, when we'll have two pawns for the exchange. Black is too passive... }
