[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ We have finally arrived to the main bulk of our coverage on the French, and our very last topic to cover for Part 1! This is the Winawer Variation, named after Szymon Winawer and popularized later in the 1940s by the greats Nimzowitch and Botvinnik. Black pins the knight and thus attacks the pawn on e4 so we're forced to make a decision in the center. }
4. e5
{ This is by far the most challenging move against the Winawer. We're gaining additional space while we're also limiting Black's knight on g8 as it can no longer jump to f6. }
4... c5
{ Black's main move challenges our center immediately, a necessary course of action to obtain the desired counterplay on the queenside. }
5. a3
{ By far the most played move as this is the only way to maintain the strong pawn chain. }
5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Ne7 7. h4 Nbc6
{ The old move, given as an alternative option by Giri. } 8. h5 Qa5 9. Bd2 Bd7
{ Has been Black's most popular move, with the intention of castling queenside as soon as possible. }
10. h6 { Our pawn keeps marching, according to plan! } 10... gxh6 11. Rb1
{ Is once again a very strong move, with Rxb7 and Rb5 in mind. } 11... O-O-O
12. Rb5
{ Black has to make an important decision on where to place the queen. } 12...
Qa4 { Is Black's best move, with a pretty sneaky idea in mind. } 13. Qb1
{ Applying pressure on the b7-pawn, forcing the knight to move from c6 so we can capture on c5 with check.   13.Rxc5?  falls into Black's trap after  13...b6  14.Rb5  Nxd4  . }
13... Na5
{ 13...Nxd4?  Has lead to three draws in my base, but it looks like a very speculative sacrifice.  14.cxd4  Bxb5  15.Bxb5  Qxd4  16.Nf3  Black has currently three pawns extra, but our minor pieces work incredibly well together.  16...Qg4  17.Rh2  Nf5  18.Be2  With several discovery attacks in mind, the queen has to move again.  18...Qa4  And now I think  19.Qb3  Qxb3  20.cxb3+-  Is winning for us, as I don't think Black's rooks and pawns can match our minor pieces. Bd3 is coming soon, followed by a capture on f5 and h6. Black's pawns will fall like pears. }
14. Rxc5+ Kb8 15. Rxh6
{ The rook is headed to f6 in order to harass the pawn on f7.   I don't get  15.Rh3  which was Morozevich, A - Lputian, S Sochi 2007, when Black should have played  15...Nc4  when White probably loses the exchange. The game remains even, however. }
15... Rdg8
{ This move is Black's best try. The subtle point behind it is that it stops Bg5, making Nc4 a lot more effective. }
16. Rf6 { We need to maintain the pressure. } 16... Be8 17. Nh3
{ The knight is flexible on h3 where it can move to g5 or f4. } 17... Nc4 18.
Bxc4 dxc4 19. Nf4 { Stopping Rxg2 while preparing d5. } 19... b6 20. Be3
{ There's a storm coming with d5, when everything could very quickly fall apart for Black.. . }
20... Nc6
{ The only defense, intending to play Nd8 when e6 will be under protection. }
21. d5 { And now the following line is forced: } 21... Nd8 22. dxe6 fxe6 23.
Nxe6 Rxg2
{ An incredibly important intermezzo.  23...Nxe6  24.Rxe6  is hopeless due to the threat of  Rxb6+  , for instance. }
24. Kd2
{ Black forces our king to this unfortunate square where it blocks the d-file and a potential infiltration with the queen. }
24... Nxe6 25. Rxe6 Rg6 26. Rf6 Rxf6 27. exf6
{ White was pressing for victory in Rasmussen,E -Koehl,R ICCF email 2019, but the defense was too hard to break in the end. }
