[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "25. French Defense (1...e6) Winawer Old Mainlines"]
[Black "Giri's 7...Qc7 (8...O-O)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ We have finally arrived to the main bulk of our coverage on the French, and our very last topic to cover for Part 1! This is the Winawer Variation, named after Szymon Winawer and popularized later in the 1940s by the greats Nimzowitch and Botvinnik. Black pins the knight and thus attacks the pawn on e4 so we're forced to make a decision in the center. }
4. e5
{ This is by far the most challenging move against the Winawer. We're gaining additional space while we're also limiting Black's knight on g8 as it can no longer jump to f6. }
4... c5
{ Black's main move challenges our center immediately, a necessary course of action to obtain the desired counterplay on the queenside. }
5. a3
{ By far the most played move as this is the only way to maintain the strong pawn chain. }
5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Ne7 7. h4 Qc7
{ This move is rather new, played by Nepo in the Candidates 2020 and advocated by the French-guru Anish Giri in his Chessable Course. The reason for this arising trend is the fact that the engines prefer it over the plans with Qa5. }
8. Rb1
{ There are many interesting possibilities in this position like for example  8.h5  h6  9.Rh3!?  , but I decided to follow the footsteps of the world's best players.  8.Rb1  moves the rook to the open b-file where it controls a lot of squares, but more importantly,  Qg4  is on the table as the rook will no longer hang on  a1  . The standard move order has usually been  8.h5  , but this allows an extra possibility in  8...cxd4  for Black. After  9.cxd4  Qc3+  10.Bd2  Qxd4  11.Nf3  Qe4+  12.Be2  Nf5  13.Kf1  White has the upper hand, but the game remains complicated. }
8... O-O
{ Castling short is a move Black won't consider in case he has studied Giri's course, as he regularly points out that the dangers of doing so.   8...b6  Has been Black's most common reply, when we transpose to the Nepo Variation after  9.h5 }
9. Bd3 Nbc6
{ Black's best practical attempt is to press our d4-pawn.   9...f6  Is a logical attempt to neutralize our attack. We should meet it with  10.exf6  Rxf6  11.Qh5  Nf5   Necessary, as  11...h6  would lose to  12.Qe8+  followed by  Bh7+  .  12.Nh3!  A strong move, intending Ng5 or Bf4.  12...Nc6   12...cxd4  is also met by  13.g4  .  13.g4  c4  14.Bxf5  Black is struggling immensely on the dark squares after  14...exf5  15.g5  Qf7  16.Qxf7+  Rxf7  17.Nf4+-  Black's awful coordination grants him a dead lost endgame.   9...c4?  This move is tactically flawed due to  10.Bxh7+!  The Greek Gift delivers once again.  10...Kxh7  11.Qh5+  Kg8  12.Nf3  Black doesn't have adequate defense to deal with the massacre on the kingside.  12...f6  Is Black's best try, refuted by the beauty  13.Ng5!  Another piece is sacrificed, but the open h-file is lethal for Black.  13...fxg5  14.hxg5  Nbc6  Black couldn't do anything about g6 anyway.  15.g6  Nxg6  16.Qxg6  Nxe5!  A very clever defense, intending Qxe5+ followed by Qf5 when our attack is stopped.  17.Qh7+  Kf7  18.Bh6  We should ignore the hanging knight for now.  18...Ke8   18...Rg8  is met by  19.Rh3  , with  Rg3  to follow. White wins.  19.Bxg7+-  We will win the rook on f8. The queens will be traded, when our rooks are much stronger than Black's pieces. }
10. Qh5 Ng6
{ This time the black knight has to head to g6, as   10...Nf5  loses to  11.g4  c4  12.gxf5  cxd3  13.f6  , with mate to come. }
11. Be3 { Keeping an eye on the pawn on d4. } 11... Qa5 12. Bd2
{ I managed to make  12.Nf3  work as well, but the text is much simpler. }
12... c4 13. Bxg6 { 13.Be2  allows  13...f6  , when Black is fine. } 13... fxg6
{ 13...hxg6?  is suicidal after  14.Qg4  , with  h5  coming. } 14. Qg4 Qa4 15.
Rc1
{ Our attack is decisive with  h5  coming next. Black can delay this advance with  15...Rf5  , but after  16.Qh3  , g4-h5 will follow suit with deadly effect. }
