[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ We have finally arrived to the main bulk of our coverage on the French, and our very last topic to cover for Part 1! This is the Winawer Variation, named after Szymon Winawer and popularized later in the 1940s by the greats Nimzowitch and Botvinnik. Black pins the knight and thus attacks the pawn on e4 so we're forced to make a decision in the center. }
4. e5
{ This is by far the most challenging move against the Winawer. We're gaining additional space while we're also limiting Black's knight on g8 as it can no longer jump to f6. }
4... c5
{ Black's main move challenges our center immediately, a necessary course of action to obtain the desired counterplay on the queenside. }
5. a3
{ By far the most played move as this is the only way to maintain the strong pawn chain. }
5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Ne7 7. h4 Qc7
{ This move is rather new, played by Nepo in the Candidates 2020 and advocated by the French-guru Anish Giri in his Chessable Course. The reason for this arising trend is the fact that the engines prefer it over the plans with Qa5. }
8. Rb1 Bd7 { Is a thematic way to play, but it's the wrong timing. } 9. h5
{ Our usual scheme. } 9... Ba4
{ Was played in Aldama Degurnay,D - Sevillano,E Monterey Park 2013, when we should stick to our plan and keep advancing with }
10. h6 cxd4
{ Black should probably bite the bullet with  10...gxh6  , when we have an excellent game after  11.Bd3  . However, the text is trickier. }
11. Rb4
{ Chasing the bishop away from a4 is the refutation, with the idea of playing cxd4 next. }
11... Qxc3+ 12. Bd2 Bxc2
{ A lot of trades will follow, but the exchanges favor us. } 13. hxg7 Rg8 14.
Bxc3 Bxd1 15. Bxd4 Nbc6
{ 15...Bc2  is also very good for us after  16.Rxb7  Nbc6  17.Bc5  . } 16. Kxd1
Nxb4 17. axb4 Rxg7 18. Bc3
{ A strong move, stopping a5. This is rather crucial to stop, as Black's rook could become very active in the open file. Black has to fight tooth and nail for a draw in the ensuing ending, as the bishop pair could very quickly outperform Black's rooks. }
