[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "25. French Defense (1...e6) Winawer Old Mainlines"]
[Black "Giri's 7...Qc7 (8...Bd7 2)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ We have finally arrived to the main bulk of our coverage on the French, and our very last topic to cover for Part 1! This is the Winawer Variation, named after Szymon Winawer and popularized later in the 1940s by the greats Nimzowitch and Botvinnik. Black pins the knight and thus attacks the pawn on e4 so we're forced to make a decision in the center. }
4. e5
{ This is by far the most challenging move against the Winawer. We're gaining additional space while we're also limiting Black's knight on g8 as it can no longer jump to f6. }
4... c5
{ Black's main move challenges our center immediately, a necessary course of action to obtain the desired counterplay on the queenside. }
5. a3
{ By far the most played move as this is the only way to maintain the strong pawn chain. }
5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Ne7 7. h4 Qc7
{ This move is rather new, played by Nepo in the Candidates 2020 and advocated by the French-guru Anish Giri in his Chessable Course. The reason for this arising trend is the fact that the engines prefer it over the plans with Qa5. }
8. Rb1 Bd7 { Is a thematic way to play, but it's the wrong timing. } 9. h5
{ Our usual scheme. } 9... h6 10. Qg4
{ Black doesn't have any decent ways of guarding the pawn on  g7  . Giri's amazing idea with  10...Rg8  would not work at all here, as we have  11.Bd3  followed by  Bh7  , when there's no capture on  e5! }
10... Nbc6
{ Black aims to castle queenside, but our kingside initiative is too powerful...   10...Ba4?  One game in my base proceeded like this, when Black has far from enough compensation for the pawn after  11.Qxg7  Rg8  12.Qxh6  cxd4   12...Bxc2  is met by  13.Rb2  Bf5  14.Ne2  , with  f3  and  g4  next.  13.Bd3!  It's essential that we defend the pawn on c2.  13...Qxe5+  14.Ne2  Nd7  15.Bf4  With a completely winning ending after  15...Qh8  16.Qxh8  Rxh8  17.cxd4+-  Due to our incredible pair of bishops and passer on h5.   10...cxd4  Isn't adequate for Black either after  11.Qxg7  Rg8  12.Qxh6  Nf5?   Is an error.  12...Qxe5+  is better, with a really pleasant endgame after  13.Ne2  dxc3  14.Qe3  Qxe3  15.Bxe3  .  13.Qf4  Qxc3+  Was Shevchenko,K - Nikologorskiy,K Chess.com INT 2020, when  14.Qd2+-  Is important, as the c2-pawn must be guarded. White is winning as the h-pawn marches up the board with deadly effect. When h7 is achieved, Qxc3 followed by Bg5 is an idea to keep in mind with Bf6 to come. }
11. Qxg7 O-O-O 12. Qf6 { Our queen shouldn't linger in the enemy territory... }
12... Qa5
{ Black's most testing option.  12...cxd4  should be met by  13.Nf3  dxc3  14.Bxh6  . }
13. Ne2 cxd4 14. Bd2
{ Black regains a pawn, but the opening of the queenside gives us a decisive edge. }
14... dxc3 15. Nxc3 { The knight is heading to the juicy square on d6 via b5. }
15... Qc7 { And now a forced line goes } 16. Nb5 Qxe5+ 17. Qxe5 Nxe5 18. Nd6+
Kc7 19. Nxb7 { Black's king is too weak. } 19... Rb8
{ And now the only move that wins is } 20. Ba5+
{ An essential move, as it takes away the c6-square for Black's knight on e7. }
20... Kc6 21. Bc3 Rxb7
{ Black neutralizes our play on the queenside, but is still lost after } 22.
Rxb7 Kxb7 23. Bxe5
{ White is just winning because of the monster on e5 and our champion pawn on h5.   A thematic line is  23...Rg8  24.f3  Nc6  25.Bf6  , when White breaks through with g4-g5. }
