[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "25. French Defense (1...e6) Winawer Old Mainlines"]
[Black "Giri's 7...Qc7 (8...Nbc6)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ We have finally arrived to the main bulk of our coverage on the French, and our very last topic to cover for Part 1! This is the Winawer Variation, named after Szymon Winawer and popularized later in the 1940s by the greats Nimzowitch and Botvinnik. Black pins the knight and thus attacks the pawn on e4 so we're forced to make a decision in the center. }
4. e5
{ This is by far the most challenging move against the Winawer. We're gaining additional space while we're also limiting Black's knight on g8 as it can no longer jump to f6. }
4... c5
{ Black's main move challenges our center immediately, a necessary course of action to obtain the desired counterplay on the queenside. }
5. a3
{ By far the most played move as this is the only way to maintain the strong pawn chain. }
5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Ne7 7. h4 Qc7
{ This move is rather new, played by Nepo in the Candidates 2020 and advocated by the French-guru Anish Giri in his Chessable Course. The reason for this arising trend is the fact that the engines prefer it over the plans with Qa5. }
8. Rb1 Nbc6
{ This move looks very natural indeed, but there's a lot more to it than what initially meets the eye... The alternative option is Nepo's  8...b6  , which is the last thing we'll cover in this course! Giri explains that he feels that his choice is more reliable than Nepo's in the long run. I'll take his word for it... }
9. h5 { There's no reason for us to avoid including h5-h6. } 9... h6 10. Nf3
{ This might be surprising to the reader, as  8.Rb1  was played in order to prepare  Qg4  . Giri's incredible idea is shown after  10.Qg4  Rg8  11.Bd3  c4  12.Bh7  Nxe5!  , when Black's point is that our bishop on  h7  is trapped after  13.dxe5  Qxe5+  14.Kd2  Rh8  or   13.Qg3  Nd3+!  14.cxd3  Qxg3  15.fxg3  Rh8  with an equal game after  16.Be4  dxe4  17.dxe4  . }
10... c4
{ Giri's suggestion is to close the position at once.  10...Bd7  has been more common, and covered in the next chapter. }
11. Bf4
{ Our bishop develops to f4 so we can take control of the c1-h6 diagonal with Qc1. This makes the f6-break harder for Black to achieve, as the h6-pawn often ends up hanging. Another benefit is that it helps us prepare the break g4-g5, which Black won't be able to stop with f6 due to the aforementioned hanging pawn on h6. }
11... Qa5
{ A typical plan we must consider. I have chosen to label the alternative,  11...Bd7  , as 'The Flexible Giri, ' as this was Giri's suggestion when I interacted with him on twitter after the release of 'Destroy the French' on chess24! This is covered in the succeeding chapter. }
12. Qc1 { We must guard our queenside pawns. } 12... b6
{ 12...Bd7?  fails to  13.Rxb7  , so Black must play this move before continuing with the queenside development. }
13. Be2 Bd7 14. Qb2
{ This is my improvement over my suggestion  14.Kf1  on chess24, with the intention of placing the king on  d2  in the instead!  I think this is a much better placement for our king, as it allows us to coordinate a lot easier on the kingside. It also 'threatens' to play a4, as Black can't take the pawn due to Ra1. }
14... O-O-O { Let's see what happens if Black allows us to play a4. } 15. a4
{ Our position has improved with a4 on the board as it allows us to place our queen on the improved square on a3. The arising position is very pleasant and fairly easy to play for us, with the plan of playing Be3-Nh4-g4-f4 and break through on the kingside. }
15... Rhf8 { A logical reaction, Black wants to play f6 some day. } 16. Qa3 Kb7
17. g4 { Our pawn storm commences. } 17... Ka8
{ For the sake of being instructive, let's see what to do in case Black refrains from breaks in the center.   17...f6  Is not the right time for Black to play this break, as we're well prepared.  18.exf6  Rxf6  19.Bg3+-  Black has only helped us by opening up the position.   17...Ng8  Black aims to capture on f6 with the knight.  18.O-O !  Another advantage with waiting with the king move. In this particular case, Black is too passive to cause problems for us on the kingside. Bg3-Nh4-f4 comes really quickly, when we'll be dominating.  18...g5   Black needs to do something.  18...f6  is easily met by  19.Bg3  .  19.hxg6  fxg6  20.Be3±  Black's position is really tough to play. Our idea is rather simple with slow-improving moves like f3-Nh4-Ng2, etc. Some day we'll play f4. Also, remember to defend the pawn on a4 with Ra1 in case Black moves the knight from c6. }
18. Be3 { This move prepares Nh4, as Nh4 right away drops the pawn on d4! }
18... Rb8
{ Black could throw in this move, with the intention of playing b5. This can always be met by }
19. Ra1 { And b5 is no longer anything to worry about. } 19... Rbe8 20. Nh4
{ The position plays itself: f4-Kd2-Rhg1-Raf1 and then f5/g5 at the right time. }
*

