[Round "?"]
[White "25. French Defense (1...e6) Winawer Old Mainlines"]
[Black "Giri's 7...Qc7 (8...Nbc6 2)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ We have finally arrived to the main bulk of our coverage on the French, and our very last topic to cover for Part 1! This is the Winawer Variation, named after Szymon Winawer and popularized later in the 1940s by the greats Nimzowitch and Botvinnik. Black pins the knight and thus attacks the pawn on e4 so we're forced to make a decision in the center. }
4. e5
{ This is by far the most challenging move against the Winawer. We're gaining additional space while we're also limiting Black's knight on g8 as it can no longer jump to f6. }
4... c5
{ Black's main move challenges our center immediately, a necessary course of action to obtain the desired counterplay on the queenside. }
5. a3
{ By far the most played move as this is the only way to maintain the strong pawn chain. }
5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Ne7 7. h4 Qc7
{ This move is rather new, played by Nepo in the Candidates 2020 and advocated by the French-guru Anish Giri in his Chessable Course. The reason for this arising trend is the fact that the engines prefer it over the plans with Qa5. }
8. Rb1 Nbc6
{ This move looks very natural indeed, but there's a lot more to it than what initially meets the eye... The alternative option is Nepo's 8... b6, which is the last thing we'll cover in this course! Giri explains that he feels that his choice is more reliable than Nepo's in the long run. I'll take his word for it... }
9. h5 { There's no reason for us to avoid including h5-h6. } 9... h6 10. Nf3 c4
{ Giri's suggestion is to close the position at once.  10...Bd7  has been more common, and covered in the next chapter. }
11. Bf4
{ Our bishop develops to f4 so we can take control of the c1-h6 diagonal with Qc1. This makes the f6-break harder for Black to achieve, as the h6-pawn often ends up hanging. Another benefit is that it helps us prepare the break g4-g5, which Black won't be able to stop with f6 due to the aforementioned hanging pawn on h6. }
11... Qa5 12. Qc1 { We must guard our queenside pawns. } 12... b6
{ 12...Bd7?  fails to  13.Rxb7  , so Black must play this move before continuing with the queenside development. }
13. Be2 Bd7 14. Qb2
{ This is my improvement over my suggestion  14.Kf1  on chess24, with the intention of placing the king on  d2  in the instead!  I think this is a much better placement for our king, as it allows us to coordinate a lot easier on the kingside. It also 'threatens' to play a4, as Black can't take the pawn due to Ra1. }
14... Qa4 { Black can't allow a4. } 15. Nh4
{ Our plan is rather similar to the one we saw under  14...O-O-O  . g4-Be3-Kd2-f4 and break through on the kingside! }
15... Nf5
{ This move is given by the engine, but it looks very unnatural to me.   15...a6!?  Is a highly interesting idea, intending to place the knight on b5 with decent queenside counterplay.  16.Kd2!  This move is strong as it coordinates our rooks and protects the pawn on c3.  16...Na7  Black has to stick with the plan.  17.Qb4!  It's best to head for an endgame, as Black's counterplay with Nb5+Qa4 is rather annoying.  17...Qxb4   17...Qc6  is met by  18.g4  with  g5  coming, so Black doesn't really have a choice.  18.Rxb4  Nb5   Black's best choice.  18...b5  is met by  19.g4  , when we get a nice initiative on the kingside. Black doesn't have much on the queenside.  19.Ra1  a5  20.Rb2  a4  Black blocks the queenside and maintains the annoying knight on b5.  21.Nf3±  Our knight is on its way to g4 via h2. From there it could head to e3 or f6 depending on what Black does. If Black does nothing, it will head to e3 followed by g4-g5. I am pretty sure that Black will have to play g5 at some point, when we'll get a nice square on f6. It's not going to be easy to break through, but the position bears no risk for us. A satisfying end to the opening, that's for sure. }
16. Nxf5 exf5 17. Bf3 Qa5
{ 17...Be6  allows  18.Qb5  when we're much better in the ending. } 18. O-O O-O
19. Ra1
{ We're playing for a4 so we can open the a3-f8 diagonal. Black also has to worry about Qb5 which could be lethal in some lines. This looks like pure misery if you ask me. }
19... Be6 20. a4
{ Qb5 is now a threat, as we will quickly break through on the queenside without the queens. Rfb1-Bc1-Ba3-Bd6-Rb5. Simple! }
20... Rac8 { Black stops our idea, as Qb5 drops the c3-pawn. } 21. Rfb1
{ Black's position is probably defendable for an engine, but I can't imagine that a human being will be able to survive in the long run. Black has pretty much no plans, so he has to wait for us to do something significant. We will slowly improve our pieces. One particularly cool plan is to play Qa3 to provoke a6, and then shuffle with Qc1-Qe1-Bc1-Ba3. We have all the time in the world... }
