11... Qa5 12. Qc1 { We must guard our queenside pawns. } 12... b6
{ 12... Bd7? fails to 13. Rxb7, so Black must play this move before continuing with the queenside development. }
13. Be2 Bd7 14. Qb2
{ This is my improvement over my suggestion  14.Kf1  on chess24, with the intention of placing the king on  d2  in the instead!  I think this is a much better placement for our king, as it allows us to coordinate a lot easier on the kingside. It also 'threatens' to play a4, as Black can't take the pawn due to Ra1. }
14... Qa4 { Black can't allow a4. } 15. Nh4
{ Our plan is rather similar to the one we saw under 14... O-O-O. g4-Be3-Kd2-f4 and break through on the kingside! }
15... f6 16. exf6 gxf6 17. O-O
{ Simple development! Black is miles away from achieving any sort of attack! }
17... O-O-O 18. Rbe1
{ Our rook moves to the open e-file and presses Black's e6-pawn. } 18... e5
{ Black should advance before it's too late. } 19. Bh2 Rhg8
{ 19...e4?  is thematic, but here it's just bad after  20.f3  f5  21.fxe4  dxe4  22.d5  and Black has to take.  22...Nxd5  23.Nxf5  and White is winning. }
20. Qc1
{ Our queen targets the h6-pawn, but also intends to move to e3 where it will target the e5-pawn. Bd1 could be played as well to increase the pressure on e5.   I think Black is in big trouble here. Note that we meet  20...Qa5  with  21.Qe3  , as we can't allow Black to take on  c3! }
