11... Qa5 12. Qc1 { We must guard our queenside pawns. } 12... b6
{ 12...Bd7?  fails to  13.Rxb7  , so Black must play this move before continuing with the queenside development. }
13. Be2 Bd7 14. Qb2
{ This is my improvement over my suggestion  14.Kf1  on chess24, with the intention of placing the king on  d2  in the instead!  I think this is a much better placement for our king, as it allows us to coordinate a lot easier on the kingside. It also 'threatens' to play a4, as Black can't take the pawn due to Ra1. }
14... Qa4 { Black can't allow a4. } 15. Nh4
{ Our plan is rather similar to the one we saw under  14...O-O-O  . g4-Be3-Kd2-f4 and break through on the kingside! }
15... O-O-O 16. Be3
{ This move aligns with our plan on the kingside, while it also makes g5 less effective. }
16... g5
{ Black needs to do something before we're able to execute on plan.   16...f6  Should be met by  17.f4  f5  Is a standard idea by Black in these positions, intending to follow up with Rdg8 and g5 at a later stage.  18.g4  We should open the g-file at once to avoid Black's plan.  18...fxg4  19.Bxg4  Rhg8  Black aims to open the position with g6.  20.Kd2  g6  21.Rbg1  gxh5  22.Bxh5  Black has opened the g-file, but is still rather cramped.  22...Rdf8  Black should prevent Bf7 which would give us free g-file access.  23.Rxg8  Rxg8  24.Bf3±  We maintain a powerful pressure on Black's position, with the idea of striking with  f5  at some point followed by Ng2-Nf4.  24...Nd8  is one way to meet this idea, with the point of going exf and  Ne6  . In that case, I'd suggest  25.Qb4  with a clearly better endgame. }
17. hxg6 fxg6 18. Nf3
{ Our knight heads back, where it can eventually reach f6 via h2-g4.   I analyzed  18.g4  , but to my disappointment, I discovered that Black's position is really difficult to break after  18...Rh7  19.Kd2  Rdh8  20.Rh3  Be8  21.Rbh1  Nd8  22.Ng2  Nf7  . }
18... Nf5
{ I don't like  18...h5  which weakens the dark squares to a horrible extent.   18...g5  isn't too impressive either, when I suggest  19.Nh2  with  Ng4  to come. }
19. Kd2
{ Our king coordinates our rooks with the intention of doubling in the h-file. }
19... g5 20. g4 Nxe3 21. fxe3 Rdg8
{ Is the only move that avoids a lost position. Black's point is to play Be8 followed by a quick h5.   21...Be8  right away would fail to  22.Nxg5  . }
22. Nh2
{ Our knight is headed to g3, while our b-rook is going to f1. Black is under a lot of pressure. Note that we should more often than not head into an ending with Qb4 in case Black goes Ne7. }
