{ This move looks very natural indeed, but there's a lot more to it than what initially meets the eye... The alternative option is Nepo's  8...b6  , which is the last thing we'll cover in this course! }
9. h5 { There's no reason for us to avoid including h5-h6. } 9... h6 10. Nf3
Bd7 { This has pretty much always been played in this position. } 11. Be2
{ We don't need to do anything fancy, simple development suffice. } 11... O-O-O
{ If Black goes  11...c4  , the game will one way or another transpose to  10...c4  , for example  12.Bf4  O-O-O  13.Qc1  Kb8  14.a4  Ka8  15.g4  . }
12. a4 Qa5 13. Qd2 c4
{ This approach doesn't look very sensible to me, because it allows our bishop to become a monster on a3. That being said, it is playable. }
14. Ba3 Kb8
{ The standard way to play is to get the king out of the danger zone before thinking about any breaks on the kingside. }
15. Nh2
{ Showing off a new plan! The knight is heading to g4 where it can head to e3 and support a f4-f5 break. Additionally, it can head to f4 via g2 in case Black closes the shop with f5. The standard plan with Nh4-g2-f4 is very much possible here as well, though. }
15... Ka8 16. Ng4 Rdf8 { It's the same old same old for Black... } 17. Ne3 f6
{ 17...f5!?  Black can move the pawn two steps, intending to someday play g5 with some space and activity.  18.g3!  This move is very good, as it allows our knight to maneuver to g2 where it can reach f4 or even h4.  18...Rf7!   Black moves out of the pin.  18...Rfg8  is an alternative, when we should react with  19.Ng2  . We're much better after something like  19...g5  20.hxg6  Nxg6  21.Bh5  Nce7  22.Ke2  due to our space advantage and activity.  19.Ra1  A prophylactic move, making sure that Qxa4 is never on the cards. I generally believe that Qxa4 is way too risky for Black in most cases, but it doesn't hurt to have it covered. Additionally, we could now be considering to drive Black's queen away with Bb4 followed by a5, with a nice increase in space.  19...f4!   Black should do something. The other pawn break doesn't seem fun for Black:  19...g5  20.hxg6  Nxg6  21.Bh5  Rg7  22.Ng2  , with a really nice position. In case Black does nothing we can go: Ng2-Nf4-Qe2-Kf2-f3-Rhg1-g4. Also,  19...Qxa4  is met by  O-O  when the queen is in trouble.  20.gxf4  Rxf4  21.Ng2   Note that  21.Nxc4  fails to  dxc4  , as the rook on  a1  will hang when we capture Black's rook on  f4  .  21...Rf7  22.Nh4!  Preventing Black from launching the g-pawn forward.  22...Rg8   If Black tries  22...Rhf8  , we have  23.Ng6  when Black has nothing better than giving an exchange with  23...Nxg6  24.hxg6  Rxf2  25.Bxf8  Rxf8  . Black has compensation I guess, but I don't think it's enough.  23.Bc5  Nf5  24.Ng6±  There is a complicated struggle ahead, but our huge space advantage makes it rather clear who has the best chances. A sample line is:  24...Re8  25.Bg4  Qc7  26.Rh3  b6  27.Ba3  a5  28.Rf3  Nd8  29.Kd1  Bxa4  30.Bxf5  Rxf5  31.Rxf5  exf5  32.Bd6  Qd7  33.f4  Nf7  34.Ba3  when we're playing for two results. }
18. f4 Rf7
{ Is best met by   18...Qxa4  Should now be met by  19.Qc1  Qa5  20.Qb2  Just in time!  20...Bc8  21.O-O  ↑ With a powerful initiative for the missing pawn. A nice sample line is:  21...fxe5  22.dxe5  g5  23.Ra1  Qc7  24.Bd6  Qd8  25.Bc5  Qc7  26.Rxa7+!  Nxa7  27.Bb6  Qb8  28.Bxa7  Qxa7  29.Ra1  Nc6  30.Rxa7+  Nxa7  31.fxg5  hxg5  32.Qa3  and White is winning. }
19. O-O
{ We can now start thinking about exf6 followed by Ng4-Ne5 or even f5. } 19...
f5
{ Fails to a pretty nasty trick   19...Rg8  We don't need to worry about a potential attack on our king, as we can always escape with  20.Bf3  f5  21.Kf2  g5  22.hxg6  Nxg6  23.g3±  When Black has only achieved to give us the h-file. }
20. Bxc4 { Out of the blue! } 20... dxc4 21. Nxc4 Qa6 22. Nd6
{ Black is just completely lost, as c4-d5 will soon follow suit. We may even take on b7 if we so desire. }
*

