[Black "Giri's 7...Qc7 (10...Bd7 2)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ We have finally arrived to the main bulk of our coverage on the French, and our very last topic to cover for Part 1! This is the Winawer Variation, named after Szymon Winawer and popularized later in the 1940s by the greats Nimzowitch and Botvinnik. Black pins the knight and thus attacks the pawn on e4 so we're forced to make a decision in the center. }
4. e5
{ This is by far the most challenging move against the Winawer. We're gaining additional space while we're also limiting Black's knight on g8 as it can no longer jump to f6. }
4... c5
{ Black's main move challenges our center immediately, a necessary course of action to obtain the desired counterplay on the queenside. }
5. a3
{ By far the most played move as this is the only way to maintain the strong pawn chain. }
5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Ne7 7. h4 Qc7 8. Rb1 Nbc6
{ This move looks very natural indeed, but there's a lot more to it than what initially meets the eye... The alternative option is Nepo's  8...b6  , which is the last thing we'll cover in this course! }
9. h5 { There's no reason for us to avoid including h5-h6. } 9... h6 10. Nf3
Bd7 { This has pretty much always been played in this position. } 11. Be2
{ We don't need to do anything fancy, simple development suffice. } 11... O-O-O
12. a4 { Preparing to place the bishop on the a3-f8 diagonal. } 12... Qa5 13.
Qd2 c4
{ This approach doesn't look very sensible to me, because it allows our bishop to become a monster on a3. That being said, it is playable. }
14. Ba3 Kb8
{ The standard way to play is to get the king out of the danger zone before thinking about any breaks on the kingside. }
15. Nh2
{ Showing off a new plan! The knight is heading to g4 where it can head to e3 and support a f4-f5 break. Additionally, it can head to f4 via g2 in case Black closes the shop with f5. The standard plan with Nh4-g4-f4 is very much possible here as well, though. }
15... Ka8 16. Ng4 Rdf8 { It's the same old same old for Black... } 17. Ne3 f6
18. f4 fxe5 19. fxe5 Rf7
{ This move is incredibly annoying. Black delays the pawn capture with one move.  19...Qxa4  is worse, as we quickly get a very powerful initiative after  20.Qc1  . Two sample lines:  20...Rf7  21.Qb2  Qa6  22.Ra1  Nc8  23.Bc5  Na5  24.Kd2  b6  25.Rhb1  Bc6  26.Bb4  Qb7  27.Bf3  and Black's defenses will collapse.  20...Qa5  is better, but still poor after  21.Qb2  Bc8  22.Bg4  Qc7  23.Bd6  Qd7  24.Ra1  . }
20. Ra1
{ We don't want to place the rook on a1 yet, but we have no other choice. Now Black don't have to deal with the annoying mate threat on b7, a huge improvement. }
20... Qxa4 { Black should obviously take the pawn while he still can. } 21. Bf3
Qa5 22. O-O Qc7 23. Qe1
{ We maintain some initiative for the missing pawn with the plan of playing Qg3-Qh3-Bg4 and press e6. We can place the f-rook in the b-file and bother Black with our dark-squared bishop on d6 or c5. This can definitely be fine for a computer, but over the board it's tough to play Black. }
