{ We have finally arrived to the main bulk of our coverage on the French, and our very last topic to cover for Part 1! This is the Winawer Variation, named after Szymon Winawer and popularized later in the 1940s by the greats Nimzowitch and Botvinnik. Black pins the knight and thus attacks the pawn on e4 so we're forced to make a decision in the center. }
4. e5
{ This is by far the most challenging move against the Winawer. We're gaining additional space while we're also limiting Black's knight on g8 as it can no longer jump to f6. }
4... c5
{ Black's main move challenges our center immediately, a necessary course of action to obtain the desired counterplay on the queenside. }
5. a3
{ By far the most played move as this is the only way to maintain the strong pawn chain. }
5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Ne7 7. h4 Qc7 8. Rb1 Nbc6
{ This move looks very natural indeed, but there's a lot more to it than what initially meets the eye... The alternative option is Nepo's  8...b6  , which is the last thing we'll cover in this course! }
9. h5 { There's no reason for us to avoid including h5-h6. } 9... h6 10. Nf3
Bd7 { This has pretty much always been played in this position. } 11. Be2
{ We don't need to do anything fancy, simple development suffice. } 11... O-O-O
12. a4 { Preparing to place the bishop on the a3-f8 diagonal. } 12... f6
{ Black should attack our center right away. } 13. Ba3
{ The next couple of moves are forced: } 13... fxe5 14. Bxc5 e4
{ Other moves are hopeless, for example  14...Nf5?  15.dxe5  Nxe5  16.Nxe5  Qxe5  17.Bxa7  and White is totally winning. }
15. Ne5
{ Our knight jumps into the center and threatens a fork on the f7-square. Black has different ways to dodge the threat, but only two are viable... }
15... Rhf8
{ Black defends the threat of Nf7, but it makes little sense to willingly put the knight on e7 in a pin. }
16. Qc1
{ Our queen heads to a3 where it will put Black under additional pressure. }
16... Rf5
{ 16...Nxe5  is given by the engine, but  17.Bxe7  Qxc3+  18.Qd2  Qxd2  19.Kxd2  is just an exchange down.   16...Be8  is also far from satisfactory after  17.Nxc6  Bxc6  18.Bxa7  . }
17. Qa3 Be8
{ Forced.  17...Re8  is hopeless after  18.Bd6  Qd8  19.Ba6  bxa6  20.Qc5  , when  Rb8#  is a decisive threat. Black must give the queen. }
18. Rb3 { A mysterious move, with the cunning plan of O-O followed by Rfb1. }
18... Na5
{ The engine move.   18...Nxe5  19.dxe5!   Not  19.Bxe7?  when Black has  19...Nc4!  19...Nc6  20.Bd6  Qf7  21.O-O  +-  Our dark-squared bishop puts Black's position to shame. }
19. Bxe7 { Extra material? Yes, please! } 19... Nxb3 20. Rh3
{ This move is absolutely stunning. We're dominating Black so much that we have time to guard the pawn on c3.   20.cxb3  Qxc3+  21.Kf1  Qxd4  22.Qc1+  Kb8  23.Ng4  is also winning, but Black has some practical chances. }
20... Na5 21. Bg4
{ It's incredible, but both of Black's rooks are in serious trouble. } 21...
Rf6 { The only way to avoid the loss of both rooks. } 22. Rg3
{ Another brilliant move. The plan is Be2 when g7 falls. Black will be completely doomed. }
22... Nc6 { Black forces us to grab the rook. } 23. Bxf6 gxf6 24. Bxe6+ Kb8 25.
Nxc6+ Bxc6 26. Rg6
{ We're currently up a pawn and just about to win another one. } 26... Qf4
{ Black's best try, but it's still hopeless after } 27. g3 Qf3 28. Bg4 Qg2 29.
Qe7
{ When our extra pawns provide us with a decisive edge. In case you're unsure, a sample line is:  29...Re8  30.Qxf6  e3  31.Qf4+  Ka8  32.Re6  exf2+  33.Qxf2  Qh1+  34.Kd2  and Black can resign. }
