{ We have finally arrived to the main bulk of our coverage on the French, and our very last topic to cover for Part 1! This is the Winawer Variation, named after Szymon Winawer and popularized later in the 1940s by the greats Nimzowitch and Botvinnik. Black pins the knight and thus attacks the pawn on e4 so we're forced to make a decision in the center. }
4. e5
{ This is by far the most challenging move against the Winawer. We're gaining additional space while we're also limiting Black's knight on g8 as it can no longer jump to f6. }
4... c5
{ Black's main move challenges our center immediately, a necessary course of action to obtain the desired counterplay on the queenside. }
5. a3
{ By far the most played move as this is the only way to maintain the strong pawn chain. }
5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Ne7 7. h4 Qc7 8. Rb1 Nbc6
{ This move looks very natural indeed, but there's a lot more to it than what initially meets the eye... The alternative option is Nepo's  8...b6  , which is the last thing we'll cover in this course! }
9. h5 { There's no reason for us to avoid including h5-h6. } 9... h6 10. Nf3
Bd7 { This has pretty much always been played in this position. } 11. Be2
{ We don't need to do anything fancy, simple development suffice. } 11... O-O-O
12. a4 { Preparing to place the bishop on the a3-f8 diagonal. } 12... f6
{ Black should attack our center right away. } 13. Ba3
{ The next couple of moves are forced: } 13... fxe5 14. Bxc5 e4 15. Ne5
{ Our knight jumps into the center and threatens a fork on the f7-square. Black has different ways to dodge the threat, but only two are viable... }
15... Rdf8
{ This is better than  15...Rhf8  as we no longer have  Bxe7  with a double attack, but that doesn't mean that this move is good. }
16. Bxe7
{ Our strategy changes. We're going to castle kingside and open the position with c4 to create a powerful initiative on the queenside. }
16... Nxe7 17. O-O Rhg8
{ Black goes for direct counterplay. A move like  17...Rf6  gives us an easy game after  18.c4  Nc6  19.Nxd7  Qxd7  20.cxd5  Qxd5  21.c3  . }
18. c4 { We're faster! } 18... g6 19. cxd5 gxh5
{ And now we must find   19...Nxd5  20.Bb5!  A strong continuation, forcing the trade of bishops and removing another piece from Black's defense.  20...Bxb5  21.Rxb5  Kb8   21...Nc3  is met by  22.Qg4  , followed by  Qxe6+  .  22.hxg6  Nc3  Black can grab the exchange, but our knight on e5 is a monster.  23.Qe1  Nxb5  24.axb5  Rd8  25.Qxe4  Qc3  26.Rd1+-  I think it's fair to say that we have compensation for the missing exchange...   19...exd5  Should be met by  20.c4!  When we're opening the c-file.  20...gxh5  21.cxd5  Nxd5  22.Ba6!!  A beautiful tactic, intending Rc1 followed by Qd2 if Black takes.   Not  22.Rc1?  right away, as things are no longer as clear after  22...Bc6!  22...Nc3  23.Qd2  Nxb1  24.Rxb1  bxa6  25.Rc1+-  Our Q+N coordinate beautifully together. Black's rooks can't do anything. }
20. Bb5
{ This move is strong as it gives us a powerful rook on b5 while it also makes it easier for our queen to get into the game. }
20... Bxb5 21. Rxb5
{ Rc5 is now a threat, so Black doesn't have time for Nxd5. } 21... Qd6
{ 21...exd5  is met by  22.Qxh5  . } 22. dxe6 Qxe6 23. Qe2 Nd5
{ Black still has some tricks, but the move } 24. f4 { Kills the game. } 24...
exf3 { 24...Nxf4  25.Qxe4  Rxg2+  26.Qxg2  is the point!, when  f8  hangs. }
25. Rxf3 Nc7 { 25...Nf4  is met by  26.Qf1  . } 26. Rc3
{ Pinning the knight and threatening Qe4. } 26... Kb8
{ A beautiful line is:  26...Rg7  27.Qe4  Qa6  28.Ng6  Rfg8  29.Ne7+  Kd8  30.Nc6+  bxc6  31.Rb8+  Kd7  32.Rxg8  Rxg8  33.Qh7+  . }
27. Nc6+
{ The simplest path to Rome.  27.Rxc7  is a computer line, but I find it unnecessary. }
27... Ka8 28. Rxb7 { The beautiful point. Now we win Black's queen by force. }
28... Kxb7 29. Nd8+ Rxd8 30. Rxc7+ Kxc7 31. Qxe6
{ Our queen and extra pawns are much stronger than Black's rooks. } *

