1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ We have finally arrived to the main bulk of our coverage on the French, and our very last topic to cover for Part 1! This is the Winawer Variation, named after Szymon Winawer and popularized later in the 1940s by the greats Nimzowitch and Botvinnik. Black pins the knight and thus attacks the pawn on e4 so we're forced to make a decision in the center. }
4. e5
{ This is by far the most challenging move against the Winawer. We're gaining additional space while we're also limiting Black's knight on g8 as it can no longer jump to f6. }
4... c5
{ Black's main move challenges our center immediately, a necessary course of action to obtain the desired counterplay on the queenside. }
5. a3
{ By far the most played move as this is the only way to maintain the strong pawn chain. }
5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Ne7 7. h4 Qc7 8. Rb1 Nbc6
{ This move looks very natural indeed, but there's a lot more to it than what initially meets the eye... The alternative option is Nepo's  8...b6  , which is the last thing we'll cover in this course! }
9. h5 { There's no reason for us to avoid including h5-h6. } 9... h6 10. Nf3
Bd7 { This has pretty much always been played in this position. } 11. Be2
{ We don't need to do anything fancy, simple development suffice. } 11... O-O-O
12. a4 { Preparing to place the bishop on the a3-f8 diagonal. } 12... f6
{ Black should attack our center right away. } 13. Ba3
{ The next couple of moves are forced: } 13... fxe5 14. Bxc5 e4 15. Ne5
{ Our knight jumps into the center and threatens a fork on the f7-square. Black has different ways to dodge the threat, but only two are viable... }
15... Be8
{ Can be played, when Black gets ready to capture on e5 and on e7 with the queen. }
16. Nxc6 Nxc6 17. O-O
{ With castle on the board we aim to dismantle Black's center with f3 next. This is a really powerful threat, so Black must act fast. }
17... g6 { Black gains counterplay by opening the g-file. } 18. f3 gxh5 19.
fxe4 dxe4 20. Rf6
{ Targeting the pawn on e6, while also setting a pretty neat trap. } 20... Rg8
{ Black goes for direct counterplay in the g-file. } 21. Rxe6
{ 21.Bc4  would allow the trick  21...Rxg2+  followed by  Qg7+  , when Black is winning. }
21... Qg3 22. Qf1 h4
{ Black goes for it at once and aims to blast through on our kingside with h3. We would have liked to play Bf3 here, but there's a pawn on e4... So how to react? }
23. Kh1
{ Moving the king out of harm's way is the best try. The alternative is  23.Rxe4  , when the play is quite forced. I looked at  23...h3  24.Bf3  hxg2  25.Qb5  Na5  26.Qe2  Bc6  27.Bg4+  Rxg4  28.Qxg4+  Qxg4  29.Rxg4  Nc4  30.Rf4  Nd2  when I think Black has enough counterplay to save the game. }
23... h3 { Black opens our camp at once. } 24. gxh3 Bd7
{ I took a look at  24...Kb8  as well, but the problem for Black is that it allows us to consolidate with  25.Bg4  , intending  Qa6  and keeping an eye on  h3  . Black has  25. ..Rxg4  which looks like it's winning, but the move  26.Bd6!  saves the day after  26...Rxd6  27.Rxe8+  Nd8  28.hxg4  Qxg4  29.Qg2  when our material advantage grants us a winning game. }
25. Bd6
{ Our bishop pushes Black's queen away while it also covers the b8-square for the black monarch. I'm skeptical about  25.Rxh6  due to  25...Qe3  26.Rh5  Rh8  when I think Black has a really scary attack. }
25... Qe3
{ This is Black's best move, with the point being that there is no discovered check to win the queen like in the 25... Qxc3 line. Additionally, the queen on e3 covers the g1-square, so Rg1+ is often a really helpful resource for Black.   25...Qxc3  I think any human would grab the pawn without hesitation.  26.Ba6!  Black is suddenly under a vicious attack.  26...Na5   Black has nothing else, as  26...Bxe6  fails to  27.Rxb7!!  when we're threatening mate. Black is forced to go  27. ..Rxd6  , but then  28.Rb3+  wins the queen.  27.Bb4  And now the following line is forced:  27...Qf3+  28.Qxf3  exf3  29.Bxa5  Bxe6  30.Bxb7+  Kd7  31.Bxd8  Rxd8  32.Bxf3  Bxh3  33.Kh2  Bf5  34.Rc1±  The dust has settled and we have arrived at an ending that is almost winning for us. }
26. Bc4 { Calmly defending the rook on e6. } 26... Rg1+
{ As pointed out, this is one of the advantages with the queen placement on e3.   26...Qxc3  leads to  25...Qxc3  after  27.Ba6  . }
27. Qxg1 { And now the following is forced: } 27... Qxh3+ 28. Bh2 Bxe6 29. Qg3
Rd7 { Black defends, just barely! } 30. Qxh3 Bxh3 31. Rg1
{ Our bishop pair give us excellent winning chances in the ending. } *

