Bd7 { This has pretty much always been played in this position. } 11. Be2
{ We don't need to do anything fancy, simple development suffice. } 11... O-O-O
12. a4 { Preparing to place the bishop on the a3-f8 diagonal. } 12... f6
{ Black should attack our center right away. } 13. Ba3
{ The next couple of moves are forced: } 13... fxe5 14. Bxc5 e4 15. Ne5
{ Our knight jumps into the center and threatens a fork on the f7-square. Black has different ways to dodge the threat, but only two are viable... }
15... Be8
{ Can be played, when Black gets ready to capture on e5 and on e7 with the queen. }
16. Nxc6 Nxc6 17. O-O
{ With castle on the board we aim to dismantle Black's center with f3 next. This is a really powerful threat, so Black must act fast. }
17... g6 { Black gains counterplay by opening the g-file. } 18. f3 gxh5 19.
fxe4 dxe4 20. Rf6
{ Targeting the pawn on e6, while also setting a pretty neat trap. } 20... Rg8
{ Black goes for direct counterplay in the g-file. } 21. Rxe6 Qg3 22. Qf1 h4
{ Black goes for it at once and aims to blast through on our kingside with h3. We would have liked to play Bf3 here, but there's a paw on e4... So how to react? }
23. Kh1 Bd7
{ Black chases our rook and prepares to break down our defenses with h3. } 24.
Ba6 { Counterattack! } 24... h3
{ It's incredible, but Black can actually ignore our threats around his king.  24...Bxe6?  would not suffice for Black after  25.Rxb7!!  when Black must play  25.. .Qxg2+  26.Qxg2  Rxg2  and now  27.Rh7+!  before taking the rook on  g2  , as Black was threatening  Nb8!   24...Na5?  Would lose at once after  25.Rxb7  Nxb7  26.Bxb7+  Kc7   26...Kxb7  is met by  27.Qa6+  .  27.Bd6++-  Black loses the queen and is thus completely lost, for example  27...Qxd6  28.Qc4+  Kxb7  29.Rxd6  . }
25. Bxb7+
{ We have no choice!  25.gxh3?  would lose immediately to  25...Bxe6  26.Rxb7  Qxh3+  , and we have no good discovered checks! }
25... Kc7 { And now we reach an ending by force: } 26. Bd6+ Qxd6 27. Rxd6 hxg2+
28. Qxg2 Rxg2 29. Rxd7+ Rxd7 30. Kxg2
{ With a pawn up we obtain winning chances in the ending, but it's holdable for Black with perfect play @@StartBracket@@as usual in the game of chess!@@EndBracket@@ }
