1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ We have finally arrived to the main bulk of our coverage on the French, and our very last topic to cover for Part 1! This is the Winawer Variation, named after Szymon Winawer and popularized later in the 1940s by the greats Nimzowitch and Botvinnik. Black pins the knight and thus attacks the pawn on e4 so we're forced to make a decision in the center. }
4. e5
{ This is by far the most challenging move against the Winawer. We're gaining additional space while we're also limiting Black's knight on g8 as it can no longer jump to f6. }
4... c5
{ Black's main move challenges our center immediately, a necessary course of action to obtain the desired counterplay on the queenside. }
5. a3
{ By far the most played move as this is the only way to maintain the strong pawn chain. }
5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Ne7 7. h4 Qc7 8. Rb1 Nbc6
{ This move looks very natural indeed, but there's a lot more to it than what initially meets the eye... The alternative option is Nepo's  8...b6  , which is the last thing we'll cover in this course! }
9. h5 { There's no reason for us to avoid including h5-h6. } 9... h6 10. Nf3
Bd7 { This has pretty much always been played in this position. } 11. Be2
{ We don't need to do anything fancy, simple development suffice. } 11... O-O-O
12. a4 { Preparing to place the bishop on the a3-f8 diagonal. } 12... f6
{ Black should attack our center right away. } 13. Ba3
{ The next couple of moves are forced: } 13... fxe5 14. Bxc5 e4 15. Ne5
{ Our knight jumps into the center and threatens a fork on the f7-square. Black has different ways to dodge the threat, but only two are viable... }
15... Be8
{ Can be played, when Black gets ready to capture on e5 and on e7 with the queen. }
16. Nxc6 Nxc6 17. O-O
{ With castle on the board we aim to dismantle Black's center with f3 next. This is a really powerful threat, so Black must act fast. }
17... g6 { Black gains counterplay by opening the g-file. } 18. f3 gxh5 19.
fxe4 dxe4 20. Rf6
{ Targeting the pawn on e6, while also setting a pretty neat trap. } 20... Rg8
{ Black goes for direct counterplay in the g-file. } 21. Rxe6 Bd7
{ Should be met by } 22. Rxe4 Rg3
{ Black's trickiest approach.  22...Bh3  is easily stopped by  23.Bf3  Qg3  24.Qe2  when Black has nothing. }
23. Bf3 Rdg8
{ Black doubles the rooks in the g-file and aims to infiltrate our camp with Rh3-Qh2+, or play Bh3. }
24. Qe2 { Defending g2 while preparing to meet Bh3 with Re8+. } 24... Rh3
{ Black goes straight for the kill, or maybe handshake, as there are tons of threefold repetitions in the air.   24...b6  25.d5!  An important intermezzo, with the point being that we remove the knight from c6 and have the resource d5-d6 at hand to close the queen's diagonal.  25...Ne5   This is forced. If Black moves to the rim with  25...Na5  , we can play  26.Bf2  Rh3  27.d6!  when Black's king is the one in trouble as showcased after  27...Qxd6  28.Qa6+  Kd8  29.Qxa7  Qh2+  30.Kf1  .   25...Rxf3  intends  26.Qxf3?  Nxe5  , but instead  26.d6  first wins!  26.Rxe5  Rxf3   26...Qxc5?  leads nowhere after  27.Kh1  .  27.Qa6+!  Qb7  28.Qc4  Kb8   28...Qc7??  29.d6!  and Black's rook on  g8  falls.  29.Bd6+  Ka8  30.Re7+-  Black's initiative is completely under control. Best play from both sides goes:  30...Rf5  31.Rd1  h4  32.Rd2  h3  33.g3  , with  Kh2  next. }
25. d5 { It's quite significant that our bishop's diagonal has been opened. }
25... Qh2+
{ 25...Rxf3  is nothing special now, as we can respond with  26.Qxf3  Ne5  27.Qe3  Ng4  28.Rxg4  Rxg4  29.Bxa7  .   25...Ne5  Is Black's best bet, but it's not particularly tricky as it leads to some piece trades.  26.Rxe5  Rxf3   26...Qxc5+  27.Qe3!  , not  27.Qf2??  which would lose to  27...Rh1+  .  27.Qxf3  Qxe5  28.a5  Our a-pawn storms forward.  28...a6   Black should stop our pawn. If Black goes  28...Bg4?  29.Qf7  Qg7  30.Rxb7  is a winning ending, while if Black tries  28...Qg3?  we have the beautiful line  29.Qxg3  Rxg3  30.a6  b6  31.Bxb6  axb6  32.Rxb6  , when our a-pawn promotes.  29.Bd4  Qf5   Black is in trouble after  29...Qg5  30.Rb4!  which stops Black from playing  30...Qg4  ,  because of the check on c4.  30.Rf1  Qxc2   30...Rf8  31.c4  Qxf3  32.gxf3  looks excellent too.  31.Be5  h4  32.Rf2  We can't allow Black play h3.  32...Qc1+  33.Kh2+-  With Black's counterplay out of the way, we're winning. }
26. Kf1
{ The placement of our bishop is well shown here, as it can go to the rescue after  26...Qh1+  27.Bg1  . }
26... Rxf3+ { Black has no choice. } 27. Qxf3 Ne5 28. Qf2 Bh3
{ 28...Ng4  doesn't do the job either, after for example  29.Rc4  Kd8  30.Re1  Qh1+  31.Qg1  Nh2+  32.Kf2  Ng4+  33.Kf3  Nh2+  34.Ke3  Ng4+  35.Kd2  and our king escapes. }
29. Rf4
{ This is strong, as we're intending to neutralize Black's forces with Rf8+. }
29... Qh1+ { 29...Bxg2+  30.Ke1  and Black has nothing. } 30. Ke2 Qxb1 31. Rf8+
{ The tactics work in our favor. } 31... Rxf8 32. Qxf8+ Kc7 33. Qe7+
{ We will regain material with some checks with a winning ending. For example  33...Nd7  34.Bd6+  Kb6  35.Qe3+  Ka6  36.Qd3+  Ka5  37.gxh3  and White wins.  33...Bd7  is better, but also lost for Black after  34.Qxe5+  Kc8  35.Bxa7  . }
