[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ We have finally arrived to the main bulk of our coverage on the French, and our very last topic to cover for Part 1! This is the Winawer Variation, named after Szymon Winawer and popularized later in the 1940s by the greats Nimzowitch and Botvinnik. Black pins the knight and thus attacks the pawn on e4 so we're forced to make a decision in the center. }
4. e5
{ This is by far the most challenging move against the Winawer. We're gaining additional space while we're also limiting Black's knight on g8 as it can no longer jump to f6. }
4... c5
{ Black's main move challenges our center immediately, a necessary course of action to obtain the desired counterplay on the queenside. }
5. a3
{ By far the most played move as this is the only way to maintain the strong pawn chain. }
5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Ne7 7. h4 Qc7 8. Rb1 Nbc6
{ This move looks very natural indeed, but there's a lot more to it than what initially meets the eye... The alternative option is Nepo's  8...b6  , which is the last thing we'll cover in this course! }
9. h5 { There's no reason for us to avoid including h5-h6. } 9... h6 10. Nf3
Bd7 { This has pretty much always been played in this position. } 11. Be2
{ We don't need to do anything fancy, simple development suffice. } 11... O-O-O
12. a4 { Preparing to place the bishop on the a3-f8 diagonal. } 12... f6
{ Black should attack our center right away. } 13. Ba3
{ The next couple of moves are forced: } 13... fxe5 14. Bxc5 e4 15. Ne5
{ Our knight jumps into the center and threatens a fork on the f7-square. Black has different ways to dodge the threat, but only two are viable... }
15... Be8
{ Can be played, when Black gets ready to capture on e5 and on e7 with the queen. }
16. Nxc6 Nxc6 17. O-O
{ With castle on the board we aim to dismantle Black's center with f3 next. This is a really powerful threat, so Black must act fast. }
17... g6 { Black gains counterplay by opening the g-file. } 18. f3 gxh5 19.
fxe4 dxe4 20. Rf6
{ Targeting the pawn on e6, while also setting a pretty neat trap. } 20... Rg8
{ Black goes for direct counterplay in the g-file. } 21. Rxe6 h4
{ We must consider what happens if Black pushes the pawn to h3 at once. } 22.
Bg4 Kb8
{ Black needs to get the king out of the way.  22...Bd7?  would lose immediately to  23.Bd6  Qa5  24.d5  when Black has problems with the knight. We do have to be precise though...  24...Ne5  25.Bxe5  Rxg4  26.Qd4!  Bxe6  27.Qc4+  Kd7  28.dxe6+  Ke8  29.Qf1  Qc5+  30.Bd4  Qc7  31.e7  Qxe7  32.Qb5+  Qd7  33.Qe5+  Kf7  34.Qf6+  Ke8  35.Qh8+  Ke7  36.Bf6+  Ke6  37.Bxd8  and we're finally material up! }
23. Rxe4
{ With a pawn up, we're soon ready to consolidate with moves such as Qe2, Re3, Rf1 etc. Black needs to maintain the pressure, otherwise he'll be in trouble... }
23... Bf7 { Black is ready to place the bishop on d5 where it will target g2. }
24. Bh3 Ba2
{ This move is incredibly annoying, as we're forced to place our rook on an inferior square.  24...Bd5  right away is calmly met by  25.Re3  , when we're ready to consolidate with for example Qd3-Rf1.   24...Qg3  isn't a big deal either, as we can play  25.Qd3  . The arising ending looks winning for us. }
25. Ra1 Bd5
{ It's a big advantage for Black that we no longer have our rook in the active b-file. Black will now be able to play b6, when our pressure decreases. }
26. Rg4
{ Our best try for an advantage is to watch over the g-file. I looked at  26.Rxh4  , but after the accurate  26...Rg5  followed by  Rdg8  the game ends in a draw. }
26... b6
{ Black pushes our bishop away and obtains some air at the same time for the king. If Black were to try  26...Rge8  , we could play a rather sophisticated maneuver in  27.Ba3  Na5  28.Bc1  Ka8  29.Bxh6  Nc4  30.Bf4  when we have the upper hand. }
27. Ba3 Ne7
{ Black targets c3.   27...Na5?  would be much worse, when I think we're doing very well after  28.Rxg8  Rxg8  29.Qh5  . }
28. c4 Bxc4 29. a5
{ 29.Rxg8  Rxg8  30.Qh5  is another path we can take, when Black must find  30...Ng6! }
29... Nd5
{ Black's knight is very well placed on d5.   29...Bd5?  would be rather poor after  30.axb6  axb6  31.c4!  Bxc4  32.Qa4  when our attack is decisive.   29...Rxg4  Should be met by  30.axb6  axb6  31.Bxg4  Nc6  32.c3⩲  Our position looks much easier to handle with Bf3 coming next. Black's king is exposed. }
30. axb6 axb6 31. Qf3
{ 31.Rxg8  leads to a forced draw after  31...Rxg8  32.Qf3  Nf4!!  only move.  33.Bd6  Nxh3+  34.Kh1  Nf2+  35.Kg1  with a threefold. }
31... Rxg4 32. Bxg4 Qf4 33. Re1 Qxd4+ 34. Kh2
{ Our bishop pair give us a tiny tiny edge, but objectively Black is not far away from drawing. This is an appropriate place to stop. I leave you with a sample line:   34...Ba6  35.Re4  Qg7  36.Qf2  Qc7+  37.Kg1  Bb7  38.Rd4  Ne7  39.Rxd8+  Qxd8  40.Qf6  Nc6  41.Qxd8+  Nxd8  42.Bd6+  Ka7  43.Be7  Nf7  44.Bxh4=  Our bishop pair give us a tiny hope for a win, but of course it should be a draw. }
