[White "26. French Defense (1...e6) Winawer Modern Mainlines"]
[Black "Giri's 7...Qc7 (10...Bd7 11)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ We have finally arrived to the main bulk of our coverage on the French, and our very last topic to cover for Part 1! This is the Winawer Variation, named after Szymon Winawer and popularized later in the 1940s by the greats Nimzowitch and Botvinnik. Black pins the knight and thus attacks the pawn on e4 so we're forced to make a decision in the center. }
4. e5
{ This is by far the most challenging move against the Winawer. We're gaining additional space while we're also limiting Black's knight on g8 as it can no longer jump to f6. }
4... c5
{ Black's main move challenges our center immediately, a necessary course of action to obtain the desired counterplay on the queenside. }
5. a3
{ By far the most played move as this is the only way to maintain the strong pawn chain. }
5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Ne7 7. h4 Qc7 8. Rb1 Nbc6
{ This move looks very natural indeed, but there's a lot more to it than what initially meets the eye... The alternative option is Nepo's  8...b6  , which is the last thing we'll cover in this course! }
9. h5 { There's no reason for us to avoid including h5-h6. } 9... h6 10. Nf3
Bd7 { This has pretty much always been played in this position. } 11. Be2
{ We don't need to do anything fancy, simple development suffice. } 11... O-O-O
12. a4 { Preparing to place the bishop on the a3-f8 diagonal. } 12... f6
{ Black should attack our center right away. } 13. Ba3
{ The next couple of moves are forced: } 13... fxe5 14. Bxc5 e4 15. Ne5
{ Our knight jumps into the center and threatens a fork on the f7-square. Black has different ways to dodge the threat, but only two are viable... }
15... Nxe5
{ Taking the knight seems like the most natural way to proceed as Black. } 16.
Bxe7 Rde8 { Black avoids the exchange sac. } 17. Bc5 b6
{ 17...Nc6  also defends  a7  , but after  18.c4  we have a nice initiative. }
18. Bxb6
{ If we play  18.Bb4  , Black is completely fine after  18...Nc4  , so our best chance is to take. }
18... axb6 19. dxe5
{ I analyzed this position for a while, and came to the conclusion that this was a better try than the alternative,  19.Ba6+  . My issue was that  19.Ba6+  gave Black plenty of additional options, something I wanted to avoid as the evaluation is around the same. }
19... Qxc3+ 20. Qd2
{ 20.Kf1  is the alternative if you prefer keeping queens on the board. The position that arises is quite complex, but it seems like it's harder for Black than for us. A sample line is:  20...Qxe5  21.Rh3  Kc7  22.Qd2  Ra8  23.Qb4  Kd8  24.f4!?  Qxf4  25.Kg1  Qe5  26.Rf1  Rxa4  27  Qxb6+  Qc7  28.Qb2  Qc5+  29.Kh2  d4  30.Qb8+  Bc8  31.Rh4  . There are numerous alternatives along the way obviously, but just for you to get an idea on how the game could proceed. The final position is evaluated with the computerish 0.00, but the game still goes on. }
20... Qxd2+ 21. Kxd2 Kc7
{ Black should defend the pawn on b6 before considering grabbing the pawn on a4. }
22. Rh3 { The threat of Rc3+ followed by Rcb3 or a5 is quite severe. } 22...
Bxa4 { Black has no choice but to grab the pawn. } 23. Rg3 Rhg8
{ 23...Re7?  Would be a huge error because of  24.Rc3+  Kb7  25.Ra3   Black's problem is that he can't play  25...Ra8  due to  26.Rba1  , showing the problem with  Re7  . Now we can infiltrate Black's camp.  25...Bc6  26.Ba6+  Kb8   26...Kc7  is even worse because of  27.Rc3  .  27.Rxb6+  Kc7  28.Rab3+-  We're winning as Black can't stop us from breaking through, for example  28...Ra8  29.Ke3  Ba4  30.Rb2  Bc6  31.Kd4  Bd7  32.Kc5  . }
24. Rb4 Ra8
{ An important move, as Black needs to keep the a4-square under control. Otherwise we'll play Rc3+ and Rcb3 and win the pawn on b6. }
25. Rg6 Bd7 26. f3
{ We attack Black's pawn on e4 and hope that he'll take the pawn. This will allow Rbg4, when Black loses g7 or e6. And now Black must find }
26... Kc6
{ The only move that equalizes, but for a human this looks extremely curious. Black's point is to play Kc5 where it will contribute well as we often play fxe4. This will leave a square for the king on d5 where it can attack the pawn on e5.   26...exf3?!  Is the natural way to proceed, but after  27.Bxf3  Black is under a lot of pressure as either Bg4 or Rbg4 comes next, when Black loses a pawn. }
27. Bb5+ { The best try for a win. } 27... Kc5 28. Bxd7 Kxb4 29. Rxe6 exf3 30.
c3+ Kb3 31. gxf3
{ Our powerful pawn on e5 gives us some practical chances, but Black should draw with accurate play. }
