{ We have finally arrived to the main bulk of our coverage on the French, and our very last topic to cover for Part 1! This is the Winawer Variation, named after Szymon Winawer and popularized later in the 1940s by the greats Nimzowitch and Botvinnik. Black pins the knight and thus attacks the pawn on e4 so we're forced to make a decision in the center. }
4. e5
{ This is by far the most challenging move against the Winawer. We're gaining additional space while we're also limiting Black's knight on g8 as it can no longer jump to f6. }
4... c5
{ Black's main move challenges our center immediately, a necessary course of action to obtain the desired counterplay on the queenside. }
5. a3
{ By far the most played move as this is the only way to maintain the strong pawn chain. }
5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Ne7 7. h4 Qc7 8. Rb1 Nbc6
{ This move looks very natural indeed, but there's a lot more to it than what initially meets the eye... The alternative option is Nepo's  8...b6  , which is the last thing we'll cover in this course! }
9. h5 { There's no reason for us to avoid including h5-h6. } 9... h6 10. Nf3
Bd7 { This has pretty much always been played in this position. } 11. Be2
{ We don't need to do anything fancy, simple development suffice. } 11... O-O-O
12. a4 { Preparing to place the bishop on the a3-f8 diagonal. } 12... f6
{ Black should attack our center right away. } 13. Ba3
{ The next couple of moves are forced: } 13... fxe5 14. Bxc5 e4 15. Ne5
{ Our knight jumps into the center and threatens a fork on the f7-square. Black has different ways to dodge the threat, but only two are viable... }
15... Nxe5
{ Taking the knight seems like the most natural way to proceed as Black. } 16.
Bxe7 Qxc3+ { Black sacrifices an exchange for two pawns. } 17. Kf1
{ Because of Bb4, there's no way for Black to avoid the loss of the exchange. }
17... Nc6 18. Bxd8 Rxd8 19. Rh3
{ Black's clash of pawns could become dangerous rather quickly, so it's essential that we activate our pieces. }
19... Qxd4 20. Qxd4 Nxd4 21. Rg3
{ Applying pressure on Black's kingside pawns. } 21... Rg8
{ If Black tries defending the pawn with  21...Nf5  , we can swing over to the queenside.  22.Rc3+  Kb8  23.a5  with a dangerous initiative. }
22. a5 Nf5
{ Should once again be met by   22...a6  23.c4  We need open files and targets for our rooks in order to break through some day.  23...Bc6  24.cxd5  exd5  25.Rd1  Nf5!   25...Nxe2?  26.Kxe2  would leave Black far too weak on the dark squares.  26.Rg6  Kc7  27.Bg4  Our pieces are starting to infiltrate Black's camp.  27...Rf8   Forced, as  27...Nh4  28.Re6  Rf8  29.Re7+  Kd6  30.Rxe4  is hopeless.  28.Bxf5  Rxf5  29.Rxg7+  Kd6  30.g4  Rf4  31.Ke2  Ba4  32.Rg1  d4  Black's central pawns are dangerous, but it turns out that we have it under control.  33.Ke1!  We don't want to allow Black to play Bb5 with a tempo.  33...Bb5  34.Rg6+  Ke7  35.Rxh6+-  Our kingside pawns decide the game:  35...e3  36.Rh7+  Ke6  37.fxe3  dxe3  38.Rxb7  Rb4  39.Rxb5  Rxb5  40.Ke2  Rxa5  41.g5  Kf7  42.g6+  Kg7  43.h6+  and White wins. }
23. Rc3+ Kb8 24. Ke1
{ Our king moves out of any potential checks. With the king out of danger, Ba6 is now a threat, as Black no longer has   24.Ba6  Nd6  25.Bxb7?  Bb5! }
24... Nd6 25. Rbb3 { Another rook swings to the third rank. } 25... Rf8
{ Black can't do more than just wait. } 26. Ba6
{ Bxb7 followed by a6 is a deadly threat. Black has to play } 26... Rc8 27.
Rxc8+ Kxc8 28. Be2 { And here I don't think Black can survive the ending. } *

