[White "26. French Defense (1...e6) Winawer Modern Mainlines"]
[Black "Giri's 7...Qc7 (10...c4)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ We have finally arrived to the main bulk of our coverage on the French, and our very last topic to cover for Part 1! This is the Winawer Variation, named after Szymon Winawer and popularized later in the 1940s by the greats Nimzowitch and Botvinnik. Black pins the knight and thus attacks the pawn on e4 so we're forced to make a decision in the center. }
4. e5
{ This is by far the most challenging move against the Winawer. We're gaining additional space while we're also limiting Black's knight on g8 as it can no longer jump to f6. }
4... c5
{ Black's main move challenges our center immediately, a necessary course of action to obtain the desired counterplay on the queenside. }
5. a3
{ By far the most played move as this is the only way to maintain the strong pawn chain. }
5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Ne7 7. h4 Qc7 8. Rb1 Nbc6
{ This move looks very natural indeed, but there's a lot more to it than what initially meets the eye... The alternative option is Nepo's  8...b6  , which is the last thing we'll cover in this course! }
9. h5 { There's no reason for us to avoid including h5-h6. } 9... h6 10. Nf3 c4
{ Giri's suggestion is to close the position at once. } 11. Bf4
{ Our bishop develops to f4 so we can take control of the c1-h6 diagonal with Qc1. This makes the f6-break harder for Black to achieve, as the h6-pawn often ends up hanging. Another benefit is that it helps us prepare the break g4-g5, which Black won't be able to stop with f6 due to the aforementioned hanging pawn on h6. }
11... Bd7
{ When I interacted with Giri on Twitter, he said: '11... Bd7, your move, Sebastian.' His point is that he thinks it's no longer necessary to go to a5 with the queen in order to stop a4-Ba3, because our bishop stands on f4 at this very moment. A natural way to proceed, of course. On chess24 I somehow forgot to mention this option, as I only focused on 10... Bd7. }
12. Qc1 O-O-O 13. g4
{ We don't waste any time and start our kingside advancement right away. }
13... Kb8 { It makes sense for Black to improve the position of his king. } 14.
Be2 Ka8 15. a4 { This move should be played if Black allows us to. } 15... Rhf8
{ Black's only sensible plan is to break through with f6 at some point. There are obviously many ways Black could play, when the play will be rather similar to what we saw in the previous chapter with Nh4-Be3/Bg3-f4, etc. Our queen should be placed on a3 as well. }
16. Qb2
{ This is a move played to annoy Black, with a lingering mating threat on b7. }
16... b6 { This move only loses valuable time for Black. } 17. Bg3 Qc8 18. Qa3
{ Our queen is strongly placed on the a3-square where it targets Black's knight. }
18... f6
{ 18...Rde8  Black defends the knight and prepares to play f6 next, but after  19.Nh4  f6  20.f4±   Black's position looks nightmarish. A sample line could be:  20...Qc7  21.Kd2  Bc8  22.Rbf1  ,  when Kc1 and Rhg1 could follow suit. We'll answer fxe5 with fxe5. I don't see what Black is supposed to do... }
19. a5
{ Is the point! Black can't capture the pawn with the knight as the other knight hangs on e7, so he's forced to open the b-file with bxa5. }
19... bxa5 20. Kd2 Rde8 21. Qc5
{ Black's position looks paralyzed. There are no sensible moves.  21...fxe5  is logical, but the ending after  22.Nxe5  Nxe5  23.Qxc8+  Rxc8  24.Bxe5  is just horrendous for Black.   21...f5  is met by  22.g5  f4  23.Bh4  , with  gxh6  coming. }
*

