[White "26. French Defense (1...e6) Winawer Modern Mainlines"]
[Black "Giri's 7...Qc7 (10...c4 2)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ We have finally arrived to the main bulk of our coverage on the French, and our very last topic to cover for Part 1! This is the Winawer Variation, named after Szymon Winawer and popularized later in the 1940s by the greats Nimzowitch and Botvinnik. Black pins the knight and thus attacks the pawn on e4 so we're forced to make a decision in the center. }
4. e5
{ This is by far the most challenging move against the Winawer. We're gaining additional space while we're also limiting Black's knight on g8 as it can no longer jump to f6. }
4... c5
{ Black's main move challenges our center immediately, a necessary course of action to obtain the desired counterplay on the queenside. }
5. a3
{ By far the most played move as this is the only way to maintain the strong pawn chain. }
5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Ne7 7. h4 Qc7 8. Rb1 Nbc6
{ This move looks very natural indeed, but there's a lot more to it than what initially meets the eye... The alternative option is Nepo's  8...b6  , which is the last thing we'll cover in this course! }
9. h5 { There's no reason for us to avoid including h5-h6. } 9... h6 10. Nf3 c4
{ Giri's suggestion is to close the position at once. } 11. Bf4
{ Our bishop develops to f4 so we can take control of the c1-h6 diagonal with Qc1. This makes the f6-break harder for Black to achieve, as the h6-pawn often ends up hanging. Another benefit is that it helps us prepare the break g4-g5, which Black won't be able to stop with f6 due to the aforementioned hanging pawn on h6. }
11... Bd7
{ When I interacted with Giri on Twitter, he said: '11... Bd7, your move, Sebastian.' His point is that he thinks it's no longer necessary to go to a5 with the queen in order to stop a4-Ba3, because our bishop stands on f4 at this very moment. A natural way to proceed, of course. On chess24 I somehow forgot to mention this option, as I only focused on 10... Bd7. }
12. Qc1 O-O-O 13. g4
{ We don't waste any time and start our kingside advancement right away. }
13... Kb8 { It makes sense for Black to improve the position of his king. } 14.
Be2 Ka8 15. a4 { This move should be played if Black allows us to. } 15... Rhf8
{ Black's only sensible plan is to break through with f6 at some point. There are obviously many ways Black could play, when the play will be rather similar to what we saw in the previous chapter with Nh4-Be3/Bg3-f4, etc. Our queen should be placed on a3 as well. }
16. Qb2
{ This is a move played to annoy Black, with a lingering mating threat on b7. }
16... Qc8 { Black's queen moves out of the way to push f6. } 17. Rg1
{ I concluded that this was the best way to meet f6, as we often want to play g5 and open the g-file. }
17... f6 18. exf6 Rxf6 19. Bd6
{ The downside of playing f6 for Black, is that it leaves him rather weak on the dark squares. }
19... g5
{ Black takes some dark-square control and gains some additional space.   19...Rdf8  A logical move is to apply pressure on our pawn on f2, but this move is essentially an exchange sacrifice.  20.Ne5  Black can't really due anything about the threat of playing Nxc6 followed by Bxf8, as for example   20...Rg8  is terrible after  21.f4  .  20...Rxf2  21.Qa3!  This move is incredibly strong, as it applies pressure in the diagonal while preparing a5.  21...Qe8!   The only move, as Black doesn't get enough after  21...Nxe5  22.Bxe7  Nc6  23.Bxf8  Rxf8  24.Kd2  .  22.a5!   Incredibly strong, forcing a concession.  22.Nxc6  doesn't work due to  22...Qf7!!  when we're suddenly under a vicious attack. There's a long forced draw here:  23.Bg3  Nxc6  24.Kd2  Rxe2+  25.Kxe2  Qf3+  26.Kd2  Nxd4  27.Kc1  Ne2+  28.Kb2  Nxg1  29.Rxg1  d4  30.cxd4  Qxa3+  31.Kxa3  .  22...Nxe5  23.Bxe7  Qf7  Black's point is that the N+Q creates some tricks around our king: The play is forced from both sides:  24.Bxf8  Rxe2+  25.Kxe2  Qf3+  26.Kd2  Qf4+  27.Kd1  Nf3  28.Qc1  Qe4  This position is quite incredible. Black has only a piece for two rooks, but would have been winning after Ba4 if it was his turn to move. Truly beautiful.  29.Qb2  It's essential that Black's bishop can't join the attack.  29...Bc6  30.Rf1  Nh2  31.Qa3!   Our queen needs to give the b2-square to the king. Not  31.Qb4?  as Black draws after  31...Nxf1  32.Kc1  Ne3  33.Kb2  Qxc2+  34.Ka1  Qf2  . The queen placement's importance is shown after  35.Rb2  Nc2+  ,  36.Ka2  would have been winning with the queen on  a3  . This time though, Black takes our queen with check!  31...Nxf1  32.Kc1  Ne3  33.Kb2  Our king barely escapes.  33...Qxc2+  34.Ka1+-  And Black's attack fades away. I analyzed a bit longer, and apparently an endgame is reached by force after  34...Qd2  35.Qb2  Nc2+  36.Ka2  b6  37.axb6  axb6  38.Rc1  Ba4  39.Kb1  Kb7  40.Rxc2  Bxc2+  41.Qxc2  Qf4  42.Bxg7  Qxg4  43.Bxh6  Qxh5  44.Bf4  . This is not so easy to win, but I think White will always win in the long run. }
20. Qa3 Re8 21. Kd2 { Coordinating our rooks. } 21... Qd8
{ It makes sense for Black to prepare Nc8 in order to drive our annoying bishop on d6 out of the camp. }
22. Ne5
{ We're trading a knight to get additional control over the square on e5. }
22... Nxe5
{ 22...Rxf2?  Taking the pawn loses for Black.  23.Rbf1  We're trading rooks and achieving total domination.  23...Rxf1  24.Rxf1  Nxe5  25.dxe5  Taking with the bishop is also strong enough, but this is even better.  25...Nc8   25...Nc6  is no better, with the simplest win being  26.Rf8  Rxf8  27.Bxf8  Nxe5  28.Bxh6  . The h-pawn decides the game.  26.Bc5  b6  27.Bf8!  This move is incredibly strong. Black can't untangle!  27...Qc7  Black's only hope of getting sufficient counterplay.  28.a5!  Opening up Black's defenses.  28...bxa5   28...Qxe5  also loses, as  29.axb6  Nxb6  30.Rf7  is too problematic for Black's king. For example  30...d4  31.cxd4  Qxd4+  32.Ke1  Qg1+  33.Rf1  Qh2  34.Bd6  e5  35.Bf3+  and Black has to give the queen.  29.Rf7  The harmony of our pieces is stunning.  29...Qxe5  30.Qc5  Nb6  31.Bd6+-  Black loses decisive material. }
23. Bxe5 Rxf2
{ I think most humans would choose to grab the pawn.   23...Rf7  Is actually not so bad, as Black wants to play e5 rather quickly with the help of Nc6.  24.Bg3  Nc6  25.Qc5!  Preventing Black's idea by attacking the pawn on d5.   25.Qd6  allows  25...Qa5  , when I think Black has a lot of counterplay.   After  25.Qc5  we're intending to play a5 to take complete dark-square control, followed by a rook to e1.  25...b6  26.Qd6  We can now safely go to d6, as Black doesn't have any counterplay with Qa5. Our idea now is to play f4 as soon as we can. This can often be achieved by playing a5, and after Nxa5, f4. This is to avoid tricks with e5.  26...Kb7  27.Rgf1   27.f4?  would allow Black's trap with  27...gxf4  28.Bxf4?  e5!!  when Black is completely winning after  29.Bxe5  Qg5+  30.Kd1  Nxe5  31.dxe5  Rxe5  .  27...Rf6  Black prepares to play e5.  28.Rbe1  e5  And now some trades we'll follow when we'll have a really nice endgame:  29.Qxd5  exd4  30.cxd4  Bxg4!   This works, as  31.Qxd8  Rxd8  32.Bxg4?  fails to  32...Rxd4+  followed by  Rxg4  .  31.Bxc4  Qxd5  32.Bxd5  Rd8  33.Be5!  Keeping the pawn on d4 protected while attacking the rook.  33...Rf5   33....Rff8  loses to  34.Bg7  .  34.Be4±  And now Black needs to give the exchange as he is completely pinned down:  34...Rxe5  35.Bxc6+  Kxc6  36.Rxe5  Rxd4+  37.Kc1  Rxa4  38.Rfe1  , when I think Black is on the verge of losing. }
24. Rgf1 { Our compensation lies in our much better pieces. } 24... Ref8 25.
Bd6 R2f7 { 25...Rxf1  loses to the intermezzo  26.Bxe7  , hitting the queen. }
26. a5
{ Forcing another concession in Black's camp. Black is in fact almost zugzwang! }
26... a6 { Black can't allow a6. } 27. Qc5 Bc6
{ As we saw in the previous note, it's essential that we don't have Qc8+.   27...Bb5?  Loses the game immediately due to  28.Bxe7  Rxe7  29.Rxf8  Qxf8  30.Rf1+-  And we penetrate by playing Rf6. The difference in this position compared to the text is that with Bc6 included, we don't have the check on c8! This is an important factor in the line  30...Qg7  31.Qc8+  Ka7  32.Rf8  . Without this refutation, Black would have been fine! }
28. Rbe1
{ Black is so close to being zugzwang, but yet again there's one move that holds! }
28... Qe8 29. Kc1
{ Maneuvering our king to b2 where it will be better placed. } 29... Bd7
{ Black can't do much more than moving back and forth. For example,  29...Rxf1?  would lose to  30.Bxf1  when  e6  falls. }
30. Kb2 Bc8
{ Black needs to keep  e6  protected.  30...Bc6?  fails to  31.Rxf7  Rxf7  32.Bxc4!  followed by  Rxe6  .   30...Ba4  can be met by the sophisticated  31.Rf3!  with the idea of playing  Re3  . If Black takes,  e6  falls. }
31. Rf3 Rxf3 32. Bxf3 Rxf3 33. Bxe7 Qb5+ 34. Kc1 Qxc5 35. dxc5
{ Black has made it into an opposite-colored bishop ending, but the draw isn't clear yet as his king is quite exposed, while the kingside pawns are vulnerable. An important point is that the king is stuck on a8 due to Bd6+. }
*

