11... Bd7
{ When I interacted with Giri on Twitter, he said: '11... Bd7, your move, Sebastian.' His point is that he thinks it's no longer necessary to go to a5 with the queen in order to stop a4-Ba3, because our bishop stands on f4 at this very moment. A natural way to proceed, of course. On chess24 I somehow forgot to mention this option, as I only focused on 10... Bd7. }
12. Qc1 O-O-O 13. g4
{ We don't waste any time and start our kingside advancement right away. }
13... Kb8 { It makes sense for Black to improve the position of his king. } 14.
Be2 Ka8 15. a4 { This move should be played if Black allows us to. } 15... Rhf8
{ Black's only sensible plan is to break through with f6 at some point. There are obviously many ways Black could play, when the play will be rather similar to what we saw in the previous chapter with Nh4-Be3/Bg3-f4, etc. Our queen should be placed on a3 as well. }
16. Qb2
{ This is a move played to annoy Black, with a lingering mating threat on b7. }
16... Qc8 { Black's queen moves out of the way to push f6. } 17. Rg1
{ I concluded that this was the best way to meet f6, as we often want to play g5 and open the g-file. }
17... f6 18. exf6 gxf6
{ Black sacrifices a pawn in order to keep the e5-square under control, while he hopes to eventually advance with e6-e5 to gain counterplay for the missing pawn. }
19. Bxh6 { We should accept the challenge and grab the pawn. } 19... Rg8 20.
Rg3
{ This peculiar move is the best path forward. It's a prophylactic move of sorts, as it's beneficial for us to cover the c3-square. I analyzed  20.Be3  which unfortunately leads to a forced draw after  20...e5  21.dxe5  fxe5  22.g5  Nf5  23.g6  d4  24.Bg5  Rde8  25.Bxc4  dxc3  26.Qxb7+  Qxb7  27.Rxb7  Kxb7  28.Bxg8  Rxg8  29.h6  Nxh6  30.Bxh6  and Black should hold. }
20... e5 21. dxe5 Bxg4 { Taking on g4 is critical. } 22. exf6 Nf5 23. f7
{ Forced, otherwise we'll lose material. } 23... Rgf8
{ The most accurate defense.   23...Rh8?!  So natural, but inaccurate.  24.Rxg4  Nxh6  25.Rf4  Rhf8  26.Ng5  It's important that we hang onto the f7-pawn for as long as we can!  26...Rd7  Black attacks the pawn and simultaneously defends against the threat of Ne6!  27.Qb5!  The only way to maintain our advantage is this move, with the point that d5 falls when Black takes on f7.  27...Nxf7   27...a6  28.Qc5  We maintain our attack on the d5-pawn.  28...Nxf7   Black needs to grab the pawn. There aren't really alternatives. For example  28...Re7  29.Rf6  Nxf7  30.Rxc6  Rxe2+  31.Kxe2  bxc6  32.Nf3  , when Black has saved the material but not the game as we'll break through on the queenside with  Rb6  ,  Qa5  and  Nd4  .  29.Nxf7  Rfxf7  30.Rxf7  Rxf7  31.Qxd5  We're winning due to the extra pawn and strong passer on h5.  31...Qg8  32.Rd1+-  We're protecting the queen so we can place our king on the f1-square next. Now it's all a matter of technique!  28.Nxf7  Qc7  29.Rf3  Qh2  Is a decent try for counterplay.  30.Ne5!  This move forces an endgame which is very close to winning.  30...Qg1+  31.Kd2  Qg5+  32.Re3  Nxe5  33.Qc5!  Targeting Black's rook on f8 while making sure that the rook can't leave the 8th rank due to the back rank mate on c8. We're also intending to play f4 followed by Qd4, trading queens.  33...Rdf7   33...Qh6  can also be tried, when we should play  34.Kc1!  with the idea of bringing the king safely to  b2  .  34.f4!  We need to get the queens off the board in order to win the game.  34...Qxf4   34...Rxf4  is refuted by  35.Qc7  , when the line goes  35...Nf3+  36.Bxf3  R3f7  37.Qe5  Qxe5  38.Rxe5  Rxf3  39.Rh1  and White wins.  35.Qd4±  Black has to trade queens and fight tooth and nail in order to save the game. It's almost winning, but almost is never enough... }
24. Bxf8
{ Necessary, as  24.Rxg4  Nxh6  is a much better version for Black of  23...Rh8  . }
24... Nxg3 25. fxg3 Rxf8 26. Ng5 { Keeping the pawn protected. } 26... Bxe2 27.
Kxe2 Nd8
{ Black has to immediately grab the pawn. This move is also better than  27...Ne5  , as Black also stops the mate on  b7  . }
28. Qb4 Nxf7 29. Nxf7 Rxf7 30. Re1 Qg4+ 31. Kd2 Qg5+ 32. Kd1 Qxh5+ 33. Kc1
{ When both sides play like a super computer it usually ends in a draw! However, we maintain a slight edge here due to our passer on g3 and Black's vulnerable pawns in the center. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "26. French Defense (1...e6) Winawer Modern Mainlines"]
[Black "Giri's 7...Qc7 (10...c4 4)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ We have finally arrived to the main bulk of our coverage on the French, and our very last topic to cover for Part 1! This is the Winawer Variation, named after Szymon Winawer and popularized later in the 1940s by the greats Nimzowitch and Botvinnik. Black pins the knight and thus attacks the pawn on e4 so we're forced to make a decision in the center. }
4. e5
{ This is by far the most challenging move against the Winawer. We're gaining additional space while we're also limiting Black's knight on g8 as it can no longer jump to f6. }
4... c5
{ Black's main move challenges our center immediately, a necessary course of action to obtain the desired counterplay on the queenside. }
5. a3
{ By far the most played move as this is the only way to maintain the strong pawn chain. }
5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Ne7 7. h4 Qc7 8. Rb1 Nbc6
{ This move looks very natural indeed, but there's a lot more to it than what initially meets the eye... The alternative option is Nepo's  8...b6  , which is the last thing we'll cover in this course! }
9. h5 { There's no reason for us to avoid including h5-h6. } 9... h6 10. Nf3 c4
{ Giri's suggestion is to close the position at once. } 11. Bf4
{ Our bishop develops to f4 so we can take control of the c1-h6 diagonal with Qc1. This makes the f6-break harder for Black to achieve, as the h6-pawn often ends up hanging. Another benefit is that it helps us prepare the break g4-g5, which Black won't be able to stop with f6 due to the aforementioned hanging pawn on h6. }
11... Bd7
{ When I interacted with Giri on Twitter, he said: '11... Bd7, your move, Sebastian.' His point is that he thinks it's no longer necessary to go to a5 with the queen in order to stop a4-Ba3, because our bishop stands on f4 at this very moment. A natural way to proceed, of course. On chess24 I somehow forgot to mention this option, as I only focused on 10... Bd7. }
12. Qc1 O-O-O 13. g4
{ We don't waste any time and start our kingside advancement right away. }
13... Kb8 { It makes sense for Black to improve the position of his king. } 14.
Be2 Ka8 15. a4 { This move should be played if Black allows us to. } 15... Rhf8
{ Black's only sensible plan is to break through with f6 at some point. There are obviously many ways Black could play, when the play will be rather similar to what we saw in the previous chapter with Nh4-Be3/Bg3-f4, etc. Our queen should be placed on a3 as well. }
16. Qb2
{ This is a move played to annoy Black, with a lingering mating threat on b7. }
16... Qc8 { Black's queen moves out of the way to push f6. } 17. Rg1
{ I concluded that this was the best way to meet f6, as we often want to play g5 and open the g-file. }
17... f6 18. exf6 gxf6
{ Black sacrifices a pawn in order to keep the e5-square under control, while he hopes to eventually advance with e6-e5 to gain counterplay for the missing pawn. }
19. Bxh6 { We should accept the challenge and grab the pawn. } 19... Rg8 20.
Rg3 { This peculiar move is the best path forward. } 20... e5 21. dxe5 fxe5
{ The position we have on the board is very complicated, as Black's strong center could quickly become very dangerous. }
22. Ng5 { Defending the pawn on g4 while threatening Nf7. } 22... Qc7
{ 22...Rde8?  Logical, but it loses to  23.Nf7  Qc7  24.Nd6!  The point! The knight can't capture due to the mate on b7!  24...Rb8  25.Nb5  Qa5  26.Be3  Black's center is no longer dangerous, so the extra pawn gives us a decisive advantage.  26...a6  27.Nd6  Qc7  28.Qa3+-  White is completely dominating. }
23. Nf7 Rb8
{ 23...Rde8  transposes to  22.Rde8  , when we saw that  24.Nd6  is really good for us. The text move guards  b7  and therefore prevents this idea. }
24. Qa3 Nc8 { Black must prevent the infiltration on d6. } 25. Bf8
{ We'll get to d6 no matter what! } 25... Bxg4
{ 25...Be6  can also be tried, when I think  26.Nh6  Rh8  27.g5  N8e7  28.Bxe7  Nxe7  29.a5  looks promising for us, with a6 coming. Later on we can progress with Rd1 followed by Qc1 and g6. }
26. Nd6 Qd7
{ 26...Be6  Is met by  27.Nb5  Qd8  28.Bg7+-  The pawn marches on to h6 when I don't think Black can save the game. }
27. Nb5 a6
{ Black needs to get some breathing space for the king.   27...b6  Leads to a favorable ending for us after  28.Bd6  Nxd6   28...Rb7  looks very passive after  29.Kd2  followed by  Rbg1  .  29.Qxd6  Qxd6  30.Nxd6  Be6  31.Kd2±  Our passed pawn grants us excellent winning chances in the ending. }
28. Qc5 { The queen controls the escape route on a7, so Bxg4 is now a threat. }
28... Rxf8 { The only move!  28...b6  29.Qxd5!  is a beautiful trick. } 29.
Qxf8 Bxe2 30. Kxe2 Qh7
{ Another only move. The queen moves to a defending post on the queenside, while allowing the other pieces to get out on the board. }
31. Kf1 N8e7 32. Qf3
{ Black has compensation, but needs to play pixel perfect in order to avoid losing. My analysis continued for 20 additional moves, but I must stop somewhere:  32...e4  33.Qh1  Nf5  34.Rg5  Nce7  35.Nc7+  Ka7  36.Qh2  Qh6  37.Qf4  Rf8  38.a5  Qf6  39.Kg2  e3  40.fxe3  Qxc3  41.Kg1  Qxc2  42.Rf1  c3  43.Qb4  Qd3  44.Qb6+  Kb8  45.Ne6  d4  46.Qxb7+  Kxb7  47.Nc5+  Kc6  48.Nxd3  dxe3  49.h6  Rh8  50.Rh5  Kd7  51.Rf3  Rxh6  52.Rxh6  Nxh6  53.Rxe3  and draw is imminent. A fun line! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "26. French Defense (1...e6) Winawer Modern Mainlines"]
[Black "Nepo's 7...Qc7 8...b6 10.Qg4 Alternate"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ We have finally arrived to the main bulk of our coverage on the French, and our very last topic to cover for Part 1! This is the Winawer Variation, named after Szymon Winawer and popularized later in the 1940s by the greats Nimzowitch and Botvinnik. Black pins the knight and thus attacks the pawn on e4 so we're forced to make a decision in the center. }
4. e5
{ This is by far the most challenging move against the Winawer. We're gaining additional space while we're also limiting Black's knight on g8 as it can no longer jump to f6. }
4... c5
{ Black's main move challenges our center immediately, a necessary course of action to obtain the desired counterplay on the queenside. }
5. a3
{ By far the most played move as this is the only way to maintain the strong pawn chain. }
5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Ne7 7. h4 Qc7 8. Rb1 b6
{ This is Nepo's choice in the Candidates, so we should take it seriously. We've seen the idea behind this move lots of times in our coverage. Black wants to play Ba6 and trade the 'French-bishop.' }
9. h5 { We will include h5 and h6, just like we did against Giri's line. } 9...
h6 10. Qg4
{ This was MVL's choice in the Candidates, and a rather thematic move, so this is obviously a critical choice. There are extensive analysis required for venturing into some of the madness that ensues. As this is an alternative, I will only provide some guidance along the way. }
10... Rg8
{ Nepo's choice in the Candidates.   10...Nf5?!  This is not the right approach to take.  11.Bb5+!  The idea with this move is the same as our mainline. Black needs to play a concession of some sorts, making the desired idea with Ba6 impossible.  11...Nc6  12.Nf3  Bd7  13.Bd3±   With a really comfortable game. A model game went  13...O-O  14.Qf4  f6  15.exf6  Qxf4  16.Bxf4  Rxf6  17.Ne5  Be8  18.Nxc6  Bxc6  19.Be5  with a strong positional advantage in Bartel, M - Petr, M Czech Republic 2016.   10...Kf8  Wesley So tried this move in a couple of blitz games. We've seen earlier how the casual sidestep to f8 tends to create strong attacking chances for us. This position is no exception.  11.Rh3!  The thematic rook swing is still holding up!  11...Ba6  12.Rf3  Threatening Qxe6.  12...Nf5  Is the engine's choice, when I suggest   12...cxd4?  Was Toma,K - Osmak,I Antalya 2019, but it's not a good idea as it allows us to correct our pawn structure for nothing in return.  13.cxd4  Nf5   13...Bxf1  14.Qxe6  works for us tactically.  14.Bxa6  Nxa6  15.Ne2  Qxc2  16.Rbb3!  The other rook joins the attack.  16...Kg8  17.Rbc3  Qa4  18.Rxf5!  A fantastic exchange sac.  18...exf5  19.Qxf5+-  Black's knight on a6 and rook on h8 are essentially completely out of the game. We will calmly improve our position with for example Qd3-Ng3-Nf5 with a devastating initiative.  13.Bxa6  Nxa6  14.Ne2±  Our attack looks promising, with thematic ideas such as Qf4, a4-Ba3, etc. We may push g4 in the future to remove the knight on f5.   10...cxd4  This move leads to crazy complications in Winawer style!  11.Qxg7  Rg8  12.Qxh6  Qxe5+  13.Ne2   13.Kd1!?  is also worth considering. White had some success with it in Motylev, A - Studer, N Tallinn 2019, as Black went wrong pretty much immediately.  13...dxc3   Black has to grab the pawn, as  13...Nbc6  14.cxd4  Nxd4  15.Qd2  Nxe2  16.Qxe2  is close to winning for us because of our h-pawn.  14.Bf4   The most dangerous approach. The three games I found went  14.Qf4  Qxf4  15.Bxf4  , but I don't think this is so testing for Black. One of the games was Caruana, F - Nepo, I chess24.com INT 2020.  14...Qe4  15.Rb4  Qxc2  16.Rh3  Targeting the pawn on c3.  16...e5!  17.Rxc3  Qf5  The point is that Black has untangled.  18.Ng3  Qe6!  Black has no choice but to head for an ending.  19.Qxe6  Bxe6  20.Bb5+  Bd7!  It's essential that Black can play Nbc6, otherwise he won't be able to untangle and stop our passer.  21.Bxe5  Nbc6!  Black barely makes it.  22.Bxc6  Nxc6  23.Rxc6!  The h-pawn marches in, so this is possible.  23...Bxc6  24.h6⩲  Black still needs to be accurate, but we can stop here. }
11. Bb5+
{ This thematic idea again. We're provoking one of the minor pieces to move, so Black can't play Ba6. }
11... Kf8
{ Nepo's solution is not to move any minor pieces at all! Giri also mentions this position, and he points out in his comments that he also took a look at the funky  11...Kd8!?  Indeed, this is a bizarre-looking move, but it's a viable alternative! I analyzed  12.Qf4  cxd4  13.Ne2  dxc3  14.Rb3  Nd7  15.Bxd7  Qxd7  16.Qxf7  Qe8  17.Qxe8+  Rxe8  18.Rxc3  with a clearly better ending for White. }
12. Bd3
{ MVL drops his bishop back to d3 now that it doesn't do anything on b5.   12.dxc5!?  is a pretty interesting alternative, with Giri stating that he's not comfortable with Black's position at all. The engine agrees... The text move is also decent though. }
12... Ba6 13. dxc5
{ MVL shows that he's well prepared. This is an excellent move, with a few points.   1: The b-file will be opened, so our rook on b1 becomes much stronger.   2: Black's counterplay in the c-file decreases.   3: Black will take on d3 one day, so the doubled pawns are a non-issue. }
13... Bxd3 14. cxd3 Nd7 15. d4 bxc5 16. Qd1
{ MVL's choice in MVL - Nepo, I Ekaterinburg 2020, however he also tried  16.Ne2  later in the Magnus Carlsen Invitational. I came across Romain Edouard's annotation on Chessbase, and I liked his take so much that I would like to share it below: 'Until now both players had spent little time and both seemed to be inside their home preparation. Engines give equality here, and online commentators claimed that Black is doing alright. Even Magnus Carlsen said: 'this is probably the best  ...Kf8  Winawer I have ever seen'. But I fully disagree with that assessment. White is behind in development but has a future for his pieces and especially his king, while Black doesn't have as long as queens are on the board. I definitely prefer White here.' I 100% agree with the Frenchman here. After all, there's a reason the guru himself, Anish Giri, discarded this option for Black! As we can see in our little alternative section, this is a very decent alternative for us. Let's now return to the text! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "26. French Defense (1...e6) Winawer Modern Mainlines"]
[Black "Nepo's 7...Qc7 8...b6 (10...Bd7)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ We have finally arrived to the main bulk of our coverage on the French, and our very last topic to cover for Part 1! This is the Winawer Variation, named after Szymon Winawer and popularized later in the 1940s by the greats Nimzowitch and Botvinnik. Black pins the knight and thus attacks the pawn on e4 so we're forced to make a decision in the center. }
4. e5
{ This is by far the most challenging move against the Winawer. We're gaining additional space while we're also limiting Black's knight on g8 as it can no longer jump to f6. }
4... c5
{ Black's main move challenges our center immediately, a necessary course of action to obtain the desired counterplay on the queenside. }
5. a3
{ By far the most played move as this is the only way to maintain the strong pawn chain. }
5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Ne7 7. h4 Qc7 8. Rb1 b6
{ This is Nepo's choice in the Candidates, so we should take it seriously. We've seen the idea behind this move lots of times in our coverage. Black wants to play Ba6 and trade the 'French-bishop.' }
9. h5 { We will include h5 and h6, just like we did against Giri's line. } 9...
h6 10. Bb5+
{ This move was a novelty when I gave it on chess24, but since then it has been tried! As mentioned previously, this move aims to provoke Black into developing a minor piece when Ba6 won't be possible. }
10... Bd7 11. Bd3
{ Now that Black can no longer trade bishops with Ba6, we can safely drop back to d3. }
11... Nbc6
{ Black attacks our pawn on  d4  and prepares the trick  12.Nf3  cxd4  13.cxd4  Nxd4!  followed by  Qc3+  .   11...Ba4!?  Is an interesting option for Black.  12.f4!   I had to spend some additional time in this position, when I discovered that my suggestion on chess24,  12.Rh3  , was totally fine for Black after  12...Nbc6  13.Nf3  c4  14.Be2  . The text move grabs extra terrain on the kingside, a plan we often utilize.  12...Nbc6  13.Nf3  c4  14.Be2  O-O-O  15.g4⩲  We're going to play Be3-Kd2-Nh4-Bf3-Qe2 and press for the f4-f5 break. Our king may even hide on the queenside with Kd2-Kc1-Kb2 if we feel like it. A complex struggle is ahead, but in a practical game I think it's easier to play White as our moves are quite straightforward. }
12. Qg4 { The natural way to respond to Black's threat. } 12... c4
{ This looks forced.  12...Rg8  runs into  13.Bh7  , when  12...Kf8  gives us the same excellent attack after  13.Rh3  . }
13. Be2 Rg8
{ Black can safely defend the pawn with the rook, now that there's no Bh7.   13...O-O-O ?  It's a big mistake to give the pawn on g7, but we must take a look at the line as it's quite concrete.  14.Qxg7  f6  This is Black's only chance, with the point  15.Qxf6  Nf5  When our queen is suddenly in grave danger.  16.g4!  The solution to the problem is a powerful queen sacrifice!  16...Rdf8  17.Qxf8+   17.Qg6  is possible, but this is even stronger.  17...Rxf8  18.gxf5  Rxf5  19.Bxh6  Be8  20.Be3+-  We're down material, but Black has serious problems dealing with our h-pawn which can freely march to h6. Black has to stop it with Qh7, when I think a plan such as Kd2-Bg4-Ne2-f3 looks very powerful. }
14. a4
{ This move is always in the air in these positions, and in this very position it's the best move. The point is of course to place the bishop in the juicy diagonal. }
14... O-O-O
{ If Black were to try  14...f6  , it's important to respond with  15.f4  , maintaining our center. }
15. f4
{ I think we should expand on our kingside as soon as possible. I gave  15.Ba3  on chess24, but during my revisit I discovered that Black is doing fine after  15...f6  16.Nf3  Rde8  17.Bd6  Qd8  18.Nh4  Kb7  19.Ng6  Nc8  20.Ba3  a5  with a complex game. }
15... Kb7
{ Black should wait a bit with playing  15...f6  now that we have played  f4  . A good response is  16.Bf3  Kb7  17.Ne2  , when our position looks promising with  Ba3  and  Kd2  coming next. }
16. Bf3 a5
{ Black is truly a Winawer-expert if he plays this move with the intention of placing the king on the hideout on a6. If Black just waits, our plan is straightforward as an arrow: Ne2-Kd2-Ba3-Qh4-g4-Rhg1 and crash through. }
17. Ne2 Ka6 18. Kd2 Na7 19. Ra1
{ We must defend our pawn, as the open a-file wouldn't benefit our position in any way whatsoever. }
19... Bc6
{ Black prepares to play  Qd7  and grab the pawn.  19...f6  only harms Black in this position, as the pawn on  e6  is weakened. }
20. Qh4 { Targeting Black's knight and preparing g4. } 20... Rde8 21. g4 Qd7
{ Black has no time to waste.  21...Nac8  looks too slow after  22.Ba3  Qd7  23.f5  Bxa4  24.Nf4  exf5  25.g5  with really strong play on the kingside. Black's extra pawn matters little. }
22. Ba3 Nec8
{ The right knight as Black's knight on a7 comes to life after Bxa4. } 23. g5
{ We must be quick in order to obtain sufficient counterplay. } 23... Bxa4 24.
gxh6
{ The alternative move  24.f5  is very dangerous as well, with the main line going  24.f5  hxg5  25.fxe6  Qd8  26.e7  Nxe7  27.Qxg5  Bc6  28.Bxe7  Rxe7  29.Rag1  with a lot of pressure. }
24... gxh6 25. f5 Nb5
{ 25...Rg5  is met by  26.f6!  when our bishop will return to  c1  . } 26. Bb2
Ne7
{ This move is Black's only viable move in the position. Other moves will allow f6, when our pawn chain will be way too strong.  26...exf5  is met by  27.Rxa4  . This is justified as Black's pawn on  d5  falls in the gunfire. }
27. f6
{ Amazingly enough, Black has more than enough compensation after  27.Rxa4  Nxf5  28.Qf2  Nbd6  29.Raa1  Ne4+  30.Bxe4  dxe4  . }
27... Nf5 28. Qh3 Nc7 29. Ra2
{ Black has a strong wall which will be tough to break down. I suggest to play Rha1 next, chasing Black's bishop away from a4 so we can re-route our king to f2. We will play Bg4 at some point, when Ke1-Kf2-Bc1 follows suit, when threats like Bxf5 followed by Bxh6 are suddenly possible. It's important to have the bishop present on the c1-h6 diagonal, in order to prevent Black from doubling the rooks in the g-file with Rg5. If you dislike this closed position, then 24. f5 is the alternative as mentioned earlier! }
