h6 10. Bb5+
{ This move was a novelty when I gave it on chess24, but since then it has been tried! As mentioned previously, this move aims to provoke Black into developing a minor piece when Ba6 won't be possible. }
10... Kf8
{ This move is in the style of Nepo. Black maintains the option of playing Ba6. }
11. Bd3 { Our bishop returns before Black is able to trap it with c4. } 11...
Ba6 12. Bxa6 Nxa6 13. Qd3 { Hitting the knight while developing our queen. }
13... Nb8
{ 13...c4  is the alternative, when it's once again a question of whether or not we can breakthrough. This will be covered in the last part of the course. }
14. Ne2
{ We don't want to place our knight on f3 as that would block the path to our f-pawn. Our play involves around the break f4-f5, so this is quite important. }
14... Nbc6 15. O-O
{ Not  15.f4?  when I don't think we can break through after  15...cxd4  16.cxd4  f5! }
15... Na5 { Is met by } 16. f4 Nc4
{ Now  16...cxd4  is met by  17.Nxd4!  when f5 follows suit with a really dangerous attack. }
17. g4 { Now Black needs to play the drastic } 17... cxd4 18. cxd4 f5
{ Before we'll completely overthrow him on the kingside. } 19. Ng3 Qd7 20. Rf2
{ I like our attacking chances here with the idea of playing gxf5 followed by Bd2, Rg2, Kh1 and Rg1. If Black is not careful, Re2 could potentially be deadly, with gxf5 followed by e6. }
