[Round "?"]
[White "26. French Defense (1...e6) Winawer Modern Mainlines"]
[Black "Nepo's 7...Qc7 8...b6 (10...Kf8 2)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ We have finally arrived to the main bulk of our coverage on the French, and our very last topic to cover for Part 1! This is the Winawer Variation, named after Szymon Winawer and popularized later in the 1940s by the greats Nimzowitch and Botvinnik. Black pins the knight and thus attacks the pawn on e4 so we're forced to make a decision in the center. }
4. e5
{ This is by far the most challenging move against the Winawer. We're gaining additional space while we're also limiting Black's knight on g8 as it can no longer jump to f6. }
4... c5
{ Black's main move challenges our center immediately, a necessary course of action to obtain the desired counterplay on the queenside. }
5. a3
{ By far the most played move as this is the only way to maintain the strong pawn chain. }
5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Ne7 7. h4 Qc7 8. Rb1 b6
{ This is Nepo's choice in the Candidates, so we should take it seriously. We've seen the idea behind this move lots of times in our coverage. Black wants to play Ba6 and trade the 'French-bishop.' }
9. h5 { We will include h5 and h6, just like we did against Giri's line. } 9...
h6 10. Bb5+
{ This move was a novelty when I gave it on chess24, but since then it has been tried! As mentioned previously, this move aims to provoke Black into developing a minor piece when Ba6 won't be possible. }
10... Kf8
{ This move is in the style of Nepo. Black maintains the option of playing Ba6. }
11. Bd3 { Our bishop returns before Black is able to trap it with c4. } 11...
Ba6 12. Bxa6 Nxa6 13. Qd3 { Hitting the knight while developing our queen. }
13... Nb8 14. Ne2
{ We don't want to place our knight on f3 as that would block the path to our f-pawn. Our play involves around the break f4-f5, so this is quite important. }
14... Nbc6 15. O-O Rc8
{ The logical attempt to get counterplay is creating something down the c-file. }
16. f4 Na5
{ Black prepares cxd4 followed by either Qxc3 or Qxc2, depending on how we recapture on d4.   16...f5?  Loses immediately due to the beautiful  17.exf6  gxf6  18.f5+-   When we breach Black's defenses.  18...e5  is met by  19.dxe5  Nxe5  20.Qg3  , followed by  Nf4  next. Our f5-pawn gives us a fantastic outpost on  e6  .   18...Nxf5  is simply met by  19.Nf4  . The pawn capture   18...exf5  is not hard to deal with either, when we can play  19.Ng3  and take on  f5  anytime. The capture will be even deadlier after Bd2-Rf2-Rbf1 with a massacre down the f-file. }
17. Bd2 Nc4
{ 17...cxd4?  Would now be very poor due to  18.cxd4!  Black may win the c-pawn, but our play in the c-file surpasses the extra pawn. Black's problem is the fact that he's too undeveloped. 18. Nxd4 would also be rather strong here, but the pawn capture just wins.  18...Qxc2   The only critical move. After  17...Nc4  Black would be busted after  18.Bb4  when we will capture on  e7  followed by f5-Nf4 next.  19.Qxc2  Rxc2  20.Bxa5  Rxe2   20...bxa5  is refuted by  21.f5!  when Black's poor coordination is excellently showed after  21...exf5  22.Nf4  Rc8  23.Rb7  . We can calmly start capturing Black's pawns. Black's only way to untangle would be to play  23...g5  , but then we can simply go  24.hxg6  fxg6  25.Rxa7  . Rfb1-Rbb7 comes soon.  21.Bb4  Rc2  22.Rfc1+-  Our infiltration in the c-file is deadly. For example:  22...Rc4  23.Rxc4  dxc4  24.Rc1  b5  25.a4  and Black can't stop us from breaking through, as  25...a6  is met by  26.axb5  axb5  27.Ra1  . }
18. Be1
{ Our bishop is ready to contribute to our kingside attack via h4, while g4-f5 is coming rapidly. Black needs to be very careful. }
18... Qd7 { Is a good attempt to start our investigation. Now I suggest: } 19.
g4 { To keep pushing for our breakthrough on the kingside. } 19... g6
{ Black can choose to play this move without the inclusion of cxd4 like in the main line. }
20. hxg6 fxg6 21. Bh4 { Suddenly there's a juicy square on f6 for our bishop. }
21... Rg8
{ Is a logical way to stop f5, but it's only temporary...   21...h5  Almost works for Black, but almost is never enough!  22.f5!!  We're annihilating Black in the f-file.  22...exf5  Also fails due to the same reason   22...gxf5  Is easily refuted by  23.gxf5  Rg8+  24.Kh2  Nxf5  25.Ng3+-  Black won't survive the onslaught.  23.gxf5  Nxf5  24.Ng3+-  Black will be waving the white flag soon. }
22. Kh1 Ke8
{ Note that after  22...h5  23.f5!  still does the trick.  23...gxf5  and now we must play  24.gxh5!  Black is lost as we'll quickly occupy the open g-file. I analyzed:  24...cxd4  25.cxd4  Qe8  26.Nf4  Rg4  27.Qh3  Qf7  28.Qxg4  fxg4  29.Nxe6+  Ke8  30.Rxf7  Kxf7  31.Ng5+  Kg7  32.Rf1  and White wins. Pretty nifty! }
23. Bf6
{ Placing our bishop in enemy territory. There's no need to rush f5, unless Black goes }
23... h5 { And now we should play } 24. f5 hxg4
{ Again,  24...gxf5  is met by  25.gxh5  . } 25. fxe6 Qxe6 26. Kg1
{ A really powerful prophylactic move, placing our king on a safe square. Nf4 followed by Rbe1 is soon coming with a deadly initiative.   A sample line is:  26...g3  27.Nf4  Qg4  28.Bxe7  g2  29.Rf3  Rh8  30.Qxg6+  Qxg6  31.Nxg6  Rh1+  32.Kxg2  Rxb1  33.e6  Rf1  34.Rh3  with a winning position. }
