[Round "?"]
[White "26. French Defense (1...e6) Winawer Modern Mainlines"]
[Black "Nepo's 7...Qc7 8...b6 (10...Kf8 3)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ We have finally arrived to the main bulk of our coverage on the French, and our very last topic to cover for Part 1! This is the Winawer Variation, named after Szymon Winawer and popularized later in the 1940s by the greats Nimzowitch and Botvinnik. Black pins the knight and thus attacks the pawn on e4 so we're forced to make a decision in the center. }
4. e5
{ This is by far the most challenging move against the Winawer. We're gaining additional space while we're also limiting Black's knight on g8 as it can no longer jump to f6. }
4... c5
{ Black's main move challenges our center immediately, a necessary course of action to obtain the desired counterplay on the queenside. }
5. a3
{ By far the most played move as this is the only way to maintain the strong pawn chain. }
5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Ne7 7. h4 Qc7 8. Rb1 b6
{ This is Nepo's choice in the Candidates, so we should take it seriously. We've seen the idea behind this move lots of times in our coverage. Black wants to play Ba6 and trade the 'French-bishop.' }
9. h5 { We will include h5 and h6, just like we did against Giri's line. } 9...
h6 10. Bb5+
{ This move was a novelty when I gave it on chess24, but since then it has been tried! As mentioned previously, this move aims to provoke Black into developing a minor piece when Ba6 won't be possible. }
10... Kf8
{ This move is in the style of Nepo. Black maintains the option of playing Ba6. }
11. Bd3 { Our bishop returns before Black is able to trap it with c4. } 11...
Ba6 12. Bxa6 Nxa6 13. Qd3 { Hitting the knight while developing our queen. }
13... Nb8 14. Ne2
{ We don't want to place our knight on f3 as that would block the path to our f-pawn. Our play involves around the break f4-f5, so this is quite important. }
14... Nbc6 15. O-O Rc8
{ The logical attempt to get counterplay is creating something down the c-file. }
16. f4 Na5 17. Bd2 Nc4 18. Be1
{ Our bishop is ready to contribute to our kingside attack via h4, while g4-f5 is coming rapidly. Black needs to be very careful. }
18... Qd7 { Is a good attempt to start our investigation. Now I suggest: } 19.
g4 { To keep pushing for our breakthrough on the kingside. } 19... cxd4
{ Black can insert this move before playing g6. } 20. cxd4
{ Normally we would take with the knight, but after  20.Nxd4  Nc6  Black is only slightly worse. }
20... g6 21. hxg6 fxg6 22. Bh4
{ It's the same strategy, it's all about placing the bishop on the juicy square on f6 and pushing f5 at some point. }
22... Rg8
{ If Black goes  22...Ke8  , I suggest the fine  23.Kf2!  intending playing  Bf6  and then  Rh1  when we get lots of play down the h-file. }
23. Kh1 Ke8 24. Rf2
{ It's rather beneficial for us to place our rook on a square where it can defend our forces after the opening of the files. Additionally, our useless rook on b1 may swing to g1 as well. }
24... h5 { This direct move is Black's best defense. } 25. f5 { Of course! }
25... exf5
{ 25...gxf5  would still be met by  26.gxh5  , while  25...hxg4  26.fxe6  Qxe6  27.Rf6  Qd7  28.Nf4  is winning for us, for example  28...g5  29.Qh7  gxh4  30.Rf7  . }
26. gxf5
{ The machine says that  26.Bg5  is even better, but that move looks insane to me! }
26... Nxf5 27. Bg5
{ Stopping a knight jump to e3. Now we're ready to play Rbf1 and even follow up with an exchange sac in some lines. We could also consider placing a rook on g1. }
27... Qc6 { Black prepares to escape with the king. } 28. Rbf1 Kd7 29. Ng3 Kc7
30. Nxf5 gxf5 31. Rxf5
{ We have managed to blast open the f-file, but in return Black has secured his king. }
31... Kb7 32. Rf7+ Ka6
{ It certainly looks tough to gain progress from here, but } 33. Qh7
{ Is very strong. Suddenly Black needs to guard a mate threat. } 33... Qa8
{ Black can also defend the pawn with the queen.   33...Ra8  Should be met by  34.Rxa7+  Rxa7  35.Qxg8+-  When our e-pawn creates problems for Black. It might be holdable, but it's not so easy.  35...Na5   The best defense. Most humans would consider  35...Nxa3  , but this loses after  36.e6  Qxc2  37.Qf8  and the pawn marches. Black has to sacrifice the knight with  37...Qe4+  38.Qf3  Qxe6  39.Qxa3+  Kb7  40.Qf3  , but it's lost.  36.Bf6  The g-file is opened, so now the queen could reach the defensive square on g2 if necessary.  36...Ra8  37.Qg2  Nc4  38.Rf3⩲  Black has decent chances to save the game, but he is not out of the woods yet. }
34. Rg1 Rcf8 35. Rd7 Rh8 36. Qe7 Rf3 37. a4
{ We're pressing as Black's queen is quite badly placed. A sample line:  37...Rhf8  38.Rg2  h4  39.Kh2  h3  40.Re2  Rg8  41.Bh6  Rh8  42.Qg7  Rd8  43.Qg4  Rxd7  44.Qxf3  Rh7  45.Qf8  Qc6  46.e6  Nd6  47.Bf4  Ne4  48.e7  Qc4  49.Rd2  Rxe7  50.Qxe7  Nxd2  51.Bxd2  Qf1  52.Qg5  Qf2+  53.Kxh3=  With perfect defense, Black has neutralized our initiative and should thus draw the game from here. }
