[Round "?"]
[White "26. French Defense (1...e6) Winawer Modern Mainlines"]
[Black "Nepo's 7...Qc7 8...b6 (10...Kf8 4)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ We have finally arrived to the main bulk of our coverage on the French, and our very last topic to cover for Part 1! This is the Winawer Variation, named after Szymon Winawer and popularized later in the 1940s by the greats Nimzowitch and Botvinnik. Black pins the knight and thus attacks the pawn on e4 so we're forced to make a decision in the center. }
4. e5
{ This is by far the most challenging move against the Winawer. We're gaining additional space while we're also limiting Black's knight on g8 as it can no longer jump to f6. }
4... c5
{ Black's main move challenges our center immediately, a necessary course of action to obtain the desired counterplay on the queenside. }
5. a3
{ By far the most played move as this is the only way to maintain the strong pawn chain. }
5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Ne7 7. h4 Qc7 8. Rb1 b6
{ This is Nepo's choice in the Candidates, so we should take it seriously. We've seen the idea behind this move lots of times in our coverage. Black wants to play Ba6 and trade the 'French-bishop.' }
9. h5 { We will include h5 and h6, just like we did against Giri's line. } 9...
h6 10. Bb5+
{ This move was a novelty when I gave it on chess24, but since then it has been tried! As mentioned previously, this move aims to provoke Black into developing a minor piece when Ba6 won't be possible. }
10... Kf8
{ This move is in the style of Nepo. Black maintains the option of playing Ba6. }
11. Bd3 { Our bishop returns before Black is able to trap it with c4. } 11...
Ba6 12. Bxa6 Nxa6 13. Qd3 { Hitting the knight while developing our queen. }
13... Nb8 14. Ne2
{ We don't want to place our knight on f3 as that would block the path to our f-pawn. Our play involves around the break f4-f5, so this is quite important. }
14... Nbc6 15. O-O Rc8
{ The logical attempt to get counterplay is creating something down the c-file. }
16. f4 Na5
{ Black prepares cxd4 followed by either Qxc3 or Qxc2, depending on how we recapture on d4. }
17. Bd2 Nc4 18. Be1
{ Our bishop is ready to contribute to our kingside attack via h4, while g4-f5 is coming rapidly. Black needs to be very careful. }
18... Rg8
{ Black prepares to play g6 and capture with the rook, but it's one move too slow! }
19. f5 { The pawn break comes just in time! } 19... Nxf5 20. Rxf5
{ A really powerful exchange sac. Black's kingside is too vulnerable without the defending knight, while the pawn on d5 also becomes a target. }
20... exf5 21. Qxf5 Re8 { Black stops us from playing e6/Ne6. } 22. Nf4 Rh8
{ The only viable way to dodge the mate threat. } 23. Bf2
{ Compare our knight on f4 to the stupid rook on h8! After Bf2, we're simply preparing Re1 followed by e6, when we'll break through. }
23... Kg8 24. Re1 Qb7
{ Black can't do anything about the pawn break other than making the damage as little as possible. After Qb7, Black defends the pawn on b7 at least. }
25. Re2
{ It is quite crazy, but this little waiting move wins the game. The point is that our rook is slightly better placed on e2 than on e1, and Black has no clear way to improve his position.   This is better than rushing with  25.e6  like I suggested on chess24, when Black somehow survives:  25...fxe6  26.Rxe6  Rf8  27.Qg6  Rxf4  28.Bh4  Ne3  29.Re7  Rf1+  30.Kh2  Qb8+  31.Bg3  Qf8  32.Re8  Rf6  33.Bd6  Qxe8  34.Qxe8+  Kh7  35.Qxe3  Rxd6  and Black is 'only' clearly worse. sigh }
25... Nxa3
{ Black's only chance is to grab the pawn.  25...Rf8  makes e6 less effective, but we can simply play  26.Qg4  followed by Qf3-Nxd5.  Bh4  will always come in case Black defends with  Rd8  . }
26. Bh4 Nb5 27. e6
{ Now it's time! exf7+ followed by Qxe8 and Ng6 is a very powerful threat. }
27... fxe6
{ 27...Nxc3  28.Re3  Nb5  We need to be accurate against this move. After all, Black is threatening to win a third pawn.  29.Nxd5!  Our attack is too powerful with ideas such as Ne7 and Nf6+ looming in the air.  29...Nd6  Is a better defensive move, but also refuted.   29...Nxd4  Should be met by  30.Qe4  When Black is really struggling against the threat of Nf6+.  30...Qc6  Looks necessary, when our attack is decisive after  31.exf7+  Kxf7  32.Qf4+  Kg8  33.Ne7+  Rxe7  34.Rxe7+-   34...Qd5  is met by  35.Qg4  , while   34...Kh7  is met by  35.Bf6  . The line goes:  35...Rg8  36.Kh2  Qd5  37.Qg4  Nf5  38.Qg6+  Kh8  39.Be5  and White wins.  30.Nf6+!  Open Black's king.  30...gxf6  31.Rg3+  Kf8  32.Qxf6  Rh7  It looks like Black is hanging on, but  33.d5!  Seals Black's fate! Black is in zugzwang!  33...Re7   Black prepares to chase away our queen with  Ne8  .  33...Ne4  would fail to  34.Qf5  Nxg3  35.Qxh7  when Black is forced to give the queen. A random waiting move like  33...a5  is met by  34.Qe5  , when  34...Qc7  35.e7+  Rxe7  36.Bxe7+  Qxe7  37.Rg8+  wins.  34.Bg5!  This is a funny move, but it allows us to enter Black's camp.  34...hxg5  35.Qxg5  Rc7  And now  36.Qg8+  Ke7  37.Re3+-  Wins the game. Such a beautiful final position. }
28. Qg6
{ Not  28.Nxe6??  when  28...Qd7!  29.Qg6  Nc7!  just wins. We have nothing! }
28... Qf7
{ A move like  28...Nc7  is too passive, when for example  29.Bf6  Rh7  30.Be5  gives us a decisive edge.  Bxc7  followed by a capture on  e6  comes next. }
29. Nxd5
{ Without this trick we wouldn't have had anything! Ne7+ followed by Bxe7 and Rxe6 is now a decisive threat. }
29... Nd6 30. Ne7+ Kf8 31. Rf2
{ White wins. The only way to prevent the queen loss is  31...Nf5  , but that allows the beautiful  32.Nxf5  Qxg6  33.hxg6  exf5  34.Rxf5+  Kg8  35.d5  , when Black's rook on  h8  is non-existent. Funny position. }
