9. h5 { We will include h5 and h6, just like we did against Giri's line. } 9...
h6 10. Bb5+
{ This move was a novelty when I gave it on chess24, but since then it has been tried! As mentioned previously, this move aims to provoke Black into developing a minor piece when Ba6 won't be possible. }
10... Kf8
{ This move is in the style of Nepo. Black maintains the option of playing Ba6. }
11. Bd3 { Our bishop returns before Black is able to trap it with c4. } 11...
Ba6 12. Bxa6 Nxa6 13. Qd3 { Hitting the knight while developing our queen. }
13... Nb8 14. Ne2
{ We don't want to place our knight on f3 as that would block the path to our f-pawn. Our play involves around the break f4-f5, so this is quite important. }
14... Nbc6 15. O-O Rc8
{ The logical attempt to get counterplay is creating something down the c-file. }
16. f4 Na5
{ Black prepares cxd4 followed by either Qxc3 or Qxc2, depending on how we recapture on d4. }
17. Bd2 Nc4 18. Be1
{ Our bishop is ready to contribute to our kingside attack via h4, while g4-f5 is coming rapidly. Black needs to be very careful. }
18... Rg8
{ Black prepares to play g6 and capture with the rook, but it's one move too slow! }
19. f5 { The pawn break comes just in time! } 19... Nxf5 20. Rxf5
{ A really powerful exchange sac. Black's kingside is too vulnerable without the defending knight, while the pawn on d5 also becomes a target. }
20... exf5 21. Qxf5 Ke8
{ Black tries to escape to the queenside. Note that  21...Rh8  22.Nf4  Re8  transposes to  21...Re8  , while  21...g5  is met by  22.hxg6  Rxg6  23.Nf4  when Black needs to return the exchange. }
22. Bh4
{ Our bishop takes control of some important squares in Black's camp, making e6 followed by Re1 a serious threat. }
22... Qd7
{ Black offers the trade of queens, but Qd7 takes away the escape route to d7. }
23. Qh7 { Luckily we can invade in this fashion. } 23... Rf8 24. Qxg7
{ It's time to start collecting pawns. } 24... Ne3
{ Black is in desperate need of counterplay, and this is a decent attempt as Black has moves like Qg4 or Nf5 coming our way. I also checked what happened in case Black defends h6 with   24...Rc6  , when I figured out that  25.dxc5!  just wins. The line goes  25...Rxc5  26.Nd4  Ne3  27.Qg3  Nf5  28.Nxf5  Qxf5  29.Rf1  Qe6  and we break through with  30.Rf6  . }
25. Qxh6 { Grabbing the pawn with a tempo. } 25... Nxg2
{ The strongest defense. Black forces us to head into an ending.  25...cxd4?  loses after  26.Qg5!  which prevents Qg4. Next, Nxd4 will follow, with for example Re1 and e6 to come.  25...Qg4  won't save the day either, as our attack after  26.Qxe3  Qxh4  27.Rf1  Qxh5  28.e6  is too strong. }
26. e6 { We can't allow the check on g4. } 26... Qxe6 27. Qxe6+ fxe6 28. Kxg2
cxd4 { And now it's important that we play } 29. Re1
{ With Nxd4 or Nf4 if Black moves the rook to h8 next.   29.Nxd4?  would be poor as Black's rook is really active after  29...Rxc3  . Looks drawish. }
