10... Kf8
{ This move is in the style of Nepo. Black maintains the option of playing Ba6. }
11. Bd3 { Our bishop returns before Black is able to trap it with c4. } 11...
Ba6 12. Bxa6 Nxa6 13. Qd3 { Hitting the knight while developing our queen. }
13... Nb8 14. Ne2
{ We don't want to place our knight on f3 as that would block the path to our f-pawn. Our play involves around the break f4-f5, so this is quite important. }
14... Nbc6 15. O-O Rc8
{ The logical attempt to get counterplay is creating something down the c-file. }
16. f4 Na5
{ Black prepares cxd4 followed by either Qxc3 or Qxc2, depending on how we recapture on d4. }
17. Bd2 Nc4 18. Be1
{ Our bishop is ready to contribute to our kingside attack via h4, while g4-f5 is coming rapidly. Black needs to be very careful. }
18... Rg8
{ Black prepares to play g6 and capture with the rook, but it's one move too slow! }
19. f5 { The pawn break comes just in time! } 19... Nxf5 20. Rxf5
{ A really powerful exchange sac. Black's kingside is too vulnerable without the defending knight, while the pawn on d5 also becomes a target. }
20... exf5 21. Qxf5 Ke8 22. Bh4
{ Our bishop takes control of some important squares in Black's camp, making e6 followed by Re1 a serious threat. }
22... Qc6 23. Qh7 Kd7
{ 23...Rf8  would now be hopeless after  24.Nf4  . Black has no counterplay. }
24. Rf1 { Targeting the now vulnerable pawn. } 24... Rcf8 25. a4
{ There are no words that can describe this breathtaking move. Black has no good moves! I'm sure you're curious about the point, though... And the point is highlighted in the line  25.Rf2  Qe6  26.Nf4  Qg4  27.Nxd5  Qxh4  28.Qd3  b5  ,  when the game is equal. However, this is not possible with the inclusion of a4! }
25... a5
{ This is actually the best move!  25...Ne3  looks logical, but after  26.Rf3  cxd4  27.Be1!  Black is busted. Be1's point is to prevent a capture on  c3  after  Nxd4  .  25...a6  doesn't help either, as we have  26.Rxf7!+  With  a4  and  a6  included, we have a much improved version over  25.Rxf7+  . After  26...Rxf7  27.Qxg8  Qe6  28.Qd8+  Kc6  29.Bg3  ,  Nf4  is coming next with devastating effect. }
26. Rf2
{ Another waiting move that improves our position. These nuances are stunning! }
26... Kc7
{ Black's best defense.   26...Ne3  Is still possible, when I suggest that we stick to the same procedure with  27.Rf3  cxd4  28.Be1  We're once again getting ready to capture on d4, now that we keep d4 protected with a fantastic attack.  28...Rh8   Is the engine's suggestion. I also looked at  28...Qe6  , but Black is in big trouble after  29.Bg3  Nc4  30.Nxd4  Qg4  31.Qd3  when our initiative is extremely powerful. For example:  31...Qe4  32.Qf1  f6  33.e6+  Kc8  34.Qb1  Kb7  35.Qb5  Rd8  36.Rf1  Ne3  37.Rf2  Nc4  38.Re2  Qg4  and now we finally break through with  39.e7  .  29.Qxg7  Qe6  30.Nf4  Qe7  Black is ready to play Rfg8, so we must escape with the queen.  31.Qg3  Nxc2  32.Nxd5  Qe6  33.c4!  Keeping the knight on d5.  33...f5  Black stops us from playing Rf6, but leaves the king even more open.  34.Qg7+!  The only path to victory.  34...Qf7  35.Rg3  This is such a crazy position, we're casually allowing an ending with an exchange down.  35...Kc6   Black's best practical chance is to get the king out of the way.  36.Rg6+  Kc5  37.Ne7!  Black's king is in trouble.  37...Kxc4  38.Rc6+  Kd3  It's rather peculiar, but after this move there's no way for us to checkmate the black king! Rest assured, we're winning, as Black can't defend without losing material.   38...Kb3  And now  39.Qg3+  Does the trick.  39...Ne3  40.Rxb6+  Ka3  41.e6  The queen's diagonal is closed, so Black is mated after  41...Qxe7  42.Qf2  Nc4  43.Rb1+-  When Black can't stop Ra1+ followed by Qa2#. }
27. Be7
{ This is the downside of moving the king, but Black simply has to accept the fact that f7 falls. }
27... Re8 28. Rxf7 Qe6
{ Black is just in time and forces a queen trade before we're able to prevent it with Nf4. }
29. Bd6+ Kd8
{ Black would lose after  29...Kc8  , due to  30.Rc7+  Kd8  31.Qd3  when our attack springs back to life. After  31...Nxd6  32.Rc6  c4  33.Qf3  Rgf8  34.Nf4  Black can resign. }
30. Bc7+ { Against other moves Black gets sufficient counterplay with Qg4. }
30... Kc8 31. Qg6 Qxg6 32. hxg6
{ And endgame is on the board where we have an exchange down, but in return have very active and powerful pieces. It's really hard for Black to neutralize our pressure. }
