[Black "Nepo's 7...Qc7 8...b6 (10...Kf8 7)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ We have finally arrived to the main bulk of our coverage on the French, and our very last topic to cover for Part 1! This is the Winawer Variation, named after Szymon Winawer and popularized later in the 1940s by the greats Nimzowitch and Botvinnik. Black pins the knight and thus attacks the pawn on e4 so we're forced to make a decision in the center. }
4. e5
{ This is by far the most challenging move against the Winawer. We're gaining additional space while we're also limiting Black's knight on g8 as it can no longer jump to f6. }
4... c5
{ Black's main move challenges our center immediately, a necessary course of action to obtain the desired counterplay on the queenside. }
5. a3
{ By far the most played move as this is the only way to maintain the strong pawn chain. }
5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Ne7 7. h4 Qc7 8. Rb1 b6
{ This is Nepo's choice in the Candidates, so we should take it seriously. We've seen the idea behind this move lots of times in our coverage. Black wants to play Ba6 and trade the 'French-bishop.' }
9. h5 { We will include h5 and h6, just like we did against Giri's line. } 9...
h6 10. Bb5+
{ This move was a novelty when I gave it on chess24, but since then it has been tried! As mentioned previously, this move aims to provoke Black into developing a minor piece when Ba6 won't be possible. }
10... Kf8
{ This move is in the style of Nepo. Black maintains the option of playing Ba6. }
11. Bd3 { Our bishop returns before Black is able to trap it with c4. } 11...
Ba6 12. Bxa6 Nxa6 13. Qd3 { Hitting the knight while developing our queen. }
13... Nb8 14. Ne2
{ We don't want to place our knight on f3 as that would block the path to our f-pawn. Our play involves around the break f4-f5, so this is quite important. }
14... Nbc6 15. O-O Rc8
{ The logical attempt to get counterplay is creating something down the c-file. }
16. f4 Na5
{ Black prepares cxd4 followed by either Qxc3 or Qxc2, depending on how we recapture on d4. }
17. Bd2 Nc4 18. Be1
{ Our bishop is ready to contribute to our kingside attack via h4, while g4-f5 is coming rapidly. Black needs to be very careful. }
18... g6 { Black's best choice is to go for this move right away. } 19. hxg6
fxg6 20. dxc5
{ This move is quite strong as it forces Black to give up his counterplay in the c-file or give away the square on d4. }
20... bxc5
{ 20...Qxc5?  looks terrible after  21.Nd4  . For example  21...Kf7  22.Bh4  Nf5  23.Rb5  Qc7  24.Nxf5  gxf5  25.Rxd5!!  and White wins. }
21. Bf2
{ Playing against Black's c5-pawn, so Black needs to be on the lookout for moves like Rb5. }
21... a6
{ Blacks stops our idea of playing Rb5, but this move allows for another beauty in }
22. f5 exf5
{ 22...Nxf5  fails to  23.g4  , while  22...gxf5  gives us a decisive attack after  23.Nf4  Kf7  24.Bh4  Rhg8  25.Qh3  , when  Bxe7  followed by  Nxe6  is lurking around the corner. }
23. Bh4 { A really strong move, aiming against Black's defensive piece on e7. }
23... g5
{ It's logical to stop the bishop from completing its mission. Note that  23...Nxe5  loses to  24.Qxa6  .   23...Qxe5?  Loses for several reasons, for example  24.Nf4  When Rbe1 comes.  24...Qe3+  Forces a queen trade, but it's all for nothing as  25.Qxe3  Nxe3  26.Rf3  g5  27.Rxe3  gxh4  28.Rb7+-  Is hopeless. }
24. Ng3 { We have found ourselves a new target, namely the f5-pawn! } 24... f4
25. Nh5
{ Black is toast, as there's nothing he can do from stopping a powerful sac on the pawn on f4 with a massacre. }
25... Ke8 { Black's best try. } 26. e6
{ A strong move, taking control of additional squares in Black's camp. } 26...
gxh4
{ It's fair to ask what happens if Black captures the hanging piece...   26...Qc6  And now the move  27.Rxf4!!  Is a rather stunning blow!  27...gxf4  And now the trick is  28.Nf6+  Kf8  29.Nxd5+-  When Black has no defense.   26...Ne3  I remember looking at this position when I recorded my video series on chess24, wondering what happened in case Black went for this logical move, defending d5?  27.Qxa6  Is the answer, when  27...Nxf1  28.Rb7  Leads to the very stunning line  28...Qe5  29.Qb5+  Nc6   Only move, as  29...Kf8  30.Rxe7  loses on the spot.  30.Qe2!!  A stunning tactical shot. Black is mated in case he takes the queen!  30...Ne3   The best move is  30...Rc7  , but this loses very easily after  31.Qxe5  Nxe5  32.Rxc7  Kd8  33.Ra7  , when Black can't defend both the rook and the knight on  f1  .  31.Nf6+!!  Another point with Qe2!  31...Qxf6  32.Qh5+  And Black can resign in view of  32...Kf8  33.Rf7+  . A breathtaking sequence. }
27. Nf6+ Kf8
{ 27...Kd8  is hopeless after  28.Nxd5  Nxd5  29.Qxd5+  Nd6  30.Qe5  Rf8  31.Rfd1  Ke7  32.Rxd6  Qxd6  33.Rb7+  . }
28. Rbe1
{ The point of this move is to support the pawn, while preventing defensive resources such as Ne3 or Ne5. }
28... Rd8 { Black stops the fork on d7 and is now ready to play Ne5. } 29. Nh5
Ne5 30. Rxf4+ Kg8 31. Qh3
{ Black can't defend the attack, for example  31...Rf8   31...N7g6  32.Rf6  Kh7  33.Rxe5  Nxe5  34.Qf5+  Kg8  35.Rg6+  Nxg6  36.Qxg6+  Kf8  37.Qf6+  Kg8  38.e7+-  And Black is mated.  32.Rg4+  N5g6  33.Rxg6+  Nxg6  34.e7  Nxe7  35.Qg4+  Kf7  36.Rf1+  Ke8  37.Ng7+  Kd8  38.Ne6+  Kc8  39.Nxc7+  Kxc7  40.Re1+-  With material up with a strong attack, White is completely winning. }
