fxg6 20. dxc5
{ This move is quite strong as it forces Black to give up his counterplay in the c-file or give away the square on d4. }
20... bxc5
{ 20...Qxc5?  looks terrible after  21.Nd4  . For example  21...Kf7  22.Bh4  Nf5  23.Rb5  Qc7  24.Nxf5  gxf5  25.Rxd5!!  and White wins. }
21. Bf2
{ Playing against Black's c5-pawn, so Black needs to be on the lookout for moves like Rb5. }
21... Qc6 22. a4 { Maintaining the threat of placing a rook on b5. } 22... a6
{ Taking the pawn on a4 would allow an invasion on the 7th rank, so Black can't do that. }
23. Nc1
{ Our knight is on it's way to b3 where it will target the pawn on c5. } 23...
Kf7 { Black coordinates the rooks. } 24. Qe2
{ Our queen moves out of the way before we go Nb3. } 24... Nf5
{ Black can't do anything about the pawn, and aims for counterplay. } 25. Nb3
h5 26. Nxc5 Ng3
{ Believe it or not, this move right here 'forces' the game into a draw! I was so blown away that I couldn't even be upset when I discovered this. Such is the game of chess, it's tough to win! }
27. Qd3 { This move is very strong, as the queen targets Black's pawn on g6. }
27... Nxf1 28. Rb7+
{ And now the point behind our little trick is shown after } 28... Rc7 29.
Rxc7+ Qxc7 30. Nxe6 { Really flashy stuff! Black loses a lot of pawns. } 30...
Kxe6 31. Qxg6+ Kd7 32. Qg7+ Kc6 33. Qxh8 Nfe3
{ This knight jump is important, as  33...Nfd2  allows  34.f5! } 34. Qh6+ Kb7
35. Qxh5
{ We have a lot of pawns for the missing piece, but it turns out that it's not possible to win in case Black plays all the best moves.   35...Qd7!!  The only defensive move that holds. Don't ask me why...  36.a5!  Keeping the pawn.   36...Qe6!  Another necessity, believe it or not.  37.Qh7+  Kb8  38.Qg7!  This move puts Black in a sort of zugzwang. But...  38...d4!!  Somehow works out for Black...  39.cxd4  Qd5  The computer shows +4 but it realizes that it is a draw moments later.  40.Qf8+  Kb7!!   This move is the only move, for a pretty funny reason. The point being that  40...Kc7??  fails to  41.Bxe3  Nxe3  42.Kf2  Qxd4  43.Qd6+  when we're forcing the trade of queens.  42...Nc4  is forced, but after  43.c3  Nxa5  44.g4  , our pawns are unstoppable.  41.Bxe3  Nxe3  42.Qb4+  Ka8!  Another only move.  43.Kf2  Qe4!  And another one...  44.Qf8+  Kb7  45.Qf7+  Kc8!  46.Qe8+  Kc7  47.Qf7+  Kc8  48.e6  Nf5!  Black stops our king from moving to g3.  49.Qe8+  Kc7  50.Qd7+  Kb8  51.Qd8+  Kb7  52.Qb6+  Kc8!!  53.Qxa6+  Kd8!!  White is not able to play  Qe5  in time.  54.Qb6+  Kc8!!  Black stops us from checking ourselves to the e5-square.  55.Qc5+  Kd8  56.Qe5  Qxc2+  57.Kf3  Qd1+!!  And Black draws after  58.Ke4  Qc2+  59.Kf3  Qd1+=  It's safe to say that winning in chess is tough! }
