{ The point behind this move is to infiltrate Black's camp with Qf4, but this obviously depends on what Black does. Nf3 is also in the air, of course. Another point with Qe3 is that it keeps Black's queen on a1 for now. }
23... Kf8 24. Rb7
{ We must move to  b7  , as  24.Rc7  places our rook in front of our passed pawn. }
24... Nf7 25. Qf4 Rh7 { Black defends against mating threats, but } 26. c6
{ Poses another question to Black. What should he do with our passer? } 26...
e5
{ Black's best try is to get the queen back into the game.  26...Rc8  would be met by the simple  27.Nf3  ,  when the knight jumps to e5 next. }
27. Qf6 Qd4+ 28. Ke1 Qg4
{ The queen controls some squares, but it doesn't help... } 29. Nf3 Kg8
{ The pawn can't be stopped after  29...Qe4+  30.Kf1  Qd3+  31.Kg1  Qd1+  32.Kh2  Qxc1  33.c7  . }
30. c7 { The marches on. The sophisticated  30.Bxh6  also wins. } 30... Qc8 31.
Qc6 { We must obviously defend our rook. } 31... Nd6 32. Qxd5+ Rf7
{ Our rook is almost trapped, but. .. } 33. Rb8 { Leads to victory after }
33... Rxb8 34. cxb8=Q Qxb8 35. Nxe5 { With a winning position. } *

