{ By far the most played move as this is the only way to maintain the strong pawn chain. }
5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Ne7 7. h4 Qc7 8. Rb1 b6
{ This is Nepo's choice in the Candidates, so we should take it seriously. We've seen the idea behind this move lots of times in our coverage. Black wants to play Ba6 and trade the 'French-bishop.' }
9. h5 { We will include h5 and h6, just like we did against Giri's line. } 9...
h6 10. Bb5+
{ This move was a novelty when I gave it on chess24, but since then it has been tried! As mentioned previously, this move aims to provoke Black into developing a minor piece when Ba6 won't be possible. }
10... Kf8
{ This move is in the style of Nepo. Black maintains the option of playing Ba6. }
11. Bd3 { Our bishop returns before Black is able to trap it with c4. } 11...
Ba6 12. Bxa6 Nxa6 13. Qd3 { Hitting the knight while developing our queen. }
13... c4
{ The last question we must ask ourselves! Can we break through if Black closes the position? }
14. Qf3
{ The queen heads to f3 where it contributes greatly to the kingside attack. }
14... Qc6 15. Rh4
{ Our rook is heading to f4 where it will cause problems for the black monarch. }
15... Ke8
{ Is Black's best move, and indeed it's not so hard to see why. Black's rook on h8 gets additional squares, while the king can bail to the queenside if necessary.   15...Kg8  This is a zero-fun position for Black.  16.g4  Qa4  17.Kd1  Nc7  18.Ne2→  With a really dangerous attack as g5 is coming soon. }
16. Rf4 Rf8 17. Qg3
{ Our queen moves so our knight can jump to f3. Black's position looks like a really sad scheme, as there's barely any queenside counterplay. }
17... Rg8 18. Nf3 Nc7 19. Nh2
{ Our knight moves again, with the destination being e3 via g4/ f1. } 19... Qa4
{ 19...Nf5  would be rather pointless after  20.Qf3  when we're ready to push it away with g4 in the next move. }
20. Kd2 { Our king takes care of the black queen's shenanigans. } 20... Na6 21.
Nf1 Rc8 22. Ne3
{ Our knight has reached its destination. I analyzed three options here for Black, but it seems like it's almost impossible to get any counterplay. }
22... Nb8
{ I analyzed this move as well, but placing the knight on c6 won't change much for Black.   22...Rc6  Is one of those moves that doesn't do anything.  23.Bb2  Rc8  24.Rh1  We're simply improving our pieces. Our queenside rook will join the attack!  24...Qb5  25.Kc1  Qd7  26.Rhh4  Nc7  27.Rhg4+-   And Black's defenses fall apart. For example  27...Kf8  28.Qf3  Nc6  29.Rxf7+  Qxf7  30.Rf4  .   22...b5  Is another approach, but our kingside play is way faster.  23.Rg4  Kf8  24.f4!  It's time to start launching the f-pawn towards Black's king!  24...Nc7  25.Qf3  Nf5  Black's only way to stop f5, but it doesn't help.  26.Nxf5  exf5  27.Rh4+-  There is another pawn breakthrough on the cards, namely g4! Our attack plays itself. Black has no counterplay. }
23. Rg4 Kf8 24. Rb4
{ A pretty neat idea, forcing the black queen away so we can play a4 and open the diagonal for our bishop. }
24... Qa6 25. a4
{ Black will win the pawn on a4, but it won't matter as our bishop on a3 is extremely strong. }
25... Nbc6 26. Rb1 Qxa4 27. Bb2
{ Black can't stop us from completing our plan. } 27... Qa6 28. Ra1 Qb7 29. Ba3
{ f4-f5 is coming really quickly.   When Black plays  29...b5  , we should respond with  30.Bc5  Black has nothing. }
