[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "26. French Defense (1...e6) Winawer Modern Mainlines"]
[Black "Nepo's 7...Qc7 8...b6 (13...c4 4)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ We have finally arrived to the main bulk of our coverage on the French, and our very last topic to cover for Part 1! This is the Winawer Variation, named after Szymon Winawer and popularized later in the 1940s by the greats Nimzowitch and Botvinnik. Black pins the knight and thus attacks the pawn on e4 so we're forced to make a decision in the center. }
4. e5
{ This is by far the most challenging move against the Winawer. We're gaining additional space while we're also limiting Black's knight on g8 as it can no longer jump to f6. }
4... c5
{ Black's main move challenges our center immediately, a necessary course of action to obtain the desired counterplay on the queenside. }
5. a3
{ By far the most played move as this is the only way to maintain the strong pawn chain. }
5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Ne7 7. h4 Qc7 8. Rb1 b6
{ This is Nepo's choice in the Candidates, so we should take it seriously. We've seen the idea behind this move lots of times in our coverage. Black wants to play Ba6 and trade the 'French-bishop.' }
9. h5 { We will include h5 and h6, just like we did against Giri's line. } 9...
h6 10. Bb5+
{ This move was a novelty when I gave it on chess24, but since then it has been tried! As mentioned previously, this move aims to provoke Black into developing a minor piece when Ba6 won't be possible. }
10... Kf8
{ This move is in the style of Nepo. Black maintains the option of playing Ba6. }
11. Bd3 { Our bishop returns before Black is able to trap it with c4. } 11...
Ba6 12. Bxa6 Nxa6 13. Qd3 { Hitting the knight while developing our queen. }
13... c4
{ The last question we must ask ourselves! Can we break through if Black closes the position? }
14. Qf3
{ The queen heads to f3 where it contributes greatly to the kingside attack. }
14... Qd7 { I also checked this move. } 15. Rh4
{ Our plan doesn't change. Now Black should once again choose the placement of the king. }
15... Kg8 { I remain yet again rather unimpressed with this move. } 16. Ne2
{ We keep developing. Our plan is simple, we'll play g4-g5 at the right circumstances. }
16... Rf8
{ 16...Qa4  17.Kd1  Rf8  Should be met by  18.g4→   With a deadly initiative.  18...f6  looks forced, but we can just go  19.exf6  Rxf6  20.Bf4  with a fantastic position. Black's pawn on  e6  is weak, while he's struggling on the dark squares.  g5  could come as well, but it should be prepared first. }
17. Ra1
{ This looks a bit strange, but the point is that we threaten to play a4, making the black queen move there to stop it. }
17... Qa4
{ 17...f6?  Looks dreadful after  18.exf6  Rxf6  19.Rf4  Rxf4  20.Bxf4+-  When we're in full control. }
18. Kd1 { Our king takes control of Black's threats. } 18... Nc7 19. g4
{ It's time to start playing for the pawn breakthrough on the kingside. } 19...
Nb5 20. g5 { There's no need to wait with the pawn break. } 20... Nf5 21. Rg4
hxg5 22. Rxg5
{ We have a really dangerous attack, while Black has pretty much no counterplay on the kingside. Soon we may consider an exchange sac on f5, followed by for example Ng3-Nxf5.   A sample line is:  22...Rh7  23.Bd2  Re8  24.h6  g6  25.Rxf5  exf5  26.Nf4  Nc7  27.Nxd5  Nxd5  28.Qxd5  Re6  29.Bg5  , with a winning position. Our bishop is way stronger than Black's terrible rook on  h7  . }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "26. French Defense (1...e6) Winawer Modern Mainlines"]
[Black "Nepo's 7...Qc7 8...b6 (13...c4 5)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ We have finally arrived to the main bulk of our coverage on the French, and our very last topic to cover for Part 1! This is the Winawer Variation, named after Szymon Winawer and popularized later in the 1940s by the greats Nimzowitch and Botvinnik. Black pins the knight and thus attacks the pawn on e4 so we're forced to make a decision in the center. }
4. e5
{ This is by far the most challenging move against the Winawer. We're gaining additional space while we're also limiting Black's knight on g8 as it can no longer jump to f6. }
4... c5
{ Black's main move challenges our center immediately, a necessary course of action to obtain the desired counterplay on the queenside. }
5. a3
{ By far the most played move as this is the only way to maintain the strong pawn chain. }
5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Ne7 7. h4 Qc7 8. Rb1 b6
{ This is Nepo's choice in the Candidates, so we should take it seriously. We've seen the idea behind this move lots of times in our coverage. Black wants to play Ba6 and trade the 'French-bishop.' }
9. h5 { We will include h5 and h6, just like we did against Giri's line. } 9...
h6 10. Bb5+
{ This move was a novelty when I gave it on chess24, but since then it has been tried! As mentioned previously, this move aims to provoke Black into developing a minor piece when Ba6 won't be possible. }
10... Kf8
{ This move is in the style of Nepo. Black maintains the option of playing Ba6. }
11. Bd3 { Our bishop returns before Black is able to trap it with c4. } 11...
Ba6 12. Bxa6 Nxa6 13. Qd3 { Hitting the knight while developing our queen. }
13... c4
{ The last question we must ask ourselves! Can we break through if Black closes the position? }
14. Qf3
{ The queen heads to f3 where it contributes greatly to the kingside attack. }
14... Qd7 { I also checked this move. } 15. Rh4
{ Our plan doesn't change. Now Black should once again choose the placement of the king. }
15... Ke8
{ If Black heads to the queenside, I suggest once again that we play } 16. Rf4
Rf8 17. Qg3
{ Black's queen placement doesn't change our procedure. Nf3-Nh4-Rg4 is the plan, when Black will have serious problems defending without making a serious concession. }
17... Rg8 18. Nf3 Nc7
{ 18...Rc8?  Would allow us to easily carry out our plan with  19.Nh4  Nc7  20.Rg4  Everything falls apart for Black, for example,  20...Kg7  21.Rxg7  Rxg7  22.Bxh6  . }
19. Kd1
{ This prophylactic move is nice to throw in, as it covers Black's targets on the queenside. Going for  19.Nh4  right away is possible as well, but I dislike that Black complicates the game after  19...g5  20.hxg6  fxg6  21.Qf3  Nf5  . }
19... Nf5
{ And here I found a beautiful exchange sac   19...Rc8  Is now met by  20.Nh4!  We take control of the f5-square and aim to go Rg4 next, so Black should play  20...g5  21.hxg6  fxg6  Black has saved the pawn for the prize of weakening his kingside.  22.Rf6  g5  23.Nf3  Black is struggling a lot with the exposed kingside, for example  23...Kd8  24.Qh2!  Our queen targets h6 while moving out of the fork on f5.  24...g4   24...Nf5  fails to  25.g4  .  25.Nh4+-  Black's exposed kingside gives him a miserable position. }
20. Rxf5 { With the point that we win a pawn after } 20... exf5 21. Bxh6
{ Black's pawn on f5 is rather weak, while the absence of the h6-pawn allows us to gain additional control of the dark squares by playing h6 at some point. Black's rooks do not have any open files, so here they're not significant. }
21... Ne6 22. Nh4
{ We maintain our pressure and immediate target Black's weak pawn on f5. }
22... Kf8 23. Bg5 Rh8
{ Black wins the h-pawn, but it doesn't matter as our bishop becomes a beast after }
24. h6 gxh6 25. Bf6 Rg8 26. Qf3
{ A strong move, intending Qh5-Qxh6, while targeting f5. } 26... Ng5 27. Qh5
Ne4
{ Black has re-routed the knight to the e4-square, but we're still much better after }
28. Qxh6+ Ke8 29. Qh7 Rf8 30. Nxf5 Qc6
{ Black creates an escape route for the king.  30...Nxc3+  would fail to  31.Kc1  Qc7  32.Nd6+  Kd7  33.Qh3+  Kc6  34.Qxc3  . }
31. Nd6+ { The simplest, winning back the exchange by force. } 31... Nxd6 32.
exd6 Qxd6 33. Bg7
{ Black has to fight hard for a draw in the ending that ensues as he's a pawn down. A sample line is:  33...Kd7  34.Bxf8  Rxf8  35.Qg7  Qe7  36.a4  Re8  37.Qg4+  Kc7  38.Kd2  . }
