[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "27. Model Games"]
[Black "1. Mihajlov, Sebastian vs. Al Tarbosh, Ward"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 b6 2. d4 Bb7 3. Nc3 e6 4. Bd3 Bb4 5. Ne2 d5 6. e5 Be7
{ When I prepared for my game, I was thrilled when I saw that my opponent played 1... b6 now and then. The line can be annoying for the unprepared player, but due to the making of this very course I certainly had a huge advantage right of the bat, aside from being the rating favorite. My opponent had blitzed out every single move, including this one, so apparently he also had a sense of what was going on! 6... Be7 prepares for c5, while the bishop is covering the d6-square. The con is that the bishop prevents the knight on g8 from developing to e7, meaning that the knight would have to find a home on h6 if it wants to contribute to the game. I had to find a way to meet the annoying c7-c5 though, so that begs the question, how do we react? }
7. Nb1
{ Knowing well that it's desirable to maintain the strong pawn structure, it wasn't difficult for me to come up with this move. With the knight gone from c3, we can now defend Black's pawn break perfectly with c2-c3. The knight on b1 can find a new home on the square on f3, by jumping to d2. }
7... c5 8. c3 Nc6
{ I was slightly surprised by this move, as I expected Black to prepare Ba6 by playing   8...Qd7  . A natural reaction would have been  9.Nd2  , followed by either  Bxa6  or  Bc2  . Both options are good. Black is struggling with the development of his pieces, so we can already claim a clearly better game. }
9. Be3
{ Now that I am analyzing my game, I am slightly puzzled why I didn't go for the more natural  9.O-O  or  9.Nd2  . The bishop isn't badly placed on  e3  by any means though, as it controls the g1-a7 diagonal. }
9... Qd7
{ Black prepares to castle queenside in the foreseeable future, while also preventing a check on b5 or a4. }
10. O-O
{ Developing is natural, but  10.Nd2  is more accurate! I was scared of  10...cxd4  11.cxd4  Nb4  12.Bb1  Ba6  13.Nf3  Qb5  , but apparently I have everything under control after  14.Nc1  as I am ready to push away Black's knight with  a3  next. }
10... f6
{ Against  10...cxd4  I was certain that I was better after  11.cxd4  Nb4  12.Nbc3  , which is true. An even better move is  11.Bxd4  , when I can claim a pretty nice edge, going for a quick  f4  . }
11. f4 Nh6
{ I was not so happy with what I had achieved out of the opening, as Black has somehow almost completed his development while having decent control of the light squares. Besides, I need to waste a tempo defending the threat of Ng4, something that wouldn't have been an issue if I had played Nd2 first. }
12. Ng3 O-O-O
{ My opponent has a sharp style of playing and castled queenside without hesitation, however it's a poor choice. The problem is that Black kills his queenside potential  @@StartBracket@@cxd4 followed by Rc8, Nb4 etc@@EndBracket@@, while the attack on the kingside is far from being anything remotely close to dangerous.   After  12...O-O  , I guess I would have played  13.a3  to stop  Nb4  . Black is still worse, but the position is very much acceptable after for example  13...fxe5  14.fxe5  Rxf1+  15.Bxf1  . }
13. Nd2 f5
{ Black takes control over the g4-square and prepares a g7-g5 break in the future. }
14. Kh1
{ Dealing with the threat of Ng4 as it frees g1 for our bishop.   Nothing is wrong with  14.h3  , but I want to abstain from making any unnecessary concessions in my camp. }
14... Ng4
{ I was a bit surprised by the fact that Black played this move so quickly, as I can easily kick away the knight with h3. But then, I discovered that Black can actually sac the piece...   14...Nf7  is more sensible, but I am definitely better after }
15. Bg1 h5
{ My opponent stays faithful to his style, as Black can leave the knight hanging on g4 due to the opening of the h-file. }
16. h3 Kb8 17. Nf3
{ At this point I felt that I had regained some control and that the game was going my way. My pieces are well placed and I have complete control over Black's forces on the kingside. I'm also enjoying a nice space advantage. }
17... Rdg8
{ Black wants to play  g5  as soon as possible to open the g-file.  17...g6  attempts to keeps things blocked, but after  18.dxc5  bxc5  19.Ne2  My initiative on the queenside commences, while Black has nothing on the kingside. }
18. Ne2 g5
{ This move loses, but what else?  18...c4  is the lesser evil, but after  19.Bc2  I can use the c4-pawn as a hook and open the queenside with  b3  . }
19. fxg5
{ My engine tells me that  19.Bb5  is even stronger, but that move was beyond my imagination. }
19... Bxg5 20. Nxg5 Rxg5 21. Nf4
{ Black has opened the g-file, but the knight on f4 is perfectly placed to deal with the threats. }
21... Rhg8
{ A brave decision, leaving the knight up for grabs.  21...Ne7  is better, but the situation is dire after  22.Qd2  Rg7  23.a4  c4  24.Be2  Nc6  25.b4  . }
22. hxg4
{ I couldn't help myself and grabbed the material. It's correct, but a move like  22.Qd2  might be even stronger as Black has no follow-up. As stated before, the attack isn't there. }
22... hxg4 23. g3
{ Sealing the knight on f4 and preparing an escape route for the king. } 23...
Nxe5 { Black makes use of the strong bishop on b7. } 24. Qe2
{ This move diminishes my edge by over one pawn, as I completely missed Black's pretty incredible resource.  24.Re1!  wins, as Black doesn't have anything after  24...Nf3  25.Rxe6  . }
24... Nxd3 25. Nxd3
{ One piece left to deal with, so I was sure I was completely winning. My opponent was also running out of time, having only minutes left. }
25... f4
{ The right idea, but not the most accurate execution. Starting with  25...Qh7+  is the most accurate, as  26.Kg2  f4  27.Nxf4  is a lot less effective due to  27...e5  . This stuff is complex, but after  25.f4  I can take with the knight and go for a quick Ng2-Nh4, blocking the h-file. }
26. Rxf4
{ However, I took with the rook!  26.Nxf4  e5  27.Ng2  Qh7+  28.Nh4  is the point, when Black won't break through. However, he still regains some material after the brilliant  28...Ba6!!  when we can't take due to an invasion on  e4  followed by  Rh5  with a deadly attack. The exchange is lost, but we still have two pieces for the rook and decent winning chances. }
26... Ba6
{ I didn't expect this move at all, and was unpleasantly surprised by the fact that Qh7+ was looming in the air. }
27. Kg2 Qh7 28. Rd1
{ I was rather nervous at this point, but luckily my opponent's seconds were ticking down... }
28... Rh8
{ Natural, but Black needed to be even more aggressive! The move  28...e5  opens more files and gives Black sufficient compensation after  29.dxe5  Re8  30.e6  Ka8!!  @@StartBracket@@only move@@EndBracket@@  31.Rf7  Qg6  32.Qe3  d4!!  and I think I must give back the piece with  33.cxd4  followed by  34.Qf4  . Crazy, but no chance a human could see this with so little time. }
29. Kf2 { I continued the evacuation of the monarch. All hands on deck! } 29...
e5 { It's one move to late! } 30. dxe5 Qh1 31. Rf1 Qh7
{ My opponent showed me that  31...Bxd3  32.Qxd3  Rxe5  33.Rxg4  worked out for me after the game. The engine nods in agreement. }
32. Ke3
{ A truly horrible move to make, but I was only playing against my opponent clock as I was setting up a neat trap. Instead, I should have gone back with  32.Rd1  , when  32...Qh1  is refuted by  33.Qe3  Rh2+  34.Bxh2  Qxd1  35.Ne1  . }
32... Rxe5+
{ Black falls into the trap. Both of us missed the simple  32...c4  , when I must suddenly convert a better ending after  33.Kd2  Qxd3+  34.Qxd3  cxd3  35.Re1  . }
33. Nxe5 d4+ 34. cxd4 cxd4+ 35. Kd2
{ The point of the trap is that the queen isn't hanging as I am winning Black's queen with Rf8+ followed by Rf7+ in case Black takes it. Black played on for a bit longer, but it's hopeless with the missing material. }
35... Rc8 36. Nd3 Qd7 37. Bxd4 Qa4
{ My opponent resigned before I was able to play the cute  38.Be5+  .  I had an excellent start to the Championship with 2.5/4, as I had drawn GM Hammer, GM Agdestein and IM Haldorsen in the previous rounds. Unfortunately, I only obtained 0.5 points in the next three rounds, and ended on a rather mediocre result. Chess is tough! Black's 6... Be7 was an interesting concept, but I think the position after 7. Nb1! is pretty bad as we have a really good French. However, it's never easy and Black got back into the game as I proceeded carelessly. Luckily things worked out in the end! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "27. Model Games"]
[Black "2. Kotronias, Vasilios vs. Short, Nigel D"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "2kr1b1r/pppq1ppp/1nn1p3/4Pb2/2PP4/2N1BN2/PP2B1PP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 0 11"]
[SetUp "1"]

11... f6
{ GM Nigel Short tried this poor move in Gibraltar 2003 against the famous theoretician, GM Kotronias, but it doesn't work for Black. }
12. d5
{ Kotronias answers by striking in the center, and indeed this is the refutation. Perhaps the Greek GM was still in book? }
12... Nxe5
{ 12...exd5  Is answered by  13.Bxb6!  As the knight on b6 needs to go before we can capture Black's pawn on b5.  13...axb6  14.cxd5  Bc5+  15.Kh1  Nxe5  It may seem like that we have lost a pawn, buuuut...  16.Nxe5  fxe5  17.Rxf5+-  Black will lose the queen if he captures the rook. }
13. Nxe5 fxe5 14. a4
{ This move aims to force the black knight to an inferior square by playing a5. Another excellent move! }
14... a5 { Naturally, the British GM stops the plan. } 15. Nb5
{ This move is sort of the nail in the coffin when d5-d6 is extremely unpleasant. Note that the pawn on d5 is still not hanging due to Rxf5! }
15... Bb4 16. d6 Na8
{ A heartbreaking retreat, but the move  16...c5  doesn't help! After  17.Bg5  Rdf8  18.Bd2  Kb8  19.Bxb4  cxb4  20.Qb3  Qc6  21.Qe3  e4  22.Rfd1  Black resigned in Nolte, K - Lau, J corr Germany 1993. }
17. c5 { Kotronias is completely dominating. Truly a beautiful sight. } 17...
Kb8 18. Bf3 c6
{ Black pushes the knight away and hopes to untangle in the future with b7-b6. }
19. Na3 { A strong retreat, as the knight can reach c4 if necessary. } 19... e4
20. Be2 b6 21. cxb6 { Not the most accurate, but every move wins... } 21...
Qxd6 22. Qxd6+
{ A simple practical decision by Kotronias, who knows that the resulting ending is not too tricky to convert. }
22... Rxd6 23. Rad1 { Not  23.Bf4?  when Black is fine after  23...Nxb6! }
23... Rhd8 24. Rxd6 Rxd6 25. g4
{ Removing the defender on f5, the last obstacle before the rook will infiltrate Black's camp on the 8th rank. }
25... Bd2
{ A last trick.  25...Bg6  is met by  26.Rf8+  followed by  Ba6+  and  Rxa8+  , when the passed pawn decides. }
26. Bf2
{ A simple retreat refutes Black's scheme. Black's position is hopeless as he loses decisive material. The rest is easy for Kotronias. }
26... Kb7 27. Nc4 Rd5 28. gxf5 exf5 29. Rd1 Bb4 30. Be3 g6 31. Kf2 Rxd1 32.
Bxd1 c5 33. Bb3 Nxb6 34. Nxb6 Kxb6 35. Bg8
{ Black's pawns fall like pears, so Short resigned. A really nice game by Kotronias! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "27. Model Games"]
[Black "3. Sinnett, Glyn vs. Lewyk, Ihor"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rn1qkb1r/ppp2ppp/4bn2/8/2PP4/2N2P2/PP4PP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 0 7"]
[SetUp "1"]

7... Qe7
{ This move is a decent attempt to trick us. Black needs to prove that there is enough compensation for the pawn. Our main 'weakness' is that it's not so easy to develop our pieces on the kingside, but our king may find a nice home on f2.' }
8. Kf2
{ 8.Qe2?  was played in a recent blitz game, when  8...Nc6  gave White problems. For example,  9.Be3  would be met by  9...Bxc4!  The text move is much better, since our king is surprisingly safe on  f2  when Black does not have enough for the missing pawn. }
8... Nbd7
{ Black prepares to castle queenside and gain counterplay against our center somehow. The same guy tried  8...Qd7  , but it quickly became pure misery after  9.Be3  c6  10.h3  Bd6  11.f4  Kf8  12.Nf3  h5  13.Ne5  Qc8  14.Bd3  . Graham, O - Lewyk, I ICCF email 2018. }
9. Bd3 O-O-O 10. Nge2
{ White goes for simple natural development. The king is perfectly safe on f2 as pointed out earlier. With the center and a pawn up, White's advantage is already crossing decisive barriers. }
10... Nc5 { The knight leaps forward to grab the bishop on d3. } 11. Be3
{ All of White's minor pieces are finally out on the board. Black has no compensation. }
11... Nxd3+ 12. Qxd3 h5
{ Black grabs some space on the kingside, but the situation truly is hopeless. My engine is showing as much as +4! }
13. Rhe1
{ White keeps playing natural moves, placing the rook in the e-file. Black has to watch out for d5, which could come anytime. }
13... Re8 14. d5 { It's finally time to push and open the diagonal. } 14... Bd7
15. Bd4 { Calmly improving the position. } 15... b6 16. Rab1
{ It's time to start a queenside invasion. Black has no antidote. } 16... h4
17. b4 Qd8 18. c5 { The pawns are moving at really great speed. } 18... Kb8 19.
a4 g6 20. a5 Bf5 { Black is desperately fighting... } 21. Qb5 Bxb1 22. Bxf6
{ A nice detail, as the rook on e8 is hanging in case Black recaptures. } 22...
Bxc5+ 23. bxc5 Qxf6 24. Rxb1
{ With two knights for a rook and a decisive attack, White is completely winning. Especially with engine help! }
24... Qe7 25. Ne4 f5 26. Nd4 Qf7 27. cxb6 { White finally breaks through. }
27... cxb6 28. axb6 a6 29. Nc6+
{ Black resigned as he'll be mated in short order. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "27. Model Games"]
[Black "4. Moreto Quintana, Alexandre vs. Saevich, Yury Vladimirovich"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r2qkb1r/pp1n1ppp/2p1pn2/8/3P4/2NBBQ1P/PPP2PP1/2KR3R b kq - 0 10"]
[SetUp "1"]

10... Nb6 11. Kb1
{ This side-step is almost always a good idea, as the pawn on a2 is no longer hanging. }
11... Bd6 12. Bc1
{ By moving the bishop, Black will never get a tempo with a knight jump to d5, meaning that White is all set to go for a kingside massacre with h4-g4-g5. }
12... Nbd5 13. Nxd5
{ White captures the knight and indeed this is an accurate choice. White saves a tempo, and may also push the c-pawn forward. }
13... Nxd5
{ 13...cxd5  Looks like the lesser evil, but after  14.g4↑  White has a decisive initiative on the kingside with h4 coming in short order. }
14. c4
{ Another strong move, pushing the knight away and gaining further control of the center. }
14... Nb4 15. Be2
{ There's no need to give the bishop. Black's knight on b4 has to head back to a6 as there are no other squares available. }
15... Qf6
{ The engine's recommendation is to take a rather miserable ending.   15...a5  Is more human, but Black's position is just dreadful after something like  16.a3  Na6  17.g4  Qe7  18.Rhe1  As Black is way too passive. }
16. Qxf6 gxf6
{ This ending is winning for White, but it might not be so easy for the average player to tell how to proceed. Let's see how Moreto Quintana increases his advantage. }
17. Bh5 Rg8 18. Rhe1
{ A nice trick, threatening Rxe6+ due to the pin of the f7-pawn. } 18... Ke7
19. Bf3 { The bishop can head back as Black dodged the threat. } 19... Rad8 20.
Re4
{ I really like this move, intending to harass Black's pawns on the kingside. }
20... Kd7 21. Rh4 Rh8 22. Rh6 Be7
{ It's hard for Black to keep everything together. } 23. a3 Na6 24. Be3
{ White doesn't rush and spends additional time to prepare d4-d5. However, the move could have been played already at this very moment. }
24... Kc7 25. Bh5 Rdf8
{ Black can't do more with his pieces than defend the targets in the position. }
26. Ka2 { This is almost mockery at this point, but Black has no moves! } 26...
b6 27. b4 Nb8 28. d5 { White finally goes for the long-awaited pawn break. }
28... cxd5 29. cxd5 exd5
{ If Black tries  29...e5  , then  30.d6+  followed by  Rxf6  is curtains. }
30. Bf4+ Bd6 31. Rc1+ Kd7 32. Bg4+
{ It's beautiful to see how well the bishop pair works together. } 32... Ke7
33. Re1+ Be5 34. Bg3
{ The bishop is heading to h4, while f4 is also a threat. } 34... Kd8 35. Bh4
Nd7
{ Black has nothing else, as  35...Kc7  36.f4  Bxf4  37.Rxf6  loses material as well due to White's powerful forces. }
36. Rxe5 { A simple trick seals the victory. } 36... Nxe5 37. Bxf6+ Ke8 38.
Bxe5 Rhg8 39. Bd6 Rxg4 40. hxg4 Rg8 41. Bb8
{ With a piece down, Black resigned. A brilliant game showing how well the bishop pair can work together. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "27. Model Games"]
[Black "5. Kurnosov, Igor vs. Varga, Zoltan"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rn2kb1r/pp2pppp/2p2n2/q4b2/2BP4/2N2N2/PPPB1PPP/R2QK2R b KQkq - 0 7"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ In this Model Game we'll take a look at what happens in the event of 7... Qb6, played in a bit more than 100 games. The moves does make a decent amount of sense, as Black dodges nasty discovery attacks. }
7... Qb6 8. Qe2 { White carries on with the usual plan of castling queenside. }
8... e6
{ 8...Bxc2?  Loses pretty much immediately after  9.Ne5  Bg6  10.h4+-  When Black has immense problems with his light-squared bishop as h5 is coming.   8...Qxb2?  Is also suicidal, when  9.Rb1  Qxc2  10.Rxb7  e6  11.O-O  +-  Is the end for Black as the queen gets trapped. }
9. O-O-O Nbd7 10. Nh4
{ There are many good moves in the position, but I think that the decision of grabbing the bishop pair is the best. }
10... Bg6 11. Nxg6 hxg6 12. h4
{ Kurnosov plays well, grabbing space and control of the g5-square. Black doesn't have any weaknesses, but is incredibly passive so White can already claim a much better game! }
12... O-O-O 13. Bg5 { The bishop is really well placed on g5. } 13... Bb4
{ Black has also tried  13...Qc7  which was shown in a couple of instructive games. Black can't do much else than just wait, as a pawn break may easily backfire due to our powerful bishop pair. The theme for these positions is that Black has little to do due to the lack of space, while we can slowly improve our position. }
14. Ne4 Rde8 15. Kb1 Be7 { Varga is struggling to find anything useful to do. }
16. Bc1
{ The bishop heads back, so Black has to worry about Ng5. Therefore, the Hungarian doesn't hesitate with the knight trade. }
16... Nxe4 17. Qxe4 Qa5 18. g3
{ Kurnosov makes simple moves that improve his position. g3 is a nice move as it covers the h4-pawn while also taking additional control of the f4-square. Again, Black has nothing to do! }
18... Nf6 19. Qe2 Qh5
{ Black offers a queen trade, which should obviously be declined. } 20. Qe1 Bd6
21. Bg5 Qf3
{ Black's queen doesn't have many available squares and goes into White's camp, but it makes things even worse.   21...Qg4  Looks slightly better, but it's still rather miserable after something like  22.Rg1  Bc7  23.Qf1±  Intending f3-g4. Nice and easy, no need to rush! :@@EndBracket@@ }
22. Rd3 Qf5
{ This move loses immediately, as Black loses material.   22...Qg4  Was once again necessary, when the same plan applies with  23.Rg1±  Intending f3-g4. We can also take additional control of the center with Bb3-c4. }
23. f3 { Black's queen is in major trouble. } 23... Bc7 24. Ra3
{ No escape to a5! } 24... e5 { And now everything falls apart after } 25. Bxf7
exd4
{ Black tried giving away the exchange, but it's hopeless. Kurnosov has no problems with converting his advantage. }
26. Bxe8 Rxe8 27. Qd1 Bd6 28. g4 Qe5 29. Rd3 Nd5 30. Rxd4 Ba3 31. Bc1
{ Another great example of how powerful a space advantage and the bishop pair is! White didn't make any difficult moves, it was all logical along the way. You got to love it. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "27. Model Games"]
[Black "6. Danin, Alexandre vs. Troyke, Christian"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 c5 4. dxc5 Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 Qa5 6. Qd4 Nf6 7. Qb4 Nc6 8.
Qxa5 Nxa5 9. Bd3 O-O 10. Ne2
{ White has the bishop pair and a pawn up, so he can surely claim a much better game. As a matter of fact, my engine even goes ballistic and suggests that this position is already lost for Black! However, it's not so easy to convert the advantage over the board so I wanted to show you how the Russian GM, Alexandre Danin, masterfully converts his advantage. }
10... b6
{ Black needs to get rid of the c5-pawn in order to develop his pieces and obtain compensation for the material deficit. After all, we do have doubled pawns in the c-file so Black won't be doing too badly if he's able to take over the file and place a knight on c4. }
11. Ba3 { Placing the bishop on a nice diagonal while defending the pawn. }
11... Bb7 12. f3
{ It was important not to get tempted with  12.cxb6  , as Black has  12...Rfe8  when things are no longer as easy. White is better after  13.f3  axb6  , but Black has gotten some extra chances. }
12... bxc5 13. Bxc5
{ A key difference between the aforementioned line is that Black doesn't have an open a-file. }
13... d6 14. Bb4
{ I would prefer placing the bishop on f2 where it targets the pawn on a7, but this move is also good. }
14... Nc6
{ Black is forced to head back, meaning that the plan of placing a knight on c4 is on hold. }
15. Rb1 Rab8 16. Kd2 { Danin coordinates his rooks. } 16... Rfc8
{ This is natural, but it makes an already dire situation a tad more difficult.   16...Ne5  Was a better attempt, when Black maintains some coordination after  17.Rb3  Nfd7  18.Rhb1  Nb6  Although it should still be quite bad, of course as Black is under immense pressure. }
17. Rb3
{ Danin wastes no time and prepares a doubling of the rooks in the b-file. }
17... Nd7 18. Rhb1
{ The rooks are now placed where they belong, in the open b-file. } 18... Nb6
19. Ke1
{ The Russian GM plays calmly and places the king where it can't be targeted.  19.Ra3!  was even stronger though, with the idea of playing  Ba5  . Such sophistication is not necessary, but worth pointing out anyway. }
19... Ba8
{ Black doesn't know what to do and makes a waiting move of his own.   19...Ne5  Is a better move, similar to what we saw earlier.  20.Ba5  Ned7  21.Nd4+-  And Black is still under immense pressure. One day Black will crack. }
20. Nd4 Kg7 21. Kd1
{ Danin doesn't hurry and waits for his opponent to error.. } 21... Na4 22. Kd2
{ Again, there's no rush! } 22... Rc7
{ Black finally cracks.   22...Nb6  Should have been played, but it's still lost after  23.Kc1  Rc7  24.Ra3  h5  25.Nb5  Rcb7  26.c4+-  The bishop can re-route itself to e3 via d2. Black can only wait for the final blow. }
23. Nxc6 Rxc6
{ Allows the nice trick   23...Bxc6  Is also hopeless after  24.Ba5  Rcb7  25.Bc7  Rxb3  26.axb3  Rb7  27.Ba5+-  When the ending is dead lost for Black. }
24. Bxd6 Rxb3 25. axb3 Rxd6 26. bxa4 { Another pawn has been obtained. } 26...
Rb6 27. Rxb6 axb6 28. e5 { Black is dead lost so he resigned. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "27. Model Games"]
[Black "7. Garcia Rodriguez, Ildefonso vs. Bonoldi, Fabio"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. h3 Bg7 5. Be3 c6 6. f4 O-O 7. Nf3 Nbd7 8. e5
dxe5 9. dxe5 Nd5
{ Black has to play actively. After  9...Nh5  , we can play  10.Kf2!  when  g4  will follow suit. Black will get smashed on the kingside. }
10. Nxd5 cxd5
{ Black's clever idea is the fact that the pawn on  d5  is not hanging due to the tactical shot  11.Qxd5  Nxe5! }
11. g4
{ White minds his own business and launches the g-pawn forward. I approve, as it's a move we'll make sooner or later anyways. }
11... e6
{ This is a natural move, but it's more or less Black's death sentence.   11...Nb6  Was necessary, as Black needs to play actively.  12.Qe2  Qc7  13.O-O-O  Nc4  14.Kb1±  Black's attack is getting nowhere. He might have to fight our space with the weakening f6, when we can defend with Bc1. Note that a capture on e5 is met by a rook capture on d5. }
12. g5
{ A fantastic move, preventing f7-f6 forever. Black is tied down and will have to find a way to meet the break h4-h5. }
12... Qc7 13. h4 Nc5
{ Black tries activating his pieces, but the compensation isn't there... } 14.
Qd2
{ White prepares to castle long, but it was even possible to go for the pawn break right away. }
14... Bd7 15. O-O-O Rfc8 16. Qh2
{ 16.Bxc5!  Qxc5  17.h5+-  Was much better as Black has nothing on the queenside. }
16... b5
{ Black's only chance is to launch the b-pawn forward and hope for the best. }
17. h5 b4 18. Kb1
{ Necessary, moving the king out of any possible nasty tricks down the c-file. }
18... a5 19. hxg6 hxg6
{ The h-file is open, but it doesn't look easy to break through as Black's bishop on g7 keeps things under control for now. }
20. Rc1
{ A typical prophylactic move, making sure that the c-pawn is never hanging. }
20... a4 21. Qh7+
{ White throws in a check, freeing the h2-square for the rook where it can join the defense, but it's inaccurate.   21.Bd3±  Was better, as the bishop contributes to the defense and attack alike. }
21... Kf8 22. Rh2 { The idea. } 22... a3 23. b3 Ne4
{ Black's attack is suddenly looking quite threatening, and indeed, the game has become quite complex. }
24. Bd3 Nc3+ 25. Ka1 Nb5
{ Black threatens mate, but it loses by force.   25...Bb5!  Was the way to go, leading to a pretty stunning sequence.  26.f5  26. Nd4 is a better try when White is apparently slightly better, but I wanted to show off the text as it's simply stunning.  26...exf5  27.Bd4  Bxd3  28.cxd3  Ne2!!  Is a pretty wild line, when the evaluation is 0.00. This must have been what Black missed. It's understandable, considering the engines were significantly inferior back in 2006.  29.Rxc7  Rxc7  30.Be3  Rac8  White's king has no shelter.  31.Rh1  Rc2  32.Qh4  d4!  33.Bd2  Ke8!  34.Rb1  Rxd2  35.Nxd2  Rc2  It's crazy that White's not winning.  36.Qh1  Nc3  37.Qa8+=  White's forced to give a perpetual. Mind-blowing! }
26. c4
{ I am a fan of this move, killing Black's counterplay down the c-file. However,  26.Bd2!  was somehow even better. }
26... bxc3
{ This move makes things even easier.   26...dxc4  Was better, but the same blow still wins  27.Bxg6!  fxg6  28.Rch1  There's suddenly a mate threat to deal with.  28...Re8  Is the only move, when  29.Qxg6  cxb3  30.Rh8+  Ke7  31.Qxg7+  Kd8  32.Rxe8+  Bxe8  33.Qf6+  Kc8  34.Qxe6+  Kb7  35.Qxb3  Wins! Beautiful stuff. }
27. Bxg6 { Tearing down Black's walls! } 27... d4 28. Bxf7
{ The black king loses its shelter. } 28... Kxf7 29. g6+ Kf8 30. f5
{ Black can't dodge both f6 and Bh6. } 30... exf5 31. Bh6 Be6 32. Qh8+ Bg8 33.
Ng5 { The knight joins the party. } 33... Re8 34. Bxg7+
{ Black resigned as he loses decisive material.  34...Qxg7  is met by  35.Nh7+  , while   34...Ke7  is met by  35.Bf8+  Rxf8  36.Rh7+  Bxh7+  37.Qxh7+  Kd8  38.Ne6+  . This was a really fun game to examine. Despite White's inaccuracies, I found it really instructive how he was able to tear down Black's defenses. The pawn breaks h4-h5 and f4-f5 are quite thematic and always in the air in these positions. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "27. Model Games"]
[Black "8. Nekhaev, Andrey Ivanovich vs. Conterno, Dominique"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. f3 a6 5. Be3 b5 6. Qd2 Nbd7 7. h4 h5 8. Nh3 Bb7
9. Ng5 Bg7 10. O-O-O O-O 11. g4 e5 12. d5
{ As mentioned previously, the safe route is to play 12. dxe5, hence why I suggest it in my course. Anyway, this game is a real beauty so I wanted to share it. }
12... hxg4 { Black's only chance is to grab the pawn. } 13. Ne2
{ The knight reroutes to g3 where it covers the important squares on e4 and h5 simultaneously.   13.h5  Has been a thematic response to hxg4, but in this very position Black gets a lot of counterplay.  13...Nxh5  14.fxg4  Nf4  According to my engine things aren't as clear any longer. White must play 15. Nh7 followed by g5 and Nf6, with a crazy mess. Still, the mess does favor us... }
13... gxf3 14. Ng3
{ The knight has reached its desirable destination on g3, meaning that h5 is now a deadly threat. Black must act fast, otherwise he'll get slaughtered on the kingside. }
14... Ng4
{ Black's knight leaps forward to grab our bishop on e3. Without the bishop, Black can meet h5 with Bh6, when we will have problems in the diagonal. Black may also create a sort of defense with Ndf6 if necessary. }
15. Bh3
{ This move is great as White keeps up the pressure. There's no time to waste. }
15... Nxe3
{ 15...Ndf6  After this move I think  16.Nxf3+-  Is simple and strong, as h5 will soon follow suit with a deadly attack. }
16. Qxe3 Nb6 17. Kb1
{ Moving the king out of harm's way. That being said, there was nothing wrong with capturing the pawn immediately. }
17... Qf6
{ Black's queen joins the game and essentially prevents Qxf3. Nekhaev is therefore forced to take with the knight. }
18. Nxf3 Nc4 19. Qf2 c6
{ Black needs to open the position in order to obtain any counterplay. } 20. h5
{ Nekhaev doesn't care ad keeps pushing the h-pawn. } 20... cxd5 21. Qh2
{ A breathtaking move, simply ignoring all the hanging material. The attack is too strong! }
21... dxe4 22. hxg6 exf3
{ Where's the attack you may ask? Well Nekhaev has the answer... } 23. Be6
{ This move is just fantastic, as Black's pawn on f7 is pinned. This prevents Black from escaping with fxg6. }
23... Qxg6 24. Bf5 { Black is now forced to give away decisive material. }
24... Qh6 25. Qf2 Qe3
{ Things barely work out for White, hence why the engine doesn't initially spot that 19. Qf2 is the best move.   25...Qg6  Is a funny way to fight on, when we should just leave the queen hanging with  26.Rdg1  With Nh5 coming or penetration in the g-file.  26...Rfc8  Is the engine's choice, when I think  27.Bxg6  fxg6  28.Nf5  gxf5  29.Qh4+-  Is a really beautiful line. Black gets mated one way or another. }
26. Bh7+ Kh8 27. Be4+ Bh6
{ The best chance.   27...Kg8  28.Nf5  f6  29.Rdg1+-  Is a swift death for Black. }
28. Rxh6+ Qxh6 29. Bxb7
{ White's still down material, but Black's exposed king means that this won't last long. }
29... Ra7 30. Bd5 { The rook was hanging, but this is even better. Funny. }
30... Rc7 31. Rh1
{ The queen falls. Black still has quite a few pieces on the board, but the rest is easy with engine-help. }
31... Qxh1+ 32. Nxh1 f5 33. Bxf3 f4 34. Be4 Kg8 35. Qh2 Ne3 36. Qh6 Rg7 37. b3
b4 38. Qe6+ Kh8 39. Bg6 Nd5 40. Nf2 f3 41. Bd3 Nf4 42. Qxd6 Rg1+ 43. Kb2 Nxd3+
44. Nxd3 Kg8 45. Qd5+ Kg7 46. Qxe5+ Kg8 47. Qe6+ Kg7 48. Qxa6 Rg4 49. Qa7+ Rf7
50. Qxf7+ { A nice trick to end a really beautiful game. } *

