[White "27. Model Games"]
[Black "10. Pundak, Maksim Bogdanovich vs. Burmeister, Ferdinand"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 Nbd7 4. f4 e5 5. Nf3 exd4 6. Qxd4 c6 7. Bd2 d5 8.
O-O-O Bc5 9. Qd3 O-O 10. exd5 Qc7 11. Ng5 Bd6 12. dxc6 bxc6 13. Qf3 Rb8 14.
Nge4 Bb4
{ By playing Bb4, Black provokes the advance of a2-a3, but I don't think this is such a big deal as there are no clear ways for Black to make use of this concession. }
15. a3 Be7 16. Bc4
{ This is an important move, as the bishop can block Black's play in the b-file with Bb3. }
16... Kh8
{ Black's king moves to a safer square, meaning that Nb6 followed by Bg4 is now a threat. The difference is that we no longer have Nxf6+ followed by Qxg4, after Bg4. }
17. Rde1 { Taking control of the open e-file. } 17... Nb6 18. Bb3
{ It's already becoming clear that Black's compensation for the missing pawn isn't very impressive. }
18... Bg4 { Black needs to do something, so playing actively makes sense. } 19.
Qe3 Nbd5 20. Qf2 Bf5
{ 20...Be6  Could be tried as well, playing against the bishop on b3.  21.Rhf1  21...Nxc3  This leads to a forced sequence  22.Bxc3  Bxb3  23.Nxf6  Bxf6  24.Bxf6  gxf6  25.Qd4!  A very nice intermezzo.  25...Kg7  26.Rf3  Bxc2  27.Kxc2  Qd8  28.Rg3+  Kh8  29.Qxd8  Rbxd8  30.Re4+-  Black has regained the pawn but is left with a lost ending anyway. }
21. Ng3
{ Forcing the bishop away, not allowing any counterplay.   21.Rhf1?  Would be poor as Black gets a lot of play after  21...Nxc3  22.Nxc3  Qb7=∞  When tricks like Bxc2 are suddenly in the air. }
21... Bc8 22. f5
{ Another strong move, taking terrain and making Black's bishop on c8 even worse. }
22... Rd8 23. Nxd5 { Being up material, it's natural to trade pieces. } 23...
cxd5 { 23...Nxd5?  Is even worse, as  24.Ne4+-  Is just fantastic for White. }
24. Ba5 { Trading another piece. } 24... Qxa5 25. Rxe7 Bb7 26. Rd1
{ Black is objectively lost, so this is one out of many decent moves. The text prevents Black from gaining counterplay with  d4  , which can be seen after  26.Rxf7  d4  . Still, that variation should also be winning but the engine doesn't think it's as convincing. Luxury problem! }
26... Kg8 27. Rde1
{ Having the king on g8 changes things drastically apparently as d4 would have worked if Pundak went Rhe1 right away. Ah, those lovely details! }
27... h6 28. Qf3
{ 28.Qd4  I instinctively want to make this move, as it keeps Black dominated. Text move is still good, though. }
28... d4
{ Black goes for counterplay. Other moves should be met by Nh5 when Black is lost. The following is now forced: }
29. Bxf7+ Kf8 30. Qd3 Ba6 31. Qd2 Qxd2+ 32. Kxd2 d3
{ Black is just in time to trade the vulnerable pawn.   32...Rxb2  Is met by  33.Bb3+-  When the rook is trapped. }
33. b4 dxc2+ 34. Kxc2
{ Burmeister has fought tooth and nail. There are less pieces on the board, but it should still be rather problematic for Black as he is two pawns down! }
34... Rbc8+ 35. Kb1
{ The only move, as other king moves would give Black too much counterplay after Rd3+ or Rd2+. }
35... Nd5
{ Black keeps up the momentum and forces White to give up the bishop. } 36.
Bxd5 Rxd5 37. Ka1
{ This is a brilliant prophylactic move, preventing any checks. } 37... Bb5 38.
R7e5 { Trading another pair of rooks to neutralize Black's counterplay. } 38...
Bc6 39. Nh5 Rxe5 40. Rxe5 Bxg2
{ Black has regained a pawn, but the queenside pawns are too dangerous. } 41.
Ra5 Bf3 42. Nf4 Kf7
{ Black's only chance is to hope that he'll be able to grab the f5-pawn and then run with the kingside pawns. }
43. Rxa7+ Kf6 44. b5
{ You don't believe it until you see it, but this move costs Pundak the game. The engine doesn't realise that the final position in the variation is drawn!   44.Kb2!  It was necessary to bring the king into the game.  44...Kxf5  45.Rf7+  45. Nd3 should also lead to victory.  45...Ke4  46.Ne6  g5  47.a4  g4  48.a5  Kd5  49.Nc7+  Kc4  50.Ka3  A really nice point, the king supports the queenside pawns. Black's kingside pawns aren't fast enough.  50...h5  51.a6  h4  52.Ka4  White must have Ka5 before playing b5, as we can't allow Kc5-Kb6.  52...Rg8  53.Ka5  Be4  54.Re7  Kd4  55.Ne6+  Kc4  56.a7  g3  Black promotes the g-pawn, but we're in time to sacrifice the knight for it.  57.hxg3  hxg3  58.Rc7+  Kb3  58... Kd3 would fail to 59. Nc5+ followed by Nxe4.  59.Nd4+  Kb2  60.b5  g2  61.Ne2  g1=Q  62.Nxg1  Rxg1  63.b6  Black can't stop the pawns. I analyzed the following:  63...Ra1+  64.Kb5  Ra3  65.Kc5  Rb3  66.Re7  Bf3  67.Rf7  Be4  68.Rf4  Bh1  69.Rb4  Kc3  70.Rxb3+  Kxb3  71.Kd6+-  White promotes. }
44... Kxf5 45. Rf7+ Ke4 46. Ne6 g5
{ Things are similar to the line I pointed out, but the key difference is that the white king is unable to support the queenside pawns. }
47. b6
{ 47.Kb2  g4  48.a4  Ke5  49.Nc7  h5  50.a5  h4  51.b6  Rh8=  Looks drawn to me as Black's pawns are incredibly fast. }
47... Rb8 48. Nc5+ Ke3 49. Nd7 Re8
{ Initially, my engine goes nuts and gives as much as +5! Unbelievable, as the resulting position is drawn. }
50. Rxf3+ Kxf3 51. b7 { It's now a race... } 51... h5 52. a4 g4 53. a5 h4 54.
Ne5+
{ 54.Nf6  Rb8  55.a6  g3  56.hxg3  hxg3  57.a7  g2  58.axb8=Q  g1=Q+=  Is somehow a TB draw. I doubt a human would be able to check on the right squares, but it's no problems for a machine. }
54... Rxe5 55. b8=Q Rxa5+ 56. Kb2 Kg2
{ My engine gave +9.00 for a sec, and suddenly dropped to less than +1.00... Must have been a nasty surprise for Pundak. }
57. Qb4 Kxh2 58. Qxg4
{ Is a tablebase draw, so the players agreed to a draw.  58.Qxa5  was also drawn. I think it was instructive to see how White neutralized Black's initiative, showing that Black really doesn't have enough. An incredible turnaround at the end, but those things are what I love about the game of chess. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "27. Model Games"]
[Black "11. Stockfish Latest vs. LCZeroCPU Latest"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r2k3r/pppn2pp/8/4pb2/8/bBP1B3/P1P1NPPP/3RK2R b K - 0 12"]
[SetUp "1"]

12... Re8 { Leela's choice was this rook swing to e8. } 13. h4 Be6
{ The point of Re8 is now revealed, but it does weaken the control of the e4-square. }
14. h5 h6 15. Ng3 Ke7 16. Rh4
{ The h4-square is a useful post for the h1-rook. Here, its biggest job is that it covers the square on e4. }
16... Nf6 17. Ke2 { Improving our pieces. } 17... Rh8
{ A bizarre move, but I am sure Leela had a reason for placing the rook there.   17...Rad8?  Looks human, but it would fail to  18.Rxd8  Rxd8  19.Ra4±  When the pawn on a7 falls.   17...b6  Could be played, when I think the ending looks really pleasant after  18.Ne4⩲ }
18. Bxe6 Kxe6 19. Ne4
{ The main strategy for White will be to dominate on the light-squares, a strategy that ultimately succeeds as we shall see. }
19... Be7 20. c4
{ Placing the pawns on the opposite square of the bishop is a nice strategy to remember. Also, a great start to the domination on the light squares. }
20... b6 21. a4 Rab8
{ Black doesn't have too much to do, so she simply makes waiting moves. } 22.
Rdh1 Rhg8 23. g3 Kf5
{ I have a feeling Leela missed the following continuation when calculating moves earlier. @@StartBracket@@It's biggest weakness is that it has a tendency to miss tactics@@EndBracket@@.   23...Rbd8  Is a better attempt, but Black is under pressure after  24.a5⩲ }
24. Nxf6 Bxf6 25. Re4
{ A wonderful move. White maintains the control of the light-squares, meaning that the strategy is one step further in succeeding. The rook can't be taken as Black's king is trapped in a mating net after g4 followed by f3#. Simply stunning. }
25... Rge8 26. g4+ Ke6 27. Rb1 { White's pressure is getting stronger. } 27...
a6 { Leela prevents Stockfish from playing a5. } 28. f4 Kd7 29. f5
{ White has obtained full control on the light squares, so I suspect the position is almost objectively lost. Usually for these engines, a 'nano-mistake' is enough for the position to be impossible to save... }
29... Kc6 30. Bd2 Rbd8 31. Bc3 Rd7 32. Kf3
{ Stockfish is maneuvering his pieces to ideal squares, but it takes some triangulation to make it happen. Watch and enjoy. }
32... Kc5 33. Rbe1 Ree7 34. Kg2 Re8 35. Kg3 a5 36. R1e3 Kd6 37. Bb2 Kc5 38. Kf3
Kd6 39. Rb3 Kc6 40. Rd3
{ The advantage keeps on increasing, meaning that I think it's actually just lost at this point! }
40... Ree7
{ Makes things easier for Stockfish.   40...Rd6  Is apparently the best defense, but I do suspect it's also lost after  41.Rde3  Rd2  42.Bxe5  Rxe5  43.Rxe5  Bxe5  44.Rxe5  Rxc2  45.Re6+  Kb7  46.Rg6+-  As the kingside pawns are very fast. And indeed, as I am writing this, the evaluation suddenly jumped to +3. }
41. Rxd7 Kxd7
{ One rook is off the board and from here it's easy. White will grab control of the d-file and place the king on the beautiful e4-square. }
42. Ba3 Re8 43. Re3
{ The only move that wins, as it is important that White can take control of the d-file with Rd3. }
43... Kc6 44. Ke4 Rd8 45. Rd3 Rb8 46. Rd5
{ White has full control, so from here it's easy. Even for a human. } 46... Re8
47. Bc1 Rh8 48. Be3 Ra8 49. Rb5 Kd7 50. c5 bxc5 51. Bxc5 Ke8 52. Be3 Ke7 53. c4
Kd6 54. Bd2 c6 55. c5+ Kc7 56. Rb1 Kd7 57. Rb7+ Ke8 58. Rc7 Rd8 59. Bc3 Rd1 60.
Rxc6 Rc1 61. Bxa5 Ra1 62. Kd5 Rxa4 63. Bb6 Kf7 64. Rc7+ Be7 65. c6 Kf6 66. Ra7
Rxg4 67. c7 Rb4 68. c8=Q Kg5 69. Rxe7 Kf4 70. Qc1+ Kf3 71. Qf1+ Kg3 72. Rxg7+
Rg4
{ A beautiful victory by Stockfish, showing that the ending is far from easy for Black. }
