[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "27. Model Games"]
[Black "12. Romm, Mikhail Yakovlevich vs. Stoeckert, Mario"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r2q1rk1/ppp3pp/2n1pb1n/3p1b2/3P1P2/2P2N2/PP1NB1PP/R1BQ1RK1 b - - 0 10"]
[SetUp "1"]

10... a5
{ As mentioned in the Main Chapter, I think this move makes more sense than  10...Qe8  , as Black grabs space and prevents our thematic pawn launch. }
11. a4 b6 12. h3
{ Again, if we want to achieve something we should limit Black's pieces by playing g4 at some point. }
12... Be7 13. g4 Bg6 14. Qe1
{ The queen will be well placed on g3 where it can support the kingside pawns and contribute to the attack. }
14... Bd6 { 14...Rxf4  was met by  15.Bb5  , when the pawn on  e6  falls. } 15.
Ne5
{ White has a lot of space and a very comfortable position. Black can't really allow the knight to stay on e5, so therefore he decides to capture it. }
15... Nxe5 16. dxe5
{ The right way to capture.  16.fxe5  allows  16...Rxf1!  when our initiative is fading away like merchandise on Black Friday. }
16... Bc5+ 17. Kh2 Nf7 18. Qg3
{ White's pawn majority on the kingside gives him a promising position. Black's pieces aren't ideally placed either, especially the poor knight on f7. White's ideas contain a potential f5-break or h4-h5 break or Nb3 followed by Be3 to trade the dark squared bishops. }
18... Qd7 19. Nb3 Rae8 20. Be3 { Romm decides to trade bishops. } 20... Bxe3
{ 20...Be7?  21.Nd4+-  Would be catastrophic for Black. } 21. Qxe3 Be4
{ This is more or less a waiting move. Black doesn't have many moves that improve his position. }
22. Nd2
{ The knight doesn't do too much on b3, so White decides to reroute it. } 22...
Bc2 { Targeting the a4-pawn so White must defend it with } 23. b3 h6 24. Rac1
Bg6 25. Rce1 Bc2 26. c4
{ White opens the position, a necessary cause of action in order to make progress. }
26... Rd8 27. cxd5 Qxd5 28. Nc4 Qd4 29. Qg3
{ Black would even be slightly better in an ending, so it's not acceptable to trade queens. }
29... Qd7 30. h4 { It's time to start pushing the kingside pawns. } 30... Kh8
31. Rc1 Be4 32. Qe3 Qd4 33. Rc3
{ White is now much better prepared for an ending. } 33... Rd7 34. Kg3 Qxe3+
35. Rxe3
{ Black needs to play incredibly precise in order to save this, as White's space advantage and strong kingside majority gives him a huge edge in the ending. Black doesn't have any activity - the bread of butter of endings! }
35... Bd5 36. g5 { 36.f5±  Is perhaps even better, aiming for f5-f6. } 36...
Nd8 37. Rd3
{ White's pawns are now ideally placed, so Romm takes over the d-file. } 37...
Nc6 38. Ne3 Nb4 39. Rd4 g6
{ I will admit that I don't understand this move very well.   39...hxg5  40.hxg5  g6  Looks a better version to me, but White is still winning after  41.Nxd5  Rxd5  42.Rxd5  exd5  43.Rc1  c5  44.Bb5+-  As the e-pawn is too strong, combined with the R+B. }
40. gxh6 { A free pawn is a free pawn! } 40... Rdd8
{ 40...Kh7  Is the natural instinct for a human, but after  41.h5  gxh5  42.Bxh5  Kxh6  43.f5+-  Black is lost as he can't deal with our powerful pieces due to his exposed king. Black can't take the bishop either, as he'll be mated in short notice after Rh4+ followed by Rg1. }
41. Nxd5
{ Grabbing the bishop is strong, as Black will struggle to defend the light squares. }
41... Nxd5 42. Rfd1 c6 43. Bg4 Rde8 44. Rc4
{ This exchange sacrifice is just brilliant. } 44... Ne3 45. Rd6 Nxc4 46. bxc4
{ Black is up an exchange, but can't do anything to save the hanging pawns. }
46... b5 { Is an attempt for counterplay, when } 47. cxb5
{ Is an important capture.  47.axb5  right away would give Black lots of compensation after  47...a4  . I believe that this is a problem as the c4-pawn stands in the way for the bishop, making the a-pawn harder to stop. }
47... cxb5 48. axb5 a4 49. Bxe6 a3 50. Ba2
{ The bishop deals easily with Black's passer. } 50... Kh7 51. b6 Kxh6 52. b7
Rd8 53. f5 Rxd6 54. exd6 gxf5 55. Kf4
{ Black resigned, as he can't stop all of White's pawns. A very instructive game. }
