[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "27. Model Games"]
[Black "13. Tari, Aryan vs. Firouzja, Alireza"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r3brk1/ppq2ppp/2nbpn2/3p4/3P4/2PB1N1P/PP2QPP1/RNB1R1K1 w - - 0 13"]
[SetUp "1"]

13. Nbd2
{ As I mentioned in the theory section, Aryan was able to get revenge after the defeat in Norway Chess. This game was played in the Champion's Chess Tour, in the New in Chess Classic, Preliminary stage. Aryan has gotten an edge after the opening, let's see how the game unfolds! }
13... Nh5
{ Firouzja jumps to the rim and aims to place the knight on the nice square on f4. A highly logical way to proceed. }
14. Nb3
{ Aryan decides to place the knight on b3.   14.Nf1  Is another nice square for the knight. We have a comfortable game after  14...Nf4  15.Bxf4  Bxf4  16.Rad1  Bd6  17.h4  Bd7  18.Ne3  Rad8  19.g3⩲  Black has to play f6 or f5 to prevent the Bxh7+ tactic which is looming in the air.   14.Bxh7+!?  Is very tricky, but apparently Black is completely fine. The line goes  14...Kxh7  15.Ng5+  Kh6  16.Ndf3  Nf4  17.Qe3  Kg6  18.Qd2  Bd7  19.g3  Rh8  20.h4∞  When the position is just very complicated. }
14... Nf4 15. Bxf4 Bxf4 16. Ne5
{ Aryan decides to jump to  e5  right away. There's nothing wrong with the calm  16.Rad1  or  16.h4  , with similar play to  14.Nf1  . }
16... g6
{ Firouzja prevents a potential tactic in the b1-h7 diagonal, while the bishop could also be placed on g7 one day. }
17. a4
{ Aryan decides to expand on the queenside, but I prefer the calmer  17.g3  . Black's queenside play is nothing to worry about, so I think we should focus our attention on the kingside. }
17... a6 18. a5 Rc8 19. h4
{ Slightly inaccurate, but correct plan.   19.g3!  Was the right way to proceed, when the play may transpose to the game. }
19... Qe7
{ I am not a fan of this move. The queen provokes Aryan into playing g3, which is a move which will only do him a favor.   19...Nxe5  Was a missed opportunity by Firouzja.  20.dxe5  f6!   I'm sure Firouzja saw this, but disliked his position after  21.g3  Bxe5  22.f4  , when the e6-pawn hangs. However, he has  21.g3  fxe5!  Which is a phenomenal piece sacrifice.  22.gxf4  e4⩱  I think Black is not just better objectively, but also practically as it's easier to handle Black. We should not forget that this was played in a rapid game, so brilliancies like these occur rather seldom as they're so difficult to spot. }
20. g3 Bh6
{ 20...Bxe5  21.dxe5  d4⇆  Was the right path, when Firouzja has some counterplay. }
21. h5
{ Aryan has now obtained a clearly better position with a very dangerous initiative. }
21... Nxe5 22. dxe5 g5
{ Firouzja is desperate and tries to keep the position blocked.   22...f5  Is the engine's choice, but it looks incredibly ugly.  23.hxg6  Bxg6  24.f4±  It's no doubt that Aryan is in the driving seat. Still, it's better than the game... }
23. Nd4
{ It's beautiful to look at White's position here. Firouzja is famous for his tricks, but can he get out of this pickle? }
23... Bd7 24. Nf3
{ The most logical plan in the world. However, the move 24. Ra3! was much better. The idea is Rb3-Rb6, when ideas like Nf5 show up suddenly. Of course, it's not realistic for a human to find such a move, especially in a game with a short time control. }
24... Bg7 25. h6 Bh8
{ Firouzja doesn't dare to take the pawn, but it was the necessary approach. }
26. Nh2
{ Very logical, but it gives Black some hope to get back into the game. 26. Nd4 was better, with ideas like f4. }
26... f5 27. exf6 Bxf6 28. Ng4
{ It looks like a nightmare to handle Black's position, but the game is still going for Firouzja. It's not over until the fat lady sings... }
28... Rce8 29. Ne5
{ There's no need to be hasty.   29.Rad1+-  Was much stronger, with the simple plan of playing Bc2-Qd3 next. }
29... Bxe5 30. Qxe5
{ Black is quite solid, so a potential endgame won't be easy to win. } 30...
Rf3 { 30... Qf6 is the way to go, with a slightly worse endgame. } 31. Re3 Ref8
{ Believe it or not, this is Firouzja's decisive mistake. Black needs both of the rooks to cope with all of White's threats. With one rook gone, it's impossible to defend.  31...Rf7  was the way. There are few margins in chess! }
32. Rxf3 Rxf3 33. Bc2
{ Aryan's technique from here is pretty much as flawless as it gets with little time on the clock. }
33... Rf8 34. Rf1 Bc8 35. f4 g4 36. Re1 Rf7 37. Qh5
{ Things finally fall apart for Firouzja. } 37... Bd7 38. Qxg4+ Kf8 39. Re5
Qc5+ 40. Kg2 Qb5 41. Qg5 Qxb2 42. Qd8+ Be8 43. Qd6+ Re7 44. Re2 Qxc3 45. Bxh7
Qc6 46. Qa3 Qa4 47. Qxa4 Bxa4
{ Aryan has obtained a completely winning endgame and converts his advantage easily. }
48. Bb1 d4 49. g4 Bb5 50. Rd2 d3 51. Kf3 e5 52. fxe5 Rxe5 53. Bxd3 Bxd3 54.
Rxd3 Rxa5 55. Rd8+
{ Well played by Aryan who got his revenge! The game was a rollercoaster ride in the middlegame, but that's expected in a game with short time control. All in all, the position after the opening is more pleasant for White. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "27. Model Games"]
[Black "14. Voveris, Saulius vs. Lagergren, Henry"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 e5 6. dxe5 Nxe5 7. Qe2 Qe7 8.
Be3 Nxd3+ 9. Qxd3 Qc7 10. Nd2 Bd6 11. Qxd5 Ne7 12. Qc4 O-O 13. Ne2 Re8 14. Nd4
Bd7 15. Qxc7 Bxc7 16. O-O
{ I wanted to show this game, as the situation at hand is rather typical in the lines where Black decides to go for an isolani-type of position. Black has given the weak pawn away, but has in return obtained the bishop pair. It's far from easy to win, so it's instructive to see how the strong correspondence player, Voveris, does it. }
16... Nd5 17. Rfe1 Rad8
{ Black gets the last piece into the game and can be happy with the amount of activity he has for the missing pawn. }
18. N2b3 { White needs to untangle somehow. } 18... Nxe3
{ Lagergren grabs the bishop before Voveris is able to pull it back to d2. A correct decision. }
19. Rxe3 Rxe3 20. fxe3
{ The trading of one rook is in White's favor, as the bishop pair combined with a pair of rooks is often a powerful combination. White has a weak pawn on e3, but it's not too difficult to guard. }
20... Bc8 21. Nd2 { Voveris reroutes the knight to the f3-square. } 21... b6
{ This move is okay, but I somehow feel like it's a bit too slow.   21...g5  Seems like a better attempt if you ask me, as Black gets more activity and space. A sample line is  22.Kf2  f6  23.N2f3  Kf7  24.h4  Kg6  25.a4⩲  White maintains a better game of course, but Black's drawing chances are definitely there. }
22. Kf2 f6 23. N2f3
{ White slowly improves his position, the bread and butter for converting advantages. }
23... a6 { Black can't allow Nc6 which would lose a pawn. } 24. Rc1
{ Voveris places the rook behind the c-pawn, as he intends to create a passed pawn there in the future. }
24... Bd6 25. Rd1
{ This is typical engine behavior - suddenly it discovers that the rook is in fact better placed on d1! }
25... Kf7 26. Rd2 { White prepares to trade rooks. } 26... g5
{ Black grabs space, but compared to the variation we saw earlier it's definitely less effective. }
27. g3 { Not allowing any nonsense in the diagonal. } 27... h6 28. b3
{ It's time to slowly push the queenside pawns forward. There's no rush! }
28... Bd7
{ 28...b5  Is a better move, when  29.Ke2  Bc7  30.c4  bxc4  31.Rc2  Bb6  32.Rxc4⩲  Gives Black an easier time in the game. However, Black is definitely not out of the woods. }
29. Ne2 Bc8 30. Rd4
{ Note how White just keeps improving his position, finding excellent squares for his pieces. The rook is very well placed in the 4th rank where it contributes to pawn breaks such as a4 in case Black tries b5. }
30... Bb7 31. c4 { The pawn is finally pushed forward. } 31... Ke6 32. Nc3
{ It's now time to find a new home for the knight. } 32... f5 33. Nd5 b5
{ Black fights well and is now able to trade a pawn. The standard strategy to hold endings - trade pawns! }
34. Rd2 bxc4 35. bxc4 Rd7
{ This move looks too passive.   35...Rc8  Was better, when a sequence is  36.Nd4+  Ke5  37.Nb6  Rc7  38.Nxf5  Bc5  39.Nd5  This is kind of similar to the game, but Black has a better version.  39...Rf7  40.g4  h5  41.Ke2⩲  I think Black will hold, as the pair of bishops is so incredibly good. Still, it's not over yet... }
36. h4 { Voveris provokes Black into making an undesirable move. } 36... Rg7
37. Nd4+ Ke5 38. Nb3 Ke6 39. Rd1
{ White keeps improving the position, Lagergren can only wait. } 39... Ke5 40.
h5 Ke6 41. Nb6 Rc7
{ This is similar to the sequence we saw after 35... Rc8, but the difference here is that Black has less counterplay.   41...Be4  Is a better try, but Black is on the verge of losing after  42.c5  Bc7  43.Rd4±  When the rook is heading to a4. }
42. Nd4+ Ke5 43. Nxf5 Bc5 44. Nd5 Rf7 45. g4
{ Everything works out tactically. Black wins back a pawn, but the cost of giving away one of the bishops is high. }
45... Bc8 46. Ke2 Bxf5 47. gxf5 Rxf5 48. Nc7 a5 49. Ne8
{ The knight is a nuisance for Black as it keeps jumping around creating annoying threats. Black can't do anything about Rd5+ followed by Nd6+. }
49... a4 50. Rd5+ Ke4 51. Nd6+ { A winning rook ending is now forced. } 51...
Bxd6 52. Rxd6 Rc5 53. Rd4+ Ke5 54. Kd3
{ With tablebase implemented, it's easy for Voveris to win the game. } 54... a3
55. Rd8 Rc7 56. Rd5+ Ke6 57. Ra5 g4 58. Ra6+ Kf5 59. Rxh6 Rd7+ 60. Kc3 Rc7 61.
Kb4 Kg5 62. Rh8 Rg7 63. h6 Rg6 64. h7 Kh6 65. Rf8 Kxh7 66. Rf1 g3 67. c5 Rg8
68. c6 g2 69. Rg1 Rb8+ 70. Kxa3 Rb6 71. c7 Rc6 72. Kb4 Rxc7 73. Rxg2 Rb7+
{ A theoretical win for White, so Lagergren saves the ink and resigns. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "27. Model Games"]
[Black "15. Shankland, Samuel L vs. Liang, Awonder"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "2kr1b1r/pp2qppp/2n2n2/3p4/3P1pP1/1QPB4/PP1N1PP1/R4KNR b - - 0 11"]
[SetUp "1"]

11... g6
{ Awonder blocks the diagonal of the d3-bishop, but the downside to this move is that we're allowed to play g5, meaning that Black will become rather passive as the knight on f6 is forced to move. }
12. Re1 Qc7 13. g5
{ Sam's moves come very naturally, as Black is getting pushed back. It's tough to find good squares for the pieces. }
13... Nh5
{ Black is ready to neutralize our pressure with h6, but Sam is observant and prevents it. }
14. Be2 Ng7 15. Ngf3 Ne6
{ The knight has ended up on e6 after a pretty long journey. } 16. Bb5
{ Sam keeps playing well and aims to reinforce the pressure on Black's position with Qa4, and potentially Bxc6. }
16... Bg7
{ Black has finally coordinated his forces, but it's slightly inaccurate.  16...Ne7  is best, so  17.Qa4  can be dodged with  17...Kb8  . It's essential that we can't take on  c6  in this position.  17.Bd3  is apparently best with a very interesting position. We are in the driving seat as we have some initiative on both sides of the board, but the advantage isn't more than slightly better. }
17. Qa4 Rd6
{ 17...a6  I'm sure Awonder considered this move, but the ending after  18.Bxc6  Qxc6  19.Qxc6+  bxc6  20.Nb3±  Won't be too difficult for a player of Sam's caliber to convert. Ke2-Kd2 comes followed by a doubling in the h-file. }
18. Nb3
{ Sam's move is extremely natural, but it's inaccurate.   18.b4+-  Was more precise when the knight on b3 will soon find a nice home on c5. }
18... b6
{ 18...a6!  Is Black's best defense, but Black's position remains shaky after  19.Bxc6  Rxc6  20.Nc5  Nxc5  21.dxc5↑  Rh4 comes next. It's important to highlight that the pawn on c5 can't be taken due to Re8+, when h7 falls at the end of the variation. }
19. Nc1 { The knight gets ready for a journey to the juicy square on b4. }
19... Nb8 20. Nd3 Kb7 21. Nb4
{ Sam is already completely winning, as the pressure is too strong. Black has no counterplay at all! }
21... Qd8 22. Ne5 { Sam improves the other knight. } 22... Qc7
{ 22...Nxg5  23.Nec6+-  Would lead to a resignation at once. } 23. Qb3
{ Black's defenses are overloaded, so one pawn must bite the dust. } 23... Rhd8
24. Rxh7 a6 25. Bd3 Ka7
{ Awonder keeps fighting, but a miracle is required in order to save this game. }
26. Qa4 a5 27. Bb5 Kb7 28. Nbd3
{ 28.Nbc6  Would have lead to a nice direct sequence where White has a completely winning rook ending. However, the text is more than good enough!  28...Nxc6  29.Bxc6+  Rxc6  30.Qxc6+  Qxc6  31.Nxc6  Kxc6  32.Rxe6+  fxe6  33.Rxg7+-  A beautiful line, but being so sophisticated wasn't required! }
28... Rg8 29. Nf3 { Simple chess, defending the pawn on g5. } 29... Rh8 30.
Rxh8 Bxh8 31. a3
{ Sam has all the time in the world and improves his position bit by bit. }
31... Nc6 32. Bxc6+ Rxc6 33. Nde5 Bxe5 34. Nxe5 Rd6 35. Qe8
{ Sam finally breaks through. } 35... Rd8
{ 35...Nxg5  36.Nxf7+-  Was the point. } 36. Qxf7 Nxg5 37. Qxc7+ Kxc7 38. Nxg6
{ Sam wins another pawn. } 38... f3 39. Nf4 Kc6 40. gxf3 Nxf3 41. Re6+ Kb5 42.
Ke2 Ng1+ 43. Kd3
{ Awonder puts an end to the suffering and resigns. Excellent played by Sam! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "27. Model Games"]
[Black "16. Morozov, Dmitry Viktorovich vs. Kochan, Igor"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 e6 2. e4 d5 3. Nc3 h6 4. Bd3 Nf6 5. e5 Nfd7 6. Nce2 c5 7. c3
{ White has achieved a fantastic set-up. Technically, there isn't much more needed to be said as White is already doing very well due to his space advantage. However, I think it's very instructive to see how one should proceed when this set-up is achieved. }
7... Nc6 8. f4
{ White takes extra terrain on the kingside by pushing the f-pawn forward. e5 gains additional support, while a pawn break with f4-f5 will eventually be on the cards, particularly if Black castles kingside. }
8... cxd4
{ Black immediately releases the tension in the center. To me this looks sensible, as Black at least gains control over the b4-square. }
9. cxd4 a5
{ This move doesn't look very natural, but the point is that Black plans to take terrain on the queenside as that side of the board is his main source of counterplay.   9...Bb4+  Could simply be met by  10.Kf2±  As the king is perfectly safe here. Next, we're planning h4 followed by Nf3. We may even consider pushing the g-pawn forward or a rook swing with Rh3-Rg3. }
10. Nf3 Nb6 11. O-O a4
{ Black has gotten more space and will eventually place a knight on the active square on c4. The question is if it's enough to withstand our pressure on the kingside? }
12. Nc3
{ Morozov moves back to c3 now that b5 has become an available destination. It's also worth mentioning that there are no longer any worries of Qb6 like earlier. }
12... Bd7 13. Kh1
{ It always feels good to make this move as all tactics in the a7-g1 diagonal are essentially gone forever. }
13... Be7 14. Rb1
{ This is a typical engine move as the rook is better placed on b1 instead of on a1. One point is that there will never be any forks on c2 in case we decide to play Qe1. }
14... Rc8 15. Qe1 Nb4 16. Be2
{ The prophylactic 14. Rb1 shows its point! The queen is now heading to g3 when Black will be under a nasty attack. }
16... a3 17. b3 O-O 18. g4
{ The attack plays itself. Rg1-f5-Qg3 etc. Where is Black's counterplay? }
18... Rxc3
{ Desperation is how to describe this move.   18...f6  Looks like the best try if you ask me, but Black's position remains miserable after  19.exf6  Bxf6  20.Qd2  As Black can't defend the pawn on a3, for example  20...Ra8  21.Na4  Nxa4  22.bxa4  Nc6  23.Bxa3+-   18...Nc6  Defends the pawn, but it's way too passive.  19.Bd2+-  Black can only watch as he'll get destroyed on the kingside. }
19. Qxc3 Nxa2 20. Qd2 Nxc1 21. Rbxc1
{ Black has obtained the bishop pair and a passed pawn on a3, but the missing exchange is too strong. Enjoy how Morozov converts his advantage. }
21... Nc8 22. Bd3 Na7 23. g5 Nc6 24. gxh6 g6 25. Rg1 Be8 26. Qe3 Kh8 27. Rg2
Rg8 28. Rcg1 Bd7 29. Bb1 Qf8 30. Ng5 Be8 31. h4
{ The last thing required in order to win is to open Black's camp with h4-h5. }
31... Bxg5
{ This move is the same as resigning, but Black had nothing better.   31...Qxh6  Was met by  32.h5±  When White will break through. }
32. fxg5 Qb4 33. Rd2 Qe7 34. h5 Nb8 35. Rf2 Nd7 36. b4 Nf8 37. hxg6 fxg6 38.
Qxa3
{ Without the passed pawn, Black has no chances at all. The game went on for 20 more moves, but a resignation would have been very appropriate at this moment, especially with computer help! }
38... Nh7 39. Qe3 Qxb4 40. Kh2 Qe7 41. Kh3 Ba4 42. Bd3 Be8 43. Kg4
{ A funny maneuver, but an effective one. } 43... Qa3 44. Rb1 Qe7 45. Ra2 Bc6
46. Rba1 b6 47. Ra7 Qe8 48. Rc1 Qb8 49. Rxh7+ Kxh7 50. Rxc6 Kh8 51. Qc1 Qe8 52.
Qc2 b5 53. Rc7 b4 54. Bxg6 Rxg6 55. Rc8 Rg8 56. Rxe8 Rxe8 57. Qc7 Rg8 58. Kh5
b3 59. g6
{ A convincing and beautiful win by the strong correspondence player, Morozov. }
