[White "27. Model Games"]
[Black "19. Yeo, Gareth vs. Merkuriev, Vyacheslav Aleksand"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r3k2r/1b2qpp1/pnn1p2p/1pppP3/3P1PPP/PP3N2/2PQN3/R3KB1R b KQkq - 0 14"]
[SetUp "1"]

14... Rc8
{ Let's take a look at a highly instructive game between two very strong Correspondence players. Yeo is aiming to limit Black's counterplay on the queenside, essentially taking complete control over both sides of the board. After the text move, Merkuriev hopes to achieve something on the queenside. }
15. dxc5 Qxc5 16. Ned4
{ This thematic plan occurs over and over, so remember it! Note how we defend everything with the knight on d4. Merkuriev's plan has already failed big time. }
16... Qe7
{ The queen heads back as it has nothing to on c5. With the queen gone, Black might think about maneuvering the knight on b6 to c5 via d7. }
17. Qe3 Nd7 { The aforementioned plan is a fact, but easily prevented. } 18. b4
{ There's no need to allow Black to carry out that plan, despite the fact that Black gets a square on c4 for the knight. }
18... Nb6
{ Black has a square for the stallion, but unfortunately for him it's too slow! }
19. f5 Na4
{ A strange move, but  19...Nc4  is no better. After  20.Bxc4  dxc4  21.O-O-O  , our strong initiative on the kingside gives us a winning position. }
20. Bd3 Kd8 21. O-O-O { White's position is already completely dominating. }
21... Kc7 22. f6
{ Yeo sacrifices a pawn for positional domination.  22.g5  looks just as good. }
22... gxf6 23. Nxc6 Bxc6 24. exf6 Qd6
{ I suspect that most humans would play  24...Qxf6  , but after  25.Ne5  Qg7  26.Rhf1  Rhf8  27.g5  Black's position is horrendous. }
25. Qa7+ Bb7 26. Qd4
{ The knight is heading to e5 when Black will be completely tied down. } 26...
Rcf8 27. Ne5 Nb6 28. g5 { The moves come automatically... } 28... Nd7 29. Nxd7
Kxd7 30. g6 { White finally breaches Black's defenses. } 30... fxg6 31. Bxg6
Kc7
{ 31...e5  32.Qa7  Kc7  33.Rh3  Qc6  34.Rxd5  Qxd5  35.Rc3+  Kd6  36.Rd3  is a nice variation, but by no means forced. }
32. f7 e5 33. Qc3+ Bc6 34. Rhg1 { Black has zero counterplay. } 34... d4 35.
Qg3 Rd8 36. Rde1 Rhf8 37. Qxe5
{ Merkuriev resigns as his engine was showing a sky high advantage for White. It's not so hard to see why, as the f7-pawn decides the game. A strategical masterclass by Yeo! }
