1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5 Be7 5. e5 Nfd7 6. h4 Bxg5 7. hxg5 Qxg5 8.
Nh3 Qe7 9. Qg4 g6 10. Ng5 h5 11. Qf4 a6 12. O-O-O b5 13. g4 h4 14. Rd3 Nc6 15.
Rdh3
{ I pointed out in the chapter that we were doing very well here, as we regain the pawn and gain the h-file to our disposal afterwards. Let's see how Schulz handles the position. }
15... Bb7 { Black must obviously castle before it's too late. } 16. Rxh4 Rxh4
17. Rxh4 O-O-O 18. Rh7 Nxd4
{ The most sensible move, as  18...Rf8  is too passive. } 19. Rxf7 Qc5
{ Black has achieved something at least, but is it enough? } 20. Bd3 Rh8
{ Black searches for counterplay. } 21. Kd2
{ A brilliant move, with the point being } 21... Nb6 22. b3
{ Which stops Black's knight from jumping to c4. The king guards the c3-knight and is perfectly safe on d2. White is now ready to play Ne2 when Black will get huge problems on e6. The king will be just as safe on e2. }
22... Kb8 23. Qf6 Rh1 { The most active.  23...Re8  is met by  24.Ne2  . } 24.
Qe7 { Clever, forcing a queen trade. } 24... Qxe7
{ Forced, as 24... Qc6 loses the knight after 25. Qb4. } 25. Rxe7
{ Black's kingside pawns are too weak while White's kingside pawns are too strong. The endgame is lost. Schulz's technique is flawless, even back in 2008. }
25... Bc8 26. Re8 Rh4 27. Ne2 Nc6 28. f4 Ka7 29. Bxg6 Rxg4 30. Bf7 Nxe5 31.
Bxe6 Bxe6 32. Nxe6 Nc6 33. Rh8 Ne7 34. Nxc7 Kb7 35. Ne6 Nbc8 36. Rh7 Kb6 37.
N2d4 Nc6 38. Nxc6 Kxc6 39. Nd4+
