[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "27. Model Games"]
[Black "21. Korneev, Oleg vs. Jerez Perez, Alfonso"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rn2k1nr/pp3ppp/4p3/3pP3/1P1p1P2/P2P1N2/3B2PP/R2bK2R w KQkq - 0 14"]
[SetUp "1"]

14. Kxd1
{ We have established that White has a much better ending due to the space advantage and Black's passive pieces. However, the path to victory is still far away, so I thought I'd share with you how the strong GM Korneev converts his advantage. }
14... Ne7
{ 14...a6?  gives Black problems after  15.a4!  with the idea of playing Ke2-b5. Indeed, after  15...Ne7  16.Ke2  Kd7  17.b5  , White's advantage was already decisive in Neubauer, M - Testor, S Oberwart 2004. }
15. Ke2 Na6
{ Is apparently best, which speaks for itself! The usual square for the knight,  15...Nbc6  is dreadful for Black after  16.b5  . }
16. Rhc1
{ Korneev doesn't hurry with the capturing of the pawn on d4, as he can take it whenever he wants. }
16... Kd7 { Black needed to find a way to meet b5. } 17. b5 Nc7 18. a4
{ Black's position is already looking incredibly difficult to defend due to the cramped nature of the position. Notice how Korneev has slowly improved his position. }
18... f6
{ Black errors while searching for counterplay.  18...h5  was the best try, with the point of placing a knight on  f5  . Still, White is close to winning after  19.Bb4  Nf5  20.h3  h4  21.Bc5  b6  22.Bxd4  . }
19. g3
{ Korneev guards the pawn on f4 and essentially prepares to play Bb4.   However, there was no need to do so as  19.Bb4  could have been played right away as  19...Ng6  is met by  20.g3  . }
19... Rhc8
{ A natural move as Black wants to make sure that the rook stays in the game after Ne8. }
20. Bb4 Ne8
{ This makes the path to victory simple for Korneev.  20...Ng6  would maybe hold for a bit longer, but not change the result after a simple move like  21.h4  . }
21. Bxe7 { Korneev trades pieces, but gains a monstrous knight on d4. } 21...
Kxe7 22. Nxd4 { Black barely has any moves in the position. } 22... Kd7 23. Kd2
Rxc1
{ If Black waits with a move such as  23...h5  , White can play  24.Re1  when the game will more or less win by itself.  24...f5  25.Reb1  b6  26.a5  Nc7  27.Rc1  and White breaks through. }
24. Rxc1 Nc7 25. g4 { Korneev advances on the kingside. } 25... g5
{ This is basically a way to immediately resign the game.  25...h6  only prolongs the misery, as White will some day break through with a5-b6. }
26. exf6 gxf4 27. f7
{ Black can't avoid the loss of material, as Rxc7+ followed by Nxe6 and f8=Q comes. }
27... Rc8
{ Black resigned as he made the move due to the aforementioned tactic. A nice squeeze by Korneev who didn't do anything special, he only improved his position step by step. Very instructive. }
