1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e5 Ne7 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 c5 7. Qg4 Kf8 8. a4
Qa5 9. Bd2 c4 10. Qd1 Nbc6 11. Ne2 Bd7 12. Ng3 h6 13. Be2 Nd8 14. Nh5 Kg8 15.
O-O Rh7 16. f4 Kh8 17. g4
{ White is winning here as mentioned in the chapter, so technically there isn't too much to look at. However, it remains instructive to take a look at how White would eventually break through in a position like this as it may not be too apparent to the reader. }
17... Ndc6 18. Bf3
{ The bishop doesn't do anything on e2, so Haugen places it on the f3-square where it will target d5 the day f4-f5 comes. }
18... Ng8
{ Not a retreat you want to make, but Galanov wants to play g6 to get rid of the annoying knight on h5. The f6-square had to be covered before he can continue with that plan, hence the retreat. }
19. Rb1 g6 20. Ng3 Rb8 21. f5
{ Haugen has all the measures necessary to carry out this pawn break. } 21...
Qxa4 { Black's only chance. } 22. f6
{ It's time to say goodbye to the knight on g8... Paesi... Che non ho mai :@@EndBracket@@ }
22... Qa5 23. Qe1
{ A prophylactic move that gives White the option of moving the dark-squared bishop if he fancies that. }
23... Qd8 24. h4
{ The pawn chain will get even stronger by the time the g4-pawn reaches g5. }
24... a5 25. g5 h5
{ Black keeps the kingside blocked, but it won't last for long as a sacrifice on h5 is imminent. }
26. Ne2 Be8 27. Bc1
{ The bishop heads to the a3-f8 diagonal where it will take complete control over Black's queenside pawns. }
27... b5 28. Ba3 Rb7 29. Bf8
{ This move doesn't really have a purpose as Bg7+ would only help Black, but it's a funny move to make. }
29... Bd7 30. Bd6 Be8
{ Black can't do more than watch as White breaches the defenses. } 31. Nf4 a4
{ Black kills all possible queenside counterplay with this move, but the position was hopeless anyway. }
32. Bb4 Rb8 33. Qe3
{ White prepares a complete blockade of Black's pawns, which doesn't take too long to achieve. }
33... Ra8 34. Ne2 Qd7 35. Ra1 Rc8 36. Ra3 Ra8 37. Rf2 Qa7 38. Kf1 Rb8 39. Ke1
Rd8 40. Kd1 Qc7 41. Kc1 Ra8 42. Kb2 Rd8 43. Ra1 Rc8 44. Ka3
{ The king reaches its destination. Haugen is just sadistic at this point. }
44... Ra8 45. Bxh5 { The sacrifice is finally on the board. } 45... gxh5
{ 45...Rxh5  46.Nf4  Rh7  47.h5  wins easily. } 46. Nf4 Qb6 47. Rg2
{ It's only a matter of time before g5-g6 comes. } 47... Nge7 48. fxe7 Nxb4 49.
cxb4 Qc7 50. Qf3 Qxe7 51. Nxh5 f5 52. g6 Rh6 53. Rag1 Qxh4 54. g7+
{ The 2500-rated Correspondence player Galanov decides that enough is enough. }
