[White "27. Model Games"]
[Black "23. Vocaturo, Daniele vs. Hillarp Persson, Tiger"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "2kr3r/3bnp1p/p1nPp2p/2p1P3/3P4/q7/2PB1PP1/1Q2KBNR w K - 0 18"]
[SetUp "1"]

18. Rh3 Qa4 19. Rb3
{ When you turn on the engine, it says that  19.Rc3  is even better, with the point being that Black has almost no moves as  Rxc5  is coming. }
19... Nd5
{ 19...c4  is a better way to fight, but after  20.Rc3  Black is still in dire straits. }
20. dxc5 Rdg8
{ Black's rook is one move to slow... If it was Black to move in this very moment, Rg4 would have been winning. The nuances in chess! }
21. c4 { The knight perishes. } 21... Nde7 22. Ne2
{ But White doesn't take it! Instead, White aims to play Nc3 when the black queen is in trouble. }
22... Qxc4
{ The queen gets out, but the extra tempos make the assault on the king unstoppable. }
23. Nc3 Qxc5 24. Ne4 Qxe5
{ Black has regained some pawns, but it matters little as he's mated by force. }
25. dxe7 Nxe7 26. Rb8+ { A sweet combination. } 26... Qxb8 27. Bxa6+ Kc7 28.
Ba5+ Kc6 29. Qc2+ Kd5 30. Qd3+ Ke5 31. Bc3+ Kf5 32. Nd6+ Kg5 33. Qg3+ Kh5 34.
Be2+ Rg4 35. Qxg4#
{ It's very rare to see mate on the board in a GM encounter, but here it is! A truly fantastic game by the Italian, who's now a strong GM rated above 2600. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "27. Model Games"]
[Black "24. Van Assche, Jeroen vs. Trasciatti, Mirko"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e5 c5 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Qa5 7. Bd2 Qa4 8. h4
Nc6 9. h5 Nge7 10. h6 gxh6 11. Rb1 a6 12. Nf3 cxd4 13. cxd4 Nxd4 14. Bd3 Nef5
15. Rb4
{ Van Assche forces the trade of the strong knight in the center, while also making use of the fact that Black's queen doesn't have many squares available. }
15... Nxf3+ 16. Qxf3 Qxa3 17. O-O
{ White's major lead in development means that Black is lost already! } 17...
b5 { Black tries grabbing some space, but it's too late! } 18. Bc3
{ A very nice trick, using the discovered check to his advantage. White is now threatening to play Ra1 when the queen will be trapped. }
18... a5 { Is forced, as it's the only move that doesn't lose the queen. } 19.
Bxb5+ Bd7 20. Bxd7+ Kxd7 21. Rb7+ Ke8 22. Rfb1
{ Black has saved the queen, but it matters little as his king is now in big trouble. }
22... Rg8
{ 22...Rc8  23.Qh5  Rf8  24.Bd2  is also hopeless, as the pawn on  h6  falls. }
23. Qd3 { Black loses material by force due to the powerful attack. } 23... Kf8
24. Ra1
{ As a matter of fact, Black would have been better if it wasn't for this move! But it matters little... }
24... Qc5 25. Bb4
{ The trick, winning an exchange. It's easy for Van Assche to convert the advantage. }
25... axb4 26. Rxa8+ Kg7 27. Raa7 Qc4 28. Rxf7+ Kg6 29. Qh3 Qh4 30. Qxh4 Nxh4
31. f4 Kh5 32. Rg7 Rxg7 33. Rxg7 Ng6 34. f5
{ Black resigns as he must give the knight for the passer. An excellent game! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "27. Model Games"]
[Black "25. Vachier Lagrave, Maxime vs. Nepomniachtchi, Ian"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e5 c5 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Ne7 7. h4 Qc7 8. h5
h6 9. Rb1 b6 10. Qg4 Rg8 11. Bb5+ Kf8 12. Bd3 Ba6 13. dxc5 Bxd3 14. cxd3 Nd7
15. d4 bxc5 16. Qd1 Qa5
{ Black needs to get counterplay somehow, and this is the way to do so. } 17.
Bd2
{ MVL has no choice but to sacrifice the pawn on  a3  , as Nepo's pressure against  d4  would be quite annoying after for example  17.Bd2  Nc6  . }
17... Rb8
{ Another good fighting move by Nepo who aims to neutralize Maxime's pressure by trading pieces.   17...Qxa3  Grabbing the pawn on a3 is certainly possible, when Maxime has the typical compensation after  18.Ne2  Qa6  19.O-O  ±  f4-f5 or Be1-f3-Bh4 are ideas that are looming in the air while it's not entirely clear what Black is supposed to do due to his exposed king. }
18. Ne2 c4
{ We have seen in earlier chapters that Black must be careful when making this move as he completely stops his pressure against the pawn on d4. This may often make our life significantly easier as we can calmly proceed on the kingside without ever worrying about the queenside counterplay. As we shall see, this is the case in this very position.   18...Rxb1  19.Qxb1  Qa6  Is what the engine wants to do, as it's not possible for White to castle.  20.a4  White maintains some pressure as the capture of the pawn would make it possible to castle, while a waiting move would give White a better ending after Qb5. A sample line is:  20...f6!  21.exf6  Nxf6  22.dxc5  Kf7  Black has obtained some counterplay as the rook is free to move on the board, but is still under pressure after  23.Rh4  Rc8  24.Rb4  When an entry on b7 will follow suit. }
19. O-O
{ MVL peacefully castles as Black no longer has the annoying Qa6 or pressure against d4. }
19... Rb6 20. Qc2
{ Maxime improves his position by coordinating his pieces. Also, f4-f5 is now supported by the queen, while even an entry on h7 could be playable in some lines. }
20... Rh8
{ This move characterizes the position well as Nepo has no idea what to do.   20...Nb8  Makes some sense as Black intends to place the knight on c6, but the position is still far from impressive after  21.Rxb6  axb6  22.a4  Nbc6  23.Bc1  The bishop is heading to the strong a3-f8 diagonal.  23...Ke8  24.Ba3  Kd7  Is a necessary defense, when I found  25.Ra1  Ra8  26.Qb1  Qa6  27.f4±  White is close to winning as g4-f5 or even Qh7 comes next. Black has nothing in the a-file. }
21. a4
{ Maxime carries out the standard plan of rerouting the bishop to the a3-f8 diagonal. A plan you hopefully recognize! }
21... Ke8 22. Rb4
{ Strong, but he also could have taken on b6 right away followed by Bc1-Ba3. }
22... Nc6 23. f4 { Maxime completely ignores the threat. A very nice move. }
23... Ne7
{ Nepo heads back to stop f4-f5.   23...Nxb4?  Would quickly lead to a defeat for Nepo after  24.cxb4  Qa6  25.b5  Qb7  26.f5+-  When Black gets slaughtered on the kingside. Also, Ba5 is a threat which would eliminate Black's material edge. }
24. Rfb1
{ Maxime takes over the b-file. Slow improvement, there's no need to rush! }
24... f5 { Nepo stops f4-f5 at all cost. } 25. Rb5 Qa6 26. Bc1
{ It's finally time to place the bishop in the juicy diagonal. } 26... Kf7 27.
Ba3
{ Maxime has slowly improved his position, but the question is how to break through? }
27... Rhb8 28. Bxe7 Kxe7 29. g4
{ This is the way. With the knight gone from e7, Black can't keep the kingside intact. This means the end for the pawns on the kingside, as the queen will soon be ready to collect them. }
29... Rxb5 30. axb5 Rxb5 31. gxf5
{ 31.Rxb5  As Edouard points out, this would be an error as Black has very good drawing chances after  31...Qxb5  32.gxf5  Qb3± }
31... Rxb1+ 32. Qxb1 exf5 33. Ng3
{ The pawn on f5 perishes, meaning that Black's defenses are essentially breached. The pawns are too weak. }
33... Qb6 34. Nxf5+ Kf8 35. Qa1
{ Avoiding the queen trade while pressuring Black's a7-pawn. } 35... Qe6
{ Nepo's only chance of counterplay is to enter the kingside, but a simple knight jump takes care of everything. }
36. Ng3
{ The knight covers h5 while the knight can be defended by the king. Also, the knight is a very strong shield meaning that Black won't get anywhere close to a threefold. }
36... Qg4 37. Kg2 Qxf4 38. Qxa7 { Black's defense finally crumbles. } 38... Ke7
39. Qa3+ Kd8 40. Qd6 g5 41. hxg6 h5 42. g7
{ Nepo throws in the towel, meaning that MVL had gotten an excellent start to the event after a well played game! However, Nepo struck back and won the event in the end, becoming a contender for the World Champion title! }
*

